const DATA={"questions": [{"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a problem situation regarding a construction loan that might be concealed using change orders?", "options": {"A": "The original project is not feasible.", "B": "Collusive bidding is occurring.", "C": "Shortcuts are shoring up other problems.", "D": "Design changes were requested."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Change orders are often submitted along with draw requests. Although many times the change orders represent legitimate construction changes (for design, cost, or other things), they can also be indicators of fraud schemes. For example, an increasing trend in the number of change orders or amounts on change orders might be an indication that construction changes have taken place that would alter the originally planned project to such an extent as to render the underwriting inappropriate. Change orders might have the same impact on a project as altering the original documents. As with anything that is contracted for on a bid basis, change orders could also be an indication of collusive bidding. Furthermore, change orders might be an indication that the original project was not feasible and that shortcuts are shoring up other problem areas. Change orders should be approved by the architect and engineer on the project in addition to the lender's inspector."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Which of the following is an example of an off-book fraud?", "options": {"A": "Cash larceny", "B": "Skimming", "C": "Ghost employee schemes", "D": "Billing schemes"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Skimming is the removal of cash from a victim entity prior to its entry in an accounting system. Employees who skim from their companies steal sales or receivables before they are recorded in the company books. Because of this aspect of their nature, skimming schemes are known as off-book frauds; they leave no direct audit trail. Cash larceny, billing schemes, and ghost employee schemes all involve the misappropriation of cash that has already been recorded on the victim's books."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Real estate scams are easily recognized, as there is almost always an element of time pressure or \"now-or-never\" pitch from the perpetrator.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Real estate scams are easily recognized. There is almost always an element of time pressure, with the victims being convinced they are participating in a “once-in-a-lifetime, now-or-never” deal.  Perpetrators mislead victims into thinking they will miss the opportunity to make a fortune if they do not act fast."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is an information security goal that an e-commerce system should endeavor to meet for its users and asset holders?", "options": {"A": "Exactness", "B": "Access authority", "C": "Non-repudiation", "D": "Systems reliability"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Non-repudiation is an information security goal that an e-commerce system should strive to provide its users and asset holders. It refers to a method used to guarantee that the parties involved in an e-commerce transaction cannot repudiate (deny) participation in that transaction. Non-repudiation is obtained through the use of digital signatures, confirmation services, and timestamps. Additional information security goals that should be achieved to ensure the security of information systems for users and account holders include: Confidentiality of data Integrity of data Availability of data Authentication"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Which of the following real estate loan schemes would be best described as an air loan?", "options": {"A": "A loan applicant falsifies his income sources to qualify for a mortgage.", "B": "A fraudster files fraudulent property transfer documents with the property owner’s forged signature, and then takes out a loan using the property as collateral.", "C": "A property developer applying for a loan submits instances of previous development experience that are fictitious or that he had no part in.", "D": "A builder, in collusion with an appraiser and other real estate insiders, fraudulently applies for a loan to construct a building on a nonexistent property and keeps the proceeds."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "An air loan is a loan for a nonexistent property—with air symbolizing the loan’s fraudulent absence of collateral. Most or all of the documentation is fabricated, including the borrower, the property ownership documents, and the appraisal. This type of scheme involves a high level of collusion, and perpetrators might have even set up a fictitious office with people pretending to be participants in the transaction, such as the borrower’s employer, the appraiser, and the credit agency. Usually, air loans go into early payment default. Since there are no actual properties on which to foreclose, the losses on these loans can be enormous."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Shredding sensitive documents with a cross-cut shredder, sending and receiving mail at a secure site, and employing a perimeter security system at the office are all measures aimed to do which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Prevent misappropriation of office supplies.", "B": "Protect digital documentation.", "C": "Catch a fraudster in the act.", "D": "Guard manual file systems."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Organizations must take reasonable measures to protect manual file systems, which are composed of all human-readable files and documents. These include items like contact lists, schedules, and calendars. To attack a manual file system, an information thief might pilfer trash, act as a cleaning crew member, or commit theft or burglary. Reasonable measures to protect manual file systems include the following: Place sensitive documents in high-grade locked filing cabinets. It is advisable to lock sensitive documents in a safe when not in use. Use a cross-cut shredder for sensitive documentary waste, or have sensitive trash disposed of by a bonded waste-disposal company. Receive and send mail at a secure site (e.g., mail drops, post office boxes, or locked mailboxes). The key is that the site remains secure. Provide reasonable perimeter security for offices by using an alarm system and securing locks to doors and windows. Pay attention to securing auxiliary materials."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "All of the following are correct statements about identity theft EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Identity thieves often engage in pretexting by impersonating the victim’s bank.", "B": "Solicitations for pre-approved credit cards are especially valuable to identity thieves.", "C": "The type of malware most commonly associated with identity theft is ransomware.", "D": "One way to conceal identity theft is to change the victim’s mailing address."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Identity thieves use malware to steal personal and business information from computers. The type of malware most commonly associated with identity theft is spyware, software that collects and reports information about a computer user without the user’s knowledge or consent. Dumpster diving can yield bills, credit card receipts, bank statements, and other items that contain a person’s name, address, and telephone number. Solicitations for pre-approved credit cards are especially valuable to identity thieves, but even nonfinancial information can be useful. Another way to obtain personal or business information is to surreptitiously change the victim’s mailing address (or email address) to an address selected by the identity thief. In this way, the identity thief receives the victim’s mail directly, and no theft is required. Identity thieves often engage in pretexting by impersonating the victim’s bank or another financial institution with which the victim has a business relationship."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a symptom that might indicate a malware infection?", "options": {"A": "A system’s files are erased with no warning.", "B": "Excessive pop-up windows appear without cause.", "C": "Several system programs launch automatically at startup.", "D": "Unexplained changes to the system’s memory occur."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Detecting malware might be as simple as reading a message on the screen, but some malware goes undetected. The following are some symptoms that might indicate a malware infection: The system suddenly, and for no apparent reason, slows down its response time to commands. The computer stops responding or locks up frequently. The computer crashes and then restarts every few minutes. The computer restarts on its own. The computer does not run as usual. The computer experiences a sudden and sometimes dramatic decrease of free space. The size of some files increases. The operating system or other programs and applications begin behaving in unpredictable ways. Files cannot be accessed or are suddenly erased with no warning. There has been a change in the length of executable files, a change in their content, or a change in their file date or timestamps. Disks or disk drives are inaccessible. An attachment that was recently opened has a double extension, such as a .jpg, .vbs, .gif, or .exe extension. The system does not boot up. There are unusual graphics and messages. The user cannot access a hard disk drive. There are unexplained and repeated maintenance repairs. There are unexplained changes to memory. System or data files disappear or become fragmented. Items cannot be printed correctly. Unusual error messages appear. Menus and dialog boxes are distorted. New icons, which are not associated with any new programs, appear on the desktop. Programs experience unexplained changes in size. Antivirus program is disabled for no reason."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a type of physical access control device that can be used to control access to physical objects?", "options": {"A": "Electronic access cards", "B": "Profiling software", "C": "Locks and keys", "D": "Biometric systems"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "There are various types of physical access control devices that can be used to control access to physical objects. Some common types of physical access control devices include: Locks and keys Electronic access cards Biometric systems Profiling software is a type of logical access control device that authenticates users by monitoring their statistical characteristics, such as typing speed and keystroke touch."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Mario, an employee of a person-to-person payment company, has been writing down the account numbers and passwords of customer accounts with the intent of fraudulently using them to pay for items he purchases online. Mario is engaging in:", "options": {"A": "Check fraud", "B": "Credit card fraud", "C": "EFT fraud", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Mario is committing an electronic funds transfer (EFT) scheme by misappropriating customers’ account and password information. There are several ways in which fraud can be perpetrated through the electronic transfer of funds. Potential sources of fraud include the following: A biller might send a bill for services not rendered or for goods never sent. A person who has obtained information about another person’s bank account might instruct a biller to obtain payment from the other person’s account. A hacker might obtain passwords and usernames from an aggregator and use that information to direct transfers from a consumer’s bank account. An employee at the site providing electronic bill payment services who knows consumers’ usernames and passwords for screen-scraping purposes might use that information to direct transfers from consumers’ bank accounts. A bank employee might use customer information to direct transfers from a customer’s account."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Like most other types of fraud, the motivation for financial statement fraud almost always involves personal gain.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Unlike some other types of fraud (such as embezzlement), the motivation for financial statement fraud does not always involve personal gain. Most commonly, financial statement fraud is used to make a company’s earnings appear better on paper. Financial statement fraud occurs through a variety of methods, such as valuation judgments and manipulating the timing of transaction recording. These more subtle types of fraud are often dismissed as either mistakes or errors in judgment and estimation. Some of the more common reasons why people commit financial statement fraud include: To encourage investment through the sale of stock To demonstrate increased earnings per share or partnership profits interest, thus allowing increased dividend/distribution payouts To cover inability to generate cash flow To avoid negative market perceptions To obtain financing, or to obtain more favorable terms on existing financing To receive higher purchase prices for acquisitions To demonstrate compliance with financing covenants To meet company goals and objectives To receive performance-related bonuses"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Pass-through schemes are usually undertaken by employees who receive inventory on the victim company's behalf.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Pass-through schemes are usually undertaken by employees in charge of purchasing on the victim company's behalf. Instead of buying merchandise directly from a vendor, the employee sets up a shell company and purchases the merchandise through that fictitious entity. He then resells the merchandise to his employer from the shell company at an inflated price, thereby making an unauthorized profit on the transaction."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "question": "Jeremy is involved in an automobile accident but does not have insurance. To be reimbursed for the damages, he gets insurance, waits a short time, and then reports the vehicle as having been in an accident. He has committed an insurance scam known as _____________.", "options": {"A": "Past posting", "B": "Ditching", "C": "Churning", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Past posting is a scheme in which a person becomes involved in an automobile accident but does not have insurance. After the accident, the person gets insurance, waits a short time, and then reports the vehicle as having been damaged in some manner, thus collecting for the earlier loss."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "_________ is an attack in which a user is fooled into entering sensitive data into a malicious website that imitates a legitimate website.", "options": {"A": "Pharming", "B": "Spear phishing", "C": "Phishing", "D": "SMiShing"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Pharming is an attack in which a user is fooled into entering sensitive data (such as a password or credit card number) into a malicious website that imitates a legitimate website. It is different from phishing in that the attacker in a pharming scheme does not have to rely on having the user click on a link in an email or other message to direct him to the imitation website."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Which of the following is a recommended step that individuals should take to protect themselves from identity theft?", "options": {"A": "Use passwords that are at least eight characters long", "B": "Create unique answers for security questions", "C": "Limit personal information shared on social media", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following are some of the steps individuals can take to protect their personal information and prevent identity theft: Do not give out government identification numbers unless absolutely necessary. Do not carry government identification cards (or numbers) in purses or wallets. Create complex passwords or passphrases that are at least eight characters in length and contain upper- and lower-case letters, numbers, and symbols. Do not reuse passwords. Use a different password for every website, account, or device. Never send personal information, such as a password or government identification number, via email. Reputable organizations will not request personal information by email. When available, use biometric authentication (e.g., fingerprints, voice recognition). Create unique answers for security questions. Do not choose answers containing personal information that is publicly available (e.g., name of high school, mother’s maiden name). Protect computers with strong and regularly updated firewall and antivirus software, and promptly install all security updates and patches. Avoid suspicious websites. Delete messages from unknown senders without opening them. Only download software from trusted websites. Avoid using unsecured, public Wi-Fi networks. Limit the amount of personal information shared on social media. Use software to permanently erase all data from hard drives before disposing of computers, smartphones, copiers, printers, and other electronic devices. Secure physical mailboxes with a lock, check physical mail regularly, and instruct the post office to suspend mail during vacations. Shred all sensitive documents. Opt out of unsolicited offers for pre-approved credit cards or other lines of credit. Pay attention to billing cycles and review all bills and statements. Check credit reports regularly."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a red flag of a procurement fraud scheme in which vendors are colluding to circumvent the competitive bidding process?", "options": {"A": "Qualified contractors do not submit bids", "B": "The winning bidder subcontracts work to losing bidders", "C": "Some bids do not meet the requirements of the solicitation documents", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Common red flags of procurement fraud schemes involving collusion among contractors include: The industry has limited competition. The same contractors bid on each project or product. The winning bid appears too high. All contractors submit consistently high bids. Qualified contractors do not submit bids. The winning bidder subcontracts work to one or more losing bidders or to non-bidders. Bids appear to be complementary bids by companies unqualified to perform the work. Some bids fail to conform to the essential requirements of the solicitation documents (i.e., some bids do not comply with bid specifications). Some losing bids were poorly prepared. Fewer competitors than usual submit bids on a project or product. When a new contractor enters the competition, the bid prices begin to fall. There is a rotational pattern to winning bidders (e.g., geographical, customer, job, or type of work). There is evidence of collusion in the bids (e.g., bidders make the same mathematical or spelling errors; bids are prepared using the same typeface, handwriting, stationery, or envelope; or competitors submit identical bids). There is a pattern where the last party to bid wins the contract. There are patterns of conduct by bidders or their employees that suggest the possibility of collusion (e.g., competitors regularly socialize, hold meetings, visit each other’s offices, or subcontract with each other)."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following best describes phishing?", "options": {"A": "A method for acquiring sensitive information by falsely claiming through electronic communication to be from an entity with which the target does business", "B": "A method for acquiring sensitive information needed to facilitate a specific scheme by searching through large quantities of available data", "C": "A method for acquiring sensitive information in which an attacker hides near the target to gain unauthorized access to a computer system", "D": "A method for acquiring sensitive information by bypassing a computer system’s security through the use of an undocumented operating system and network functions"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Phishing is a type of social engineering scheme that involves impersonating a trusted individual or entity. Generally, phishers manipulate victims into providing sensitive information by falsely claiming to be from an actual business, bank, Internet service provider (ISP), or other entity with which the target does business. In these schemes, phishers typically use emails to direct Internet users to websites that look like legitimate e-commerce websites, such as online banks, retailers, or government agencies. Phishers control these imitation websites and use them to steal sensitive information, such as bank account details and passwords."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "When an employee or official uses force or fear to demand money in exchange for making a particular business decision, that individual is engaging in:", "options": {"A": "Bribery", "B": "A kickback scheme", "C": "An illegal gratuity scheme", "D": "Economic extortion"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Extortion is defined as the obtaining of property from another, with the other party’s consent induced by wrongful use of actual or threatened force or fear. Economic extortion is present when an employee or official, through the wrongful use of actual or threatened force or fear, demands money or some other consideration to make a particular business decision. Thus, an example of an economic extortion scheme is if an employee or government official demands money in exchange for making a business decision. Similarly, if a politician threatens to shut down a business if it does not pay a bribe, this is also an example of an economic extortion scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding the methods typically used for making corrupt payments in bribery and corruption schemes?", "options": {"A": "Payers often make corrupt payments by offering recipients loans on extremely favorable terms", "B": "Payers often make corrupt payments by selling property to recipients at prices lower than the property’s market value", "C": "Payers often make corrupt payments by paying off the recipient’s credit card debt", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Corrupt payments often take the form of loans. Three types of loans often turn up in fraud cases: An outright payment that is falsely described as an innocent loan A legitimate loan in which a third party—the corrupt payer—makes or guarantees payments to satisfy the loan A legitimate loan made on favorable terms (e.g., an interest-free loan) A corrupt payment can be in the form of credit card use or payments toward a party’s credit card debt. The payer might use a credit card to pay a recipient’s transportation, vacation, or entertainment expenses, or the payer might pay off a recipient’s credit card debt. In some instances, the recipient might carry and use the corrupt payer’s credit card. Corrupt payments also might come in the form of promises of favorable treatment. In addition, corrupt payments might occur in the form of transfers for a value other than fair market. In such transfers, the corrupt payer might sell or lease property to the recipient at a price that is less than its market value, or the payer might agree to buy or rent property from the recipient at an inflated price. The recipient might also “sell” an asset to the payer but retain the title or use of the property."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding the methods typically used for making corrupt payments in bribery and corruption schemes?", "options": {"A": "Payers often make corrupt payments by offering recipients loans on extremely favorable terms", "B": "Payers often make corrupt payments by selling property to recipients at prices lower than the property’s market value", "C": "Payers often make corrupt payments by paying off the recipient’s credit card debt", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Corrupt payments often take the form of loans. Three types of loans often turn up in fraud cases: An outright payment that is falsely described as an innocent loan A legitimate loan in which a third party—the corrupt payer—makes or guarantees payments to satisfy the loan A legitimate loan made on favorable terms (e.g., an interest-free loan) A corrupt payment can be in the form of credit card use or payments toward a party’s credit card debt. The payer might use a credit card to pay a recipient’s transportation, vacation, or entertainment expenses, or the payer might pay off a recipient’s credit card debt. In some instances, the recipient might carry and use the corrupt payer’s credit card. Corrupt payments also might come in the form of promises of favorable treatment. In addition, corrupt payments might occur in the form of transfers for a value other than fair market. In such transfers, the corrupt payer might sell or lease property to the recipient at a price that is less than its market value, or the payer might agree to buy or rent property from the recipient at an inflated price. The recipient might also “sell” an asset to the payer but retain the title or use of the property."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "It is considered acceptable practice to deviate from generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) in which of the following circumstances?", "options": {"A": "It is common practice in the industry to give particular transactions a specific accounting treatment", "B": "Adherence to GAAP would produce misleading results", "C": "There is concern that assets or income would be overstated", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The question of when it is appropriate to stray from generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) is a matter of professional judgment; there is no clear-cut set of circumstances that justify such a departure. It can be assumed that adherence to GAAP almost always results in financial statements that are fairly presented. However, the standard-setting bodies recognize that, upon occasion, there might be an unusual circumstance when the literal application of GAAP would render the financial statements misleading. In these cases, a departure from GAAP is the proper accounting treatment. Departures from GAAP can be justified in the following circumstances: It is common practice in the entity’s industry for a transaction to be reported in a particular way. The substance of the transaction is better reflected (and, therefore, the financial statements are more fairly presented) by not strictly following GAAP. If a transaction is considered immaterial (i.e., it would not affect a decision made by a prudent reader of the financial statements), then it need not be reported. There is concern that assets or income would be overstated and expenses or liabilities would be understated (the conservatism constraint requires that when there is any doubt, one should avoid overstating assets and income or understating expenses and liabilities). The results of departure appear reasonable under the circumstances, especially when strict adherence to GAAP will produce misleading financial statements and the departure is properly disclosed."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Research and development personnel often inadvertently divulge confidential information through which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Articles written for industry journals", "B": "Discussions with colleagues at conferences", "C": "Hiring outside academic professionals", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Often, intelligence professionals target research and development (R&D) employees because their positions generally involve the communication of information. For example, many R&D employees attend or participate in trade shows, conferences, or other industry functions where it is common to network with other professionals in their field and exchange ideas. Such events provide intelligence spies with the opportunity to learn key product- or project-related details simply by listening to a presentation or asking the right questions. R&D employees’ publications are also a good source of information for intelligence professionals. Researchers sometimes inadvertently include sensitive project details when writing articles about their findings for industry journals or other mediums. This is particularly true in the case of academic professionals who might be hired by a company to perform research or conduct a study. If a company hires an academician to conduct research, management must ensure that the academician understands the need to keep the results confidential. In addition, management must make sure that the academician’s use of teaching assistants or graduate students is kept to a minimum and that those individuals understand the confidentiality requirements."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "When looking at a set of financial statements, on which statement would you find notes payable, current assets, retained earnings, and accumulated depreciation?", "options": {"A": "Statement of changes in owners’ equity", "B": "Balance sheet", "C": "Statement of cash flows", "D": "Income statement"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Notes payable, current assets, retained earnings, and accumulated depreciation can all be found on the balance sheet. The balance sheet is an expansion of the accounting equation, Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity. That is, it lists a company’s assets on one side and its liabilities and owners’ equity on the other side. Assets are classified as either current or noncurrent. Current assets consist of cash or other liquid assets that are expected to be converted to cash, sold, or used up, usually within a year or less. Current assets listed on the balance sheet include cash, accounts receivable, inventory, supplies, and prepaid expenses. Following the current assets are the long-term assets, or those assets that will likely not be converted to cash within one year, such as fixed assets and intangible assets. A company’s fixed assets are presented net of accumulated depreciation, an amount that represents the cumulative expense taken for normal wear and tear on a company’s property. Liabilities are presented in order of maturity. Like current assets, current liabilities are those obligations that are expected to be paid within one year, such as accounts payable (the amount owed to vendors by a company for purchases on credit), accrued expenses (e.g., taxes payable or salaries payable), and the portion of long-term debts that will come due within the next year. Those liabilities that are not due for more than a year are listed under the heading long-term liabilities. The most common liabilities in this group are bonds, notes, and mortgages payable."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "How does vertical analysis differ from horizontal analysis?", "options": {"A": "Vertical analysis expresses the percentage of component items to a specific base item, while horizontal analysis analyzes the percentage change in individual financial statement items from one year to the next.", "B": "Vertical analysis compares items on one financial statement to items on a different financial statement, while horizontal analysis compares items on the same financial statement.", "C": "Vertical analysis is a means of measuring the relationship between any two different financial statement amounts, whereas horizontal analysis examines the relationship between specific financial statement ratios.", "D": "Vertical analysis compares the performance of a parent company to its subsidiary, while horizontal analysis compares different companies across an industry."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Vertical analysis is the expression of the relationship or percentage of component items to a specific base item on the income statement or balance sheet. Horizontal analysis is a technique for analyzing the percentage change in individual financial statement items from one year to the next. Ratio analysis is a means of measuring the relationship between any two different financial statement amounts. The relationship and comparison are the keys to any of these types of financial analyses."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE regarding the balance sheet?", "options": {"A": "The balance sheet shows the financial performance of a company over a certain period of time, such as a quarter or a year.", "B": "Assets are generally presented on the balance sheet in order of liquidity.", "C": "The accounts that appear on the balance sheet include revenues and expenses.", "D": "Balance sheets are usually manipulated by understating assets or overstating liabilities."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The balance sheet, or statement of financial position, shows a “snapshot” of a company’s financial situation at a specific point in time, generally the last day of the accounting period. The balance sheet is an expansion of the accounting equation, Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity. That is, it lists a company’s assets on one side and its liabilities and owners’ equity on the other side. Assets are the resources owned by a company. Generally, assets are presented on the balance sheet in order of liquidity (i.e., how soon they are expected to be converted to cash). Generally, in a financial statement fraud scheme, the balance sheet is manipulated to appear stronger by overstating assets and/or understating liabilities."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Implementing privilege escalation and using buffer overflow exploits are examples of administrative controls used for securing computer systems and communication networks.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Computer networks and communications are inherently insecure and vulnerable to attack and disruption. Consequently, management must use technical and administrative controls to protect systems against threats like unauthorized use, disclosure, modification, destruction, or denial of service. Technical security involves the use of safeguards incorporated in computer hardware, operations or applications software, communications hardware and software, and related devices. Administrative security involves the use of tools to provide an acceptable level of protection for computing resources. Common technical and administrative controls used to secure computer systems and communication networks include: Logical access controls Network security Operating system security Encryption Application security Separation of duties Buffer overflows and privilege escalation are not controls to prevent computer fraud. Rather, they are both methods of exploiting design flaws in computer systems to gain unauthorized access."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Not every company that runs its business using a pyramid structure is operating an illegal pyramid scheme.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Not all organizations with a pyramid structure are engaging in illegal activity. Some legitimate merchandising companies use a pyramid structure to rank their employee-owners and to determine those people’s compensation. A pyramid structure becomes an illegal pyramid scheme when the recruitment of new members takes precedence over the product or service that the company is ostensibly promoting. The more members that are recruited, the higher the investor is purported to rise in the ranks of the enterprise, and the more money the investor is supposed to make."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "The type of fraud that targets groups of people who have some social connection, such as neighborhoods of racial minorities or immigrant groups, is known as:", "options": {"A": "Consolation", "B": "Affinity fraud", "C": "Reloading", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Affinity fraud targets groups of individuals who have some social connection. Neighborhoods chiefly populated by racial minorities, especially immigrant groups, are often the site of affinity frauds, and the elderly and language minorities are frequent targets as well. In addition, religious and professional ties are often exploited."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Which of the following scenarios is an example of a kickback scheme?", "options": {"A": "A politician threatens to shut down a business if it does not pay a bribe", "B": "A government official demands money in exchange for making a business decision", "C": "A vendor inflates the amount of an invoice submitted to the company for payment", "D": "An employee receives a payment for directing excess business to a vendor"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Kickbacks are improper, undisclosed payments made to obtain favorable treatment. Thus, an employee who receives a payment for directing excess business to a vendor is an example of a kickback scheme. In such cases, there might not be any overbilling involved; the vendor simply pays the kickbacks to ensure a steady stream of business from the purchasing company. Extortion is defined as the obtaining of property from another, with the other party’s consent induced by wrongful use of actual or threatened force or fear. Economic extortion is present when an employee or official, through the wrongful use of actual or threatened force or fear, demands money or some other consideration to make a particular business decision. Thus, an example of an economic extortion scheme is if a government official demands money in exchange for making a business decision. Similarly, if a politician threatens to shut down a business if it does not pay a bribe, this is also an example of an economic extortion scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "White, an employee of ABC Corporation, intentionally issued two payments for the same invoice. After the checks had been mailed, White called the vendor and explained that a double payment had been made by mistake. She asked the vendor to return one of the checks to her attention. When the vendor returned the check, White took it and cashed it. This is an example of:", "options": {"A": "A shell company scheme", "B": "A receivables skimming scheme", "C": "A pay and return scheme", "D": "A pass-through scheme"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Instead of using shell companies in their overbilling schemes, some employees generate fraudulent disbursements by using the invoices of legitimate third-party vendors who are not a part of the fraud scheme. In a pay and return scheme, an employee intentionally mishandles payments that are owed to legitimate vendors. One way to do this is to purposely double-pay an invoice. For instance, a clerk might intentionally pay an invoice twice and then call the vendor and request that one of the checks be returned. The clerk then intercepts the returned check."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Katie is a sales clerk at a jewelry store. She watched another sales clerk, Helen, type her access code into her register and memorized it. When Helen called in sick, Katie logged in to the cash register using Helen’s code and processed customer transactions as usual. After completing one sale, she left the drawer open and slipped a large sum of money into her pocket from the register drawer. What type of scheme did she commit?", "options": {"A": "An understated sales scheme", "B": "A skimming scheme", "C": "A register disbursement scheme", "D": "A cash larceny scheme"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In some retail organizations, there is one cash register and each employee has a different access code. By using someone else’s access code to enter the register and then steal cash under their name, the perpetrator makes sure that another employee will be the prime suspect in the theft. Katie’s theft was not a skimming scheme because the cash she stole was already in the company’s possession and recorded in the register. An understated sales scheme is a type of skimming scheme in which a fraudster records a sale for less than it actually is and skims the difference. Katie did not commit a register disbursement scheme because register disbursement schemes involve a fraudulent transaction that justifies the removal of cash from the register, such as a false return or a voided sale. Katie did not make any entry that would account for the missing money—she simply took money out of the register under Helen’s name so that she could avoid blame. Therefore, Katie committed a cash larceny scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Harold, a medical provider, is compensated based on each service that he provides to patients. Which of the following best describes this method of compensation?", "options": {"A": "Capitation", "B": "Episode-of-care", "C": "Salary", "D": "Fee-for-service"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There are several types of reimbursements for providers: fee-for-service, capitation, episode-of-care, and salary. Each has advantages and disadvantages from an anti-fraud perspective. Fee-for-service reimbursement occurs when providers receive payment for each service rendered. The disadvantage of fee-for-service payment is that it creates an incentive for providers to increase their compensation by performing excess and unnecessary services. However, providers tend to like this payment system because it gives them wide discretion in selecting the services that meet the patient’s needs. Capitation is a reimbursement method in which providers receive one lump sum for each patient that they treat, regardless of how many services the provider renders. While this method avoids some of the incentives for providers to perform unnecessary services, it might give providers a reason to focus on the quantity of patients they see rather than the quality of service. Additionally, capitation does little to stop schemes involving fictitious patients. Episode-of-care reimbursement is a health care payment method in which providers receive one lump sum for all the services they provide related to a condition or disease (as opposed to capitation, which is a lump sum per patient). This method captures some of the benefits of capitation by removing incentives to provide unnecessary services, but it is also (in theory) more fair to providers than capitation because it compensates them more when multiple health issues are treated. When governments directly operate health care facilities, it is common to pay providers a basic salary rather than offer service-based compensation. Even so, some medical services might be provided through contractors instead of government employees."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Excessive write-offs are a form of concealment for which of the following schemes?", "options": {"A": "Phantom loans", "B": "Embezzlement", "C": "Conflicts of interest", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Excessive write-offs are a form of concealment for phantom loans, conflicts of interest, and embezzlement. Therefore, if all write-offs are subject to management review before they are written off, then management reduces the potential environment for fraud."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "___________ is the deliberate scrambling of a message so that it is unreadable except to those who hold the key for unscrambling the message.", "options": {"A": "Alteration of input", "B": "Customer validation", "C": "Encryption", "D": "Firewall security"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Encryption is one of the most effective methods of protecting networks and communications against attacks. Encryption is the deliberate scrambling of a message so that it is unreadable except to those who hold the key for unscrambling the message. Any confidential information or credit card numbers should be encrypted in their entirety."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Pam is the purchasing manager at a retail store. She decides to form her own shell company and purchase merchandise through this entity. She then sells the merchandise to her employer at an inflated price as if she were a legitimate vendor. What type of scheme is Pam committing?", "options": {"A": "A pay and return scheme", "B": "A cash larceny scheme", "C": "A pass-through scheme", "D": "A need recognition scheme"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Pass-through schemes are usually undertaken by employees in charge of purchasing on the victim company's behalf. Instead of buying merchandise directly from a vendor, the employee sets up a shell company and purchases the merchandise through that fictitious entity. He then resells the merchandise to his employer from the shell company at an inflated price, thereby making an unauthorized profit on the transaction."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a method that is used to conceal inventory shrinkage?", "options": {"A": "Selling merchandise without recording the sale", "B": "Writing off stolen inventory as scrap", "C": "Placing empty boxes on warehouse shelves", "D": "Performing a forced reconciliation of the inventory records"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Some fraudsters try to make it appear that there are more assets present in the warehouse or stockroom than there actually are by physically padding the inventory. In one case, employees stole liquor from their stockroom and restacked the containers for the missing merchandise. This made it appear that the missing inventory was present when in fact there were really empty boxes on the stockroom shelves. Another method would be to fill boxes with bricks or other inexpensive materials and stack the boxes on warehouse shelves. One of the simplest methods for concealing shrinkage is to decrease the perpetual inventory record so that it matches the physical inventory count. This is also known as a forced reconciliation of the account. Basically, the perpetrator just changes the numbers in the perpetual inventory to make them match the amount of inventory on hand. Writing off inventory as obsolete, damaged, or unsellable is also a relatively common way for fraudsters to remove assets from the books before or after they are stolen. This is beneficial to the fraudster because it eliminates the problem of shrinkage that inherently exists in every case of noncash asset misappropriation. Selling merchandise without recording the sale would actually increase the amount of shrinkage on a company's books because the physical inventory would be depleted without a corresponding adjustment to the perpetual inventory."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "High percentages of returns, missing compliance certificates, and evidence of falsified test inspection results are red flags of which of the following procurement fraud scenarios?", "options": {"A": "A contractor delivering goods or services that do not conform to the contract specifications", "B": "Two or more competing contractors agreeing to refrain from bidding", "C": "A procuring employee manipulating the bidding process to benefit a favored contractor", "D": "A contractor charging the procuring entity for labor costs that are not allowable"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Nonconforming goods or services fraud, also known as product substitution or failure to meet contract specifications, refers to attempts by contractors to deliver goods or services to the procuring entity that do not conform to the underlying contract specifications. Once contractors deliver goods that do not conform to the contract, they bill and receive payment for conforming goods or services without informing the purchaser of the deficiency. The following is a list of potential red flags for nonconforming schemes: High percentage of returns for noncompliance with specifications Missing, altered, or modified product compliance certificate Compliance certificates signed by employees with no quality assurance responsibilities Materials testing done by supplier, using the supplier’s own personnel and facilities Evidence that test or inspection results were falsified (e.g., documents appear altered or modified, test documents are illegible, signatures on documents are illegible, documents were signed by unqualified or inappropriate personnel, or test reports are similar or identical to sample descriptions and test results) Highest profit product lines have the highest number of material return authorizations or reshipments Discrepancy between product’s description or normal appearance and actual appearance (e.g., a new product appears to be used) Used, surplus, or reworked parts are delivered Delivery of products that appear counterfeit (e.g., product packaging, appearance, and description do not appear genuine; items that are consistently defaced in the same area; items that appear different from each other) Offers by contractors to select the sample and prepare it for testing Delivery of look-alike goods Unusually high number of early replacements Contractor restricts or avoids inspections of goods or services upon delivery"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Debits increase asset and liability accounts.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Entries to the left side of an account are referred to as debits, and entries to the right side of an account are referred to as credits. Debits increase asset and expense accounts, whereas credits decrease these accounts. On the other side of the equation, credits increase liabilities, revenue, and owners’ equity accounts. Conversely, debits decrease liabilities, revenues, and owners’ equity. While debits do in fact increase assets, they reduce liabilities."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Jill is an accountant who needs to satisfy continuing professional education (CPE) requirements throughout the year to maintain her professional license. Her supervisor usually signs off on these requests without paying them much attention or scrutiny. Wanting to use this to her advantage, Jill figures out that it would be easy to copy the image of the logo from a popular CPE provider and generate a receipt using basic computer software. She creates a fraudulent receipt and submits it to her supervisor for reimbursement. What type of scheme is Jill committing?", "options": {"A": "A mischaracterized expense scheme", "B": "A fictitious expense scheme", "C": "Collusion with a supervisor", "D": "A multiple reimbursement scheme"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Expense reimbursements are sometimes sought by employees for wholly fictitious items. Instead of overstating a real business expense or seeking reimbursement for a personal expense, an employee just invents a purchase that needs to be reimbursed. One way to generate a reimbursement for a fictitious expense is to create fraudulent support documents, such as false receipts. Using simple computer software, it is easy for employees to create realistic-looking counterfeit receipts at home. These counterfeits are often very sophisticated, even including the logos of the stores in which goods or services were allegedly purchased."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "For corporate espionage purposes, technical surveillance generally consists of gathering documentary evidence or information that can be found via open sources.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Technical surveillance is the practice of covertly acquiring audio, visual, or other types of data from targets through the use of technical devices, procedures, and techniques. When corporate spies resort to the use of technical surveillance, it is usually to gather nondocumentary evidence or information that cannot be found through open sources."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a type of loan that frequently turns up in corruption cases?", "options": {"A": "A legitimate loan made at market rates", "B": "A legitimate loan in which a third party makes the loan payments", "C": "A legitimate loan made on favorable terms", "D": "An outright payment falsely described as an innocent loan"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Corrupt payments often take the form of loans. Three types of loans often turn up in fraud cases: An outright payment that is falsely described as an innocent loan A legitimate loan in which a third party—the corrupt payer—makes or guarantees payments to satisfy the loan A legitimate loan made on favorable terms (e.g., an interest-free loan) A legitimate loan made at market rates would not typically turn up in a corruption case because the loan recipient would not be receiving anything unusual or special."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "How do smart cards differ from ordinary credit cards?", "options": {"A": "Smart cards are designed to prevent fraudulent online card-not-present transactions.", "B": "Smart cards are immune from physical, side-channel, and environmental attacks.", "C": "Smart cards contain special holograms that identify the cardholder.", "D": "Smart cards are embedded with a microchip that is not easily replicated."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A smart card is a plastic card, the size of a credit card, embedded with a microchip. A key advantage of smart cards is that, unlike regular magnetic stripe credit cards, they cannot be easily replicated. Similarly, smart cards cannot be easily counterfeited, which greatly reduces the potential for fraud. Smart cards include a wide variety of hardware and software features capable of detecting and reacting to tampering attempts and countering possible attacks. If someone tries to tamper with a chip on a smart card, the card detects the intrusion and shuts itself down, rendering the card useless. Although smart cards are designed to withstand different kinds of potential attacks on security, they are not immune from attacks. There are four main classes of attacks on smart cards: physical, side-channel, software, and environmental. While the adoption of smart cards has significantly reduced fraud for card present (CP) transactions, much of the fraud has been displaced to card-not-present (CNP) transactions on the Internet. The United Kingdom, France, and Australia have experienced significant increases in CNP fraud in the years following their transitions to smart cards. Large-scale data breaches and the continued increase in online spending have also contributed to the rising volume of CNP fraud."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Which of the following best describes how a baiting scheme works in the context of identity theft?", "options": {"A": "Fraudsters impersonate the victim’s bank to persuade the victim into releasing information.", "B": "Fraudsters use imitation websites to trick computer users into entering sensitive data.", "C": "Fraudsters use telephone calls or voice messages to manipulate targets into revealing personal or business information.", "D": "Fraudsters trick victims into inserting malware-infected data storage devices into their computers."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In a baiting scheme, fraudsters leave malware-infected USB flash drives, CD-ROMs, or similar items in places where people will find them, such as parking lots. The items often have a label designed to elicit curiosity or greed in the victims (e.g., “FREE PRIZE”). Alternatively, the item could be left in a workplace break room with a label that seems relevant (e.g., “Year-end report 2018”). When the item is inserted into the victim’s computer, the computer or network is infected, giving the identity thief access to information. In the context of identity theft, social engineering refers to the psychological manipulation of people to trick them into revealing personal or business information. Social engineering often involves pretexting, the act of using an invented scenario (i.e., a pretext) to persuade a person to release information or perform an action. Identity thieves often engage in pretexting by impersonating the victim’s bank or another financial institution with which the victim has a business relationship. Vishing (or voice phishing) schemes use telephone calls or voice messages to trick targets into revealing personal or business information. In a pharming scheme, Internet users are automatically redirected from a legitimate website to an imitation website."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Which of the following statements about the methods used to make corrupt payments in bribery and corruption schemes is INCORRECT?", "options": {"A": "Payers often make corrupt payments by making outright payments falsely described as innocent loans.", "B": "Payers often make corrupt payments by selling property to recipients at prices higher than the property’s market value.", "C": "Payers often make corrupt payments by buying assets from recipients and allowing the recipients to retain title or use of the items.", "D": "Payers often make corrupt payments by using their credit cards to pay recipients’ transportation, vacation, and entertainment expenses."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Corrupt payments often take the form of loans. Three types of loans often turn up in fraud cases: An outright payment that is falsely described as an innocent loan A legitimate loan in which a third party—the corrupt payer—makes or guarantees payments to satisfy the loan A legitimate loan made on favorable terms (e.g., an interest-free loan) A corrupt payment can be in the form of credit card use or payments toward a party’s credit card debt. The payer might use a credit card to pay a recipient’s transportation, vacation, or entertainment expenses, or the payer might pay off a recipient’s credit card debt. In some instances, the recipient might carry and use the corrupt payer’s credit card. Corrupt payments also might come in the form of promises of favorable treatment. In addition, corrupt payments might occur in the form of transfers for a value other than fair market. In such transfers, the corrupt payer might sell or lease property to the recipient at a price that is less than its market value, or the payer might agree to buy or rent property from the recipient at an inflated price. The recipient might also “sell” an asset to the payer but retain the title or use of the property."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "A property flipping scheme occurs when someone purchases a piece of real estate and sells it shortly thereafter at an unjustly inflated value.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Property flipping is the process by which an investor purchases a home and then resells it at a higher price shortly thereafter. For example, an investor buys a house in need of work for $250,000 in July, renovates the kitchen and bathrooms, and landscapes the yard at a cost of $50,000. He then resells the house two months later (the time it takes to make the renovations) for a price that is reflective of the market for a house in that condition. This is a legitimate business transaction, and many individuals and groups make an honest living flipping properties. Property flipping is not intrinsically illegal or fraudulent, but it becomes so when a property is purchased and resold within a short period of time at an artificially or unjustly inflated value, often as the result of a fraudulent appraisal. In a flipping scheme, the property is sold twice in rapid succession at a significant increase in value (also known as an ABC transaction, where the property moves from party A to party B to party C very quickly)."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Daniel, a plant manager for a utility company, has his own commercial cleaning business on the side. Daniel threatened to withhold business from any vendors of the utility company that did not hire his cleaning business for their office cleaning needs. Which of the following best describes the type of corruption scheme in which Daniel engaged?", "options": {"A": "Economic extortion scheme", "B": "Kickback scheme", "C": "Illegal gratuity scheme", "D": "Collusion scheme"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Extortion is defined as the obtaining of property from another, with the other party’s consent induced by wrongful use of actual or threatened force or fear. Economic extortion is present when an employee or official, through the wrongful use of actual or threatened force or fear, demands money or some other consideration to make a particular business decision. Thus, because Daniel threatened to withhold business from any vendors of the utility company that did not hire his cleaning business for their office cleaning needs, he engaged in an extortion scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "ABC Corporation is the defendant in a class-action lawsuit for selling defective consumer products. While the lawsuit is estimated to continue for several more years, ABC’s management believes that it is reasonably possible that the company will lose the lawsuit and be ordered to pay a significant amount of damages to the plaintiffs. ABC does NOT have to disclose a liability related to the lawsuit in its financial statements.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Typical liability omissions include the failure to disclose loan covenants or contingent liabilities. Loan covenants are agreements, in addition to or as part of a financing arrangement, that a borrower has promised to keep as long as the financing is in place. The agreements can contain various types of covenants, including certain financial ratio limits and restrictions on other major financing arrangements. Contingent liabilities are potential obligations that will materialize only if certain events occur in the future. A corporate guarantee of personal loans received by a company officer and potential losses from ongoing litigation are examples of contingent liabilities. Under generally accepted accounting principles, a company’s potential liability must be disclosed in the notes to the financial statements if the liability is reasonably possible. A potential liability must be recorded if it is probable that a loss will occur and the amount of the loss can be reasonably estimated."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "______________ is a term used to classify malicious software that is intended to facilitate criminal behavior.", "options": {"A": "Adware", "B": "Botnet", "C": "Freeware", "D": "Crimeware"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Crimeware is not a type of malware but rather a classification of malware denoted by its intent to facilitate criminal behavior. Crimeware can be described as malware designed to simplify or automate online criminal activities, such as programs to fraudulently obtain financial gain from the affected user or other third parties."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Which of the following is a poor information security procedure that contributes to loss of proprietary information?", "options": {"A": "Failure to guard documents maintained in manual file systems", "B": "Failure to practice data minimization", "C": "Failure to implement data retention and destruction policies", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To prevent the loss or misuse of sensitive data or proprietary information, organizations should develop and implement risk-based information-security systems designed to detect and prevent unauthorized access to sensitive information. An information security system requires controls that are designed to ensure that data are used as intended, and such controls will depend on the combination and coordination of people, processes, technologies, and other resources. To be effective, a system for safeguarding sensitive and proprietary information should include the following: Task force Security risk assessments Security policies and procedures Awareness training Nondisclosure agreements Noncompetition agreements Data classification Data retention and destruction policies Data minimization Security controls Measures to guard manual file systems Monitoring of visitor access Quiet room The failure to include any of these measures is a poor information security practice that can contribute to the loss of proprietary information."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Chapman Inc. has always used the first-in, first-out (FIFO) inventory valuation method when calculating its cost of goods sold. This is also the standard inventory valuation method for other comparable entities in Chapman’s industry. Chapman’s controller wants to change to the weighted-average cost method because it will make Chapman’s net income appear much larger than FIFO valuation will. After several years of poor performance, management wants to boost the company’s appearance to potential investors. However, Chapman must continue to use the FIFO inventory valuation method. This is reflected in which of the qualitative characteristics of financial reporting?", "options": {"A": "Comparability", "B": "Going concern", "C": "Relevance", "D": "Valuation"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Users of financial statements base their decisions on comparisons between different entities and on similar information from a single entity for another reporting period. Comparability is the qualitative characteristic that enables users to identify and understand similarities and differences between such items. Consistency, although related to comparability, is not the same. Consistency refers to the use of the same methods for the same items, either from period to period within a reporting entity or in a single period across entities. Comparability is the goal; consistency helps to achieve that goal. However, both comparability and consistency do not prohibit a change in an accounting principle previously employed. An entity’s management is permitted to change an accounting policy only if the change is required by a standard or interpretation or results in the financial statements providing more reliable and relevant information about the effects of transactions; other events; or conditions on the entity's financial position, financial performance, or cash flows. The entity’s financial statements must include full disclosure of any such changes. Standards used to value inventory, depreciate assets, or accrue expenses should be consistent from one accounting period to the next. Any changes in accounting policy or procedures must be disclosed in the supplemental notes to the financial statements. The desire to project an artificially strong performance is not a justifiable reason for a change in accounting principle. Since Chapman has always used FIFO, and since FIFO is the industry norm, a change to the weighted-average cost method is not justifiable."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "If a customer reports the loss or theft of an access device, the financial institution should attempt to prevent fraud related to electronic funds transfers by canceling the existing card, PIN, or other form of access and issuing a new one.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The following are safeguards that banks can perform to reduce the risk that they or their customers become victimized by unauthorized electronic funds transfers: Confirm phone and mailing addresses on the application to ensure that they are consistent with information about the applicant that is available from other sources and, with respect to existing customers, consistent with current records about these customers. This might involve obtaining credit reports about the applicant or obtaining copies of utility bills that show the applicant’s address. Make sure that the area or city code in the applicant’s telephone number matches the geographical area for the applicant’s address. Send a “welcome” letter to the address on the application with the bank’s return address so that the letter is returned if the applicant does not live there. Verify by telephone or additional mailings any change of address requests in the same way that new account applications are verified. If a customer reports the loss or theft of an access device, cancel the existing card, PIN, or other form of access and issue a new one. If a customer reports that a person previously authorized to use an access device no longer has that authority, cancel all cards, PINs, or other access devices and issue new ones to the customer. Always mail PINs separately from other information, such as usernames, with which they are associated. Separate the responsibility of bank employees who have custody of information relating to access devices from those who have responsibility for issuance, verification, or reissuance of PINs. Ensure that any communication concerning usernames or passwords is sent in a secure encrypted format. Require customers who register for EBPP or P2P systems to provide information indicating that they are authorized to use the bank account or credit card from which payments will be made. Employ multifactor authentication to verify transfers via EBPP or P2P systems."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "A contractor who delivers materials of lesser quality than specified in the contract or uses a lower quality staff than specified in the contract might be involved in which of the following types of procurement fraud schemes?", "options": {"A": "Nonconforming goods or services fraud", "B": "Labor mischarging fraud", "C": "Material mischarging fraud", "D": "Product division fraud"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Nonconforming goods or services fraud, also known as product substitution or failure to meet contract specifications, refers to attempts by contractors to deliver goods or services to the procuring entity that do not conform to the underlying contract specifications. Once contractors deliver goods that do not conform to the contract, they bill and receive payment for conforming goods or services without informing the purchaser of the deficiency. These schemes can involve a wide variety of conduct, but, generally, they include any deliberate departures from contract requirements to increase profits or comply with contract time schedules."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "If a bank loan is a nonperforming loan, it might be a red flag for fraud. Which of the following is a fraud scheme that is often connected to a nonperforming loan?", "options": {"A": "Land flips", "B": "Construction over-budget items", "C": "Bribery", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A nonperforming loan is a loan that is in default or close to being in default. The interest and principal payments might be overdue, and the creditor has reason to believe the loan will not be collected in full. This is often indicative of a fraud scheme. Fraud schemes resulting in a nonperforming loan include: Fraudulent appraisals—The cash flow cannot support an inflated loan and resulting debt amount. False statements—The loan was made on false or fraudulently presented assumptions. Equity skimming—The borrower never intended to make the underlying loan payments. Construction over-budget items—The amount over budget might be a concealment method for other schemes such as embezzlement, misappropriation, or false statements. Bribery—The loan was made because the lender received a bribe or a kickback from the borrower. Land flips—The purpose of the loan was to finance the seller out of a property that has an artificially inflated value. Disguised transactions—The loans are sham transactions without substance, made to conceal other ills."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "After paying the ransom demanded by the fraudster, a ransomware victim is always granted access to all locked files on the compromised computer.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Ransomware, as its name implies, is a form of malware that locks a user’s operating system and restricts access to data files until a ransom is paid. While some ransomware simply prevents access to files, other forms actually encrypt users’ files. This is of particular concern to businesses due to the potentially disastrous threat of encrypted network drives. These schemes typically promise that, after payment is received, the user will be provided with a key to release the system and unencrypt files; however, even after money is transferred, many victims find that the virus remains installed on their machine and a key is never provided. Less sophisticated forms of ransomware have also appeared that claim to have encrypted victims’ files when the malware has simply deleted the files, thus tricking victims into paying to regain access to files that no longer exist. Some forms of this imitation ransomware go a step farther by deleting the restore points and registry keys needed to reboot a system in safe mode or overwriting deleted files to make them nearly impossible to recover."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "When a medical provider performs a service for a patient but bills the patient’s health care program for a more complex and more expensive service, this practice is called upcoding.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Upcoding occurs when a provider bills for a higher level of service than actually rendered. One common form of upcoding involves generic substitution—filling a prescription with a less expensive drug, while billing for the more expensive form of the drug."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "A medical provider billed a health care program for a name-brand drug, while providing the patient with a generic version of the drug. This inflated billing scheme is known as which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Replacement fraud", "B": "Undercharging", "C": "Upcoding", "D": "Unbundling"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Upcoding occurs when a provider bills for a higher level of service than actually rendered. One common form of upcoding involves generic substitution—filling a prescription with a less expensive drug, while billing for the more expensive form of the drug."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Which of the following scenarios illustrates a fraudster’s use of social engineering?", "options": {"A": "A fraudster has lunch at a restaurant where a target company’s employees are known to eat with the intention of overhearing sensitive conversations", "B": "A fraudster calls a company employee and requests sensitive information while claiming to be a coworker whose systems are down", "C": "A fraudster without an employee badge gains access to a secure facility by following legitimate employees who are oblivious to his presence", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Social engineering is the act of using deceptive techniques to manipulate people into taking certain actions or disclosing information. In social engineering schemes, social engineers use various forms of trickery, persuasion, threats, or cajolery to encourage their targets to release information that the engineers can use and exploit to achieve their goals. Attackers engage in social engineering for various reasons. Some use social engineering to gain unauthorized access to systems or obtain confidential communication so they can commit fraud, intrude into networks, gain access to buildings, steal another party’s secrets, commit identity theft, or engage in some other nefarious act. In some situations, attackers use social engineering to procure information that will give them a competitive advantage, whereas others might engage in social engineering to find ways in which they can install malware."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is the most accurate definition of a firewall?", "options": {"A": "A system that blocks unauthorized or unverified access to network assets by surveying incoming and outgoing transmissions", "B": "A system that authenticates users by monitoring their statistical characteristics, such as typing speed and keystroke touch", "C": "A device that takes information and scrambles it so that it is unreadable by anyone who does not have a specific code", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Firewalls are network hardware and software that block unauthorized or unverified access to computer systems and network assets. These tools survey incoming and outgoing transmissions and decide what type of traffic to permit onto an organization’s internal network based on factors such as origination or destination address, content of the message, protocol being used to transmit the message, and other filtering methods."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Which of the following does NOT constitute an electronic funds transfer?", "options": {"A": "A customer’s use of a debit card to purchase dinner at a restaurant", "B": "An airline ticket purchased through the Internet with the use of a credit card", "C": "The computer-initiated deposit of an employee’s paycheck directly into the employee’s bank account", "D": "A transfer of funds from a checking account to a savings account performed on a personal computer"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "An electronic funds transfer (EFT) is any transfer of funds, other than one originated by a check or similar paper instrument, that is initiated through an electronic terminal, telephonic instrument, or computer or magnetic tape that orders or purports to authorize a financial institution to debit or credit an account. Because it does not result in a transfer of funds, the use of a credit card to make a payment does not constitute an EFT. Each of the following could be considered an EFT: A customer’s withdrawal of funds from the customer’s own account by use of an ATM A customer’s transfer of funds from the customer’s checking account to the customer’s savings account at the same financial institution initiated by the customer through a personal computer A customer’s transfer of funds from the customer’s checking account to the customer’s savings account at the same financial institution initiated by the customer through the bank’s automated telephone service A customer’s use of a debit card to purchase goods from a merchant who swipes the card through a point-of-sale (POS) device to authorize the deduction of the amount of the sale from the customer’s checking account A customer’s transfer of funds from the customer’s bank account to a third party initiated by the customer through a personal computer An employer’s instruction, initiated by computer or through a magnetic tape, to a financial institution to deposit funds representing an employee’s pay into the employee’s account A noncustomer’s instruction, initiated by computer or through a magnetic tape, to a financial institution to withdraw funds from a customer’s checking account and transfer the funds to a noncustomer’s bank account"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Employment identity theft occurs when a fraudster impersonates a business to commit financial fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Business identity theft occurs when a fraudster impersonates a business to commit financial fraud. In an employment identity theft scheme, a fraudster impersonates another person to secure a job."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following is the best description of what is shown on a company’s income statement?", "options": {"A": "The company’s sources and uses of cash during a particular period of time", "B": "The changes in the total owners’ equity amount listed on the balance sheet", "C": "How much profit (or loss) the company earned over a particular period of time", "D": "The company’s financial position at a specific point in time"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Whereas the balance sheet shows a company’s financial position at a specific point in time, the income statement, or statement of profit or loss and other comprehensive income, details how much profit (or loss) a company earned during a period of time, such as a quarter or a year. The statement of changes in owners’ equity details the changes in the total owners’ equity amount listed on the balance sheet. The statement of cash flows reports a company’s sources and uses of cash during a particular period of time."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Tim, a cash register attendant at a department store, regularly inflates the amount of customer refunds. For instance, if a customer returns an item for $100, Tim records a $150 refund. Then Tim gives the customer $100 and keeps $50 for himself. This scheme is known as:", "options": {"A": "Skimming", "B": "An overstated refund scheme", "C": "A false void scheme", "D": "A fictitious refund scheme"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "One type of register disbursement scheme is the overstated refund. Rather than creating an entirely fictitious refund, a fraudster might overstate the value of a real customer's refund, pay the customer the actual amount owed for the returned merchandise, and then keep the excess portion of the return. In a fictitious refund scheme, an employee processes a transaction as if a customer were returning merchandise, even though there is no actual return. Then the employee takes cash from the register in the amount of the false return. The customer might or might not be aware of the scheme taking place. Fictitious voids are similar to refund schemes in that they make fraudulent disbursements from the register appear to be legitimate. To process a false void, the first thing the perpetrator needs is the customer’s copy of the sales receipt. Typically, when an employee sets about processing a fictitious void, the employee simply withholds the customer’s receipt at the time of the sale. In many cases, customers do not notice that they are not given a receipt. Skimming is the removal of cash from a victim entity prior to its entry in an accounting system."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following lists the information security goals that an e-commerce system should achieve for its users and asset holders?", "options": {"A": "Exactness, invulnerability, accuracy, materiality, and data/systems response", "B": "Penetrability, accuracy, exactness, materiality, and systems reliability", "C": "Confidentiality, integrity, availability, authentication, and non-repudiation", "D": "Penetrability, accuracy, availability, authentication, and systems reliability"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "All branches of an information system, including the e-commerce branch, strive to provide security to their users and asset holders. The following is a list of common information security goals that should be achieved to ensure the security of information systems for users and account holders: Confidentiality of data Integrity of data Availability of data Authentication Non-repudiation"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a common red flag of a bid tailoring scheme?", "options": {"A": "Competitive awards vary among several suppliers.", "B": "Only a few bidders respond to bid requests.", "C": "There are unusually broad specifications for the type of goods or services being procured.", "D": "A contract is not rebid even though fewer than the minimum number of bids are received."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Bid tailoring schemes (also known as specifications schemes) occur during the presolicitation phase. In these schemes, an employee with procurement responsibilities, often in collusion with a contractor, drafts bid specifications in a way that gives an unfair advantage to a certain contractor. Some common red flags of bid tailoring include: Weak controls over the bidding process Only one or a few bidders respond to bid requests Contract is not rebid even though fewer than the minimum number of bids are received Similarity between specifications and the winning contractor’s product or services Bid specifications and statements of work are tailored to fit the products or capabilities of a single contractor Unusual or unreasonably narrow or broad specifications for the type of goods or services being procured Requests for bid submissions do not provide clear bid submission information (e.g., no clear time, place, or manner of submitting bids) Unexplained changes in contract specifications from previous proposals or similar items High number of competitive awards to one supplier Socialization or personal contacts among contracting personnel and bidders Specifications developed by or in consultation with a contractor who is permitted to compete in the procurement High number of change orders for one supplier"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Visitors to a company’s facilities should be allowed unrestricted access as long as they have signed in as a visitor in the company’s logbook and have been issued a visitor’s badge.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Management should monitor and limit visitor access. Visitors should be required to sign in and out of an organization logbook. It is considered a best practice to issue visitors a badge that identifies them as a non-employee. Also, visitors should be escorted by a host at all times, and visitors should not be allowed into areas containing sensitive information. Additionally, locks on doors leading to secure areas should be changed or reprogrammed regularly, especially if an employee has recently quit or been terminated."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT an appropriate technique for detecting a nonconforming goods or services scheme?", "options": {"A": "Review the contractor’s statements, claims, invoices, and supporting documents.", "B": "Review correspondence and contract files for indications of noncompliance.", "C": "Segregate and identify the source of the suspect goods or materials.", "D": "Review the number of qualified bidders who submitted proposals."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Nonconforming goods or services fraud, also known as product substitution or failure to meet contract specifications, refers to attempts by contractors to deliver goods or services to the procuring entity that do not conform to the underlying contract specifications. Once contractors deliver goods that do not conform to the contract, they bill and receive payment for conforming goods or services without informing the purchaser of the deficiency. To detect nonconforming schemes, the fraud examiner should, at a minimum, examine the following for red flags: Contract or purchase order specifications Contractor’s statements, claims, invoices, and supporting documents Received product Test and inspection results for the relevant period, searching for discrepancies between tests and inspection results and contract specifications Additionally, to detect nonconforming schemes, the fraud examiner should: Review correspondence and contract files for indications of noncompliance. Request assistance from outside technical personnel to conduct after-the-fact tests. Inspect or test questioned goods or materials by examining packaging, appearance, and description to determine if the items are appropriate. Segregate and identify the source of the suspect goods or materials. Review inspection reports to determine whether the work performed and materials used in a project were inspected and considered acceptable. Review the contractor’s books, payroll, and expense records to see if they incurred necessary costs to comply with contract specifications. Review the inspection and testing reports of questioned goods or materials. Conduct routine and unannounced inspections and tests of questioned goods or materials. Examine the contractor’s books and manufacturing or purchase records for additional evidence, looking for discrepancies between claimed and actual costs, contractors, etc. Interview procurement personnel about the presence of any red flags or other indications of noncompliance. Search and review external records (e.g., court records, prior complaints, audit reports, investigative reports, media sources) to determine if there is any history of misconduct."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a common method that fraudsters use to conceal liabilities and expenses in order to make a company appear more profitable than it actually is?", "options": {"A": "Improperly capitalizing costs rather than expensing them", "B": "Omitting liabilities or expenses", "C": "Failing to disclose warranty costs and product-return liabilities", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Understating liabilities and expenses is one of the ways financial statements can be manipulated to make a company appear more profitable than it actually is. Because pre-tax income will increase by the full amount of the expense or liability not recorded, this financial statement fraud method can significantly affect reported earnings with relatively little effort by the fraudster. There are three common methods for concealing liabilities and expenses: Omitting liabilities and/or expenses Improperly capitalizing costs rather than expensing them Failing to disclose warranty costs and product-return liabilities"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Common methods of inflating health care billings include all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Added services", "B": "Altered claims", "C": "Sliding policies", "D": "Code manipulation"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Health care billings can be inflated by providers as well as beneficiaries. The following are some of the most common fraud schemes encountered by investigators and claims approvers: Altered claims Added services Code manipulation"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a common reason why people commit financial statement fraud?", "options": {"A": "To demonstrate compliance with loan covenants", "B": "To cover inability to generate cash flow", "C": "To encourage investment through the sale of stock", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Unlike some other types of fraud (such as embezzlement), the motivation for financial statement fraud does not always involve personal gain. Most commonly, financial statement fraud is used to make a company’s earnings appear better on paper. Financial statement fraud occurs through a variety of methods, such as valuation judgments and manipulating the timing of transaction recording. These more subtle types of fraud are often dismissed as either mistakes or errors in judgment and estimation. Some of the more common reasons why people commit financial statement fraud include: To encourage investment through the sale of stock To demonstrate increased earnings per share or partnership profits interest, thus allowing increased dividend/distribution payouts To cover inability to generate cash flow To avoid negative market perceptions To obtain financing, or to obtain more favorable terms on existing financing To receive higher purchase prices for acquisitions To demonstrate compliance with financing covenants To meet company goals and objectives To receive performance-related bonuses"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "When a construction developer submits a draw request to a lender, all of the following would be red flags for loan fraud EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Omission of developer’s personal account statements", "B": "Failure to include lien releases from each subcontractor", "C": "Invoice documentation that appears altered", "D": "Missing inspection reports"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Construction loan advances are generally supported by draw requests. A draw request is the documentation substantiating that a developer has incurred the appropriate construction expenses and is now seeking reimbursement or direct payment. Generally, a draw request is made once a month and is verified by a quantity surveyor (QS) or other authorized entity as agreed to by the financial institution. The request should be accompanied by the following documents: Paid invoices for raw materials Lien releases from each subcontractor Inspection reports Canceled checks from previous draw requests Bank reconciliation for construction draw account for previous month Loan balancing form demonstrating that the loan remains in balance Change orders, if applicable Wiring instructions, if applicable Proof of developer contribution, if applicable Any missing or altered documentation is a red flag that something is amiss with the draw request. All advances on the loan should be adequately documented. The developer’s personal account statements would never be included with a draw request."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Nondisclosure agreements are generally an expensive and inefficient means of protecting an organization’s proprietary information.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Generally, a nondisclosure agreement is a written agreement providing that signatories must keep all trade secrets and proprietary information learned during their employment confidential. Nondisclosure agreements are one of the least expensive and most efficient methods for controlling the loss of proprietary information."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is the most accurate definition of a Trojan horse?", "options": {"A": "A program or command procedure that gives the appearance that it is useful but in fact contains hidden malicious code that causes damage", "B": "A software program that contains various instructions that are carried out every time a computer is turned on", "C": "A virus that changes its structure to avoid detection", "D": "A type of software that collects and reports information about a computer user without the user’s knowledge or consent"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A Trojan horse is a program or command procedure that gives the appearance that it is useful but in fact contains hidden malicious code that causes damage. When the hidden code in a Trojan horse is activated, it performs some unwanted or harmful function. Often, viruses and worms attach themselves to other legitimate programs, becoming Trojan horses and spreading to other systems."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following is the correct accounting model?", "options": {"A": "Assets + Liabilities = Owners' Equity", "B": "Assets = Liabilities - Owners' Equity", "C": "Assets = Liabilities + Owners' Equity", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Accounting is based on the following model or accounting equation: Assets = Liabilities + Owners' Equity."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "The person who is responsible for the shipment of inventory should also be responsible for the conversion of inventory to scrap.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Separation of duties is among the measures commonly used to prevent inventory theft. The following duties should be handled by different personnel: Requisition of inventory Receipt of inventory Disbursement/shipment of inventory Conversion of inventory to scrap Receipt of proceeds from disposal of scrap"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Due to the paper trail involved and the emphasis placed on the problem by law enforcement, the vast majority of check fraud offenders are pursued and prosecuted.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Many merchants overburden police and prosecutors with reports of check fraud rather than implementing effective training and controls to help prevent such schemes from the outset; therefore, law enforcement and prosecutors do not have the time or manpower to pursue all such cases and are often not eager to do so. Furthermore, check fraud perpetrators frequently migrate from one location to another, making their apprehension and prosecution difficult."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "A virus that loads itself onto the target system's memory, infects other files, and then unloads itself is called a:", "options": {"A": "Direct-action virus", "B": "Boot sector virus", "C": "Network virus", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Direct-action viruses load themselves onto the target system's memory, infect other files, and then unload themselves."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "A health care provider's practice of charging a comprehensive code, as well as one or more component codes, by billing separately for subcomponents of a single procedure is known as ______________.", "options": {"A": "Segregating", "B": "Unbundling", "C": "Subdividing", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Because health care procedures often have special reimbursement rates for a group of procedures typically performed together (e.g., blood test panels by clinical laboratories), some providers attempt to increase profits by billing separately for procedures that are actually part of a single procedure. This process is called unbundling or coding fragmentation. Simple unbundling occurs when a provider charges a comprehensive code, as well as one or more component codes."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following best describes a mischaracterized reimbursement expense scheme?", "options": {"A": "An employee produces a fictitious receipt and includes it with an expense report.", "B": "An employee who travels frequently on business submits receipts from a hotel stay during a family vacation as a business expense.", "C": "An employee submits a receipt for an item in one expense report and an email confirmation for the same item in the next period’s expense report.", "D": "An employee alters a receipt to reflect a higher cost than what the employee actually paid and submits it for reimbursement."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "One of the most basic expense schemes is perpetrated by simply requesting reimbursement for a personal expense, claiming that it is business related. Examples of mischaracterized expenses include claiming personal travel as a business trip, listing dinner with a friend as “business development” or “client entertainment,” and so on. Employees might submit the receipts from their personal expenses along with their expense reports but concoct business reasons for the incurred costs. Instead of seeking reimbursement for personal expenses, some employees overstate the cost of actual business expenses. This is considered an overstated expense reimbursement scheme. In a fictitious expense reimbursement scheme, an employee seeks reimbursement for wholly fictitious expenses. Instead of overstating a real business expense or seeking reimbursement for a personal expense, an employee just invents an expense by producing a fictitious receipt and requests that it be reimbursed. In a multiple reimbursement scheme, an employee submits several types of support for the same expense in order to get reimbursed multiple times."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements about ransomware is TRUE?", "options": {"A": "Ransomware is a classification of malware designed to simplify or automate online criminal activities.", "B": "Ransomware is a program or command procedure that gives the appearance of being useful but in fact contains hidden malicious code that causes damage.", "C": "Ransomware is a form of malware that locks a user’s operating system and restricts access to data files until a payment is made.", "D": "Ransomware is a type of software that collects and reports information about a computer user without the user’s knowledge or consent."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Ransomware, as its name implies, is a form of malware that locks a user’s operating system and restricts access to data files until a ransom is paid. To intimidate Internet users into compliance, ransomware often employs a convincing professional interface, commonly emblazoned with police insignia or an official government logo. Messages sometimes consist of threatening accusations that the user has been caught viewing illegal videos, downloading pirated media, or otherwise accessing forbidden Internet content, with the only remedy being to pay a fine. Other forms are far more direct and make no effort to conceal their obvious attempts at extortion. Spyware is a type of software that collects and reports information about a computer user without the user’s knowledge or consent. A Trojan horse is a program or command procedure that gives the appearance of being useful but in fact contains hidden malicious code that causes damage. When the hidden code in a Trojan horse is activated, it performs some unwanted or harmful function. Often, viruses and worms attach themselves to other legitimate programs, becoming Trojan horses and spreading to other systems. Crimeware is not a type of malware but rather a classification of malware denoted by its intent to facilitate criminal behavior. Crimeware can be described as malware designed to simplify or automate online criminal activities, such as programs to fraudulently obtain financial gain from the affected user or other third parties."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following types of malware can be used to generate illicit income in the form of cryptocurrency, while slowing down an infected computer and causing victims to incur costs related to power usage or cloud storage?", "options": {"A": "Spyware", "B": "Overwrite viruses", "C": "Coin miners", "D": "Keyloggers"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Coin miners, or cryptojacking malware, are programs that, upon infecting a computer, use that computer’s processing power to mine for cryptocurrencies without the owner’s knowledge or consent. Many criminals who once used other malware and computer fraud methods for generating illicit income have shifted their focus to cryptojacking due to an increase in the value of numerous cryptocurrencies. Coin miners are relatively simple programs, so there is a low barrier of entry for cyber fraudsters. Cryptojacking can slow down infected devices due to the processing power required for cryptocurrency mining and potentially cause serious or permanent damage. Victims, including companies or corporate networks, can also incur exorbitant costs for power usage or cloud storage related to coin miners. IOT devices could be of particular risk due to their frequent lack of security or monitoring."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "All of the following are measures that would be helpful in preventing cash larceny schemes EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Having all employees use the same cash register for their transactions", "B": "Assigning an employee’s duties to another individual when that employee goes on vacation", "C": "Sending out a company-wide communication informing employees of the company’s surprise cash count policy", "D": "Ensuring that the duties of making bank deposits and performing bank reconciliations are assigned to different individuals"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Surprise cash counts and supervisory observations are a useful fraud prevention method if properly used. It is important that employees know that cash will be counted on a periodic and unscheduled basis. Having all employees use the same cash register will not deter cash larceny. However, each employee should have a unique code to the cash registers to facilitate detection of such schemes. Mandatory vacations are an excellent method of detecting cash fraud. If mandatory vacations are within the company’s policies, it is important that during the employee’s absence, that employee's normal workload be performed by another individual. The purpose of mandatory vacations is lost if the work is allowed to remain undone during the employee’s time off. The primary means of preventing cash fraud is separation of duties. Whenever one individual has control over the entire accounting transaction (e.g., authorization, recording, and custody), the opportunity is present for cash fraud. Each of the following duties/responsibilities should be separated: Cash receipts Bank deposits Bank reconciliation Cash disbursements Therefore, no one person, including the accounts receivable clerk, should be responsible for both depositing cash at the bank and performing bank reconciliations."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following describes the primary purpose of an ACH filter?", "options": {"A": "It is a tool used by auditors to examine electronic payment activity on the bank records.", "B": "It requires the bank to contact the account holder before any payments are made.", "C": "It matches the details of incoming payments with those on a list of expected payments provided by the account holder.", "D": "It enables account holders to provide their banks with a list of criteria to ensure only designated individuals get paid."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Most large banks offer multiple security services that can help business account holders mitigate fraud through early detection and prevention of fraudulent electronic payments. For example, ACH blocks allow account holders to notify their banks that ACH debits should not be allowed on specific accounts. ACH filters enable account holders to provide their banks with a list of defined criteria (such as the sending company ID, account number, and transaction code) against which banks can filter ACH debits and reject any unauthorized transactions. Positive pay for ACH is another security feature offered by banks to their account holders. With positive pay, banks match the details of ACH payments with those on a list of legitimate and expected payments provided by the account holder. Only authorized electronic transactions are allowed to be withdrawn from the account; exceptions are reported to the customer for review."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Michael, a medical provider, performs an appendectomy, a procedure that is supposed to be billed as one code. Instead, he intentionally submits two codes for the same procedure, one for an abdominal incision and one for removal of the appendix. Which of the following best describes Michael’s scheme?", "options": {"A": "Procedure compounding", "B": "Decompressing", "C": "Unbundling", "D": "Fictitious services"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Because health care procedures often have special reimbursement rates for a group of procedures typically performed together (e.g., blood test panels by clinical laboratories), some providers attempt to increase profits by billing separately for procedures that are actually part of a single procedure. This process is called unbundling or coding fragmentation. Simple unbundling occurs when a provider charges a comprehensive code, as well as one or more component codes."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE with regard to a fictitious revenue scheme?", "options": {"A": "Uncollected accounts receivable are a red flag of fictitious revenue schemes.", "B": "If a fictitious revenue scheme has taken place, there will typically be no accounts receivable on the books.", "C": "The debit side of a fictitious sales entry usually goes to accounts payable.", "D": "Fictitious revenues must involve sales to a fake customer."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Fictitious or fabricated revenues involve the recording of sales of goods or services that did not occur. Fictitious sales most often involve fake customers but can also involve legitimate customers. At the end of the accounting period, the sale will be reversed (as will all revenue accounts), which will help to conceal the fraud. Recording the sales revenue is easy, but the challenge for the fraudster is how to balance the other side of the entry. A credit to revenue increases the revenue account, but the corresponding debit in a legitimate sales transaction typically either goes to cash or accounts receivable. Since no cash is received in a fictitious revenue scheme, increasing accounts receivable is the easiest way to get away with completing the entry. Unlike revenue accounts, however, accounts receivable are not reversed at the end of the accounting period. They stay on the books as an asset until collected. If the outstanding accounts never get collected, they will eventually need to be written off as bad debt expense. Mysterious accounts receivable on the books that are long overdue are a common sign of a fictitious revenue scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Shareholders' reports and company newsletters might give a competitor valuable information about a company's product secrets.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Publications such as newsletters or reports to shareholders and speeches or papers that are presented at conferences can inadvertently provide valuable information to competitors. A company’s website might also contain accidental leaks. Corporate spies frequently visit their targets’ websites to gather information that these companies have unknowingly made public. Employee telephone and email directories, financial information, key employees’ biographical data, product features and release dates, details on research and development, and job postings can all be found on many corporate websites."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is the term used to describe the method of gaining unauthorized access to a computer system in which attackers use an automated process to guess a system user's passwords?", "options": {"A": "Password logging", "B": "Password cracking", "C": "Password sniffing", "D": "Password engineering"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Password cracking is an automated process by which an attacker attempts to guess a system user's most likely passwords."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "In order to understate net income, therefore lowering income tax liability, an accountant could fraudulently expense costs rather than properly capitalizing them to an asset account.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Typically, a fraudster’s goal when committing a financial statement fraud scheme is to make the entity look stronger and more profitable. This goal is often achieved by concealing liabilities and/or expenses. To do this, he might fraudulently understate liabilities or improperly capitalize a cost that should be expensed. Just as capitalizing expenditures that should be expensed is improper, so is expensing costs that should be capitalized. The organization might do this to minimize its net income due to tax considerations. Expensing an item that should be depreciated over a period of time would help accomplish just that—net income is lower and so are taxes."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following would be considered a forged maker scheme?", "options": {"A": "Jeff is an employee at Carlisle Company. He obtains a check intended for Lewis, one of Carlisle’s vendors. Jeff covers up Lewis’s name with correction fluid, inserts his own name, and cashes the check for himself.", "B": "Lindsay’s employer writes her a check to reimburse her for travel expenses. The check is for $350. She carefully changes the 3 to an 8 so that the check amount now appears to be $850.", "C": "Erica steals a check from her employer, makes it payable to herself, and then forges the CFO’s signature on the check. The CFO is an authorized check signer at the company.", "D": "Stewart intercepts a check written from his employer, Alamo Corp., to Richard Johnson, one of Alamo’s contractors. He then forges Johnson’s name on the check’s endorsement line and cashes it for himself."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The person who signs a check is known as the “maker” of the check. A forged maker scheme is defined as a check tampering scheme in which an employee misappropriates a check and fraudulently affixes the signature of an authorized maker thereon. Erica committed a forged maker scheme because she forged the signature of the CFO, an authorized maker, on her employer’s check. In a forged endorsement scheme, an employee intercepts a company check intended for a third party and converts the check by endorsing it with the third party’s name. Stewart committed a forged endorsement scheme because he signed Johnson’s name on the back of the check and cashed it himself. In an altered payee scheme, an employee intercepts a company check intended for a third party and alters the payee designation so that the employee or an accomplice can convert the check. The employee inserts his own name, the accomplice’s name, or a fictitious entity’s name on the check’s payee line. In addition to altering the payee designation, the amount of the check can be altered by tacking on extra numbers if the person preparing the check is careless and leaves space for extra numbers in the “amount” portion of the check. Jeff and Lindsay both committed altered payee schemes. Jeff altered the payee line by inserting his own name on the check intended for Lewis, and Lindsay altered the amount on the check that was intended for her."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "What is the primary difference between a Ponzi scheme and a pyramid scheme?", "options": {"A": "A pyramid scheme promotes itself as a pyramid, whereas a Ponzi scheme promotes itself as an investment opportunity.", "B": "In a pyramid scheme, old investors are paid with money from new investors.", "C": "A Ponzi scheme is promoted by encouraging victim members to recruit new members.", "D": "All pyramid schemes are legal, whereas all Ponzi schemes are illegal."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The difference between a Ponzi scheme and an illegal pyramid lies in how the operation is promoted. Illegal pyramids are promoted as pyramids, whereas Ponzi schemes are promoted as investment opportunities. In an illegal pyramid, the pyramidal structure helps draw new players, each believing that they will rise through the ranks of the pyramid. A Ponzi scheme, on the other hand, masquerades as some type of investment."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Skimming schemes can involve the theft of cash sales or the theft of accounts receivable payments.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Skimming is the removal of cash from a victim entity prior to its entry in an accounting system. Employees who skim from their companies steal sales OR accounts receivable payments before they are recorded in the company books."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "An analytical review reveals that Rollins Company’s cost of goods sold increased by 80% last year. Its sales, however, only increased by 40%. What might this discrepancy indicate?", "options": {"A": "Sales were unusually poor this year versus last year.", "B": "There were more sales returns this year than in the prior year.", "C": "Inventory has been depleted by theft.", "D": "The quantity of items purchased decreased."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Inventory fraud might be detected by using an analytical review because certain trends become immediately clear. For example, sales and cost of goods sold should move together since they are directly related. However, if the cost of goods sold increases by a disproportionate amount relative to sales, and no changes occur in the purchase prices, quantities purchased, or quality of products purchased, the cause of the disproportionate increase in cost of goods sold might be one of three things: (1) ending inventory has been depleted by theft, (2) someone has been embezzling money through a false billing scheme, or (3) someone has been skimming sales revenue."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "A fraudster uses the email account of a company’s president to impersonate the president and ask an employee to make a wire transfer. This can best be described as which of the following types of fraud schemes?", "options": {"A": "Pharming", "B": "Rock phishing", "C": "Reverse social engineering", "D": "Business email compromise"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Business email compromise (BEC) is a form of spear phishing attack that directly targets executives or other high-ranking corporate employees who have the ability to make large payments. BEC schemes typically involve fraudulent emails that appear to be from the company’s own CEO or from the head of a foreign supplier that the company has done business with for years. The emails often instruct the employee to perform a time-sensitive wire transfer to ensure that the supply chain is not disturbed. Increasingly, these emails are paired with an insistent phone call from someone posing as the email sender or as the sender’s attorney. Rock phishers use botnets to send massive amounts of phishing emails to huge volumes of Internet users. The emails contain a message from a financial institution, enticing users to click on a fraudulent URL. Pharming is a type of attack in which a user is fooled into entering sensitive data (such as a password or credit card number) into a malicious website that imitates a legitimate website. It is different from phishing in that in pharming schemes, the attacker does not have to rely on having the user click on a link in an email or other message to direct him to the malicious website that is impersonating a legitimate website. In most social engineering scams, the attacker approaches the computer user, pretending that he needs help; however, in reverse social engineering schemes, the attacker gets the user to make the contact. In these schemes, the attacker disguises himself as a technical assistant or someone from whom the user needs help (a need often created by the attacker through sabotage beforehand). It is the reverse of social engineering—the user asks the attacker for help."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "For employee expense reimbursement requests, electronic receipts are preferred to paper receipts because they are more difficult to alter or forge.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Requiring receipts to be submitted electronically is NOT a recommended form of expense reimbursement fraud prevention. In fact, electronic receipts are often much easier to forge or alter than paper receipts."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a common red flag of procurement fraud schemes involving collusion among contractors?", "options": {"A": "Bid prices begin to fall when a new competitor enters the competition.", "B": "There is limited competition within the industry.", "C": "The same contractors bid on each project or product.", "D": "More competitors than usual submit bids on a project or product."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Common red flags of procurement fraud schemes involving collusion among contractors include: The industry has limited competition. The same contractors bid on each project or product. The winning bid appears too high. All contractors submit consistently high bids. Qualified contractors do not submit bids. The winning bidder subcontracts work to one or more losing bidders or to non-bidders. Bids appear to be complementary bids by companies unqualified to perform the work. Some bids fail to conform to the essential requirements of the solicitation documents (i.e., some bids do not comply with bid specifications). Some losing bids were poorly prepared. Fewer competitors than usual submit bids on a project or product. When a new contractor enters the competition, the bid prices begin to fall. There is a rotational pattern to winning bidders (e.g., geographical, customer, job, or type of work). There is evidence of collusion in the bids (e.g., bidders make the same mathematical or spelling errors; bids are prepared using the same typeface, handwriting, stationery, or envelope; or competitors submit identical bids). There is a pattern where the last party to bid wins the contract. There are patterns of conduct by bidders or their employees that suggest the possibility of collusion (e.g., competitors regularly socialize, hold meetings, visit each other’s offices, or subcontract with each other)."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Physical access controls refer to the process by which users are allowed access to computer programs, systems, and networks.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Physical access controls refer to the process by which users are allowed access to physical objects (e.g., buildings). In contrast, logical access controls are tools used to control access to computer information systems and their components."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Which of the following health care frauds would be best described as a fictitious provider scheme?", "options": {"A": "A provider operates a mobile lab that bills a health care program for unnecessary tests and then relocates.", "B": "A doctor at a hospital inflates the cost of his services by coding them as being more complex than they should be.", "C": "A thief steals a health care provider’s identifier and bills a government health care program under the name of a fake clinic.", "D": "A group of people posing as medical professionals provide services without proper licenses."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In a fictitious provider scheme, corrupt providers or other criminals fraudulently obtain and use another provider’s identification information and steal or purchase lists of patient identifying information. Thereafter, the perpetrator submits bills using the fictitious provider’s information to the insurance provider or government health care program for medical services, although no services are performed."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT considered to be a red flag of a Ponzi scheme?", "options": {"A": "An investment that has a history of inconsistent returns coinciding with fluctuations in financial markets", "B": "A financial manager who manages, administers, and retains custody of the investment funds", "C": "A financial manager who puts an unusual amount of pressure on investors to act immediately", "D": "An investment that promises extremely high or short-term returns with little risk involved"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The following red flags can help investigators uncover Ponzi schemes: Sounds too good to be true: If an investment sounds too good to be true, it probably is. Promises of low risk or high rewards: Promoters of Ponzi schemes typically promise implausibly high or quick returns with little risk. As all legitimate investments include some degree of risk, any guarantee that an investment will perform in a certain way is a clear signal that it might be part of a Ponzi scheme. History of consistent returns: Any firm that generates remarkably consistent returns regardless of market conditions should raise suspicions. High-pressure sales tactics: Reputable investment firms and agents do not push potential investors to act immediately, and legitimate investment opportunities are rarely that time sensitive. Pressure to reinvest: Often, fraudsters keep Ponzi schemes alive by convincing investors to reinvest their profits rather than take a payout. Complex trading strategies: Legitimate agents should be able to provide clear explanations about their investment strategies. For obvious reasons, Ponzi-scheme boosters purposefully employ complicated strategies that confound unsophisticated investors. Lack of transparency or access: Secrecy surrounding the operations of a financial company should be an immediate warning sign. Ponzi operators are often unlicensed and their supposed investments are typically unregistered. Additionally, a lack of access to regular statements or an online account should trigger alarm. Lack of segregation of duties: Investors should be wary of any financial manager who manages, administers, and retains custody of the fund in question."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "In a _________, a bank buys, sells, and swaps its bad loans for the bad loans of another bank, creating new documentation in the process.", "options": {"A": "Daisy chain", "B": "Reciprocal loan arrangement", "C": "False swap scheme", "D": "Linked financing arrangement"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In a daisy chain, a bank buys, sells, and swaps its bad loans for the bad loans of another bank, creating new documentation in the process. Its purpose is to mask or hide bad loans by making them look like they are recent and good."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "When a task force is charged with developing a program for safeguarding proprietary information (SPI), which of the following should be the first step that it takes?", "options": {"A": "Develop an employee awareness program.", "B": "Institute an encryption policy.", "C": "Determine what information should be protected.", "D": "Shred sensitive documents."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "To coordinate a company-wide program for safeguarding proprietary information (SPI), management should establish a task force and charge it with developing the program. The task force should include managers and staff from departments that deal with proprietary information, such as research and development and production. The task force should also include representatives from the following departments: corporate security, human resources, records management, data processing, and legal. Once the task force is assembled, it must identify the information that is to be protected. To make this determination, the task force should identify those areas that give the company its competitive edge (e.g., quality of the product, service, price, manufacturing technology, marketing, and distribution). When doing so, the task force should ask, “What information would a competitor like to know?”"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "A financial fund operator who insists that investors continually reinvest their profits, rather than take payouts, is a red flag of a Ponzi scheme.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The following red flags can help investigators uncover Ponzi schemes: Sounds too good to be true: If an investment sounds too good to be true, it probably is. Promises of low risk or high rewards: Promoters of Ponzi schemes typically promise implausibly high or quick returns with little risk. As all legitimate investments include some degree of risk, any guarantee that an investment will perform in a certain way is a clear signal that it might be part of a Ponzi scheme. History of consistent returns: Any firm that generates remarkably consistent returns regardless of market conditions should raise suspicions. High-pressure sales tactics: Reputable investment firms and agents do not push potential investors to act immediately, and legitimate investment opportunities are rarely that time sensitive. Pressure to reinvest: Often, fraudsters keep Ponzi schemes alive by convincing investors to reinvest their profits rather than take a payout. Complex trading strategies: Legitimate agents should be able to provide clear explanations about their investment strategies. For obvious reasons, Ponzi-scheme boosters purposefully employ complicated strategies that confound unsophisticated investors. Lack of transparency or access: Secrecy surrounding the operations of a financial company should be an immediate warning sign. Ponzi operators are often unlicensed and their supposed investments are typically unregistered. Additionally, a lack of access to regular statements or an online account should trigger alarm. Lack of segregation of duties: Investors should be wary of any financial manager who manages, administers, and retains custody of the fund in question."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a reason why an identity thief might choose to target a business rather than an individual?", "options": {"A": "Businesses’ identification numbers are often publicly available online.", "B": "Businesses are less likely to notice new or unusual financial transactions.", "C": "Businesses usually engage in fewer transactions than individuals do.", "D": "Businesses tend to have easier access to credit and a higher credit limit."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "For identity thieves, there are a number of reasons to target a business rather than an individual. First, the potential rewards are greater; businesses tend to have larger bank account balances, easier access to credit, and higher credit limits than individuals. Second, businesses are less likely to notice new or unusual financial transactions because they tend to engage in more transactions than individuals. Finally, the information necessary to commit business identity theft (e.g., business or tax identification numbers) is often publicly available online or in government records."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "All of the following are best practices for ensuring separation of duties within the information technology department and between information systems and business unit personnel EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Program developers should not be responsible for testing programs.", "B": "End users should not have access to production data outside the scope of their normal job duties.", "C": "Only programmers should be server administrators.", "D": "IT departments should not overlap with information user departments."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Separation of duties is a key element in a well-designed internal control system, and it is fundamental to data security. There are various options for achieving separation of duties in information security, and the options vary depending on department responsibilities. For example, some of the best practices for ensuring separation of duties within the information technology department and between information systems and business unit personnel are as follows: Programmers should not have unsupervised access to production programs or have access to production data sets (data files). Information systems personnel’s access to production data should be limited. Application system users should only be granted access to those functions and data required for their job duties. Program developers should be separated from program testers. System users should not have direct access to program source code. Computer operators should not perform computer programming. Development staff should not have access to production data. Development staff should not access system-level technology or database management systems. End users should not have access to production data outside the scope of their normal job duties. End users or system operators should not have direct access to program source code. Programmers should not be server administrators or database administrators. IT departments should be separated from information user departments. Functions involving the creation, installation, and administration of software programs should be assigned to different individuals. Managers at all levels should review existing and planned processes and systems to ensure proper separation of duties. Employees’ access to documents should be limited to those that correspond with their related job tasks."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a way in which an electronic funds transfer (EFT) fraud scheme can be committed?", "options": {"A": "An employee of a person-to-person (P2P) provider misappropriates a customer’s account and password information", "B": "A person who has stolen information about another person’s bank account instructs a biller to obtain payment from that account", "C": "A hacker obtains consumer account and password information to direct funds from consumers’ accounts", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There are several ways in which fraud can be perpetrated through the electronic transfer of funds. Potential sources of fraud include the following: A biller might send a bill for services not rendered or for goods never sent. A person who has obtained information about another person’s bank account might instruct a biller to obtain payment from the other person’s account. A hacker might obtain passwords and usernames from an aggregator and use that information to direct transfers from a consumer’s bank account. An employee at the site providing electronic bill payment services who knows consumers’ usernames and passwords for screen-scraping purposes might use that information to direct transfers from consumers’ bank accounts. A bank employee might use customer information to direct transfers from a customer’s account."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "In a take-the-money-and-run scheme, fraudsters lure potential victims using fake vacation rental listings or websites advertising properties that do not actually exist.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A take-the-money-and-run scheme is a variation of an advance-fee scheme that occurs when a fraudster creates a fake vacation rental listing or website. The fraudster takes photos of properties directly off the Internet and uses random interior photos from other rental sites to make the properties appear to be lived in. In reality, the advertised property does not exist or is not at the address provided. As part of the scam, the fraudster usually asks the victim to wire funds for the first and last night’s stay or even requires the victim to pay in full. After receiving the funds and passing off fake information about the short-term rental to the victim, the fraudster disappears and is no longer reachable. The victim shows up at the address provided and realizes the rental property does not exist."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Falsified prescriptions for equipment, excessive supplies, noncovered supplies, and scooter scams are forms of fraud commonly involving what type of health care entity?", "options": {"A": "Out-patient services groups", "B": "Special care facilities", "C": "Reusable medical equipment suppliers", "D": "Hospitals"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Reusable medical equipment, often called durable medical equipment (DME), includes items such as crutches, wheelchairs, and specialized patient beds. Fraud schemes perpetrated by reusable medical equipment suppliers frequently involve: Falsified prescriptions for equipment or supplies Intentionally providing excessive supplies Equipment not delivered or billed before delivery Billing for equipment rental beyond when the equipment was checked out Billing for supplies not covered by the insurance policy or health care program Scooter scams (i.e., billing for electric-powered wheelchairs that are either unnecessary or are of poorer quality than the model billed for)"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is the most accurate definition of a computer worm?", "options": {"A": "Any software application in which advertising banners are displayed while a program is running", "B": "A type of software that, while not definitely malicious, has a suspicious or potentially unwanted aspect to it", "C": "A self-replicating computer program that penetrates operating systems to spread malicious code to other systems", "D": "A program or command procedure that gives the appearance that it is useful but in fact contains hidden malicious code that causes damage"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A computer worm is a malicious self-replicating computer program that penetrates operating systems to spread malicious code to other computers."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "_________________ is the most common type of identity theft.", "options": {"A": "Financial identity theft", "B": "Criminal identity theft", "C": "Business identity theft", "D": "Medical identity theft"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Financial identity theft occurs when a fraudster uses an individual’s personal information for fraudulent financial transactions. Examples of financial identity theft include: Using an individual’s stolen credit card or credit card number to purchase goods (account takeover) Impersonating an individual to gain access to the individual’s bank account (account takeover) Using an individual’s personal information to open a new credit card account (true name fraud) Most identity theft involves accessing existing financial accounts or creating new financial accounts. Therefore, most identity theft is financial identity theft."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Jacob was on a business trip in another city. One night, he met up with some friends (unrelated to his work) at an expensive restaurant and paid for the group's entire meal on his credit card, announcing that “the company would pay for it.” He submitted the receipt for the dinner along with the rest of his legitimate business receipts from the trip and described the dinner as “client entertainment.” What type of scheme did Jacob commit?", "options": {"A": "A fictitious expense scheme", "B": "A multiple reimbursement scheme", "C": "A mischaracterized expense scheme", "D": "An overstated expense scheme"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "One of the most basic expense reimbursement schemes is perpetrated by simply requesting reimbursement for a personal expense, claiming that it is business related. Examples of mischaracterized expenses include claiming personal travel as a business trip, listing dinner with a friend as “business development” or “client entertainment,” and so on. Employees might submit the receipts from their personal expenses along with their expense reports but concoct business reasons for the incurred costs."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "A doctor provides services to both patients who pay directly and patients whose bills are paid by a government program. To make his services more attractive to patients outside the coverage of the government program, he gives patients who pay directly a discount that is not applicable to patients under the program. Which of the following best describes the provider’s scheme?", "options": {"A": "Upcoding", "B": "Disparate price", "C": "Fictitious claim", "D": "Overutilization"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Many government health care programs require that they receive the best available price that providers offer. In a disparate price scheme, providers charge some patients (e.g., those in direct payment situations) a lower rate than they charge the government. This disparate bill rate causes the government to pay a higher rate in violation of regulations mandating that the government receive the lowest rate. In addition, some government health programs require that wholesale pharmacies provide the program at the average wholesale price. However, providers might manipulate their data and provide false information to the government program."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following activities is included in the bid evaluation and award phase of procurements involving open and free competition?", "options": {"A": "The procuring employees issue the solicitation document.", "B": "The procuring employees perform their contractual obligations.", "C": "The procuring employees develop the bid specifications.", "D": "The procuring employees assess the bids or proposals."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In the bid evaluation and award phase, the procuring employees evaluate the bids or proposals, conduct discussions and negotiations, and give the bidders an opportunity to revise their proposals. Procuring employees then select the winning bid or proposal."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "A forged maker scheme is a check tampering scheme in which an employee intercepts a company check intended for a third party and converts the check by signing the third party’s name on the check’s endorsement line.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Forged endorsement frauds are those check tampering schemes in which an employee intercepts a company check intended for a third party and converts the check by signing the third party’s name on the check’s endorsement line. The person who signs a check is known as the “maker” of the check. A forged maker scheme is defined as a check tampering scheme in which an employee misappropriates a check and fraudulently affixes the signature of an authorized maker thereon."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Which of the following is a typical method used to make corrupt payments in bribery and corruption schemes?", "options": {"A": "Checks and other financial instruments", "B": "Payment of credit card bills", "C": "Gifts, travel, and entertainment", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Often, corruption schemes involve corrupt payments—items of value paid to procure a benefit contrary to the rights of others. There are various ways to make corrupt payments, and many do not involve money. Any tangible benefit given or received with the intent to corruptly influence the recipient can be an illegal payment, and traditional methods of making corrupt payments include: Gifts, travel, and entertainment Cash payments Checks and other financial instruments Hidden interests Loans Credit cards Transfers not at fair market value Promises of favorable treatment"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "_______________ is a system by which the bank verifies checks presented for payment against the list provided by the company of approved checks written on the account.", "options": {"A": "Check matching", "B": "Payment patrol", "C": "Verification control", "D": "Positive pay"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Positive pay allows a company and its bank to work together to detect fraudulent items presented for payment. The company provides the bank with a list of checks and amounts that are written each day. The bank verifies items presented for payment against the company’s list. The bank rejects items that are not on the list. Investigations are conducted as to the origin of the “unlisted” items."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "All of the following are types of medical provider fraud EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Fictitious services", "B": "Smurfing", "C": "Clinical lab schemes", "D": "Fictitious providers"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fictitious services, clinical lab schemes, and fictitious providers are all types of medical provider fraud. In a fictitious services scheme, legitimate health care providers charge or bill a health care program for services that were not rendered at all. Often, the providers submit bills for patients they have never seen but whose private patient information they purchased from someone involved in identity theft or someone who otherwise improperly obtained it. In a fictitious provider scheme, corrupt providers or other criminals fraudulently obtain and use another provider’s identification information and steal or purchase lists of patient identifying information. Thereafter, the perpetrator submits bills using the fictitious provider’s information to the insurance provider or government health care program for medical services, although no services are performed. Clinical lab schemes occur when a provider advises a patient that additional medical testing is needed to diagnose a problem when the testing is not actually required or advisable. The fee for the unnecessary work often is split with physicians. In some cases, physicians own the medical testing service. Additional medical testing, which is later viewed as excessive, is not always fraud. Many doctors have a genuine fear of retaliation from their patients; they are afraid of malpractice lawsuits that might result from a delayed or erroneous diagnosis. Smurfing is a scheme to launder funds through financial institutions."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Credits decrease asset and expense accounts.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Entries to the left side of an account are referred to as debits, and entries to the right side of an account are referred to as credits. Debits increase asset and expense accounts, whereas credits decrease these accounts. On the other side of the equation, credits increase liability, revenue, and owners’ equity accounts. Conversely, debits decrease liabilities, revenues, and owners’ equity."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is the most accurate definition of a software keylogger?", "options": {"A": "A self-replicating computer program that penetrates operating systems to spread malicious code to other systems", "B": "A program or command procedure that gives the appearance that it is useful but in fact contains hidden malicious code that causes damage", "C": "A type of program that monitors and logs the keys pressed on a system’s keyboard", "D": "A type of software that, while not definitely malicious, has a suspicious or potentially unwanted aspect to it"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Keyloggers monitor and log (or track) the keys pressed on a system’s keyboard, and they can be either software or hardware based. Accordingly, some keyloggers are malware, but others are not."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Which of the following situations is often present in real estate fraud schemes?", "options": {"A": "The services of an arms-length legal representative", "B": "No expert assistance at closing", "C": "A false appraisal report", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Real estate transactions assume a willing buyer and a willing seller. Fraud can occur when the transaction breaks down or the expert assistance is not at arm's length. Many real estate fraud schemes have a false appraisal report as a condition precedent."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "The accounts receivable clerk should be responsible for preparing the bank deposit.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The bank deposit should be made by someone other than the cashier or the accounts receivable clerk. A person independent of the cash receipts and accounts receivable functions should compare entries to the cash receipts journal with: Authenticated bank deposit slips The deposit per the bank statements"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "All of the following are methods of identity theft prevention recommended for individuals EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Use biometric authentication when available.", "B": "Avoid using unsecured, public Wi-Fi networks.", "C": "Instruct the post office to suspend mail during vacations.", "D": "Use the same password or passphrase for all accounts."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following are some of the steps individuals can take to protect their personal information and prevent identity theft: Do not give out government identification numbers unless absolutely necessary. Do not carry government identification cards (or numbers) in purses or wallets. Create complex passwords or passphrases that are at least eight characters in length and contain upper- and lower-case letters, numbers, and symbols. Do not reuse passwords. Use a different password for every website, account, or device. Never send personal information, such as a password or government identification number, via email. Reputable organizations will not request personal information by email. When available, use biometric authentication (e.g., fingerprints, voice recognition). Create unique answers for security questions. Do not choose answers containing personal information that is publicly available (e.g., name of high school, mother’s maiden name). Protect computers with strong and regularly updated firewall and antivirus software, and promptly install all security updates and patches. Avoid suspicious websites. Delete messages from unknown senders without opening them. Only download software from trusted websites. Avoid using unsecured, public Wi-Fi networks. Limit the amount of personal information shared on social media. Use software to permanently erase all data from hard drives before disposing of computers, smartphones, copiers, printers, and other electronic devices. Secure physical mailboxes with a lock, check physical mail regularly, and instruct the post office to suspend mail during vacations. Shred all sensitive documents. Opt out of unsolicited offers for pre-approved credit cards or other lines of credit. Pay attention to billing cycles and review all bills and statements. Check credit reports regularly."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "The assumption that a business will continue indefinitely is reflected in the accounting concept of:", "options": {"A": "Going concern", "B": "Objective evidence", "C": "Comparability", "D": "Relevance"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A company's management is required to provide disclosures when existing events or conditions indicate that it is more likely than not that the entity might be unable to meet its obligations within a reasonable period of time after the financial statements are issued. There is an underlying assumption that an entity will continue as a going concern; that is, the life of the entity will be long enough to fulfill its financial and legal obligations. Any evidence to the contrary must be reported in the entity’s financial statements."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Brittany, a cash register teller, signed onto her register, rang a \"no sale\" transaction to open the drawer, and then removed a large sum of money. Which of the following schemes has taken place?", "options": {"A": "A cash larceny scheme", "B": "A register disbursement scheme", "C": "A skimming scheme", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The most straightforward cash larceny scheme is one in which the perpetrator just opens the register and removes currency. This might be done as a sale is being conducted to make the theft appear to be part of the transaction, or perhaps when no one is around to notice the perpetrator digging into the cash drawer. For instance, a teller could simply sign onto a register, ring a “no sale,” and take currency from the drawer. This scheme is not a register disbursement scheme because register disbursement schemes involve a fraudulent transaction that justifies the removal of cash from the register, such as a false return or a voided sale. Brittany did not make any entry that would account for the missing money. In addition, the scheme is not a skimming scheme because the money in the register was already a part of the company's accounting system. There was no indication that the cash was part of an unrecorded or understated sale."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Fraudulent kickbacks in the health care industry can include which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Payment for additional medical coverage", "B": "Waiver of deductibles and copayments", "C": "Payment for referral of patients", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Kickbacks in the health care industry can come from several sources. Examples of kickbacks include: Payment for referral of patients Waiver of deductibles and copayments Payment for additional medical coverage Payment for vendor contracts Payments to adjusters"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Which of the following factors enables or enhances fraudsters’ abilities to conduct account takeover schemes?", "options": {"A": "Customers regularly checking their online accounts for changes", "B": "The increased use of multifactor authentication", "C": "Payment accounts offering the ability to be notified when they are accessed or changed", "D": "Consumers using the same login and password information on multiple accounts"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Account takeover fraud occurs when a fraudster surreptitiously takes control of a payment account. Targeted accounts can include credit cards, banking, brokerage, or any type of online retail account (e.g., Amazon). Because consumers often use the same username and password for multiple accounts, hackers commonly create code that can run credentials obtained from a data breach at one company to see if they are valid for another. Account takeover fraud has increased significantly in recent years. Consumers should opt for multifactor authentication when available, request notification of account access or changes when offered, and regularly check any online accounts that hold payment information."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Reconciling the cash register total to the amount of cash in the drawer is an ineffective method of detecting a cash larceny scheme.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In contrast to skimming schemes, the register records should NOT match up with the cash in the drawer when a cash larceny scheme has occurred. For this reason, cash larceny schemes are much easier to detect than skimming schemes—they leave an audit trail. To detect a cash larceny scheme, one recommended practice is to perform independent reconciliations of the register totals to the amount of cash in the drawer."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Telemarketing schemes target individuals, not businesses.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Telemarketing offenses are classified as consumer fraud, yet many businesses are affected by office supply and marketing services scams. The nature of phone rooms, the geographical distances between the perpetrators and their victims, and the resources and priorities of law enforcement agencies all make enforcement efforts difficult."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Payers can make corrupt payments by giving recipients hidden interests in profit-making enterprises.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A payer might make a corrupt payment by giving the recipient a hidden interest in a joint venture or other profit-making enterprise."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Management has an obligation to disclose all events and transactions in the financial statements that are likely to have a material effect on the entity's financial position.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Accounting principles require that financial statements include all the information necessary to prevent a reasonably discerning user of the financial statements from being misled. Disclosures only need to include events and transactions that have or are likely to have a material impact on the entity’s financial position."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT an example of a business email compromise scheme?", "options": {"A": "Fraudsters posing as a company’s foreign supplier send an email to the company and request that funds be transferred to an alternate account controlled by the fraudsters.", "B": "Fraudsters use botnets to send massive amounts of emails for the purpose of enticing users to click on a fraudulent URL.", "C": "Fraudsters use the compromised email account of a high-level executive to request employees’ tax information or other personally identifiable information from the person responsible for maintaining such information.", "D": "Fraudsters use the compromised email account of a high-level executive to pose as the executive and ask an employee to transfer funds to the fraudsters’ account."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Business email compromise (BEC) is a form of spear phishing attack that directly targets executives or other high-ranking corporate employees who have the ability to make large payments. BEC schemes typically involve fraudulent emails that appear to be from the company’s own CEO or from the head of a foreign supplier that the company has done business with for years. The emails often instruct the employee to perform a time-sensitive wire transfer to ensure that the supply chain is not disturbed. Increasingly, these emails are paired with an insistent phone call from someone posing as the email sender or as the sender’s attorney. Although these schemes can take numerous forms, the FBI has identified five common scenarios for BEC schemes: Business working with a foreign supplier: Fraudsters posing as a company’s foreign supplier send an email to the company and request that funds be transferred to an alternate account controlled by the fraudsters. Business executive requesting a wire transfer: Fraudsters use the compromised email account of a high-level executive to pose as the executive and ask an employee to transfer funds to the fraudsters’ account. Vendors receiving fraudulent request for payment: Fraudsters use an employee’s compromised email account to identify the company’s vendors and ask them to transfer funds to the fraudsters’ account. Attorney impersonation: Fraudsters posing as the company’s attorney contact an employee and request a transfer of funds to the fraudsters’ account, often insisting that the employee act quickly and secretly. Data theft: Fraudsters use the compromised email account of a high-level executive to request employees’ tax information or other personally identifiable information from the person responsible for maintaining such information (e.g., human resources personnel). This stolen data may then be used to commit one of the BEC schemes described above. Rock phishers use botnets to send massive amounts of phishing emails to huge volumes of Internet users. The emails contain a message from a financial institution, enticing users to click on a fraudulent URL. There is some indication that rock phishers cycle through multiple email lists and attempt to reach the Internet users most likely to use the brands that they are targeting."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "In credit repair scams, the fraudster promises to “erase” or “doctor” an applicant’s credit history, but in reality there is no way to erase bad credit.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Similar to loan scams are those that promise to repair credit. Pitch men like to say that they can “wipe away,” “doctor,” or “cosmeticize” negative items on credit, insinuating they have ways of changing or disguising a person’s credit history. Despite the fact that there is really no way to erase bad credit, many people fall for this scam, paying large sums of money to expunge their records."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following practices is a potential indicator of a bid splitting scheme?", "options": {"A": "Low employee turnover in an organization's procurement department", "B": "Two or more purchases from the same supplier in amounts just above competitive bidding limits", "C": "Sequential purchases under the competitive bidding limits that are followed by change orders", "D": "Frequent use of sole-source procurement contracts"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In general, procuring entities must use competitive methods for projects over a certain amount. To avoid this requirement, a dishonest employee might break up a large project into several small projects that fall below the mandatory bidding level and award some or all of the component jobs to a contractor with whom the employee is conspiring. Some common red flags of bid splitting schemes include: Two or more similar or identical procurements from the same supplier in amounts just under upper-level review or competitive-bidding limits Two or more consecutive related procurements from the same contractor that fall just below the competitive-bidding or upper-level review limits Unjustified split purchases that fall under the competitive-bidding or upper-level review limits Sequential purchases just under the upper-level review or competitive-bidding limits Sequential purchases under the upper-level review or competitive-bidding limits that are followed by change orders"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is the correct calculation of the quick ratio?", "options": {"A": "(Cash + marketable securities) / accounts payable", "B": "(Cash + marketable securities + receivables) / current liabilities", "C": "Current assets / current liabilities", "D": "(Cash + receivables) / current liabilities"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The quick ratio, commonly referred to as the acid test ratio, compares quick assets (i.e., those that can be immediately liquidated) to current liabilities. This ratio is a measure of a company’s ability to meet sudden cash requirements. It is important to note that while the current ratio includes inventory in its current assets, the quick ratio does not. Thus, the quick ratio offers a more conservative view of a company’s liquidity because it excludes inventory and other current assets that are more difficult to rapidly turn into cash. The equation for the quick ratio is: Quick ratio = (cash + marketable securities + receivables) / current liabilities."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following statements is NOT true regarding the statement of cash flows?", "options": {"A": "There are three types of cash flows: cash flows from operating activities, from investing activities, and from financing activities.", "B": "The statement of cash flows reports a company’s sources and uses of cash during the accounting period.", "C": "The statement of cash flows is often used in tandem with the income statement to determine a company’s true financial performance.", "D": "The statement of cash flows shows a company’s financial position at a specific point in time."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The statement of cash flows reports a company’s sources and uses of cash during the accounting period. This statement is often used by potential investors and other interested parties in tandem with the income statement to determine a company’s true financial performance during the period being reported. The statement of cash flows is broken down into three sections: cash flows from operating activities, cash flows from investing activities, and cash flows from financing activities. The balance sheet shows a company’s financial position at a specific point in time."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Early revenue recognition is classified as what type of financial fraud scheme?", "options": {"A": "Improper disclosures", "B": "Fictitious revenues", "C": "Timing differences", "D": "Improper asset valuations"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Financial statement fraud might involve timing differences—that is, the recording of revenues or expenses in improper periods. This can be done to shift revenues or expenses between one period and the next, increasing or decreasing earnings as desired. Early revenue recognition is a common type of timing difference scheme since companies are often trying to make themselves look as profitable as possible. This practice is also referred to as income smoothing."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "A fraudster can understate expenses and their related liabilities to make a company appear more profitable than it actually is.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Understating liabilities and expenses is one of the ways financial statements can be manipulated to make a company appear more profitable. Because pre-tax income will increase by the full amount of the expense or liability not recorded, this financial statement fraud method can significantly affect reported earnings with relatively little effort by the fraudster. There are three common methods for concealing liabilities and expenses: Omitting liabilities and/or expenses Improperly capitalizing costs rather than expensing them Failing to disclose warranty costs and product-return liabilities"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a means of measuring the relationship between two different financial statement amounts?", "options": {"A": "Transaction detail analysis", "B": "Relational comparison", "C": "Statement comparison", "D": "Ratio analysis"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Ratio analysis is a means of measuring the relationship between two different financial statement amounts. The relationship and comparison are the keys to the analysis, which allows for internal evaluations using financial statement data. Traditionally, financial statement ratios are used in comparisons to an entity’s industry average. They can be very useful in detecting red flags for a fraud examination."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Pharming differs from phishing in that in a pharming scheme:", "options": {"A": "The attacker delivers the solicitation message via SMS (the protocol used to transmit text messages via mobile devices) instead of email.", "B": "The attacker has to rely on having the user click on a link in an email or other message to direct him to the malicious website that is imitating a legitimate website.", "C": "The attacker delivers the solicitation message via telephones using Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) instead of email.", "D": "The attacker does not have to rely on having the user click on a link in an email or other message to direct him to the malicious website that is imitating a legitimate website."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Pharming is an attack in which a user is fooled into entering sensitive data (such as a password or credit card number) into a malicious website that imitates a legitimate website. It is different from phishing in that the attacker in a pharming scheme does not have to rely on having the user click on a link in an email or other message to direct him to the imitation website."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Smart cards include a wide variety of hardware and software features capable of detecting and reacting to tampering attempts and countering possible attacks.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A smart card is a plastic card, the size of a credit card, embedded with a microchip. A key advantage of smart cards is that, unlike regular magnetic stripe credit cards, they cannot be easily replicated. Similarly, smart cards cannot be easily counterfeited, which greatly reduces the potential for fraud. Smart cards include a wide variety of hardware and software features capable of detecting and reacting to tampering attempts and countering possible attacks. If someone tries to tamper with a chip on a smart card, the card detects the intrusion and shuts itself down, rendering the card useless."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Victims of consumer fraud are more likely to be organizations or businesses rather than individuals.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Consumer fraud schemes involve a range of fraudulent conduct, usually committed by professional scammers, against unsuspecting victims. Scammers are skilled fraudsters who develop strategies, select targets, and use an appropriate method of delivery to lure their victims. Scammers usually act alone, but they might group together for a particularly complex endeavor. The victims can be organizations but more commonly are individuals. Victims can be old or young, male or female, or wealthy or poor, and they are usually dispersed geographically. Many victims who become the targets of consumer fraud are considered to be in the naïve segments of the population, such as the elderly. It is important to note, however, that even the savviest consumers can become targets if they are not aware of the schemes involving consumer fraud."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Maria, a successful restaurateur, has been informed of an unusually attractive investment opportunity by a recent acquaintance and decides to invest in it. Several months and a couple of underwhelming payments later, Maria grows frustrated with the diminishing disbursements and attempts to withdraw her money. After several weeks of delay, she realizes that the promoter seems to have vanished, along with her investment. Maria is the victim of which of the following fraudulent ploys?", "options": {"A": "A fly and buy scheme", "B": "A Ponzi scheme", "C": "A dog and pony scam", "D": "An illegal pyramid"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A Ponzi scheme is generally defined as an illegal business practice in which new investors’ money is used to make payments to earlier investors. The investment opportunity is typically presented with the promise of uncommonly high returns. While the scam is presented as a legitimate investment, there is little or no actual commerce involved. When an enterprise promotes an investment opportunity that invests little or none of the participants’ money and uses new investments to make dividend payments, the enterprise is running a Ponzi scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "A company must disclose all contingent liabilities in the notes to the financial statements, regardless of the liabilities’ probability or materiality.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Contingent liabilities are potential obligations that will materialize only if certain events occur in the future. A corporate guarantee of personal loans received by a company officer and potential losses from ongoing litigation are examples of contingent liabilities. Under generally accepted accounting principles, a company’s potential liability must be disclosed in the notes to the financial statements if the liability is reasonably possible. A potential liability must be recorded if it is probable that a loss will occur and the amount of the loss can be reasonably estimated."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "When should an employee be made aware of the need to maintain the confidentiality of an organization’s proprietary information, as well as which information is considered confidential?", "options": {"A": "Upon being hired", "B": "During an exit interview", "C": "When signing a nondisclosure agreement", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Often, employees are willing to abide by nondisclosure agreements, but they do not understand that the information they are communicating might be confidential. To more effectively implement nondisclosure agreements, employees must be clearly informed as to what information is considered confidential upon hiring, upon signing a nondisclosure agreement, and during exit interviews."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Lindsey, a medical provider, provides monetary payments to existing patients and to other providers for referring new patients to her practice. Which of the following best describes Lindsey’s scheme?", "options": {"A": "Kickback", "B": "Beneficiary fraud", "C": "Fictitious services", "D": "Deductible forfeiture"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Kickbacks in the health care industry can come from several sources. Examples of kickbacks include: Payment for referral of patients Waiver of deductibles and copayments Payment for additional medical coverage Payment for vendor contracts Payments to adjusters Providers in an area of high competition will pay runners to recruit new patients. In addition, patients might receive a monetary reward if they refer another patient to a provider. The provider makes up for the kickback in the unnecessary billing of medical expenses or false claims. In addition, providers will pay kickbacks to other physicians for patient referrals."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Sean is responsible for delivering timesheets to the payroll department on behalf of his supervisor. One day he decides to withhold his timesheet from those being sent to his supervisor for approval. He falsely increases the number of hours he has worked and then forges his supervisor’s signature on his timesheet. He adds the timesheet to the stack of authorized sheets and delivers them to payroll. This is an example of:", "options": {"A": "A ghost employee scheme", "B": "A check tampering scheme", "C": "A fictitious reimbursement scheme", "D": "A falsified hours and salary scheme"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "For hourly employees, the size of a paycheck is based on two essential factors: the number of hours worked and the rate of pay. Therefore, for hourly employees to fraudulently increase the size of their paycheck, they must either falsify the number of hours they have worked or change their wage rate. One form of control breakdown that is common in falsified hours and salary schemes is the failure to maintain proper control over timecards. In a properly run system, once timecards are authorized by management, they should be sent directly to payroll. Those who prepare the timecards should not have access to them after they have been approved. When this procedure is not observed, the person who prepared a timecard can alter it after that person’s supervisor has approved it but before it is delivered to payroll. Common ways to commit a falsified hours and salary scheme include: Inflating the number of hours worked Inflating the rate of pay Forging a supervisor’s signature Collusion with a supervisor Implementing poor custody procedures Altering a timesheet after it has been approved"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Favorite targets for intelligence-gathering purposes include employees in all of the following departments EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Research and development", "B": "Purchasing", "C": "Marketing", "D": "Shipping and receiving"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Some of the favorite targets of intelligence gatherers include employees in the following departments: research and development, marketing, manufacturing and production, human resources, sales, and purchasing."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "For a ghost employee scheme involving an hourly employee to be successful, all of the following must happen EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Timekeeping information must be collected for the ghost employee.", "B": "A paycheck must be issued to the ghost employee.", "C": "The ghost employee must be added to the payroll.", "D": "The ghost employee must be a fictitious person."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "For a ghost employee scheme to work, four things must happen: (1) the ghost must be added to the payroll, (2) timekeeping (for an hourly employee) and wage rate information must be collected, (3) a paycheck must be issued to the ghost, and (4) the check must be delivered to the perpetrator or an accomplice. The ghost employee may be a fictitious person or a real individual who simply does not work for the victim employer. When the ghost is a real person, it is often the perpetrator’s friend or relative. In some cases, the ghost employee is an accomplice of the fraudster who cashes the fraudulent paychecks and splits the money with the perpetrator."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following could be used to balance the accounting equation if cash were stolen?", "options": {"A": "Reducing a liability", "B": "Reducing revenue", "C": "Increasing another asset", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The accounting equation, Assets = Liabilities + Owners' Equity, is the basis for all double-entry accounting. If an asset (e.g., cash) is stolen, the equation can be balanced by increasing another asset, reducing a liability, reducing an owners' equity account, reducing revenues (and thus retained earnings), or creating an expense (and thus reducing retained earnings)."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "In which of the following scenarios might a credit card skimming scheme be conducted?", "options": {"A": "A server walks away from a customer’s table to process a credit card payment", "B": "A retail employee processes a payment outside of the customer’s view", "C": "A customer is pumping gasoline and notices a strange device attached to the self-payment apparatus", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A credit card skimming scheme requires a device, often referred to as a skimmer or a wedge, that scans and stores a large amount of credit card numbers. Credit card skimming is more frequent in businesses where an employee is able to remove the card from the customer’s view to process the transaction before returning it to the customer. Skimming can also be performed via the attachment of covert devices to ATMs, automated fuel dispensers, vending machines, or self-service checkout kiosks. These devices are occasionally paired with a tiny hidden camera meant to record the input of a user’s PIN code."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Fraudulent disbursement schemes include which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Check tampering schemes", "B": "Register disbursement schemes", "C": "Payroll schemes", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "All of the following are types of fraudulent disbursement schemes: Register disbursement schemes Check tampering schemes Payroll schemes Billing schemes Expense reimbursement schemes"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following schemes refers to the falsification of personnel or payroll records, causing paychecks to be generated to someone who does not actually work for the victim company?", "options": {"A": "Ghost employee scheme", "B": "Record alteration scheme", "C": "Inflated commission scheme", "D": "Falsified salary scheme"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The term ghost employee refers to someone on the payroll who does not actually work for the victim company. Through the falsification of personnel or payroll records, a fraudster causes paychecks to be generated to a non-employee, or ghost. The fraudster or an accomplice then converts these paychecks. The ghost employee may be a fictitious person or a real individual who simply does not work for the victim employer."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE with regard to gross margin?", "options": {"A": "Gross margin is equal to net sales less cost of goods sold.", "B": "Gross margin is another term for net income.", "C": "Gross margin is the top line of the income statement.", "D": "Gross margin is equal to revenues less operating expenses."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Two basic types of accounts are reported on the income statement—revenues and expenses. Revenues represent amounts received from the sale of goods or services during the accounting period. Most companies present net sales as the first line item on the income statement. The term net means that the amount shown is the company’s total sales minus any sales refunds, returns, discounts, or allowances. From net sales, an expense titled cost of goods sold or cost of sales is deducted. Regardless of the industry, this expense denotes the amount a company spent (in past, present, and/or future accounting periods) to produce the goods or services that were sold during the current period. The difference between net sales and cost of goods sold is called gross profit or gross margin, which represents the amount left over from sales to pay the company’s operating expenses."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Which of the following methods might be used to conceal a sham loan transaction in which the loan officer receives part of the proceeds (kickback)?", "options": {"A": "\"Digging\" the loan on the books", "B": "Charging off the loan as a bad loan", "C": "Turning the loan over to a collections agency", "D": "Letting the loan go into arrears"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Loan officers will sometimes make loans to accomplices who then share all or part of the proceeds with the lending officer. This is called a sham loan scheme. In some instances, the loans are charged off as bad debts; in other instances, the fake loans are paid off with the proceeds of new fraudulent loans."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Which of the following are signs that a multilevel marketing organization's activities might be illegal?", "options": {"A": "The organization offers participants large payments for each new recruit", "B": "The organization recruits distributors into a pyramid-style compensation plan", "C": "The organization spends more time promoting its distributor levels than its product lines", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "As a general rule, any organization that recruits distributors into a pyramid-style compensation plan, offers big payoffs for recruiting, and spends more time extolling its distributor levels than its product lines is probably illegal."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "The chances of being arrested and prosecuted for check fraud are high, and the penalties are relatively severe.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Check fraud is considered a relatively low-risk crime; the chances of being arrested and prosecuted are low, and the penalties are relatively mild."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "question": "Workers’ compensation schemes are generally broken into four categories. Which of the following is NOT one of these categories?", "options": {"A": "Double duty fraud", "B": "Agent fraud", "C": "Premium fraud", "D": "Claimant fraud"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Workers’ compensation schemes are generally broken into four categories: premium fraud, agent fraud, claimant fraud, and organized fraud schemes. Premium fraud involves the misrepresentation of information to the insurer by employers to lower the cost of workers’ compensation premiums. For example, an employer might understate the amount of the payroll for higher-risk classifications, thus receiving lower-cost premiums. Agent fraud schemes consist primarily of pilfering premiums and conspiring to reduce premiums. Underhanded agents sometimes issue certificates of coverage to the ostensibly insured customer while misappropriating the premium rather than forwarding it to the insurance carrier. Agents might also conspire to alter or improperly influence insurance applications to offer lower premiums to their clients. Claimant fraud involves misrepresenting the circumstances of any injury or fabricating that an injury occurred. Organized fraud schemes are composed of the united efforts of a lawyer, a capper, a doctor, and the claimant. This type of scheme is used not only in workers’ compensation cases but also in other medical frauds, such as automobile injuries."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Lack of employee education concerning nondisclosure agreements is one of the primary reasons employees communicate confidential information to outside parties.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Lack of employee education concerning nondisclosure agreements is one of the primary reasons employees communicate confidential information to outside parties. Often, employees are willing to abide by nondisclosure agreements, but they do not understand that the information they are communicating might be confidential. To more effectively implement nondisclosure agreements, employees must be clearly informed as to what information is considered confidential upon hiring, upon signing a nondisclosure agreement, and during exit interviews."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Examples of fraud schemes perpetrated by health care institutions and their employees include all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Improper contractual relationships", "B": "DRG creep", "C": "Unintentional misrepresentation of the diagnosis", "D": "Billing for experimental procedures"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Fraud schemes perpetrated by institutions and their employees include those commonly used by doctors and other providers. However, the more common schemes in which hospitals are primarily involved include: Filing of false cost reports DRG creep Billing for experimental procedures Improper contractual and other relationships with physicians Revenue recovery firms to (knowingly or unknowingly) bill extra charges"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "A Ponzi scheme can best be described as an illegal business structure that might offer merchandise or services but generates almost all of its revenues from the relentless recruitment of new members.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A Ponzi scheme is generally defined as an illegal business practice in which new investors’ money is used to make payments to earlier investors. The investment opportunity is typically presented with the promise of uncommonly high returns. While the scam is presented as a legitimate investment, there is little or no actual commerce involved. In contrast, an illegal pyramid scheme is unique in that the more members that are recruited, the higher the investor is purported to rise in the ranks of the enterprise, and the more money the investor is supposed to make."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Loyalty programs are susceptible to fraud for all of the following reasons EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Loyalty points can only be used for products or services offered by the original company.", "B": "Some airlines allow the conversion of travel points for tickets in another person’s name.", "C": "Many loyalty programs allow the transfer of points from one account to another.", "D": "Loyalty points can often be used to purchase sellable items such as gift cards."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Loyalty fraud typically results from fraudsters gaining access to a rewards account by obtaining login credentials through phishing or hacking. Fraudulent transactions can be difficult to recognize because many consumers use their points to purchase gifts for others, with many airlines even allowing the conversion of travel points for tickets in another person’s name. Increasingly, points programs from one company are joined with programs from other companies to enhance the options and utility available for consumers. Whereas airline points at one time might have only been valid toward the purchase of an airline ticket with the issuing airline, rewards programs are increasingly offered as part of an alliance of expanded loyalty networks that allow consumers to exchange their points for numerous unrelated products and services, such as hotel stays, retail purchases, or gift cards. The ability to convert loyalty points to sellable items such as gift cards allows fraudsters to leverage compromised loyalty accounts for cash. Furthermore, many loyalty programs allow the transfer of points from one account to another within the expanded program network, thus allowing fraudsters to transfer points from numerous compromised accounts into whichever program is most conducive to their scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following financial statement manipulations is NOT a type of improper asset valuation scheme?", "options": {"A": "Recording expenses in the wrong period", "B": "Booking of fictitious assets", "C": "Inflated inventory valuation", "D": "Overstated accounts receivable"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Most improper asset valuations involve the fraudulent overstatement of inventory or receivables, with the goal being to strengthen the appearance of the balance sheet and/or certain financial ratios. Other improper asset valuations include manipulation of the allocation of the purchase price of an acquired business to inflate future earnings, misclassification of fixed and other assets, or improper capitalization of inventory or start-up costs. Improper asset valuations usually take the form of one of the following classifications: Inventory valuation Accounts receivable Business combinations Fixed assets"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Electronic payment tampering is generally easier to detect than traditional check tampering because it leaves a clear audit trail.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Electronic payment tampering is generally more difficult to detect than traditional check tampering schemes. As with other schemes, once the fraudulent payment has been made, the employee must cover his tracks. However, the lack of physical evidence and forged signatures can make concealment of fraudulent electronic payments less challenging than other check tampering schemes. Some fraudsters attempt to conceal their schemes by altering the bank statement, miscoding transactions in the accounting records, or sending fraudulent payments to a shell company with a name similar to that of an existing vendor. Others merely rely on the company’s failure to monitor or reconcile its accounts."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "The primary reason for a company’s management to construct an electronically and acoustically shielded quiet room is to protect the company’s computer servers and other sensitive electronic equipment.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Management can prevent corporate spies from listening in on meetings through the use of a quiet room. A quiet room is an area that is acoustically and radio-frequency shielded so that conversations that occur within the room cannot be monitored or heard from outside the room."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "A large amount of overdue accounts receivable on the books is a red flag of a fictitious revenue scheme.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Fictitious or fabricated revenues involve the recording of sales of goods or services that did not occur. Fictitious sales most often involve fake customers but can also involve legitimate customers. Recording the sales revenue is easy, but the challenge for the fraudster is how to balance the other side of the entry. A credit to revenue increases the revenue account, but the corresponding debit in a legitimate sales transaction typically either goes to cash or accounts receivable. Since no cash is received in a fictitious revenue scheme, increasing accounts receivable is the easiest way to get away with completing the entry. However, accounts receivable stay on the books as an asset until they are collected. If the outstanding accounts never get collected, they will eventually need to be written off as bad debt expense. Mysterious accounts receivable on the books that are long overdue are a common sign of a fictitious revenue scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Which of the following best describes the difference between a flipping scheme and a flopping scheme in the context of mortgage fraud?", "options": {"A": "In a flopping scheme, the original seller always ends up as the final owner of the property.", "B": "In a flopping scheme, the lender is not one of the potential victims of the scheme.", "C": "In a flopping scheme, the value of the first transaction is deflated instead of inflating the second transaction.", "D": "In a flopping scheme, the second transaction in the scheme usually occurs several years after the first."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Property flipping is the process by which an investor purchases a home and then resells it at a higher price shortly thereafter. For example, an investor buys a house in need of work for $250,000 in July, renovates the kitchen and bathrooms, and landscapes the yard at a cost of $50,000. He then resells the house two months later (the time it takes to make the renovations) for a price that is reflective of the market for a house in that condition. This is a legitimate business transaction, and many individuals and groups make an honest living flipping properties. Property flipping is not intrinsically illegal or fraudulent, but it becomes so when a property is purchased and resold within a short period of time at an artificially or unjustly inflated value, often as the result of a fraudulent appraisal. In a flipping scheme, the property is sold twice in rapid succession at a significant increase in value (also known as an ABC transaction, where the property moves from party A to party B to party C very quickly). Property flopping is a variation on property flipping, but it generally involves a property subject to a short sale (meaning the owner sells the property at a lower value than the unpaid mortgage amount on the property). This variation typically is conducted by industry insiders or unscrupulous entrepreneurs rather than the homeowner. Property flopping involves a rapid transfer of property with an unjustified, significant change in value (like the ABC transaction in flipping schemes), but instead of inflating the value on the second transaction, the value on the first transaction is deflated. To prevent problematic short sale flopping, some lenders are starting to require all interested parties to sign an affidavit requiring disclosure of an immediate subsequent sale."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Which of the following types of transactions is LEAST likely to use a person-to-person (P2P) payment system?", "options": {"A": "A person making an online donation to a charity", "B": "A person buying groceries at a supermarket", "C": "A person transferring money to a friend abroad", "D": "A person paying for an item on an online auction site"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Person-to-person payment systems, often called P2P or peer-to-peer payment systems, are an increasingly popular method for making payments between individuals or between an individual and a business. P2P payments are commonly used to make online payments but are not as common for in-person payments, such as paying for clothes at a department store or buying groceries at a supermarket. These services are also used to move money internationally and between various currencies at exchange rates that rival traditional methods of currency exchange. Transferwise and PayPal are examples of popular P2P payment systems. Mobile payment applications or digital wallets, such as Venmo or Apple Pay, might also have P2P payment features."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Credit card counterfeiting operations might include the use of which of the following?", "options": {"A": "High-speed printing facilities", "B": "Embossed blank plastic cards", "C": "Desktop computers, embossers, tipping foil, and laminators", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "One common method of producing counterfeit credit cards includes the use of blank plastic cards. This scheme uses credit-card-sized plastic with embossed account numbers and names. This scheme often works in conjunction with a corrupt and collusive merchant or a merchant’s employee. Other counterfeit cards are wholly manufactured using high-speed printing facilities. Additional common tools in the reproduction process include desktop computers, embossers, tipping foil, and laminators."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "Jackson is a receiving clerk at a warehouse. His job is to count the number of units in incoming shipments, record the figures in receiving reports, and forward copies of the reports to the accounts payable department. One day, Jackson received a box of 20 laptop computers at the warehouse. His wife’s computer just broke, so he stole one of the computers from the box. To conceal his scheme, Jackson sent a receiving report to accounts payable that 20 computers arrived, but he only recorded 19 on the copy of the receiving report used for the inventory records. What type of scheme did Jackson commit?", "options": {"A": "A noncash larceny scheme", "B": "A purchasing and receiving scheme", "C": "An asset transfer scheme", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "One of the most common examples of an employee abusing the purchasing and receiving functions occurs when a person charged with receiving goods on the victim company’s behalf—such as a warehouse supervisor or receiving clerk—falsifies the records of incoming shipments. If, for example, 1,000 units of a particular item are received, the perpetrator indicates that only 900 were received. By marking the shipment short, the perpetrator can steal the 100 unaccounted-for units. The obvious problem with this kind of scheme is the fact that the receiving report does not match the vendor’s invoice, which will likely cause a problem with payment. Some employees avoid this problem by altering only one copy of the receiving report. The copy that is sent to accounts payable indicates receipt of a full shipment, so the vendor will be paid without any questions. The copy used for inventory records indicates a short shipment so that the assets on hand will equal the assets in the perpetual inventory."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "As a sale is made, the appropriate charges for cost of goods sold, or other expenses directly corresponding to the sale, should be recorded in the same accounting period.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Expenses are recognized in the income statement on the basis of a direct association between the costs incurred and the earning of specific items of income. This process, commonly referred to as the matching principle, involves the simultaneous or combined recognition of revenues and expenses that result directly and jointly from the same transactions or other events; for example, the various components of expense making up the cost of goods sold are recognized at the same time as the income derived from the sale of the goods."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Unauthorized credit card activity resulting from a stolen card typically takes place within hours of the card’s theft and before the victim reports the loss.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Fraudulent activity normally occurs within hours of the loss or theft, before most victims have called to report the loss. Victims are commonly unaware that their credit cards are being used fraudulently until they review their monthly statement."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Which of the following can best be described as fraud perpetrated by medical practitioners, medical suppliers, or medical institutions on patients or health care programs to increase their own income by illicit means?", "options": {"A": "Uncovered party fraud", "B": "Provider fraud", "C": "Beneficiary fraud", "D": "Insurer fraud"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Provider fraud consists of practices by health care providers (including practitioners, medical suppliers, and medical institutions) that cause unnecessary costs to health care programs or patients through reimbursement for unnecessary or excessive services, or services that do not meet the recognized standards for health care."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the key phases of procurement processes that employ competitive bidding mechanisms?", "options": {"A": "The solicitation phase", "B": "The presolicitation phase", "C": "The post-award and administration phase", "D": "The purchase and procurement phase"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "For the purpose of fraud detection, procurement processes that employ competitive bidding mechanisms can be reduced to four basic stages: The presolicitation phase The solicitation phase The bid evaluation and award phase The post-award and administration phase"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Failing to record bad debt expense for the period will result in fraudulently overstated accounts receivable.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Managers can overstate their company’s accounts receivable balance by failing to record bad debt expense. Bad debt expense is recorded to account for any uncollectible accounts receivable. The debit side of the entry increases bad debt expense, and the credit side of the entry increases the allowance (or provision) for doubtful accounts, which is a contra account that is recorded against accounts receivable. Therefore, if the controller fails to record bad debt expense, the allowance (or provision) for doubtful accounts will be understated."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a common reason why someone might commit financial statement fraud?", "options": {"A": "To harm a competitor's reputation", "B": "To misuse company assets", "C": "To attempt to get a coworker fired", "D": "To obtain favorable terms on financing"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Unlike some other types of fraud (such as embezzlement), the motivation for financial statement fraud does not always involve personal gain. Most commonly, financial statement fraud is used to make a company’s earnings appear better on paper. Financial statement fraud occurs through a variety of methods, such as valuation judgments and manipulating the timing of transaction recording. These more subtle types of fraud are often dismissed as either mistakes or errors in judgment and estimation. Some of the more common reasons why people commit financial statement fraud include: To encourage investment through the sale of stock To demonstrate increased earnings per share or partnership profits interest, thus allowing increased dividend/distribution payouts To cover inability to generate cash flow To avoid negative market perceptions To obtain financing, or to obtain more favorable terms on existing financing To receive higher purchase prices for acquisitions To demonstrate compliance with financing covenants To meet company goals and objectives To receive performance-related bonuses"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "The warehouse supervisor at South Corp. has stolen $50,000 worth of inventory over the last year. He has made no effort to conceal his theft in any of the inventory records. During an analytical review of the financial statements, which of the following red flags might South Corp.’s auditors find that would indicate the inventory theft?", "options": {"A": "Sales and cost of goods sold moved together.", "B": "The percentage change in sales was significantly higher than the percentage change in cost of goods sold.", "C": "The percentage change in cost of goods sold was significantly higher than the percentage change in sales.", "D": "None of the above possible outcomes would indicate inventory theft."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Inventory fraud might be detected by using an analytical review because certain trends become immediately clear. For example, sales and cost of goods sold should move together since they are directly related. However, if the cost of goods sold increases by a disproportionate amount relative to sales, and no changes occur in the purchase prices, quantities purchased, or quality of products purchased, the cause of the disproportionate increase in cost of goods sold might be one of three things: (1) ending inventory has been depleted by theft, (2) someone has been embezzling money through a false billing scheme, or (3) someone has been skimming sales revenue."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Which of the following groups is NOT a favorite target of identity thieves?", "options": {"A": "Members of the military", "B": "College students", "C": "Seniors", "D": "Independent contractors"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Anyone can be a victim of identity theft. The following groups, however, are favorite targets of identity thieves: Children Seniors Members of the military College students The deceased"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "A register disbursement scheme is easier to conceal when register employees have the authority to void their own transactions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Red flags of fraudulent register disbursements include the following: Inappropriate separation of duties exists. Cashiers, rather than supervisors, have access to the control keys necessary for refunds and voids. Register employees have the authority to void their own transactions. Register refunds are not carefully reviewed. Multiple cashiers operate from a single cash drawer without separate access codes. Personal checks from cashiers are found in the register. Voided transactions are not properly documented or approved by a supervisor. Voided cash receipt forms (manual systems) or supporting documents for voided transactions (cash register systems) are not retained on file. Gaps exist in the sequence of transactions on the register log. There is an excessive number of refunds, voids, or no-sales on the register log. Inventory totals appear forced. There are multiple refunds or voids for amounts just under the review limit."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Vertical analysis can best be described as a technique for analyzing a percentage change from one accounting period to the next.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Vertical analysis is the expression of the relationship or percentage of component items to a specific base item on the income statement or balance sheet. Horizontal analysis is a technique for analyzing the percentage change in individual financial statement items from one accounting period to the next. Ratio analysis is a means of measuring the relationship between any two different financial statement amounts. The relationship and comparison are the keys to any of these types of financial analyses."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a method that a fraudster might use to conceal inventory shrinkage?", "options": {"A": "Falsely increasing the perpetual inventory figure", "B": "Writing off stolen inventory as scrap", "C": "Altering the perpetual inventory records to decrease the balance", "D": "Physical padding of inventory"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Altering the perpetual inventory figure is one method that can be used to conceal inventory shrinkage. However, increasing the perpetual inventory record would only worsen the shrinkage problem. Instead, a fraudster should falsely decrease the perpetual inventory record to match the lower physical inventory count. Alternatively, some employees try to make it appear that there are more assets present in the warehouse or stockroom than there actually are. Empty boxes or boxes filled with bricks or other inexpensive materials, for example, might be stacked on shelves to create the illusion of extra inventory. This is known as physical padding of inventory. Fraudulently writing off stolen inventory as scrap is also a relatively common way to remove assets from the books before or after they are stolen. This is beneficial to the fraudster because it eliminates the problem of shrinkage that inherently exists in every case of noncash asset misappropriation. One of the simplest methods for concealing shrinkage is to alter the perpetual inventory record so that it matches the physical inventory count. This is also known as a forced reconciliation of the account. In the case of misappropriated inventory, the physical count would be lower than the perpetual records, so the perpetual inventory figure would have to be decreased."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "If compliance with generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) would be significantly more expensive than a different method that isn’t GAAP, use of an alternative method is permitted.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The question of when it is appropriate to stray from generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) is a matter of professional judgment; there is no clear-cut set of circumstances that justify such a departure. However, the fact that complying with GAAP would be more expensive or would make the financial statements look weaker is not a reason to use a non-GAAP method of accounting for a transaction."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Which of the following is a basic method used to prove corrupt payments in bribery and corruption schemes?", "options": {"A": "Secretly infiltrating ongoing transactions", "B": "Turning an inside witness", "C": "Identifying and tracing payments through audit steps", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There are three basic ways to prove corrupt payments: Turn an inside witness. Secretly infiltrate or record ongoing transactions. Identify and trace the corrupt payments through audit steps."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a common way a procuring employee might engage in a bid manipulation scheme?", "options": {"A": "Altering bids", "B": "Opening bids prematurely", "C": "Extending bid opening dates without justification", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In bid manipulation schemes, a procuring employee manipulates the bidding process to benefit a favored contractor or supplier. Some common ways to commit these schemes include: Opening bids prematurely Altering bids Extending bid opening dates without justification"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Which of the following is the best example of shoulder surfing?", "options": {"A": "Watching a customer enter a PIN code at an ATM machine", "B": "Leaving a spyware-infected flash drive in a workplace break room", "C": "Following an authorized person into a restricted area", "D": "Accessing a computer network by convincing an authorized user to share log-in information"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Shoulder surfing is the practice of observing another person (e.g., looking over the person’s shoulder) to gather personal information. Shoulder surfing is especially effective in crowded areas where a fraudster can stand close to a victim without being noticed. While in close proximity, the fraudster can eavesdrop on the victim’s telephone conversation, view the victim’s credit card number, or gather other personal information. Identity thieves often watch victims as they enter their PIN codes at ATM machines and fill out bank deposit slips at their banks. Leaving a spyware-infected flash drive in a workplace break room is an example of a baiting scheme. The other two scenarios are examples of piggybacking."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "To help detect cash larceny, the person responsible for collecting incoming cash should also prepare the bank deposits.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The primary means of preventing cash fraud is separation of duties. Whenever one individual has control over the entire accounting transaction (e.g., authorization, recording, and custody), the opportunity is present for cash fraud. Each of the following duties/responsibilities should be separated: Cash receipts Bank deposits Bank reconciliation Cash disbursements If one person has the authority to collect the cash, deposit the receipts, record that collection, and disburse company funds, the risk is high that fraud can occur."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Julia runs a printing company and has an antique printing press that she uses in her business. She purchased the press from a friend for $5,000. Similar presses are selling on the market today for about $8,000. Julia has a colleague who recently paid $9,000 for an antique printing press. According to the historical cost basis of asset measurement, how much should Julia initially record the printing press for on her books?", "options": {"A": "$9,000", "B": "$3,000", "C": "$8,000", "D": "$5,000"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "According to the historical cost basis of asset measurement, assets are recorded at the amount of cash or cash equivalents paid or the fair value of the consideration given to acquire them at the time of their acquisition. This basis is the one most commonly adopted by entities in preparing their financial statements. In this example, Julia should list the printing press on her balance sheet for the amount she originally purchased it for—$5,000."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning fraud involving special care facilities is TRUE?", "options": {"A": "Many patients in special care facilities are less likely to report fraud because they often are not responsible for their own financial affairs", "B": "It is difficult for fraud in special care facilities to be committed in high volume because patients are located in close proximity to each other", "C": "When fraud is committed against special care facilities, it is common for victims to obtain repayment from the perpetrators", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Medical facilities that offer special care services, such as nursing homes and psychiatric hospitals, and the patients in them are at a greater risk of fraud than most other medical institutions. Many health care fraud schemes are revealed after a patient reports strange charges or other red flags. Unfortunately, criminals take advantage of the fact that patients in special care facilities are more vulnerable to fraud. There are several features unique to special care facilities that make them particularly vulnerable to fraud: Unscrupulous providers can operate their schemes in volume because the patients are all in the same facility. Many patients in special care facilities do not have the legal capacity or ability to be responsible for their own financial affairs and, consequently, are not as likely to report fraud involving their care. In some instances, special care facilities make patient records available to outside providers who are not responsible for the direct care of the patient (sometimes in violation of regulations). In automated claims environments, scrutiny of the claims at the processor level is inadequate because the automated systems used do not accumulate data that would flag indications of improbably high charges or levels of service in a timely manner. Even when abusive practices are detected and prosecuted, repayment is rarely received from wrongdoers because they usually go out of business or deplete their resources so that they lack any resources to repay the funds. Patient personal funds are often controlled by the facility’s administration and are an inviting target for embezzlement. Individually, patients generally maintain a relatively small balance in their personal funds accounts. Collectively, however, these funds generate a considerable source of income for an unscrupulous special care facility operator or employee."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "According to the going concern disclosure requirements, if there is substantial doubt about a company’s ability to fulfill its financial obligations over a reasonable period of time, it must be disclosed in the company’s financial statements.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A company’s management is required to provide disclosures when existing events or conditions indicate that it is more likely than not that the entity might be unable to meet its obligations within a reasonable period of time after the financial statements are issued. There is an underlying assumption that an entity will continue as a going concern; that is, the life of the entity will be long enough to fulfill its financial and legal obligations. Any evidence to the contrary must be reported in the entity’s financial statements."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "In a/an _____________ scheme, the company that initially conned a consumer contacts that consumer and offers to help retrieve the lost money. However, the investigation requires an upfront fee and the consumer is swindled again.", "options": {"A": "Retrieval", "B": "Scavenger", "C": "Double-hustle", "D": "Advance-fee"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The scavenger or revenge scheme involves the company that initially conned the consumer. Using a different company’s name, the outfit contacts the consumer again and asks if he would like to help put the unethical company out of business and get his money back. Naturally, an upfront fee is required to finance the investigation."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "The purpose of draw requests in construction lending is to provide:", "options": {"A": "Documentation that all architectural and engineering designs and quotes have been completed", "B": "Documentation that costs have been incurred and reimbursement is sought", "C": "Documentation that the design is approved by the International Union of Architects", "D": "Documentation that the construction project cannot continue without additional funding"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Construction loan advances are generally supported by draw requests. A draw request is the documentation substantiating that a developer/borrower has incurred the appropriate construction expenses and is now seeking reimbursement or direct payment. A typical fraud scheme involves requesting advances on the loan for inappropriate costs, such as personal expenses and/or construction costs for an unrelated project. Draw requests might provide the greatest opportunity for a developer to commit fraud because the lender relies upon the developer's documentation."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Generally, if the dollar amount of an embezzlement scheme at a financial institution is small enough such that the targeted entity's financial statements will not be materially affected, the scheme can be most effectively detected through which of the following methods?", "options": {"A": "Conducting a financial statement analysis", "B": "Reviewing all disbursements below the approval limit", "C": "Educating employees who are responsible for handling currency", "D": "Conducting a review of source documents"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There are several methods by which embezzlement can be detected. Generally, if the dollar amount of an embezzlement scheme is small enough such that the targeted entity's financial statements will not be materially affected, embezzlement fraud can be most effectively detected through the review of source documents (e.g., receipts, deposit slips). There can be many types of clues in the source documents, and the particular situation will often determine what the fraud examiner needs to look for. The following are common red flags in source documents that might indicate that embezzlement has occurred: Missing source documents Payees on source documents (e.g., checks) do not match entries in the general ledger Receipts or invoices lack professional quality Duplicate payment documents for different transactions Payee identification information that matches an employee’s information or that of his relatives Apparent signs of alteration to source documents Lack of original source documents (photocopies only) If the scheme is so large that the financial statements of the institution are affected, then a review of the source documents will serve to confirm or refute an allegation that an embezzlement scheme has occurred or is occurring. Generally, for large embezzlements, the most efficient method of detection is an analysis of the financial statements."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Grey, a controller for a small company, took a large sum of money from the company deposits and concealed the theft by making false accounting entries. The money Grey stole had already been recorded in his company's accounting system. Grey’s scheme can best be classified as a(n):", "options": {"A": "Illegal gratuities scheme", "B": "Skimming scheme", "C": "Cash larceny scheme", "D": "Fraudulent financial statement scheme"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Skimming is defined as the theft of off-book funds. Cash larceny schemes, however, involve the theft of money that has already appeared on a victim company’s books. Neither of the other choices is correct because neither of those schemes is a type of asset misappropriation scheme. Grey's scheme involves the misappropriation of company assets (cash)."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "There is nothing inherently wrong with a company engaging in related-party transactions, as long as the transactions are fully disclosed.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There is nothing inherently wrong with related-party transactions, as long as they are fully disclosed. If the transactions are not fully disclosed, the company might injure its shareholders by engaging in economically harmful dealings without their knowledge."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "In a grandparent scheme targeting the elderly, which of the following is a way to confirm if a caller is the grandparent’s actual grandchild?", "options": {"A": "Ask relatives if they know of any issues with the grandchild", "B": "Hang up the phone and contact the grandchild directly", "C": "Ask the caller questions only the grandchild would know", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There are ways the elderly can protect themselves against grandparent schemes. If they receive a call from someone claiming to be their grandchild, they should confirm the person’s identity before sending any money. Several ways to confirm the legitimacy of the caller would be to: Ask questions an imposter would not know, such as the birth date of the grandchild’s father or a pet’s name. Hang up the phone and contact the grandchild directly. Contact friends or relatives and ask if they are aware of any issues with the grandchild."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Which of the following health care frauds would be best described as a fictitious services scheme?", "options": {"A": "A doctor uses the identifying information of patients he has never serviced to bill an insurer or health care program.", "B": "A patient who is not covered under a health care program pretends to be a covered party to receive medical services.", "C": "A doctor intentionally submits a bill to an insurer or health care program using improper codes for the services provided.", "D": "A patient fraudulently reports symptoms he does not actually have to receive a prescription."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In a fictitious services scheme, legitimate health care providers charge or bill a health care program for services that were not rendered at all. Often, the providers submit bills for patients they have never seen but whose private patient information they purchased from someone involved in identity theft or someone who otherwise improperly obtained it."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following is an acceptable justification for a departure from generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP)?", "options": {"A": "Departing from GAAP would make the company appear more profitable", "B": "The literal application of GAAP would render the financial statements misleading", "C": "Adhering to GAAP is significantly more expensive than using an alternative method", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The question of when it is appropriate to stray from generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP) is a matter of professional judgment; there is no clear-cut set of circumstances that justify such a departure. However, the fact that complying with GAAP would be more expensive or would make the financial statements look weaker is not a reason to use a non-GAAP method of accounting for a transaction. It can be assumed that adherence to GAAP almost always results in financial statements that are fairly presented. However, the standard-setting bodies recognize that, upon occasion, there might be an unusual circumstance when the literal application of GAAP would render the financial statements misleading. In these cases, a departure from GAAP is the proper accounting treatment. Departures from GAAP can be justified in the following circumstances: It is common practice in the entity’s industry for a transaction to be reported in a particular way. The substance of the transaction is better reflected (and, therefore, the financial statements are more fairly presented) by not strictly following GAAP. If a transaction is considered immaterial (i.e., it would not affect a decision made by a prudent reader of the financial statements), then it need not be reported. There is concern that assets or income would be overstated and expenses or liabilities would be understated (the conservatism constraint requires that when there is any doubt, one should avoid overstating assets and income or understating expenses and liabilities). The results of departure appear reasonable under the circumstances, especially when strict adherence to GAAP will produce misleading financial statements and the departure is properly disclosed."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "Which of the following is a method that would help prevent the theft of company inventory?", "options": {"A": "Separating the duties of handling incoming shipments and filling out the inventory requisition form", "B": "Restricting inventory access to authorized personnel", "C": "Using prenumbered shipping documents, perpetual inventory records, and inventory receiving reports", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There are four basic measures that might help prevent inventory fraud, if properly installed and implemented. They are proper documentation, separation of duties (including approvals), independent checks, and physical safeguards. The following duties should be handled by different personnel: Requisition of inventory Receipt of inventory Disbursement of inventory Conversion of inventory to scrap Receipt of proceeds from disposal of scrap In addition, all merchandise should be physically guarded and locked; access should be limited to authorized personnel only. Finally, the following documents should be prenumbered and controlled: Requisitions Receiving reports Perpetual records Raw materials requisitions Shipping documents Job cost sheets"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the three common methods for concealing liabilities and expenses on a company’s financial statements?", "options": {"A": "Liability/expense omissions", "B": "Channel stuffing", "C": "Failure to disclose warranty costs and product-return liabilities", "D": "Capitalized expenses"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "There are three common methods for concealing liabilities and expenses: Omitting liabilities and/or expenses Improperly capitalizing costs rather than expensing them Failing to disclose warranty costs and product-return liabilities"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "If a company hires an employee from a competitor, it might open itself up to claims from the competitor that it is unlawfully using proprietary information taken by the employee.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Organizations must also prevent their employees from appropriating the proprietary information belonging to others. A new hire from a competitor, for example, might expose the new employer to liability by using or disclosing secrets obtained from his previous employer in the course of his employment. Moreover, a company can be held liable for misappropriation of proprietary information even if it is not aware that its employee is using or disclosing secrets in the course of his employment."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Credit card receipts, bank statements, and birthday cards can all provide dumpster divers with useful information for committing an identity theft scheme.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Dumpster diving involves looking through someone else’s trash. Fraudsters often engage in dumpster diving to find the personal and business information that makes identity theft possible. Most people do not destroy their personal financial data; they simply throw it away with the rest of their trash. Dumpster diving can yield bills, credit card receipts, bank statements, and other items that contain a person’s name, address, and telephone number. Solicitations for pre-approved credit cards are especially valuable to identity thieves, but even nonfinancial information can be useful. For example, a discarded birthday card might contain a potential victim’s name, birthdate, and address."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "question": "Insurance agent/broker fraud includes which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Premium theft", "B": "Fictitious payees", "C": "Fictitious death claims", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Types of insurance agent/broker fraud include: Premium theft—An agent collects the premium but does not remit the payment to the insurance company. Thus, the insured unknowingly has no coverage available upon a qualifying event. Fictitious payees—An agent or a clerk changes the beneficiary on record to a fictitious person and subsequently submits the necessary papers to authorize the issuance of a payment. Fictitious death claims—An agent or employee obtains a fictitious death certificate and requests that a death claim payment be issued. The agent then steals the payment."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Because it is a common occurrence, the fact that documents are missing from a loan file is generally not a red flag for loan fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Missing or altered documentation is a red flag for any type of fraud scheme, and it is a particular concern for loan fraud. While it is true that many loan files have missing documents, it is important to determine if the documents have been misplaced or were never received. A waiver of certain documents is one common way for lenders to conceal fraud schemes."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "A patient goes to the doctor for a medical condition. The doctor identifies the condition, but he decides to order additional lab testing that he knows to be unnecessary. The doctor owns the lab that he sends the patient to, and he will profit from the unnecessary testing. Which of the following best describes the doctor’s scheme?", "options": {"A": "Clinical lab scheme", "B": "Fictitious provider scheme", "C": "Fictitious services scheme", "D": "Front organization scheme"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Clinical lab schemes occur when a provider advises a patient that additional medical testing is needed to diagnose a problem when the testing is not actually required or advisable. The fee for the unnecessary work often is split with physicians. In some cases, physicians own the medical testing service. Additional medical testing, which is later viewed as excessive, is not always fraud. Many doctors have a genuine fear of retaliation from their patients; they are afraid of malpractice lawsuits that might result from a delayed or erroneous diagnosis."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Generally speaking, _________________ is the proper basis for initially recording a piece of equipment on a company's books.", "options": {"A": "Appraised value", "B": "Current market value", "C": "Estimated replacement value", "D": "Historical cost"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Standard accounting principles require that property, plant, and equipment be initially recognized at historical cost. According to the historical cost basis of asset measurement, assets are recorded at the amount of cash or cash equivalents paid or the fair value of the consideration given to acquire them at the time of their acquisition."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "question": "All of the following are red flags of fraudulent insurance claims EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "A theft claim includes a lot of recently purchased expensive property.", "B": "A fire loss claim does not include family heirlooms or other sentimental items.", "C": "The insured does not have a history of making insurance claims.", "D": "A claim is made a short time after the policy's inception."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Claim fraud might well represent an insurance company's largest fraud risk. Most claims are legitimate; however, some claims are illegitimate. Red flags of insurance claim fraud include the following: The claim is made a short time after the policy's inception or after a coverage increase or change. The insured has a history of many insurance claims. The insured previously asked the insurance agent hypothetical questions about coverage in the event of a loss similar to the actual claim. In a theft or fire loss claim, the claim includes a lot of recently purchased, expensive property, but the insured cannot provide receipts, owner's manuals, or other proof-of-purchase documentation. In a fire loss claim, the claim does not include personal or sentimental items, such as photographs or family heirlooms, that would usually be listed among the lost property. The insured has discarded the claimed damaged property before the adjuster can examine it."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following is a red flag of fraudulent register disbursements?", "options": {"A": "There are multiple refunds or voids just under the review limit", "B": "Personal checks from cashiers are found in the register", "C": "Voided transactions are not properly documented or approved by a supervisor", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Red flags of fraudulent register disbursements include the following: Inappropriate separation of duties exists. Cashiers, rather than supervisors, have access to the control keys necessary for refunds and voids. Register employees have the authority to void their own transactions. Register refunds are not carefully reviewed. Multiple cashiers operate from a single cash drawer without separate access codes. Personal checks from cashiers are found in the register. Voided transactions are not properly documented or approved by a supervisor. Voided cash receipt forms (manual systems) or supporting documents for voided transactions (cash register systems) are not retained on file. Gaps exist in the sequence of transactions on the register log. There is an excessive number of refunds, voids, or no-sales on the register log. Inventory totals appear forced. There are multiple refunds or voids for amounts just under the review limit."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Annika, a bookkeeper for a small company, created checks to a local vendor and had her boss sign them. She then used correctional fluid to cover up the vendor's name and insert her own. She also changed the amounts of the checks in the same manner. Then she cashed the checks. What kind of scheme did Annika commit?", "options": {"A": "A forged endorsement scheme", "B": "A cash larceny scheme", "C": "An altered payee scheme", "D": "A forged maker scheme"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The altered payee scheme is a type of check tampering fraud in which an employee intercepts a company check intended for a third party and alters the payee designation so that the check can be converted by the employee or an accomplice. The fraudster inserts his own name, the name of a fictitious entity, or some other name on the check’s payee line."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a technical or administrative control for securing computer systems and communication networks?", "options": {"A": "Encrypting sensitive data files", "B": "Installing network security defenses", "C": "Installing operating system security", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Computer networks and communications are inherently insecure and vulnerable to attack and disruption. Consequently, management must use technical and administrative controls to protect systems against threats like unauthorized use, disclosure, modification, destruction, or denial of service. Technical security involves the use of safeguards incorporated in computer hardware, operations or applications software, communications hardware and software, and related devices. Administrative security involves the use of tools to provide an acceptable level of protection for computing resources. Common technical and administrative controls used to secure computer systems and communication networks include: Logical access controls Network security Operating system security Encryption Application security Separation of duties"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Employees are often willing to abide by nondisclosure agreements, but they sometimes do not understand that the information they are communicating might be confidential.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Often, employees are willing to abide by nondisclosure agreements, but they do not understand that the information they are communicating might be confidential. To more effectively implement nondisclosure agreements, employees must be clearly informed as to what information is considered confidential upon hiring, upon signing a nondisclosure agreement, and during exit interviews."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following methods would be useful in detecting a ghost employee scheme?", "options": {"A": "Comparing personnel records to payroll data", "B": "Examining payroll checks for dual endorsements", "C": "Analyzing payroll withholdings", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Comparing personnel records maintained by the human resources department to payroll data can be useful in detecting ghost employee schemes. An analysis of payroll withholdings might also reveal either ghost employees or trust account abuses. Ghost employees often will have no withholding taxes, insurance, or other normal deductions. Therefore, a listing of any employee without these items might reveal a ghost employee. Another way to detect a ghost employee scheme is to examine paychecks for dual endorsements. This might indicate that the fraudster has forged an endorsement in order to deposit the ghost’s paychecks into the fraudster's own account."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Heather is a fraud examiner who is investigating a fraud case at a bank. Which of the following of Heather’s findings might be a red flag of embezzlement?", "options": {"A": "Only photocopies are available as source documents instead of originals", "B": "Some source documents are missing or altered", "C": "Payees on source documents do not match entries on the general ledger", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There are several methods by which embezzlement can be detected. Generally, if the dollar amount of an embezzlement scheme is small enough such that the targeted entity's financial statements will not be materially affected, embezzlement fraud can be most effectively detected through the review of source documents (e.g., receipts, deposit slips). There can be many types of clues in the source documents, and the particular situation will often determine what the fraud examiner needs to look for. The following are common red flags in source documents that might indicate that embezzlement has occurred: Missing source documents Payees on source documents (e.g., checks) do not match entries in the general ledger Receipts or invoices lack professional quality Duplicate payment documents for different transactions Payee identification information that matches an employee’s information or that of his relatives Apparent signs of alteration to source documents Lack of original source documents (photocopies only)"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Cooper is an intelligence professional for Whetstone Intelligence, a competitive intelligence firm. She is tasked with gathering intelligence about Cryptic Global, the major competitor of Whetstone’s biggest client. To gather the intelligence, Cooper infiltrates Cryptic Global’s office by posing as a member of its cleaning crew and collects information left around employees’ computers and desks. Cooper’s approach is an example of:", "options": {"A": "Spoofing", "B": "Scavenging", "C": "Dumpster diving", "D": "Shoulder surfing"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Scavenging involves collecting information left around computer systems (e.g., on desks or workstations). Dumpster diving involves obtaining sensitive information by looking through someone else’s trash (e.g., via dumpsters and other trash receptacles). Shoulder surfing involves observing an unsuspecting target from a nearby location while the target enters a username and password into a system, talks on the phone, fills out financial forms, or performs some other task from which valuable information can be obtained. Spoofing refers to the process whereby an individual impersonates a legitimate user to obtain access to the target’s network."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "All of the following are types of expense reimbursement schemes EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Fictitious expenses", "B": "Mischaracterized expenses", "C": "Multiple reimbursements", "D": "Ghost expense reports"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The four main types of expense reimbursement schemes are: Mischaracterized expenses Overstated expenses Fictitious expenses Multiple reimbursements There is no such scheme as ghost expense reports. Ghost employees, however, are a common payroll fraud scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Financial statement fraud is the intentional or erroneous misrepresentation of the financial condition of an enterprise.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Financial statement fraud is the deliberate misrepresentation of the financial condition of an enterprise accomplished through the intentional misstatement or omission of amounts or disclosures in the financial statements to deceive financial statement users. Note that financial statement fraud, much like all types of fraud, is an intentional act."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "When a fraudster calls someone at the target company and cajoles or tricks the person into providing valuable information, that corporate espionage technique is referred to as which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Social engineering", "B": "Replicating", "C": "Spamming", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Social engineering is the act of using deceptive techniques to manipulate people into taking certain actions or disclosing information. In social engineering schemes, social engineers use various forms of trickery, persuasion, threats, or cajolery to encourage their targets to release information that the engineers can use and exploit to achieve their goals. Attackers engage in social engineering for various reasons. Some use social engineering to gain unauthorized access to systems or obtain confidential communication so they can commit fraud, intrude into networks, gain access to buildings, steal another party’s secrets, commit identity theft, or engage in some other nefarious act. In some situations, attackers use social engineering to procure information that will give them a competitive advantage, whereas others might engage in social engineering to find ways in which they can install malware."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a method that can be used to destroy or manipulate data?", "options": {"A": "Transmitting data to an outside destination without authorization", "B": "Using malware to infect computers", "C": "Wire tapping into a computer’s communication links", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Data manipulation refers to the use or manipulation of a computer to perpetrate a crime, and data destruction involves the unauthorized modification, suppression, or erasure of computer data or computer functions, with the intent to alter or hinder the normal functions of the targeted system. Data manipulation and destruction involves either direct or covert unauthorized access to a computer system by the introduction of malicious software such as viruses, worms, or logic bombs. Some of the methods used to destroy and manipulate data include: Using malware to infect computers Using the salami technique to steal a substantial amount of money by “slicing” off “thin” amounts of cash repeatedly over time Entering false or misleading information into a system to achieve a specific fraudulent purpose Transmitting data to an outside destination without authorization Wire tapping into a computer’s communication links Launching a buffer overflow attack Exploiting a vulnerability in an operating system or software application to gain access that is beyond the user’s authorized access level"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "All of the following are options for authenticating users in information systems EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Encryption", "B": "Card-based systems", "C": "Profiling software", "D": "Biometrics"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Logical access controls are tools used for identification, authentication, and authorization in computer information systems. All of the following are options for authenticating users in information systems: Passwords Card-based systems Biometrics Profiling software Encryption is the process whereby information is taken and scrambled so that it is unreadable by anyone who does not have the decryption code."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Which of the following is NOT an effective control to protect against skimming schemes?", "options": {"A": "Installing visible video cameras to monitor a store’s cash registers", "B": "Reconciling the sales records to the cash receipts", "C": "Reconciling the physical inventory count with the perpetual inventory records", "D": "Restricting the accounts receivable clerk from preparing the bank deposit"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Since skimming is an off-book fraud, routine account reconciliation is not likely to prevent or detect a skimming scheme. If such a scheme is taking place, reconciling the sales records to the amount of cash received will not indicate there is anything amiss; because the skimmed sale was never recorded, the books will remain in balance. Reconciling the physical inventory count with the perpetual inventory records, however, might reveal that there is shrinkage and therefore a skimming scheme. As with most fraud schemes, internal control procedures are a key to the prevention of skimming schemes. For instance, employees who have access to the cash register should not also be responsible for delivering the bank deposit. The accounts receivable clerk should be restricted from preparing the bank deposit, accessing the accounts receivable journal, and having access to collections from customers. An essential part of developing control procedures is management’s communication to employees. Controlling whether an employee will not record a sale, understate a sale, or steal incoming payments is extremely difficult. Some physical controls can be put in place to prevent employee skimming, such as video cameras monitoring employees who handle cash and implementing a lockbox."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "When an employee signs a legally enforceable noncompetition agreement, the provisions of the noncompetition agreement continue after the employee leaves the company where he signed the agreement.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A noncompetition agreement is an agreement whereby an employee agrees not to work for competing companies within a certain period of time after leaving his current employer. If an organization uses a noncompetition agreement, management should remind its employees about the agreement’s provisions during an exit interview conducted before the end of their employment. When employees leave a company, it is a good idea to have them sign a statement in which they acknowledge that they understand the noncompetition agreement’s terms and that they will abide by its provisions."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "The removal of cash from a victim organization before the cash is entered in the organization's accounting system is:", "options": {"A": "Cash larceny", "B": "Lapping", "C": "Skimming", "D": "A fraudulent disbursement"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Skimming is the removal of cash from a victim entity prior to its entry in an accounting system. Employees who skim from their companies steal sales or receivables before they are recorded in the company books. Because of this aspect of their nature, skimming schemes are known as off-book frauds; they leave no direct audit trail."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a red flag for new bank account fraud?", "options": {"A": "A customer leaves out requested information on the account application", "B": "A customer lists a mail drop as the account’s mailing address", "C": "A customer requests a large cash withdrawal immediately after opening the account", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fraud is much more likely to occur in new accounts than in established accounts. New account fraud is generally defined as fraud that occurs on an account within the first 90 days that it is open; often, perpetrators open these accounts with the sole intent of committing fraud. Prompt, decisive action is necessary to manage and/or close apparent problem accounts. Some of the more common red flags of potential new account schemes are: Customer residence outside the bank's trade area Dress and/or actions inconsistent or inappropriate for the customer's stated age, occupation, or income level New account holder requesting immediate cash withdrawal upon deposit Request for large quantity of temporary checks Services included with the account that do not match the customer’s purpose Missing or inaccurate customer application information Invalid phone numbers or addresses in customer account information Use of a mail drop address (a service where a non-affiliated party collects and distributes a person or entity’s mail) Large check or ATM deposits followed by rapid withdrawal or transfer of funds (a flow-through account) Business accounts without standard business transactions, such as payroll or transactions that would be expected in that business Transactions without a clear purpose in jurisdictions known for high levels of corruption Opening deposit that is a nominal cash amount Rare customer ID type Applicants over the age of 25 with no credit history Customers who cannot remember basic application information (phone number, address, etc.)"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Performing a physical inventory count is an effective way to detect a skimming scheme.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Performing an inventory count can be an effective way to detect a skimming scheme. In these schemes, the fraudster either fails to report sales or understates them. The inventory balance on the books will be higher than the physical inventory on hand, since the fraudster is handing over inventory to paying customers and pocketing their cash without recording the sale. In other words, inventory leaves the company’s possession, but the inventory balance on the books does not reflect this. This is referred to as shrinkage."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE concerning the different types of workers’ compensation fraud schemes?", "options": {"A": "In an organized fraud scheme, a lawyer, a capper, a doctor, and the claimant often collude to defraud the insurance company", "B": "In an agent fraud scheme, agents sometimes issue certificates of coverage to the insured customer while pilfering the premium", "C": "In premium fraud, an employer might understate the amount of the payroll for higher-risk classifications to get a lower-cost premium", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Workers’ compensation schemes are generally broken into four categories: premium fraud, agent fraud, claimant fraud, and organized fraud schemes. Premium fraud involves the misrepresentation of information to the insurer by employers to lower the cost of workers’ compensation premiums. For example, an employer might understate the amount of the payroll for higher-risk classifications, thus receiving lower-cost premiums. Agent fraud schemes consist primarily of pilfering premiums and conspiring to reduce premiums. Underhanded agents sometimes issue certificates of coverage to the ostensibly insured customer while misappropriating the premium rather than forwarding it to the insurance carrier. Agents might also conspire to alter or improperly influence insurance applications to offer lower premiums to their clients. Claimant fraud involves misrepresenting the circumstances of any injury or fabricating that an injury occurred. Organized fraud schemes are composed of the united efforts of a lawyer, a capper, a doctor, and the claimant. This type of scheme is used not only in workers’ compensation cases but also in other medical frauds, such as automobile injuries."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "A pyramid scheme is promoted by encouraging victim investors to recruit new members. The more members recruited, the higher the investor rises in the ranks of the enterprise, and the more money the investor is supposed to make.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In an illegal pyramid scheme, the more members that are recruited, the higher the investor is purported to rise in the ranks of the enterprise, and the more money the investor is supposed to make. The difference between a Ponzi scheme and an illegal pyramid lies in how the operation is promoted. Illegal pyramids are promoted as pyramids, whereas Ponzi schemes are promoted as investment opportunities. In an illegal pyramid, the pyramidal structure helps draw new players, each believing that they will rise through the ranks of the pyramid. A Ponzi scheme, on the other hand, masquerades as some type of investment."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Which of the following best illustrates the concept of human intelligence?", "options": {"A": "A corporate spy installs software on the computer of an employee from a competing company to monitor that employee’s communications.", "B": "A corporate spy creates a deceptive website that tricks employees from a competing company into divulging confidential information.", "C": "A corporate spy poses as a customer of a competing company to elicit information from the competitor’s salespeople.", "D": "A corporate spy breaks into a competing company’s office and steals sensitive information while employees are attending an off-site event."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Intelligence professionals might gather data through human intelligence (i.e., through direct contact with people). Generally, human intelligence is gathered from subject matter experts and informed individuals. Such efforts typically target individuals who can provide the most valuable information. For example, an intelligence professional might gather intelligence by posing as a customer of the target entity. This approach exploits two weaknesses of corporate culture: (1) all salespeople want to make a sale and (2) many salespeople will do almost anything to make a sale. Other approaches include: Employment interviews (real and fake) False licensing negotiations False acquisition or merger negotiations Hiring an employee away from a target entity Planting an agent in a target organization Social engineering"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following is a method of committing a falsified hours and salary scheme?", "options": {"A": "Forging a supervisor’s signature", "B": "Altering a timesheet after it has been approved", "C": "Colluding with a supervisor", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The most common method of misappropriating funds from the payroll is the overpayment of wages. For hourly employees, the size of a paycheck is based on two factors: the number of hours worked and the rate of pay. Therefore, for hourly employees to fraudulently increase the size of their paycheck, they must either falsify the number of hours they have worked or change their wage rate. Common ways to commit a falsified hours and salary scheme include: Inflating the number of hours worked Inflating the rate of pay Forging a supervisor’s signature Collusion with a supervisor Implementing poor custody procedures Altering a timesheet after it has been approved"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is the best definition of the automobile insurance scheme known as ditching?", "options": {"A": "An agent inflates his commissions by pressuring customers to unnecessarily replace existing policies for new ones.", "B": "An insured has two insurance policies in place and files claims with both.", "C": "An agent collects a customer’s premium, but he does not remit the payment to the insurance company.", "D": "An insured falsely reports a vehicle as stolen to collect on an insurance policy."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Ditching, also known as owner give-ups, involves getting rid of a vehicle to collect on an insurance policy or to settle an outstanding loan. The vehicle is normally expensive and purchased with a small down payment. The owner falsely reports the vehicle as stolen while orchestrating its destruction or disappearance in some way, such as by having it stripped for parts, burned, or submerged in a large body of water. In some cases, the owner just abandons the vehicle, hoping that it actually will be stolen. The scheme also sometimes involves a homeowner's insurance claim for the property that was supposedly in the vehicle when it was “stolen.”"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following would be considered a timing difference financial statement fraud scheme?", "options": {"A": "Waiting to record revenue on a contract until a construction job is complete", "B": "Recording revenue in Year 1 when the payment is received, even though the service won’t be performed until Year 2", "C": "Recognizing revenue in Year 1 when the service is performed, even though the customer doesn’t have to pay until Year 2", "D": "Recognizing a percentage of revenue on a construction project corresponding to the percentage of the project that is complete"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Financial statement fraud often involves timing differences—that is, the recording of revenues or expenses in improper periods. This can be done to shift revenues or expenses between one period and the next, increasing or decreasing earnings as desired. This practice is also referred to as income smoothing. Examples of timing difference fraud schemes include: Premature revenue recognition—in general, revenue is recognized when (or as) an entity satisfies a performance obligation by transferring a promised good or service (asset) to a customer. Consequently, even if the seller has received payment for a service, revenue cannot be recognized until the service has been performed, thus satisfying the performance obligation. Long-term contracts—in some jurisdictions, revenue on long-term contracts can be recognized under one of two methods. The completed-contract method does not record revenue until the project is 100% complete. The percentage-of-completion method, on the other hand, recognizes revenues and expenses in proportion to what percentage of the project is complete. Recording expenses in the wrong period—per the matching principle, expenses must be recognized in the same period as the corresponding revenues. The timely recording of expenses is sometimes compromised due to pressures to meet budget projections and goals."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Which of the following is a recommended step that businesses should take to protect their customers and employees from identity theft?", "options": {"A": "Conduct regular employee training on information-handling best practices", "B": "Require employees to use complex passwords or passphrases", "C": "Only retain personal information for as long as it is necessary", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following are some of the steps businesses can take to protect personal information and prevent identity theft: Limit the personal information collected from customers. For example, do not collect customers’ government identification numbers unless there is a legal requirement to do so. Restrict employees’ access to the personal information of customers and coworkers. Use network-security tools to monitor who accesses personal information. Do not retain personal information for longer than necessary. Adopt an information-handling policy that governs how personal information is stored, protected, and disposed of. Strictly enforce the policy, and discipline employees who violate it. Conduct regular employee training regarding the company’s information-handling policy and best practices for preventing identity theft. Ensure the security of buildings by using locks, access codes, and other security features. Keep physical documents containing personal information in locked rooms or locked file cabinets. Secure all computer networks and electronic information. Use encryption to protect all personal information stored by the company or sent to third parties. Encryption should also be used to protect information sent over the company’s wireless network. Restrict the use of laptops to those employees who need them to do their jobs. Require employees to use complex passwords or passphrases. Where permitted by law, perform background checks on prospective employees. Thoroughly investigate contractors and vendors before hiring them. Do not use government identification numbers as employee identification numbers or print them on paychecks. Perform regular audits of information-handling practices, network security, and other internal controls. Create a data breach response plan."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Large businesses are usually at greater risk for business identity theft than smaller ones.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Small businesses are particularly at risk for business identity theft because they have the lines of credit, capital, and other features desired by fraudsters, while often lacking the resources and technology needed to properly defend against identity theft."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "The ____________ details how much profit (or loss) a company earned over a particular period of time.", "options": {"A": "Statement of changes in owners' equity", "B": "Statement of cash flows", "C": "Balance sheet", "D": "Income statement"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Whereas the balance sheet shows a company’s financial position at a specific point in time, the income statement, or statement of profit or loss and other comprehensive income, details how much profit (or loss) a company earned during a period of time, such as a quarter or a year. The statement of changes in owners' equity details the changes in the total owners’ equity amount listed on the balance sheet. The statement of cash flows reports a company’s sources and uses of cash during a particular period of time."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Zach was booking travel arrangements for a business trip. He purchased an airline ticket online using his own funds and obtained a receipt for the ticket via email. Using photo-editing software, Zach inflated the ticket price on the electronic receipt and submitted the altered receipt to his employer for reimbursement. This is an example of what type of fraud scheme?", "options": {"A": "Mischaracterized expense scheme", "B": "Overstated expense scheme", "C": "Personal purchases with company funds", "D": "Multiple reimbursement scheme"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Instead of seeking reimbursement for personal expenses, some employees overstate the cost of actual business expenses. The most fundamental example of an overstated expense reimbursement scheme occurs when an employee alters a receipt or other supporting documentation to reflect a higher cost than what the employee actually paid."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "The asset turnover ratio is calculated by dividing net sales by average total assets.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The asset turnover ratio is used to determine the efficiency with which assets are used during the period. The asset turnover ratio is typically calculated by dividing net sales by average total assets (net sales / average total assets). However, average operating assets can also be used as the denominator (net sales / average operating assets)."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following types of procurement fraud schemes involves procurement employees who convince their employer, the procuring entity, that it needs excessive or unnecessary products or services?", "options": {"A": "Need recognition schemes", "B": "Bid tailoring schemes", "C": "Bid manipulation schemes", "D": "Nonconforming goods schemes"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Generally, procurement actions begin with the procuring entity making a determination of its general needs. These initial determinations include assessments of the types and amounts of goods or services required to meet the entity’s needs. In need recognition schemes, procurement employees convince their employer that it needs excessive or unnecessary products or services."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "The accounts receivable clerk should be responsible for both collecting cash and disbursing company funds.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The primary means of preventing cash fraud is separation of duties. Whenever one individual has control over the entire accounting transaction (e.g., authorization, recording, and custody), the opportunity is present for cash fraud. Each of the following duties/responsibilities should be separated: Cash receipts Bank deposits Bank reconciliation Cash disbursements If one person has the authority to collect the cash, deposit the receipts, record that collection, and disburse company funds, the risk is high that fraud can occur."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Bank reconciliations should be performed by an authorized signatory on the account.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "To prevent check fraud, bank reconciliations should NOT be performed by an authorized check signatory. Bank statements should be reviewed and reconciled by more than one person each month."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "question": "Jan, a Certified Fraud Examiner for a major insurance company, has received an anonymous tip that an employee in the claims department is processing claims for his own benefit during non-working hours. To gather information about the validity of this tip, Jan should look at which of the following reports?", "options": {"A": "Manual override report", "B": "Address similarity report", "C": "Exception report", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Jan could look at several different types of reports to determine the validity of the tip. For instance, address similarity reports electronically compare multiple payments going to the same address. They are extremely useful because they might show a payment defalcation or funds going to another insurance company, broker, or fictitious payee. Additionally, the exception or manual override reports list all exceptions to normal electronic processing, thereby pointing out when a computer is being used outside the normal processing time—such as on the weekend."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a technical or administrative control for securing computer systems and communication networks?", "options": {"A": "Using an intrusion admission system", "B": "Implementing privilege escalation", "C": "Implementing logical access controls", "D": "Installing a network address prevention system"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Computer networks and communications are inherently insecure and vulnerable to attack and disruption. Consequently, management must use technical and administrative controls to protect systems against threats like unauthorized use, disclosure, modification, destruction, or denial of service. Technical security involves the use of safeguards incorporated in computer hardware, operations or applications software, communications hardware and software, and related devices. Administrative security involves the use of tools to provide an acceptable level of protection for computing resources. Common technical and administrative controls used to secure computer systems and communication networks include: Logical access controls Network security Operating system security Encryption Application security Separation of duties Privilege escalation is not a control, but it is in fact a way that hackers gain unauthorized access to a computer system."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Which of the following is a common avenue through which proprietary company information is compromised?", "options": {"A": "Speeches by executives", "B": "Publications", "C": "Company website", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Publications such as newsletters or reports to shareholders and speeches or papers that are presented at conferences can inadvertently provide valuable information to competitors. A company’s website might also contain accidental leaks. Corporate spies frequently visit their targets’ websites to gather information that these companies have unknowingly made public. Employee telephone and email directories, financial information, key employees’ biographical data, product features and release dates, details on research and development, and job postings can all be found on many corporate websites."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "ABC Paving and XYZ Asphalt are the only two companies in Greenwood County that lay asphalt. An audit reveals that the government is paying more for asphalt work in Greenwood County than in other counties in the region. A review of the records reveals that of the last ten asphalt contracts awarded in Greenwood County, five have gone to ABC and five have gone to XYZ. Which of the following procurement fraud schemes is most likely occurring?", "options": {"A": "Bid rotation", "B": "Need recognition", "C": "Defective pricing", "D": "Product substitution"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Based on the facts provided, ABC Paving and XYZ Asphalt could be engaged in a bid rotation (or bid pooling) scheme, which is a form of collusion among contractors. Bid rotation occurs when two or more contractors conspire to alternate the business among themselves on a rotating basis. Instead of engaging in competitive contracting, the bidders exchange information on contract solicitations to guarantee that each contractor will win a share of the purchasing entity’s business and potentially enable them to charge inflated prices for their contracts."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "If a fraudster wants to conceal the removal of a liability from the books, which of the following actions will NOT balance the accounting equation?", "options": {"A": "Increasing revenue", "B": "Increasing an asset", "C": "Increasing a different liability", "D": "Increasing owners’ equity"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The accounting equation, Assets = Liabilities + Owners' Equity, is the basis for all double-entry accounting. Suppose that in order to make an organization appear that it has less debt, an accountant fraudulently removes a liability. This would leave the accounting equation unbalanced since the assets side would be greater than liabilities plus owners’ equity. In this particular case, the equation can be balanced by decreasing an asset, increasing a different liability, increasing an owners' equity account, increasing revenues (and thus retained earnings), or reducing an expense (and thus increasing retained earnings). Increasing an asset would only make the equation further out of balance."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a method by which contractors can inflate material costs in negotiated contracts?", "options": {"A": "Estimating costs based on valid cost allocation methods", "B": "Failing to disclose discounts and credits", "C": "Obtaining materials at stated prices from third parties", "D": "Disclosing residual inventory"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Defective pricing arises when contractors intentionally use inaccurate cost or pricing data to inflate costs in negotiated contracts (i.e., the contracting method that permits negotiations between the procuring entity and prospective contractors). A contractor can use various defective pricing schemes to increase the cost of the contract and thereby its profits, but, generally, defective pricing schemes involve inflated labor costs or inflated material costs. A contractor can inflate material costs by: Failing to disclose discounts and credits Using outdated standard costs Using small-quantity costs to price large-quantity purchases Subcontracting to or purchasing from affiliated companies at inflated prices Failing to disclose residual inventory Using phantom suppliers to inflate costs Failing to disclose changes in “make or buy” decisions Estimating costs based on invalid cost allocation methods Using unsupported cost escalation factors"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "When developing a program for safeguarding proprietary information (SPI), an organization should form a company task force to develop the program, and the task force should include representatives from relevant departments across the company, such as research and development, corporate security, and records management.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "To coordinate a company-wide program for safeguarding proprietary information (SPI), management should establish a task force and charge it with developing the program. The task force should include managers and staff from departments that deal with proprietary information, such as research and development and production. The task force should also include representatives from the following departments: corporate security, human resources, records management, data processing, and legal. Once the task force is assembled, it must identify the information that is to be protected. To make this determination, the task force should identify those areas that give the company its competitive edge (e.g., quality of the product, service, price, manufacturing technology, marketing, and distribution). When doing so, the task force should ask, “What information would a competitor like to know?”"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Which of the following scenarios is an example of a conflict of interest?", "options": {"A": "An employee for a phone installation company works as a fishing guide on weekends, but he does not tell the phone company about his other job.", "B": "An employee is related to a party that works for one of his company’s vendors and informs his employer of the relationship.", "C": "An employee has an undisclosed personal relationship with a company that does business with his employer.", "D": "An employee for a pharmaceutical company has an economic interest in a company that does business with his employer and discloses it to his employer."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A conflict of interest occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence his professional role. Thus, an employee with an undisclosed personal relationship with a company that does business with his employer is engaged in a conflict of interest. An employee who has an undisclosed side job would not be engaged in a conflict of interest provided that the job is in a different industry, does not create a time conflict, and does not create any personal or economic interest that could influence his ability to act in his primary employer's best interest. Most conflicts of interest occur because the fraudster has an undisclosed economic interest in a transaction, but a conflict can exist when the fraudster’s hidden interest is not economic. In some scenarios, an employee acts in a manner detrimental to his company to provide a benefit to a friend or relative, even though the fraudster receives no financial benefit. Conflicts of interest do not necessarily constitute legal violations, as long as they are properly disclosed. Thus, to be classified as a conflict of interest scheme, the employee’s interest in the transaction must be undisclosed. The crux of a conflict case is that the fraudster takes advantage of his employer; the victim organization is unaware that its employee has divided loyalties. If an employer knows of the employee’s interest in a business deal or negotiation, there can be no conflict of interest, no matter how favorable the arrangement is for the employee."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "All of the following are methods of identity theft prevention recommended for businesses EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Limit employees’ access to customers’ personal information.", "B": "Restrict the use of laptops to those employees who need them to do their jobs.", "C": "Perform audits of information-handling practices only when required to do so by regulators.", "D": "Conduct background checks on prospective employees when permitted by law to do so."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The following are some of the steps businesses can take to protect personal information and prevent identity theft: Limit the personal information collected from customers. For example, do not collect customers’ government identification numbers unless there is a legal requirement to do so. Restrict employees’ access to the personal information of customers and coworkers. Use network-security tools to monitor who accesses personal information. Do not retain personal information for longer than necessary. Adopt an information-handling policy that governs how personal information is stored, protected, and disposed of. Strictly enforce the policy, and discipline employees who violate it. Conduct regular employee training regarding the company’s information-handling policy and best practices for preventing identity theft. Ensure the security of buildings by using locks, access codes, and other security features. Keep physical documents containing personal information in locked rooms or locked file cabinets. Secure all computer networks and electronic information. Use encryption to protect all personal information stored by the company or sent to third parties. Encryption should also be used to protect information sent over the company’s wireless network. Restrict the use of laptops to those employees who need them to do their jobs. Require employees to use complex passwords or passphrases. Where permitted by law, perform background checks on prospective employees. Thoroughly investigate contractors and vendors before hiring them. Do not use government identification numbers as employee identification numbers or print them on paychecks. Perform regular audits of information-handling practices, network security, and other internal controls. Create a data breach response plan."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Traditionally, there are two methods of percentage analysis of financial statements. They are:", "options": {"A": "Vertical and historical analysis", "B": "Balance sheet and income statement analysis", "C": "Horizontal and vertical analysis", "D": "Horizontal and historical analysis"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Traditionally, there are two methods of percentage analysis of financial statements. Vertical analysis is a technique for analyzing the relationships among the items on an income statement, balance sheet, or statement of cash flows by expressing components as percentages of a specified base value. Horizontal analysis, on the other hand, is a technique for analyzing the percentage change in individual financial statement items from one year to the next. The first period in the analysis is considered the base, and the changes to subsequent periods are computed as a percentage of the base period."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "A recommended practice to detect expense reimbursement schemes is to compare current period expenses to both historical expenditure amounts and budgeted expense amounts.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Generally, expense account review uses one of two methods: historical comparisons or comparisons with budgeted amounts. A historical comparison compares the balance expended this period in relation to the balance spent in prior, similar periods. Budgets are estimates of the money or time necessary to complete a task. They are based on past experience with consideration for current and future business conditions. Therefore, when comparing actual and budgeted expenses, determining excessive expenses or inaccurate budget estimates is important."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a common area for construction loan fraud schemes?", "options": {"A": "Retainage", "B": "Developer overhead", "C": "Estimates of costs to complete", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Construction lending has different vulnerabilities than other permanent or interim lending. More risks are associated with construction projects than with already-built projects. Construction loan fraud schemes are numerous; the more common ones are related to estimates of costs to complete, developer overhead, draw requests, and retainage/holdback schemes."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which accounting principle requires corresponding expenses and revenue to be recorded in the same accounting period?", "options": {"A": "Comparability", "B": "Going concern", "C": "Matching", "D": "Faithful representation"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Expenses are recognized in the income statement on the basis of a direct association between the costs incurred and the earning of specific items of income. This process, commonly referred to as the matching principle, involves the simultaneous or combined recognition of revenues and expenses that result directly and jointly from the same transactions or other events; for example, the various components of expense making up the cost of goods sold are recognized at the same time as the income derived from the sale of the goods."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Why is the health care industry concerned about the potential effect of the Electronic Data Interchange (EDI) on fraudulent activity?", "options": {"A": "Only a few types of health care transactions can be processed by EDI", "B": "The tools required to detect EDI fraud are difficult to use", "C": "The efficiency of EDI allows for more vendors and thus more claims to process", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The reasons the health care industry is concerned about EDI’s potential to stimulate fraudulent activity include: There is a lack of tools to detect EDI fraud. The variety of health care services increases the potential for dissimilar frauds. The efficiency of EDI allows for more vendors and thus more claims to account for. The swiftness in which transactions take place allows less time to uncover fraud."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "In most construction contracts, a certain amount will be withheld from each draw request by the contractor. This amount is not paid until the contract has been finished and approved by the owner. The withheld amount is referred to as which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Withholding", "B": "Retainage", "C": "Good faith deposit", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Retainage (sometimes called the holdback) is the amount withheld from each draw request until such time as the construction is complete and the lien period has expired."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "The method of concealing a receivables skimming scheme whereby one customer account is credited for a payment that was made on another account is called which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Currency substitution", "B": "Altered payee designation", "C": "Inventory padding", "D": "Lapping"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Lapping customer payments is one of the most common methods of concealing skimming. It is a technique that is particularly useful to employees who skim receivables. Lapping is the crediting of one account through the abstraction of money from another account. For example, suppose a company has three customers: A, B, and C. When A’s payment is received, the fraudster takes it for himself instead of posting it to A’s account. Customer A expects that his account will be credited with the payment he has made, but this payment has actually been stolen. When A’s next statement arrives, he will see that his payment was not applied to his account and will complain. To avoid this, some action must be taken to make it appear that the payment was posted. When B’s payment arrives, the fraudster takes this money and posts it to A’s account. Payments now appear to be up-to-date on A’s account, but B’s account is short. When C’s payment is received, the perpetrator applies it to B’s account."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Wealth in a virtual economy can only be generated by spending significant time and effort participating in massively multiplayer online (MMO) gaming platforms to slowly earn in-game currency.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Wealth in a virtual economy is typically generated by spending significant time and effort participating in massively multiplayer online (MMO) gaming platforms to slowly earn in-game currency, or it can be generated by simply paying for in-game currency using outside payment methods, such as credit cards, PayPal, or bitcoin."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "In investigating whether financial statements have been manipulated to make a company appear more profitable, a Certified Fraud Examiner should look for liabilities that have been overstated.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Understating liabilities and expenses is one of the ways financial statements can be manipulated to make a company appear more profitable. Because pre-tax income will increase by the full amount of the expense or liability not recorded, this financial statement fraud method can significantly affect reported earnings with relatively little effort by the fraudster. There are three common methods for concealing liabilities and expenses: Omitting liabilities and/or expenses Improperly capitalizing costs rather than expensing them Failing to disclose warranty costs and product-return liabilities"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Gaps in the sequence of transactions on the register log might indicate that a fraudulent register disbursement scheme is taking place.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Red flags of fraudulent register disbursements include the following: Inappropriate separation of duties exists. Cashiers, rather than supervisors, have access to the control keys necessary for refunds and voids. Register employees have the authority to void their own transactions. Register refunds are not carefully reviewed. Multiple cashiers operate from a single cash drawer without separate access codes. Personal checks from cashiers are found in the register. Voided transactions are not properly documented or approved by a supervisor. Voided cash receipt forms (manual systems) or supporting documents for voided transactions (cash register systems) are not retained on file. Gaps exist in the sequence of transactions on the register log. There is an excessive number of refunds, voids, or no-sales on the register log. Inventory totals appear forced. There are multiple refunds or voids for amounts just under the review limit."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Credit card fraud is difficult to execute because the chances of getting caught are quite high.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Credit card fraud is successful because the chances of being caught are low and prosecution is not ensured. Retailers have identified credit card thieves and contacted law enforcement, but they often receive little or no response regarding the crime."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "To conduct an electronic payment using a person-to-person (P2P) system, the two individuals must meet in person at a financial institution to sign an order requesting the transfer of money from one person’s account to the other.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Individuals can pay each other for goods or services electronically, which is known as the person-to-person (P2P) system. Many credit cards and banks offer this service to their customers. P2P payments can now be made through a variety of services using a computer, smartphone application, or email address."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "ABC Company purchases a material amount of products from another entity whose operating policies can be controlled by ABC Company’s management, but it does not disclose this situation on its financial statements. In which type of improper disclosure scheme has ABC Company engaged?", "options": {"A": "Improper asset valuation", "B": "Related-party transaction", "C": "Significant event", "D": "Accounting change"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Related-party transactions are business deals or arrangements between two parties who hold a pre-existing connection prior to the transaction. These transactions generally occur when a company does business with another entity whose management or operating policies can be controlled or significantly influenced by the company or by some other party in common. There is nothing inherently wrong with related-party transactions, as long as they are fully disclosed. If the transactions are not fully disclosed, the company might injure its shareholders by engaging in economically harmful dealings without their knowledge. The financial interest that a company official might have might not be readily apparent. For example, common directors of two companies that do business with each other, any corporate general partner and the partnerships with which it does business, and any controlling shareholder of the corporation with which he/she/it does business are all illustrations of related parties. Family relationships can also be considered related parties, such as all direct descendants and ancestors, without regard to financial interests. Related-party transactions are sometimes referred to as self-dealing."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following activities is included in the post-award and administration phase of procurements involving open and free competition?", "options": {"A": "The procuring entity issues the solicitation document.", "B": "The procuring entity evaluates the bids or proposals.", "C": "The procuring entity performs its contractual obligations.", "D": "The procuring entity develops the bid specifications."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "During the post-award and administration phase, the contracting parties fulfill their respective duties through the performance of their contractual obligations. Activities that occur during this phase include contract modifications (i.e., change orders); review of completed portions and release of monies; and assessment of deliverables for compliance with the contract terms, including quality control."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "David is an accounts receivable clerk at Richmond Storage Rental. Carson, who rents one of the company’s storage units, submits his monthly payment to Richmond’s office. Instead of applying the payment to Carson’s account, David takes the money and keeps it for himself. The next payment that arrives comes from Fisher. Instead of applying Fisher’s payment to the correct account, David applies it to Carson’s account so that it doesn’t appear delinquent. The next payment that arrives gets applied to Fisher’s account, and David continues to apply incoming customer payments to the previous customer’s account so that no one discovers his theft of Carson’s payment. What type of scheme is David committing?", "options": {"A": "Padding", "B": "Substitution", "C": "Kiting", "D": "Lapping"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Lapping customer payments is one of the most common methods of concealing skimming. It is a technique that is particularly useful to employees who skim receivables. Lapping is the crediting of one account through the abstraction of money from another account. For example, suppose a company has three customers: A, B, and C. When A’s payment is received, the fraudster takes it for himself instead of posting it to A’s account. Customer A expects that his account will be credited with the payment he has made, but this payment has actually been stolen. When A’s next statement arrives, he will see that his payment was not applied to his account and will complain. To avoid this, some action must be taken to make it appear that the payment was posted. When B’s payment arrives, the fraudster takes this money and posts it to A’s account. Payments now appear to be up-to-date on A’s account, but B’s account is short. When C’s payment is received, the perpetrator applies it to B’s account."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a way that dishonest contractors collude to circumvent the competitive bidding process?", "options": {"A": "Submit invoices for work that was not performed or materials that were not delivered.", "B": "Submit token bids that are not serious attempts to win the contract.", "C": "Use obscure publications to publish bid solicitations.", "D": "Submit bids that are competitive in price."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Schemes involving collusion among contractors seek to circumvent the competitive bidding process. In these schemes, competitors in the same market collude to defeat competition or to inflate the prices of goods and services artificially. Complementary bidding (also known as protective, shadow, or cover bidding) is a common form of collusion between competitors, and it occurs when competitors submit token bids that are not serious attempts to win the contract. Token bids give the appearance of genuine bidding, but, by submitting token bids, the conspirators can influence the contract price and who is awarded the contract."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "James is a purchaser for a large government entity. ABC Inc. tells James that if he will award ABC at least $5 million in contracts over the next two years, ABC will hire James at the end of the two years at twice his current salary. Because no actual money changes hands, this could not be considered a bribery or corruption scheme.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Bribes do not necessarily involve direct payments of cash or goods. Bribery may be defined as the offering, giving, receiving, or soliciting of corrupt payments—items of value paid to procure a benefit contrary to the rights of others—to influence an official act or business decision. Promises of favorable treatment can constitute corrupt payments. Such promises commonly take the following forms: A payer might promise a government official lucrative employment when the recipient leaves government service. An executive leaving a private company for a related government position might be given favorable or inflated retirement and separation benefits. The spouse or other relative of the intended recipient might also be employed by the payer company at an inflated salary or with minimal actual responsibility."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "The most effective way to prevent and detect electronic payment fraud is through proper separation of duties.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The most important practice for preventing and detecting electronic payment fraud is separation of duties. For example, in the case of online bill payments, such as those made through a bank’s website or a third-party business-to-business payment service, separate individuals should be responsible for maintaining payment templates, entering payments, and approving payments. For wire transfers, duties for creating, approving, and releasing wires should be segregated. And to prevent attempts to conceal fraudulent electronic payment activity, no individual involved in the payment process should reconcile the bank statement or even have access to it. In addition to separating duties, companies should consider segregating their bank accounts to maintain better control over them—for example, separate accounts can be used for paper and electronic transactions."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "___________ involve paying individuals to undergo unnecessary medical procedures that are then billed to the patient's insurer or health care program.", "options": {"A": "DRG creep schemes", "B": "Fictitious patient schemes", "C": "Rent-a-patient schemes", "D": "False cost reporting schemes"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "So-called rent-a-patient schemes involve paying individuals to undergo unnecessary medical procedures that are then billed to the patient’s insurer or health care program. These schemes occur in countries using a third-party-payer system or single-payer system that allows private providers to bill health care programs."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Baker, the managing partner in a small law firm, is the authorized signer on all company checks. When his personal phone bill arrived last month, Baker prepared and signed a company check to pay the bill. He did not disclose this payment to his partners. Baker committed:", "options": {"A": "An authorized maker scheme", "B": "A false billing scheme", "C": "A forged maker scheme", "D": "A mischaracterized expense scheme"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "An authorized maker scheme is a type of check tampering fraud in which an employee with signature authority on a company account writes fraudulent checks for his own benefit and signs his own name as the maker. The most common example occurs when a majority owner or sole shareholder uses his company to pay personal expenses directly out of company accounts. Baker's scheme is not a billing scheme because he wrote the check himself and there is no indication that he submitted the phone bill to the firm's regular payment cycle."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding an overstated refund scheme?", "options": {"A": "An employee overstates the amount of a legitimate refund and keeps the excess cash.", "B": "It requires collusion between the customer and the employee.", "C": "The company’s inventory balance on the books will be understated.", "D": "It is based on an entirely fictitious refund transaction."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Rather than create an entirely fictitious refund, some employees merely overstate the amount of a legitimate refund and steal the excess money. For example, if a customer returns $100 worth of merchandise, the employee might ring up a $200 return. The employee gives the customer $100 in return for the merchandise and then keeps the remaining $100. The customer might or might not be aware of the scheme taking place. This will result in shrinkage of $100 worth of inventory. In other words, the inventory balance on the books will be overstated by the amount of the excess refund."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Non-repudiation refers to a method used to guarantee that parties involved in an e-commerce transaction cannot deny their participation in it.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Non-repudiation refers to a method used to guarantee that the parties involved in an e-commerce transaction cannot repudiate (deny) participation in that transaction. In e-commerce, non-repudiation is obtained through the use of digital signatures, confirmation services, and timestamps."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "A medical institution receives funding based on all the services it provides related to a condition or disease. This system of compensation is referred to as capitation.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "There are several types of reimbursements for providers: fee-for-service, capitation, episode-of-care, and salary. Each has advantages and disadvantages from an anti-fraud perspective. Capitation is a reimbursement method in which providers receive one lump sum for each patient that they treat, regardless of how many services the provider renders. While this method avoids some of the incentives for providers to perform unnecessary services, it might give providers a reason to focus on the quantity of patients they see rather than the quality of service. Additionally, capitation does little to stop schemes involving fictitious patients. Episode-of-care reimbursement is a health care payment method in which providers receive one lump sum for all the services they provide related to a condition or disease (as opposed to capitation, which is a lump sum per patient). This method captures some of the benefits of capitation by removing incentives to provide unnecessary services, but it is also (in theory) more fair to providers than capitation because it compensates them more when multiple health issues are treated."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Heidi, a Certified Fraud Examiner and internal auditor for a health care program, has been asked to review the program's system of internal controls in the claims processing area. Heidi has decided to present the management of the unit with a list of general indicators for fraud that are applicable to many health insurance fraud schemes by program beneficiaries. All of the following would be included on Heidi's list EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Anonymous telephone or email inquiries regarding the status of a pending claim", "B": "Individuals who mail their claim and ask for their claim payment to be sent through direct bank transfer", "C": "Pressure by a claimant to pay a claim quickly", "D": "Threats of legal action when a claim is not paid quickly"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A fraud examiner should be aware of the following indicators of fraud by insured individuals and beneficiaries under health care programs: Pressure by a claimant to pay a claim quickly Individuals who hand-deliver claims and insist on picking up their payment in-person Threats of legal action if a claim is not paid quickly Anonymous telephone or email inquiries regarding the status of a pending claim Identical claims for the same patient in different months or years Dates of service just prior to termination of coverage or just after coverage begins Services billed that do not appear to agree with the medical records Billing for services or equipment that are clearly unsuitable for the patient’s needs Of course, everyone wants their claim paid as soon as possible. Red flags don't arise unless the person continually pressures for payment or continually threatens legal action."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Assets, liabilities, and owners’ equity are all items that appear on a company’s balance sheet.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The balance sheet, or statement of financial position, shows a “snapshot” of a company’s financial situation at a specific point in time, generally the last day of the accounting period. The balance sheet is an expansion of the accounting equation, Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity. That is, it lists a company’s assets on one side and its liabilities and owners’ equity on the other side."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Bruce is a purchaser for Acme Widgets. Bruce’s brother-in-law is a salesperson for Olson Electronics, one of Acme’s largest suppliers. Bruce told his supervisor about the relationship, and she approved his ordering of supplies from his brother-in-law as long as the purchases were reviewed by a senior manager. Bruce did not receive any favors or money from his brother-in-law in return for the sales. A year after Bruce discussed the situation with his supervisor, Acme’s management discovers that another supplier offers the same parts as Olson Electronics but at a cheaper price. Acme Widgets is considering suing Bruce for conflict of interest. Which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE statement about Acme’s chances of success?", "options": {"A": "Acme’s chances are poor because the company was aware of the situation and it allowed Bruce to do business with his brother-in-law’s company despite the relationship.", "B": "Acme’s chances are good because it is clear that Bruce had a conflict of interest in dealing with his brother-in-law.", "C": "Acme’s chances are poor because Bruce did not actually receive any money from his brother-in-law for sending him business.", "D": "Acme’s chances are good because it could have gotten the supplies at a lower price."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A conflict of interest occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence his professional role. But to be classified as a conflict of interest scheme, the employee’s interest in the transaction must be undisclosed. The crux of a conflict case is that the fraudster takes advantage of his employer; the victim organization is unaware that its employee has divided loyalties. If an employer knows of the employee’s interest in a business deal or negotiation, there can be no conflict of interest, no matter how favorable the arrangement is for the employee."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "The qualitative financial reporting characteristic of comparability prohibits any change in an accounting principle previously employed.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Comparability is the qualitative characteristic that enables users to identify and understand similarities in, and differences among, items. Information about a company is more useful if it can be compared with similar information about other entities and with similar information about the same entity for another period or another date. Although a single economic occurrence can be faithfully represented in multiple ways, permitting alternative accounting methods for the same economic occurrence diminishes comparability. Consistency, although related to comparability, is not the same. Consistency refers to the use of the same methods for the same items, either from period to period within a reporting entity or in a single period across entities. Comparability is the goal; consistency helps to achieve that goal. However, both comparability and consistency do not prohibit a change in an accounting principle previously employed. An entity’s management is permitted to change an accounting policy only if the change is required by a standard or interpretation or results in the financial statements providing more reliable and relevant information about the effects of transactions; other events; or conditions on the entity's financial position, financial performance, or cash flows. The entity’s financial statements must include full disclosure of any such changes. Examples of changes in accounting principles include a change in the method of inventory pricing, a change in the depreciation method for previously recorded assets, and a change in the method of accounting for long-term construction contracts. The disclosure for a change in accounting principles should include the justification for the change and should explain why the newly adopted principle is preferable."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "All of the following activities are included in the presolicitation phase of procurements involving open and free competition EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "The procuring entity develops the bid specifications.", "B": "The procuring entity determines the method for acquiring the goods or services.", "C": "The procuring entity issues the solicitation document.", "D": "The procuring entity identifies its needs."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In the presolicitation phase, the procuring entity identifies its needs, develops the bid specifications (what, how much, and how good), determines the method to use for acquiring the goods or services, and develops the criteria used to award the contract. Bid specifications are a list of elements, measurements, materials, characteristics, required functions, and other specific information detailing the goods and services that a procuring entity needs from a contractor. The procuring entity issues the solicitation document in the solicitation phase of the procurement process."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is an example of the piggybacking method used to gain access to restricted areas?", "options": {"A": "Following behind an individual who has been cleared for access into a restricted area", "B": "Pretending to be a member of a large crowd of people authorized to enter a restricted area", "C": "Taking advantage of a legitimate computer user’s active session when the user attends to other business while still logged on", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Piggybacking is a method used to gain access to restricted areas, including computer systems, in which the attacker exploits another person's access capability. Unlike most other methods of attack, piggybacking can be done to gain physical or electronic access. Physical access via piggybacking involves gaining access to an area that is secured by locked doors, and it occurs when an attacker exploits a false association with another person who has legitimate access to the area. Examples of piggybacking to gain physical access into a restricted area would include: Following behind an individual who has been cleared for access into the restricted area Tricking an authorized individual into believing the piggybacker is authorized and convincing the individual to agree to allow the piggybacker to tag along into the restricted area Surreptitiously following behind an individual who has been cleared for access into a restricted area, giving the appearance of being legitimately escorted Pretending to be a member of a large crowd of people authorized to enter a restricted area Electronic piggybacking occurs when an attacker gains access to an electronic system by exploiting the access capability of another person with legitimate access. One type of electronic piggybacking occurs when the attacker takes advantage of a legitimate computer user’s active session when the user did not properly terminate the session, the user’s logoff is unsuccessful, or the user attends to other business while still logged on."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "The solicitation phase of procurements involving open and free competition includes which of the following activities?", "options": {"A": "The prospective contractors prepare and submit their bids.", "B": "The procuring entity identifies its needs and develops the criteria used to award the contract.", "C": "The procuring entity determines the method for acquiring the goods or services.", "D": "The procuring entity performs its contractual obligations."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The solicitation phase involves the bid solicitation, bid preparation, and bid submission. During this phase, the procuring entity prepares the solicitation document, provides notices of solicitation, and issues the solicitation document. After the procuring entity issues the solicitation document, the bidders prepare and submit their bids or proposals."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE with regard to the statement of cash flows?", "options": {"A": "There are four types of cash flows: cash flows from operating activities, from investing activities, from financing activities, and from revenue activities.", "B": "The statement of cash flows shows a company’s financial position at a specific point in time.", "C": "The statement of cash flows is not always necessary because most companies operate under cash-basis accounting rather than accrual accounting.", "D": "The statement of cash flows is often used in tandem with the income statement to determine a company’s true financial performance."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The statement of cash flows reports a company’s sources and uses of cash during the accounting period. This statement is often used by potential investors and other interested parties in tandem with the income statement to determine a company’s true financial performance during the period being reported. The nature of accrual accounting allows (and often requires) the income statement to contain many noncash items and subjective estimates that make it difficult to fully and clearly interpret a company’s operating results. However, it is much harder to falsify the amount of cash that was received and paid during the year, so the statement of cash flows enhances the financial statements’ transparency. The balance sheet shows a company’s financial position at a specific point in time."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "_____________________ is the deliberate misrepresentation of the financial condition of an enterprise accomplished through the intentional misstatement or omission of amounts or disclosures in the financial statements to deceive financial statement users.", "options": {"A": "Occupational fraud", "B": "Accounting fraud", "C": "Material misstatement", "D": "Financial statement fraud"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Financial statement fraud is the deliberate misrepresentation of the financial condition of an enterprise accomplished through the intentional misstatement or omission of amounts or disclosures in the financial statements to deceive financial statement users."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Which of the following would be helpful in detecting a skimming scheme?", "options": {"A": "Examining journal entries for false credits to inventory", "B": "Examining journal entries for accounts receivable write-offs", "C": "Confirming customers’ outstanding account balances", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Skimming can sometimes be detected by reviewing and analyzing all journal entries made to the cash and inventory accounts. Journal entries involving the following topics should be examined: Credits to inventory to conceal unrecorded or understated sales Write-offs of lost, stolen, or obsolete inventory Write-offs of accounts receivable accounts Irregular entries to cash accounts A skimming scheme that involves lapping can be detected by independent confirmation of customers’ account balances. In a receivables skimming scheme, the fraudster skims a customer’s payment instead of posting it to his account. The next payment that arrives gets posted to the skimming victim’s account, and so on. Therefore, in a skimming scheme, at least one customer account will appear delinquent on the books, even though that customer has paid."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Fraud in financial statements generally takes the form of overstated assets or revenue and understated liabilities and expenses.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Fraud in financial statements takes the form of overstated assets or revenue and understated liabilities and expenses. Overstating assets or revenue falsely reflects a financially stronger company by inclusion of fictitious asset costs or artificial revenues. Understated liabilities and expenses are shown through exclusion of costs or financial obligations. Both methods result in increased equity and net worth for the company. This overstatement and/or understatement results in increased earnings per share or partnership profit interests or a more stable picture of the company’s financial situation."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is most indicative that the winning bid on an original construction project was not feasible?", "options": {"A": "High turnover in developer’s personnel", "B": "Increasing trend in the number of change orders", "C": "Draw requests", "D": "Missing documentation"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "An increasing trend in the number of change orders or amounts on change orders might be an indication that construction changes have taken place that would alter the originally planned project to such an extent as to render the underwriting inappropriate. Alternatively, some projects—especially large projects—tend to have many change orders. It might be more abnormal in situations like these to have few change orders or none at all than to have many. For instance, a lack of change orders for a large project might suggest that progress is not actually being made. Ultimately, the key characteristic that the fraud examiner should look for in change orders is abnormality, which can come in many forms. Fraud examiners should discover what the normal trend for change orders is in terms of both quantity and content with the particular type of industry and project, and then they can look for deviations from those trends."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "All of the following can help prevent a computer from being infected by malicious software EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Updating the operating system regularly", "B": "Installing shareware into a system's root directory", "C": "Using anti-malware software", "D": "Updating with the latest security patches"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The following measures can help avoid infection from a malicious program: Use anti-malware software to scan all incoming email messages and files. Regularly update virus definitions in anti-malware programs. Use precaution when opening emails from acquaintances. Do not open email attachments unless they are from trusted sources. Only download files from reputable sources. Regularly update the operating system. Regularly update the computer with the latest security patches available for the operating system, software, browser, and email programs. Ensure that there is a clean boot disk to facilitate testing with antivirus software. Use a firewall and keep it turned on. Consider testing all computer software on an isolated system before loading it. In a network environment, do not place untested programs on the server. Secure the computer against unauthorized access from external threats such as hackers. Keep backup copies of production data files and computer software in a secure location. Scan pre-formatted storage devices before using them. Consider preventing the system from booting with a removable storage device; this might prevent accidental infection. Establish corporate policies and an employee education program to inform employees of how malware is introduced and what to do if malware is suspected. Encourage employees to protect their home systems as well. Many malware infections result from employees bringing infected storage devices or files from home."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Frequent check deposits in round numbers or for the same amount and checks written to individuals for large, even amounts might be indicators of check fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Frequent deposits in round numbers or for the same amount and checks issued to individuals for large, even amounts are both indicators of check fraud."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a common scheme perpetrated by suppliers of reusable medical equipment?", "options": {"A": "Providing a poorer quality wheelchair or scooter than billed for", "B": "Billing for equipment rental after it is returned", "C": "Falsifying prescriptions for medical equipment", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Reusable medical equipment, often called durable medical equipment (DME), includes items such as crutches, wheelchairs, and specialized patient beds. Fraud schemes perpetrated by reusable medical equipment suppliers frequently involve: Falsified prescriptions for equipment or supplies Intentionally providing excessive supplies Equipment not delivered or billed before delivery Billing for equipment rental beyond when the equipment was checked out Billing for supplies not covered by the insurance policy or health care program Scooter scams (i.e., billing for electric-powered wheelchairs that are either unnecessary or are of poorer quality than the model billed for)"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Which of the following situations would be MOST indicative of a customer committing new account fraud at a bank?", "options": {"A": "A customer opens a business account and soon after has payroll transactions on the account.", "B": "A customer deposits a substantial amount of funds in a new personal account and does not spend or withdraw them for several months.", "C": "An invalid address or phone number is listed in the customer’s account information.", "D": "A customer opens a new personal account and immediately requests two ATM cards."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Fraud is much more likely to occur in new accounts than in established accounts. New account fraud is generally defined as fraud that occurs on an account within the first 90 days that it is open; often, perpetrators open accounts with the sole intent of committing fraud. Prompt, decisive action is necessary to manage and/or close apparent problem accounts. Some of the more common red flags of potential new account schemes are: Customer residence outside the bank's trade area Dress and/or actions inconsistent or inappropriate for the customer's stated age, occupation, or income level New account holder requesting immediate cash withdrawal upon deposit Request for large quantity of temporary checks Services included with the account that do not match the customer’s purpose Missing or inaccurate customer application information Invalid phone numbers or addresses in customer account information Use of a mail drop address (a service where a non-affiliated party collects and distributes a person or entity’s mail) Large check or ATM deposits followed by rapid withdrawal or transfer of funds (a flow-through account) Business accounts without standard business transactions, such as payroll or transactions that would be expected in that business Transactions without a clear purpose in jurisdictions known for high levels of corruption Opening deposit that is a nominal cash amount Rare customer ID type Applicants over the age of 25 with no credit history Customers who cannot remember basic application information (phone number, address, etc.)"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT an appropriate technique for detecting a nonconforming goods or services scheme?", "options": {"A": "Determine if contract costs have exceeded or are expected to exceed the contract value.", "B": "Conduct unannounced inspections of questioned goods or materials.", "C": "Review the inspection and testing reports of questioned goods or materials.", "D": "Interview procurement personnel about the presence of any red flags."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Nonconforming goods or services fraud, also known as product substitution or failure to meet contract specifications, refers to attempts by contractors to deliver goods or services to the procuring entity that do not conform to the underlying contract specifications. Once contractors deliver goods that do not conform to the contract, they bill and receive payment for conforming goods or services without informing the purchaser of the deficiency. To detect nonconforming schemes, the fraud examiner should, at a minimum, examine the following for red flags: Contract or purchase order specifications Contractor’s statements, claims, invoices, and supporting documents Received product Test and inspection results for the relevant period, searching for discrepancies between tests and inspection results and contract specifications Additionally, to detect nonconforming schemes, the fraud examiner should: Review correspondence and contract files for indications of noncompliance. Request assistance from outside technical personnel to conduct after-the-fact tests. Inspect or test questioned goods or materials by examining packaging, appearance, and description to determine if the items are appropriate. Segregate and identify the source of the suspect goods or materials. Review inspection reports to determine whether the work performed and materials used in a project were inspected and considered acceptable. Review the contractor’s books, payroll, and expense records to see if they incurred necessary costs to comply with contract specifications. Review the inspection and testing reports of questioned goods or materials. Conduct routine and unannounced inspections and tests of questioned goods or materials. Examine the contractor’s books and manufacturing or purchase records for additional evidence, looking for discrepancies between claimed and actual costs, contractors, etc. Interview procurement personnel about the presence of any red flags or other indications of noncompliance. Search and review external records (e.g., court records, prior complaints, audit reports, investigative reports, media sources) to determine if there is any history of misconduct."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a method by which contractors can inflate labor costs in negotiated contracts?", "options": {"A": "Subcontract to affiliated companies at inflated rates.", "B": "Use higher-wage personnel to perform work at lower rates.", "C": "Account for learning-curve cost reductions.", "D": "Use valid cost schedules."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Defective pricing arises when contractors intentionally use inaccurate cost or pricing data to inflate costs in negotiated contracts (i.e., the contracting method that permits negotiations between the procuring entity and prospective contractors). A contractor can use various defective pricing schemes to increase the cost of the contract and thereby its profits, but, generally, defective pricing schemes involve inflated labor costs or inflated material costs. A contractor can inflate labor costs by: Using outdated cost schedules Using lower-wage personnel to perform work at higher rates Using salaried personnel to perform uncompensated overtime Failing to account for learning-curve cost reductions Subcontracting to affiliated companies at inflated rates"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "There are two methods for recognizing revenue on long-term construction contracts. Which of the following is one of those methods?", "options": {"A": "Contract-valuation method", "B": "Partial-contract method", "C": "Percentage-of-completion method", "D": "Cost-to-completion method"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Long-term contracts can cause special problems for revenue recognition. In some jurisdictions, for example, revenues and expenses from long-term construction contracts can be recorded using either the completed-contract method or the percentage-of-completion method, depending on the circumstances. The completed contract method does not record revenue until the project is 100% complete. The percentage-of-completion method, on the other hand, recognizes revenues and expenses as measurable progress on a project is made. This method is particularly vulnerable to manipulation because managers can falsify the percentage of completion and the estimated costs to complete a construction project in order to recognize revenues prematurely and conceal contract overruns."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "All of the following are classifications of billing schemes EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Bid rigging", "B": "Shell company schemes", "C": "Personal purchases with company funds", "D": "Invoicing via nonaccomplice vendors"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are three principal types of billing schemes: Invoicing via shell companies Invoicing via nonaccomplice vendors Personal purchases with company funds"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following statements is NOT true regarding the statement of changes in owners’ equity?", "options": {"A": "It lists the major company shareholders and the change in their ownership equity over the fiscal year.", "B": "It serves a similar purpose to the statement of retained earnings.", "C": "It shows how amounts on the income statement flow through to the balance sheet.", "D": "It acts as the connecting link between the balance sheet and the income statement."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The statement of changes in owners’ equity details the changes in the total owners’ equity amount listed on the balance sheet. Because it shows how the amounts on the income statement flow through to the balance sheet, it acts as the connecting link between the two statements. The balance of the owners’ equity at the beginning of the year is the starting point for the statement. The transactions that affect owners’ equity are listed next and are added together. The result is added to (or subtracted from, if negative) the beginning-of-the-year balance, which provides the end-of-the-year balance for total owners’ equity. The statement of changes in owners’ equity is a summary overview of the effects of owner investment and company net income on the owners’ equity balance. It does not name any shareholders or their individual ownership stake in the company. Some companies present a statement of retained earnings rather than a statement of changes in owners’ equity. Similar to the statement of changes in owners’ equity, the statement of retained earnings starts with the retained earnings balance at the beginning of the year."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Automatic debit program schemes occur when fraudsters obtain a consumer’s bank account information and then use this information to draft money from the consumer’s bank account without that person’s consent.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Automatic debit programs are a convenient way to pay bills, such as recurring charges for mortgages and car loans. Fraudsters exploit these programs by obtaining consumers’ bank account information through telemarketing schemes. Fraudsters then use this information to draft money from consumers’ bank accounts without their consent."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Common fraud schemes involving ATMs include all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Unauthorized access to PINs and account codes", "B": "Counterfeit ATM cards", "C": "Credit data blocking", "D": "Employee manipulation"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "There are a number of fraud schemes that are being perpetrated with regard to ATMs. These schemes include: Theft of card and/or unauthorized access to PINs and account codes for ATM transactions by unauthorized persons Employee manipulation Counterfeit ATM cards Counterfeit ATMs Magnetic strip skimming devices Shimming devices that target chip-based cards ATM deposit fraud"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "A detailed expense report should require which of the following components?", "options": {"A": "Explanation of the business purpose of each expense", "B": "Time period when the expense occurred", "C": "Original receipts (when possible)", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Detailed expense reports should require the following information: Receipts or other support documentation Explanation of the expense, including specific business purpose Time period when the expense occurred Place of expenditure Amount When possible, require that employees submit original paper receipts. Given the amount of electronic and Internet commerce that happens in today’s world, this is not always possible. Keep in mind that electronic copies of receipts are often much easier to forge and alter than paper receipts. Special attention should be paid to any receipts that come via email or email attachment. Consider corroborating prices on Internet receipts with those found on the vendor’s website. It is not enough to have the detailed reports submitted if they are not reviewed. A policy requiring the periodic review of expense reports, coupled with examining the appropriate detail, will help deter employees from submitting personal expenses for reimbursement."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is an accurate definition of SMiShing?", "options": {"A": "Stealing private financial data through the use of voice mail", "B": "Stealing data from payroll accounts through the use of computers", "C": "Obtaining sensitive data by impersonating a government official", "D": "Obtaining sensitive data through the use of short message services"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "SMiShing is a hybrid of phishing and short message service (text messaging). These schemes use text messages or other short message systems to conduct phishing activities. That is, in SMiShing schemes, the attacker uses text messages or other short message systems to dupe an individual or business into providing sensitive data by falsely claiming to be from an actual business, bank, ISP, or other entity with which the target does business."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Billing for experiments with new medical devices that have not yet been approved by a jurisdiction's health care authority is one form of medical fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "One form of medical fraud is the billing for experimental use of new medical devices that have not yet been approved by the jurisdiction’s health care authority. Some hospitals are deliberately misleading third-party payers by getting them to pay for the manufacturer’s research. Many of the doctors involved are alleged to have stock in the manufacturing companies."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a common type of credit card fraud?", "options": {"A": "Card counterfeiting", "B": "Skimming", "C": "Advance payments", "D": "Profiling"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Advance payments, card counterfeiting, and skimming are all forms of credit card fraud; profiling is not a type of credit card fraud."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Delta, a Certified Fraud Examiner, was hired to serve as an expert accounting witness in a case of alleged financial statement fraud. As part of her expert testimony, Delta explained how, under International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS), management must make every effort to ensure that the company’s financial statements are complete, neutral, and free from error. Delta was explaining the concept of:", "options": {"A": "Going concern", "B": "Comparability", "C": "Faithful representation", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Financial information must faithfully represent the economic data of the enterprise that it purports to represent. Every effort shall be made to maximize the qualities of perfectly faithful representation: complete, neutral, and free from error. A complete depiction includes all information necessary to understand the data presented. A neutral depiction is without bias in the selection or presentation of financial information. Free from error means there are no material errors or omissions in the financial reporting data and that the process used to produce the reported information has been selected and applied with no errors."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Password cracking is a method that attackers use to gain unauthorized access to a computer system by bypassing password security through the use of undocumented system functions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Password cracking is an automated process by which an attacker attempts to guess a system user's most likely passwords."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "DRG creep occurs when staff members at medical institutions intentionally manipulate diagnostic and procedural codes in a pattern to increase claim reimbursement amounts.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Diagnostic-related groupings (DRG) is a reimbursement methodology for the payment of institutional services. This method or similar models have become more popular in various countries for the purposes of determining costs and reimbursing institutional providers. DRG categorizes patients who are medically related with respect to various types of information, such as primary and secondary diagnosis, age, gender, weight, length of stay, and complications. Reimbursements are determined by the DRG. DRG creep occurs when medical staff members manipulate diagnostic and procedural codes to increase reimbursement amounts or other forms of funding. When it becomes a pattern and intent is established, it becomes fraud. For example, a hospital might repeatedly and incorrectly code angina (pain or discomfort in the chest due to some obstruction of the arteries) as a myocardial infarction (a more serious event, commonly known as a heart attack), and thus be reimbursed at a higher level."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following control procedures will NOT help prevent payroll fraud?", "options": {"A": "Prenumbering payroll checks and issuing them in numerical sequence", "B": "Having the employee who prepares the payroll also review and sign all payroll checks", "C": "Keeping the payroll accounting function independent of the general ledger function", "D": "Maintaining personnel records separately from payroll and timekeeping functions"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "There are two basic preventive measures for payroll-related fraud: segregation of duties and periodic payroll review and analysis. The following activities should be separated: Payroll preparation Payroll disbursement (into payroll and withholding tax accounts) Payroll distribution Payroll bank reconciliations Human resource departmental functions Therefore, the employee who prepares the payroll should NOT review or sign any payroll checks."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is the most accurate description of logical access?", "options": {"A": "The process by which computer systems’ contents are encrypted", "B": "The process by which users are allowed to access and use physical objects", "C": "The process by which users can bypass application security over the software and libraries", "D": "The process by which users are allowed to use computer systems and networks"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Logical access refers to the process by which users are allowed to use computer systems and networks, and logical access control refers to a process by which users are identified and granted certain privileges to information, systems, or resources. These controls are designed to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of informational resources. Logical access controls can be used to verify a person’s identity and privileges before granting the person logical access to information or other online resources."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "The primary purpose of physical access controls is to prevent unauthorized access to computer software.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Physical access controls refer to the process by which users are allowed access to physical objects (e.g., buildings). In contrast, logical access controls are tools used to control access to computer information systems and their components."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Corruption is the wrongful use of influence to procure a benefit for the actor or another person, contrary to the duty or the rights of others.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Corruption is the wrongful use of influence to procure a benefit for the actor or another person, contrary to the duty or the rights of others."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "The statement of changes in owners’ equity acts as the connecting link between which two financial statements?", "options": {"A": "Income statement and balance sheet", "B": "Statement of cash flows and balance sheet", "C": "Balance sheet and statement of retained earnings", "D": "Income statement and statement of cash flows"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The statement of changes in owners’ equity details the changes in the total owners’ equity amount listed on the balance sheet. Because it shows how the amounts on the income statement flow through to the balance sheet, it acts as the connecting link between the two statements. The balance of the owners’ equity at the beginning of the year is the starting point for the statement. The transactions that affect owners’ equity are listed next and are added together. The result is added to (or subtracted from, if negative) the beginning-of-the-year balance, which provides the end-of-the-year balance for total owners’ equity."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Liam, a loan officer, and other real estate insiders colluded to steal a homeowner’s identity, take out a second mortgage on the individual’s property, and split the proceeds. Liam and his co-conspirators’ actions would best be described as a fraudulent second lien scheme.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Fraudulent second liens are a variation of the fraudulent sale scheme. In a second lien scheme, a person assumes a homeowner’s identity and takes out an additional loan or a second mortgage in the homeowner’s name. If there is not enough equity in the home to warrant a second loan, an inflated appraisal is obtained. This scheme often involves a high level of collusion between a loan officer, an appraiser, and a title agent (or other real estate document service provider)."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "David runs a local catering company. He keeps his books on a calendar year and uses the accrual basis of accounting. In December of Year 1, a customer placed an order with him to cater the food for a party that would take place in February of Year 2. The contract was signed and the balance was paid in full when the order was placed in December. When should David report the revenue from this party and the associated expenses of catering it?", "options": {"A": "Both the revenue and expenses should be recorded in December.", "B": "The revenue should be recorded in December when David received the cash, and the expenses should be recorded in February after the party takes place.", "C": "Both the revenue and expenses should be recorded in February.", "D": "It doesn’t matter; it is up to David to decide whether he reports the revenue and expenses in December or February."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Expenses are recognized in the income statement on the basis of a direct association between the costs incurred and the earning of specific items of income. This process, commonly referred to as the matching principle, involves the simultaneous or combined recognition of revenues and expenses that result directly and jointly from the same transactions or other events; for example, the various components of expense making up the cost of goods sold are recognized at the same time as the income derived from the sale of the goods. In this example, since the expenses will not be incurred until David caters the event in February, the revenue David received should not be recorded until February as well."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "A favored device of phony charities is to send school-age children door to door to say that they are raising money for antidrug programs or for a group that takes underprivileged kids on trips.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A favored device of phony charities is to send school-age children door to door to say that they are raising money for antidrug programs or for a group that takes underprivileged kids on trips. Some of the children repeat what they are told in exchange for a few dollars. Others believe they will receive rewards and free trips when in fact they, too, are being scammed."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "A skimming scheme is easier to detect than a cash larceny scheme because it leaves an audit trail.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Cash receipts schemes are what we typically think of as the outright stealing of cash. Perpetrators do not rely on the submission of phony documents or the forging of signatures; they simply grab the cash and take it. The theft schemes fall into two categories: skimming and larceny schemes. Skimming is defined as the theft of off-book funds. Cash larceny schemes, however, involve the theft of money that has already appeared on a victim company’s books. Cash larceny schemes are easier to detect than skimming schemes because they leave an audit trail."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Unscrupulous debt consolidation schemes include each of the following EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "The debt consolidation company collects payments but does not appropriately forward them.", "B": "The debt consolidation company charges an upfront processing fee and then disappears.", "C": "The debt consolidation company writes a letter to the debtor's creditors and arranges a payment plan.", "D": "The debt consolidation company guarantees the debtor will receive a loan or credit card regardless of the debtor's credit ratings."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Unscrupulous debt consolidation schemes often involve the agency collecting the money from the debtor but not forwarding it to the creditors. In some instances, considerable time can pass before the debtor finds out that his money has been misappropriated. Another variation of the debt consolidation scheme occurs when customers are guaranteed that they will receive a loan or a credit card regardless of their credit rating. Typically, the victims have been rejected by legitimate financial institutions because their credit ratings are poor. The victim must pay a processing fee for the application to be accepted. After the victim pays the fee, the con artist disappears."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a fictitious expense reimbursement scheme?", "options": {"A": "An employee alters an electronic receipt using photo editing software to reflect a higher cost than what the employee actually paid.", "B": "An employee generates a fake receipt using basic computer software and includes it with an expense report.", "C": "An employee submits a receipt for a hotel reservation in one expense report and a copy of his credit card statement reflecting the same reservation in the next period’s expense report.", "D": "An employee who travels frequently on business submits receipts from a hotel stay during a family vacation as a business expense."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Expense reimbursements are sometimes sought by employees for wholly fictitious items. Instead of overstating a real business expense or seeking reimbursement for a personal expense, an employee just invents a purchase that needs to be reimbursed. One way to generate a reimbursement for a fictitious expense is to create fraudulent support documents, such as false receipts. Using simple computer software, it is easy for employees to create realistic-looking counterfeit receipts at home. These counterfeits are often very sophisticated, even including the logos of the stores in which goods or services were allegedly purchased. Instead of seeking reimbursement for personal expenses, some employees overstate the cost of actual business expenses. This is considered an overstated expense reimbursement scheme. In a multiple reimbursement scheme, an employee submits several types of support for the same expense in order to get reimbursed multiple times. In a mischaracterized expense scheme, an employee requests reimbursement for a personal expense, claiming that it is business related."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE regarding e-commerce?", "options": {"A": "Digital signatures function to authenticate e-commerce transactions", "B": "E-commerce entities must make sure that they can determine with whom they (or their computers) are communicating", "C": "In e-commerce transactions, non-repudiation is obtained through confirmation services and timestamps", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Authentication refers to the authentication of a customer’s identity. E-commerce entities must make sure that they can determine with whom they (or their computers) are communicating. Digital signatures function to authenticate e-commerce transactions. Non-repudiation refers to a method used to guarantee that the parties involved in an e-commerce transaction cannot repudiate (deny) participation in that transaction. In e-commerce, non-repudiation is obtained through the use of digital signatures, confirmation services, and timestamps."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Ed Smith, a city commissioner, negotiated a land development deal with a group of private investors. After the deal was approved, the investors rewarded Smith with an all-expenses-paid trip, even though giving such rewards to government officials is prohibited by law. Which of the following is the most appropriate term to describe what has taken place?", "options": {"A": "Economic extortion", "B": "Need recognition", "C": "Illegal gratuity", "D": "Collusion"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Illegal gratuities are items of value given to reward a decision, often after the recipient has made the decision. Illegal gratuities are similar to bribery schemes except that, unlike bribery schemes, illegal gratuity schemes do not necessarily involve an intent to influence a particular decision before the fact. That is, an illegal gratuity occurs when an item of value is given for, or because of, some act. Often, an illegal gratuity is merely something that a party who has benefited from a decision offers as a “thank you” to the person who made the beneficial decision."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Green, a door-to-door appliance salesman, sold several appliances to households in a neighborhood. Green took the money the customers gave him as down payments for the sales and spent it. He did not turn the orders in to his employer. Green’s scheme can best be classified as:", "options": {"A": "A cash larceny scheme", "B": "A commission scheme", "C": "An understated sales (skimming) scheme", "D": "An unrecorded sales (skimming) scheme"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Green's scheme is an unrecorded sales (skimming) scheme. An unrecorded sales scheme occurs when an employee sells goods or services to a customer and collects the customer’s payment but makes no record of the sale. Independent salespersons are in a good position to perform sales skimming schemes. A prime example is a person who sells goods door-to-door and does not turn in the orders to his employer. In this case, Green did not remit any of his sales to the appliance company, so the skimming scheme that took place was an unrecorded sales scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Seniors are usually more likely to report identity theft than younger victims.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Identity thieves target seniors because, compared to younger victims, seniors often have more available cash, check their credit reports less frequently, and are less aware of identity theft and other fraud. Generally, seniors are less likely to report identity theft than younger victims."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Which of the following steps are often taken during an account takeover scheme?", "options": {"A": "Steal account login information using phishing emails", "B": "Place orders using funds from the overtaken account", "C": "Change customer contact information on the overtaken account", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Account takeover fraud occurs when a fraudster surreptitiously takes control of a payment account. Targeted accounts can include credit cards, banking, brokerage, or any type of online retail account (e.g., Amazon). To take over an account, thieves obtain email addresses or other login information and use various means to obtain passwords, such as phishing emails or password-cracking botnet attacks. Once the thief overtakes an account, communication methods and contact information are altered to keep the account holder unaware of the fraudulent activity. The thief is then free—depending on the type of account—to place orders using stored payment information, transfer funds, or request duplicate credit cards."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Baker used his company credit card to pay for a business dinner at which he was entertaining a client, knowing the credit card bill would be paid by Baker's employer. Baker saved the receipt and later filed an expense report seeking reimbursement for the cost of the meal, attaching the receipt as support. This is an example of what kind of fraud?", "options": {"A": "Personal purchases with company funds", "B": "False billing scheme", "C": "Mischaracterized expense scheme", "D": "Multiple reimbursement scheme"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A multiple expense reimbursement scheme involves the submission of a single expense several times to receive multiple reimbursements. The most frequent example of such a scheme is the submission of several types of support for the same expense. However, rather than file two expense reports, employees might also charge an item to the company credit card, save the receipt, and attach it to an expense report as if they paid for the item themselves. The victim company therefore ends up paying twice for the same expense."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "A Ponzi scheme can be characterized as an ostensibly legitimate, yet ultimately fraudulent, investment opportunity wherein the promoter pays previous investors with money gained from new victims.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A Ponzi scheme is generally defined as an illegal business practice in which new investors’ money is used to make payments to earlier investors. The investment opportunity is typically presented with the promise of uncommonly high returns. While the scam is presented as a legitimate investment, there is little or no actual commerce involved. When an enterprise promotes an investment opportunity that invests little or none of the participants’ money and uses new investments to make dividend payments, the enterprise is running a Ponzi scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Matthew receives a voice mail message telling him that his credit card might have been used fraudulently. He is asked to call a phone number. When he calls the number, he hears a menu and a list of choices that closely resembles those used by his credit card company. The phone number even appears to be similar to that of his card issuer. Of which of the following types of schemes has Matthew become the target?", "options": {"A": "Pharming", "B": "SMiShing or tishing", "C": "Spear phishing", "D": "Vishing"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Vishing, or voice phishing, is the act of leveraging Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) in using the telephone system to falsely claim to be a legitimate enterprise in an attempt to scam users (both consumers and businesses) into disclosing personal information. Government and financial institutions, as well as online auctions and their payment services, can be targets of voice phishing. A vishing scheme is generally transmitted as an incoming recorded telephone message that uses a spoofed (fraudulent) caller ID matching the identity of a misrepresented organization. The message uses an urgent pretext to direct unsuspecting users to another telephone number. The victim is invited to punch his personal information on his telephone keypad. The criminals capture the key tones and convert them back to numerical format."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "If a fraudster wants to conceal the misappropriation of cash, which of the following actions will NOT result in a balanced accounting equation?", "options": {"A": "Decreasing another asset", "B": "Reducing owners’ equity", "C": "Decreasing a liability", "D": "Creating an expense"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The accounting equation, Assets = Liabilities + Owners' Equity, is the basis for all double-entry accounting. If an asset (e.g., cash) is stolen, the equation can be balanced by increasing another asset, reducing a liability, reducing an owners' equity account, reducing revenues (and thus retained earnings), or creating an expense (and thus reducing retained earnings)."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE regarding a fictitious refund scheme?", "options": {"A": "Inventory is returned to the store", "B": "The victim company’s inventory is understated", "C": "The amount of cash in the register balances with the register log", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In a fictitious refund scheme, an employee processes a transaction as if a customer were returning merchandise, even though no actual return takes place. The register log balances with the amount of cash in the register because the money that was taken by the fraudster is supposed to have been removed and given to the customer as a refund. Instead, however, the employee keeps this cash. The second thing that happens in a fictitious refund scheme is that a debit is made to the inventory system showing that the merchandise has been returned. Since the transaction is fictitious, no merchandise is actually returned. The result is that the company’s inventory is overstated."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "The equipment needed to run a check fraud ring is very expensive and difficult to obtain.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Check fraud rings thrive because the items needed to commit check fraud are easily obtainable and the cost is minimal. Often, the only necessary equipment for a check fraud ring is a scanner, printer, and personal computer."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is the most accurate definition of spyware?", "options": {"A": "A program or command procedure that gives the appearance that it is useful but in fact contains hidden malicious code that causes damage", "B": "A type of software that collects and reports information about a computer user without the user’s knowledge or consent", "C": "A self-replicating computer program that penetrates operating systems to spread malicious code to other systems", "D": "Any software application in which advertising banners are displayed while a program is running"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Spyware is a type of software that collects and reports information about a computer user without the user’s knowledge or consent."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Bribery and Corruption", "question": "Kickbacks are improper, undisclosed payments made to obtain favorable treatment.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Kickbacks are improper, undisclosed payments made to obtain favorable treatment. For example, in a kickback scheme, an employee might receive compensation in exchange for directing excess business to a vendor. Such compensation could involve monetary payments, entertainment, travel, or other favorable perks."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following best describes social engineering?", "options": {"A": "A method for gaining unauthorized access to a computer system in which an attacker hides near the target to obtain sensitive information that he can use to facilitate his intended scheme", "B": "A method for gaining unauthorized access to a computer system in which an attacker bypasses a system’s security through the use of an undocumented operating system and network functions", "C": "A method for gaining unauthorized access to a computer system in which an attacker deceives victims into disclosing personal information or convinces them to commit acts that facilitate the attacker’s intended scheme", "D": "A method for gaining unauthorized access to a computer system in which an attacker searches through large quantities of available data to find sensitive information that he can use to facilitate his intended scheme"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Social engineering is a method for gaining unauthorized access to a computer system in which the attacker deceives victims into disclosing personal information or convinces them to commit acts that facilitate the attacker’s intended scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "When fabricating a counterfeit credit card, which of the following is the most difficult facet to reproduce?", "options": {"A": "The magnetic strip", "B": "The embossed numbers", "C": "The hologram", "D": "The card thickness"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The hologram is the most difficult aspect of a credit card to reproduce. True holograms use a lenticular refraction process; counterfeits are generally only reflected materials, usually foil with an image stamped on it. These decals are attached to the card's surface rather than fixed into the plastic, as is the case with legitimate cards. Some fraudulent holograms do not change colors—as legitimate ones do—when viewed from various angles."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following types of accounts are increased by credits?", "options": {"A": "Revenue", "B": "Owners’ equity", "C": "Liability", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Entries to the left side of an account are referred to as debits, and entries to the right side of an account are referred to as credits. Debits increase asset and expense accounts, whereas credits decrease these accounts. On the other side of the equation, credits increase liabilities, revenue, and owners’ equity accounts. Conversely, debits decrease liabilities, revenues, and owners’ equity."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "ABC Bank recently acquired a new portfolio of consumer loans. Because this particular loan portfolio is experiencing a higher than normal default rate, management has asked Bradley, a Certified Fraud Examiner, to evaluate the portfolio. Bradley notices that the loan package was sold without recourse to the broker, the brokerage fee was high relative to other purchases, and the broker is no longer in business. Which of the following types of schemes has Bradley most likely uncovered?", "options": {"A": "Letter of credit fraud", "B": "Money transfer fraud", "C": "Daisy chain fraud", "D": "Brokered loan fraud"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Loan brokering applies to either packages of individual residential (consumer) loans or single commercial loans. A variation of a brokered loan is loan participation, where multiple parties purchase and have interests in a loan or a package of loans. The fraud schemes associated with brokered loans or loan participation generally involve selling phony loans (packages) or selling participations in loans that have not been properly underwritten. Normally, a large fee is charged for these brokered loans. With residential loan packages, the broker sells the package, takes the money, and disappears. Brokered loans are not usually sold with any recourse to the broker. Therefore, the purchaser must look to the borrower and the underlying collateral for debt satisfaction. With loan participations, the lead bank generally performs the underwriting. However, this does not relieve the participating bank from its obligation to perform its own due diligence."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Zane obtained a loan from Bank A, agreeing to give the bank a security interest in his commercial property. Before Bank A’s lien was filed, Zane managed to get another loan from Bank B using the same commercial property as collateral (unbeknownst to Bank B). In which of the following schemes did Zane engage?", "options": {"A": "Double-pledging collateral", "B": "Sham loan", "C": "Linked financing", "D": "Daisy chain"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In a double-pledging collateral scheme, borrowers pledge the same collateral with different lenders before liens are recorded and without telling the lenders."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "Which of the following is considered misuse of a noncash asset?", "options": {"A": "Olivia had access to a company vehicle while on an out-of-town assignment. She used the vehicle to run some personal errands after she was finished with work for the day, but she provided false written and oral information regarding the nature of her use of the vehicle.", "B": "Mike works for a lawn care service. One of his customers lives on his street. After Mike finishes mowing the customer’s lawn, he uses his employer’s lawnmower to mow his own lawn.", "C": "Lisa is a paralegal, but she also works as a personal fitness trainer on the weekends. She stays after work at the law office one day to print off invoices for her personal training clients.", "D": "All of the above are considered misuses of noncash assets."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There are basically two ways a person can misappropriate a company asset. The asset can be misused (or “borrowed”) or it can be stolen. Assets that are misused but not stolen typically include company vehicles, supplies, computers, and other office equipment. For example, suppose an employee made personal use of a company vehicle while on an out-of-town assignment. The employee provided false information, both written and verbal, regarding the nature of his use of the vehicle. The vehicle was returned unharmed and the cost to the perpetrator’s company was only a few hundred dollars. Despite the modest financial impact, such unauthorized use of a company asset constitutes fraud, particularly when a false statement accompanies the use."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "Jessica worked at the cash register of a department store. Her friend Molly came to the store one day to help Jessica steal a watch she wanted but couldn’t afford. Molly took the watch to Jessica’s register and, instead of charging Molly for it, Jessica rang a \"no sale\" on the register. Molly pretended to give Jessica cash to make it look like she was paying for the watch. Molly then took the watch out of the store and later gave it to Jessica. What type of scheme did Molly and Jessica commit?", "options": {"A": "A false sale scheme", "B": "A skimming scheme", "C": "A purchasing and receiving scheme", "D": "A register disbursement scheme"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In many cases, corrupt employees use outside accomplices to help steal inventory. The false, or fake, sale is one method that depends upon an accomplice. Like most inventory thefts, the fake sale is not complicated. The employee-fraudster’s accomplice pretends to buy merchandise, but the employee does not ring up the sale. The accomplice then takes the merchandise without paying for it. To a casual observer, it will appear that the transaction is a normal sale. The employee bags the merchandise and might act as though a transaction is being entered on the register when in fact the “sale” is not recorded. The accomplice might even pass a nominal amount of money to the employee to complete the illusion. A related scheme occurs when an employee sells merchandise to an accomplice at an unauthorized discount."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Publicly available information that anyone can lawfully obtain by request, purchase, or observation is known as which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Free-source information", "B": "Wide-source information", "C": "Confidential-source information", "D": "Open-source information"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Open-source information is information in the public domain; it can be defined as publicly available data \"that anyone can lawfully obtain by request, purchase, or observation.\""}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Events occurring after the close of the period that could have a significant effect on the entity's financial position must be disclosed in the entity’s financial statements.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Events occurring or becoming known after the close of the period that could have a significant effect on the entity's financial position must be disclosed. Fraudsters typically avoid disclosing court judgments and regulatory decisions that undermine the reported values of assets, that indicate unrecorded liabilities, or that adversely reflect upon management’s integrity. A review of subsequent financial statements, if available, might reveal whether management improperly failed to record a subsequent event that it had knowledge of in the previous financial statements. Public record searches can also help reveal this information."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "The quick ratio is used to determine the efficiency with which a company uses its assets.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The quick ratio, commonly referred to as the acid test ratio, compares quick assets (i.e., those that can be immediately liquidated) to current liabilities. This calculation divides the total of cash, securities, and receivables by current liabilities to yield a measure of a company’s ability to meet sudden cash requirements. The quick ratio offers a more conservative view of a company’s liquidity because it excludes inventory and other current assets that are more difficult to rapidly turn into cash. The asset turnover ratio is used to determine the efficiency with which asset resources are used by the entity."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following are information security goals that an e-commerce system should endeavor to meet for its users and asset holders?\nI.   Penetrability of data\nII.  Materiality of data\nIII. Integrity of data\nIV.  Availability of data", "options": {"A": "I, II, and III only", "B": "I, II, III, and IV", "C": "II and III only", "D": "III and IV only"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": ""}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Jason, a server at a popular restaurant, takes a customer’s credit card to process a payment. While he is on the other side of the dining area with his back turned, Jason swipes the card through a small device that he regularly uses to steal his customers’ credit card information. Jason is engaging in a scheme known as credit card ________.", "options": {"A": "Skimming", "B": "Scanning", "C": "Pinching", "D": "Probing"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A credit card skimming scheme requires a device, often referred to as a skimmer or a wedge, that scans and stores a large amount of credit card numbers. Credit card skimming is more frequent in businesses where an employee is able to remove the card from the customer’s view to process the transaction before returning it to the customer. This scam might occur in a retail situation in which a credit card is processed behind a concealable counter or in a restaurant scenario wherein a server walks away with a customer’s card to process the transaction."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "If an employee is aware that surprise cash counts are conducted, he will generally be less inclined to commit a cash larceny scheme.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Surprise cash counts and supervisory observations are a useful fraud prevention method if properly used. It is important that employees know that cash will be counted on a periodic and unscheduled basis. These surprise counts must be made at all steps of the process, from receiving the check, to reconciling the register log to the cash in the drawer, to depositing funds in the bank."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Which of the following schemes are often used by fraudsters to take advantage of the elderly?", "options": {"A": "Work-at-home schemes", "B": "Sweepstake and prize schemes", "C": "Homeownership schemes", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fraudsters often use homeownership to take advantage of the elderly. In a homeownership fraud scheme, the fraudster recommends a friend who can perform needed home repairs for the elderly individual at a reasonable price. This friend might require the homeowner to sign a document upon completion, confirming repairs were made. In some cases, the elderly victims later learn they signed the title of their house over to the repairperson. In other cases, not only is the elderly victim overcharged, but the work is also performed improperly. Another consumer fraud scheme targeting the elderly is related to sweepstakes and prizes. Fraudsters inform elderly individuals they won a prize but must pay a fee to receive it. The fraudsters then convince their victims that they can eventually win the grand prize if they send in another fee. This cycle continues until the victims catch onto the scheme or are no longer able to send fees because they have depleted their savings. Work-at-home business opportunities target elderly individuals who need extra income to supplement their retirement benefits. These business opportunities might include assembly crafts, chain letters, coupons, envelope stuffing, medical billings, and report writing."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "One method competitive intelligence professionals commonly use to gather data about a competitor involves posing as a job applicant and interviewing with key employees at the competing company. This practice is best described as conducting surveillance.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Intelligence professionals might gather data through human intelligence (i.e., through direct contact with people). Generally, human intelligence is gathered from subject matter experts and informed individuals. Such efforts typically target individuals who can provide the most valuable information. For example, an intelligence professional might gather intelligence by posing as a customer of the target entity. This approach exploits two weaknesses of corporate culture: (1) all salespeople want to make a sale and (2) many salespeople will do almost anything to make a sale. Other approaches include: Employment interviews (real and fake) False licensing negotiations False acquisition or merger negotiations Hiring an employee away from a target entity Planting an agent in a target organization Social engineering"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "A ____________ scheme involves the theft of cash BEFORE it appears on a company’s books, and a __________ scheme involves the theft of cash AFTER it appears on the books.", "options": {"A": "Fraudulent disbursement; skimming", "B": "Cash larceny; skimming", "C": "Skimming; cash larceny", "D": "Cash larceny; revenue"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Cash receipts schemes are what we typically think of as the outright stealing of cash. Perpetrators do not rely on the submission of phony documents or the forging of signatures; they simply grab the cash and take it. The theft schemes fall into two categories: skimming and larceny schemes. Skimming is defined as the theft of off-book funds. Skimming occurs before money appears on a company’s books. Cash larceny schemes, however, involve the theft of money that has already appeared on a victim company’s books."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "The asset turnover ratio is used to assess a company’s ability to meet sudden cash requirements.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The asset turnover ratio (net sales divided by average total assets) is used to determine the efficiency with which asset resources are used by the entity. The asset turnover ratio is one of the more reliable indicators of financial statement fraud. A sudden or continuing decrease in this ratio is often associated with improper capitalization of expenses, which increases the denominator without a corresponding increase in the numerator. The quick ratio is used to assess a company's ability to meet sudden cash requirements. The quick ratio, commonly referred to as the acid test ratio, compares quick assets (i.e., those that can be immediately liquidated) to current liabilities. It is calculated by dividing the total of cash, securities, and receivables by current liabilities. The quick ratio offers a more conservative view of a company’s liquidity because it excludes inventory and other current assets that are more difficult to rapidly turn into cash."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Sheila, an accounts payable supervisor for ABC Company, bought supplies for a company she owns on the side. Sheila entered vouchers in ABC Company's accounts payable system for the cost of the supplies. Checks were cut to pay for these unauthorized expenses during normal daily check runs. The goods were drop-shipped to a location where Sheila could collect them. What type of occupational fraud is this?", "options": {"A": "A personal purchases with company funds scheme", "B": "A pay and return scheme", "C": "An invoice kickback scheme", "D": "An expense reimbursement scheme"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Instead of undertaking billing schemes to generate cash, many fraudsters simply purchase personal items with their company’s money. Company accounts are used to buy items for employees, their businesses, their families, and so on. This type of scheme is classified as a fraudulent billing scheme rather than theft of inventory. The heart of the scheme is not the theft of the items but rather the purchase of them. The perpetrator causes the victim company to purchase something it did not actually need, so the damage to the company is the money lost in purchasing the item."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Traditional identity theft involves the use of entirely fabricated personal information or a combination of real and fabricated information to create a new identity.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Synthetic identity theft involves the use of entirely fabricated personal information or a combination of real and fabricated information to create a new identity. In traditional identity theft, a fraudster steals an individual’s personal information and pretends to be that individual. For example, a fraudster might use an individual’s name, government identification number, and date of birth to impersonate the individual and gain access to the individual’s bank account. This is called an account takeover. Another type of traditional identity theft is true name fraud, in which a fraudster uses an individual’s personal information to open a new account in the individual’s name. Unlike an account takeover, which involves an existing account, true name fraud involves a new account."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Many health care claims are now paid via EDI (Electronic Data Interchange). Because EDI leaves no paper trail, it makes detecting fraud in the health care industry easier.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "EDI frustrates fraud examiners' ability to detect fraud in the health care industry in three ways: The automation of claims has erased claims professionals’ ability to detect suspicious-looking claims. Because they are used to handling the paperwork of claims, EDI hampers the claims professional from getting a good picture of the overall nature of an account, instead reducing each transaction to individual claims. Because of the impersonal nature of electronic transactions, EDI raises the temptation of would-be fraudsters to commit white-collar crime. EDI leaves no paper trail, making the process of fraud detection difficult for the fraud examiner."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "In a construction loan, developer overhead is a ripe area for abuse. The purpose of developer overhead is to provide:", "options": {"A": "Operating capital", "B": "Budget shortfall", "C": "Labor reimbursements", "D": "Profit margin"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "It is not uncommon in construction financing to have a budget line item for developer overhead. This is a ripe area for abuse. The purpose of developer overhead is to supply the developer with operating capital while the project is under construction. This overhead allocation should not include a profit percentage, as the developer realizes profit upon completion."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a red flag that might indicate the existence of a need recognition scheme?", "options": {"A": "The purchasing entity has large numbers of surplus items written off as scrap.", "B": "The purchasing entity has unusually high requirements for stock and inventory levels.", "C": "The purchasing entity does not have a satisfactory list of backup suppliers.", "D": "The purchasing entity's materials are being ordered at the optimal reorder point."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Generally, procurement actions begin with the procuring entity making a determination of its general needs. These initial determinations include assessments of the types and amounts of goods or services required to meet the entity’s needs. In need recognition schemes, procurement employees convince their employer that it needs excessive or unnecessary products or services. There are several red flags that might indicate a need recognition scheme. An organization with unusually high requirements for stock and inventory levels might reveal a situation in which a corrupt employee is seeking to justify unnecessary purchases from a certain supplier. Likewise, if an organization’s materials are not being ordered at the optimal reorder point, this should raise a red flag. An employee might also justify unnecessary purchases of inventory by writing off large numbers of surplus items as scrap. As these items leave the inventory, they open up spaces to justify additional purchases. Another indicator of a need recognition scheme is a need that is defined in a way that can only be met by a certain supplier or contractor. In addition, the failure to develop a satisfactory list of backup suppliers might reveal an unusually strong attachment to a primary supplier—an attachment that is explainable by the acceptance of bribes from that supplier."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a common carrier of malware?", "options": {"A": "Freeware and shareware files", "B": "Email attachments", "C": "Dual in-line memory modules", "D": "Files downloaded from the Internet"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Malware can infect computer systems from many sources. Some of the more common carriers of malware include: Unknown or unchecked application software Infected websites Banner ads Software or media that employees bring to work Files downloaded from the Internet Infected software from vendors and suppliers Uncontrolled and shared program applications Demonstration software Freeware and shareware files Email attachments"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Jeff works as a teller at a bank. One of Jeff’s friends came in as a customer and presented a cashier's check. Jeff could tell that the item was counterfeit, but the friend convinced him to cash it for a share of the proceeds. Which of the following best describes the scheme in which Jeff engaged?", "options": {"A": "Theft of physical property", "B": "False accounting entry", "C": "Unauthorized use of collateral", "D": "Unauthorized disbursement of funds to outsiders"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There are various embezzlement schemes that have been used over time against financial institutions. The scheme in this scenario involves an employee abusing his authority to approve a fraudulent (counterfeit, forged, stolen, etc.) instrument to make an unauthorized disbursement of funds to an outsider."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE with regard to factoring companies?", "options": {"A": "Factoring is illegal in all jurisdictions.", "B": "Factoring companies approach banks on a telemarketer’s behalf in order to secure credit card processing services.", "C": "Factoring groups buy credit card receipts from telemarketing operations at a discount.", "D": "Factoring companies in Asian and European countries tend to charge more for their services than factoring companies in other countries."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Telemarketing operations commonly engage factoring companies. These groups buy credit card receipts from telemarketing operations at a discount, and then use their merchant bank accounts to convert the receipts into cash. Some factors charge as much as 30% of the receipts’ gross value to launder the slips. Factoring is illegal in some jurisdictions, though perpetrators find loopholes or ways to disguise their alliances. Factoring through Asian and European merchants is becoming increasingly common. Factoring companies in these countries tend to charge a lower price for their services than some other countries—between 9 and 10% of the gross."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Glenn has just inherited a large amount of money from a deceased relative. Several weeks later, a colleague of Glenn’s suggests an investment in a security that is certain to generate returns of 20% every six months. Glenn is intrigued, but also worried that it might be a Ponzi scheme. Which of the following actions should Glenn take before investing?", "options": {"A": "Find out if the financial manager is licensed and if the security is registered", "B": "Determine if the investment’s returns have been abnormally consistent", "C": "Ensure that he can comprehend the details and strategy of the investment", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following red flags can help investigators uncover Ponzi schemes: Sounds too good to be true: If an investment sounds too good to be true, it probably is. Promises of low risk or high rewards: Promoters of Ponzi schemes typically promise implausibly high or quick returns with little risk. As all legitimate investments include some degree of risk, any guarantee that an investment will perform in a certain way is a clear signal that it might be part of a Ponzi scheme. History of consistent returns: Any firm that generates remarkably consistent returns regardless of market conditions should raise suspicions. High-pressure sales tactics: Reputable investment firms and agents do not push potential investors to act immediately, and legitimate investment opportunities are rarely that time sensitive. Pressure to reinvest: Often, fraudsters keep Ponzi schemes alive by convincing investors to reinvest their profits rather than take a payout. Complex trading strategies: Legitimate agents should be able to provide clear explanations about their investment strategies. For obvious reasons, Ponzi-scheme boosters purposefully employ complicated strategies that confound unsophisticated investors. Lack of transparency or access: Secrecy surrounding the operations of a financial company should be an immediate warning sign. Ponzi operators are often unlicensed and their supposed investments are typically unregistered. Additionally, a lack of access to regular statements or an online account should trigger alarm. Lack of segregation of duties: Investors should be wary of any financial manager who manages, administers, and retains custody of the fund in question."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Karl finds a residential property with a non-resident owner. He then forges contractual property documents showing that the owner is transferring ownership of the property completely to Karl, such as would normally happen during a property sale. The property owner is unaware that Karl has created and filed the documents. Later, Karl takes the falsified documents to a lender and borrows money against the property. Which of the following best describes Karl’s scheme?", "options": {"A": "Unauthorized draw on home equity line of credit", "B": "Fraudulent sale", "C": "Air loan", "D": "Property flipping"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraudulent sale scams are particularly harmful because they involve the fraudulent acquisition of real estate by filing a fraudulent deed or respective real estate document that makes it appear that the property legally belongs to the criminal. This scam does not happen at the origination of the loan, but rather it might occur without the homeowner’s knowledge decades after the property was originally sold. The perpetrator identifies a property—typically belonging to an estate or non-resident owner—that is owned free and clear. He then creates fictitious property transfer documents that purport to grant all rights and title on the property to the fraudster. The true owner’s signature is forged on the documents, and the scammer files them in the jurisdiction’s real property records. Once the ownership documents are filed, he applies for and executes a loan on the property (using a straw borrower). Often, the value is inflated. He absconds with 100% of the loan proceeds."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a common red flag of a defective pricing procurement fraud scheme?", "options": {"A": "A contractor uses valid cost schedules.", "B": "A contractor delivers products that appear to be counterfeit.", "C": "A contractor’s cost estimates are inconsistent with its prices.", "D": "A contractor submits a request for change orders."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Defective pricing arises when contractors intentionally use inaccurate cost or pricing data to inflate costs in negotiated contracts (i.e., the contracting method that permits negotiations between the procuring entity and prospective contractors).  A contractor can use various defective pricing schemes to increase the cost of the contract and thereby its profits, but, generally, defective pricing schemes involve inflated labor costs or inflated material costs. The following are general red flags that relate directly to defective pricing schemes: Contractor provides inadequate, inaccurate, or incomplete documentation to support cost proposals. Contractor is late in providing, delays providing, or cannot provide supporting cost or pricing data. Contractor’s cost estimates are inconsistent with its prices (i.e., discrepancy between quoted prices and actual prices). Contractor uses out-of-date pricing information (e.g., outdated cost schedules) in cost proposals. Contractor fails to update cost or pricing data when past activity showed that costs or prices have decreased. Contractor fails to disclose internal documents on discounts, rebates, and so on. Contractor fails to disclose information regarding significant cost issues that reduce proposal costs. Contractor uses vendors or subcontractors during contract performance that are different from the ones named in the proposal or contract. Materials, supplies, or components that the contractor used in production are different than those listed in the proposal or contract. Contractor delays releasing information that could result in price reductions. There is evidence of falsifications or alterations of documentation used to support cost calculations. Contractor has unrealistically high profit margins on completed work. Contractor fails to correct known system deficiencies that lead to defective pricing. Unqualified personnel developed cost or pricing data used in contractor’s estimating process."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE with regard to detecting a cash larceny scheme?", "options": {"A": "Reconciling the cash register total to the amount of cash in the drawer is helpful in detecting a cash larceny scheme", "B": "If an employee who handles cash goes on vacation, another employee should take over his duties", "C": "Someone other than the accounts receivable clerk should prepare the bank deposit", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Mandatory vacations are an excellent method of detecting cash fraud. If mandatory vacations are within the company’s policies, it is important that during the employee’s absence, that employee's normal workload be performed by another individual. The purpose of mandatory vacations is lost if the work is allowed to remain undone during the employee’s time off. In contrast to skimming schemes, the register records should NOT match up with the cash in the drawer when a cash larceny scheme has occurred. For this reason, cash larceny schemes are much easier to detect than skimming schemes—they leave an audit trail. To detect a cash larceny scheme, one recommended practice is to perform independent reconciliations of the register totals to the amount of cash in the drawer. The bank deposit should be made by someone other than the cashier or the accounts receivable clerk. A person independent of the cash receipts and accounts receivable functions should compare entries to the cash receipts journal with: Authenticated bank deposit slips The deposit per the bank statements"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following is considered a red flag of check tampering?", "options": {"A": "Large gaps in the check register", "B": "Payee addresses that match employee addresses", "C": "Non-payroll checks payable to employees", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following are red flags of check tampering: Missing checks or large gaps in the check register might indicate lax control over the physical safekeeping of checks. Stop payments should be issued for all missing checks. Checks payable to employees, with the exception of regular payroll checks, should be closely scrutinized. Such an examination might indicate other schemes, such as conflicts of interest, fictitious vendors, or duplicate expense reimbursements. Altered endorsements or dual endorsements of returned checks might indicate possible tampering. Returned checks with obviously forged or questionable signature endorsements should be verified with the original payee. Altered payees on returned checks should be verified with the intended payee. Duplicate or counterfeit checks indicate fraud. These checks might be traceable to the depositor through bank check coding. An examination of all cash advances might reveal that not all advances are properly documented and, therefore, inappropriate payments have been made to employees. A questionable payee or payee address on a check should trigger review of the corresponding check and support documentation. Checks payable to cash are typically considered suspicious and merit further investigation."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "A confidence scheme designed to part victims from their money by falsely promising the future delivery of a product or service in exchange for an upfront payment is called a(n):", "options": {"A": "Scavenger scheme", "B": "Bait and switch", "C": "Home-based business scheme", "D": "Advance-fee swindle"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Advance-fee swindles are structured to obtain an illegal gain by falsely promising the delivery of a product or service. In some schemes, the product is marketed to a large number of customers, and then the operation is shut down prior to the delivery stage. Common scenarios used to commit advance-fee scams include the following: A home improvement contractor requires pre-payment for materials. Notice of a supposed inheritance from an unknown relative is received. Various exorbitant fees are required prior to securing financial assistance or advice."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "What happens when an employee records a fictitious refund of goods at the employee's cash register?", "options": {"A": "Inventory is returned to the store", "B": "The victim company's inventory is overstated", "C": "The register total is out of balance with the register log", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A refund shows a disbursement of money from the register as the customer gets his money back. In a fictitious refund scheme, an employee processes a transaction as if a customer were returning merchandise, even though no actual return takes place. Two things result from this fraudulent transaction. First, the employee takes cash from the register in the amount of the false return. Since the register log shows that a merchandise return has been made, it appears that the disbursement is legitimate. The second thing that happens in a fictitious refund scheme is that a debit is made to the inventory system showing that the merchandise has been returned. Since the transaction is fictitious, no merchandise is actually returned. The result is that the company’s inventory is overstated."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following types of accounts are decreased by debits?", "options": {"A": "Owners’ equity", "B": "Liabilities", "C": "Revenue", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Entries to the left side of an account are referred to as debits, and entries to the right side of an account are referred to as credits. Debits increase asset and expense accounts, whereas credits decrease these accounts. On the other side of the equation, credits increase liabilities, revenue, and owners’ equity accounts. Conversely, debits decrease liabilities, revenues, and owners’ equity."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "Sales and cost of goods sold almost always move together, unless there have been changes in purchase prices, quantities purchased, or quality of products being purchased.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Inventory fraud might be detected by using an analytical review because certain trends become immediately clear. For example, sales and cost of goods sold should move together since they are directly related. However, if the cost of goods sold increases by a disproportionate amount relative to sales, and no changes occur in the purchase prices, quantities purchased, or quality of products purchased, the cause of the disproportionate increase in cost of goods sold might be one of three things: (1) ending inventory has been depleted by theft, (2) someone has been embezzling money through a false billing scheme, or (3) someone has been skimming sales revenue."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Anna works as a cashier in an antiques store. Since the merchandise lacks barcodes, she has to enter the prices manually. One customer purchased a piece of furniture that cost $250 and paid in cash. Anna recorded the sale at $200 and kept the $50 bill. What type of fraud did Anna commit?", "options": {"A": "A cash larceny scheme", "B": "Lapping of receivables", "C": "An unrecorded sales (skimming) scheme", "D": "An understated sales (skimming) scheme"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Understated sales schemes are commonly undertaken by employees who work at the cash register. In a typical scheme, an employee enters a sales total that is lower than the amount actually paid by the customer. The employee skims the difference between the actual purchase price of the item and the sales figure recorded on the register. In this case, the item was sold for $250, but Anna rang up the sale of a $200 item and skimmed the excess $50. Rather than reduce the price of an item, an employee might record the sale of fewer items. If 100 units are sold, for instance, an employee might only record the sale of 50 units and skim the excess receipts."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "A draw request on a construction loan should be accompanied by all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Lien releases from subcontractors", "B": "Change orders, if applicable", "C": "Expenses from similar contracts", "D": "Inspection reports"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A draw request is the documentation substantiating that a developer has incurred the appropriate construction expenses and is now seeking reimbursement or direct payment. Generally, draw requests on construction loans are made on a periodic schedule (e.g., once a month) and are verified by a quantity surveyor (QS) or other authorized entity as agreed to by the financial institution. The request should be accompanied by the following documents: Paid invoices for raw materials Lien releases from each subcontractor Inspection reports Canceled checks from previous draw requests Bank reconciliation for construction draw account for previous month Loan balancing form demonstrating that the loan remains in balance Change orders, if applicable Wiring instructions, if applicable Proof of developer contribution, if applicable"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Revenue should not be recognized for work that is to be performed in subsequent accounting periods, even though the work might currently be under contract.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In general, revenue is recognized or recorded when it becomes realized or realizable and earned. According to the revenue recognition principle, revenue should not be recognized for work that is to be performed in subsequent accounting periods, even though the work might currently be under contract. In general, revenue should be recognized in the period in which the work is performed."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Loyalty fraud typically results from fraudsters gaining access to a rewards account by obtaining login credentials through phishing or hacking.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Loyalty fraud typically results from fraudsters gaining access to a rewards account by obtaining login credentials through phishing or hacking."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Which of the following best illustrates the use of technical surveillance for purposes of corporate espionage?", "options": {"A": "A spy hacks into a target computer and monitors an employee’s communications.", "B": "A spy uses a phony employee badge to enter an office and take a sensitive document.", "C": "A spy creates a deceptive website to trick employees into entering confidential information.", "D": "A spy impersonates a help desk representative to obtain an employee's network password."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Technical surveillance is the practice of covertly acquiring audio, visual, or other types of data from targets through the use of technical devices, procedures, and techniques. When corporate spies resort to the use of technical surveillance, it is usually to gather nondocumentary evidence or information that cannot be found through open sources. Corporate spies might employ various forms of technological surveillance, such as aerial photography, bugging and wiretapping, video surveillance, photographic cameras, mobile phones, monitoring computer emanations, and computer system penetrations."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "An identity thief steals a victim’s credit card and uses it to buy an expensive TV. This scheme is an example of which of the following?", "options": {"A": "An account takeover", "B": "Business identity theft", "C": "Criminal identity theft", "D": "True name fraud"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Financial identity theft occurs when a fraudster uses an individual’s personal information for fraudulent financial transactions. Examples of financial identity theft include: Using an individual’s stolen credit card or credit card number to purchase goods (account takeover) Impersonating an individual to gain access to the individual’s bank account (account takeover) Using an individual’s personal information to open a new credit card account (true name fraud) Business identity theft occurs when a fraudster impersonates a business to commit financial fraud. In addition to impersonating an existing business, fraudsters can use government business filings to reinstate a closed or dissolved business. They can also trick third parties by creating a new business with a name similar to an existing business. Criminal identity theft occurs when fraudsters falsely identify themselves as other people to law enforcement while being arrested or investigated for a crime. The crime is then incorrectly attributed to the other person instead of the fraudster."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following is one of the four major categories of check tampering schemes?", "options": {"A": "Forged endorsement schemes", "B": "Forged maker schemes", "C": "Altered payee schemes", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The four major categories of check tampering schemes include: Forged maker schemes Forged endorsements Altered payees Authorized maker schemes"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a way that dishonest contractors collude to circumvent the competitive bidding process?", "options": {"A": "Alternate business among themselves on a rotating basis", "B": "Refrain from submitting bids on certain contracts", "C": "Agree to stay out of each other’s designated markets", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Schemes involving collusion among contractors seek to circumvent the competitive bidding process. In these schemes, competitors in the same market collude to defeat competition or to inflate the prices of goods and services artificially. The following schemes are common forms of collusion between competitors: Bid rotation: Bid rotation, also known as bid pooling, occurs when two or more contractors conspire to alternate the business among themselves on a rotating basis. Bid suppression: Bid suppression occurs when two or more contractors enter into an illegal agreement whereby at least one of the conspirators refrains from bidding or withdraws a previously submitted bid. Market division: Market division (or market allocation) schemes involve agreements among competitors to divide and allocate markets and to refrain from competing in each other’s designated portion of the market."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "To ensure separation of duties within the information technology department and between information systems and business unit personnel, computer operators should be responsible for performing computer programming.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Separation of duties is a key element in a well-designed internal control system, and it is fundamental to data security. There are various options for achieving separation of duties in information security, and the options vary depending on department responsibilities. For example, some of the best practices for ensuring separation of duties within the information technology department and between information systems and business unit personnel are as follows: Programmers should not have unsupervised access to production programs or have access to production data sets (data files). Information systems personnel’s access to production data should be limited. Application system users should only be granted access to those functions and data required for their job duties. Program developers should be separated from program testers. System users should not have direct access to program source code. Computer operators should not perform computer programming. Development staff should not have access to production data. Development staff should not access system-level technology or database management systems. End users should not have access to production data outside the scope of their normal job duties. End users or system operators should not have direct access to program source code. Programmers should not be server administrators or database administrators. IT departments should be separated from information user departments. Functions involving the creation, installation, and administration of software programs should be assigned to different individuals. Managers at all levels should review existing and planned processes and systems to ensure proper separation of duties. Employees’ access to documents should be limited to those that correspond with their related job tasks."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following refers to the type of network security systems that are designed to supplement firewalls and other forms of network security by detecting malicious activity coming across the network or on a host?", "options": {"A": "Network access controls", "B": "Intrusion detection systems", "C": "Network address prevention systems", "D": "Intrusion admission systems"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "An intrusion detection system (IDS) is a device or software application that monitors an organization’s inbound and outbound network activity and identifies any suspicious patterns of activity that might indicate a network or system attack or security policy violations. These systems are designed to supplement firewalls and other forms of network security by detecting malicious activity coming across the monitored entity’s network or system activities. They act much like a motion sensor would by detecting individuals who have bypassed perimeter security."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "To help promote employee awareness of sensitive information, company data should be classified into different security levels based on value and sensitivity.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "According to the CERT Insider Threat Center, organizations should implement a data classification policy that establishes what protections must be afforded to data of different value and sensitivity levels. Data classification allows organizations to follow a structured approach for establishing appropriate controls for different data categories. Moreover, establishing a data classification policy will help employee awareness. In short, classifying an organization’s data involves: (1) organizing the entity’s data into different security levels based on the data’s value and sensitivity and (2) assigning each level of classification different rules for viewing, editing, and sharing the data."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Calendars and schedules displayed at an employee’s workstation can inadvertently provide a company’s competitors with valuable proprietary information.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Organizations must take reasonable measures to protect manual file systems, which are composed of all human-readable files and documents. These include items like contact lists, schedules, and calendars located at employees’ workstations. To attack a manual file system, an information thief might pilfer trash, act as a cleaning crew member, or commit theft or burglary."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Which of the following is a common method used by fraudsters to physically infiltrate and spy on organizations?", "options": {"A": "Fabricate or steal an employee badge", "B": "Pose as a contractor", "C": "Secure a position as an employee", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Corporate spies might use physical infiltration techniques to obtain sensitive information. Physical infiltration is the process whereby an individual enters a target organization to spy on the organization’s employees. One common infiltration technique is to secure a position, or pose, as an employee or contract laborer of the target organization. For example, a spy might obtain work as a security officer or a member of the janitorial crew for the target organization. Another common physical infiltration technique is to steal or fabricate employee badges belonging to the target organization."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "question": "__________ is the term used for including additional coverages in an insurance policy without the insured's knowledge.", "options": {"A": "Churning", "B": "Sliding", "C": "Twisting", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Sliding is the term used for including additional coverage in an insurance policy without the insured's knowledge. The extra charges are hidden in the total premium. Since the insured is unaware of the coverage, few claims are ever filed. For example, motor club memberships, accidental death, and travel accident coverage can usually be added to the policy without the insured's knowledge."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "question": "Roxanne works in the accounting department of a bank but is having difficulty paying her personal expenses. She decides to debit the bank's general ledger and credit her own account. Which of the following best describes Roxanne’s scheme?", "options": {"A": "False accounting entry", "B": "Sham loan", "C": "Daisy chain", "D": "Unrecorded cash payment"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are various embezzlement schemes that have been used over time against financial institutions. In false accounting entries schemes, employees debit the general ledger to credit their own accounts or to cover up a theft from a customer account."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "Advance-fee swindles, debt consolidation schemes, and diploma mills are all examples of consumer fraud schemes.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Consumer fraud schemes involve a range of fraudulent conduct, usually committed by professional scammers, against unsuspecting victims. Scammers are skilled fraudsters who develop strategies, select targets, and use an appropriate method of delivery to lure their victims. Scammers usually act alone, but they might group together for a particularly complex endeavor. Some examples of consumer fraud schemes include advance-fee swindles, debt consolidation schemes, and diploma mills."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Which of the following situations is an example of DRG creep?", "options": {"A": "A hospital regularly sends duplicate reimbursement claims to a health care program for a particular treatment.", "B": "A medical provider sells numerous patient information files to third parties who use them to make false medical claims.", "C": "A medical provider habitually creates false diagnoses for patients and bills for services never performed.", "D": "A hospital has a pattern of incorrectly coding and documenting minor cuts and scratches as major lacerations."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Diagnostic-related groupings (DRG) is a reimbursement methodology for the payment of institutional services. This method or similar models have become more popular in various countries for the purposes of determining costs and reimbursing institutional providers. DRG categorizes patients who are medically related with respect to various types of information, such as primary and secondary diagnosis, age, gender, weight, length of stay, and complications. Reimbursements are determined by the DRG. DRG creep occurs when medical staff members manipulate diagnostic and procedural codes to increase reimbursement amounts or other forms of funding. When it becomes a pattern and intent is established, it becomes fraud. For example, a hospital might repeatedly and incorrectly code angina (pain or discomfort in the chest due to some obstruction of the arteries) as a myocardial infarction (a more serious event, commonly known as a heart attack), and thus be reimbursed at a higher level."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "At the end of each fiscal year, the accounts reflected on the income statement are reduced to a zero balance.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The accounts reflected on the income statement are temporary; at the end of each fiscal year, they are reduced to a zero balance (closed), with the resulting net income (or loss) added to (or subtracted from) retained earnings on the balance sheet."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Bruce, a manager for a retail store, suspects his cashiers of skimming sales. Bruce will be able to detect this kind of scheme by comparing their register totals to the amount of money in their cash drawers.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When an employee skims money by making off-book sales of merchandise, it is impossible to detect theft by comparing the register to the cash drawer because the sale was not recorded on the register."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "Roger, a CFE, is an auditor for the government’s Office of Audit and Evaluation. While conducting a routine audit of ten construction contracts from the Public Works Department, Roger notices some unusual characteristics in the contracts’ bidding documents. The contracts were all awarded to the same contractor, and the specifications in all ten contracts had unreasonably narrow specifications for the types of goods being procured. Which of the following types of procurement fraud schemes is most likely at issue here?", "options": {"A": "A procurement employee has intentionally included unallowable costs in the projects’ contracts and budgets.", "B": "A procurement employee broke up a large project into several small projects that fall below the mandatory bidding level.", "C": "A procurement employee has drafted bid specifications in a way that gives an unfair advantage to a certain contractor.", "D": "A procurement employee convinced his employer that it needs excessive or unnecessary products or services."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Bid tailoring schemes (also known as specifications schemes) occur during the presolicitation phase. In these schemes, an employee with procurement responsibilities, often in collusion with a contractor, drafts bid specifications in a way that gives an unfair advantage to a certain contractor. Some common red flags of bid tailoring include: Weak controls over the bidding process Only one or a few bidders respond to bid requests Contract is not rebid even though fewer than the minimum number of bids are received Similarity between specifications and the winning contractor’s product or services Bid specifications and statements of work are tailored to fit the products or capabilities of a single contractor Unusual or unreasonably narrow or broad specifications for the type of goods or services being procured Requests for bid submissions do not provide clear bid submission information (e.g., no clear time, place, or manner of submitting bids) Unexplained changes in contract specifications from previous proposals or similar items High number of competitive awards to one supplier Socialization or personal contacts among contracting personnel and bidders Specifications developed by or in consultation with a contractor who is permitted to compete in the procurement High number of change orders for one supplier"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "In double-entry accounting, every transaction in the accounting records will have both a debit and a credit side, and these sides will always be equal.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Entries to the left side of an account are debits, and entries to the right side of an account are credits. Debits increase asset and expense accounts, while credits decrease them. Conversely, credits increase liability, owners’ equity, and revenue accounts; debits decrease them. Every transaction recorded in the accounting records will have both a debit and a credit, thus the term double-entry accounting. The debit side of an entry will always equal the credit side so that the accounting equation remains in balance."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "Both falsely increasing the perpetual inventory balance and failing to reconcile inventory records are ways a fraudster might conceal inventory shrinkage.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Falsely increasing the perpetual inventory record would only worsen the shrinkage problem. Instead, a fraudster seeking to conceal shrinkage would falsely decrease the perpetual inventory record to match the lower physical inventory count. In addition, failing to reconcile inventory records would likely cause more suspicion to arise. One of the simplest methods for concealing shrinkage is to change the perpetual inventory record so that it matches the physical inventory count. This is also known as a forced reconciliation of the account. The perpetrator simply changes the numbers in the perpetual inventory to make them match the amount of inventory on hand. For example, the employee might credit (decrease) the perpetual inventory and debit (increase) the cost of sales account to lower the perpetual inventory numbers so that they match the actual inventory count. Instead of using correct entries to adjust the perpetual inventory, some employees simply delete or cover up the correct totals and enter new numbers."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "Second-hand computers, media drives, and mobile phones are safe from identity thieves if the former owner has manually deleted all personal information from such devices.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraudsters commonly obtain personal and business information from improperly discarded computers, media drives, copiers, printers, mobile phones, and other devices. Like computers, some copiers and printers have internal hard drives that store sensitive data. Because it is possible to recover deleted data, fraudsters might search for sensitive information on second-hand devices they purchase online or obtain from another source. Data can be permanently erased from such devices with specialized software."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "___________________ is the unaccounted-for reduction in a company's inventory that results from error or theft.", "options": {"A": "Shrinkage", "B": "Defalcation", "C": "Depreciation", "D": "Shortness"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Inventory shrinkage is the unaccounted-for reduction in the company’s inventory that results from error or theft. For instance, assume a computer retailer has 1,000 computers in stock. After work one day, an employee loads ten computers into a truck and takes them home. Now the company only has 990 computers, but since there is no record that the employee took ten computers, the inventory records still show 1,000 units on hand. The company has experienced inventory shrinkage in the amount of ten computers."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Julia, a fraud examiner, is performing tests to look for potential asset misappropriation schemes at her company. One of her routine tests is to compare the payroll records to the human resources files. What type of fraud scheme is she most likely looking for when performing this test?", "options": {"A": "A ghost employee scheme", "B": "A falsified hours and wages scheme", "C": "A fraudulent commissions scheme", "D": "A check tampering scheme"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Comparing personnel records maintained by the human resources department to payroll data can be useful in detecting ghost employee schemes. The term ghost employee refers to someone on the payroll who does not actually work for the victim company. Through the falsification of personnel or payroll records, a fraudster causes paychecks to be generated to a non-employee, or ghost. For example, comparing employee names, addresses, government identification numbers, and bank account numbers can determine if there are any unexpected duplicates or discrepancies that would indicate a ghost on the payroll."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "To detect provider fraud, a fraud examiner should be alert for which of the following red flags?\nI.   Pressure for rapid processing of claims\nII.  Frequent telephone inquiries on claim status\nIII. No supporting documentation for charges (e.g., lab results)\nIV.  Patient's address on the claim form is the same as the provider's", "options": {"A": "I, II, III, and IV", "B": "I and II only", "C": "II and III only", "D": "III and IV only"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": ""}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Jason, an employee at Go Marketing, has just informed his supervisor that he intends to leave the company and go to work for a competitor. Upon accepting his resignation, Jason’s boss reminds him of a document that he signed several years prior in which Jason agreed not to divulge confidential or proprietary company information. What is the name of the document that Jason signed?", "options": {"A": "Employee testimonial statement", "B": "Employee awareness statement", "C": "Noncompetition agreement", "D": "Nondisclosure agreement"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Generally, a nondisclosure agreement is a written agreement providing that signatories must keep all trade secrets and proprietary information learned during their employment confidential. Nondisclosure agreements are one of the least expensive and most efficient methods for controlling the loss of proprietary information. A noncompetition agreement is an agreement whereby an employee agrees not to work for competing companies within a certain period of time after leaving his current employer."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "The most common giveaway scheme, in which a postcard arrives in the mail telling the recipient he has already won a prize such as a luxurious vacation or cash, is known as:", "options": {"A": "The \"Fly and Buy\"", "B": "The \"Bait and Switch\"", "C": "The \"1-in-5\"", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The most common giveaway scheme is known as the “1-in-5.” In this scheme, a consumer receives a letter or postcard in the mail informing that individual that he has already won a prize. The prizes usually include luxurious vacations, new cars, or cash. Unfortunately, the odds of winning any of the prizes are extremely low. Victims might receive items of minimal or no value or coupons redeemable only for the company’s substandard merchandise."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Examples of expense reimbursement schemes include which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Listing dinner with a friend as a business development expense", "B": "Listing personal travel as business travel", "C": "Requesting reimbursement for an expense that was never incurred", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Employees can manipulate an organization’s expense reimbursement procedures to generate fraudulent disbursements. The four most common types of expense reimbursement schemes are mischaracterized expenses, overstated expenses, fictitious expenses, and multiple reimbursements."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "The debt-to-equity ratio is computed by dividing current liabilities by total equity.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The debt-to-equity ratio is computed by dividing total liabilities by total equity. This financial leverage ratio is one that is heavily considered by lending institutions. It provides a clear picture of the comparison between the long-term and short-term debt of the company and the owner's financial injection plus earnings to date. Debt-to-equity requirements are often included as borrowing covenants in corporate lending agreements."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "The statement of cash flows includes the following categories: cash flows from strategic activities, cash flows from operating activities, cash flows from investing activities, and cash flows from financing activities.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The statement of cash flows reports a company’s sources and uses of cash during the accounting period. This statement is often used by potential investors and other interested parties in tandem with the income statement to determine a company's true financial performance during the period being reported. The statement of cash flows is broken down into three sections: Cash flows from operating activities Cash flows from investing activities Cash flows from financing activities"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following are considered red flags of insider computer fraud?\nI.   Access privileges limited to those required to perform assigned tasks.\nII.  Access logs are not reviewed.\nIII. Production programs are run during normal business hours.\nIV.  Exception reports are not reviewed and resolved.", "options": {"A": "I and III only", "B": "III and IV only", "C": "I, II, III, and IV", "D": "II and IV only"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": ""}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Cryptocurrencies are subject to significant monitoring and government regulation.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Cryptocurrencies have been relatively anonymous and have not been subject to significant monitoring or regulation by governments or financial institutions thus far, although many countries are developing controls and regulations that could affect their classification as assets, how they are traded and purchased, or how they can be spent. For these reasons, they are attractive vehicles for various fraud schemes."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Loyalty accounts are attractive targets for fraudsters for which of the following reasons?", "options": {"A": "Loyalty accounts often lack fraud prevention mechanisms", "B": "Thieves often think of loyalty points in terms of cash", "C": "Consumers tend to monitor loyalty accounts infrequently", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Thieves often think of loyalty points in terms of cash and, as such, these programs are increasingly subject to fraud. Loyalty accounts are also attractive fraud targets because they are often less secure than accounts with financial institutions, commonly lacking fraud prevention mechanisms such as multifactor identification or account activity monitoring. And while consumers regularly check accounts held with financial institutions, rewards accounts tend to be monitored much less frequently."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Liam is the manager of a small bank that has recently experienced an increase in the amount of fraud related to electronic funds transfers (EFT). Which of the following methods can Liam implement to reduce his bank’s exposure to EFT fraud?", "options": {"A": "Ensure that PINs are mailed separately from other associated account information", "B": "Send a “welcome” letter to new customers to determine if the address submitted on the account application is valid", "C": "Separate the duties of bank employees so that responsibilities for the issuance of access devices are separate from the issuance of PINs", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following are safeguards that banks can perform to reduce the risk that they or their customers become victimized by unauthorized electronic funds transfers: Confirm phone and mailing addresses on the application to ensure that they are consistent with information about the applicant that is available from other sources and, with respect to existing customers, consistent with current records about these customers. This might involve obtaining credit reports about the applicant or obtaining copies of utility bills that show the applicant’s address. Make sure that the area or city code in the applicant’s telephone number matches the geographical area for the applicant’s address. Send a “welcome” letter to the address on the application with the bank’s return address so that the letter is returned if the applicant does not live there. Verify by telephone or additional mailings any change of address requests in the same way that new account applications are verified. If a customer reports the loss or theft of an access device, cancel the existing card, PIN, or other form of access and issue a new one. If a customer reports that a person previously authorized to use an access device no longer has that authority, cancel all cards, PINs, or other access devices and issue new ones to the customer. Always mail PINs separately from other information, such as usernames, with which they are associated. Separate the responsibility of bank employees who have custody of information relating to access devices from those who have responsibility for issuance, verification, or reissuance of PINs. Ensure that any communication concerning usernames or passwords is sent in a secure encrypted format. Require customers who register for EBPP or P2P systems to provide information indicating that they are authorized to use the bank account or credit card from which payments will be made. Employ multifactor authentication to verify transfers via EBPP or P2P systems."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Horizontal analysis is a technique for analyzing the relationships among the items on an income statement, balance sheet, or statement of cash flows by expressing line items as percentages of a specific base item.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Horizontal analysis is a technique for analyzing the percentage change in individual income statement or balance sheet items from one year to the next. The first period in the analysis is considered the base period, and the changes in the subsequent period are computed as a percentage of the base period. Vertical analysis is the expression of the relationship or percentage of component items to a specific base item on the income statement or balance sheet. Ratio analysis is a means of measuring the relationship between any two different financial statement amounts. The relationship and comparison are the keys to any of these types of financial analyses."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "A fraud scheme in which an accountant fails to write down obsolete inventory to its current fair market value has what effect on the company’s current ratio?", "options": {"A": "The current ratio will be artificially deflated.", "B": "It is impossible to determine.", "C": "The current ratio will be artificially inflated.", "D": "The current ratio will not be affected."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Many schemes are used to inflate current assets at the expense of long-term assets. In the case of such schemes, the net effect is seen in the current ratio, which divides current assets by current liabilities to evaluate a company’s ability to satisfy its short-term obligations. By misclassifying long-term assets as short-term, the current ratio will appear artificially stronger. This type of misclassification can be of critical concern to lending institutions that often require certain financial ratio minimums to be maintained. This is of particular consequence when the loan covenants are on unsecured or under-secured lines of credit and other short-term borrowings. Sometimes these misclassifications are referred to as window dressing."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Which of the following types of accounting changes must be disclosed in an organization's financial statements?\nI.   Changes in estimates\nII.  Changes in accounting principles\nIII. Changes in reporting entities", "options": {"A": "II and III only", "B": "I and II only", "C": "I and III only", "D": "I, II, and III"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In general, three types of accounting changes must be disclosed to avoid misleading the user of financial statements: changes in accounting principles, estimates, and reporting entities. Although the required treatment for these accounting changes varies for each type and across jurisdictions, they are all susceptible to manipulation. For example, fraudsters might fail to properly retroactively restate financial statements for a change in accounting principle if the change causes the company’s financial statements to appear weaker. Likewise, they might fail to disclose significant changes in estimates such as the useful lives and estimated salvage values of depreciable assets or the estimates underlying the determination of warranty or other liabilities. They might even secretly change the reporting entity by adding entities owned privately by management or by excluding certain company-owned units to improve reported results."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "What effect would the improper recording of an expenditure as a capitalized asset rather than as an expense have on the financial statements?", "options": {"A": "Expenses would be overstated, giving the appearance of poor financial performance", "B": "Assets would be falsely overstated, giving the appearance of a stronger company", "C": "Net income would be falsely understated, lowering the company’s tax liability", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Improperly capitalizing expenses is one way to increase income and assets and make the entity's financial position appear stronger. If ineligible expenditures are capitalized as assets and not expensed during the current period, income will be overstated. As the assets are depreciated, income in following periods will be understated."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Identity Theft", "question": "To help prevent identity theft, businesses should strive to limit the personal information they collect from customers.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The following are some of the steps businesses can take to protect personal information and prevent identity theft: Limit the personal information collected from customers. For example, do not collect customers’ government identification numbers unless there is a legal requirement to do so. Restrict employees’ access to the personal information of customers and coworkers. Use network-security tools to monitor who accesses personal information. Do not retain personal information for longer than necessary. Adopt an information-handling policy that governs how personal information is stored, protected, and disposed of. Strictly enforce the policy, and discipline employees who violate it. Conduct regular employee training regarding the company’s information-handling policy and best practices for preventing identity theft. Ensure the security of buildings by using locks, access codes, and other security features. Keep physical documents containing personal information in locked rooms or locked file cabinets. Secure all computer networks and electronic information. Use encryption to protect all personal information stored by the company or sent to third parties. Encryption should also be used to protect information sent over the company’s wireless network. Restrict the use of laptops to those employees who need them to do their jobs. Require employees to use complex passwords or passphrases. Where permitted by law, perform background checks on prospective employees. Thoroughly investigate contractors and vendors before hiring them. Do not use government identification numbers as employee identification numbers or print them on paychecks. Perform regular audits of information-handling practices, network security, and other internal controls. Create a data breach response plan."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "If an employee intercepts a company check intended for a third party and converts that check for his own benefit, he has committed:", "options": {"A": "Skimming", "B": "Check tampering", "C": "Economic extortion", "D": "Billing fraud"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Check tampering is a type of fraudulent disbursement scheme in which an employee either (1) prepares a fraudulent check for his own benefit or (2) intercepts a check intended for a third party and converts the check for his own benefit."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Rock phishing is a type of phishing scheme that uses text messages or other short message systems to dupe an individual or business into providing sensitive data by falsely claiming to be from an actual business, bank, ISP, or other entity.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "SMiShing is a hybrid of phishing and short message service (text messaging). These schemes use text messages or other short message systems to conduct phishing activities. That is, in SMiShing schemes, the attacker uses text messages or other short message systems to dupe an individual or business into providing sensitive data by falsely claiming to be from an actual business, bank, ISP, or other entity with which the target does business. Rock phishers use botnets to send massive amounts of phishing emails to huge volumes of Internet users. The emails contain a message from a financial institution, enticing users to click on a fraudulent URL. There is some indication that rock phishers cycle through multiple email lists and attempt to reach the Internet users most likely to use the brands that they are targeting."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "All of the following are payroll scheme types EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Ghost employees", "B": "Commission schemes", "C": "Falsified hours and salary", "D": "Stolen paychecks"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In general, payroll schemes fall into one of the following categories: Ghost employees Falsified hours and salary Commission schemes If an employee stole paychecks, this would fall under check tampering, not payroll fraud. The reason is that the heart of the scheme is stealing the check, not generating false payroll disbursements."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Joe formed a company called Glenn Corp. He opened a bank account in Glenn Corp.’s name and used his home computer to create fraudulent invoices from Glenn Corp. for \"consulting services.\" However, Glenn Corp. is a fictitious entity that was created solely to commit fraud, and no services have been rendered. Joe mailed these invoices to his employer, Paisley Company. Paisley Company promptly submitted payment to Glenn Corp., not realizing that the company was fake, and Joe deposited the money. What type of billing scheme did Joe commit?", "options": {"A": "A shell company scheme", "B": "A pass-through scheme", "C": "A pay and return scheme", "D": "A cash larceny scheme"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Shell companies, though sometimes created for legitimate purposes, are often fictitious entities created for the sole purpose of committing fraud. They might be nothing more than a fabricated name and address that an employee uses to collect disbursements from false billings. However, since the checks received are made out in the name of the shell company, the perpetrator normally also sets up a bank account in the shell company’s name. Once a shell company has been formed and a bank account has been opened, the corrupt employee is in a position to begin billing his employer by mailing forged invoices for fictitious goods or services."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following is recommended to prevent fraud in electronic payments?", "options": {"A": "Positive pay for ACH transactions", "B": "Having separate bank accounts for paper checks and electronic payments", "C": "Implementing ACH blocks and filters", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Most large banks offer multiple security services that can help business account holders mitigate fraud through early detection and prevention of fraudulent electronic payments. For example, ACH blocks allow account holders to notify their banks that ACH debits should not be allowed on specific accounts. ACH filters enable account holders to provide their banks with a list of defined criteria against which banks can filter ACH debits and reject any unauthorized transactions. Positive pay for ACH is another security feature offered by banks to their account holders. With positive pay, banks match the details of ACH payments with those on a list of legitimate and expected payments provided by the account holder. Only authorized electronic transactions are allowed to be withdrawn from the account; exceptions are reported to the customer for review. Companies should consider segregating their bank accounts to maintain better control over them—for example, separate accounts can be used for paper and electronic transactions. Having separate bank accounts will facilitate the audit process and help the fraud examiner identify any electronic payments that seem suspicious."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "James runs an electronics store. One of the main challenges in his business is keeping up with technological advances. Because of this, his auditors want to ensure inventory is not fraudulently overstated on the store's balance sheet. Which of the following actions should the auditors take to ensure inventory is not overstated?", "options": {"A": "Ensure that James has written off obsolete inventory", "B": "Ensure that inventory is recorded at the lower of cost or net realizable value", "C": "View the inventory and conduct a physical count", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Under many countries’ accounting standards, including U.S. GAAP and IFRS, inventory must be recorded at the lower of cost or net realizable value. This means that inventory must be valued at its acquisition cost, except when the cost is determined to be higher than the net realizable value, in which case it should be written down to its net realizable value or written off altogether if it has no value. Failing to write down or write off inventory results in overstated assets and the mismatching of cost of goods sold with revenues. Other methods by which inventory can be improperly stated include manipulation of the physical inventory count, inflation of the unit costs used to price out inventory, and failure to adjust inventory for the costs of goods sold. Fictitious inventory schemes usually involve the creation of fake documents, such as inventory count sheets and receiving reports. In some instances, friendly co-conspirators claim to be holding inventory for companies in question. Other times, companies falsely report large values of inventory in transit, knowing that it would be nearly impossible for the auditors to observe. When possible, fraud examiners should perform a physical inventory count, checking to make sure the inventory exists as described in the records. There have been cases of fraudsters assembling pallets of inventory with hollow centers, placing bricks in sealed boxes instead of high-value products, and shuttling inventory overnight between locations."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Which of the following appears on the balance sheet?", "options": {"A": "Cost of goods sold", "B": "Current assets", "C": "Revenues", "D": "Expenses"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The balance sheet, or statement of financial position, is an expansion of the accounting equation, Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity. That is, it lists a company’s assets on one side and its liabilities and owners’ equity on the other side. Assets are classified as either current or noncurrent. Current assets consist of cash or other liquid assets that are expected to be converted to cash, sold, or used up, usually within a year or less. Current assets listed on the balance sheet include cash, accounts receivable, inventory, supplies, and prepaid expenses. Revenues, expenses, and cost of goods sold are all items that appear on a company’s income statement."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "question": "The restitution against loss to a third party when the insured fails to fulfill a specific undertaking for the third party's benefit is referred to as:", "options": {"A": "Disability insurance", "B": "An indemnity bond", "C": "Fidelity insurance", "D": "Casualty insurance"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "An indemnity bond reimburses its holder for any loss to third-party beneficiaries when the insured fails to fulfill a specific undertaking for the third party's benefit. Property insurance indemnifies against pecuniary loss to the insured's property for specific losses; for example, from fire, theft, or auto collision. Casualty insurance indemnifies against legal liability to others for injury or damage to persons, property, or other defined legal interests because of specified risks or conduct. Fidelity insurance indemnifies against economic loss to the insured because of employee dishonesty. Disability insurance indemnifies against income loss under defined circumstances."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "The emerging environment of everyday objects that use embedded sensors to collect and transmit data through the Internet is best known as:", "options": {"A": "The Emerging Technology Domain", "B": "The Deep Web", "C": "The Smart Technology Network", "D": "The Internet of Things"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The Internet of Things (IOT) is the emerging environment of everyday objects that use embedded sensors to collect and transmit data through the Internet. Examples of useful IOT applications include wearable fitness devices, home-automation products, and smart parking systems. Unfortunately, the development of IOT technology tends to focus on innovative design rather than privacy or security. IOT devices commonly connect to networks using inadequate security and can be impractical to update when vulnerabilities are detected. This is a concern because as the number of potentially vulnerable smart products increases so, too, do the opportunities for fraudsters seeking alternate ways into otherwise secure networks. Furthermore, IOT devices often record huge volumes of sensitive data and personal information that must be protected from misuse and cybercriminals."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "A pyramid scheme is designed to pay off its earliest investors.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Pyramid schemes are designed to pay off their earliest investors but not later investors. Probability studies have shown that 93 to 95% of the participants in a pyramid scheme (all but those who join at the earliest stage) will lose most of their money. Half can expect to lose all the money they invest."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "question": "Elizabeth, a grocery store cashier, slips on a wet floor and falls while at work. She is unharmed, but she pretends to suffer an injury from the fall. She files a claim against the store's workers' compensation insurance policy, and she collects payments from the insurance carrier. She also misses several weeks of work, even though she is fully capable of working. Under which category of workers’ compensation schemes does Elizabeth’s scheme fall?", "options": {"A": "Agent fraud", "B": "Claimant fraud", "C": "Organized fraud", "D": "Premium fraud"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Elizabeth's scheme is classified as claimant fraud. Claimant fraud involves misrepresenting the circumstances of any injury or fabricating that an injury occurred. Such schemes are perpetrated by employees who stage accidents or exaggerate minor injuries, sometimes in collusion with unethical doctors, to fraudulently receive compensation benefits. Workers' compensation is essentially an employee benefit, entitling those persons who are injured on the job to compensation while they heal. The primary victim of a workers' compensation scheme is not the employer but the insurance carrier for the employer. It is the insurance carrier who pays for the perpetrator's fraudulent medical bills and unnecessary absences. Nevertheless, the employer is a tertiary victim of these crimes, as the fake claims can result in higher premiums for the company in the future."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "What financial statement fraud scheme involves recording revenues and expenses in improper periods?", "options": {"A": "Timing differences", "B": "Improper disclosures", "C": "Improper asset valuations", "D": "Concealed expenses"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Financial statement fraud often involves timing differences—that is, the recording of revenues or expenses in improper periods. This can be done to shift revenues or expenses between one period and the next, increasing or decreasing earnings as desired. This practice is also referred to as income smoothing."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Which of the following measures should be in place to help prevent check tampering schemes?", "options": {"A": "Checks should be mailed immediately after they are signed", "B": "Companies should set up a positive pay system with their bank", "C": "Bank reconciliations should be performed by someone who is NOT an authorized signatory on the account", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Companies should work in a cooperative effort with banks to prevent check fraud. Consider the following control measures that might be taken in regard to a firm’s checking accounts: Establish maximum amounts above which the company’s bank will not accept checks drawn against the account. Use positive pay banking controls. Positive pay allows a company and its bank to work together to detect fraudulent items presented for payment. The company provides the bank with a list of checks and amounts that are written each day. The bank verifies items presented for payment against the company’s list. The bank rejects items that are not on the list. Investigations are conducted as to the origin of the “unlisted” items. In addition, the following activities will help tighten controls and possibly deter employees from giving in to the temptation to commit check fraud: Checks should be mailed immediately after signing. Bank reconciliations should not be performed by signatories on the account."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Cash theft schemes fall into which of the following two categories?", "options": {"A": "Register manipulation and understated sales", "B": "Skimming and cash larceny", "C": "Unrecorded sales and false discounts", "D": "Skimming and unrecorded sales"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Cash theft schemes fall into two categories: skimming and cash larceny. The difference between the two types of schemes depends completely on when the cash is stolen. Cash larceny is the theft of money that has already appeared on a victim organization’s books, while skimming is the theft of cash that has not yet been recorded in the accounting system. The way in which an employee extracts the cash might be exactly the same for a cash larceny or skimming scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Laura, the sales manager of Sam Corp., is afraid sales revenue for the period is not going to meet company goals. To make up for the shortfall, she decides to mail invoices to fake customers and credit (increase) revenue on the books for these sales. What account will she most likely debit to balance these fictitious revenue entries and conceal her scheme?", "options": {"A": "Inventory", "B": "Accounts payable", "C": "Cash", "D": "Accounts receivable"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fictitious or fabricated revenues involve the recording of sales of goods or services that did not occur. Fictitious sales most often involve fake customers but can also involve legitimate customers. At the end of the accounting period, the sale will be reversed (as will all revenue accounts), which will help to conceal the fraud. Recording the sales revenue is easy, but the challenge for the fraudster is how to balance the other side of the entry. A credit to revenue increases the revenue account, but the corresponding debit in a legitimate sales transaction typically either goes to cash or accounts receivable. Since no cash is received in a fictitious revenue scheme, increasing accounts receivable is the easiest way to get away with completing the entry. Unlike revenue accounts, however, accounts receivable are not reversed at the end of the accounting period. They stay on the books as an asset until collected. If the outstanding accounts never get collected, they will eventually need to be written off as bad debt expense. Mysterious accounts receivable on the books that are long overdue are a common sign of a fictitious revenue scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE?", "options": {"A": "Skimming schemes are generally more difficult to detect than cash larceny schemes.", "B": "Cash distraction is the most difficult type of cash receipts scheme to detect.", "C": "Cash larceny schemes are generally more difficult to detect than skimming schemes.", "D": "Both cash larceny and skimming are equally difficult to detect."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Because the cash stolen by an employee in a larceny scheme has already been recorded, its absence ought to be more easily detectable than the off-book funds taken in a skimming scheme. Consequently, we would expect larceny schemes to be less common and less successful than skimming schemes. Cash distraction is not a recognized type of cash receipts scheme."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Failure to record corresponding revenues and expenses in the same accounting period will result in an understatement of net income in the period when the revenue is recorded and an overstatement of net income in the period in which the corresponding expenses are recorded.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "According to generally accepted accounting principles, revenue and corresponding expenses should be recorded or matched in the same accounting period. The timely recording of expenses is often compromised due to pressures to meet budget projections and goals or due to lack of proper accounting controls. As the expensing of certain costs is pushed into periods other than the ones in which they actually occur, they are not properly matched against the income that they help produce. For example, revenue might be recognized on the sale of certain items, but the cost of goods and services that went into the items sold might intentionally not be recorded in the accounting system until the following period. This might make the sales revenue from the transaction almost pure profit, inflating earnings. In the next period, earnings would have fallen by a similar amount."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a red flag of a fraudulent credit card transaction?", "options": {"A": "A customer buys a small number of expensive items at one time.", "B": "A customer charges many expensive items to a newly valid card.", "C": "A customer insists on taking a large item home even when delivery is included.", "D": "A customer cannot provide a photo identification when requested."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "While any of the following can occur in a perfectly legitimate transaction, these characteristics frequently are present during fraudulent transactions. Tellers and merchants should be advised to be alert for customers who: Purchase an unusually large number of expensive items. Make random purchases, selecting items with little regard to size, quality, or value. Do not ask questions on major purchases. Sign the sales draft slowly or awkwardly. Charge expensive items on a newly valid credit card. Cannot provide a photo identification when asked. Rush the merchant or teller. Purchase a large item, such as a television, and insist on taking it at the time, even when delivery is included in the price. Make purchases and leave the store, but then return to make more purchases. Become argumentative with the teller or merchant while waiting for the transaction to be completed. Make large purchases just as the store is closing."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "In a financial statement fraud scheme in which capital expenditures are recorded as expenses rather than assets, the transactions will have the following effect on the organization's financial statements:", "options": {"A": "Sales revenue will be overstated", "B": "Net income will be overstated", "C": "Total assets will be understated", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Typically, a fraudster’s goal when committing a financial statement fraud scheme is to make the entity look stronger and more profitable. This goal is often achieved by concealing liabilities and/or expenses. To do this, he might fraudulently understate liabilities or improperly capitalize a cost that should be expensed. Just as capitalizing expenditures that should be expensed is improper, so is expensing costs that should be capitalized. Improperly expensing costs will result in a lower net income, as well as understated assets. There are several reasons an entity might want to make itself look worse than it actually is. For example, the organization might want to minimize its net income due to tax considerations. Expensing an item that should be depreciated over a period of time would help accomplish just that—net income would be lower and so would taxes. The result for the current accounting period is that total assets will be understated, and expenses will be overstated."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Special care facilities generally have the capability to meet all of their patients’ needs without the services of outside providers, leading to a lower likelihood of fraud involving such institutions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Medical facilities that offer special care services, such as nursing homes and psychiatric hospitals, and the patients in them are at a greater risk of fraud than most other medical institutions. Many health care fraud schemes are revealed after a patient reports strange charges or other red flags. Unfortunately, criminals take advantage of the fact that patients in special care facilities are more vulnerable to fraud. Many special care facilities do not have the in-house capability to provide all the services and supplies their patients need. Accordingly, outside providers market their services and supplies to special care facilities to meet the needs of their patients. Some special care facilities allow outside providers or their representatives to review patient medical records; these providers can obtain all the information necessary to order and bill for services and supplies that are not necessary or even provided."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Cash Receipts Schemes", "question": "Off-book sales of goods always cause shrinkage.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Off-book sales of goods, otherwise known as skimming, will always leave an inventory shortage and a corresponding rise in the cost of goods sold. When a sale of goods is made, the physical inventory is reduced by the amount of merchandise sold. If a retailer sells a pair of shoes, for instance, it has one less pair of shoes in the stock room. However, if this sale is unrecorded, the shoes remain on the inventory records. Thus, there is one less pair of shoes on hand than the records indicate. Such a reduction in the physical inventory without a corresponding reduction in the perpetual inventory is known as shrinkage."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "question": "AD&N Railway solicits bids to lay several miles of new railroad track. Bob, who works for AD&N, writes the specifications for the project to provide that AD&N will only contract with companies that have more than 25 years of experience. Bob knows that only B&P Track Co., one of the prospective bidders, has more than 25 years of experience. What type of procurement fraud scheme has taken place?", "options": {"A": "Bid suppression", "B": "Bid alteration", "C": "Bid tailoring", "D": "Bid division"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Bid tailoring schemes (also known as specifications schemes) occur during the presolicitation phase. In these schemes, an employee with procurement responsibilities, often in collusion with a contractor, drafts bid specifications in a way that gives an unfair advantage to a certain contractor. Bid specifications are a list of elements, measurements, materials, characteristics, required functions, and other specific information detailing the goods and services that a procuring entity needs from a contractor. Specifications assist prospective contractors in the bidding process, informing them of what they are required to do and providing a firm basis for making bids, and they provide procurement officials with a firm basis for selecting bids. There are three primary methods used to commit bid tailoring schemes. One method involves drafting narrow specifications. In these schemes, a corrupt employee tailors the bid specifications to accommodate a vendor’s capabilities and to eliminate other competitors so that the favored contractor is effectively guaranteed to win the contract. For instance, the tailored bid might require potential contractors to have a certain percentage of female or minority ownership. Such a requirement is not illegal, but if it is placed in the specifications as a result of a bribe, then the employee has sold his influence to benefit a dishonest vendor. A second method involves drafting broad specifications. In these schemes, a corrupt employee of the buyer designs unduly broad qualification standards to qualify an otherwise unqualified contractor. A third method involves drafting vague specifications. In these schemes, the buyer’s personnel and the contractor collude to write vague specifications or intentionally omit bid specifications. This enables subsequent contract amendments, allowing the contractor to raise the contract’s price."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Computer and Internet Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a measure that management can take to prevent an organization’s computers from being infected by malicious software?", "options": {"A": "Require that users reuse passwords for important accounts.", "B": "Prevent employees from opening any emails with attachments.", "C": "Only allow systems to boot with removable storage devices.", "D": "Regularly update the organization’s operating systems."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following measures can help avoid infection from a malicious program: Use anti-malware software to scan all incoming email messages and files. Regularly update virus definitions in anti-malware programs. Use precaution when opening emails from acquaintances. Do not open email attachments unless they are from trusted sources. Only download files from reputable sources. Regularly update the operating system. Regularly update the computer with the latest security patches available for the operating system, software, browser, and email programs. Ensure that there is a clean boot disk to facilitate testing with antivirus software. Use a firewall and keep it turned on. Consider testing all computer software on an isolated system before loading it. In a network environment, do not place untested programs on the server. Secure the computer against unauthorized access from external threats such as hackers. Keep backup copies of production data files and computer software in a secure location. Scan pre-formatted storage devices before using them. Consider preventing the system from booting with a removable storage device; this might prevent accidental infection. Establish corporate policies and an employee education program to inform employees of how malware is introduced and what to do if malware is suspected. Encourage employees to protect their home systems as well. Many malware infections result from employees bringing infected storage devices or files from home."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "Most shell company schemes involve the purchase of fictitious:", "options": {"A": "Supplies", "B": "Goods", "C": "Inventory", "D": "Services"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Most shell company schemes involve the purchase of services rather than goods. The primary reason for this is that services are not tangible. If an employee sets up a shell company to make fictitious sales of goods to his employer, these goods will obviously never arrive. By comparing its purchases to its inventory levels, the victim organization might detect the fraud. It is much more difficult for the victim organization to verify that the services were never rendered. For this reason, many employees involved in shell company schemes bill their employers for things like “consulting services.”"}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Fraudulent Disbursements", "question": "All of the following measures are recommended to help mitigate the risk of billing schemes EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Provide objective compensation for purchasing staff.", "B": "Prohibit competitive bidding.", "C": "Separate the purchasing function from the payment function.", "D": "Implement a hotline function."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The prevention of purchasing fraud can be especially difficult. Probably the most effective purchasing fraud prevention measure is education and training of the purchasing and accounts payable personnel. The second most effective purchasing fraud prevention measure is an objective compensation arrangement with people responsible for purchasing decisions. For the best results and accountability, each company sufficient in size should have a separate purchasing department. Regardless of the company size, the purchasing function should be separate from the payment function. Furthermore, companies should implement a hotline function to provide a forum for complaints and fraud tips by employees and outsiders. Whenever possible, companies should enforce competitive bidding. Competitive bidding is a transparent procurement method in which bids from competing contractors, suppliers, or vendors are invited by openly publicizing the scope, specifications, and terms and conditions of the proposed contract, as well as the criteria by which the bids will be evaluated. Competitive bidding aims at obtaining goods and services at the lowest prices by stimulating competition and preventing partiality and fraud."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "question": "Entries to the left side of an account are referred to as credits, while entries to the right side of an account are debits.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Entries to the left side of an account are referred to as debits, and entries to the right side of an account are referred to as credits. Asset and expense accounts are increased with debits and decreased with credits, while liabilities, owners' equity, and revenue accounts are increased with credits and decreased with debits."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "Of the following, who should conduct physical observations of a company's inventory in order to most effectively prevent inventory theft?", "options": {"A": "Sales representative", "B": "Purchasing agents", "C": "Purchasing supervisor", "D": "Warehouse personnel"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Someone independent of the purchasing or warehousing functions should conduct physical observation of inventory. For example, sales representatives usually communicate with customers and encourage them to buy the company’s products, but they typically have no access to the physical inventory. The personnel conducting the physical observations also should be knowledgeable about the inventory."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "question": "All organizations with a pyramid structure are illegal.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Not all organizations with a pyramid structure are engaging in illegal activity. Some legitimate merchandising companies use a pyramid structure to rank their employee-owners and to determine those people’s compensation. A pyramid structure becomes an illegal pyramid scheme when the recruitment of new members takes precedence over the product or service that the company is ostensibly promoting. The more members that are recruited, the higher the investor is purported to rise in the ranks of the enterprise, and the more money the investor is supposed to make."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "question": "Which financial ratio is calculated by dividing current assets by current liabilities?", "options": {"A": "Profit margin", "B": "Quick ratio", "C": "Receivable turnover", "D": "Current ratio"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The current ratio—current assets divided by current liabilities—is probably the most-used liquidity ratio in financial statement analysis. This comparison measures a company’s ability to meet present obligations from its liquid assets; specifically, the current ratio measures the amount of times current assets would be able to pay back current liabilities. In detecting fraud, this ratio can be a prime indicator of manipulation of accounts involved. Embezzlement will cause the ratio to decrease. Liability concealment will cause a more favorable ratio."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Inventory and Other Assets", "question": "Unauthorized personal use of a company vehicle constitutes misuse of a noncash asset, a form of asset misappropriation.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are basically two ways a person can misappropriate a company asset. The asset can be misused (or “borrowed”) or it can be stolen. Assets that are misused but not stolen typically include company vehicles, supplies, computers, and other office equipment."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "question": "Which of the following scenarios illustrates a fraudster’s use of social engineering?", "options": {"A": "A fraudster calls a company employee and requests sensitive information while claiming to be a coworker whose systems are down", "B": "A fraudster has lunch at a restaurant where a target company’s employees are known to eat with the intention of overhearing sensitive conversations", "C": "A fraudster without an employee badge gains access to a secure facility by following legitimate employees who are oblivious to his presence", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Social engineering is the act of using deceptive techniques to manipulate people into taking certain actions or disclosing information. In social engineering schemes, social engineers use various forms of trickery, persuasion, threats, or cajolery to encourage their targets to release information that the engineers can use and exploit to achieve their goals. Attackers engage in social engineering for various reasons. Some use social engineering to gain unauthorized access to systems or obtain confidential communication so they can commit fraud, intrude into networks, gain access to buildings, steal another party’s secrets, commit identity theft, or engage in some other nefarious act. In some situations, attackers use social engineering to procure information that will give them a competitive advantage, whereas others might engage in social engineering to find ways in which they can install malware."}, {"domain": "Fin. Trsn & Frd Schm", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "question": "Common methods of inflating health care billings include all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Altered claims", "B": "Code manipulation", "C": "Added services", "D": "Sliding policies"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Health care billings can be inflated by providers as well as beneficiaries. The following are some of the most common fraud schemes encountered by investigators and claims approvers: Altered claims Added services Code manipulation"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "All of the following are basic principles for the protection of data privacy on which most data privacy laws are built EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "All personal information must be kept indefinitely.", "B": "All personal information must be used only for the original specified purpose.", "C": "All personal information must be obtained fairly and lawfully.", "D": "All personal information must be accessible to the data subject."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Most countries have data privacy laws (also known as information privacy or data protection laws) that protect personal information about individuals from disclosure, unauthorized access, and misuse. And even though countries have their own requirements for the protection of data privacy, most countries impose requirements that converge around the principles that all personal information must be: Obtained fairly and lawfully Used only for the original specified purpose Adequate, relevant, and not excessive to the specified purpose Kept accurate and up-to-date Accessible to the data subject Protected by reasonable security safeguards Destroyed after its purpose is completed"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In jurisdictions that recognize corporate criminal liability, which of the following is/are required to hold the corporation vicariously liable for the acts of one of its employees?", "options": {"A": "The employee was acting within the scope of his employment", "B": "The employee was acting for the benefit of the corporation", "C": "An employee committed each element of a criminal violation", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In many jurisdictions, corporations and similar business entities may be vicariously liable (the absolute liability of one party for the misconduct of another party) for criminal and civil violations. Typically, a business entity is liable for the acts of its employees if those acts occur within the scope of employment and with some intent to benefit the corporation. Therefore, the employee needs to have committed each element of the crime for liability to be transferred to the corporation. Generally, vicarious liability is very broad and imposes liability on a corporation even if those in management had no knowledge or participation in the underlying events. Moreover, the acts of any employee, from the lowest clerk to the CEO, can impute liability upon a corporation, and a corporation may be liable for the acts of its employees that violate securities laws, banking laws, anti-bribery laws, and many others."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Which of the following parties decides the scope of the examinations and breadth of authority of a court-appointed expert witness in an inquisitorial court?", "options": {"A": "The expert witness", "B": "A panel of the expert’s professional peers", "C": "The judge", "D": "The parties to the litigation"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Inquisitorial courts typically appoint their own experts to evaluate technical matters. Expert witnesses in inquisitorial jurisdictions are subject to various examinations by the judge and the parties and might have to conduct their own examinations of witnesses. Usually, all of the expert’s activities related to the case are controlled by the judge, who determines the scope of the expert’s testimony and analysis, the expert’s authority to access certain items of evidence, whom the expert can interview, and several other functions. Because some jurisdictions allow parties to submit testimony or evidence from their own experts in addition to the court-appointed expert, the latter might need to interview the parties’ experts. The expert should carefully follow the judge’s instructions, especially since the instructions are usually made available to the parties of the proceeding."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "Walters is the mayor of a mid-size town. Because he is well-known and liked in the town, the prosecutor wants to move the trial to another town in which Walters is not known. The prosecution believes that such a move will ensure a more unbiased verdict. If the prosecution wishes to move the trial to a different city, it must request which of the following?", "options": {"A": "An appeal", "B": "A new trial", "C": "Change of venue", "D": "Change of jurisdiction"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Most jurisdictions require the court to have proper venue as an element of jurisdiction. Venue is the physical location where the lawsuit is to be tried. Rules of venue can be based on a mixture of factors, including convenience to the parties (e.g., where they reside) and where the acts that underlie the case occurred. In some instances, there will be multiple courts that have jurisdiction over a case, and the parties that believe they are subject to prejudice in a court will seek to change the venue to a court more favorable to themselves."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "To determine whether authorization by a judicial officer or other sanctioned official (e.g., a search warrant) is required to conduct a search in a jurisdiction with laws granting people the right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by authorities, it is necessary to first determine whether or not  _____________ is/are involved in the search.", "options": {"A": "Investigative suspicion", "B": "Probable cause", "C": "Criminal activity", "D": "Government authorities"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Most countries have laws that provide the public with the right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities, and though the interpretation may vary, this right sometimes requires that the government obtain authorization (e.g., a search warrant) by a judicial officer or other authorized person before it conducts a search. A search warrant is a court order that grants government authorities the right to search a premises or property for information pertinent to a case. The requirements for search warrants or other similar authorization, however, do not apply to private parties acting on their own accord because the right to be free from unreasonable searches and seizures does not protect against actions by such parties. Instead, it protects individuals from actions by government authorities. Thus, to determine whether a search warrant or similar authorization is required for a search to be conducted in an investigation, it is necessary to first determine whether or not government authorities are involved in the search."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "In adversarial systems, which of the following is generally NOT a purpose of opposing counsel during the cross-examination of a witness?", "options": {"A": "To discredit the witness’s testimony itself", "B": "To obtain information about the witness’s testimony previously unknown to opposing counsel", "C": "To diminish the importance of the witness’s testimony", "D": "To make the witness contradict former statements the witness made during the litigation process"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Cross-examination refers to the questioning of one side’s witness by the opposing side, and it is truly the highlight of the adversarial court system. Cross-examination, however, is uncommon in inquisitorial systems, although some civil law jurisdictions allow counsel for the parties to question witnesses in limited circumstances. Cross-examination is geared to allow opposing counsel or another questioning party either to clarify or to make points at the witness’s expense. Questions during cross-examination might concern anything that might refute or embarrass the witness. During adversarial cross-examination, the witness’s credibility will constantly be called into question. First, opposing counsel will seek to diminish the importance of the testimony presented by the witness. Second, opposing counsel will seek to have the witness testify in support of the opposing position by providing a series of assumptions. Third, opposing counsel will attack the witness’s report or expert opinion (as applicable) itself to show the inadequacies, thereby discrediting the opinion, the report, and the witness. The opposing counsel can attack or question anything that has been said or entered into court. This includes notes, working papers, affidavits, reports, and preliminary trial or discovery transcripts. Often, cross-examination creates an atmosphere of confrontation and contradiction. Opposing counsel will generally not ask a question to which it does not already know the answer."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "All of the following are basic options by which organizations can legitimize cross-border transfers of personal information EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Rely on adequacy decisions (if transmitting from the European Union).", "B": "Obtain approval from a Certified Information Privacy Professional (CIPP).", "C": "Establish a contract between the entities exchanging the information.", "D": "Obtain the consent of the data subject."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Many countries have adopted legal restrictions on international data transfers, but there are discrepancies in the implementation and application of such protections among the different countries. Given the wide range of legislation and practices regarding cross-border transfer laws and restrictions, fraud examiners working in other countries must become familiar with laws governing privacy and must adapt their procedures according to local rules. Nevertheless, there are three basic options by which organizations can legitimize cross-border transfers of personal information: Obtain the consent of the data subject. Establish a contract between the entities exchanging the information (i.e., between the transmitting entity and the receiving entity). If transmitting from the European Union to non-European Union countries, rely on adequacy decisions by the European Commission. That is, limit the transfer of data to countries that offer an adequate level of protection, as determined by the European Commission."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a commonly available defense to tax fraud accusations?", "options": {"A": "Bankruptcy", "B": "Amending the fraudulently submitted information", "C": "Death of the taxpayer", "D": "Mental illness"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Some defenses will be ineffective against charges for tax crimes. The death of the taxpayer often cannot be used as a defense because taxes owed due to tax evasion typically survive the taxpayer’s death, meaning the deceased taxpayer’s estate will be held liable. Also, liabilities owed as a result of tax evasion may not be discharged in bankruptcy proceedings. If a person commits a tax fraud offense, amending fraudulent information held by the government will not generally relieve the taxpayer of criminal liability. Mental illness, however, may be an appropriate defense."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "During a criminal trial involving allegations of corruption, the prosecution introduces a diagram illustrating the organizational structure of a company allegedly involved in the corruption. The diagram is an example of:", "options": {"A": "Direct evidence", "B": "Documentary evidence", "C": "Real evidence", "D": "Demonstrative evidence"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There are three basic forms, as distinguished from types, of evidence: testimonial, real, and demonstrative. Testimonial evidence refers to the oral or written statements made by witnesses under oath. Real evidence refers to physical objects that played a part in the issues being litigated. Demonstrative evidence is a tangible item that illustrates some material proposition (e.g., a map, a chart, or a summary). Demonstrative evidence differs from real evidence in that demonstrative evidence was not part of the underlying event; it was created specifically for the trial. Its purpose is to provide a visual aid for the fact finder. Nonetheless, demonstrative evidence is evidence and can be considered by the fact finder in reaching a verdict."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "The commencement of a civil action begins with the filing of a(n):", "options": {"A": "Supposition, usually in the jurisdiction in which the defendant resides", "B": "Pleading, usually in the jurisdiction in which the defendant resides or where the claim arose", "C": "Information, usually in the jurisdiction in which the plaintiff resides", "D": "Information, usually in the jurisdiction in which the defendant or plaintiff resides or where the claim arose"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A civil action begins when the plaintiff files a pleading with the appropriate court, usually in the jurisdiction in which the defendant resides or where the claim arose. The pleading sets out the complaint against the defendant and the remedy that the plaintiff is seeking. Depending on the practice and procedure of the court in which the action is commenced, such a document may be called a writ of summons, a statement of claim, a declaration, or an application."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Which of the following refers to investments that are designed to yield a tax benefit to the investor?", "options": {"A": "Secrecy jurisdictions", "B": "Tax shelters", "C": "Money laundering havens", "D": "Tax havens"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Individuals frequently use tax shelters, tax havens, and secrecy jurisdictions to evade taxes. Tax shelters are investments that are designed to yield a tax benefit to the investor. Such investments are made to produce tax write-offs, generate deductions, or convert ordinary income into capital gains taxed at a lower rate. Tax shelters might be legal or illegal; they are generally aimed at avoidance, although they might, on occasion, cross the line into evasion if they take abusive forms."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Bert is the lead suspect in an ongoing civil investigation in a common law jurisdiction that will likely result in litigation. Before any litigation occurs, Bert loses original documents that are key to the investigation. Which of the following statements is CORRECT?", "options": {"A": "Bert violated his duty to preserve relevant information only if the opposing party loses its case because he lost the documents", "B": "Bert did not violate his duty to preserve relevant information because no litigation was pending when he lost the documents", "C": "Bert likely violated his duty to preserve relevant information because he lost evidence valuable to anticipated litigation", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Common law jurisdictions, in which litigants are usually obligated to disclose relevant information to the opposing side, impose a duty on litigants to take affirmative steps to preserve relevant evidence, and this duty might arise prior to the commencement of litigation. For litigation occurring in common law courts, the duty to preserve relevant evidence typically arises when litigation is reasonably anticipated or contemplated. When an organization is involved in litigation, this duty to preserve applies to the organization’s management, and it extends to employees likely to have relevant information. A violation of the duty to preserve occurs when information that is relevant to anticipated or existing litigation is lost, destroyed, or otherwise made unavailable. Violating the duty to preserve relevant information can result in several adverse sanctions for the offending party, and such sanctions can arise from both intentional acts and accidental acts through negligence. The adverse consequences can include, but are not limited to, monetary penalties, the drawing of adverse inferences of fact, and criminal penalties. The theory behind such consequences is that the individual who makes evidence unavailable following the probable initiation of a lawsuit is aware of its detrimental effect upon a case. Examples of situations that could give rise to sanctions for failing to preserve evidence include intentionally or accidentally: Erasing computer files (e.g., documents, images, or databases) relevant to anticipated or existing litigation Losing or destroying physical evidence relevant to anticipated or existing litigation Losing, destroying, or altering documents or records relevant to anticipated or existing litigation Failing to suspend routine destruction of electronic data relevant to anticipated or existing litigation"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is a basic exception for the requirement that a police officer must obtain a search warrant before conducting a search of a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime?", "options": {"A": "Searches conducted pursuant to a valid, voluntary consent", "B": "Searches when a confession has been made", "C": "Searches where there is circumstantial proof that the suspect is guilty", "D": "Searches where there is \"reasonable belief\" in the suspect's guilt"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Even if a warrant is technically required, there are a number of recognized exceptions to the warrant requirement. Two key exceptions are consent searches and evidence in plain view."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "An action for fraud may be based on the concealment of material facts, but only if:", "options": {"A": "The defendant had a duty in the circumstances to disclose.", "B": "The defendant had a duty to investigate the material facts.", "C": "The victim had a duty in the circumstances to disclose.", "D": "The victim relied on the misrepresentation."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "An action for fraud may be based on the concealment of material facts, but only if the defendant had a duty in the circumstances to disclose."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Which of the following would be classified as a falsified tax deduction scheme?", "options": {"A": "A taxpayer fraudulently claims income or wealth was earned in a foreign jurisdiction to reduce tax liability", "B": "A taxpayer bribes a vendor to create a fictitious invoice that appears to increase the taxpayer’s costs of goods sold", "C": "A taxpayer smuggles cigarettes into the country to avoid excise taxes", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In the context of income and wealth taxes, tax deductions are itemized expenses subtracted from gross income or assets to reduce the taxpayer’s total liability. For instance, a company that is taxed by a percentage of its gross sales might be allowed to deduct the cost of making the goods (materials, employee costs, etc.). Deductions are designed to make certain taxes fairer, but they can also be used inappropriately by tax evaders. Examples of the fraudulent use of deductions include: Falsifying expenses, such as recording fictitious salaries to nonexistent employees Fraudulently inflating expenses, such as bribing a supplier to inflate an invoice Submitting false information to qualify for improper deductions, such as pretending to qualify for a tax deduction for having children living at home Misclassifying nondeductible expenses as deductible"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "In adversarial judicial jurisdictions, which of the following is NOT a question that must typically be asked in determining whether an expert may testify before the jury?", "options": {"A": "Is the person well-educated on the subject?", "B": "Is the person qualified as an expert?", "C": "Is the testimony relevant to the facts of the case?", "D": "Is the testimony reliable?"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Generally, before allowing an expert to testify before the jury in an adversarial jurisdiction, the judge will make three determinations: Is the person qualified as an expert witness? Will the expertise of the witness assist the jury in understanding the evidence or determining a fact at issue? In other words, is the proposed testimony relevant to the facts of the case? Is the testimony reliable?"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following statements about the consent exception to the requirement that government agents must obtain a warrant before conducting a search for evidence of a crime is INCORRECT?", "options": {"A": "Generally, government agents do not have to warn subjects that they have a right to refuse to consent to a search.", "B": "To be valid, an individual’s consent to a search by government agents must be voluntary.", "C": "Government agents do not need a warrant to perform a search if a person with proper authority consents to the search.", "D": "Even if obtained by bribery or force, consent to search constitutes a valid waiver of the person’s right to be free from unreasonable searches."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Consent is a recognized exception to the requirement that government agents must obtain a warrant before they search a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime. Individuals are always free to consent to searches. If a suspect consents to a search or seizure by police or a government agent, the consent eliminates the need for a search warrant. That is, the consent to search serves to waive the person’s right to be free from government searches. Thus, the government does not need a warrant to perform a search if a person with proper authority consents to a search. To be valid, an individual’s consent to a search or seizure must be voluntary. Consents to searches or seizures by government agents obtained by force, duress, or bribery are generally held to be involuntary and invalid; therefore, such consent does not constitute a valid waiver of the person’s right to be free from unreasonable searches. Jurisdictions are mixed, however, as to whether consents obtained by deceit constitute valid waiver. Also, there is generally no requirement that government agents warn suspects that they have a right to refuse consent."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Under the United Nations’ International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR), those accused of criminal charges are generally entitled to a fair hearing that is private, the results of which should not be disclosed to the public.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Most countries have signed and ratified the United Nations’ International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR), which commits them to recognizing various rights of citizens. Part III of the ICCPR includes the rights of those accused of crimes. As one of these rights, the ICCPR states that all people accused of crimes are entitled to a fair hearing before a court or other tribunal and that the results of the trial should be made public to protect the criminal justice system’s transparency. This right includes: Adequate time to prepare a defense The ability to be represented by legal counsel of the defendant’s choosing and to freely communicate with counsel The right to have accusations and the procedures explained through a translator for free, if necessary The right to be tried for charges without undue delay The right to examine or have examined the witnesses against the accused Freedom from testifying against oneself or compelled confessions"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Which of the following would be an example of direct evidence?", "options": {"A": "In an embezzlement trial, witness testimony about a suspicious situation in which the defendant was involved", "B": "In a misappropriation trial, testimony that the defendant deposited $2,000 into his account and that, on the same day, $2,000 was stolen from his employer", "C": "In a misappropriation trial, eyewitness testimony of someone saying that she saw the defendant steal items from his employer’s inventory", "D": "In an embezzlement trial, expert testimony regarding the defendant’s mental functioning and drug addiction"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Direct evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue directly, such as eyewitness testimony or a confession. The testimony of someone who saw the defendant committing the crime would be considered direct evidence in a misappropriation trial. Alternatively, witness testimony about a suspicious situation in which the defendant was involved would be considered circumstantial evidence, as would testimony that a defendant deposited $2,000 into his account on the same day that $2,000 was stolen. Circumstantial evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove facts in issue indirectly, by inference."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "During cross-examination in adversarial proceedings, it is a general rule for opposing counsel to cross-examine a witness only if it would benefit the case.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "It is critical to never underestimate the expertise of the opposing counsel in adversarial proceedings. Often, opposing counsel will be underplaying its understanding of the issues to lull the witness into a sense of security. This can lead the witness into a difficult situation. Opposing counsel's golden rule is to cross-examine only if it would benefit the case. In asking questions of the witness, opposing counsel will generally ask either short questions in plain words or will ask leading questions. Opposing counsel usually knows the answers to the questions it poses."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is an element that a plaintiff generally must prove to recover damages for a claim alleging the common law civil wrong for intentional infliction of emotional distress?", "options": {"A": "The plaintiff suffered distress that manifested itself for at least two years", "B": "The defendant engaged in extreme and outrageous conduct", "C": "The plaintiff was an employee of the defendant", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "To recover for intentional infliction of emotional distress, the plaintiff must prove all of the following elements: The defendant engaged in extreme and outrageous conduct. The defendant acted intentionally or recklessly (i.e., the defendant intended that his conduct would cause severe emotional distress, or he acted recklessly with regard to whether his actions would cause severe emotional distress). The victim actually did suffer emotional or mental distress as a result of the defendant's conduct."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "All of the following may restrict the way in which employers can conduct interviews EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Equity and trust law", "B": "Employment contracts", "C": "The common law", "D": "Laws protecting labor rights"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Interviews, and especially interviews of suspects, can expose the organizational powers administering the interview and the individual conducting the interview to certain legal risks. Thus, before engaging in an interview, the fraud examiner must understand the ramifications of his actions, which requires an understanding of certain legal issues and how they limit or affect the ways in which an interview may be conducted. Of particular significance is the fact that most jurisdictions have restrictions concerning the ways in which employers can conduct interviews. Such restrictions might originate from employment contracts, collective labor laws, laws protecting labor rights, the common law, laws protecting fundamental rights, other applicable statutes, and so on."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "Which of the following most accurately reflects the recommendations regarding secured interests in the World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes?", "options": {"A": "Countries should allow for secured interests in all types of assets.", "B": "Countries should allow for secured interests in tangible property but not intangible property.", "C": "Countries should allow for security interests in property currently possessed by the debtor but not property that might be possessed in the future.", "D": "Countries should allow for secured interests in movable property but not immovable property."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "While bankruptcy laws and creditor rights vary from jurisdiction to jurisdiction, there is an international trend toward making such systems more uniform. According to the World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes, the legal framework for secured lending addresses the fundamental features and elements for the creation, recognition, and enforcement of security interests, including both possessory and non-possessory interests, in all types of assets on a global basis. This includes movable and immovable assets, as well as those that are tangible and intangible (including inventories, receivables, proceeds, and future property). The law should encompass any or all of a debtor’s obligations to a creditor, present or future, and between all types of people."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a legal element that must be shown to prove a claim for commercial bribery?", "options": {"A": "The principal suffered damages as a result of the bribe.", "B": "The defendant gave or received a thing of value.", "C": "The defendant acted with corrupt intent.", "D": "The defendant acted without the victim’s knowledge or consent."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Commercial bribery refers to the corruption of a private individual to gain a commercial or business advantage. That is, in commercial bribery schemes, something of value is offered to influence a business decision rather than an official act. The elements of commercial bribery vary by jurisdiction, but they typically include: The defendant gave or received a thing of value. The defendant acted with corrupt intent. The defendant’s scheme was designed to influence the recipient’s action in a business decision. The defendant acted without the victim’s knowledge or consent."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Relevant evidence is evidence that tends to make some fact at issue more or less likely than it would be without the evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The admissibility of evidence depends on the discretion of the presiding judge, but a basic requirement of admissibility in both common and civil law systems is that evidence must be relevant. Evidence is relevant if it tends to make some fact at issue more or less likely than it would be without the evidence."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "A client hires an attorney in a jurisdiction that provides a legal professional privilege. If the attorney shares client communications that are confidential and subject to the legal professional privilege with an outside consultant hired to help provide legal advice to the attorney’s client, the client will automatically lose any protection the legal professional privilege provided over the communications.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Legal professional privileges are not absolute; they are subject to waiver. Because these privileges only protect confidential communications, the protection they provide will be waived for communications disclosed to third parties who have little or nothing to do with the client’s pursuit of legal representation because such disclosures demonstrate a lack of confidentiality. Generally, waiver occurs when the client, who holds the privilege, voluntarily discloses (or consents to or encourages someone else disclosing) any significant part of the privileged communications. Although the client holds the privilege, the privilege can be waived by the client’s attorney or a third party—someone who is neither the attorney nor the client. Although legal professional privileges only apply to confidential communications between a legal representative and the legal representative's client, in most jurisdictions, the protection afforded by these privileges extends to communications with third-party consultants hired to help provide legal advice to the client (e.g., fraud examiners, accountants, bankers, or other experts). Thus, waiver does not occur when an attorney shares privileged information with an outside consultant hired in a role that concerns the client’s pursuit of legal representation and when the communication is made for the purpose of effectuating legal representation for the client."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "If a person consents to a search by a government officer, but the consent is obtained by force, duress, or bribery, the consent will not constitute a valid waiver of the person’s right to be free from unreasonable searches.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Consent is a recognized exception to the requirement that government agents must obtain a warrant before they search a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime. Individuals are always free to consent to searches. If a suspect consents to a search or seizure by police or a government agent, the consent eliminates the need for a search warrant. That is, the consent to search waives the person’s right to be free from government searches. Thus, the government does not need a warrant to perform a search if a person with proper authority consents to a search. To be valid, an individual’s consent to a search or seizure must be voluntary. Consents to searches or seizures by government agents obtained by force, duress, or bribery are generally held to be involuntary and invalid; therefore, such consent does not constitute a valid waiver of the person’s right to be free from unreasonable searches. Jurisdictions are mixed, however, as to whether consents obtained by deceit constitute valid waiver. Also, there is generally no requirement that government agents warn suspects that they have a right to refuse consent."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Blue is a defendant on trial for fraud in a common law jurisdiction. One of the key pieces of evidence in the trial is a handwritten letter written by Blue that indicates his intent to commit the fraud. Before the letter can be admitted into evidence, Blue’s authorship of the letter must be established. Which of the following statements about establishing the authenticity of the letter is CORRECT?", "options": {"A": "The letter’s authenticity can be established by having a witness testify that he saw Blue write the letter", "B": "The letter’s authenticity can be established by having the jury review the document and vote on its authenticity", "C": "Because the letter is self-authenticating, it needs no additional authentication to be admitted", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In common law systems using adversarial processes, exhibits—the tangible objects presented as evidence—are inadmissible unless they are relevant and established as authentic. Thus, to be admissible at trial, evidence, other than testimonial evidence, must be properly authenticated; that is, the party offering the item must produce some evidence (e.g., testimony from a person with firsthand knowledge) to show it is, in fact, what the party says it is and to show it is in the same condition as when it was seized. If an exhibit cannot be authenticated, it will not be admitted even if it is plainly relevant. In general, authentication of a writing consists of establishing who authored the document. Depending on the document and situation, this is done in one of several ways: (1) the author testifies and claims authorship; (2) a witness testifies to seeing the author write the document; (3) with handwritten letters, a witness verifies the author’s penmanship; (4) with typed or machine-written documents, the witness verifies the author’s signature; (5) a witness testifies that the contents of the document point decisively to the author. These and many other document issues might require the participation of a document expert."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is an element that must be established to prove fraud based on the concealment of material facts?", "options": {"A": "The defendant acted with intent to mislead or deceive the victim(s).", "B": "The victim failed to exercise due care in relying on the defendant’s actions.", "C": "The defendant had knowledge of a material fact that concerned a matter within the jurisdiction of a government agency.", "D": "The defendant knew for certain the victim would be harmed."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "An action for fraud may be based on the concealment of material facts, but only if the defendant had a duty in the circumstances to disclose. The essential elements of fraud based on the failure to disclose material facts are: The defendant had knowledge of a material fact. The defendant had a duty to disclose the material fact. The defendant failed to disclose the material fact. The defendant acted with intent to mislead or deceive the victim(s). It is not necessary to prove that the defendant knew for certain that the victim would be harmed. It is only necessary to prove that he intended to mislead or deceive the victim."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements about general partners is CORRECT?", "options": {"A": "General partners have management responsibility for the enterprise and assume liability for the partnership’s debts.", "B": "General partners assume liability for the partnership’s debts but have no management responsibility for the enterprise.", "C": "General partners cannot incur obligations on behalf of the partnership.", "D": "General partners have management responsibility for the enterprise but assume no liability for the partnership’s debts."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are various partnership forms, including general partnerships and limited partnerships. General partnerships are associations of two or more persons acting as co-owners in a business for profit. In a general partnership, each general partner can incur obligations on behalf of the partnership, and each partner assumes unlimited liability for the partnership’s debts. Thus, a general partner has unlimited personal liability. Also, in a general partnership, the partners take an active role in the business's operation (i.e., they have management responsibilities)."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Which of the following would be an example of a narrative question that an attorney might ask an expert witness during direct examination in an adversarial system?", "options": {"A": "“Weren’t there three inaccuracies on the financial statement?”", "B": "“You couldn’t find any direct evidence implicating the suspect, could you?”", "C": "“At what point did you begin to suspect that the subject was lying?”", "D": "“Could you please describe the steps you took during your examination?”"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Direct examination is the initial questioning of a witness by the party that called the witness (in adversarial jurisdictions) or the judge (in inquisitorial jurisdictions). Most of the time, direct examination is a nonconfrontational questioning aimed at exposing the facts and issues of the case. During direct examination in adversarial systems, expert witnesses present their findings in various ways, such as narrative questions, hypotheticals, specialized materials, and special exhibits. Experts are commonly asked to answer narrative questions, which are broad, open-ended questions that allow experts to present their opinions in their own words with minimal prompting. Fraud cases, with their divergent paths of activity and intrigue, can require complex summarizing for the facts to make any sense. Average jurors and some judges have never considered how someone could manipulate store inventories to drive up the company’s stock price and then make a profit on the phony surge. The expert witness in cases dealing with such issues often will begin testimony by recounting the narrative background of a case, the tests and experiments that were performed during the investigation, and a summary of the findings based on the witness's professional expertise. For example, during a direct examination, the judge or counsel for the party presenting the expert witness might ask open questions, such as, “Could you please tell us about the background of this case?” or “What procedures did you perform in your examination?” In contrast, a cross-examining attorney needs to control the flow of testimony and would not likely ask an expert witness a narrative question. Instead, cross-examining attorneys often attempt to ask leading questions, where the answer is suggested in the question. They might also ask questions that would call for the expert to go beyond the proper scope of his testimony."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "The UK Bribery Act has a broader application than the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) because, unlike the FCPA, it makes commercial bribery a crime.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Both the UK Bribery Act and the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) make it a crime to offer foreign public officials bribes or to accept bribes from them in connection with international business transactions, and their prohibitions on bribing foreign government officials are broadly comparable. Thus, like the FCPA, the Bribery Act seeks to punish corruption on a global level, but the Bribery Act has an even broader application than the FCPA. One way in which the Bribery Act has a broader application than the FCPA is that it makes commercial bribery—bribes paid to people working in the private sector—a crime, whereas the FCPA only prohibits bribes involving foreign government officials."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In jurisdictions that recognize corporate criminal liability, to find a corporation vicariously liable for the acts of one of its employees, it is typically necessary that someone in management was involved in the offense or knew about the offense and should have stopped it.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In many jurisdictions, corporations and similar business entities may be vicariously liable (the absolute liability of one party for the misconduct of another party) for criminal and civil violations. Typically, a business entity is liable for the acts of its employees if those acts occur within the scope of employment and with some intent to benefit the corporation. Therefore, the employee needs to have committed each element of the crime for liability to be transferred to the corporation. Generally, vicarious liability is very broad and imposes liability on a corporation even if those in management had no knowledge or participation in the underlying events. Moreover, the acts of any employee, from the lowest clerk to the CEO, can impute liability upon a corporation, and a corporation may be liable for the acts of its employees that violate securities laws, banking laws, anti-bribery laws, and many others."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "In most countries, which of the following is something that a government prosecutor must prove in order to convict someone of the crime of making a false statement to the government?", "options": {"A": "The individual made the statement directly to the government.", "B": "The government was influenced by or suffered a loss because of the statement.", "C": "The statement was the result of a mistake or other innocent reason.", "D": "The individual acted knowingly and willfully when making the statement."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Laws prohibiting false claims and statements to government agencies make it illegal for a person to lie to, or conceal material information from, a government agency. A false claim is an assertion of a right to government money, property, or services that contains a misrepresentation. A false statement is an oral or written communication, declaration, or assertion that is factually untrue. Generally, to prove a violation, the government must show that the defendant: Knowingly and willfully (or with reckless disregard for truth or falsity) Made a false claim or statement (or used a false document) That was material (i.e., sufficiently important or relevant to influence decision making) Regarding a matter within the jurisdiction of a government agency With knowledge of its falsity An act is done knowingly and willfully if it is done voluntarily and intentionally and not by mistake or another innocent reason."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "In jurisdictions that recognize the civil wrongs constituting invasion of privacy, the civil wrong regarding intrusion into an individual’s private matters occurs when one party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Public disclosure of private facts occurs when one party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern. The civil wrong regarding intrusion into an individual’s private matters (often referred to as intrusion upon seclusion) occurs when an individual intentionally intrudes into another individual’s private matters and the intrusion would be highly offensive or objectionable to a reasonable person."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a favorite front business for laundering money?", "options": {"A": "Restaurants", "B": "Electronics stores", "C": "Wholesale distribution", "D": "Vending machines"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Bars, restaurants, and nightclubs are commonly used to front money laundering operations. These businesses charge relatively high prices, and customers vary widely in their purchases. Vending machine operations also possess many characteristics favorable to a money laundering operation. Wholesale distribution businesses have historically been a prominent part of money laundering. Wholesale distribution is attractive for money laundering because it is well embedded in a community’s economic fabric."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a legal element that must be shown to prove a claim for fraudulent misrepresentation of material facts?", "options": {"A": "The defendant made a false statement (i.e., a misrepresentation of fact).", "B": "The defendant had a duty to disclose the information.", "C": "The defendant acted negligently.", "D": "The victim failed to exercise due care in relying on the representation."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Fraudulent misrepresentation of material facts is most often thought of when the term fraud is used. The specific elements of proof required to establish a misrepresentation claim vary somewhat according to where the fraud occurred and whether the case is brought as a criminal or civil action, but the elements normally include: The defendant made a false statement (i.e., a misrepresentation of fact). The false statement was material (i.e., the statement was sufficiently important or relevant to influence the making of a decision). The defendant knew the representation was false. The victim relied on the misrepresentation. The victim suffered damages as a result of the misrepresentation."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "At a trial in an adversarial system, an attorney asks an expert witness, “Could you please tell us about the background of this case?” This question is most likely being presented as part of direct examination of the expert witness.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Direct examination is the initial questioning of a witness by the party that called the witness (in adversarial jurisdictions) or the judge (in inquisitorial jurisdictions). Most of the time, direct examination is a nonconfrontational questioning aimed at exposing the facts and issues of the case. During direct examination in adversarial systems, expert witnesses present their findings in various ways, such as narrative questions, hypotheticals, specialized materials, and special exhibits. Experts are commonly asked to answer narrative questions, which are broad, open-ended questions that allow experts to present their opinions in their own words with minimal prompting. Fraud cases, with their divergent paths of activity and intrigue, can require complex summarizing for the facts to make any sense. Average jurors and some judges have never considered how someone could manipulate store inventories to drive up the company’s stock price and then make a profit on the phony surge. The expert witness in cases dealing with such issues often will begin testimony by recounting the narrative background of a case, the tests and experiments that were performed during the investigation, and a summary of the findings based on the witness's professional expertise. For example, during a direct examination, the judge or counsel for the party presenting the expert witness might ask open questions, such as, “Could you please tell us about the background of this case?” or “What procedures did you perform in your examination?” In contrast, a cross-examining attorney needs to control the flow of testimony and would not likely ask an expert witness a narrative question."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "In tax fraud cases, willfulness to commit the offense can be inferred from all of the following types of conduct EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Concealing assets", "B": "Destroying books or records", "C": "Covering up sources of income", "D": "Keeping a single set of books"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To establish criminal liability for tax evasion, most jurisdictions require a willful attempt to evade or defeat taxes in an unlawful manner. Willfulness can be inferred from conduct such as: Keeping a double set of books (not to be confused with keeping separate books and tax records, which might require different recording techniques) Making false entries or alterations or creating false invoices or documents Destroying books or records Concealing assets Covering up sources of income Avoiding making records that are typical in transactions of the kind Moving taxable assets beyond the government's reach (e.g., into offshore accounts) Engaging in misleading or deceitful conduct"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "In civil law jurisdictions, which of the following best describes a major role of the parties’ attorneys or advocates during civil litigation?", "options": {"A": "To ensure that the judge accurately creates the trial record", "B": "To request and obtain documentary evidence from each other prior to the trial", "C": "To examine and cross-examine witnesses", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The parties’ attorneys/advocates in civil law jurisdictions are still involved in the evidence-gathering process, but they play a more advisory role compared to attorneys in common law systems. For instance, the parties formulate questions for the judges to ask witnesses and make recommendations on how to interpret the evidence. The judge orchestrates the proceedings by calling witnesses and eliciting testimony, as well as collecting documents and physical evidence. Rather than keep a verbatim record of witness testimony, the judge makes a synopsis of the evidence that will later be used in the decision-making portion of the trial. The parties also work to ensure that the judge accurately creates the trial record and argue to frame it in a way that represents their interests."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Blue, a Certified Fraud Examiner, conducted an investigation of Brown, a fraud suspect. Brown became so upset at being investigated that he sued Blue for the common law civil wrong of intentional infliction of emotional distress. For Brown to prevail, he has to show that:", "options": {"A": "Blue acted intentionally or recklessly", "B": "Brown actually suffered severe distress as a result of Blue's conduct", "C": "Blue engaged in extreme and outrageous conduct", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To recover for intentional infliction of emotional distress, the plaintiff must prove all of the following elements: The defendant engaged in extreme and outrageous conduct. The defendant acted intentionally or recklessly (i.e., the defendant intended that his conduct would cause severe emotional distress, or he acted recklessly with regard to whether his actions would cause severe emotional distress). The victim actually did suffer emotional or mental distress as a result of the defendant's conduct."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "In the event that the person questioning a witness at trial is using blatantly unfair practices, which of the following is the best way for the witness to respond?", "options": {"A": "Continue answering questions unless otherwise directed by the court.", "B": "Argue with the questioner.", "C": "Appeal to the judge.", "D": "Refuse to answer further questions."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "It is not the witness’s job to argue with or challenge the person conducting questioning. The witness should simply try to get through the questioning in the most professional way possible. If the questioning party uses blatantly unfair practices, the fact finder will take note, and such practices might hurt the opposing side's case. In no circumstances should the witness argue. In adversarial proceedings, the counsel who called the witness is tasked with objecting to questioning that is improper, so the witness should continue answering the questions until an objection is made, and then follow the court’s directions. In inquisitorial proceedings, the judge should intervene if questioning is improper."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Because the Certified Fraud Examiner (CFE) credential denotes proven expertise in fraud prevention, detection, and deterrence, CFEs are automatically qualified to give testimony as to their opinion about fraud-related issues involved in a case.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Before admitting expert testimony, the judge must make sure the person is qualified. In adversarial jurisdictions, the evaluation process mainly centers around the candidate’s formal education and work experience—whether that includes 30 years in law enforcement or ten years in a large accounting firm. But credentials also cover the candidate’s: awards and honors; licensing or certification; technical training; published books and journal articles; and positions in professional associations, societies, and organizations. The important thing to remember is that a person can be qualified as an expert based on either special training or experience. Although professional designations are considered in evaluating credentials as an expert witness, the determination of whether someone is an \"expert\" is made on a case-by-case basis. Therefore, a professional designation does not automatically qualify someone as an expert for purposes of testifying in court. Inquisitorial systems tend to have more standardized requirements for expert witnesses, such as nationalized qualifications or certifications. Even so, the CFE designation alone will not meet these standards, and judges may still make a discretionary determination regarding the expert’s qualifications."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "In general, for a contract, transaction, or scheme to be classified as an investment contract, the instrument must be purchased by investors who display management activity in the instrument’s enterprise and have expectations of making profits that are to be derived from their own efforts.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In many countries, the term security includes investment contracts. The leading global definition of investment contract provides that a contract, transaction, or scheme is an investment contract if all of the following four elements are met: There is an investment of money or other asset. The investment is in a common enterprise. The investment was made with expectations of making a profit. The profits are to come solely from the efforts of people other than the investor. To qualify as a security under this definition of investment contract, the essential managerial efforts, which affect the success or failure of the enterprise, must come from someone other than the investor. As a general rule, the more actively involved an investor is in the enterprise, the less likely it is that an investment contract will be found to exist."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is an element that must be proven to establish a perjury offense?", "options": {"A": "The defendant made the statement with knowledge of its falsity", "B": "The defendant made a false statement while under oath", "C": "The defendant made a false statement that was material", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Perjury is an intentional false statement given under oath on a material point at issue. The basic elements for the crime of perjury are as follows: The defendant made a false statement. The defendant made the false statement while under oath. The false statement was material or relevant to the proceeding. The defendant made the statement with knowledge of its falsity. Laws that criminalize perjury, however, do not require that the false statement be given in a court of law. Generally, the forum for a perjurious statement includes any court proceeding, depositions in connection with litigation, bail hearings, venue hearings, suppression hearings, and so on. Thus, an individual can commit perjury for false statements made somewhere other than a court of law. Also, for a statement to be perjurious, it must be material. Generally, a statement is material if it tends to influence, or is capable of influencing, the decision of the decision-making body to whom it is addressed."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following best describes the prosecution’s right to obtain disclosure of information from defendants in criminal proceedings in adversarial jurisdictions?", "options": {"A": "The prosecution is not entitled to any disclosures.", "B": "The prosecution is entitled to any relevant disclosures.", "C": "The prosecution is heavily limited in disclosures it may obtain, but it might be entitled to some types of evidence that form the basis of the defendant’s case.", "D": "The prosecution is typically entitled to more disclosures from the defendant than parties in civil litigation."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Generally speaking, discovery in adversarial jurisdictions is more secretive than in inquisitorial systems, especially in criminal cases. Both the defense and the prosecution typically have far fewer rights to access information possessed by the other party than parties in noncriminal (i.e., civil) litigation. The prosecution is heavily limited in disclosures it may obtain, and the defendant typically has the right to refuse to testify. The prosecution generally must obtain evidence through search warrants or other means, rather than by requesting the items from the defendant. However, the defense might still be required to turn over certain types of evidence that it intends to use at trial, such as the basis for any legal defenses raised, documents or tangible items, results of tests intended to be used at trial, statements of expert witnesses it plans to use at trial, and other items as required by the laws of the jurisdiction. The defense is similarly limited in what it may request from the prosecution. The defendant typically does not have a right to the work product of the prosecutor, which includes reports, memoranda, and other internal documents made by the prosecuting attorney in preparing for and prosecuting the case. However, most jurisdictions also require prosecutors to turn over all exculpatory evidence that would tend to refute the guilt or mitigate the punishment of the defendant."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning mobile payments is FALSE?", "options": {"A": "Mobile payments or transactions are those facilitated through the use of an account associated with a mobile phone.", "B": "In most countries, mobile phone accounts that can be used to send funds or purchase items are regulated in the same way as bank accounts.", "C": "Money launderers often use mobile phone accounts to send funds to foreign accounts or otherwise layer illicit assets.", "D": "Mobile payments allow for the money launderer to potentially remain anonymous if a prepaid phone is used."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Mobile payments, also known as mobile banking, involve using an account associated with a mobile phone—as opposed to cash, credit cards, and debit cards—to facilitate transactions. Similar to the way in which credit and debit cards significantly cut into the use of checks and cash for consumer transactions, mobile payments are likely to grow in popularity. As compared to other transaction methods, mobile payments are vulnerable to money laundering schemes in a few key ways. For one thing, given that mobile payments are still in the process of growing and developing definition, regulations are not as sophisticated or complete as they are for older payment systems. For another thing, many developing countries lack functional AML and anti-terrorism laws, making mobile payments outside of the jurisdiction even more difficult to prevent and trace. Also, a user can send mobile payments to almost anywhere in the world, making them a tool that launderers often use to move funds to foreign jurisdictions. In addition, the use of prepaid phones causes substantial money laundering issues because the owner of a prepaid phone can be virtually anonymous. Prepaid phones can be purchased with cash, and the user typically does not need to provide personal information to open or add funds to an account associated with the phone. Anonymity is a strong attraction for launderers because it helps to obscure the paper/digital trail leading back to them."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "In civil cases in some common law jurisdictions, the jury verdict does not need to be unanimous.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When juries are used for civil trials in common law jurisdictions, the requirements are typically less stringent than in criminal trials. For instance, it is common for the minimum number of jurors to be lower for civil cases. Additionally, in many jurisdictions, civil trials are less likely to require a unanimous jury verdict than criminal trials."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "To launder funds, a consultant reports payments for services that he never actually provided. He then deposits unrelated illicit assets disguised as payments for the fake services. This laundering technique is called overstating revenues.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Overstating revenues occurs when the money launderer records more income on a business’s books than the business actually generates. The fictitious revenue accounts for the illegal funds that are secretly inserted into the company."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "A report by a Certified Fraud Examiner states that $11,354.56 was withdrawn without authorization from the plaintiff’s business on December 3, and, on December 6 of the same year, $11,354.56 was deposited into an account owned by the defendant. During a criminal trial for theft against the defendant, the government introduces this information as evidence of the defendant’s guilt. What type of evidence is the information contained in this report?", "options": {"A": "Circumstantial evidence", "B": "Indirect evidence", "C": "Inferential evidence", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are two basic types of admissible evidence: direct evidence and circumstantial evidence. Direct evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue directly, such as eyewitness testimony or a confession. Circumstantial evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove facts in issue indirectly, by inference."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following most accurately describes the primary purpose of securities regulation?", "options": {"A": "To balance the legitimate needs of businesses to raise capital against the need to protect investors", "B": "To restrict the exchange of securities between buyers and sellers", "C": "To eliminate market risk", "D": "To prevent banking panics"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The primary purpose of securities regulation is to balance the legitimate needs of businesses to raise capital against the need to protect investors."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Assuming that the relevant jurisdiction recognizes each of the legal defenses below, which of the following is the best defense against a tax fraud charge, provided that the facts will support the defense?", "options": {"A": "Lack of deficiency", "B": "Reliance on an attorney", "C": "Reliance on an accountant", "D": "Ignorance of the law"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A suspect or a criminal defendant might raise various defenses to accusations of tax fraud. For example, the defendant can establish that there is no deficiency. If there is no deficiency, there is no tax liability. This is generally the best defense, if available, because several other defenses might negate willfulness, but do not necessarily eliminate a tax liability with interest and penalties."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "In systems using adversarial processes, an attorney may impeach an opposing party’s witness by showing that the witness:", "options": {"A": "Is influenced by bias or self-interest", "B": "Has a reputation for untruthfulness", "C": "Made prior inconsistent statements", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Impeachment is the practice of questioning a witness’s knowledge or credibility. In adversarial processes, the adverse party is usually entitled to offer evidence to impeach the testimony or credibility of a witness during cross-examination. However, because cross-examination is absent from inquisitorial processes, impeachment is not an issue for civil law systems using inquisitorial processes. There are numerous ways an attorney might impeach a witness, but the most common ways include efforts to show that the witness: Is influenced by bias or self-interest Has an impaired ability to observe Made prior inconsistent statements Has been convicted of a felony or equivalent crime Has a reputation for untruthfulness"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE statement about laws criminalizing false statements to government agencies?", "options": {"A": "An individual can be found guilty for making a false statement even if the government did not suffer a loss in reliance on it.", "B": "An individual can be found guilty for making a false statement only if the statement is made directly to a governmental department or agency.", "C": "An individual can be found guilty for making a false statement only if the statement was made under oath.", "D": "An individual can be found guilty for making a false statement even if the individual did not know the statement was false at the time the statement was made."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Laws prohibiting false claims and statements to government agencies make it illegal for a person to lie to, or conceal material information from, a government agency. A false claim is an assertion of a right to government money, property, or services that contains a misrepresentation. A false statement is an oral or written communication, declaration, or assertion that is factually untrue. Generally, to prove a violation, the government must show that the defendant: Knowingly and willfully (or with reckless disregard for truth or falsity) Made a false claim or statement (or used a false document) That was material (i.e., sufficiently important or relevant to influence decision making) Regarding a matter within the jurisdiction of a government agency With knowledge of its falsity An act is done knowingly and willfully if it is done voluntarily and intentionally and not by mistake or another innocent reason. Thus, an individual can be found guilty for making a false statement or claim only if the individual knew the statement or claim was false at the time it was made. Also, the following are general rules with regard to laws criminalizing false claims and statements to government agencies: An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the claim or statement is not made directly to a governmental department or agency. That is, a false claim or statement need not be made directly to the government; it can be made to a third party as long as it involves a matter within the jurisdiction of a governmental department or agency. An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the government was not deceived by the falsity. An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the government did not rely on the falsity. An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the government did not suffer a loss in reliance on the falsity. For an individual to be found guilty of making a false claim or statement, the claim or statement at issue must have been capable of influencing the government entity involved."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Greg purchased restaurant supplies from a supplier with a lump sum of $15,000 in cash. Under the best practices in the Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations concerning large cash transactions with customers, the restaurant supplier would be required to report the transaction to the government.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Under the best practices provided in the FATF’s Recommendations, countries should implement a reporting requirement for financial institutions and designated nonfinancial businesses and professions (DNFBPs) that engage in cash transactions above the jurisdiction's designated threshold. The reports should cover domestic and international cash transactions. Many jurisdictions implement this reporting requirement. Note that the recommended reporting requirement does not apply to everyone; it only applies to financial institutions and DNFBPs. DNFBPs include: Casinos (including Internet- and ship-based casinos) Real estate agents Dealers in precious metals and stones Legal professionals at professional firms (not internal legal professionals) Trust and company service providers"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "During the examining phase of a criminal proceeding in inquisitorial jurisdictions, a judge or magistrate reviews evidence from the investigation, collects further evidence, and creates the written evidentiary record to be used at trial.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Criminal proceedings in inquisitorial jurisdictions typically are divided into three phases: the investigative phase, the examining phase, and the trial. The discovery process occurs primarily in the first two of these three phases. In the investigative stage, the public prosecutor, judge, or both (depending on the jurisdiction’s process) collect documentary and tangible evidence regarding the case. The investigating party then decides whether there is sufficient evidence to submit the case for prosecution. If there is sufficient evidence, the case moves on to the examining phase, which is mostly conducted in writing. The judge completes a written record of the evidence and may also collect testimony and additional evidence. If the judge certifies that there is a valid case against the accused, the matter moves forward to trial. The trial commences with the exhibition of the examining record before the parties and the trial judge, jury, or panel. The parties argue their case before the trial judge (or jury, if applicable). In inquisitorial trial proceedings, the evidentiary record is already available at the outset of the trial, whereas the entirety of each party’s evidence is produced and recorded at trial in adversarial jurisdictions."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Steven, an investment professional, was responsible for managing the brokerage account of his client Joe Fisher. Joe had little investment experience and trusted Steven to control his account. Over an eight-month period, Steven executed more than one hundred trades on Joe’s behalf for the purpose of increasing his own commissions. Steven executed the trades without regard for Joe’s investment goals. This securities fraud scheme is best known as:", "options": {"A": "Common law system", "B": "Statutory law system", "C": "Civil law system", "D": "Precedential law system"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Churning is the excessive trading of a customer account to generate commissions while disregarding the customer’s interests. Specifically, churning occurs when an investment professional excessively trades an account for the purpose of increasing his commissions instead of furthering the customer’s investment goals. Overview of the Legal System 59 of 354 In a particular country, the judicial system involves courts applying laws from codified statutes to each case. The court is not required to consider previous similar court decisions when deciding legal issues. Which of the following best describes this judicial system? Almost every country can be classified as having either a common law or a civil law judicial system; knowing the differences between the two is essential to understanding how legal and judicial processes work in foreign jurisdictions. Civil law systems apply laws from an accepted set of codified principles or compiled statutes. Individual cases are then decided in accordance with these basic tenets. Under a civil law system, judges or judicial administrators are bound only by the civil code and not by the previous decisions of other courts. In deciding legal issues, a civil law judge applies the various codified principles to each case."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "In most common law jurisdictions, plaintiffs in a civil trial must prove their case beyond a reasonable doubt.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In common law jurisdictions, the burden of proof for the civil plaintiff is lower than for the criminal prosecutor. In most cases, civil plaintiffs must prove their case only by the preponderance of the evidence, meaning that it is more probable than not that the defendant is liable. In contrast, criminal prosecutors must prove their case beyond a reasonable doubt."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Which of the following documents is at the heart of the international money laundering control effort?", "options": {"A": "The Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations", "B": "Model Money Laundering Crime Control Act", "C": "The Hague Convention", "D": "The Swiss Convention"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) releases various model policies and data to help countries combat money laundering, the most influential of which is its International Standards on Combating Money Laundering and the Financing of Terrorism and Proliferations: the FATF Recommendations (referred to as the Recommendations). The FATF created the most comprehensive standard with which to measure a country’s anti-money laundering, counterterrorism, and nuclear proliferation laws and policies. They serve as a basic framework of laws that its members should have."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Craig and Donna each own 40% of the shares of Indiewealth and serve on its board of directors. George is also a shareholder, but he is not a member of the board of directors. Donna dies, and her son, Steven, inherits her shares of Indiewealth and replaces her on the board. Steven, however, is inattentive to Indiewealth’s corporate affairs. During this time, Craig diverts corporate funds for personal use, and consequently, Indiewealth becomes insolvent. If George decides to sue Steven for violating his fiduciary duties, under what theory is he likely to file the suit?", "options": {"A": "Violating the duty of responsibility", "B": "Violating the duty of reasonableness", "C": "Violating the duty of loyalty", "D": "Violating the duty of care"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Steven failed to act as a reasonably prudent director would under similar circumstances; therefore, George would likely file suit against Steven for violating his duty of care. People in a position of trust or fiduciary relationship—such as officers, directors, high-level employees of a corporation or business, and agents and brokers—owe certain duties to their principals or employers, and any action that runs afoul of such fiduciary duties constitutes a breach. The principal fiduciary duties are loyalty and care. The duty of loyalty requires that the employee/agent act solely in the best interest of the employer/principal, free of any self-dealing, conflicts of interest, or other abuse of the principal for personal advantage. The duty of care means that people in a fiduciary relationship must act with such care as an ordinarily prudent person would employ in similar positions."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Of the choices below, which is the proper sequence of cycles in a money laundering process?", "options": {"A": "Placement, bank complicity, and structuring", "B": "Layering, placement, and integration", "C": "Placement, layering, and integration", "D": "Integration, structuring, and placement"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Placement is the first stage of the money laundering process. In this stage, the launderer introduces his illegal profits into the financial system. It is at this stage that legislation has been developed to prevent launderers from depositing or converting large amounts of cash at financial institutions or taking cash out of the country. Money laundering schemes are most often detected at the placement stage. If the placement of the initial funds goes undetected, the launderer can design numerous financial transactions in complex patterns to prevent detection. For example, the launderer can move funds between bank accounts, transfer funds from one form of currency to another, or transfer money between businesses. This stage of the money laundering process is referred to as layering. Integration is the final stage in the laundering process. In this stage, the money is integrated back into the economy in a way that makes it appear to be part of a legitimate business transaction."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Which of the following tax evasion schemes would be accurately classified as an income and wealth tax evasion scheme?", "options": {"A": "Smuggling goods into a jurisdiction to avoid paying excise taxes", "B": "Fraudulently applying for a refund of a value-added tax", "C": "Pretending to transfer assets to another person or entity to lower tax liability", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Taxes on periodic income or wealth (e.g., real property taxes) are a source of revenue for many governments, but fraudsters often commit tax evasion by falsifying or omitting material information. Common forms of criminal income and wealth tax evasion include: Failing to submit a report of one’s taxable income, if such a report is required Intentionally misrepresenting one’s income or wealth Pretending to transfer assets to another person or entity to lower tax liability Intentionally failing to withhold the taxable portion of an employee’s income, if so required Failing to report foreign bank accounts or other taxable assets, if required Falsely claiming income was earned in another jurisdiction to lower tax liability Abusing excise and value-added taxes would fall under consumption tax evasion schemes."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Page, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is investigating a suspect's sources of income. Page notices that funds available to the suspect include the suspect's interest in a restaurant/bar. Page has surveilled the establishment several times and notices that the business has very few customers, even during peak times. Yet the income reported from this restaurant/bar is substantial. Of the following list, in which money laundering scheme might the suspect be involved?", "options": {"A": "Bankruptcy scheme", "B": "Front business scheme", "C": "Alternative remittance system scheme", "D": "Trade-based laundering scheme"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Money laundering is the disguising of the existence, nature, source, control, beneficial ownership, location, and disposition of property derived from criminal activity. Bars, restaurants, and nightclubs are commonly used to front money laundering operations for a number of reasons. These businesses charge relatively high prices, and customers vary widely in their purchases. Sales are generally in cash, and it is difficult to match the cost of providing food, liquor, and entertainment with the revenues they produce. As a result, a red flag of front businesses is observing a low amount of business, despite the business’s books showing a relatively high income for that period."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "A money laundering scheme cannot be successful until the _________ is eliminated or made so complex that individual steps cannot be easily traced.", "options": {"A": "Placement", "B": "Paper trail", "C": "Evidence of the initial fraud", "D": "Modus operandi"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A money laundering scheme cannot be successful until the paper trail is eliminated or made so complex that individual steps cannot be easily traced. The number of steps used depends on how much distance the money launderer wishes to put between the illegally earned cash and the laundered asset into which it is converted. A greater number of steps increases the complexity of tracing the funds, but it also increases the length of the paper trail and the chance that the transaction will be reported."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "In civil law systems, the standard of proof in civil trials and criminal trials is generally the same.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The standard of proof in civil law jurisdictions typically does not change in criminal and civil trials; it is often described as the inner conviction of the judge, sometimes called the conviction intime standard. This standard requires stronger evidence than the common law preponderance of evidence standard, but not as much as the common law beyond a reasonable doubt standard."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning civil trials in common law jurisdictions is most accurate?", "options": {"A": "The judge typically presents the evidence at trial.", "B": "The defendant is typically the first party to present evidence at trial.", "C": "The plaintiff is typically the first party to present evidence at trial.", "D": "The jury typically decides the order in which evidence is presented."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In the adversarial process present in most common law jurisdictions, the trial begins with the plaintiff presenting the evidence against the defendant. The plaintiff calls witnesses to testify as to facts and present documents, photographs, or other kinds of evidence. The defendant may then cross-examine the plaintiff's witnesses to test their evidence. Once the plaintiff has presented his case, the defendant can present his own evidence, which may include calling witnesses, and the plaintiff can cross-examine the defendant's witnesses."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "In the context of an employee interview, all of the following actions could result in liability for false imprisonment EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Locking the door to an interview room", "B": "Telling the interviewee he may not leave the room", "C": "Telling the interviewee that he is required to answer questions", "D": "Standing in front of an exit to an interview room"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "False imprisonment is the unlawful restraint by one person of the physical liberty of another without consent or legal justification. A claim of false imprisonment might arise if an employee is detained in any way during a search or interview. Generally, an employer is entitled to question an employee at work about a violation of company policy without incurring liability as long as the employee submits to the questioning voluntarily; that is, not as a result of threats or force. There are no precise rules as to when a false imprisonment occurs, but factors such as the length, nature, and manner of the interview might determine whether liability arises. Other factors used to determine if an individual has been falsely imprisoned include: Conducting an interview in a room that is small and confined in nature (e.g., small, windowless, not easily accessible) Conducting an interview in a room with severe lighting Requiring the employee’s presence or continued presence by any amount of physical force (e.g., holding the employee’s arm to escort him or pushing the employee into a chair) Using violent behavior of any kind during the interview, including yelling, pounding on desks, or kicking furniture or walls Using a physical barrier to restrain the employee (e.g., locking the interview room’s door or standing in front of an interview room’s exit) Making threats of immediate physical force to restrain the employee Conducting an interview in the presence of numerous people"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE definition of insider trading?", "options": {"A": "Issuing equity illegally through capital markets", "B": "Trading in securities based on material, nonpublic information", "C": "Using publicly available information to manage investment portfolios", "D": "Systematically trading accounts against each other"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Insider trading occurs when an insider—someone who possesses inside information about a security—buys or sells securities on the basis of material information about the security that is not available to the public. Inside information is any material, nonpublic information about a security that is not generally available to the public and that could affect the security’s price. Examples of insider trading include: Corporate officers, directors, and employees who traded their corporation’s securities after learning of significant, confidential business developments Friends, business associates, family members of corporate officers, directors, and employees who traded the corporation’s securities after learning of significant, confidential business developments Employees of law, banking, and accounting firms who were given inside information to provide services to the corporation whose securities they traded Government employees who traded a corporation’s securities after learning of inside information about the corporation because of their employment with the government"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Bailey, a Certified Fraud Examiner in an adversarial system, is being cross-examined in court on his expert opinion relating to a fraud matter. Darwin, a defense attorney, asks Bailey a question that is phrased in an overly and unnecessarily complex manner. Which of the following is the best way for Bailey to respond?", "options": {"A": "Object to the question's phrasing.", "B": "Ask the judge for a recess.", "C": "Request that the question be rephrased.", "D": "Avoid answering the question by talking about something else."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Generally, witnesses should never give away or volunteer free information during cross-examination in adversarial proceedings. When providing an answer during cross-examination, it might be difficult to avoid getting trapped in various assumptions, what-if scenarios, and generalities presented by counsel. Opposing counsel might also pose overly complex questions in an attempt to convolute the witness’s responses. If this occurs, the witness should retrench by asking for the question to be rephrased in smaller components."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Which of the following is the cross-examination technique that entails getting the expert witness to admit a great amount of time being spent on a specific matter, and then selecting an area to highlight in which the witness has not done much work?", "options": {"A": "Sounding board", "B": "Sidelining", "C": "Myopic vision", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "During cross-examination, the questioning party might employ various methods to discredit a witness or to diminish the importance of a witness’s testimony. Myopic vision, a tactic primarily used against expert witnesses, entails getting the expert witness to admit excessive time being spent on a specific matter, and then selecting an area to highlight in which the witness is unsure or has not done much work. This area might not be central to the issues in the case or to the conclusions reached. Then, the questioning party will make a large issue of it and prove that the witness's vision is myopic in that the work was limited in extent or scope and, as such, substandard."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning judges and juries is MOST ACCURATE?", "options": {"A": "Juries primarily decide issues of law in adversarial jurisdictions.", "B": "In a bench trial in adversarial jurisdictions, the judge only decides questions of law.", "C": "Inquisitorial judicial processes are those that do not use juries in a fact-finding role.", "D": "In serious cases, some inquisitorial jurisdictions use juries that include both judges and laypersons."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "While juries can be found in both adversarial and inquisitorial jurisdictions, most adversarial jurisdictions actively use juries as the fact-finding body, while the judge decides issues of law. However, some cases in adversarial jurisdictions (often called bench trials) are decided factually and legally by a judge. The judge in an inquisitorial process both serves as the traditional fact finder and makes determinations on issues of law. However, some inquisitorial systems will use juries, laypersons, or a combination of judges (or legal professionals) and laypersons in serious cases."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Assuming a jurisdiction is adhering to the Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations, if a securities broker suspects that a client might be engaging in transactions to launder money, the broker is required to report the suspicious transactions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Under FATF Recommendation 20, a financial institution should be required to file a report when it “suspects or has reasonable grounds to suspect that funds are the proceeds of a criminal activity, or are related to terrorist financing.” The Recommendations define financial institutions to include: Depository and lending institutions (i.e., traditional banks) Money services businesses Financial guarantors Securities brokers or traders Security issuing services Investment portfolio managers Parties that invest, administer, or manage funds or assets on behalf of others Insurance companies servicing life insurance and other investment-related insurance"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "In an adversarial system, the testimony of an expert witness will be admitted if the testimony is informative, at least to some extent, to any issue.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A trial judge will not admit an expert witness’s testimony unless the judge determines that the expert is a qualified practitioner and that the testimony being offered by the expert is relevant to the facts of the case and reliable. The qualification element addresses whether the individual is qualified to assist the trier of fact. Relevant testimony will assist the jury in understanding the evidence or determining a fact at issue. To be relevant, the proposed testimony must be sufficiently related to the facts of the case so that it will aid the jury in resolving a factual dispute. To be reliable, the testimony must be based on sufficient facts and data, and it must be the product of reliable methodology that has been reliably applied to the facts of the case."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Harris is retained to provide an opinion involving specialized knowledge in the accounting field for a trial. Which of the following best describes his role?", "options": {"A": "Informal expert", "B": "Consulting expert", "C": "Expert witness", "D": "Fact witness"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Harris is providing expert testimony at trial, making him an expert witness. Testifying expert witnesses give opinion testimony when specialized knowledge is needed to help the fact finder understand evidence or determine a fact in issue. Unlike fact (or lay) witnesses, expert witnesses usually may express opinions or draw conclusions in their testimony."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Prosecutorial bargaining does not occur in civil law systems.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A method of disposing of cases in a growing number of countries is through bargaining agreements, which occur when a defendant makes an agreement with prosecutors to plead guilty or submit a recorded confession in exchange for lesser charges or a reduced sentence. Most civil law countries do not have pleas, per se (i.e., there is no option to enter a guilty plea), but there can still be bargaining agreements. A defendant can enter a confession, but the confession is submitted as evidence in an otherwise standard proceeding. However, a confession in evidence clearly reduces the difficulty of prosecuting the case, so an agreement between the prosecution, the defendant, and the court can be made to reduce the sentence in exchange for a voluntary confession."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is a basic principle for the protection of data privacy on which most data privacy laws are built?", "options": {"A": "All personal information must be used only for the original specified purpose", "B": "All personal information must be kept accurate and up-to-date", "C": "All personal information must be obtained fairly and lawfully", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Most countries have data privacy laws (also known as information privacy or data protection laws) that protect personal information about individuals from disclosure, unauthorized access, and misuse. Even though countries have their own requirements for the protection of data privacy, most countries impose requirements that converge around the principles that all personal information must be: Obtained fairly and lawfully Used only for the original specified purpose Adequate, relevant, and not excessive to the specified purpose Kept accurate and up-to-date Accessible to the data subject Protected by reasonable security safeguards Destroyed after its purpose is completed"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Digital currencies are attractive to money launderers because these payment devices often allow anonymity in transactions and tend to be less strictly regulated than other payment systems.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Digital currencies are a type of online payment method that has emerged as a money laundering concern. Broadly defined, digital currencies are currencies that exist and are traded in a digital format. The term typically excludes government-backed currencies, despite the fact that they can also exist and be traded digitally. Digital currencies can come in several forms and can have limited or broad uses. Among the most popular digital currencies is Bitcoin, which features a peer-to-peer network that allows users to send units of the currency to each other online without the use of a traditional financial institution. Digital currencies are often vulnerable to money laundering because many of them function as international person-to-person payment systems that cross jurisdictional boundaries, creating difficulties for authorities pursuing enforcement or legal actions. As is typical with developing payment systems, digital currencies face less strict regulations than payments made through traditional financial institutions. Furthermore, many service providers who exchange or otherwise deal with digital currencies do not have effective customer identification or recordkeeping practices, while others actively promote anonymous payments."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a legal element that the government must show to prove a criminal conspiracy?", "options": {"A": "The defendant entered into an agreement to commit an illegal act", "B": "The defendant knew the purpose of the agreement and intentionally joined in the agreement", "C": "At least one of the conspirators knowingly committed at least one overt act in furtherance of the conspiracy", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Conspiracy refers to a situation in which two or more people agree to commit an illegal act. The essential elements that must be shown to prove a conspiracy are as follows: The defendant entered into an agreement with at least one other person to commit an illegal act. The defendant knew the purpose of the agreement and intentionally joined in the agreement. At least one of the conspirators knowingly committed at least one overt act in furtherance of the conspiracy. Under the first element, the government must prove that the defendant reached an agreement or understanding to commit an illegal act with at least one other person. The conspirators must agree about the precise illegal act. Under the second element, the government must establish that the defendant knew of the conspiracy’s existence and its objective. The government, however, does not have to establish that the defendant knew all the details or objectives of the conspiracy, and it does not have to prove that the defendant knew the identity of all the participants in the conspiracy. Finally, the purpose of the conspiracy need not be accomplished for a violation to occur, but at least one of the co-conspirators must have carried out at least one overt act in furtherance of the conspiracy. The overt act need not be criminal and could be as innocuous as making a phone call or writing a letter."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Smurfing is a money laundering scheme where a criminal purchases multiple life insurance contracts and exercises the redemption clauses in each of them.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Many countries require financial institutions to report all currency transactions above a certain threshold (e.g., more than $10,000) to the government. However, criminals might attempt to illegally evade these laws. Structuring occurs when a deposit or other transfer is made using a method that is specifically designed to avoid regulatory reporting requirements or an institution’s internal controls. The most common type of illegal structuring scheme in the money laundering context is smurfing, where the launderer breaks up the illicit money into smaller amounts and deposits it into bank accounts or purchases cashier’s checks, traveler’s checks, or money orders. A red flag of a smurfing scheme is a customer who attempts to make many deposits just under the reporting threshold."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Baron is currently being prosecuted for financial statement fraud for allegedly intentionally over-reporting earnings. Although Baron did over-report income, he did not do so on purpose. Under these facts, Baron would likely benefit the most from using mistake as his legal defense, provided that his jurisdiction recognizes this defense.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A defense is an assertion by a defendant in a criminal or civil suit that seeks to explain away guilt or civil liability for damages. The facts indicate that Baron lacked the intent to over-report earnings and that his doing so was a mistake. In some situations, mistake may be used as a defense. Whether a defendant can raise a defense depends on the offense and the existence and availability of defenses in the relevant jurisdiction. Common defenses include: alibi, consent, the court’s lack of jurisdiction, duress, entrapment, ignorance of facts, infancy, insanity, legal impossibility, mistake, necessity of the act, protection of others, protection of property, public duty, self-defense, statute of limitations (common law systems) or period of prescriptions (civil law systems), and triviality of the offense."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Which of the following is a reason why litigants involved in cross-border litigation should not expect to have the privilege laws from their own jurisdiction applied when engaged in cross-border litigation?", "options": {"A": "Courts are more familiar with local privilege laws than the laws of foreign jurisdictions", "B": "Characterizations and conceptualizations of privileges vary among different countries", "C": "Courts are more inclined to apply their own privilege laws than the laws of foreign jurisdictions", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The rise of global markets and multi-jurisdictional transactions has resulted in an increase in disputes that span multiple jurisdictions, and the privileges that are available vary substantially by jurisdiction. There are no standardized rules of privilege for litigation in cross-border disputes, and, in some cases, there will be conflicting rules of privilege. For example, the litigants in a cross-border dispute might be required to disclose information in one jurisdiction that is protected by privilege in another jurisdiction. Accordingly, there is a lack of standardization and predictability with respect to privileges in cross-border litigation, and privilege law is a key source of uncertainty for litigants in cross-border disputes. Generally, litigants involved in cross-border litigation should not expect to have the privilege laws from their own jurisdiction applied when engaged in litigation abroad. There are several reasons for this. First, courts are more inclined to apply their own privilege law because they are more familiar with local law than the laws of foreign jurisdictions. Second, characterizations and conceptualizations of privileges vary among different countries. For instance, common law jurisdictions typically view privileges as the right of the client, but civil law jurisdictions do not. In civil law jurisdictions, communications are protected by secrecy laws that require confidentiality."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Walsh, a Certified Fraud Examiner, interviews Brock, a fraud suspect. Walsh, Brock, and Brock’s supervisor are present in the interview during which Walsh accuses Brock of cheating on his wife with a coworker. Later, Brock, angry that Walsh revealed the unflattering (albeit true) information about the affair to his supervisor, files a claim of defamation against Walsh. Brock’s claim is likely to succeed.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Generally speaking, defamation refers to the unprivileged publication of false statements about a person that causes harm to that person’s reputation. To recover for defamation, the plaintiff must generally prove all of the following elements: The defendant made an untrue statement of fact. The statement was communicated (published) to third parties. The statement was made on an unprivileged occasion. The statement damaged the subject's reputation. To be defamatory, a statement must be a statement of fact (not opinion) and be untrue. Thus, truth is an absolute defense to defamation. Here, Walsh’s statement that Brock was cheating on his wife with a coworker was true, and thus the statement was not defamatory. Accordingly, Brock’s suit for defamation will not succeed."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a smurfing scheme?", "options": {"A": "A criminal disguises illicit assets by making them appear to have originated from various small loans.", "B": "A criminal pays down debt in small chunks using electronic transfers from foreign accounts.", "C": "A criminal habitually deposits cash or purchases bearer instruments in amounts just under the jurisdiction’s currency reporting requirements.", "D": "A criminal makes large cash deposits that are well over the jurisdiction’s cash transaction threshold on a regular basis to avoid suspicion."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Many countries require financial institutions to report all currency transactions above a certain threshold (e.g., more than $10,000) to the government. However, criminals might attempt to illegally evade these laws. Structuring occurs when a deposit or other transfer is made using a method that is specifically designed to avoid regulatory reporting requirements or an institution’s internal controls. The most common type of illegal structuring scheme in the money laundering context is smurfing, where the launderer breaks up the illicit money into smaller amounts and deposits it into bank accounts or purchases cashier’s checks, traveler’s checks, or money orders. A red flag of a smurfing scheme is a customer who attempts to make many deposits just under the reporting threshold."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "In all inquisitorial court systems, parties are not allowed to hire their own expert witnesses.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Generally, inquisitorial courts appoint their own expert witness, whose testimony will be the primary expertise considered by the court. However, in some inquisitorial jurisdictions, the parties might also be able to (or required to) make experts available for the court-appointed expert to question. Therefore, while not procedurally the same, expert witnesses in both adversarial and inquisitorial systems must be prepared to have their testimony withstand the scrutiny of the opposing party’s legal counsel or the court-appointed expert."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "Judges in civil law jurisdictions are not bound by previous court decisions, but, in practice, many do use previous decisions to guide their interpretations of codes and statutes.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Almost every country can be classified as having either a common law or a civil law legal system. One of the main distinctions between civil law jurisdictions and common law jurisdictions is that judges under common law systems are bound by precedent while judges under civil law systems are not; instead, judges under civil law systems are bound by the civil code. Judges in civil law systems will, of course, have to interpret the code, but they need not rely on previous cases in doing so. As a practical matter, however, most civil judges do consider previous decisions to guide their interpretations of the code."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "If a broker who is subject to rules prohibiting securities broker-dealers from making unsuitable recommendations on investments or investment strategies recommends an investment to a client without ascertaining relevant personal and financial information about the client, the broker has violated the rules prohibiting unsuitable recommendations.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In many countries, securities laws and regulations impose a suitability requirement on broker-dealers. Broker-dealers subject to a suitability requirement are prohibited from recommending investments or investment strategies that are unsuitable for their clients. Thus, making unsuitable recommendations (e.g., recommending high-risk options to a senior citizen with limited assets) is prohibited in countries with such suitability requirements. In most countries, a suitability requirement only arises when broker-dealers make recommendations or provide advice to clients to purchase a product. Essentially, there are two rules relating to suitability: the know-your-customer rule and the suitability rule. The know-your-customer rule provides that securities broker-dealers must know their customer financially to effectively service the customer’s account and minimize the risk of recommending an inappropriate investment. To comply with the know-your-customer rule, broker-dealers must use due diligence to ascertain relevant personal and financial information about clients and potential clients in regard to opening and maintaining accounts. Thus, this form of suitability violation occurs when a broker recommends an investment or an investment strategy to a client without having conducted due diligence to ascertain relevant personal and financial information about the client. In addition to the know-your-customer requirement, there are suitability requirements that broker-dealers must follow when making recommendations to a client. Suitability rules prohibit broker-dealers from making recommendations to clients if they do not have reasonable grounds for believing that the recommendations are suitable for the respective clients. That is, a suitability rule requires a broker-dealer to make a customer-specific determination of suitability and to tailor his recommendations to the customer’s financial profile and investment objectives."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "To prove that a defendant committed criminal perjury, the government prosecutor must show that the defendant, while in a court of law, knowingly made a false statement that influenced the jury’s decision.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Perjury is an intentional false statement given under oath on a material point at issue. The basic elements for the crime of perjury are as follows: The defendant made a false statement. The defendant made the false statement while under oath. The false statement was material or relevant to the proceeding. The defendant made the statement with knowledge of its falsity. Laws that criminalize perjury, however, do not require that the false statement be given in a court of law or that the false statement influence a jury’s decision. Generally, the forum for a perjurious statement includes any court proceeding, depositions in connection with litigation, bail hearings, venue hearings, suppression hearings, and so on. Thus, an individual can commit perjury for false statements made somewhere other than a court of law."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Which of the following does NOT accurately reflect the customer due diligence procedures for financial institutions under the Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations?", "options": {"A": "The institution should identify the beneficial owner of the account.", "B": "The customer’s business relationships and transactions should be checked once to ensure they are consistent with the customer’s profile.", "C": "The customer’s identity should be verified through reliable, independent sources.", "D": "The institution should discover the intended nature of the customer’s account or service."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The FATF's Recommendations state that the customer’s business relationships and transactions should be subject to ongoing monitoring and not just a single check. The Recommendations set out the fundamental measures that financial institutions must take to identify and verify the identity of customers and beneficial owners. Although it is most important to conduct due diligence when a business relationship is first established, due diligence should be exercised on an ongoing basis. These requirements set firm and detailed standards while also providing flexibility and allowing adaptation to new industry practices. In addition to the fundamental obligations, the Recommendations also deals with other issues, such as the timing of verification, the measures to be taken with respect to existing customers and for legal persons or arrangements, and when simplified customer due diligence (CDD) measures may be appropriate. According to the Recommendations, the CDD measures to be taken by financial institutions and designated nonfinancial businesses and professions are: Identifying the customer and verifying the customer’s identity through reliable, independent source documents or data Identifying the beneficial owner of the account or service, including the ownership and control structure of organizations Obtaining information and understanding the purpose and intended nature of the business relationships involved in the account or service Conducting ongoing due diligence on the business relationship and transactions of the customer to ensure that they are consistent with the customer’s profile"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "A statute that prohibits fraud involving the use of a jurisdiction’s mail or telecommunication systems is most properly characterized as what type of law?", "options": {"A": "Common law", "B": "Procedural", "C": "Substantive", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Law can be categorized as substantive or procedural law. Substantive law defines the type of conduct permissible and the penalties for violation; it is composed of the basic laws of rights and duties. When people say an act is “against the law,” they are referring to substantive law. A statute that prohibits fraud involving the use of a jurisdiction’s mail or telecommunication systems would be considered a criminal statute; therefore, it is most properly characterized as substantive law."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Chad has been retained by an attorney to testify as an expert witness at John’s trial. Coincidentally, Chad also met John while attending a university many years earlier. The attorney is compensating Chad for his services. Which of the following statements concerning conflicts of interest is MOST ACCURATE?", "options": {"A": "Chad can only serve as an expert witness if he is able to objectively evaluate and present the case issues.", "B": "Chad can serve as an expert witness because there are not conflicts of interest in this case.", "C": "Chad should not serve as an expert witness because he is being compensated, which is a conflict of interest.", "D": "Chad should not serve as an expert witness because he knew John from attending the university, which is a conflict of interest."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When retained, experts must quickly determine if any conflicts of interest exist—or even appear to exist—in a particular case because a conflict might preclude participation. A conflict of interest exists when an expert’s ability to objectively evaluate and present an issue for a client will be impaired by any current, prior, or future relationship with parties to the litigation. Prior or ongoing relationships might suggest to others that the expert cannot provide undivided loyalty to the cause and the client. Whether a relationship causes a conflict of interest depends on the facts. Simply meeting a person does not necessarily cause a conflict, but a close personal or business relationship is more likely to give the perception of a conflict. Compensation (whether from the parties or from the court) for expert testimony services is standard, and it is not generally considered a conflict of interest. The amount of compensation can be brought up at trial, so the payment should not be above normal."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "A fraud examiner discovers that Fred, a fraud suspect, has made dozens of cash deposits over the last few months into a bank account. None of the deposits have been $10,000 or more, and none of them have been below $8,500, either. The currency reporting threshold for cash deposits at financial institutions in the jurisdiction is $10,000. Based on this information, which of the following schemes is Fred most likely committing?", "options": {"A": "Channel stuffing", "B": "Sizing currency transactions", "C": "Check tampering", "D": "Smurfing"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Many countries require financial institutions to report all currency transactions above a certain threshold (e.g., more than $10,000) to the government. However, criminals might attempt to illegally evade these laws. Structuring occurs when a deposit or other transfer is made using a method that is specifically designed to avoid regulatory reporting requirements or an institution’s internal controls. The most common type of illegal structuring scheme in the money laundering context is smurfing, where the launderer breaks up the illicit money into smaller amounts and deposits it into bank accounts or purchases cashier’s checks, traveler’s checks, or money orders. A red flag of a smurfing scheme is a customer who attempts to make many deposits just under the reporting threshold."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "The U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) not only prohibits bribes to foreign officials, it also requires publicly traded companies subject to the FCPA’s jurisdiction to keep accurate books and records and adopt internal controls to prevent improper use of corporate funds.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The U.S. FCPA has two principal components: the anti-bribery provisions and the accounting provisions. In short, the anti-bribery provisions make it unlawful to bribe foreign government officials to obtain or retain business, and the accounting provisions require publicly traded companies subject to the FCPA’s jurisdiction to keep accurate books and records and adopt internal controls to prevent improper use of corporate funds."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Which of the following scenarios would potentially result in the waiver of a client’s legal professional privilege over confidential communications with the client's attorney?", "options": {"A": "The client's legal representative shares privileged communications with an unrelated third party who has no need to know the information", "B": "The client intentionally shares privileged communications with an unrelated third party who has no need to know the information", "C": "The client inadvertently forwards an email with privileged information to unrelated third parties who have no need to know the information", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Legal professional privileges are not absolute; they are subject to waiver. Because these privileges only protect confidential communications, the protection they provide will be waived for communications disclosed to third parties who have little or nothing to do with the client’s pursuit of legal representation because such disclosures demonstrate a lack of confidentiality. Generally, waiver occurs when the client, who holds the privilege, voluntarily discloses (or consents to or encourages someone else disclosing) any significant part of the privileged communications. Although the client holds the privilege, the privilege can be waived by the client’s attorney or a third party—someone who is neither the attorney nor the client. Additionally, privilege might be lost if the client, the attorney, or a third party carelessly or inadvertently discloses confidential communications to an outside party. That is, even inadvertent disclosure can result in a waiver of privilege."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "In an insurance prepayment scheme, a money launderer purchases life insurance or a similar policy with a redemption provision and redeems the policy with the intent to make the income appear legitimate.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Insurance policies are designed to protect assets (as well as life and health), but they are also assets in their own right. As is the case with most assets, they can become part of a money laundering scheme. This scenario is a redemption scheme. A person can redeem some insurance policies, such as life insurance, before the event that triggers the insurance occurs. In other words, the insurer agrees to pay the beneficiary of the policy an amount less than what the payout on a claim occurrence (in the case of life insurance, the death of the insured) would be. Using illicit assets, launderers can purchase life insurance or other redeemable contracts for themselves or their associates. If the investigator did not know that the launderer bought the insurance policy with illicit assets, the redemption payout would appear legitimate. In an insurance prepayment scheme, the launderer makes advance payments on insurance premiums. For instance, if a health insurer allowed $10,000 in advance premium payments, then the launderer could use the illicit assets to “store” those funds. Perhaps the launderer was going to buy that health insurance anyway; now illicit assets have taken care of that bill."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "Acme Corporation initiated a bankruptcy proceeding in which all of its assets will be sold and the proceeds will be distributed to creditors. Under the World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes, which of the following parties is an appropriate option for managing Acme’s estate in the proceedings?", "options": {"A": "Acme’s creditors", "B": "Acme’s directors", "C": "An independent insolvency representative", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Under the World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes, in liquidation proceedings, management should be replaced by an insolvency representative with authority to administer the estate in the interest of creditors. Control of the estate should be surrendered immediately to the insolvency representative. In creditor-initiated filings, where circumstances warrant, an interim administrator with limited functions should be appointed to monitor the business to ensure that creditor interests are protected. Due to conflicts of interest, creditors typically do not administer estates or the debtor’s business in bankruptcy proceedings."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "An injunction is a type of equitable remedy in which a court orders a party to perform, or refrain from performing, a specific act.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "If the plaintiff in a civil case prevails, the remedy to which the plaintiff is entitled depends upon a number of factors, such as the relief sought, the facts, and the authority given to the court to grant specific relief. There are various types of civil remedies, but the following three types are most common: monetary remedies (damages), declaratory remedies, and equitable remedies. Equitable remedies are remedies used when the legal remedy by itself would be inadequate compensation for the wrong suffered. That is, equitable remedies are used when the plaintiff has no adequate remedy at law (i.e., damages are inadequate). One of the primary equitable remedies is the injunction, which is a court order by which a party is required to perform, or is restrained from performing, a specific act."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "A criminal wants to launder money by sending it to a co-conspirator in a foreign country. Rather than sending funds through a financial institution, the party pays Broker A the funds, and Broker A then directs Broker B, who lives in the foreign country, to pay the co-conspirator. Later, Broker A offsets his debt to Broker B by paying someone at the direction of Broker B. Which of the following best describes this payment scheme?", "options": {"A": "Alternative remittance system", "B": "Money services business", "C": "Prepaid access", "D": "Back-to-back loan"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Alternative remittance systems (also called parallel banking systems) are methods of transferring funds from a party at one location to another party (whether domestic or foreign) without the use of formal banking institutions. These systems are characterized by the lack of direct physical or digital transfer of currency from the sender to the receiver. Instead, in the typical alternative remittance system, the payer transfers funds to a local broker who has a connection to another broker in the region where the payee is located. The latter broker then distributes the funds to the payee. The parties involved in alternative remittance systems form a network and track their exchanges on an informal ledger. Unlike formal financial institutions, these ledgers will not generally list specific information about the payers and payees (such as bank account numbers and names) but will keep track of amounts owed. When the first broker requests that another broker in the network distribute funds, the debt is recorded in the ledgers. These debts between brokers could be paid back by offsetting transactions (i.e., the first broker pays someone locally at the request of the second broker). Alternatively, the parties could meet to settle all outstanding debts at a later time."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "The OECD Recommendation on Combating Bribery in International Business (Recommendation) urges member states to combat the bribery of foreign public officials by taking steps to improve certain areas within their respective infrastructures. Which of the following is NOT one of those primary areas?", "options": {"A": "Banking and accounting requirements and practices", "B": "Tax systems and regulations", "C": "Laws and regulations covering the handling of sensitive protected data", "D": "Criminal, civil, commercial, and administrative laws"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The Recommendation on Combating Bribery in International Business (Recommendation), which was published by the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) in 1994, urges member states to deter and penalize the bribery of foreign public officials by taking “concrete and meaningful steps” to improve the following areas within their respective infrastructures: Criminal, civil, commercial, and administrative laws Tax systems and regulations Banking and accounting requirements and practices Laws and regulations related to public subsidies, licenses, and contract procurement"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "All of the following are red flags indicating that an entity is operating a security business without the proper license or registration EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Agents with criminal records", "B": "Justified gaps in a promoter’s work history", "C": "A history of regulatory problems", "D": "Prior customer complaints"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "True brokerages are required to register and meet certain financial thresholds, and broker-dealers must register with the appropriate regulatory authority. Thus, operating a security business without a license or acting as broker-dealer without proper registration violates the law. Also, the personnel at true brokerages must be registered, and often, the salespeople at such firms must pass certain tests. There might also be other licensing or registration requirements depending on the type of business in which the brokerage engages. The following red flags might indicate that an entity is operating a security business without the proper license or registration: Agents with criminal records Unexplained gaps in a promoter’s work history Prior customer complaints A history of regulatory problems Questionable credentials Website lacks background information or contains generic contact information"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "XYZ Manufacturing has a document destruction procedure in which emails are automatically deleted after a specified period. A trading partner filed a civil lawsuit against XYZ in a civil law jurisdiction, claiming that XYZ sent fraudulent invoices via email. Under most civil law systems, the court would establish when XYZ should preserve and produce documents.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Most civil litigation concerning fraud involves many documents, tangible items, or digital information that might serve as evidence. Each jurisdiction has rules for how potential evidence should be handled. Typically, in civil law jurisdictions, the issue of when to take affirmative steps to preserve evidence is established by the court, meaning the court will dictate what evidence must be preserved and produced by the parties or others with relevant information. Due to privacy requirements in many civil law jurisdictions, retaining personal information (a very broad class of information regarding individuals) for longer than necessary might be illegal without a court order. Some civil law jurisdictions allow a party to apply for a court order to preserve evidence prior to a lawsuit being filed."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following parties might serve to make factual findings in criminal proceedings in various civil law systems?", "options": {"A": "A jury", "B": "A panel of both professional and lay judges", "C": "A judge", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In civil law systems, judges serve various roles. They are active participants in gathering evidence from the parties. Unless the civil law system allows for juries, the judge also serves as the fact finder and decides matters of law. Juries are less frequently used in a civil law system than in a common law system; they are usually reserved for serious crimes, and some countries do not use them at all. Several civil law systems feature a mixture of judges and laypersons when juries are used. For instance, a panel could have three judges and nine laypersons who would decide the outcome of the case. Alternatively, some civil law systems feature criminal trials with a panel of both professional judges and lay judges. These panels are unlike juries in the sense that they do not include randomly selected peers of the defendant, but they serve a fact-finding function that is similar to juries."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "In jurisdictions that provide a legal professional privilege, such as the attorney-client privilege, an attorney’s client can waive any protection the privilege provides over confidential communications if the client discloses the privileged information to unrelated third parties who have no need to know the information.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Legal professional privileges are not absolute; they are subject to waiver. Because these privileges only protect confidential communications, the protection they provide will be waived for communications disclosed to third parties who have little or nothing to do with the client’s pursuit of legal representation because such disclosures demonstrate a lack of confidentiality. Generally, waiver occurs when the client, who holds the privilege, voluntarily discloses (or consents to or encourages someone else disclosing) any significant part of the privileged communications. Although the client holds the privilege, the privilege can be waived by the client’s attorney or a third party—someone who is neither the attorney nor the client."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is the civil wrong that occurs when one party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern?", "options": {"A": "Injury to an individual’s reputation", "B": "Intrusion into an individual’s private matters", "C": "Public disclosure of private facts", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Public disclosure of private facts occurs when one party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern. For instance, disclosing information obtained in an interview conducted as part of a fraud investigation to individuals not involved in the investigation might constitute public disclosure of private facts."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following terms refers to the inappropriate practice of an investment professional who engages in the excessive trading of a customer account to generate commissions while disregarding the customer’s interests?", "options": {"A": "Selling away", "B": "Pump and dump", "C": "Parking", "D": "Churning"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Churning is the excessive trading of a customer account to generate commissions while disregarding the customer’s interests. Specifically, churning occurs when an investment professional excessively trades an account for the purpose of increasing his commissions instead of furthering the customer’s investment goals."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "A photograph can be either demonstrative evidence or real evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are three basic forms, as distinguished from types, of evidence: testimonial, real, and demonstrative. A photograph can be either demonstrative evidence or real evidence. Real evidence describes physical objects that played a part in the issues being litigated. The term includes both documentary evidence—such as canceled checks, invoices, ledgers, and letters—as well as other types of physical evidence. Demonstrative evidence is a tangible item that illustrates some material proposition (e.g., a map, a chart, or a summary). Accordingly, a photograph can be real evidence if it was part of the underlying event, or it can be demonstrative evidence if it was created specifically for the trial."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In inquisitorial jurisdictions, which of the following parties may access the full evidentiary record prior to the trial phase of criminal proceedings?", "options": {"A": "The prosecution only", "B": "The defense only", "C": "Both the prosecution and the defense", "D": "The judge and the prosecution only"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The evidence available in inquisitorial jurisdictions is substantially less private than in adversarial jurisdictions. The entire record, as submitted by the judge presiding over the examining stage of the litigation, is provided to the parties before the trial phase commences. The defense has full access to the dossier on the case. Therefore, there is rarely an element of surprise, as all parties have examined what evidence is expected to be presented. The judge may obtain the defendant’s testimony, but the defendant usually has the right to remain silent. Since the discovery process is mainly the responsibility of the court, the parties do not submit pretrial discovery requests to each other, although they can request that the judge obtain certain items of evidence."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Testimonial evidence refers to the oral or written statements made by witnesses under oath.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are three basic forms, as distinguished from types, of evidence: testimonial, real, and demonstrative. Testimonial evidence refers to the oral or written statements made by witnesses under oath. Real evidence refers to physical objects that played a part in the issues being litigated. Demonstrative evidence is a tangible item that illustrates some material proposition (e.g., a map, a chart, or a summary)."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "The duty of loyalty means that people in a fiduciary relationship must act with such care as an ordinarily prudent person would employ in similar positions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "People in a position of trust or fiduciary relationship—such as officers, directors, high-level employees of a corporation or business, and agents and brokers—owe certain duties to their principals or employers, and any action that runs afoul of such fiduciary duties constitutes a breach. The principal fiduciary duties are loyalty and care. The duty of loyalty requires that the employee/agent act solely in the best interest of the employer/principal, free of any self-dealing, conflicts of interest, or other abuse of the principal for personal advantage. The duty of care means that people in a fiduciary relationship must act with such care as an ordinarily prudent person would employ in similar positions."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "For a conflict of interest claim to be actionable against an agent, the agent must have:", "options": {"A": "Breached the duty of fidelity that he owed to his principal", "B": "Purported to act on behalf of, or as an agent for, an identified principal", "C": "Had an undisclosed interest in a matter that could influence his professional role", "D": "Informed the principal of his actions"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A conflict of interest occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence his professional role. Conflicts of interest do not necessarily constitute legal violations, as long as they are properly disclosed. Thus, for a conflict of interest claim to be actionable, the conflict must be undisclosed."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements regarding secured interests is TRUE?", "options": {"A": "A creditor’s claim is considered unsecured in most jurisdictions if the debt is secured by property that is worth less than the amount of the debt.", "B": "In jurisdictions that distinguish between secured and unsecured creditors in bankruptcy, unsecured creditors are typically paid before secured creditors.", "C": "A secured creditor is a creditor who holds a secured interest in some of a debtor’s property.", "D": "A claim is considered a secured interest if it is more than one year old."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Many jurisdictions recognize a distinction between secured and unsecured creditors during bankruptcy proceedings. A secured creditor is one who has a secured interest in some of the debtor’s property, meaning that if the debtor defaults on payments to the creditor, the creditor may possess or liquidate the secured property to satisfy the debt. Creditors with secured interests generally have priority over unsecured claims, meaning they normally get paid before unsecured claims in the distributions to creditors made by the trustee or debtor-in-possession. The most common example of a secured interest occurs when a lender finances a debtor’s purchase of a particular property (e.g., a home or vehicle) and, as part of the debt agreement, takes a collateral interest in the financed property. A secured creditor’s claim is secured to the extent of the property’s value on the petition date. When the debt is undersecured (i.e., the debt is secured by property that is worth less than the amount of the debt), the debt will be considered both unsecured and secured. For example, if a note for $500 is secured by property having a value of $400 on the petition date, there will be a secured claim for $400 and an unsecured claim for $100."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "The U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) has two major parts. The first part criminalizes the bribery of a foreign public official to obtain or retain business. The second part pertains to money laundering, requiring publicly traded companies to adopt policies, procedures, and internal controls reasonably designed to prevent money laundering.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The FCPA has two principal components: the anti-bribery provisions and the accounting provisions. In short, the anti-bribery provisions make it unlawful to bribe foreign government officials to obtain or retain business, and the accounting provisions require publicly traded companies subject to the FCPA’s jurisdiction to keep accurate books and records and adopt internal controls to prevent improper use of corporate funds."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "A particular tax levied by the central government in a country imposes a one-time tax that only applies to imported alcohol products. Which of the following best describes this type of tax?", "options": {"A": "Excise tax", "B": "Credit tax", "C": "Value-added tax", "D": "Income tax"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Consumption taxes are those collected from the proceeds of the sale of goods or services. Some of the common taxes include: Sales tax: a tax on goods or services, usually assessed at the consumer level and collected by the retailer or seller at the point of sale Value-added tax (VAT): a system that imposes a tax on an item that is assessed incrementally based on its increase in value at each point along a supply chain, from manufacture, to wholesale, to retailer, to consumer; the tax is collected by the seller in each transaction, and only the difference between the price paid by the initial purchaser and the price paid by the subsequent purchaser is taxed Excise tax: a tax on a narrow class of goods or services (e.g., tobacco or gasoline), usually assessed one time (per jurisdiction) at the manufacturer or wholesaler level"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "For a conflict of interest claim to be actionable, the conflict must be undisclosed.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A conflict of interest occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence his professional role. Conflicts of interest do not necessarily constitute legal violations, as long as they are properly disclosed. Thus, for a conflict of interest claim to be actionable, the conflict must be undisclosed."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is an element the government must prove to establish that an individual violated a law criminalizing false statements to government agencies?", "options": {"A": "The false statement was material", "B": "The defendant made a false statement", "C": "The statement concerned a matter within the jurisdiction of a government agency", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Laws prohibiting false claims and statements to government agencies make it illegal for a person to lie to, or conceal material information from, a government agency. A false claim is an assertion of a right to government money, property, or services that contains a misrepresentation. A false statement is an oral or written communication, declaration, or assertion that is factually untrue. Generally, to prove a violation, the government must show that the defendant: Knowingly and willfully (or with reckless disregard for truth or falsity) Made a false claim or statement (or used a false document) That was material (i.e., sufficiently important or relevant to influence decision making) Regarding a matter within the jurisdiction of a government agency With knowledge of its falsity"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Transactions involving money services businesses (MSBs) generally have a lower money laundering risk than those at other financial institutions because MSBs have more stringent regulatory requirements.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Money services business (MSB) is a term used with growing frequency to define a regulatory class of non-depository financial service providers that transmit or convert money. Although an MSB has particular meanings in different jurisdictions, it generally includes any business that operates in one or more of the following capacities: Currency exchangers Check cashers Issuers, sellers, or redeemers of traveler’s checks, money orders, or stored value Money transmitters Prepaid access providers or sellers MSBs offer an alternative to depository institutions for both financial services and money laundering. For this reason, an individual unable to transfer illegal funds into the traditional depository banking system might turn to an MSB. In addition, most MSBs operate under less strict regulations than traditional financial institutions. For example, an MSB might not check a customer’s credit report before opening an account, or it might require less rigorous proof of a customer’s identity than a traditional bank. These overall less stringent requirements tend to raise the money laundering risk in certain transactions involving users of MSBs. However, there is a regulatory trend to expand certain requirements, such as customer due diligence programs, to MSBs."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Which of the following types of remedies in civil litigation involves the victim recovering money from the defendant for compensation, reimbursement, or reparation for the defendant’s offense?", "options": {"A": "Damages", "B": "Declaratory relief", "C": "Injunction", "D": "Equitable relief"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "If the plaintiff in a civil case prevails, the remedy to which the plaintiff is entitled depends upon a number of factors, such as the relief sought, the facts, and the authority given to the court to grant specific relief. There are various types of civil remedies, but the following three types are most common: monetary remedies (damages), declaratory remedies, and equitable remedies. Damages are remedies for the victim’s recovery of money from the defendant because of, and as compensation, reimbursement, or reparation for, the defendant’s legal offense. Damages are the remedy most commonly available to the successful plaintiff, and the main purpose of damages is to compensate the plaintiff for the loss caused by the defendant."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "The protection of investors is one of the objectives on which the International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO) Objectives and Principles of Securities Regulation are based.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The IOSCO Objectives and Principles of Securities Regulation are based on the following three objectives: The protection of investors Ensuring that markets are fair, efficient, and transparent The reduction of systemic risk"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Unlike the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, the UK Bribery Act makes it a crime to bribe a foreign public official in connection with international business transactions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Both the UK Bribery Act and the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) make it a crime to offer foreign public officials bribes or to accept bribes from them in connection with international business transactions, and their prohibitions on bribing foreign government officials are broadly comparable. Thus, like the FCPA, the Bribery Act seeks to punish corruption on a global level, but the Bribery Act has an even broader application than the FCPA. One way in which the Bribery Act has a broader application than the FCPA is that it makes commercial bribery—bribes paid to people working in the private sector—a crime, whereas the FCPA only prohibits bribes involving foreign government officials."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "Which of the following best describes the primary source(s) of law in civil law jurisdictions?", "options": {"A": "Codified principles or statutes", "B": "A combination of judge-made law and codified principles or statutes", "C": "Judge-made law", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Almost every country can be classified as having either a common law or a civil law judicial system; knowing the differences between the two is essential to understanding how legal and judicial processes work in foreign jurisdictions. Civil law systems apply laws from an accepted set of codified principles or compiled statutes. Individual cases are then decided in accordance with these basic tenets. Under a civil law system, judges or judicial administrators are bound only by the civil code and not by the previous decisions of other courts. In deciding legal issues, a civil law judge applies the various codified principles to each case."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Employee protections afforded by contract law protect employees from actions by private, but not government, employers.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Employees involved in investigations of suspected fraud have certain duties and rights, whether they are merely bystanders who might have some information relevant to the investigation or are suspected of committing fraud. Employee duties and rights vary among jurisdictions and from case to case, but generally, such duties and rights apply to employees who work in government and private-sector workplaces. Thus, private and government employers can violate their employees' legal rights. Employees may have contractual rights that are enforceable against their employers. That is, employers and employees may enter into contracts that govern the employment relationship, and if the employer violates the contract, the employee can sue for breach of contract. Such contractual rights can affect the employer-employee relationship, and in particular, they can limit the ability of the employer to compel full cooperation in a fraud examination."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "In addition to prohibiting bribes to foreign officials for business purposes, the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) prohibits facilitating payments, or grease payments, made to foreign officials to facilitate the officials’ ability to perform their duties.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "While the FCPA prohibits bribes to foreign officials for business purposes, it does not prohibit all payments to foreign officials. It contains an explicit exception for certain types of payments, known as facilitating payments, or grease payments, made to expedite or secure performance of a routine governmental action by a foreign official, political party, or party official that relates to the performance of that party’s ordinary and routine functions. For example, the payment of a foreign corporation fee that is statutorily required in a country in order to do business in that country would fall under this exemption and would not be considered a violation of the FCPA."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is an element that must be established to prove fraud based on the concealment of material facts?", "options": {"A": "The defendant acted with intent to mislead or deceive the victim(s)", "B": "The defendant failed to disclose a material fact that he had a duty to disclose", "C": "The defendant had knowledge of a material fact that he had a duty to disclose", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "An action for fraud may be based on the concealment of material facts, but only if the defendant had a duty in the circumstances to disclose. The essential elements of fraud based on the failure to disclose material facts are: The defendant had knowledge of a material fact. The defendant had a duty to disclose the material fact. The defendant failed to disclose the material fact. The defendant acted with intent to mislead or deceive the victim(s)."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "____________ is any intentional or deliberate act to deprive another of property or money by guile, deception, or other unfair means.", "options": {"A": "Embezzlement", "B": "Extortion", "C": "Bribery", "D": "Fraud"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fraud includes any intentional or deliberate act to deprive another of property or money by guile, deception, or other unfair means."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "One of the main objectives of the International Organization of Securities Commissions is to assist its members in promoting high standards of regulation in order to maintain just, efficient, and sound markets.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO) is an international organization comprised of securities commissioners and administrators responsible for securities regulation and the administration of securities laws in their respective countries. IOSCO is recognized as the international standard setter for securities markets, and the organization’s members regulate more than 95% of the world’s securities markets. IOSCO’s main objectives are to assist its members to: Cooperate to promote high standards of regulation in order to maintain just, efficient, and sound markets. Exchange information on their respective experiences in order to promote the development of domestic markets. Unite their efforts to establish standards and an effective surveillance of international securities transactions. Provide mutual assistance to promote the integrity of the markets through a rigorous application of the standards and effective enforcement against offenses."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning criminal bargaining agreements is most accurate?", "options": {"A": "Bargaining agreements are more commonly accepted in civil law jurisdictions than in common law jurisdictions.", "B": "Bargaining agreements are only allowed in civil law jurisdictions.", "C": "Bargaining agreements are only allowed in common law jurisdictions.", "D": "Bargaining agreements are more commonly accepted in common law jurisdictions than in civil law jurisdictions."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A method of disposing of cases in a growing number of countries is through bargaining agreements, which occur when a defendant makes an agreement with prosecutors to plead guilty or submit a recorded confession in exchange for lesser charges or a reduced sentence. It is usually within the prosecutor’s discretion as to whether to offer a bargain. The practice has become more popular in the last few decades, and many countries that previously resisted using bargaining agreements have introduced them in various circumstances. The bargaining process works differently in common law and civil law countries. Bargaining agreements are controversial in many countries and are not as widely used in civil law jurisdictions as in common law jurisdictions. Additionally, when they are allowed in civil law jurisdictions, the circumstances under which they are available are typically more limited."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements about the UK Bribery Act is NOT correct?", "options": {"A": "The UK Bribery Act exercises jurisdiction over all individuals and corporate entities for acts of corruption when any part of the offense occurs in the UK.", "B": "Unlike the FCPA, the UK Bribery Act does not contain an explicit exception for facilitating payments.", "C": "If an organization’s anti-corruption program complies with the FCPA, it will be sufficient for the purpose of complying with the UK Bribery Act.", "D": "The UK Bribery Act has a broader application than the FCPA because, unlike the FCPA, it makes commercial bribery a crime."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Both the UK Bribery Act and the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) make it a crime to offer foreign public officials bribes or to accept bribes from them in connection with international business transactions, and their prohibitions on bribing foreign government officials are broadly comparable. Thus, like the FCPA, the Bribery Act seeks to punish corruption on a global level, but the Bribery Act has an even broader application than the FCPA. One way in which the Bribery Act has a broader application than the FCPA is that it makes commercial bribery—bribes paid to people working in the private sector—a crime, whereas the FCPA only prohibits bribes involving foreign government officials. Consequently, even if an organization’s anti-corruption program is sufficiently robust for the purpose of complying with the FCPA, it might not be sufficient for the purpose of complying with the UK Bribery Act. Therefore, it is important for international organizations to be aware of the differences between the FCPA and the Bribery Act. Another way that the UK Bribery Act differs from the FCPA concerns facilitating payments. The FCPA does not prohibit all payments to foreign officials; it contains an explicit exception for facilitating payments made to expedite or secure performance of a routine governmental action. The Bribery Act, however, makes no such exception. The Bribery Act exercises broad jurisdiction over all individuals and corporate entities for acts of corruption when any part of the offense occurs in the UK. Furthermore, liability exists for acts committed outside the UK by individuals and entities with a close connection to the UK, including: British citizens, overseas citizens, overseas territories’ citizens, and any person declared a British subject under the 1981 British Nationality Act Individuals who normally reside in the UK An entity incorporated under the law of any part of the UK More specifically, foreign companies that have offices in the UK, employ UK citizens, or provide any services to a UK organization are responsible for complying with the UK Bribery Act. A listing on the London Stock Exchange will not, in itself, subject a company to the Act."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "Under a common law legal system, judges are not bound by precedent and are free to decide cases based on their interpretation of the matters at issue.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Almost every country can be classified as having either a common law or a civil law legal system; knowing the differences between the two is essential to understanding how legal processes work in foreign jurisdictions. In most common law systems, there are laws that judges develop through court decisions (called the common law), as well as codes and statutes that establish laws. The common law is developed on a case-by-case basis. That is, the common law is a system of legal principles developed by judges through decisions made in courts. It consists of the usages and customs of a society as interpreted by the judiciary, and it is often referred to as judge-made law. In the modern era of law, the trend in common law countries has been to move away from rules that originate in common law and instead rely on statutory law—laws created by a legislature or other governing authority—as the basis of a dispute. However, an additional feature of the common law system that remains important is the precedential value of court decisions. Due to the ambiguity or incompleteness of statutes, legal disputes often arise in which parties support competing interpretations of a law. To decide disputes in common law systems, judges analyze prior cases with similar circumstances and apply the basic principles set forth in those cases to the problem at hand. Common law originated as a legal system in England, and some of the principles established hundreds of years ago in court decisions remain influential to contemporary legal issues. Today, common law systems exist in the United Kingdom, the United States, India, Australia, and many other countries that were once part of the British Empire or were influenced by such legal systems."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements about the United Nations Convention Against Corruption (UN Convention) is correct?", "options": {"A": "Member states must ensure the existence of independent anti-corruption bodies that oversee the implementation of the UN Convention policies", "B": "Member states must exercise jurisdiction over acts of corruption committed within their territories or by their nationals", "C": "Member states must implement the necessary mechanisms to detect and prevent the transfer of assets obtained through illicit activities", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The UN Convention devotes its first chapter to preventive measures aimed at both the public and private sectors. Member states must ensure the existence of independent anti-corruption bodies that oversee implementation of the UN Convention policies and disseminate relevant information. The UN Convention lists specific acts of corruption, but it does not require member states to criminalize every one of the listed acts. Instead, it requires member states to criminalize only certain acts of corruption, and it requires them to merely consider criminalizing others. The UN Convention requires member states to establish liability for legal persons and to exercise jurisdiction over acts of corruption committed within their territories or by their nationals. In addition, any legislation criminalizing an act of corruption must include knowledge or specific intent as an element of the offense. Member states must implement the necessary mechanisms to detect and prevent the transfer of assets obtained through illicit activities."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning expert witnesses in inquisitorial systems is most accurate?", "options": {"A": "Generally, the court is primarily responsible for appointing expert witnesses.", "B": "The court may appoint expert witnesses, but generally, the parties select the primary expert witnesses.", "C": "Expert testimony is generally prohibited in inquisitorial systems.", "D": "Usually, the parties select a pool of expert witnesses, and the jury votes on which expert is most qualified to testify."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In most inquisitorial systems, the primary experts are appointed by the court. Experts are subject to various examinations and might have to conduct their own examinations of witnesses. Usually, all of the expert’s activities related to the case are controlled by the judge, who determines the scope of the expert’s analysis, the expert’s authority to access certain items of evidence, whom the expert can interview, and several other functions. Because some jurisdictions allow parties to submit testimony or evidence from their own experts in addition to the court-appointed expert, the latter might need to interview the parties’ experts. The expert should carefully follow the judge’s instructions, especially since the instructions are usually made available to the parties of the proceeding."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "When does the duty to preserve relevant evidence regarding civil litigation typically arise for litigation in common law countries?", "options": {"A": "When litigation is reasonably anticipated", "B": "As soon as the plaintiff files the lawsuit", "C": "As soon as the defendant files an answer or response to the plaintiff’s pleading or complaint", "D": "A short time period after the plaintiff files the lawsuit, typically 30 days"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Most civil litigation concerning fraud involves many documents, tangible items, or digital information that might serve as evidence. Each jurisdiction has rules for how potential evidence should be handled. Generally, common law jurisdictions impose a duty on parties in civil litigation to take affirmative steps to preserve relevant evidence, and this duty might arise prior to the commencement of litigation. For litigation occurring in common law courts, the duty to preserve relevant evidence typically arises when the litigation in question is reasonably anticipated. For instance, if a company receives a letter from a vendor that alleges a credible allegation of fraud and a threat to sue, the company's duty to preserve evidence has most likely arisen."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "With the powers recommended under the World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes, the bankruptcy administrator can request relevant information from third parties with knowledge of the debtor’s affairs (such as banks and customers) but cannot compel the third parties to provide the information.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Most bankruptcy processes, whether through a court or otherwise, appoint a person or group with administrative powers to oversee the process. The name of this appointee varies between jurisdictions, but often is called the administrator, trustee, receiver, examiner, or supervisor. The World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes recommends that the administrator have broad powers, including: The right to cancel fraudulent contracts or transactions entered into by the debtor The power to collect, preserve, and dispose of the debtor’s property The ability to interfere with contracts to meet the objectives of the insolvency process The power to examine the debtor, the debtor’s agents, or other people with knowledge of the debtor’s affairs and compel them to provide relevant information"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Which of the following is an element that must be present for communications between an attorney and the attorney's client to be protected by a legal professional privilege?", "options": {"A": "Purpose of the communications was to seek or provide legal advice", "B": "Intent to keep the communications confidential", "C": "Communication between a legal advisor and a client", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Legal professional privileges protect the communications between professional legal advisors (e.g., solicitor, barrister, or attorney) and their clients. These privileges are designed to encourage open and honest communications between legal professionals and their clients, and they go by many names depending on the jurisdiction (e.g., attorney-client privilege, legal advice privilege, or solicitor-client privilege). The requirements for the application of these privileges vary among jurisdictions, but, generally, the following elements must be present for communications between an attorney and the attorney's client to be protected by a legal professional privilege: A communication between a legal professional and a client The communication was made to seek or give legal advice The parties intended the communications to be confidential To be protected under a legal professional privilege, it is typically not necessary that the communication take place after a lawsuit has been filed."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "An employee may have contractual rights that limit the ability of the employer to compel full cooperation in a fraud examination.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Employees may have contractual rights that are enforceable against their employers. That is, employers and employees may enter into contracts that govern the employment relationship, and if the employer violates the contract, the employee can sue for breach of contract. Such contractual rights can affect the employer-employee relationship, and in particular, they can limit the ability of the employer to compel full cooperation in a fraud examination."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE with regard to partnerships?", "options": {"A": "Unlike general partnership interests, interests in limited partnerships can be considered investment contracts.", "B": "In a limited partnership, limited partners manage the enterprise’s activities.", "C": "In a general partnership, the liability of each partner is limited to the amount of his investment in the company.", "D": "A limited partner is liable for all debts of the partnership."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A limited partnership is similar to a general partnership, except that in addition to one or more general partners, limited partnerships also have one or more limited partners. In contrast to a general partner, who has unlimited personal liability, a limited partner is a passive investor whose liability is limited to the amount of his investment in the company. Thus, in a limited partnership, the general partners manage the enterprise’s activities, and the limited partners supply the funding. Limited partners do not manage the enterprise’s activities. Unlike general partnership interests, interests in limited partnerships generally constitute investment contracts."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Two parties entered into a real estate contract for various properties, but the vague nature of the contract led to confusion about who owned a particular property. The parties took the issue to court, and the court interpreted and stated the rights of each party under the contract. What type of remedy did the court provide?", "options": {"A": "Monetary relief", "B": "Declaratory relief", "C": "Punitive damages", "D": "Exemplary damages"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "If the plaintiff in a civil case prevails, the remedy to which the plaintiff is entitled depends upon a number of factors, such as the relief sought, the facts, and the authority given to the court to grant specific relief. There are various types of civil remedies, but the following three types are most common: monetary remedies (damages), declaratory remedies, and equitable remedies. Declaratory remedies are those in which the court states or declares the rights of the parties. For example, when a court interprets a will or a contract, its decision is declaratory in nature. Similarly, the decision of a court as to the ownership of personal property or land is also declaratory."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "The body of judge-made law that developed from England and is still used today in many jurisdictions is called:", "options": {"A": "Statutory law", "B": "Original law", "C": "Common law", "D": "Consensus law"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Almost every country can be classified as having either a common law or a civil law legal system; knowing the differences between the two is essential to understanding how legal processes work in foreign jurisdictions. In most common law systems, there are laws that judges develop through court decisions (called the common law), as well as codes and statutes that establish laws. The common law is developed on a case-by-case basis. That is, the common law is a system of legal principles developed by judges through decisions made in courts. It consists of the usages and customs of a society as interpreted by the judiciary, and it is often referred to as judge-made law. Common law originated as a legal system in England, and some of the principles established hundreds of years ago in court decisions remain influential to contemporary legal issues. Today, common law systems exist in the United Kingdom, the United States, India, Australia, and many other countries that were once part of the British Empire or were influenced by such legal systems."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Which of the following best describes the purpose of expert testimony in judicial proceedings?", "options": {"A": "Assist the trier of fact to understand the evidence or to determine the fact in issue", "B": "Provide evidence based on personal knowledge and perceptions of the events at issue", "C": "Assist in proving and establishing one essential circumstance among many others", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Experts can serve one of two roles in the trial process: testifying expert or consulting expert. Testifying expert witnesses give technical testimony when specialized knowledge is needed to help the fact finder understand evidence or determine a fact in issue."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is a correct statement about employees’ legal rights?", "options": {"A": "The International Treaty on Human Rights grants employees certain fundamental rights, and it applies equally to employees of private companies and government agencies.", "B": "For a violation of an employee’s legal rights to occur, there must be some form of government action.", "C": "Private employers cannot be found guilty of violating the legal rights of their employees.", "D": "None of the above are correct."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Employees involved in investigations of suspected fraud have certain duties and rights, whether they are merely bystanders who might have some information relevant to the investigation or are suspected of committing fraud. Employee duties and rights vary among jurisdictions and from case to case, but generally, such duties and rights apply to employees who work in both government and private-sector workplaces. Thus, private and government employers can violate their employees' legal rights. There is no International Treaty on Human Rights."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "In most jurisdictions, the plaintiff’s initial pleading requires various kinds of information. Which of the following is NOT one of them?", "options": {"A": "Specific facts on which the party’s claim relies", "B": "Grounds for legal relief", "C": "All documents that might be introduced as evidence during the proceedings", "D": "A summary of the evidence"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A civil action begins when the plaintiff files a pleading with the appropriate court, usually in the jurisdiction in which the defendant resides or where the claim arose. The pleading sets out the complaint against the defendant and the remedy that the plaintiff is seeking. The required contents of the plaintiff’s pleadings will vary somewhat between jurisdictions, but most jurisdictions require fact pleadings, meaning the plaintiff must identify: The grounds for legal relief A summary of the evidence The specific facts on which the party’s claim relies Key items of expected evidence Some jurisdictions have elevated pleading requirements and also require witness lists and the production of specific documents. A minority of jurisdictions require simpler notice pleadings in which the facts in the pleading must merely put the defendant on notice of the alleged claims; notice pleadings do not need to include the specific facts underlying the case."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a legal element that must be shown to prove a claim for fraudulent misrepresentation of material facts?", "options": {"A": "The defendant knew the representation was false", "B": "The victim suffered damages as a result of the misrepresentation", "C": "The victim relied on the misrepresentation", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fraudulent misrepresentation of material facts is most often thought of when the term fraud is used. The specific elements of proof required to establish a misrepresentation claim vary somewhat according to where the fraud occurred and whether the case is brought as a criminal or civil action, but the elements normally include: The defendant made a false statement (i.e., a misrepresentation of fact). The false statement was material (i.e., the statement was sufficiently important or relevant to influence the making of a decision). The defendant knew the representation was false. The victim relied on the misrepresentation. The victim suffered damages as a result of the misrepresentation."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Which of the following types of taxes are considered consumption taxes?", "options": {"A": "Sales taxes", "B": "Value-added taxes", "C": "Excise taxes", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Consumption taxes are those collected from the proceeds of the sale of goods or services. Some of the common taxes include: Sales tax: a tax on goods or services, usually assessed at the consumer level and collected by the retailer or seller at the point of sale Value-added tax (VAT): a system that imposes a tax on an item that is assessed incrementally based on its increase in value at each point along a supply chain, from manufacture, to wholesale, to retailer, to consumer; the tax is collected by the seller in each transaction, and only the difference between the price paid by the initial purchaser and the price paid by the subsequent purchaser is taxed Excise tax: a tax on a narrow class of goods or services (e.g., tobacco or gasoline), usually assessed one time (per jurisdiction) at the manufacturer or wholesaler level"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "_______________ is comprised of the basic laws of rights and duties. When people refer to something that is \"against the law,\" they are usually referring to this type of law.", "options": {"A": "Substantive law", "B": "Administrative law", "C": "Natural law", "D": "Procedural law"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Substantive law defines the type of conduct permissible and the penalties for violation; it is comprised of the basic laws of rights and duties. When people say an act is “against the law,” they are referring to substantive law."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Country A and Country B both follow the Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations concerning cross-border transfers of currency. Jessica is about to travel from Country A to Country B while carrying cash above Country A’s designated threshold for cross-border currency transfers. Will Jessica be required to disclose to Country A the amount of currency she is carrying?", "options": {"A": "Yes, because a disclosure is required for any amount of currency physically transferred out of the country.", "B": "Yes, because she is transferring currency above the designated threshold out of Country A.", "C": "No, because disclosure is only required for currency coming into Country A.", "D": "No, because she is traveling to Country B, which also requires the disclosure of cross-border currency transportation."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Under the Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendation 32, countries should implement disclosure requirements for individuals who are physically carrying currency or currency equivalents (i.e., bearer instruments) into or out of the country in amounts above the jurisdiction’s designated threshold. Generally, individuals who are carrying currency or the equivalent above the designated threshold while attempting to cross jurisdictional borders should be required to disclose the amount to authorities, and they will face penalties if they fail to do so."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "The Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations provide that countries should take certain measures to reduce the prevalence of money laundering and terrorist financing, but they do not specifically advise countries to criminalize such activities.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is an intergovernmental body that was established at the G-7 Summit in 1989. Its purpose is to develop and promote standards and policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing at both the national and international levels. The FATF’s Recommendations, revised in 2012, created the most comprehensive standard with which to measure a country’s anti-money laundering, counterterrorism, and nuclear proliferation laws and policies. They serve as a basic framework of laws that its members should have. While the recommendations are not required by members and the FATF acknowledges that following each rule might not be possible, members of the FATF often adopt them. Some of the key measures in the Recommendations provide that countries should: Use a risk-based approach when setting anti-money laundering policies. Create policies that increase cooperation and coordination with other countries. Specifically criminalize money laundering and terrorist financing. Enable authorities to trace, freeze, and confiscate assets suspected in laundering and terrorist financing. Require financial institutions to keep certain records and establish anti-money laundering policies, avoid correspondent banking with shell banks, and continuously monitor wire transfers."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the three stages of a criminal proceeding in an inquisitorial jurisdiction?", "options": {"A": "The trial phase", "B": "The investigative phase", "C": "The sentencing phase", "D": "The examining phase"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Criminal proceedings in inquisitorial jurisdictions typically are divided into three phases: the investigative phase, the examining phase, and the trial. The discovery process occurs primarily in the first two of these three phases. In the investigative stage, the public prosecutor, judge, or both (depending on the jurisdiction’s process) collect documentary and tangible evidence regarding the case. The investigating party then decides whether there is sufficient evidence to submit the case for prosecution. If there is sufficient evidence, the case moves on to the examining phase, which is mostly conducted in writing. The judge completes a written record of the evidence and may also collect testimony and additional evidence. If the judge certifies that there is a valid case against the accused, the matter moves forward to trial. The trial commences with the exhibition of the examining record before the parties and the trial judge, jury, or panel. The parties argue their case before the trial judge (or jury, if applicable). Unlike in adversarial jurisdictions, sentencing is generally not a separate phase and occurs at the end of the trial."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "The Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations state that countries should require certain organizations to monitor suspicious activity and file a report to disclose known or suspected criminal offenses or transactions that involve money laundering or terrorist financing. Which of the following scenarios would NOT require such a report to be filed under the Recommendations?", "options": {"A": "A customer in a jewelry store buys jewelry using cash.", "B": "A casino customer appears to be depositing cash for money laundering purposes, rather than to gamble.", "C": "Money that appears to be proceeds from illegal drug sales is deposited in a bank account.", "D": "A transaction that appears to involve proceeds of an illegal bribe is conducted through a bank."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Under FATF Recommendation 20, financial institutions and certain other businesses should be required to file a report when they “suspect or have reasonable grounds to suspect that funds are the proceeds of a criminal activity, or are related to terrorist financing.” The transactions in all but one of the choices are suspected of stemming from money laundering or the proceeds of predicate illegal conduct, while the correct answer is not necessarily suspicious. It is not unusual for a customer to purchase jewelry using cash."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Which of the following is a determination that judges need to make before allowing an expert to testify before a jury in an adversarial jurisdiction?", "options": {"A": "Is the expert well-educated on the subject on which he is expected to testify?", "B": "Was the expert paid for his testimony?", "C": "Does the expert have a tendency to reflect a personal bias toward one of the parties?", "D": "Will the expertise of the proposed witness assist the jury in understanding the evidence or determining a fact at issue?"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Generally, before allowing an expert to testify before the jury in an adversarial jurisdiction, the judge will make three determinations: Is the person qualified as an expert witness? Will the expertise of the witness assist the jury in understanding the evidence or determining a fact at issue? In other words, is the proposed testimony relevant to the facts of the case? Is the testimony reliable? Bias and payment are relevant issues. However, in adversarial systems, these issues are readily addressable by the parties’ legal representatives, rather than being predetermined by the judge."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In criminal proceedings in adversarial jurisdictions, which of the following best describes the defendant’s right to access relevant information from the prosecution?", "options": {"A": "The defense is not entitled to any information held by the prosecution.", "B": "The defense may access all relevant information held by the prosecution, including attorney work product.", "C": "The defense has the same right to information held by the prosecution as parties in civil litigation.", "D": "The defense has a limited right to information, but it is entitled to exculpatory information."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Generally speaking, discovery in adversarial jurisdictions is more secretive than in inquisitorial systems, especially in criminal cases. Both the defense and the prosecution typically have far fewer rights to access information possessed by the other party than parties in noncriminal (i.e., civil) litigation. The prosecution is heavily limited in what disclosures it may obtain, and the defendant typically has the right to refuse to testify. The prosecution generally must obtain evidence through search warrants or other means, rather than by requesting the items from the defendant. However, the defense might still be required to turn over certain types of evidence that it intends to use at trial, such as the basis for any legal defenses raised, documents or tangible items, results of tests intended to be used at trial, statements of expert witnesses it plans to use at trial, and other items as required by the laws of the jurisdiction. The defense is similarly limited in what it may request from the prosecution. The defendant typically does not have a right to the work product of the prosecutor, which includes reports, memoranda, and other internal documents made by the prosecuting attorney in preparing for and prosecuting the case. However, most jurisdictions also require prosecutors to turn over all exculpatory evidence that would tend to refute the guilt or mitigate the punishment of the defendant."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Fidelity insurance financially covers a party against losses caused by customers.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Given the prevalence of fraud, and given the fact that it is difficult to fully recover losses from fraud, many businesses have fidelity insurance that covers fraud losses. Fidelity insurance (also known as crime insurance and employee dishonesty insurance) is an often-overlooked method of recovery for losses due to internal fraud. Fidelity insurance is a type of insurance under which the insured entity is covered against losses caused by the dishonest or fraudulent acts of its employees. Dishonest or fraudulent acts typically are defined as those acts committed with the intent to: Cause the insured to sustain a loss. Obtain a financial benefit for the employee, or for any third party intended by the employee, other than his proper compensation."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In most common law jurisdictions, to prevail in a criminal case, the prosecution must prove its case ___________________.", "options": {"A": "Beyond a reasonable doubt", "B": "With clear and convincing evidence", "C": "By a preponderance of the evidence", "D": "True beyond any possible doubt"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The burden of proof is the evidence one party must present to prove each element of a cause of action. In criminal cases, the burden of proof is typically the highest level found in the jurisdiction. In most common law systems, the burden is phrased as beyond a reasonable doubt, and therefore, the verdict must be based on assurance beyond a reasonable doubt. Plainly put, \"beyond a reasonable doubt\" requires the fact finder to be as sure as possible that the defendant committed the acts as charged to find him guilty."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "Suzanne runs her own business, but she has decided to close it and file for bankruptcy. Before she does so, she orders a large quantity of inventory on credit and resells it for cash. She closes the business and leaves the suppliers with almost nothing to recover in the bankruptcy proceeding that follows. Which of the following best describes Suzanne’s scheme?", "options": {"A": "Concealed asset scheme", "B": "Pump and dump scheme", "C": "Bustout scheme", "D": "Multiple filings scheme"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A bustout is a planned and fraudulent bankruptcy. It can take many different forms, but the basic approach is for an apparently legitimate business to order large quantities of inventory or other goods on credit, and then dispose of those goods through legitimate or illegitimate channels. Because the point of the bustout scheme is to quickly resell the goods for cash, the fraudster is likely to purchase more liquid items like inventory than real estate, insurance policies, or services. The perpetrator then closes shop, absconding with the proceeds and leaving the suppliers unpaid. The debtor might then go into bankruptcy. Often, by this point the debtor has already made false accounting entries or taken other steps to conceal the assets or make the sales look legitimate. Other times, debtors simply flee the jurisdiction or do not show up at the proceedings."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Officers and directors of a corporation have a fiduciary duty to act solely in the best interest of non-shareholder constituencies.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "People in a position of trust or fiduciary relationship—such as officers, directors, high-level employees of a corporation or business, and agents and brokers—owe certain duties to their principals or employers, and any action that runs afoul of such fiduciary duties constitutes a breach. The principal fiduciary duties are loyalty and care. The duty of loyalty requires that the employee/agent act solely in the best interest of the employer/principal, free of any self-dealing, conflicts of interest, or other abuse of the principal for personal advantage. Employees/agents who owe a duty of loyalty must act solely in the best interest of their principal and may not seek to advance their personal interests to the detriment of their principal. The duty of care means that people in a fiduciary relationship must act with such care as an ordinarily prudent person would employ in similar positions. In general, officers and directors do not owe fiduciary duties to other constituencies, such as creditors, whose rights are purely contractual."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "In a particular country’s judicial process, the judge oversees the investigation of a case, is primarily responsible for questioning witnesses, and generally plays a larger role in the evidence-gathering process than the parties’ legal counsel. Which of the following best describes this type of judicial process?", "options": {"A": "Inquisitorial process", "B": "Adversarial process", "C": "Substantive law process", "D": "Common law process"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Adversarial and inquisitorial judicial processes refer to the type of approach that courts take to discover evidence in a case. Theoretically, neither of these processes is exclusive of common law or civil law systems. Civil law jurisdictions, however, almost always favor an inquisitorial process, while common law systems typically feature an adversarial system. An inquisitorial process refers to a fact-finding approach that places the primary responsibility of discovering evidence on the presiding judge. In an inquisitorial process, the primary goal is to find the truth. Rather than serving as a referee over the parties’ production of evidence, the judge is actively involved in discovery. For instance, judges may request relevant documents on their own accord and ask factual questions of witnesses themselves. As a result, attorneys play a smaller role in the evidentiary process than in an adversarial process."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning the examinations of expert witnesses in most inquisitorial jurisdictions is accurate?", "options": {"A": "Only the parties may question the credibility of a court-appointed expert witness.", "B": "Neither the judge nor the parties may question the credibility of a court-appointed expert witness.", "C": "Both the judge and the parties may question the credibility of a court-appointed expert witness.", "D": "Only the judge may question the credibility of a court-appointed expert witness."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Since the primary expert or experts are obtained by the court itself, they are generally seen as inherently less biased than experts in adversarial proceedings. Additionally, the selection of the expert is an extension of the court’s authority and discretion. Therefore, for a party’s legal counsel to attack the expert’s credibility in an adversarial way would be strategically unwise in most circumstances. However, parties usually are allowed to raise limited objections to an expert if they believe the expert is biased. For example, the expert might have a relationship with one of the parties to the litigation. The parties also are often allowed to question the expert’s analysis or methods used. While this process is less confrontational, a poor performance can lead to the court rejecting the expert’s testimony. The judge may also question the expert’s credibility and qualifications and ultimately decides the weight of the expert’s testimony."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Nelson, a CFE, works for Electric Avenue Manufacturing, a private company that operates in a jurisdiction with civil laws for defamation, invasion of privacy, and conflict of interest. Nelson searched the purse of Harriet, one of Electric Avenue’s employees. Assuming that Harriet had a reasonable expectation of privacy in the purse and Nelson conducted the search without a legitimate interest or authority, under which of the following claims would Harriet most likely be able to recover damages against Nelson?", "options": {"A": "Libel", "B": "Slander", "C": "Conflict of interest", "D": "Intrusion into Harriet’s private matters"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The civil wrong regarding intrusion into an individual’s private matters (often referred to as intrusion upon seclusion) occurs when an individual intentionally intrudes into another individual’s private matters and the intrusion would be highly offensive or objectionable to a reasonable person. The elements of this civil wrong include: An intentional intrusion Into an area where an individual has a reasonable expectation of privacy The intrusion would be highly offensive or objectionable to a reasonable person Here, if Nelson searches Harriet’s purse without legitimate interest or authority, she may be able to recover from Nelson for intrusion into her private matters."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Which of the following crimes would best be described as money laundering?", "options": {"A": "A person who is applying for a loan provides fraudulent data to the bank to make his credit seem better than it really is.", "B": "A criminal engages in a process to disguise the criminal nature of stolen funds to make it seem as though he earned them legitimately.", "C": "A corporate officer is entrusted with assets that belong to the organization, but he fraudulently sells them for personal gain.", "D": "A corrupt employee accepts a kickback from his organization’s vendor in return for rewarding the vendor a contract."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Money laundering is the disguising of the existence, nature, source, control, beneficial ownership, location, and disposition of property derived from criminal activity. Put differently, money laundering is the process by which criminals attempt to disguise illicit assets as legitimate assets that they have a right to possess and spend. In this context, the term assets assumes the wider definition of that which is physical, intangible, or represented in the form of rights or obligations, such as a pension or trust fund. Money laundering operations are designed to take the proceeds of illegal activity, such as profits from drug trafficking, and cause them to appear to come from a legitimate source. Once illegal money has been laundered, the perpetrator is able to spend or invest the illicit income in legitimate assets."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following accurately describes a benefit of deferred prosecution agreements?", "options": {"A": "They encourage an organization to reform poor policies", "B": "They help reduce the risk of illegal practices at an organization", "C": "They help the justice system resolve a corporate case while still punishing malfeasance", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Some jurisdictions that allow for corporate criminal liability also use deferred prosecution agreements. Generally, deferred prosecution agreements occur when prosecutors file criminal charges against a company, but then they agree not to prosecute the claims as long as the company successfully complies with the deferral agreement’s terms. These requirements typically focus on getting the business to reform its policies and reduce the risk of illegal practices. Essentially, deferred prosecution agreements help companies avoid indictment, trial, and conviction while providing a jurisdiction’s justice system with another channel for resolving a corporate case that punishes malfeasance and effectuates changes in a company’s culture. Similar to plea bargaining, deferred prosecution agreements are controversial, and many countries do not provide for such resolutions of criminal cases. However, the complexity and public cost of trying massive fraud cases has led to more jurisdictions adopting such strategies."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "The ACFE Code of Professional Ethics prohibits fraud examiners from expressing opinions regarding the guilt or innocence of any person or party. This means that a fraud examiner who serves as an expert witness may NOT answer questions about whether the defendant committed actions that are characteristic of fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Certain standards for fraud examiners are found in the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics. Specifically, fraud examiners are prohibited from expressing opinions as to the guilt or innocence of any person or party. This is not to say that the witness cannot testify to the badges, hallmarks, or characteristics of fraud found in the case. It also does not mean that the fraud examiner cannot testify that, based on the evidence, he believes that the accused might have committed the offense. But the ultimate guilt or innocence of any person or party is the sole responsibility of the fact finder. The fraud examiner typically will not be permitted to testify to the ultimate fact questions."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Which of the following best describes the standard of proof for civil trials in civil law jurisdictions?", "options": {"A": "More likely than not", "B": "Clear and convincing", "C": "The inner conviction of the judge", "D": "Preponderance of evidence"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The standard of proof in civil law jurisdictions typically does not change in criminal and civil trials; it is often described as the inner conviction of the judge, sometimes called the conviction intime standard. This standard requires stronger evidence than the common law preponderance of evidence standard, but not as much as the common law beyond a reasonable doubt standard."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Abel is an auditor who works for XYZ, a private company. Abel suspects that Beta, an employee for XYZ, has embezzled money from XYZ. Abel plans to conduct an internal investigation into the missing funds, and during the investigation, Abel plans to interview Beta. Based on these facts, which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE statement?", "options": {"A": "Beta has a fundamental right to have an attorney present at any interview conducted by Abel.", "B": "XYZ cannot fire Beta if he refuses to participate in the interview because of whistleblower protections.", "C": "Before interviewing Beta, Abel must inform Beta that he has a right to remain silent.", "D": "Beta likely has a duty to cooperate with the investigation as part of the employer-employee relationship."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In most jurisdictions, a duty to cooperate exists in every employer-employee relationship, but such duties vary between jurisdictions. Generally, the duty to cooperate extends to workplace investigations; therefore, employees have a duty to cooperate during an internal investigation as long as what is requested from them is reasonable."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "If the evidence clearly shows that a suspect has committed a crime, it is permissible for a fraud examiner to testify that, in his opinion, the suspect is guilty because the evidence has established all of the essential elements of the offense charged.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Certain standards for fraud examiners are found in the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics. Specifically, fraud examiners are prohibited from expressing opinions as to the guilt or innocence of any person or party. This is not to say that the witness cannot testify to the badges, hallmarks, or characteristics of fraud found in the case. It also does not mean that the fraud examiner cannot testify that, based on the evidence, he believes that the accused may have committed the offense. But the ultimate guilt or innocence of any person or party is the sole responsibility of the fact finder. The fraud examiner typically will not be permitted to testify to the ultimate fact questions."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Evidence that proves or disproves facts by inference is called direct evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "There are two basic types of admissible evidence: direct evidence and circumstantial evidence. Direct evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue directly, such as eyewitness testimony or a confession. Circumstantial evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove facts in issue indirectly, by inference."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "A criminal is attempting to launder stolen funds. To confuse the money trail for the funds, he purchases an expensive insurance contract with the illicit funds, cancels the policy shortly after, and receives a refund in a foreign bank account. Which of the following best describes the criminal’s money laundering scheme?", "options": {"A": "Prepayment scheme", "B": "Integration scheme", "C": "Canceled policy scheme", "D": "Redemption scheme"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Insurance policies are designed to protect assets (as well as life and health), but they are also assets in their own right. As is the case with most assets, they can become part of a money laundering scheme. Launderers do not always need to keep or redeem the insurance policies they purchase. Many policies have cancellation provisions that, for a certain amount of time, allow the launderer to cancel the policy and have any unused premiums returned. This technique can be used to temporarily store illicit assets and confuse the money trail by having the cancellation paid out to a different account."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "In limited partnerships, the limited partners manage the enterprise’s activities.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In limited partnerships, the general partners manage the enterprise’s activities, and the limited partners supply the funding. Limited partners do not manage the enterprise’s activities."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Generally, after a civil trial, only the losing side may appeal from an adverse judgment.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Generally, both sides in a civil case may appeal from an adverse judgment, either as to liability or damages. In common law systems, the civil appellate court is largely limited to reviewing the legal decision of the trial court, rather than the factual determination of the jury. The appeals court may reverse and remand for a new trial on some or all of the issues, order that a certain portion of the awarded damages be remitted, or enter final judgment, if legal grounds are clear, in favor of either party. In most civil law systems, the civil appellate court may review issues of both law and fact, meaning it may obtain additional witness testimony, gather new documentary evidence, obtain new expert opinions, and so forth. The appellate court may reverse, affirm, remand for additional proceedings, and (in some jurisdictions) modify the trial court’s decision."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Under the best practices listed in the Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations, which of the following should be required to submit reports to the government when they engage in large cash transactions with customers?", "options": {"A": "Depository institutions (banks)", "B": "Casinos", "C": "Real estate agents", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Under the best practices provided in the FATF’s Recommendations, countries should implement a reporting requirement for financial institutions and designated nonfinancial businesses and professions (DNFBPs) that engage in cash transactions above the jurisdiction's designated threshold. The reports should cover domestic and international cash transactions. Many jurisdictions implement this reporting requirement. Note that the recommended reporting requirement does not apply to everyone; it only applies to financial institutions and DNFBPs. DNFBPs include: Casinos (including Internet- and ship-based casinos) Real estate agents Dealers in precious metals and stones Legal professionals at professional firms (not internal legal professionals) Trust and company service providers"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "The purpose of the authentication requirement in most common law systems is to ensure that hearsay is not admitted into evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In common law systems using adversarial processes, exhibits—the tangible objects presented as evidence—are inadmissible unless they are relevant and established as authentic. The authentication requirement serves to ensure that evidence is what it purports to be and is genuine, not a forgery."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "If, in a country with comprehensive whistleblower protection laws, an employee qualifies as a whistleblower for reporting unlawful conduct by his employer, the employer cannot fire the whistleblowing employee for any reason, including his engagement in an unrelated fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Many jurisdictions have whistleblower laws designed to encourage individuals to bring forth complaints of wrongdoing by providing protections for those who report unlawful conduct. These laws shield employees who report their employers for misconduct by protecting them from any adverse employment action or retaliatory action from their employers. Whistleblower laws do not, however, prevent individuals from being fired for engaging in unrelated fraudulent behavior."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Compared to adversarial jurisdictions, inquisitorial jurisdictions tend to have more confrontational examinations of expert witnesses.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Given that most lay and expert witnesses in inquisitorial jurisdictions are called by the judge, the closest thing to cross-examination in inquisitorial systems occurs when the parties object to or examine the witness. There are several considerations for experts in inquisitorial systems. Since the primary expert or experts are obtained by the court itself, they are generally seen as inherently less biased than experts in adversarial proceedings. Additionally, the selection of the expert is an extension of the court’s authority and discretion. Therefore, for legal counsel to attack the expert’s credibility in an adversarial way would be unacceptable in most circumstances. However, parties usually are allowed to raise objections to experts if they believe they are biased. For example, the expert might have a relationship with one of the parties to the litigation. The parties also are often allowed to question the expert’s analysis or methods used. While this process is less confrontational, a poor performance can lead to the court rejecting the expert’s testimony."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Waiver of a legal professional privilege occurs when a client shares privileged information with an outside party who has nothing to do with the client’s pursuit of legal representation.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Legal professional privileges are not absolute; they are subject to waiver. Because these privileges only protect confidential communications, the protection they provide will be waived for communications disclosed to third parties who have little or nothing to do with the client’s pursuit of legal representation because such disclosures demonstrate a lack of confidentiality. Generally, waiver occurs when the client, who holds the privilege, voluntarily discloses (or consents to or encourages someone else disclosing) any significant part of the privileged communications. Although the client holds the privilege, the privilege can be waived by the client’s attorney or a third party—someone who is neither the attorney nor the client."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "Which of the following property interests is best classified as a secured interest?", "options": {"A": "An energy company’s mineral rights to a parcel of real property", "B": "An heir’s interest in the deceased’s estate", "C": "A home lender’s right to possess and liquidate a debtor’s home if the debtor defaults", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Many jurisdictions recognize a distinction between secured and unsecured creditors during bankruptcy proceedings. A secured creditor is one who has a secured interest in some of the debtor’s property, meaning that if the debtor defaults on payments to the creditor, the creditor may possess or liquidate the secured property to satisfy the debt."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "XYZ Bank has an anti-money laundering program that provides for internal controls and procedures to prevent money laundering, money laundering awareness training for employees, and a regular independent audit function to test the bank’s procedures. If these are the extent of XYZ’s anti-money laundering measures, which of the following elements suggested under the Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations is missing from the anti-money laundering program?", "options": {"A": "Prohibition of large consumer cash deposits", "B": "A mandatory 30-day waiting period before cash deposits can be transferred", "C": "Reporting of all foreign bank transfers to the government", "D": "The designation of a compliance officer at the management level"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Under the FATF’s Recommendations, countries should require financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering and terrorist financing programs. A financial institution’s anti-money laundering (AML) program is highly dependent on which jurisdictions it operates in, as well as the services that it offers. Generally, financial institutions should adopt the AML policies and procedures in the Recommendations, but they need to tailor their programs to the requirements of the specific jurisdictions in which they operate. According to the Recommendations, these programs should include: The development of internal procedures and controls, including adequate screening procedures to ensure high standards in employee hiring Ongoing employee training programs on money laundering risks An independent audit function to test the effectiveness of the programs The designation of a compliance officer at the management level While the FATF does recommend reports from financial institutions to the government on large cash transactions and suspicious transactions, it does not recommend the other choices mentioned."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "A civil action is a legal proceeding brought by a private (non-government) party.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A civil action, as opposed to a criminal action, is an action for wrongdoing that does not result in a criminal fine or incarceration. In contrast to criminal actions, which are brought by the government, civil actions may be brought by private individuals or organizations, usually without the involvement or permission of the government or court. However, a civil action is not necessarily brought by a private party; government entities may also bring civil actions to pursue noncriminal remedies against other parties."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "In cross-examination of an expert witness, the questioning party often will use the \"Is it not true?\" and \"Would you agree with me?\" approach. This technique of cross-examination is used to:", "options": {"A": "Show that the witness's bias prevents him from objectively considering an issue or situation.", "B": "Make the witness appear to be a sounding board by generally agreeing with the questioning party's position.", "C": "Lull the witness into a feeling of false security.", "D": "Confuse the witness in the hope that he might contradict himself."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "During cross-examination, the questioning party might employ various methods to discredit an expert witness or to diminish the importance of his testimony. The sounding board cross-examination method uses the witness as a sounding board to reacquaint the judge or jury with the favorable aspects of the questioning party's theory. This technique often uses the \"Is it not true?\" and \"Would you agree with me?\" approach. Constant, nonstop agreement is used to intimidate the witness. In the eyes of the judge or jury, agreement with various questions raised by the questioning party also might be assumed to be general concurrence with the questioning party. This often is a very valuable psychological tool."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a function that securities exchanges serve?", "options": {"A": "Serving as indicators of economic trends", "B": "Providing a mechanism for private enterprises to raise investment funds", "C": "Supplying investors with a forum to liquidate their holdings", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A securities exchange is a market in which stocks, bonds, and other securities are traded. That is, a securities exchange is a market that provides services for brokers and traders to buy and sell securities. Securities exchanges do not buy or sell securities; they simply provide the location and services for brokers who buy and sell securities. Securities exchanges provide many essential functions. They provide a mechanism for private enterprises to raise investment funds, supply investors with a forum to liquidate their holdings, help in the valuation of securities, and serve as indicators of economic trends."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Paul is on the boards of two companies that compete in the highway construction industry. Paul does not disclose this conflict, and he does not step down from the board of either company. If Paul’s acts are discovered and he is sued for violating his fiduciary duties, under what theory is the suit most likely to be filed?", "options": {"A": "Violating the duty of fair competition", "B": "Violating the duty of care", "C": "Violating the duty of loyalty", "D": "Violating the duty to disclose"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "People in a position of trust or fiduciary relationship—such as officers, directors, high-level employees of a corporation or business, and agents and brokers—owe certain duties to their principals or employers, and any action that runs afoul of such fiduciary duties constitutes a breach. The principal fiduciary duties are loyalty and care. The duty of loyalty requires that the employee/agent act solely in the best interest of the employer/principal, free of any self-dealing, conflicts of interest, or other abuse of the principal for personal advantage. Thus, as part of his duty of loyalty, Paul is obligated to act solely in the best interest of his principal, free of any conflicts of interest. But here, Paul is engaged in an undisclosed conflict of interest by being on the boards of both companies at the same time."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Blake, a Certified Fraud Examiner, testifies during a criminal trial that $25,000 was withdrawn without authorization from the plaintiff’s business, and, one week later, $20,000 was deposited into an account owned by the defendant. In the criminal trial of the defendant for theft, Blake’s testimony would be considered what type of evidence?", "options": {"A": "Circumstantial evidence", "B": "Demonstrative evidence", "C": "Direct evidence", "D": "Real evidence"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are two basic types of admissible evidence: direct evidence and circumstantial evidence. Direct evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue directly, such as eyewitness testimony or a confession. Circumstantial evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove facts in issue indirectly, by inference."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In civil law jurisdictions, judges most commonly serve as the fact finder in criminal proceedings, but some jurisdictions use juries or panels of professional judges and lay judges for serious cases.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In civil law systems, judges serve various roles. They are active participants in gathering evidence from the parties. Unless the civil law system allows for juries, the judge also serves as the fact finder and decides matters of law. Juries are less frequently used in a civil law system than in a common law system; they are usually reserved for serious crimes, and some countries do not use them at all. Several civil law systems feature a mixture of judges and laypersons when juries are used. For instance, a panel could have three judges and nine laypersons who would decide the outcome of the case. Alternatively, some civil law systems feature criminal trials with a panel of both professional judges and lay judges. These panels are unlike juries in the sense that they do not include randomly selected peers of the defendant, but they serve a fact-finding function that is similar to juries."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is a common law invasion of privacy civil wrong that occurs when an individual intentionally encroaches into an area where another individual has a reasonable expectation of privacy and the encroachment would be highly offensive or objectionable to a reasonable person?", "options": {"A": "Slander", "B": "Intrusion into an individual’s private matters", "C": "Infliction of emotional distress", "D": "Public disclosure of private facts"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The civil wrong regarding intrusion into an individual’s private matters (often referred to as intrusion upon seclusion) occurs when an individual intentionally intrudes into another individual’s private matters and the intrusion would be highly offensive or objectionable to a reasonable person. The elements of this civil wrong include: An intentional intrusion Into an area where an individual has a reasonable expectation of privacy The intrusion would be highly offensive or objectionable to a reasonable person"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "Which of the following types of law is/are created by legislatures?", "options": {"A": "Common law", "B": "Case law", "C": "Statutory law", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In common law countries, there are two sources of substantive law: statutory law and common law. Statutory law includes statutes passed by legislatures (and regulations passed by administrative bodies). The common law is developed on a case-by-case basis. That is, the common law is a system of legal principles developed by judges through decisions made in courts. It consists of the usages and customs of a society as interpreted by the judiciary, and it is often referred to as judge-made law. In the modern era of law, the trend in common law countries has been to move away from rules that originate in common law and instead rely on statutory law—laws created by a legislature or other governing authority—as the basis of a dispute. Additionally, civil law systems use statutory law or a codified set of principles as their primary source of law."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In most civil law jurisdictions, a defendant’s guilt and punishment (if the defendant is found guilty) are each decided during separate proceedings.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Civil law systems typically do not provide for a separate hearing for sentencing. The decisions of guilt and punishment are made and announced together. In common law jurisdictions, when a defendant is convicted of a crime, the court typically holds a sentencing hearing to determine the manner in which the defendant will serve his sentence. Before the sentencing hearing, a government worker will prepare a pre-sentence report that will review the defendant’s character, background, associates, prior criminal record, and other factors relevant to setting an appropriate sentence. The report is designed to assist the sentencing judge in assessing punishment."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "In most common law jurisdictions, courts are bound by two sources of substantive law—law from statutes (including codes or other laws passed by legislatures) and judge-made law based on previous court decisions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Almost every country can be classified as having either a common law or a civil law judicial system; knowing the differences between the two is essential to understanding how legal and judicial processes work in foreign jurisdictions. In most common law systems, there are laws that judges develop through court decisions (called the common law), as well as codes and statutes that establish laws. As opposed to legislative statutes, the common law is developed on a case-by-case basis. That is, the common law is a system of legal principles developed by judges through decisions made in courts. It consists of the usages and customs of a society as interpreted by the judiciary, and it is often referred to as judge-made law. Common law originated as a legal system in England, and some of the principles established hundreds of years ago in court decisions remain influential to contemporary legal issues. Today, common law systems exist in the United Kingdom, the United States, India, Australia, and many other countries that were once part of the British Empire or were influenced by such legal systems. In common law countries, there are two sources of substantive law: statutory law and common law. Statutory law includes statutes passed by legislatures (and regulations passed by administrative bodies)."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Abel, a fraud examiner, interviewed Beta, a fraud suspect. No other people were present at the interview. During the interview, Abel accused Beta of committing fraud. This accusation later turned out to be erroneous, and Beta sued Abel for damages. Under these facts, which of the following statements is CORRECT?", "options": {"A": "If Beta sued Abel for slander, Beta would not recover damages because Abel did not publish the accusation to a third party.", "B": "If Beta sued Abel for defamation, Beta would recover damages because Abel made an untrue statement of fact on an unprivileged occasion.", "C": "If Beta sued Abel for libel, Beta would not recover damages because Abel believed the accusation to be true.", "D": "If Beta sued Abel for defamation, Beta would recover damages because Abel made public statements about Beta’s private life on an unprivileged occasion."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Generally speaking, defamation refers to the unprivileged publication of false statements about a person that causes harm to that person’s reputation. To recover for defamation, the plaintiff must generally prove all of the following elements: The defendant made an untrue statement of fact. The statement was communicated (published) to third parties. The statement was made on an unprivileged occasion. The statement damaged the subject's reputation. Even though Abel made an untrue statement, it was not broadcast to a third party or parties. As a result, the statement does not meet the test of defamation. So, Abel did not commit slander, and Beta would not recover any damages. Also, Beta cannot recover damages for libel because Abel's accusation was not in written form. It does not matter whether Abel believed the accusation to be true."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "Most common law jurisdictions feature an adversarial judicial process in which the parties primarily drive the evidence-gathering portion of judicial proceedings.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Adversarial and inquisitorial judicial processes refer to the type of approach that courts take to discover evidence in a case. Theoretically, neither of these processes is exclusive of common law or civil law systems. Civil law jurisdictions, however, almost always favor an inquisitorial process, while common law systems typically feature an adversarial system. Adversarial processes are those in which the parties to a proceeding drive the discovery process (the search for evidence). The theory behind this approach is that the competing interests of the parties will serve to expose the relevant facts of the case. In adversarial systems, the parties to the litigation gather and present the evidence to the court. For example, the parties (usually through legal counsel) conduct questioning of fact and expert witnesses. The fact finder of the court, which can be a judge, jury, or administrator, is unaware of the details of the case until the parties present evidence. Judges facilitate the production of evidence between the parties, but they generally do not seek evidence on the court’s behalf."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Which of the following describes a conflict of interest for a testifying expert witness?", "options": {"A": "The testifying expert knew or met any parties or their attorneys before being retained as an expert", "B": "The testifying expert has received any form of compensation for serving as an expert witness", "C": "The testifying expert’s ability to objectively evaluate and present a client’s issue is impaired by any relationship with any parties", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "When retained, experts must quickly determine if any conflicts of interest exist—or even appear to exist—in a particular case because a conflict might preclude participation. A conflict of interest exists when an expert’s ability to objectively evaluate and present an issue for a client will be impaired by any current, prior, or future relationship with parties to the litigation. Prior or ongoing relationships might suggest to others that the expert cannot provide undivided loyalty to the cause and the client. Whether a relationship causes a conflict of interest depends on the facts. Simply meeting a person does not necessarily cause a conflict, but a close personal or business relationship is more likely to give the perception of a conflict. Compensation (whether from the parties or from the court) for expert testimony services is standard, and it is not generally considered a conflict of interest. The amount of compensation can be brought up at trial, so the payment should not be above normal."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is one of the objectives on which the International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO) Objectives and Principles of Securities Regulation are based?", "options": {"A": "Enhancing the financial system’s growth", "B": "Harmonizing securities laws and standards across the globe", "C": "Ensuring that markets are fair, efficient, and transparent", "D": "Eliminating market risk"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The IOSCO Objectives and Principles of Securities Regulation are based on the following three objectives: The protection of investors Ensuring that markets are fair, efficient, and transparent The reduction of systemic risk"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following statements about an employee monitoring program is MOST ACCURATE?", "options": {"A": "Most countries require employers to give employees notice before implementing an employee monitoring program.", "B": "Most countries permit employers to implement a covert employee monitoring program.", "C": "Employers are always required to give employees notice and obtain their consent before implementing an employee monitoring program.", "D": "Employers are always required to obtain employee consent before implementing an employee monitoring program."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Nearly every country prohibits covert employee monitoring, unless a specific criminal activity has been identified. Therefore, nearly every employer is required to notify its employees before implementing an employee monitoring program. The notice should be clear and comprehensive, and it should be made in writing. While employees must consent to employee monitoring in some countries, this requirement does not apply to all jurisdictions."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "If an employer is investigating an employee who is a member of a union, the union contract might contain certain clauses that restrict the employer’s investigatory procedures.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Employees may have contractual rights that are enforceable against their employers and that might limit the employers’ ability to compel full cooperation in a fraud examination. Employers and employees may enter into contracts that govern the employment relationship, and if the employer violates the contract, the employee can sue for breach of contract. Often, employee contractual rights at issue during investigations arise from a union contract, a collective bargaining agreement, or an employment contract. For example, if the employee is a member of a union, the union contract or collective bargaining agreement might contain certain restrictions on the employer’s investigatory procedures."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a legal element that a plaintiff must prove to recover for defamation?", "options": {"A": "The statement was printed and distributed.", "B": "The defendant made an untrue statement of fact.", "C": "The statement damaged the subject’s reputation.", "D": "The statement was communicated (published) to third parties."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "To recover for defamation, the plaintiff must generally prove all of the following elements: The defendant made an untrue statement of fact. The statement was communicated (published) to third parties. The statement was made on an unprivileged occasion. The statement damaged the subject’s reputation."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "In adversarial jurisdictions, if an individual is qualified as an expert, the judge must allow his expert testimony at trial.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Simple qualification is not sufficient. Generally, before allowing an expert to testify before the jury in an adversarial jurisdiction, the judge will make three determinations: Is the person qualified as an expert witness? Will the expertise of the witness assist the jury in understanding the evidence or determining a fact at issue? In other words, is the proposed testimony relevant to the facts of the case? Is the testimony reliable?"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning the United Nations’ International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR) is FALSE?", "options": {"A": "It states that the results of criminal hearings should be publicized in most cases to promote transparency in the criminal justice system.", "B": "It states that the right of the accused to a fair hearing includes adequate time to prepare a defense.", "C": "It states that the right of the accused to a fair hearing includes the right to trial by jury.", "D": "It states that the right of the accused to a fair hearing includes the right to examine or have examined witnesses against the accused."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Most countries have signed and ratified the United Nations’ International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR), which commits them to recognizing various rights of citizens. Part III of the ICCPR includes the rights of those accused of crimes. As one of these rights, the ICCPR states that all people accused of crimes are entitled to a fair hearing before a court or other tribunal and that the results of the trial should be made public to protect the criminal justice system’s transparency. This right includes: Adequate time to prepare a defense The ability to be represented by legal counsel of the defendant’s choosing and to freely communicate with counsel The right to have accusations and the procedures explained through a translator for free, if necessary The right to be tried for charges without undue delay The right to examine or have examined the witnesses against the accused Freedom from testifying against oneself or compelled confessions While the ICCPR states that countries should establish a right to a fair and impartial hearing, it does not specifically require a trial by jury."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Generally, to establish an illegal gratuity violation, the government must prove that the gratuity was given for the purpose of influencing an official act.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "An illegal gratuity charge doesn’t require proof that the gratuity was given for the purpose of influencing an official act. That is, an illegal gratuity charge only requires that the gratuity be given for, or because of, an official act."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "In most jurisdictions with inquisitorial judicial processes, which of the following parties selects expert witnesses to provide testimony to the court?", "options": {"A": "The judge selects a neutral expert to interpret the facts for the court.", "B": "The members of the jury vote to select an expert to interpret the facts.", "C": "The expert is chosen from a lottery of qualified listed experts in the field.", "D": "Each party selects its own expert to present its interpretation of the facts."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Before an individual can testify as an expert, the proposed witness must be qualified as an expert. But what constitutes expert status? Generally, the term expert witness refers to someone whose education and professional credentials establish his knowledge of a particular set of practices. The process for qualifying as an expert varies between countries, but there are some common approaches in adversarial and inquisitorial jurisdictions. The primary experts in inquisitorial jurisdictions are usually appointed and presented by the judge, rather than the parties. Like in adversarial jurisdictions, the judge makes the final determination of whether an expert is qualified. Many jurisdictions (through the courts, chambers of commerce, or other organizations) maintain lists of experts in particular fields from which the courts may choose for the case at hand. These experts are qualified if they meet national standards, such as being certified in a particular field (e.g., an accounting certification). Some jurisdictions allow judges to look outside of the lists for experts. In some jurisdictions, the courts allow parties to collectively agree on an expert to advise the court or even submit their own experts. However, even in cases where the parties submit their own experts, the court will generally appoint its own neutral expert to evaluate the case and the other experts’ claims."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "The Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations advise that countries should require financial institutions to keep certain records and establish anti-money laundering policies.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is an intergovernmental body that was established at the G-7 Summit in 1989. Its purpose is to develop and promote standards and policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing at both the national and international levels. The FATF’s Recommendations, revised in 2012, created the most comprehensive standard with which to measure a country’s anti-money laundering, counterterrorism, and nuclear proliferation laws and policies. They serve as a basic framework of laws that its members should have. While the recommendations are not required by members and the FATF acknowledges that following each rule might not be possible, members of the FATF often adopt them. Some of the key measures in the Recommendations provide that countries should: Use a risk-based approach when setting anti-money laundering policies. Create policies that increase cooperation and coordination with other countries. Specifically criminalize money laundering and terrorist financing. Enable authorities to trace, freeze, and confiscate assets suspected in laundering and terrorist financing. Require financial institutions to keep certain records and establish anti-money laundering policies, avoid correspondent banking with shell banks, and continuously monitor wire transfers."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Litigation privileges and other similar evidentiary protections, such as the U.S. attorney work-product doctrine, protect documents and materials prepared by an attorney, but their protection does not extend to documents and materials prepared by third parties.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Litigation privileges and other similar evidentiary protections, such as the U.S. attorney work-product doctrine, protect materials that are prepared in anticipation of litigation. Thus, they apply only to documents and things prepared in anticipation of litigation or for trial. These protections prevent the disclosure of communications made and documents prepared for the purpose of litigation. Consequently, the protections they afford may extend to communications of, and documents created by, third-party agents (e.g., consultants or fraud examiners) in preparation for litigation."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "In common law jurisdictions with civil laws for defamation and invasion of privacy, under which cause of action can an investigator be held liable for a TRUE statement made about a suspect?", "options": {"A": "Public disclosure of private facts", "B": "Defamation", "C": "Intrusion upon seclusion", "D": "Slander"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Invasion of privacy laws concern a person’s right to keep his life private and free from intrusion, and in many common law countries, invasion of privacy is a civil wrong that can be addressed by a court through a lawsuit. The two most common forms of invasion of privacy applicable to fraud examinations are intrusion into an individual’s private matters and publicity of private facts. The civil wrong regarding intrusion into an individual’s private matters (often referred to as intrusion upon seclusion) occurs when an individual intentionally intrudes into another individual’s private matters and the intrusion would be highly offensive or objectionable to a reasonable person. Public disclosure of private facts occurs when one party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern. Unlike the requirements to establish a claim for defamation, liability for the public disclosure of private facts cause of action can arise even if the statements at issue are true. The key to this cause of action is that the information must be private in nature and not a matter of public interest."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "The International Councils of Securities Associations (ICSA) is recognized as the international standard setter for securities markets.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO) is an international organization comprised of securities commissioners and administrators responsible for securities regulation and the administration of securities laws in their respective countries. IOSCO is recognized as the international standard setter for securities markets, and the organization’s members regulate more than 95% of the world’s securities markets."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Gerald is involved in pretrial civil litigation in a common law jurisdiction and believes the other party knows several facts that are relevant to the case. Which of the following statements is MOST ACCURATE?", "options": {"A": "Gerald may request the information from the party through a written pretrial examination.", "B": "Gerald may not request information from the other party in civil litigation.", "C": "Gerald must wait for the judge to obtain the information during the judge’s investigation.", "D": "Gerald will have to wait until trial to request that the other party provide this information."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "After the parties have submitted pleadings to the court, the evidence-gathering process begins. The system for collecting evidence varies from country to country, especially along the lines of adversarial processes (generally common law systems) and inquisitorial processes (generally civil law systems). In common law jurisdictions, a party may be examined or questioned by the other party either orally or through written questions. Some common law jurisdictions might not allow for pretrial oral discovery, although written pretrial discovery is still available. A written examination for discovery, or interrogatory, is simply a list of questions that the party, usually through a lawyer, is required to answer in writing."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning tax shelters is most accurate?", "options": {"A": "Tax shelters are always legal.", "B": "Tax shelters are inherently illegal.", "C": "Tax shelters are generally illegal in most countries.", "D": "Tax shelters may be legal or illegal."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Tax shelters are investments that are designed to yield a tax benefit to the investor. Such investments are made to produce tax write-offs, generate deductions, or convert ordinary income into capital gains taxed at a lower rate. Tax shelters might be legal or illegal; they are generally aimed at avoidance, although they might, on occasion, cross the line into evasion if they take abusive forms. An illegal, abusive shelter is one that involves artificial transactions with little or no economic reality. For example, abusive tax shelters might artificially inflate the value of donations to charity; falsely identify an asset for business use that is mainly intended for pleasure; claim excess depreciation or depletion; or engage in the cross-leasing of luxury items such as automobiles, boats, vacation homes, and aircrafts."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "The purpose of a liquidation bankruptcy filing is to allow the debtor respite from creditors so that the debtor can reorganize its financial affairs and continue as a going concern.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The structure of bankruptcy proceedings varies by jurisdiction, so it is always important to study the rules of the relevant jurisdiction when dealing with potential bankruptcy fraud. However, there are common types of bankruptcy filings, and most countries have adopted a similar version of at least one. Liquidation is the most basic type of bankruptcy proceeding and involves accounting for all dischargeable debts the subject owes, identifying all of the subject’s assets, and liquidating nonexempt assets to pay off creditors. This process allows the debtor to get a court or administrative order under which some or all debts may be eliminated. Unlike liquidation, which seeks to give the debtor a fresh start, the purpose of reorganization bankruptcy is to allow the debtor respite from creditors so that the debtor can reorganize its financial affairs and continue as a going concern. Some reorganization proceedings involve putting the debtor’s business under receivership for a certain period to ensure as much debt is paid back as possible."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Moore, a transportation officer for his government’s defense department, is responsible for awarding contracts to private freight carriers for the defense department’s freight shipments. Moore awarded Zantigo Freight a shipment contract to transport defense department equipment, and, as a gesture of thanks, Zantigo gave Moore a new laptop computer. Based on these facts, the government would be more likely to bring illegal gratuity charges against Moore than bribery charges.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Illegal gratuities are items of value given to reward a decision, often after the recipient has made the decision. Illegal gratuities are similar to official bribery schemes, and most illegal gratuity laws outlaw gratuities in the public sector. In general, the elements of an illegal gratuity are: A thing of value Given, offered, or promised to (or demanded, sought, received, or accepted by) A (present, former, or future) public official For or because of any official act performed or to be performed by that public official Under these facts, there is no evidence that Zantigo gave the laptop to Moore to influence his decision, since the gift occurred after the decision was made. The government would be more likely to bring illegal gratuity charges against Moore, charging that the gift was for, or because of, Moore’s official act."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "To determine if a misrepresentation in the offer or sale of any securities is material, a fraud examiner should consider which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Whether the person who made the representation had authorization to make the statements", "B": "Whether the person who made the representation believed that it was suitable for potential investors", "C": "Whether the person who made the representation intended to mislead potential investors", "D": "Whether a reasonable investor would wish to know the information to make an informed decision"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Securities laws require that the investor receive full and fair disclosure of all material information, and they make it unlawful for anyone to obtain money or property by using a material misstatement or omission in the offer or sale of any securities. As a general rule, to determine materiality, the fraud examiner needs to answer the following question: “Would a reasonable investor wish to know this information to make an informed decision?” If the answer is “yes,” then this information, or the lack thereof, has a high likelihood of being deemed material. (If an actual investor acted based on the misrepresentation, that clearly strengthens the case, but it is not essential that the false or misleading statement influenced an investor, merely that a reasonable investor could have been so influenced.)"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Which of the following is an acceptable way of authenticating digital records in most common law systems?", "options": {"A": "Having a witness with personal knowledge of the records offer testimony", "B": "Accompanying the evidence with a written certification by the custodian of records", "C": "Providing evidence of distinctive characteristics of the records", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In common law systems using adversarial processes, exhibits—the tangible objects presented as evidence—are inadmissible unless they are relevant and established as authentic. Thus, to be admissible at trial, evidence, other than testimonial evidence, must be properly authenticated; that is, the party offering the item must produce some evidence (e.g., testimony from a person with firsthand knowledge) to show it is, in fact, what the party says it is and to show it is in the same condition as when it was seized. If an exhibit cannot be authenticated, it will not be admitted even if it is plainly relevant. The most likely methods of authenticating digital records are: Testimony from a witness with personal knowledge (e.g., an authenticating witness attests to the process by which the digital records are created, acquired, maintained, and preserved) Circumstantial evidence of distinctive characteristics (e.g., a person's business habit is consistent with the document) Certified copies of business records (e.g., digital records are accompanied by a custodian's written certification)"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following must a plaintiff show to recover for a claim of false imprisonment?", "options": {"A": "The defendant restrained the plaintiff without consent or legal justification.", "B": "The defendant was not protected under the qualified business privilege.", "C": "The defendant knew his conduct was illegal.", "D": "The defendant was a law enforcement officer."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "False imprisonment is the unlawful restraint by one person of the physical liberty of another without consent or legal justification. To recover for a claim of false imprisonment, the plaintiff generally must prove all of the following elements: The defendant used words or actions intended to restrain the plaintiff. The defendant’s words or actions resulted in the restraint of the plaintiff without the plaintiff’s consent (i.e., against the plaintiff’s will) and without legal justification. The plaintiff was aware that he was being restrained. A claim of false imprisonment might arise if an employee is detained in any way during a search or interview. Generally, an employer is entitled to question an employee at work about a violation of company policy without incurring liability as long as the employee submits to the questioning voluntarily; that is, not as a result of threats or force."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Illegal pyramid schemes and Ponzi schemes can qualify as investment contracts under certain conditions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Many fraudulent schemes involving exotic investments can be argued to constitute the offer or sale of investment contracts. The following are types of investments that frequently qualify as investment contracts: Ponzi schemes Illegal pyramid schemes Prime-bank note schemes Investment schemes involving precious metals or stones Viatical settlements Partnerships Joint ventures Oil, gas, and mineral interests Hedge funds Promissory notes"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is a common legal defense to tax evasion?", "options": {"A": "The taxpayer engaged in tax avoidance, not tax evasion", "B": "The taxpayer relied on an attorney or accountant", "C": "The taxpayer was mentally ill at the time of the conduct", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A suspect or a criminal defendant might raise various defenses to accusations of tax evasion. Whether these defenses are legally recognized depends on the laws of the jurisdiction. The following are common defenses to tax evasion: No tax deficiency: The defendant can establish that there is no deficiency. In most jurisdictions, if there is no deficiency, there is no tax liability. This is generally the best defense, if available, because several other defenses might negate willfulness, but do not necessarily eliminate a tax liability with interest and penalties. Lack of willfulness: A lack of willfulness reduces the defendant’s culpability for fraud. A good faith belief that one is not violating the tax law, based on a misunderstanding caused by the law’s complexity, negates willfulness. Avoidance, not evasion: A taxpayer charged with tax crimes might argue that he engaged in legal means of lowering his tax bill through legitimate avoidance mechanisms, such as deductions, credits, and shelters. Thus, establishing that the taxpayer was engaging in tax avoidance and not evasion provides a defense to tax fraud. Reliance on an attorney or accountant: If a taxpayer properly relied on expert advice for the conduct in question, the jurisdiction might find no criminal liability. Mental illness: Certain mental illnesses and incapacitating conditions negate criminal intent for tax crimes."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "To determine if a misrepresentation in the offer or sale of any securities is ________, the fraud examiner should answer the following question: \"Would a reasonable investor wish to know this information to make an informed decision?\"", "options": {"A": "Relevant", "B": "Promotional", "C": "Material", "D": "Privileged"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Securities laws require that the investor receive full and fair disclosure of all material information, and they make it unlawful for anyone to obtain money or property by using a material misstatement or omission in the offer or sale of any securities. As a general rule, to determine materiality, the fraud examiner needs to answer the following question: “Would a reasonable investor wish to know this information to make an informed decision?” If the answer is “yes,” then this information, or the lack thereof, has a high likelihood of being deemed material. (If an actual investor acted based on the misrepresentation, that clearly strengthens the case, but it is not essential that the false or misleading statement influenced an investor, merely that a reasonable investor could have been so influenced.)"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "In alternative remittance systems, which of the following types of information are typically found in the ledgers that the brokers use to keep track of amounts owed to each other?", "options": {"A": "The names of the senders", "B": "The names of the receivers", "C": "The bank account numbers of the senders and receivers", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Alternative remittance systems (also called parallel banking systems) are methods of transferring funds from a party at one location to another party (whether domestic or foreign) without the use of formal banking institutions. These systems are characterized by the lack of direct physical or digital transfer of currency from the sender to the receiver. Instead, in the typical alternative remittance system, the payer transfers funds to a local broker who has a connection to another broker in the region where the payee is located. The latter broker then distributes the funds to the payee. The parties involved in alternative remittance systems form a network and track their exchanges on an informal ledger. Unlike formal financial institutions, these ledgers will not generally list specific information about the payers and payees (such as bank account numbers and names) but will keep track of amounts owed. When the first broker requests that another broker in the network distribute funds, the debt is recorded in the ledgers. These debts between brokers could be paid back by offsetting transactions (i.e., the first broker pays someone locally at the request of the second broker). Alternatively, the parties could meet to settle all outstanding debts at a later time."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In a particular jurisdiction, criminal trials often involve a single judge responsible for determining factual issues. In serious cases, the court uses a panel comprised of both professional judges and lay judges to determine such issues. Based on this information alone, the jurisdiction would likely be characterized as which of the following systems?", "options": {"A": "Federal system", "B": "Civil law system", "C": "Common law system", "D": "Unitary system"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In civil law systems, judges serve various roles. They are active participants in gathering evidence from the parties. Unless the civil law system allows for juries, the judge also serves as the fact finder and decides matters of law. Juries are less frequently used in a civil law system than in a common law system; they are usually reserved for serious crimes, and some countries do not use them at all. Several civil law systems feature a mixture of judges and laypersons when juries are used. For instance, a panel could have three judges and nine laypersons who would decide the outcome of the case. Alternatively, some civil law systems feature criminal trials with a panel of both professional judges and lay judges. These panels are unlike juries in the sense that they do not include randomly selected peers of the defendant, but they serve a fact-finding function that is similar to juries. Unitary and federal systems refer to types of government structures unrelated to the fact-finding function of a jurisdiction’s courts."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "One function of a securities exchange is to buy and sell stocks.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A securities exchange is a market in which stocks, bonds, and other securities are traded. That is, a securities exchange is a market that provides services for brokers and traders to buy and sell securities. Securities exchanges do not buy or sell securities; they simply provide the location and services for brokers who buy and sell securities. Securities exchanges provide many essential functions. They provide a mechanism for private enterprises to raise investment funds, supply investors with a forum to liquidate their holdings, help in the valuation of securities, and serve as indicators of economic trends."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "The fact that an item of evidence is relevant does not automatically mean that it will be admitted in adversarial trials. Evidence might be relevant but still excluded for other reasons. Which of the following is one of those reasons?", "options": {"A": "Waste of time", "B": "Misleading", "C": "Unduly prejudicial", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In common law systems using adversarial processes, the fact that an item of evidence is relevant does not automatically mean that it will be admitted. Relevant evidence might be excluded if it is unduly prejudicial, threatens to confuse or mislead the jury, threatens to cause unnecessary delay or waste of time, or is merely cumulative."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "A private UK company transfers $60,000 to a Chinese public official to influence the award of a public construction contract. This act would constitute a violation of the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA).", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The anti-bribery provisions of the FCPA make it unlawful to bribe a foreign official for business purposes. Only regulated parties, such as issuers, domestic concerns, and foreign nationals or businesses, are subject to FCPA jurisdiction. An issuer is a corporation that has issued securities that have been registered in the United States or that is required to file periodic reports with the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC). A domestic concern is any citizen, national, or resident of the United States, or any business entity that has its principal place of business in the United States or that is organized under the laws of a state, territory, possession, or commonwealth of the United States. Moreover, the FCPA applies extraterritorially to U.S. citizens working for foreign subsidiaries of domestic companies. A foreign national or business is subject to the FCPA if it takes any act in furtherance of a corrupt payment within U.S. territory. Additionally, the agents, subsidiaries, or other third-party representatives who act on behalf of an issuer, a domestic concern, or a foreign national or business are liable under the same conditions as the issuer, domestic concern, or foreign national or business. The FCPA’s anti-bribery provisions extend only to corrupt payments made to foreign officials. Although the UK private company is attempting to influence a foreign official, the UK company did not violate the FCPA because it is not subject to FCPA jurisdiction. The UK company does not have its principal place of business in the United States, and it is not organized under the laws of the United States. Also, the UK company is a private company, so it is not an issuer. Moreover, the UK company did not take any act in furtherance of a corrupt payment within U.S. territory; the $60,000 transfer was made to a Chinese public official. Therefore, the $60,000 transfer does not violate the FCPA."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following statements regarding the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) is MOST ACCURATE?", "options": {"A": "An organization must immediately notify all data subjects affected by a data breach, regardless of the breach’s severity.", "B": "An organization must always delete a data subject’s personal information upon that individual’s request.", "C": "An organization must inform data subjects that they can withdraw their consent for the collection of data at any time.", "D": "An organization is not required to confirm or deny its possession of a data subject’s personal data, even upon request."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Under the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), organizations must obtain the consent of data subjects before collecting or processing their personal data. Data subjects must give their consent via a statement or clear affirmative action. In addition, data subjects must be informed that they can withdraw their consent at any time, and withdrawal of their consent must be as easy as providing consent. Upon a data subject’s request, an organization must confirm or deny that it possesses the data subject’s personal data. The organization also must provide the data subject with a free copy of the personal data and any other specified information, such as the purpose of the data collection or the length of time that the information will be stored. Under some circumstances, organizations can be compelled to delete personal data upon request. For example, a data subject may request the erasure of personal data if the data are no longer necessary in relation to the purpose for which they were collected, the data subject withdraws consent, the data were unlawfully collected or processed, or the data subject was a child when the data were collected. Organizations must respond to such requests without undue delay. In the event of a data breach, the GDPR generally requires an organization to notify all affected data subjects without undue delay if the breach is likely to result in a high risk to their rights and freedoms. However, the organization is not required to notify data subjects if the breach only involved encrypted or otherwise unintelligible data or if the organization took actions after the breach that substantially minimized the risk to data subjects."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "In an arbitration proceeding, the arbitrator acts as a judge or jury by deciding the case on its merits.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Arbitration is the process whereby a dispute is submitted to an impartial third person (known as an arbitrator) who then decides the outcome of the case (i.e., which party should win). The arbitrator acts as a judge or jury by deciding the case on its merits. Arbitration can be either binding or nonbinding. If the arbitration is binding, then the decision of the arbitrator is final, and the parties cannot later submit their dispute to a judge or jury for determination. Conversely, if the arbitration is nonbinding, the arbitrator’s determination is not binding upon the parties."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Michael Caston, a fraud suspect, confesses to a fraud. During Caston’s trial for the fraud, the government introduces the confession as evidence of Caston’s intent to commit the fraudulent act for which he is charged. What type of evidence is Caston’s confession?", "options": {"A": "Testimonial", "B": "Character", "C": "Circumstantial", "D": "Direct"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There are two basic types of admissible evidence: direct evidence and circumstantial evidence. Direct evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue directly, such as eyewitness testimony or a confession. Circumstantial evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove facts in issue indirectly, by inference."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Which of the following is a method of pretrial civil discovery used in most common law jurisdictions?", "options": {"A": "Injunctions", "B": "Pretrial written examinations", "C": "Indictments", "D": "Requests for agreement"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In common law jurisdictions, a party may be examined or questioned by the other party either orally or through written questions during the pretrial stage of litigation. A pretrial written examination for discovery, or interrogatory, is simply a list of questions that the party, usually through a lawyer, is required to answer in writing."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Litigation privileges and other similar evidentiary protections, such as the U.S. attorney work-product doctrine, apply only to documents and things prepared in anticipation of litigation or for trial.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Litigation privileges and other similar evidentiary protections, such as the U.S. attorney work-product doctrine, protect materials that are prepared in anticipation of litigation. Thus, they apply only to documents and things prepared in anticipation of litigation or for trial. These protections prevent the disclosure of communications made and documents prepared for the purpose of litigation. Also, the protections they afford may extend to communications of, and documents created by, third-party agents (e.g., consultants or fraud examiners) in preparation for litigation. The litigation privilege arises once litigation is reasonably anticipated. Accordingly, communication is only privileged under the litigation privilege if litigation was contemplated at the time the communication was created. Therefore, the privilege does not cover documents that came into existence before litigation was contemplated."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "The ABC Company, a UK company with securities that are registered in the United States, transferred $40,000 to a Japanese public official to influence the award of lucrative overseas contracts. This act would constitute a violation of the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) and the UK Bribery Act.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The FCPA’s anti-bribery provisions make it unlawful for regulated parties (such as issuers, domestic concerns, and foreign nationals or businesses) to bribe foreign government officials to obtain or retain business. An issuer is a corporation that has issued securities that have been registered in the United States or that is required to file periodic reports with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC). Thus, the ABC Company is a regulated party under the FCPA because it is an issuer. The Bribery Act is the United Kingdom’s analogue of the FCPA, although with several distinctions. In short, the Bribery Act contains a specific offense for the bribery of foreign public officials; it contains a general commercial bribery offense; and it creates a corporate offense of failure to prevent bribery. The Bribery Act exercises broad jurisdiction over all individuals and corporate entities for such acts when any part of the offense occurs in the UK. Furthermore, liability exists for acts committed outside the UK by individuals and entities with a close connection to the UK, including: British citizens, overseas citizens, overseas territories' citizens, and any person declared a British subject under the 1981 British Nationality Act Individuals who normally reside in the UK An entity incorporated under the law of any part of the UK"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Which of the following best describes the differences between the appointment of expert witnesses in most adversarial and inquisitorial jurisdictions?", "options": {"A": "The court has the power to appoint expert witnesses in inquisitorial jurisdictions but not in adversarial jurisdictions.", "B": "Expert witnesses are allowed to be appointed in adversarial jurisdictions but not in inquisitorial jurisdictions.", "C": "Experts are usually selected and appointed by the court in adversarial systems, but the parties primarily select experts in inquisitorial jurisdictions.", "D": "Experts in inquisitorial jurisdictions are primarily appointed and presented by the court, whereas the parties usually select and present experts in adversarial jurisdictions."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Most expert witnesses in adversarial proceedings are chosen by the parties to the litigation (although adversarial courts may also appoint independent experts). In adversarial systems, the expert and the retaining party are “allies” in the sense that legal counsel will attempt to paint the expert’s testimony in the best light during direct examination and will try to correct any issues in the expert’s testimony that the opposing party raises. However, it is important that the expert never allow his opinion or best judgment to be supplanted by that of the retaining party. In most inquisitorial systems, the primary experts are obtained by the court. Expert witnesses in inquisitorial jurisdictions are subject to various examinations and might have to conduct their own examinations of witnesses. Usually, all of the expert’s activities related to the case are controlled by the judge, who determines the scope of the expert’s analysis, the expert’s authority to access certain items of evidence, whom the expert can interview, and several other functions. Because some jurisdictions allow parties to submit testimony or evidence from their own experts in addition to the court-appointed expert, the latter might need to interview the parties’ experts. The expert should carefully follow the judge’s instructions, especially since the instructions are usually made available to the parties of the proceeding."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Black, a Certified Fraud Examiner, interviews Green, a fraud suspect. No one else is present at the interview. During the interview, Black accuses Green of committing fraud. Later, it turns out that Green is innocent. Green can sue and recover damages from Black on a claim of defamation if he can show that Black knowingly made the false statement on an unprivileged occasion and that the statement caused economic harm.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Even though Green is innocent, he generally will not be able to recover under a defamation theory because Black's statement was not \"published\" to a third party. Generally speaking, defamation refers to the unprivileged publication of false statements about a person that causes harm to that person’s reputation. To recover for defamation, the plaintiff must generally prove all of the following elements: The defendant made an untrue statement of fact. The statement was communicated (published) to third parties. The statement was made on an unprivileged occasion. The statement damaged the subject's reputation."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "In adversarial judicial processes, which of the following parties typically gathers evidence for the case and conducts the questioning of witnesses at trial?", "options": {"A": "The jury", "B": "The parties or their legal counsel", "C": "The court clerk", "D": "The judge or magistrate"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Adversarial and inquisitorial judicial processes refer to the type of approach that courts take to discover evidence in a case. Adversarial processes are those in which the parties to a proceeding drive the discovery process (the search for evidence). The theory behind this approach is that the competing interests of the parties will serve to expose the relevant facts of the case. In adversarial systems, the parties to the litigation gather and present the evidence to the court. For example, the parties (usually through legal counsel) conduct questioning of fact and expert witnesses. The fact finder of the court, which can be a judge, jury, or administrator, is unaware of the details of the case until the parties present evidence. Judges facilitate the production of evidence between the parties, but they generally do not seek evidence on the court’s behalf."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "The stage in which money laundering schemes are most often detected is called:", "options": {"A": "Placement", "B": "Integration", "C": "Layering", "D": "Washing"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Placement is the first stage of the money laundering process. In this stage, the launderer introduces his illegal profits into the financial system. It is at this stage that legislation has been developed to prevent launderers from depositing or converting large amounts of cash at financial institutions or taking cash out of the country. Money laundering schemes are most often detected at the placement stage."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following outcomes to criminal allegations of fraud against an organization occurs when prosecutors agree not to prosecute claims as long as the organization reforms its practices and reduces the risk of illegal activities?", "options": {"A": "Judgment notwithstanding the verdict", "B": "Plea bargaining agreement", "C": "Deferred prosecution agreement", "D": "Sentencing agreement"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Some jurisdictions that allow for corporate criminal liability also use deferred prosecution agreements. Generally, deferred prosecution agreements occur when prosecutors file criminal charges against a company, but then they agree not to prosecute the claims as long as the company successfully complies with the deferral agreement’s terms. These requirements typically focus on getting the business to reform its policies and reduce the risk of illegal practices. Essentially, deferred prosecution agreements help companies avoid indictment, trial, and conviction while providing a jurisdiction’s justice system with another channel for resolving a corporate case that punishes malfeasance and effectuates changes in a company’s culture. Similar to plea bargaining, deferred prosecution agreements are controversial, and many countries do not provide for such resolutions of criminal cases. However, the complexity and public cost of trying massive fraud cases has led to more jurisdictions adopting such strategies. In a plea bargaining agreement, the defendant pleads guilty to a violation in exchange for some sort of leniency; deferred prosecution agreements can result in no conviction if the agreement is fulfilled. In sentencing agreements, the defendant submits a confession or pleads guilty in exchange for a reduced sentence or other lenient treatment."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning the alternative dispute resolution process is CORRECT?", "options": {"A": "Arbitration decisions are binding until a party challenges the decision in court.", "B": "Mediation agreements are generally nonbinding.", "C": "Arbitration decisions are always binding.", "D": "Mediation agreements are enforceable as binding contracts."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Alternative dispute resolution in fraud cases usually involves one of two types of methods: mediation or arbitration. Mediation is the process whereby an impartial third person assists the parties in reaching a resolution to the dispute. The mediator does not decide who should win but instead works with the parties to reach a mutually agreeable settlement. Any mediation agreement will be enforced as a binding contract. Arbitration is the process whereby a dispute is submitted to an impartial third person (known as an arbitrator) who then decides the outcome of the case (i.e., which party should win). The arbitrator acts as a judge or jury by deciding the case on its merits. Arbitration can be either binding or nonbinding. If the arbitration is binding, then the decision of the arbitrator is final, and the parties cannot later submit their dispute to a judge or jury for determination. Conversely, if the arbitration is nonbinding, the arbitrator’s determination is not binding upon the parties."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements about the International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO) is TRUE?", "options": {"A": "IOSCO is recognized as the international standard setter for securities markets", "B": "IOSCO is comprised of securities commissioners and administrators responsible for securities regulation and the administration of securities laws in their respective countries", "C": "One of IOSCO’s main objectives is to assist its members in promoting high standards of regulation in order to maintain just, efficient, and sound markets", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO) is an international organization comprised of securities commissioners and administrators responsible for securities regulation and the administration of securities laws in their respective countries. IOSCO is recognized as the international standard setter for securities markets, and the organization’s members regulate more than 95% of the world’s securities markets. IOSCO’s main objectives are to assist its members to: Cooperate to promote high standards of regulation in order to maintain just, efficient, and sound markets. Exchange information on their respective experiences in order to promote the development of domestic markets. Unite their efforts to establish standards and an effective surveillance of international securities transactions. Provide mutual assistance to promote the integrity of the markets through a rigorous application of the standards and effective enforcement against offenses."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "Which of the following refers to a court’s power to hear and decide a given case?", "options": {"A": "Res judicata", "B": "Jurisdiction", "C": "Political domain", "D": "Venue"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Jurisdiction is the power of a court to hear and decide a given case; it refers to both the subject matter and people over which lawful authority may be exercised by a court. For instance, a country might have a system of probate courts that only have jurisdiction to hear cases whose subject matter is related to wills, inheritance, and other probate matters. Some countries have low-level trial courts that only have jurisdiction to hear matters under a certain monetary amount. Similarly, a court’s jurisdiction is defined by the parties that it may hear a case about. For example, courts usually do not have jurisdiction over foreign parties who have never been to and have had no business or presence in the court’s jurisdiction. Venue refers to the geographical area covered by the court; it is the physical location where the lawsuit is to be tried. Venue is technically an element of the court’s jurisdiction. This issue may be important in deciding where to file charges or claims."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In inquisitorial criminal trial proceedings, the evidentiary record is already available at the outset of the trial.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Criminal proceedings in inquisitorial jurisdictions typically are divided into three phases: the investigative phase, the examining phase, and the trial. The discovery process occurs primarily in the first two of these three phases. In the investigative stage, the public prosecutor, judge, or both (depending on the jurisdiction’s process) collect documentary and tangible evidence regarding the case. The investigating party then decides whether there is sufficient evidence to submit the case for prosecution. If there is sufficient evidence, the case moves on to the examining phase, which is mostly conducted in writing. The judge completes a written record of the evidence and may also collect testimony and additional evidence. If the judge certifies that there is a valid case against the accused, the matter moves forward to trial. The trial commences with the exhibition of the examining record before the parties and the trial judge, jury, or panel. The parties argue their case before the trial judge (or jury, if applicable). In inquisitorial trial proceedings, the evidentiary record is already available at the outset of the trial, whereas the entirety of each party’s evidence is produced and recorded at trial in adversarial jurisdictions."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "In inquisitorial judicial processes, criminal defendants are generally required to provide testimony, if so directed by the court.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Adversarial and inquisitorial judicial processes refer to the type of approach that courts take to discover evidence in a case. Theoretically, neither of these processes is exclusive of common law or civil law systems. Civil law jurisdictions, however, almost always favor an inquisitorial process, while common law systems typically feature an adversarial system. One of the most significant departures from the adversarial process is that defendants in criminal inquisitorial proceedings may be required by the court to testify (whereas in adversarial systems, the defendant may testify but does not have to do so). Note that civil (as opposed to criminal) proceedings under both adversarial and inquisitorial processes typically allow the defendant to be called to testify."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "According to the Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations, which of the following should financial institutions implement as part of their anti-money laundering programs?", "options": {"A": "An ongoing employee training program", "B": "A designated compliance officer", "C": "Employee screening procedures", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Under the FATF’s Recommendations, countries should require financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering and terrorist financing programs. A financial institution’s anti-money laundering (AML) program is highly dependent on which jurisdictions it operates in, as well as the services that it offers. Generally, financial institutions should adopt the AML policies and procedures in the Recommendations, but they need to tailor their programs to the requirements of the specific jurisdictions in which they operate. According to the Recommendations, these programs should include: The development of internal procedures and controls, including adequate screening procedures to ensure high standards in employee hiring Ongoing employee training programs on money laundering risks An independent audit function to test the effectiveness of the programs The designation of a compliance officer at the management level"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements about securities laws and regulations is TRUE?", "options": {"A": "Securities regulation refers to laws enacted by securities markets and exchanges.", "B": "Most securities markets are regulated on an international basis.", "C": "Securities exchanges are regulated entities that have regulatory authority.", "D": "National securities laws and regulations have no extraterritorial reach."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Securities regulation refers to laws, rules, and procedures enacted by a legislative body and administered by dedicated agencies that govern the way in which companies, consumers, and financial professionals behave when trading securities. The power to prescribe and enforce securities laws is territorial, and most securities markets are regulated by laws and regulations enacted and promulgated on a national basis. But because securities transactions have extraterritorial effects, national securities laws and regulations have some extraterritorial reach. A securities exchange is a market in which stocks, bonds, and other securities are traded. That is, a securities exchange is a market that provides services for brokers and traders to buy and sell securities. Securities exchanges are largely self-regulatory, which means that they regulate themselves. These self-regulatory exchanges exercise some degree of authority to create and enforce industry regulations and standards in the markets they organize. Although exchanges have regulatory authority, they are also regulated entities to the extent that they are subject to national control and supervision."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "The European Union’s General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) generally requires an organization to notify all affected data subjects without undue delay if a data breach is likely to result in a high risk to their rights and freedoms.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The European Union’s General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) generally requires an organization to notify all affected data subjects without undue delay if the data breach is likely to result in a high risk to their rights and freedoms."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "In most common law systems, a party can introduce relevant exhibits as evidence in trial even if the items are not established as authentic.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In common law systems using adversarial processes, exhibits—the tangible objects presented as evidence—are inadmissible unless they are relevant and established as authentic. Thus, to be admissible at trial, evidence, other than testimonial evidence, must be properly authenticated; that is, the party offering the item must produce some evidence (e.g., testimony from a person with firsthand knowledge) to show it is, in fact, what the party says it is and to show it is in the same condition as when it was seized. If an exhibit cannot be authenticated, it will not be admitted even if it is plainly relevant."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Balancing the legitimate needs of businesses to raise capital against the need to protect investors is the primary purpose of what?", "options": {"A": "Securities insurance", "B": "Securities offerings", "C": "Securities speculation", "D": "Securities regulation"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The primary purpose of securities regulation is to balance the legitimate needs of businesses to raise capital against the need to protect investors."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Under the Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations, which of the following should be subject to requirements for reporting suspicious transactions related to potential money laundering or terrorist financing?", "options": {"A": "Banks", "B": "Casinos", "C": "Securities brokers", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Under FATF Recommendation 20, a financial institution should be required to file a report when it “suspects or has reasonable grounds to suspect that funds are the proceeds of a criminal activity, or are related to terrorist financing.” The Recommendations define financial institutions to include: Depository and lending institutions (i.e., traditional banks) Money services businesses Financial guarantors Securities brokers or traders Security issuing services Investment portfolio managers Parties that invest, administer, or manage funds or assets on behalf of others Insurance companies servicing life insurance and other investment-related insurance Additionally, the parties that should file suspicious transaction reports include designated nonfinancial businesses and professions (DNFBPs), which include: Casinos (including Internet- and ship-based casinos) Real estate agents Dealers in precious metals and stones Legal professionals at professional firms (not internal legal professionals) Trust and company service providers"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following acts would constitute violations under the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act’s (FCPA) anti-bribery provisions?", "options": {"A": "A U.S. company transfers $45,000 to a foreign official to influence the official to award it a public construction contract", "B": "To induce a public construction contract award, a U.S. company promises to pay a foreign official $45,000 upon securing the contract", "C": "A German company that is publicly traded on the New York Stock Exchange transfers $45,000 to a foreign official to influence the official to award it a public construction contract", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Each of the above acts would constitute a violation under the FCPA. For individuals and businesses within its jurisdiction, the FCPA prohibits the payment or offer of anything of value to a foreign official for the purpose of obtaining or retaining business. Promises to pay are considered items of value. Furthermore, foreign companies are within the reach of the FCPA if they have registered securities or are otherwise required to file under the U.S. Securities and Exchange Act of 1934. Here, the German company would be subject to the FCPA because it is publicly traded on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE), which requires registration with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC). The anti-bribery provisions of the FCPA make it unlawful to bribe a foreign official for business purposes. Only regulated parties, such as issuers, domestic concerns, and foreign nationals or businesses, are subject to FCPA jurisdiction. An issuer is a corporation that has issued securities that have been registered in the United States or that is required to file periodic reports with the SEC. A domestic concern is any citizen, national, or resident of the United States, or any business entity that has its principal place of business in the United States or that is organized under the laws of a state, territory, possession, or commonwealth of the United States. Moreover, the FCPA applies extraterritorially to U.S. citizens working for foreign subsidiaries of domestic companies. A foreign national or business is subject to the FCPA if it takes any act in furtherance of a corrupt payment within U.S. territory. Additionally, the agents, subsidiaries, or other third-party representatives who act on behalf of an issuer, a domestic concern, or a foreign national or business are liable under the same conditions as the issuer, domestic concern, or foreign national or business. The FCPA’s anti-bribery provisions extend only to corrupt payments made to foreign officials. The FCPA does not, however, prohibit all payments to foreign officials; it contains an explicit exception for certain types of payments, known as facilitating payments, or grease payments, made to expedite or secure performance of a routine governmental action by a foreign official, political party, or party official that relates to the performance of that party’s ordinary and routine functions."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "The reduction of systemic risk is one of the objectives on which the International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO) Objectives and Principles of Securities Regulation are based.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The IOSCO Objectives and Principles of Securities Regulation are based on the following three objectives: The protection of investors Ensuring that markets are fair, efficient, and transparent The reduction of systemic risk"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following is generally considered a proper legal defense asserted by defendants in criminal cases?", "options": {"A": "Mistake", "B": "Alibi", "C": "Duress", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A defense is an assertion by a defendant in a criminal or civil case that seeks to explain away the defendant's guilt or civil liability for damages. Whether a defendant can raise a defense depends on the offense and the existence and availability of defenses in the relevant jurisdiction. Common defenses include: alibi, consent, the court’s lack of jurisdiction, duress, entrapment, ignorance of facts, infancy, insanity, legal impossibility, mistake, necessity of the act, protection of others, protection of property, public duty, self-defense, statute of limitations (common law systems) or period of prescriptions (civil law systems), and triviality of the offense."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "The key issue to consider when assessing whether an employee has a reasonable expectation of privacy in an area or item is whether the employee has an ownership interest in, or has legal custody over, the area or item.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Different countries often have very different approaches to the issue of workplace privacy. In some jurisdictions, privacy laws generally prohibit unreasonable workplace searches and surveillance in areas where employees have a reasonable expectation of privacy. Depending on the circumstances, an employee might have a reasonable expectation of privacy in a desk drawer, a file cabinet, a locker, or even an entire office. Reasonable expectations of privacy can also attach to communications, such as data stored on hard drives and other electronic communications like phone calls, emails, and text messages. The key issue to consider when assessing the existence of a reasonable expectation of privacy is whether a reasonable person would expect the area or item to be free from intrusion. Employees tend to regard purses, briefcases, and other personal effects as personal items that they reasonably expect to be private. An employee does not need to have an ownership interest in, or legal custody over, the area or item to have a reasonable expectation of privacy in it. Thus, even though an employer owns the office where an employee works, the employee can still have a reasonable expectation of privacy in parts of the office. Another important factor is the amount of control an individual exercises over the area. If an employee has exclusive control over an area, this tends to show that the employee has a reasonable expectation of privacy in that area."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Under the European Union’s General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), organizations are not required to obtain the consent of data subjects before collecting or processing their personal information.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Under the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), organizations must obtain the consent of data subjects before collecting or processing their personal data. Data subjects must give their consent via a statement or clear affirmative action. In addition, data subjects must be informed that they can withdraw their consent at any time, and withdrawal of their consent must be as easy as providing consent."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "While the parties in adversarial systems may sometimes choose expert witnesses, normally the court does so.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Most expert witnesses in adversarial proceedings are chosen by the parties to the litigation (although adversarial courts may also appoint independent experts). In adversarial systems, the expert and the retaining party are “allies” in the sense that legal counsel will attempt to paint the expert’s testimony in the best light during direct examination and will try to correct any issues in the expert’s testimony that the opposing party raises. However, it is important that the expert never allow his opinion or best judgment to be supplanted by that of the retaining party."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Smith, a CFE, works for the ABC Company, a publicly traded company. One day, Smith’s manager asks him to search the personal belongings of Green, an employee for the ABC Company, for evidence of securities fraud, even though there is no direct government authorization or order for the search. Smith seizes and searches Green’s personal tablet. Assuming that these facts occur in a jurisdiction with laws that provide the public with the right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities, which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE statement regarding Green’s rights?", "options": {"A": "Tax systems and regulations", "B": "Banking and accounting requirements and practices", "C": "Laws and regulations related to public subsidies, licenses, and contract procurement", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Submit Answer Law Related to Fraud 245 of 354 The OECD Recommendation on Combating Bribery in International Business (Recommendation) urges member states to combat the bribery of foreign public officials by taking steps to improve which of the following areas? The Recommendation on Combating Bribery in International Business (Recommendation), which was published by the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) in 1994, urges member states to deter and penalize the bribery of foreign public officials by taking “concrete and meaningful steps” to improve the following areas within their respective infrastructures: Criminal, civil, commercial, and administrative laws Tax systems and regulations Banking and accounting requirements and practices"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "If employees have a duty to cooperate during an internal investigation as part of the employer-employee relationship, the duty exists as long as what is requested from them is reasonable.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In most jurisdictions, a duty to cooperate exists in every employer-employee relationship, but such duties vary between jurisdictions. Generally, the duty to cooperate extends to workplace investigations; therefore, employees have a duty to cooperate during an internal investigation as long as what is requested from them is reasonable."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "While conducting a fraud examination, Black, a Certified Fraud Examiner, obtained a document in Year 1. Since Black obtained the document, several individuals have had it in their possession. In Year 2, the document was introduced at trial. The document's authenticity, however, was questioned because there was no record of who had possession of it and what they did with it. The question concerning the document’s authenticity is based on a failure to maintain _____________.", "options": {"A": "Who validated the evidence", "B": "The attorney's evidence records", "C": "The chain of custody", "D": "The best form of the evidence"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "If evidence is subject to change over time, or is susceptible to alteration, the offering party might need to establish that the evidence has not been altered or changed from the time it was collected through its production in court. This is done by establishing a chain of custody. Thus, the chain of custody can be an important factor in establishing authenticity. The chain of custody is both a process and a document that memorializes (1) who has had possession of an object and (2) what they have done with it; it is simply a means of establishing that there has not been a material change or alteration to a piece of evidence."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Some common law countries allow parties to conduct a(n) _____________, which is sworn testimony given by a party or witness upon questioning by counsel for one of the parties before trial and outside of court, usually in a lawyer’s office.", "options": {"A": "Interrogatory", "B": "Oral examination", "C": "Request for admission", "D": "Indictment"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In common law jurisdictions, a party may be examined or questioned by the other party either orally or through written questions. A pretrial oral examination, or deposition, is sworn testimony given by a party or witness upon questioning by counsel for one of the parties before trial and outside of court, usually in a lawyer’s office. Opposing counsel and a stenographer, who administers the oath and transcribes the testimony, also are present. An oral examination may be used to obtain evidence about the party’s own case or the opponent’s, or it may be used to preserve testimony for trial. Some common law jurisdictions do not allow pretrial oral examinations, but pretrial written examinations are still available."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO) is an international oversight body responsible for issuing and enforcing regulatory standards that govern all international securities markets.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO) is an international organization comprised of securities commissioners and administrators responsible for securities regulation and the administration of securities laws in their respective countries. IOSCO is recognized as the international standard setter for securities markets, and the organization’s members regulate more than 95% of the world’s securities markets. IOSCO develops, implements, and promotes adherence to recognized standards for securities regulation, and while IOSCO’s documents are not binding, IOSCO’s work shapes securities regulation worldwide."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following terms refers to laws, rules, and procedures enacted by a legislative body and administered by dedicated agencies that govern the way in which companies, consumers, and financial professionals behave when trading securities?", "options": {"A": "Securities codes of jurisprudence", "B": "Securities exchange programs", "C": "Securities market ordinances", "D": "Securities regulation"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Securities regulation refers to laws, rules, and procedures enacted by a legislative body and administered by dedicated agencies that govern the way in which companies, consumers, and financial professionals behave when trading securities."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Most jurisdictions have restrictions concerning the ways in which employers can conduct interviews.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Interviews, and especially interviews of suspects, can expose the organizational powers administering the interview and the individual conducting the interview to certain legal risks. Thus, before engaging in an interview, the fraud examiner must understand the ramifications of his actions, which requires an understanding of certain legal issues and how they limit or affect the ways in which an interview may be conducted. Of particular significance is the fact that most jurisdictions have restrictions concerning the ways in which employers can conduct interviews. Such restrictions might originate from employment contracts, collective labor laws, laws protecting labor rights, the common law, laws protecting fundamental rights, other applicable statutes, and so on."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "The primary reason for maintaining the chain of custody is to prevent opposing parties from accessing an item of evidence without a court order.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The primary reason for maintaining the chain of custody on an item of evidence is to establish that the evidence has not been altered or changed. If evidence is subject to change over time, or is susceptible to alteration, the offering party might need to establish that the evidence has not been altered or changed from the time it was collected through its production in court. This is done by establishing a chain of custody. Thus, the chain of custody can be an important factor in establishing authenticity. The chain of custody is both a process and a document that memorializes (1) who has had possession of an object and (2) what they have done with it."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In most civil law countries, a criminal appellate court may review issues of both law and fact independently of the trial court’s determinations.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In most jurisdictions, a convicted individual has the right to appeal the trial court’s decision. An appeal is the procedure for obtaining review by a higher court to ensure that the trial was conducted in a lawful manner and that the judgments comply with the law. In an appeal, the appealing party petitions an appellate court to overturn or modify the lower court’s decision. The appellate court can reverse a conviction if the error denied the defendant a fair trial. A divergence exists between common law and civil law systems in their appellate processes. In most civil law systems, courts can review cases for both issues of fact and law. The appellate court usually may perform de novo reviews (meaning it evaluates the cases independently of the trial court’s determinations) of both the factual and legal determinations by evaluating the compiled evidentiary dossier."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following can affect the rights that employees may have during an internal investigation?", "options": {"A": "Existence of a collective bargaining agreement", "B": "Existence of a union contract", "C": "Existence of an employment contract", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Employees may have contractual rights that are enforceable against their employers and that might limit the employers’ ability to compel full cooperation in a fraud examination. Employers and employees may enter into contracts that govern the employment relationship, and if the employer violates the contract, the employee can sue for breach of contract. Often, employee contractual rights at issue during investigations arise from a union contract, a collective bargaining agreement, or an employment contract. For example, if the employee is a member of a union, the union contract or collective bargaining agreement might contain certain restrictions on the employer’s investigatory procedures."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements about securities laws and regulations is TRUE?", "options": {"A": "The power to prescribe and enforce securities laws and regulations is territorial", "B": "Most securities markets are regulated on a national basis", "C": "National securities laws and regulations have some extraterritorial reach", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The power to prescribe and enforce securities laws and regulations is territorial, and most securities markets, which are the markets in which securities are traded, are regulated by laws and regulations enacted and promulgated on a national basis. But because securities transactions have extraterritorial effects, national securities laws and regulations have some extraterritorial reach."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Charles operates a movie theater, but he also has a stream of illegal cash income. To launder the cash, he over-reports the amount of tickets he sells and disguises the illicit cash as proceeds from those fake sales. Which of the following best describes Charles’s scheme?", "options": {"A": "Fictitious liabilities", "B": "Skimming", "C": "Depositing, but not recording, revenue", "D": "Overstating revenues"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Overstating revenues occurs when the money launderer records more income on a business’s books than the business actually generates. The fictitious revenue accounts for the illegal funds that are secretly inserted into the company."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Which of the following would NOT be classified as a falsified tax deduction scheme?", "options": {"A": "A corporate taxpayer intentionally underreports its carbon pollution emissions to qualify for a government tax credit.", "B": "A corporate taxpayer records fictitious employees and salaries in its books to increase the costs of goods sold and lower its tax liability.", "C": "An individual taxpayer fraudulently deducts interest payments from his taxable income on loans that do not qualify for such deductions.", "D": "An individual taxpayer misclassifies nondeductible expenses as deductible in tax records submitted to the government."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In the context of income and wealth taxes, tax deductions are itemized expenses subtracted from gross income or assets to reduce the taxpayer’s total liability. For instance, a company that is taxed by a percentage of its gross sales might be allowed to deduct the cost of making the goods (materials, employee costs, etc.). Deductions are designed to make certain taxes fairer, but they can also be used inappropriately by tax evaders. Examples of the fraudulent use of deductions include: Falsifying expenses, such as recording fictitious salaries to nonexistent employees Fraudulently inflating expenses, such as bribing a supplier to inflate an invoice Submitting false information to qualify for improper deductions, such as pretending to qualify for a tax deduction for having children living at home Misclassifying nondeductible expenses as deductible Similar to tax deductions, tax credits are an amount subtracted from a person's or entity’s tax liability. Additionally, some tax credits might result in a tax refund if the credits are greater than the person’s total tax liability. For instance, a government might give tax credits to individuals with low income to reduce their tax liability. Tax credits are often used to encourage certain behavior, such as making energy-efficient upgrades to homes. Taxpayers might attempt to evade taxes by misrepresenting their eligibility for a tax credit (e.g., an energy company underreporting its carbon emissions)."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Most inquisitorial judicial jurisdictions have more standardized requirements for expert witnesses than adversarial jurisdictions, such as the use of national standards to qualify experts.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The primary experts in inquisitorial jurisdictions are usually appointed and presented by the judge, rather than the parties. Like in adversarial jurisdictions, the judge makes the final determination of whether an expert is qualified. However, most inquisitorial jurisdictions have more standardized qualification requirements. Many jurisdictions (through the courts, chambers of commerce, or other organizations) maintain lists of experts in particular fields from which the courts may choose for the case at hand. These experts are qualified if they meet national standards, such as being certified in a particular field (e.g., an accounting certification). Some jurisdictions allow judges to look outside of the lists for experts."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Vendor A and Vendor B both operate in a jurisdiction with a 20% value-added tax (VAT). Vendor A sells goods to Vendor B and collects the VAT. Rather than turning the VAT over to the government, Vendor A simply pockets the money and disappears. Which of the following best describes this type of fraud scheme?", "options": {"A": "Income tax scheme", "B": "Falsified deduction scheme", "C": "Missing trader scheme", "D": "Wealth tax scheme"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Consumption taxes are those collected from the proceeds of the sale of goods or services. As with any form of tax, there are common schemes by which fraudsters attempt to evade consumption taxes. One form is the missing trader scheme, in which the culprit collects a value-added tax from a large transaction but, rather than paying the tax to the government, disappears with the proceeds."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Sanctions for violating the common law duty to preserve information relevant to anticipated or existing litigation can arise only from intentional acts, not from negligent acts.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Common law jurisdictions, in which litigants are usually obligated to disclose relevant information to the opposing side, impose a duty on litigants to take affirmative steps to preserve relevant evidence, and this duty might arise prior to the commencement of litigation. For litigation occurring in common law courts, the duty to preserve relevant evidence typically arises when litigation is reasonably anticipated or contemplated. When an organization is involved in litigation, this duty to preserve applies to the organization’s management, and it extends to employees likely to have relevant information. A violation of the duty to preserve occurs when information that is relevant to anticipated or existing litigation is lost, destroyed, or otherwise made unavailable. Violating the duty to preserve relevant information can result in several adverse sanctions for the offending party, and such sanctions can arise from both intentional acts and accidental acts through negligence. The adverse consequences can include, but are not limited to, monetary penalties, the drawing of adverse inferences of fact, and criminal penalties. The theory behind such consequences is that the individual who makes evidence unavailable following the probable initiation of a lawsuit is aware of its detrimental effect upon a case. Examples of situations that could give rise to sanctions for failing to preserve evidence include intentionally or accidentally: Erasing computer files (e.g., documents, images, or databases) relevant to anticipated or existing litigation Losing or destroying physical evidence relevant to anticipated or existing litigation Losing, destroying, or altering documents or records relevant to anticipated or existing litigation Failing to suspend routine destruction of electronic data relevant to anticipated or existing litigation"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Which of the following best describes what is typically included in the trial record of a civil lawsuit in civil law jurisdictions?", "options": {"A": "A verbatim transcript of all oral testimony", "B": "The judge’s summaries of the evidence", "C": "Every document submitted as evidence", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In civil trials in civil law systems, the judge orchestrates the proceedings by calling witnesses and eliciting testimony, as well as collecting documents and physical evidence. Rather than keep a verbatim record of witness testimony, the judge makes a synopsis of the evidence that will later be used in the decision-making portion of the trial. Typically, the trial record consists of the judge’s summaries of evidence, as opposed to every document or item of evidence submitted. However, key documents or particularly important statements might be included. The parties also work to ensure that the judge accurately creates the trial record and argue to frame it in a way that represents their interests."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Officer Knight, a police officer, obtains a warrant to search a suspect’s personal work locker at the suspect's place of employment. The warrant is based on probable cause that the locker contains contraband of theft. Officer Knight searches the locker, but he finds nothing relevant. As Knight is about to leave, he notices a folder sitting on the suspect’s desk. Having no idea what the folder might contain, he flips through its contents and eventually finds incriminating evidence. Which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE statement regarding the admissibility of the folder’s contents under the plain-view exception to the warrant requirement?", "options": {"A": "The evidence is not admissible because Officer Knight had no authority to search the folder.", "B": "The evidence is admissible because it is implied that Officer Knight’s search warrant covers a search of the suspect’s workspace.", "C": "The evidence is admissible only if it concerns a crime related to the search warrant.", "D": "The evidence is admissible under the plain-view doctrine because Officer Knight was acting lawfully when he spotted the folder."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In many countries with a warrant requirement, the plain-view doctrine is an exception to the general rule that the government must obtain a search warrant before conducting a search of a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime. Under this doctrine, evidence in plain view of a law enforcement officer who has a right to be in a position to observe it may be seized without a warrant. The plain-view doctrine applies when a government official inadvertently discovers contraband or evidence of another crime during a search or arrest, even if there was no prior authority to seize the evidence. Thus, the doctrine applies only if a police officer is legally authorized to search the premises in which he inadvertently discovers the additional evidence in plain view. The plain-view doctrine does not apply unless the police officer discovered the evidence inadvertently. Thus, if discovery of the evidence is anticipated, and no other exception applies, the officer must first obtain a warrant. That is, if the officer knows in advance the location of certain evidence and relies on the plain-view doctrine to seize the evidence, the seizure will be considered illegal. Also, evidence will not be admissible under the plain-view doctrine unless it is apparent to the police that the items observed were evidence of a crime or otherwise subject to search and seizure. Here, Officer Knight had to open the folder and examine the contents to determine what the folder contained because the incriminating character of the evidence was not immediately apparent to Officer Knight. By opening the folder, the officer abandoned his original authorized search for evidence in the suspect’s work locker and began a new search for evidence. Thus, the incriminating evidence is not admissible because it was not authorized by the warrant. If, however, Officer Knight knew the incriminating nature of the evidence when he saw the folder, the plain-view doctrine likely would apply."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "A lay witness (or fact witness) is anyone who provides nonexpert testimony in a legal proceeding.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are two basic kinds of testimony. The first is lay testimony (sometimes called factual testimony), where witnesses testify about what they have experienced firsthand and their factual observations. The second kind is expert testimony, where a person who, by reason of education, training, skill, or experience, is qualified to render an expert opinion concerning certain issues at hand. A lay witness (or fact witness) is anyone who provides nonexpert testimony. Note, however, that an expert witness might also provide lay testimony. Typically, a fraud examiner who worked on a case will be capable of providing lay testimony based on observations made during the investigation. When a trial involves issues that are complex or unfamiliar to most people, as is common in incidents of fraud, expert testimony is appropriate to help the fact finder understand these issues."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "A successful liquidation bankruptcy case results in the selling of the debtor’s property to pay creditors and the discharging of the debtor's dischargeable debts.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The structure of bankruptcy proceedings varies by jurisdiction, so it is always important to study the rules of the relevant jurisdiction when dealing with potential bankruptcy fraud. However, there are common types of bankruptcy filings, and most countries have adopted a similar version of at least one. Liquidation is the most basic type of bankruptcy proceeding and involves accounting for all dischargeable debts the subject owes, identifying all of the subject’s assets, and liquidating nonexempt assets to pay off creditors. This process allows the debtor to get a court or administrative order under which some or all of his debts may be eliminated. Each jurisdiction determines what exceptions exist in terms of debts that may not be discharged and assets that may not be liquidated. Some debts, like taxes owed or child support payments, might be non-dischargeable, meaning the bankruptcy will not wipe these debts away. Typical items that may not be liquidated include the debtor’s primary residence, items of nominal value, or assets deemed necessary for the debtor to maintain employment."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In most jurisdictions, police must always have a warrant to arrest a person for investigative purposes.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Most countries provide some degree of protection from unreasonable arrests by the government. Generally, the government may not make an arrest unless there is a good reason to believe that the suspect committed an offense. Many countries require a warrant signed by a judge or magistrate to authorize an arrest. However, even where warrants are required, there are typically exceptions that allow law enforcement officials to make arrests without warrants. Typical examples of such exceptions include: An offense that occurred in the presence of an officer The discovery of contraband in the suspect’s possession Emergency situations"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the three basic options by which organizations can legitimize cross-border transfers of personal information?", "options": {"A": "Obtain a warrant granting permission to transfer the data.", "B": "Get the consent of the data subject.", "C": "Rely on adequacy decisions (if transmitting from the European Union).", "D": "Establish a contract between the entities exchanging the information."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Many countries have adopted legal restrictions on international data transfers, but there are discrepancies in the implementation and application of such protections among the different countries. Given the wide range of legislation and practices regarding cross-border transfer laws and restrictions, fraud examiners working in other countries must become familiar with laws governing privacy and must adapt their procedures according to local rules. Nevertheless, there are three basic options by which organizations can legitimize cross-border transfers of personal information: Obtain the consent of the data subject. Establish a contract between the entities exchanging the information (i.e., between the transmitting entity and the receiving entity). If transmitting from the European Union to non-European Union countries, rely on adequacy decisions by the European Commission. That is, limit the transfer of data to countries that offer an adequate level of protection, as determined by the European Commission."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "During a bankruptcy proceeding in a jurisdiction that distinguishes between secured and unsecured creditors, the debtor’s only assets (equipment worth $150,000) are being liquidated to pay the only two creditors. Creditor A has a $100,000 unsecured claim against the debtor, and creditor B has a $100,000 secured interest in the equipment. How will the $150,000 from the sale of the equipment most likely be distributed?", "options": {"A": "Creditor A will receive $50,000 and creditor B will receive $100,000.", "B": "Creditors A and B will receive an equal share ($75,000 each).", "C": "Creditor A will receive $100,000 and creditor B will receive nothing.", "D": "Creditor A will receive nothing and creditor B will receive $100,000."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Many jurisdictions recognize a distinction between secured and unsecured creditors during bankruptcy proceedings. A secured creditor is one who has a secured interest in some of the debtor’s property, meaning that if the debtor defaults on payments to the creditor, the creditor may possess or liquidate the secured property to satisfy the debt. Creditors with secured interests generally have priority over unsecured claims, meaning they normally get paid before unsecured claims in the distributions to creditors made by the trustee or debtor-in-possession. The most common example of a secured interest occurs when a lender finances a debtor’s purchase of a particular property (e.g., a home or vehicle) and, as part of the debt agreement, takes a collateral interest in the financed property. A secured creditor’s claim is secured to the extent of the property’s value on the petition date. When the debt is undersecured (i.e., the debt is secured by property that is worth less than the amount of the debt), the debt will be considered both unsecured and secured. For example, if a note for $500 is secured by property having a value of $400 on the petition date, there will be a secured claim for $400 and an unsecured claim for $100."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In jurisdictions that allow criminal bargaining agreements, which of the following parties generally has/have the discretion to decide whether to settle charges with a bargaining agreement?", "options": {"A": "The jury", "B": "The defendant's counsel", "C": "The prosecution", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Whether criminal cases are actually brought to trial might depend on prosecutorial discretion, meaning that the decision to prosecute and the decision to allow a bargaining agreement are left to the discretion of the appropriate jurisdictional authority. All countries provide some measure of prosecutorial discretion; the prosecutor will not (theoretically) pursue cases for which there is no evidence. However, countries vary widely on how much discretion the government has to prosecute criminal cases—from almost total discretion to almost none. Where bargaining agreements are acceptable practice, the discretion is generally with the prosecution."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning the criminal discovery process in adversarial jurisdictions is most accurate?", "options": {"A": "Although the prosecution may request information, the defendant is not allowed to request information unless the judge approves.", "B": "Most discovery between the parties occurs during the pretrial stage.", "C": "Neither party may request evidence from the opposing party until after the trial begins.", "D": "If a party to the litigation fails to comply with a discovery request, the prosecution settles the dispute and may order the party to comply."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In adversarial jurisdictions, the parties involved in litigation primarily drive the discovery process, while the judge ensures that discovery procedures are followed correctly. The adversarial process can be divided into the pretrial and trial stages. Most discovery between the parties is conducted in the pretrial stage. Both parties may request limited information from each other, and alleged failures to comply with evidentiary rules may be submitted to the judge, who may then order a party to comply. The prosecution, working with law enforcement, gathers all evidence on the government's behalf. Some evidence, however, will not be available to a party until it is introduced as evidence during the trial by an opposing party."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Which of the following is the alternative dispute process whereby an impartial third person assists the parties to a dispute in reaching a mutually agreeable settlement?", "options": {"A": "Court-annexed conciliation", "B": "Mediation", "C": "Arbitration", "D": "Propitiation"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Alternative dispute resolution in fraud cases usually involves one of two types of methods: mediation or arbitration. Mediation is the process whereby an impartial third person assists the parties in reaching a resolution to the dispute. The mediator does not decide who should win but instead works with the parties to reach a mutually agreeable settlement. Arbitration is the process whereby a dispute is submitted to an impartial third person (known as an arbitrator) who then decides the outcome of the case (i.e., which party should win). The arbitrator acts as a judge or jury by deciding the case on its merits."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "In most jurisdictions, a taxpayer will typically be guilty of conducting a criminal tax offense \"willfully\" even though he had a good faith or legitimate misunderstanding of the law's requirements.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "To establish criminal liability for tax evasion, most jurisdictions require a willful attempt to evade or defeat taxes in an unlawful manner. In the context of tax evasion, a good faith or legitimate misunderstanding of the applicable law typically negates willfulness (the voluntary, intentional violation of a known legal duty). That is, honest mistakes, in contrast to willful evasion, do not constitute tax evasion. However, a court might find that a defendant’s claimed misunderstanding of the law is implausible given the evidence presented."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "In common law jurisdictions, civil juries must be composed of the same number of jurors as in the jurisdiction’s criminal trials.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When juries are used for civil trials in common law jurisdictions, the requirements are typically less stringent than in criminal trials. For instance, it is common for the minimum number of jurors to be lower for civil cases. Additionally, in many jurisdictions, civil trials are less likely to require a unanimous jury verdict than criminal trials."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, fraud examiners who testify as witnesses are prohibited from:", "options": {"A": "Testifying to opinions that the trier of fact cannot test empirically", "B": "Testifying to opinions concerning the defendant's innocence", "C": "Testifying to opinions regarding the quality of other witnesses' expert testimony", "D": "Testifying that, according to the evidence, they believe the accused committed the offense"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Certain standards for fraud examiners are found in the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics. Specifically, fraud examiners are prohibited from expressing opinions as to the guilt or innocence of any person or party. This is not to say that the witness cannot testify to the badges, hallmarks, or characteristics of fraud found in the case. It also does not mean that the fraud examiner cannot testify that, based on the evidence, he believes that the accused may have committed the offense. But the ultimate guilt or innocence of any person or party is the sole responsibility of the fact finder. The fraud examiner typically will not be permitted to testify to the ultimate fact questions."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "For a false statement to violate a law criminalizing false statements to government agencies, it need not be made directly to the government; it can be made to a third party as long as it involves a matter within the jurisdiction of a governmental department or agency.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Laws prohibiting false claims and statements to government agencies make it illegal for a person to lie to, or conceal material information from, a government agency. A false claim is an assertion of a right to government money, property, or services that contains a misrepresentation. A false statement is an oral or written communication, declaration, or assertion that is factually untrue. Also, the following are general rules with regard to laws criminalizing false claims and statements to government agencies: An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the claim or statement is not made directly to a governmental department or agency. That is, a false claim or statement need not be made directly to the government; it can be made to a third party as long as it involves a matter within the jurisdiction of a governmental department or agency. An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the government was not deceived by the falsity. An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the government did not rely on the falsity. An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the government did not suffer a loss in reliance on the falsity. For an individual to be found guilty of making a false claim or statement, the claim or statement at issue must have been capable of influencing the government entity involved."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Litigants involved in cross-border litigation should expect to have the privilege laws from their own jurisdiction applied when engaged in cross-border litigation.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Generally, litigants involved in cross-border litigation should not expect to have the privilege laws from their own jurisdiction applied when engaged in litigation abroad. There are several reasons for this. First, courts are more inclined to apply their own privilege law because they are more familiar with local law than the laws of foreign jurisdictions. Second, characterizations and conceptualizations of privileges vary among different countries. For instance, common law jurisdictions typically view privileges as the right of the client, but civil law jurisdictions do not. In civil law jurisdictions, communications are protected by secrecy laws that require confidentiality."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "Allan and Michael live in two different countries. Allan believes that he has been financially harmed by Michael and wants to bring a lawsuit against him. Which of the following courts would be the most likely to have jurisdiction to hear the case?", "options": {"A": "Whichever court in which Michael, the defendant, prefers the case to be brought", "B": "Whichever court in which Allan, the plaintiff, prefers the case to be brought", "C": "A court in the country where the harm was done", "D": "Any court that hears cases involving the type of financial harm caused"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Being a plaintiff or defendant does not automatically entitle either party to choose any court to hear the case; a case may only be heard before a court that has proper jurisdiction. Jurisdiction is the power of a court to hear and decide a given case; it refers to both the subject matter and people over which lawful authority may be exercised by a court. A particular court’s jurisdiction is defined by the laws of its jurisdiction, but, generally, there are three common elements to consider when determining whether a given court has the power to hear and determine a case. First, does the court hear cases of the type in question? For example, if a plaintiff brings a civil complaint claiming $500,000 in damages, the plaintiff needs a court that hears civil complaints of that magnitude. Second, does the court have the authority to exercise its power over a particular defendant or piece of property? This element usually requires the party to have some level of current or past presence or activity within the jurisdiction. Courts generally do not have jurisdiction over foreign parties who have had no activities or presence in the court’s jurisdiction. Third, most jurisdictions require the court to have proper venue as an element of jurisdiction. Venue is the physical location where the lawsuit is to be tried. Rules of venue can be based on a mixture of factors, including convenience to the parties (e.g., where they reside) and where the acts that underlie the case occurred."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "In most common law jurisdictions, for a document to be admitted into evidence, it must be properly __________; that is, the party offering the document must produce some evidence to show it is, in fact, what the party says it is.", "options": {"A": "Validated", "B": "Authenticated", "C": "Certified", "D": "Marked"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In common law systems using adversarial processes, exhibits—the tangible objects presented as evidence—are inadmissible unless they are relevant and established as authentic. Thus, to be admissible at trial, evidence, other than testimonial evidence, must be properly authenticated; that is, the party offering the item must produce some evidence (e.g., testimony from a person with firsthand knowledge) to show it is, in fact, what the party says it is and to show it is in the same condition as when it was seized. If an exhibit cannot be authenticated, the evidence will not be admitted even if it is plainly relevant."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following entities is recognized as the international standard setter for securities markets?", "options": {"A": "The International Capital Market Association (ICMA)", "B": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO)", "C": "The World Federation of Exchanges (WFE)", "D": "The International Councils of Securities Associations (ICSA)"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO) is an international organization comprised of securities commissioners and administrators responsible for securities regulation and the administration of securities laws in their respective countries. IOSCO is recognized as the international standard setter for securities markets, and the organization’s members regulate more than 95% of the world’s securities markets."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "Suppose that a court is deciding a case involving a transaction between parties and assets located in different countries. Which of the following statements concerning how courts choose which jurisdiction’s laws to apply is MOST ACCURATE?", "options": {"A": "Most courts apply the procedural laws of foreign jurisdictions.", "B": "Most courts apply the procedural laws of their own jurisdiction.", "C": "Most courts apply both their own procedural and substantive laws to all cases.", "D": "Most courts apply the substantive laws of foreign jurisdictions."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraud cases involving assets or parties from diverse jurisdictions can lead to several legal issues of which fraud examiners should be aware. Courts must choose which jurisdiction’s laws to apply to each issue in a case. Problems arise because the outcome of a case might depend on which jurisdiction’s laws are applied. In other words, conduct that is fraudulent in one jurisdiction might be legal, carry different penalties, or result in different remedies in another jurisdiction. In terms of procedural law, almost every court will apply the procedural rules of its own jurisdiction (which includes choice-of-law rules). However, the way that courts choose substantive law is less consistent. Generally, most courts will consider some mixture of the following factors to determine which jurisdiction's laws apply: The nationality of the parties to the litigation The current residence of the parties (whether temporary or permanent) The parties’ current or past physical presence in the relevant jurisdictions The jurisdiction where the transaction or underlying cause of action(s) occurred"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "The operation of alternative remittance systems involves inherently illegal activities.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Alternative remittance systems (also called parallel banking systems) are methods of transferring funds from a party at one location to another party (whether domestic or foreign) without the use of formal banking institutions. These systems are characterized by the lack of direct physical or digital transfer of currency from the sender to the receiver. Instead, in the typical alternative remittance system, the payer transfers funds to a local broker who has a connection to another broker in the region where the payee is located. The latter broker then distributes the funds to the payee. Transferring funds in this manner is not necessarily illegal (although some jurisdictions require brokers to register with the government). If available, using such systems can be beneficial because the commission that the networked brokers take might be lower than a banking fee for international transactions. Additionally, the payers and payees do not need to have bank accounts to perform the transactions."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "If an employee commits internal fraud, the only feasible way for the employer to make up for the losses is to get them back from the employee through agreement or litigation.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Given the prevalence of fraud, and given the fact that it is difficult to fully recover losses from fraud, many businesses have fidelity insurance that covers fraud losses. Fidelity insurance (also known as crime insurance and employee dishonesty insurance) is an often-overlooked method of recovery for losses due to internal fraud. Fidelity insurance is a type of insurance under which the insured entity is covered against losses caused by the dishonest or fraudulent acts of its employees."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "A debtor in a bankruptcy proceeding took steps to hide his books and records from a creditor. What kind of scheme did the debtor commit?", "options": {"A": "An asset misappropriation scheme", "B": "A concealed assets scheme", "C": "A petition mill scheme", "D": "A bustout scheme"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The most common type of bankruptcy fraud scheme involves the concealment of assets rightfully belonging to the debtor’s estate to avoid forfeiting the assets in bankruptcy. In these schemes, concealed assets might include cash, consumer property, houses, and interests in partnerships and corporations, as well as lawsuits in which the debtor is a plaintiff. Concealed assets might also include the debtor’s books and records."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "A debtor in a bankruptcy proceeding took steps to hide his books and records from a creditor. What kind of scheme did the debtor commit?", "options": {"A": "An asset misappropriation scheme", "B": "A concealed assets scheme", "C": "A petition mill scheme", "D": "A bustout scheme"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The most common type of bankruptcy fraud scheme involves the concealment of assets rightfully belonging to the debtor’s estate to avoid forfeiting the assets in bankruptcy. In these schemes, concealed assets might include cash, consumer property, houses, and interests in partnerships and corporations, as well as lawsuits in which the debtor is a plaintiff. Concealed assets might also include the debtor’s books and records."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "In a bustout scheme, which of the following types of assets does the fraudster typically purchase and then sell prior to closing the business?", "options": {"A": "Business insurance policies", "B": "Real estate", "C": "Legal or accounting services", "D": "Inventory or goods"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A bustout is a planned and fraudulent bankruptcy. It can take many different forms, but the basic approach is for an apparently legitimate business to order large quantities of inventory or other goods on credit, and then dispose of those goods through legitimate or illegitimate channels. Because the point of the bustout scheme is to quickly resell the goods for cash, the fraudster is likely to purchase more liquid items like inventory than real estate, insurance policies, or services. The perpetrator then closes shop, absconding with the proceeds and leaving the suppliers unpaid. The debtor might then go into bankruptcy. Often, by this point the debtor has already made false accounting entries or taken other steps to conceal the assets or make the sales look legitimate. Other times, debtors simply flee the jurisdiction or do not show up at the proceedings."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "To recover for a claim of false imprisonment, a plaintiff must show that the defendant knew he had no legal right to restrain the plaintiff’s physical liberty.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "False imprisonment is the unlawful restraint by one person of the physical liberty of another without consent or legal justification. To recover for a claim of false imprisonment, the plaintiff generally must prove all of the following elements: The defendant used words or actions intended to restrain the plaintiff. The defendant’s words or actions resulted in the restraint of the plaintiff without the plaintiff’s consent (i.e., against the plaintiff’s will) and without legal justification. The plaintiff was aware that he was being restrained. A claim of false imprisonment might arise if an employee is detained in any way during a search or interview. Generally, an employer is entitled to question an employee at work about a violation of company policy without incurring liability as long as the employee submits to the questioning voluntarily; that is, not as a result of threats or force."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following statements best describes when a custodial arrest occurs?", "options": {"A": "A custodial arrest occurs when a law enforcement officer informs the suspect of his rights as a criminal defendant.", "B": "A custodial arrest occurs when a law enforcement officer indicates that the suspect is no longer free to leave.", "C": "A custodial arrest occurs when a law enforcement officer communicates his intent to arrest the suspect.", "D": "A custodial arrest occurs when the suspect is questioned by a law enforcement officer."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A custodial arrest occurs whenever a government officer has a person in custody, meaning an officer has indicated that the person is not free to leave. It is important to determine when an arrest occurs to establish what rights the subject of the arrest had at a given time."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE statement about closing arguments in criminal trials in most common law jurisdictions?", "options": {"A": "In the closing arguments, defense counsel cannot comment on the motives and credibility of the government's witnesses.", "B": "Closing arguments themselves can only be counted as evidence in favor of the prosecution.", "C": "Closing arguments themselves can only be counted as evidence in favor of or against the defendant.", "D": "Closing arguments provide an opportunity for attorneys to summarize how the evidence supports their case."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Once all evidence has been presented, the normal procedure is for the judge to allow the defense to summarize what the evidence has shown and to argue for the judge or jury to acquit. The prosecutor then makes his own final points, trying to convince the judge or jury to convict. Closing arguments are not evidence; they provide an opportunity for attorneys to summarize how the evidence supports their case. The remarks in closing arguments are limited to issues pertinent to the case and confined to evidence presented during the trial."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "White, a Certified Fraud Examiner, believes that Blue, a fraud suspect, is guilty of embezzlement. White shares his theory with his supervisor. Blue later turns out to be innocent. Blue can sue and probably recover from White on a theory of defamation.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Generally speaking, defamation refers to the unprivileged publication of false statements about a person that causes harm to that person’s reputation. To recover for defamation, the plaintiff must generally prove all of the following elements: The defendant made an untrue statement of fact. The statement was communicated (published) to third parties. The statement was made on an unprivileged occasion. The statement damaged the subject's reputation. For a statement to qualify as defamatory, the occasion in which the statement is made must be an unprivileged one. If the statement is made on a privileged occasion, then no liability can attach to the speaker. Basically, the law recognizes that there are some circumstances in which the need to share information is so important that people will be allowed to make mistakes from time to time without having to worry about being sued for defamation. Statements that are made in these circumstances are said to be privileged."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "To prove a criminal conspiracy, the government must prove that the defendant knew all the details or objectives of the conspiracy, that the defendant knew the identity of all the participants in the conspiracy, and that the conspirators accomplished the purpose of the conspiracy.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Conspiracy refers to a situation in which two or more people agree to commit an illegal act. The essential elements that must be shown to prove a conspiracy are as follows: The defendant entered into an agreement with at least one other person to commit an illegal act. The defendant knew the purpose of the agreement and intentionally joined in the agreement. At least one of the conspirators knowingly committed at least one overt act in furtherance of the conspiracy. Under the first element, the government must prove that the defendant reached an agreement or understanding to commit an illegal act with at least one other person. The conspirators must agree about the precise illegal act. Under the second element, the government must establish that the defendant knew of the conspiracy’s existence and its objective. The government, however, does not have to establish that the defendant knew all the details or objectives of the conspiracy, and it does not have to prove that the defendant knew the identity of all the participants in the conspiracy. Finally, the purpose of the conspiracy need not be accomplished for a violation to occur, but at least one of the co-conspirators must have carried out at least one overt act in furtherance of the conspiracy. The overt act need not be criminal and could be as innocuous as making a phone call or writing a letter."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "___________ refers to any fraudulent actions a taxpayer commits to avoid reporting or paying taxes.", "options": {"A": "Tax evasion", "B": "Tax reduction", "C": "Tax avoidance", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The term tax evasion refers to any fraudulent actions that a taxpayer commits to avoid reporting or paying taxes. Tax evasion, however, should not be confused with tax avoidance. Tax avoidance refers to a legal means of lowering one’s tax bill through legitimate deductions, credits, and shelters. The intent of the taxpayer to wrongly file a tax return or provide other false tax information will determine the difference between tax evasion and tax avoidance. The primary distinguishing characteristic of tax evasion as compared to tax avoidance is that tax evasion is illegal, but tax avoidance is legal."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following would most likely be considered a security that is subject to registration and regulation regarding trading?", "options": {"A": "An investment contract", "B": "A notarized contract", "C": "An instrument that represents ownership interest", "D": "Anything of material value or usefulness"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In many countries, the term security includes investment contracts. The leading global definition of investment contract provides that a contract, transaction, or scheme is an investment contract if all of the following four elements are met: There is an investment of money or other asset. The investment is in a common enterprise. The investment was made with expectations of making a profit. The profits are to come solely from the efforts of people other than the investor."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Which of the following types of questions is an expert witness most likely to be asked during direct examination in an adversarial system?", "options": {"A": "A hostile question", "B": "A leading question", "C": "A two-part question", "D": "A narrative question"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Direct examination is the initial questioning of a witness by the party that called the witness (in adversarial jurisdictions) or the judge (in inquisitorial jurisdictions). Most of the time, direct examination is a nonconfrontational questioning aimed at exposing the facts and issues of the case. Direct examinations in adversarial jurisdictions are conducted by the attorney who retained the expert. Because experts are hired for their opinions, they are often not subject to the usual restrictions about statements of judgment. Expert witnesses present their findings in various ways, such as narrative questions, hypotheticals, specialized materials, and special exhibits. Experts are commonly asked to answer narrative questions, which are broad, open-ended questions that allow experts to present their opinions in their own words with minimal prompting. Fraud cases, with their divergent paths of activity and intrigue, can require complex summarizing for the facts to make any sense. Average jurors and some judges have never considered how someone could manipulate store inventories to drive up the company’s stock price and then make a profit on the phony surge. The expert witness in cases dealing with such issues often will begin testimony by recounting the narrative background of a case, the tests and experiments that were performed during the investigation, and a summary of the findings based on the witness's professional expertise. Compound (two-part) and hostile questions do not generally occur in the direct examination process. Additionally, leading questions are generally not allowed during direct examination (e.g., “The results were negative, weren’t they?”)."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Mistake is not a legal defense that may properly be used by a defendant in a criminal case, regardless of the jurisdiction.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A defense is an assertion by a defendant in a criminal or civil case that seeks to explain away the defendant's guilt or civil liability for damages. Whether a defendant can raise a defense depends on the offense and the existence and availability of defenses in the relevant jurisdiction. Common defenses include: alibi, consent, the court’s lack of jurisdiction, duress, entrapment, ignorance of facts, infancy, insanity, legal impossibility, mistake, necessity of the act, protection of others, protection of property, public duty, self-defense, statute of limitations (common law systems) or period of prescriptions (civil law systems), and triviality of the offense."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "In systems using adversarial processes, counsel may be able to impeach an opposing party’s witness by showing that the witness has an impaired ability to observe.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Impeachment is the practice of questioning a witness’s knowledge or credibility. In adversarial processes, the adverse party is usually entitled to offer evidence to impeach the testimony or credibility of a witness during cross-examination. However, because cross-examination is absent from inquisitorial processes, impeachment is not an issue for civil law systems using inquisitorial processes. There are numerous ways an attorney might impeach a witness, but the most common ways include efforts to show that the witness: Is influenced by bias or self-interest Has an impaired ability to observe Made prior inconsistent statements Has been convicted of a felony or equivalent crime Has a reputation for untruthfulness"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE description of the civil wrong of public disclosure of private facts?", "options": {"A": "One party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern.", "B": "An individual makes an unprivileged publication of a false statement in writing about a person that causes harm to that person's reputation.", "C": "An individual makes an unprivileged oral publication of a false statement about a person that causes harm to that person's reputation.", "D": "An individual intentionally intrudes into an area where another individual has a reasonable expectation of privacy."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Invasion of privacy laws concern a person’s right to keep his life private and free from intrusion, and in many common law countries, invasion of privacy is a civil wrong that can be addressed by a court through a lawsuit. The two most common forms of invasion of privacy applicable to fraud examinations are intrusion into an individual’s private matters and publicity of private facts. The civil wrong regarding intrusion into an individual’s private matters (often referred to as intrusion upon seclusion) occurs when an individual intentionally intrudes into another individual’s private matters and the intrusion would be highly offensive or objectionable to a reasonable person. Public disclosure of private facts occurs when one party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern. Unlike the requirements to establish a claim for defamation, liability for the public disclosure of private facts cause of action can arise even if the statements at issue are true. The key to this cause of action is that the information must be private in nature and not a matter of public interest."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "The death of the taxpayer and bankruptcy proceedings typically serve as legal defenses against criminal tax evasion.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Some defenses will be ineffective against charges for tax crimes. For example, the death of the taxpayer often cannot be used as a defense because taxes owed due to tax evasion typically survive the taxpayer’s death, meaning the deceased taxpayer’s estate will be held liable. Also, liabilities owed as a result of tax evasion may not be discharged in bankruptcy proceedings. If a person commits a tax fraud offense, amending fraudulent information held by the government will not generally relieve the taxpayer of criminal liability."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Bars, restaurants, and nightclubs are favorite businesses through which to launder funds because:", "options": {"A": "Sales are generally in cash.", "B": "It is easy to match the cost of providing food, liquor, and entertainment with the revenues they produce.", "C": "They charge relatively low prices for services.", "D": "All of these choices are correct."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Bars, restaurants, and nightclubs are commonly used to front money laundering operations for a number of reasons. These businesses charge relatively high prices, and customers vary widely in their purchases. Sales are generally in cash, and it is difficult to match the cost of providing food, liquor, and entertainment with the revenues they produce."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In countries that require arrest warrants, which of the following is NOT a typical exception to the warrant requirement?", "options": {"A": "The offense occurs in the presence of a police officer.", "B": "An emergency situation occurs.", "C": "Contraband is discovered in the suspect’s possession.", "D": "The person is arrested at home."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Most countries provide some degree of protection from unreasonable arrests by the government. Generally, the government may not make an arrest unless there is a good reason to believe that the suspect committed an offense. Many countries require a warrant signed by a judge or magistrate to authorize an arrest. However, even where warrants are required, there are typically exceptions that allow law enforcement officials to make arrests without warrants. Typical examples of such exceptions include: An offense that occurred in the presence of an officer The discovery of contraband in the suspect’s possession Emergency situations"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "If a subject has purchased a large number of bearer instruments, each for less than the jurisdiction’s threshold for mandatory reports on currency transactions, this could be an indication of which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Forged check scheme", "B": "Smurfing/structuring operation", "C": "Counterfeit checks scheme", "D": "Entrapment scheme"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Bearer instruments (such as cashier’s checks) could provide evidence of smurfing operations. Many countries require financial institutions to report all currency transactions above a certain threshold (e.g., more than $10,000) to the government. However, criminals might attempt to illegally evade these laws. Structuring occurs when a deposit or other transfer is made using a method that is specifically designed to avoid regulatory reporting requirements or an institution’s internal controls. The most common type of illegal structuring scheme in the money laundering context is smurfing, where the launderer breaks up the illicit money into smaller amounts and deposits it into bank accounts or purchases bearer instruments, such as cashier’s checks, traveler’s checks, or money orders. A red flag of a smurfing scheme is a customer who attempts to make many transactions just under the reporting threshold."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning appellate procedure in common law and civil law jurisdictions is most accurate?", "options": {"A": "Appellate courts in civil law jurisdictions generally may review issues of both fact and law independently of the trial court’s determinations.", "B": "Appellate courts in civil law jurisdictions generally may only review issues of fact independently of the trial court’s determinations.", "C": "Appellate courts in common law jurisdictions generally may review issues of both fact and law independently of the trial court’s determinations.", "D": "Appellate courts in common law jurisdictions generally may only review issues of fact independently of the trial court’s determinations."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In most jurisdictions, a convicted individual has the right to appeal the trial court’s decision. An appeal is the procedure for obtaining review by a higher court to ensure that the trial was conducted in a lawful manner and that the judgments comply with the law. In an appeal, the appealing party petitions an appellate court to overturn or modify the lower court’s decision. The appellate court can reverse a conviction if the error denied the defendant a fair trial. A divergence exists between common law and civil law systems in their appellate processes. In most common law countries, appellate courts consider potential errors of law de novo (meaning they evaluate them independently of the trial court’s determinations), but they generally adopt the factual findings of the trial court. No jury is present, and there is typically no new evidence entered into the record. Therefore, appeals in common law systems are typically limited to issues of law. Very rarely will an appellate court reverse a factual finding of the trial court in a common law jurisdiction, such as when there is an egregious and obvious mistake. In most civil law systems, courts can review cases for both issues of fact and law. The appellate court usually may perform de novo reviews of both the factual and legal determinations by evaluating the compiled evidentiary dossier."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In criminal trials in common law jurisdictions, a jury must serve as the fact finder.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "While jury trials are typically used in criminal proceedings in common law jurisdictions, this is not always the case. For some cases, usually minor criminal offenses, a jury trial might not be available. In serious cases, however, jury trials are typically available. Additionally, many common law jurisdictions allow the defendant to waive the right to trial by jury. When no jury is present, the judge serves as the fact finder. Most juries in a common law criminal court consist of 12 or fewer jurors. The jurors are selected from the local population, often by a random lottery using voter registration records and the like."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "An individual is a defendant in a civil fraud lawsuit filed by his employer. In the same proceeding, the jurisdiction allows the defendant to file a claim stating the employer owes him backpay. The defendant’s claim in this case is called a counterclaim.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In addition to allowing defenses against the plaintiff’s claims, many jurisdictions allow the defendant to raise counterclaims (also known as countersuits), in which the defendant levels a claim against the plaintiff. The specifics of the counterclaim might be filed as part of the defendant’s answer or as a separate document. If a defendant files a counterclaim, the counterclaim and the original complaint will be tried concurrently, with the final judgment stipulating a decision on each side’s claim."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is one of the areas of primary concern in which the OECD Recommendation on Combating Bribery in International Business (Recommendation) urges member states to take steps to combat the bribery of foreign public officials?", "options": {"A": "Laws and regulations covering e-commerce", "B": "Public safety systems and regulations", "C": "Tax systems and regulations", "D": "Sensitive data protection laws"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The Recommendation on Combating Bribery in International Business (Recommendation), which was published by the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) in 1994, urges member states to deter and penalize the bribery of foreign public officials by taking “concrete and meaningful steps” to improve the following areas within their respective infrastructures: Criminal, civil, commercial, and administrative laws Tax systems and regulations Banking and accounting requirements and practices Laws and regulations related to public subsidies, licenses, and contract procurement"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Black, a Certified Fraud Examiner who lives and works in a common law legal system with a litigation privilege, discovers a potential fraud at the ABC Company while auditing ABC's procedures. She immediately notifies ABC’s in-house counsel. As a result, Black's work up until that point is protected by:", "options": {"A": "The investigator/client privilege", "B": "The employer/employee privilege", "C": "The CFE/client privilege", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Although the work undertaken by a fraud examiner may be protected by a litigation privilege or other similar evidentiary protections, such as the U.S. attorney work-product doctrine, to receive protection, the work must be done in anticipation of litigation and at the attorney's direction. Here, even if Black's work was done at the attorney's direction, her work was not prepared in anticipation of litigation because no litigation was actually planned. Therefore, the litigation privilege does not cover the documents because they came into existence before litigation was contemplated."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "The placement stage of the money laundering process occurs when a criminal first steals or obtains illicit proceeds.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The three stages of money laundering are placement, layering, and integration. Placement is the first stage of the money laundering process. In this stage, the launderer introduces his illegal profits into the financial system. Placement occurs after the initial act of stealing or receiving illicit assets. If the placement of the initial funds goes undetected, the launderer can design numerous financial transactions in complex patterns to prevent detection. For example, the launderer can move funds between bank accounts, transfer funds from one form of currency to another, or transfer money between businesses. This stage of the money laundering process is referred to as layering. Integration is the final stage in the laundering process. In this stage, the money is integrated back into the economy in a way that makes it appear to be part of a legitimate business transaction."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Which of the following could give rise to sanctions for violating the common law duty to preserve evidence relevant to anticipated litigation?", "options": {"A": "Accidentally shredding documents relevant to a lawsuit", "B": "Failing to suspend routine destruction of electronic data relevant to a lawsuit", "C": "Accidentally erasing a digital image relevant to a lawsuit", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Common law jurisdictions, in which litigants are usually obligated to disclose relevant information to the opposing side, impose a duty on litigants to take affirmative steps to preserve relevant evidence, and this duty might arise prior to the commencement of litigation. For litigation occurring in common law courts, the duty to preserve relevant evidence typically arises when litigation is reasonably anticipated or contemplated. When an organization is involved in litigation, this duty to preserve applies to the organization’s management, and it extends to employees likely to have relevant information. A violation of the duty to preserve occurs when information that is relevant to anticipated or existing litigation is lost, destroyed, or otherwise made unavailable. Violating the duty to preserve relevant information can result in several adverse sanctions for the offending party, and such sanctions can arise from both intentional acts and accidental acts through negligence. The adverse consequences can include, but are not limited to, monetary penalties, the drawing of adverse inferences of fact, and criminal penalties. The theory behind such consequences is that the individual who makes evidence unavailable following the probable initiation of a lawsuit is aware of its detrimental effect upon a case. Examples of situations that could give rise to sanctions for failing to preserve evidence include intentionally or accidentally: Erasing computer files (e.g., documents, images, or databases) relevant to anticipated or existing litigation Losing or destroying physical evidence relevant to anticipated or existing litigation Losing, destroying, or altering documents or records relevant to anticipated or existing litigation Failing to suspend routine destruction of electronic data relevant to anticipated or existing litigation"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "A criminal defendant in a common law jurisdiction was convicted at trial for fraud. The defendant wants to appeal the decision, arguing that the jury made a factual error. Will the defendant likely be successful in his appeal?", "options": {"A": "Yes, as long as the defendant has evidence to support his claim.", "B": "Yes, because the defendant was denied a fair trial.", "C": "No, because only the government may appeal issues of fact in common law jurisdictions.", "D": "No, because issues of fact are generally not appealable in common law jurisdictions."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In most jurisdictions, a convicted individual has the right to appeal the trial court’s decision. An appeal is the procedure for obtaining review by a higher court to ensure that the trial was conducted in a lawful manner and that the judgments comply with the law. In an appeal, the appealing party petitions an appellate court to overturn or modify the lower court’s decision. The appellate court can reverse a conviction if the error denied the defendant a fair trial. A divergence exists between common law and civil law systems in their appellate processes. In most common law countries, appellate courts consider potential errors of law de novo (meaning they evaluate them independently of the trial court’s determinations), but they generally adopt the factual findings of the trial court. No jury is present, and there is typically no new evidence entered into the record. Therefore, appeals in common law systems are typically limited to issues of law. Very rarely will an appellate court reverse a factual finding of the trial court in a common law jurisdiction, such as when there is an egregious and obvious mistake. In most civil law systems, courts can review cases for both issues of fact and law."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is an example of insider trading?", "options": {"A": "Smith sells shares of his company's stock because he knows that the company is about to announce poor earnings", "B": "Roger purchases shares of his company's stock after he learns that his company is about to announce a new joint venture with a very successful and well-known multinational corporation", "C": "Albert buys shares of a company after the company’s CEO tells him about earnings growth a day before making the news public", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Insider trading occurs when an insider—someone who possesses inside information about a security—buys or sells securities on the basis of material information about the security that is not available to the public. Inside information is any material, nonpublic information about a security that is not generally available to the public and that could affect the security’s price. Examples of insider trading include: Corporate officers, directors, and employees who traded their corporation’s securities after learning of significant, confidential business developments Friends, business associates, and family members of corporate officers, directors, and employees who traded the corporation’s securities after learning of significant, confidential business developments Employees of law, banking, and accounting firms who were given inside information to provide services to the corporation whose securities they traded Government employees who traded a corporation’s securities after learning of inside information about the corporation because of their employment with the government Most jurisdictions have rules that forbid investors from buying or selling securities where the decision to buy or sell is based on material, nonpublic information, but the rules and efforts to enforce them vary widely. Some countries are strengthening their existing insider trading laws, some countries are only beginning to establish insider trading laws, and others do not enforce the laws already in place."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following investments are commonly recognized as securities?", "options": {"A": "Bonds", "B": "Fixed insurance policies", "C": "Retirement plans", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Types of investments most commonly recognized as securities include: stocks, bonds, and certificates of deposit (CDs). Retirement plans and fixed insurance policies are not generally recognized as securities."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "Under the World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes, which of the following statements MOST ACCURATELY represents the recommended powers of a bankruptcy administrator (or equivalent appointee)?", "options": {"A": "The administrator must abide by all contracts the debtor entered into prior to bankruptcy.", "B": "The administrator is not authorized to compel testimony from third parties with knowledge of the debtor’s financial affairs.", "C": "The administrator is allowed to collect and preserve the debtor’s property but has no power to dispose of it.", "D": "The administrator has the ability to cancel fraudulent transactions entered into by the debtor."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Most bankruptcy processes, whether through a court or otherwise, appoint a person or group with administrative powers to oversee the process. The name of this appointee varies between jurisdictions, but often is called the administrator, trustee, receiver, examiner, or supervisor. The World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes recommends that the administrator have broad powers, including: The right to cancel fraudulent contracts or transactions entered into by the debtor The power to collect, preserve, and dispose of the debtor’s property The ability to interfere with contracts to meet the objectives of the insolvency process The power to examine the debtor, the debtor’s agents, or other people with knowledge of the debtor’s affairs and compel them to provide relevant information"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a legal element that must be shown to prove a claim for official bribery?", "options": {"A": "The defendant gave or received a thing of value.", "B": "The government suffered damages as a result.", "C": "The recipient was (or was selected to be) a public official.", "D": "The defendant acted with corrupt intent."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Official bribery refers to the corruption of a public official to influence an official act of government. Illegal payments to public officials can be prosecuted as official bribery, and they can give rise to stiff penalties. The elements of official bribery vary by jurisdiction, but they generally include: The defendant gave or received (offered or solicited) a thing of value. The recipient was (or was selected to be) a public official. The defendant acted with corrupt intent. The defendant’s scheme was designed to influence an official act or duty of the recipient."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Which of the following claims in a civil lawsuit would be considered a counterclaim?", "options": {"A": "A plaintiff’s challenge of the ruling in another case", "B": "A defendant’s claim against the original plaintiff of the action", "C": "A plaintiff’s response to a defendant’s affirmative defense", "D": "A defendant’s claim against another defendant in the same proceeding"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In addition to allowing defenses against the plaintiff’s claims, many jurisdictions allow the defendant to raise counterclaims (also known as countersuits), in which the defendant levels a claim against the plaintiff. The specifics of the counterclaim might be filed as part of the defendant’s answer or as a separate document. If a defendant files a counterclaim, the counterclaim and the original complaint will be tried concurrently, with the final judgment stipulating a decision on each side’s claim."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Melanie lives in a jurisdiction that requires her to report her foreign bank accounts to the government annually, but she intentionally fails to report an account she has in a foreign secrecy jurisdiction. Which of the following best describes this type of tax evasion scheme?", "options": {"A": "Tax credit scheme", "B": "Income and wealth tax evasion", "C": "Consumption tax evasion", "D": "Falsified deductions scheme"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Taxes on periodic income or wealth (e.g., real property taxes) are a source of revenue for many governments, but fraudsters often commit tax evasion by falsifying or omitting material information. Common forms of criminal income and wealth tax evasion include: Failing to submit a report of one’s taxable income, if such a report is required Intentionally misrepresenting one’s income or wealth Pretending to transfer assets to another person or entity to lower tax liability Intentionally failing to withhold the taxable portion of an employee’s income, if so required Failing to report foreign bank accounts or other taxable assets, if required Falsely claiming income was earned in another jurisdiction to lower tax liability"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "ABC Corporation is involved in a reorganization bankruptcy proceeding, after which it will continue operations. Under the World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes, which of the following parties is an appropriate option for managing ABC during the proceedings?", "options": {"A": "Supervision of ABC’s management is undertaken by an independent insolvency representative", "B": "Exclusive control by an independent insolvency representative", "C": "ABC’s management maintains control", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Under the World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes, there are typically three preferred approaches in reorganization proceedings: Exclusive control of the proceeding is entrusted to an independent insolvency representative. Governance responsibilities remain invested in management. Supervision of management is undertaken by an impartial and independent insolvency representative or supervisor."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE statement about the judicial treatment of privileges from foreign jurisdictions in cross-border litigation?", "options": {"A": "The Hague Evidence Convention established a set of standardized rules of privilege for cross-border litigation.", "B": "Litigants involved in cross-border litigation should expect to have the privilege laws from their own jurisdiction applied when engaged in litigation abroad.", "C": "There is a lack of standardization and predictability with respect to privileges in cross-border litigation.", "D": "The Transnational Principles and Rules established a set of standardized rules of privilege for cross-border litigation."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The rise of global markets and multi-jurisdictional transactions has resulted in an increase in disputes that span multiple jurisdictions, and the privileges that are available vary substantially by jurisdiction. There are no standardized rules of privilege for litigation in cross-border disputes, and, in some cases, there will be conflicting rules of privilege. For example, the litigants in a cross-border dispute might be required to disclose information in one jurisdiction that is protected by privilege in another jurisdiction. Accordingly, there is a lack of standardization and predictability with respect to privileges in cross-border litigation, and privilege law is a key source of uncertainty for litigants in cross-border disputes. Generally, litigants involved in cross-border litigation should not expect to have the privilege laws from their own jurisdiction applied when engaged in litigation abroad. There are several reasons for this. First, courts are more inclined to apply their own privilege law because they are more familiar with local law than the laws of foreign jurisdictions. Second, characterizations and conceptualizations of privileges vary among different countries. For instance, common law jurisdictions typically view privileges as the right of the client, but civil law jurisdictions do not. In civil law jurisdictions, communications are protected by secrecy laws that require confidentiality."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Blue, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is a government agent in a jurisdiction with a warrant requirement. Based on evidence that White is manufacturing forged identification documents to facilitate large-scale identity theft, Blue obtains a valid warrant to search White’s residence. While conducting a lawful search, Blue immediately recognizes several plastic bags containing many different types of illegal drugs. Even though the items were not mentioned in the search warrant, Blue retrieves the items without a warrant based on the:", "options": {"A": "Incidental evidence doctrine", "B": "Warrantless search doctrine", "C": "Plain-view doctrine", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In many countries with a warrant requirement, the plain-view doctrine is an exception to the general rule that the government must obtain a search warrant before conducting a search of a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime. Under this doctrine, evidence in plain view of a law enforcement officer who has a right to be in a position to observe it may be seized without a warrant. The plain-view doctrine applies when a government official inadvertently discovers contraband or evidence of another crime during a search or arrest, even if there was no prior authority to seize the evidence. Thus, the doctrine applies only if a police officer is legally authorized to search the premises in which he inadvertently discovers the additional evidence in plain view. The plain-view doctrine does not apply unless the police officer discovered the evidence inadvertently. Thus, if discovery of the evidence is anticipated, and no other exception applies, the officer must first obtain a warrant. That is, if the officer knows in advance the location of certain evidence and relies on the plain-view doctrine to seize the evidence, the seizure will be considered illegal. Also, evidence will not be admissible under the plain-view doctrine unless it is apparent to the police that the items observed were evidence of a crime or otherwise subject to search and seizure."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Which of the following best describes the reporting requirement regarding large cash transactions with customers for financial institutions and designated nonfinancial businesses and professions (DNFBPs) under the Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations?", "options": {"A": "Domestic and international transactions over the designated threshold should require a report to the government.", "B": "All transactions between financial institutions should require a report to the government.", "C": "Only domestic transactions over the designated threshold should require a report to the government.", "D": "Only international transactions over the designated threshold should require a report to the government."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Under the best practices provided in the FATF’s Recommendations, countries should implement a reporting requirement for financial institutions and designated nonfinancial businesses and professions (DNFBPs) that engage in cash transactions above the jurisdiction's designated threshold. The reports should cover domestic and international cash transactions. Many jurisdictions implement this reporting requirement. Note that the recommended reporting requirement does not apply to everyone; it only applies to financial institutions and DNFBPs. DNFBPs include: Casinos (including Internet- and ship-based casinos) Real estate agents Dealers in precious metals and stones Legal professionals at professional firms (not internal legal professionals) Trust and company service providers"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "One expert cannot testify about the opinions of another expert.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Depending on the rules of the jurisdiction, the expert witness may be called by the court (i.e., the judge) or the parties. If called by the prosecution or plaintiff, fraud examiners might testify to their findings, and if called by the defense, they might testify regarding opinions expressed by the prosecution’s or plaintiff’s expert—to create doubt in the fact finder’s mind about the credibility or weight to be given to that expert. Alternatively, an expert might be called upon to give an opinion different from that reached by an equally credible expert called by the court or on the other side. This might be due to different interpretations of the facts of the case. In some instances, given equally plausible alternatives, the case might be decided based on which expert witness was the most credible."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Expert witnesses may not express opinions or draw conclusions in their testimony during a legal proceeding.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Testifying expert witnesses give opinion testimony when specialized knowledge is needed to help the fact finder understand evidence or determine a fact in issue. Unlike fact (or lay) witnesses, who generally can only testify about things they have personally observed, expert witnesses usually may express opinions or draw conclusions in their testimony."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "All of the following would violate rules prohibiting securities broker-dealers from making unsuitable recommendations on investments or investment strategies EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "A broker makes an investment that is inconsistent with the client’s objectives.", "B": "A broker makes an investment without obtaining prior approval for making the transaction.", "C": "A broker recommends an investment without ascertaining relevant financial information about the client.", "D": "A broker recommends an investment strategy that is unsuitable for the client."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In many countries, securities laws and regulations impose a suitability requirement on broker-dealers. Broker-dealers subject to a suitability requirement are prohibited from recommending investments or investment strategies that are unsuitable for their clients. Thus, making unsuitable recommendations (e.g., recommending high-risk options to a senior citizen with limited assets) is prohibited in countries with such suitability requirements. In most countries, a suitability requirement only arises when broker-dealers make recommendations or provide advice to clients to purchase a product. Essentially, there are two rules relating to suitability: the know-your-customer rule and the suitability rule. The know-your-customer rule provides that securities broker-dealers must know their customer financially to effectively service the customer’s account and minimize the risk of recommending an inappropriate investment. To comply with the know-your-customer rule, broker-dealers must use due diligence to ascertain relevant personal and financial information about clients and potential clients in regard to opening and maintaining accounts. Thus, this form of suitability violation occurs when a broker recommends an investment or an investment strategy to a client without having conducted due diligence to ascertain relevant personal and financial information about the client. In addition to the know-your-customer requirement, there are suitability requirements that broker-dealers must follow when making recommendations to a client. Suitability rules prohibit broker-dealers from making recommendations to clients if they do not have reasonable grounds for believing that the recommendations are suitable for the respective clients. That is, a suitability rule requires a broker-dealer to make a customer-specific determination of suitability and to tailor his recommendations to the customer’s financial profile and investment objectives."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Marco, a fraud examiner employed by the Jones Corporation, is asked to testify at trial concerning firsthand observations he made while investigating an embezzlement case. Marco can be best described as a:", "options": {"A": "Expert witness", "B": "Confirming witness", "C": "Lay witness", "D": "Observational witness"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "There are two basic kinds of testimony. The first is lay testimony (sometimes called factual testimony), where witnesses testify about what they have experienced firsthand and their factual observations. The second kind is expert testimony, where a person who, by reason of education, training, skill, or experience, is qualified to render an expert opinion concerning certain issues at hand. A lay witness (or fact witness) is anyone who provides nonexpert testimony. Note, however, that an expert witness might also provide lay testimony. Typically, a fraud examiner who worked on a case will be capable of providing lay testimony based on observations made during the investigation. When a trial involves issues that are complex or unfamiliar to most people, as is common in incidents of fraud, expert testimony is appropriate to help the fact finder understand these issues."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "The United Nations’ International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR) guarantees which of the following rights?", "options": {"A": "Right of the accused to be informed of criminal charges", "B": "The presumption of innocence until the accused is proven guilty according to law", "C": "Freedom from arbitrary arrests", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Most countries have signed and ratified the United Nations’ International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR), which commits them to recognizing various rights of citizens. Part III of the ICCPR includes the rights of those accused of crimes. Among the rights most relevant to fraud examiners, the ICCPR entitles the criminally accused to the following: Freedom from arbitrary arrest or detention Right of the accused to be informed of criminal charges Right to a fair hearing Presumption of innocence until proven guilty according to law Right to appeal a criminal conviction and sentence Right to privacy and protection from privacy violations"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "The Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendations regarding cross-border cash transfers state that countries should require individuals to disclose currency or currency equivalents (i.e., bearer instruments) above the designated threshold only if they are transporting money OUT of the country.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Under the Financial Action Task Force’s Recommendation 32, countries should implement disclosure requirements for individuals who are physically carrying currency or currency equivalents (i.e., bearer instruments) into or out of the country in amounts above the jurisdiction’s designated threshold. Generally, individuals who are carrying currency or the equivalent above the designated threshold while attempting to cross jurisdictional borders should be required to disclose the amount to authorities, and they will face penalties if they fail to do so."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "What is the recommendation regarding a secured interest registration system under the World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes?", "options": {"A": "There should be a private registration system for secured interests in personal property.", "B": "There should be no registration system for secured interests.", "C": "There should be a public registration system for secured interests in real property but not personal property.", "D": "There should be a public registration system for secured interests in all types of property."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "While bankruptcy laws and creditor rights vary from jurisdiction to jurisdiction, there is an international trend toward making such systems more uniform. According to the World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/Debtor Regimes, the legal framework for secured lending addresses the fundamental features and elements for the creation, recognition, and enforcement of security interests, including both possessory and non-possessory interests, in all types of assets on a global basis. This includes movable and immovable assets, as well as those that are tangible and intangible (including inventories, receivables, proceeds, and future property). The law should encompass any or all of a debtor’s obligations to a creditor, present or future, and between all types of people. In addition, it should provide for effective notice and registration rules that can be adapted to all types of property, as well as clear rules of priority on competing claims or interests in the same assets. For security rights and notices to third parties to be effective, they must be capable of being publicized at reasonable costs and be easily accessible to stakeholders. A reliable and affordable public registry system is essential to promoting optimal conditions for asset-based lending. Where several registries exist, the registration system should be integrated to the maximum extent possible so that all notices recorded under the secured transactions legislation can be easily retrieved."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Generally, for a contract, transaction, or scheme to qualify as an investment contract, four elements must be met. Which of the following is one of those four elements?", "options": {"A": "There is an investment of money or other asset", "B": "The investment is in a common enterprise", "C": "The investment was made with expectations of making a profit", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In many countries, the term security includes investment contracts. The leading global definition of investment contract provides that a contract, transaction, or scheme is an investment contract if all of the following four elements are met: There is an investment of money or other asset. The investment is in a common enterprise. The investment was made with expectations of making a profit. The profits are to come solely from the efforts of people other than the investor."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Blake, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is testifying in court as a witness in an adversarial system. During cross-examination, opposing counsel keeps getting extremely close to Blake, invading his body space. What should Blake do?", "options": {"A": "Move toward opposing counsel, decreasing body space.", "B": "Get through the questioning without complaining or arguing.", "C": "Ask the judge to intervene.", "D": "Attempt to move away from opposing counsel."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Opposing counsel might attempt to take psychological control of a witness by: Using physical presence to intimidate Making nonstop eye contact Challenging the witness’s space Asking questions at a fast pace to confuse the witness Not allowing the witness to explain or deviate from the exact question It is not the witness’s job to argue with or challenge the person conducting questioning. The witness should simply try to get through the cross-examination in the most professional way possible. If the questioning party uses blatantly unfair practices, the judge or jury will take note, and such practices might hurt the opposing side's case. In no circumstances should the witness argue. In adversarial proceedings, the counsel who called the witness is tasked with objecting to improper questioning, so the witness should continue answering questions until an objection is made, and then follow the court’s directions. In inquisitorial proceedings, the judge should intervene if questioning is improper."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Which of the following best describes the civil trial process in a civil law jurisdiction?", "options": {"A": "The judge generally rules on the admissibility of the evidence at the beginning of the trial.", "B": "It is a continual series of meetings and written correspondences, rather than a single event.", "C": "It is generally divided into the pretrial stage and the trial stage.", "D": "The judge is responsible for the trial record, which is a word-for-word transcript of the proceedings."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Civil cases in civil law jurisdictions vary considerably from common law civil cases. The most obvious difference is that civil law trials are a continual series of meetings and written correspondences, rather than a single event, as in common law systems. Throughout the process, evidence is introduced and evaluated by the court, and motions are submitted and decided on by the judge. The division between pretrial and trial stages found in common law civil trials, therefore, does not apply in the typical civil law setting. Throughout the trial, the judge evaluates evidence and records it in the trial record. The record is generally a summary of the evidence, rather than a word-for-word transcript of the proceedings. At the final hearing, the judge rules on the admissibility and relevance of the evidence in the record and presents it. This final hearing usually resembles the trial stage in common law jurisdictions. After presenting the evidence in court, the judge, jury, or judge panel (depending on the jurisdiction and type of case) rules on the issues in the case."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Over time, Herman stole $500,000 in cash from his employer. He deposited the cash in small increments into a bank account to avoid reporting requirements. He then transferred the stolen funds to an overseas account and proceeded with several additional transfers and fake loans to foreign entities that he controlled. Finally, he moved the funds back home, disguising them as profits from investments. Which of the following stages of money laundering was Herman performing when he engaged in transfers and fake loans to foreign entities?", "options": {"A": "Placement", "B": "Structuring", "C": "Layering", "D": "Integration"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The three stages of money laundering are placement, layering, and integration. Placement is the first stage of the money laundering process. In this stage, the launderer introduces his illegal profits into the financial system. Herman “placed” his stolen funds into the financial system when he incrementally deposited cash into a bank account. If the placement of the initial funds goes undetected, the launderer can design numerous financial transactions in complex patterns to prevent detection. For example, the launderer can move funds between bank accounts, transfer funds from one form of currency to another, or transfer money between businesses. This stage of the money laundering process is referred to as layering. This is the stage Herman was engaged in when he created additional transfers and fake loans involving foreign entities that he controlled. Integration is the final stage in the laundering process. In this stage, the money is integrated back into the economy in a way that makes it appear to be part of a legitimate business transaction. Herman performed this stage when he brought the funds home and integrated them as seemingly legitimate proceeds from investments."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Which of the following best describes the process of eliciting testimony from expert witnesses in most inquisitorial judicial systems?", "options": {"A": "The expert submits a report and the parties are able to ask limited questions concerning the expert’s qualifications.", "B": "The parties to litigation must unanimously approve the expert’s qualifications to testify.", "C": "The parties are allowed to cross-examine the expert and ask any relevant questions concerning the expert’s qualifications.", "D": "The expert’s testimony is automatically admissible."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The primary experts in inquisitorial jurisdictions are usually appointed and presented by the judge, rather than the parties. Like in adversarial jurisdictions, the judge makes the final determination of whether an expert is qualified. However, most inquisitorial jurisdictions have more standardized qualification requirements. After being initially selected by the judge, expert witnesses are usually required to submit a report to the court and are subject to questioning by the parties to the litigation. The parties’ representatives may ask questions concerning the expert’s qualifications, potential biases, and report, but are generally more limited in the scope of questioning than parties in adversarial proceedings. The judge has already reviewed the witness by this point and there are generally more specific requirements in inquisitorial systems, so there is a lower perceived need to allow parties to challenge the expert."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following MOST ACCURATELY describes the legal elements that must be shown to prove a claim for official bribery?", "options": {"A": "The defendant, while acting negligently, gave or received a thing of value that was intended to influence an act or duty of the recipient who was (or was selected to be) a public official.", "B": "The defendant, while acting negligently, gave or received a thing of value that was intended to influence an act or duty of the recipient who was (or was selected to be) a public official, causing the government to suffer damages.", "C": "The defendant, while acting without due care, gave or received a thing of value that was intended to influence an act or duty of the recipient who was (or was selected to be) a public official.", "D": "The defendant, while acting with corrupt intent, gave or received a thing of value that was intended to influence an act or duty of the recipient who was (or was selected to be) a public official."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Official bribery refers to the corruption of a public official with intent to influence an official act of government. Illegal payments to public officials can be prosecuted as official bribery, and they can give rise to stiff penalties. The elements of official bribery vary by jurisdiction, but they generally include: The defendant gave or received (offered or solicited) a thing of value. The recipient was (or was selected to be) a public official. The defendant acted with corrupt intent. The defendant’s scheme was designed to influence an official act or duty of the recipient."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "In civil litigation in civil law jurisdictions, when is the trial record typically created?", "options": {"A": "After the judge has announced the court’s decision", "B": "In the pretrial stage", "C": "After the court has completed the evidence-gathering process", "D": "Throughout the trial as the court gathers evidence"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In the inquisitorial process commonly found in civil law jurisdictions, the evidence is gathered and entered into the trial record contemporaneously with the trial, as opposed to the common law method of having the parties gather evidence over time and enter it into the record all at once during the trial stage. Civil law legal systems tend to value documentary and written evidence over oral testimony. When witnesses give testimony, the judge orchestrates the questioning instead of the parties. The judge is also responsible for collecting documents and physical evidence."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "Which of the following best describes the government’s burden of proof in criminal cases in civil law jurisdictions that use an inquisitorial court process?", "options": {"A": "Inner conviction of the judge", "B": "More likely than not", "C": "Beyond a reasonable doubt", "D": "Absolute certainty"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The burden of proof is the evidence one party must present to prove each element of a cause of action. Most civil law systems that use an inquisitorial court process apply a different standard than beyond a reasonable doubt, as is used in most common law jurisdictions. This civil law standard is sometimes called the conviction intime or inner conviction of the judge. It means that the fact finder needs to be convinced at an inner, deep-seated level. While this standard is still quite high, it is generally thought to be somewhat less certain than beyond a reasonable doubt. Additionally, civil law systems typically have the same burden of proof for civil and criminal cases."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Which of the following is an example of the use of a digital currency?", "options": {"A": "Wire transfers", "B": "Bitcoin transactions", "C": "Credit card transactions", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Digital currencies are a type of online payment method that has emerged as a money laundering concern. Broadly defined, digital currencies are currencies that exist and are traded in a digital format. The term typically excludes government-backed currencies, despite the fact that they can also exist and be traded digitally. Digital currencies can come in several forms and can have limited or broad uses. Among the most popular digital currencies is Bitcoin, which features a peer-to-peer network that allows users to send units of the currency to each other online without the use of a traditional financial institution."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Jean intended to defraud the government by failing to withhold taxes on her employee’s income, but it turns out there was no tax deficiency because her employee was exempt from such taxes. In most jurisdictions, would Jean be criminally liable for tax evasion for this conduct?", "options": {"A": "No, because failing to collect taxes on employee income is not a criminal offense.", "B": "Yes, because she intended to defraud the government.", "C": "No, because there was no tax deficiency.", "D": "Yes, because she did not collect taxes on the employee’s income."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A suspect or a criminal defendant might raise various defenses to accusations of tax fraud. Whether these defenses are legally recognized depends on the laws of the jurisdiction. The following are common defenses to tax evasion: No tax deficiency: The defendant can establish that there is no deficiency. In most jurisdictions, if there is no deficiency, there is no tax liability. This is generally the best defense, if available, because several other defenses might negate willfulness, but do not necessarily eliminate a tax liability with interest and penalties. Lack of willfulness: A lack of willfulness reduces the defendant’s culpability for fraud. A good faith belief that one is not violating the tax law, based on a misunderstanding caused by the law’s complexity, negates willfulness. Avoidance, not evasion: A taxpayer charged with tax crimes might argue that he engaged in legal means of lowering his tax bill through legitimate avoidance mechanisms, such as deductions, credits, and shelters. Thus, establishing that the taxpayer was engaging in tax avoidance and not evasion provides a defense to tax fraud. Reliance on an attorney or accountant: If a taxpayer properly relied on expert advice for the conduct in question, the jurisdiction might find no criminal liability. Mental illness: Certain mental illnesses and incapacitating conditions negate criminal intent for tax crimes."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Which of the following money laundering schemes would be classified as depositing, but not recording, revenue?", "options": {"A": "Over-reporting expenses at a company to mask illicit income", "B": "Over-reporting revenue at a company to disguise illegal proceeds", "C": "Placing illicit proceeds into a company’s account without entering them as a sale", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In one of the most common schemes at the local level, launderers deposit illicit cash into the front company’s bank account rather than disguising it as revenue. These funds are not recorded like the money that flows into and out of a business as revenues and expenses. Like a loan, this excess cash represents the proceeds of a transaction that is handled outside of the front business’s daily activity. Also, like a loan, it appears on the company’s balance sheet, which includes both assets and liabilities. Every legitimate asset in a company’s possession must come from somewhere—if not from revenues, then from a limited number of other credible alternatives. The basic alternative sources include loans, proceeds from the sale of property or equipment, and capital investments from shareholders."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Criminal Justice System", "question": "In common law jurisdictions, which of the following parties typically serves as the fact finder in criminal trials?", "options": {"A": "The prosecution", "B": "The judge", "C": "A jury", "D": "One professional judge and a panel of lay judges"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Most juries in a common law criminal court consist of 12 or fewer jurors. The jurors are selected from the local population, often by a random lottery using voter registration records and the like. While jury trials are typically used in criminal proceedings in common law jurisdictions, this is not always the case. For some cases, usually minor criminal offenses, a jury trial might not be available. In serious cases, however, jury trials are typically available. Additionally, many common law jurisdictions allow the defendant to waive the right to trial by jury. When no jury is present, the judge serves as the fact finder."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "In most civil law jurisdictions, oral testimony is favored over written evidence in civil litigation.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In the inquisitorial process commonly found in civil law jurisdictions, the evidence is gathered by the court and entered into the trial record. Civil law legal systems tend to value documentary and written evidence over oral testimony, and oral testimony is often reduced to written summaries."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "The main distinction between mediation and arbitration is that with arbitration, the arbitrator actually decides who wins the case. In contrast, in mediation, the mediator simply tries to help the parties work out a settlement.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Alternative dispute resolution in fraud cases usually involves one of two types of methods: mediation or arbitration. Mediation is the process whereby an impartial third person assists the parties in reaching a resolution to the dispute. The mediator does not decide who should win but instead works with the parties to reach a mutually agreeable settlement. Arbitration is the process whereby a dispute is submitted to an impartial third person (known as an arbitrator) who then decides the outcome of the case (i.e., which party should win). The arbitrator acts as a judge or jury by deciding the case on its merits."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "ndividual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Employees’ privacy rights that can affect the employer-employee relationship may arise from statutory law but not contract law.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Employees have certain privacy rights that can affect numerous aspects of the employer-employee relationship, such as conducting investigations, surveillance and monitoring, and workplace searches. An employee’s privacy rights can arise from, and be protected by, various sources of law, including constitutional law, statutory law, common law, human rights law, labor law, data protection law, contract law, and other sources."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "In most common law systems, relevant documents in civil cases are listed and described by the party that holds them in which of the following devices?", "options": {"A": "Subpoena coram non judice", "B": "Affidavit of documents or records", "C": "Writ of attachment", "D": "Injunctions list"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "After statements of claim and defense are filed in common law jurisdictions, each party is entitled to pretrial discovery. In most common law jurisdictions, each party must file an affidavit of documents, or affidavit of records, which lists and describes all documents in its possession that are relevant to any matter at issue in the case. The party filing the affidavit must allow the other party to inspect or copy any such documents. If any of the documents are privileged, the privilege should be asserted in the affidavit of documents. If requested, the judge will examine the documents to determine if the privilege applies. Some jurisdictions also allow the parties to make a request for documents or records, in which they ask another party to turn over a specific document or other record."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "question": "Which of the following is an example of insider trading?", "options": {"A": "An individual buys a company’s shares because the company operates in an industry that is growing rapidly.", "B": "An employee sells shares of his company's stock because he knows that the company is about to publicly announce it is filing for bankruptcy.", "C": "An individual sells his shares in a company after reading a news article about an explosion at the company’s factory.", "D": "A bank manager tells a customer that the interest rates for thirty-year-mortgages have reached an all-time low."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Insider trading occurs when an insider—someone who possesses inside information about a security—buys or sells securities on the basis of material information about the security that is not available to the public. Inside information is any material, nonpublic information about a security that is not generally available to the public and that could affect the security’s price. Examples of insider trading include: Corporate officers, directors, and employees who traded their corporation’s securities after learning of significant, confidential business developments Friends, business associates, and family members of corporate officers, directors, and employees who traded the corporation’s securities after learning of significant, confidential business developments Employees of law, banking, and accounting firms who were given inside information to provide services to the corporation whose securities they traded Government employees who traded a corporation’s securities after learning of inside information about the corporation because of their employment with the government Most jurisdictions have rules that forbid investors from buying or selling securities where the decision to buy or sell is based on material, nonpublic information, but the rules and efforts to enforce them vary widely. Some countries are strengthening their existing insider trading laws, some countries are only beginning to establish insider trading laws, and others do not enforce the laws already in place."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "question": "Although expert witnesses are allowed to present their opinions in narrative form, they are not allowed to provide their opinions on hypothetical situations presented by the questioning party because hypotheticals are not adequately grounded in the evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Expert witnesses present their findings in various ways, such as narrative questions, hypotheticals, specialized materials, and special exhibits. Experts are commonly asked to answer narrative questions, which are broad, open-ended questions that allow experts to present their opinions in their own words with minimal prompting. Expert witnesses also are typically allowed to demonstrate their findings by using hypotheticals, which are fictional situations, analogous to the act in question, that clarify and highlight particular aspects of the dispute. But to be effective, hypotheticals must be constructed exquisitely."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "Which of the following MOST ACCURATELY describes the legal elements that must be shown to prove a claim for commercial bribery?", "options": {"A": "The defendant, while acting without due care, gave or received a thing of value that was intended to influence the recipient’s action in a business decision, causing his principal to suffer damages.", "B": "The defendant, while acting negligently and without the victim’s knowledge or consent, gave or received a thing of value that was intended to influence the recipient’s action in a business decision.", "C": "The defendant, while acting with corrupt intent, gave or received a thing of value that was intended to influence the recipient’s action in a business decision, causing his principal to suffer damages.", "D": "The defendant, while acting with corrupt intent and without the victim’s knowledge or consent, gave or received a thing of value that was intended to influence the recipient’s action in a business decision."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Commercial bribery refers to the corruption of a private individual to gain a commercial or business advantage. That is, in commercial bribery schemes, something of value is offered to influence a business decision rather than an official act. The elements of commercial bribery vary by jurisdiction, but they typically include: The defendant gave or received a thing of value. The defendant acted with corrupt intent. The defendant’s scheme was designed to influence the recipient’s action in a business decision. The defendant acted without the victim’s knowledge or consent."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Law Related to Fraud", "question": "To establish that a defendant violated a law criminalizing false statements to government agencies, the government must prove that the defendant made a false statement regarding a matter within the jurisdiction of a government agency, and the agency relied on the false statement to its detriment.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Laws prohibiting false claims and statements to government agencies make it illegal for a person to lie to, or conceal material information from, a government agency. A false claim is an assertion of a right to government money, property, or services that contains a misrepresentation. A false statement is an oral or written communication, declaration, or assertion that is factually untrue. Generally, to prove a violation, the government must show that the defendant: Knowingly and willfully (or with reckless disregard for truth or falsity) Made a false claim or statement (or used a false document) That was material (i.e., sufficiently important or relevant to influence decision making) Regarding a matter within the jurisdiction of a government agency With knowledge of its falsity Also, the following are general rules with regard to laws criminalizing false claims and statements to government agencies: An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the claim or statement is not made directly to a governmental department or agency. That is, a false claim or statement need not be made directly to the government; it can be made to a third party as long as it involves a matter within the jurisdiction of a governmental department or agency. An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the government was not deceived by the falsity. An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the government did not rely on the falsity. An individual can be found guilty for making a false claim or statement even if the government did not suffer a loss in reliance on the falsity. For an individual to be found guilty of making a false claim or statement, the claim or statement at issue must have been capable of influencing the government entity involved."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Which of the following statements is CORRECT?", "options": {"A": "Neither tax evasion nor tax avoidance is illegal.", "B": "Tax avoidance is illegal, but tax evasion is not.", "C": "Tax evasion is illegal, but tax avoidance is not.", "D": "Both tax evasion and tax avoidance are illegal."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The term tax evasion refers to any fraudulent actions that a taxpayer commits to avoid reporting or paying taxes. Tax evasion, however, should not be confused with tax avoidance. Tax avoidance refers to a legal means of lowering one’s tax bill through legitimate deductions, credits, and shelters. The intent of the taxpayer to wrongly file a tax return or provide other false tax information will determine the difference between tax evasion and tax avoidance. The primary distinguishing characteristic of tax evasion as compared to tax avoidance is that tax evasion is illegal, but tax avoidance is legal."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning the Financial Action Task Force’s (FATF) Recommendations is TRUE?", "options": {"A": "They suggest that countries should adopt a risk-based approach when setting anti-money laundering policies", "B": "They suggest that countries should create policies that increase cooperation and coordination with other countries", "C": "They suggest that countries should enable authorities to trace, freeze, and confiscate assets suspected in money laundering and terrorist financing", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is an intergovernmental body that was established at the G-7 Summit in 1989. Its purpose is to develop and promote standards and policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing at both the national and international levels. The FATF’s Recommendations, revised in 2012, created the most comprehensive standard with which to measure a country’s anti-money laundering, counterterrorism, and nuclear proliferation laws and policies. They serve as a basic framework of laws that its members should have. While the recommendations are not required by members and the FATF acknowledges that following each rule might not be possible, members of the FATF often adopt them. Some of the key measures in the Recommendations provide that countries should: Use a risk-based approach when setting anti-money laundering policies. Create policies that increase cooperation and coordination with other countries. Specifically criminalize money laundering and terrorist financing. Enable authorities to trace, freeze, and confiscate assets suspected in laundering and terrorist financing. Require financial institutions to keep certain records and establish anti-money laundering policies, avoid correspondent banking with shell banks, and continuously monitor wire transfers."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "The most common type of bankruptcy fraud scheme is the concealment of assets.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The most common type of bankruptcy fraud scheme involves the concealment of assets rightfully belonging to the debtor’s estate to avoid forfeiting the assets in bankruptcy. In these schemes, concealed assets might include cash, consumer property, houses, and interests in partnerships and corporations, as well as lawsuits in which the debtor is a plaintiff. Concealed assets might also include the debtor’s books and records."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "question": "Sandra, who has no accounting experience, completed tax documents for her new business. The information was more complex than she realized, and she improperly (although unintentionally) completed the documents. Which of the following statements is MOST ACCURATE?", "options": {"A": "Sandra will be subject to criminal penalties because she incorrectly completed the documents.", "B": "Sandra will not be subject to criminal penalties because her improper act was not willful.", "C": "Sandra will only be subject to criminal penalties if the government suffered an actual loss.", "D": "Sandra will not be subject to criminal penalties because new businesses have one year of immunity from criminal tax liability."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Tax evasion refers to any fraudulent actions that a taxpayer commits to avoid reporting or paying taxes. To establish criminal liability for tax evasion, most jurisdictions require a willful attempt to evade or defeat taxes in an unlawful manner. In the context of tax evasion, a good faith or legitimate misunderstanding of the applicable law typically negates willfulness (the voluntary, intentional violation of a known legal duty). That is, honest mistakes, in contrast to willful evasion, do not constitute tax evasion. However, a court might find that a defendant’s claimed misunderstanding of the law is implausible given the evidence presented."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "If a party obtains a domestic judgment against a foreign defendant in a fraud case, the party will be able to enforce that judgment in any jurisdiction where the defendant resides.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A domestic judgment against a foreign defendant is usually helpful for recovering the defendant’s assets located in the domestic country, but it might be worthless for obtaining the defendant’s assets in a foreign country. Some, but not all, countries will enforce foreign judgments concerning parties or assets within their jurisdiction. Whether the country will enforce a foreign court’s judgment usually depends on the circumstances in which the internal laws of the jurisdiction recognize foreign judgments and whether the two countries of each court have an enforcement treaty."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Civil Justice System", "question": "Integrative bargaining is the process whereby an impartial third person assists the parties to a dispute in reaching a resolution.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Mediation is the process whereby an impartial third person assists the parties in reaching a resolution to the dispute. The mediator does not decide who should win but instead works with the parties to reach a mutually agreeable settlement."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to The Institute of Internal Auditors’ International Standards for the Professional Practice of Internal Auditing, the internal audit activity must evaluate risk exposures relating to the organization's governance, operations, and information systems regarding all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Compliance with laws, regulations, and contracts", "B": "Effectiveness and efficiency of operations", "C": "Reliability and integrity of financial and operational information", "D": "Sale of tangible and intangible assets"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "According to The Institute of Internal Auditors' Standard 2120.A1, the internal audit activity must evaluate risk exposures relating to the organization's governance, operations, and information systems regarding the: Achievement of the organization’s strategic objectives Reliability and integrity of financial and operational information Effectiveness and efficiency of operations Safeguarding of assets Compliance with laws, regulations, and contracts"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "Evidence that proves or disproves facts by inference is called direct evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "There are two basic types of admissible evidence: direct evidence and circumstantial evidence. Direct evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue directly, such as eyewitness testimony or a confession. Circumstantial evidence is evidence that tends to prove or disprove facts in issue indirectly, by inference."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "Which of the following financial institutions is NOT considered a money services business?", "options": {"A": "A depository investment bank", "B": "A check cashing company", "C": "A currency exchange", "D": "A prepaid access card provider"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Money services business (MSB) is a term used with growing frequency to define a regulatory class of non-depository financial service providers that transmit or convert money. Although an MSB has particular meanings in different jurisdictions, it generally includes any business that operates in one or more of the following capacities: Currency exchangers Check cashers Issuers, sellers, or redeemers of traveler’s checks, money orders, or stored value Money transmitters Prepaid access providers or sellers MSBs offer an alternative to depository institutions for both financial services and money laundering. For this reason, an individual unable to transfer illegal funds into the traditional depository banking system might turn to an MSB. In addition, most MSBs operate under less strict regulations than traditional financial institutions. For example, an MSB might not check a customer’s credit report before opening an account, or it might require less rigorous proof of a customer’s identity than a traditional bank. These overall less stringent requirements tend to raise the money laundering risk in certain transactions involving users of MSBs. However, there is a regulatory trend to expand certain requirements, such as customer due diligence programs, to MSBs."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "a", "question": "Nearly every country prohibits ________ employee monitoring, unless a specific criminal activity has been identified.", "options": {"A": "Remote", "B": "Covert", "C": "Ongoing", "D": "Digital"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Nearly every country prohibits covert employee monitoring, unless a specific criminal activity has been identified. Therefore, nearly every employer is required to notify its employees before implementing an employee monitoring program. The notice should be clear and comprehensive, and it should be made in writing."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "question": "Suppose that a party obtains a judgment against a foreign defendant in a domestic court. Which of the following accurately describes the effect of that judgment?", "options": {"A": "The judgment might be used to seize the defendant’s assets in a foreign jurisdiction whose internal laws recognize the judgment", "B": "The judgment might be used to seize the defendant’s assets in a foreign jurisdiction that has a treaty with the domestic jurisdiction for the enforcement of judgments", "C": "The judgment might be used to seize the defendant’s assets located in the domestic country", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A domestic judgment against a foreign defendant is usually helpful for recovering the defendant’s assets located in the domestic country, but it might be worthless for obtaining the defendant’s assets in a foreign country. Some, but not all, countries will enforce foreign judgments concerning parties or assets within their jurisdiction. Whether the country will enforce a foreign court’s judgment usually depends on the circumstances in which the internal laws of the jurisdiction recognize foreign judgments and whether the two countries of each court have an enforcement treaty."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "question": "The hard drive of a compromised computer system was given to Brad, a forensic examiner, for analysis. If Brad cannot verify who provided him with the computer’s hard drive for analysis, then:", "options": {"A": "The hard drive must be imaged.", "B": "The hard drive must be rehashed.", "C": "The chain of custody is broken.", "D": "The best-evidence rule is invoked."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "If evidence is subject to change over time, or is susceptible to alteration, the offering party might need to establish that the evidence has not been altered or changed from the time it was collected through its production in court. This is done by establishing a chain of custody. Thus, the chain of custody can be an important factor in establishing authenticity. The chain of custody is both a process and a document that memorializes (1) who has had possession of an object and (2) what they have done with it; it is simply a means of establishing that there has not been a material change or alteration to a piece of evidence."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "One of the most common methods of laundering funds is to filter the money through a front business. A front business can be useful to a criminal for which of the following reasons?\nI.   It provides a safe place for organizing and managing criminal activity.\nII.  It provides a base of operations where the comings and goings of large numbers of people will not arouse undue suspicion.\nIII. It is an easy way for the criminal to avoid paying taxes on illegal sources of revenue.\nIV.  The front that does the legitimate business provides cover for delivery and transportation related to illegal activity.", "options": {"A": "II and IV only", "B": "II, III, and IV", "C": "I, II, and IV", "D": "I, II, and III"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Submit Answer One of the most common methods of laundering funds is to filter the money through a seemingly legitimate business, known as a front business. A front business can be a very effective way to launder money for a number of reasons. Front businesses provide a safe place for organizing and managing criminal activity, where the comings and goings of large numbers of people will not arouse undue suspicion. In addition, a front that conducts legitimate business provides cover for delivery and transportation related to illegal activity. The expenses from illegal activity can be attributed to the legitimate enterprise, and the illegal revenues can be easily placed into the enterprise. One disadvantage to this, however, is that launderers usually end up having to pay taxes on their illegal income."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "question": "A bustout is a planned bankruptcy. To perpetrate this type of scheme, in which order must the following steps be taken by the underlying business?", "options": {"A": "III then II then IV then I", "B": "I then IV then III then II", "C": "III then II then I then IV", "D": "II then III then IV then I"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Submit Answer A bustout is a planned and fraudulent bankruptcy. It can take many different forms, but the basic approach is for an apparently legitimate business to order large quantities of inventory or other goods on credit, and then dispose of those goods through legitimate or illegitimate channels. Because the point of the bustout scheme is to quickly resell the goods for cash, the fraudster is likely to purchase more liquid items like inventory than real estate, insurance policies, or services. The perpetrator then closes shop, absconding with the proceeds and leaving the suppliers unpaid. The debtor might then go into bankruptcy. Often, by this point the debtor has already made false accounting entries or taken other steps to conceal the assets or make the sales look legitimate. Other times, debtors simply flee the jurisdiction or do not show up at the proceedings."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "question": "Smith, a CFE, works for the ABC Company, a publicly traded company. One day, Smith’s manager asks him to search the personal belongings of Green, an employee for the ABC Company, for evidence of securities fraud, even though there is no direct government authorization or order for the search. Smith seizes and searches Green’s personal tablet. Assuming that these facts occur in a jurisdiction with laws that provide the public with the right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities, which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE statement regarding Green’s rights?", "options": {"A": "Green’s rights were likely violated because all publicly traded companies are considered “government actors” for purposes of determining rights to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities.", "B": "The search did not violate Green’s right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities because such rights do not apply to searches in the workplace.", "C": "The search did not violate Green’s right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities because ABC is not a government authority.", "D": "Green’s right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities was likely violated because Smith conducted the search without direct authorization from the government."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Submit Answer Most countries have laws that provide the public with the right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities, and though the interpretation may vary, this right sometimes requires that the government obtain authorization (e.g., a search warrant) by a judicial officer or other authorized person before it conducts a search. A search warrant is a court order that grants government authorities the right to search a premises or property for information pertinent to a case. The requirements for search warrants or other similar authorization, however, do not apply to private parties acting on their own accord because the right to be free from unreasonable searches and seizures does not protect against actions by such parties. Instead, it protects individuals from actions by government authorities. Thus, to determine whether a search warrant or similar authorization is required for a search to be conducted in an investigation, it is necessary to first determine whether or not government authorities are involved in the search. Also, the right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities can apply to searches in the workplace."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "question": "One of the most common methods of laundering funds is to filter the money through a front business. A front business can be useful to a criminal for which of the following reasons?\nI.   It provides a safe place for organizing and managing criminal activity.\nII.  It provides a base of operations where the comings and goings of large numbers of people will not arouse undue suspicion.\nIII. It is an easy way for the criminal to avoid paying taxes on illegal sources of revenue.\nIV.  The front that does the legitimate business provides cover for delivery and transportation related to illegal activity.", "options": {"A": "II, III, and IV", "B": "II and IV only", "C": "I, II, and IV", "D": "I, II, and III"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Submit Answer One of the most common methods of laundering funds is to filter the money through a seemingly legitimate business, known as a front business. A front business can be a very effective way to launder money for a number of reasons. Front businesses provide a safe place for organizing and managing criminal activity, where the comings and goings of large numbers of people will not arouse undue suspicion. In addition, a front that conducts legitimate business provides cover for delivery and transportation related to illegal activity. The expenses from illegal activity can be attributed to the legitimate enterprise, and the illegal revenues can be easily placed into the enterprise. One disadvantage to this, however, is that launderers usually end up having to pay taxes on their illegal income."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Investigation", "question": "Which of the following is a type of information that can be obtained from the deep Web?", "options": {"A": "An archived version of a Web page that is no longer online", "B": "An old version of a Web page that has since been updated", "C": "Web content indexed by standard search engines", "D": "Websites without any links pointing to them"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The deep Web (also known as the invisible Web) refers to Web content that is not indexed by standard search engines. There are a number of reasons why the deep Web exists. For instance, there are websites where Web crawlers (search engine robots or spiders) cannot enter. Web crawlers are scripts that create copies of visited Web pages that are indexed by a search engine to provide faster searches. These deep Web resources include websites without any links pointing to them, certain file formats that search engines cannot handle, websites that have been blocked from Web crawler access, password-protected websites, and information stored in databases. Also, search engines limit the depth of their crawl on a website. Moreover, Web crawlers cannot crawl as quickly as pages are added or updated. Alternatively, the term Internet archives refers to archived versions of Web pages that have since been updated or are no longer available online. The most popular tool for searching the Internet archives is the Wayback Machine, located at https://archive.org. The Wayback Machine allows users to see archived versions of Web pages throughout time. Fraud examiners can use the Wayback Machine to find historical information, such as: A photo posted on a website that has been removed Content, views, writing, and opinions rescinded by an author A company's old job ads, statements, affiliations, or product lines"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "By examining the probate records of a deceased individual, a fraud examiner can discover:", "options": {"A": "An indication of the value of the property willed to the deceased's heirs", "B": "The manner in which the deceased’s assets will be dispersed", "C": "The names of individuals with an interest in the deceased’s estate", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Some jurisdictions have separate probate courts to determine the dispersal of assets after a subject’s death. The probate court conducts an investigation to verify any debts owed by an individual's estate and sees to the dispersal of assets after all debts are paid. Probate court records include documents filed to show the dispersal of assets after a subject’s death. The debts left in an individual’s estate will give the investigator information on the following: Names of individuals with an interest in the deceased’s estate The subject’s financial position at the time of death The dispersal of assets will reveal: The names and addresses of heirs to the deceased Some indication of the value of the property willed to them"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "When searching regulatory securities records for information on a publicly traded company, which of the following information is LEAST LIKELY to be found?", "options": {"A": "Identity of the company’s officers and directors", "B": "Identity of major owners of the company", "C": "Major events that are of interest to investors", "D": "The complete books and records of the company"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "While jurisdictions treat the concept of securities differently, governments or self-regulatory bodies generally set rules for the issuing and trading of certain types of securities. Among the most common and important rules are disclosure requirements for companies with publicly traded securities. These rules are designed to make sure that investors are reasonably informed about stock that they purchase. Beyond helping investors, these disclosures typically are made public, and they can provide a wealth of information about the filing company, including its type of business, history, organizational structure, auditor, balance sheets, and income statements. Different regulators have varying disclosure requirements, but these records might include the following information: Corporate financial statements Identification of officers and directors Identification of significant owners (e.g., those with more than 10% of a business’s stock) A description of the registrant’s properties and businesses A description of the significant provisions of the security to be offered for sale and its relationship to the registrant’s other capital securities Identification of events of interest to investors Identification of accountants and attorneys A history of the business The complete books and records of a company, however, are not available in securities records searches."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "Which of the following is typically the most effective way to document chain of custody for a piece of evidence?", "options": {"A": "A video recording of the fraud examiner explaining the process used to collect the evidence", "B": "A memorandum with the custodian of the evidence when the evidence is received", "C": "Photographs of the evidence that clearly show what the evidence is and where it was originally found", "D": "An affidavit signed by the fraud examiner swearing to the evidence's contents"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "From the moment evidence is received, its chain of custody must be maintained for it to be accepted by the court. The chain of custody is both a process and a document that memorializes who has had possession of an object and what they have done with it. Essentially, the chain of custody is a recordkeeping procedure similar to physical inventory procedures. In general, to establish the chain of custody, fraud examiners must make a record of when they receive an item or when it leaves their care, custody, or control. This is best handled by creating a memorandum with the custodian of the records when the evidence is received. The memorandum should state: What items were received When they were received From whom they were received Where they are maintained"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning public records is MOST ACCURATE?", "options": {"A": "Public records are those maintained by public companies.", "B": "Public records are valuable for obtaining background information on individuals.", "C": "Public records are useful for searching banking records.", "D": "Public records are the primary source of individual health information."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Public records are documents that a governmental agency is required to keep by law or that are necessary to discharge the duties imposed by law. Public records, which can generally be accessed by the public and are thus available to anyone who wishes to use them, can be helpful to fraud examiners for a number of reasons. They can supply invaluable background information on entities, employees, suspects, and witnesses. They can also be used to corroborate or refute witness statements, help investigators track the flow of stolen money or other assets, and aid efforts to recover losses. Banking, health records, and consumer credit records are typically nonpublic information."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "The General Data Privacy Regulation (GDPR) only applies to organizations that collect or process European Union (EU) residents’ data if those organizations are based in the European Union.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which took effect on May 25, 2018, is the primary regulation governing the collection and processing of the personal data of European Union (EU) residents. Although the GDPR only concerns the personal data of EU residents, it applies to any organization worldwide that collects or processes this information, regardless of where the organization is based. In other words, an organization does not have to be based in the EU for the GDPR to apply to it. For example, an organization based in the United States (a non-EU country) that has a branch located in Germany (an EU country) will be required to comply with the GDPR when collecting personal information about, or monitoring the activities of, its employees at the German branch."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a data analysis function that can be performed to help detect fraud through examination of payroll accounts?", "options": {"A": "Compare customer credit limits and current or past balances.", "B": "Generate depreciation to asset cost reports.", "C": "Compare approved vendors to the cash disbursement payee list.", "D": "Identify paycheck amounts over a certain limit."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following are examples of data analysis queries that can be performed by data analysis software on payroll accounts to help detect fraud: Summarize payroll activity by specific criteria for review. Identify changes to payroll or employee files. Compare timecard and payroll rates for possible discrepancies. Prepare check amount reports for amounts over a certain limit. Check proper supervisory authorization on payroll disbursements."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Which of the following is a unique challenge of cloud forensics not faced in traditional forensic practices?", "options": {"A": "Lack of data control", "B": "Lack of frameworks and specialist tools", "C": "Lack of information accessibility", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Conducting digital forensic investigations in the cloud environment (i.e., cloud forensics) presents challenges not faced in traditional forensic practices. Some of the important challenges of acquiring evidence from the cloud are: Lack of frameworks and specialist tools Lack of information accessibility Lack of data control Jurisdiction of storage Electronic discovery Preserving chain of custody Resource sharing Lack of knowledge"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Fraud examination is best described as which of the following?", "options": {"A": "A method for proving the culpability of a suspect", "B": "A methodology for resolving fraud allegations from inception to disposition", "C": "A method for finding evidence of guilt", "D": "The science of detecting fraud"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The term fraud examination refers to a process of resolving allegations of fraud from inception to disposition, and it is the primary function of the anti-fraud professional. The fraud examination process encompasses a variety of tasks that might include: Obtaining evidence Reporting Testifying to findings Assisting in fraud detection and prevention"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is an indirect method of proving illicit income circumstantially by showing that a person’s assets or expenditures for a given period exceed that which can be accounted for from known or admitted legitimate sources of income?", "options": {"A": "Net-worth method of analysis", "B": "Fundamental analysis", "C": "Regression analysis", "D": "Bank deposit method of analysis"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The net-worth method (or comparative net-worth analysis) is used to prove illicit income circumstantially by showing that a person’s assets or expenditures for a given period exceed that which can be accounted for from known or admitted legitimate sources of income. Fraud examiners should use the net-worth method when several of the subject’s assets or liabilities have changed during the period under examination and when the target’s financial records are not available."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following is the facilitator of communication that refers to an individual’s need for the esteem of others?", "options": {"A": "Catharsis", "B": "Altruism", "C": "Recognition", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "All human beings need the recognition of others. Social interaction often depends on an exchange of social goods. People will \"perform\" in exchange for recognition and other social rewards. The need for recognition can be fulfilled by attention from people outside the individual's social circle. The skillful and insightful interviewer takes advantage of every opportunity to give the respondent sincere recognition."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Asset hiders generally prefer the financial vehicles they use to conceal assets to be traceable, inaccessible, illiquid, and exclusive.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Generally, asset hiders look to conceal their assets with financial vehicles that have certain characteristics. For one thing, asset hiders want products that are difficult to trace or untraceable. With such instruments, asset hiders can break or obscure links between the initial receipt of the assets and their final disposition. For another thing, asset hiders want products that are secure and accessible. Asset hiders also want products that are liquid."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Suppose you need to prove a suspect’s illicit income circumstantially. Which of the following methods of tracing assets would yield the best result when the suspect is using his illicit funds to accumulate wealth and acquire assets, thus causing his net worth to increase?", "options": {"A": "The asset method", "B": "The expenditures method", "C": "The income correlation method", "D": "The bank deposits method"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The asset method, the expenditures method, and the bank deposits method can all be used to establish a subject’s sources of income using circumstantial proof. The asset method allows the fraud examiner to prove income circumstantially by showing that the subject’s assets for a given period exceed those that can be accounted for from known or admitted sources of income. Fraud examiners should use the asset method when it is suspected that the subject has accumulated wealth and acquired assets with illicit proceeds, which causes the subject’s net worth—the difference between a person’s assets and liabilities at a particular point in time—to increase. The expenditures method (also known as the sources and application of funds method) compares the suspect’s known expenditures and known sources of funds during a given period of time. That is, this analysis seeks to quantify the cost of the subject’s lifestyle and determine whether the subject’s reported income is sufficient to support his lifestyle. The expenditures method is best used when the subject spends illicit income on consumables (e.g., travel and entertainment) that would not cause an increase in net worth. The bank deposits method of tracing illicit funds is recommended as a primary method of proof when most of the subject’s income is deposited and the subject’s books and records are unavailable, withheld, incomplete, or maintained on a cash basis. The income correlation method is not a method of tracing illicit funds."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "The General Data Privacy Regulation (GDPR) only concerns the personal data of European Union (EU) residents.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which took effect on May 25, 2018, is the primary regulation governing the collection and processing of the personal data of European Union (EU) residents. Although the GDPR only concerns the personal data of EU residents, it applies to any organization worldwide that collects or processes this information, regardless of where the organization is based. In other words, an organization does not have to be based in the EU for the GDPR to apply to it."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "During the analysis phase in digital forensic investigations, the fraud examiner should look for both inculpatory and exculpatory evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When analyzing data for evidence, the fraud examiner should look for inculpatory evidence (i.e., evidence that serves to incriminate the subject of the investigation) and exculpatory evidence (i.e., evidence that serves to disprove the subject’s involvement in the misconduct)."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "During an admission-seeking interview, Cynthia has just accused a suspect of committing a crime. The suspect begins to deny the accusation. The best practice would be for Cynthia to interrupt the suspect’s denial at this point.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Once the accused utters a denial in an admission-seeking interview, it becomes extremely difficult for him to change his response because doing so would be an admission that he lied. Therefore, the interviewer must prevent an outright denial, thereby making it easier for the subject to confess at a later time. An innocent person is unlikely to allow the interviewer to prevail in stopping the denial. Cynthia should not allow the suspect to continue with his denial of the accusations. She can use several techniques to stop or interrupt the denial, including delays, repeated interruptions, and reasoning."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Which of the following is a recommended tactic for interrupting an accused’s denials during an admission-seeking interview?", "options": {"A": "Reasoning", "B": "Repeated interruptions", "C": "Delays", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Once the accused utters a denial in an admission-seeking interview, it becomes extremely difficult for him to change his response because doing so would be an admission that he lied. Therefore, the interviewer must prevent an outright denial, thereby making it easier for the subject to confess at a later time. An innocent person is unlikely to allow the interviewer to prevail in stopping the denial. Fraud examiners can use several techniques to stop or interrupt denials, including delays, repeated interruptions, and reasoning."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "___________ refers to an instance when law enforcement officers or government agents induce a person to commit a crime that he is not previously disposed to commit.", "options": {"A": "False imprisonment", "B": "Collusion", "C": "Entrapment", "D": "Covert operation"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Many jurisdictions recognize the legal defense of entrapment. Entrapment occurs when law enforcement officers or government agents induce a person to commit a crime that he is not previously disposed to commit. Entrapment also poses a legal problem in covert operations, particularly in undercover operations, because the defendant might not be found liable if it appears that he was improperly induced to commit the crime. Therefore, it is imperative that adequate predication exists before the operation is commenced. The law enforcement officer or government agent must act based on more than mere suspicion. For example, if the officer received a reliable tip that a suspect committed fraud, then that could serve as adequate predication. Covert operations must not be used for aimless searches for information performed without notions of what might be uncovered."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In most interviews, more than half of the respondent's communications with the interviewer are likely to be nonverbal.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The interviewer must be skilled in interpreting the respondent’s reactions to questions. Social scientists say that more than half of the communication between individuals is unspoken. The interviewer must, therefore, observe systematically, though in a nondescript manner, the various responses the respondent gives throughout the conversation. To observe the respondent’s reactions, the fraud examiner should move from comfortable to sensitive questions. That is, the interview process should begin by posing comfortable questions while establishing rapport. Asking comfortable questions will help the interviewer find some common ground on which to connect with the respondent."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Which of the following computer event logs records events executed on an operating system, such as starting up and shutting down, configuration updates, and system crashes?", "options": {"A": "Application log", "B": "Security log", "C": "System log", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Every operating system generates event logs, or files that record events or transactions on a computer. In fact, a log entry is created for each event or transaction that takes place on any computer, and consequently, there are numerous types of event logs. Some common types of logs include system logs, application logs, and security logs. System logs record events executed on an operating system, including miscellaneous events and those generated during system startup, like hardware and controller failures. Common types of system events include starting up and shutting down, configuration updates, and system crashes. Application logs record the events regarding access to application data. Such events would include data files being opened or closed; specific actions such as reading, editing, deleting, or printing of application files; or the modification of records in an application file. Security logs track security-related events like logon and logoff times and changes to access rights."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE regarding note-taking during an admission seeking interview?", "options": {"A": "Conspicuous note-taking can reveal what the interviewer finds significant", "B": "Extensive note-taking can be distracting to the suspect", "C": "In some admission-seeking interviews, taking notes should be avoided if possible", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When conducting an admission-seeking interview, note-taking should be kept to a minimum. In some cases, taking notes should be avoided. Because the admission-seeking interview’s ultimate goal is to obtain a signed statement of guilt, it is not necessary to take extensive notes. Such notes can distract the suspect and reveal what points the fraud examiner believes to be important; thus, if the fraud examiner determines that note-taking is necessary, he should do so in a way that does not reveal the information’s significance."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Which of the following terms is defined as the totality of circumstances that would lead a reasonable, professionally trained, and prudent individual to believe a fraud has occurred, is occurring, or will occur?", "options": {"A": "Declaration", "B": "Suspicion", "C": "Fraud theory", "D": "Predication"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fraud examinations must adhere to the law; therefore, fraud examiners should not conduct or continue fraud examinations without proper predication. Predication is the totality of circumstances that would lead a reasonable, professionally trained, and prudent individual to believe that a fraud has occurred, is occurring, or will occur. In other words, predication is the basis upon which a fraud examination, and each step taken during the examination, is commenced. A fraud examiner acts on predication when there is a sufficient basis and legitimate reason to take each step in an examination. Accordingly, fraud examiners should begin a fraud examination only when there are circumstances that suggest fraud has occurred, is occurring, or will occur, and they should not investigate beyond the available predication. If fraud examiners cannot articulate a factual basis or good reason for an investigative step, they should not do it. Therefore, fraud examiners should reevaluate the predication as the fraud examination proceeds. That is, as a fraud examination progresses and new information emerges, fraud examiners should continually reevaluate whether there is adequate predication to take each additional step in the examination. If fraud examiners act without predication, they might expose themselves and their clients or employers to liability."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "In general, which of the following types of information is commonly available through a municipal or regional building inspector's office?", "options": {"A": "Blueprints and plans submitted with applications", "B": "Building inspectors' reports", "C": "Building permits", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following information is generally available through a municipal or regional building inspector’s office: Building permits showing the names of the applicants, the address of construction, the estimated costs, and the name of the builder or contractor Blueprints and plans showing construction details that are often submitted with applications for building permits Building inspectors’ reports containing information regarding compliance with construction specifications"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following is the most appropriate type of question for fraud examiners to ask during interviews to confirm facts that are already known?", "options": {"A": "Narrative", "B": "Leading", "C": "Open", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Leading questions are questions that are framed in a way that evokes a specific reply from the respondent; they are questions that contain a suggested answer. Most commonly, leading questions are used to confirm facts already known. This type of question gives the subject much less room to maneuver than an open or closed question because these questions direct the subject to answer in a particular way. Leading questions imply that the interviewer already knows the answer, asking the subject to confirm what is already known. They can be particularly effective in interview situations. Examples of leading questions include: \"So there have been no changes in the operation since last year?\"; \"Are you still employed by the Westbrook Furnishings Corporation?\"; \"You got promoted, right?\"; \"Don't you get your income from various sources?\""}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Even if incriminating files have been deleted from a target computer, it might be possible to recover those files.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are, in fact, a variety of ways of recovering deleted or hidden data from a target computer, and digital forensic experts are specially trained for such tasks. Deleted files are recoverable until they are overwritten because data are not erased from a computer’s hard drive until the operating system overwrites all or some of the files."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Which of the following is a method that investigators can use to detect steganography?", "options": {"A": "Looking for visual anomalies in jpeg, bmp, gif, and other image files", "B": "Analyzing files on a computer system for structural oddities that suggest manipulation", "C": "Determining whether the statistical properties of files deviate from the expected norm", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Steganography is the process of hiding one piece of information within an apparently innocent file. For example, a user can use the least significant bits of a bitmap image to hide a message. By hiding the message in the least significant bits of an image, there is almost no perceivable change in the bitmap image itself. And without directly comparing the altered image to the original, it is practically impossible to tell that the image was altered. Some common methods of detecting the use of steganography are: Visual detection by looking for visual anomalies in jpeg, bmp, gif, and other image files Audible detection by looking for audible anomalies in wav, mp3, mpeg, and other media files Statistical detection by determining whether the statistical properties of files deviate from the expected norm Structural detection by looking for structural oddities that suggest manipulation (e.g., size differences, date differences, time differences, or content modification)"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "A fraud examiner is planning a data analysis engagement. Which of the following should the fraud examiner understand prior to determining which tests to run on the data?", "options": {"A": "What data are available for analysis", "B": "Areas of data at risk for being overlooked", "C": "The structure of the data", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Although the purpose of data analysis involves running targeted tests on data to identify anomalies, the ability of such tests to help detect fraud depends greatly on what the fraud examiner does before and after actually performing the data analysis techniques. Without sufficient time and attention devoted to planning early on, the fraud examiner risks analyzing the data inefficiently, lacking focus or direction for the engagement, running into avoidable technical difficulties, and possibly overlooking key areas for exploration. As a first step in the planning process—long before determining which tests to run—the fraud examiner must know what data are available to be analyzed and how those data are structured. Understanding the structure of the existing data will not only help ensure that the fraud examiner builds workable tests to be run on the data but might also help identify additional areas for exploration that might otherwise have been overlooked."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following will affect the verbal and nonverbal behaviors that provide clues about whether a person is lying?", "options": {"A": "Mental illness", "B": "Cultural differences", "C": "Drugs and alcohol", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Behavioral clues are harder to read when the respondent is mentally unstable or is under the influence of alcohol or drugs. That is, people who are mentally unstable or are under the influence of drugs will be unsuitable to interview, and the behavioral clues of such individuals are unreliable. Additionally, racial, ethnic, and economic factors should be carefully considered when observing a respondent’s behavior. Some cultures, for example, discourage looking directly at someone. Other cultures use certain body language that might be misinterpreted."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "In admission-seeking interviews, an innocent person often reacts differently to the initial accusation than a culpable person. Which of the following reactions to the initial accusation is common to an innocent person?", "options": {"A": "Strong denials", "B": "Weak denials", "C": "Silence", "D": "Mumbled denials"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When accused of wrongdoing, the typical guilty person reacts with silence. If the accused does deny culpability, those denials are usually weak. In some cases, the accused almost mumbles the denial. It is common for culpable individuals to avoid outright denials. Rather, they will give reasons why they could not have committed the act in question. Conversely, innocent people sometimes react with genuine shock at being accused. It is not at all unusual for an innocent person, wrongfully accused, to react with anger. In contrast to the guilty person, the typical innocent person will strongly deny committing the act or acts in question."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following are questions that contain a suggested answer?", "options": {"A": "Leading", "B": "Compound", "C": "Complex", "D": "Closed"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Leading questions are questions that are framed in a way that evokes a specific reply from the respondent; they are questions that contain a suggested answer. Most commonly, leading questions are used to confirm facts already known. This type of question gives the subject much less room to maneuver than an open or closed question because these questions direct the subject to answer in a particular way. Leading questions imply that the interviewer already knows the answer, asking the subject to confirm what is already known. They can be particularly effective in interview situations. Examples of leading questions include: \"So there have been no changes in the operation since last year?\"; \"Are you still employed by the Westbrook Furnishings Corporation?\"; \"You got promoted, right?\"; \"Don't you get your income from various sources?\""}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following is a verbal clue of deception when displayed by a respondent being interviewed?", "options": {"A": "Oaths", "B": "Comments regarding the interview", "C": "Change in voice pitch", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Verbal clues refer to how an individual conveys information vocally, including tone, pitch, volume, and rate of speech; verbal clues are not only about word choice. Verbal clues are those relating to wordings, expressions, and responses to specific questions. Some examples of verbal clues include: Changes in speech patterns (e.g., changes in voice pitch) Comments regarding the interview Oaths"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "A(n) _____________ is a type of visual aid, in the form of a grid, that shows the relationship (or points of contacts) between a number of entities.", "options": {"A": "Organization chart", "B": "Matrix", "C": "Decision chart", "D": "Time-flow diagram"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Reporting the results of fraud examinations is often facilitated through the use of visual aids. A matrix is a type of visual aid, in the form of a grid, that shows the relationship (or points of contacts) between a number of entities."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Which of the following is an important consideration when preparing a room for an admission-seeking interview?", "options": {"A": "Whether the room affords sufficient privacy", "B": "Whether there are any windows or wall hangings", "C": "Whether the door is locked", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When preparing a room for an admission-seeking interview, it is important that the interviewer consider the privacy afforded by the room. The location should establish a sense of privacy. The door should be closed but not locked, there should be no physical barriers preventing the target from leaving, and the suspect should be made aware that he is free to leave. Distractions should be kept to a minimum. Ideally, there should be no photographs, windows, or other objects in the room. Chairs should be placed about four to six feet apart, and the accused should not be permitted to sit behind any physical barriers, such as chairs, tables, or desks. This is to prevent a physical barrier from becoming a psychological barrier that might inhibit responses from the accused."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "To properly prepare an organization for a formal fraud investigation, all employees should be notified of the investigation’s existence and purpose.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Generally, it is not good practice to alert all of an organization’s employees that an investigation will be taking place, nor should the investigation’s purpose be explained to all employees. However, it might be necessary to take some steps to prepare the subject organization for the formal investigation before it officially commences (and especially before starting the evidence-collection process). Preparing an organization for an investigation involves such things as preparing the managers of the employees who will be involved in the investigation, notifying key decision makers when the investigation is about to begin, and notifying the organization’s in-house or outside counsel when the investigation is about to commence. Note that while it might be necessary to prepare the managers of the employees who will be involved in the investigation, those responsible should not do so by explaining the investigation's purpose, why the investigation is happening, when it is happening, or who is involved."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "The expenditures method (also known as the sources and application of funds method) for proving illicit income involves identifying all assets held by the subject that were acquired earlier, identifying the amount of the subject’s current liabilities, and taking the difference between the two values.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The expenditures method (also known as the sources and application of funds method) compares the suspect’s known expenditures and known sources of funds during a given period of time. That is, this analysis seeks to quantify the cost of the subject’s lifestyle and determine whether the subject’s reported income is sufficient to support his lifestyle. The expenditures method is best used when the subject spends illicit income on consumables (e.g., travel and entertainment) that would not cause an increase in net worth. Identifying assets previously acquired, identifying current liabilities, and taking the difference between the two is the process involved in the asset method, not the expenditures method."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "In most jurisdictions, which of the following statements about bankruptcy court records is CORRECT?", "options": {"A": "Bankruptcy documents are usually located in the jurisdiction where the most debt was incurred", "B": "Only the party filing for bankruptcy and the creditors may access bankruptcy records", "C": "A bankruptcy file typically contains the bankruptcy petition or filing document", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Many jurisdictions provide bankruptcy records to the authorized parties or the general public. Bankruptcy proceedings generally occur in the jurisdiction in which the debtor resides. It is common for countries to have separate bankruptcy courts that handle most or all of such cases. The information available in bankruptcy records varies, but common items include: The bankruptcy petition or other type of filing document, which might include the subject’s government identification number; street address and primary place of business; location of principal assets of business; type of business; name of legal representative; estimated amount of assets; estimated number of creditors, liabilities, and employees; financial data; and a list of corporate shareholders Claim documents by creditors listing the amounts that the debtor allegedly owes A final accounting that shows which claims were paid A descriptive list of the debtor’s property at the time of filing (real estate, personal property, investments, accounts receivables, etc.) Filings that describe the debtor’s income and expenditures The bankruptcy plan (some jurisdictions allow bankrupt parties to reorganize businesses or participate in a debt reduction plan, as opposed to liquidating all assets) Details from a fraud examination if the bankrupt party was suspected of bankruptcy fraud"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In interview situations, the process of observing behavior before asking critical questions is called:", "options": {"A": "Deception analysis", "B": "Calibrating", "C": "Kinetic analysis", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Calibrating (or norming) is the process of observing behavior before critical questions are asked, as opposed to doing so during questioning. Calibrating should be a routine part of all interviews. People with truthful attitudes will answer questions one way; those with untruthful attitudes will generally answer them differently."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following is one of the five general types of questions that an interviewer can ask when conducting an interview?", "options": {"A": "Introductory", "B": "Informational", "C": "Admission-seeking", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When conducting an interview, there are five general types of questions an interviewer can ask: introductory, informational, assessment, closing, and admission-seeking."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "The use of trickery and deceit to obtain a confession will always render the confession inadmissible in a court of law.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The use of deception to gain information can sometimes be employed legally, but fraud examiners should check with counsel regarding the applicable laws and regulations before engaging in such activity. In cases where deception is legal, the theory is that information can be obtained by nearly any means, with the exception of force or threats. The interviewer, however, may not employ any deception likely to cause the innocent person to confess. The use of deception is generally not justified regarding promises of leniency or confidentiality, nor is it usually justified to obtain a monetary or business advantage."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Even when a victim refers a fraud case for criminal prosecution, the government will usually not disclose the contents of nonpublic records with the victim during the investigation.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A wronged organization may make a criminal referral so that records can be subpoenaed by the government or obtained by a legal order (e.g., a search warrant). Records obtained while executing a search warrant or similar legal order usually are available only to the government during the underlying investigation, and perhaps thereafter if they are not disclosed at trial. In addition, law enforcement agencies may also subpoena records, but, depending on the jurisdiction, might not disclose the contents of such records with the victim or third parties."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "Covert operations are designed to obtain legal and admissible evidence through the use of agents whose true intentions are not communicated to the target.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A covert operation is an investigation technique designed to obtain evidence by use of agents whose true intentions are not communicated to the target."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "While examining a document, a fraud examiner notices some very faint indented writings that might aid the examination if revealed. Which of the following would be the fraud examiner’s BEST course of action in analyzing these indented writings?", "options": {"A": "Performing the pencil-scratching method", "B": "Employing an expert to use an electrostatic detection apparatus", "C": "Performing the pencil-shading method", "D": "Applying a few drops of liquid and observing the liquid’s flow in the indentations"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Indented writing is the impression a writing instrument leaves on sheets of paper below the sheet that contains the original writing. Fraud examiners should be alert for the presence of incriminating indented writings or the absence of logical indentations, both of which can be valuable in proving fraud. Fraud examiners should never attempt to develop indented writings by shading or scratching on the surface of a sheet of paper with a pencil. Although this method will reveal deep indentations, it will not reveal faint indentations and will prevent experts from analyzing them. Moreover, shading or scratching with a pencil might prevent other types of technical examinations. Likewise, fraud examiners should not apply any sort of liquid to an original document with indented writings, as doing so can damage the document’s ability to be analyzed. Some indented writings can be seen by employing an oblique-lighting method. In this method, the fraud examiner takes the document into an area with subdued overhead lighting, places the document on a flat surface, and shines a bright beam of light—from a small-beam flashlight or small high-intensity lamp—across the document at a low oblique angle or parallel to the surface. Because shadows in the indentations will only show at right angles to the beam of light, it is necessary to move the light around and note the changing shadows as they form the text of the indentations. Forensic document experts can perform advanced analysis to reveal messages in indented writings. They can use special lighting, photographic techniques, and sensitive instruments, such as the electrostatic detection apparatus (ESDA), to detect and permanently record extremely faint indented writings that cannot be seen by the oblique-lighting method."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following is a good practice when searching the Internet for information?", "options": {"A": "Use more than one search engine", "B": "Use filters to focus searches", "C": "Use specific nouns instead of pronouns", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following is a list of tips and guidelines for searching the Internet for information: Use more than one search engine. Everyone has their favorite search engine, but relying on one search engine is not sufficient because every search engine collects and catalogs information differently. Be clear about what is being looked for. Define the search topic as clearly and succinctly as possible. Use unique, specific keywords. Be specific when entering search terms. Use nouns for keywords. Use format terms (e.g., transcript, document, report, statistics, pdf, policy, dictionary) in addition to subject words. Exclude articles (e.g., a, an, the) and pronouns (e.g., he, she, it, they) from search terms, unless they are part of a key phrase. Use correct spelling and include alternative spellings (e.g., \"colour OR color\"). Use filters to focus searches. Filters tell search engines to screen out specified types of pages or files. Check all the tips and features of any search engine to be used and make use of them. Increase the number of results displayed per page. Customize searches using advanced search operators, such as the minus (-) operator and quotation marks, to narrow the search results. Search for phrases. Search for a sequence of words in a specific order, using quotation marks around the phrase. Search for base words (drop suffixes) to avoid excluding relevant pages. Use metasearch engines if early searches are unsuccessful. Set a time limit for searching, and when the set amount of time has elapsed, stop and try another method. Use a browser's find feature to find a word or phrase on a Web page and help navigate search results."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Fraud examiners should take which of the following steps when securing a computer to help ensure that the machine can be fully analyzed?", "options": {"A": "Examine and document the machine's surroundings", "B": "Inspect the machine for traps", "C": "Implement a system to manage the evidence", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To ensure that a machine can be fully analyzed, the fraud examiner should adhere to the following practices: 1. Examine and document the machine’s surroundings. 2. Inspect for traps. 3. If the computer is off, leave it off. 4. Consider collecting volatile data “live.” 5. Secure the evidence. 6. Image the system hard drives. 7. Document the collection process. 8. Implement a system to manage the evidence."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Which of the following is the most appropriate example of an alternative question?", "options": {"A": "“Did you deliberately plan this, or did it just happen?”", "B": "“How else might this situation be explained?”", "C": "“Did you, or did you not, commit this crime?”", "D": "“Will you repay the money now or later?”"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The alternative question forces the accused to make one of two choices, both of which imply guilt. One alternative provides the accused with a morally acceptable reason for the misdeed; the other portrays the accused negatively. Regardless of which answer the accused chooses, he is acknowledging guilt."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "A fraud examiner can request a business’s bank records even if the business is not legally obligated to comply.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The simplest way to obtain relevant documents, such as bank records, is to request them. This usually works for fraud examiners representing large organizations that are important customers to the party with the information. Vendors and other customers of the company conducting the investigation might cooperate voluntarily if they have nothing to hide (or think that incriminating evidence cannot be found) and are anxious to maintain good relations with the company. A subject can consent to produce the records or execute a written consent for the fraud examiner to obtain such records from banks, credit agencies, or the taxing authority. If the business does not voluntarily provide the records, fraud examiners may pursue them through subpoenas and other legal processes."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Aston, a forensic investigator for Cadence Irrigation, is conducting an internal investigation into the alleged theft of trade secrets from Cadence. Kirby, a Cadence employee, is the prime suspect. Aston decides to seize Kirby’s work computer for forensic examination. If, at the time of seizure, Kirby’s computer is turned off, Aston should turn it on before seizing it.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A computer system that is switched off should not be turned on during the seizure process. Turning a system on might damage and taint any evidence that it contains."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Which of the following is NOT correct with regard to fraud response plans?", "options": {"A": "A fraud response plan enables management to respond to suspected incidents of fraud in a consistent manner.", "B": "A fraud response plan should be complex and extremely detailed to ensure its effectiveness.", "C": "A fraud response plan can send a message that management takes fraud seriously.", "D": "A fraud response plan should be flexible and allow appropriate responses based on the particular event."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A response plan allows management to respond to suspected and detected incidents of fraud in a consistent and comprehensive manner. Having a response plan in place sends a message that management takes fraud seriously. Also, a response plan should not be unduly complicated; for a response plan to work in high-pressure and time-sensitive situations, it must be simple to understand and administer. While the appropriate response will vary based on the event, management should include a range of scenarios in the response plan, taking into consideration previous frauds within the organization and fraud risks specific to the industry or business sector in which it operates. Organizations without a fraud response plan might not be able to respond to issues properly, and will likely expend more resources and suffer greater harm than those that have such a plan in place. Conversely, having a response plan puts an organization in the best position to respond promptly and effectively."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Understanding the structure and availability of existing data during a data analysis engagement helps to ensure that the fraud examiner can build workable tests to run on it.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Although the purpose of data analysis involves running targeted tests on data to identify anomalies, the ability of such tests to help detect fraud depends greatly on what the fraud examiner does before and after actually performing the data analysis techniques. Without sufficient time and attention devoted to planning early on, the fraud examiner risks analyzing the data inefficiently, lacking focus or direction for the engagement, running into avoidable technical difficulties, and possibly overlooking key areas for exploration. As a first step in the planning process—long before determining which tests to run—the fraud examiner must know what data are available to be analyzed and how those data are structured. Understanding the structure of the existing data will not only help ensure that the fraud examiner builds workable tests to be run on the data but might also help identify additional areas for exploration that might otherwise have been overlooked."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Green believes that Blue, a fraud suspect, has purchased hidden personal property through suspicious financing. Which of the following sources, if available, would most likely contain information that Green could use to locate Blue’s possible hidden assets?", "options": {"A": "Commercial filings", "B": "Health department records", "C": "Surveyor office records", "D": "Registrar of voters"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Commercial filings are records that can help fraud examiners identify personal property that an individual or business has financed. These filings and supporting documents can help fraud examiners uncover hidden ownership or relationships between parties by viewing the names of all listed debtors and their addresses. The fraud examiner might find information linking individuals to the companies they own or discover information about a company’s subsidiaries, branch offices, or parent company. Additionally, discovering financed assets can reveal information about a person or organization’s financial condition."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following is the most accurate statement about trying to locate a subject using online records?", "options": {"A": "Online records are generally not useful in locating subjects whose address is unknown.", "B": "If an individual has moved, obtaining a past address is usually of no help.", "C": "Obtaining a past address of the subject should be the first step in trying to locate a subject using online records.", "D": "Efforts to locate a subject using online records should begin with a search of the suspect’s vehicle records."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "To locate people using online records, fraud examiners should adhere to three principles. First, when searching for an individual, the fraud examiner should obtain a past address of the subject, and search activities should begin with that information. Second, the fraud examiner should consider the cost effectiveness of the search activity and avoid ordering online searches that yield unnecessary or impractical information. Third, the fraud examiner should know the most powerful and useful types of searches."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a recommended approach to dealing with a hostile or argumentative respondent during an interview?", "options": {"A": "Avoid showing any kind of reaction to the respondent’s hostile behavior.", "B": "Attempt to reason with the respondent.", "C": "Disarm the respondent by agreeing with his points whenever possible.", "D": "Make it difficult for the respondent to say “no” to any points raised."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The interviewer will invariably encounter a few difficult people. There are five common-sense steps to take with such people: Don't react. There are three natural reactions for an interviewer who is verbally assailed by the respondent: to strike back, to give in, or to terminate the interview. None of these tactics is satisfactory because none of these responses lead to a productive interview. Disarm nonreceptive respondents. A common mistake that interviewers make is to try to reason with an unreceptive person. To disarm the person, listen, acknowledge the point, and agree wherever possible. In some situations, changing tactics to reduce hostility might be the only viable option. Make it easy to say “yes” by agreeing with one of the respondent’s statements and go from there. Make it hard for the respondent to say “no.”"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "For the purpose of a Benford's Law analysis, an employee identification number would be considered a natural number.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Benford’s Law distinguishes between natural and non-natural numbers, and it is important to understand the difference between the two types because Benford’s Law cannot be applied to data sets with non-natural numbers. Natural numbers are those numbers that are not ordered in a particular numbering scheme and are not human-generated or generated from a random number system. For example, most vendor invoice totals or listings of payment amounts will be populated by currency values that are natural numbers. Conversely, non-natural numbers (e.g., employee identification numbers and telephone numbers) are designed systematically to convey information that restricts the natural nature of the number. Any number that is arbitrarily determined, such as the price of inventory held for sale, is considered a non-natural number."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Carlos is conducting a background investigation of a corporation and its management. Which of the following can Carlos obtain without a legal order or subpoena?", "options": {"A": "The company's banking records", "B": "The history of medical expenses of the company's employees", "C": "The tax records of the company's owner", "D": "The company’s business filings"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Nonpublic records—financial or otherwise—might be needed to prove fraud or to provide leads in a fraud examination. Nonpublic records include information about a person or business considered to be private and confidential. Nonpublic records are not available to everyone, and because fraud examiners do not have an absolute right to see these personal records, obtaining access might be difficult or impossible. Individuals generally will not willingly give their private records to a fraud examiner, and often, the authority of institutions to disclose nonpublic records is restricted by law. Some of the most valuable types of personal records include: Banking records Tax records Credit records of individuals Phone records Credit card account records Personal health care records Basic business organization—whether for businesses with a single owner or large corporations—is generally governed under the laws of the country in which the entity is organized. Most jurisdictions require business entities to file various types of records that contain information that might be useful in a fraud examination, and generally, such filings are available to the public."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is the best definition of the indirect method of tracing financial transactions?", "options": {"A": "Using circumstantial evidence to analyze the relationship between a suspect’s receipt and subsequent disposition of funds or assets", "B": "Using bank records and financial statements to identify and analyze information about the target’s personal characteristics to identify sources of hidden wealth or assets", "C": "Using the subject’s books and records to analyze the relationship between the subject’s receipt and subsequent disposition of funds or assets", "D": "Using financial analysis to discover all significant expenses the target incurred during the relevant period to develop the financial profile"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Generally, fraud examiners can trace illicit transactions using a direct method or an indirect method. An indirect method employs circumstantial evidence to analyze the relationship between a suspect’s receipt and subsequent disposition of funds or assets. In contrast, a direct method uses the subject’s books and records (or financial transaction records belonging to third parties) to analyze the relationship between a suspect’s receipt and subsequent disposition of funds or assets."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "To stimulate conversation during the information phase of the interview, the interviewer should ask:", "options": {"A": "Closed questions designed to keep the witness focused on the intended topic", "B": "Specific questions designed to obtain all of the information known by the witness", "C": "Open questions that call for a monologue response", "D": "Leading questions that aim for a particular response"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "To stimulate conversation during the information phase of the interview, the interviewer should endeavor to primarily ask open questions. Open questions are those worded in a way that makes it difficult for the respondent to answer “yes” or “no.” Also, the answer to an open question is not dependent on the question. The typical open question calls for a monologue response, and it can be answered in several different ways."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Mario wants to locate Jim, a fraud suspect. Mario calls Jim’s parents posing as an old friend and asks for Jim’s address, which they give him. This act would be considered illegal pretexting in all jurisdictions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Broadly defined, pretexting is the act of impersonating someone else or making false or misleading statements to obtain, sell, or buy information about a person or organization. Under the broad definition, pretexting for nonfraudulent purposes is not always illegal, but it should be used with caution. For example, if a fraud examiner is trying to find a witness or a suspect, he might call the person’s relative and pretend to be an old friend who is requesting the individual’s phone number. This type of pretexting might be permissible. However, it is more often illegal to use pretexting to obtain certain types of information, such as financial records and phone history records."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "All of the following are signs of deceptive behavior in an interview subject EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "The subject frequently uses subtle hand gestures when talking.", "B": "The subject slouches unnaturally in his chair.", "C": "The subject plays with a pencil during direct questioning.", "D": "The subject appears casual and unconcerned."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The dishonest person will often try to appear casual and unconcerned, will frequently adopt an unnatural slouching posture, and might manipulate objects, such as a pencil. He also might react to questions with nervous or false laughter or feeble attempts at humor. Nonverbal indications of deception include: Full-body motions away from the interviewer Physical responses such as sweating or labored breathing Changes in the use of illustrators Interruptions to the flow of speech Hands over the mouth Manipulation of objects such as a pencil Body positioned in a fleeing position Crossing of the arms Unnatural or casual reaction to evidence"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Link analysis can be used to visually map connections between entities that share an address.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Link analysis software is used by fraud examiners to create visual representations (e.g., charts with lines showing connections) of data from multiple data sources to track the movement of money; demonstrate complex networks; and discover communications, patterns, trends, and relationships. Link analysis is very effective for identifying indirect relationships and relationships with several degrees of separation. For this reason, link analysis is particularly useful when conducting a money laundering investigation, since it can track the placement, layering, and integration of money as it moves around unexpected sources. It could also be used to detect a fictitious vendor (shell company) scheme. For instance, the investigator could map visual connections between a variety of entities that share an address and bank account number to reveal a fictitious vendor created to embezzle funds from a company."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "To protect the security of a covert investigation, reports or memoranda of the covert operation should not be committed to paper.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Before conducting a covert operation, it is essential that the basis for the operation be committed to writing, preferably in a memorandum. The memorandum should clearly state: The information upon which the covert operation will be based The information that is expected to be gained from the operation The identities of suspects, if known Operatives under the fraud examiner's care, custody, or control (confidential sources’ identities should not be disclosed, but such sources should be referred to with a symbol)"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Smith, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is conducting an admission-seeking interview of Green, a fraud suspect. To encourage Green to confess, Smith should express disgust and moral condemnation for Green’s actions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "People rarely confess voluntarily unless they perceive that the benefits of confession outweigh the penalties. A good interviewer, through the application of sophisticated techniques, is able to convince the respondent that the confession is in his best interest. In doing so, the interviewer must not express disgust, outrage, or moral condemnation about the confessor’s actions, as this goes against the basic logic of obtaining confessions, which can be summed up as maximize sympathy and minimize the perception of moral wrongdoing."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "During the introductory portion of an interview, the interviewer must state the interview's purpose in a general way. This is known as:", "options": {"A": "Providing the introduction", "B": "Establishing rapport", "C": "Establishing the interview theme", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The interviewer must state the interview's purpose in some way prior to the commencement of serious questioning. Otherwise, the respondent might be confused, threatened, or overly cautious. Stating the purpose of the interview is known as establishing the interview theme."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Mario, a fraud investigator, has arrived unannounced at Johnson’s office to conduct an interview. When Mario requests that Johnson take some time to talk about some issues he’s looking into, Johnson replies that he’s too busy. How should Mario handle this situation?", "options": {"A": "Stress that the interview will not be difficult", "B": "Emphasize that the interview will be short", "C": "Point out that he is already there", "D": "Any of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When the interviewer contacts the respondent without a previous appointment, there is a possibility that the respondent will be too busy at the moment to cooperate. \"I'm too busy\" is also used as an excuse for the real source of the person's resistance, which might be lethargy, ego threat, or dislike of talking to strangers. These situations can be diffused by the interviewer stressing that: The interview will be short. The interviewer is already there. The project is important. The interview will not be difficult. The interviewer needs help."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "_____________ is a method of using software to extract usable information from unstructured data.", "options": {"A": "The Fog Index", "B": "Textual analytics", "C": "Linguistic analytics", "D": "Benford’s Law"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Textual analytics is a method of using software to extract usable information from unstructured text data. Through the application of linguistic technologies and statistical techniques—including weighted fraud indicators (e.g., fraud keywords) and scoring algorithms—textual analytics software can categorize data to reveal patterns, sentiments, and relationships indicative of fraud. For example, an analysis of email communications might help fraud examiners to gauge the pressures/incentives, opportunities, and rationalizations to commit fraud that exist in an organization."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Able, a fraud examiner, is investigating a suspected embezzlement by one of XYZ Corporation’s employees. As part of the investigation, he is assembling a financial profile of the suspect. Among other things, he wants to see if the suspect has made any significant real estate purchases since the embezzlement scheme began. Information on real estate transactions such as deeds, grants, transfers, and mortgages is usually located:", "options": {"A": "With the jurisdiction’s organizational filing agency", "B": "With the jurisdiction’s commercial filing registrar", "C": "With the jurisdiction’s land registry office", "D": "With the local court clerk or judicial records agency"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Most jurisdictions have a land registry office that maintains various information on real property and its owner(s). Both the level of government where these records are found and the information they contain will vary by jurisdiction, but the following information is often present: Documents pertaining to real estate transactions—including deeds, grants, real estate transfers and mortgages, releases of mortgages, powers of attorney, and leases that have been acknowledged or approved Mortgages on real property Security interests or liens on property Wills admitted to probate Official bonds Notices of mechanic’s liens Transcripts of judgments that are made liens on real estate Notices of attachment on real estate Land cadastre (a registry of land surveys that specifically detail each plot of real estate in an area and may contain information about value, ownership rights, and other details) Papers in connection with bankruptcy Certified copies of decrees and judgments of courts of record Other documents permitted by law to be recorded Historical sale prices Residences and addresses of the buyer and seller Identity of the party financing the property, if applicable Improvements to a property"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE about using computer-created metadata in forensic investigations?", "options": {"A": "Metadata information can help determine who wrote a document", "B": "Metadata information can help determine who received a document", "C": "Metadata information can help determine when a document was created", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Metadata is a type of computer-generated data that can be helpful in a fraud investigation. Metadata is data about data, and these files contain a tremendous amount of information. Metadata information can help determine who wrote a document; who received, opened, copied, edited, moved, or printed the document; and when these events occurred."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Why would a fraud examiner perform duplicate testing on data?", "options": {"A": "To identify transactions with matching values in the same field", "B": "To identify missing items in a sequence or series", "C": "To determine the relationship among different variables in raw data", "D": "To determine whether company policies are met by employee transactions"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Duplicate testing is used to identify transactions with duplicate values in specified fields. This technique can quickly review the file, or several files joined together, to highlight duplicate values of key fields. In many systems, the key fields should contain only unique values (no duplicate records). For example, a fraud examiner would expect fields such as check numbers, invoice numbers, and government identification numbers to contain only unique values within a data set; searching for duplicates within these fields can help the fraud examiner find anomalies that merit further examination."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Finn, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is conducting an admission-seeking interview of Vince, a fraud suspect. Finn's theme for establishing rationalization for Vince's fraud was that Vince was treated unfairly at work. But Vince doesn't seem to accept this theme. What should Finn do?", "options": {"A": "Select another theme", "B": "Terminate the interview", "C": "Continue to repeat the theme", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "If the subject does not confess to the misconduct when faced with direct accusations, the interviewer should try to convince the respondent that confessing is the most advantageous option available. To do this, the interviewer must offer a morally acceptable reason that allows the accused to confess to a misdeed without feeling ashamed. If the accused does not relate to one theme, the interviewer should move on to another until one seems to fit. Thereafter, the interviewer should fully develop the theme. Note that the theme development explains away the moral, but not the legal, consequences of the misdeed. The interviewer should not make any statements that might lead the accused to believe that cooperation will eliminate legal liability."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Baker, a Certified Fraud Examiner, has obtained an oral confession from Gamma, a fraud suspect. Gamma confessed to committing fraud, and he admitted to smuggling drugs in an unrelated case. How should Baker handle these admissions in Gamma's written confession?", "options": {"A": "Baker should take separate statements for each of the unrelated crimes", "B": "Baker should omit the information concerning the drug smuggling", "C": "Baker should include both crimes in the same statement", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When taking a signed statement from a suspect, there should not be more than one written statement for each offense. If facts are inadvertently omitted, the fraud examiner can add them later to the original statement as an addendum. For legal purposes, prepare separate statements for unrelated offenses. This rule applies because the target may be tried more than once—once for each offense."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following pieces of information is NOT usually contained on the signature card of a personal bank account?", "options": {"A": "The address of the person opening the account", "B": "The identification number of the person opening the account", "C": "The thumbprint of the person opening the account", "D": "The telephone number of the person opening the account"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "To open a personal account, the individual opening the account must provide a signature card, or similar document, evidencing a contract between the customer and bank. The signature card is a source of valuable information. Although its form varies, the card usually contains the person’s name, address, telephone number, identification number, amount of the opening deposit (and possibly the source of the opening deposit), and security data (e.g., mother’s maiden name). The person’s identification information might be significant, especially if the depositor used an alias. Also, a fraud examiner might be able to trace the opening deposit through the bank’s records to disclose a source of income. While a bank signature card evidencing a contract between the customer and bank contains several important pieces of identifying information, it typically does not contain the fingerprints of the account holder."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "In most countries, the entire history of court records is accessible through a single location or website.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "To perform court records searches, fraud examiners need to be familiar with the structure of a jurisdiction’s court system. Most jurisdictions implement a tiered court structure in which minor offenses and causes of action (e.g., small claims) are held in one set of courts and more serious offenses or issues are held in another set. Similarly, a jurisdiction might have courts that are divided based on local/municipal, state/provincial, and central/federal levels of government. Court records are typically maintained by a clerk or administrative office of the court that heard the case. However, there might be an agency that maintains records from multiple court levels. Therefore, to conduct a thorough search of court records, fraud examiners might need to search at multiple court levels. It is rare for there to be a central public database that maintains all court records at every level of a jurisdiction, and there are no parties that maintain a comprehensive database of court records on a global basis (despite what some records merchants might claim)."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "For purposes of evaluating deception, illustrators can be defined as:", "options": {"A": "Expressions made with the face, the meanings of which are clearly understood", "B": "Verbal statements that illustrate a point", "C": "Motions made primarily with the hands to demonstrate a point", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Illustrators are motions made primarily with the hands that demonstrate points when talking. During nonthreatening questions, the respondent’s illustrators might occur at one rate, and during threatening questions, the respondent’s use of illustrators might increase or decrease."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following is the facilitator of communication that refers to an individual’s need to identify with a higher value beyond immediate self-interest?", "options": {"A": "Extrinsic rewards", "B": "Altruism", "C": "Catharsis", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "There seems to be a need for humans to identify with some higher value or cause beyond immediate self-interest. This might take the form of identification with the objectives of some larger group. Altruistic deeds usually increase self-esteem whether or not the deeds have been made public. This distinguishes altruism from publicity. Altruism is of major importance in motivating many respondents. Interviewers who understand the respondent's value system can use strategies and techniques that appeal to altruism."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "“Aren’t you responsible for reviewing and approving your employees’ timesheets?” is an example of which of the following types of questions?", "options": {"A": "Assessment", "B": "Double-negative", "C": "Open", "D": "Leading"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Leading questions are questions that are framed in a way that evokes a specific reply from the respondent; they are questions that contain a suggested answer. Most commonly, leading questions are used to confirm facts already known. This type of question gives the subject much less room to maneuver than an open or closed question because these questions direct the subject to answer in a particular way. Leading questions imply that the interviewer already knows the answer, asking the subject to confirm what is already known. They can be particularly effective in interview situations. Examples of leading questions include: \"So there have been no changes in the operation since last year?\"; \"Are you still employed by the Westbrook Furnishings Corporation?\"; \"You got promoted, right?\"; \"Don't you get your income from various sources?\""}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In interviews, introductory questions are designed to meet which of the following objectives?", "options": {"A": "To establish rapport", "B": "To provide the introduction", "C": "To establish the interview theme", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Introductory questions are designed to meet four objectives: provide the introduction, establish rapport, establish the interview theme, and observe the respondent's reactions."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Lee manages a house painting company. He notices paint expenses have increased substantially from the prior year, which is unexpected because the company had much less business this year and painted fewer houses. Which of the following data analysis functions would be the most useful in helping Lee determine the relationship between paint expense and houses painted?", "options": {"A": "Stratification", "B": "Benford's Law analysis", "C": "Verifying multiples of a number", "D": "Correlation analysis"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Using the correlation analysis function, fraud examiners can determine the relationships among different variables in the raw data. Fraud examiners can learn a lot about data files by learning the relationship between two variables. For example, we should expect a strong correlation between the following independent and dependent variables because a direct relationship exists between the two variables. Hotel costs should increase as the number of days traveled increases. Gallons of paint used should increase as the number of houses painted increases."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In interview situations, a(n)_______________ is an orderly, continuous account of an event or incident given by a respondent with minimal or no prompting.", "options": {"A": "Informational response", "B": "Free narrative", "C": "Unprompted script", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The free narrative is an orderly, continuous account of an event or incident, given with minimal or no prompting. It is used to get a quick synopsis of what is known about a matter. But when seeking to obtain a free narrative, be sure to designate specifically the occurrence that you wish to discuss. Sometimes the respondent must be controlled to prevent unnecessary digression. Otherwise, avoid interrupting the respondent, and do not stop the narrative without good reason. The respondent will sometimes provide valuable clues when talking about things that are only partially related to the matter under inquiry."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Grigori, a fraud suspect, has confessed to Dmitri, a Certified Fraud Examiner, that he has embezzled funds. Dmitri is unsure whether Grigori had an accomplice. Which of the following is the most appropriate question concerning accomplices?", "options": {"A": "\"Did someone else know?\"", "B": "\"Was anyone else involved?\"", "C": "\"Who else knew about this besides you?\"", "D": "\"We have evidence someone else is involved. Who is it?\""}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Although most fraudsters commit their crimes without the aid of an accomplice, the interviewer should determine whether others were involved. To obtain this information, the interviewer should not ask if anyone else assisted the fraudster; instead, he should phrase the question similar to this: \"Who else knew about this besides you?\" By asking who else “knew,” the interviewer is not only asking for the names of possible conspirators, he is also asking about others who might have known what was going on and failed to report it. This question should be worded as “Who else knew?” rather than “Did someone else know?”"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "___________ questions are considered a less threatening form of questioning and are therefore well suited for volatile interviews.", "options": {"A": "Direct", "B": "Hypothetical", "C": "Leading", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Hypothetical questions are generally considered less threatening and are therefore ideally suited for the potentially volatile interview. For example, suppose you are interviewing Mr. Smith regarding Mr. Jones. Rather than asking, \"Did Mr. Jones do it?\" ask \"Is there any reason why Mr. Jones would have done it?\""}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "When preparing a room for an admission-seeking interview, the suspect's chair should be:", "options": {"A": "As comfortable as possible", "B": "Behind a desk or table", "C": "Within full view of the fraud examiner", "D": "Higher than the interviewer’s chair"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "When preparing a room for an admission-seeking interview, chairs should be placed about four to six feet apart, and the accused should not be permitted to sit behind any physical barriers, such as chairs, tables, or desks. This is to prevent a physical barrier from becoming a psychological barrier that might inhibit responses from the accused."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "When seizing a computer for examination, the seizing party should look around the area for passwords because many people leave passwords written down near their computers.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Because many people write down or record their passwords near their computers, fraud examiners should look around for notes that might appear to be passwords. This might aid in discovering passwords needed to access encrypted or password-protected data if the individual who knows the password is uncooperative and will not divulge it. Although there are ways to access encrypted information without an encryption key—decryption, emergency keys, forcing cooperation—having the passwords for protected files will save time and reduce efforts."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "When questioning a witness as part of a fraud examination, the interviewer should usually ask the questions in what order?", "options": {"A": "From closed questions to open questions", "B": "In random order", "C": "From the general details to the specific details", "D": "In reverse order"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "As a general rule, questioning should proceed from the general to the specific; that is, it is best to seek general information before seeking details. A variation to this approach is to “reach backward” with the questions by beginning with known information and working toward unknown areas. An efficient method of doing this is to recount the known information and then frame the next question as a logical continuation of the facts previously related."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Which of the following steps should a fraud examiner take prior to seizing evidence in a digital forensic investigation to ensure its admissibility?", "options": {"A": "Ensure that all forensic equipment is legitimate, reliable, and used correctly", "B": "Consider potential privacy issues related to the item(s) being searched", "C": "Obtain any necessary legal orders", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Before the fraud examiner can seize evidence, he must take certain steps to help ensure that the evidence will be admissible. Such steps include determining whether there are any privacy interests in the item(s) to be searched; making appropriate preparations if the investigation involves the use of a legal order; and ensuring that all equipment used in a forensic capacity is legitimate and reliable (e.g., only use licensed software applications, independently validate all forensic equipment and maintain the validation on file). In addition, the fraud examiner must also ensure that he is properly trained to employ relevant digital forensic tools and that equipment is employed in the manner for which it was designed (e.g., know when to use write-blocking software prior to viewing data, confirm that imaging software was designed for use with the applicable operating system)."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following is a purpose of closing questions in interview situations?", "options": {"A": "To maintain goodwill", "B": "To reconfirm facts", "C": "To obtain additional facts", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Closing questions seek to close the interview positively. In routine interviews, closing questions serve the following purposes: reconfirm facts, gather additional facts, and conclude the interview in a manner required to maintain goodwill."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "What is a letter rogatory?", "options": {"A": "A formal request by the courts of one country seeking judicial assistance from the courts of another country", "B": "A letter whereby a criminal defendant requests that the government release exculpatory information", "C": "A formal request by the government of a country seeking information from a defendant residing in another country", "D": "A letter in which a judge in one country orders the government in another country to release a defendant from jail"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Government officials may be authorized to make a formal government-to-government request for assistance, or letter rogatory, to obtain foreign evidence. Letters rogatory are formal requests that a court in one country makes to seek judicial assistance from a court in another country. Letters rogatory also permit formal communication between the judiciary, a prosecutor, or a law enforcement official of one country and their counterpart in another country. The most common types of assistance sought by letters rogatory are service of process and taking of evidence."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is the main purpose of conducting a net-worth analysis?", "options": {"A": "To show that the subject’s assets or expenditures exceed his reported income", "B": "To prove that the subject purchased an asset with appreciated value", "C": "To prove that the subject’s assets equal his liabilities", "D": "To show that a subject's actions caused a decrease in the victim’s net worth"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The net-worth method (or comparative net-worth analysis) is used to prove illicit income circumstantially by showing that a person’s assets or expenditures for a given period exceed that which can be accounted for from known or admitted legitimate sources of income. The net-worth method is a reliable method for estimating a person’s ill-gotten gains. The method is used extensively by criminal investigators around the world, especially in drug and money laundering cases."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is a common method that fraudsters use to hide their ill-gotten gains?", "options": {"A": "Prepaying a home mortgage", "B": "Purchasing a life insurance policy", "C": "Transferring assets into foreign trusts", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Any type of asset can be hidden (e.g., real property, jewelry, stocks, bonds, vehicles, cash), and there are many techniques that a fraudster might use to hide ill-gotten gains. Some common techniques for hiding assets include transferring assets into foreign trusts, overpaying taxes, prepaying on a home mortgage, obtaining a life insurance policy, and transferring assets into someone else’s name."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a characteristic that asset hiders generally look for in the financial vehicles they use to conceal assets?", "options": {"A": "Transparency", "B": "Liquidity", "C": "Security", "D": "Accessibility"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Generally, asset hiders look to conceal their assets with financial vehicles that have certain characteristics. For one thing, asset hiders want products that are difficult to trace or untraceable. With such instruments, asset hiders can break or obscure links between the initial receipt of the assets and their final disposition. For another thing, asset hiders want products that are secure and accessible. Asset hiders also want products that are liquid."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "When circumstantial evidence is offered to prove that a subject has more income available than can be accounted for from legitimate sources, the subject often responds with which of the following defenses?", "options": {"A": "The subject has no taxable income.", "B": "The subject’s excess funds were received as gifts.", "C": "The subject’s excess funds were deobligated.", "D": "The subject incurred substantial debts."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "If a party uses an indirect method to prove the defendant’s illicit assets circumstantially, the defendant will try to rebut such evidence. Often, the defendant will claim that the excess income came from legitimate sources. The defendant might claim that the funds are cash that he accumulated earlier or cash from other legitimate sources, such as loans or gifts from relatives."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "A fraud examiner is deciding whether to conduct a traditional or a covert examination for a suspected fraud. Which of the following factors would be most favorable to conducting a covert examination?", "options": {"A": "The fraud examiner has several avenues through which he can obtain the necessary information.", "B": "There are sufficient details at the present time to apprehend the suspect.", "C": "The fraud examiner would like to determine who is responsible for known losses occurring in a certain area.", "D": "The fraud examiner finds it important to collect information in a direct manner from people possessing it."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The following situations are those in which covert operations have traditionally worked well: There is reliable information about criminal activity or asset losses, but there is insufficient detail for prevention or apprehension. Losses are known to be occurring in an area, but there is no information as to how they are occurring or who is responsible. It is desirable to gather information concerning personal relationships or to identify the contacts made with or by certain people. It is desirable to compare actual practices with supposed or required practices. It is important to obtain information in an indirect manner from people believed to possess it. Covert operations should be used when there is no other practical way to obtain necessary information."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "As long as the fraud examiner is not a government employee, promises of unqualified confidentiality for informants or sources are encouraged to get them to participate.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Whether working in private or government sectors, fraud examiners are not in a position to offer unqualified confidentiality to informants. Therefore, any promises made to an informant or source should be qualified with the caveat that no absolute assurances of confidentiality can be given. For example, a fraud examiner might say that he cannot guarantee that the source's identity will be kept secret, but that he will do so if possible. In the case of a fraud examiner who is employed by a governmental agency, there might be an absolute duty not to hold sources and informants in confidence. In many law enforcement agencies, an investigator might not have informants or sources who are unknown to the agency. Investigative agencies also regularly share information on criminal investigations with prosecutors, including the identity of the source of information. The same regulations and considerations could govern business entities."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "In general, the subject of an investigation should be interviewed first.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraud examinations should begin with general information that is known, starting at the periphery, and then move to the more specific details. In most examinations, fraud examiners should start interviewing at the periphery of all possible interview candidates and move toward the witnesses who appear more involved in the matters that are the subject of the examination. Thus, neutral third-party witnesses should generally be interviewed first, followed by parties suspected of complicity, starting with the least culpable and moving to the most culpable. The primary suspect should be interviewed last."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "A fraud examiner is conducting textual analytics on journal entry data and runs a keyword search using the terms deadline, quota, and trouble. With which leg of the Fraud Triangle are these fraud keywords typically associated?", "options": {"A": "Rationalization", "B": "Pressure", "C": "Opportunity", "D": "Capability"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In conducting a textual analytics examination, the fraud examiner should come up with a list of fraud keywords that are likely to point to suspicious activity. This list will depend on the industry, the suspected fraud schemes or types of fraud risk present, and the data set the fraud examiner has available. In other words, if he is running a search through journal entry details, he will likely search for different fraud keywords than if he were running a search of emails. The factors identified in the Fraud Triangle are helpful when coming up with a fraud keyword list. One of these factors is pressure; consequently, the fraud examiner should consider how someone in the entity might be under pressure to commit fraud. For example, many people commit fraud because of something that has happened in their life that motivates them to steal. Maybe they find themselves in debt, or perhaps they must meet a certain goal to qualify for a performance-based bonus. Keywords that might indicate pressure include deadline, quota, trouble, short, problem, and concern."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "Which of the following facts would best support the defense of a law enforcement officer against an allegation of entrapment?", "options": {"A": "The officer acted without malice", "B": "The officer acted based on his suspicion of fraud", "C": "The officer acted based on a tip from a reliable source", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Many jurisdictions recognize the legal defense of entrapment. Entrapment occurs when law enforcement officers or government agents induce a person to commit a crime that he is not previously disposed to commit. Entrapment also poses a legal problem in covert operations, particularly in undercover operations, because the defendant might not be found liable if it appears that he was improperly induced to commit the crime. Therefore, it is imperative that the operation be properly predicated. The law enforcement officer or government agent must act based on more than mere suspicion. For example, if the officer received a reliable tip that a suspect committed fraud, then that could serve as adequate predication. Covert operations must not be used for aimless searches for information performed without notions of what might be uncovered."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "Which of the following methods can be used to obtain documentary evidence?", "options": {"A": "Subpoena", "B": "Oral consent", "C": "Written consent", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Documentary evidence can be obtained in a number of ways. The preferred method is to obtain evidence by consent, if both parties agree. In some cases, consent can be oral, but when information is obtained from possible adverse witnesses or the target of the examination, it is recommended that the consent be in writing. Certain types of records can be obtained by consent only if the subject of the records consents in writing. Accessing a subject’s bank records from financial institutions, for instance, generally requires written consent. If no consent is given and evidence is held by other parties or in uncontrolled locations, specific legal action might be required. Most often, the legal process used takes the form of a subpoena or other court order to produce the documents and records (including electronic records). Other forms of court orders can be used to obtain witness evidence and statements."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding textual analytics?", "options": {"A": "The purpose of performing textual analytics is to search for and find an admission of fraud that can be presented in court.", "B": "Textual analytics is used to figure out whether someone is lying or telling the truth based on context clues.", "C": "There is a universal list of fraud keywords to use when implementing textual analytics that is applicable to any fraud examination.", "D": "Textual analytics can be used to categorize data to reveal patterns, sentiments, and relationships indicative of fraud."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Textual analytics is a method of using software to extract usable information from unstructured text data. Through the application of linguistic technologies and statistical techniques—including weighted fraud indicators (e.g., fraud keywords) and scoring algorithms—textual analytics software can categorize data to reveal patterns, sentiments, and relationships indicative of fraud. For example, an analysis of email communications might help fraud examiners to gauge the pressures/incentives, opportunities, and rationalizations to commit fraud that exist in an organization. Textual analytics provides the ability to uncover additional warning signs of potentially fraudulent employee behavior. Depending on the type of fraud risk present in a fraud examiner’s investigation, he will want to come up with a list of fraud keywords that are likely to point to suspicious activity. This list will depend on the industry, fraud schemes, and the data set the fraud examiner has available. In other words, if he is running a search through journal entry details, he will likely search for different fraud keywords than if he were running a search of emails. It might be helpful to look at the Fraud Triangle when coming up with a keyword list. Additionally, it can be helpful to consider the three factors identified in the Fraud Triangle when coming up with a keyword list."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "If the accused becomes withdrawn after his alibis have been diffused, the interviewer’s best course of action is to remain silent until the accused makes a confession.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "After the interviewer diffuses the accused’s alibis, the accused often becomes quiet and withdrawn. Some people in this situation might cry. If this occurs, the interviewer must be comforting. The interviewer should not remain silent or discourage the accused from showing emotion. Generally, such reactions indicate that the accused is considering whether to confess. At this point in the interview, the interviewer should present an alternative question. The alternative question forces the accused to make one of two choices, both of which constitute a benchmark admission (i.e., an answer that implies guilt). Once the benchmark admission is made, the subject has made a subconscious decision to confess."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "For a signed, written confession to be admissible in court, the statement must be:", "options": {"A": "In the handwriting of the declarant", "B": "In the wording of the declarant", "C": "Signed by at least two witnesses", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "There is no legal requirement that a statement must be in the handwriting or wording of the declarant. A statement’s wording should be precise, and because the fraud examiner usually knows how to draft a valid statement, it is generally not a good idea to let a confessor draft the statement. In addition, while there is no legal requirement for the confession to be signed by at least two witnesses, it is recommended that two people witness the signing of a statement."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Unlike a fraud examination report, an expert report should include specific information detailing the fraud examiner’s opinions of a case, as well as the fraud examiner’s qualifications and bases for providing those opinions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Fraud examiners who serve as expert witnesses in litigation are tasked with providing an expert report, which requires them to provide particular information about their qualifications, their opinions, the bases of those opinions, and various other pieces of information. The purpose of an expert report is to inform the parties, the judge, and the jury (if applicable) about the expert’s opinion of the case, as well as his credibility for commenting on such issues. A fraud examination report documents the results of a fraud examination and is generally created by one or more critical members of the fraud examination team. Documenting results is a particularly important function in fraud examinations. The fraud examination report conveys all evidence necessary to evaluate the case, and it can be used to corroborate previously known facts. An accurate report will add credibility to the fraud examination and to the fraud examiner’s work."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "When a fraud examiner prepares a memorandum reflecting the information furnished by a confidential source, how should the fraud examiner identify the source?", "options": {"A": "The fraud examiner should not write confidential source information in a memorandum.", "B": "The fraud examiner should identify the source by the source’s full name.", "C": "The fraud examiner should identify the source using the source’s initials.", "D": "The fraud examiner should use symbols to denote the source’s identity."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "It is recommended that all contact with informants and sources be reported on a memorandum, although the confidential source or informant’s identity should not be included in the report. Instead of including the source or informant’s identity, the fraud examiner should use symbols to denote the source’s identity. It is further recommended that sources be preceded with an “S,” followed by a unique identifier (i.e., source #1 would be “S-1”; source #2 would be “S-2”). The symbols for informants would then be “I-1” and “I-2.”"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "The net-worth analysis method of tracing illicit funds is recommended as a primary method of proof when most of the subject’s income is deposited in a financial institution and the subject’s books and records are unavailable, withheld, incomplete, or maintained on a cash basis.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The bank deposits method is recommended as a primary method of proof when most of the subject’s income is deposited in a financial institution and the subject’s books and records are unavailable, withheld, incomplete, or maintained on a cash basis. The net-worth method of tracing assets would yield the best result when several of the subject’s assets or liabilities have changed during the period under examination and the subject’s financial records are not available."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "With cloud computing, clients of cloud service providers do not have physical control of the media or the network on which their data reside, which can complicate forensic investigations in cloud environments.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Conducting digital forensic investigations in the cloud environment (i.e., cloud forensics) presents challenges not faced in traditional forensic practices, and lack of data control is one factor that complicates such investigations. Lack of data control exists because with cloud computing, clients of cloud service providers do not have physical control of the media or the network on which their data reside. This can complicate efforts to collect data stored on the cloud."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "When confessing to fraud, suspects tend to provide accurate details on the amount of funds involved and number of instances to relieve themselves of the guilt of their dishonest actions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In fraud matters especially, it is common for the accused to underestimate the amount of funds involved, as well as the number of instances. This is probably because of the human mind’s natural tendency to block out unpleasant matters. If the subject provides an estimate of these items, the interviewer should be skeptical of the figure’s accuracy. If the accused’s response is, “I don’t know,” start high with the amounts and gradually come down."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Sergio, a nonunion suspect, arrived at a scheduled admission-seeking interview accompanied by his manager, insisting that the manager be present during the interview. Should this interview be allowed to continue?", "options": {"A": "No, because the presence of a third party could have liability consequences.", "B": "Yes, because the manager is not a legal professional and therefore may not interfere in a legitimate investigatory interview.", "C": "Yes, because a third-party witness to a confession is valuable in court.", "D": "No, because the manager's presence would not be lawful."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Other than the subject and two fraud examiners, no other observers should be permitted in the admission-seeking interview because, among other reasons, the presence of third parties could have liability consequences. If the accused is in a union, a union representative (or a union attorney) might have the right to attend. However, this might present legal problems in allowing a third party to hear any allegations made. Also, because it is very difficult to obtain a confession with witnesses present, the fraud examiner should consider whether the case can be proven without the admission-seeking interview."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "When planning for an interview, which of the following steps should be taken?", "options": {"A": "Contemplate what the interview is intended to accomplish and state an objective", "B": "Ensure that the interview is held in a venue where the subject will feel comfortable", "C": "Prepare a brief list of key points to discuss during the interview", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To effectively prepare for the interview phase of an investigation, the fraud examiner must first develop a plan. The fraud examiner should contemplate what the interview is intended to accomplish and state an objective. He should also review the case file to ensure that it does not contain important information that has been overlooked. Prior to the commencement of the interviews, the fraud examiner should clearly determine what information might be gleaned from each of the potential witnesses, as well as the best strategy to go about obtaining it. When possible, the interview should be held in a venue where the subject will feel comfortable and secure, although it is not recommended that the interview take place in an environment that is particularly familiar to the subject, such as the interviewee’s home or office. The most appropriate member of the investigative team should be selected to conduct the interview based on the specifics of the interview. Rather than devise an exhaustive list of questions to ask the subject, the fraud examiner should instead formulate a brief outline of key points to discuss during the interview. Additionally, an investigator should consider which evidentiary documents to bring to the interview, if any, as well as which documents he might seek from the subject."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "When tracing financial transactions, the method that involves using the subject’s books and records to analyze the relationship between the subject’s receipt and subsequent disposition of funds or assets is called which of the following?", "options": {"A": "The direct method", "B": "The asset method", "C": "The bank records method", "D": "The indirect method"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Generally, fraud examiners can trace illicit transactions using a direct method or an indirect method. A direct method uses the subject’s books and records (or financial transaction records belonging to third parties) to analyze the relationship between a suspect’s receipt and subsequent disposition of funds or assets. In contrast, an indirect method employs circumstantial evidence to analyze the relationship between a suspect’s receipt and subsequent disposition of funds or assets."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "A company's organizational filing with the government generally includes information about the company's ownership, initial shareholders, and the location of its principal office.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Companies are formed by submitting some type of organizational filing to the government of the jurisdiction in which the entity is incorporated. These filings might be referred to in various ways in different jurisdictions (e.g., articles of incorporation, corporate constitution, or corporate charter). Organizational filings are generally public records and usually include: Corporate name Ownership information Nominal stock value Names of initial shareholders Names of the directors and officers Registered agent(s) Location of the principal office Date of incorporation Standing/status"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "When conducting fraud examinations, fraud examiners should adhere to the fraud theory approach.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When conducting fraud examinations, fraud examiners should adhere to the fraud theory approach. The fraud theory approach is an investigative tool designed to help fraud examiners organize and direct examinations based on the information available at the time. According to the fraud theory approach, when conducting investigations into allegations or signs of fraud, the fraud examiner should: Analyze the available data. Create a hypothesis. Test the hypothesis. Refine and amend the hypothesis."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Black, a fraud examiner, is conducting textual analytics on emails sent to and from specific employees that his client has identified as fraud suspects. He is using the Fraud Triangle to come up with a list of fraud keywords to use in his search. Which of the following words found in email text might indicate a fraudster is rationalizing his actions?", "options": {"A": "Quota", "B": "Deserve", "C": "Override", "D": "Write off"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In conducting a textual analytics examination, the fraud examiner should come up with a list of fraud keywords that are likely to point to suspicious activity. This list will depend on the industry, the suspected fraud schemes or types of fraud risk present, and the data set the fraud examiner has available. In other words, if he is running a search through journal entry details, he will likely search for different fraud keywords than if he were running a search of emails. The factors identified in the Fraud Triangle are helpful when coming up with a fraud keyword list. One of these factors is rationalization; consequently, the fraud examiner should consider how someone in the entity might be able to rationalize committing fraud. Because most fraudsters do not have a criminal background, justifying their actions is a key part of committing fraud. Some keywords that might indicate a fraudster is rationalizing his actions include reasonable, deserve, and temporary. Other keywords can be used to identify the other factors indicated by the Fraud Triangle. For example, write off and override would indicate opportunity to commit fraud, while quota suggests pressure to commit fraud."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Understanding the data, determining whether predication exists, and building a profile of potential frauds are all steps of which phase of the data analysis process?", "options": {"A": "The post-analysis phase", "B": "The preparation phase", "C": "The testing and interpretation phase", "D": "The planning phase"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "As with most tasks, proper planning is essential in a data analysis engagement. Without sufficient time and attention devoted to planning early on, the fraud examiner risks analyzing the data inefficiently, lacking focus or direction for the engagement, running into avoidable technical difficulties, and possibly overlooking key areas for exploration. The first phase of the data analysis process is the planning phase. This phase consists of several important steps, including: Understanding the data Defining examination objectives Building a profile of potential frauds Determining whether predication exists"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "When determining a subject’s net worth for asset-tracing purposes, all assets should be valued at current market value to eliminate any question about estimates.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When computing a subject’s net worth, these issues should be considered: All assets should be valued at cost, not fair market value. Subsequent appreciation or depreciation of assets should be ignored. The amount of funds available to the subject from legitimate sources should be estimated or computed generously. The subject should be interviewed to identify all alleged sources of funds and to negate defenses that he might raise later."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Closed questions are worded in a way that makes it difficult for the respondent to answer “yes” or “no.”", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Closed questions are those that require a precise answer, such as “yes” or “no.” Closed questions also deal with specifics, such as amounts, dates, and times. As far as possible, closed questions should be avoided in the informational part of the interview. They are used extensively in closing questions. Examples of closed questions include “Have you ever had a key to the mailroom?” and “How many years have you been in charge of the department?”"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Carter, a Certified Fraud Examiner for Universal Design, learns that Wallace, a shrewd salesperson with an unscrupulous attitude, has close relationships with several Universal Design customers. Carter also knows that Wallace has excessive gambling habits. Carter has sufficient predication to:", "options": {"A": "Alert management that Wallace might have committed fraud.", "B": "Accuse Wallace directly of having committed fraud.", "C": "Conduct discreet inquiries into Wallace's work as a salesperson.", "D": "Look for evidence of misconduct in Wallace’s computer and desk area."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Fraud examinations must adhere to the law; therefore, fraud examiners should not conduct or continue fraud examinations without proper predication. Predication is the totality of circumstances that would lead a reasonable, professionally trained, and prudent individual to believe that a fraud has occurred, is occurring, or will occur. Fraud examiners should begin a fraud examination only when there are circumstances that suggest fraud has occurred, is occurring, or will occur, and they should not investigate beyond the available predication. If fraud examiners cannot articulate a factual basis or good reason for an investigative step, they should not do it. Therefore, fraud examiners should reevaluate the predication as the fraud examination proceeds. That is, as a fraud examination progresses and new information emerges, fraud examiners should continually reevaluate whether there is adequate predication to take each additional step in the examination. Carter's actions should match the predication. There is insufficient predication to confront Wallace or to make any direct allegations about fraud, but Carter does have adequate predication to make discreet inquiries into Wallace's work as a salesperson."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following would be the most successful method of proving illicit income when several of the subject’s assets or liabilities have changed during the period under examination and the subject’s financial records are not available?", "options": {"A": "Net-worth method of analysis", "B": "Sampling sources method of analysis", "C": "Benford's method of analysis", "D": "Attribute method of analysis"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The net-worth method (or comparative net-worth analysis) is used to prove illicit income circumstantially by showing that a person’s assets or expenditures for a given period exceed that which can be accounted for from known or admitted legitimate sources of income. Fraud examiners should use the net-worth method when several of the subject’s assets or liabilities have changed during the period under examination and when the target’s financial records are not available."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Scott, a fraud examiner, is concerned that employees are abusing their expense accounts and are spending more than the thirty dollars allowed per day for meals. Which of the following is the most appropriate data analysis function for locating meal expenses greater than thirty dollars?", "options": {"A": "Gap testing", "B": "Compliance verification", "C": "Multi-file processing", "D": "Duplicate search"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Compliance verification determines whether company policies are met by employee transactions. If a company limits the amount of its reimbursements, the software can check to see that this limit is being observed. Many times, fraud examiners can find early indications of fraud by testing detail data for values above or below specified amounts. For example, when employees are out of town, do they adhere to company policy of not spending more than thirty dollars a day for meals? To start, fraud examiners can look at all expense report data and select those with daily meal expenses exceeding thirty dollars. With the information returned from this simple query, there is a starting point for suspecting fraud."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "Black, a Certified Fraud Examiner, has obtained an oral confession from Green, a fraud suspect. Black wants to examine Green's bank accounts. Which of the following would be the LEAST effective way to obtain permission to examine Green's bank records?", "options": {"A": "Obtain Green’s written consent.", "B": "Obtain a court order.", "C": "Obtain Green’s oral consent.", "D": "Obtain a subpoena."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Documentary evidence can be obtained in a number of ways. The preferred method is to obtain evidence by consent, if both parties agree. In some cases, consent can be oral, but when information is obtained from possible adverse witnesses or the target of the examination, it is recommended that the consent be in writing. Certain types of records can be obtained by consent only if the subject of the records consents in writing. Accessing a subject’s bank records from financial institutions, for instance, generally requires written consent. If no consent is given and evidence is held by other parties or in uncontrolled locations, specific legal action might be required. Most often, the legal process used takes the form of a subpoena or other court order to produce the documents and records (including electronic records). Other forms of court orders can be used to obtain witness evidence and statements."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "________ is a data analysis software function that allows users to relate several files by defining relationships in collected data, without the use of the Join command.", "options": {"A": "Multi-file processing", "B": "Record selection", "C": "Correlation analysis", "D": "Verifying multiples of a number"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Multi-file processing allows the user to relate several files by defining relationships between multiple files, without the use of the Join command. A common data relationship would be to relate an outstanding invoice master file to an accounts receivable file based on the customer number. The relationship can be further extended to include an invoice detail file based on invoice number. This relationship will allow the user to see which customers have outstanding invoices sorted by date."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Under which of the following circumstances would a fraud examiner need to comply with the European Union’s (EU) General Data Privacy Regulation (GDPR)?", "options": {"A": "The fraud examiner is based in France (an EU country) and is collecting public information from the Internet regarding a company based in Canada (a non-EU country)", "B": "The fraud examiner is based in Spain (an EU country) and is collecting personal information from human resources files about an employee based in the United States (a non-EU country)", "C": "The fraud examiner is based in the United States (a non-EU country) and is collecting personal information from human resources files about an employee based in Germany (an EU country)", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which took effect on May 25, 2018, is the primary regulation governing the collection and processing of the personal data of European Union (EU) residents. Although the GDPR only concerns the personal data of EU residents, it applies to any organization worldwide that collects or processes this information, regardless of where the organization is based. In other words, an organization does not have to be based in the EU for the GDPR to apply to it. For example, an organization based in the United States (a non-EU country) that has a branch located in Germany (an EU country) will be required to comply with the GDPR when collecting personal information about, or monitoring the activities of, its employees at the German branch. Generally speaking, the GDPR could limit the availability of EU residents’ personal information for fraud examiners, whether they or their organization is collecting that information or attempting to access personal information collected and disclosed by other organizations."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In interview situations, _______________ questions are those worded in a way that makes it difficult for the respondent to answer “yes” or “no.”", "options": {"A": "Open", "B": "Complex", "C": "Monologue", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Open questions are those worded in a way that makes it difficult for the respondent to answer “yes” or “no.” Also, the answer to an open question is not dependent on the question. The typical open question calls for a monologue response, and it can be answered in several different ways."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In interview situations, certain social-psychological forces make the conversation easier to accomplish. These forces are known as:", "options": {"A": "Facilitators of communication", "B": "Ego enhancers", "C": "Inhibitors of communication", "D": "Alleviations"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Facilitators of communication are those social-psychological forces that make conversations, including interviews, easier to accomplish. These facilitators require a basic understanding of what motivates people. The facilitators are: fulfilling expectations, recognition, altruistic appeals, sympathetic understanding, new experience, catharsis, need for meaning, and extrinsic rewards."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Hugo, a Certified Fraud Examiner, has obtained an oral confession from David, a fraud suspect. Hugo reduced the confession into a short, concise written statement for David to sign. After David signed the statement, he remembered a significant detail that should have been included. How should Hugo handle this omitted information?", "options": {"A": "Omit the significant detail", "B": "Destroy the old statement and prepare a new one", "C": "Add an addendum to the existing statement", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "When taking a signed statement from a suspect, there should not be more than one written statement for each offense. If facts are inadvertently omitted, the fraud examiner can add them later to the original statement as an addendum. For legal purposes, prepare separate statements for unrelated offenses. This rule applies because the target may be tried more than once—once for each offense."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following is a good practice for taking notes during an interview?", "options": {"A": "Slow down the interview process if necessary to take accurate notes.", "B": "Write down verbatim all responses given by the subject during the interview.", "C": "Avoid making notes regarding opinions or impressions about a witness.", "D": "Make any necessary additions to interview notes within several weeks of the interview."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "When taking notes during an interview, fraud examiners should follow a few basic rules. First, they should take accurate, but not necessarily verbatim, notes during the interview. Taking too many notes will make the interview process cumbersome, and it might inhibit the respondent. Fraud examiners should also avoid slowing down the interview process for note-taking. Instead, they should write down key words or phrases and then go back over the details at the end of the interview. In general, it is better to err on the side of taking too few notes rather than too many. These notes should be expounded upon as soon as possible following the interview to ensure accuracy. Finally, fraud examiners should avoid making notes regarding their overall opinions or impressions of the subject. Such notes can cause credibility problems if they are later produced in court."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "When reporting the results of fraud examination matters, the Certified Fraud Examiner (if qualified as an expert on such matters) may issue an opinion on which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Whether the entity's financial statements conform to generally accepted accounting principles", "B": "The effectiveness of the entity’s operations", "C": "The adequacy of the entity’s internal controls", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fraud examiners must be cautious about providing conclusions and stating their opinions. Opinions regarding technical matters, however, are permitted if the fraud examiner is qualified as an expert in the matter being considered. For example, a permissible expert opinion might address the relative adequacy of an entity’s internal controls. Another opinion might discuss whether financial statements conform to generally accepted accounting principles. Also, recommended remedial measures to prevent future occurrences of similar frauds are essentially opinions but are acceptable in fraud examination reports; however, it is better for the fraud examiner to convey recommendations related to flawed internal controls and other organizational failings to management in person or in a separate document. If included in the primary report, this information could potentially be seized upon by defense attorneys at a trial or by representatives at an unemployment hearing to push blame away from the suspect’s actions and toward the organization’s shortcomings."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Because digital evidence is different from tangible evidence, the rules regarding its admissibility in court are very different from the rules governing the admissibility of tangible evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Although digital evidence is different from tangible evidence, the rules regarding the admissibility of digital evidence in court are really no different from the rules regarding the admissibility of any other type of evidence. If a fraud examiner collects digital evidence, he should be able to state unequivocally that the evidence was not changed in any way by his actions. This requires that strict forensic methodologies be followed to satisfy the stringent evidentiary standards necessary to ensure the integrity of the evidence beyond a reasonable doubt for presentation in court. That is, digital evidence must be properly preserved in a forensically sound manner so that it will be admissible."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "When conducting a routine interview, a fraud examiner should introduce himself by stating his name, company, and title.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A fraud examiner must introduce himself before the interview commences. Generally, an interviewer should indicate his name and company, but he should avoid stating his title if possible. In some instances, the interviewer cannot avoid giving his title, and in such cases, the interviewer should use a title that will not conjure up emotions or possible fear in the respondent’s mind."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Suppose that a fraud examiner is going to testify at trial about an examination report for a complex case, and the report contains summaries of key documents that were created by someone other than the fraud examiner. Which of the following best describes what the fraud examiner should know about the documents underlying the summaries?", "options": {"A": "The fraud examiner should conduct a complete review of the documents underlying the summaries.", "B": "The fraud examiner does not need to review the documents underlying the summaries.", "C": "The fraud examiner only needs to review some of the documents underlying the summaries for quality assurance.", "D": "The fraud examiner must have read and analyzed every document in the case."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Sometimes cases involve thousands or even millions of documents, but someone must present a report on the review of those documents at trial. Such cases might make it impractical or impossible to timely analyze all of the documents. It is common for complex cases to require delegation of tasks to create an examination report, such as subordinates searching for key documents and creating document summaries. One important problem in the preparation of reports and accounting summaries arises from delegation of tasks to subordinates. If the expert presenting evidence has not had direct knowledge of or has not examined the specific documents or prepared the accounting summaries, it might be possible that the expert will be trapped under the hearsay rule (if applicable). Thus, if the tasks are delegated, it is important that the expert review the delegated work and compare all original work documentation, especially if the delegated tasks play an important role in the examination's findings. It is also important to know the effect of the other assumptions on the conclusion or opinion reached in the report. It is often possible to trap an expert into giving alternative opinions based upon other assumptions that had not been considered. The work should be planned carefully enough in advance so that the work papers and supporting documentation do not show contradictory conclusions that the opposing side could seize upon."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "Alex, a fraud examiner, receives an anonymous call from someone who claims to have information regarding a fraud at Alex’s company. The whistleblower says he will only provide the information if he is given unqualified confidentiality. Alex says he cannot make that promise. Was Alex’s statement prudent under the circumstances?", "options": {"A": "Yes, because Alex must report all details concerning the whistleblower to his client.", "B": "No, because whistleblowers are allowed unqualified confidentiality.", "C": "No, because Alex will likely lose the whistleblower as a source, resulting in harm to his client.", "D": "Yes, because Alex may attempt to protect the whistleblower’s confidentiality but cannot guarantee it."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When dealing with a confidential informant, the fraud examiner is not in a position to offer unqualified confidentiality. Therefore, any promises made to the informant should be qualified with the caveat that no absolute assurances of confidentiality can be given. The fraud examiner should explain to the informant that all possible steps will be taken to ensure complete confidentiality."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "In jurisdictions that regulate the processing and dissemination of personal credit information and personal data, such information cannot be obtained on an individual under any circumstances without the person’s consent.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In the case of consumer (individual) credit records and personal data, a growing number of jurisdictions regulate both how such information is collected and stored, as well as who may access this information and for what purpose. In many cases, the consumer must be notified and must consent to the use of the report. In jurisdictions that regulate credit information and personal data, a fraud examiner will generally need a legally acceptable reason for accessing such information from third parties. However, simply suspecting an individual of fraud is generally not sufficient grounds for obtaining credit and personal data regarding the person from a reporting agency or data controller. The specific exceptions for allowing the processing and dissemination of credit and personal data vary, but some common circumstances include when: The individual has given consent. It is necessary for the extension of credit or to enter into a contract with the subject. It is necessary to protect the subject’s vital interest. It is necessary to comply with other legal requirements. An employer is conducting a background check for hiring or other employment purposes (consent is still required in many jurisdictions). It is necessary to serve the public interest."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is a valid legal defense to allegations of entrapment against a fraud examiner who is a federal law enforcement officer?", "options": {"A": "The fraud examiner had suspicion of foul play.", "B": "The suspect made exculpatory statements.", "C": "There is proof of the suspect’s modus operandi.", "D": "The fraud examiner acted with adequate predication."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Many jurisdictions recognize the legal defense of entrapment. Entrapment occurs when law enforcement officers or government agents induce a person to commit a crime that he is not previously disposed to commit. Entrapment also poses a legal problem in covert operations, particularly in undercover operations, because the defendant might not be found liable if it appears that he was improperly induced to commit the crime. Therefore, it is imperative that adequate predication exists before the operation is commenced. The law enforcement officer or government agent must act based on more than mere suspicion. For example, if the officer received a reliable tip that a suspect committed fraud, then that could serve as adequate predication. Covert operations must not be used for aimless searches for information performed without notions of what might be uncovered."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is LEAST likely to be revealed by analyzing a subject’s electronic payment records?", "options": {"A": "Assets the subject has purchased", "B": "Loans the subject has obtained", "C": "The funds the subject has tied up in real property", "D": "The locations of the subject’s residences and businesses"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Electronic payments (or e-payments) refers to any type of noncash payment that does not involve a paper check. Electronic payment records can reveal, among other things: Assets the subject has purchased The locations of the subject’s assets (e.g., through the payment of real estate taxes, broker’s fees, or utility payments) The locations of the subject’s residences and businesses (e.g., through analyzing the payments of utility bills) Loans the subject has obtained (e.g., through analyzing loan payments) Payments made to nonexistent employees with direct deposit The cities and countries in which the subject conducts business (e.g., through analyzing the payments for carrier services to deliver packages) Transfers of funds between individuals without an established business relationship Assets ostensibly owned by family members or close associates but effectively controlled, held, or gifted by the subject Hotel payments The true owner of a property (e.g., through analyzing the mortgage payments and payments for home owner insurance)"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following types of information are NOT typically open to the public for inspection?", "options": {"A": "Real property records", "B": "Death records", "C": "Personal telephone records", "D": "Divorce and probate court records"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Generally, a person’s private phone lines, such as home phone and personal mobile devices, will be considered private. Therefore, to access the records for these lines, investigators will need consent from subjects, a warrant or subpoena, or another legal order."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE concerning the volatility of digital evidence?", "options": {"A": "The failure to preserve the integrity of digital evidence could result in evidence being deemed inadmissible in a legal proceeding", "B": "Once the integrity of digital evidence has been violated through alteration or destruction, it usually cannot be restored", "C": "Digital evidence is more volatile than tangible evidence because data can be altered or destroyed more easily than tangible information", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Digital evidence is more volatile than tangible information because digital data can be altered or destroyed more easily than tangible information. Because digital evidence can be easily altered or destroyed, the integrity of digital evidence must be preserved. Data that have been altered or destroyed are considered violations of data integrity. What is more, the alteration or destruction of digital evidence is typically irreversible. So, once the integrity of digital evidence has been violated, it usually cannot be restored. Additionally, the failure to preserve the integrity of digital evidence could result in evidence being deemed inadmissible in a legal proceeding, or, even if admitted, it might not be given much weight because evidence of questionable authenticity does not provide reliable proof."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Smith, a Certified Fraud Examiner for the XYZ Corp., is in the process of interviewing Alfred, a parts clerk, about a theft of inventory. Smith is unsure if Alfred is involved in the theft. In concluding the interview, Smith should:", "options": {"A": "Tell Alfred that he could be considered a suspect in the theft and observe his reaction.", "B": "Avoid revisiting any previously discussed topics to prevent Alfred from knowing what Smith considers important.", "C": "Review the key points discussed during the interview to ensure he has understood everything Alfred has said.", "D": "Tell Alfred that there is not enough evidence to consider him a suspect and therefore he is free to go."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "It is not unusual for the interviewer to have misunderstood or misinterpreted the respondent’s statements. Therefore, to ensure that the interviewer understood the information that the witness provided, he should review the key facts during the closing phase of the interview. However, the interviewer should not attempt to revisit all the information provided by the subject, only the facts that are most relevant."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is a step in the general process for tracing illicit transactions?", "options": {"A": "Selecting a response team", "B": "Building a financial profile", "C": "Implementing litigation hold procedures", "D": "Establishing reporting protocols"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Although the procedures performed during a tracing investigation vary depending on the circumstances, an actual investigation to trace transactions generally should involve the following elements: Collect information. Profile the subject (i.e., assemble the personal—financial and behavioral—profile). Review information for leads and prioritize leads. Trace the illicit transactions."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Why do fraud examiners perform textual analytics?", "options": {"A": "To gauge the pressures/incentives, opportunities, and rationalizations to commit fraud", "B": "To uncover warning signs of potentially fraudulent employee behavior", "C": "To reveal patterns, sentiments, and relationships indicative of fraud", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Textual analytics is a method of using software to extract usable information from unstructured text data. Through the application of linguistic technologies and statistical techniques—including weighted fraud indicators (e.g., fraud keywords) and scoring algorithms—textual analytics software can categorize data to reveal patterns, sentiments, and relationships indicative of fraud. For example, an analysis of email communications might help fraud examiners to gauge the pressures/incentives, opportunities, and rationalizations to commit fraud that exist in an organization. Textual analytics provides the ability to uncover additional warning signs of potentially fraudulent employee behavior. Depending on the type of fraud risk present in a fraud examiner’s investigation, he will want to come up with a list of fraud keywords that are likely to point to suspicious activity. This list will depend on the industry, fraud schemes, and the data set the fraud examiner has available. In other words, if he is running a search through journal entry details, he will likely search for different fraud keywords than if he were running a search of emails. Additionally, it can be helpful to consider the three factors identified in the Fraud Triangle when coming up with a keyword list."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Credit card records and statements pertaining to a subject can provide insight into the subject’s movements and habits, but they do not reveal people with whom the subject does business.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Credit card records are important in tracing assets because they reveal a great deal of personal and business information about the account holder or cardholder. Among other things, credit card records show card purchasing limits, previous payment history, account balance, when and where the subject has traveled, restaurants frequented by the subject, and assets the subject has acquired. In short, these records show the movements and habits of the person to whom the records pertain. Credit card statements also contain a great deal of important information. Generally, these statements contain the name of the credit card issuer, the cardholder’s account number, a summary of the transactions on the account, payment information, and a list of all the transactions that occurred during that month’s billing cycle (i.e., purchases, payments, credits, cash advances, and balance transfers). Credit card records can document out-of-town travel, and, often, the records will name people or entities with whom the subject conducts business."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "When drafting a fraud examination report, fraud examiners should write with the expectation that opposing legal counsel will have access to the information it contains.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When drafting a report, fraud examiners must consider who might end up reading it. Fraud examiners should keep in mind that the fraud examination report will be read by the general public and adverse parties. Under no circumstances should the fraud examiner prepare a communication with the idea that the information will not be disclosed to adverse third parties. Fraud examiners should draft their reports with this caveat in mind. There are many parties that might read a fraud examination report, including: Company insiders (managers, board of directors, owners, investors, etc.) Attorneys (legal counsel, prosecutors, regulators, and defense counsel) Defendants and witnesses Media outlets Judges or juries"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Acme Services, a new business, has just been registered as a corporation in a particular country. Acme’s management wants to expand business outside of the country. Which of the following is most accurate?", "options": {"A": "Acme must register as a business entity in foreign jurisdictions in which it wishes to conduct business.", "B": "Acme can only be incorporated in one jurisdiction.", "C": "Being incorporated in one country allows Acme to conduct business in most countries.", "D": "Acme may now conduct business anywhere in the world."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Most jurisdictions require that foreign corporations (corporations which were incorporated in another jurisdiction) be registered with the domestic business organization agency if the foreign corporations transact business in that jurisdiction. For example, if a corporation that was chartered in Country A wishes to transact business in Country B, it must create a business organization filing in Country B."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following is NOT an example of a data analysis function that can be performed to detect fraud through examination of accounts payable?", "options": {"A": "Review recurring monthly expenses and compare to posted/paid invoices.", "B": "Sort asset values by asset type or monetary amount.", "C": "Summarize large invoices by amount and vendor.", "D": "Identify debits to expense accounts outside of set default accounts."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The following are typical examples of data analysis queries that can be performed by data analysis software on accounts payable: Audit paid invoices for manual comparison with actual invoices. Summarize large invoices by amount, vendor, etc. Identify debits to expense accounts outside of set default accounts. Reconcile check registers to disbursements by vendor invoice. Verify vendor tax forms (e.g., U.S. Form 1099 or Value Added Tax (VAT) forms). Create vendor detail and summary analysis reports. Review recurring monthly expenses and compare to posted/paid invoices. Generate a report on specified vouchers for manual audit or investigation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following witnesses should be interviewed by surprise?", "options": {"A": "Friendly witnesses", "B": "Volatile witnesses", "C": "Neutral witnesses", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Surprise should be employed in any interview that is considered potentially volatile. In many instances, the potentially volatile respondent is unaware that he is going to be questioned, and he will therefore be unprepared. If the interview is not conducted by surprise, the interviewer runs the risk of the respondent not showing up, showing up with a witness, or being present with counsel. A target's friends, relatives, and romantic interests often make for a difficult interview. They perceive that the fraud examiner is deliberately targeting someone close to them."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "If, during an admission-seeking interview, the interviewer wants to reduce the accused’s perception of the moral seriousness of the act in question, which of the following would be an appropriate statement for the interviewer to make?", "options": {"A": "\"It's really not a big problem, legally.\"", "B": "\"It's just a technical violation.\"", "C": "\"This doesn't mean you're Bernie Madoff.\"", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In many cases, the interviewer can reduce the accused's perception of the moral seriousness of the matter. But the moral seriousness should not be confused with the legal seriousness. Fraud examiners and interviewers should be careful to avoid making statements that could be construed as relieving legal responsibility. For example, the fraud examiner should not state: \"It is not a big problem, legally. It's just a technical violation.\" Instead, the interviewer should minimize the moral side's importance. One effective way is through comparisons, such as: \"Everything is relative. What you've done doesn't even come close to some of the other things that have happened. You're not Bernie Madoff, right?\""}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "On which of the following data fields would a fraud examiner be most likely to run a duplicate test to search for a duplicate value?", "options": {"A": "Inventory counts", "B": "Customer account balances", "C": "Product numbers", "D": "Invoice numbers"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Duplicate testing is used to identify transactions with duplicate values in specified fields. This technique can quickly review the file, or several files joined together, to highlight duplicate values of key fields. In many systems, the key fields should contain only unique values (no duplicate records). For example, a fraud examiner would expect fields such as check numbers, invoice numbers, and government identification numbers to contain only unique values within a data set; searching for duplicates within these fields can help the fraud examiner find anomalies that merit further examination."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following information CANNOT be obtained from a subject’s safe deposit box record(s)?", "options": {"A": "The signatures of people entering the safe deposit box", "B": "The record of contents contained in the safe deposit box", "C": "The time and date of people entering the safe deposit box", "D": "The identity of people who have access to the safe deposit box"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Banks keep no record of safe deposit box contents and rarely know what the boxes contain, but, generally, banks maintain the following related records: Rental contract records Access records and entry logs A safe deposit box’s rental contract records identify the renters, the person or people who have access to the box, their signatures, and the dates of the original agreements and later renewals. They also might contain other identifying information, including the name of the initiating bank officer. The officer’s name could be significant if the subject (who might have used an alias in renting the box) must be identified. Records showing access to the boxes vary from bank to bank. But generally, they contain the signatures of the people entering the boxes and usually the dates and times of entry. The entry records are filed in box-number order. The frequency of entry and the times and dates of entries might be significant and might correspond to the times and dates of deposits, withdrawals from other accounts, or the purchases and sales of securities or property. Of course, proper authorization must be obtained before the bank will turn over any such records."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE regarding data mining?", "options": {"A": "Data mining can be used to streamline raw data into understandable patterns", "B": "Data mining is an effective way for fraud examiners to develop fraud targets for further investigation", "C": "Data mining is the science of searching large volumes of data for patterns", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Data mining is the science of searching large volumes of data for patterns. It combines several different techniques essential to detecting fraud, including the streamlining of raw data into understandable patterns. Data mining can also help prevent fraud. Additionally, it is an effective way for fraud examiners to develop fraud targets for further investigation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "In data analysis, date fields are generally not a problem when importing and exporting data because standard formats are always used.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When conducting data analysis, the fraud examiner must consider the data format and structure. This consideration is important when the fraud examiner wishes to import or export data with his computer. A date can be formatted into a number of different styles, such as mm/dd/yyyy. The structure of the data will also be important, along with the extension. A text file will have a .txt extension associated with it. In what format are the current data? What format will the computer require? How does the fraud examiner get the data from here to there if the data formats and structures are different?"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is a method of tracing illicit funds in which deposits to financial institutions are compared to legitimate income?", "options": {"A": "Asset method", "B": "Bank deposit analysis method", "C": "Income correlation method", "D": "Installment transaction analysis method"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The bank deposits method is a method of tracing illicit funds in which deposits to financial institutions are compared to legitimate income. The asset method is another method of tracing illicit funds, but it involves identifying assets previously acquired, identifying current liabilities, and taking the difference between the two. The installment transaction analysis method and the income correlation method are not methods of tracing illicit funds."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following types of records is/are commonly available from local governments?", "options": {"A": "Health and fire department records", "B": "Voter registration records", "C": "Utility records", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following items are basic types of public records that can commonly be accessed at the local level of government: Building inspector records Building permit records Health and fire department records Birth and death records Public school records Coroner’s register Voter registration records Utility records Marriage records"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Bianca, a fraud examiner for the Levine Corporation, suspects that an employee of another company has committed a fraud scheme against Levine Corporation. The relevant jurisdiction regulates the distribution of credit information and personal data. Although Bianca has not obtained the suspect employee's consent, she will likely be allowed to access his credit report from a third party.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In the case of consumer (individual) credit records and personal data, a growing number of jurisdictions regulate both how such information is collected and stored, as well as who may access this information and for what purpose. In many cases, the consumer must be notified and must consent to the use of the report. In jurisdictions that regulate credit information and personal data, a fraud examiner will generally need a legally acceptable reason for accessing such information from third parties. However, simply suspecting an individual of fraud is generally not sufficient grounds for obtaining credit and personal data regarding the person from a reporting agency or data controller. Some jurisdictions provide an exception to this rule when a party is conducting a background check for employment purposes, but since the suspect in this case is not an employee of the investigating party, the exception would not apply."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "A fraud examiner in an organized crime investigation believes a particular commercial restaurant is being used as a place of operation for the suspects. Which of the following types of records would be the LEAST likely to help the fraud examiner discover who owns the building in which the restaurant operates?", "options": {"A": "Voter registration records", "B": "Building permit records", "C": "Health department records", "D": "Fire department records"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are many public records often found at the local level that can help fraud examiners gather various types of information. To determine who owns a particular property, there might be direct information or leads found in the records of several agencies, including health and fire departments. Many local health or fire departments conduct routine inspections of businesses for health and safety code or fire code violations. These inspection records might contain valuable information about the business, its operations, the employees, and the owners. If a business or an individual constructs a new building or makes improvements to an existing building, there should be a building permit on file with the local building authority. In addition, before most businesses can open their doors, the local agencies might require that they possess certain permits. In many cases, the person applying for permits will be the owner or someone traceable to the owner. Voter registration records are not public in all jurisdictions, but if they are available, they might contain useful information. Usually, much of the information contained in such records is withheld from the public for privacy purposes, but voter registration records might contain a person’s date of birth, mailing address, and political affiliation. However, this information is less likely than the other sources listed to identify the owner of a commercial building."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Forensic analysis should not be performed directly on suspect devices because doing so can alter or damage digital evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Once a computer system is seized and before any analysis occurs, it should be imaged for analysis. Forensic analysis should not be performed on suspect devices directly because doing so can alter or damage digital evidence. Imaging the data from suspect devices allows a fraud examiner to view and analyze a computer's contents without altering the original data in any way. Imaging refers to the process whereby a forensic image of a hard drive or other digital media is made and imaged to another hard disk drive or other media for forensic analysis. A forensic image (also called a forensic copy, mirror image, or ghost image) is a duplicate or exact copy of a hard drive or other digital media."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "To preserve the confidentiality of a fraud investigation, management should always implement a blanket policy prohibiting employees from discussing anything related to employee investigations.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "To preserve the confidentiality of an investigation, management might (if legally permissible) remind participants to refrain from discussing investigation information with anyone or require participants to sign a confidentiality oath vowing not to divulge any information regarding the investigation. Generally, an employer can ask employees to keep an investigation confidential when there are legitimate business justifications for making such requests. However, it is usually not wise for management to implement a blanket policy prohibiting employees from discussing employee investigations, because doing so could violate certain employee rights. Some jurisdictions guarantee private-sector employees the right to organize and engage in other concerted activities for the purpose of collective bargaining or other mutual aid or protection. If an employer in such a jurisdiction has a routine policy or practice of asking employees not to discuss matters that are under investigation, the policy or practice might violate the employees’ right to organize and engage in other concerted activities. Therefore, it is best to tailor confidentiality requests to the specific case at hand and not use automatic, absolute policies."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Forensic accounting differs from fraud examination in that forensic accounting is the use of professional accounting skills in matters involving potential or actual civil or criminal litigation and may or may not involve fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Forensic accounting is the use of professional accounting skills in matters involving potential or actual civil or criminal litigation. The word forensic is defined by Black’s Law Dictionary as “used in or suitable to courts of law or public debate.” Therefore, forensic accounting is actually litigation support involving accounting. Accordingly, many fraud examinations can be considered forensic accounting, but not all forensic accounting is fraud examination. For example, an individual hired to appraise property in a minority shareholder derivative suit would engage in forensic accounting even if the engagement does not involve fraud."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is considered a red flag indicating that a subject is seeking to conceal ill-gotten assets through a loan repayment?", "options": {"A": "Large paydowns", "B": "Accelerated payments", "C": "Payments in odd amounts", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Generally, fraud examiners should look for loans with unusual repayments and trace them. Lump-sum payments, payments in odd amounts, accelerated payments, and large paydowns are unusual. These are all considered red flags indicating that an individual is seeking to conceal ill-gotten assets through a loan repayment, and loans with any such red flag should be investigated further."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Generally, the rules of admissibility for digital evidence are stricter than such rules for tangible evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Although digital evidence is different from—and more volatile than—tangible evidence, the rules regarding the admissibility of digital evidence in court are really no different from the rules regarding the admissibility of any other type of evidence."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Catharsis refers to the process by which a person obtains a release from unpleasant emotional tensions by talking about the source of these tensions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Catharsis is the process by which a person obtains a release from unpleasant emotional tensions by talking about the source of these tensions. We often feel better by talking about something that upsets us. Although we all are familiar with the frequent necessity for catharsis in ourselves, we do not always perceive the same need in others. The need for sympathetic understanding and the need for catharsis are related, but they are not the same thing. The interviewer who does not have time to listen to what he considers inconsequential or egocentric talk will often find the respondent unwilling to share important consequences."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "The goal of establishing an interview theme should be to:", "options": {"A": "Get the respondent to make a commitment to assist before commencing serious questioning.", "B": "Determine the respondent’s guilt or innocence.", "C": "Declare that the interviewer suspects the respondent of wrongdoing.", "D": "Inform the respondent that an official inquiry is being conducted."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "After providing the introduction and establishing rapport, the interviewer must state the interview’s purpose in some way prior to the commencement of serious questioning. Otherwise, the respondent might be confused, threatened, or overly cautious. Stating the purpose of the interview is known as establishing the interview theme. The goal of the theme is to get the respondent to make a commitment to assist. Failure to get a commitment to assist from the respondent is one of the common mistakes made by interviewers. Obtaining a commitment to assist is a critical step in setting the tone for the interview. A commitment for assistance requires positive action on the part of the person being interviewed. Remaining silent or simply nodding the head in response to a request for assistance is generally not sufficient."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In interview situations, it is usually advisable to err on the side of taking too many notes rather than too few.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraud examiners should take accurate, but not necessarily verbatim, notes during the interview. Do not try to write down all the information you are given during an interview, only write down the pertinent facts. Taking too many notes will make the interview process cumbersome, and it might inhibit the respondent. If, however, a quote is particularly relevant, try to write it down verbatim. Enclose all direct quotes in quotation marks. Furthermore, do not slow down the interview process for note-taking. Instead, write down key words or phrases, and then go back over the details at the end of the interview. In general, it is better to err on the side of taking too few notes rather than too many."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Gamma, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is interviewing Beta, a fraud suspect. Gamma asks Beta, \"Who in the company could be responsible for this situation?\" If Beta is guilty, he is more likely to say:", "options": {"A": "\"It wasn't me, that's for sure.\"", "B": "\"It could have been anybody.\"", "C": "\"It could be Green, but I'm not sure.\"", "D": "\"It wasn't anyone I work with.\""}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Both the honest respondent and the liar have a natural reluctance to name others involved in misdeeds. However, the liar frequently refuses to implicate possible suspects, no matter how much pressure the interviewer applies. This is because the culpable person does not want the circle of suspicion to be narrowed. Additionally, both honest and dishonest people normally object to and deny a direct accusation. But when compared to an innocent person, a culpable person is more likely to avoid an outright denial (“I didn’t do it.”) and is more apt to provide the interviewer with explanations as to why he is not the responsible party. An innocent person is unlikely to allow the interviewer to prevail in stopping the denial."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "When making a direct accusation in an admission-seeking interview, it is usually best to use strong words such as steal, fraud, or crime to reinforce the seriousness of the crime to the suspect.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The admission-seeking part of an interview begins with a direct accusation. The accusation should be made in the form of a statement, not a question. Also, emotive words such as steal, fraud, and crime should be avoided during the accusatory process. The accusation should be phrased as though the accused’s guilt has already been established, trapping the accused with no way out."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "When attempting to diffuse a suspect's alibi in a case where there is little physical evidence, a recommended technique is to discuss the accused’s prior deceptions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A useful technique to diffuse an alibi is to discuss the accused’s prior deceptions. The goal is to appeal to the accused’s logic, not to scold or degrade. This technique is particularly useful in cases with a lack of physical evidence. As with other interview situations, the word lying should be avoided."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Lucas, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is conducting an admission-seeking interview of William, a fraud suspect. Lucas asked William: \"Did you just want extra money, or did you do this because you had financial problems?\" This is called a(n):", "options": {"A": "Alternative question", "B": "Rationalization question", "C": "Benchmark question", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "After the interviewer diffuses the accused’s alibis, the accused often becomes quiet and withdrawn. Some people in this situation might cry. If this occurs, the interviewer must be comforting. The interviewer should not remain silent or discourage the accused from showing emotion. Generally, such reactions indicate that the accused is considering whether to confess. At this point in the interview, the interviewer should present an alternative question. The alternative question forces the accused to make one of two choices, both of which imply guilt. One alternative provides the accused with a morally acceptable reason for the misdeed; the other portrays the accused negatively. Regardless of which answer the accused chooses, he is acknowledging guilt. Examples of alternative questions include: \"Did you plan this deliberately, or did it just happen?\" \"Did you just want extra money, or did you do this because you had financial problems?\""}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "Harold, a fraud examiner, collects a computer hard drive as potential evidence in an investigation. He creates a memorandum to record the chain of custody and documents what item was received, when it was received, and from whom it was received. To meet the minimum standard for a chain of custody memorandum, what else would Harold need to include?", "options": {"A": "The name of the judge who signed the seizure order, if applicable", "B": "An explanation of why the item was collected", "C": "The value of the noncash item received", "D": "Where the item is maintained"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "From the moment evidence is received, its chain of custody must be maintained for it to be accepted by the court. The chain of custody is both a process and a document that memorializes who has had possession of an object and what they have done with it. Essentially, the chain of custody is a recordkeeping procedure similar to physical inventory procedures. In general, to establish the chain of custody, fraud examiners must make a record of when they receive an item or when it leaves their care, custody, or control. This is best handled by creating a memorandum with the custodian of the records when the evidence is received. The memorandum should state: What items were received When they were received From whom they were received Where they are maintained"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a data analysis function that can be performed on cash disbursements to help detect fraud?", "options": {"A": "Generate vendor cash activity summary for further analysis", "B": "Identify disbursements by department, supervisor approval, or amount limits", "C": "Verify audit trail for all disbursements by purchase order, vendor, department, etc.", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following are examples of data analysis queries that can be performed by data analysis software on cash disbursements to help detect fraud: Summarize cash disbursements by account, bank, department, vendor, etc. Verify audit trail for all disbursements by purchase order, vendor, department, etc. Generate vendor cash activity summary for analysis. Identify disbursements by department, supervisor approval, or amount limits."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "With proper analysis, fraud examiners can accurately determine how long ink, typewriting, or photocopier/printer toner have been on paper.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraud examiners using forensic document examination techniques might be able to prove or disprove the purported date of a document by analyzing details, such as when the ink used was manufactured, who manufactured the paper and when it was produced, or what kind of machine was used to produce the document and when those machines were first used. However, there are currently no methods for accurately determining how long ink, typewriting, or photocopier/printer toner have been on paper."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Because the laws of evidence generally protect written fraud examination reports from being disclosed to adverse third parties, fraud examiners can prepare written reports with the understanding that the information will not be disclosed to anyone outside the company.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When drafting a report, fraud examiners must consider who might end up reading it. Fraud examiners should keep in mind that the fraud examination report will be read by the general public and adverse parties. Under no circumstances should the fraud examiner prepare a communication with the idea that the information will not be disclosed to adverse third parties. Fraud examiners should draft their reports with this caveat in mind. There are many parties that might read a fraud examination report, including: Company insiders (managers, board of directors, owners, investors, etc.) Attorneys (legal counsel, prosecutors, regulators, and defense counsel) Defendants and witnesses Media outlets Judges or juries"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Which of the following is NOT part of the fraud examination process?", "options": {"A": "Testifying to findings", "B": "Assisting in the detection and prevention of fraud", "C": "Determining whether the subject is guilty or innocent", "D": "Writing reports"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The term fraud examination refers to a process of resolving allegations of fraud from inception to disposition, and it is the primary function of the anti-fraud professional. The fraud examination process encompasses a variety of tasks that might include: Obtaining evidence Reporting Testifying to findings Assisting in fraud detection and prevention"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding the types of information that digital forensic experts typically can recover from computer systems?", "options": {"A": "Digital forensic specialists can recover deleted emails, link files, and documents", "B": "Digital forensic specialists can recover information about websites visited", "C": "Digital forensic specialists can recover time and date information about files", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Digital forensics encompasses the recovery and investigation of material found in digital devices, and digital forensic experts are individuals who specialize in identifying, recovering, collecting, preserving, processing, and producing digital data for use in investigations and litigation. Sometimes retrieving digital data is as easy as searching the target computer’s hard drive, but other times retrieval requires a thorough knowledge of computers. For example, many fraudsters delete or hide incriminating files, and in these instances, efforts must be made to recover or find such data. There are, in fact, a variety of ways to recover deleted or hidden data from a target computer, and digital forensic experts are specially trained for such tasks. Deleted files are recoverable until they are overwritten because data are not erased from a computer’s hard drive until the operating system overwrites all or some of the files. So, deleted files that have been overwritten generally are not recoverable. Digital forensic specialists can recover, among other things, the following types of information from computers: Deleted files and other data that have not been overwritten (e.g., deleted documents, images, link or shortcut files, and email messages) Temporary auto-save files Print-spool files Websites visited, even where the browser history and cache have been deleted Communications sent via chat or instant messenger Financial-based Internet transactions Documents, letters, and images created, modified, or accessed, even if the data were not saved on the computer in some situations Data that have been copied, corrupted, or moved The time and date information about files (e.g., when files were created, accessed, modified, installed, deleted, or downloaded) Data from a drive that has been defragmented or reformatted"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Which of the following is a function of a fraud examination report?", "options": {"A": "To convey all the evidence necessary for other parties to thoroughly evaluate the case", "B": "To corroborate previously known facts", "C": "To add credibility to the fraud examination and to the fraud examiner’s work", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A fraud examination report documents the results of a fraud examination and is generally created by one or more critical members of the fraud examination team. Documenting results is a particularly important function in fraud examinations. The fraud examination report conveys all evidence necessary to evaluate the case, and it can be used to corroborate previously known facts. An accurate report will add credibility to the fraud examination and to the fraud examiner’s work."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following steps is included in the planning phase of the data analysis process?", "options": {"A": "Defining examination objectives", "B": "Determining whether predication exists", "C": "Building a profile of potential frauds", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "As with most tasks, proper planning is essential in a data analysis engagement. Without sufficient time and attention devoted to planning early on, the fraud examiner risks analyzing the data inefficiently, lacking focus or direction for the engagement, running into avoidable technical difficulties, and possibly overlooking key areas for exploration. The first phase of the data analysis process is the planning phase. This phase consists of several important steps, including: Understanding the data Defining examination objectives Building a profile of potential frauds Determining whether predication exists"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "It is recommended that any witnesses who are considered potentially volatile be interviewed without advance notice.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Surprise should be employed in any interview that is considered potentially volatile. In many instances, the potentially volatile respondent is unaware that he is going to be questioned, and he will therefore be unprepared. If the interview is not conducted by surprise, the interviewer runs the risk of the respondent not showing up, showing up with a witness, or being present with counsel. A target's friends, relatives, and romantic interests often make for a difficult interview. They perceive that the fraud examiner is deliberately targeting someone close to them."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "A fraud examiner is preparing his fraud examination report at the conclusion of a fraud investigation. When including information regarding the interviews conducted during the examination, the fraud examiner should:", "options": {"A": "Include all information provided by all the witnesses, regardless of the relevance.", "B": "Report the details of each witness interview in a separate memorandum.", "C": "Use signed copies of his notes from the interviews as the primary recording document.", "D": "Include only the facts provided by the witnesses that substantiate the fraud allegation."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Written fraud examination reports must be accurate. Inaccuracies will affect the credibility of the report and the report’s author. Each contact a fraud examiner makes during the course of a fraud examination should be recorded on a timely basis in a separate memorandum that documents the details of the interview. Ordinarily, there is no need to recapitulate testimony word for word in the report, but the fraud examiner should include all facts of possible relevance for accuracy’s sake. Also, relevant facts should be included regardless of which side they favor or what they prove or disprove. The written report conveys all evidence necessary to evaluate the case, and it can be used to corroborate previously known facts. An accurate report will add credibility to the fraud examination and to the fraud examiner’s work. Additionally, requiring a written report will force the fraud examiner to consider his actions during an investigation by ensuring that he documents his process. A well-written report will also omit irrelevant information, thereby allowing pertinent facts to stand out."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Which of the following is the most accurate statement about a fraud investigation plan?", "options": {"A": "An investigation plan should inform employees at all levels about the investigation.", "B": "An investigation plan should establish which individuals violated the law.", "C": "An investigation plan should establish the investigation’s time frame.", "D": "An investigation plan should make a commitment to eradicate the fraudulent activity."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Once it is determined that an allegation or issue will be investigated, and the investigation team has been assembled, the team should develop an investigation plan. An investigation plan should not establish which employees violated the law. In general, an investigation plan should encompass matters such as the goals of the investigation, the scope of the investigation, the team members’ roles and tasks, the time frame, and the course of action. An investigation plan should not include an organization-wide communication that notifies employees about the investigation. It should also refrain from promising a particular outcome."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "There should be two interviewers involved in a potentially volatile interview.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There should be two interviewers involved in potentially volatile situations. Having two people present provides psychological strength for the interviewers. Additionally, the second person can serve as a witness in the event that an interview turns bad."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Black, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is conducting an admission-seeking interview of Red, a fraud suspect. Black asks Red: \"Did you do this because you were mad, or was there a reason you did this?\" Red replies: \"I had a reason.\" Which of the following is the most appropriate response for Black to make?", "options": {"A": "\"I don't believe you.\"", "B": "“Everyone says that.”", "C": "\"I'm glad you had a good reason to do this.\"", "D": "\"It couldn't have been a very good reason.\""}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Once the accused makes the benchmark admission, the interviewer should reinforce the confessor’s decision by returning to the theme for his rationalization. This helps the confessor feel comfortable and lets him know that the interviewer does not look down upon him. For example: \"I am glad to hear that you had a good reason to do this. That reinforces what I thought all along—that you were caught up in extraordinary circumstances. When was the first time you did it?\""}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is a reason why a subject’s credit card records can be useful in asset tracing investigations?", "options": {"A": "Credit card records are available online for public inspection.", "B": "Credit card charges can provide leads to identifying hidden assets.", "C": "Credit card records can show signs of skimming.", "D": "Credit card statements show the source of the funds used to pay a credit card bill."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Credit card records are important in tracing assets because they reveal a great deal of personal and business information about the account holder. Among other things, information on credit card charges might provide leads to identifying hidden assets. For example, if a fraud examiner notices that the subject used his credit card to purchase items at a marina, the fraud examiner should investigate further to determine if the subject owns a boat. The credit card application and the monthly statements that the bank sends to the cardholder are the records that are most valuable to fraud examiners. Credit card applications require an applicant to disclose financial information, and they generally require the same type of information found on a bank loan application. In today’s environment, credit cards might be tied to bank accounts and might not require a separate application. Credit card statements also contain a great deal of important information. Generally, these statements contain the name of the credit card issuer, the cardholder’s account number, a summary of the transactions on the account, payment information, and a list of all the transactions that occurred during that month’s billing cycle (i.e., purchases, payments, credits, cash advances, and balance transfers). Credit card records can document out-of-town travel, and, often, the records will name people or entities with whom the subject conducts business."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the three general approaches for obtaining a verbal confession?", "options": {"A": "In reverse chronology", "B": "By event", "C": "Chronologically", "D": "By transaction"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In an admission-seeking interview, the interviewer should transition to the verbal confession when the accused provides the first detailed information about the offense. There are three general approaches to obtaining the verbal confession: chronologically, by transaction, or by event. The approach taken should be governed by the circumstances of the case. Once a verbal confession is obtained, the interviewer must probe gently for additional details—preferably details that only the subject knows."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "The records of a wire transfer identify the amount of the wire, where it was sent, and the date it was sent, but they do not identify who sent the wire.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The records of a wire transfer identify who sent the wire, where it was sent, the date it was sent, and its amount."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "During the introductory phase of the interview, the interviewer should avoid terms such as:", "options": {"A": "Inquiry", "B": "Investigation", "C": "Review", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Interviewers are encouraged to formulate their questions in a way that will not bring about a strong emotional reaction from the respondent, and emotive words of all types should be avoided during the introductory phase. Such words put people on the defensive, making them more reluctant to answer and cooperate. Words such as investigation and audit should be avoided. It is better to use words with a softer meaning, such as inquiry or examination."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "What is mutual legal assistance (MLA)?", "options": {"A": "A process by which countries request and provide assistance in law enforcement matters", "B": "A formal request by the courts of one country seeking judicial assistance from the courts of another country", "C": "A formal request by the government of a country seeking information from a defendant residing in another country", "D": "A letter whereby a criminal defendant requests that the government release exculpatory information"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Mutual legal assistance (MLA) is a process by which countries request and provide assistance in law enforcement matters, such as gathering information, obtaining provisional remedies, and enforcing foreign orders and judgments. To obtain assistance from a foreign government, the government seeking assistance makes an MLA request. An MLA request is a written request to the government of a foreign country that is used to obtain assistance in law enforcement matters. Generally, MLA can be used to obtain assistance in matters such as conducting searches, gathering evidence, compelling sworn testimony and the production of documents, issuing search warrants, issuing subpoenas, serving process, exchanging affidavits, obtaining provisional remedies, and providing assistance in forfeiture proceedings."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "In jurisdictions that protect the processing and dissemination of credit information and personal data, businesses are not subject to the same protections that individuals have.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In the case of consumer (individual) credit records and personal data, a growing number of jurisdictions regulate both how such information is collected and stored, as well as who may access this information and for what purpose. In many cases, the consumer must be notified and must consent to the use of the report. Agencies that process and disseminate such information are called credit reporting agencies, data controllers, and similar names, depending on the jurisdiction. Information on a business organization's creditworthiness may also be obtained from credit reporting agencies. The responses for such searches might include payment trends from creditors, public records, banking information, and key facts as to the type of business and ownership. But unlike consumer credit information, business credit information is generally not subject to the same legal protections that individuals have."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "To better prepare for the possibility that interview documents will be subpoenaed, fraud examiners should record their notes for each interview on a separate document.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The interviewer will frequently need to take notes during the interview. Interviews without notes are limited in their value because they leave the results of the interview open to interpretation or dispute. When taking notes, fraud examiners should follow a few basic rules. First, the interview notes for each interview should be recorded on a separate document. This can be especially helpful if documents from a particular interview are subpoenaed. Second, take accurate, but not necessarily verbatim, notes during the interview. Do not try to write down all the information you are given during an interview, only write down the pertinent facts. Taking too many notes will make the interview process cumbersome, and it might inhibit the respondent. If, however, a quote is particularly relevant, try to write it down verbatim. Enclose all direct quotes in quotation marks. Third, do not slow down the interview process for note-taking. Instead, write down key words or phrases, and then go back over the details at the end of the interview. In general, it is better to err on the side of taking too few notes rather than too many."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "When reporting the results of a fraud examination, the Certified Fraud Examiner generally should include his opinion regarding the credibility of the witnesses.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The fraud examiner should be careful not to include any statement of opinion as to the integrity or veracity of any witness, even if the fraud examiner is convinced that the witness is being untruthful. Truthfulness, or lack thereof, can be demonstrated through conflicting statements by the witness or suspect."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "Undercover covert operations often use disguise and deceit to obtain evidence directly from people involved in the offense, whereas surveillance operations use the skill of observation to gather information about individuals' activity.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The two main forms of covert operations are undercover operations and surveillance operations. Undercover operations often use deception and disguise to obtain evidence directly from those involved in the illicit activity. Agents engaged in undercover operations actively attempt to elicit the desired information. In contrast, surveillance operations use observation to gather information about individuals suspected of misconduct. For example, a surveillance operation might involve observing a suspect from afar while he meets with a potential co-conspirator. Alternatively, the investigator might pose as the co-conspirator’s agent and engage the suspect in conversation in an attempt to gather information; this would be an example of an undercover operation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "In interview situations, admission-seeking questions should be phrased as \"Did you do it?\" rather than \"Why did you do it?\"", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "People generally do not confess if they believe that there is doubt in the accuser's mind regarding their guilt. Thus, the interviewer must convey absolute confidence in the admission-seeking interview—even if not fully convinced. The interviewer must make the accusation in the form of an implied statement of fact. Accusatory questions do not ask, “Did you do it?” They ask, “Why did you do it?”"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Jeff, an employee at a retail store, is accused of skimming money from the register. During an admission-seeking interview with Jeff, the investigator states: “This is a huge corporation with more than a hundred stores, so it’s not like a few dollars here and there is going to affect anyone personally. Is that how you saw it?\" This technique is known as:", "options": {"A": "Unfair treatment", "B": "Extrinsic rewards", "C": "Depersonalizing the victim", "D": "Genuine need"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "If the subject does not confess to the misconduct when faced with direct accusations, the interviewer should try to convince the respondent that confessing is the most advantageous option available. To do this, the interviewer must offer a morally acceptable reason that allows the accused to confess to a misdeed without feeling ashamed. In cases involving employee theft, an effective rationalization technique is to depersonalize the victim. The accused is better able to cope with the moral dilemma of his actions if the victim is a faceless corporation or agency. Examples include: \"It isn't like you took something from a friend or neighbor. I can see how you could say, 'Well, this would be okay to do as long as it was against the company and not my coworkers.' Isn't that right?\" \"It's not like what you've done has really hurt one person. Maybe you thought of it this way: 'At most, I've cost each shareholder a few cents.' Isn't that the way it was?\""}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is an accurate statement about tracing the disposition of loan proceeds?", "options": {"A": "Tracing loan proceeds can determine if hidden accounts were used for loan payments", "B": "Tracing loan proceeds can uncover hidden assets or unknown witnesses", "C": "Tracing loan proceeds can determine if the proceeds were deposited into hidden accounts", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "If a fraud examination involves a loan with proceeds that have been disposed, the fraud examiner should trace the disposition of the loan’s proceeds. A fraud examiner can trace loan proceeds to determine if hidden accounts were used for loan payments or if the proceeds were deposited into hidden accounts. Also, because loans might be secured by hidden assets or co-signed by previously unknown cohorts, tracing loan proceeds can uncover hidden assets or unknown witnesses. Moreover, if the subject has taken out a loan for someone else, tracing the disposition of the loan proceeds will uncover those leads."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Fraud examiners should generally conduct interviews as closely as possible to the event in question.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The interview should be conducted as closely as possible to the event in question. With the passage of time, the memories of potential witnesses and respondents can become faulty, and critical details can be distorted or forgotten."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following is a core data analysis function that can be performed with most data analysis software applications?", "options": {"A": "Duplicate searches", "B": "Joining files", "C": "Sorting", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Computers can scan database information for several specific types of information, creating a red flag system. To perform this, most software packages use a combination of different functions. These functions are: Sorting Record selection Joining files Multi-file processing Correlation analysis Verifying multiples of a number Compliance verification Duplicate searches Expressions and equations Filter and display criteria Fuzzy logic matching Gap tests Pivot tables Regression analysis Sort and index Statistical analysis Stratification Date functions Benford's Law analysis"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "All written fraud examination reports must include a follow-up/recommendations section.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A follow-up/recommendations section is generally an optional part of a written fraud examination report. This section identifies any aspect of the investigation that remains outstanding, usually because it is outside the mandate of the investigator. This could include the recovery of property that is in the possession of third parties or the collection of information held by vendors or suppliers."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "To protect privacy interests, courts generally find that audit clauses within business partner contracts are void, and most jurisdictions have laws that prohibit businesses from making threats to terminate a business relationship over a contracting party’s refusal to turn over nonpublic information.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "There are several ways to obtain nonpublic information. An organization may demand that a supplier, vendor, or agent turn over relevant documents as a condition of continued business. Taking this action is legal, in appropriate circumstances. Of course, management and counsel should be consulted before such demands are made, particularly if the other party has a contractual relationship with the demanding organization. An audit clause allows parties to a contract the right to access another party's books. Often, audit clauses are too narrow to provide useful information. However, if properly constructed, an audit clause can be a powerful method by which on-book information can be obtained."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is the most accurate description of the net-worth (or comparative net-worth) method of analysis?", "options": {"A": "The net-worth method refers to the process of assigning forecasted income and expenses to accounts, which will be compared to actual income and expenses for analysis of variances.", "B": "The net-worth method refers to the process of using a subject’s books and records to determine the subject’s financial condition and identify the receipt or disposition of funds or assets.", "C": "The net-worth method is an indirect method of proving illicit income circumstantially by showing that a person’s assets or expenditures for a given period exceed that which can be accounted for from known or admitted legitimate sources of income.", "D": "The net-worth method is an indirect method of proving illicit income circumstantially by measuring and recording income as earned and recording expenses as incurred."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The net-worth method (or comparative net-worth analysis) is used to prove illicit income circumstantially by showing that a person’s assets or expenditures for a given period exceed that which can be accounted for from known or admitted legitimate sources of income. Fraud examiners should use the net-worth method when several of the subject’s assets or liabilities have changed during the period under examination and when the target’s financial records are not available."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "A fraud response plan outlines the actions an organization will take when suspicions of fraud have arisen.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When evidence of misconduct arises, management must respond in an appropriate and timely manner. During the initial response, time is critical. To help ensure that an organization responds to suspicious fraud-related activity efficiently, management should have a response plan in place. A fraud response plan outlines the actions an organization will take when suspicions of fraud have arisen."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following is the most accurate statement regarding what fraud examiners should do when collecting information from social media sites?", "options": {"A": "The information from social networking sites should be preserved so that it can be established as authentic if used in court.", "B": "Fraud examiners can use the contents of each social networking website to authenticate the websites themselves.", "C": "Conducting a forensic shutdown of the computer while a social networking site is open will preserve the website’s metadata for authentication purposes.", "D": "Saving a social networking Web page as a “bookmark” is sufficient to preserve the information on the site for authentication purposes."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Generally, documentary evidence, including digital evidence, will not be admitted in a legal proceeding, or it will not be given much weight, unless it is established as authentic (i.e., the evidence is what it purports to be and is in the same condition as when it was seized). There are a number of techniques used to authenticate information from social media. Often, authenticity can be established through the testimony of a witness who verifies that the exhibit at issue accurately reflects what he observed on the site, and typically, the witness is the party who collected the evidence. Consequently, fraud examiners who collect evidence from social media often become a form of eyewitness, and for this reason, fraud examiners must capture, download, and preserve any useful information as soon as they discover it. They must memorialize each step of the collection process, creating a record of what they see at any point in the investigation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Cleansing and normalizing data during a data analysis engagement includes reviewing data to ensure that any inconsistencies are fixed, isolated, or eliminated.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The results of a data analysis test will only be as good as the data used for the analysis. Thus, before running tests on the data, the fraud examiner must make certain the data being analyzed are relevant and reliable for the objective of the engagement. The phrase “garbage in, garbage out” is applicable in the preparation phase. Depending on how the data was collected and processed, as well as the results of the data verification process, the fraud examiner might need to cleanse and convert the data to a format suitable for analysis before executing any data analysis tests. For example, certain field formats (e.g., date, time, or currency) might need to be modified to make the information consistent and ready for testing. The data must also be normalized so that all data being imported for analysis can be analyzed consistently. Common data fields from multiple systems must be identified, and data must be standardized. In normalizing the data for analysis, table layout, fields/records, data length, data format, and table relationships are all important considerations. Additionally, the following inconsistencies in the data must be addressed: Known errors Special/unreadable characters in the data Other unusable entries When possible, such situations should be addressed by fixing, isolating, or eliminating them. Any issues that cannot be cleaned up will require special consideration during the testing and interpretation phase."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "When conducting interviews as part of a fraud examination, it is usually best to seek known information before seeking unknown information.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "As a general rule, questioning should proceed from the general to the specific; that is, it is best to seek general information before seeking specific details. A variation is to \"reach backward\" with the questions by beginning with known information and working toward unknown areas. An efficient method of doing this is to recount the known information and then frame the next question as a logical continuation of the facts previously related."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Records obtained from financial institutions are perhaps the single most important financial source available to fraud examiners for purposes of tracing assets.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Records obtained from financial institutions are perhaps the single most important financial source available to fraud examiners for asset-tracing purposes. They can be used as evidence for fraud, as well as to: Identify witnesses and other evidence. Uncover criminal profits. Identify criminal assets. Locate assets that can be used to satisfy a judgment. Identify localities where assets are stored. Determine the lifestyle of an account holder. Determine the financial health of an organization. Determine the source of funds placed into an account. Determine the use of the funds from an account."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following types of information on corporations whose stocks and securities are sold to the public might be available from regulatory securities records?", "options": {"A": "Identities of officers and directors", "B": "Financial statements", "C": "Identities of accountants and attorneys", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "While jurisdictions treat the concept of securities differently, governments or self-regulatory bodies generally set rules for the issuing and trading of certain types of securities. Among the most common and important rules are disclosure requirements for companies with publicly traded securities. These rules are designed to make sure that investors are reasonably informed about stock that they purchase. Beyond helping investors, these disclosures typically are made public, and they can provide a wealth of information about the filing company, including its type of business, history, organizational structure, auditor, balance sheets, and income statements. Different securities regulators have varying disclosure requirements, but these records might include the following information: Corporate financial statements Identification of officers and directors Identification of significant owners (e.g., those with more than 10% of a business’s stock) A description of the registrant’s properties and businesses A description of the significant provisions of the security to be offered for sale and its relationship to the registrant’s other capital securities Identification of events of interest to investors Identification of accountants and attorneys A history of the business"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Each fraud examination should be conducted with the assumption that the case will end in litigation.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Each fraud examination should be conducted with the assumption that the case will end in litigation. This will ensure that the fraud examiner maintains accordance with the proper rules of evidence and remains well within the guidelines established by the legal systems."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Allen, a Certified Fraud Examiner for Cole Inc., has conducted an examination into allegations of misconduct against Roberts, the company's controller. Allen plans to meet with Roberts to ask him about the allegations and to obtain a confession of wrongdoing. Allen's meeting with Roberts is referred to as a(n):", "options": {"A": "Confrontation", "B": "Admission-seeking interview", "C": "Custodial interrogation", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Admission-seeking questions are designed to obtain a legal admission of wrongdoing, and admission-seeking interviews are reserved specifically for individuals whose culpability is reasonably certain; all other reasonable investigative steps have been completed and as much information as possible has been developed from other sources; and the interviewer can reasonably control the interview's place, time, and subject matter."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following is a common use of public records in fraud examinations?", "options": {"A": "Tracing and recovering assets", "B": "Accessing an individual’s income tax filings", "C": "Obtaining a person’s credit records", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Public records are documents that a governmental agency is required to keep by law or that are necessary to discharge the duties imposed by law. Public records, which can generally be accessed by the public and are thus available to anyone who wishes to use them, can be helpful to fraud examiners for a number of reasons. They can supply invaluable background information on entities, employees, suspects, and witnesses. They can also be used to corroborate or refute witness statements, help investigators track the flow of stolen money or other assets, and aid efforts to recover losses. Individual tax records and consumer credit records are typically nonpublic information."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Jones, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is conducting an interview of Adams, an accounts receivable clerk for Ajax Inc. At the beginning of the interview, Jones asked Adams a series of nonthreatening questions to observe his reactions. Jones was:", "options": {"A": "Determining the witness’s equilibrium", "B": "Establishing an interview theme", "C": "Calibrating the witness", "D": "Assessing the witness’s knowledge base"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Calibrating (or norming) is the process of observing behavior before critical questions are asked. Calibrating should be a routine part of all interviews. People with truthful attitudes will answer questions one way; those with untruthful attitudes will generally answer them differently. The best way to calibrate a witness is through the use of noncritical questions on background information, place of employment, and the like. If the witness displays general nervousness or other verbal and nonverbal clues during this phase of questioning, subsequent indicators might not be reliable. The key is to observe changes in behavior when pertinent questions are asked. Examples of noncritical questions include “When did you start with the company?” and “How long is your commute?”"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following types of records for a personal bank account would most likely contain the account holder’s name, address, telephone number, and government identification number?", "options": {"A": "Deposit slip", "B": "Canceled check", "C": "Signature card", "D": "ATM withdrawal slip"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "To open a personal account, the individual opening the account must provide a signature card, or similar document, evidencing a contract between the customer and bank. The signature card is a source of valuable information. Although its form varies, the card usually contains the person’s name, address, telephone number, identification number, amount of the opening deposit (and possibly the source of the opening deposit), and security data (e.g., mother’s maiden name). The person’s identification information might be significant, especially if the depositor used an alias. Also, a fraud examiner might be able to trace the opening deposit through the bank’s records to disclose a source of income."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "When a fraud examiner is conducting an examination and is in the process of collecting documents, he should leave the original document where it was discovered and take only a copy of the document for examination.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Here are a few general rules regarding the collection of documents: Obtain original documents where feasible. Make working copies for review, and keep the originals segregated. Do not touch originals any more than necessary; they might later have to undergo forensic analysis. Maintain a dependable filing system for the documents. This is especially critical when large numbers of documents are obtained. Losing a key document is very problematic and can damage the case. Documents can be stamped sequentially for easy reference."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "When seizing a running computer for forensic examination, the seizing party should perform a graceful shutdown by turning the computer off using the normal shutdown process.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When seizing a computer that is running, the seizing party should not perform a graceful shutdown by turning it off using the normal shutdown process. If a system is turned off using normal shutdown routines, a number of temporary files will be deleted and possibly overwritten during the shutdown process, and such files might be important to the investigation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "A bank credit department generally maintains which of the following types of basic loan records?", "options": {"A": "The accounting journal", "B": "The credit or loan file", "C": "The master appropriation file", "D": "The cash record"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Loan records can provide important information regarding a subject. When a bank makes a commercial loan to an individual, it requires detailed statements of assets and liabilities from the borrower, and these records will be contained in the loan records. The loan file also might include the results of credit inquiries regarding paying habits, loan amounts, and present unpaid balances. A bank credit department generally maintains the following basic records: The credit or loan file: This file includes the customer's loan application, financial statements, and general economic history. The liability ledger: This contains the customer’s past and present liability to the bank. These sheets also contain information such as the loan date, note number, amount of the loan, interest rate, due date, and payments. The collateral file: This contains a complete description of the items pledged as security for loans. Records of such collateral can provide valuable information about a subject’s assets."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "During the analysis phase in digital forensic investigations, it is best to use just one forensic tool for identifying, extracting, and collecting digital evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The analysis phase involves the use of specialized software designed to give the fraud examiner the means to identify, extract, collect, examine, and store digital artifacts that will be used as evidence in the investigation. There are a number of analytical review products that can assist in analyzing volumes of data for relevant evidence. But generally, these products employ various ways to search and analyze data for relevant materials. Unfortunately, due to the vast array of digital devices available, there is no single perfect tool or platform. No single analytical review tool can recover everything; each tool has its own strengths and weaknesses. Therefore, it is best to use a combination of the various tools during the analysis phase, allowing for the identification and recovery of more information."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Characteristics of a well-written fraud examination report include which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Impartiality", "B": "Accuracy", "C": "Clarity", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A well-written report contains the following four characteristics: Accuracy Clarity Impartiality and relevance Timeliness The facts in a report should only be those relevant to the case, filtering out unnecessary details. Moreover, fraud examiners should not make determinations of guilt or innocence in their reports."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Characteristics of a well-written fraud examination report include which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Impartiality", "B": "Accuracy", "C": "Clarity", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A well-written report contains the following four characteristics: Accuracy Clarity Impartiality and relevance Timeliness The facts in a report should only be those relevant to the case, filtering out unnecessary details. Moreover, fraud examiners should not make determinations of guilt or innocence in their reports."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "question": "In interview situations, ___________ are questions that often suggest an answer opposite to the correct one.", "options": {"A": "Reverse", "B": "Inverted", "C": "Complex", "D": "Double-negative"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Double-negative questions are questions that have two forms of negation within a single clause. Double-negative questions, or statements containing double negatives, are confusing and often suggest an answer opposite to the correct one. Therefore, they should not be used. For example: \"Didn't you suspect that something wasn't right?\""}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following is a type of information that can be obtained from the Internet archives?", "options": {"A": "Content on websites without any links pointing to them", "B": "Content on websites not indexed by standard search engines", "C": "Content posted on a website that has been removed", "D": "Content on a website that is protected by passwords"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The term Internet archives refers to archived versions of Web pages that have since been updated or are no longer available online. The most popular tool for searching the Internet archives is the Wayback Machine, located at https://archive.org. The Wayback Machine allows users to see archived versions of Web pages throughout time. Fraud examiners can use the Wayback Machine to find historical information, such as: A photo posted on a website that has been removed Content, views, writing, and opinions rescinded by an author A company's old job ads, statements, affiliations, or product lines Alternatively, the deep Web (also known as the invisible Web) refers to Web content that is not indexed by standard search engines. There are a number of reasons why the deep Web exists. For instance, there are websites where Web crawlers (search engine robots or spiders) cannot enter. Web crawlers are scripts that create copies of visited Web pages that are indexed by a search engine to provide faster searches. These deep Web resources include websites without any links pointing to them, certain file formats that search engines cannot handle, websites that have been blocked from Web crawler access, password-protected websites, and information stored in databases. Also, search engines limit the depth of their crawl on a website. Moreover, Web crawlers cannot crawl as quickly as pages are added or updated."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "All of the following are advantages to using data analysis software EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Fraud examiners can use data analysis software to search for red flags of possible fraud.", "B": "Fraud examiners can use data analysis software to produce accurate results from bad data.", "C": "Fraud examiners can use data analysis software to ensure that an investigation is accurate and complete.", "D": "Fraud examiners can use data analysis software to centralize fraud investigations."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "There are five significant advantages to using data analysis software. First, data analysis software allows the fraud examiner to centralize an investigation, relying less on others to gather data. Second, data analysis software allows the fraud examiner to ensure that an investigation is accurate and complete. Third, data analysis allows the fraud examiner to base predictions about the probability of a fraudulent situation on reliable statistical information. Fourth, data analysis allows the fraud examiner to search entire data files for red flags of possible fraud. Finally, data analysis can assist the fraud examiner in developing reference files for ongoing fraud detection and investigation work."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a nonverbal clue to deception?", "options": {"A": "Placing the hands over the mouth", "B": "Leaning toward the interviewer when questions are serious", "C": "Displaying no interest in implicating evidence", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Nonverbal clues refer to clues that are illustrated by an individual’s body language. When asked sensitive or emotive questions, the dishonest person will sometimes change his posture completely, as if moving away from the interviewer. Frequently, dishonest people will cover the mouth with the hand or fingers when being deceptive. Also, in an attempt to show concern, the guilty person might display a keen interest in implicating evidence. Nonverbal indications of deception include: Full-body motions away from the interviewer Physical responses such as sweating or labored breathing Changes in the use of illustrators Interruptions to the flow of speech Hands over the mouth Manipulation of objects such as a pencil Body positioned in a fleeing position Crossing of the arms Unnatural or casual reaction to evidence"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Nathan, a Certified Fraud Examiner, has obtained an oral confession from Gabriel, a fraud suspect. Nathan wants to probe Gabriel for additional details. Which of the following is the most appropriate question Nathan should ask Gabriel to find out if there are any remaining proceeds that can be used to reduce losses?", "options": {"A": "\"What do you have left?\"", "B": "“It’s all gone, isn’t it?”", "C": "\"Did you spend everything?\"", "D": "\"Is there anything left?\""}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In appropriate situations, the interviewer should find out whether there are unspent or available assets that the confessor can use to reduce losses. The interviewer should ask the accused “What’s left?” rather than asking “Is there anything left?”"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Which of the following general statements about a fraud investigation plan is CORRECT?", "options": {"A": "An investigation plan should establish the goals of the investigation", "B": "An investigation plan should establish the investigation’s time frame", "C": "An investigation plan should identify the scope of the investigation", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Once it is determined that an allegation or issue will be investigated, and the investigation team has been assembled, the team should develop an investigation plan. An investigation plan should not establish which employees violated the law. In general, an investigation plan should encompass matters such as the goals of the investigation, the scope of the investigation, the team members’ roles and tasks, the time frame, and the course of action."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Simone, a manager at a major company, is suspected of financial statement fraud. During an admission-seeking interview with Simone, the investigator states: “A lot of employees count on the company doing well. I know you only did this to help the company succeed. Isn’t that right?” This technique is known as:", "options": {"A": "Genuine need", "B": "Altruism", "C": "Extrinsic rewards", "D": "Depersonalizing the victim"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "If the subject does not confess to the misconduct when faced with direct accusations, the interviewer should try to convince the respondent that confessing is the most advantageous option available. To do this, the interviewer must offer a morally acceptable reason that allows the accused to confess to a misdeed without feeling ashamed. In many cases, the moral seriousness of the matter can be reduced by claiming the action was for the benefit of others. This is especially true if the accused views himself as a caring person. This is known as \"altruism.\" In establishing this rationalization, the interviewer might say something similar to the following examples: \"I know you didn't do this for yourself. I have looked into this matter carefully, and I think you did this to help your husband, didn't you?\" \"You have a big responsibility in this company. A lot of people depend on you for their jobs. I just know you did this because you thought you were doing the right thing for the company, didn't you?\""}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "When evidence of fraud arises, management should respond by:", "options": {"A": "Preserving relevant documents", "B": "Identifying who should be informed", "C": "Conducting an initial assessment", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Generally, when evidence of fraud arises, management should respond by engaging in the following actions: Activating the response team Engaging legal counsel, if necessary Considering whether to contact insurance providers Addressing immediate concerns (e.g., preserving relevant documents and identifying who should be informed) Conducting an initial assessment Documenting the initial response"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Forensic investigations in cloud environments can be complicated by the lack of physical access to evidence stored on the cloud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Conducting digital forensic investigations in the cloud environment (i.e., cloud forensics) presents challenges not faced in traditional forensic practices, and lack of information accessibility is one factor that complicates such investigations. Cloud computing complicates the collection of data because cloud storage systems are not local; therefore, investigators generally do not have physical access to evidence stored on the cloud—something that investigators typically have when examining traditional privately owned and locally hosted systems. Lack of information accessibility also means that often, cloud customers do not have much information about the physical locations of their data."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a piece of information contained on most wire transfers?", "options": {"A": "The recipient's government identification number", "B": "The name of the sender or originator", "C": "The amount of the transfer", "D": "The date of the transfer"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The information contained on a wire transfer generally will include the following items: The amount of the transfer The date of the transfer The purpose of the transfer The name of the sender or originator The routing number of the originating bank or financial institution The identity of the designated beneficiary or receiver of the funds The routing number of the recipient bank However, the government identification number for the recipient is not typically included in most wire transfer records."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "When a fraud examiner identifies suspicious indented writings on a pad of paper, the fraud examiner should develop the writings by shading the pad's surface with a pencil.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Indented writing is the impression a writing instrument leaves on sheets of paper below the sheet that contains the original writing. Fraud examiners should be alert for the presence of incriminating indented writings or the absence of logical indentations, both of which can be valuable in proving fraud. Fraud examiners should never attempt to develop indented writings by shading or scratching on the surface of a sheet of paper with a pencil. Although this method will reveal deep indentations, it will not reveal faint indentations and will prevent experts from analyzing them. Moreover, shading or scratching with a pencil might prevent other types of technical examinations."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following steps takes place during the preparation phase of a data analysis engagement?", "options": {"A": "Building a profile of potential frauds", "B": "Cleansing and normalizing the data", "C": "Defining examination objectives", "D": "Determining whether predication exists"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Defining the examination objectives, determining whether predication exists, and building a profile of potential frauds are all steps of the planning phase of the data analysis process, which is the first phase that should be undertaken. The second phase of the data analysis process is the preparation phase. The results of a data analysis test will only be as good as the data used for the analysis. Thus, before running tests on the data, the fraud examiner must make certain the data being analyzed are relevant and reliable for the objective of the engagement. During the preparation phase of the data analysis process, the fraud examiner must complete several important steps, including: Identifying the relevant data Obtaining the requested data Verifying the data Cleansing and normalizing the data"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "When shifting from assessment questions to admission-seeking questions, the fraud examiner should provide a transitional theme that is designed to make the subject believe that he has been caught.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A transitional theme is necessary when proceeding from assessment-seeking questions to admission-seeking questions. In part, the theme should be designed to make the subject believe that he has been caught. Under the ideal circumstance, the interviewer should leave the room for a few minutes before proceeding to admission-seeking questions, saying that he has to “check on something.”"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Steganography refers to procedures used to convert information using an algorithm (called a cipher) that makes the information unreadable.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Encryption refers to procedures used to convert information using an algorithm (called a cipher) that makes the information unreadable. Steganography is the process of hiding one piece of information within an apparently innocent file. For example, a user can use the least significant bits of a bitmap image to hide a message. By hiding the message in the least significant bits of an image, there is almost no perceivable change in the bitmap image itself. And without directly comparing the altered image to the original, it is practically impossible to tell that the image was altered."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Tangible evidence is more volatile than digital evidence because tangible information is subject to claims of spoliation, whereas digital evidence is not.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Digital evidence is more volatile than tangible information because digital data can be altered or destroyed more easily than tangible information. Additionally, both digital and tangible evidence are subject to claims of spoliation (the act of intentionally or negligently destroying documents relevant to litigation). If proven, such claims could lead to monetary fines and sanctions, adverse inference jury instruction sanctions, or dismissal of claims or defenses."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Suppose you suspect there is a ghost employee scheme taking place in your organization and you want to compare the payroll records to the employee master file. Which data analysis technique would you use to match these two data records?", "options": {"A": "The Join function", "B": "Correlation analysis", "C": "Compliance verification", "D": "Gap testing"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The Join function gathers the specified parts of different data files. Joining files combines fields from two sorted input files into a third file. Join is used to match data in a transaction file with records in a master file, such as matching invoice data in an accounts receivable file to a master cluster. For example, you might need to compare two different files to find differing records between them."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Before removing a computer system from a scene for further analysis, it is important to document the system's setup with photographs or diagrams.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The first step in the evidence-collection process is to examine and document the machine’s surroundings. The party seizing the computer should collect all printouts, disks, notes, and other physical evidence for further analysis, and he should document the scene with photographs or a diagram, depending on the complexity of the setup. Documenting the machine’s surroundings is important because the party seizing the computer might have to testify about what the area looked like on the day of the seizure, and it might be a year or longer before such testimony occurs."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "In admission-seeking interviews, the transition from the accusatory process to the verbal confession should occur when the accused provides the first detailed information about the offense.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In an admission-seeking interview, the interviewer should transition to the verbal confession when the accused provides the first detailed information about the offense. There are three general approaches to obtaining the verbal confession: chronologically, by transaction, or by event. The approach taken should be governed by the circumstances of the case. Once a verbal confession is obtained, the interviewer must probe gently for additional details—preferably details that only the subject knows."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Which of the following is an appropriate moral excuse clause to include in a signed confession?", "options": {"A": "\"I didn't know it was illegal.\"", "B": "“I didn’t mean to do it.\"", "C": "“I didn’t mean to hurt anyone.\"", "D": "“I didn’t do it on purpose.\""}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The signed statement should include the confessor’s moral excuse, but the fraud examiner should ensure that the wording of the excuse clause does not diminish legal responsibility. Instead of using language like “I didn’t mean to do it,” which implies lack of intent, the interviewer should focus on an excuse that provides only a moral explanation for the misconduct."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a data analysis function that can be performed to help detect fraud through examination of asset accounts?", "options": {"A": "Compare book and tax depreciation and indicate variances", "B": "Select samples for asset existence verification", "C": "Recalculate expense and reserve amounts using replacement costs", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following are examples of data analysis queries that can be performed by data analysis software on asset accounts to help detect fraud: Generate depreciation to cost reports. Compare book and tax depreciation and indicate variances. Sort asset values by asset type or monetary amount. Select samples for asset existence verification. Recalculate expense and reserve/provision amounts using replacement costs."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "If you are seizing a computer for forensic analysis, it is generally not necessary to seize copiers connected to it.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Copiers, scanners, and other multifunction devices—machines that provide printing, copying, scanning, and faxing functionalities in one device—have internal hard drives that might contain information relevant to a fraud examination. In fact, almost every copier built since 2002 has a hard drive that stores images of documents the machines have copied, scanned, or emailed. Some copiers store user access records and a history of copies made. And, as with most file systems, it might be possible to retrieve information from a copier’s hard drive that has been deleted. So, when seizing a computer for forensic analysis, it is generally necessary to seize any copiers connected to it."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Once a suspect has confessed in an interview, it is important to get copies of as much physical evidence as possible. Bank records are of particular importance. Which of the following is the recommended method for obtaining bank records after a confession?", "options": {"A": "Obtain an oral authorization for the release of the bank records.", "B": "Ask the subject to bring the records to the next interview session.", "C": "Obtain a separate written authorization for the release of the bank records.", "D": "Ask to meet the subject the next day at his bank."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Interviewers should obtain physical evidence from the confessor—regardless of how limited it might be. In many instances, fraudsters deposit illicit income directly into their bank accounts. The interviewer should typically ask the confessor to voluntarily surrender his banking records for review. It is recommended that either (1) a separate written authorization be obtained or (2) specific language be added to the confession noting the voluntary surrender of banking information. The first method is generally preferable."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Generally, it is an indication of deception when an interview subject accused of fraud becomes angry while denying wrongdoing.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When accused of wrongdoing, the typical guilty person reacts with silence. If the accused does deny culpability, those denials are usually weak. In some cases, the accused almost mumbles the denial. It is common for culpable individuals to avoid outright denials. Rather, they give reasons why they could not have committed the act in question. Conversely, innocent people sometimes react with genuine shock at being accused. It is not at all unusual for an innocent person who is wrongfully accused to react with anger. In contrast to the guilty person, the typical innocent person will strongly deny committing the act or acts in question."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Prior to conducting an interview, an investigator should prepare a thorough list of questions to ensure that the interview is well structured and that no predetermined lines of inquiry are forgotten.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Whenever possible, do not prepare a list of predetermined questions to ask the subject. The interview should flow freely. The interviewer might, however, want to develop a list of key points to cover during the interview. Also, do not provide the subject with a list of predetermined questions. Allowing the respondent to read a written list of questions can give him an opportunity to fabricate his answer."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a data analysis function that can be performed to detect fraud through an examination of the general ledger?", "options": {"A": "Analyze and confirm specific ledger accounts for legitimate transaction activity", "B": "Create actual-to-budget comparison reports", "C": "Calculate financial ratios", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following are typical examples of data analysis queries that can be performed by data analysis software on the general ledger: Select specific journal entries for analysis. Create actual-to-budget comparison reports. Analyze and confirm specific ledger accounts for legitimate transaction activity. Speed account reconciliation through specialized account queries. Calculate financial ratios. Calculate percentage comparison ratio between accounts. Prepare custom reports, cash flow, profit/loss, and asset and liability total reports. Compare summaries by major account in any order (low-high, high-low). Create reports in any format by account, division, department, etc."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "When a potentially deceptive interview respondent asks the interviewer to repeat a question or repeats the question himself, the respondent is usually just trying to make sure that he has fully understood the question being asked.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Repeating the question is a means for a deceptive respondent to gain more time to think of what to say. The respondent might repeat the question verbatim or might frame the answer with a request to repeat the question (e.g., “What was that again?” or similar language). Conversely, a truthful subject usually does not have to contemplate an answer."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following is a data analysis tool that is effective in identifying indirect relationships and relationships with several degrees of separation?", "options": {"A": "Geospatial analysis", "B": "Tree maps", "C": "Word maps", "D": "Link analysis"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Link analysis software is used by fraud examiners to create visual representations (e.g., charts with lines showing connections) of data from multiple data sources to track the movement of money; demonstrate complex networks; and discover communications, patterns, trends, and relationships. Link analysis is very effective for identifying indirect relationships and relationships with several degrees of separation. For this reason, link analysis is particularly useful when conducting a money laundering investigation, since it can track the placement, layering, and integration of money as it moves around unexpected sources. It could also be used to detect a fictitious vendor (shell company) scheme. For instance, the investigator could map visual connections between a variety of entities that share an address and bank account number to reveal a fictitious vendor created to embezzle funds from a company."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In interview situations, ______________ is defined as a \"harmonious accord or relation that fosters cooperation, communication, or trust.\"", "options": {"A": "Rapport", "B": "Active listening", "C": "Norming", "D": "Calibration"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Merriam-Webster's Dictionary defines rapport as a \"harmonious accord or relation that fosters cooperation, communication, or trust.\" In other words, there must be some common ground established before questioning begins. This is usually accomplished by the interviewer spending a few minutes engaging the respondent in casual conversation. For example, the interviewer might pay the respondent a compliment, make a joke, or ask a friendly question. This aspect, however, should not be overdone, as most people are aware that the interviewer is there for a meaningful purpose."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "The information in a computer system’s event logs can yield valuable evidence because such logs record events and transactions that have occurred on the computer.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Every operating system generates event logs, or files that record events or transactions on a computer. In fact, a log entry is created for each event or transaction that takes place on any computer, and consequently, there are numerous types of event logs. Some common types of logs include system logs, application logs, and security logs. System logs record events executed on an operating system, including miscellaneous events and those generated during system startup, like hardware and controller failures. Common types of system events include starting up and shutting down, configuration updates, and system crashes. Application logs record the events regarding access to application data. Such events would include data files being opened or closed; specific actions such as reading, editing, deleting, or printing of application files; or the modification of records in an application file. Security logs track security-related events like logon and logoff times and changes to access rights."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "During the analysis phase in digital forensic investigations, the fraud examiner’s primary concern is to protect the collected information from seizure.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The primary concern when analyzing digital evidence is to maintain the integrity of the data at all times. Fraud examiners must be especially careful with computer equipment because a careless investigator might inadvertently alter important evidence. Therefore, it is helpful to develop procedures to prevent the opposing party from raising allegations that the methodology used to collect or analyze data was improper and could have damaged or altered the evidence."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Which of the following would NOT be an acceptable section to include in a written fraud examination report?", "options": {"A": "A findings section that summarizes the facts and findings of the examination", "B": "A conclusion section that evaluates the guilt or innocence of the suspect(s)", "C": "A scope section that describes the range of issues reviewed in the examination", "D": "An executive summary section that gives an overview of what occurred during the investigation"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "While there are many report forms and each might serve its own purpose, the following sections generally should be included in written fraud examination reports: Background: Generally, a written report should contain a background section. The background section should state why the fraud examination was conducted (e.g., an anonymous tip was received, an anomaly was discovered during an audit, money or property was missing). Executive summary: A written report should also include an executive summary, which should provide the reader with an overview of what was done during the examination process. Scope: Generally, a written report should include a section that identifies the examination’s scope. Approach: A written report should include a section about the approach used. Findings: A written report should include a section that summarizes the investigation findings. Summary: A written report should include a summary of the results of the fraud examination. Impact: A written report should also include a section addressing the impact of any misconduct identified during the investigation. Follow-up/recommendations: If requested, a written report might include a section for recommendations related to procedures and controls; however, it is better for the fraud examiner to convey recommendations related to flawed internal controls and other organizational failings to management in person or in a separate document. Opinions or conclusions concerning the guilt or innocence of a fraud suspect is outside the scope of a fraud examination and should never be included in a report."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning court records is most accurate?", "options": {"A": "There are multiple databases that contain a comprehensive database of court documents from all court cases in every country.", "B": "When searching for records for a particular court case, a fraud examiner needs only to search the central/federal court records, as they serve as a repository for all cases heard at all court levels.", "C": "In most countries, court records are not public records and require judicial authorization to access.", "D": "In most countries, reliable court records are best obtained from the court in which the case was heard or filed."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A great deal of litigation occurs each year, and many people might be subject to judicial action, voluntarily or not. Court records are a common direct and indirect source of information for fraud examinations. Many jurisdictions allow fraud examiners to search court records, and there are also a variety of services that compile and search such records. To perform court records searches, fraud examiners need to be familiar with the structure of the jurisdiction’s court system. Many jurisdictions implement a tiered court structure in which minor offenses and causes of action (e.g., small claims) are held in one set of courts and more serious offenses or issues are held in another set. Similarly, a jurisdiction might have courts that are divided based on local/municipal, state/provincial, and central/federal levels of government. Court records are typically maintained by a clerk or administrative office of the court that heard the case. However, there might be an agency that maintains records from multiple court levels. Therefore, to conduct a thorough search of court records, fraud examiners might need to search at multiple court levels. It is rare for there to be a central public database that maintains all court records at every level of a jurisdiction, and there are no parties that maintain a comprehensive database of court records on a global basis (despite what some records merchants might claim)."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "A memorandum that outlines the basis for a covert operation should state which of the following?", "options": {"A": "The information expected to be gained", "B": "The operatives under the fraud examiner’s care or control", "C": "The identities of any known suspects", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Before conducting a covert operation, it is essential that the basis for the operation be committed to writing, preferably in a memorandum. The memorandum should clearly state: The information upon which the covert operation will be based The information that is expected to be gained from the operation The identities of suspects, if known Operatives under the fraud examiner's care, custody, or control (confidential sources’ identities should not be disclosed, but such sources should be referred to with a symbol)"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "If a fraud examiner was gathering information about a fraud suspect, which of the following types of information would likely require access to nonpublic sources of information to obtain?", "options": {"A": "Where the subject currently resides", "B": "The subject’s phone records", "C": "The subject’s habits and lifestyle", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Nonpublic records—financial or otherwise—might be needed to prove fraud or to provide leads in a fraud examination. Nonpublic records include information about a person or business considered to be private and confidential. Nonpublic records are not available to everyone, and because fraud examiners do not have an absolute right to see these personal records, obtaining access might be difficult or impossible. Some of the most valuable types of personal records include: Banking records Tax records Credit records of individuals Phone records Credit card account records Personal health care records"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "In many jurisdictions, when an individual purchases real estate, he usually becomes a registrant in which of the following records?", "options": {"A": "Real property records", "B": "Tax assessor records", "C": "Property tax records", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Real property records are extremely important, and in many jurisdictions, they are relatively easy to access and contain a vast amount of information. It is common for real property records to be found at the local level of government, but some jurisdictions might keep them at a centralized location. When an individual purchases real estate, he becomes a registrant in real property records, property tax records, and tax assessor records (if applicable)."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "During which phase of the data analysis process does the fraud examiner identify, obtain, and verify the relevant or requested data?", "options": {"A": "The planning phase", "B": "The preparation phase", "C": "The testing and interpretation phase", "D": "The post-analysis phase"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The second phase of the data analysis process is the preparation phase. The results of a data analysis test will only be as good as the data used for the analysis. Thus, before running tests on the data, the fraud examiner must make certain the data being analyzed are relevant and reliable for the objective of the engagement. During the preparation phase of the data analysis process, the fraud examiner must complete several important steps, including: Identifying the relevant data Obtaining the requested data Verifying the data Cleansing and normalizing the data"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which type of question is used to establish the respondent’s credibility?", "options": {"A": "Closed", "B": "Assessment", "C": "Leading", "D": "Open"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Assessment questions seek to establish the respondent's credibility. They are used only when the interviewer considers previous statements by the respondent to be inconsistent because of possible deception. When evaluating a subject’s response to an assessment question for credibility, it is critical to observe both verbal and nonverbal reactions."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "Spencer, a fraud examiner, plans to use a confidential informant. The informant agrees to aid Spencer in exchange for cash. Spencer prepares a receipt for the transfer of cash to the informant and asks the informant to sign it, but the informant refuses. What should Spencer do?", "options": {"A": "Have a witness observe the transfer of cash and sign a statement attesting to the transaction", "B": "Give the informant the cash, but make no record of the transaction", "C": "Refuse to pay the cash without a receipt, even if it means the informant will not aid Spencer", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "If the fraud examiner decides to pay an informant or source, he should make the payment in cash and obtain a receipt. If the source will not sign a receipt, the fraud examiner should not pay him. There have been numerous instances where a receipt was not obtained and the informant subsequently denied receiving funds or challenged the amount paid. If this happens, the fraud examiner will have to defend himself without proof; indeed, some investigators have been accused of having embezzled the payments. Payments should only be made on a cash-on-delivery-of-information basis."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Which of the following best describes the image acquisition process used in examinations involving digital evidence?", "options": {"A": "Analyzing the system's data in order to identify evidence", "B": "Taking photos of the digital equipment’s physical layout and connections", "C": "Acquiring the digital evidence from the suspect", "D": "Creating an exact duplicate of the data on original storage media"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Once a computer system is seized and before any analysis occurs, it should be imaged for analysis. Forensic analysis should not be performed on suspect devices directly because doing so can alter or damage digital evidence, and imaging the data from suspect devices allows a fraud examiner to view and analyze a computer's contents without altering the original data in any way. Imaging refers to the process whereby a forensic image of a hard drive or other digital media is made and imaged to another hard disk drive or other media for forensic analysis. A forensic image (also called a forensic copy, mirror image, or ghost image) is a duplicate or exact copy of a hard drive or other digital media."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Link analysis is particularly useful when investigating which type of fraud scheme?", "options": {"A": "Shell company", "B": "Fictitious vendor", "C": "Money laundering", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Link analysis software is used by fraud examiners to create visual representations (e.g., charts with lines showing connections) of data from multiple data sources to track the movement of money; demonstrate complex networks; and discover communications, patterns, trends, and relationships. Link analysis is very effective for identifying indirect relationships and relationships with several degrees of separation. For this reason, link analysis is particularly useful when conducting a money laundering investigation, since it can track the placement, layering, and integration of money as it moves around unexpected sources. It could also be used to detect a fictitious vendor (shell company) scheme. For instance, the investigator could map visual connections between a variety of entities that share an address and bank account number to reveal a fictitious vendor created to embezzle funds from a company."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following functions does a Benford’s Law analysis help to achieve?", "options": {"A": "Extracting usable information from unstructured text data", "B": "Measuring the relationship between items on financial statements by expressing accounts as percentages", "C": "Identifying fictitious numbers", "D": "Identifying duplicate payments"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The goal of a Benford’s Law analysis is to identify fictitious numbers. Benford’s Law provides that the distribution of the digits in multi-digit natural numbers is not random; instead, it follows a predictable pattern. That is, Benford’s Law maintains that certain digits show up more than others do when dealing with natural numbers. A “1” appears as the first non-zero digit roughly 30% of the time; “2” is the leading digit almost 18% of the time; and “9” leads off only 4.6% of the time. Moreover, “0” is most likely to be the second digit, appearing 12% of the time. Many fraudsters fail to consider the Benford’s Law pattern when creating false documentation or transactions to cover their tracks. Consequently, testing data sets for the occurrence or non-occurrence of the predictable digit distribution can help identify included numbers that are not legitimate."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Which of the following is a measure that can be taken to avoid alerting suspected perpetrators who are under investigation?", "options": {"A": "Inform only those who need to know", "B": "Know what information the suspect can access", "C": "Investigate during nonbusiness hours", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When responding to a sign or allegation of fraud, those responsible must work to avoid alerting those suspected of fraud. The following are some basic measures that organizations and fraud examiners can take to avoid notifying suspected perpetrators who are under investigation: Know who is being investigated and what they can access. Limit the extent of any discussions. Inform only those who need to know. Inform employees of the consequences of a confidentiality breach. Work discreetly without disrupting the office's normal course of business so that employees do not know that an investigation is being performed. Work fast. Investigate during nonbusiness hours."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "When asked a \"yes\" or \"no\" question, it is generally easier for an individual to answer \"yes\" than it is to answer \"no.\"", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Throughout the interview process—from the introduction to the close—the interviewer should seek continual agreement by attempting to phrase the questions so that they can be answered “yes.” It is generally easier for people to reply in the affirmative than in the negative."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following types of investigations would generally benefit from investigating external sources of information?", "options": {"A": "Searching for ownership of competitors and vendors", "B": "Conducting a background investigation", "C": "Locating assets and witnesses", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A large amount of information and documentary evidence can be gathered from external sources. External sources can be particularly crucial in helping investigators locate missing assets; locate witnesses and suspects; determine ownership in vendors, competitors, and other related parties; research the suspects' assets and financial condition; and document the suspects' lifestyle and background information. All of this information will help an investigator build a case and will provide the basis for conducting interviews and obtaining confessions later in the investigation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Suppose you need to prove a suspect’s illicit income circumstantially. Which of the following methods of tracing assets would yield the best result when the suspect is spending his illicit funds on items that would not cause an increase in net worth, such as travel and entertainment?", "options": {"A": "The bank deposits method", "B": "The income correlation method", "C": "The expenditures method", "D": "The asset method"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The expenditures method (also known as the sources and application of funds method) compares the suspect’s known expenditures and known sources of funds during a given period of time. That is, this analysis seeks to quantify the cost of the subject’s lifestyle and determine whether the subject’s reported income is sufficient to support his lifestyle. The expenditures method is best used when the subject spends illicit income on consumables (e.g., travel and entertainment) that would not cause an increase in net worth."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following pieces of information about financed personal property can be found in a commercial filing?", "options": {"A": "The name of the debtor or joint debtors", "B": "The type of collateral pledged as security", "C": "The name of the financial lender or creditor", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Commercial filings are records that can help fraud examiners identify personal property that an individual or business has financed. Banks, finance companies, and other lenders will generate records or recorded filings of financial transactions conducted with individuals and businesses, such as purchases of household furniture, appliances, boats and yachts, automobiles, aircraft, and business equipment. To secure repayment, the financing party retains an interest in the debtor’s property. This interest is referred to as a security interest or a charge, depending on the jurisdiction. To document this interest, the creditors might create a commercial filing, which will be publicly searchable in some jurisdictions. In jurisdictions where commercial filings are not public record, access might be restricted to those who have a court order compelling the records' release or a relationship with the debtor or creditor. These filings might help to identify: Name(s) of the debtor or joint debtors Current address of the debtor Name of the financial lender or creditor Type of collateral pledged as security Date of filing and continuations"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Tobias, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is conducting an admission-seeking interview of Frederik, a fraud suspect. Tobias has a great deal of documentary evidence that he plans on using to diffuse Frederik's alibis. The proper technique for using the evidence is for Tobias to display it all at once so that Frederik will be demoralized by the overwhelming amount of evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "One technique for diffusing alibis is to display the evidence. It is common for most guilty people to overestimate the amount of physical evidence. The interviewer should try to reinforce this notion in the way the evidence is presented to the accused. The physical evidence—usually documents in fraud matters—generally should be displayed one piece at a time, in reverse order of importance. In this way, the accused does not immediately know the full extent of the evidence. When the accused no longer denies culpability, the interviewer should stop displaying evidence. Each time a document or piece of evidence is presented to the accused, the interviewer should note its significance. During this phase, the accused is still trying to determine how to react to being caught. The interviewer should, therefore, expect that the accused will attempt to lie his way out of the situation. Like denials, the interviewer should stop the alibis and other falsehoods before they are fully articulated."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "When drafting a written fraud examination report, fraud examiners should, whenever possible, include technical jargon to demonstrate expertise in the accurate detection of fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraud examination reports must show clarity. Thus, fraud examiners should try to avoid using jargon because the report might be read by people who are not familiar with esoteric or technical terminology. Use complex or technical terms in their proper contexts, and, where necessary, explain their meaning."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "An organization’s fraud response plan should outline how the organization will conduct fraud examinations in every single case, regardless of the type of fraud being conducted.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When evidence of misconduct arises, management must respond in an appropriate and timely manner. During the initial response, time is critical. To help ensure that an organization responds to suspicious fraud-related activity efficiently, management should have a response plan in place. A fraud response plan outlines the actions that members of an organization will take when suspicions of fraud have arisen. Because every fraud is different, the response plan should not specify how every fraud examination should be conducted. Instead, it should help organizations manage their responses and create environments to minimize risk and maximize the potential for success. While the appropriate response will vary based on the event, management should include a range of scenarios in the response plan, taking into consideration previous frauds within the organization and fraud risks specific to the industry or business sector in which it operates."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In the context of an interview with a fraud suspect, which of the following is a nonverbal indication of deception?", "options": {"A": "The suspect is facing the interviewer while his hips and legs are shifted toward the door", "B": "The suspect leans away from the interviewer when asked a tough question", "C": "The suspect manipulates objects or uses excessive illustrators when responding to questions", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Nonverbal clues refer to clues that are illustrated by an individual’s body language. When asked sensitive or emotive questions, the dishonest person will sometimes change his posture completely, as if moving away from the interviewer. He also might manipulate objects, use excessive illustrators, and adopt a fleeing position. Nonverbal indications of deception include: Full-body motions away from the interviewer Physical responses such as sweating or labored breathing Changes in the use of illustrators Interruptions to the flow of speech Hands over the mouth Manipulation of objects such as a pencil Body positioned in a fleeing position Crossing of the arms Unnatural or casual reaction to evidence"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "Keeping track of the amount of paper generated is one of the biggest challenges in fraud cases. Which of the following is generally NOT a recommended practice when organizing evidence?", "options": {"A": "Segregate documents by witness.", "B": "File all papers chronologically.", "C": "Establish a database early.", "D": "Make a key document file."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Keeping track of the amount of paper generated is one of the biggest problems in fraud cases. Effective organization in complex cases includes the following: Segregating documents by either witness or transaction Making a key document file for easy access to the most relevant documents Establishing a database early in the investigation During the evidence-gathering stage of an investigation, organizing the documents chronologically is not recommended because it makes searching for relevant information more difficult. It is generally better to organize the documents by transaction or by party. The fraud examination report often follows a chronological timeline to give a narrative of a fraud scheme, in which case displaying key documents chronologically often makes sense. But in the organization phase, there usually is too much clutter for chronological organization to be effective."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Turnbull, a fraud victim, hired Kennedy, a CFE, to trace a fraudster’s assets to facilitate the recovery of the illicit proceeds obtained by the fraudster. Which of the following typically will be the MOST useful source of information for Kennedy in his efforts to trace the fraudster’s assets?", "options": {"A": "Surveillance footage", "B": "Third-party witnesses", "C": "The fraudster’s paystubs", "D": "The fraudster’s bank records"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Records obtained from financial institutions are perhaps the single most important financial source available to a fraud examiner for asset-tracing purposes. They can be used as evidence for fraud, as well as to: Identify witnesses and other evidence. Uncover criminal profits. Identify criminal assets. Locate assets that can be used to satisfy a judgment. Identify localities where assets are stored. Determine the lifestyle of an account holder. Determine the financial health of an organization. Determine the source of funds placed into an account. Determine the use of the funds from an account."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "Jones, a Certified Fraud Examiner and director of security for ABC Inc., obtained several boxes of documents while conducting a fraud examination. While inventorying the boxes and marking the evidence, Jones discovers a stock certificate he feels will be damaged if he marks it with his initials and the date. To maintain the proper chain of custody, Jones should:", "options": {"A": "Photograph and store the document.", "B": "Place the document in a marked envelope.", "C": "Mark the document regardless of the potential for damage.", "D": "Copy the document, and initial and date the copy."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "To preserve the chain of custody, all evidence received should be marked so that it can later be identified. The most common way to mark the evidence is with the date and initials of the person obtaining the documents. If it is not practical to mark the document, or if marking it would damage the document, then it should be placed in an acid-free envelope that has been marked and sealed. To avoid creating indentations on the original document, do not write on the envelope after the document has been placed inside of it."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "The verbal and nonverbal clues to deception are produced primarily by stress.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In most people, lying produces stress. The human body will attempt to relieve this stress (even in practiced liars) through verbal and nonverbal clues. Conclusions concerning behavior must be tempered by a number of factors. The physical environment in which the interview is conducted can affect behavior. If the respondent is comfortable, he might exhibit fewer behavioral quirks. The more intelligent the respondent, the more reliable verbal and nonverbal clues will be. If the respondent is biased toward the interviewer, or vice versa, this will affect behavior. In detecting deception during an interview, the interviewer must remember that the interviewee or target might already be under stress because of the situation. While lying and deception do indeed cause stress, it is not necessarily true that all stress exhibited during an interview is caused by lying."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In interview situations, a(n)______________ is any social-psychological barrier that impedes the flow of relevant information by making the respondent unwilling or unable to provide information to the interviewer.", "options": {"A": "Antecedent", "B": "Repressor", "C": "Facilitator", "D": "Inhibitor"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To be an effective interviewer, one must understand that certain matters inhibit communication, while others facilitate it. It is the interviewer's task to minimize inhibitors and maximize facilitators. An inhibitor is any social-psychological barrier that impedes the flow of relevant information by making the respondent unable or unwilling to provide the information to the interviewer."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "A fraud examiner is planning how he will organize and present information in the report writing stage of a fraud examination. Which of the following statements is most accurate?", "options": {"A": "The fraud examiner should present the information either by transaction or chronologically.", "B": "The fraud examiner should only present the information chronologically.", "C": "The fraud examiner should present the information alphabetically with respect to parties and document titles.", "D": "The fraud examiner should present the information either by transaction or by party."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Because of the amount of information and the number of documents that might be collected during a fraud examination, it is imperative that the fraud examiner properly organize the information. If circumstances permit, an information database should be established in the early phases of the case. Information can be presented either in chronological order or by transaction when writing the fraud examination report. In contrast, during the evidence-gathering stage of an investigation, chronologically organizing the documents that will later be used in drafting the report is not recommended because it will make searching for relevant information more difficult. It is generally better to organize documents by transaction or by party while evidence gathering is still occurring."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is LEAST likely to be revealed by analyzing a subject’s electronic payment records?", "options": {"A": "If the subject is skimming employer funds", "B": "Loans the subject has obtained", "C": "The cities and countries in which the subject conducts business", "D": "The locations of the subject’s assets"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Electronic payments (or e-payments) refers to any type of noncash payment that does not involve a paper check. Electronic payment records can reveal, among other things: Assets the subject has purchased The locations of the subject’s assets (e.g., through the payment of real estate taxes, broker’s fees, or utility payments) The locations of the subject’s residences and businesses (e.g., through analyzing the payments of utility bills) Loans the subject has obtained (e.g., through analyzing loan payments) Payments made to nonexistent employees with direct deposit The cities and countries in which the subject conducts business (e.g., through analyzing the payments for carrier services to deliver packages) Transfers of funds between individuals without an established business relationship Assets ostensibly owned by family members or close associates but effectively controlled, held, or gifted by the subject Hotel payments The true owner of a property (e.g., through analyzing the mortgage payments and payments for home owner insurance)"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "A fraud examiner discovers a paper document believed to include both the suspect’s indented writings and latent fingerprints. Which of the following is the BEST preservation method to use when collecting the document?", "options": {"A": "Insert the document into a plastic bag using a pair of tweezers.", "B": "Put the document in a briefcase for analysis at a later point in time.", "C": "Leave the document in place for a forensic document examiner to collect later.", "D": "Place the document into a sealable, acid-free paper envelope while handling it with protective gloves."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fraud examiners should preserve evidentiary documents that contain latent fingerprints by placing them into labeled protective containers, such as sealable, acid-free paper envelopes. Many types of paper and plastic containers can leach acids that damage originals over long periods of storage. While some plastic containers, such as those made of polyethylene or polypropylene, do not leach acid, they might cause harmful condensation to develop on the document. To avoid smudging and contamination of the fingerprints, fraud examiners should wear protective gloves or carefully use tweezers when handling latent fingerprint evidence. However, tweezers should not be used on documents if indented writing or photocopier examinations are planned."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Accessing commercial filings will help identify:", "options": {"A": "Real estate ownership information", "B": "Personal property that is subject to a security interest or a charge", "C": "A list of all companies that an individual is an officer or registered agent of", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Commercial filings are records that can help fraud examiners identify personal property that an individual or business has financed. Banks, finance companies, and other lenders will generate records or recorded filings of financial transactions conducted with individuals and businesses, such as purchases of household furniture, appliances, boats and yachts, automobiles, aircraft, and business equipment (but not real estate; these records are only for personal property). To secure repayment, the financing party retains an interest in the debtor’s property. This interest is referred to as a security interest or a charge, depending on the jurisdiction. To document this interest, the creditors might create a commercial filing, which will be publicly searchable in some jurisdictions. In jurisdictions where commercial filings are not public record, access might be restricted to those who have a court order compelling the records' release or a relationship with the debtor or creditor. These filings might help to identify: Name(s) of the debtor or joint debtors Current address of the debtor Name of the financial lender or creditor Type of collateral pledged as security Date of filing and continuations"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "In many jurisdictions, all of the following information can usually be obtained from real property records EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Who financed the purchase of a property, if applicable", "B": "A property owner’s credit report", "C": "The addresses of a property's buyer and seller", "D": "A property’s historical sales price"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Real property records are extremely important, and in many jurisdictions, they are relatively easy to access and contain a vast amount of information. It is common for real property records to be found at the local level of government, but some jurisdictions might keep them at a centralized location. When an individual purchases real estate, he becomes a registrant in real property records, property tax records, and tax assessor records (if applicable). Most jurisdictions have a land registry office that maintains various information on real property and its owner(s). Both the level of government where these records are found and the information they contain will vary by jurisdiction, but the following information is often present: Documents pertaining to real estate transactions—including deeds, grants, transfers and mortgages of real estate, releases of mortgages, powers of attorney, and leases that have been acknowledged or approved Mortgages on real property Security interests or liens on property Wills admitted to probate Official bonds Notices of mechanic’s liens Transcripts of judgments that are made liens on real estate Notices of attachment on real estate Land cadastre (a registry of land surveys that specifically detail each plot of real estate in an area and may contain information about value, ownership rights, and other details) Papers in connection with bankruptcy Certified copies of decrees and judgments of courts of record Other documents permitted by law to be recorded Historical sale prices Residences and addresses of the buyer and seller Identity of the party financing the property, if applicable Improvements to a property A credit report involves a third party’s assessment of a person’s credit history and capacity to take out and repay debt; this information is not found in public property records."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following pieces of information is usually contained on the signature card of a personal bank account?", "options": {"A": "The identification number of the person opening the account", "B": "The address of the person opening the account", "C": "The name of the person opening the account", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To open a personal account, the individual opening the account must provide a signature card, or similar document, evidencing a contract between the customer and bank. The signature card is a source of valuable information. Although its form varies, the card usually contains the person’s name, address, telephone number, identification number, amount of the opening deposit (and possibly the source of the opening deposit), and security data (e.g., mother’s maiden name). The person’s identification information might be significant, especially if the depositor used an alias. Also, a fraud examiner might be able to trace the opening deposit through the bank’s records to disclose a source of income."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is the type of covert operation in which a fraud examiner uses disguise and deceit to actively seek out evidence from people involved in the offense?", "options": {"A": "A surveillance operation", "B": "An entrapment operation", "C": "An undercover operation", "D": "An informant operation"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The two main forms of covert operations are undercover operations and surveillance operations. Undercover operations often use deception and disguise to obtain evidence directly from those involved in the illicit activity. Agents engaged in undercover operations actively attempt to elicit the desired information. In contrast, surveillance operations use observation to gather information about individuals suspected of misconduct. For example, a surveillance operation might involve observing a suspect from afar while he meets with a potential co-conspirator. Alternatively, the investigator might pose as the co-conspirator’s agent and engage the suspect in conversation in an attempt to gather information; this would be an example of an undercover operation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "When gathering information for a fraud investigation, virtually all helpful documentary evidence will come from internal sources.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Internal sources—those generated and kept within the subject organization—are often the only resource for certain types of documents, such as private business tax records or employee personnel files, unless the fraud examiner has the subject’s consent or a legal order to obtain those documents from other parties. Even so, a large amount of information and documentary evidence can also be gathered from external sources. External sources can be particularly crucial in helping investigators locate missing assets; locate witnesses and suspects; determine ownership in vendors, competitors, and other related parties; research the suspects’ assets and financial condition; and document the suspects' lifestyle and background information. All of this information will help an investigator build a case and will provide the basis for conducting interviews and obtaining confessions later in the investigation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "When evaluating a respondent's behavior for signs of deception during an interview, it is important that the interviewer remember that:", "options": {"A": "The interviewer cannot legally accuse the witness of deception", "B": "No single behavior should be isolated, and no single conclusion should be drawn from it", "C": "Most witnesses can hide the obvious signs of deception", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Because it is easy to draw the wrong conclusions when evaluating signs of deception, no single behavior should be isolated, and no single conclusion should be drawn from it. Behaviors should be considered together. For example, a subject’s failure to make eye contact during an interview is not necessarily proof of deception."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "When people engage in conversations, including interviews, they respond automatically with expressions that have little real meaning, such as \"Good morning\" and \"How are you today?\" These kinds of expressions are called:", "options": {"A": "Ritualistic", "B": "Expressionistic", "C": "Therapeutic", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Some aspects of conversation are ritualistic; that is, they merely are a form of verbal behavior that has no real significance other than to provide security in interpersonal relations. Examples include \"Good morning\" and \"How are you today?\" In interviewing, we must learn to detect ritualistic answers by the respondent and avoid giving them ourselves. The interviewer must be aware of the danger of engaging in ritualistic conversation and then confusing the results with valid information."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Management of the ABC Company hired Michael, a fraud examiner, to investigate Deborah, an employee in ABC’s accounting department, for embezzlement. According to the fraud examination methodology, which of the following individuals should Michael interview first?", "options": {"A": "Roger, an employee for the ABC Company, who is suspected of being an accomplice to Deborah’s scheme", "B": "John, Deborah’s spouse", "C": "Deborah", "D": "Amanda, a neutral employee, who is the director of ABC’s accounting department"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fraud examinations should begin with general information that is known, starting at the periphery, and then move to the more specific details. In most examinations, fraud examiners should start interviewing at the periphery of all possible interview candidates and move toward the witnesses who appear more involved in the matters that are the subject of the examination. Thus, neutral third-party witnesses should generally be interviewed first, followed by parties suspected of complicity, starting with the least culpable and moving to the most culpable. The primary suspect should be interviewed last."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE statement about the types of information that digital forensic experts typically can recover from computer systems?", "options": {"A": "Deleted files that have been overwritten generally cannot be recovered.", "B": "Data that are corrupted cannot be uncorrupted.", "C": "Hidden files can never be recovered.", "D": "Communications sent via chat or instant messenger cannot be recovered."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Digital forensics encompasses the recovery and investigation of material found in digital devices, and digital forensic experts are individuals who specialize in identifying, recovering, collecting, preserving, processing, and producing digital data for use in investigations and litigation. Sometimes retrieving digital data is as easy as searching the target computer’s hard drive, but other times retrieval requires a thorough knowledge of computers. For example, many fraudsters delete or hide incriminating files, and in these instances, efforts must be made to recover or find such data. There are, in fact, a variety of ways to recover deleted or hidden data from a target computer, and digital forensic experts are specially trained for such tasks. Specifically, digital forensic experts are capable of analyzing digital media at the hexadecimal level, which means that such experts can view every sector, and all the bytes in those sectors, on a system. Thus, digital forensic experts can recover data from deleted files, both those that have been purposefully deleted and those that were accidentally deleted. Deleted files are recoverable until they are overwritten because data are not erased from a computer’s hard drive until the operating system overwrites all or some of the files. So, deleted files that have been overwritten generally are not recoverable. Digital forensic specialists can recover, among other things, the following types of information from computers: Deleted files and other data that have not been overwritten (e.g., deleted documents, images, link or shortcut files, and email messages) Temporary auto-save files Print-spool files Websites visited, even where the browser history and cache have been deleted Communications sent via chat or instant messenger Financial-based Internet transactions Documents, letters, and images created, modified, or accessed, even if the data were not saved on the computer in some situations Data that have been copied, corrupted, or moved The time and date information about files (e.g., when files were created, accessed, modified, installed, deleted, or downloaded) Data from a drive that has been defragmented or reformatted"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Net worth can be defined as the difference between assets and liabilities at a particular point in time.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Net worth can be defined as the difference between assets and liabilities at a particular point in time."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a purpose of the follow-up/recommendations section of a written fraud examination report?", "options": {"A": "To identify any aspect of the investigation that remains outstanding", "B": "To calculate the amount of loss caused by any misconduct identified during the investigation", "C": "To state necessary remedial measures for the organization to undertake", "D": "To make recommendations related to procedures and controls"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A follow-up/recommendations section is generally an optional part of a written fraud examination report. This section identifies any aspect of the investigation that remains outstanding, usually because it is outside the mandate of the investigator. This could include the recovery of property that is in the possession of third parties or the collection of information held by vendors or suppliers. If requested, the fraud examiner might make recommendations related to procedures and controls; however, it is better for the fraud examiner to convey recommendations related to flawed internal controls and other organizational failings to management in person or in a separate document. If included in the primary report, this information could potentially be seized upon by defense attorneys at a trial or by representatives at an unemployment hearing to push blame away from the suspect’s actions and toward the organization’s shortcomings. Follow-ups or recommendations should state what action is necessary or recommended, including remedial measures such as a review of internal controls, the introduction of a fraud hotline, or an increase in security."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Beta, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is conducting a routine interview of someone who does not know him. In such situations, it is usually best for Beta to omit his title when introducing himself.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Beta must introduce himself before the interview commences. Generally, an interviewer should indicate his name and company, but he should avoid stating his title if possible. In some instances, the interviewer cannot avoid giving his title, and in such cases, the interviewer should use a title that will not conjure up emotions or possible fear in the respondent’s mind."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Which of the following is a recommended method for organizing and presenting information in a fraud examination report?", "options": {"A": "By party", "B": "Chronologically", "C": "By the order in which the information was discovered", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Because of the amount of information and the number of documents that might be collected during a fraud examination, it is imperative that the fraud examiner properly organize the information. If circumstances permit, an information database should be established in the early phases of the case. Information can be presented either in chronological order or by transaction when writing the fraud examination report. In contrast, during the evidence-gathering stage of an investigation, chronologically organizing the documents that will later be used in drafting the report is not recommended because it will make searching for relevant information more difficult. It is generally better to organize documents by transaction or by party while evidence gathering is still occurring."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "When a forensic investigator is seizing a running computer for examination, he can retrieve data from the computer directly via its normal interface if the evidence needed exists only in the form of volatile data.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When seizing a computer that is running, the party seizing the system should not, in most situations, search the computer for evidence because doing so might damage and taint relevant evidence. But in some situations, it might be appropriate to perform live evidence collection (i.e., collect evidence from a suspect system while the system is open and running via its normal interface). Generally, live evidence collection is appropriate when a formally trained computer investigator is seizing the system, and the evidence that the investigator needs to collect exists only in the form of volatile data."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Sullivan is conducting an interview with Marsha, a potential co-conspirator in a fraud scheme. Throughout the interview, Marsha continuously moves around in her chair and touches her hair, indicating that she is nervous and under stress. Based on these signs, Sullivan should conclude that Marsha is lying to him.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In detecting deception during an interview, the interviewer must remember that the interviewee or target might already be under stress because of the situation. While lying and deception do indeed cause stress, it is not necessarily true that all stress exhibited during an interview is caused by lying."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In the course of establishing rapport, it is important that an interviewer observe a subject’s reaction to normal conversation to establish a baseline against which answers to more sensitive questions can be compared.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "After the interviewer establishes rapport through normal conversation, he must observe the respondent’s reactions. This will serve as a baseline for observing behavior when questions that are more sensitive are asked. If the respondent’s verbal and nonverbal behaviors are inconsistent from one type of question to another, the interviewer should attempt to determine why."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "When conducting a data analysis engagement to detect fraud, it is important to build a profile of potential frauds before identifying, obtaining, and analyzing the data.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "To maximize the potential success of detecting fraud through data analysis, the analysis performed should be based on an understanding of the entity’s existing fraud risks. To do so, the fraud examiner must first build a profile of potential frauds by identifying the organization’s risk areas, the types of frauds possible in those risk areas, and the resulting exposure to those frauds. Using the profile of potential frauds as a guide, the fraud examiner must identify the target data for analysis. Specifically, for each specific fraud scenario assessed to be a high risk to the organization, the fraud examiner should determine which data fields and records would be affected by such a scheme. The fraud examiner must then identify the logistics involved with obtaining this information, including: What specific data (i.e., fields, records) are available Who generates and maintains the data Where the data are stored Timing of the data extraction (e.g., date range, cutoff dates/times) How the fraud examiner will receive and store the data (i.e., data format and storage/transfer mechanism) Control totals needed for verification How to validate the sources of data"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "If a fraud examiner thinks that information from a social media website will be used in court as evidence, the fraud examiner must take steps to capture the information so that it can be established as authentic.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Generally, documentary evidence, including digital evidence, will not be admitted in a legal proceeding, or it will not be given much weight, unless it is established as authentic (i.e., the evidence is what it purports to be and is in the same condition as when it was seized). There are a number of techniques used to authenticate information from social media. Often, authenticity can be established through the testimony of a witness who verifies that the exhibit at issue accurately reflects what he observed on the site, and typically, the witness is the party who collected the evidence. Consequently, fraud examiners who collect evidence from social media often become a form of eyewitness, and for this reason, fraud examiners must capture, download, and preserve any useful information as soon as they discover it. They must memorialize each step of the collection process, creating a record of what they see at any point in the investigation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Text-based data are typically considered:", "options": {"A": "Documentary data", "B": "Unstructured data", "C": "Structured data", "D": "Narrative data"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Data are either structured or unstructured. Structured data are the type of data found in a database, consisting of recognizable and predictable structures. Examples of structured data include sales records, payment or expense details, and financial reports. Unstructured data, by contrast, are data that would not be found in a traditional spreadsheet or database. They are typically text based."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Morris, a CFE, is investigating Crump, who is active on an online social networking site in which he voluntarily shares information about himself. Morris wants to search and extract information from Crump’s social network profile. Which of the following is the most accurate statement about the privacy of information Crump shared through his social network profile?", "options": {"A": "The Privacy of Social Networks Treaty is an international law that makes it illegal for Morris to seek the login credentials from Crump’s social networking account.", "B": "Morris could be liable for violating Crump’s privacy rights if he hacks or breaks into areas of the social networking site Crump has designated as private.", "C": "To access any information posted on Crump’s social network profile, Morris must obtain some type of legal order from the jurisdiction in which Crump resides.", "D": "To search for information that Crump posted and made available to the public through his social network profile, Morris must provide Crump notice beforehand."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Social media sites might contain valuable information. Fraud examiners are free to search and extract information from a subject’s page if it is open to the public, but there are limitations to the information fraud examiners can access on a social networking site due to privacy settings and anonymity. Many users set their privacy settings in a way that prevents anyone besides their friends from seeing their profile information, and this creates several issues of legal access and privacy rights. Accessing information that is set to private could result in claims under privacy laws. Thus, accessing information on social media sites that is restricted by privacy settings could result in liability for fraud examiners due to violation of users’ privacy rights. Privacy rights, however, vary between countries."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Which of the following is a limitation of conducting a search for public records using online databases?", "options": {"A": "Online coverage of public records varies widely from jurisdiction to jurisdiction", "B": "Information from online databases must be validated for accuracy and timeliness", "C": "Online public records searches are limited in the area they cover, often requiring fraud examiners to search multiple jurisdictions", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The main limitations of conducting searches for public records using online databases include: Online coverage of public records varies widely from jurisdiction to jurisdiction, and therefore, there are many degrees of accessibility to public records between jurisdictions. Online public records searches are limited in the area they cover. Therefore, when looking for information on a subject, fraud examiners often must search for public records in multiple jurisdictions. Often, online public records are brief abstracts of the original public record. The source of the information compiled in an online database must be reliable. Fraud examiners must validate information retrieved from online databases to determine if it is accurate and up-to-date. The public records compiled in an electronic format might cover only a limited period. Online searches can be erratic in the information they return."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "The primary purpose of an expert report is to document the results of a fraud examination.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A fraud examination report documents the results of a fraud examination and is generally created by one or more critical members of the fraud examination team. Documenting results is a particularly important function in fraud examinations. The fraud examination report conveys all evidence necessary to evaluate the case, and it can be used to corroborate previously known facts. An accurate report will add credibility to the fraud examination and to the fraud examiner’s work. Fraud examiners who serve as expert witnesses in litigation are tasked with providing an expert report, which requires them to provide particular information about their qualifications, their opinions, the bases of those opinions, and various other pieces of information. The purpose of an expert report is to inform the parties, the judge, and the jury (if applicable) about the expert’s opinion of the case, as well as his credibility for commenting on such issues."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is something that might be revealed by analyzing a subject’s electronic payment records?", "options": {"A": "Assets effectively controlled or held by the subject", "B": "Assets the subject has purchased", "C": "The cities and countries in which the subject conducts business", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Electronic payments (or e-payments) refers to any type of noncash payment that does not involve a paper check. Electronic payment records can reveal, among other things: Assets the subject has purchased The locations of the subject’s assets (e.g., through the payment of real estate taxes, broker’s fees, or utility payments) The locations of the subject’s residences and businesses (e.g., through analyzing the payments of utility bills) Loans the subject has obtained (e.g., through analyzing loan payments) Payments made to nonexistent employees with direct deposit The cities and countries in which the subject conducts business (e.g., through analyzing the payments for carrier services to deliver packages) Transfers of funds between individuals without an established business relationship Assets ostensibly owned by family members or close associates but effectively controlled, held, or gifted by the subject Hotel payments The true owner of a property (e.g., through analyzing the mortgage payments and payments for home owner insurance)"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "A fraud examiner is conducting textual analytics on journal entry data and runs a keyword search using the terms override, write off, and reserve/provision. With which leg of the Fraud Triangle are these fraud keywords typically associated?", "options": {"A": "Pressure", "B": "Capability", "C": "Rationalization", "D": "Opportunity"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In conducting a textual analytics examination, the fraud examiner should come up with a list of fraud keywords that are likely to point to suspicious activity. This list will depend on the industry, the suspected fraud schemes or types of fraud risk present, and the data set the fraud examiner has available. In other words, if he is running a search through journal entry details, he will likely search for different fraud keywords than if he were running a search of emails. The factors identified in the Fraud Triangle are helpful when coming up with a fraud keyword list. One of these factors is opportunity; consequently, the fraud examiner should consider how someone in the entity might have the opportunity to commit fraud. Examples of keywords that indicate the opportunity to commit fraud include override, write off, recognize revenue, adjust, discount, and reserve/provision."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Which of the following is considered a basic fraud examination reporting document?", "options": {"A": "Exhibits", "B": "Memoranda", "C": "Transmittal letter", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Reporting formats vary widely. Some organizations, especially governmental investigative bodies, use report forms so that case information is provided in a consistent manner. The basic reporting documents are: Memoranda Cover page Exhibits, documents, or enclosures Forms Indexes Transmittal letter"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Audrey wants to obtain bank account statements from her client’s employee, who she has reason to believe is accepting bribes in exchange for contract awards. Audrey asks the employee to turn over the account statements, but the employee refuses her request. Which of the following methods of obtaining the account statements would be IMPROPER?", "options": {"A": "Requesting the records from the bank and threatening to sue the bank president for impeding justice if the bank does not turn over the records", "B": "Filing a civil suit and obtaining a subpoena or legal order for the records", "C": "Referring the case for criminal prosecution and working with law enforcement to obtain a search warrant", "D": "Filing an administrative action and obtaining a subpoena or legal order for the records"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Fraud examiners might be able to obtain nonpublic records even if the subject does not volunteer the records. Subpoenas and other legal processes, such as depositions and document requests, are available if a civil or criminal action is filed. For example, a wronged organization may file a civil or administrative action or make a criminal referral so that records can be subpoenaed or obtained by a legal order (e.g., a search warrant). In a civil case, both private and public parties may obtain nonpublic records such as bank account, brokerage account, travel, credit card, credit agency, and telephone toll records by subpoena or other legal order. However, records obtained while executing a search warrant or similar legal order usually are available only to the government during the underlying investigation, and perhaps thereafter if they are not disclosed at trial. In addition, law enforcement agencies may also subpoena records, but, depending on the jurisdiction, might not disclose the contents of such records with the victim or third parties. In most jurisdictions, third-party organizations that maintain nonpublic records, such as banks and hospitals, are usually prohibited from revealing such records without express authorization from the subject or a legal order."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is a common method that fraudsters use to conceal illegally acquired assets?", "options": {"A": "Creating a will to allocate assets at death", "B": "Purchasing a used vehicle", "C": "Placing assets in probate", "D": "Transferring assets into another person’s name"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Any type of asset can be hidden (e.g., real property, jewelry, stocks, bonds, vehicles, cash), and there are many techniques that a fraudster might use to hide ill-gotten gains. Some common techniques for hiding assets include transferring assets into foreign trusts, overpaying taxes, prepaying on a home mortgage, obtaining a life insurance policy, and transferring assets into someone else’s name."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Which of the following should be done to prepare an organization for a formal fraud investigation?", "options": {"A": "Prepare the managers of the employees who will be involved in the investigation", "B": "Notify the organization’s legal counsel when the investigation is about to commence", "C": "Notify key decision makers when the investigation is about to begin", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Before commencing a formal investigation (and especially before starting the evidence-collection process), it might be necessary to prepare the subject organization for the investigation. Preparing an organization for an investigation involves such things as preparing the managers of the employees who will be involved in the investigation, notifying key decision makers when the investigation is about to begin, and notifying the organization’s in-house or outside counsel when the investigation is about to commence."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Playing with a pencil while talking is an example of a displacement behavior for reducing nervousness that a subject might exhibit during an interview.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Manipulators are motions like picking lint from clothing, playing with objects such as pencils, or holding one’s hands while talking. Manipulators are displacement activities that reduce nervousness."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following documents is likely to be included with the account-opening documents for a corporation’s business account?", "options": {"A": "Copies of corporate resolutions of the board of directors authorizing the opening of the account", "B": "A list of all shareholders", "C": "A copy of the corporation’s board-authorized personnel policies", "D": "A copy of all shareholders' meeting minutes"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "To open a business account for a corporation, the opening party must provide a signature card, or similar document, and copies of corporate resolutions of the board of directors authorizing the opening of the bank account and naming the person who may authorize payments on the account. Also, the bank might require a copy of the company’s organizational or business filings (such as articles of incorporation). These documents should indicate who the company’s corporate officers are and its date of incorporation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "The proper way an interviewer should start the calibration of a witness is through the use of:", "options": {"A": "Questions designed to produce stress in the witness", "B": "Noncritical questions on background information", "C": "Questions designed to make the witness lie", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The best way to calibrate a witness is through the use of noncritical questions on background information, place of employment, and the like. If the witness displays general nervousness or other verbal and nonverbal clues during this phase of the questioning, subsequent indicators might not be reliable. The key is to observe changes in behavior when pertinent questions are asked. Examples of noncritical questions include “When did you start with the company?” and “How long is your commute?”"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "As a general rule, the more intelligent the witness, the less reliable that individual's verbal and nonverbal clues of deception will be.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Conclusions concerning behavior must be tempered by a number of factors. As a general rule, the more intelligent the respondent, the more reliable verbal and nonverbal clues will be. A higher level of intelligence breeds more consistency in responses from which deviations are more clearly recognizable. People of lower intelligence tend to be more erratic in their behavior, and thus meaningful deviations are more difficult to discern."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "In taking a verbal confession, which of the following items of information should an interviewer obtain?", "options": {"A": "The accused's motive for the offense", "B": "That the accused knew the conduct was wrong", "C": "Estimates of the number of instances, dates, and amounts involved", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The interviewer should obtain the following items of information during the verbal confession: An admission that the accused knew the conduct in question was wrong Facts known only to the confessor (e.g., estimates of the number of instances and the total amount of money involved) The accused's motive for the offense The approximate date and time that the offense started The approximate date and time that the offense was terminated Information about the involvement of others Physical evidence Information about what happened to any illicit income derived from the misdeeds Information about any residual assets that the confessor can use to reduce losses Information about the specifics of each offense"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "Which of the following is a matter that fraud examiners should consider when engaging in examinations involving computers?", "options": {"A": "What to look for and where to look for it", "B": "Whether law enforcement should be notified", "C": "Whether an outside forensic expert is needed", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Once an organization has received evidence that misconduct involving digital devices has occurred, it should determine the need for law enforcement assistance. If it is determined that the victim organization will make a formal referral to law enforcement or a prosecuting agency, then the organization should notify the authorities before conducting an investigation to determine whether law enforcement personnel should participate in the examination. When conducting an examination involving computers, fraud examiners should determine whether a digital forensic expert is needed. Digital forensic experts are individuals who specialize in identifying, recovering, collecting, preserving, processing, and producing digital data for use in investigations and litigation. To conduct a successful examination, fraud examiners must know what to look for and where to look for it, but this can be difficult because digital data can be stored in large volumes and in a number of different locations. For example, the fraud examiner should know where to look for information on any suspect computer systems, information on a suspect’s workstation (including any peripherals or other portable media devices that contain data), information stored on any network from which the suspect’s traffic flows, and information stored in cloud storage services."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Which of the following best describes predication?", "options": {"A": "The basis upon which a fraud examination is undertaken", "B": "The means by which individuals justify their unethical actions", "C": "The initial phase of the investigative process", "D": "The initial phase of an interview"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Fraud examinations must adhere to the law; therefore, fraud examiners should not conduct or continue fraud examinations without proper predication. Predication is the totality of circumstances that would lead a reasonable, professionally trained, and prudent individual to believe that a fraud has occurred, is occurring, or will occur. In other words, predication is the basis upon which a fraud examination, and each step taken during the examination, is commenced. A fraud examiner acts on predication when there is a sufficient basis and legitimate reason to take each step in an examination. Accordingly, fraud examiners should begin a fraud examination only when there are circumstances that suggest fraud has occurred, is occurring, or will occur, and they should not investigate beyond the available predication. If fraud examiners cannot articulate a factual basis or good reason for an investigative step, they should not do it. Therefore, fraud examiners should reevaluate the predication as the fraud examination proceeds. That is, as a fraud examination progresses and new information emerges, fraud examiners should continually reevaluate whether there is adequate predication to take each additional step in the examination. If fraud examiners act without predication, they might expose themselves and their clients or employers to liability."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Patricia, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is interviewing a person whose truthfulness is unknown. Which of the following responses to questions posed by Patricia might indicate a deceptive answer?", "options": {"A": "“I just can’t seem to remember.”", "B": "“Why would I do that?”", "C": "“What was that again?”", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Repeating the question is a means for a deceptive respondent to gain more time to think of what to say. The respondent might repeat the question verbatim or might frame the answer with a request to repeat the question (e.g., “What was that again?” or similar language). Conversely, a truthful subject usually does not have to contemplate an answer. Dishonest people will frequently make excuses about things that look bad for them, such as: “I’m always nervous; don’t pay any attention to that.” In some cases, the deceptive person will have a fine memory for insignificant events, but when it comes to the important facts, he will say something like: “I just can’t seem to remember.” Rather than deny the allegations outright, the dishonest person is more likely to answer with a question, such as: “Why would I do something like that?” As a variation, the deceptive person will sometimes question the interview procedure by asking: “Why are you tormenting me?”"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Which of the following statements about how fraud examiners should approach fraud examinations is CORRECT?", "options": {"A": "In most examinations, fraud examiners should start interviewing the suspect and then work outward", "B": "If an individual appears to be involved in the fraud scheme, that person should be interviewed first", "C": "Fraud examinations should begin with general information that is known, starting at the periphery, and then move to the more specific details", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Fraud examinations should begin with general information that is known, starting at the periphery, and then move to the more specific details. In most examinations, fraud examiners start interviewing at the periphery of all possible interview candidates and move toward the witnesses who appear more involved in the matters that are the subject of the examination."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "When conducting an investigation, it is often advantageous to administer interviews with two or more subjects simultaneously due to the likelihood that they will denounce each other.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "One of the basic rules of interviewing is to question only one person at a time. When two subjects are questioned simultaneously, the testimony of one respondent invariably influences the testimony of another. There are few absolute rules of interviewing, but this is one of them. Another basic rule is to conduct interviews under conditions of privacy. The interview is best conducted out of the sight and sound of friends, relatives, or fellow employees, as people are very reluctant to furnish information if others might be able to hear the conversation. Ideally, an interview should take place in an environment that can be controlled by the interviewer."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Abel, a Certified Fraud Examiner, conducted an interview of Baker, the controller of the ABC Company. Abel asked the following question: \"Since you were here when the controls were developed, can you tell me how they came about?\" This kind of question is called a ____________________.", "options": {"A": "Double-negative question", "B": "Controlled answer technique", "C": "Complex question", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Controlled answer techniques may be used to stimulate a desired answer or impression. These techniques direct the interview toward a specific point. For example, it might be possible to get a person to admit knowledge of a matter by phrasing the question: \"I understand you were present when the internal controls were developed; would you please describe how they were constructed?\" This phrasing provides a stronger incentive for the respondent to admit knowledge than does: \"Were you present when the internal controls were developed?\" To stimulate the person to agree to talk or provide information, you might use a prompt such as the following: \"Because you are not involved in this matter, I am sure you would not mind discussing it with me.\" This provides a stronger incentive to cooperate than: \"Do you have any objections to telling me what you know?\" Avoid negative construction such as \"I don't guess you would mind answering a few questions?\""}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "When a fraud examiner identifies suspicious indented writings on a pad of paper, the fraud examiner might be able to discern the text of the indentations by shining a bright-beam light at an oblique angle across the writing to reveal the shadows of the indented text.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Indented writing is the impression a writing instrument leaves on sheets of paper below the sheet that contains the original writing. Fraud examiners should be alert for the presence of incriminating indented writings or the absence of logical indentations, both of which can be valuable in proving fraud. Some indented writings can be seen by employing an oblique-lighting method. In this method, the fraud examiner takes the document into an area with subdued overhead lighting, places the document on a flat surface, and shines a bright beam of light—from a small-beam flashlight or small high-intensity lamp—across the document at a low oblique angle or parallel to the surface. Because shadows in the indentations will only show at right angles to the beam of light, it is necessary to move the light around and note the changing shadows as they form the text of the indentations."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Which of the following is an objective of an admission-seeking interview?", "options": {"A": "To distinguish innocent individuals from culpable ones", "B": "To obtain a signed written statement acknowledging the facts", "C": "To obtain a valid confession", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The admission-seeking interview is designed to obtain a legal admission of wrongdoing. It also serves various other purposes. For example, it seeks to clear an innocent person and encourage a culpable person to confess. A culpable individual usually confesses during the admission-seeking phase of an interview, while an innocent person does not do so unless threats or coercion are used. Also, the interviewer will seek to obtain a valid confession. And finally, admission-seeking interviews are designed to convince the confessor to sign a written statement acknowledging the facts."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Which of the following conditions indicates it is the appropriate time to ask admission-seeking questions?", "options": {"A": "All reasonable investigative steps and sources have been exhausted", "B": "The interviewer can control the interview’s time, place, and subject matter", "C": "The interviewer believes there is a reasonable probability that the subject is responsible for the act in question", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Normally, the interviewer should ask accusatory or admission-seeking questions when all of the following are true: There is a reasonable probability that the respondent has committed the act in question. All other reasonable investigative steps have been completed and as much information as possible has been developed from other sources. The interviewer can reasonably control the interview's place, time, and subject matter."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "A link-network diagram is a type of chart used to show relationships between people, organizations, and events.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Link-network diagrams show the relationships between people, organizations, and events. In these diagrams, different symbols are used to represent different entities: a square can symbolize an organization; a circle, a person; a triangle, an event; and so forth. It does not matter which symbols are used as long as they are used consistently. In link-network diagrams, confirmed connections between entities can be represented by a solid line or enclosure within another symbol. Speculative or presumed relationships can be indicated by broken lines. To achieve its intended purpose, a graphic should always be clear. Therefore, these diagrams should not contain lines that are crossed, if possible."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "The proper method for developing latent fingerprints that have been absorbed into porous materials, such as paper, is to dust them with fingerprint powder.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraud examiners should never try to develop latent fingerprints that have been absorbed into paper or other porous materials by dusting with fingerprint powder or any other means. Such efforts will not only be unsuccessful, but they will prevent additional examinations. Instead, fraud examiners should preserve evidentiary documents that contain latent fingerprints by placing them into labeled protective containers, such as sealable, acid-free paper envelopes. Also, fraud examiners should label the item’s container with their initials, the current date, where the document was obtained, and an identifying exhibit number (if any). Experts use various methods to examine fingerprints on porous surfaces, including iodine fuming and brushing or spraying silver nitrate solution or ninhydrin spray, which reacts with the body chemicals and other substances in the latent prints that have soaked into the absorbent surface. Some of these methods will permanently discolor a document."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "When seizing a computer that is running, the seizing party should generally not search the computer for evidence because doing so might damage and taint relevant evidence.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When seizing a computer that is running, the party seizing the system should not, in most situations, search the computer for evidence because doing so might damage and taint relevant evidence. But in some situations, it might be appropriate to perform live evidence collection (i.e., collect evidence from a suspect system while the system is open and running via its normal interface). Generally, live evidence collection is appropriate when a formally trained computer investigator is seizing the system, and the evidence that the investigator needs to collect exists only in the form of volatile data."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "An admission-seeking interview is specifically designed to:", "options": {"A": "Determine if the subject has withheld key information", "B": "Gather background information about the subject", "C": "Obtain a legal admission of wrongdoing", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The admission-seeking interview is designed to obtain a legal admission of wrongdoing. It also serves various other purposes. For example, it seeks to clear an innocent person and encourage a culpable person to confess. A culpable individual usually confesses during the admission-seeking phase of an interview, while an innocent person does not do so unless threats or coercion are used. Also, the interviewer will seek to obtain a valid confession. And finally, admission-seeking interviews are designed to convince the confessor to sign a written statement acknowledging the facts."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "The fraud examiner should document the details of an interview as soon as possible after the interview date.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Written reports must be timely. The timeliness of reports is extremely important because it tends to enhance the accuracy of witness testimony, as well as preserve the fraud examiner’s memory of the interview(s). Thus, all interviews should be transcribed and documented in a memorandum of interview as soon as possible after the questioning takes place—preferably on the same day of the interview."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Paige is going to testify as a witness regarding her team’s fraud examination report for a complex fraud case involving thousands of documents. She delegated much of the document analysis to subordinates at her firm, who wrote summaries of the key documents they found. In preparing for her testimony, Paige only needs to analyze the summaries prepared by her subordinates.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Paige should, wherever practicable, conduct a complete review of supporting documents. One important problem in the preparation of reports and accounting summaries arises from delegation of tasks to subordinates. If the expert presenting evidence has not had direct knowledge of or has not examined the specific documents or prepared the accounting summaries, it might be possible that the expert will be trapped under the hearsay rule (if applicable). Thus, if the tasks are delegated, it is important that the expert review the delegated work and compare all original work documentation, especially if the delegated tasks play an important role in the examination's findings. It is also important to know the effect of the other assumptions on the conclusion or opinion reached in the report. It is often possible to trap an expert into giving alternative opinions based upon other assumptions that had not been considered. The work should be planned carefully enough in advance so that the work papers and supporting documentation do not show contradictory conclusions that the opposing side could seize upon."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "When reducing a suspect's verbal confession into a written statement, the fraud examiner should include which of the following points?", "options": {"A": "Language indicating that the statement is true", "B": "Acknowledgement that the confessor read the statement", "C": "A statement that the confession is voluntary", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When reducing a suspect's verbal confession into a written statement, the fraud examiner should include a number of points. The signed statement should contain language expressly stating that the confessor is voluntarily making the confession. The signed statement should contain language indicating the subject knowingly and intentionally committed the act and that the subject knew the act was wrong. The signed statement should also include the approximate dates of the offense, the approximate amounts of losses, and the approximate number of instances. Also, the signed statement should include language indicating the subject’s willingness to cooperate. The signed statement should include the confessor’s moral excuse, but the fraud examiner should ensure the wording of the excuse clause does not diminish legal responsibility. The confessor must acknowledge that he read the statement, and he should initial all the pages of the statement. The written statement should state specifically that it is true."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Examinations", "question": "Which of the following is the type of covert operation in which a fraud examiner observes situations and interactions to gather information about individuals' activity?", "options": {"A": "An entrapment operation", "B": "A source operation", "C": "A surveillance operation", "D": "An undercover operation"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The two main forms of covert operations are undercover operations and surveillance operations. Undercover operations often use deception and disguise to obtain evidence directly from those involved in the illicit activity. Agents engaged in undercover operations actively attempt to elicit the desired information. In contrast, surveillance operations use observation to gather information about individuals suspected of misconduct. For example, a surveillance operation might involve observing a suspect from afar while he meets with a potential co-conspirator. Alternatively, the investigator might pose as the co-conspirator’s agent and engage the suspect in conversation in an attempt to gather information; this would be an example of an undercover operation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "A fraud examiner is conducting an investigation involving ABC Company, a multi-national, publicly traded company, and wants to obtain regulatory securities records regarding the company. Which of the following best describes where the fraud examiner should check to find these records?", "options": {"A": "Only domestic securities exchanges located in the jurisdiction where the company is incorporated", "B": "Only the securities exchanges in the jurisdiction where the company does most of its business", "C": "Only domestic securities exchanges and exchanges in jurisdictions where the corporation has a substantial business presence", "D": "Both domestic and foreign securities exchanges, including those in jurisdictions where the company has minimal business presence"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "While jurisdictions treat the concept of securities differently, governments or self-regulatory bodies generally set rules for the issuing and trading of certain types of securities. Among the most common and important rules are disclosure requirements for companies with publicly traded securities. These rules are designed to make sure that investors are reasonably informed about stock that they purchase. Fraud examiners should keep in mind that if a public company does not report to its domestic securities regulator, it might be registered with regulators of foreign securities exchanges. Even if the company has minimal or no presence in the foreign jurisdiction, it might be registered there to benefit from foreign investment. Therefore, searching multiple securities exchanges might be necessary for conducting a thorough securities records search."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Where permitted by law, searches of all of the following sources of information can be useful in developing background information for pre-employment purposes EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Civil court records searches", "B": "Bankruptcy records searches", "C": "Criminal court records searches", "D": "Income tax records"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Some of the searches useful in developing background information for employment purposes are listed below (where permitted by law): Credit header searches are useful in confirming address and national identification number information. Civil court records can be searched to determine if candidates are or have been involved in legal actions. Criminal court records may be used to uncover past criminal problems. Fraud examiners can search tax court liens to determine if candidates have been sued by tax authorities. Aircraft mechanics, airmen, medical licenses, and other licenses are available to ensure that basic job requirements are met in the appropriate circumstance. Consumer credit reports may be used for employee selection, retention, and promotion. Bankruptcy filings, tax liens, and judgments may be used to identify adverse financial matters that can serve as potential motivators for fraud, defamation, and embezzlement. Where a prospective or current employee drives a personally owned vehicle or an employer-owned vehicle, such activity might expose the employer to liability for damages; therefore, driving records must be checked in such circumstances. A candidate’s prior education and employment can be verified by conducting education and employment verification searches. In most jurisdictions, income tax records are not public records and cannot be accessed for pre-employment purposes."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "In interview situations, _____________ questions consist of a series of interrelated questions and frequently require more than one answer, such as “What are your duties here, and how long have you been employed?”", "options": {"A": "Reverse", "B": "Complex", "C": "Closed", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Complex questions are those that consist of a series of interrelated questions. For example: \"What are your duties here, and how long have you been employed?\" Complex questions and statements are too complicated to be easily understood, cover more than one subject or topic, require more than one answer, or require a complicated answer. Therefore, fraud examiners should avoid asking complex questions."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Freddie calls Alex’s bank, claiming to be Alex, with the intention of stealing Alex’s identity. Freddie tells the bank representative that he needs to make sure the bank has the correct government identification number on his account because he had noticed an error on his statement. The bank representative refuses to give the number, so Freddie hangs up. Assuming that each of the following is illegal in the relevant jurisdiction, which of the following crimes did Freddie commit?", "options": {"A": "Fraud in the inducement", "B": "Pretexting with a financial institution", "C": "Defalcation", "D": "Embezzlement"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Broadly defined, pretexting is the act of impersonating someone else or making false or misleading statements to obtain, sell, or buy information about a person or organization. Under the broad definition, pretexting for nonfraudulent purposes is not always illegal, but it should be used with caution. For example, if a fraud examiner is trying to find a witness or a suspect, he might call the person’s relative and pretend to be an old school friend who is requesting the individual’s phone number. This type of pretexting might be permissible. However, it is more often illegal to use pretexting to obtain certain types of information, such as financial records and phone history records. Several jurisdictions have prohibited pretexting against financial institutions, even if no fraudulent intent is present. In the context of financial institutions, pretexting is the act of obtaining or attempting to obtain customer information from financial institutions using deceptive tactics. Some individuals used pretexting as a means to gather financial information about a subject. Pretexters would contact a financial institution and pretend to be the customer or an authorized individual to obtain financial information and trick the financial institution into providing information about the subject."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is a reason why a fraud examiner might be tasked with tracing illicit transactions?", "options": {"A": "To facilitate the recovery of criminal proceeds", "B": "To determine if a potential defendant can pay if a judgment is ordered", "C": "To identify a judgment debtor’s assets", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Often, CFEs are tasked with tracing illicit transactions to assist: A victim of fraud who wants a tracing search to facilitate the recovery of criminal proceeds A potential plaintiff who wants a tracing search to determine if the potential defendant can pay a court-ordered sum if a judgment is ordered A judgment creditor who needs to identify the judgment debtor’s assets"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Analyzing Documents", "question": "A fraud examiner needs to protect an evidentiary document with a latent fingerprint on it by placing it into a protective container. Which of the following should the fraud examiner include on the container’s label?", "options": {"A": "The fraud examiner’s initials", "B": "The location where the document was obtained", "C": "The date the item was placed in the container", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fraud examiners should preserve evidentiary documents that contain latent fingerprints by placing them into labeled protective containers, such as sealable, acid-free paper envelopes. To avoid smudging and contamination of the fingerprints, fraud examiners should wear protective gloves or carefully use tweezers when handling latent fingerprint evidence. Also, fraud examiners should label the item’s container with their initials, the current date, where the document was obtained, and an identifying exhibit number (if any)."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Blue, a Certified Fraud Examiner, has just begun an interview of White. After introducing himself and establishing rapport with White, what should Blue do next?", "options": {"A": "Establish a transitional statement", "B": "Establish the interview theme", "C": "Start asking questions", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "After providing the introduction and establishing rapport, the interviewer must state the interview’s purpose in some way prior to the commencement of serious questioning. Otherwise, the respondent might be confused, threatened, or overly cautious. Stating the purpose is known as establishing the interview theme."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following is a category of informational interview questions?", "options": {"A": "Leading", "B": "Closed", "C": "Open", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Once the proper format for the interview is set, the interviewer then turns to informational questions to gather unbiased factual information. Typically, the interviewer will ask three types of questions during the fact-gathering portion of an interview: open, closed, and leading."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "Which of the following statements concerning documentation in a formal fraud examination report is most accurate?", "options": {"A": "The originals of important documents should be included in the report.", "B": "A reference to the current location where the original documents can be found is sufficient.", "C": "Copies of important documents should be included in the report.", "D": "A reference to any important documents is sufficient."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Most evidence in fraud cases will be in document form, and when reporting the results of a fraud examination, it is best to include copies (not originals) of important documents in the formal report or in the attached appendices. Also, when operating under a lawful court order that compels a custodian to furnish original documents, the fraud examiner should copy those documents (preferably in the presence of the custodian). Then the fraud examiner should furnish the custodian with a receipt describing the documents copied or taken."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following data analysis functions can be used to determine the relationship between two variables in raw data?", "options": {"A": "Gap testing", "B": "Correlation analysis", "C": "Duplicate testing", "D": "Benford's Law analysis"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Using the correlation analysis function, fraud examiners can determine the relationships among different variables in the raw data. Fraud examiners can learn a lot about data files by learning the relationship between two variables. For example, we should expect a strong correlation between the following independent and dependent variables because a direct relationship exists between the two variables. Hotel costs should increase as the number of days traveled increases. Gallons of paint used should increase as the number of houses painted increases."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Liam, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is attempting to get a fraud suspect to admit guilt. Liam should:", "options": {"A": "Show the suspect incriminating evidence", "B": "Directly accuse the suspect", "C": "Give the suspect an excuse for his behavior", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "People rarely confess voluntarily unless they perceive that the benefits of confession outweigh the penalties. A good interviewer, through the application of sophisticated techniques, is able to convince the respondent that the confession is in his best interest. The admission-seeking part of an interview begins with a direct accusation. The accusation should be made in the form of a statement, not a question. Additionally, to obtain an admission of guilt, the interviewer must offer a morally acceptable reason for the confessor’s behavior. The interviewer cannot convey an opinion that the accused is a “bad person.” Guilty people almost never confess under such conditions. To obtain a confession, the interviewer must be firm, but he must also project compassion, understanding, and sympathy. Even when the interviewer presents the accused with an appropriate rationalization, it is likely that he will continue to deny culpability. In these situations, the interviewer must quickly and decisively diffuse these alibis by convincing the accused of the weight of the evidence against him. Interviewers can often diffuse alibis by displaying physical evidence. The physical evidence—usually documents in fraud matters—generally should be displayed one piece at a time, in reverse order of importance. In this way, the accused does not immediately know the full extent of the evidence."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "To preserve the confidentiality of a fraud investigation by ensuring that it is afforded protection under a legal professional privilege, the investigation should be conducted at the direction of, or under the supervision of, a government official.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "To prevent third parties, including the subject of the investigation, from having access to the investigative materials, management should consider conducting the investigation under any applicable evidentiary privilege that provides the right to keep certain information from being disclosed without permission. If an evidentiary privilege applies to information, the general rule is that the court and the party seeking the information will be denied access to it, and the triers of fact must disregard any evidence they do actually hear if it is deemed privileged afterward; however, legal jurisdictions vary on which communications are protected by such privileges. Typically, the most relevant types of evidentiary privileges for keeping investigations confidential are legal professional privileges. These privileges protect the communications between a professional legal advisor (e.g., solicitor, barrister, or attorney) and his clients, and in some situations, fraud investigations can be structured so that they are afforded protection under such privileges. Generally, to receive protection under a legal professional privilege, an investigation must be conducted at the direction of, or under the supervision of, a legal professional, not a government official."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Geoff, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is preparing for the interview phase of his investigation. When planning for interviews, Geoff should do which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Review the case file to ensure he has not overlooked important information.", "B": "Go into each interview with an undefined objective to catch the subject off guard.", "C": "Select an uncomfortable venue for each of the witnesses.", "D": "Prepare a detailed list of questions to ask each subject."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "To effectively prepare for the interview phase of an investigation, the fraud examiner must first develop a plan. The fraud examiner should contemplate what the interview is intended to accomplish and state an objective. He should also review the case file to ensure that it does not contain important information that has been overlooked. Prior to the commencement of the interviews, the fraud examiner should clearly determine what information might be gleaned from each of the potential witnesses, as well as the best strategy to go about obtaining it. When possible, the interview should be held in a venue where the subject will feel comfortable and secure, although it is not recommended that the interview take place in an environment that is particularly familiar to the subject, such as the interviewee’s home or office. The most appropriate member of the investigative team should be selected to conduct the interview based on the specifics of the interview. Rather than devise an exhaustive list of questions to ask the subject, the fraud examiner should instead formulate a brief outline of key points to discuss during the interview. Additionally, an investigator should consider which evidentiary documents to bring to the interview, if any, as well as which documents he might seek from the subject."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Some of the most effective information-seeking questions are phrased as subtle commands.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "During the information phase of the interview, the interviewer should endeavor to ask primarily open questions to stimulate conversation. Some of the best open questions are subtle commands."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the designed purposes of asking introductory questions in interview situations?", "options": {"A": "To give a detailed reason for the interview", "B": "To establish rapport", "C": "To get agreement from the respondent to cooperate", "D": "To provide the introduction"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Introductory questions are designed to meet four objectives: to provide an introduction, to establish rapport, to get the respondent to agree verbally to cooperate in the interview (i.e., establish the interview theme), and to observe the respondent’s reactions to questions."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Paul, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is conducting an admission-seeking interview of Luca, a fraud suspect. Luca has decided to confess. How should Paul go about getting all the relevant information?", "options": {"A": "Get the general information and then move to the specifics", "B": "Obtain the details in reverse chronological order", "C": "Obtain the details in order of relevance", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "During the admission-seeking interview, it is best to first confirm the general details of the offense. For example, the interviewer will want the accused to provide estimates of the amounts involved, name other parties involved in the offense, and give the location of physical evidence. After obtaining these basic facts, the interviewer can return to the specifics, in chronological order."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following data analysis functions is most useful in testing for hidden journal entries?", "options": {"A": "Aging analysis", "B": "Gap testing", "C": "Identifying duplicates", "D": "Statistical sampling"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Gap testing is used to identify missing items in a sequence or series, such as missing checks or invoice numbers. It can also be used to find sequences where none are expected to exist (e.g., employee government identification numbers). In reviewing journal entries, gaps might signal possible hidden entries."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterview Theory and Application", "question": "An interview subject’s intelligence level rarely has an effect on an investigator’s ability to accurately discern behavioral clues during an interview.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Conclusions concerning behavior must be tempered by a number of factors. The more intelligent the respondent, the more reliable verbal and nonverbal clues will be. A higher level of intelligence breeds more consistency in responses from which deviations are more clearly recognizable. People of lower intelligence tend to be more erratic in their behavior, and thus meaningful deviations are more difficult to discern."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "question": "If you are seizing a computer for forensic analysis, it is generally not necessary to seize printers connected to it.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Printers might contain valuable evidence. Many printers have internal hard drives that might contain information relevant to a fraud examination. In general, any information sent to and stored by a printer is recoverable unless the printer has overwritten the data. So, when seizing a computer for forensic analysis, it is generally necessary to seize any printers connected to it."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Jane is a Certified Fraud Examiner working on an investigation at Mill Corp. During an interview, Colin, an employee at Mill Corp., confesses to Jane that he has been embezzling money from the company. Which of the following pieces of information does Jane NOT have to obtain from Colin?", "options": {"A": "The approximate date Colin started embezzling the money", "B": "An estimate of the amount of money Colin embezzled", "C": "A statement from Colin that his conduct was an accident", "D": "Information about the involvement of other Mill Corp. employees"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "If a fraud examiner gets a verbal confession from the fraudster, it does not matter whether the fraudster claims his conduct was an accident. The interviewer should obtain the following items of information during the verbal confession: An admission that the accused knew the conduct in question was wrong Facts known only to the confessor (e.g., estimates of the number of instances and the total amount of money involved) The accused's motive for the offense The approximate date and time that the offense started The approximate date and time that the offense was terminated Information about the involvement of others Physical evidence Information about what happened to any illicit income derived from the misdeeds Information about any residual assets that the confessor can use to reduce losses Information about the specifics of each offense"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "question": "Which of the following is a limitation of Benford’s Law?", "options": {"A": "Benford’s Law can only be applied to data sets listed in currency amounts.", "B": "Benford’s Law only works on data sets with assigned numbers, such as bank account or telephone numbers.", "C": "Benford’s Law applies best to data sets with three-digit numbers.", "D": "Benford’s Law cannot be applied to data sets with non-natural numbers, such as check or invoice numbers."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Benford’s Law distinguishes between natural and non-natural numbers, and it is important to understand the difference between the two types because Benford’s Law cannot be applied to data sets with non-natural numbers. Natural numbers are those numbers that are not ordered in a particular numbering scheme and are not human-generated or generated from a random number system. For example, most vendor invoice totals or listings of payment amounts will be populated by currency values that are natural numbers. Conversely, non-natural numbers (e.g., employee identification numbers and telephone numbers) are designed systematically to convey information that restricts the natural nature of the number. Any number that is arbitrarily determined, such as the price of inventory held for sale, is considered a non-natural number."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following documents is typically included with the account-opening documents for a corporation’s business account?", "options": {"A": "A signature card", "B": "Copies of corporate resolutions of the board of directors naming the person who may authorize payments on the account", "C": "Copies of corporate resolutions of the board of directors authorizing the opening of the account", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To open a business account for a corporation, the opening party must provide a signature card, or similar document, and copies of corporate resolutions of the board of directors authorizing the opening of the bank account and naming the person who may authorize payments on the account. Also, the bank might require a copy of the company’s organizational or business filings (such as articles of incorporation). These documents should indicate who the company’s corporate officers are and the company’s date of incorporation."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "Gamma, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is attempting to locate the exact birthplace of Theta, a fraud suspect. Where is Gamma most likely to find such a record, if it exists?", "options": {"A": "The local commercial filing agency", "B": "The jurisdiction’s health records agency", "C": "The local property records agency", "D": "The jurisdiction’s tax assessor"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Some local health records agencies maintain birth and death records. The content and availability of these records varies widely, but they might include the name of the individual, address, sex, age, race, birthplace, birth date, death place, date and time of death, government identification number, close family members, occupational information, medical certificate, and coroner’s certificate. If such records are not available locally, there might be a state/provincial or national health office that maintains them."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "question": "Which of the following is an example of an indirect method of locating assets or tracing illicit funds?", "options": {"A": "Correlation analysis", "B": "Financial condition analysis", "C": "Net-worth analysis", "D": "The specific-items method"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Often, when a fraud examiner must locate a subject's assets or trace illicit funds, the subject’s books and records are not made available. In such cases, the fraud examiner must use an indirect approach, such as net-worth analysis or the bank deposit analysis method, to prove income."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "James, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is conducting an admission-seeking interview. Which of the following strategies should James follow in his attempt to obtain a confession?", "options": {"A": "Minimize sympathy and maximize the perception of wrongdoing.", "B": "Avoid potential liability by making the accusation in the presence of outsiders.", "C": "Imply that time is of the essence to pressure the subject into confessing.", "D": "Conduct the interview in a firm, yet compassionate, manner."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Admission-seeking interviews should be conducted only when there is sufficient privacy and time is not a factor. Additionally, the interviewer must not express disgust, outrage, or moral condemnation about the confessor’s actions, as this goes against the basic logic of obtaining confessions, which can be summed up as maximize sympathy and minimize the perception of moral wrongdoing. The interviewer must offer a morally acceptable reason for the confessor’s behavior. The interviewer cannot convey an opinion that the accused is a “bad person.” Guilty people almost never confess under such conditions. To obtain a confession, the interviewer must be firm, but he must also project compassion, understanding, and sympathy. The threat of a lawsuit is always present when allegations of wrongdoing are made against certain employees. It is, therefore, important that fraud examiners understand exactly what actions are permitted so that they can avoid potential liability. It is generally legal to accuse innocent people of misdeeds they did not commit as long as: The accuser has reasonable suspicion or predication to believe the accused has committed an offense. The accusation is made under conditions of privacy. The accuser does not take any action likely to make an innocent person confess. The accusation is conducted under reasonable conditions."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "nterviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "Green, a Certified Fraud Examiner, is conducting an admission-seeking interview of Brown, a fraud suspect. Brown has confessed to having committed the fraud, but he is denying anyone else was involved. However, Green knows this is untrue. What should Green do next?", "options": {"A": "Proceed directly to present his evidence against Brown’s co-conspirators.", "B": "Get Brown's written admission before continuing the interview.", "C": "Proceed as if the falsehood has been accepted as truth and return to it later.", "D": "Mention the penalties involved in perjury."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Because of the psychology of confessions, most confessors lie about one or more aspects of the offense, even though they confirm overall guilt. When this happens during the verbal confession, the interviewer should make a mental note of the discrepancy and proceed as if the falsehood had been accepted as truth. Such discrepancies should be saved until the accused provides all other relevant facts. If the discrepancies are material to the offense, the interviewer should either resolve them at the end of the verbal confession or wait and correct them in the written confession. If not material, such information can be omitted from the written confession."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "question": "Which of the following is the LEAST appropriate participant on a team assembled to investigate fraud?", "options": {"A": "Industry specialist", "B": "Legal counsel", "C": "Auditor", "D": "Suspect's supervisor"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fraud examinations usually require a cooperative effort among different areas of expertise; therefore, if members of management decide to investigate suspicions of fraud, they must determine who should lead and be involved in the investigation. Typically, participants on a fraud investigation team should not include individuals with vested personal or corporate interest in the matter or individuals with a close personal or professional relationship with the subject or the complainant. Thus, in most situations, the suspect’s supervisor should not be included on a fraud investigation team. The don’ts for selecting the participants on a team assembled to investigate fraud include: Don't select team members based on friendship. Don't select team members to repay a favor. Don't select team members with negative attitudes. Don't overlook team members with untraditional knowledge that can contribute to the investigation (e.g., people with experience in a particular industry). Don't select members who might have personality conflicts with other members. Don't select members with a vested personal or corporate interest in the matter. Don't select members with a close personal or professional relationship with the subject or the complainant. Don't select members who lack restraint and a sense of discretion."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "question": "When preparing a fraud examination report, which of the following opinions is permissible to include in the report?", "options": {"A": "Opinions on a party's guilt", "B": "Expert opinions regarding technical matters", "C": "Opinions on the veracity of witnesses", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraud examiners must be cautious about stating their opinions. The fraud examiner must avoid stating opinions regarding the guilt or innocence of any person or party involved. The ACFE Code of Professional Ethics specifically prohibits statements of opinions regarding guilt or innocence, as this is the job of the judge or jury. Similarly, the fraud examiner should be careful not to include any statement of opinion as to the integrity or veracity of any witness, even if the fraud examiner is convinced that the witness is being untruthful. Truthfulness, or lack thereof, can be demonstrated through conflicting statements by the witness or suspect. Opinions regarding technical matters, however, are permitted if the fraud examiner is qualified as an expert in the matter being considered. For example, a permissible expert opinion might address the relative adequacy of an entity’s internal controls. Another opinion might discuss whether financial statements conform to generally accepted accounting principles."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "A fraud examiner in an organized crime investigation believes a particular commercial restaurant is being used as a place of operation for the suspects. Which of the following types of records would be the LEAST likely to help the fraud examiner discover who owns the building in which the restaurant operates?", "options": {"A": "Fire department records", "B": "Building permit records", "C": "Voter registration records", "D": "Health department records"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Submit Answer There are many public records often found at the local level that can help fraud examiners gather various types of information. To determine who owns a particular property, there might be direct information or leads found in the records of several agencies, including health and fire departments. Many local health or fire departments conduct routine inspections of businesses for health and safety code or fire code violations. These inspection records might contain valuable information about the business, its operations, the employees, and the owners. If a business or an individual constructs a new building or makes improvements to an existing building, there should be a building permit on file with the local building authority. In addition, before most businesses can open their doors, the local agencies might require that they possess certain permits. In many cases, the person applying for permits will be the owner or someone traceable to the owner. Voter registration records are not public in all jurisdictions, but if they are available, they might contain useful information. Usually, much of the information contained in such records is withheld from the public for privacy purposes, but voter registration records might contain a person’s date of birth, mailing address, and political affiliation. However, this information is less likely than the other sources listed to identify the owner of a commercial building."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Interviewing Suspects and Signed Statements", "question": "When taking notes during an admission-seeking interview, the interviewer should do so in a manner that suggests to the suspect that he has been caught in a lie. This strategy will increase pressure on the suspect and increase the likelihood of a confession.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Submit Answer When conducting an admission-seeking interview, note-taking should be kept to a minimum. In some cases, taking notes should be avoided. Because the admission-seeking interview’s ultimate goal is to obtain a signed statement of guilt, it is not necessary to take extensive notes. Such notes can distract the suspect and reveal what points the fraud examiner believes to be important; thus, if the fraud examiner determines that note-taking is necessary, he should do so in a way that does not reveal the information’s significance."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "question": "A fraud examiner in an organized crime investigation believes a particular commercial restaurant is being used as a place of operation for the suspects. Which of the following types of records would be the LEAST likely to help the fraud examiner discover who owns the building in which the restaurant operates?", "options": {"A": "Building permit records", "B": "Health department records", "C": "Voter registration records", "D": "Fire department records"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Submit Answer There are many public records often found at the local level that can help fraud examiners gather various types of information. To determine who owns a particular property, there might be direct information or leads found in the records of several agencies, including health and fire departments. Many local health or fire departments conduct routine inspections of businesses for health and safety code or fire code violations. These inspection records might contain valuable information about the business, its operations, the employees, and the owners. If a business or an individual constructs a new building or makes improvements to an existing building, there should be a building permit on file with the local building authority. In addition, before most businesses can open their doors, the local agencies might require that they possess certain permits. In many cases, the person applying for permits will be the owner or someone traceable to the owner. Voter registration records are not public in all jurisdictions, but if they are available, they might contain useful information. Usually, much of the information contained in such records is withheld from the public for privacy purposes, but voter registration records might contain a person’s date of birth, mailing address, and political affiliation. However, this information is less likely than the other sources listed to identify the owner of a commercial building."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "question": "________ in the context of corporate governance generally refers to the clarity, accuracy, completeness, and timeliness of the financial statements and other information provided by management to shareholders.", "options": {"A": "Transparency", "B": "Accountability", "C": "Fairness", "D": "Responsibility"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Transparency in the context of corporate governance generally refers to the clarity, accuracy, completeness, and timeliness of the financial statements and other information provided by management to shareholders. The organization’s governance processes must include policies and procedures designed to ensure transparent disclosure of all material matters that the shareholders need to make timely and informed decisions regarding their investment in the company. An independent audit of the financial statements is one such mechanism that helps meet this objective."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Which of the following most exemplifies the rationalization leg of the Fraud Triangle?", "options": {"A": "“I need the money to repay my drug dealer so that no one will find out about my habit.”", "B": "“I’m confident I won’t get caught.”", "C": "“I’m in so much debt; I don’t have any other way to pay my bills.”", "D": "“Management is dishonest, so why shouldn’t I be?”"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "One leg of the Fraud Triangle represents rationalization. Cressey pointed out that rationalization is not an ex post facto means of justifying a theft that has already occurred. Significantly, rationalization is a necessary component of the crime before it takes place; in fact, it is a part of the motivation for the crime. Because the embezzler does not view himself as a criminal, he must justify his misdeeds before he ever commits them. Examples of rationalizations include “The company owes me,” “Management is dishonest, so why shouldn’t I be?,” and “No one will really get hurt by such a small amount of missing money.”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to The Institute of Internal Auditors’ International Standards for the Professional Practice of Internal Auditing, the internal audit activity must evaluate risk exposures relating to the organization's governance, operations, and information systems regarding all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Reliability and integrity of financial and operational information", "B": "Sale of tangible and intangible assets", "C": "Compliance with laws, regulations, and contracts", "D": "Effectiveness and efficiency of operations"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "According to The Institute of Internal Auditors' Standard 2120.A1, the internal audit activity must evaluate risk exposures relating to the organization's governance, operations, and information systems regarding the: Achievement of the organization’s strategic objectives Reliability and integrity of financial and operational information Effectiveness and efficiency of operations Safeguarding of assets Compliance with laws, regulations, and contracts"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Which of the following is among the board of directors’ responsibilities pertaining to fraud risk management?", "options": {"A": "Overseeing the organization’s fraud risk management activities", "B": "Setting realistic expectations of management to enforce an anti-fraud culture", "C": "Raising awareness of the risks of fraud throughout the organization", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To ensure that the fraud risk management program is effective in both operation and design, it must be fully embraced by those charged with governing and overseeing the organization. Specifically, the board of directors must recognize the true and specific risks of fraud to the organization, as well as their potential impact, and respond by: Setting an appropriate tone and realistic expectations of management to enforce an anti-fraud culture Gaining a working knowledge of the organization’s activities and the environments in which it operates Raising awareness of the risks of fraud throughout the organization Developing a strategy to assess and manage fraud risks that aligns with the organization’s risk appetite and strategic plans Overseeing the organization’s fraud risk management activities Maintaining open communications with senior management and other personnel"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Failing to properly supervise all assistants and others who are delegated work on a fraud examination engagement is a violation of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Failing to properly supervise all assistants and others who are delegated work on a fraud examination engagement would be in violation of Article I of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics. This article states that: \"An ACFE Member shall, at all times, demonstrate a commitment to professionalism and diligence in the performance of his or her duties.\" The “diligence in the performance of his or her duties” phrase in this rule refers to several activities that collectively define high-quality fraud examination work, including properly planning assignments and supervising assistants and colleagues, avoiding conflicts of interest, performing tasks with competence, obtaining sufficient evidence to establish a basis for opinions, maintaining confidential relations, and avoiding distortion of facts."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "In identifying the inherent fraud risks that could apply to the organization, the fraud risk assessment team should specifically discuss the potential for management override of controls.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The fraud risk assessment team should brainstorm to identify the inherent fraud risks that could apply to the organization. Brainstorming should include discussions regarding incentives, pressures, and opportunities to commit fraud, including the incentive programs and how those might affect employee behavior; the potential for management’s override of controls; and the universe of fraud risks and the subset of risks, including reputation risk, pertaining to specific categories of fraud that apply to a particular organization."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to COSO, the effectiveness of an overall system of internal controls can be determined by assessing whether several specific components are in place, functioning effectively, and operating together in an integrated manner.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "COSO's Internal Control—Integrated Framework identified five interrelated components of internal control: control environment, risk assessment, control activities, information and communication, and monitoring. The effectiveness of internal controls can be determined from an assessment of whether (1) each of these five components is in place and functioning effectively and (2) the five components are operating together in an integrated manner."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "The reason the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics restricts the types of opinions fraud examiners may express is to protect the fraud examiner from claims of:", "options": {"A": "Compounding a felony", "B": "False imprisonment", "C": "Libel", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Libel and slander can cause personal injury and subject a fraud examiner to a lawsuit for damages. Libel is a written defamation of someone else’s character. Slander is a spoken defamation. The content of a libelous or slanderous message must: Contain words that injure another person’s character or reputation or expose him to ridicule or contempt. Be communicated orally or in writing to other people. Cause an actual damage to the person who is the subject of the communication. The risks involved in libel and slander are reasons for having the rule in the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics that prohibits expression of opinions on the guilt or innocence of people."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "Which of the following is true according to the differential reinforcement theory?", "options": {"A": "Behavior is weakened when punishment is avoided.", "B": "Behavior is reinforced when rewards are gained.", "C": "Behavior is weakened by positive stimuli.", "D": "Behavior is reinforced by negative stimuli."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "According to the differential reinforcement theory, people learn social behavior by operant conditioning—behavior controlled by stimuli that follow the behavior. Behavior is reinforced when positive rewards are gained (positive reinforcement) or punishment is avoided (negative reinforcement). It is weakened by negative stimuli (punishment) and loss of reward (negative punishment). Whether deviant or criminal behavior begins or persists depends on the degree to which it has been rewarded or punished, as well as the rewards or punishments attached to its alternatives."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "When determining the relevance of certain fraud risk factors within an entity, the auditor should consider:", "options": {"A": "The size of the entity", "B": "The complexity of the entity", "C": "The ownership of the entity", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "According to International Standard on Auditing 240, the entity's size, complexity, and ownership characteristics have a significant influence on the consideration of relevant fraud risk factors. For example, in the case of a large entity, there might be factors that generally constrain improper conduct by management, such as: Effective oversight by those charged with governance An effective internal audit function The existence and enforcement of a written code of conduct"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "According to the OECD Principles of Corporate Governance, companies should disclose all financial information to investors, regardless of the cost burden of the disclosure or the disclosure’s possible negative effects on the company’s competitive position.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "According to Chapter V of the OECD Principles of Corporate Governance, “the corporate governance framework should ensure that timely and accurate disclosure is made on all material matters regarding the corporation, including the financial situation, performance, ownership, and governance of the company.” However, such disclosure requirements are not expected to place unreasonable administrative or cost burdens on enterprises. Nor are companies expected to disclose information that may endanger their competitive position unless disclosure is necessary to fully inform the investment decision and to avoid misleading the investor. To determine what information should be disclosed at a minimum, many countries apply the concept of materiality. Material information can be defined as information whose omission or misstatement could influence the economic decisions taken by users of that information."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "According to the differential reinforcement theory, behavior is weakened by negative stimuli (punishment) and loss of reward (negative punishment).", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "According to the differential reinforcement theory, people learn social behavior by operant conditioning—behavior controlled by stimuli that follow the behavior. Behavior is reinforced when positive rewards are gained (positive reinforcement) or punishment is avoided (negative reinforcement). It is weakened by negative stimuli (punishment) and loss of reward (negative punishment). Whether deviant or criminal behavior begins or persists depends on the degree to which it has been rewarded or punished, as well as the rewards or punishments attached to its alternatives."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "The two primary strategies to control corporate criminal behavior are:", "options": {"A": "Compliance and deterrence", "B": "Deterrence and enforcement", "C": "Enforcement and compliance", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Enforcement strategies include two main theories: compliance and deterrence. Compliance is designed to achieve conformity to the law without having to detect, process, or penalize violators. Compliance systems provide economic incentives for voluntary compliance to the laws and use administrative efforts to control violations before they occur. In contrast, deterrence is designed to detect law violations, determine who is responsible, and penalize offenders to deter future violations. Deterrence systems try to control the immediate behavior of individuals, not the long-term behaviors targeted by compliance systems."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, fraud examiners are strictly prohibited from expressing opinions on technical matters.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Article V of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics states: \"An ACFE Member, in conducting examinations, will obtain evidence or other documentation to establish a reasonable basis for any opinion rendered. No opinion shall be expressed regarding the guilt or innocence of any person or party.\" Opinions, under Article V, may be given if there is a reasonable basis for them. The only opinions strictly not allowed are those regarding the guilt or innocence of any person or party. Additionally, opinions regarding technical matters generally are permitted if the fraud examiner is qualified as an expert in the matter. For example, a permissible opinion might address the relative adequacy of an entity’s internal controls. Likewise, a permissible opinion might regard whether financial transactions conform to generally accepted accounting principles."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Most experts agree that it is much easier to detect fraud than it is to prevent it.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Most experts agree that it is much easier to prevent fraud than to detect it. To prevent fraud, we should understand something about the potential perpetrator’s mind. Increasing the perception of detection might be the most effective fraud prevention method. Controls, for example, do little good in preventing theft and fraud if those at risk do not know of the presence of possible detection."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Communications regarding the organization's anti-fraud policy should be presented in a positive, non-accusatory manner.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "It obviously does little good to have an anti-fraud or ethics policy if it is not communicated to the employees. This communication can be accomplished in several ways, such as during employee orientation and annual training sessions, via interoffice memoranda or newsletters, and through posters displayed in common areas. In all of these mechanisms, the communication of the policy should be presented in a positive, non-accusatory manner."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "The risk that an organization might be victimized by an individual who is able to combine the three elements of the Fraud Triangle is called _______________.", "options": {"A": "Audit risk", "B": "Insider risk", "C": "Environmental risk", "D": "Fraud risk"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Cressey’s Fraud Triangle teaches that there are three interrelated elements that enable someone to commit fraud: the motive or pressure that drives a person to want to commit the fraud, the opportunity that enables him to commit the fraud, and the ability to rationalize the fraudulent behavior. The vulnerability that an organization faces from individuals capable of combining all three elements of the Fraud Triangle is fraud risk. Fraud risk can come from sources both internal and external to the organization."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Dr. Steve Albrecht conducted research that focused on fraud-related red flags in two principal categories: perpetrator characteristics and organizational environment. Which of the following was the organizational-environment factor that was most present in the frauds studied?", "options": {"A": "Inadequate attention to details", "B": "Too much trust in key employees", "C": "Lack of clear lines of authority", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Albrecht’s research included an examination of red flags or indicators of occupational fraud and abuse that fell into two principal categories: perpetrator characteristics and organizational environment. The purpose of the study was to determine which of the red flags were most important to the commission (and therefore to the detection and prevention) of fraud. The researchers gave study participants two sets of 25 motivating factors and asked which factors were present in the frauds they had dealt with. Participants were asked to rank these factors on a seven-point scale indicating the degree to which each factor existed in their specific frauds. The ten most highly ranked factors from the list dealing with organizational environment were: 1. Placing too much trust in key employees 2. Lack of proper procedures for authorization of transactions 3. Inadequate disclosures of personal investments and incomes 4. No separation of authorization of transactions from the custody of related assets 5. Lack of independent checks on performance 6. Inadequate attention to details 7. No separation of custody of assets from the accounting for those assets 8. No separation of duties between accounting functions 9. Lack of clear lines of authority and responsibility 10. Department that is not frequently reviewed by internal auditors"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Document retention policies should cover which of the following types of documents?", "options": {"A": "Accounting records", "B": "Client correspondence", "C": "Employment records", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "One of the first steps in implementing a document retention policy (DRP) is to identify the types of documents that need to be retained or destroyed. It is important to remember that every organization is different; thus, an organization might require the retention of documents that are not provided for in this text. All types of documents produced by an organization must be initially accounted for. This includes tangible and electronic documents and is never limited to financial documents. Accounting records, corporate tax records, bank records, employment records, various workplace records (including in-house emails and client correspondence), and legal records must be considered when constructing a DRP for a particular organization."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Preventive anti-fraud controls include all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Segregation of duties", "B": "Hiring policies and procedures", "C": "Continuous audit techniques", "D": "Fraud awareness training"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Preventive controls, which are intended to prevent fraud before it occurs, include: Bringing awareness of the fraud risk management program to personnel throughout the organization Performing background checks on employees (where permitted by law) Hiring competent personnel and providing them with anti-fraud training Conducting exit interviews Implementing policies and procedures Segregating duties Implementing physical security measures Implementing security measures to restrict electronic access to data Ensuring proper alignment between an individual’s authority and level of responsibility Reviewing third-party and related-party transactions Continuous audit procedures are an example of detective controls, which are intended to detect fraud if it does occur."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Which of the following principles of corporate governance pertains to the duty of internal parties to act in the best interest of the organization?", "options": {"A": "Responsibility", "B": "Transparency", "C": "Fairness", "D": "Accountability"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Responsibility, as it pertains to corporate governance, applies both to the duty of internal parties (e.g., employees, managers, directors, and owners) to act in the best interest of the organization and to the duty of the organization as a whole to act in society’s best interest. Both of these considerations include acting within legal, regulatory, and ethical bounds. Responsible corporate governance is reflected in the concepts of corporate ethics and corporate citizenship."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "The risk of an auditor not detecting a material misstatement resulting from fraud is higher than the risk of an auditor not detecting a material misstatement resulting from error.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The risk of an auditor not detecting a material misstatement resulting from fraud is higher than the risk of an auditor not detecting one resulting from error. This is because fraud might involve sophisticated and carefully organized schemes designed to conceal it, such as forgery; deliberate failure to record transactions; or intentional misrepresentations being made to the auditor."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "The fraud risk assessment should be formally incorporated into the annual audit planning process.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The fraud risk assessment should play a significant role in informing and influencing the audit process. In addition to being used in the annual audit planning process, the fraud risk assessment should drive thinking and awareness in the development of audit programs for areas that have been identified as having a moderate-to-high risk of fraud. Although auditors should always be on guard for things that might be indicators of fraud risk, the results of the fraud risk assessment can help them design audit procedures in a way that enables them to look for fraud in known areas of high risk."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Fraud risk management programs should focus on:", "options": {"A": "Responding to identified fraud", "B": "Detecting fraud", "C": "Preventing fraud", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Fraud risk management programs must address fraud before, during, and after it occurs. Consequently, effective fraud risk management programs must incorporate policies and procedures designed to do all of the following: Prevent fraud—These activities focus on proactively identifying and assessing fraud risks and taking steps to address those risks; they are the first line of defense against fraud in the organization and generally include policies, procedures, training, and communication. Detect fraud—These activities seek to identify fraud occurrences as soon as possible after they begin to limit the damage done. Respond to identified fraud—These activities include investigating the allegation to determine the party or parties responsible, the means of the infraction, and the extent of the resulting damage; punishing the perpetrator, whether through employment sanctions or legal action; remediating the control weaknesses that allowed the fraud to be undertaken; and rebuilding stakeholders’ confidence in the organization."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "In general, a corporation cannot be held vicariously liable for the acts of an employee unless the employee acted for the ostensible purpose of benefiting the corporation.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Corporations and other organizations may be held liable for criminal acts of their employees if those acts are done in the course and scope of their employment and for the ostensible purpose of benefiting the corporation. An employee’s acts are generally considered to be in the course and scope of employment if the employee has actual authority or apparent authority to engage in those acts. Apparent authority means that a third party would reasonably believe the employee is authorized to perform the act on behalf of the company. Therefore, an organization could be held liable for something an employee does on behalf of the organization even if the employee is not authorized to perform that act. An organization will not be vicariously liable (i.e., liable for the misconduct of another party) for the acts of an employee unless the employee acted for the ostensible purpose of benefiting the corporation. This does not mean the corporation has to receive an actual benefit from the illegal acts of its employee. All that is required is that the employee intended to benefit the corporation."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "White-collar defendants are less likely to insist on a trial than other offenders.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "White-collar defendants are more likely to insist on a trial than other offenders. In at least 90% of criminal cases, defendants will plead guilty, avoiding the expense and effort of a trial. But in one notable study, more than 18% of white-collar defendants (as opposed to the usual 10%) pleaded “not guilty.” In cases like bank embezzlement, usually “simple cases with clear evidence,” plea bargains are easily negotiated and “prosecutors may actively seek guilty pleas.”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Which of the following individuals would generally be the best choice for a sponsor for a fraud risk assessment?", "options": {"A": "A staff accountant", "B": "An independent audit committee member", "C": "A mid-level sales manager", "D": "A CFO who has been known to command the use of extremely aggressive earnings-management practices"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Having the right sponsor for a fraud risk assessment is extremely important in ensuring its success and effectiveness. The sponsor must be senior enough in the organization and command the employees' respect to elicit full cooperation in the process. The sponsor has to be someone who is committed to learning the truth about where the company’s fraud vulnerabilities really are. He can’t be someone who is prone to rationalization or denial; he must be a truth seeker. In the ideal situation, the sponsor would be an independent board director or audit committee member. However, a good CEO or other internal senior leader can be equally as effective."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "The Treadway Commission was established with the purpose of defining the responsibility of the auditor in preventing and detecting fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The National Commission on Fraudulent Financial Reporting (commonly known as the Treadway Commission) was established in 1985 with the purpose of defining the responsibility of the auditor in preventing and detecting fraud. The commission was formed and sponsored by five predominant professional auditing organizations at the time—the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants, The Institute of Internal Auditors, the American Accounting Association, Financial Executives International, and the Institute of Management Accountants."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to ACFE research, employees are the most common source of tips that lead to the detection of fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Employees are a valuable source of information for discovering potential fraud. The ACFE 2018 Report to the Nations shows that slightly more than half of all tips (53%) that led to the detection of fraud were provided by employees of the victim organizations. This is more than twice the amount provided by any other source."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to COSO, internal control is a process “designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the achievement of objectives relating to operations, reporting, and compliance.”", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In its Internal Control—Integrated Framework, the Committee on Sponsoring Organizations (COSO) defines internal control as “a process, effected by an entity’s board of directors, management, and other personnel, designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the achievement of objectives relating to operations, reporting, and compliance.” As noted in this definition, internal controls should be designed to assist management in meeting the following three categories of objectives: 1. Operations objectives, which pertain to the effectiveness and efficiency of the organization’s operations 2. Reporting objectives, which pertain to the reporting of financial and nonfinancial information to internal and external parties 3. Compliance objectives, which pertain to the organization’s adherence to the laws and regulations to which it is subject"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "According to Managing the Business Risk of Fraud, an organization's anti-fraud policy should include consequences for individuals who condone fraudulent activity.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Organizations should enact policies that reflect the consequences and processes for individuals who commit or condone fraudulent activity. Such consequences might include termination of employment (or a contract, for nonemployees), reporting of the incident to law enforcement or regulatory authorities, and pursuit of civil or criminal action against the perpetrator(s). It is important for management to ensure that any corrective action taken is applied consistently for all involved in the fraudulent act. The organization should also have specific policies in place to identify and remediate any control deficiencies that allowed fraudulent conduct to occur."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "The success of the fraud risk assessment process depends on how effectively the results are reported and what the organization then does with those results.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The success of the fraud risk assessment process depends on how effectively the results are reported and what the organization then does with those results. A poorly communicated report can undermine the entire process and bring all momentum established to a halt. The report should be delivered in a style most suited to the language of the business. If management prefers succinct PowerPoint presentations, the fraud risk assessment team should not deliver a 50-page Word document."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "When performing a fraud risk assessment, the fraud examiner should only designate an area as high risk if the assessment has conclusively revealed that fraud is occurring there.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Assessing an area as having a high level of fraud risk does not conclusively mean that fraud is occurring there. However, the fraud risk assessment is useful in identifying areas to proactively investigate to determine whether fraud has in fact occurred. In addition, putting activity in high-risk areas under increased scrutiny can deter potential fraudsters by increasing their perception of detection."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "______________ is a process aimed at proactively identifying and addressing an organization’s vulnerabilities to internal and external fraud.", "options": {"A": "An internal control audit", "B": "A fraud risk assessment", "C": "A management ethics assessment", "D": "A fraud examination"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraud risk assessment is a process aimed at proactively identifying and addressing an organization’s vulnerabilities to internal and external fraud. A fraud risk assessment starts with an identification and prioritization of fraud risks that exist in the business. The process evolves as the results of that identification and prioritization begin to drive education, communication, organizational alignment, and action around effectively managing fraud risk and identifying new fraud risks as they emerge."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Edward Gross and other criminologists have asserted that organizations are inherently:", "options": {"A": "Averse to misconduct", "B": "Exploitative", "C": "Criminogenic", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Sociologist Edward Gross has asserted that all organizations are inherently \"criminogenic\" (i.e., prone to committing crime), but they are not necessarily criminal. Without necessarily meaning to, organizations can invite fraud as a means of obtaining goals. Gross makes this assertion because of the reliance on \"the bottom line.\""}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "A detailed anti-fraud policy can give management legal grounds to investigate and punish violators.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "To avoid being overly broad in nature, and thus difficult to enforce, anti-fraud policies should include specific examples of fraud. The scope of fraud within an organization might range from internal theft of cash in small amounts to a third-party billing scheme worth millions. Regardless of the materiality of a fraud, management should clearly define all types of fraud that could occur within the company. Doing so both lays out specific guidance so employees can understand what actions constitute fraud and provides management with the legal grounds to investigate and punish violators. Examples of fraudulent offenses include: Using company equipment (e.g., office supplies, company vehicles, mobile phones, computers) for personal reasons Stealing company assets (e.g., cash, receivables, inventory) Inflating reported hours worked Forging or altering checks and other documents Disclosing proprietary information to competitors Accepting bribes from or paying bribes to vendors or customers Engaging in transactions in which the employee has an undisclosed conflict of interest Destroying company records with malicious intent Intentionally misstating financial statements"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "The evaluation and communication of internal control deficiencies in a timely manner to those parties responsible for taking corrective action is a principle related to which component of COSO’s Internal Control—Integrated Framework?", "options": {"A": "Information and communication", "B": "Monitoring", "C": "Control activities", "D": "Risk assessment"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Monitoring is the process that assesses the effectiveness of a control system over time. This component of COSO’s Internal Control—Integrated Framework should include both ongoing evaluations and periodic, separate evaluations, the findings of which should be evaluated against predefined criteria. The following are the Framework principles supporting this component: The organization selects, develops, and performs ongoing and separate evaluations to ascertain whether the components of internal control are present and functioning. The organization evaluates and communicates internal control deficiencies in a timely manner to those parties responsible for taking corrective action, including senior management and the board of directors, as appropriate."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to COSO, the control environment of an organization:", "options": {"A": "Is established by directors and senior management", "B": "Sets the moral and ethical tone of the organization", "C": "Provides the foundation for the overall internal control system", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The control environment provides the foundation for the internal control system throughout the entire organization. Established by the directors and senior management, it sets the moral and ethical tone of an organization, which reinforces the importance of internal controls and expected standards of conduct. COSO provides five principles supporting the design and implementation of an effective control environment: Personnel at all levels demonstrate a commitment to integrity and ethical values. The board of directors is independent from management and oversees the development and performance of internal control. With board oversight, management establishes the structures, reporting lines, and appropriate authorities and responsibilities in the pursuit of organizational objectives. The organization demonstrates a commitment to attract, develop, and retain competent individuals in alignment with objectives. The organization holds individuals accountable for their internal control responsibilities in the pursuit of objectives."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Risk management involves weighing an organization’s strategic, operational, reporting, and compliance objectives against how much risk management is willing to accept.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Risk management involves the identification, prioritization, treatment, and monitoring of risks that threaten an organization’s ability to provide value to its stakeholders, whether increasing profitability and shareholder value for a for-profit entity or achieving program-specific goals for a nonprofit or governmental agency. More specifically, risk management balances risk appetite—how much risk management is willing to accept—with the ability to meet the organization’s strategic, operational, reporting, and compliance objectives."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Surprise audits can be effective in both preventing and detecting fraudulent conduct.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In addition to regularly scheduled fraud audits, surprise fraud audits of business functions in which fraud is most likely to occur can be effective both in increasing employees’ perception of detection and in uncovering actual frauds that have been perpetrated. The surprise element must be present for this control to be effective; predictability allows perpetrators the time to conceal their acts by altering, destroying, or misplacing records and other evidence."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Designating an area as having a high fraud risk and putting the related activity under increased scrutiny can deter potential fraudsters by increasing their perception of detection.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Assessing an area as having a high level of fraud risk does not conclusively mean that fraud is occurring there. However, the fraud risk assessment is useful in identifying areas to proactively investigate to determine whether fraud has in fact occurred. In addition, putting activity in high-risk areas under increased scrutiny can deter potential fraudsters by increasing their perception of detection."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following types of personnel can potentially bind a corporation through their own misconduct?", "options": {"A": "Independent contractors", "B": "Executive officers and directors", "C": "Low-level employees", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The corporate compliance policy should be communicated to everyone who can potentially bind a corporation through their own misconduct. This includes the following: Board of directors Executive officers Managers and supervisors Low-level employees Independent contractors"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Proactive audit procedures, such as fraud assessment questioning and surprise audits, can help demonstrate management’s intention to aggressively seek out fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Implementing proactive audit procedures demonstrates management’s intention to aggressively seek out possible fraudulent conduct instead of waiting for instances to come to management's attention. Such techniques include the use of analytical review procedures, fraud assessment questioning, and surprise audits where possible."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "A detailed anti-fraud policy should outline the types of actions that are considered to be fraud. Which of the following should be included on that list?", "options": {"A": "Forging or altering documents", "B": "Using company equipment for personal reasons", "C": "Disclosing proprietary information to competitors", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To avoid being overly broad in nature, and thus difficult to enforce, anti-fraud policies should include specific examples of fraud. The scope of fraud within an organization might range from internal theft of cash in small amounts to a third-party billing scheme worth millions. Regardless of the materiality of a fraud, management should clearly define all types of fraud that could occur within the company. Doing so both lays out specific guidance so employees can understand what actions constitute fraud and provides management with the legal grounds to investigate and punish violators. Examples of fraudulent offenses include: Using company equipment (e.g., office supplies, company vehicles, mobile phones, computers) for personal reasons Stealing company assets (e.g., cash, receivables, inventory) Inflating reported hours worked Forging or altering checks and other documents Disclosing proprietary information to competitors Accepting bribes from or paying bribes to vendors or customers Engaging in transactions in which the employee has an undisclosed conflict of interest Destroying company records with malicious intent Intentionally misstating financial statements"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following parties has some responsibility regarding an organization’s fraud detection and prevention efforts?", "options": {"A": "Management", "B": "In-house legal counsel", "C": "Board of directors", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The IIA’s Practice Guide: Internal Auditing and Fraud discusses various parties' typical roles and responsibilities for fraud detection and prevention. These parties include: Board of directors: The board of directors is responsible for effective and responsible corporate fraud governance and is tasked with overseeing management’s actions to manage fraud risks. Audit committee: The audit committee’s role is to evaluate management’s identification of fraud risks and the implementation of anti-fraud measures, as well as to provide the tone at the top that fraud will not be accepted in any form. The audit committee is also responsible for overseeing controls to prevent or detect management fraud. Management: Management is responsible for overseeing the activities of employees, assessing the entity's vulnerability to fraud, and establishing and maintaining an effective internal control system at a reasonable cost. Legal counsel: Legal counsel advises the organization on legal matters pertaining to fraud. External auditors: External auditors have a responsibility to comply with professional standards and to plan and perform the audit of the organization’s financial statements to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatements, whether caused by error or fraud. Loss prevention manager: The loss prevention manager deals with crimes, disasters, accidents, waste, and other business risks, and he usually works closely with internal auditors to identify areas of weak internal controls within the organization. Fraud investigators: Fraud investigators are responsible for detecting and investigating fraud, as well as recovering assets. Other employees: All employees have a responsibility to report suspicious activity to a hotline, the internal audit department, or management."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Establishing and communicating the proper flow of information to everyone in the organization is an essential component of a fraud prevention program.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A well-designed organizational structure—with key areas of authority and clear and proper lines of reporting—can be an effective fraud prevention measure. A confused structure, in contrast, makes it easier for a fraudster to perpetrate and conceal his misdeeds. Establishing and communicating the proper flow of information to everyone in the organization is an essential component of a well-designed organizational structure. Flowcharts displaying organizational and departmental hierarchies can be a helpful tool for this purpose. To ensure that information is being properly received and that instructions are being carried out, such checks must be established."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Managers should be instructed to observe employees' lifestyles for warning signs of fraud, and employees should know that supervisors are watching for unexplained or suspicious anomalies of this nature.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "It is common for employees who steal to use the proceeds for lifestyle improvements. Some examples include more expensive cars, extravagant vacations, expensive clothing, new or remodeled homes, expensive recreational property, and outside investments. Managers should be educated to be observant of these signs. To further increase the deterrent effect, employees should know that supervisors are watching for unexplained or suspicious anomalies of this nature."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the factors that Diane Vaughan cites as contributing to organizations being inherently prone to committing crime?", "options": {"A": "Organizations tend to recruit and attract similar individuals.", "B": "Long-term loyalty is encouraged through company retirement and benefits.", "C": "Loyalty is encouraged through social interaction, such as company parties and social functions.", "D": "Rewards are given to employees who challenge the status quo."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Organizations can be criminogenic because they encourage loyalty. According to Diane Vaughan, the reasons are that: The organization tends to recruit and attract similar individuals. Rewards are given out to those who display characteristics of the “company man.” Long-term loyalty is encouraged through company retirement and benefits. Loyalty is encouraged through social interaction, such as company parties and social functions. Frequent transfers and long working hours encourage isolation from other groups. Specialized job skills can discourage personnel from seeking employment elsewhere."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "An entity’s corporate culture is most effectively assessed using a checklist of initiatives to make sure all the elements of a strong tone at the top are in place.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A strong corporate culture can most often be observed by its outcome, rather than by any individual component. Fostering a culture of ethics and compliance runs deeper than simply implementing a checklist of initiatives; similarly, a culture of corruption can exist even in companies with seemingly sound policies in place."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "The Fraud Triangle hypothesis can be used to explain every instance of fraudulent conduct.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Cressey’s classic Fraud Triangle helps explain the nature of many—but not all—occupational offenders. For example, although academicians have tested his model, it has still not fully found its way into practice in terms of developing fraud prevention programs. Common sense dictates that no one model—not even Cressey's—fits every situation."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "When gathering information as part of a fraud risk assessment, surveys and anonymous feedback mechanisms both provide an effective way to conduct candid one-on-one conversations with employees.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Several techniques can be successfully used to gather information as part of a fraud risk assessment. These include: Interviews, which can be an effective way to conduct candid one-on-one conversations with employees Focus groups, which can enable the assessor to observe the interactions among a group of employees as they collectively discuss a question or issue Surveys, which are electronic or paper questionnaires that can be either anonymous or directly attributable to the individual participants Anonymous feedback mechanisms, which can include means for anonymous employee suggestions or responses to questions posed"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Fraud examiners should consider the nature of the assignment and the preliminary information available in forming the engagement hypothesis.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "As part of exercising professional integrity and competence, fraud examiners must always perform their work with a mindset of professional skepticism and begin assignments with the belief that something is wrong or someone is committing a fraud (depending on the nature of the assignment and the preliminary information available). Furthermore, fraud examiners should relax their attitude of skepticism only when the evidence shows no signs of fraudulent activity. At no time is a fraud examiner entitled to assume a fraud problem does not exist. Thus, professional skepticism can be dispelled only by evidence. As a result, opinions or attestations about a fraud-free environment are absolutely prohibited for ACFE members."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Research shows that a criminal’s social status or class is the determinant aspect of white-collar crime.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Of all factors, organizational opportunity remains the determinant aspect of white-collar crime. Research shows that a criminal’s position in an organization and his ability to organize the scheme have far more bearing on the crime than social status or class alone."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Fraudulent customer payments, corporate espionage, and hacking schemes are all fraud risks pertaining to which of the following categories?", "options": {"A": "Regulatory and legal misconduct", "B": "External fraud", "C": "Asset misappropriation", "D": "Reputation risk"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "External fraud risks include: Fraud committed by customers (e.g., fraudulent customer payments) Fraud committed by vendors (e.g., overbilling by a vendor or collusion between bidding contractors to inflate contract price) Fraud committed by competitors (e.g., corporate espionage) Fraud committed by unrelated third parties (e.g., hacking)"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the responsibilities that the internal auditor should carry out in conducting audit engagements?", "options": {"A": "Be alert to opportunities that could allow fraud, such as control deficiencies.", "B": "Report all findings of fraud to the Securities and Exchange Commission within ten working days.", "C": "Have sufficient knowledge of fraud to identify red flags indicating fraud might have been committed.", "D": "Consider fraud risks in the assessment of internal control design and determination of audit steps to perform."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "To help auditors comply with their responsibilities pertaining to fraud, the IIA released IPPF—Practice Guide: Internal Auditing and Fraud. Although not mandatory, the guidance included in the Practice Guide is strongly recommended. Specifically, this Guide states that, in conducting audit engagements, the internal auditor should: Consider fraud risks in the assessment of internal control design and determination of audit steps to perform. Have sufficient knowledge of fraud to identify red flags indicating fraud might have been committed. Be alert to opportunities that could allow fraud, such as control deficiencies. Evaluate whether management is actively retaining responsibility for oversight of the fraud risk management program, whether timely and sufficient corrective measures have been taken with respect to any noted control deficiencies or weaknesses, and whether the plan for monitoring the program continues to be adequate for the program’s ongoing success. Evaluate the indicators of fraud and decide whether any further action is necessary or whether an investigation should be recommended. Recommend investigation when appropriate."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "White-collar criminals are more likely to be fined than to face prison terms as punishment.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "More often than prison, the punishment of choice for white-collar criminals is the imposition of fines. Whereas 6% of the “common criminals” in one notable survey received fines, all of the antitrust violators received fines."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding a fraud risk assessment?", "options": {"A": "It can be used to improve employee fraud awareness", "B": "The results should be used to develop plans to mitigate fraud risk", "C": "It can help management identify individuals who put the organization at the greatest risk of fraud", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Every organization should conduct a fraud risk assessment and should create processes to keep the assessment current and relevant. Not only is doing so a sound corporate governance strategy, but it also makes good business sense. The benefits of conducting a fraud risk assessment include enabling the organization to: Improve communication and awareness about fraud. Identify where it is most vulnerable to fraud and what activities put the company at the greatest risk. Know who puts the organization at the greatest risk. Develop plans to mitigate risk. Develop techniques to investigate and determine if fraud has occurred in areas of high risk. Assess internal controls. Comply with regulations and professional standards."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Which of the following parties is responsible for overseeing business operations by assessing the strategy and underlying purpose of management’s decisions and actions?", "options": {"A": "Shareholders", "B": "The board of directors", "C": "External auditors", "D": "Industry regulators"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A corporation’s board of directors is made up of individuals who are generally elected by the entity’s voting members (e.g., shareholders in the case of a corporation or members in the case of an association). The directors represent the middlemen between the corporation’s owners (i.e., shareholders) and those carrying out its activities (i.e., management), and they act as guardians of the organization’s resources and assets. As such, the board oversees business operations by assessing the strategy and underlying purpose of management’s decisions and actions."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "The term _______ refers to the oversight responsibilities of different parties for an organization’s direction, operations, and performance.", "options": {"A": "Corporate governance", "B": "Risk management", "C": "Fraud risk assessment", "D": "Corporate compliance"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The term corporate governance refers to a corporation’s government; the term is broadly used to describe the oversight responsibilities of different parties for an organization’s direction, operations, and performance. More specifically, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) defines corporate governance as: “[The] procedures and processes according to which an organisation is directed and controlled. The corporate governance structure specifies the distribution of rights and responsibilities among the different participants in the organisation—such as the board, managers, shareholders and other stakeholders—and lays down the rules and procedures for decision-making.”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Roger has just completed a fraud examination report containing confidential information for ABC Inc., a client. He received a call from the local police requesting a copy of the report. Which of the following statements is FALSE?", "options": {"A": "Roger can turn over the report if it is demanded by a court order.", "B": "Roger can turn over the report if his client consents.", "C": "Roger can turn over the report if the information is requested in a search warrant.", "D": "Roger can turn over the report without any repercussions because he owns the information contained in the document."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Confidential information, for all practical purposes, is any and all information a fraud examiner might obtain in the course of work, whether it be from the company or client for whom an investigation is performed or from any other source consulted during the work. However, there is no legal privilege that exists between a fraud examiner and his client. That means that although the fraud examiner is not allowed to reveal confidential information without authorization from the client, if the information is subject to a legal court order or search warrant, the fraud examiner must turn it over."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to the 2018 Report to the Nations, more occupational frauds are committed by men than by women.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A sizeable majority of the fraudsters in the 2018 Report to the Nations study (69%) were males. Men also caused much larger median losses (USD 156,000) than females (USD 89,000). This is consistent with our past studies, which have all shown males to be responsible for between 65% and 70% of frauds along with a significant disparity in fraud loss."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Which of the following is/are included in the five fraud risk management principles described in the COSO/ACFE Fraud Risk Management Guide?", "options": {"A": "Communicating the expectations of those governing the fraud risk management program", "B": "Performing comprehensive fraud risk assessments to identify specific fraud schemes", "C": "Developing ongoing evaluations for each fraud risk management principle", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The COSO/ACFE Fraud Risk Management Guide describes five broad principles of fraud risk management, one for each of the five interrelated components of internal control listed in COSO’s Internal Controls—Integrated Framework: fraud risk governance, fraud risk assessment, fraud control activities, fraud investigation and corrective action, and fraud risk management monitoring activities. Each of these principles is then supported by several points of focus. The principles and underlying points of focus combine to create a full framework that can be used to design, implement, and assess an effective fraud risk management program. Under the fraud risk governance principle, the organization establishes and communicates a fraud risk management program that demonstrates the expectations of the board of directors and senior management and their commitment to high integrity and ethical values regarding managing fraud risk. Under the fraud risk assessment principle, the organization performs comprehensive fraud risk assessments to identify specific fraud schemes and risks, assess their likelihood and significance, evaluate existing fraud control activities, and implement actions to mitigate residual fraud risks. Under the fraud risk management monitoring activities principle, the organization selects, develops, and performs ongoing evaluations to ascertain whether each of the five principles of fraud risk management is present and functioning, and communicates deficiencies in the fraud risk management program in a timely manner to parties responsible for taking corrective action, including senior management and the board of directors."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to a study conducted by Dr. Steve Albrecht, occupational crime perpetrators who were interested primarily in \"beating the system\" committed larger frauds than those who believed their pay was not adequate.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "According to Dr. Steve Albrecht, perpetrators who were interested primarily in “beating the system” committed larger frauds. However, perpetrators who believed their pay was not adequate committed primarily small frauds. Lack of segregation of responsibilities, placing undeserved trust in key employees, imposing unrealistic goals, and operating on a crisis basis were all pressures or weaknesses associated with large frauds. College graduates were less likely to spend their illegal income on extravagant vacations, recreational property, extramarital relationships, and expensive automobiles. Finally, those with lower salaries were more likely to have a prior criminal record."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Management must assign a quantitative measure to its risk appetite so that it can accurately measure the fraud risk management program’s effectiveness.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Management can choose whether to use a quantitative measure or a qualitative one to express risk appetite. An important component in defining the objective of the fraud risk management program is determining management’s risk appetite. Risk appetite should be expressed in a manner that is appropriate for the organization’s culture and operations, whether qualitatively—low, medium, or high, for example—or quantitatively, using a numeric scale. For example, a company’s management might decide that it prefers to reduce the residual risk of fraud down to a “low” level, implying a desire for strong controls and monitoring of such controls over a particular area of the business. Another company might decide that any risk rated three or higher (on a risk scale of one to five) is unacceptable. Risk appetite can also be broken down into specific types or sources of fraud, which allows for prioritization of fraud risk management strategies based on the assessed components."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, fraud examiners are strictly prohibited from revealing confidential client information under any circumstances.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Two articles of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics apply in situations regarding release of confidential client information. Article IV states: \"An ACFE Member will comply with the lawful orders of the courts, and will testify to matters truthfully and without bias or prejudice.\" Article VI says: \"An ACFE Member shall not reveal any confidential information obtained during a professional engagement without proper authorization.\" However, fraud examiners are not bound by confidentiality when doing so would violate the law. Thus, fraud examiners can reveal client confidences when responding to a legal court order."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Leo, a Certified Fraud Examiner, conducted a fraud examination at Blue Corp. Anna was a prime suspect in the disappearance of money, but Leo could not prove it. Later, Leo discovered Anna had been recently hired by Red Corp., another client of his. Under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, Leo must:", "options": {"A": "Not inform Red Corp.", "B": "Inform Red Corp.", "C": "Inform Red Corp. if the evidence is clear and convincing", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Article VI says that: \"An ACFE Member shall not reveal any confidential information obtained during a professional engagement without proper authorization.\" Under this scenario, Leo may not disclose information about Anna's employment at Blue Corp. or that she was a suspect in the disappearance of money without the authorization of Blue Corp. However, even if that authorization was received, Leo is limited as to what he can disclose. Anna was a suspect; she did not confess, nor was she convicted of a crime. If Leo does disclose this information, he could run the risk of serious legal problems."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Which of the following is an effective way to help prevent fraud through the organization’s performance measurement and management programs?", "options": {"A": "Tying employee compensation to aggressive organizational performance goals", "B": "Establishing loosely defined job descriptions that enable employees flexibility in their roles", "C": "Including ethics-based metrics as a component of performance evaluations", "D": "Placing the responsibility for identifying training needs and performance deficiencies in the employee’s hands"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Organizations should provide employees with well-defined job descriptions and performance goals. Performance goals should be routinely reviewed to ensure that they do not set unrealistic standards, and training should be provided on a consistent basis to ensure that employees maintain the skills needed to perform their tasks effectively. Management should also quickly determine where deficiencies in an employee’s conduct exist and work with the employee to fix the problem. Additionally, there is a fine line between performance goals that motivate employees to challenge themselves and those that are so ambitious that the only way employees can meet them is to perpetrate fraud. When employee compensation, including bonuses, or job security is tied to unachievable performance goals, employees have the incentive to mastermind creative (i.e., fraudulent) approaches to meeting them. Including ethics-based metrics—those that focus on how employees do business, not just how much business they do—as a component of performance goals and evaluation can be an especially effective way to foster ethical behavior and reinforce the importance of ethics as the guiding factor in making business decisions."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "During a fraud examination, John, a CFE, becomes aware of a situation that might appear to others as though he has a conflict of interest, even though there is no actual conflict. To address the situation, John’s best course of action is to:", "options": {"A": "Immediately disclose the situation to company management", "B": "Immediately withdraw from the engagement without disclosing the potential conflict to management", "C": "Continue working on the assignment without disclosing the potential conflict but take care to avoid any areas where an actual conflict might arise", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "ACFE members are responsible for maintaining independence in attitude and appearance and for approaching and conducting fraud examinations in an objective and unbiased manner. Independence of attitude requires impartiality and fairness in conducting fraud examinations and in reaching resulting conclusions and judgments. Fraud examiners must also be sensitive to the appearance of independence so that conclusions and judgments will be accepted as impartial by knowledgeable third parties. Fraud examiners who become aware of a situation or relationship that could be perceived to impair independence, whether or not actual impairments exist, should inform management immediately and take steps to eliminate the perceived impairment, including withdrawing from the examination if necessary. Objectivity refers to the ability to conduct fraud examinations without being influenced by one’s own personal feelings or the feelings and motives of others. To ensure objectivity in performing examinations, fraud examiners must maintain an independent mental attitude, reach judgments on examination matters without undue influence from others, and avoid being placed in positions where they would be unable to work in an objective professional manner. All possible conflicts of interest should be disclosed."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Professional organizations, such as the Association of Certified Fraud Examiners, have codes of ethics because:", "options": {"A": "They provide more direct solutions to professional ethical dilemmas than might exist under general ethical principles", "B": "They facilitate practical enforcement and profession-wide internal discipline", "C": "They serve as a reference and benchmark for ethical guidance", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A code of conduct serves a useful purpose as a reference and benchmark for ethical guidance. A code makes explicit the conduct that is expected in a particular profession. Thus, codes of professional ethics can provide some direct solutions that might not be available from general ethics theories. Furthermore, individuals will have a better understanding of what is expected of them when a code of ethical conduct is in place. From the viewpoint of an organized profession, a code is a public declaration of principled conduct and a means of facilitating enforcement of standards of conduct. Practical enforcement and profession-wide internal discipline would be much more difficult if members were not first put on notice of the standards."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Risk management includes which of the following activities with regard to the risks that threaten an organization?", "options": {"A": "Treatment", "B": "Monitoring", "C": "Identification", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Risk management involves the identification, prioritization, treatment, and monitoring of risks that threaten an organization’s ability to provide value to its stakeholders, whether increasing profitability and shareholder value for a for-profit entity or achieving program-specific goals for a nonprofit or governmental agency. More specifically, risk management balances risk appetite—how much risk management is willing to accept—with the ability to meet the organization’s strategic, operational, reporting, and compliance objectives."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Effective corporate governance is the foundation of fraud risk management.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The importance of active and committed board participation in the fraud risk management process cannot be overstated. As stated in the joint COSO/ACFE Fraud Risk Management Guide, fraud risk governance is one of the principles of effective fraud risk management, and “the board of directors and senior management provide a solid foundation of fraud risk management.” Managing the Business Risk of Fraud: A Practical Guide, the predecessor to the COSO/ACFE publication, expanded this point, noting, “effective governance processes are the foundation of fraud risk management. Lack of effective corporate governance seriously undermines any fraud risk management program.”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "The fraud risk assessment team should include:", "options": {"A": "Individuals with experience gathering and eliciting information", "B": "Individuals with diverse knowledge, skills, and perspectives", "C": "Individuals who are credible", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Before conducting the fraud risk assessment, the organization should build a fraud risk assessment team consisting of individuals with diverse knowledge, skills, and perspectives that will lead and conduct the fraud risk assessment. The size of the team will depend on the size of the organization and the methods used to conduct the assessment. The team should have individuals who are credible and who have experience in gathering and eliciting information. The team members might include internal and external sources, such as accounting and finance personnel, operations personnel, members of the legal department, internal auditors, internal security or investigative personnel, external consultants with fraud and risk expertise, and any business leader with direct accountability for the effectiveness of the organization’s fraud risk management efforts."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Components necessary to develop, implement, and manage a comprehensive ethics program include:", "options": {"A": "A vision statement", "B": "Sanctions for unethical behavior", "C": "A designated ethics official", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The following 12 components are necessary to develop, implement, and manage a comprehensive ethics program: Focus on ethical leadership Vision statement Values statement Code of ethics Designated ethics official Ethics task force or committee Ethics communication strategy Ethics training Ethics help and fraud report telephone line Ethical behavior rewards and sanctions Comprehensive system to monitor and track ethics data Periodic evaluation of ethics efforts and data"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Management at Blue Sky Inc. has decided to implement a formal risk management program and is using a risk management framework as a starting point. In developing the program, management should tailor the framework to the organization’s:", "options": {"A": "Culture", "B": "Regulatory environment", "C": "Financial condition", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "While an established risk management framework can be a helpful starting point in developing a risk management program, every organization faces a unique set of risks based upon its industry, financial condition, regulatory environment, culture, and a host of other factors. As such, management should consider all of these factors when developing an organization’s risk management program. An entity’s risk management program must be tailored to the specifics of the organization for it to be effective."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Which of the following is an example of the non-shareable financial need leg of the Fraud Triangle?", "options": {"A": "Credit card debt from excessive shopping", "B": "Gambling debts", "C": "Addiction problems", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "One leg of the Fraud Triangle represents a perceived non-shareable financial need. As Cressey explained, “In all cases of trust violation encountered, the violator considered that a financial problem which confronted him could not be shared with persons who, from a more objective point of view, probably could have aided in the solution of the problem.” In addition to being non-shareable, the problem that drives the fraudster is described as “financial” because these are problems that can generally be solved by the theft of cash or other assets. Examples of such situations include financial needs caused by gambling debts, addiction problems, or credit card debt from excessive shopping."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "The risk of the auditor not detecting a material misstatement resulting from employee fraud is greater than the risk of the auditor not detecting a material misstatement resulting from management fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The risk of the auditor not detecting a material misstatement resulting from management fraud is greater than for employee fraud because management is frequently in a position to directly or indirectly manipulate accounting records, present fraudulent financial information, or override control procedures designed to prevent similar frauds by other employees."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "The fraud risk assessment should include input from both management and auditors to ensure a holistic view of the organization's risks, but it should exclude all others to maintain the independence and objectivity of the assessment process.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Risk assessments created or performed by management and auditors without the input of the staff performing the operational tasks will be ineffective. It is crucial to include members of all levels of the organization in the risk assessment process to ensure that all relevant risks are addressed and reviewed from many different perspectives. Additionally, asking employees at lower levels of the organization specific questions about the company culture or eliciting ideas to strengthen internal controls can provide incredibly valuable information that might not be obtainable from any other source."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding a corporation’s board of directors?", "options": {"A": "The directors represent the middlemen between the shareholders and management", "B": "The directors oversee business operations by assessing the strategy and underlying purpose of management’s decisions and actions", "C": "The directors are generally elected by the company's shareholders", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A corporation’s board of directors is made up of individuals who are generally elected by the entity’s voting members (e.g., shareholders in the case of a corporation or members in the case of an association). The directors represent the middlemen between the corporation’s owners (i.e., shareholders) and those carrying out its activities (i.e., management), and they act as guardians of the organization’s resources and assets. As such, the board oversees business operations by assessing the strategy and underlying purpose of management’s decisions and actions."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Unless specific unacceptable conduct is detailed in an anti-fraud policy, there can be legal problems in discharging a dishonest employee.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In developing the anti-fraud policy, management should check with legal counsel regarding any legal considerations with respect to the policy. One of the most important legal considerations is to ensure everyone and every allegation is handled in a uniform manner. Additionally, if the type of conduct that is considered unacceptable is not accurately detailed, there might be legal problems in discharging a dishonest employee."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Criminal activities involving corporations stem primarily from the organization's subcultures and values, rather than from the attitudes and characteristics of the individuals carrying out the crimes.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Criminal activities involving corporations often originate from organizational subcultures and values and are developed over time. While individuals carry out the criminal enterprise, their attitudes and characteristics are of little importance, as an organization will replace those employees unwilling to participate in a criminal activity."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "A person’s social status plays no role in his ability to commit white-collar crime.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "What is loosely called “class” or “social status” does have an effect on crimes. For example, one defendant used his position as chairman of a local bank board to set up loans for his ailing wood chip company. The loans would never have been approved without the chairman’s influence, and he never reported them in his proxy statement to the bank’s shareholders."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Which of the following is among the audit committee’s responsibilities for fraud risk management?", "options": {"A": "Performing and regularly updating the fraud risk assessment", "B": "Receiving regular reports on the status of reported or alleged fraud", "C": "Monitoring and proactively improving the fraud risk management program", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "As a sub-group of the board of directors, the audit committee is often delegated oversight of the organization’s financial, accounting, and audit matters and reports to the full board. As part of this responsibility, the committee must take an active role in overseeing the assessment and monitoring of the organization’s fraud risks. This involves: Receiving regular reports on the status of reported or alleged fraud Being aware of fraud risks that are common in the organization’s industry Meeting regularly with key internal parties (e.g., the chief audit executive or other senior financial persons) to discuss identified fraud risks and the steps being taken to prevent and detect fraud Understanding how internal and external audit strategies address fraud risk Providing external auditors with evidence that the audit committee is dedicated to effective fraud risk management Engaging in open conversations with external auditors about any known or suspected fraud Seeking advice of legal counsel whenever it deals with allegations of fraud Monitoring and improving the fraud risk management program and performing and maintaining the fraud risk assessment are both part of senior management's responsibilities for addressing fraud risk."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "To ensure the independence of the team members, a fraud risk assessment must be conducted by a consultant or other external party.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A good fraud risk assessment can be effectively conducted either by people inside the organization or with external sources. However, the people leading and conducting the fraud risk assessment need to be independent and objective throughout the assessment process. Additionally, they must also be perceived as independent and objective by others."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Good corporate governance practices:", "options": {"A": "Ensure that no single party is capable of making all the business decisions without influence, input, or approval of other parties", "B": "Define the relationships and expectations of the parties involved", "C": "Provide clear lines of accountability and reporting", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "An organization’s corporate governance structure provides the lines of accountability and reporting, defines the relationships and expectations of the parties involved, and sets the rules and practices that these parties must follow in carrying out their responsibilities. The checks-and-balances system of corporate governance ensures that no single party is capable of making all the business decisions without influence, input, or approval of other parties."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "In the context of a fraud examination, the preservation of integrity requires that the fraud examiner avoid all differences of opinion regarding all material matters with the other parties to the engagement.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Integrity requires honesty, truthfulness, trustworthiness, and confidentiality. It also requires subordination of desires for personal gain to the interests of clients, employers, and the public. It requires independence of mental attitude and avoidance of conflicts of interest. Additionally, integrity means that a fraud examiner should have a well-developed sense of moral philosophy—an ability to analyze situations where no rules of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics are specifically applicable and to be able to distinguish right from wrong. It does not mean, however, that an ACFE member must be perfect in all technical matters, nor does it mean that fraud examiners and others cannot have honest differences of opinion. In the course of a fraud examination, inadvertent errors, mistakes of judgment, and other problems might cause conflict. In such cases, a fraud examiner can preserve integrity either by admitting error or by convincingly justifying a difference of perception or opinion."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "In response to a risk identified during a fraud risk assessment, management decides to implement appropriate countermeasures, such as prevention and detection controls. This response is known as:", "options": {"A": "Mitigating the risk", "B": "Transferring the risk", "C": "Avoiding the risk", "D": "Assuming the risk"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When responding to the organization’s residual fraud risks, management can help mitigate a risk by implementing appropriate countermeasures, such as prevention and detection controls. The fraud risk assessment team should evaluate each countermeasure to determine if it is cost effective and reasonable given the probability of occurrence and impact of loss."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to International Standard on Auditing (ISA) 240, ________ involves intentional misstatements in financial statements to deceive financial statement users.", "options": {"A": "A financial reporting error", "B": "A financial report item adjustment", "C": "Fraudulent financial reporting", "D": "An auditor misrepresentation"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "According to ISA 240, fraudulent financial reporting involves intentional misstatements, including omissions of amounts or disclosures, in financial statements to deceive financial statement users. It can be caused by the efforts of management to manage earnings in order to deceive financial statement users by influencing their perceptions as to the entity’s performance and profitability."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "The size of the fraud risk assessment team will depend on the size of the organization and the methods used to conduct the assessment.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Before conducting the fraud risk assessment, the organization should build a fraud risk assessment team consisting of individuals with diverse knowledge, skills, and perspectives that will lead and conduct the fraud risk assessment. The size of the team will depend on the size of the organization and the methods used to conduct the assessment. The team should have individuals who are credible and who have experience in gathering and eliciting information. The team members might include internal and external sources, such as accounting and finance personnel, operations personnel, members of the legal department, internal auditors, internal security or investigative personnel, external consultants with fraud and risk expertise, and any business leader with direct accountability for the effectiveness of the organization’s fraud risk management efforts."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "In defining the objectives of the fraud risk management program, management can choose to express risk appetite either quantitatively or qualitatively.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "An important component in defining the objective of the fraud risk management program is determining management’s risk appetite. Risk appetite should be expressed in a manner that is appropriate for the organization’s culture and operations, whether qualitatively—low, medium, or high, for example—or quantitatively, using a numeric scale. For example, a company’s management might decide that it prefers to reduce the residual risk of fraud down to a “low” level, implying a desire for strong controls and monitoring of such controls over a particular area of the business. Another company might decide that any risk rated three or higher (on a risk scale of one to five) is unacceptable. Risk appetite can also be broken down into specific types or sources of fraud, which allows for prioritization of fraud risk management strategies based on the assessed components."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Cressey found that embezzlers' offenses are motivated by situations that either threaten their current status or threaten to prevent them from achieving a higher status.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Through his research, Cressey found that the non-shareable problems encountered by the people he interviewed arose from situations that could be divided into six basic categories: violation of ascribed obligations, problems resulting from personal failure, business reversals, physical isolation, status gaining, and employer-employee relations. All of these situations in some way dealt with status-seeking or status-maintaining activities by the subjects. In other words, the non-shareable problems threatened the status of the subjects, or threatened to prevent them from achieving a higher status than the one they occupied at the time of their violation."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "The fraud risk management program should include the formal procedures management takes in response to a fraud, such as punishing the perpetrator, remediating the control weaknesses that allowed the fraud to occur, and rebuilding stakeholders’ confidence in the organization.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Fraud risk management programs must address fraud before, during, and after it occurs. Consequently, effective fraud risk management programs must incorporate policies and procedures designed to do all of the following: Prevent fraud—These activities focus on proactively identifying and assessing fraud risks and taking steps to address those risks; they are the first line of defense against fraud in the organization and generally include policies, procedures, training, and communication. Detect fraud—These activities seek to identify fraud occurrences as soon as possible after they begin to limit the damage done. Respond to identified fraud—These activities include investigating the allegation to determine the party or parties responsible, the means of the infraction, and the extent of the resulting damage; punishing the perpetrator, whether through employment sanctions or legal action; remediating the control weaknesses that allowed the fraud to be undertaken; and rebuilding stakeholders’ confidence in the organization."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Effective corporate governance practices are most important for which of the following organizations?", "options": {"A": "A small souvenir shop in a tourist town that employs four retail clerks, in addition to the store’s owners", "B": "An advertising firm with 75 employees and four partners, all of whom actively participate in the business", "C": "A financial services company whose stock shares are traded on a public securities exchange", "D": "A sole-practitioner dentist’s office"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Solid corporate governance practices are most necessary in an organization in which the owners are not also the individuals responsible for setting its strategy and carrying out its business activities (such as a publicly traded company)."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Which of the following influences the level of fraud risk faced by an organization?", "options": {"A": "The ethics of its leadership team", "B": "The effectiveness of its internal controls", "C": "The geographic regions in which it operates", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Many factors influence how at-risk an organization is to fraud. Some of the main factors are: The nature of the business in which it is engaged (i.e., its industry and operations) The environment in which it operates (e.g., physical storefront or Internet-based, geographical location) The effectiveness of the internal controls within the business processes The ethics and values of the company and its employees"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to Diane Vaughan, an employee who is truly loyal to a company would never commit fraud on the company's behalf.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Diane Vaughan, the author of Controlling Unlawful Organizational Behavior: Social Structure and Corporate Misconduct, believes that organizations can be criminogenic because they encourage loyalty. This, in turn, causes company personnel to sometimes perceive that the organization might be worth committing crime for to maintain and further its goals. The use of formal and informal rewards and punishments, plus social activities and pressures to participate, link an employee’s needs and goals to the company's success. When a company achieves its goals, its employees prosper. In short, the interests of an organization and its employees coincide, and that situation might set the stage for unlawful conduct by individuals on the organization’s behalf."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "During the course of a fraud examination, Omar, an employee of XYZ Inc., approaches Maryam, a Certified Fraud Examiner and fellow employee of XYZ, and tells Maryam that he knows of a major fraud being committed by company management. However, Omar says he can only provide details if Maryam promises him absolute confidentiality. In response to Omar’s condition, Maryam should agree to keep the source of the information confidential, even though she knows she will eventually have to reveal Omar’s identity.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraud examiners must remember that the confidentiality relationship runs first to the client or employer, and the promise of confidentiality is understood to exist without being spoken. In the case of Omar (the employee/informant), Maryam (the Certified Fraud Examiner) does not have an understood or unspoken promise of confidentiality. Maryam should tell Omar that she will try to keep the information as confidential as possible, but it would be unethical for Maryam to promise confidentiality to the employee; her first obligation is to the employer."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Following the conclusion of the fraud risk assessment process, management should:", "options": {"A": "Use the results to promote awareness, education, and action planning", "B": "Track and measure progress against agreed-upon action plans", "C": "Use the assessment findings to monitor the performance of key internal controls", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To make the most of the fraud risk assessment process, management should use the results to: Begin a dialogue across the company that promotes awareness, education, and action planning to reduce fraud risk. Look for fraud in high-risk areas. Hold action owners accountable for progress against agreed-upon plans. Keep the assessment process alive and relevant. Modify or create the code of conduct or ethics policy. Monitor key internal controls."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "In response to a risk identified during a fraud risk assessment, management chooses to accept the risk, rather than to implement any responsive measures. This approach is known as:", "options": {"A": "Avoiding the risk", "B": "Assuming the risk", "C": "Mitigating the risk", "D": "Transferring the risk"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Management may choose to assume the risk if it determines that the probability of occurrence and impact of loss are low. Management may decide that it is more cost effective to assume the risk than it is to eliminate the asset or discontinue the activity, buy insurance to transfer the risk, or implement countermeasures to mitigate the risk."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "In response to a risk identified during a fraud risk assessment, management decides to purchase a bond to help protect the company against the associated risk of loss. This response is known as:", "options": {"A": "Avoiding the risk", "B": "Assuming the risk", "C": "Transferring the risk", "D": "Mitigating the risk"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "When responding to the organization’s residual fraud risks, management may transfer some or all of the risk by purchasing fidelity insurance or a bond. The cost to the organization is the premium paid for the insurance or bond. The covered risk of loss is then transferred to the insurance company."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "During an audit, auditors should validate that the organization is appropriately managing the moderate-to-high fraud risks identified in the fraud risk assessment. Ways to do so include:", "options": {"A": "Identifying within the moderate-to-high fraud risk areas whether there is a moderate-to-high risk of management override of internal controls", "B": "Identifying and mapping the existing controls that pertain to the moderate-to-high fraud risks identified in the fraud risk assessment", "C": "Designing and performing tests to evaluate whether the identified controls are operating effectively and efficiently", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In the course of their work, auditors should validate that the organization is appropriately managing the moderate-to-high fraud risks identified in the fraud risk assessment. Ways to do so include: Identifying and mapping the existing preventive and detective controls that pertain to the moderate-to-high fraud risks identified in the fraud risk assessment Designing and performing tests to evaluate whether the identified controls are operating effectively and efficiently Identifying within the moderate-to-high fraud risk areas whether there is a moderate-to-high risk of management override of internal controls Developing and delivering reports that incorporate the results of their validation and testing of the fraud risk controls"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "A corporation cannot be held criminally liable for its employees' actions if there were specific policies in place that prohibited the activity undertaken by the employees.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A corporation can generally be held criminally responsible for criminal acts committed by its employees even if those in management had no knowledge of or participation in the underlying criminal events and even if there were specific policies or instructions prohibiting the activity undertaken by the employees. The acts of any employee, from the lowest clerk to the CEO, can impute liability upon a corporation. In fact, in many jurisdictions, a corporation can be criminally responsible for the collective knowledge of several of its employees even if no single employee intended to commit an offense."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "A fraud risk assessment report should reflect the assessment team’s subjective perspective and opinions that were formed during the assessment engagement.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Much instinct and judgment go into performing the fraud risk assessment. When reporting the results of the assessment, however, the team must report only the facts and keep all opinions and biases out of the report. A report that is interspersed with the assessment team’s subjective perspective will dilute and potentially undermine the results of the work."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to Dr. Steve Albrecht's Fraud Scale model, the variables that drive the occurrence of occupational fraud include:", "options": {"A": "Perceived opportunity", "B": "Situational pressure", "C": "Personal integrity", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Dr. Steve Albrecht developed the Fraud Scale, which included the components of situational pressures, perceived opportunities, and personal integrity. The Fraud Scale shows that when situational pressures and perceived opportunities are high and personal integrity is low, occupational fraud is much more likely to occur than when the opposite is true."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "The Public Interest Oversight Board (PIOB) is responsible for which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Overseeing the process for setting international auditing standards", "B": "Promulgating best practices for corporate governance for global organizations", "C": "Establishing international standards for financial reporting", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The Public Interest Oversight Board (PIOB) is the global independent oversight body that seeks to improve the quality and public-interest focus of the international auditing, education, and ethics standards promulgated by the International Federation of Accountants (IFAC). Through its oversight activities, the PIOB works to bring greater transparency and integrity to the global audit profession, thereby contributing to the enhanced quality of international financial reporting. The PIOB's objective is to increase the confidence of investors and others that the public interest activities of IFAC—including the setting of standards by independent boards operating under the auspices of IFAC—are properly responsive to the public interest. To meet this objective, the PIOB provides independent oversight of IFAC’s full standard-setting process to help ensure that the resulting standards meet stakeholder needs and are accountable and transparent."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "The individuals conducting the fraud risk assessment should incorporate their existing biases regarding employees and processes into their assessment of overall fraud risk.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The people leading and conducting the fraud risk assessment should be mindful about any personal biases they might have regarding the organization and the people within it, and they should take steps to reduce or eliminate all biases that might affect the fraud risk assessment process. For example, if an employee on the fraud risk assessment team had a bad experience with someone in the accounts payable department, he might allow that experience to affect his evaluation of the fraud risks related to that area of the business. To preclude this possibility, someone else should perform the fraud risk assessment work related to the accounts payable department’s activities."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "The ACFE Code of Professional Ethics prohibits fraud examiners from engaging in undisclosed conflicts of interest. Which of the following situations should a fraud examiner avoid to ensure compliance with this rule?", "options": {"A": "Undertaking engagements that create a hardship or loss to the fraud examiner’s full-time employer", "B": "Undertaking engagements for both sides to a particular controversy or issue", "C": "Undertaking an engagement to secretly infiltrate the fraud examiner’s employing organization and transmit inside information to another party", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The ACFE Code of Professional Ethics states that ACFE members shall not engage in undisclosed conflicts of interest. A conflict of interest exists when a fraud examiner’s ability to objectively evaluate and present an issue for a client is impaired by a current, prior, or potential future relationship with parties to the fraud examination. Deciding if a conflict or a community of interests exists depends on the facts of each particular situation; however, the following are some general rules concerning conflicts of interest: A fraud examiner employed full time by a company should not engage in other jobs that create a hardship or loss to the employer. A fraud examiner should not be a “double agent” who is employed by one company but retained by another company or person to infiltrate the employer and transmit inside information (unless, of course, the employing company agrees to the arrangement in order to apprehend other parties employed by the company). A fraud examiner should not accept engagements from both sides to a controversy—just like lawyers are prohibited from representing both parties in a transaction, lawsuit, or trial."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Sound corporate governance practices ensure that all stakeholders are treated equitably and are given just and appropriate consideration.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "One of the core principles or values of corporate governance is fairness. Sound corporate governance practices ensure that all stakeholders (e.g., shareholders, creditors, employees, management, and others) are treated equitably and are given just and appropriate consideration."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "COSO identified five interrelated components of _________________.", "options": {"A": "Internal control", "B": "Fraud", "C": "Ethical theories", "D": "Professional development"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "COSO's Internal Control—Integrated Framework identified five interrelated components of internal control: control environment, risk assessment, control activities, information and communication, and monitoring. The effectiveness of internal controls can be determined from an assessment of whether (1) each of these five components is in place and functioning effectively and (2) the five components are operating together in an integrated manner."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "An organization’s board of directors does not necessarily have to be knowledgeable about the implementation of an organization's compliance and ethics program if the board has delegated that responsibility to a compliance officer.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A company’s governing authority must be knowledgeable about the content and operation of the compliance and ethics program and exercise reasonable oversight with respect to the program's implementation and effectiveness. Governing authority is defined as the board of directors, or if the organization does not have a board of directors, the organization's highest-level governing body. Although the program's day-to-day operations can be delegated, the duties outlined above cannot."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Which of the following techniques for gathering information during a fraud risk assessment involves obtaining individuals’ responses through a formal electronic or paper questionnaire?", "options": {"A": "Interviews", "B": "Surveys", "C": "Focus groups", "D": "Anonymous feedback mechanisms"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Several techniques can be successfully used to gather information as part of a fraud risk assessment. These include: Interviews, which can be an effective way to conduct candid one-on-one conversations with employees Focus groups, which can enable the assessor to observe the interactions among a group of employees as they collectively discuss a question or issue Surveys, which are electronic or paper questionnaires that can be either anonymous or directly attributable to the individual participants Anonymous feedback mechanisms, which can include means for anonymous employee suggestions or responses to questions posed"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "An accounting clerk stealing incoming customer payments is an example of:", "options": {"A": "Neither organizational crime nor occupational crime", "B": "Both organizational crime and occupational crime", "C": "Organizational crime", "D": "Occupational crime"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Organizational crime is that which is committed by businesses, particularly corporations, and the government. In contrast, occupational crime involves legal offenses committed by individuals in the course of their occupation. For example, an accounting clerk stealing incoming customer payments would be considered an occupational crime. An antitrust offense, such as bid rigging or price fixing, would be an organizational crime. Organizational crime occurs in the context of complex relationships and expectations among boards of directors, executives, and managers on one hand, and among parent corporations, corporate divisions, and subsidiaries on the other."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Ownership of an equity share in a publicly traded company provides an investor with a right to certain information about the corporation and a right to influence the corporation through participation in general shareholder meetings and by voting.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Equity investors have certain property rights. For example, an equity share in a publicly traded company can be bought, sold, or transferred. An equity share also entitles the investor to participate in the profits of the corporation, with liability limited to the amount of the investment. In addition, ownership of an equity share provides a right to information about the corporation and a right to influence the corporation, primarily by participation in general shareholder meetings and by voting."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to The Institute of Internal Auditors’ International Standards for the Professional Practice of Internal Auditing, the internal audit team must evaluate the potential for the occurrence of fraud, as well as the organization's fraud risk management initiatives.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "According to The Institute of Internal Auditors’ Standard 2120.A2, the internal audit activity must evaluate the potential for the occurrence of fraud and how the organization manages fraud risk."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "Which of the following behavioral responses involves withdrawing a positive stimulus or applying a negative stimulus in response to an undesired behavior?", "options": {"A": "Punishment", "B": "Negative reinforcement", "C": "Positive reinforcement", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Reinforcement and punishment of behavior are distinguished by the way that positive and negative forces are applied. A positive reinforcement presents a positive stimulus in exchange for the desired response. For example, a parent might say to a child, “You’ve cleaned your room. Good. Here’s the key to the car.” The behavior (cleaning) is reinforced by the awarding of the positive stimulus (the car key). In contrast, a negative reinforcement withdraws a negative stimulus in exchange for the desired response. Continuing the example, the parent might say, “I’ll stop hassling you if you clean this room.” The negative stimulus (hassling) is withdrawn when the appropriate behavior is performed. In an act of punishment, the polarities, so to speak, are reversed. Punishment involves withdrawing a positive stimulus or applying a negative stimulus in response to an undesired behavior. For example, faced with an undesired behavior, the punisher applies a negative stimulus. A father, hearing his son use profanity, puts a bar of soap into the boy’s mouth. Punishment may also be administered by withdrawing a positive stimulus, such as, “Your room is still filthy, so you can’t use the car.”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "According to B. F. Skinner's behaviorist theories, destructive workplace behavior, such as fraud, can be deterred by rewarding honesty and openness.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Skinner says that we can condition incompatible behavior that interferes with the person’s usual acts. Instead of punishing a child’s emotional tantrums, for example, the behaviorist rewards the child for controlling emotional outbursts; we drive the tantrums into extinction by not responding, and reinforce the stoical behavior. A destructive behavior is offset by an incompatible productive one. Since fraud involves dishonesty, secretiveness, and antagonistic behaviors, the astute manager finds ways to reward the opposite behaviors—honesty, openness, and cooperation."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "As part of their responsibilities under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, in collecting evidence, fraud examiners must:", "options": {"A": "Obtain and document evidence such that the chain of custody is preserved", "B": "Ensure that all necessary evidence is obtained", "C": "Preserve the integrity of relevant evidence", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "As part of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, ACFE members are required to collect and evaluate a sufficient amount of relevant evidence to afford a reasonable and logical basis for decisions. Thus, fraud examiners must collect evidence, whether exculpatory or incriminating, that supports fraud examination results and will be admissible in subsequent proceedings. To do so, the fraud examiner must obtain and document the evidence in a manner that ensures that all necessary evidence is obtained and that the chain of custody is preserved. Additionally, fraud examiners must act prudently to preserve the integrity of relevant evidence and material."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "A mid-level manager at the XYZ Company inflated revenue figures to meet the company’s quarterly targets. The officers and directors of XYZ did not know the fraud was occurring; therefore, the company cannot be held criminally liable for the fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A corporation can generally be held criminally responsible for criminal acts committed by its employees even if those in management had no knowledge of or participation in the underlying criminal events and even if there were specific policies or instructions prohibiting the activity undertaken by the employees. The acts of any employee, from the lowest clerk to the CEO, can impute liability upon a corporation. In fact, in many jurisdictions, a corporation can be criminally responsible for the collective knowledge of several of its employees even if no single employee intended to commit an offense."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Having an auditor ask employees questions such as, \"Has anyone ever asked you to do anything that you felt was illegal or unethical?\" can be an effective method of uncovering fraud within an organization.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Fraud assessment questioning is a non-accusatory interview technique used as a part of a normal audit. It operates on the theory that employees’ attitudes are a good indicator of potential problems and that one of the most effective ways to assess potential fraud is to ask about it. Examples of questions that can be used in this approach include the following: Part of my duty as an auditor is to find fraud, waste, and abuse. Do you understand that? Do you think fraud is a problem for business in general? Do you think this company has any particular problem with fraud? Has anyone ever asked you to do anything that you felt was illegal or unethical? If you felt that there was a problem in the company with respect to fraud, what would you do? Do you have any indication that there is fraud occurring in the company now?"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Factors that affect employees' ethical decisions include:", "options": {"A": "The law and other government regulations", "B": "Industry and organizational ethical codes", "C": "Tension between personal standards and organizational needs", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The collection of a person’s beliefs and morals makes up a set of principles known as ethics. Ethics are the judgments about right and wrong, or, more specifically, a person’s moral obligations to society that determine a person’s actions. Determining ethical rights and wrongs is complicated by the fact that moral standards and generally accepted social behavior change with time. In addition, different groups in the same society might have conflicting ideas of right and wrong. Individuals' values and ethics are reflected in their actions as employees. There are four factors that generally affect employees' ethical decisions: The law and other government regulations Industry and organizational ethical codes Social pressures Tension between personal standards and organizational needs"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "The purpose of corporate governance is to:", "options": {"A": "Encourage the efficient use of resources and require accountability for the stewardship of those resources.", "B": "Ensure the accuracy and reliability of the organization’s financial reports.", "C": "Provide reasonable assurance regarding the organization’s compliance with applicable laws and regulations.", "D": "Prevent and detect financial misstatements, whether caused by errors or fraud."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Sir Adrian Cadbury, chairman of the committee that developed the foundational corporate governance guidance, The Cadbury Report, stated that the purpose of corporate governance is “to encourage the efficient use of resources and equally to require accountability for the stewardship of those resources. The aim is to align as nearly as possible the interests of individuals, corporations, and society.”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to the 2018 Report to the Nations, what was the most common behavioral red flag displayed by perpetrators prior to the discovery of their frauds?", "options": {"A": "Addiction problems", "B": "Living beyond their means", "C": "Divorce or family problems", "D": "Complaining about lack of authority"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "As part of the study underlying the 2018 Report to the Nations, survey respondents were presented with a list of common warning signs and asked which, if any, were displayed by the perpetrator prior to the discovery of the fraud. The most frequently cited behavioral red flag in the reported cases involved fraudsters living beyond their financial means. This warning sign was noted in 41% of all cases in our study."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Good corporate governance is based on a framework that:", "options": {"A": "Takes into account the organization’s cultural and ethical environment", "B": "Is appropriate for the organization’s legal and regulatory environment", "C": "Remains adaptable", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Corporate governance structure and practices vary widely and should be determined based on each organization’s specific needs. In developing a corporate governance framework for an organization, directors and management must consider the legal, regulatory, institutional, and ethical environments in which the company operates. Additionally, good corporate governance is fluid—that is, it maintains the ability to find a different course when its current direction runs into barriers, such as changes in the corporate landscape, new regulations or legal requirements, or shifts in organizational strategy. However, even while remaining adaptable, sound corporate governance is based on established best practices."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "A fraud risk management program must include mechanisms specifically designed to monitor, identify, and address breaches in compliance.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The fraud risk management program must include mechanisms specifically designed to monitor, identify, and address breaches in compliance. Such breaches might include failures in the design or operation of anti-fraud controls, as well as outright occurrences of fraud. A specific individual or team should be designated as responsible for monitoring compliance with the fraud risk management program and for handling suspected instances of noncompliance. Formal sanctions for intentional noncompliance must be well-publicized and carried out in a consistent and firm manner."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "The OECD Principles of Corporate Governance is required to be implemented by all corporations in the jurisdictions that have officially adopted the Principles.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The OECD Principles of Corporate Governance is regarded as one of the hallmark sources of guidance for corporate governance practices for organizations throughout the world. The Principles are nonbinding, as their implementation must be adapted to different legal, economic, and cultural circumstances. This is a key strength of the Principles that makes them a useful tool worldwide, both in developed economies and in emerging markets."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "For its compliance program to be effective, an organization must communicate the program to all its employees through training programs.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The U.S. Corporate Sentencing Guidelines provide a benchmark and foundational guidance for organizations in all countries for developing an effective compliance program. Under the Guidelines, organizations must conduct “effective training programs.” Organizations are also required to periodically and appropriately communicate the program’s compliance requirements and procedures to all employees affected by the program, including upper-level personnel. These programs should be designed to inform employees about the company’s stance on corporate compliance. They should also inform employees about what kinds of acts and omissions are prohibited by the law and by the organization."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "To reinforce an anti-fraud culture, management should:", "options": {"A": "Create an environment in which employees feel safe challenging management’s decisions", "B": "Visibly adhere to the same set of ethics policies that are required of all employees", "C": "Show employees that unethical behavior will not be tolerated", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To achieve an organizational culture with a strong value system founded on integrity, management must show employees through its words and actions that dishonest or unethical behavior will not be tolerated. Management must also create an environment in which employees feel safe to challenge management’s decisions or speak up if they think something is wrong. A culture that encourages employees to share their concerns can reduce the risk of fraud significantly because employees often feel more loyal to their superiors. Such a culture might also prevent unethical behavior because issues of anger or stress can be addressed before they escalate to the point of a fraud. Additionally, management must exude ethics in order to model the behavior that is expected of the staff. When management believes and acts as though it is “above the law” with respect to company policies, staff members are much less likely to follow rules. Staff members frequently resent management for expecting them to behave in a certain way when members of management do not behave in the same way themselves. However, when management acts ethically and follows organizational policies, the staff tends to respect and appreciate the behavior and copy it."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Sociologist Edward Gross has asserted that organizations' reliance on profit makes them inherently prone to committing fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Sociologist Edward Gross has asserted that all organizations are inherently \"criminogenic\" (i.e., prone to committing crime), but they are not necessarily criminal. Gross makes this assertion because of the reliance on “the bottom line.” Without necessarily meaning to, organizations can invite fraud as a means of obtaining goals. Economist Oliver Williamson noted that because of a department’s concern with reaching its goals, managers might tend to maximize their department’s own interests to the detriment of the organization."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "The fraud risk assessment team should consider both qualitative and quantitative factors when assessing the organization's fraud risks.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The fraud risk assessment team should consider qualitative and quantitative factors when assessing the organization's fraud risks. For example, a particular fraud risk that might only pose an immaterial direct financial risk to the organization, but that could greatly affect its reputation, would likely be deemed a significant risk to the organization."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Which of the following should be covered in employee anti-fraud training?", "options": {"A": "A detailed explanation of the company’s anti-fraud controls", "B": "The exact procedures that management uses to detect fraud", "C": "Examples of past transgressions and how they were handled", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The content covered by the organization’s anti-fraud training should focus on the specific risks faced by the organization to provide employees with practical, implementable knowledge. However, it should not give employees the information they need to circumvent the normal rules by explaining the details of controls and procedures used to detect fraud. In that regard, the following topics form the basis of an effective training program: What fraud is, including examples of what behavior is acceptable and what is not How fraud hurts the organization How fraud hurts employees Common characteristics that lead individuals to commit fraud (i.e., pressure, opportunity, and ability to rationalize the act) How to identify fraud (i.e., specific examples of financial, transactional, behavioral, and other red flags to watch for) How to report fraud The punishment for dishonest acts, including examples of past transgressions and how they were handled"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "According to the social control theory, the more important that social relationships are to a person, the less likely it is that the person will commit crimes.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "According to Travis Hirschi, social control theory “assumes the bond of affection for conventional persons is a major deterrent to crime. The stronger this bond, the more likely the person is to take it into account when and if he contemplates a criminal act.” What essentially happens, the theory suggests, is that people confronted with the possibility of violating a law are likely to ask themselves questions such as, “What will my spouse—or my mother and father—think if they find out?” To the extent that individuals believe that other people whose opinions are important to them will be disappointed or ashamed, and to the extent that they care deeply that these people will feel this way, they will be deterred from committing a criminal act."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "An effective system of internal controls:", "options": {"A": "Mitigates the risk of fraud but cannot completely eliminate it", "B": "Increases the perception that fraud will be detected", "C": "Involves balancing preventive controls and detective controls", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "No system of internal controls can fully eliminate the risk of fraud, but well-designed and effective internal controls can deter the average fraudster by reducing the opportunity to commit the fraud and increasing the perception of detection. With the right balance of preventive and detective controls, a good system of internal controls can greatly reduce an organization’s vulnerability to fraud."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to ISA 240, the auditor’s assessment of the risk of material misstatement due to fraud at the financial statement level should have an effect on which of the following aspect(s) of an audit?", "options": {"A": "Assignment and supervision of personnel", "B": "Consideration of accounting principles used", "C": "Choice of auditing procedures", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Although fraud is a broad legal concept, for the purposes of ISA 240, the auditor is concerned with fraud that causes a material misstatement in the financial statements. Under this standard, the auditor shall determine overall responses to address the assessed risks of material misstatement due to fraud at the financial statement level. To do so, the auditor shall: Assign and supervise personnel, taking account of the knowledge, skill, and ability of the individuals to be given significant engagement responsibilities and the auditor’s assessment of the risks of material misstatement due to fraud for the engagement; this might include assigning additional individuals with specialized skill and knowledge, such as forensic and IT specialists, or assigning more experienced individuals to the engagement. Evaluate whether the selection and application of accounting policies by the entity, particularly those related to subjective measurements and complex transactions, might be indicative of fraudulent financial reporting resulting from management’s effort to manage earnings. Incorporate an element of unpredictability in the selection of the nature, timing, and extent of audit procedures, such as by using differing sampling methods, and performing procedures at different locations or at locations on an unannounced basis."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "What is the objective of a fraud risk assessment?", "options": {"A": "To provide an estimate of an organization’s fraud losses", "B": "To assess the design and effectiveness of an organization’s internal controls over financial reporting", "C": "To help an organization identify what makes it most vulnerable to fraud", "D": "To establish the guilt or innocence of an employee suspected of committing fraud"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In the simplest terms, the objective of a fraud risk assessment is to help an organization identify what makes it most vulnerable to fraud. Through a fraud risk assessment, the organization is able to identify where fraud is most likely to occur, enabling proactive measures to be considered and implemented to reduce the chance that it could happen."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "Which of the following is regarded as the essential factor that makes a leader's authority effective?", "options": {"A": "Experience in similar roles", "B": "Strong morals", "C": "Legitimacy", "D": "Ability to instill fear in subordinates"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Legitimacy is regarded as the essential ingredient in what gives governments and leaders authority. The idea is that if the authorities have legitimacy, the public will obey the law. Effective authorities recognize that without the goodwill of those they serve, they could not function. Consequently, their aim must be to maximize compliance and minimize hostility toward laws and rules while gaining legitimacy in the eyes of the public. To effectively govern, a leader must be considered legitimate by the public. Otherwise, compliance will not occur."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Research has shown that many executives justify illegal behavior as simply common practice in the business world.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In his research, Dr. Gilbert Geis found that quite often, individuals are trained in illegal behavior as part of their occupational roles. Similarly, Schrager and Short say criminal behavior stems more from the roles an employee is expected to fulfill than from individual pathology. Many executives know their behavior is illegal but tend to justify their behavior as simply common practice in the business world. Clinard and Yeager believed that in rationalizing their behavior, corporations follow a general tendency to obey laws selectively (i.e., obeying according to situational needs and determined by factors like social class and occupation)."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Fraud risks that remain after the effect of internal controls are considered inherent risks.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When considering the fraud risks faced by an organization, it is helpful to analyze how significant a risk is before and after risk response. Risks that are present before the effect of internal controls are described as inherent risks. The risks that remain after the effect of internal controls are described as residual risks. For example, there is an inherent risk that the employee in charge of receiving customer payments at a small company might embezzle incoming cash. Controls, such as segregation of duties and oversight from the company owner, can be implemented to help mitigate this risk; however, even with such controls in place, some residual risk will likely remain in that the bookkeeper might still manage to embezzle funds. The objective of the controls is to make the residual risk significantly smaller than the inherent risk."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Under an effective document retention policy, when an organization is faced with potential litigation or a legal document request is pending or imminent, the destruction of documents should cease.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "An organization must cease destruction of documents when faced with potential litigation or when a legal document request is pending or imminent. Destruction under a valid document retention policy (DRP) will be ineffective if documents were not actually destroyed before a potential litigation trigger occurs. Thus, it is imperative that the DRP provides for complete destruction of documents that can be validly expunged during the proper periods under the policy. Documents should be destroyed by shredding or by some other means that will render them unreadable. Similarly, a protocol for the destruction of electronic data should be in place to ensure that documents to be destroyed are actually destroyed. The deletion of emails or other files on one’s computer does not mean that such records are removed from evidence."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to COSO, an internal control system should be designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the achievement of the organization’s objectives pertaining to which of the following?", "options": {"A": "The organization’s adherence to the laws and regulations to which it is subject", "B": "The effectiveness and efficiency of the organization’s operations", "C": "The reporting of financial and nonfinancial information to internal and external parties", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In its Internal Control—Integrated Framework, the Committee on Sponsoring Organizations (COSO) defines internal control as \"a process, effected by an entity’s board of directors, management, and other personnel, designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the achievement of objectives relating to operations, reporting, and compliance.” As noted in this definition, internal controls should be designed to assist management in meeting the following three categories of objectives: 1. Operations objectives, which pertain to the effectiveness and efficiency of the organization’s operations 2. Reporting objectives, which pertain to the reporting of financial and nonfinancial information to internal and external parties 3. Compliance objectives, which pertain to the organization’s adherence to the laws and regulations to which it is subject"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "The criminologist responsible for the well-known hypothesis of the Fraud Triangle is:", "options": {"A": "Marshall B. Clinard", "B": "Immanuel Kant", "C": "Donald R. Cressey", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "While working on his Ph.D. in the 1940s, Donald R. Cressey focused his research on embezzlers. His findings resulted in a hypothesis that, over the years, has become known as the Fraud Triangle. One leg of the triangle represents a perceived non-shareable financial need. The second leg is for perceived opportunity, and the final leg is for rationalization. The role of the non-shareable problem is important. Cressey said, “When the trust violators were asked to explain why they refrained from violation of other positions of trust they might have held at previous times, or why they had not violated the subject position at an earlier time, those who had an opinion expressed the equivalent of one or more of the following quotations: (a) ‘There was no need for it like there was this time.’ (b) ‘The idea never entered my head.’ (c) ‘I thought it was dishonest then, but this time it did not seem dishonest at first.’”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "A positive reinforcement presents a positive stimulus in exchange for the desired response.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Reinforcement and punishment of behavior are distinguished by the way that positive and negative forces are applied. A positive reinforcement presents a positive stimulus in exchange for the desired response. For example, a parent might say to a child, “You’ve cleaned your room. Good. Here’s the key to the car.” The behavior (cleaning) is reinforced by the awarding of the positive stimulus (the car key). In contrast, a negative reinforcement withdraws a negative stimulus in exchange for the desired response. Continuing the example, the parent might say, “I’ll stop hassling you if you clean this room.” The negative stimulus (hassling) is withdrawn when the appropriate behavior is performed. In an act of punishment, the polarities, so to speak, are reversed. Punishment involves withdrawing a positive stimulus or applying a negative stimulus in response to an undesired behavior. For example, faced with an undesired behavior, the punisher applies a negative stimulus. A father, hearing his son use profanity, puts a bar of soap into the boy’s mouth. Punishment may also be administered by withdrawing a positive stimulus, such as, “Your room is still filthy, so you can’t use the car.”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "The OECD Principles of Corporate Governance supports establishing stronger protection for foreign shareholders than for domestic shareholders as a means to encourage increased international investment.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The OECD Principles of Corporate Governance covers six main areas, which are divided into chapters. The Principles: Request that governments have in place an effective legal, regulatory, and institutional framework to support good corporate governance practices (Chapter I). Call for a corporate governance framework that protects the exercise of shareholders’ rights and supports the equal treatment of all shareholders, including minority and foreign shareholders (Chapter II). Address the effect of institutional investors and other intermediaries in stock markets and the resulting corporate governance implications (Chapter III). Recognize the importance of the role of stakeholders in corporate governance (Chapter IV). Examine the importance of timely, accurate, and transparent disclosure mechanisms (Chapter V). Address board structures, responsibilities, and procedures (Chapter VI). Chapter II of the OECD Principles of Corporate Governance states: “The corporate governance framework should protect and facilitate the exercise of shareholders’ rights and ensure the equitable treatment of all shareholders, including minority and foreign shareholders.” As such, the Principles support equal treatment for foreign and domestic shareholders in corporate governance. They do not address government policies to regulate foreign direct investment."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Efforts to control corporate crime generally include which of the following approaches?", "options": {"A": "Consumer action", "B": "Voluntary changes in corporate attitudes", "C": "Government intervention", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Efforts to control corporate crime follow three approaches: voluntary change in corporate attitudes and structure; strong intervention by the government to force changes in corporate structure, accompanied by legal measures to deter or punish; or consumer action. Voluntary changes would involve the development of stronger business ethics and certain corporate organizational reforms. Government controls might involve corporate chartering, deconcentration and divestiture, larger and more effective enforcement staffs, stiffer penalties, wider use of publicity as a sanction, and possibly the nationalization of corporations. Consumer group pressures might be exerted through lobbying, selective buying, boycotts, and the establishment of large consumer cooperatives."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "In a public company, the CEO should be charged with having primary responsibility for the oversight of the company’s compliance program.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "If a board of directors exists, such as in a public company, the board must be knowledgeable about the content and operation of the compliance program and oversee its implementation. Accordingly, it is preferable for the board of directors or one of the board’s committees to control the organization's compliance program. For instance, many companies place their compliance programs under the control of audit committees. There are four principal benefits to this practice: The involvement of the board of directors provides a sense of authority to the compliance program. It clearly identifies the program as a matter of company policy. The involvement of a board committee provides oversight to the operation of the program by personnel who are not involved in the program’s day-to-day operation. Efforts to implement an effective compliance program can be documented in the committee’s meeting minutes. This documentation can prove useful if the company ever has to defend its actions and seek mitigation of a criminal fine. The involvement of those board members who are on the audit committee will help ensure that the board is knowledgeable about the content and operation of the compliance program."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "The managements from several IT consulting firms conspire to take turns submitting the lowest bids for all contracts in their area; this is considered an organizational crime.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Organizational crime is that which is committed by businesses, particularly corporations, and the government. In contrast, occupational crime involves legal offenses committed by individuals in the course of their occupation. An antitrust offense, such as bid rigging or price fixing, would be an organizational crime; accepting or offering bribes is an occupational offense. Organizational crime occurs in the context of complex relationships and expectations among boards of directors, executives, and managers on one hand, and among parent corporations, corporate divisions, and subsidiaries on the other."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "In reporting the results of a fraud examination, a fraud examiner is required to disclose any information that, if not disclosed, would change a user’s perceptions and conclusions.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Article VII of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics states: \"An ACFE Member shall reveal all material matters discovered during the course of an examination, which, if omitted, could cause a distortion of the facts.\" This rule demands full and fair reporting of the findings made in investigations. Two words—material and distortion—are key to this requirement. Information is material if having knowledge of such information might reasonably be expected to influence a client's or employer’s decisions based on a fraud examiner’s report. Accordingly, materiality is a user-oriented concept. Thus, an item of information that, if omitted from a report, would change a user’s perceptions and conclusions is material. When determining what information is material, fraud examiners should not consider what they themselves think is important and material; instead, they should try to decide what users will consider important and material. Thus, fraud examiners must project a decision-making process onto the users. This rule also provides that fraud examiners shall disclose all material matters discovered during the course of a fraud examination that, if omitted, could distort the facts. The “distortion of facts” portion of the rule refers to omissions. Distortion is related to materiality and users’ decisions. The distortion of facts in a report could cause users to undertake inappropriate actions."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to the 2018 Report to the Nations, the majority of occupational frauds are committed by ____________; median losses are highest in frauds committed by ___________.", "options": {"A": "Employees; employees", "B": "Owners/executives; managers", "C": "Owners/executives; employees", "D": "Employees; owners/executives"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "According to the 2018 Report to the Nations, staff-level employees commit the most fraud schemes; our study indicates that 44% of the cases were perpetrated by nonmanagement-level employees. ACFE research also shows that there is a strong correlation between the fraud perpetrator’s level of authority and the size of the fraud. While owners/executives only committed 19% of the frauds in our study, the schemes committed by these individuals resulted in a median loss of USD 850,000, which was nearly six times larger than the median loss caused by managers, and 17 times larger than the median loss caused by low-level employees. A significant correlation between authority and fraud loss has been found in every edition of the report dating back to 1996. This correlation likely reflects the fact that high-level fraudsters tend to have greater access to an organization’s assets than low-level personnel. They might also have greater technical ability to commit and conceal fraud, and they may be able to use their authority to override or conceal their crimes in ways that low-level employees cannot."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "The board of directors holds the primary responsibility for designing, implementing, monitoring, and improving the fraud risk management program.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The board of directors is responsible for developing and supporting the organization’s underlying fraud risk management strategy. However, the primary responsibility for designing, implementing, monitoring, and improving the fraud risk management program is held by senior management. As part of this responsibility, senior management must: Be intimately familiar with the organization’s fraud risks. Ensure that the organization has specific and effective internal controls in place to prevent and detect fraud. Set a tone at the top and monitor the company culture to ensure it appropriately supports the organization’s fraud prevention and detection strategies. Senior management must exude ethics for staff to be inspired and feel obligated to follow suit. Clearly communicate—both in words and actions—that fraud is not tolerated. Take seriously all reports of fraud and undertake investigations for any such reports deemed reliable. Punish perpetrators of discovered fraud appropriately. Punishing perpetrators reinforces the culture of ethics and the fact that fraud will not be tolerated. Take any steps necessary to remediate weaknesses that allowed frauds to occur. Report to the board of directors on a regular basis regarding the effectiveness of the organization’s fraud risk management program."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding fraud risks?", "options": {"A": "The objective of anti-fraud controls is to make the inherent fraud risk significantly smaller than the residual fraud risk.", "B": "Risks that are present before the effect of internal controls are described as residual risks.", "C": "The objective of anti-fraud controls is to make the residual fraud risk significantly smaller than the inherent fraud risk.", "D": "The objective of anti-fraud controls is to completely eliminate residual fraud risks."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "When considering the fraud risks faced by an organization, it is helpful to analyze how significant a risk is before and after risk response. Risks that are present before the effect of internal controls are described as inherent risks. The risks that remain after the effect of internal controls are described as residual risks. For example, there is an inherent risk that the employee in charge of receiving customer payments at a small company might embezzle incoming cash. Controls, such as segregation of duties and oversight from the company owner, can be implemented to help mitigate this risk; however, even with such controls in place, some residual risk will likely remain in that the bookkeeper might still manage to embezzle funds. The objective of the controls is to make the residual risk significantly smaller than the inherent risk."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to the 2018 Report to the Nations, which of the three major categories of occupational fraud is the most common?", "options": {"A": "Asset misappropriation", "B": "Corruption", "C": "Financial statement fraud", "D": "Identity theft"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "All occupational frauds fall into one of three major categories: asset misappropriation, corruption, or financial statement fraud. Of these categories, asset misappropriation is by far the most common, occurring in 89% of the cases in the 2018 Report to the Nations study. However, asset misappropriation is also the least costly, causing a median loss of USD 114,000. Corruption schemes are the next most common form of occupational fraud, with 38% of the cases in our study involving some form of corrupt act. These schemes resulted in a median loss to the victim organizations of USD 250,000. The least common and most costly form of occupational fraud is financial statement fraud, which occurred in 10% of the cases and caused a median loss of USD 800,000."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "The theory of differential association is used frequently to explain white-collar criminality. Which of the following is one of the assertions or principles of differential association?", "options": {"A": "Learning is the same as pure imitation.", "B": "Criminal behavior is explained by an individual’s general needs and values.", "C": "People are genetically predisposed to be criminals.", "D": "Criminal behavior is acquired through participation with intimate personal groups."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The theory of differential association was developed by criminologist Edwin Sutherland. It states that: (1) criminal behavior is learned; (2) it is learned from other people in a process of communication; (3) criminal behavior is acquired through participation with intimate personal groups; (4) the learning process includes the shaping of motives, drives, rationalizations, and attitudes; (5) the directions of motives are learned from the favorable or unfavorable interpretations of applicable laws; (6) a person becomes a criminal because of an excess of conclusions favorable to violation of the law over conclusions unfavorable to violation of the law; (7) differential association may vary in frequency, duration, priority, and intensity; (8) learning criminal behavior involves all the mechanisms of other learning; (9) learning differs from pure imitation; and (10) while criminal behavior is an expression of general needs and values, it is not explained by these needs and values."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "If a fraud examiner makes a mistake in judgment, he should avoid admitting to the error, as it could compromise the integrity of his case.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The ACFE Code of Professional Ethics requires ACFE members to exhibit the highest level of integrity at all times. This does not mean, however, that an ACFE member must be perfect in all technical matters, nor does it mean that fraud examiners and others cannot have honest differences of opinion. In the course of a fraud examination, inadvertent errors, mistakes of judgment, and other problems might cause conflict. In such cases, a fraud examiner can preserve integrity either by admitting error or by convincingly justifying a difference of perception or opinion."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding organizational structure?", "options": {"A": "Companies with departments that are isolated geographically have a reduced risk of fraud", "B": "The existence of many specialized departments within a company generally increases the overall risk of fraud within the organization", "C": "Misbehavior is more likely to be detected in a complex organizational structure than in a simple organizational structure", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Complex companies provide a structure that can foster misbehavior. They provide many settings where misconduct is possible. They isolate those settings in departments and in locations around a city, a country, or the world. This isolation, in turn, means that information about what one part of a company is doing might be unknown in another part. All this reduces the risk that misbehavior will be detected and punished. The larger a company grows, the more specialized its subunits tend to become, and this specialization thereby breeds a higher risk of fraud. An internally diversified company might have few employees who fully understand the detailed workings. Additionally, specialization tends to hide illegal activities, especially where a firm’s tasks are kept separate and unrelated. Employees cannot garner knowledge about all the particulars of how a firm works. This protects a company from the effects of personnel turnover and leaks of information because no employee knows all the intricacies of the company. The same secrecy, however, raises the chances for misconduct."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "The OECD Principles of Corporate Governance includes which of the following?", "options": {"A": "An emphasis on the importance of timely, accurate, and transparent disclosure mechanisms", "B": "Recognition of the importance of the role of stakeholders in corporate governance", "C": "A request that governments have in place an appropriate framework to support good corporate governance practices", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The OECD Principles of Corporate Governance covers six main areas, which are divided into chapters. The Principles: Request that governments have in place an effective legal, regulatory, and institutional framework to support good corporate governance practices (Chapter I). Call for a corporate governance framework that protects the exercise of shareholders’ rights and supports the equal treatment of all shareholders, including minority and foreign shareholders (Chapter II). Address the effect of institutional investors and other intermediaries in stock markets and the resulting corporate governance implications (Chapter III). Recognize the importance of the role of stakeholders in corporate governance (Chapter IV). Examine the importance of timely, accurate, and transparent disclosure mechanisms (Chapter V). Address board structures, responsibilities, and procedures (Chapter VI)."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "According to the joint COSO and ACFE publication Fraud Risk Management Guide, who has responsibility for managing fraud risk?", "options": {"A": "Executive management", "B": "Internal audit", "C": "The board of directors", "D": "Personnel at all levels of the organization"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "According to the joint COSO/ACFE Fraud Risk Management Guide, “personnel at all levels of the organization—including every level of management, staff, and internal auditors—have responsibility for managing fraud risk.”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a risk factor relating to the incentive or pressure to commit fraudulent financial reporting?", "options": {"A": "Low morale among senior management", "B": "Deficient internal controls", "C": "Excessive pressure on management or operating personnel to meet financial targets", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The following are examples of risk factors relating to the incentives for misstatements arising from fraudulent financial reporting, as provided in the appendix to ISA 240: Financial stability or profitability is threatened by economic, industry, or entity operating conditions. Excessive pressure exists for management to meet the requirements or expectations of third parties. Information available indicates that the personal financial situation of management or those charged with governance is threatened by the entity’s financial performance. There is excessive pressure on management or operating personnel to meet financial targets established by those charged with governance, including sales or profitability incentive goals."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "During a fraud risk assessment, the assessment team should consider the way employees make decisions, behave, or treat others and assess how those actions affect the company’s vulnerability to fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The actions of certain individuals can significantly increase the company’s vulnerability to fraud. The risk can be driven from the way in which someone makes decisions, behaves, or treats others within and outside the organization. A fraud risk assessment can help home in on those people and their activities that might increase the company’s overall fraud risk."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to the 2018 Report to the Nations, the use of proactive data monitoring and analysis can help reduce the financial impact of fraud on an organization.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "As part of the study for the 2018 Report to the Nations, we compared the losses experienced by the victim organizations that had specific controls in place against the losses experienced by those that had not implemented each control. Interestingly, the presence of every control we analyzed was correlated with lower fraud losses. For example, the use of proactive data monitoring and analysis was associated with a more than 50% reduction in fraud losses. We similarly analyzed the duration of fraud schemes based on the presence or absence of each anti-fraud control. Proactive data monitoring and analysis was also correlated with the most significant reduction in fraud duration, indicating that this control is among the most useful tools in the fight against fraud."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE regarding the disclosure of confidential client information?", "options": {"A": "A fraud examiner is only allowed to respond to a legal court order when his client grants him authorization to do so.", "B": "Fraud examiners are always bound by confidentiality, even when refusing to disclose information violates the law.", "C": "A fraud examiner can reveal confidential client information when responding to a legal court order.", "D": "Confidential information provided to a fraud examiner by a client is considered privileged and therefore legally exempt from disclosure in all circumstances."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Two articles of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics apply in situations regarding release of confidential client information. Article IV states: \"An ACFE Member will comply with the lawful orders of the courts, and will testify to matters truthfully and without bias or prejudice.\" Article VI says: \"An ACFE Member shall not reveal any confidential information obtained during a professional engagement without proper authorization.\" However, fraud examiners are not bound by confidentiality when doing so would violate the law. Thus, fraud examiners can reveal client confidences when responding to a legal court order."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Theft of competitor trade secrets, anti-competitive practices, environmental violations, and trade and customs regulations in areas of import and export are all fraud risks pertaining to:", "options": {"A": "Asset misappropriation", "B": "Regulatory and legal misconduct", "C": "Reputation risk", "D": "Fraudulent financial reporting"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Regulatory and legal misconduct includes a wide range of risks, such as conflicts of interest, insider trading, theft of competitor trade secrets, anti-competitive practices, environmental violations, and trade and customs regulations in areas of import and export. Depending on the particular organization and the nature of its business, some or all of these risks might be applicable and should be considered in the fraud risk assessment process."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "There are five principal characteristics that distinguish professional fields from other vocations. Which of the following is NOT one of them?", "options": {"A": "A requirement for all members to have earned advanced degrees", "B": "A specialized body of knowledge", "C": "Recognition and acceptance by society", "D": "Standards of conduct governing professionals' relationships with clients, colleagues, and the public"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The five principal characteristics that help differentiate professional fields from other vocations are: A body of specialized knowledge acquired through formal education Admission to the profession governed by standards of professional qualifications Recognition and acceptance by society of professional status, and concurrent recognition and acceptance of social responsibility by the professional Standards of conduct governing relationships of the professional with clients, colleagues, and the public An organization devoted to the advancement of the obligations of the professional group"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the core principles of sound corporate governance?", "options": {"A": "Independence", "B": "Responsibility", "C": "Transparency", "D": "Fairness"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Most systems of corporate governance are focused on several core principles or values, which include: Accountability Transparency Fairness Responsibility"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Ineffective monitoring of management, a complex organizational structure, and deficient internal control components are all examples of which type of fraud risk factor relating to fraudulent financial reporting?", "options": {"A": "Pressures/incentives", "B": "Opportunities", "C": "Attitudes/rationalizations", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The following are examples of risk factors relating to the potential opportunity for misstatements arising from fraudulent financial reporting, as provided in the appendix to ISA 240: The nature of the industry or the entity’s operations provides opportunities to engage in fraudulent financial reporting. The monitoring of management is not effective. There is a complex or unstable organizational structure. Internal control components are deficient."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding the process of defining the objective of the fraud risk management program?", "options": {"A": "Management should express risk appetite in a manner that is appropriate for and unique to the organization’s culture and operations", "B": "Management must balance the investment in anti-fraud controls with the benefit of those controls and the amount of risk it is willing to accept", "C": "Management should examine previous fraud occurrences to determine how the ideal fraud risk management program would have prevented them", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Like any corporate initiative, without a clear, explicit definition of what the organization intends to accomplish through its fraud risk management program, the program will have limited success. Consequently, management must balance the following factors in determining the program’s objectives: Management’s risk appetite The investment in anti-fraud controls The prevention of frauds that are material in nature or amount An important component in defining the objective of the fraud risk management program is determining management’s risk appetite. Without an adequate understanding and articulation of just how much risk those charged with governance are willing to accept, any stated objectives of the fraud risk management program will be inaccurate. Risk appetite should be expressed in a manner that is appropriate for the organization’s culture and operations, whether qualitatively—low, medium, or high, for example—or quantitatively, using a numeric scale. Another helpful starting point in determining the fraud risk management strategy is to examine previous occurrences of fraud and explore how management’s ideal fraud risk management program would have prevented, detected, and responded to them. In examining such incidents, management should consider the factors that allowed such frauds to occur."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE about the fraud risk assessment process?", "options": {"A": "The assessment team must be perceived as independent and objective by others for the assessment to be effective", "B": "Conducting an effective fraud risk assessment requires thinking like a fraudster", "C": "Management and auditors should share ownership of the process and accountability for its success", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Both management and auditors have a responsibility for fraud risk management. However, each of these parties has unique knowledge and perspective of the fraud risks faced by the organization. Consequently, the fraud risk assessment is most effective when management and auditors share ownership of the process and accountability for its success. Additionally, a good fraud risk assessment can be effectively conducted either by people inside the organization or with external sources. Either way, it is critical that the people leading and conducting the fraud risk assessment remain independent and objective throughout the assessment process. Additionally, they must be perceived as independent and objective by others. Furthermore, most honest people are not naturally inclined to think like a criminal. In fact, many large-scale frauds that have occurred would have been deemed unthinkable by people closest to the events. But a necessary part of conducting an effective fraud risk assessment involves thinking like a fraudster. Thoughts of “it couldn’t happen here” should not be allowed to moderate the evaluation of fraud risk."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Requiring employees in certain functions (e.g., accounting clerks) to periodically rotate job duties can be an effective anti-fraud measure.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Some frauds are detected during sickness or unexpected absences of the perpetrator because they require continuous, manual intervention. Requiring employees in certain functions (e.g., accounting clerks) to periodically rotate job duties or accounts reviewed can increase the perception of detection in the potential perpetrator’s mind."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Which of the following is an example of a violation of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics’ requirement for diligent, professional behavior?", "options": {"A": "Delegating a task to a lower-level employee and overseeing that individual’s performance", "B": "Obtaining more evidence than the minimum amount needed to prove a case", "C": "Skipping vital investigation steps to improve the efficiency of a fraud examination", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Skipping vital investigation steps to improve the efficiency of a fraud examination would not only create the possibility of missing key pieces of evidence, but it would also be a violation of Article I of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics. This article states that: \"An ACFE Member shall, at all times, demonstrate a commitment to professionalism and diligence in the performance of his or her duties.\" The “diligence in the performance of his or her duties” phrase in this rule refers to several activities that collectively define high-quality fraud examination work, including properly planning assignments and supervising assistants and colleagues, avoiding conflicts of interest, performing tasks with competence, obtaining sufficient evidence to establish a basis for opinions, maintaining confidential relations, and avoiding distortion of facts."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "The Treadway Commission made which of the following recommendations to reduce the probability of fraud in financial reports?", "options": {"A": "A mandatory independent audit committee", "B": "Adequate audit committee resources and authority", "C": "A written charter for the audit committee", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The Treadway Commission made several major recommendations that, in combination with other measures, are designed to reduce the probability of fraud in financial reports: The board of directors should have a mandatory independent audit committee made up of outside directors. Companies should develop a written charter that sets forth the duties and responsibilities of the audit committee. The audit committee should have adequate resources and authority to carry out its responsibilities. The audit committee should be composed of members who are informed, vigilant, and effective."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding an organization’s ethics policy?", "options": {"A": "Access to the policy should be restricted to external parties only.", "B": "In developing the policy, management should not consider the existing ethical tone set by leadership.", "C": "Access to the policy should be restricted to company employees only.", "D": "In developing the policy, management should consider how various members of the organization define success."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A written ethics policy is an excellent method by which management can objectively communicate its philosophy and develop a successful ethics program. The policy should be disseminated among both new and old employees. Additionally, some companies have found it effective to share the ethics policy with their vendors, and many organizations make their ethics policies available for the public, such as by posting them on the company’s website. Such exposure helps reinforce the importance the organization places on ethics and provides parties outside the organization with a tool to help identify and report breaches of expected employee conduct. Identifying key organizational characteristics and issues is a start to the development of an ethics program. These considerations include: Understanding why good people can commit unethical acts Defining current—as well as desired—organizational values Determining if organizational values have been properly communicated Determining if ethics is currently a leadership issue in the organization Ascertaining how board members, stockholders, management, employees, and any other pertinent members of the organization define success Producing written ethics policies, procedures, or structures"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Of the following parties, who is responsible for developing a strategy to assess and manage fraud risks that aligns with the organization’s risk appetite and strategic plans?", "options": {"A": "The board of directors", "B": "The shareholders", "C": "The internal audit department", "D": "The legal department"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "To ensure that the fraud risk management program is effective in both operation and design, it must be fully embraced by those charged with governing and overseeing the organization. Specifically, the board of directors must recognize the true and specific risks of fraud to the organization, as well as their potential impact, and respond by: Setting an appropriate tone and realistic expectations of management to enforce an anti-fraud culture Gaining a working knowledge of the organization’s activities and the environments in which it operates Raising awareness of the risks of fraud throughout the organization Developing a strategy to assess and manage fraud risks that aligns with the organization’s risk appetite and strategic plans Overseeing the organization’s fraud risk management activities Maintaining open communications with senior management and other personnel"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "Social control theory suggests that the less attached an individual is to social institutions and groups, the greater that individual's chances of violating the law are.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Essentially, social control theory argues that the institutions of the social system train and press those with whom they are in contact into patterns of conformity. Schools train for adjustment in society; peers press the ethos of success and conventional behavior; and parents strive to instill law-abiding habits in their children—even parents who themselves sometimes violate the rules. The theory suggests that if a person fails to become attached to the variety of control agencies of the society, that person’s chances of violating the law increase."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "An organization’s fraud risk management program should include which of the following components?", "options": {"A": "Quality assurance activities", "B": "Whistleblower protection policies", "C": "A way to disclose conflicts of interest", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "According to Managing the Business Risk of Fraud, the following are ten essential components for effectively managing fraud risk: Statement of commitment—a written statement of commitment to the program from the board of directors and senior management Fraud awareness—a formal fraud risk awareness program for all employees Affirmation process—a requirement for directors, employees, and contractors to explicitly affirm that they have read, understood, and complied with the organization’s code of conduct and fraud risk management program Conflict disclosure—a mechanism for directors, employees, and contractors to self-disclose to the organization any potential or actual conflicts of interest Fraud risk assessment—the proactive identification and assessment of the organization’s fraud risks Reporting procedures and whistleblower protection—mechanisms and support for receiving fraud allegations from employees and other parties Investigation process—a formalized process that is undertaken following all reports of suspected fraud Corrective action—policies that reflect the consequences and processes for individuals who commit or condone fraudulent activity and that identify and remediate any control deficiencies that allowed the fraud to occur Process evaluation and improvement (quality assurance)—formal procedures to periodically evaluate the fraud risk management program’s effectiveness Continuous monitoring—ongoing review of the program to ensure it is addressing the organization’s current needs and risks"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "To convey their dedication to the fraud risk management program, the board of directors and senior management should provide a formal statement of commitment that:", "options": {"A": "Is in writing", "B": "Is provided to all employees, vendors, and customers", "C": "Acknowledges the organization’s vulnerability to fraud", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "As part of the fraud risk management program, the board of directors and senior management should communicate, in writing, their commitment to proactively preventing, detecting, and addressing fraud. This communication can be made as part of the organization’s written statement of values and principles, as part of the code of conduct, or in a separate short document, such as a letter, that is provided to all employees, vendors, and customers. The statement of commitment should: Be endorsed or authored by a senior executive or board member. Be provided to employees as part of the orientation process and be reissued periodically. Stress the importance of fraud risk mitigation. Acknowledge the organization’s vulnerability to fraud. Establish the responsibility of each person within the organization to support fraud risk management efforts. Reinforce management’s “no tolerance” stance on fraudulent behavior."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "COSO recommends that corporations implement control activities through formal policies that establish what is expected and procedures that put policies into action.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "According to COSO’s Internal Control—Integrated Framework, control activities are the policies and procedures that enforce management’s directives intended to mitigate risk. These actions are performed at all levels of the organization, at all stages of business processes, and through both manual and automated procedures. They can be designed to prevent the occurrence of risks, detect the occurrence of risks, or both. The following principles pertain to an organization’s control activities: The organization selects and develops control activities that mitigate risks to the achievement of objectives to acceptable levels. The organization selects and develops general control activities over technology to support the achievement of objectives. The organization deploys control activities through policies that establish what is expected and procedures that put policies into action."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the components of COSO’s Enterprise Risk Management—Integrating with Strategy and Performance?", "options": {"A": "Performance", "B": "Risk tolerance", "C": "Review and revision", "D": "Governance and culture"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "COSO’s Enterprise Risk Management—Integrating with Strategy and Performance is composed of a set of principles organized into five interrelated components and twenty supporting principles that are based on a holistic view of an organization’s risk portfolio. The five components of the ERM Framework are: Governance and culture Strategy and objective setting Performance Review and revision Information, communication, and reporting"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Justine, a CFE, was contacted regarding an engagement to investigate a complex insurance fraud case involving an organized crime ring. Justine had previously taken a self-study CPE course on insurance fraud schemes, but she had no other training or experience in such cases. However, she accepted the engagement and chose to conduct the work herself. Justine’s conduct would likely be a violation of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Based on the facts provided, Justine likely violated Article III of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, which states: \"An ACFE Member shall, at all times, exhibit the highest level of integrity in the performance of all professional assignments, and will accept only assignments for which there is reasonable expectation that the assignment will be completed with professional competence.\" Professional competence refers to how well fraud examiners do their job. Determination of competence always depends on the specific facts and circumstances of the assignment. In this situation, if Justine only had received basic training and had no other experience in insurance fraud investigations, she would not be considered qualified or professionally competent to conduct such an examination for a client. Such conduct would be a violation of Article III, which requires fraud examiners to accept only those assignments which can be completed with professional competence."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to Reiss and Biderman, _____________________ violations are those violations of law . . . that involve the use of a violator’s position of economic power, influence, or trust in the legitimate economic or political institutional order for the purpose of illegal gain, or to commit an illegal act for personal or organizational gain.", "options": {"A": "Violent crime", "B": "Organized crime", "C": "White-collar crime", "D": "Environmental crime"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Although there is no consensus within the scholarly community, one current definition of white-collar crime is that proposed by Albert J. Reiss, Jr., and Albert Biderman: \"White-collar crime violations are those violations of law to which penalties are attached that involve the use of a violator’s position of economic power, influence, or trust in the legitimate economic or political institutional order for the purpose of illegal gain, or to commit an illegal act for personal or organizational gain.\""}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "To be in compliance with the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, fraud examiners must have an expert level of skill and knowledge for every circumstance that might be encountered in a fraud examination.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraud examiners cannot be expected to have an expert level of skill and knowledge for every circumstance that might be encountered in a fraud examination. Nevertheless, they must have sufficient skill and knowledge to recognize when additional training or expert guidance is required. It is the responsibility of a fraud examiner to ensure that necessary skills, knowledge, ability, and experience are acquired or available before going forward with a fraud examination."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Detective anti-fraud controls include all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Proactive data analysis techniques", "B": "Physical inspections", "C": "Hiring policies and procedures", "D": "Hotline"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Detective controls, which are intended to detect fraud if it does occur, include: Establishing and marketing the presence of a confidential reporting system, such as a whistleblower hotline Implementing proactive controls for the fraud detection process, such as independent reconciliations, reviews, physical inspections and counts, analysis, and audits Implementing proactive fraud detection procedures, such as data analysis and continuous auditing techniques Performing surprise audits Hiring policies and procedures fall under the category of preventive controls, which are intended to prevent fraud before it occurs."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Which of the following parties is responsible for directing employees to carry out business activities and managing their performance of those tasks?", "options": {"A": "Shareholders", "B": "Management", "C": "The board of directors", "D": "External auditors"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "An organization’s management team leads the organization and its employees. Management is responsible for making the day-to-day decisions that affect company performance and, ultimately, shareholder wealth. Management’s roles pertaining to corporate governance include: Establishing strategic goals and operating objectives under the board’s oversight Directing employees to carry out business activities and managing their performance of those tasks Determining the use and allocation of company resources and assets Evaluating the organization’s successes or failures and recalibrating the strategic approach accordingly Holding responsibility for the design and operation of the organization’s internal controls Setting the organization's true ethical tone"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "When establishing a document retention policy, companies should consider:", "options": {"A": "Specific concerns related to electronic documents and data", "B": "Applicable laws and regulations regarding recordkeeping requirements", "C": "Any trade-specific rules for documenting and retaining records", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "An organization's management should ensure that the organization has a proper and effective document retention policy (DRP). When establishing a DRP, it is imperative that companies consider all applicable laws and regulations regarding recordkeeping requirements. In many jurisdictions, industries such as health care, banking, and auditing contain trade-specific rules for documenting and retaining records. Furthermore, companies should always check for legal updates concerning these requirements. Having a DRP that ignores pertinent recordkeeping requirements could lead to additional statutory violations. It is also vital that companies include protocols for preserving and destroying electronic documents in their DRPs. Companies should work with their IT departments to develop procedures for handling electronic data. Company counsel, executives, and managers should be aware of how electronic data are stored and destroyed."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "As part of an organization’s fraud risk management program, employees at all levels should:", "options": {"A": "Understand how noncompliance might create an opportunity for fraud to occur", "B": "Provide input into the design and implementation of fraud control activities when requested by management", "C": "Cooperate in investigations into suspected or alleged fraud incidents", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "According to the joint COSO/ACFE Fraud Risk Management Guide and Managing the Business Risk of Fraud, all levels of staff, including management, should: Understand the organization’s ethical culture and the organization’s commitment to that culture. Have a basic understanding of fraud and be aware of the red flags. Understand their individual roles within the organization’s fraud risk management framework, how their job procedures are designed to manage fraud risks, and when noncompliance might create an opportunity for fraud to occur or go undetected. Read and understand policies and procedures such as the organization’s fraud policy, code of conduct, whistleblower policy, procurement manuals, etc. As required, participate in creating a strong control environment, designing and implementing fraud control activities, and monitoring activities. Report suspicions or incidences of fraud. Cooperate in investigations."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "The commission formed in 1985 with the purpose of defining the responsibility of the auditor in preventing and detecting fraud is known as the:", "options": {"A": "Gephart Commission", "B": "Klaas Commission", "C": "Treadway Commission", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The National Commission on Fraudulent Financial Reporting (commonly known as the Treadway Commission) was established in the United States in 1985 with the purpose of defining the auditor’s responsibility in preventing and detecting fraud. The commission was formed and sponsored by the major professional auditing organizations—the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants, The Institute of Internal Auditors, the American Accounting Association, Financial Executives International, and the Institute of Management Accountants."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the principles involved in the risk assessment process, as laid out by COSO?", "options": {"A": "Setting clear organizational objectives", "B": "Considering the potential for fraud", "C": "Conducting ongoing monitoring of the risk management strategy", "D": "Assessing changes that could significantly impact the internal control system"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "According to the COSO Framework, “Every entity faces a variety of risks from external and internal sources. Risk is defined as the possibility that an event will occur and adversely affect the achievement of objectives.” Risk assessment involves the identification and assessment of the risks the entity faces in achieving its organizational objectives. This process is dynamic and iterative, and it forms the basis for determining how risks will be managed. According to COSO, the risk assessment involves the following principles: The organization sets sufficiently clear objectives to enable the identification and assessment of risks relating to the objectives. The organization identifies risks to the achievement of its objectives across the entity and analyzes these risks as a basis for determining how the risks should be managed. The organization considers the potential for fraud in assessing risks to the achievement of objectives. The organization identifies and assesses changes that could significantly impact the system of internal control."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Which of the following is NOT one of the eight principles for risk management provided by ISO 31000:2018?", "options": {"A": "The risk management program is based on effective leadership and commitment.", "B": "The risk management program is customized and proportionate to the organization's operations and objectives.", "C": "The risk management program takes human and cultural factors into account.", "D": "The risk management program is dynamic and responsive to change."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The following eight ISO 31000:2018 principles provide that an effective and efficient risk management program: Is integrated into all organizational activities Is structured and comprehensive Is customized and proportionate to the organization’s operations and objectives Is inclusive and provides for appropriate and timely consideration of stakeholders’ knowledge, views, and perceptions Is dynamic and responsive to change Is based upon the best available information Takes human and cultural factors into account Facilitates continuous improvement According to ISO 31000, the framework for an organization’s risk management program should be based on a foundation set by effective leadership and commitment, but this is not one of the eight principles of risk management provided by ISO 31000:2018."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to criminologist Charles McCaghy, _____________ is the single most compelling factor behind deviance by organizations.", "options": {"A": "Profit pressure", "B": "Government regulation", "C": "Employee demands", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Criminologist Charles McCaghy says profit pressure is “the single most compelling factor behind deviance by industry, whether it be price fixing, the destruction of competition, or the misrepresentation of a product,” such as making a poor-quality product that will wear out and need to be replaced. Clinard and Yeager say certain industries, such as the drug and chemical businesses, have such severe competition and strong profit drives due to demands for continual development of new products that they might feel pressured to falsify test data, market new products before their full effects are known, or engage in unethical sales techniques that can have disastrous effects on humans and the environment."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following elements is required for a corporate compliance program to be effective?", "options": {"A": "Consistent punishment for employees who violate the program", "B": "Due diligence in the hiring process", "C": "Appropriate incentives for compliance with the program", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The U.S. Corporate Sentencing Guidelines provide a benchmark and foundational guidance for organizations in all countries for developing an effective compliance program. These Guidelines set forth the following seven factors that are minimally required for a corporate compliance program to be considered effective: 1. Established standards and procedures to prevent and detect criminal conduct 2. Proper assignment of responsibility and oversight for the compliance program 3. Due diligence in the hiring process to ensure the ethics of individuals who exercise a substantial measure of discretion in acting on behalf of an organization 4. Periodic and practical communication of the compliance policy through effective training programs and other means 5. Steps to ensure program compliance through monitoring, auditing, periodically evaluating the program’s effectiveness, and having a publicized reporting system 6. Promotion and consistent enforcement of the program through appropriate incentives for compliance and appropriate disciplinary measures for violations 7. Reasonable response to any discovered criminal conduct in order to prevent further similar criminal conduct, including making any necessary modifications to the organization’s compliance and ethics program"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following is a responsibility that the internal auditor should carry out in conducting audit engagements?", "options": {"A": "Consider fraud risks in the assessment of internal control design and determination of audit steps to perform", "B": "Evaluate the indicators of fraud and decide whether any further action is necessary or whether an investigation should be recommended", "C": "Evaluate whether management is actively retaining responsibility for oversight of the fraud risk management program", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "To help auditors comply with their responsibilities pertaining to fraud, the IIA released IPPF—Practice Guide: Internal Auditing and Fraud. Although not mandatory, the guidance included in the Practice Guide is strongly recommended. Specifically, this Guide states that, in conducting audit engagements, the internal auditor should: Consider fraud risks in the assessment of internal control design and determination of audit steps to perform. Have sufficient knowledge of fraud to identify red flags indicating fraud might have been committed. Be alert to opportunities that could allow fraud, such as control deficiencies. Evaluate whether management is actively retaining responsibility for oversight of the fraud risk management program, whether timely and sufficient corrective measures have been taken with respect to any noted control deficiencies or weaknesses, and whether the plan for monitoring the program continues to be adequate for the program’s ongoing success. Evaluate the indicators of fraud and decide whether any further action is necessary or whether an investigation should be recommended. Recommend investigation when appropriate."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "The fraud risk assessment team might include:", "options": {"A": "Accounting and finance personnel", "B": "The general counsel", "C": "External consultants", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The fraud risk assessment team members might include internal and external sources, such as: Accounting and finance personnel who are familiar with the financial reporting processes and internal controls Nonfinancial business unit and operations personnel who have knowledge of day-to-day operations, customer and vendor interactions, and issues within the industry Risk management personnel who can ensure that the fraud risk assessment process integrates with the organization’s enterprise risk management program The general counsel or other members of the legal department Members of any ethics or compliance functions within the organization Internal auditors Internal security or investigative personnel who are familiar with investigations of past fraud incidents External consultants with fraud and risk expertise Any business leader with direct accountability for the effectiveness of the organization’s fraud risk management efforts"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "International Standard on Auditing (ISA) 240 delineates two types of frauds that are relevant for audit purposes: those that involve intentional fraudulent financial reporting and those that involve the misappropriation of company assets.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Although fraud is a broad legal concept, for the purposes of ISA 240, the auditor is concerned with fraud that causes a material misstatement in the financial statements. Two types of intentional misstatements are relevant to the auditor—misstatements resulting from fraudulent financial reporting and misstatements resulting from misappropriation of assets. Although the auditor might suspect or, in rare cases, identify the occurrence of fraud, the auditor does not make legal determinations of whether fraud has actually occurred."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Which of the following is FALSE regarding employee anti-fraud education?", "options": {"A": "All anti-fraud training should be based on the organization’s specific operations and fraud risks.", "B": "Fraud awareness training efforts should be restricted to formal education mechanisms.", "C": "Mid-level managers should be tasked with assisting in training their teams about fraud.", "D": "Fraud awareness training should be required for employees both at time of hire and periodically thereafter."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Like any educational efforts, frequent exposure to anti-fraud topics is the key to ensuring employees absorb—and apply—the information provided. Formal fraud awareness training should be an ongoing process that begins at the time of hire. Employees should also participate in refresher training at least annually to help keep the program alive and engrained in their minds. Formal anti-fraud training can take many forms, including live, in-class instruction; recorded video or animated courses; or interactive self-study programs. In addition, the organization should use other informal means, such as periodic newsletters or posters in break rooms, to reinforce its anti-fraud stance on a more constant basis. Perhaps most important, however, is that the training be based on the realities of the organization, rather than on generic anti-fraud messages. While providing general information is good and necessary, doing so without addressing the company's specific concerns or providing employees with practical knowledge and ideas on how to apply it will render the training program ineffective. As messages from an employee’s direct supervisor often carry the most weight with an employee, the concept of cascading training can be an especially effective means of anti-fraud education. In cascading training, managers are tasked with and specifically educated on how to provide anti-fraud training to their own staff. This allows training to be customized to each team’s own needs, as well as for the message to come directly from the team’s own leader."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "As a strategy to control crime, _________ is designed to achieve conformity to the law by providing economic incentives for voluntary adherence to the law and using administrative efforts to control violations before they occur.", "options": {"A": "Prevention", "B": "Compliance", "C": "Deterrence", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "As a strategy to control crime, compliance is designed to achieve conformity to the law without having to detect, process, or penalize violators. Compliance systems provide economic incentives for voluntary compliance to the laws and use administrative efforts to control violations before they occur. However, compliance strategies have been criticized by some criminologists. These experts believe that such strategies have little effect, as sanctions are imposed after the infraction occurs. Since economic penalties are common punishments for violators, these penalties are of little consequence in the case of large, wealthy corporations."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "In general, the lowest level of reference for making moral decisions is:", "options": {"A": "The law", "B": "Individual standards", "C": "Philosophical principles", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When faced with an ethics-related problem, it is appropriate to begin analyzing the issue by asking: Is it legal? The law, including professional rules and regulations, deals with actions that are permitted and prohibited, but it is the lowest level of reference for moral decisions; a law might permit an action that is prohibited by a profession's code of ethics. Laws, rules, and regulations function as standards by which to judge whether an action is legal or illegal but not whether the behavior is right. For instance, if you have promised an individual that you will honor a contract, you are ethically bound to do so, regardless of your legal responsibility; under these facts, upholding your promise is the right thing to do, no matter what the law says."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Which of the following is a fraud examiner permitted to express an opinion regarding?", "options": {"A": "The innocence of a particular individual", "B": "The effectiveness of an organization’s internal controls", "C": "The guilt of a particular individual", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Article V of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics states: \"An ACFE Member, in conducting examinations, will obtain evidence or other documentation to establish a reasonable basis for any opinion rendered. No opinion shall be expressed regarding the guilt or innocence of any person or party.\" The only opinions strictly not allowed are those regarding the guilt or innocence of any person or party. However, opinions regarding technical matters generally are permitted if the fraud examiner is qualified as an expert in the matter. For example, a permissible opinion might address the relative adequacy of an entity’s internal controls. Likewise, a permissible opinion might regard whether financial transactions conform to generally accepted accounting principles."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to The Institute of Internal Auditors’ International Standards for the Professional Practice of Internal Auditing, internal auditors must apply the care and skill of an expert whose primary responsibility is investigating fraud.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The Institute of Internal Auditors' Standard 1220 states that internal auditors must apply the care and skill expected of a reasonably prudent and competent internal auditor. The Standard also states, however, that due professional care does not imply infallibility."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Bryan, a CFE, locks the door to the interview room and refuses to allow the suspect to leave despite repeated requests. Later, the suspect sues (successfully), claiming that he was falsely imprisoned. Which of the following statements is true?", "options": {"A": "This conduct would be a violation of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics.", "B": "This conduct would be a violation of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics ONLY IF the suspect was innocent of fraud.", "C": "This conduct would NOT be a violation of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics under any circumstances.", "D": "This conduct would be a violation of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics ONLY IF Bryan knew the conduct was illegal."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Some rules for professionals insert the word knowingly in relation to illegal activities, saying: “One should not knowingly be a party to an illegal activity.” The ACFE Code of Professional Ethics does not include this way out. Fraud examiners are generally not entitled to claim ignorance of the law. They are expected to know a considerable amount of law in connection with investigations, and they are expected to know when to consult a lawyer. In the situation in question, even if Bryan didn't know that locking the door would constitute false imprisonment, he has still violated the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "In the context of fraud examination, integrity requires:", "options": {"A": "Subordination of desires for personal gain to the interests of clients, employers, and the public", "B": "Independence of mental attitude and avoidance of conflicts of interest", "C": "An ability to analyze situations where no professional rules are specifically applicable and determine right from wrong", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Integrity requires honesty, truthfulness, trustworthiness, and confidentiality. It also requires subordination of desires for personal gain to the interests of clients, employers, and the public. It requires independence of mental attitude and avoidance of conflicts of interest. Additionally, integrity means that a fraud examiner should have a well-developed sense of moral philosophy—an ability to analyze situations where no rules of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics are specifically applicable and to be able to distinguish right from wrong. It does not mean, however, that an ACFE member must be perfect in all technical matters, nor does it mean that fraud examiners and others cannot have honest differences of opinion. In the course of a fraud examination, inadvertent errors, mistakes of judgment, and other problems might cause conflict. In such cases, a fraud examiner can preserve integrity either by admitting error or by convincingly justifying a difference of perception or opinion."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "The ACFE Code of Professional Ethics explicitly prohibits which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Unethical conduct", "B": "Illegal conduct", "C": "Undisclosed conflicts of interest", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Article II of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics states: “An ACFE Member shall not engage in any illegal or unethical conduct, or any activity which would constitute a conflict of interest that has not been properly disclosed to the appropriate parties.” This rule is a composite of three explicit prohibitions: illegal conduct, unethical conduct, and undisclosed conflicts of interest."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "In response to a risk identified during a fraud risk assessment, management decides to eliminate an asset or discontinue an activity because the control measures required to protect the organization against the identified threat are too expensive. This response is known as:", "options": {"A": "Transferring the risk", "B": "Mitigating the risk", "C": "Assuming the risk", "D": "Avoiding the risk"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When responding to the organization’s residual fraud risks, management may decide to avoid a risk by eliminating an asset or discontinuing an activity if the control measures required to protect the organization against an identified threat are too expensive. This approach requires the fraud risk assessment team to complete a cost-benefit analysis of the value of the asset or activity to the organization compared to the cost of implementing measures to protect the asset or activity."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Which of the following is an effective method of increasing the perception of detection?", "options": {"A": "Requiring strong management oversight", "B": "Conducting surprise audits", "C": "Forcing employees to take vacation time", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Increasing the perception of detection might be the most effective fraud prevention method. Controls, for example, do little good in preventing theft and fraud if those at risk do not know of the presence of possible detection. In the audit profession, this means letting employees, managers, and executives know that auditors are actively seeking out information concerning internal theft. This can be accomplished in several ways, such as surprise audits, employee anti-fraud education, enforcement of mandatory vacation and job-rotation policies, strong management oversight, and effective reporting programs."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to The Institute of Internal Auditors’ International Standards for the Professional Practice of Internal Auditing, due professional care implies infallibility.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The Institute of Internal Auditors' Standard 1220 states that internal auditors must apply the care and skill expected of a reasonably prudent and competent internal auditor. The Standard also states, however, that due professional care does not imply infallibility."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "The majority of people who commit occupational fraud are repeat offenders with prior criminal records.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "ACFE research indicates that the vast majority of occupational fraudsters have no prior history of criminal fraud convictions. Only 4% of the perpetrators in the 2018 Report to the Nations study had previously been convicted of a fraud-related offense, which is consistent with our findings in every study dating back to 1996. This suggests that most occupational fraudsters are first-time offenders. Additionally, 85% of the fraudsters had never previously been punished or terminated by an employer for fraud or abuse."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "During an admission-seeking interview of a fraud suspect, Gary, a Certified Fraud Examiner, accuses the suspect of having committed a fraud. Gary's accusation violates the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Article V of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics states: \"An ACFE Member, in conducting examinations, will obtain evidence or other documentation to establish a reasonable basis for any opinion rendered. No opinion shall be expressed regarding the guilt or innocence of any person or party.\" Although it does not specifically state such, Article V really applies to statements of opinion made to third parties. If the fraud examiner was interviewing a suspect whose guilt was highly probable, the Code would not prohibit the fraud examiner from making accusations. The admission-seeking process, used extensively by fraud examiners, requires that accusations be made of the probable guilty party. As long as these accusations are not communicated to third parties, the fraud examiner would not be in violation of the Code."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "The IOSCO Principles for Auditor Oversight state that auditor oversight should:", "options": {"A": "Involve a regular review process designed to ascertain whether audit firms adhere to quality control policies and procedures", "B": "Be performed by a body that acts and is seen to act in the public interest", "C": "Take place within the audit firm, by professional associates, and through government regulation", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions’ Principles for Auditor Oversight note that auditor oversight should take place at several levels—within the audit firm, by professional associates, and through government regulation. However, the Principles for Auditor Oversight state that, within jurisdictions, audit firms should be subject to oversight by some body that acts and is seen to act in the public interest. Further, this auditor oversight body should have in place a regular review process designed to ascertain whether audit firms adhere to quality control policies and procedures that address all significant aspects of auditing."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to International Standard on Auditing (ISA) 240, the auditor is primarily concerned with fraud that:", "options": {"A": "Causes a material misstatement in the financial statements", "B": "Is perpetrated by one or more members of management", "C": "Involves the misappropriation of company assets", "D": "Is determined to meet the legal definition of fraud"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Although fraud is a broad legal concept, for the purposes of ISA 240, the auditor is concerned with fraud that causes a material misstatement in the financial statements. Two types of intentional misstatements are relevant to the auditor—misstatements resulting from fraudulent financial reporting and misstatements resulting from misappropriation of assets. Although the auditor might suspect or, in rare cases, identify the occurrence of fraud, the auditor does not make legal determinations of whether fraud has actually occurred."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "The payment of bribes to procure business is considered a fraud risk pertaining to which category of fraud?", "options": {"A": "Fraudulent financial reporting", "B": "Corruption", "C": "Asset misappropriation", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Potential corruption risks include: Payment of bribes or illegal gratuities to companies, private individuals, or public officials Receipt of bribes, kickbacks, or illegal gratuities by employees or agents of the company Aiding and abetting of fraud by outside parties, such as customers or vendors"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Systems based on the compliance theory of crime control attempt to achieve conformity to the law without having to detect, process, or penalize violators.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Enforcement strategies include two main theories: compliance and deterrence. Compliance is designed to achieve conformity to the law without having to detect, process, or penalize violators. Compliance systems provide economic incentives for voluntary compliance to the laws and use administrative efforts to control violations before they occur. In contrast, deterrence is designed to detect law violations, determine who is responsible, and penalize offenders to deter future violations. Deterrence systems try to control the immediate behavior of individuals, not the long-term behaviors targeted by compliance systems."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, evidence and conclusions are considered ___________ if knowledge of them would affect clients’ decisions based on a fraud examiner’s report.", "options": {"A": "Confidential", "B": "Circumstantial", "C": "Material", "D": "Reliable"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Evidence and conclusions are material if knowledge of them would affect clients’ decisions based on a fraud examiner’s report. Materiality is a user-oriented concept. If matters omitted from a report were known to the users, and their own perceptions and conclusions would be different due to this knowledge, the omitted information is material. Article VII requires fraud examiners to reveal all material matters discovered during the course of an examination, which, if omitted, could cause a distortion of the facts."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Under the fraud control activities principle described in the COSO/ACFE Fraud Risk Management Guide, organizations should select, develop, and deploy preventive and detective fraud control activities.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The COSO/ACFE Fraud Risk Management Guide describes five broad principles of fraud risk management, one for each of the five interrelated components of internal control listed in COSO’s Internal Controls—Integrated Framework: fraud risk governance, fraud risk assessment, fraud control activities, fraud investigation and corrective action, and fraud risk management monitoring activities. Each of these principles is then supported by several points of focus. The principles and underlying points of focus combine to create a full framework that can be used to design, implement, and assess an effective fraud risk management program. Under the fraud control activities principle, the organization selects, develops, and deploys preventive and detective fraud control activities to mitigate the risk of fraud events occurring or not being detected in a timely manner."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "Which of the following is FALSE regarding the communication of the fraud risk assessment process?", "options": {"A": "The communication should be limited to management and the board.", "B": "The communication should be in the form of a message from the assessment sponsor.", "C": "The communication should be personalized to make it more effective in encouraging employees to participate in the process.", "D": "The communication should be visibly disseminated throughout the business."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The fraud risk assessment process should be visible and communicated throughout the business. Employees will be more inclined to participate in the process if they understand why it is being done and what the expected outcomes will be. To that end, sponsors should be strongly encouraged to openly promote the process. The more personalized the communication from the sponsor, the more effective it will be in encouraging employees to participate in the process. Whether it is a video, a town hall meeting, or a company-wide email, the communication should be aimed at eliminating any reluctance employees have about participating in the fraud risk assessment process."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "A behaviorist view of the workplace advocates the use of incentive programs and task-related bonuses as a way to deter employees from ethical and legal violations.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Emotions, according to behavioral pioneer B. F. Skinner, are a predisposition for people’s actions. And since the emotional associations of any event are important factors in conditioning behavior, the associations can be manipulated in conditioning the behavior. The behaviorist view proposes that, when managers are faced with disgruntled employees, they can modify these emotional circumstances with adequate compensation and recognition of workers’ accomplishments. Incentive programs and task-related bonuses follow this principle, assuming that employees who feel challenged and rewarded by their jobs will produce more work at a higher quality and are less likely to violate the law."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, information provided to a fraud examiner by a client is considered privileged information and is therefore protected from being legally demanded by outside parties.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Privileged information is information that cannot be demanded, even by a court. Legal professional privilege precludes disclosure of confidential communications between professional legal advisors (e.g., solicitors, barristers, attorneys) and their clients. Some jurisdictions provide similar professional privileges for physicians and priests. However, fraud examiners do not have any such privilege in common law or by statute, and the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics does not assume a privileged status for the fraud examiner-client/employer relationship."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to Diane Vaughan, encouraging employee loyalty through social interactions, such as company parties and social functions, can contribute to the organization being more inherently inclined to commit crime.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Organizations can be criminogenic because they encourage loyalty. According to Diane Vaughan, the reasons are that: The organization tends to recruit and attract similar individuals. Rewards are given out to those who display characteristics of the “company man.” Long-term loyalty is encouraged through company retirement and benefits. Loyalty is encouraged through social interaction, such as company parties and social functions. Frequent transfers and long working hours encourage isolation from other groups. Specialized job skills can discourage personnel from seeking employment elsewhere. In addition, organizations are more inherently prone to committing crime when management links employees’ needs and goals to the company's success through the use of formal and informal rewards and punishments, plus social activities and pressures to participate. When a company achieves its goals, its employees prosper. In short, the interests of an organization and its employees coincide, and that situation might set the stage for unlawful conduct by individuals on the organization’s behalf."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "For analytical review procedures performed during a financial statement audit to be most effective in uncovering fraud, the scheme must materially impact the financial statements.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Some internal fraud is discovered as a result of analytical review procedures performed during a financial statement audit. To uncover fraud using such techniques, however, the scheme must materially impact the financial statements. Auditors should be especially mindful of the following trends: Increasing expenses Increasing cost of sales Increasing receivables/decreasing cash Increasing inventories Increasing sales/decreasing cash Increasing returns and allowances Increasing sales discounts"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "In white-collar crime cases, the higher an offender's status, the more likely that person is to be imprisoned.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Considering all white-collar crime offenders, the higher an individual’s status, the more likely the person is to be imprisoned. According to Crimes of the Middle Classes, \"all else being equal, doctors will have about a 30% greater likelihood of being imprisoned [for a white-collar crime] than truck drivers and almost a 13% greater likelihood than managers.\" Judges seem to find persons of higher prestige more blameworthy in the commission of their crimes."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Effective ownership and reporting structures within an organization are necessary for ensuring which of the following principles of corporate governance?", "options": {"A": "Accountability", "B": "Fairness", "C": "Responsibility", "D": "Transparency"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "One of the core principles or values of corporate governance is accountability. The ownership and reporting structures within an organization set the stage for the involved parties’ accountability. In most corporations, the owners (i.e., shareholders) are separate from the decision makers (i.e., management) and overseers (i.e., board of directors). To make sure that the organization operates effectively and efficiently, there must be mechanisms in place to ensure that management is accountable to the board and that the board is accountable to the shareholders."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "For a corporate compliance program to be effective, the company must proactively monitor, audit, and evaluate the program’s components.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The U.S. Corporate Sentencing Guidelines provide a benchmark and foundational guidance for organizations in all countries for developing an effective compliance program. These Guidelines set forth the following seven factors that are minimally required for a corporate compliance program to be considered effective: 1. Established standards and procedures to prevent and detect criminal conduct 2. Proper assignment of responsibility and oversight for the compliance program 3. Due diligence in the hiring process to ensure the ethics of individuals who exercise a substantial measure of discretion in acting on behalf of an organization 4. Periodic and practical communication of the compliance policy through effective training programs and other means 5. Steps to ensure program compliance through monitoring, auditing, periodically evaluating the program’s effectiveness, and having a publicized reporting system 6. Promotion and consistent enforcement of the program through appropriate incentives for compliance and appropriate disciplinary measures for violations 7. Reasonable response to any discovered criminal conduct in order to prevent further similar criminal conduct, including making any necessary modifications to the organization’s compliance and ethics program"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Which of the following statements is TRUE in regard to an organization’s fraud risk management program?", "options": {"A": "Formal sanctions for intentional noncompliance must be well-publicized and carried out in a consistent and firm manner", "B": "There should be measures in place to address failures in the design or operation of anti-fraud controls, as well as fraud occurrences", "C": "A specific team or individual should be designated as responsible for monitoring compliance and handling suspected instances of noncompliance", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The fraud risk management program must include mechanisms specifically designed to monitor, identify, and address breaches in compliance. Such breaches might include failures in the design or operation of anti-fraud controls, as well as outright occurrences of fraud. A specific individual or team should be designated as responsible for monitoring compliance with the fraud risk management program and for handling suspected instances of noncompliance. Formal sanctions for intentional noncompliance must be well-publicized and carried out in a consistent and firm manner."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Which of the following controls can help minimize the pressures that might lead an employee to commit fraud?", "options": {"A": "Employee support programs", "B": "Open-door management policies", "C": "Fair personnel policies and procedures", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "While most internal controls are designed to reduce the opportunity to commit and conceal fraud, organizations should also be mindful of the pressures, such as financial hardships or family problems, that can lead to fraud. Unfortunately, such pressures can be difficult to detect in employees. However, companies should take steps to increase managers’ awareness of such potential problems, as well as to assist an employee who might be having difficult times. Examples of mechanisms that help alleviate the pressures to commit fraud include: Open-door management policies Fair and equitably applied personnel policies and procedures Measures to boost employee morale, such as career development opportunities, special events for employees, and recognition for jobs well done Employee support programs, such as counseling for addiction, family and marital problems, and financial difficulties"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Which of the following represents one of the legs of the Fraud Triangle?", "options": {"A": "Perceived non-shareable financial need", "B": "Rationalization", "C": "Perceived opportunity", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "While working on his Ph.D. in the 1940s, Donald R. Cressey focused his research on embezzlers. His findings resulted in a hypothesis that, over the years, has become known as the Fraud Triangle. One leg of the triangle represents a perceived non-shareable financial need. The second leg is for perceived opportunity, and the final leg is for rationalization. The role of the non-shareable problem is important. Cressey said, “When the trust violators were asked to explain why they refrained from violation of other positions of trust they might have held at previous times, or why they had not violated the subject position at an earlier time, those who had an opinion expressed the equivalent of one or more of the following quotations: (a) ‘There was no need for it like there was this time.’ (b) ‘The idea never entered my head.’ (c) ‘I thought it was dishonest then, but this time it did not seem dishonest at first.’”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Which of the following should be emphasized in an employee reporting program?\nI.   Fraud, waste, and abuse occur in only a few companies.\nII.  The company actively encourages employees with information to come forward.\nIII. The employee's name must be disclosed.\nIV.  The report need not be made to one's immediate supervisor.", "options": {"A": "II and IV", "B": "II and III", "C": "I, II, and IV", "D": "I, II, III, and IV"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "An anonymous reporting channel, such as an ethics hotline, is an integral part of an anti-fraud control system. Employees must be made aware of the existence of the reporting mechanism, taught how to use it, and be able to trust that they can report suspicious activity anonymously or confidentially (where permitted by law) without fear of reprisal. In addition, it should be made clear to employees that reports of suspicious activity will be promptly and thoroughly evaluated. Education about a reporting program should specifically emphasize that: Fraud, waste, and abuse occur in nearly all companies. Such conduct costs the company jobs and profits. The company actively encourages any employee with information to be able to come forward. The employee can come forward and provide information anonymously and without fear of retaliation for good-faith reporting. There is an exact method for reporting an incident (e.g., a telephone number or online form). The report need not be made to one's immediate superiors."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "_____________ controls are designed to stop something bad from happening before it occurs, while _____________ controls are designed to identify something bad that has already occurred.", "options": {"A": "Investigative; deterrent", "B": "Investigative; detective", "C": "Preventive; detective", "D": "Detective; investigative"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Preventive controls are those manual or automated processes that stop something bad from happening before it occurs. Detective controls can also be manual or automated but are designed to identify something bad that has already occurred. With the right balance of preventive and detective controls, a good system of internal controls can greatly reduce an organization’s vulnerability to fraud."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Dr. Steve Albrecht’s research indicates that the personal characteristics most common among fraud perpetrators are a tendency to live beyond their means, an overwhelming desire for personal gain, and high personal debt.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In Dr. Steve Albrecht’s study, the researchers gave internal auditors at companies that had experienced frauds two sets of 25 motivating factors and asked which factors were present in the frauds they had dealt with. Participants were asked to rank these factors on a seven-point scale indicating the degree to which each factor existed in their specific frauds. Based on this study, the top three most highly ranked factors from the list of personal characteristics were (1) living beyond their means, (2) an overwhelming desire for personal gain, and (3) high personal debt."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following factors should an organization consider when designing the components of its compliance and ethics program?", "options": {"A": "Industry size and standards", "B": "Organization size", "C": "Recurrence of similar conduct", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The U.S. Corporate Sentencing Guidelines provide a benchmark and foundational guidance for organizations in all countries for developing an effective compliance program. These Guidelines state that organizations should consider the following factors when designing their compliance and ethics programs: Applicable industry size and practice—An organization’s failure to incorporate and follow industry practice or the standards called for by any applicable government regulation adversely affects a finding that the program is effective. Size of the organization—Large organizations are expected to devote more formal operations and greater resources to meeting the requirements than are small organizations. For example, smaller organizations may use available personnel rather than employ separate staff to carry out ethics and compliance. Recurrence of similar misconduct—The recurrence of a similar event creates doubt as to whether the organization took reasonable steps to meet the requirements."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, fraud examiners are absolutely prohibited from expressing opinions regarding the guilt or innocence of any party.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The guilt or innocence of any person or party is the sole judgment of the judge or jury, not of the fraud examiner. Consequently, fraud examiners are absolutely prohibited from expressing opinions regarding guilt or innocence. Article V of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics states: \"An ACFE Member, in conducting examinations, will obtain evidence or other documentation to establish a reasonable basis for any opinion rendered. No opinion shall be expressed regarding the guilt or innocence of any person or party.\""}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "The fraud risk assessment process should be conducted covertly so that assessment team members can get an accurate picture of what actually occurs in the business.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The fraud risk assessment process should be visible and communicated throughout the business. Employees will be more inclined to participate in the process if they understand why it is being done and what the expected outcomes will be. To that end, sponsors should be strongly encouraged to openly promote the process. The more personalized the communication from the sponsor, the more effective it will be in encouraging employees to participate in the process. Whether it is a video, a town hall meeting, or a company-wide email, the communication should be aimed at eliminating any reluctance employees have about participating in the fraud risk assessment process."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following parties is ultimately responsible for the prevention and detection of fraud within an organization?", "options": {"A": "External auditors", "B": "Internal auditors", "C": "Management", "D": "Board of directors"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "While many parties—including the board of directors, internal audit, and external auditors—play an important role in combatting fraud, management is ultimately responsible for the prevention and detection of fraud within an organization."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "According to the OECD Principles of Corporate Governance, a corporate governance framework should recognize the rights of which of the following parties?", "options": {"A": "Creditors", "B": "Employees", "C": "Shareholders", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Chapter IV of the OECD Principles of Corporate Governance states that “the corporate governance framework should recognize the rights of stakeholders established by law or through mutual agreements and encourage active cooperation between corporations and stakeholders in creating wealth, jobs, and the sustainability of financially sound enterprises.” Beyond just shareholders, this section of the Principles recognizes the need for organizations to consider employees, creditors, and other stakeholders in their corporate governance initiatives. A key aspect of corporate governance is concerned with ensuring the flow of external capital to companies both in the form of equity and credit. Corporate governance is also concerned with finding ways to encourage the various stakeholders in the firm to undertake economically optimal levels of investment in firm-specific human and physical capital. The competitiveness and ultimate success of a corporation is the result of teamwork that embodies contributions from a range of different resource providers, including investors, employees, creditors, customers, suppliers, and other stakeholders. Corporations should recognize that the contributions of stakeholders constitute a valuable resource for building competitive and profitable companies."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "The _______________ provide(s) guidance for policy makers in evaluating and improving the legal, regulatory, and institutional framework for corporate governance.", "options": {"A": "IIA Standards for the Professional Practice of Internal Auditing", "B": "IOSCO Principles for Auditor Oversight", "C": "INTOSAI Code of Ethics", "D": "OECD Principles of Corporate Governance"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The OECD Principles of Corporate Governance is regarded as one of the hallmark sources of guidance for corporate governance practices for organizations throughout the world. According to the OECD, the Principles “are intended to help policy makers evaluate and improve the legal, regulatory, and institutional framework for corporate governance with a view to support economic efficiency, sustainable growth, and financial stability.” Policy makers in many countries have used these Principles as a basis for legislative and regulatory corporate governance initiatives."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Of the following parties, who is responsible for the oversight of the organization’s financial, accounting, and audit matters?", "options": {"A": "The internal auditors", "B": "The external auditors", "C": "The CFO", "D": "The audit committee"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "As a sub-group of the board of directors, the audit committee is often delegated oversight of the organization’s financial, accounting, and audit matters and reports to the full board. As part of this responsibility, the committee must take an active role in overseeing the assessment and monitoring of the organization’s fraud risks. This involves: Receiving regular reports on the status of reported or alleged fraud Being aware of fraud risks that are common in the organization’s industry Meeting regularly with key internal parties (e.g., the chief audit executive or other senior financial persons) to discuss identified fraud risks and the steps being taken to prevent and detect fraud Understanding how internal and external audit strategies address fraud risk Providing external auditors with evidence that the audit committee is dedicated to effective fraud risk management Engaging in open conversations with external auditors about any known or suspected fraud Seeking advice of legal counsel whenever it deals with allegations of fraud"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "According to COSO, _________ is the culture, capabilities, and practices, integrated with strategy-setting and its performance, that organizations rely on to manage risk in creating, preserving, and realizing value.", "options": {"A": "Internal control", "B": "Fraud prevention", "C": "Enterprise risk management", "D": "Corporate governance"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In Enterprise Risk Management—Integrating with Strategy and Performance, COSO defines enterprise risk management as “the culture, capabilities, and practices, integrated with strategy-setting and its performance, that organizations rely on to manage risk in creating, preserving, and realizing value.”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "Who is responsible for holding the board of directors accountable for proper governance and oversight?", "options": {"A": "The chairman of the board", "B": "The shareholders", "C": "The external auditors", "D": "Executive management"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Shareholders are the owners of corporations; they are primarily concerned with maximizing the return on their investment. To that end, shareholders have a responsibility to be actively involved in the corporate governance process by: Remaining informed on company operations and performance Reading annual reports and other communications from management to the shareholders Attending shareholder meetings Electing capable individuals to serve as board directors Holding the board of directors accountable for proper governance and oversight Appointing or ratifying the audit committee's appointment of the organization’s independent auditors Voting on other significant issues, such as specific changes relating to business operations, the company's corporate governance framework, and the rights and responsibilities of the board of directors and executive managers"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Under the Institute of Internal Auditors’ International Standards for the Professional Practice of Internal Auditing, an organization's internal audit function is required to hold primary responsibility for all internal fraud investigations.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The role that internal audit plays in fraud investigations varies by organization. Internal audit might have primary responsibility for fraud investigations, might serve as a resource for the investigations, or might have no involvement at all in the investigations."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following factors should auditors include in their discussion on the financial statements’ susceptibility to fraud, as required by ISA 240?", "options": {"A": "Factors that indicate a culture that enables individuals to rationalize committing fraud", "B": "How and where the financial statements might be susceptible to fraud", "C": "How a company's assets could be misappropriated", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "ISA 240 requires auditors to hold a discussion regarding the potential for material misstatements due to fraud. This discussion should cover: How and where the entity’s financial statements might be susceptible to fraud How management could perpetrate and conceal fraudulent financial reporting How the entity's assets could be misappropriated This discussion should also include a consideration of known external and internal factors affecting the entity that might: Create incentives or pressures for management and others to commit fraud. Provide the opportunity for fraud to be perpetrated. Indicate a culture or environment that enables management and others to rationalize committing fraud."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "Research has shown that most individuals feel that breaking the law is morally wrong and that laws should be obeyed even when they do not agree with them.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Tom Tyler, author of Why People Obey the Law, conducted a study (called the Chicago Study) to test the concept that if authorities have legitimacy, the public will obey the law. The Chicago Study shows that people have a high level of normative commitment to abide by the law. Most participants felt that breaking the law was morally wrong and that laws should be obeyed even when one does not agree with them. Authorities who can tap into and encourage those views will inspire compliance. Similarly, employees who have a strong sense of loyalty to their employer will not violate company policies because such acts would be a betrayal to the company."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "According to the OECD Principles of Corporate Governance, an entity’s corporate governance framework should:", "options": {"A": "Encourage active cooperation between corporations and stakeholders in creating wealth and jobs", "B": "Ensure the equitable treatment of all shareholders, including minority and foreign shareholders", "C": "Ensure the timely and accurate disclosure of all material matters regarding the corporation", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The OECD Principles of Corporate Governance is regarded as one of the hallmark sources of guidance for corporate governance practices for organizations throughout the world. Broadly, the Principles state that an entity’s corporate governance framework should: Promote transparent and fair markets and the efficient allocation of resources. Be consistent with the rule of law. Support effective supervision and enforcement. Protect and facilitate the exercise of shareholders’ rights. Ensure the equitable treatment of all shareholders, including minority and foreign shareholders. Provide all shareholders with the opportunity to obtain effective redress for violation of their rights. Create sound incentives throughout the investment chain. Enable stock markets to function in a way that contributes to good corporate governance. Recognize the rights of stakeholders established by law or through mutual agreements. Encourage active cooperation between corporations and stakeholders in creating wealth, jobs, and the sustainability of financially sound enterprises. Ensure that timely and accurate disclosure is made on all material matters regarding the corporation, including the company’s financial situation, performance, ownership, and governance. Ensure the strategic guidance of the company, the effective monitoring of management by the board, and the board’s accountability to the company and the shareholders."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to criminologist Donald Cressey, which of the following is NOT essential to the commission of fraud?", "options": {"A": "General information about how the company might be defrauded", "B": "Technical skill", "C": "Absence of controls", "D": "All of the above are essential"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In Cressey’s view, there were two components of the perceived opportunity to commit a trust violation: general information and technical skill. General information is simply the knowledge that the employee’s position of trust could be violated. This knowledge might come from hearing of other embezzlements, from seeing dishonest behavior by other employees, or just from generally being aware of the fact that the employee is in a position where he could take advantage of his employer’s faith in him. Technical skill refers to the abilities needed to commit the violation. These are usually the same abilities that the employee needs to obtain and keep his position in the first place."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "The way that management handles incidents of fraud within the organization plays an important role in its fraud prevention program.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The way that management handles incidents of fraud within the organization plays an important role in its fraud prevention program. Specifically, it must be made clear to all employees that the company maintains a policy of zero tolerance for fraud; otherwise, once an employee learns that small frauds are possible, larger frauds might be committed shortly thereafter. In addition, by not consistently punishing perpetrators, a company renders its fraud prevention program less effective, if not useless. Having a public record of the incident can also be important, so reporting known incidents of fraud to law enforcement can be an effective step in making the organization’s zero-tolerance stance clear."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "The research of Dr. Steve Albrecht found which of the following personal characteristics to be the top-ranked motivating factor to commit fraud?", "options": {"A": "Dislike of company", "B": "Dislike of boss", "C": "Criminal personality", "D": "Living beyond means"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In Dr. Steve Albrecht’s study, the researchers gave internal auditors at companies that had experienced frauds two sets of 25 motivating factors and asked which factors were present in the frauds they had dealt with. Participants were asked to rank these factors on a seven-point scale indicating the degree to which each factor existed in their specific frauds. Based on this study, the top three most highly ranked factors from the list of personal characteristics were (1) living beyond their means, (2) an overwhelming desire for personal gain, and (3) high personal debt."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to the 2018 Report to the Nations, more frauds are uncovered by external audit than by any other form of detection.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "One of the principal goals of ACFE research is to identify how past frauds were detected so that organizations can apply that knowledge to their future anti-fraud efforts. The 2018 Report to the Nations shows that the leading detection methods are tips, internal audit, and management review. This finding is not surprising, as these have been the three most common means of detecting occupational fraud in every edition of the report since 2010. Collectively, these three detection methods were cited in 68% of the cases in our current study. Tips were by far the most common means of detection at 40% of cases—more than internal audit (15%) and management review (13%) combined."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following is one of the interrelated components of a company's internal control system, as laid out by COSO?", "options": {"A": "Risk assessment", "B": "Assurance function", "C": "Ethical culture", "D": "Independent oversight"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "COSO's Internal Control—Integrated Framework identified five interrelated components of internal control: control environment, risk assessment, control activities, information and communication, and monitoring. The effectiveness of internal controls can be determined from an assessment of whether (1) each of these five components is in place and functioning effectively and (2) the five components are operating together in an integrated manner."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Fraud examiners generally are not entitled to claim ignorance of the law as a defense for illegal activity.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Some rules for professionals insert the word knowingly in relation to illegal activities, saying: “One should not knowingly be a party to an illegal activity.” The ACFE Code of Professional Ethics does not include this way out. Fraud examiners are generally not entitled to claim ignorance of the law. They are expected to know a considerable amount of law in connection with investigations, and they are expected to know when to consult a lawyer."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "To show appreciation for an employee's hard work, a manager exempts the individual from several undesirable administrative tasks. This is an example of positive reinforcement.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Reinforcement and punishment of behavior are distinguished by the way that positive and negative forces are applied. A positive reinforcement presents a positive stimulus in exchange for the desired response. For example, a parent might say to a child, “You’ve cleaned your room. Good. Here’s the key to the car.” The behavior (cleaning) is reinforced by the awarding of the positive stimulus (the car key). In contrast, a negative reinforcement withdraws a negative stimulus in exchange for the desired response. Continuing the example, the parent might say, “I’ll stop hassling you if you clean this room.” The negative stimulus (hassling) is withdrawn when the appropriate behavior is performed."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Rachel, an independent CFE, was hired by Laura, the CEO of Black and White Inc., to investigate a case of alleged vendor overbilling. During the investigation, Rachel learns that Laura is involved in an unrelated fraud scheme. Under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, Rachel should resign from the engagement without disclosing the evidence against Laura.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Difficult problems arise over fraud examiners’ obligations to blow the whistle about clients’ or employers’ shady or illegal practices; thus, fraud examiners must act with prudent caution in such circumstances. In this particular case, the company’s board of directors should probably be advised and permitted to determine the next steps to take. In general, fraud examiners are not obligated to blow the whistle on clients or employers. However, circumstances might exist in which the fraud examiner is morally and legally justified in making disclosures to appropriate outside parties. Examples of such circumstances include when a client or employer has intentionally involved a fraud examiner in its illegal conduct or when a client or employer has distributed misleading reports based on the fraud examiner’s work. If Rachel were to resign without disclosing the evidence, such action would be tantamount to allowing Laura’s scheme to continue without anyone being aware of the fraud. Fraud examiners would not be able to justify doing nothing."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Which of the following mechanisms can be used to help increase the perception of detection in an organization?", "options": {"A": "Hotlines", "B": "Employee anti-fraud education", "C": "Rewards for whistleblowers", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Increasing the perception of detection might be the most effective fraud prevention method. Controls, for example, do little good in preventing theft and fraud if those at risk do not know of the presence of possible detection. This means letting employees, managers, and executives know that auditors are actively seeking out information concerning internal theft. This can be accomplished in several ways, such as: employee anti-fraud education, reporting programs, hotlines, rewards for whistleblowers, and proactive audit policies."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "The term occupational crime covers which of the following types of white-collar offenses?", "options": {"A": "Crimes by professionals", "B": "Crimes by officials", "C": "Crimes by individuals", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Gary Green, in honing the white-collar crime concept, uses the term occupational crime, which he defines as \"any act punishable by law which is committed through opportunity created in the course of an occupation which is legal.\" Green further delineates occupational crime into four categories: Crimes for the benefit of an employing organization (organizational occupational crime) Crimes by officials through exercise of their government-based authority (government authority occupational crime) Crimes by professionals in their capacity as professionals (professional occupational crime) Crimes by individuals as individuals"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "ISA 240 requires auditors to discuss how management could perpetrate and conceal fraudulent financial reporting.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "ISA 240 requires auditors to hold a discussion regarding the potential for material misstatements due to fraud. This discussion should cover: How and where the entity’s financial statements might be susceptible to fraud How management could perpetrate and conceal fraudulent financial reporting How the entity's assets could be misappropriated"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "In addition to the specific risks related to each of the primary categories of fraud, the fraud risk assessment team should consider:", "options": {"A": "Incentives for individuals to engage in fraud", "B": "Risk to information technology", "C": "Reputation risk", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The fraud risk assessment team should brainstorm to identify the inherent fraud risks that could apply to the organization. In addition to each of the major areas of fraud risks—fraudulent financial reporting, asset misappropriation, corruption, and fraud from external sources—certain other types of risks must be considered, including the risk of regulatory and legal misconduct, reputation risk, and risk to information technology (IT). Brainstorming should also include discussions regarding incentives, pressures, and opportunities to commit fraud, including the incentive programs and how those might affect employee behavior, as well as the potential for management’s override of controls."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "question": "Which of the following is one of the five fraud risk management principles described in the COSO/ACFE Fraud Risk Management Guide?", "options": {"A": "Fraud risk management monitoring activities", "B": "Fraud investigation and corrective action", "C": "Fraud risk assessment", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The COSO/ACFE Fraud Risk Management Guide describes five broad principles of fraud risk management, one for each of the five interrelated components of internal control listed in COSO’s Internal Controls—Integrated Framework. Each principle is then supported by several points of focus. The principles and underlying points of focus combine to create a full framework that can be used to design, implement, and assess an effective fraud risk management program. The following are the five principles provided in the Fraud Risk Management Guide: Fraud risk governance Fraud risk assessment Fraud control activities Fraud investigation and corrective action Fraud risk management monitoring activities"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "The primary purpose of International Standard on Auditing 240 is to:", "options": {"A": "Establish standards and provide guidance on the auditor’s responsibility to consider fraud in an audit of financial statements", "B": "Establish auditors as being primarily responsible for the prevention and detection of fraud within an organization", "C": "Establish requirements for auditors related to designing and implementing fraud-related internal controls", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The purpose of International Standard on Auditing (ISA) 240, The Auditor’s Responsibility Relating to Fraud in an Audit of Financial Statements, is to establish standards and provide guidance on the auditor’s responsibility to consider fraud in an audit of financial statements. ISA 240 also expands on how the standards and guidance in ISA 315, Understanding the Entity and its Environment and Assessing the Risks of Material Misstatement, and ISA 330, The Auditor’s Procedures in Response to Assessed Risks, are to be applied in relation to the risks of material misstatement due to fraud. The standards and guidance in ISA 240 are intended to be integrated into the overall audit process."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Of the following, which is the most effective method of preventing fraud?", "options": {"A": "Conducting covert audits", "B": "Increasing the perception of detection", "C": "Screening employees", "D": "Having an open-door policy"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Increasing the perception of detection might be the most effective fraud prevention method. Controls, for example, do little good in preventing theft and fraud if those at risk do not know of the presence of possible detection. This means letting employees, managers, and executives know that auditors are actively seeking out information concerning internal theft."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "According to B. F. Skinner, which of the following is the most effective way to modify a person's behavior?", "options": {"A": "Punishment", "B": "F. Skinner concluded that behavior is most effectively modified by managing and modifying desires through reinforcement—that is, by replacing destructive behaviors with productive ones instead of trying to punish an already existing impulse.", "C": "Ignoring it", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Further, behavioral studies, such as those conducted by Skinner, show that punishment is the least effective method of changing behavior. According to Skinner, punishment brings a temporary suppression of the behavior, but only with constant supervision and application. Punishment fights a losing battle in manipulating behavior because it works by providing negative consequences—administering penalties and taking away desirables."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Lee, a Certified Fraud Examiner, was hired to investigate a company. After he carefully examined the company, he issued a report that stated, in part, \"... in my opinion, this operation is free of material fraud.\" Such an opinion is permitted under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Fraud examiners must always perform their work with an attitude of skepticism and begin with the belief that something is wrong or someone is committing a fraud (depending on the nature of the assignment and the preliminary information available). Furthermore, fraud examiners should relax their attitude of skepticism only when the evidence shows no signs of fraudulent activity. At no time is a fraud examiner entitled to assume a fraud problem does not exist. Thus, professional skepticism can be dispelled only by evidence. As a result, opinions or attestations about a fraud-free environment are absolutely prohibited for ACFE members."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "During a fraud risk assessment, the assessment team should consider:", "options": {"A": "The inherent limitations of internal controls", "B": "Opportunities for collusion", "C": "Internal controls that might have been eliminated due to restructuring efforts", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Many organizations rely heavily on their internal control system to prevent and detect fraud. Although internal control plays a critical role in fraud prevention and detection, it is a dynamic system that requires constant reevaluation of its weaknesses. Performing a fraud risk assessment provides management with the opportunity to review the company’s internal control system for effectiveness, taking into account the following considerations: Controls that might have been eliminated due to restructuring efforts (e.g., elimination of separation of duties due to downsizing) Controls that might have eroded over time due to reengineering of business processes New opportunities for collusion Lack of internal controls in a vulnerable area Nonperformance of control procedures (e.g., control procedures compromised for the sake of expediency) Inherent limitations of internal controls, including opportunities for those responsible for a control to commit and conceal fraud (e.g., through management and system overrides)"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "The ACFE Code of Professional Ethics contains sections covering which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Professional improvement", "B": "Confidential information", "C": "Basis for opinions", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The ACFE Code of Professional Ethics is divided into eight sections covering the following topics: I. Commitment to professionalism II. Illegal or unethical conduct III. Professional competence of assignments IV. Lawful orders of the courts V. Basis for opinions VI. Confidential information VII. Reveal material matters VIII. Increase professional competence"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "An entity’s corporate governance structure specifies the distribution of rights and responsibilities among the different participants in the organization and lays down the rules and procedures for organizational decision-making.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The term corporate governance refers to a corporation’s government; the term is broadly used to describe the oversight responsibilities of different parties for an organization’s direction, operations, and performance. More specifically, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) states that: “The corporate governance structure specifies the distribution of rights and responsibilities among the different participants in the organisation—such as the board, managers, shareholders and other stakeholders—and lays down the rules and procedures for decision-making.\""}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to the authors of Crimes of the Middle Classes, advertising influences economic crimes by promising that no one has to settle for second best.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The authors of Crimes of the Middles Classes observe an overarching culture based on affluence and ever-higher levels of success. Television, and advertising in general, promises that no one has to settle for second best, prompting those who find themselves running behind to make an attempt to conceal the difference, crossing ethical and sometimes legal lines."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "According to the social control theory, an individual considering criminal behavior will likely ask himself which of the following questions?", "options": {"A": "\"What is the legal punishment if I get caught?\"", "B": "\"How likely is it that the crime will be detected?\"", "C": "\"What would my family think if they find out?\"", "D": "\"In what way can I rationalize this behavior?\""}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "According to Travis Hirschi, social control theory “assumes the bond of affection for conventional persons is a major deterrent to crime. The stronger this bond, the more likely the person is to take it into account when and if he contemplates a criminal act.” What essentially happens, the theory suggests, is that people confronted with the possibility of violating a law are likely to ask themselves questions such as, “What will my spouse—or my mother and father—think if they find out?” To the extent that individuals believe that other people whose opinions are important to them will be disappointed or ashamed, and to the extent that they care deeply that these people will feel this way, they will be deterred from committing a criminal act."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Which of the following is one of the ways Silk and Vogel found that businesses rationalize illegal or noncompliant conduct?", "options": {"A": "Compliance with government regulations is too costly", "B": "Violations aim to protect the job security of employees", "C": "The damage done by violations is diffused among a large number of parties", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In their research, Silk and Vogel found several beliefs used by businesses to rationalize illegal conduct: Government regulations are unjustified because the additional costs of regulations and bureaucratic procedures cut heavily into profits. Regulation is unnecessary because the matters being regulated are unimportant. Although some corporate violations involve large sums of money, the damage is so diffused among a large number of consumers that, individually, there is little loss. Violations are caused by economic necessity; they aim to protect the value of stock, to ensure an adequate return for stockholders, and to protect the job security of employees by ensuring the financial stability of the corporation."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to Diane Vaughan, linking employees’ needs and goals to the company's success can encourage unlawful conduct by individuals on the organization’s behalf.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Diane Vaughan, the author of Controlling Unlawful Organizational Behavior: Social Structure and Corporate Misconduct, believes that organizations can be criminogenic because they encourage loyalty. This, in turn, causes company personnel to sometimes perceive that the organization might be worth committing crime for to maintain and further its goals. The use of formal and informal rewards and punishments, plus social activities and pressures to participate, link an employee’s needs and goals to the company's success. When a company achieves its goals, its employees prosper. In short, the interests of an organization and its employees coincide, and that situation might set the stage for unlawful conduct by individuals on the organization’s behalf."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "In the context of a fraud examination, a mindset of professional skepticism means:", "options": {"A": "Fraud examiners should always begin their assignments with the belief that something is amiss", "B": "Fraud examiners should relax their attitude of skepticism only when the evidence shows no signs of fraud", "C": "The fraud examiner's professional skepticism can be dispelled only by evidence", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "As part of exercising professional integrity and competence, fraud examiners must always perform their work with a mindset of professional skepticism and begin assignments with the belief that something is wrong or someone is committing a fraud (depending on the nature of the assignment and the preliminary information available). Furthermore, fraud examiners should relax their attitude of skepticism only when the evidence shows no signs of fraudulent activity. At no time is a fraud examiner entitled to assume a fraud problem does not exist. Thus, professional skepticism can be dispelled only by evidence. As a result, opinions or attestations about a fraud-free environment are absolutely prohibited for ACFE members."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "The external auditor should perform which of the following procedures to obtain information to use in identifying the risks of material misstatement due to fraud?", "options": {"A": "Evaluate whether the information obtained from the risk assessment procedures indicates that fraud risk factors are present", "B": "Evaluate any unusual or unexpected relationships that have been identified in performing analytical procedures", "C": "Make inquiries of management and others within the entity to determine whether they have knowledge of any actual, suspected, or alleged fraud affecting the entity", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When performing risk assessment procedures and related activities to obtain an understanding of the entity and its environment, including the entity’s internal control, the auditor should perform the following procedures to obtain information for use in identifying the risks of material misstatement due to fraud: Make inquiries of management and others within the entity to determine whether they have knowledge of any actual, suspected, or alleged fraud affecting the entity. Evaluate any unusual or unexpected relationships that have been identified in performing analytical procedures. Evaluate whether the information obtained from the risk assessment procedures and related activities indicates that one or more fraud risk factors are present. Consider whether any other information obtained by the auditor indicates risks of material misstatement due to fraud."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to the 2018 Report to the Nations, which of the three major categories of occupational fraud has the highest median loss?", "options": {"A": "Identity theft", "B": "Asset misappropriation", "C": "Financial statement fraud", "D": "Corruption"}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "All occupational frauds fall into one of three major categories: asset misappropriation, corruption, or financial statement fraud. Of these categories, asset misappropriation is by far the most common, occurring in 89% of the cases in the 2018 Report to the Nations study. However, asset misappropriation is also the least costly, causing a median loss of USD 114,000. Corruption schemes are the next most common form of occupational fraud, with 38% of the cases in our study involving some form of corrupt act. These schemes resulted in a median loss to the victim organizations of USD 250,000. The least common and most costly form of occupational fraud is financial statement fraud, which occurred in 10% of the cases and caused a median loss of USD 800,000."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "When deciding on techniques to use as part of a fraud risk assessment, the assessment team should consider what methods are already commonly and effectively used throughout the organization.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "There are many ways to go about conducting the fraud risk assessment. Picking a method or combination of methods that is culturally right for the organization will help to ensure its success. The assessment team should also consider the best ways to gather candid, truthful information from people throughout all levels of the organization, starting by understanding what techniques are commonly and effectively used throughout the organization."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Which of the following is considered a white-collar crime?", "options": {"A": "A stockbroker profits from trades made based on insider knowledge about a company", "B": "An accounting clerk steals incoming payments from customers and makes falsified journal entries to cover her tracks", "C": "A city official receives kickbacks for tailoring contract requirements to specific vendors", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Although there is no consensus within the scholarly community, one current definition of white-collar crime is that proposed by Albert J. Reiss, Jr., and Albert Biderman: “White-collar crime violations are those violations of law to which penalties are attached that involve the use of a violator’s position of economic power, influence, or trust in the legitimate economic or political institutional order for the purpose of illegal gain, or to commit an illegal act for personal or organizational gain.”"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "Which of the following is a principle pertaining to the information and communication component of COSO’s Internal Control—Integrated Framework?", "options": {"A": "The organization obtains or generates and uses relevant, quality information to support the functioning of internal control", "B": "The organization internally communicates information—including objectives and responsibilities for internal control—necessary to support the functioning of internal control", "C": "The organization communicates with external parties regarding matters affecting the functioning of internal control", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The information and communication component of COSO’s Internal Control—Integrated Framework relates to the exchange of information in a way that allows employees to carry out their internal control responsibilities and achieve the organization’s objectives. According to COSO, the following principles pertain to this component: The organization obtains or generates and uses relevant, quality information to support the functioning of internal control. The organization internally communicates information—including objectives and responsibilities for internal control—necessary to support the functioning of internal control. The organization communicates with external parties regarding matters affecting the functioning of internal control."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to the authors of Crimes of the Middle Classes, which of the following factors have contributed to the rising problem of economic crime?", "options": {"A": "The increased opportunity for wrongdoing as a result of advancing information technologies", "B": "The economy's increased reliance on credit", "C": "The continued pressures of a culture that rewards affluence and success", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The authors of Crimes of the Middle Classes propose several factors that have contributed to the rising problem of economic crime: The economy increasingly runs on credit, which often means rising personal debt. The offenders in the sample often showed serious discrepancies “between their resources and their commitments.” New information technologies mean that the opportunity for wrongdoing is growing, and many of the techniques are not widely comprehended by businesses or individuals. Government programs distributing large amounts of money make an enticing target for embezzlement. The importance of credentials in a professionalized society might influence individuals “to inflate the credentials, or to make them up when they do not exist.” This tendency involves everything from cheating on school entrance exams to falsifying credit applications. Most broadly, the authors observe an overarching culture based on affluence and ever-higher levels of success. Television, and advertising in general, promises that no one has to settle for second best, prompting those who find themselves running behind to make an attempt to conceal the difference, crossing ethical and sometimes legal lines."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "In the area of criminological theory, ____________ is the theory that tries to prevent crime by using the threat of criminal sanctions.", "options": {"A": "Adherence", "B": "Deterrence", "C": "Punishment", "D": "None of the above"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "As a strategy to control crime, deterrence is designed to detect law violations, determine who is responsible, and penalize offenders to deter future violations. Deterrence systems try to control the immediate behavior of individuals, not the long-term behaviors targeted by compliance systems. Deterrence theory assumes that humans are rational in their behavioral patterns. Humans seek profit and pleasure while they try to avoid pain. Deterrence assumes that an individual’s propensity toward lawbreaking is in inverse proportion to the perceived probability of negative consequences."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "question": "Under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, a fraud examiner is strictly prohibited from accepting an assignment to uncover fraud in a company in which he has a major interest.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Article II of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics states: \"An ACFE Member shall not engage in any illegal or unethical conduct, or any activity which would constitute a conflict of interest that has not been properly disclosed to the appropriate parties.\" However, a fraud examiner does not have the same responsibilities as a Chartered Accountant or Certified Public Accountant. For example, a CA or CPA generally would not be able to express an audit opinion on a company in which he held a major financial interest. In the case of the fraud examiner, he would be able to accept such an assignment under most conditions, since the goal of the fraud examiner is to gather facts regarding a potential fraud, not to express an opinion. The fraud examiner should, however, make appropriate disclosures regarding his ownership."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Two selling points of a fraud prevention program are fraud's potentially negative impact on a company's profits and its potential effect on the organization's public image.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "One of the best ways to sell management on fraud prevention is by showing the impact on the bottom line; fraud can be very expensive. It is much more cost effective to proactively address fraud risks than to suffer preventable fraud and spend valuable resources on detecting, investigating, prosecuting, and cleaning up after it. In other words, stopping fraud before it occurs directly increases the organization’s bottom line. Additionally, many corporate executives are more sensitive to adverse publicity than almost any other issue. Certainly, one way to convince management of the importance of fraud prevention is to point out that negative publicity, even in small cases, can have a devastating impact on the bottom line. This negative impact can be eliminated or reduced by a proactive fraud prevention program."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "Misbehavior is less likely to be detected and punished in a complex organizational structure than in a simple organizational structure.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Complex companies provide a structure that can foster misbehavior. They provide many settings where misconduct is possible. They isolate those settings in departments and in locations around a city, a country, or the world. This isolation, in turn, means that information about what one part of a company is doing might be unknown in another part. All this reduces the risk that misbehavior will be detected and punished. The larger a company grows, the more specialized its subunits tend to become, and this specialization thereby breeds a higher risk of fraud. An internally diversified company might have few employees who fully understand the detailed workings. Additionally, specialization tends to hide illegal activities, especially where a firm’s tasks are kept separate and unrelated. Employees cannot garner knowledge about all the particulars of how a firm works. This protects a company from the effects of personnel turnover and leaks of information because no employee knows all the intricacies of the company. The same secrecy, however, raises the chances for misconduct."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "question": "Criminological research has generally concluded that punishing an individual for undesirable behavior will temporarily suppress the behavior as long as the punishment is applied directly and continuously, but the behavior will likely return once the punishment is discontinued.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Behavioral studies, such as those conducted by B. F. Skinner, show that punishment is the least effective method of changing behavior. According to Skinner, punishment brings a temporary suppression of the behavior, but only with constant supervision and application. In repeated experiments, Skinner found that punishment—either applying a negative stimulus or taking away a positive one—effectively extinguished a subject’s behavior, but the behavior returned when the punishment was discontinued. In other words, the subject would suppress the behavior as long as the punishment was applied directly and continuously, but, as soon as the punishment was withdrawn for a while, the behavior was attempted again; if there was no punishment following the attempt, the subject began to behave as before."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "According to the OECD Principles of Corporate Governance, governments should have in place an effective framework to support good corporate governance practices that:", "options": {"A": "Is consistent with the rule of law", "B": "Supports effective supervision and enforcement", "C": "Promotes transparent and fair markets", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Chapter I of the OECD Principles of Corporate Governance states that governments should have in place a sound legal, regulatory, and institutional framework to support good corporate governance practices. This framework typically comprises elements of legislation, regulation, self-regulatory arrangements, voluntary commitments, and business practices that are the result of a country’s specific circumstances, history, and tradition. Such a framework should promote transparent and fair markets and the efficient allocation of resources. It should be consistent with the rule of law and support effective supervision and enforcement."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Management of Blue Top Inc. is implementing a formal background check policy for its employees. Which of the following is NOT a best practice that it should implement as part of this initiative?", "options": {"A": "Run a background check on existing employees who are being promoted or moved to positions that include access to easily stolen assets.", "B": "Place a low priority on checking professional references, since most people won’t provide a bad reference.", "C": "Ask a candidate’s previous employers whether the individual is eligible for rehire.", "D": "Check the background of any employee who will have constant access to cash, checks, and credit card numbers."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Before hiring anyone, management should conduct a background check (where and to the extent permitted by law) to find out as much as possible about the employee’s previous experience with employers and law enforcement. At a minimum, employers should check the background of any employee who will have constant access to cash, checks, credit card numbers, or any other items that are easily stolen. Background checks should also be run on existing employees who are being promoted or moved to positions that include access to sensitive or valuable company resources. Even if such a check was performed on the employee at the time of hire, an updated background check should be run to identify any significant changes or occurrences that have taken place during the individual’s tenure. In assessing individuals for hire or promotion, employers should verify past employment. Even though most employers will only verify position and dates of employment, you can usually tell by their tone of voice what they think of the employee. Also, ask the previous employers whether the applicant is eligible for rehire. Additionally, the hiring manager or HR should contact the references provided by the candidate. Unfortunately, very few organizations actually do this. Most operate under the theory that someone wouldn’t provide a bad reference. However, some job applicants will list important-sounding individuals as references with the hope that the hiring organization won’t call. In addition, people often just assume, incorrectly, that a former supervisor or coworker will provide a good reference. But obtaining negative information from someone the candidate listed as a recommendation can be very telling and should serve as a serious warning sign to the hiring organization."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "question": "Which of the following factors complicates the ability of determining clear ethical rights and wrongs?", "options": {"A": "Tension often exists between personal standards and organizational needs", "B": "Different groups within the same society might have conflicting ideas of right and wrong", "C": "Moral standards and accepted social behavior change over time", "D": "All of the above"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The collection of a person’s beliefs and morals makes up a set of principles known as ethics. Ethics are the judgments about right and wrong, or, more specifically, a person’s moral obligations to society that determine a person’s actions. Determining ethical rights and wrongs is complicated by the fact that moral standards and generally accepted social behavior change with time. In addition, different groups in the same society might have conflicting ideas of right and wrong. Individuals' values and ethics are reflected in their actions as employees. There are four factors that generally affect employees' ethical decisions: The law and other government regulations Industry and organizational ethical codes Social pressures Tension between personal standards and organizational needs"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "_________ play a critical role in enhancing the reliability of financial information by attesting as to whether the financial statements prepared by management fairly present the financial position and past performance of the public enterprise in compliance with accepted accounting standards.", "options": {"A": "Members of the board of directors", "B": "Internal auditors", "C": "Government regulators", "D": "Independent auditors"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions’ Principles for Auditor Oversight state that independent auditors play a critical role in enhancing the reliability of financial information by attesting as to whether the financial statements prepared by management fairly present the financial position and past performance of the public enterprise in compliance with accepted accounting standards."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to the COSO Internal Control model, an organization should perform both ongoing evaluations and periodic, separate evaluations to ascertain whether the components of internal control are present and functioning.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Monitoring is the process that assesses the effectiveness of a control system over time. This component of COSO’s Internal Control—Integrated Framework should include both ongoing evaluations and periodic, separate evaluations, the findings of which should be evaluated against predefined criteria. The following are the Framework principles supporting this component: The organization selects, develops, and performs ongoing and separate evaluations to ascertain whether the components of internal control are present and functioning. The organization evaluates and communicates internal control deficiencies in a timely manner to those parties responsible for taking corrective action, including senior management and the board of directors, as appropriate."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "question": "According to The Institute of Internal Auditors’ International Standards for the Professional Practice of Internal Auditing, the internal audit activity must evaluate risk exposures relating to the organization's governance, operations, and information systems regarding all of the following EXCEPT:", "options": {"A": "Compliance with laws, regulations, and contracts", "B": "Effectiveness and efficiency of operations", "C": "Reliability and integrity of financial and operational information", "D": "Sale of tangible and intangible assets"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "According to The Institute of Internal Auditors' Standard 2120.A1, the internal audit activity must evaluate risk exposures relating to the organization's governance, operations, and information systems regarding the: Achievement of the organization’s strategic objectives Reliability and integrity of financial and operational information Effectiveness and efficiency of operations Safeguarding of assets Compliance with laws, regulations, and contracts"}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "question": "The OECD Principles of Corporate Governance is required to be implemented by all corporations in the jurisdictions that have officially adopted the Principles.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The OECD Principles of Corporate Governance is regarded as one of the hallmark sources of guidance for corporate governance practices for organizations throughout the world. The Principles are nonbinding, as their implementation must be adapted to different legal, economic, and cultural circumstances. This is a key strength of the Principles that makes them a useful tool worldwide, both in developed economies and in emerging markets."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "question": "A fraud risk assessment report should contain a detailed, comprehensive list of every assessment finding and all suggested responses so that management can address each issue within the company, no matter how small.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Less is often more when it comes to reporting the results of the fraud risk assessment. The team should take care not to turn the report into a tedious list of things that management will have to sort through and prioritize. Instead, the report should be presented in a way that focuses on what really matters, clearly highlighting those things that are most important and that will make the most impact on the organization’s fraud risk management efforts."}, {"domain": "Frd Prvntn and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "question": "According to the 2018 Report to the Nations, more frauds are uncovered by external audit than by any other form of detection.", "options": {"A": "True", "B": "False"}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "One of the principal goals of ACFE research is to identify how past frauds were detected so that organizations can apply that knowledge to their future anti-fraud efforts. The 2018 Report to the Nations shows that the leading detection methods are tips, internal audit, and management review. This finding is not surprising, as these have been the three most common means of detecting occupational fraud in every edition of the report since 2010. Collectively, these three detection methods were cited in 68% of the cases in our current study. Tips were by far the most common means of detection at 40% of cases—more than internal audit (15%) and management review (13%) combined."}], "flashcards": [{"front": "Preparing for Interviews", "back": "• To effectively prepare for the interview phase of an investigation, the fraud examiner must first develop a plan. This might involve:\n• Contemplating what the interview is intended to accomplish\n• Determining the necessary order of interviews\n• Deciding which evidentiary documents to take into the interview and which to request from the subject", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Interview Mechanics", "back": "• Rules for note-taking during interviews\n• Consider recording interviews electronically and covertly if permissible.\n• Err on the side of taking too few notes rather than too many.\n• Other interviewing best practices\n• Maintain eye contact as much as possible during the interview.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Interview Questions", "back": "• Five types\n• Introductory questions 1. Used to provide an introduction and to get the respondent to verbally agree to the interview\n• Admission-seeking questions 1. Reserved specifically for individuals whose culpability is reasonably certain 2. Designed to obtain a legal admission of wrongdoing", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Introductory Questions", "back": "• Designed to meet four objectives:\n• To provide an introduction 1. The interviewer generally should indicate their name and company, but they should avoid stating their title when appropriate.\n• Methodology\n• Sensitive questions and emotive words should be avoided during the introductory phase because they tend to put people on the defensive and make them more reluctant to answer and cooperate. 1. Use word", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Informational Questions", "back": "• Asked for the purpose of gathering unbiased, factual information\n• Commonly used when:\n• Conducting an interview to gain an understanding of accounting control systems\n• Sequence\n• As a general rule, questioning should proceed from the general to the specific (general information before detailed information).", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Dealing with Difficult Situations", "back": "• Resistance\n• Possible excuses for refusing a request for an interview 1. “I’m too busy.”\n• Defuse by stressing that:\n• The interview will be short.\n• The interviewer needs help. 2. “I don’t remember.”", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Closing Questions", "back": "• Seek to close the interview positively\n• Three main purposes\n• To reconfirm facts", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Assessment Questions", "back": "• Designed to establish the respondent’s credibility\n• Should be asked when the interviewer has reason to believe the respondent is being deceptive (i.e., when the interviewer considers previous statements by the respondent to be inconsistent because of p\n• The interviewer must observe the subject’s verbal and nonverbal responses to assess their credibility.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Establishing a Baseline", "back": "• The process of observing behavior before critical questions are asked, as opposed to doing so during questioning\n• The best way to establish a baseline with a witness is by asking noncritical questions on background information, place of employment, etc.\n• Assessment questions, which ask the subject to agree with matters that go against the principles of most honest people, should then be presented; people who seem truthful typically answer one way, and\n• After observing the respondent’s verbal and nonverbal behavior while answering noncritical questions, the interviewer can later compare an interviewee’s behavior during critical questions (if the admi", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Understanding Indicators of Stress", "back": "• The human body attempts to relieve the stress of lying through verbal and nonverbal actions, which provide clues to deception.\n• When evaluating signs of deception, no single behavior should be isolated and no single conclusion should be drawn from it.\n• Factors to consider when assessing signs of deception\n• Signs of stress do not always mean that a subject is lying. 1. Not all stress exhibited during an interview is caused by lying; an honest interview subject might feel stress simply by being asked poin\n• Verbal clues", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Admission-Seeking Questions", "back": "• Designed to obtain a legal admission of wrongdoing\n• Normally, the interviewer should ask accusatory or admission-seeking questions when all the following are true:\n• There is a reasonable probability that the respondent has committed the act in question.\n• Three purposes\n• To distinguish innocent (non-culpable) individuals from potentially guilty ones", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Preparing the Interview Room", "back": "• The interviewer should consider how private the room is.\n• The door should be closed but not locked.\n• There should be no physical barriers preventing the suspect from leaving.\n• The suspect should be made aware that they are free to leave.\n• Distractions should be kept to a minimum.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Presence of Outsiders", "back": "• Where allowed by law, no observers, other than the subject and up to two fraud examiners, should be permitted in the admission-seeking interview.\n• The presence of third parties could have liability consequences.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "General Rules for Conducting Admission-Seeking Interviews", "back": "• Convey absolute confidence in the admission-seeking interview.\n• Only conduct an admission-seeking interview when there is sufficient privacy and when time is not a factor.\n• Do not express disgust, outrage, or moral condemnation about the accused’s actions.\n• Be firm but also project compassion, understanding, and empathy.\n• Offer a morally acceptable reason for the accused’s behavior.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Steps in the Admission-Seeking Interview", "back": "• Make a direct accusation.\n• The accusation should be made in the form of a statement, not a question.\n• Observe the accused’s reaction.\n• When accused of wrongdoing, guilty individuals often react with silence.\n• Repeat the accusation.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Information to Obtain During the Verbal Admission", "back": "• That the accused knew the conduct was wrong\n• Intent is required in all matters involving fraud. The accused not only must have committed the act but also must have intended to commit it.\n• Facts known only to the subject (estimate of number of instances/amounts)\n• These facts include—at a minimum—the accused’s estimates of the number of instances of wrongful conduct and the total amount of money involved.\n• Motive for the offense", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Interview Theory and Application", "back": "• There is no legal requirement that a statement must be completely in the handwriting or wording of the declarant.\n• It is better for the fraud examiner to draft the statement.\n• It is recommended to have two people witness the signing.\n• There should not be more than one written statement for each offense.\n• Omitted facts can be added later as an addendum to the original statement.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Data Analysis Process", "back": "• Planning phase\n• Understand the data. 1. As a first step in the planning process—before determining which tests to run—the fraud examiner must know what data are available to be analyzed and how those data are structu\n• Preparation phase\n• Identify the relevant data.\n• Known errors", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Core Data Analysis Software Functions", "back": "• Sorting\n• Arranges data in a meaningful order so users can quickly determine what is important\n• Joining files\n• Combines fields from two sorted input files into a third file\n• Correlation analysis", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "back": "• Structured data are the type of data found in a database, consisting of recognizable and predictable structures.\n• Unstructured data, by contrast, are data not found in a traditional spreadsheet or database, such as email and social media activity.", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Advanced Data Analytics", "back": "• Advanced analytic methods examine large amounts of data using sophisticated techniques that go beyond traditional data analysis to generate new information, recognize patterns, and predict precise out\n• Common types include:\n• Artificial intelligence 1. Refers to computer systems that perform human tasks, such as visual perception and decision-making 2. Includes a subset known as machine learning, which is a learning algori\n• With supervised machine learning, humans identify patterns for the programs to look for in data sets, and the programs identify any data that fit the patterns.\n• With unsupervised machine learning, a program identifies similarities, patterns, or anomalies within a data set without the involvement of a human.", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Data Analysis Queries", "back": "• Accounts payable\n• Audit paid invoices for manual comparison with actual invoices.\n• Verify vendor tax forms (e.g., U.S. Form 1099 or value-added tax [VAT] forms).", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Textual Analytics", "back": "• A method of using software to extract usable information from unstructured text data\n• Sources of unstructured data 1. Emails 2. Journal entry explanations 3. Social media posts and comments\n• Can be used to categorize unstructured data to reveal patterns, sentiments, and relationships that are indicative of fraud through the application of linguistic technologies and statistical techniques\n• Provides the ability to uncover warning signs of potentially fraudulent employee behavior\n• For example, an analysis of email communications might help fraud examiners to gauge the pressures/incentives, opportunities, and rationalizations to commit fraud that exist in an organization.", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Visual Analytics", "back": "• Link analysis\n• Visual representations (e.g., charts with lines showing connections) of data from multiple data sources to track the movement of money; demonstrate complex networks; and discover communications, patte", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "What Is Tracing?", "back": "• The search for evidence for the purpose of showing what has happened to property, identifying the proceeds of property, and identifying those who have handled or received property or the proceeds of p\n• Might be undertaken to assist:\n• A victim of fraud who wants a tracing search to facilitate the recovery of criminal proceeds", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Direct Approach to Tracing Financial Transactions", "back": "• Employs direct evidence of the subject’s books and records (or financial transaction records belonging to third parties) to analyze the relationship between a suspect’s receipt and subsequent disposit\n• Contrasts with the indirect approach, which relies on circumstantial proof\n• Requires access to the subject’s financial records\n• Involves tracing funds the subject used to purchase assets or make deposits back to the source", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Records from Financial Institutions for Tracing", "back": "• Records from financial institutions are perhaps the single most important financial source available to a fraud examiner for tracing purposes.\n• Can be used to:\n• Identify witnesses and other evidence.\n• Identify locations where assets are stored.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Wire Transfers for Tracing", "back": "• Wire transfer records might contain evidence that money has been moved abroad.\n• Information contained on most wire transfers:\n• The amount of the transfer\n• The routing number of the originating bank or financial institution", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Correspondent Banking Records for Tracing", "back": "• A correspondent banking relationship is generally defined as an arrangement in which one bank maintains a correspondent account at another bank for the purpose of settling transactions for itself or i\n• A foreign correspondent relationship involves a correspondent banking relationship between foreign and domestic institutions.\n• Due to risks of illicit transactions, such as money laundering, most jurisdictions require financial institutions to obtain information from other financial institutions with which they maintain a for\n• The institution’s ownership details", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Electronic Payment Records for Tracing", "back": "• The term electronic payments (or e-payments) refers to any type of noncash payment that does not involve a paper check.\n• Records of these transactions can reveal:\n• Assets the subject has purchased\n• Payments made to nonexistent employees with direct deposit\n• The true owner of a property", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Loan Records for Tracing", "back": "• When a bank makes a commercial loan to an individual, it requires detailed statements of assets and liabilities from the borrower.\n• The loan file might also include the results of credit inquiries regarding paying habits, loan amounts, and present unpaid balances.\n• Loan records generally maintained by a bank credit department include:\n• The credit or loan file 1. Includes the customer’s loan application, financial statements, and general economic history\n• If a fraud examination involves a loan with proceeds that have been disposed, the fraud examiner should trace the disposition of the loan’s proceeds.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Credit Card Records for Tracing", "back": "• Credit card records might show card purchasing limits, previous payment history, account balance, when and where the subject has traveled, and assets the subject has acquired.\n• These records show the movements and habits of the person to whom the records pertain.\n• Credit card statements contain the name of the credit card issuer, the cardholder’s account number, a summary of the transactions on the account,\n• Credit card charges might provide leads to identifying hidden assets.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Indirect Approach to Tracing Financial Transactions", "back": "• In contrast to the direct approach method, which relies on specific transactions, the indirect approach relies on circumstantial proof.\n• An indirect analysis can reveal that a suspect has more money available or has acquired more assets than can be accounted for from legitimate sources.\n• Two of the basic approaches that use circumstantial proof to prove a subject’s sources of funds are the asset method (net worth) and the expenditures (source and application of funds) method.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using the Asset and Expenditures Methods to Examine Sources of Income", "back": "• The asset method\n• Use when the subject has invested illegal funds to accumulate wealth and\n• The expenditures method\n• When the subject spends illicit income on consumables (e.g., travel and entertainment), use this method because the illicit income will not cause an increase in net worth.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "–", "back": "• Asset hiders usually conceal assets in financial products that are:\n• Liquid\n• Financial products are used to obscure links between the initial receipt of the assets and their final disposition.\n• Common ways fraudsters hide assets include:\n• Hiding assets in someone else’s name (e.g., the name of a spouse, other relative, friend, business partner)", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Locating Assets Hidden Through Cryptocurrency", "back": "• Cryptocurrency is a type of digital currency that uses public or private key encryption in the currency’s creation and transfer.\n• While cryptocurrency transactions can be difficult and complicated to trace, most cryptocurrencies rely on public blockchains (digital ledgers, or databases, of transactions that allow data to be dist\n• Blockchain entries do not include direct identifying information, but they do contain senders’ and recipients’ cryptographic addresses for each transaction.\n• Cryptocurrencies are stored and transmitted through digital wallets, which act as financial accounts that securely hold and organize a user’s payment information, passwords, and transaction history.\n• Many digital wallet providers now record identifying information about their clients that can be useful in tracing efforts.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Asset Recovery", "back": "• Once fraud has been documented and the associated illicit transactions have been traced, victims might want to pursue recovery of assets.\n• A fraud examiner must often be able to evaluate the potential for asset recovery due to the fact that fraudsters often spend most, if not all, of their ill-gotten gains, leaving little to recover.\n• The following questions should be considered before commencing a legal action to recover assets:\n• Are there nonlegal recovery methods or remedies available?", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "What Is Fraud Examination?", "back": "• The process of resolving allegations of fraud from inception to disposition\n• The primary function of the anti-fraud professional\n• Tasks involved:\n• Obtaining evidence", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Examination Methodology", "back": "• Assume litigation will follow.\n• Each fraud examination should be conducted with the assumption that the case will result in legal proceedings.\n• Act on predication.\n• Fraud examinations should not be conducted without proper predication—the totality of circumstances that would lead a reasonable, professionally trained, and prudent individual to believe that a fraud\n• Begin with the general before moving to the specific.", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Develop a Fraud Response Plan", "back": "• A fraud response plan details the actions that members of an organization will take when suspicions of fraud arise.\n• Because every fraud is different, response plans should not specify how all fraud examinations should be conducted; instead, such plans should help organizations manage their responses and create envi\n• A response plan allows management to respond to suspected and detected incidents of fraud in a consistent and comprehensive manner.\n• Having a response plan in place sends a message that management takes fraud seriously.\n• Elements of a fraud response plan", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Planning and Conducting a Formal Investigation", "back": "• Assemble an investigation team.\n• To determine who should be involved in the investigation, management must identify the needed skills.\n• Develop an investigation plan.\n• When developing an investigation plan, those responsible should: 1. Review what is known and gain a basic understanding of key issues. 2. Define the goals of the investigation. 3. Identify whom to kee\n• Prepare the organization for the investigation.", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Structure the Investigation to Preserve Confidentiality", "back": "• Failure to preserve confidentiality could compromise an entire investigation and make employees reluctant to report future incidents.\n• To help preserve confidentiality, team members should:\n• Avoid alerting the suspected fraudsters. 1. Know who is being investigated and what they can access. 2. Limit the extent of any discussions. 3. Inform only those who need to know. 4. Inform employees ", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Recovering Data", "back": "• Digital forensic experts can recover, among other things, the following types of information from computer systems:\n• Deleted files and other data that have not been overwritten (e.g., deleted documents, images, link or shortcut files, and email messages)\n• Websites visited, even where the browser history and cache have been deleted\n• The time and date information about files (e.g., when files were created, accessed, modified, installed, deleted, or downloaded)", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Volatility of Digital Evidence", "back": "• Digital evidence is more volatile than tangible evidence because data can be altered or destroyed more easily than tangible information.\n• Digital information can be altered by seemingly harmless actions, such as shutting down a running system, starting up a system, or looking through files on a running computer.\n• Data that have been altered or destroyed have had their data integrity violated, and once the integrity of digital evidence has been violated, it usually cannot be restored.\n• Digital evidence that is destroyed when litigation is expected, or in progress, might give rise to claims of spoliation—intentionally or negligently destroying documents relevant to litigation—of evid\n• If litigation occurs, the failure to preserve the integrity of digital evidence could result in evidence being deemed inadmissible in a legal proceeding or, even if admitted, not being given much weig", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Computer System Files to Be Recovered", "back": "• User-created files\n• Created under the user’s direction\n• Computer-created files\n• Evidence might also be found in information generated by a computer’s operating system.\n• Files that contain information about who wrote a document; who received, opened, copied, edited, moved, or printed the document; and when these events occurred 2. Registry", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Places to Search for Digital Evidence", "back": "• Printers\n• Many printers have internal hard drives or other storage mechanisms that can contain information relevant to a fraud examination.\n• Copiers, scanners, and multifunction devices\n• Many modern copiers have a hard drive that stores images of documents the machines have copied, scanned, or emailed.\n• Fax machines", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Digital Forensic Investigation Phases", "back": "• Planning\n• Involves taking steps to help ensure that the evidence will be admissible 1. Determine whether there are any privacy issues in the item(s) to be searched. 2. Determine appropriate procedures for any r\n• Seizing\n• Involves ensuring that all relevant evidence is seized and secured in a forensically sound manner so that the evidence is not tainted or destroyed\n• Document the scene with photographs or a diagram.", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Challenges of Cloud Forensics", "back": "• A lack of frameworks and specialist tools\n• A lack of information accessibility (no physical access)\n• A lack of data control\n• A lack of knowledge\n• Jurisdiction of storage", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Reports Created by Fraud Examiners", "back": "• Fraud examination report\n• Documents the results of a fraud examination\n• Expert report\n• Written by fraud examiners who serve as expert witnesses", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Characteristics of a Good Report", "back": "• Accuracy\n• Inaccuracies damage the credibility of the report and the report’s author.\n• Clarity\n• Convey pertinent information in the clearest possible language.\n• Impartiality and relevance", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Attachments", "back": "• Copies of important documents can be included in the report, but do not include originals.", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Rules for Including Conclusions and Opinions", "back": "• Conclusions should be self-evident and do not need to be pointed out.\n• Opinions regarding guilt or innocence are not allowed.\n• Opinions regarding technical matters are permitted if the fraud examiner is qualified as an expert in the matter being considered.\n• Fraud examiners should not include any statement of opinion as to the integrity or veracity of any witness.", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Analyzing the Reader of Fraud Examination Reports", "back": "• The fraud examination report should be prepared with the expectation that it will likely be read by the general public and adverse parties.\n• Other potential readers include company insiders, attorneys, defendants and witnesses, media outlets, and judges or juries.\n• A fraud examination should provide a full understanding of the investigation and its findings without the need for additional clarification.", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Suggested Structure for Fraud Examination Reports", "back": "• Background\n• Executive summary\n• Scope\n• Approach\n• Findings", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Internal Sources", "back": "• Generated and kept within the subject organization\n• Are often the only resource for certain types of documents, such as accounting and business tax records, copies of canceled checks, or employee personnel files, unless the fraud examiner secures the s", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "External Sources", "back": "• Used to:\n• Locate missing assets.\n• Document suspects’ lifestyle and background information.", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Public Records", "back": "• Documents that a governmental agency is required to keep by law or that are necessary to discharge the duties imposed by law\n• Can supply invaluable background information on entities, employees, suspects, and witnesses\n• Can be used to corroborate or refute witness statements\n• Can help investigators track the flow of stolen money or other assets\n• Can aid in efforts to recover losses", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Local Records", "back": "• Building inspector records\n• Building permit records\n• Health and fire department records\n• Birth and death records\n• Public school records", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Marriage records", "back": "• Court records (civil and criminal) are typically maintained by a clerk or administrative office of the court that heard the case.\n• It is rare for there to be a central public database that maintains all court records at every level of a jurisdiction, and there are no parties that maintain a comprehensive database of court records\n• Types include:\n• Civil court records, which might include: 1. Personal injury suit records 2. Financial suit records 3. Divorce records\n• Names of individuals with an interest in the deceased’s estate", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Property Records", "back": "• Real property records\n• Most jurisdictions have a land registry office that maintains various information on real property and its owner(s), such as deeds, grants, and transfers and mortgages of real estate.\n• Property tax records\n• Many jurisdictions assess property taxes and require parties that purchase real estate to register as taxpayers with the jurisdiction’s property tax records system.\n• An idea of the estimated value, for tax purposes, of the property listed", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Names of former property owners", "back": "• Most jurisdictions require business entities to file various types of records that contain information useful in a fraud examination, including:\n• Organizational filings 1. If an individual wants to conduct business in a name other than their own, the law requires that they file documents, such as an organizational filing, to claim ownership of \n• Corporate name\n• Ownership information\n• Names of initial shareholders", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Nonpublic Records", "back": "• Information about a person or business considered to be private and confidential\n• Might be difficult or impossible to obtain because fraud examiners do not have an absolute right to see these personal records\n• The government usually will not share nonpublic records with a fraud victim during an investigation into the underlying fraud.\n• Types of nonpublic records\n• Banking records 1. Can be obtained through:", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Improper Pretexting", "back": "• In general, pretexting is the act of impersonating someone else or making false or misleading statements to obtain, sell, or buy information about a person or organization.\n• Some jurisdictions have prohibited pretexting against financial institutions even if no fraudulent intent is present.\n• In this context, pretexting is the act of obtaining or attempting to obtain customer information from financial institutions through deceptive tactics (e.g., pretending to be the customer or an author\n• Fraud examiners should not impersonate a member of law enforcement or an actual person (particularly the individual being investigated). To do so may lead to charges of identity theft.", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)", "back": "• A regulation designed to protect the personal data of European Union (EU) residents and harmonize data protection laws throughout Europe\n• Applies to organizations that are based in the EU that collect or process the personal data of any person, regardless of where the person is located\n• Applies to organizations that are not based in the EU if they collect or process the personal data of any person located in the EU for the purpose of:\n• Offering goods or services to the person, regardless of whether payment is required\n• Applies to most companies that have customers in the EU even if the companies have no physical presence in the EU", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using the Internet in Fraud Examinations", "back": "• The best way to use a search engine is to use two or three keywords that best describe the topic, but such searches often return too many or irrelevant results.\n• In such situations, users can employ special query words or symbols called advanced search operators (or Boolean operators) to increase the precision of a search phrase.\n• For example, placing quotation marks around a word or set of words returns pages containing the exact word or set of words. A search for “money laundering” returns pages in which the exact phrase mone", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Online Public Database Searches", "back": "• To locate people using online records, the fraud examiner should obtain a past address of the subject, and search activities should begin with that information.\n• The fraud examiner should know the most powerful and useful types of searches.\n• There are several limitations to be aware of when conducting searches for public records using online databases:\n• Online availability of public records varies widely across jurisdictions.\n• Fraud examiners must validate information retrieved from online databases to determine if it is accurate and up to date.", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Deep Web", "back": "• Web content that is not indexed by standard search engines\n• Also known as the invisible web\n• Resources include websites without any links pointing to them, certain file formats that search engines cannot handle, websites that have been blocked from access by web crawlers (i.e., scripts that c\n• An important resource for fraud examiners because standard search engines only search a small portion of the web", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Dark Web", "back": "• Websites that are only accessible through specialized web browsers meant to anonymize the origins of user traffic\n• The most popular web browser is Tor, short for “the onion router.”\n• Tor software layers encrypted communications and offers increased anonymity to users by preventing someone who is monitoring a user’s internet traffic from knowing what sites the person visits and pre", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Internet Archives", "back": "• Archived versions of web pages that have since been updated or are no longer available online\n• The most popular tool for searching the internet archives is the Wayback Machine, located at https://archive.org, which allows users to see archived versions of web pages throughout time.\n• Searching the internet archives can uncover historical information, such as:\n• A photo posted on a website that has been removed", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Social Media Sites", "back": "• The popularity of social media sites makes it easy for fraud examiners to find information about individuals who use such sites.\n• Relevant social media evidence can include photographs, status updates, a person’s location at a certain time, and direct communications.\n• Fraud examiners can use social media to:\n• Investigate complaints.", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Privacy Issues When Collecting Social Media Evidence", "back": "• Fraud examiners are free to search and extract information from a subject’s page if it is open to the public, but there are limitations to the information fraud examiners can access on a social media \n• Accessing information on social media sites that is restricted by privacy settings could result in liability for fraud examiners due to the violation of users’ privacy rights.\n• Due to confidentiality, privacy, and security concerns, courts might not allow evidence obtained by someone who misrepresents themselves to gain access to a subject’s private social network.\n• Take screen captures of relevant information.\n• Print the content.", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "What Is a Covert Operation?", "back": "• An investigation technique designed to obtain evidence by use of agents whose true intentions are not communicated to the target\n• Mistakes made during a covert operation can cause irreparable damage to an investigation; mistakes may also have reputational, financial, and legal consequences.\n• Fraud examiners should only resort to covert operations after conventional methods of gathering evidence have been exhausted and proven unsuccessful.", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Forms of Covert Operations", "back": "• Undercover operations\n• Often use deception and disguise to obtain evidence directly from those involved in the illicit activity.\n• Surveillance operations\n• Use observation to gather information about individuals suspected of misconduct.", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Information to Document", "back": "• Before conducting a covert operation, document the basis of the operation, preferably in a memorandum that clearly states:\n• The information upon which the covert operation will be based", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Legality of Recordings", "back": "• Many jurisdictions have laws that impose restrictions on electronic audio or video recordings that are not done pursuant to a search warrant or other court order.\n• Factors to consider when determining the legality of recording audio or video without a court order include:\n• The consenting party 1. For a recording of a private conversation to be permissible, most jurisdictions require consent from at least one of the parties involved in the conversation. 2. Jurisdictions ", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Entrapment", "back": "• Occurs when law enforcement officers or government agents induce a person to commit a crime that they are not previously disposed to commit\n• Poses a legal problem in covert operations because the defendant might not be found liable if it appears that they were improperly induced to commit the crime; thus, it is imperative that these operat", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Procedures When Using Sources and Informants", "back": "• Make any payments in cash and obtain a receipt for documentation purposes.\n• If a source or informant will not sign a receipt, then do not pay that person.\n• Keep the informant’s identity as confidential as possible.\n• Use symbols to denote identities when reporting contacts.", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Promises of Confidentiality", "back": "• Fraud examiners generally cannot offer unqualified confidentiality to informants. Therefore, any promises made to an informant or source should be qualified with the caveat that no absolute assurances", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Evidence", "back": "• The three primary types of evidence that fraud examiners must consider and gather when conducting their investigations are:\n• Testimonial evidence 1. Involves statements made by witnesses, neutral third parties, and suspects during interviews and/or when testifying at trial", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "General Rules for Collecting and Organizing Documents", "back": "• Obtain original documents where feasible.\n• Do not touch originals any more than necessary.\n• Maintain a dependable filing system for the documents.\n• Segregate the documents by either witness or transaction.\n• Make a key document file for easy access to the most relevant documents.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods for Obtaining Documentary Evidence", "back": "• Preferred method is by consent if both parties agree.\n• Consent can be oral, but consent should ideally be in writing when obtaining information from possible adverse witnesses or the examination’s target.\n• Documents can also be obtained through legal action.\n• Usually a subpoena or other court order is issued.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Handling Documents as Physical Evidence", "back": "• Documents should be handled carefully and stored properly in a sealed, initialed, and dated paper folder or envelope to avoid damage or contamination.\n• If necessary, make a working copy and preserve the original document for submission to a forensic document examiner.\n• Other than making unobtrusive initials for identification, do not write or mark on original documents.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Chain of Custody", "back": "• Both a process and a document that memorializes who has had possession of an object and what they have done with it\n• In general, to establish the chain of custody, fraud examiners must make a record via a memorandum when they, or any other member of the fraud examination team, receive an item and when it leaves thei\n• What items were received", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Disposal of Evidence", "back": "• Once an investigation or examination has concluded, fraud examiners might need to direct or participate in the disposal of evidence that was collected during an engagement.\n• Factors that could potentially affect evidence disposal following the conclusion of a fraud investigation or examination are:\n• The personal information about suspects or witnesses that is documented in the evidence\n• General document retention policies implemented by the organization\n• Any of these factors could require the evidence to be retained, disposed of, or returned to its owner in a specific manner.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Judicial Systems", "back": "• Common law systems\n• Courts are usually bound by two sources of substantive law: 1. Common law\n• A system of legal principles developed by judges through decisions made in court (thus, often referred to as judgemade law)\n• Consists of the usages and customs of a society as interpreted by the judiciary 2. Statutory law\n• Laws created by a legislature or other governing authority", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fact-Finding Processes", "back": "• The approach that courts take to discover (i.e., search for) evidence in a case\n• Two main types\n• Adversarial process 1. The parties to a proceeding drive the discovery process\n• The parties to the litigation gather and present the evidence to the court (usually through legal counsel) by questioning fact and expert witnesses.\n• The fact finder of the court, which can be a judge, jury, or administrator, is unaware of the details of the case until the parties present evidence.", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Overview of the Legal System", "back": "• The power of a court to hear and decide a given case\n• Refers to the subject matter or people over which lawful authority may be exercised by a court\n• For example, a country might have a system of probate courts that only have jurisdiction to hear cases whose subject matter is related to wills, inheritance, and other probate matters.\n• A particular court’s jurisdiction is defined by the laws of its country, but there are three common elements:\n• Does the court hear cases of the type in question?", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "International Issues in Fraud Cases", "back": "• Choice of law\n• Courts must choose which jurisdiction’s laws to apply to each issue in a case; this could lead to problems if the outcome of a case depends on which jurisdiction’s laws are applied.\n• Enforcement of judgments\n• A domestic judgment against a foreign defendant is usually helpful for recovering the defendant’s assets located in the domestic country, but it might be worthless for obtaining the defendant’s assets", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Civil and Criminal Actions for Fraud", "back": "• Fraud may be prosecuted criminally, civilly, or both, in sequence or simultaneously.\n• Criminal action\n• Begins with a complaint brought by the government, acting on behalf of citizens and the interest of the jurisdiction, against a person accused of violating a law\n• Civil action\n• An action for wrongdoing that does not result in a criminal fine or incarceration", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Administrative Proceedings", "back": "• Non-judicial proceedings conducted by government agencies\n• Generally operate like civil courts with their own rules of evidence and procedure\n• The ultimate decision-maker can be a special administrative judge, board, or tribunal\n• Common types of administrative penalties include:\n• Monetary fines and penalties", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Overview of Employees’ Rights", "back": "• Employees involved in investigations of suspected fraud have certain duties and rights, whether they are merely bystanders who might have some information relevant to the investigation or are suspecte\n• These duties and rights vary among jurisdictions, but generally apply to employees who work in private-sector and government workplaces; thus, both private and government employers can inadvertently v", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Employees’ Duty to Cooperate", "back": "• In most jurisdictions, a duty to cooperate exists in every employer-employee relationship.\n• Though the duty to cooperate varies, it generally extends to workplace investigations; therefore, employees have a duty to cooperate during an internal investigation if what is requested from them is ", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Employees’ Duty to Preserve Relevant Information", "back": "• Employees may have a duty to preserve relevant information, depending on their jurisdiction.\n• Common law jurisdictions: The duty to preserve relevant evidence typically arises when litigation is reasonably anticipated or contemplated; a violation occurs when information that is relevant to ant\n• In applicable jurisdictions, violating the duty to preserve relevant information can result in several adverse sanctions for the offending party.\n• Such sanctions can arise from both intentional acts and accidental acts through negligence.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Employees’ Contractual Rights", "back": "• An employee may have contractual rights that limit the employer’s ability to compel full cooperation in a fraud examination.\n• Employers and employees may enter into contracts that govern the employment relationship, and, if the employer violates the contract, then the employee can sue for breach of contract.\n• Such contracts can be express or implied.\n• Often, employee contractual rights at issue during investigations arise from a union contract, a collective bargaining agreement, or an employment contract.\n• For example, if the employee is a member of a union, then the union contract or collective bargaining agreement might contain certain restrictions on the company’s investigatory procedures.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Whistleblower Protections", "back": "• Many jurisdictions have whistleblower laws designed to encourage individuals to bring forth complaints of wrongdoing by providing protections for those who report unlawful conduct.\n• Most of these laws protect employees from any adverse employment action or retaliatory action from their employers, but they do not prevent individuals from being terminated for engaging in unrelated ", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Employees’ Privacy Rights", "back": "• Employees have certain privacy rights that can affect numerous aspects of the employer-employee relationship, such as conducting investigations, surveillance and monitoring, and workplace searches.\n• An employee’s privacy rights can arise from, and be protected by, various sources of law, including constitutional law, statutory law, common law, human rights law, labor law, data protection law, con\n• Countries vary in how they approach workplace privacy, but in some jurisdictions, privacy laws generally prohibit unreasonable searches and surveillance in areas where employees have a reasonable expe\n• The key issue to consider when assessing the existence of a reasonable expectation of privacy is whether a reasonable person would expect the area or item to be free from intrusion—the employee does n\n• Nearly every country prohibits covert employee monitoring unless a specific criminal activity has been identified; therefore, nearly every employer is required to notify its employees before implement", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Protections Relating to Government Search and Seizure", "back": "• Most countries have laws that provide the public with the right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities.\n• Though interpretation may vary, this right sometimes requires that the government obtain a search warrant before it conducts a search of a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime.\n• A search warrant is a court order that grants government authorities the right to search a premises or property for information pertinent to a case.\n• Consent searches\n• Individuals are always free to consent to searches.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Defamation", "back": "• An unprivileged publication of a false statement about a person that causes harm to that person’s reputation\n• Whether defamation is a criminal offense or a civil wrong varies by jurisdiction.\n• Elements that generally must be proven include:\n• The defendant made an untrue statement of fact.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Invasion of Privacy", "back": "• Intrusion into an individual’s private matters (intrusion upon seclusion)\n• Harm that occurs when an individual intentionally intrudes into an area where another individual has a reasonable expectation of privacy and the intrusion would be highly offensive or objectionable to\n• Public disclosure of private facts\n• Civil wrong that occurs when one party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Intentional Infliction of Emotional Distress", "back": "• Any unprivileged conduct that is so outrageous and egregious that it exceeds all bounds usually tolerated by civilized society and that is intended to cause injury (or was committed with reckless disr\n• Such conduct is mainly actionable in common law countries.\n• Elements\n• The defendant engaged in extreme and outrageous conduct.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "False Imprisonment", "back": "• The unlawful restraint by one person of the physical liberty of another without consent or legal justification\n• False imprisonment laws protect against unlawful confinement in many countries.\n• Elements\n• The defendant used words or actions intended to restrain the plaintiff.\n• A claim of false imprisonment might arise if an employee is detained in any way during a search or interview.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Data Privacy Laws", "back": "• Most countries have data privacy laws (also known as information privacy or data protection laws) that protect personal information about individuals from disclosure, unauthorized access, and misuse.\n• General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)\n• A regulation designed to protect the personal data of European Union (EU) residents and harmonize data protection laws throughout Europe\n• Organizations must have a lawful basis for collecting or processing personal data (e.g., the consent of the data subject, a legitimate interest of the organization, or compliance with a legal obligati\n• The lawful basis must be documented in a commonly used electronic format and include the name of the specific lawful basis, an explanation, and supporting facts.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Data Transfer Laws", "back": "• Data transfers cover any sharing, transferring or disclosing, giving access to, or otherwise making available information to third parties (e.g., corporate entities and government authorities).\n• Many countries have adopted legal restrictions on international data transfers; however, even when countries provide protection for cross-border data transfers, there are discrepancies in the implemen\n• Nevertheless, there are three options by which management can legitimize cross-border transfers of personal information:\n• Obtain the consent of the data subject.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "United Nation’s (UN) International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR)", "back": "• Commits those countries who have signed and ratified the covenant to recognize various rights of citizens, including the following rights for those accused of crimes:\n• Freedom from arbitrary arrest or detention 1. Under the ICCPR, individuals have the right to liberty and shall not be subject to arbitrary arrest or detention. 2. A custodial arrest occurs whenever a \n• Adequate time to prepare a defense\n• The ability to be represented by legal counsel of the defendant’s choosing and to freely communicate with counsel\n• The right to have accusations and the procedures explained through a translator for free, if necessary", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Corporate Criminal Liability", "back": "• In many jurisdictions, corporations and similar business entities may be vicariously liable (the absolute liability of one party for the misconduct of another party) for criminal and civil violations.\n• In such jurisdictions, a business entity is liable for the acts of its employees if those acts occur within the scope of employment and with some intent to benefit the corporation (doctrine of respond\n• Generally, vicarious liability is very broad and imposes liability on a corporation even if those in management had no knowledge of or participation in the underlying events.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prosecutorial Discretion and Bargaining Agreements", "back": "• Whether criminal cases are brought to trial generally depends on prosecutorial discretion, meaning that the decision to prosecute is left to the discretion of the appropriate jurisdictional authority.\n• Another method of disposing of cases in a growing number of countries is through bargaining agreements, which occur when a defendant makes an agreement with prosecutors to plead guilty or submit a rec\n• It is usually within the prosecution’s discretion as to whether to offer a bargain.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Corporate Deferred Prosecution Agreements", "back": "• Used in some of the jurisdictions that allow for corporate criminal liability\n• Typically occur when prosecutors file criminal charges against a company, but then they agree not to prosecute the claims if the company successfully complies with the deferral agreement’s terms\n• Focus on getting the business to reform its policies and reduce the risk of illegal practices\n• Used to help companies avoid indictment, trial, and conviction while providing a jurisdiction’s justice system with another channel for disposing a corporate case that punishes misconduct and effectua", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Trial Process", "back": "• Fact finders\n• Common law systems 1. Juries are typically, but not always, used in criminal proceedings.\n• A jury trial might not be available for cases involving minor criminal offenses (although jury trials are typically available for serious cases).\n• Many common law jurisdictions allow the defendant to waive the right to trial by jury.\n• When no jury is present, the judge serves as the fact finder.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Punishment", "back": "• When a defendant is found guilty of a crime, there are a variety of sanctions available, depending on the jurisdiction. Sanctions may include:\n• Probation 1. The suspension of an offender’s sentence in return for a promise of good behavior 2. Typically imposed prior to (and instead of) imprisonment 3. Laws vary by jurisdiction, but the offende\n• Parole refers to the status of offenders after they have been released from prison and are placed under supervision in the community.\n• Criminal forfeiture 1. The defendant must transfer specific property (generally property that was used to commit the crime or that was purchased with the proceeds of the crime) to the government as pa", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Appeal", "back": "• The procedure for obtaining review by a higher court to ensure that the trial was conducted in a lawful manner and that the judgments comply with the law\n• Generally, appellate courts will not accept an appeal unless the petition is filed in a timely manner (e.g., no later than thirty days after the trial court’s judgment).\n• In many jurisdictions, an appellate court will reverse a conviction only if it finds an error that likely affected the trial’s outcome and denied the defendant a fair trial.\n• Common law systems\n• In most common law countries, appellate courts consider potential errors of law de novo (meaning they evaluate them independently of the trial court’s determinations), but they generally adopt the fac", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Definition of Evidence", "back": "• Anything perceivable by the five senses that is presented to the fact finder to prove or disprove a fact in issue\n• Testimonial evidence 1. The oral or written statements made by witnesses under oath\n• Evidence is simply anything that relates to proving or disproving a fact that is of consequence in a case.", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Two Basic Categories of Admissible Evidence", "back": "• Direct evidence\n• Evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue directly, such as eyewitness testimony or a confession.\n• Circumstantial evidence\n• Evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue indirectly, by inference.\n• Many fraud cases are proved entirely by circumstantial evidence, or by a combination of circumstantial and direct evidence, but seldom by direct evidence alone.", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Admissibility of Evidence", "back": "• Relevance\n• A basic requirement of admissibility in both common and civil law systems is that evidence must be relevant (i.e., tends to make some fact that is in dispute more or less likely than it would be witho\n• Authentication\n• Common law systems 1. Evidence, other than testimonial evidence, must be properly authenticated to be admissible at trial; that is, the party offering the item must produce some evidence (e.g., testim\n• Testimony from a witness who has personal knowledge", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Impeachment", "back": "• The practice of questioning a witness’s knowledge or credibility\n• In systems using adversarial processes, the adverse party is usually entitled to offer evidence to impeach the testimony or credibility of a witness.\n• Most inquisitorial systems do not allow cross-examination of witnesses.\n• There are numerous ways an attorney might impeach a witness, but the most common include efforts to show that the witness:\n• Is influenced by bias or self-interest", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Privileges and Protections", "back": "• Prevent certain types of evidence from being discovered or produced during trial\n• The privileges and protections available and requirements for each vary substantially by jurisdiction.\n• Common law systems generally offer broader evidentiary protections than civil law systems.\n• Common types of privileges include:\n• Legal professional privilege (e.g., attorney-client privilege) 1. Precludes disclosure of confidential communications between a professional legal advisor (e.g., solicitor, barrister, or attorney) and", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Definition of Fraud", "back": "• Any intentional or deliberate act to deprive another of property or money by guile, deception, or other unfair means", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraudulent Misrepresentation of Material Facts", "back": "• The specific elements of proof required to establish a misrepresentation claim vary somewhat according to where the fraud occurred and whether the case is brought as a criminal or civil action.\n• The elements normally include:\n• The defendant made a false statement (i.e., a misrepresentation of fact).\n• The victim suffered damages because of the misrepresentation.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Bribery", "back": "• Official bribery\n• The corruption of a public official to influence an official act of government\n• Commercial bribery\n• The corruption of a private individual to gain a commercial or business advantage", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Conflict of Interest", "back": "• Occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence their professional role\n• Elements of a typical civil claim for conflict of interest include:\n• The defendant is an agent of a principal or employer.\n• For a conflict of interest claim to be actionable, the conflict must be undisclosed.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Breach of Fiduciary Duty", "back": "• People in a position of trust or fiduciary relationship—such as officers, directors, high-level employees of a corporation or business, and agents and brokers—owe certain duties to their principals or\n• The two principal fiduciary duties are:\n• Duty of loyalty 1. Requires that the employee/agent act solely in the best interest of the employer/principal without any self-dealing, conflicts of interest, or other abuse of the principal for perso", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Conspiracy", "back": "• A situation in which two or more people agree to commit an illegal act\n• The essential elements that must be shown to prove a conspiracy typically include:\n• The defendant entered into an agreement with at least one person to commit an illegal act.\n• Generally, to prove a conspiracy, the government must establish that the defendant knew of the conspiracy’s existence and its objective, but it does not need to establish that the defendant knew all t\n• Under most conspiracy laws, the purpose of the conspiracy need not be accomplished for a violation to occur, but at least one of the co-conspirators must have executed at least one overt act in furthe", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Mail Fraud", "back": "• Occurs when a country’s mail system is used to perpetrate fraud\n• Mail fraud laws only exist in some jurisdictions, such as Canada and the United States.\n• In the United States, the mail fraud statute also applies to the use of private interstate commercial carriers (e.g., FedEx, UPS, and DHL) in connection with a fraud scheme.\n• Mail fraud laws generally give the government broad authority to prosecute fraud schemes, even if parts of the scheme occur in another country.\n• For example, an international Ponzi scheme perpetrated from Nigeria could be prosecuted under the U.S. mail fraud statute if the Nigerian fraudsters used the U.S. mail system to advance the scheme in ", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Wire Fraud", "back": "• A U.S. statute that makes it a crime to defraud a victim of money or property by means of wire or other electronic communications (e.g., computer, telephone, radio, or television) in foreign or inters\n• Requires an interstate or foreign communication to constitute a violation\n• While unique to the United States, the wire fraud statute gives the U.S. federal government broad jurisdiction over a wide range of fraudulent activity, including some fraud schemes that originate out", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Obstruction of Justice", "back": "• Occurs when an individual engages in an act designed to impede or obstruct the investigation or trial of other substantive offenses\n• Jurisdictions might have several criminal obstruction statutes, but some common types are those that prohibit:\n• Influencing or injuring any officer of the court or juror by force, threats of force, intimidating communications, or corrupt influence\n• Destroying documents related to a future proceeding", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Perjury", "back": "• An intentional false statement given under oath on a material point at issue\n• The basic elements include:\n• The defendant made a false statement.\n• Laws that criminalize perjury generally do not require that the false statement be given in a court of law.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "False Claims and Statements to Government Agencies", "back": "• Laws prohibiting false claims and statements to government agencies make it illegal for a person to lie to, or conceal material information from, a government agency.\n• A false claim is an assertion of a right to government money, property, or services that contains a misrepresentation.\n• An individual can be found guilty for making a false statement or claim only if the individual knew the statement or claim was false at the time it was made.\n• Generally, to prove a violation, the government must show that the defendant:\n• Knowingly and willfully (or with reckless disregard for truth or falsity)", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "International Initiatives Against Fraud and Corruption", "back": "• The OECD Recommendation on Combating Bribery in International Business\n• Published by the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), an intergovernmental institution dedicated to democracy and the market economy\n• The U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA)\n• Prohibits making corrupt payments to foreign officials or political organizations\n• Make it unlawful to bribe foreign government officials to obtain or retain business. 2. Accounting provisions", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Testimony", "back": "• Lay (factual) testimony\n• Witnesses testify about what they have experienced firsthand and their factual observations.\n• Expert testimony\n• Testimony from a person who, by reason of education, training, skill, or experience, is qualified to render an opinion or otherwise testify in areas relevant to resolution of a legal dispute", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Experts", "back": "• Testifying expert\n• Gives opinion testimony when specialized knowledge is needed to help the fact finder understand evidence or determine a fact in issue\n• Consulting expert\n• Hired to provide technical assistance to the attorney in preparing the case; typically does not testify at trial", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Procedural Divergences Regarding Expert Witnesses in Adversarial and", "back": "• Adversarial jurisdictions (typically common law jurisdictions)\n• Most expert witnesses are chosen by the parties to the litigation (although adversarial courts may also appoint independent experts).\n• The fact finder (i.e., the judge or jury) must evaluate these competing expert opinions.\n• Inquisitorial jurisdictions (typically civil law jurisdictions)\n• The court usually hires its own expert witnesses for technical issues that require guidance; in other words, the primary experts in inquisitorial jurisdictions are typically appointed by the court (i.", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Qualifying to Testify as an Expert Witness", "back": "• Adversarial jurisdictions\n• Generally, a judge will make three determinations before allowing an expert to testify before the jury: 1. Is the person qualified as an expert witness? 2. Will the expertise of the witness assist the\n• A person does not have to be a CFE to testify as an expert on fraud prevention, detection, or investigation techniques if that person has sufficient practical experience in those techniques, but the C\n• Inquisitorial jurisdictions\n• Most inquisitorial jurisdictions have more standardized requirements for qualifying to testify and allow expert witnesses to offer their services in court more often than in adversarial jurisdictions.", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Direct Examination of Witnesses", "back": "• The initial questioning of a witness\n• Adversarial jurisdictions: Conducted by the party who retained the witness\n• Usually a nonconfrontational questioning aimed at exposing the facts and issues of the case", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods of Presenting Expert Testimony During Direct Examination", "back": "• Written reports\n• In adversarial jurisdictions, experts typically create written reports in the pretrial stage and then testify to their findings during direct examination.\n• Narratives\n• Narrative questions are broad, open-ended questions that allow experts to state their opinions in their own words with minimal prompting.\n• Hypotheticals", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Cross-Examination of Witnesses", "back": "• The questioning of one side’s witness by the opposing side\n• Allows the questioning party either to clarify or make points at the witness’s expense\n• Adversarial jurisdictions\n• During cross-examination, the witness’s credibility is constantly scrutinized.\n• If this occurs, or if asked a long or imprecise question, then the witness should ask for a question to be rephrased in smaller components. 2. Attempt to take psychological control of a witness by:", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Cross-Examination Strategies to Discredit Witnesses", "back": "• When applicable in the jurisdiction, the questioning party might employ various methods to discredit an expert witness or diminish the importance of the witness’s testimony:\n• Myopic vision", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Beginning the Civil Action", "back": "• A civil action begins when the plaintiff files a pleading with the appropriate court, usually in the jurisdiction in which the defendant or the plaintiff resides, or where the claim originated.\n• The pleading sets out the complaint against the defendant and the remedy that the plaintiff is seeking.\n• The required contents of the plaintiff’s pleadings vary somewhat between jurisdictions, but most jurisdictions require fact pleadings, meaning the plaintiff must identify:\n• The grounds for legal relief", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Counterclaims", "back": "• Claims filed by a defendant against the plaintiff in a civil action\n• Level a claim against the original plaintiff, who is now the defendant of the counterclaim", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Preservation of Evidence", "back": "• Most civil litigation concerning fraud involves many documents, tangible items, or digital information that might serve as evidence, and each jurisdiction has rules for how this potential evidence sho\n• Common law systems\n• Generally impose a duty on parties in civil litigation to take affirmative steps to preserve relevant evidence\n• Civil law systems\n• Tend to have a narrower scope of what evidence is required for litigation", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Gathering Evidence", "back": "• After the parties submit pleadings to the court, the evidence-gathering process, which varies by jurisdiction, begins.\n• Common law systems\n• Each party is entitled to pretrial discovery (the formal process whereby parties collect evidence and learn the details of the opposing side’s case).\n• Civil law systems\n• In the inquisitorial process commonly found in civil law jurisdictions, the evidence is gathered contemporaneously with the trial, as opposed to the common law method of having the parties gather evid", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Standard of Proof", "back": "• Common law systems\n• Generally, the standard of proof in a civil suit is referred to as the preponderance of the evidence, meaning that it is more probable than not that the defendant is liable.\n• Civil law systems\n• The standard of proof in civil law jurisdictions typically does not change in criminal and civil trials, so the inner conviction of the judge, or conviction intime standard, also applies in civil suit", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Civil Trial Process", "back": "• Common law systems\n• Jury composition and verdict\n• It is common for the minimum number of jurors to be lower for civil cases.\n• Civil trials are less likely to require a unanimous jury verdict than criminal trials.\n• Courts sometimes have the authority to seize assets or property temporarily while a lawsuit is pending.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Appeals", "back": "• Generally, both sides in a civil case may appeal from an adverse judgment, either as to liability or damages.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Legal Remedies", "back": "• Any processes, procedures, or consequences of a legal wrong by which a victim can be redressed for their loss\n• The remedy to which the plaintiff is entitled depends upon a number of factors, such as the relief sought, the facts of the case, and the authority given to the court to grant specific relief.\n• The three most common civil remedies are:\n• Damages (monetary remedies) 1. Remedies for the victim’s recovery of money from the defendant because of, and as compensation, reimbursement, or reparation for, the defendant’s legal offense", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fidelity Insurance", "back": "• A method that is often overlooked for recovery of losses due to internal fraud\n• Under fidelity insurance policies, the insured entity is covered against losses caused by the dishonest or fraudulent acts of its employees.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Alternative Dispute Resolution", "back": "• A means for parties to an action to resolve their disputes without the necessity of a trial\n• In fraud cases, this usually involves one of two types of methods:\n• Mediation 1. The process whereby an impartial third person (known as a mediator) assists the parties in reaching a resolution to the dispute 2. The mediator does not decide who should win, but instead", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "What Constitutes a Security?", "back": "• A security is a negotiable financial instrument that represents an interest or a right in something else.\n• Countries define the term differently, so what is considered a security varies from country to country.\n• Types of investments most commonly recognized as securities include stocks, bonds, and certificates of deposit.\n• In many countries, the term security includes investment contracts.\n• Generally, a contract, transaction, or scheme is an investment contract if: 1. There is an investment of money or another asset. 2. The investment is in a common enterprise. 3. The investment was made", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Securities Laws and Regulation", "back": "• Securities regulation refers to laws, rules, and procedures enacted by a legislative body and administered by dedicated agencies that govern the way in which companies, consumers, and financial profes\n• To be effective, securities regulation must balance the legitimate needs of businesses to raise capital against the need to protect investors.\n• Additional purposes include:\n• Promoting an active and competitive market", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO)", "back": "• An international organization comprised of securities commissioners and administrators responsible for securities regulation and the administration of securities laws in their respective countries\n• Recognized as the international standard-setter for securities markets\n• Main objectives are to assist its members to:\n• Cooperate to promote high standards of regulation in order to maintain just, efficient, and sound markets.", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Self-Regulatory Organizations (SROs)", "back": "• Nongovernmental entities that exercise some level of regulatory authority over the operations, standards of practice, and business conduct of an industry or profession\n• SROs oversee the markets in which they operate and police the members and member firms participating in those markets.\n• SROs’ regulatory responsibilities might include:\n• Creating rules to protect the integrity of the market in which they operate\n• Many SROs play an important role in the resolution of disputes arising from market transactions.", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Securities Fraud Schemes", "back": "• Churning (excessive trading)\n• The excessive trading of a customer account to generate commissions while disregarding the customer’s interests\n• Unsuitable recommendations\n• In many countries, broker-dealers who make recommendations or provide advice to clients regarding purchases of investment products are subject to a suitability requirement.\n• Securities broker-dealers must know their customers financially to effectively service their accounts and minimize the risk of recommending an inappropriate investment.", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Definition of Money Laundering", "back": "• The disguising of the existence, nature, source, control, beneficial ownership, location, and disposition of property (typically) derived from criminal activity", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Money Laundering Process", "back": "• Three stages\n• Placement 1. In this first stage, the launderer introduces their illegal profits into the financial system. 2. It is at this stage that legislation has been developed to prevent launderers from deposi", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using a Front Business to Launder Funds", "back": "• One of the most common methods of laundering funds is to filter the money through a legitimate business, known as a front business.\n• A front business provides a safe place for organizing and managing criminal activity, where the comings and goings of large numbers of people will not arouse undue suspicion.\n• In addition, a front that conducts legitimate business provides cover for delivery and transportation related to illegal activity. The expenses from illegal activity can be attributed to the legitimat\n• A red flag of a front business is the observation of minimal customers during peak operating hours.\n• Two methods commonly used to hide assets or launder money through a front business are:", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Money Laundering", "back": "• Digital currencies are currencies that exist and are traded in a digital format.\n• Among the most popular digital currencies is bitcoin, a cryptocurrency that features a peer-to-peer network that allows users to send units of the currency to each other online without the use of a tr\n• Digital currencies are vulnerable to money laundering because:\n• Many of them function as international person-to-person (P2P) payment systems that cross jurisdictional boundaries, creating difficulties for authorities pursuing enforcement or legal actions.", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Trade-Based Money Laundering to Launder Funds", "back": "• Defined by the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) as “the process of disguising the proceeds of crime and moving value through the use of trade transactions in an attempt to legitimize their illicit o\n• Schemes generally involve importers and exporters who collude to misrepresent the price, quantity, or quality of imported or exported goods or services.\n• Trade-based money laundering schemes can be used to create artificial profits for the purpose of laundering money between countries; to create a complex paper trail; and to avoid taxes, customs duties\n• Some common schemes include:\n• Over- and under-invoicing schemes 1. Importers and exporters conspire to misrepresent the price of the goods or services being traded, thus transferring additional value between the importer and expor", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Money Services Businesses to Launder Funds", "back": "• Money services businesses (MSBs) refer to non-depository financial service providers that transmit or convert money and operate in one or more of the following capacities:\n• Currency exchangers\n• Prepaid access providers or sellers\n• MSBs offer an alternative to depository institutions for both financial services and money laundering, so an individual unable to transfer illegal funds into the traditional depository banking system \n• Most MSBs operate under less strict regulations than traditional financial institutions.", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Alternative Remittance Systems to Launder Funds", "back": "• Alternative remittance systems are methods of transferring funds from a party at one location to another party (whether domestic or foreign) without the use of formal banking institutions.\n• These systems do not require a direct physical or digital transfer of currency from the sender to the receiver.\n• In the typical alternative remittance system, the payer transfers funds to a local broker who has a connection to another broker in the region where the payee is located. The second broker then distri\n• The relative anonymity and lack of a paper trail afforded by alternative remittance systems makes them attractive to money launderers, as well as to people involved in terrorist financing.", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) on Money Laundering", "back": "• An intergovernmental body established to develop and promote standards and policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing at both the national and international levels\n• The FATF Recommendations, revised in 2012, created the most comprehensive standard with which to measure a country’s AML, counterterrorism, and nuclear proliferation laws and policies, and they serve \n• Some of the key measures in the FATF Recommendations provide that countries should:\n• Use a risk-based approach when setting AML policies.\n• Require financial institutions to: 1. Keep certain records and establish AML policies. 2. Avoid correspondent banking with shell banks. 3. Continuously monitor wire transfers.", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Common Types of Bankruptcy Filings", "back": "• Liquidation\n• The most basic type of bankruptcy proceeding\n• Typical items that may not be liquidated include the debtor’s primary residence, items of nominal value, or assets deemed necessary for the debtor to maintain employment.\n• Reorganization\n• Allows the debtor respite from creditors so that the debtor can reorganize its financial affairs and continue as a going concern", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Bankruptcy Schemes", "back": "• Concealed assets\n• The most common type of bankruptcy fraud scheme is the concealment of assets rightfully belonging to the debtor’s estate to avoid forfeiting the assets in bankruptcy.\n• The planned bustout\n• A scheme involving a planned bankruptcy to defraud creditors", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/ Debtor Regimes", "back": "• A distillation of international best practices for designing a national insolvency system that is designed to be flexible enough to serve as a benchmark for the insolvency system of any country\n• Under the World Bank Principles, countries should adopt the following anti-fraud policies:\n• Administrative powers 1. Most bankruptcy processes appoint a person or group with administrative powers (e.g., an administrator, trustee, receiver, examiner, or supervisor) to oversee the process. 2. \n• The right to cancel fraudulent contracts or transactions entered into by the debtor\n• The power to collect, preserve, and dispose of the debtor’s property", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "What Constitutes Tax Fraud?", "back": "• Tax fraud refers to intentional actions that a taxpayer commits to defraud the government of owed tax dollars.\n• The intent of the taxpayer to wrongly file a return or provide other false tax information determines the difference between tax evasion and tax avoidance.\n• Tax evasion refers to any fraudulent actions that a taxpayer commits to avoid reporting or paying taxes.\n• The primary distinguishing characteristic of tax evasion as compared to tax avoidance is that tax evasion is illegal, but tax avoidance is legal.", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Willfulness vs. Good Faith Misunderstanding of the Law", "back": "• The most important distinction in determining whether an individual or company committed tax evasion is whether the party acted with criminal intent; most jurisdictions require a willful attempt to ev\n• A good faith or legitimate misunderstanding of the applicable law typically negates willfulness, the voluntary, intentional violation of a known legal duty.\n• Willfulness might be inferred from conduct such as:\n• Keeping a double set of books (not to be confused with keeping separate books and tax records, which might require different recording techniques)\n• Covering up sources of income", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Tax Evasion Schemes", "back": "• Income and wealth tax evasion\n• Fraudsters falsify or omit material information in regard to taxes on periodic income or wealth.\n• Falsifying tax deductions\n• Fraudsters inappropriately use tax deductions (the itemized expenses subtracted from gross income or assets in determining the taxable amount) to reduce the taxpayer’s total tax liability.\n• Tax credit schemes", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Tax Fraud", "back": "• No tax deficiency\n• To prove innocence of tax fraud matters, the defendant can establish that there is no tax deficiency and therefore no tax liability.\n• Avoidance, not evasion\n• Establishing that the taxpayer was engaging in tax avoidance and not evasion provides a defense to tax fraud.\n• Reliance on an attorney or accountant", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Ineffective Defenses Against Tax Fraud", "back": "• Death of taxpayer\n• Fraud penalties survive the taxpayer’s death.\n• Bankruptcy\n• Liabilities owed as a result of tax evasion may not be discharged in bankruptcy proceedings.\n• Amended or delinquent return", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Categories of Cash Receipts Schemes", "back": "• Two types\n• Skimming\n• The difference depends completely on when the cash is stolen.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Skimming", "back": "• The removal of cash from a victim entity prior to its entry in an accounting system\n• Employees steal sales or receivables before they are recorded in the company books.\n• Known as off-book frauds, meaning cash is stolen before it is recorded in the victim organization’s accounts\n• Difficult to detect due to the lack of audit trail", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Sales Skimming", "back": "• Unrecorded sales scheme\n• An employee sells goods or services to a customer and collects the customer’s payment but makes no record of the sale.\n• Understated sales scheme\n• The transaction in question is posted to the books but for a lower amount than what the perpetrator actually collected.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Skimming Receivables", "back": "• More difficult to conceal than sales skimming because payments are expected (victim organization knows the customer owes money and is waiting for the payment)\n• When receivables are skimmed, the absence of the payment appears on the books as a delinquent account.\n• To conceal a skimmed receivable, a perpetrator must account for the payment that was due but never received.\n• Lapping schemes\n• The crediting of one account through the abstraction of money from another account", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Detection of Skimming Schemes", "back": "• Receipt- or sales-level detection\n• Vertical, horizontal, and ratio analysis of sales accounts\n• Journal entry review\n• Examine journal entries for: 1. False credits to inventory to conceal unrecorded or understated sales 2. Write-offs of lost, stolen, or obsolete inventory 3. Write-offs of accounts receivable accounts\n• Confirming customers’ outstanding account balances", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention of Skimming Schemes", "back": "• General controls\n• Sales entries and general ledger access controls should include documented policies and procedures from management.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Cash Larceny", "back": "• The theft of cash that has already been recorded on the victim company’s books\n• Types of cash larceny schemes\n• Theft of cash from the register 1. Involves opening the register and removing currency or checks 2. Often committed while a sale is being conducted so that it appears to be part of the transaction", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Detection of Cash Larceny", "back": "• Cash register log totals should be reconciled to the amount of cash in the drawer.\n• The bank deposit should be made by someone other than the cashier or the accounts receivable clerk.\n• A person independent of the cash receipts and accounts receivable functions should compare entries to the cash receipts journal with:\n• Authenticated bank deposit slips\n• All employees should have unique access codes to the cash registers, and the time periods that each access code is used should be checked against employee work schedules to ensure an employee’s access", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "back": "• Separation of duties\n• Cash receipts\n• Bank reconciliations\n• Assignment rotation\n• Many internal fraud schemes are continuous in nature and require ongoing efforts by the employee to conceal the fraud, so mandatory job or assignment rotations should be implemented to uncover the con", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "What Is Intellectual Property?", "back": "• Intangible proprietary information that includes a business’s ideas, designs, and innovations, howsoever expressed or recorded", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Competitive Intelligence vs. Espionage", "back": "• Competitive intelligence is the process by which competitor data are assembled into relevant, accurate, and usable knowledge about competitors’ positions, performance, capabilities, and intentions.\n• A legitimate business function that businesses use to anticipate competitors’ research and development strategies and to determine their operating costs, pricing policies, financial strength, and capa\n• Espionage refers to the use of illegal, covert means to gather information.\n• Does not cover legitimate intelligence collection and analysis using legal means", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Basic Sources of Information", "back": "• Open-source information\n• Information in the public domain (i.e., publicly available data that anyone can lawfully obtain by request, purchase, or observation)\n• Dumpster diving\n• Involves obtaining sensitive information by looking through someone else’s trash (e.g., via dumpsters and other trash receptacles)\n• Scavenging", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "How Information Is Lost or Stolen", "back": "• Accident and negligence, such as through:\n• Conference speeches and papers\n• Poor information security procedures\n• Organizations should employ and regularly update a system for protecting and disposing of confidential information.\n• Calendars", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "back": "• A task force\n• Should include managers and staff from departments that deal with proprietary information (e.g., research and development and production), as well as representatives from the corporate security, human\n• Awareness training\n• Employees must be educated as to what information is proprietary, as well as the dangers of electronically communicating that information.\n• Nondisclosure agreements", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Common Types of Con Schemes", "back": "• Advance-fee schemes\n• Schemes structured to obtain an illegal gain by falsely promising the delivery of a product or service\n• Debt consolidation schemes\n• Often involve the consolidation agency collecting money from the debtor but not forwarding it to the creditors\n• Scavenger or revenge schemes", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Common Types of Elder Fraud Schemes", "back": "• Home improvement schemes\n• Fraudsters recommend a “friend” who can perform needed home repairs for an older individual at a reasonable price. In some cases, this friend then overcharges the individual for home repair work that \n• Travel, vacation, and timeshare schemes\n• Fraudsters post advertisements for vacation properties that are nonexistent, significantly different than promised, or not available for rent.\n• Tech-support schemes", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Ponzi Schemes", "back": "• A Ponzi scheme is generally defined as an illegal business practice in which new investors’ money is used to make payments to earlier investors.\n• The investment opportunity is typically presented with the promise of uncommonly high returns.\n• The key element in a Ponzi scheme is that initial investors are paid with subsequent investors’ money with minimal or no legitimate commerce occurring.\n• A Ponzi scheme is a pyramid scheme, but it masquerades as some type of investment.", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Red Flags of Ponzi Schemes", "back": "• Sounds too good to be true\n• Promises of low risk or high rewards\n• History of consistent returns\n• High-pressure sales tactics\n• Pressure to reinvest", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Pyramid Schemes", "back": "• Illegal pyramids generate revenue by continually recruiting new members. These operations might offer merchandise or services for sale, but the only significant revenues come from recruitment.\n• The distinguishing factor of the illegal pyramid is the continual need for new investors or members.\n• Unlike Ponzi schemes, illegal pyramids are promoted as pyramids.\n• An operation is likely to be classified as an illegal pyramid scheme if the company emphasizes the recruitment of new members over product sales and promises that riches can only be obtained through r", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods of Committing Identity Theft", "back": "• Traditional identity theft\n• Involves a fraudster stealing an individual’s personal information and pretending to be that individual\n• Synthetic identity theft\n• Involves a fraudster using entirely fabricated personal information or a combination of real and fabricated information to create a new identity", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "How Identity Thieves Steal Information", "back": "• Dumpster diving\n• Discarded devices\n• Mail theft\n• Shoulder surfing\n• The practice of observing another person (e.g., looking over their shoulder) to gather personal information", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods of Identity Theft Prevention for Individuals", "back": "• Create complex passwords or passphrases that have at least eight characters and contain upper- and lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols.\n• Do not reuse passwords.\n• Never send personal information, such as a password or government identification number, via email.\n• When available, use biometric authentication (e.g., fingerprints, voice recognition).\n• Create unique answers for security questions.", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods of Identity Theft Prevention for Businesses", "back": "• Limit the personal information collected from customers (e.g., do not collect government identification numbers from customers unless legally required to gather that information).\n• Restrict employees from accessing the personal information of customers and coworkers.\n• Do not retain personal information for longer than necessary.\n• Use encryption to protect all personal information stored by the company or sent to third parties, as well as information sent over the company’s wireless network.\n• Restrict the use of laptops to those employees who need them to do their jobs.", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Accounting Basics", "back": "• The accounting equation\n• Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity\n• Accounting methods\n• Cash-basis accounting 1. Involves recording revenues and expenses based on when a company receives or pays cash 2. The advantage is its simplicity—the only thing a company must track is cash being rec", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Accounting Concepts", "back": "• Balance sheet (or statement of financial position)\n• Provides insight into a company’s financial situation at a specific point in time, generally the last day of the accounting period\n• Includes cash, accounts receivable, inventory, and prepaid items 2. Long-term or noncurrent assets—assets that will likely not be converted to cash within one year\n• Includes fixed assets (e.g., land, buildings, equipment) and intangible assets (e.g., patents, trademarks, goodwill)\n• Liabilities are presented in the following categories in order of maturity: 1. Current liabilities—obligations expected to be paid within one year", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "120,000", "back": "• The rules by which a company’s financial transactions are recorded into their appropriate account classifications and properly reported as part of the entity’s financial statements\n• Publicly traded companies must follow the specific financial reporting practices of their jurisdiction, which differ among regions.\n• Currently, there is not a universally accepted accounting recording and reporting system in existence.\n• Commonly used accounting frameworks include U.S. GAAP and International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS), the latter of which is permitted or required by 166 international jurisdictions.\n• U.S. GAAP is a rules-based framework.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "International Financial Reporting Standards", "back": "• Qualitative characteristics of useful financial information under IFRS\n• Relevance 1. Any financial information that might affect a decision made by a user of the financial statements is considered relevant. 2. To be relevant, the information must have a predictive value (\n• An item is considered material if its omission or misstatement would affect the judgment of a reasonable person who is relying on the financial statements.\n• Complete (includes all information necessary to understand the data presented)\n• Neutral (no bias in the selection or presentation of financial information)", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Circumstances Meriting Departures from GAAP", "back": "• As with rules for most things, departures from GAAP are sometimes required, regardless of whether you are using U.S. GAAP, IFRS, or another set of accounting standards.\n• Therefore, the standard-setting bodies recognize that, upon occasion, there might be an unusual circumstance when the literal application of GAAP would render the financial statements misleading. In t\n• There is concern that assets or income would be overstated and expenses or liabilities would be understated (the conservatism constraint requires that, when there is any doubt, one should avoid overst\n• If a transaction is considered immaterial (i.e., it would not affect a decision made by a prudent reader of the financial statements), then it need not be reported.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Definition of Financial Statement Fraud", "back": "• The deliberate misrepresentation of the financial condition of an enterprise accomplished through the intentional misstatement or omission of amounts or disclosures in the financial statements to dece", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Forms That Financial Statement Fraud Typically Takes", "back": "• Overstated assets or revenue\n• Falsely reflects a financially stronger company by the inclusion of fictitious asset costs or artificial revenues\n• Understated liabilities and expenses\n• Accomplished through the exclusion of costs or financial obligations", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Five Classifications of Financial Statement Schemes", "back": "• Fictitious revenues\n• Involve the recording of sales of goods or services that did not occur\n• Timing differences\n• The recording of revenues or expenses in improper periods to move revenues or expenses between one period and the next, increasing or decreasing earnings as desired\n• Revenue is recognized when (or as) an entity satisfies a performance obligation by transferring a promised good or service (asset) to a customer.", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Financial Statement Analysis", "back": "• Vertical analysis\n• A technique for analyzing the relationships among the items on an income statement, balance sheet, or statement of cash flows during a specific accounting period by expressing components as percentage\n• Horizontal analysis\n• A technique for analyzing the percentage change in individual line items on a financial statement from one accounting period to the next\n• Ratio analysis", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Fraudulent Disbursement Schemes", "back": "• Register disbursement schemes\n• Electronic payment schemes\n• Billing schemes\n• Payroll schemes\n• Expense reimbursement schemes", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Register Disbursement Schemes", "back": "• False refunds\n• Fictitious refund scheme 1. An employee processes a transaction as if a customer were returning merchandise, even though there is no actual return. 2. The employee takes cash from the register in the \n• False voids\n• Typically, when an employee sets about processing a fictitious void, the employee withholds the customer’s receipt at the time of the sale.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Register Disbursement Scheme Red Flags", "back": "• There is inappropriate separation of duties for employees.\n• Cashiers have access to refund and void controls.\n• Cashiers are authorized to void their own transactions.\n• Register refunds are not carefully reviewed.\n• Multiple cashiers operate from a single cash drawer without separate access codes.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Electronic Payment Tampering", "back": "• Dishonest employees access their employer’s electronic payment system to fraudulently initiate or divert electronic payments to themselves or their accomplices.\n• Some of these fraudsters abuse their legitimate access while others gain access through social engineering, password theft, or by exploiting weaknesses in their employer’s internal control or electron", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Electronic Payment Tampering", "back": "• Internal controls\n• The most important practice for preventing and detecting electronic payment fraud is separation of duties. 1. For example, in the case of online bill payments, such as those made through a bank’s webs\n• Bank security services\n• Automated clearing house (ACH) blocks allow account holders to notify their banks that ACH debits should not be allowed on specific accounts.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "back": "• Invoicing via shell companies\n• Forming a shell company 1. Shell companies are business entities that typically have no physical presence (other than a mailing address) or employees and generate little, if any, independent economic \n• Invoicing via nonaccomplice vendors\n• Pay and return schemes 1. An employee intentionally mishandles payments that are owed to legitimate vendors. 2. The employee then requests the vendor to return the payment and intercepts the funds. 3.\n• Personal purchases with company funds", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Billing Schemes", "back": "• Detection methods include analytical review, data analytics, statistical sampling, vendor or outsider complaints, site visits, and audit programs.\n• Prevention methods include employee education and training, appropriate compensation, proper documentation, proper approvals, separation of duties, hotlines, and competitive bidding.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Payroll Fraud Schemes", "back": "• Ghost employees\n• The term ghost employee refers to someone on the payroll who does not work for the victim company.\n• Scheme requirements", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Payroll Fraud Schemes", "back": "• Detection methods include independent payroll distribution, analysis of payee address or accounts, duplicate identification numbers, overtime authorization, commissions, and analysis of deductions fro\n• Other methods for detecting ghost employees include:\n• Comparing employee names, addresses, government identification numbers, and bank account numbers to determine if there are any unexpected duplicates\n• Prevention methods include separation of duties (payroll preparation, payroll disbursement, payroll distribution, payroll bank reconciliations, and HR department functions) and periodic review and ana", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Expense Reimbursement Schemes", "back": "• Mischaracterized expense reimbursements\n• Employees request reimbursement for a personal expense by claiming that the expense is business related.\n• Overstated expense reimbursements\n• Some employees overstate the cost of actual business expenses.\n• Fictitious expense reimbursements", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Expense Reimbursement Schemes", "back": "• Review and analyze expense accounts.\n• Two methods: historical comparisons or comparisons with budgeted amounts\n• Require detailed expense reports and conduct a close review of them.\n• Expense reports should contain the following information: 1. Receipts or other support documentation 2. Explanation of the expense, including specific business purpose", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Check Fraud Rings", "back": "• Check fraud rings thrive because the items needed to commit check fraud are easily obtainable and the cost is minimal.\n• Often, the only necessary equipment for a check fraud ring is a scanner, printer, and personal computer.\n• The chances of being arrested and prosecuted for check fraud are low, and the penalties are relatively mild in most jurisdictions.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Payment Card Fraud", "back": "• The misuse of credit or debit card information to make purchases without the cardholder’s authorization\n• Schemes are successful because it is unlikely that the fraudster will be caught and prosecution is not ensured.\n• Types of payment card fraud schemes\n• Unauthorized use of a lost or stolen payment card 1. Fraudulent activity normally occurs within hours of the loss or theft of a card, before most victims have called to report the loss.\n• This scheme often works in conjunction with a corrupt and collusive merchant or a merchant’s employee. 2. Other counterfeit cards are wholly manufactured using highspeed printers and are used in assoc", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prepaid Card Fraud", "back": "• Involves prepaid gift and debit cards, which are commonly used by those who do not have a bank account or who prefer relatively anonymous payment methods\n• Prepaid cards are attractive to fraudsters because they can be purchased at countless retailers and are difficult to track after they have been purchased and activated.\n• Among the schemes that prepaid cards are used to facilitate are payment (i.e., credit or debit) card theft schemes.\n• Thieves use stolen payment cards to purchase prepaid debit or gift cards, thus quickly converting the illicit payment card funds into a legitimate cash equivalent.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Smart Cards", "back": "• Plastic, credit-card-sized cards that are embedded with a microchip\n• These cards can identify the user through encrypted information on the chip and must be inserted into a card reader connected to the credit provider’s network.\n• Unlike regular magnetic stripe payment cards, smart cards cannot be easily replicated or counterfeited; thus, they are generally more secure.\n• Smart cards include a wide variety of hardware and software features capable of detecting and reacting to tampering attempts and countering possible attacks.\n• If someone tries to tamper with a chip on a smart card, the card detects the intrusion and shuts itself down, rendering the card useless.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Electronic Bill Payment and Person-to-Person Payments", "back": "• Automatic payments can be set up via a bank or credit card website to pay bills.\n• Individuals can pay each other for goods or services through the person-toperson (P2P) system.\n• An electronic funds transfer (EFT) is any transfer of funds, other than one originated by a check or similar paper instrument, that is initiated through an electronic terminal, telephonic instrument, \n• Examples of EFT fraud include: 1. A biller might send a bill for services not rendered or for goods never sent. 2. A person who has obtained information about another person’s bank account might instr", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Electronic Funds Transfer Fraud", "back": "• Specific safeguards that banks can perform to reduce the risk that they or their customers become victimized by unauthorized EFTs include:\n• Send a welcome letter to the address on the application with the bank’s return address so that the letter is returned if the applicant does not live there.\n• Always mail PINs separately from other information, such as usernames, with which they are associated.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Account Takeover Fraud", "back": "• Occurs when a fraudster surreptitiously takes control of a payment account (e.g., credit cards, banking, brokerage, or online retail accounts)\n• To take over an account, thieves obtain email addresses or other login information and use various means to obtain passwords, such as phishing emails or password-cracking botnet attacks.\n• Because consumers often use the same username and password for multiple accounts, hackers commonly write code that can run credentials obtained from a data breach at one company to see if they are val\n• Once the thief overtakes an account, communication methods and contact information are altered to keep the account holder unaware of the fraudulent activity, leaving the thief free to place orders usi", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Mobile Payments", "back": "• Typically made through contactless technology, such as digital wallets or applications—also known as in-app payments.\n• Common mobile payment applications include Apple Pay, Google Pay, Zelle, PayPal, Cash App, and Venmo.\n• Most mobile payments require users to authenticate themselves.\n• The technology in many mobile devices allows for biometric authentication, such as a partial fingerprint or three-dimensional facial scan, which is difficult for fraudsters to bypass.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Recognizing Computer Intrusion", "back": "• It is important for fraud examiners and other computer system users to recognize common signs that intruders have accessed or affected a computer system or network, such as:\n• Unusual inbound or outbound network traffic 1. Abnormal traffic, which includes emails and data transmitted to or from the internet, can be an indication that an attacker has gained access to an organ\n• Geographical irregularities related to network access and traffic\n• Contacts receiving strange messages from email accounts\n• Redirected web searches", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Conditions Conducive to Insider Cyberfraud", "back": "• Access privileges are beyond those required to perform assigned job functions.\n• Exception reports are not reviewed and resolved.\n• Access logs are not reviewed.\n• Production programs are run at unusual hours.\n• Lack of separation of duties exists in the data center.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods Used to Gain Unauthorized Access to a Computer System", "back": "• Social engineering\n• A method for gaining unauthorized access to a computer system in which the attacker deceives victims into disclosing personal information, such as their password, or convinces them to commit acts that\n• Business email compromise (BEC)\n• Scheme in which fraudsters target employees who can make large payments or who have access to sensitive proprietary information\n• Pharming 1. A type of attack in which users are fooled into entering sensitive data (such as a password or credit card number) into a malicious website that imitates a legitimate website 2. Different ", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Common Carriers of Malware", "back": "• Unknown or unchecked application software\n• Infected websites\n• Banner ads\n• Software or media that employees bring to work\n• Files downloaded from the internet", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Malware", "back": "• Worms\n• Computer programs that replicate themselves and penetrate operating systems to spread malicious code to other computers\n• Trojan horse\n• A program or command procedure that appears useful but contains hidden code that causes damage\n• Spyware", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Information Security Goals", "back": "• All branches of an information system, including the e-commerce branch, should strive to achieve the following information security goals for users and asset holders:\n• Confidentiality of data 1. The information involved in an information system transaction must only be accessible to authorized parties.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Technical Security and Controls", "back": "• Technical security involves the use of safeguards incorporated into computer hardware or systems, operations or applications software, communications hardware and software, and related devices.\n• Technical controls protect systems against threats like unauthorized use, disclosure, modification, destruction, or denial of service.\n• Common types include: 1. Logical access controls\n• Process by which users are identified and granted certain privileges to information, systems, or resources 2. Network security\n• Firewalls", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Administrative Security and Controls", "back": "• Administrative security consists of management constraints, operational procedures, accountability procedures, and supplemental administrative controls established to provide an acceptable level of pr\n• Administrative controls ensure safeguards against system and network infiltration on an organizational level.\n• Common types include: 1. Security policies and awareness training 2. Separation of duties\n• Achieved by diffusing the tasks and associated privileges for a specific security process among multiple individuals to ensure that no person acting alone can compromise security controls 3. Data clas\n• Describe the actions an organization will take when a data breach occurs.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "What Is Corruption?", "back": "• The wrongful use of influence to procure a benefit for the actor or another person, contrary to the duty or rights of others", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Forms of Corruption", "back": "• Bribery\n• The offering, giving, receiving, or soliciting of corrupt payments (i.e., items of value paid to procure a benefit contrary to the rights of others) to influence an official act or business decision\n• Kickbacks\n• Improper, undisclosed payments made to obtain favorable treatment\n• Illegal gratuities", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods of Making Corrupt Payments", "back": "• Gifts, travel, and entertainment\n• Cash payments\n• Checks and other financial instruments\n• Hidden interests\n• The payer might give a hidden interest in a joint venture or other profit-making enterprise.", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Corruption", "back": "• Three ways\n• Use an inside witness.\n• Suspected on-book schemes are best approached from the point of payment.\n• Off-book schemes are most easily identified at the suspected point of receipt, through the use of an inside witness, or through surveillance.", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Conflict of Interest", "back": "• Occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence their professional role", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods of Procurement", "back": "• Competitive bidding using sealed bids\n• Contracting by negotiation\n• Simplified acquisition procedures", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Phases in the Procurement Process", "back": "• The presolicitation phase\n• Need recognition\n• The solicitation phase\n• Bid solicitation\n• The bid evaluation and award phase", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "back": "• Complementary bidding\n• Competitors submit token bids that are not genuine attempts to win the contract.\n• Bid rotation\n• Two or more contractors conspire to alternate the business among themselves on a rotating basis.\n• Bid suppression", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Red Flags of Schemes Involving Collusion Among Contractors", "back": "• The industry has limited competition.\n• The same contractors bid on each project or product.\n• The winning bid appears too high.\n• All contractors submit consistently high bids.\n• The winning bidder subcontracts work to one or more losing bidders or to nonbidders.", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Schemes Involving Collusion Between Contractors and Employees", "back": "• Need recognition\n• Procurement employees convince their employer that it needs excessive or unnecessary products or services.\n• Bid tailoring\n• An employee with procurement responsibilities, often in collusion with a contractor, drafts bid specifications in a way that gives an unfair advantage to a certain contractor.\n• Bid manipulation", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Performance Schemes", "back": "• Nonconforming goods or services (product substitution)\n• Attempts by contractors to deliver goods or services to the procuring entity that do not conform to the underlying contract specifications\n• Cost mischarging\n• A contractor charges the procuring entity for costs that are not permissible, are not reasonable, or cannot be allocated to the contract directly or indirectly.\n• A contractor knowingly charges unallowable costs to the buyer by concealing or misrepresenting them as allowable costs, or by hiding them in accounts, such as office supplies, that are not usually clo", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Contract and Procurement Fraud", "back": "• Monitoring procurement activities\n• Companies should implement a continuous, self-auditing program to monitor the performance of their procurement activities.\n• Vendor management\n• Management should take steps to prevent and detect criminal conduct by its vendors, such as: 1. Vendor background checks\n• Management must conduct adequate due diligence to identify and select competent and qualified vendors, such as reviewing their business reputation, financial soundness, and experience. 2. Controls for", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Misuse of Inventory and Other Assets", "back": "• Two ways a person can misappropriate a company asset\n• The asset can be misused (or “borrowed”) (e.g., company vehicles, supplies, computers).", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Inventory Theft Schemes", "back": "• Larceny schemes\n• Larceny is “the wrongful and fraudulent taking and carrying away by one person of the mere personal goods of another from any place, with a felonious intent to convert them to his (the taker’s) use, a\n• Purchasing and receiving schemes\n• Dishonest employees can also manipulate a company’s purchasing and receiving functions to facilitate the theft of inventory and other assets.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Concealing Inventory Shrinkage", "back": "• When inventory is stolen, the perpetrator’s key concealment issue is shrinkage.\n• Inventory shrinkage is the unaccounted-for reduction in the company’s inventory that results from error or theft.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "back": "• Altered inventory records\n• Involves changing the perpetual inventory record so that it matches the physical inventory count\n• Fictitious sales and accounts receivable\n• When the perpetrator makes an adjusting entry to the perpetual inventory and cost of sales accounts, there is no sales transaction on the books that corresponds to these entries.\n• Write-off inventory", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Detection of Inventory Schemes", "back": "• Analytical review\n• Example: Sales and cost of goods sold should move together since they are directly related. However, if the cost of goods sold increases by a disproportionate amount in relation to sales and there hav", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention of Inventory Schemes", "back": "• Proper documentation\n• The following items should be prenumbered and controlled: 1. Purchase orders 2. Receiving reports 3. Perpetual records 4. Raw materials requisitions 5. Shipping documents 6. Job cost sheets\n• Separation of duties\n• Different personnel should be responsible for the following duties: 1. Requisition of inventory 2. Receipt of inventory 3. Disbursement of inventory 4. Conversion of inventory to scrap 5. Receipt of p\n• Independent checks", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Embezzlement Schemes", "back": "• False accounting entries\n• Employees debit the general ledger to credit their own accounts or conceal a theft from a customer account (i.e., employees adjust the general ledger to conceal the stolen amount).\n• Unauthorized withdrawals\n• Employees make unauthorized withdrawals from customer accounts.\n• Unauthorized disbursement of funds to outsiders", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Loan Fraud Schemes", "back": "• Double-pledging collateral\n• Borrowers pledge the same collateral (i.e., an item of value used to secure or guarantee a loan) with different lenders before liens are recorded without telling the lenders.\n• Reciprocal loan arrangements\n• Insiders in different banks cause their banks to lend funds or sell loans to other banks with agreements to buy their loans, which is done to conceal loans and sales.\n• Residential loan fraud", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Proof of developer contribution, if applicable", "back": "• High turnover in developer’s personnel\n• Typically, when a developer experiences a high degree of turnover, something is wrong with the internal operation.\n• Change order abuse\n• The key characteristic that fraud examiners should look for in change orders is abnormality. 1. An increase in the number of change orders or amounts on change orders might indicate that construction \n• Missing documentation", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Financial Institution Fraud", "back": "• Air loan\n• Loan for a nonexistent property\n• Fraudulent sale\n• The fraudulent acquisition of a homeowner’s property by filing a fraudulent deed or respective real estate document that makes it appear that the property legally belongs to the criminal; it might occ\n• Fraudulent second lien", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "New Account Fraud", "back": "• Fraud that occurs on an account within the first ninety days that it is open\n• Fraud is much more likely to occur in new accounts than in established accounts.\n• Some common methods of new account fraud include:\n• False identification", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Provider Fraud", "back": "• Practices by health care providers (including practitioners, medical suppliers, and medical institutions) that cause unnecessary costs to health care programs or patients through reimbursement for unn\n• Common types include:\n• Fictitious providers 1. Corrupt providers or other criminals fraudulently obtain and use another provider’s identification information and steal or purchase lists of patients’ identifying information.\n• Falsified prescriptions for DME\n• Intentionally providing excessive DME", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Inflated Billing Schemes", "back": "• Altered claims\n• Altering valid claims can be accomplished using a pen; photocopier; or scanner, computer, and printer. Common alterations include: 1. Amounts 2. Date of service 3. Name of patient\n• Added services\n• Some fraudsters add on services never rendered to dates of actual services.\n• Code manipulation schemes", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "If Correctly Billed", "back": "• Common types of patient fraud perpetrated against government health care programs and private insurers include:\n• Fictitious claims 1. Beneficiaries or insureds might attempt to perpetrate a fraud by submitting fictitious claims for medical services that did not occur or for nonexistent dependents.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud by Insurance Companies", "back": "• The following fraud schemes might occur in countries that offer private insurance:\n• Submission of false documents 1. If the insurance company works in tandem with government health care programs (e.g., by acting as an intermediary for the payer), then the insurance company commits fr\n• Requesting rate increases based on fraudulent data 1. Insurance companies or carriers needing regulatory approval for rate increases might use fraudulent cost data to justify their increases. The act ", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Agent/Broker Fraud", "back": "• Cash, loan, and dividend payments\n• A company employee requests cash, a loan, or a dividend payment without the knowledge of an insured or contract holder and either deposits the money into their bank account or a fictitious account.\n• Premium theft\n• An agent collects the premium but does not remit the payment to the insurance company. Thus, the insured unknowingly has no coverage available upon a qualifying event.\n• Fictitious death claims", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Vehicle Insurance Schemes", "back": "• Ditching\n• Disposing of a vehicle to collect on an insurance policy or to settle an outstanding loan\n• Sometimes, the scheme involves a homeowner’s insurance claim for property that was supposedly in the vehicle when it was “stolen.”\n• Past posting\n• A person is involved in an automobile accident but does not have insurance. After the accident, the person gets insurance, waits a short time, and then reports the vehicle as having been in an acciden", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Red Flags of Insurance Fraud", "back": "• The claim is made soon after the policy’s inception or after an increase or change in the coverage under which the claim is made.\n• The insured has a history of multiple insurance claims and losses.\n• The insured previously asked an insurance agent hypothetical questions about coverage in the event of a loss similar to the actual claim.\n• In a burglary loss, the claim includes large, bulky property, which is unusual for a burglary.\n• In a theft or fire loss claim, the claim includes a lot of recently purchased, expensive property, but the insured cannot provide receipts, owner’s manuals, or other documentary proof of purchase.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Computer-Generated Detection Tools", "back": "• Fraud examiners can use the following data analysis tools to detect insurance fraud schemes:\n• Address similarity reports 1. These reports electronically compare multiple payments going to the same address and might show a payment defalcation or funds going to another insurance company, broker,", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Overview of Behavioral Analysis", "back": "• Behavioral studies, such as those conducted by B. F. Skinner, show that:\n• Punishment is the least effective method of changing behavior.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Reinforcement vs. Punishment of Behaviors", "back": "• Reinforcement and punishment of behavior are distinguished by the way that positive and negative forces are applied.\n• Reinforcement 1. A positive reinforcement presents a positive stimulus in exchange for the desired response. 2. A negative reinforcement withdraws a negative stimulus in exchange for the response.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Conditioning Behaviors", "back": "• Skinner suggests conditioning incompatible behavior that interferes with a person’s undesired acts by encouraging the improper behavior’s opposite (e.g., by rewarding a child for controlling emotional\n• Destructive behaviors should be offset by incompatible productive ones.\n• Since fraud involves dishonesty, secrecy, and antagonistic behaviors, an astute manager finds ways to reward the opposite behaviors—honesty, openness, and cooperation.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Theories of Crime Causation", "back": "• Rational choice theory\n• Asserts that the decision to commit a crime is a rational and careful choice on the perpetrator’s part with the goal of an intended benefit\n• Routine activities theory\n• Asserts that both the motivation to commit crime and the supply of offenders is constant\n• If someone thinks it is likely that they will be caught or there is not a suitable target, then they are less likely to commit a crime.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "What Is White-Collar Crime?", "back": "• According to Albert J. Reiss, Jr., and Albert Biderman, “Those violations of law to which penalties are attached that involve the use of a violator’s position of economic power, influence, or trust in", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Organizational Opportunity", "back": "• The determinant aspect of white-collar crime\n• Organization and complexity make a larger difference than the offender’s social status.", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Contributing Factors to the Rise of White-Collar Crime", "back": "• The economy increasingly runs on credit, which often means an increase in personal debt.\n• New information technologies mean that the opportunity for wrongdoing is growing.\n• Government programs distributing large amounts of money make an enticing target for embezzlement.\n• There is an overarching culture based on affluence and ever-higher levels of success. Media sources, and advertising in general, promise that no one has to settle for second best.", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Referring White-Collar Criminals to Law Enforcement", "back": "• According to the ACFE’s Occupational Fraud 2022: A Report to the Nations, 58% of occupational fraud cases were referred to law enforcement for prosecution.\n• The study also found that of perpetrators who were disciplined internally, 61% were terminated, 12% were either placed on probation or suspended, and 11% were permitted or required to resign.\n• For organizations that chose to handle fraud cases internally instead of referring them to law enforcement for prosecution, 50% of companies declined to refer cases because they believed their organiz", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Organizational Crime", "back": "• Organizational vs. occupational crime\n• Organizational crime is that which is committed by businesses, particularly corporations, and the government.\n• Effect of organizational structure on criminal behavior\n• Complex companies are more prone to misbehavior due to isolation of departments and locations.\n• Criminogenic nature of organizations", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Occupational Fraud", "back": "• Donald R. Cressey’s findings\n• Came up with the Fraud Triangle model to explain why people commit fraud\n• Dr. Steve Albrecht’s findings\n• The most highly ranked factors from the list of personal characteristics that contribute to fraud were: 1. Living beyond their means 2. An overwhelming desire for personal gain 3. High personal debt 4\n• Findings from the ACFE’s Occupational Fraud 2022: A Report to the Nations", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "What Is Corporate Governance?", "back": "• Refers to a corporation’s government\n• Broadly used to describe the oversight responsibilities of different parties for an organization’s direction, operations, and performance\n• More specifically, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development’s (OECD) “Glossary of Statistical Terms” defines corporate governance as:\n• [The] procedures and processes according to which an organisation is directed and controlled. The corporate governance structure specifies the distribution of rights and responsibilities among the dif\n• Sir Adrian Cadbury, chairman of the committee that developed the foundational corporate governance guidance, The Cadbury Report, stated that the purpose of corporate governance is “to encourage the ef", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Parties Involved in Corporate Governance", "back": "• The board of directors\n• Made up of individuals who are generally elected by the entity’s voting members (e.g., shareholders in the case of a corporation or members in the case of an association)\n• Oversees business operations by assessing the strategy and underlying purpose of management’s decisions and actions\n• Management\n• Responsible for making the daily decisions that affect company performance and, ultimately, shareholder wealth", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Treadway Commission’s Audit Committee Recommendations", "back": "• The Treadway Commission was formed in the United States in 1985 with the purpose of defining the auditor’s responsibility in preventing and detecting fraud.\n• It made several major recommendations designed to reduce the probability of fraud in financial reports, including:\n• The board of directors should have a mandatory independent audit committee made up of outside directors.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Role of Corporate Governance in Fighting Fraud", "back": "• As stated in the Fraud Risk Management Guide, a joint publication by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) and the ACFE, fraud risk governance is one of the princ\n• Managing the Business Risk of Fraud: A Practical Guide, the predecessor to the Fraud Risk Management Guide, expands this point, noting, “Effective governance processes are the foundation of fraud risk", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Principles of Corporate Governance", "back": "• Accountability\n• To ensure that the organization operates effectively and efficiently, there must be mechanisms in place to ensure that management is accountable to the board and that the board is accountable to the s\n• Transparency\n• Refers to the clarity, accuracy, completeness, and timeliness of the financial statements and other information provided by management to shareholders\n• Fairness", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Establishing a Corporate Governance Framework", "back": "• The G20/OECD Principles of Corporate Governance state that “there is no single model of good corporate governance.”\n• Corporate governance structure and practices vary widely and should be determined based on each organization’s specific needs.\n• In developing a corporate governance framework for an organization, directors and management must consider the legal, regulatory, institutional, cultural, and ethical environments in which the company\n• Good corporate governance maintains the ability to find a different course when its current direction runs into barriers, such as changes in the corporate landscape, new regulations or legal requireme", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Sources of Corporate Governance Guidance", "back": "• Although there is not a universal law or set of rules for corporate governance, legislators, regulators, and other bodies around the world have issued guidance that provides best practices and require\n• In many jurisdictions, organizations—particularly those that are publicly traded—are subject to specific corporate governance requirements that might take the form of legislation or conditions set for\n• As a result, companies should be familiar with the existing guidance specific to all the regions in which they operate, and those charged with governance should ensure compliance with the laws and reg", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "G20/OECD Principles of Corporate Governance", "back": "• Regarded as one of the primary sources of guidance for corporate governance practices for organizations throughout the world\n• “Intended to help policymakers evaluate and improve the legal, regulatory, and institutional framework for corporate governance with a view to support economic efficiency, sustainable growth, and fina\n• Nonbinding, as their implementation must be adapted to different legal, economic, and cultural circumstances\n• This is a key strength of the Principles that makes them a useful tool worldwide, both in developed economies and in emerging markets.\n• Includes six broad principles:", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Overview of Management’s Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "back": "• Management is ultimately responsible for the prevention and detection of fraud within an organization.\n• Management holds the primary responsibility for:\n• Designing, implementing, overseeing, and ensuring the effectiveness of the anti-fraud program", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Management’s Responsibility for Internal Controls", "back": "• It is management’s job to ensure that the proper internal controls are in place to prevent and detect fraud.\n• Although management might not execute all the controls, management is also responsible for monitoring, assessing, and remediating the internal controls to ensure they are effectively designed and oper", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "COSO Internal Control—Integrated Framework", "back": "• Based on the Treadway Commission’s recommendations, the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) was formed to provide guidance for organizations’ internal controls.\n• COSO is responsible for issuing the Internal Control—Integrated Framework (the Framework), which is meant to apply to both public and private entities, regardless of size.\n• According to the Framework, “Internal control is a process, effected by an entity’s board of directors, management, and other personnel, designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the achievem\n• Operations objectives pertain to the effectiveness and efficiency of the organization’s operations.\n• To meet these objectives, the Framework identifies five interrelated components of internal control:", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "External Audit Standards Related to Fraud", "back": "• International Standard on Auditing (ISA) 240—The Auditor’s Responsibility Relating to Fraud in an Audit of Financial Statements\n• Purpose 1. To establish standards and provide guidance on the auditor’s responsibility to consider fraud in an audit of financial statements 2. To expand on how other auditing standards and guidance s\n• Misstatements arising from fraudulent financial reporting\n• Misstatements arising from the misappropriation of assets 3. For the purposes of the ISAs, the auditor is concerned with fraud that causes a material misstatement in the financial statements.\n• According to the ISAs, “Information is material if omitting, misstating or obscuring it could reasonably be expected to influence the decisions that the primary users of general purpose financial stat", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Internal Audit Standards Related to Fraud", "back": "• IIA Standard 1210—Proficiency\n• Internal auditors must possess the knowledge, skills, and other competencies needed to perform their individual responsibilities.\n• IIA Standard 1220—Due Professional Care\n• Internal auditors must apply the care and skill expected of a reasonably prudent and competent internal auditor.\n• IIA Standard 2060—Reporting to Senior Management and the Board", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The IIA’s IPPF—Practice Guide: Internal Audit and Fraud", "back": "• The Practice Guide states that, in conducting audit engagements, the internal auditor should:\n• Evaluate the organization’s structures and process for fraud risk governance.\n• Report to senior management and the board on the adequacy and effectiveness of the fraud risk governance and management at an engagement and organization-wide level.\n• The Practice Guide also provides guidance about the internal audit function’s role in communicating any significant fraud risk, control, and governance issues with senior management and the board of d\n• Is fraud risk management comprehensive, continuous, and aligned with the organization’s strategic objectives?", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Government Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "back": "• The International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI) operates as an umbrella organization for the external government audit community and\n• INTOSAI provides high-quality standards in the form of International Standards of Supreme Audit Institutions (ISSAI) for the public sector to promote good governance.\n• ISSAI 1240 provides supplementary guidance regarding the applicability of ISA 240 to public-sector financial statement audits.\n• States that ISA 240 is applicable to auditors of public-sector entities in their role as auditors of financial statements and includes several specific considerations in applying ISA 240 to public-sec\n• The objectives of a financial audit in the public sector are often broader than expressing an opinion as to whether the financial statements have been prepared, in all material respects, in accordance", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "What Is Fraud Risk?", "back": "• The vulnerability that an organization faces from individuals capable of combining all three elements of the Fraud Triangle", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Inherent and Residual Fraud Risk", "back": "• Risks that are present before the effect of internal controls (including targeted anti-fraud controls) are described as inherent risks.\n• Risks that remain after the effect of these controls are described as residual risks.\n• The objective of an organization’s anti-fraud controls is to reduce the residual risk to a level that is significantly lower than the inherent risk.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Factors That Influence Fraud Risk in an Organization", "back": "• The nature of the business in which it is engaged\n• The environment in which it operates\n• The effectiveness of its anti-fraud controls\n• A good system of anti-fraud controls, with the right balance of preventive and detective controls, can greatly reduce an organization’s vulnerability to fraud. 1. Preventive controls stop something ba\n• The ethics and values of the company and its employees", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "back": "• An ongoing, continuous process aimed at proactively identifying and addressing an organization’s vulnerabilities to both internal and external fraud\n• What gets evaluated and how it gets assessed should be tailored to the organization, as there is not an approach that is suited to all organizations.\n• The objective of a fraud risk assessment is to help an organization recognize what makes it most vulnerable to fraud.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Why Organizations Should Conduct Fraud Risk Assessments", "back": "• To improve communication and awareness about fraud\n• A fraud risk assessment can be an effective way for an organization to start communication and raise awareness about fraud.\n• To identify where the company is most vulnerable to fraud and what activities put it at the greatest risk\n• Management must know where the company is most vulnerable to fraud to prevent it from happening.\n• To know who puts the organization at the greatest risk", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Elements of a Good Fraud Risk Assessment", "back": "• Collaborative effort of management and auditors\n• The fraud risk assessment is most effective when management and auditors share ownership of the process and accountability for its success.\n• The right sponsor\n• The sponsor must be senior enough in the organization to command the employees’ respect and elicit full cooperation in the process.\n• Independence and objectivity of the people leading and conducting the work", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "back": "• Assemble a multi-disciplinary team to lead and conduct the fraud risk assessment.\n• The team should consist of individuals with diverse knowledge, skills, and perspectives to lead and conduct the assessment.\n• Identify the information to be gathered and determine the most effective techniques to use in conducting the fraud risk assessment.\n• Information to be gathered includes: 1. The identification of inherent fraud risks 2. Discussion of past known fraud incidents and how they were handled\n• Obtain the sponsor’s agreement on:", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Identifying Potential Inherent Fraud Risks and Schemes", "back": "• Brainstorm to identify the inherent fraud risks that could apply to the organization.\n• Brainstorming should include discussions regarding:\n• Incentives, pressures, and opportunities to commit fraud\n• Fraudulent financial reporting (e.g., inappropriately reported revenues, expenses, assets, or liabilities)\n• Asset misappropriation (e.g., theft of tangible or intangible assets)", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Identifying and Mapping Existing Preventive and Detective Controls to the", "back": "• Preventive controls\n• Intended to prevent fraud before it occurs\n• Detective controls\n• Intended to detect fraud if it does occur", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Ways Management Can Respond to Residual Fraud Risks", "back": "• Avoid the risk.\n• Management might decide to avoid the risk by eliminating an asset or discontinuing an activity if the control measures required to protect the organization against an identified threat are too expensi\n• Transfer the risk.\n• Management might transfer some or all of the risk by purchasing fidelity insurance or a fidelity bond.\n• Mitigate the risk.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "back": "• The success of the fraud risk assessment process depends on how effectively the results are reported and what management then does with those results.\n• When reporting the results of the assessment:\n• Report only the facts, and keep all opinions and biases out of the report.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Making an Impact with the Fraud Risk Assessment", "back": "• Management should use the assessment results to:\n• Begin a dialogue across the company.\n• Modify or create the code of conduct or ethics policy.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Fraud Risk Assessment and the Audit Process", "back": "• The fraud risk assessment should play a significant role in informing and influencing the audit process.\n• The fraud risk assessment should motivate thinking and awareness in the development of audit programs for areas that have been identified as having a moderate-to-high risk of fraud.\n• Auditors should validate that the organization is appropriately managing the moderate-to-high fraud risks identified in the fraud risk assessment by:\n• Identifying and mapping the existing preventive and detective controls that pertain to the moderate-to-high fraud risks identified in the fraud risk assessment", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "What Is Risk Management?", "back": "• In Enterprise Risk Management—Integrating with Strategy and Performance, the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) defines enterprise risk management (ERM) as “the cu\n• Involves the identification, prioritization, treatment, and monitoring of risks that threaten an organization’s ability to provide value to its stakeholders\n• Involves balancing risk appetite—how much risk management is willing to accept—with the ability to meet the organization’s strategic, operational, reporting, and compliance objectives", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "COSO Enterprise Risk Management—Integrating with Strategy and Performance", "back": "• Composed of a set of principles organized into five components and twenty supporting principles that are based on a holistic view of an organization’s risk portfolio\n• The five components are:\n• Governance and culture 1. The organization’s governance and culture form the foundation for the ERM program. 2. Governance sets the organizational tone, reinforces the importance of risk management, a\n• Under this component, the organization:\n• Assesses substantial changes that might affect its strategy and objectives", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "ISO 31000", "back": "• The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) has developed ISO 31000:2018, a set of international standards providing principles and guidance on risk management.\n• The following eight ISO 31000:2018 principles provide that an effective and efficient risk management program:\n• Is integrated into all organizational activities\n• Is dynamic and responsive to change", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Managing Third-Party Fraud Risks", "back": "• To protect themselves from risks, it is important for organizations to implement proper due diligence procedures and compliance requirements when engaging in transactions with third parties, such as v\n• Customer due diligence (CDD)\n• There are three levels of due diligence procedures that organizations can use based on the level of risk a potential customer presents. 1. Simplified CDD\n• The lowest level of due diligence\n• Most appropriate in situations where there is little opportunity or risk of a customer engaging in illegal activity", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Who Is Responsible for Managing Fraud Risk?", "back": "• According to the Fraud Risk Management Guide, a joint publication by COSO and the ACFE, “personnel at all levels of the organization—including every level of management, staff, and internal auditors—h", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "back": "• Recognize the true and specific risks of fraud to the organization, as well as their potential impact, and respond by:\n• Setting an appropriate tone and realistic expectations of management to enforce an anti-fraud culture\n• Overseeing the organization’s fraud risk management activities", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Audit Committee’s Role", "back": "• Oversee the organization’s financial, accounting, and audit matters and report to the full board of directors.\n• Actively oversee the assessment and monitoring of the organization’s fraud risks by:\n• Receiving regular reports on the status of reported or alleged fraud\n• Providing external auditors with evidence that the audit committee is dedicated to effective fraud risk management", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Senior Management’s Role", "back": "• Hold the primary responsibility for designing, implementing, monitoring, and improving the fraud risk management program, which involves:\n• Being extremely familiar with the organization’s fraud risks\n• Taking all reports of fraud seriously and undertaking investigations for any such reports deemed reliable", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Objectives of a Fraud Risk Management Program", "back": "• Fraud risk management programs must address fraud before, during, and after it occurs.\n• Such programs must incorporate policies and procedures designed to prevent, detect, and respond to fraud.\n• Fraud prevention 1. Activities focus on proactively identifying and assessing fraud risks and taking steps to address those risks.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Risk Management Principles", "back": "• To help meet the objectives of a fraud risk management program, the Fraud Risk Management Guide describes five broad principles of fraud risk management:\n• Fraud risk governance 1. The organization establishes and communicates a fraud risk management program that demonstrates the expectations of the board of directors and senior management and their comm\n• Fraud risk management monitoring activities 1. The organization selects, develops, and performs ongoing evaluations to ascertain whether each of the five principles of fraud risk management is present", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Developing a Fraud Risk Management Program", "back": "• Define program objectives.\n• Tailor detailed objectives of the fraud risk management program to the organization’s specific needs and goals.\n• Define risk appetite.\n• Without an adequate understanding and articulation of just how much risk those charged with governance are willing to accept, any stated objectives of the fraud risk management program will be inaccur\n• Examine previous fraud incidents.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Procedures and Mechanisms to Prevent Fraud", "back": "• Increasing the perception of detection\n• Most experts agree that it is much easier to prevent fraud than to detect it.\n• Proactive audit procedures\n• Can be used to demonstrate management’s intention to aggressively look for possible fraudulent conduct instead of waiting for instances to be reported\n• Employee anti-fraud education", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Creating an Anti-Fraud Policy", "back": "• A written anti-fraud policy should specifically indicate who in an organization manages varying fraud matters under differing circumstances.\n• Among other things, the anti-fraud policy might include:\n• A policy statement that formally defines fraud and outlines management’s position or attitude toward fraud in the workplace", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Communicating the Anti-Fraud Policy", "back": "• Management must periodically and appropriately communicate the company’s anti-fraud policy to all employees and third parties.", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Legal Considerations Regarding the Anti-Fraud Policy", "back": "• It is best to detail specific unacceptable conduct to avoid legal problems in terminating a dishonest employee.\n• Management should consult legal counsel regarding any necessary legal considerations with respect to the anti-fraud policy.\n• One of the most important legal considerations is to ensure that all allegations and offenders are managed uniformly.", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Developing an Ethics Program", "back": "• A written ethics policy enables management to objectively communicate its ethical philosophy and provides a foundation for a successful ethics program.\n• Should be shared among both new and old employees\n• Key considerations when developing an ethics program include:\n• Understanding why good people can commit unethical acts\n• Ascertaining how board members, stockholders, management, employees, and any other important members of the organization define success", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Developing an Effective Corporate Compliance and Ethics Program", "back": "• An effective compliance program can be defined as one that is reasonably designed, implemented, and enforced so that it generally will be effective in preventing and detecting criminal conduct.\n• To have an effective compliance and ethics program, the organization should:\n• Exercise due diligence to prevent and detect criminal conduct.\n• Elements of an effective compliance and ethics program\n• The following seven factors are minimally required for a corporate compliance program to be considered effective: 1. Established standards and procedures to prevent and detect criminal conduct 2. Prop", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Purpose of a Code of Ethical Conduct", "back": "• Serves as a reference and benchmark for ethical guidance\n• Makes explicit the conduct that is expected in a particular profession\n• Provides direct solutions not available from general ethics theories\n• Enables individuals to have a better understanding of what is expected of them\n• Makes practical enforcement and internal discipline throughout a profession easier because members are put on notice of the standards", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Ethics and Legality", "back": "• Ethics refers to the appropriateness of a decision in consideration of morality. That is, ethics stress standards or codes of behavior expected by the group to which the individual belongs.\n• Legality refers to lawfulness by conformity to a legal statute.\n• The law is the lowest reference level for moral decisions.\n• The law might permit an action that is prohibited by a profession’s code of ethics.", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "ACFE Code of Professional Ethics", "back": "• An ACFE Member shall, at all times, demonstrate a commitment to professionalism and diligence in the performance of their duties.\n• Diligence 1. Exercised by properly planning assignments and supervising assistants and colleagues, avoiding conflicts of interest, performing with competence, obtaining sufficient evidence to establis\n• An ACFE Member shall not engage in any illegal or unethical conduct, or any activity which would constitute a conflict of interest that has not been properly disclosed to the appropriate parties.\n• Illegal conduct 1. While some activities might be obviously illegal, the legality of others might not be as apparent. 2. Fraud examiners are generally not entitled to claim ignorance of the law.\n• A fraud examiner employed full time by a company should not engage in other jobs that create a hardship or loss to the employer.", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Define: Bulk-cash smuggling, which", "back": "smuggling of cash out of the country where it was earned for deposit in foreign jurisdictions with lax financial institutions or to fund criminal enterprises, is also on the rise. The rise in bulk-cash smuggling is due to the increasingly effective AML policies and procedures at financial institutions. In typical bulk-cash smuggling operations,", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Over- And Under-Invoicing Schemes", "back": "In over- and under-invoicing schemes, importers and exporters conspire to misrepresent the price of the goods or services being traded, thus transferring additional value between the importer and exporter. These schemes can be used to create a complex paper trail for the colluding parties to launder illicit funds. The amount available to launder is the difference between the market value of the goods and the invoiced amount.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Over- And Under-Shipment Schemes", "back": "Like over- and under-invoicing schemes, over- and under-shipment schemes can be used to create a complex paper trail for the colluding parties to launder money. In an over-shipment scheme, money launderers understate the quantity of goods that are shipped. More goods are shipped than the company invoices for. For example, Company A invoices 100,000 widgets to Company B at a price of one dollar per widget. However, Company A", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Duplicate Invoicing Scheme", "back": "In a duplicate invoicing scheme, the exporter issues more than one invoice for the same trade transaction. By issuing duplicate invoices, a money launderer can justify multiple payments for the same goods or services.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "False Descriptions In Invoices", "back": "Money launderers can conceal their illicit funds by misrepresenting the quality or type of goods or services provided. For example, an exporter can substitute products or materials of lesser quality than specified in the invoice; use lower quality staff than specified; use counterfeit, defective, or used parts to produce goods; or make any other deliberate departures specified in the invoice.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Black Market Peso Exchange", "back": "Among the most notorious of trade-based money laundering operations is the Black Market Peso Exchange, a scheme where brokers purchase proceeds from narcotics in the United States from cartels and exchange them for clean pesos in Colombia.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Red Flags Of Trade-Based Money Laundering", "back": "Some red flags of trade-based money laundering schemes include: • The goods or services traded seem unrelated to the usual business of the importer • The shipping route is unusual, passing through one or more countries for no • The goods or services do not match the description, value, quantity, or quality stated in", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: assets in their own right. As", "back": "case with most assets, they can become part of a money laundering scheme. Due to the recent growth in the financial products offered by insurance agents and brokers (including savings products, investment products, and tax planning services), the insurance industry has become increasingly attractive to money launderers. One", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Legal Systems", "back": "Under the FATF Recommendations, countries should adopt legislation that effectively criminalizes acts of money laundering and establishes the widest possible range of predicate offenses. In reference to money laundering, a predicate offense is a crime whose proceeds must be converted into a legitimate form. At a minimum, every serious offense should constitute a predicate offense, regardless of where it is committed. In addition, countries", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Financial Institutions And Related Professions", "back": "The FATF Recommendations were revised over time to set stricter guidelines for financial institutions and professionals who are routinely involved in substantial financial transactions. Such professionals specifically include casinos, real estate agents, lawyers, and dealers in precious metals and precious stones. The measures address customer due diligence (CDD), reporting suspicious transactions, deterring money laundering and terrorist financing, and", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Anti-Money Laundering Programs", "back": "Under the FATF Recommendations, countries should require financial institutions to implement AML and terrorist financing programs. A financial institution’s AML program is highly dependent on which jurisdictions it operates in, as well as the services that it offers. Generally, financial institutions should adopt the AML policies and procedures in the FATF Recommendations, but they need to tailor their programs to the requirements of the specific", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Customer Due Diligence", "back": "The FATF Recommendations set out the fundamental measures that financial institutions must take to identify and verify the identity of customers and beneficial owners. Although it is most important to conduct due diligence when a business relationship is first established, due diligence should be exercised on an ongoing basis. These requirements set firm, more detailed standards while also providing flexibility and allowing adaptation to new industry", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Deterring Money Laundering And Terrorist Financing", "back": "Within certain limits, countries and institutions are free to determine the extent of measures appropriate to the specific risk of money laundering or terrorist financing they face. However, all countries are required to (1) establish an FIU to receive reports regarding suspicious transactions, (2) designate law enforcement agencies for AML/CFT investigations, and (3) involve financial supervisors in AML/CFT initiatives. These authorities should have", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reporting Of Suspicious Transactions", "back": "Under the FATF’s Recommendation 20, a financial institution should be required to file a report when it “suspects or has reasonable grounds to suspect that funds are the proceeds of a criminal activity, or are related to terrorist financing.” Some jurisdictions also set additional requirements for reporting suspicious transactions, such as if a cash transaction surpasses a certain threshold amount. The name of these reports varies by jurisdiction, but they are", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Regulation And Supervision", "back": "All countries need adequate measures to ensure that financial institutions and other businesses and professions are complying with their obligations. The required measures take into account the risks and the regulatory structures that already exist in the relevant sectors. • Financial institutions and casinos should not be owned or managed by criminals. • The measures applicable to banks, insurance, and securities firms for prudential purposes", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Large Cash Transactions", "back": "Under the best practices provided in the FATF Recommendations, countries should implement a reporting requirement for financial institutions and DNFBPs that engage in cash transactions above the jurisdiction’s designated threshold. The reports should cover domestic and international cash transactions. Many jurisdictions implement this reporting requirement.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Cross-Border Transfer Of Currency", "back": "Under the FATF’s Recommendation 32, countries should implement disclosure requirements for individuals who are physically carrying currency or currency equivalents (i.e., bearer instruments) into or out of the country in amounts that are above the country’s designated reporting threshold. Generally, individuals who are carrying currency or the equivalent above the reporting threshold while attempting to cross jurisdictional borders should be required to", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "International Cooperation", "back": "The FATF Recommendations contain several provisions that address international cooperation. Notably, the Recommendation on mutual legal assistance covers several concepts that are in the 25 Non-Cooperative Countries and Territories Criteria discussed below. The most significant provisions deal with cooperation between administrative and law enforcement authorities concerned with combating money laundering and terrorist", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: efforts. The most prevalent", "back": "Anti-Money Laundering Directive (now in its sixth iteration and referred to as the Sixth Directive). The Sixth Directive applies to the financial sector as well as to lawyers, notaries, accountants, real estate agents, casinos, and company service providers. Its scope also encompasses all providers of goods when cash payments are made or received in", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "New Deposit Accounts", "back": "For individual deposit accounts, minimum identification standards should be established. The information to be obtained should include:", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "New Loan Accounts", "back": "An institution should perform due diligence in establishing a new loan account because, if the customer is engaged in money laundering, there is a risk of forfeiture of collateral pledged on the loans. Real or personal property that is traceable to drug sales or that is purchased with laundered funds is subject to seizure by the government. If the property seized is pledged as collateral, the financial institution must prove that it was an innocent lienholder of the", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Appendix A: Engagement And Advisory Letters", "back": "Fraud Examination Engagement Letters Fraud Examination Advisory Letters", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: entitled to pretrial discovery. Discovery", "back": "the formal process whereby the parties collect evidence and learn the details of the opposing side’s case, and pretrial discovery is intended to clarify the claim against the defendant, and to permit each side to examine the evidence that will be used in court by the other side.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: whereas in inquisitorial processes, the judge", "back": "driving force. In other words, instead of the parties seeking evidence from each other, the judge seeks evidence from the parties and", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In general, the term remedy", "back": "any process, procedure, or consequence of a legal wrong by which a victim can be redressed for their loss. Thus, if the defendant is found liable in a civil case, the remedy to which the plaintiff is entitled must be considered.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: loss. Submitting a timely proof of loss", "back": "responsibility of the insured; the carrier will not conduct nor assist in any investigation efforts to obtain proof of a loss, and the carrier will not reimburse the investigative or legal costs that the insured incurred in making a claim. Most policies have express subrogation provisions providing that if the insurance company", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Arbitration", "back": "process whereby a dispute is submitted to an impartial third person (known as an arbitrator) who then decides the outcome of the case (i.e., which party should win). The Civil Justice System The arbitrator acts as a judge or jury by deciding the case on its merits. Arbitration can be", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Basic Principles Of Evidence", "back": "In general, evidence consists of anything that can be used to prove something. In a legal sense, evidence refers to the testimony, documents, exhibits, and other tangible objects offered to prove or disprove the existence of an alleged fact during court proceedings. In legal systems, the use of evidence is often regulated by an intricate set of principles that have been developed and refined over hundreds of years, designed to ensure that only", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Real evidence", "back": "physical objects that played a part in the issues being litigated. The term includes both documentary evidence—such as canceled checks, invoices, ledgers, and letters—as well as other types of physical evidence. Therefore, a printer in a case involving questioned documents is clearly real evidence, as is a tape recording since members of the", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Demonstrative Evidence", "back": "Demonstrative evidence refers to a tangible item that illustrates some material proposition. It differs from real evidence in that demonstrative evidence is not part of the underlying event; it is created specifically for the trial. Its purpose is to provide a visual aid for the jury. An exhibit used for purely “illustrative purposes” is a type of demonstrative evidence. Demonstrative evidence includes charts, graphs, and summaries that help to simplify", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Business Records And Other Documents", "back": "Business records can encompass a broad range of documents, from all sorts of organizations, including corporations, small businesses, nonprofit operations, and community groups. Like other evidence, a party offering business records must provide testimony that the exhibit is the business record in question. For proper authentication, the party offering the evidence should be able to establish the following two things:", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Government Documents", "back": "The requirements for government documents are the same as for other business records. The distinction between government and business records arose because of narrow interpretations of the law that separated nonprofit from for-profit enterprises. Today, most records, regardless of origin, are called business records.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Phone Records", "back": "To be admitted into evidence, phone records typically must meet the same authentication", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Digital Records", "back": "Courts typically accept digital files and documents as evidence. In fact, courts themselves are using more digital resources because many aspects of litigation can now be conducted Generally, to be admissible, digital records must meet the same authentication standards as hard copy records (i.e., to show that the item is what the proponent claims). Thus, to prove that a particular electronic record is authentic, those offering the evidence must demonstrate", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Text And Instant Messages", "back": "As the use of text and instant messages continues to grow, parties are offering these types of records as evidence in an increasing number of cases. The most likely methods to authenticate text and instant messages are: • Witness with personal knowledge (e.g., a witness testifies that they recognize a copy of messages that they received or drafted)", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Website Data", "back": "As with all evidence, the proponent of website evidence must be prepared to establish that the evidence is authentic. In some courts, authenticity can be established by the testimony of a witness. Like any other demonstrative exhibit, parties can authenticate a website with the testimony of a witness who verifies that the exhibit at issue accurately reflects what they observed after logging on to the site and reviewing what was there.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Photographs", "back": "Concerning the admissibility of photographs, it is necessary to establish their fidelity to the object they claim to represent. This means that the offering party must prove that the picture is unaltered and shows what the proponent claims it shows. Generally, it is enough to have a witness familiar with the object or space in a photo to corroborate it (e.g., “Yes, that is the hallway running between our two buildings.”). The matter gets more complicated when a", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: of the individual who", "back": "subject of the evidence. Similarly, juries might afford character evidence too much weight, or they might choose to punish a defendant for perceived bad character, rather than actual guilt. Additionally, character evidence is subject to Basic Principles of Evidence", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Show the accused’s ability and", "back": "of committing the crime (possession of a weapon, tool, or skill used in the commission of the act). Show the accused’s opportunity to commit the crime. Show threats or expressions of ill will by the accused.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Overview Of The Legal System", "back": "By its nature, fraud examination is a law-intensive field. Legal issues related to fraud are often complex, and their interpretation might require professional legal assistance. CFEs should always consult with legal advisors if legal questions arise during a fraud examination. Even with the availability of legal guidance, however, a fraud examiner should be familiar with certain aspects of the law. Often, the success of an investigation hinges on the fraud", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Constitutional law", "back": "body of law established by a sovereignty’s constitution, and it deals with the fundamental principles by which a government exercises its authority. Constitutions are government charters. They establish and empower the various branches of government, and they set up the rights and obligations of individuals under the", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: International law", "back": "body of legal rules, regulations, and accepted practices observed by nations, and it defines nations’ legal responsibilities in their conduct with each other and with private individuals and transnational companies. International law is enforced primarily through diplomacy and for reasons of courtesy or expediency.", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: criminal law. Civil law", "back": "body of law that provides remedies for violations of private rights, and a civil action is a legal action that does not result in a criminal fine or incarceration. A civil suit in this context has nothing to do with whether the legal system used by the particular government is a civil law jurisdiction or a common law jurisdiction. Most often, civil refers to", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Adversarial Processes", "back": "Adversarial processes are those in which the parties to a proceeding drive the discovery process (the search for evidence). The theory behind this approach is that the competing interests of the parties will serve to expose the relevant facts of the case. In adversarial systems, the parties to the litigation gather and present the evidence to the court. For example, the parties (usually through legal counsel) conduct questioning of fact", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Inquisitorial Processes", "back": "An inquisitorial process refers to a fact-finding approach that places the primary responsibility of discovering evidence on the presiding judge. In an inquisitorial process, the primary goal is to find the truth. Rather than serving as a referee over the parties’ production of evidence, the judge is actively involved in discovery. For instance, judges may request relevant documents on their own accord and ask factual", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Role Of Juries", "back": "While juries can be found in both adversarial and inquisitorial jurisdictions, most adversarial jurisdictions actively use juries as the fact-finding body, while the judge decides issues of law. However, some cases in adversarial jurisdictions (often called bench trials) are decided factually The judge in an inquisitorial process both serves as the traditional fact finder and makes determinations on issues of law. However, some inquisitorial systems use juries, laypersons,", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: and decide a given case; it", "back": "both the subject matter and people over which lawful authority may be exercised by a court. For instance, a country might have a system of probate courts that only have jurisdiction to hear cases whose subject matter is related to wills, Overview of the Legal System", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Principle Of Offset", "back": "One of the features of commodity futures markets that make them so liquid and cost effective is the principle of offset. In a futures contract, the delivery or sale of the product is assumed, and the investor has an obligation to fulfill the contract; therefore, buying or selling a futures contract does not necessarily mean that the investor will accept or make delivery of the actual commodity itself. But the obligation of the buyer (to accept future delivery) and the", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The primary", "back": "of fulfilling one’s obligation under a future’s contract is to enter into an offsetting contract. An off-setting contract is one in which a purchase (sale) of futures contracts is liquidated through the sale (purchase) of an equal number of futures contracts with the same delivery month, thus closing out a position. This legally cancels the outstanding obligation. Each futures exchange has its own clearing organization that provides clearing services with", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: respect to futures contracts. Clearing", "back": "process by which a clearing organization acts as a third-party intermediary to futures contracts and assumes the role of the buyer and seller in such contracts so that it can reconcile the orders between the transacting parties. That is, the clearing organization matches futures transactions and becomes counterparty to", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Trading On Margin", "back": "Futures are traded on margin, which is the initial amount of money that is invested by both buyers and sellers of futures contracts to ensure performance on the terms of the contract (the making or taking delivery of the commodity or the cancellation of the contract by a subsequent offsetting trade). A margin in futures is not a down payment, as in securities, but rather a performance bond. A buyer puts up an initial margin at the time a futures market", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Trading Basics", "back": "A trader who buys futures contracts (assuming this is not an offsetting transaction) is long in the market and will profit if prices rise (e.g., if a trader bought a December corn contract at $2.70 per bushel and the price rose to $2.80 per bushel, they would have an unrealized profit of $500 [10 cents x 5,000 bushels]). Because open commodity positions (transactions that are not offset) are marked to market at the end of the trading day, this $500 profit will", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The transaction counterpart of the long buyer", "back": "short seller. Using the previous example, if the trader sold a December corn contract at $2.70 per bushel and the price rose to $2.80 per bushel, they would have an unrealized loss of $500 (.10 cents x 5,000 bushels). Again, open commodity positions are marked to market at the end of the trading day, meaning that", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: value of the underlying", "back": "main (but not only) factor from which the option contract", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: date. A put option", "back": "right, but not the obligation, to sell the underlying security at the strike (exercise) price by the option’s expiration date.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In options transactions, the seller of a call option", "back": "call writer, while the seller of the put option is the put writer. Option buyers pay a premium to option writers for the options they buy. Option writers (sellers) collect this premium for the options they write and are obligated to deliver the underlying security if the option is exercised.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Relationship Of The Underlying Security To An Option", "back": "Options are derivatives; therefore, their value is derived primarily from the value of their underlying instruments. For example, XYZ common stock closed today at $88.29 per share and the strike prices of the October 2008 XYZ calls ranged from $65 per share to $135 per share. The more that the share price of XYZ is above a particular strike price, the greater the value of that option. The stock price of $88 per share is about $23 over the strike price of the", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Option Values And Premiums", "back": "There are two values that make up option premiums: intrinsic value and time value. To have any intrinsic value, an option must be in the money. Out of the money options have only time value. Returning to the previous example, the XYZ $85 call closed today at a premium of $5.70 per share. This call option is $3 in the money because the underlying XYZ stock closed above the strike price at $88 per share. The premium has $3 intrinsic value, while", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Over-The-Counter Options", "back": "Again, options can be traded OTC. A security that does not trade on a major exchange is said to trade OTC. Unlike the floor trading in physical exchanges, OTC trading is conducted electronically, through direct contact with a market maker, or through communication among professional buyers and sellers. Banks, large brokerage firms, insurance companies, and many other businesses are active in the OTC options markets.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: requirement", "back": "the success of the investor is dependent on the efforts and success of those seeking the investment of third parties (typically the promoter). The third party, who provides the entrepreneurial skill, shares in the profits (or losses) with the investor. The investment was made with expectations of making a profit. Profit is generally defined as either", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The most disturbing aspect of this case", "back": "severe handicap investigators faced because of jurisdictional questions. “This could be a monumental scam that will be nearly impossible to prosecute,” said a private investigator working on the case. “No one really has jurisdiction. The salting [of the gold samples] took place in Indonesia, but what laws were really broken", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Motive And Expectation", "back": "First, consider the issuer and buyer’s primary motives. If the issuer’s primary motive is to raise money for the general use of a business enterprise, then the note may be a security. Is the buyer motivated to make a loan or an investment-type transaction? What is a reasonable investor thinking? What are their expectations?", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Plan Of Distribution", "back": "Second, consider the plan of distribution. If there is some form of common trading, a security", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Regulation", "back": "Third, determine if there is some other regulatory system that significantly reduces the risk of the transaction, thereby rendering it unnecessary to apply the securities laws. If the transaction is deemed appropriately regulated in ways other than through the application of the securities laws, then it is less likely that securities laws will apply. Securities Laws and Regulations Securities regulation refers to laws, rules, and procedures enacted by a legislative body and", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Securities regulation", "back": "laws, rules, and procedures enacted by a legislative body and administered by dedicated agencies that govern the way in which companies, consumers, and financial professionals behave when trading securities. To be effective, securities regulation must balance the legitimate needs of businesses to raise", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Securities exchanges are largely self-regulatory, which", "back": "that they regulate themselves. That is, self-regulatory exchanges exercise some degree of authority to create and enforce industry regulations and standards in the markets they organize. Although exchanges have regulatory authority, they are also regulated entities to the extent that they are subject to", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Overview Of The Iosco Principles Of Securities Regulation", "back": "The IOSCO Principles are based on the following three objectives: • Ensuring that markets are fair, efficient, and transparent • The reduction of systemic risk There are local differences in market structures; however, these objectives form a basis for an effective system of securities regulation. Although members pledge to implement IOSCO standards in their home countries, the", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Protection Of Investors", "back": "Investors should be protected from misleading, manipulative, or fraudulent practices, including insider trading, front running or trading ahead of customers, and the misuse of Full disclosure of information material to investors’ decisions is the most important means for ensuring investor protection. Investors are, therefore, better able to assess the potential risks and rewards of their investments and, as a result, to protect their own interests. As key", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: dispute resolution) or", "back": "of redress and compensation for improper behavior. Effective supervision and enforcement depend upon close cooperation between regulators at the domestic and international levels.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Reduction Of Systemic Risk", "back": "Although regulators cannot be expected to prevent the financial failure of market intermediaries, regulation should aim to reduce the risk of failure (including through capital and internal control requirements). Where financial failure nonetheless does occur, regulation should seek to reduce the impact of that failure, and, in particular, attempt to isolate the risk Market intermediaries should, therefore, be subject to adequate and ongoing capital and other", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Revised Principles For Securities Regulations", "back": "In response to the global financial crisis that began in 2008, IOSCO published a revised version of the IOSCO Principles in 2010. The purpose of the revision was to incorporate the lessons learned from the crisis and prevent future occurrences. Eight principles were added, bringing the total to 38. The latest principles address hedge funds, credit rating agencies, information service providers, and auditor independence. IOSCO also made minor revisions", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The right to counsel", "back": "right of criminal defendants to have a lawyer assist in their defense, even if they cannot afford to pay for one. Thus, if an individual is the subject of a criminal investigation by government authorities, they may have some type of right to consult an attorney or have an attorney appointed. This right is generally found in both civil and", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Consent Searches", "back": "Consent is a recognized exception to the requirement that government agents must obtain a warrant before they search a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime. Individuals are always free to consent to searches. If a suspect consents to a search or seizure by police or government agents, the consent eliminates the need for a search warrant. That is, the consent to search waives the person’s right to be free from government searches. Thus, the", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Evidence In Plain View", "back": "In many countries with a warrant requirement, the plain-view doctrine is an exception to the general rule that the government must obtain a search warrant before conducting a search of a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime. Under this doctrine, evidence in plain view of a law enforcement officer who has a right to be in a position to observe it may be seized without a warrant. The plain-view doctrine applies when a government official", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Generally speaking, defamation", "back": "the unprivileged publication of false statements about a person that causes harm to that person’s reputation. Defamation can be a crime or a civil violation, and the law varies by jurisdiction as to whether it is a criminal offense or a civil wrong. For example, defamation actions can be brought", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: slander. Libel", "back": "defamatory statements in writing, and slander refers to spoken statements, although the distinction often is blurred in cases involving electronic media. Thus, the key difference between libel and slander is the form in which the defamatory statement is made. In other jurisdictions, there is no distinction between libel and slander. For example,", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: the key difference between libel and slander", "back": "form in which the defamatory statement is made. In other jurisdictions, there is no distinction between libel and slander. For example, German law makes no distinction between libel and slander. The threat of a defamation lawsuit is always present when allegations of wrongdoing are", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Untrue Statement Of Fact", "back": "To be defamatory, a statement must be a statement of fact (not opinion) and be untrue. Thus, truth is an absolute defense to defamation.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Communicated To Third Parties", "back": "To be defamatory, a statement must be published, either orally or in writing, to a third party. Defamation does not occur when one accuses another directly and in the presence of no other parties; to be defamatory, a statement must be heard or read by a third party.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "On An Unprivileged Occasion", "back": "Also, for a statement to qualify as defamatory, the occasion in which the statement is made must be an unprivileged one. If the statement is made on a privileged occasion, then no liability can attach to the declarant. Basically, the law recognizes that there are some circumstances in which the need to share information is so important that people will be allowed to make mistakes from time to time without having to worry about being sued for", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Public Disclosure Of Private Facts", "back": "Public disclosure of private facts occurs when one party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern. For instance, disclosing information obtained in an interview conducted as part of a fraud investigation to individuals not involved in the investigation might constitute public disclosure of private facts. To establish liability for public disclosure of private facts, the plaintiff must prove all of the", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The gist of this civil wrong", "back": "unwarranted publicity of private facts, not the discovery of private facts. In the United States, courts have held that the publicity must be broad and pervasive for liability to attach. Thus, one case found no liability when a bank gave the account information of one of its customers to the customer’s employer, and another court exonerated", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "European Union", "back": "The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) is a regulation designed to protect the personal data of EU residents and harmonize data protection laws throughout Europe. The Council of the EU adopted the GDPR in 2016, and it took effect on May 25, 2018. When it became effective, the GDPR replaced the EU Data Protection Directive of 1995 (also known as Directive 95/46/EC), which previously established the blueprint for data privacy laws", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Lawful Basis", "back": "The GDPR requires organizations to have a lawful basis for collecting or processing personal data. There are multiple lawful bases identified in the GDPR, such as the consent of the data subject, a legitimate interest of the organization, compliance with a legal obligation, the performance of a contract, or the performance of a task carried out in the public interest. The GDPR requires the lawful basis for the processing of personal data to be documented in", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Right To Access", "back": "Upon a data subject’s request, an organization must confirm or deny that it possesses the data subject’s personal data. The organization must also provide the data subject with a free copy of the personal data and any other specified information, such as the purpose of the data collection or the length of time that the information will be stored.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Right To Data Portability", "back": "Under the GDPR, data subjects may request the transfer of their personal data from one organization to another. Organizations must store personal data in a structured, commonly used, and machine-readable format so that they can comply with such transfer requests.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Right To Erasure", "back": "Under some circumstances, organizations can be compelled to delete personal data upon request. For example, a data subject may request the erasure of personal data if the data are Individual Rights During Examinations no longer necessary in relation to the purpose for which they were collected, the data subject withdraws consent, the data were unlawfully collected or processed, or the data subject was a", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Data Security", "back": "The GDPR requires organizations to implement appropriate technical and organizational measures to ensure a level of data security that is appropriate to the risk, including the encryption and pseudonymization of personal data.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Data Protection Officers", "back": "An organization must designate a data protection officer if its business involves the processing of sensitive personal data on a large scale or the regular and systematic monitoring of data subjects on a large scale. Data protection officers must have expert knowledge of data", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Privacy By Design And Default", "back": "The GDPR incorporates the concept of privacy by design, which requires organizations to take data protection into account when designing business processes. The regulation also adopts the concept of privacy by default, which means that organizations must set their default privacy settings at a high level. For example, organizations should not collect personal data unless absolutely necessary. In addition, organizations should limit access to personal data to those", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Data Breaches", "back": "An organization must report data breaches to its member country’s designated supervisory authority within 72 hours after becoming aware of the breach. Also, the organization must notify all affected data subjects without undue delay if the breach is likely to result in a high risk to their rights and freedoms. However, the organization is not required to notify data subjects if the breach only involved encrypted or otherwise unintelligible data or if the organization", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recordkeeping", "back": "The GDPR requires organizations to maintain electronic records of their data collection and processing activities. Such records must include the organization’s lawful bases for collecting Individual Rights During Examinations and processing personal data. Upon request, the records must be made available to the designated supervisory authority of the organization’s member country.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Penalties", "back": "For serious violations of the GDPR, organizations may be fined up to EUR 20 million or 4% of their global annual turnover, whichever amount is greater. The GDPR is a lengthy and complex regulation; it contains many details that are not discussed here. Any organization that is subject to the regulation should seek expert legal advice to develop a GDPR compliance program.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "United States", "back": "The United States does not have a comprehensive federal data privacy law. Instead, the United States uses a sectoral approach in which different economic sectors operate under different legal requirements. This approach, which relies on a combination of legislation, regulation, and self-regulation, creates a system in which privacy standards emerge from a complex interplay of overlapping state and federal laws and regulations, as well as industry practices.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: most significant state data privacy law to emerge", "back": "California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), which took effect on January 1, 2020. However, in November 2020, California voters approved the California Privacy Rights Act (CPRA), which amends the CCPA and takes effect on January 1, 2023. The CCPA and CPRA apply to certain domestic and foreign", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: imprisonment", "back": "unlawful restraint by one person of the physical liberty of another without consent or legal justification. To recover for a claim of false imprisonment, the plaintiff generally must prove all of the", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Intentional infliction of emotional distress", "back": "any unprivileged conduct that is so outrageous and egregious that it exceeds all bounds usually tolerated by civilized society and is intended to cause injury (or was committed with reckless disregard for the likelihood of its causing injury) to another. It is a civil action available mainly in common law countries.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Of particular significance", "back": "fact that most jurisdictions have restrictions concerning the ways in which employers can conduct interviews. Such restrictions might originate from employment contracts, collective labor laws, laws protecting labor rights, the common law, laws protecting fundamental rights, other applicable statutes, and so on.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Criminal Justice System", "back": "Criminal law deals with offenses of a public nature, whereas civil law is the body of law that provides remedies for violations of private rights. A criminal defendant has certain rights, but these rights vary substantially from jurisdiction to jurisdiction. This chapter describes several procedures and issues in criminal cases that fraud examiners should be aware of. International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Law Related To Fraud", "back": "Countries use a wide variety of laws and regulations to prohibit fraud and related crimes. This chapter covers some of the most common types of offenses, as well as several important laws and initiatives designed to combat fraud and corruption. It is important to keep in mind, however, that the legal systems in different countries or jurisdictions can vary dramatically. Thus, fraud examiners should always consult with counsel regarding local laws and regulations.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: material facts case. Materiality usually", "back": "statements sufficiently important or relevant to a reasonable person in acting or making a decision. For example, a claim that a company enjoyed a 50% growth in profits would probably be material to a prospective investor, The Law Related to Fraud", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Official Bribery", "back": "Official bribery refers to the corruption of a public official to influence an official act of government. Illegal payments to public officials can be prosecuted as official bribery, and they can result in severe penalties. The elements of official bribery vary by jurisdiction, but they • The defendant gave or received (offered or solicited) a thing of value. • The recipient was (or was selected to be) a public official.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Commercial Bribery", "back": "In contrast, commercial bribery refers to the corruption of a private individual to gain a commercial or business advantage. That is, in commercial bribery schemes, something of value is offered to influence a business decision rather than an official act. In some countries, commercial bribery might be referred to as secret commissions. Commercial bribery may not be a crime in every jurisdiction. For example, in the United", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Embezzlement", "back": "wrongful appropriation of money or property by a person to whom it has been lawfully entrusted (or to whom lawful possession was given). Embezzlement involves a breach of trust, although it is not necessary to show a fiduciary relationship—a relationship of confidence, trust, or good faith—between the parties. The elements of embezzlement vary", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Misappropriation", "back": "intentional, illegal use of the property, funds, or ideas of another person for an unauthorized purpose. In the fraud context, misappropriation claims generally involve trade secrets or other proprietary information. Trade secrets include not only secret formulas and processes, but the term also refers to more", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The information", "back": "subject of reasonable efforts to maintain its secrecy. The elements of a typical claim for misappropriation of trade secrets are: • The defendant possessed information of value. • The information was treated confidentially.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Civil Action For Misappropriation Of Trade Secrets", "back": "In most jurisdictions, a victim of trade secret theft may file a civil action for damages or request an injunction—a court order by which a party is required to perform, or is restrained from performing, a specific act—under various types of laws. Civil damages for misappropriation of trade secrets might include reimbursement for actual losses caused by the defendant, such as lost profits, reimbursement of development expenses and overhead costs,", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: that has been recognized in some jurisdictions", "back": "duty imposed on each party to deal with each other in good faith. If a party to a contract, including employment contracts, breaches the duty of good faith, the non-breaching party may have a civil claim for breach of contract. Breach of Fiduciary Duty", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The duty of care", "back": "that people in a fiduciary relationship must act with such care as an ordinarily prudent person would employ in similar positions. Corporate officers, directors, or high-level employees, as well as other people in a fiduciary relationship, must conduct their business affairs prudently with the skill and attention normally exercised by people in similar", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Conspiracy", "back": "a situation in which two or more people agree to commit an illegal act. In most jurisdictions, the crime of conspiracy is actually a separate criminal offense from the underlying crime, meaning that the underlying crime (e.g., bank fraud, bribery, securities fraud) and the conspiracy to commit it are two separate offenses.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: binding agreements. Soft law", "back": "guidelines, resolutions, codes of conduct, and other quasilegal instruments that are not directly enforceable. The OECD Recommendations discussed below are examples of soft law. In contrast, the OECD Convention on Combating Bribery of Foreign Public Officials in International Business Transactions is a legally binding agreement. At present, the OECD consists of 38 member countries: Australia, Austria, Belgium, Canada,", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "In International Business Transactions", "back": "The OECD Convention on Combating Bribery of Foreign Public Officials in International Business Transactions (OECD Anti-Bribery Convention) is a legally binding agreement that sets a uniform, minimum standard that signatory countries must implement through national legislation. Of course, countries may adopt laws that exceed that standard; the following section provides several examples of such legislation.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Officials", "back": "In 2009, the Working Group issued two additional recommendations for further combating bribery of foreign public officials in international business transactions. For the most past, these instruments merely reinforce the earlier Recommendation and OECD Anti-Bribery Convention. They encourage member countries to review, evaluate, and, where necessary, strengthen the laws and regulations relevant to the fight against foreign bribery. Members are", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Testifying", "back": "Testimonial evidence is evidence presented in the form of statements made during a legal proceeding, such as a trial, an administrative hearing, or a deposition. All testimonial evidence has specific requirements governing its admissibility that depend on the type of witness and the manner in which the witness is testifying. The judge or administrator applies these requirements to determine who can testify and what they can testify about.", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: throughout their careers. For CFEs, that", "back": "completing Continuing Professional Education (CPE), regularly reading publications in the specific field, and actively seeking new developments. Fraud schemes and the investigation and prevention measures associated with them are always evolving, so the ideal expert will stay on top of these issues.", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: rationales. Caution", "back": "byword for expert witnesses throughout the legal process. Reports and supporting documents used by experts might have to be disclosed to the opposing side in adversarial processes, and the parties in inquisitorial processes might also have a chance to review such documents. Therefore, experts should be cautious about what records they have.", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In many countries, depositions are available as a", "back": "of gathering testimonial evidence. A deposition is sworn testimony given by a party or witness upon questioning by counsel for one of the parties before trial and outside of court. A deposition serves as a powerful discovery device that may be used to compel anyone associated with the case to give oral testimony", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Over- And Under-Shipment Schemes", "back": "Like over- and under-invoicing schemes, over- and under-shipment schemes can be used to create a complex paper trail for the colluding parties to launder money. In an over-shipment scheme, money launderers understate the quantity of goods that are shipped. More goods are shipped than the company invoices for. For example, Company A invoices 100,000 widgets to Company B at a price of one dollar per widget. However, Company A", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Duplicate Invoicing Scheme", "back": "In a duplicate invoicing scheme, the exporter issues more than one invoice for the same trade transaction. By issuing duplicate invoices, a money launderer can justify multiple payments for the same goods or services.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "False Descriptions In Invoices", "back": "Money launderers can conceal their illicit funds by misrepresenting the quality or type of goods or services provided. For example, an exporter can substitute products or materials of lesser quality than specified in the invoice; use lower quality staff than specified; use counterfeit, defective, or used parts to produce goods; or make any other deliberate departures specified in the invoice.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Black Market Peso Exchange", "back": "Among the most notorious of trade-based money laundering operations is the Black Market Peso Exchange, a scheme where brokers purchase proceeds from narcotics in the United States from cartels and exchange them for clean pesos in Colombia.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Red Flags Of Trade-Based Money Laundering", "back": "Some red flags of trade-based money laundering schemes include: • The goods or services traded seem unrelated to the usual business of the importer • The shipping route is unusual, passing through one or more countries for no • The goods or services do not match the description, value, quantity, or quality stated in", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: assets in their own right. As", "back": "case with most assets, they can become part of a money laundering scheme. Due to the recent growth in the financial products offered by insurance agents and brokers (including savings products, investment products, and tax planning services), the insurance industry has become increasingly attractive to money launderers. One", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Legal Systems", "back": "Under the FATF Recommendations, countries should adopt legislation that effectively criminalizes acts of money laundering and establishes the widest possible range of predicate offenses. In reference to money laundering, a predicate offense is a crime whose proceeds must be converted into a legitimate form. At a minimum, every serious offense should constitute a predicate offense, regardless of where it is committed. In addition, countries", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Financial Institutions And Related Professions", "back": "The FATF Recommendations were revised over time to set stricter guidelines for financial institutions and professionals who are routinely involved in substantial financial transactions. Such professionals specifically include casinos, real estate agents, lawyers, and dealers in precious metals and precious stones. The measures address customer due diligence (CDD), reporting suspicious transactions, deterring money laundering and terrorist financing, and", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Anti-Money Laundering Programs", "back": "Under the FATF Recommendations, countries should require financial institutions to implement AML and terrorist financing programs. A financial institution’s AML program is highly dependent on which jurisdictions it operates in, as well as the services that it offers. Generally, financial institutions should adopt the AML policies and procedures in the FATF Recommendations, but they need to tailor their programs to the requirements of the specific", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Customer Due Diligence", "back": "The FATF Recommendations set out the fundamental measures that financial institutions must take to identify and verify the identity of customers and beneficial owners. Although it is most important to conduct due diligence when a business relationship is first established, due diligence should be exercised on an ongoing basis. These requirements set firm, more detailed standards while also providing flexibility and allowing adaptation to new industry", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Deterring Money Laundering And Terrorist Financing", "back": "Within certain limits, countries and institutions are free to determine the extent of measures appropriate to the specific risk of money laundering or terrorist financing they face. However, all countries are required to (1) establish an FIU to receive reports regarding suspicious transactions, (2) designate law enforcement agencies for AML/CFT investigations, and (3) involve financial supervisors in AML/CFT initiatives. These authorities should have", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reporting Of Suspicious Transactions", "back": "Under the FATF’s Recommendation 20, a financial institution should be required to file a report when it “suspects or has reasonable grounds to suspect that funds are the proceeds of a criminal activity, or are related to terrorist financing.” Some jurisdictions also set additional requirements for reporting suspicious transactions, such as if a cash transaction surpasses a certain threshold amount. The name of these reports varies by jurisdiction, but they are", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Regulation And Supervision", "back": "All countries need adequate measures to ensure that financial institutions and other businesses and professions are complying with their obligations. The required measures take into account the risks and the regulatory structures that already exist in the relevant sectors. • Financial institutions and casinos should not be owned or managed by criminals. • The measures applicable to banks, insurance, and securities firms for prudential purposes", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Large Cash Transactions", "back": "Under the best practices provided in the FATF Recommendations, countries should implement a reporting requirement for financial institutions and DNFBPs that engage in cash transactions above the jurisdiction’s designated threshold. The reports should cover domestic and international cash transactions. Many jurisdictions implement this reporting requirement.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Cross-Border Transfer Of Currency", "back": "Under the FATF’s Recommendation 32, countries should implement disclosure requirements for individuals who are physically carrying currency or currency equivalents (i.e., bearer instruments) into or out of the country in amounts that are above the country’s designated reporting threshold. Generally, individuals who are carrying currency or the equivalent above the reporting threshold while attempting to cross jurisdictional borders should be required to", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "International Cooperation", "back": "The FATF Recommendations contain several provisions that address international cooperation. Notably, the Recommendation on mutual legal assistance covers several concepts that are in the 25 Non-Cooperative Countries and Territories Criteria discussed below. The most significant provisions deal with cooperation between administrative and law enforcement authorities concerned with combating money laundering and terrorist", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: efforts. The most prevalent", "back": "Anti-Money Laundering Directive (now in its sixth iteration and referred to as the Sixth Directive). The Sixth Directive applies to the financial sector as well as to lawyers, notaries, accountants, real estate agents, casinos, and company service providers. Its scope also encompasses all providers of goods when cash payments are made or received in", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "New Deposit Accounts", "back": "For individual deposit accounts, minimum identification standards should be established. The information to be obtained should include:", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "New Loan Accounts", "back": "An institution should perform due diligence in establishing a new loan account because, if the customer is engaged in money laundering, there is a risk of forfeiture of collateral pledged on the loans. Real or personal property that is traceable to drug sales or that is purchased with laundered funds is subject to seizure by the government. If the property seized is pledged as collateral, the financial institution must prove that it was an innocent lienholder of the", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Services For Non-Account Holders", "back": "Banks often issue cashier’s checks, money orders, and traveler’s checks and perform currency exchanges, wire transfers, or check cashing services for non-account holders. Strict identification requirements should be established for transactions with persons who are not regular bank customers. In fact, regulations require that in some instances, banks keep a record of the identity of persons who are not established customers. Such regulations usually", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Monitoring Accounts", "back": "While identification of customers is important, it is equally important to monitor the activity of accounts. The institution should identify unusual transactions that might not be consistent with the normal business of the customer. Unusual and dramatic changes in wire transfer, monetary instrument, and check transactions are important to identify. If unusual transactions or activities are noted, the institution should take some action to protect itself. The", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Civil Justice System", "back": "This section reviews the legal aspects of actions by private parties—including fraud examiners, auditors, accountants, security personnel, private investigators, and lawyers—to investigate and recover losses due to fraud. Many of these cases will be resolved in the civil A civil action or civil suit arises when individuals or business entities (such as corporations or partnerships) disagree on a legal matter. A civil action usually involves a dispute over something", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The person who sues", "back": "plaintiff, and the person being sued is the defendant. Procedure in Civil Cases The procedure in a civil case can be quite complex. Furthermore, the terminology describing steps in the process is not consistent in legal systems throughout the world. This discussion", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: members of the European Union (EU)—there", "back": "potential for a criminal violation of such laws. Therefore, fraud examiners should consult with legal counsel on how to preserve evidence gathered during an examination.", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Accounting Concepts", "back": "Fraudulent acts are usually interconnected with money and finances. The fraud examiner must therefore understand the source and flow of financial transactions and how they affect an organization’s accounting records. Additionally, the fraud examiner should have an understanding of both financial terminology and accounting theory. Merriam-Webster.com defines accounting as “the system of recording and summarizing business", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: accounting equation, as shown below,", "back": "basis for all double-entry accounting: Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity By definition, assets consist of the net resources owned by an entity. Examples of assets include cash, receivables, inventory, property, and equipment, as well as intangible items of", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The following", "back": "income statement for XYZ Company for its first year of operations based on the sample transactions previously listed.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: on the income statement. The term net", "back": "that the amount shown is the company’s total sales minus any sales refunds, returns, discounts, or allowances. Conversely, gross revenues refer to the company’s total sales during the accounting period before any deductions are made. From net sales, an expense titled cost of goods sold or cost of sales is deducted. Regardless of the", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Relevance", "back": "Any financial information that might affect a decision made by a user of the financial statements is considered relevant. Financial information is relevant if it has predictive value, confirmatory value, or both. Predictive value is present if the information can be used as an input to processes employed by users to predict future outcomes. Confirmatory value indicates the information provides feedback about previous evaluations.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Materiality", "back": "The amount of an item is material if its omission or misstatement would affect the judgment of a reasonable person who is relying on the financial statements. Materiality is an entityspecific aspect of relevance based on the nature or magnitude, or both, of the items to which the information relates in the context of an individual entity’s financial report.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Faithful Representation", "back": "Financial information must faithfully represent the economic data of the enterprise that it purports to represent. Every effort shall be made to maximize the qualities of perfectly faithful representation: complete, neutral, and free from error. A complete depiction includes all information necessary to understand the data presented. A neutral depiction is without bias in the selection or presentation of financial information. Free from error means there are no", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Comparability And Consistency", "back": "Users of financial statements base their decisions on comparisons between different entities and on similar information from a single entity for another reporting period. Comparability is the qualitative characteristic that enables users to identify and understand similarities and differences between such items. Information about a company is more useful if it is comparable with similar information about other entities and with similar information", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Verifiability", "back": "Verifiability helps assure users that information is accurate and faithfully represents the financial position of the entity. Verifiability means that different knowledgeable and independent observers could reach consensus, although not necessarily complete agreement, that a particular depiction is a faithful representation.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Timeliness", "back": "Timeliness means providing information to decision-makers in time to be capable of influencing their decisions. In general, the older the information is, the less useful it is.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Understandability", "back": "Classifying, characterizing, and presenting information clearly and concisely makes it understandable. However, some economic data are fundamentally complex. Therefore, enough information should be provided about such events so that a reasonable financial statement user can understand what occurred. An entity’s financial statements should include all information necessary for users to make valid decisions and must not mislead them.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Going Concern", "back": "A company’s management is required to provide disclosures when existing events or conditions indicate that it is more likely than not that the entity might be unable to meet its obligations within a reasonable period of time after the financial statements are issued. There is an underlying assumption that an entity will continue as a going concern; that is, the life of the entity will be long enough to fulfill its financial and legal obligations. Any evidence to the", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Recognition", "back": "process of incorporating an item that meets the definition of an element and satisfies the criteria for recognition into the balance sheet or income statement. It involves the depiction of the item in words and by a monetary amount and the inclusion of that amount in the balance sheet or income statement totals. Items that satisfy the recognition criteria should", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Probability Of Future Economic Benefit", "back": "The concept of probability is used in the recognition criteria to refer to the degree of uncertainty that the future economic benefits associated with the item will flow to or from the entity. The concept provides for the uncertainty that characterizes the environment in which an entity operates. Assessments of the degree of uncertainty attaching to the flow of future economic benefits are made on the basis of the evidence available when the financial", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reliability Of Measurement", "back": "The second criterion for the recognition of an item is that it possesses a cost or value that can be measured with reliability. In many cases, cost or value must be estimated; the use of reasonable estimates is an essential part of the preparation of financial statements and does not undermine their reliability. When, however, a reasonable estimate cannot be made, the item is not recognized in the balance sheet or income statement.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recognition Of Assets", "back": "An asset is recognized in the balance sheet when it is probable that the future economic benefits will flow to the entity and the asset has a cost or value that can be measured reliably.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recognition Of Liabilities", "back": "A liability is recognized in the balance sheet when it is probable that an outflow of resources embodying economic benefits will result from the settlement of a present obligation and the amount at which the settlement will take place can be measured reliably.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recognition Of Income", "back": "Income is recognized in the income statement when an increase in future economic benefit related to an increase in an asset or a decrease of a liability has arisen that can be measured reliably. This means, in effect, that recognition of income occurs simultaneously with the recognition of increases in assets or decreases in liabilities (e.g., the net increase in assets arising on a sale of goods or services or the decrease in liabilities arising from the waiver of a", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recognition Of Expenses", "back": "Expenses are recognized in the income statement when a decrease in future economic benefit related to a decrease in an asset or an increase of a liability has arisen that can be measured reliably. This means, in effect, that recognition of expenses occurs simultaneously with the recognition of an increase in liabilities or a decrease in assets (e.g., the accrual of employee entitlements or the depreciation of equipment).", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: conservatism in accounting", "back": "use of the lower of cost or net realizable value as it relates to inventory valuation. If a company’s financial statements intentionally violate the conservatism constraint, they could be fraudulent.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Financial Statement Fraud", "back": "Financial statement schemes are one of a large category of frauds that comprise the Occupational Fraud and Abuse Classification System, most commonly referred to as the Fraud Tree. Occupational fraud and abuse is defined as “the use of one’s occupation for personal enrichment through the deliberate misuse or misapplication of the employing organization’s resources or assets.” Simply stated, occupational frauds are those in which an employee,", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Financial statement fraud", "back": "deliberate misrepresentation of the financial condition of an enterprise accomplished through the intentional misstatement or omission of amounts or disclosures in the financial statements to deceive financial statement users. Note that financial statement fraud, much like all types of fraud, is an intentional act. As", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Financial statement fraud is usually a", "back": "to an end rather than an end in itself. When people manipulate financial records, they might be stalling, so they can quietly “fix” business problems that prevent their company from achieving its expected earnings or complying with loan covenants. It might also be done to obtain or renew financing that would not be granted,", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Example Of Multiple Fraud Schemes", "back": "In February of 2008, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) filed financial fraud charges against Bally Total Fitness Holding Corporation (Bally), a nationwide commercial operator of fitness centers, alleging that Bally violated the antifraud, reporting, books and records, and internal control provisions of the federal securities laws (United States Securities and Exchange Commission v. Bally Total Fitness Holding Corporation).", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Example Of Fictitious Revenues", "back": "In one case, a foreign subsidiary of a U.S. company recorded several large fictitious sales to a series of companies. It invoiced the sales but did not collect any of the accounts receivable, which became severely past due. The manager of the foreign subsidiary arranged for false confirmations of the accounts receivable for audit purposes and even hired actors to pretend to be the customers during a visit from U.S. management. Background checks on the customers would have revealed", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Deceptive Sales And Customers", "back": "In what has become India’s largest corporate scandal, Satyam Computer Services Limited (Satyam) founder and chairman, B. Ramalinga Raju, suddenly quit in January 2009, confessing that he had falsified company accounts for years. In his four-and-a-half-page resignation letter, Raju revealed he had overstated the company’s reported cash balance by Satyam (renamed Mahindra Satyam in 2009), a foreign private issuer, is a large information", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: inventory costing method used. This", "back": "that inventory must be initially valued at its acquisition cost, except when the cost is determined to be higher than the net realizable value, in which case the difference should be recognized as a loss in earnings in the period it occurs. If the utility of the goods is no longer as great as their cost, the difference should be recognized as", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fictitious Accounts Receivable", "back": "Fictitious accounts receivable go hand in hand with fictitious sales, as discussed in the previous section. They are common among companies with financial problems, as well as with managers who receive a commission based on sales. The typical entry under fictitious accounts receivable is to debit (increase) accounts receivable and credit (increase) sales. Of course, these schemes are more common around the end of the accounting period, since", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Failure To Account For Uncollectible Accounts", "back": "In general, accounts receivable should be reported at net realizable value—that is, the amount of the receivable less the amount expected not to be collected. As such, companies are generally required to write off uncollectible receivables as bad debt expense. Managers can overstate their company’s accounts receivable balance by failing to record bad debt expense. Bad debt expense is recorded to account for any uncollectible accounts", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Booking Fictitious Assets", "back": "One of the easiest methods of asset misrepresentation is the recording of fictitious assets. This false creation of assets affects account totals on a company’s balance sheet. The corresponding account commonly used is the owners’ equity account. Because company assets are often physically found in many different locations, this fraud can sometimes be easily overlooked. One of the most common fictitious asset schemes is to simply create", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Misrepresenting The Value Of Fixed Assets", "back": "Fixed assets should be recorded at historical cost. Although assets might appreciate in value, this increase in value should generally not be recognized on company financial statements unless recognizing a gain upon sale in a separate balance sheet account. Many financial statement frauds involve the reporting of fixed assets at higher market values rather than the lower historical (acquisition) costs, or at even higher inflated values", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Capitalizing Non-Asset Costs", "back": "Interest and finance charges incurred in the purchase are excluded from the recorded cost of a purchased asset. For example, when a company finances a capital equipment purchase, monthly payments include both principal liability reduction and interest payments. On initial purchase, only the original cost of the asset should be capitalized. The subsequent interest payments should be charged to interest expense and not to the asset. Without a reason for", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "back": "Asset misappropriation is the most common form of occupational fraud by a considerable degree. There are three major categories of asset misappropriation schemes. Cash receipts schemes are discussed in this section, fraudulent disbursements of cash are addressed in the next section, and the following section covers schemes involving the theft of inventory and Cash is the focal point of most accounting schemes. Cash, both on deposit in banks and on", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: skimming schemes", "back": "they leave no direct audit trail. Because the stolen funds are never recorded, the victim organization might not be aware that the cash was ever received. Consequently, it can be difficult to detect that the cash has been stolen. This is the primary advantage of a skimming scheme to the fraudster.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Off-site skimming is by no", "back": "limited to the apartment rental industry. The schemes described previously can easily translate into any position where those who generate or collect revenues operate in an independent fashion. A prime example is the insurance agent who sells policies to customers, and then neglects to file the policies with the carrier. Most customers", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "False Discounts", "back": "Those employees with the authority to grant discounts might use this authority to skim sales and receivables. In a false discount skimming scheme, an employee accepts full payment for an item but records the transaction as if the customer had been given a discount. The employee skims the amount of the discount. For example, on a $100 purchase, if an employee granted a false discount of 20%, the employee could skim $20 and leave the company’s books", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: fact that the stolen checks are not posted", "back": "that some customers’ accounts are in danger of becoming past due. If this happens, the perpetrator’s scheme is in danger because these customers will almost surely complain about the misapplication of their payments. However, the misapplied payments can be concealed on the books by forcing account totals, stealing", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: skimming. Lapping", "back": "crediting of one account through the abstraction of money from", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Debits To Expense Accounts", "back": "An employee might conceal the skimming of funds by making unsupported entries in the victim company’s books. If a payment is made on a receivable, for instance, the proper entry is a debit to cash and a credit to the receivable. Instead of debiting cash, the employee might choose to debit an expense account. This transaction still keeps the company’s books in balance, but the incoming cash is never recorded. In addition, the customer’s receivable", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Debits To Aging Or Fictitious Receivables", "back": "The same method discussed previously is used when employees debit existing or fictitious accounts receivable to conceal skimmed cash. For example, an employee who has skimmed one customer’s payments might add the stolen amounts to aging accounts that will soon be written off as uncollectible or to very large accounts where a small debit might go unnoticed. Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts Some perpetrators also set up completely fictitious accounts and debit them for the cost of", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Writing Off Account Balances", "back": "Some employees cover their skimming by posting entries to contra revenue accounts such as discounts and allowances. If, for instance, an employee intercepts a $1,000 payment, the employee would create a $1,000 “discount” on the account to compensate for the missing money. Another account that might be used in this type of concealment is the bad debts A billing manager was authorized to write off certain patient balances as hardship", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: A problem for fraudsters in some skimming schemes", "back": "victim organization’s inventory. Off-book sales of goods (skimming schemes) will always leave an inventory shortage and a corresponding rise in the cost of goods sold. When a sale of goods is made, the physical inventory is reduced by the amount of", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: know the exact balance of their account. If this", "back": "case, it might be more effective to confirm by invoice and reconstruct the account balance using the source documents in the files and the results of the confirmation. If fraud is suspected, ask the customer or the bank to return a copy of both the front and the back of the check(s) used to pay specific invoices.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: cash larceny", "back": "intentional taking of an employer’s cash (the term cash includes both currency and checks) without the consent and against the will of the employer. However, recall that skimming also involves the intentional taking of an employer’s cash. The difference between skimming and cash larceny is that skimming is the theft of cash before it appears on the books.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: skimming and cash larceny is that skimming", "back": "theft of cash before it appears on the books. Cash larceny schemes involve the theft of money that has already appeared on a victim company’s books. Accordingly, cash larceny schemes are easier to detect than skimming schemes because they leave an audit trail.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: currency—rarely varies. It", "back": "methods that perpetrators use to avoid getting caught that distinguish larceny schemes. Oddly, in many instances the perpetrators have no plan for avoiding detection. A large part of fraud is rationalization; employees convince themselves that they are somehow entitled to what they are taking or that what they are doing is not", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reversing Transactions", "back": "Some employees conceal cash larceny by processing reversing transactions, which cause the register log to reconcile to the amount of cash on hand after the theft. By processing false voids or refunds, an employee can reduce the cash balance reflected on the register log. A cashier received payments from a customer and recorded the transactions on their system. The cashier stole the payments from the customers and then destroyed the company’s receipts", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Register Manipulation", "back": "Instead of using reversing entries, an employee might manually alter the register log. Again, the purpose of this activity is to force a balance between the cash on hand and the actual cash received. An employee might use correction fluid to cover up a sale where the proceeds were stolen or might simply cross out or alter the numbers on the tape so that the register total and the cash drawer balance. This type of concealment is not common because the alterations will", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Altering Cash Counts", "back": "Another method for concealing cash larceny is to alter the cash counts on registers. When cash from a register is totaled and prepared for deposit, an employee simply records the wrong amount so that the cash on hand appears to balance with the total on the register log. Obviously, employees who deal with the receipt of cash should not be charged with verifying the amount of cash on hand in their own register, but this control is often overlooked.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Destroying Register Logs", "back": "If the fraudster cannot make the cash and the tape balance, the next best thing is to prevent others from computing the totals and discovering the imbalance. Employees who are stealing from the register sometimes destroy detail tapes that would implicate them in a crime. When detail tapes are missing or defaced, it might be because someone is trying to Other Larceny of Sales and Receivables Not all receipts arrive via the cash register. Employees can just as easily steal money", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "back": "In fraudulent disbursement schemes, an employee makes a distribution of company funds for a dishonest purpose. Some examples of fraudulent disbursements include submitting false invoices for payment, altering time cards, and making personal purchases with company funds. Outwardly, the fraudulent disbursements do not appear any different from valid disbursements of cash. In many cases, the fraudster tricks the victim company into remitting payment. For", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: is not required. Where this", "back": "case, employees simply process numerous refunds that are small enough that they do not have to be reviewed. Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Employees With Access To Company Checks", "back": "One cannot forge a company check unless one first possesses a company check. Most forgery schemes are committed by accounts payable clerks, office managers, bookkeepers, or other employees whose duties typically include the preparation of company checks. These are people who have access to the company checkbook on a regular basis and are therefore in the best position to steal blank checks. Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Employees Lacking Access To Company Checks", "back": "If perpetrators do not have access to the company checkbook through their work duties, they will have to find other means of misappropriating a check. The method by which a person steals a check depends largely on how the checkbook is handled within a particular company. In some circumstances, the checkbook is poorly guarded and left in unattended areas where anyone can get to it. In other companies, the check stock might be kept in a restricted area,", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "To The Perpetrator", "back": "Once a blank check has been obtained, the perpetrator must decide to whom it should be made payable. In most instances, forged checks are made payable to the perpetrator so that they can be easily converted. Canceled checks that are payable to an employee should be closely scrutinized for the possibility of fraud. If the perpetrator owns their own business or has established a shell company, they will", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "To An Accomplice", "back": "If a fraudster is working with an accomplice, the fraudster can make the forged check payable to that person. The accomplice then cashes the check and splits the money with the employee-fraudster. Because the check is payable to the accomplice in their true identity, it is easily converted. An additional benefit to using an accomplice is that a canceled check payable to a third-party accomplice is not as likely to raise suspicion as a canceled check to an", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "To Vendors", "back": "Not all fraudsters forge company checks to obtain cash. Some employees use forged maker schemes to purchase goods or services for their own benefit. These fraudulent checks are made payable to third-party vendors who are uninvolved in the fraud. For instance, an employee might forge a company check to buy a home computer. The computer vendor is not involved in the fraud at all. Furthermore, if the victim organization regularly does", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Forging The Signature", "back": "After the employee has obtained and prepared a blank check, they must forge an authorized signature to convert the check. The most obvious method, and the one that comes to mind when one thinks of the word forgery, is to simply sign the name of an authorized maker.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Free-Hand Forgery", "back": "The difficulty a fraudster encounters when physically signing the authorized maker’s name is in creating a reasonable approximation of the true signature. If the forgery appears authentic, the perpetrator will probably have no problem cashing the check. In truth, the forged signature might not have to be particularly accurate. Many fraudsters cash forged checks at liquor stores, grocery stores, or other institutions that are known to be less than diligent in", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Photocopied Forgeries", "back": "To guarantee an accurate forgery, some employees make photocopies of legitimate signatures. The signature of an authorized signer is copied from some document (such as a business letter) onto a transparency, and then the transparency is laid over a blank check so that the signature copies onto the maker line of the check. The result is a check with a perfect signature of an authorized maker.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Automatic Check-Signing Mechanisms", "back": "Companies that issue a large number of checks sometimes use automatic check-signing mechanisms in lieu of signing each check by hand. Automated signatures are produced with manual instruments, such as signature stamps, or they are printed by computer. Obviously, a fraudster who gains access to an automatic check-signing mechanism will have no trouble forging the signatures of authorized makers. Even the most rudimentary control procedures", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Converting The Check", "back": "To convert the forged check, the perpetrator must endorse it. The endorsement is typically made in the name of the payee on the check. Since identification is typically required when one seeks to convert a check, the perpetrator usually needs fake identification if they forge checks to real or fictitious third persons. As discussed earlier, checks payable to “cash” require the endorsement of the person converting them. Without a fake ID, the perpetrator", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Employees Involved In Delivery Of Checks", "back": "Obviously, the employees in the best position to intercept signed checks are those whose duties include the handling and delivery of signed checks. The most obvious example is a mailroom employee who opens outgoing mail containing signed checks and steals the checks. Other personnel who have access to outgoing checks might include accounts payable employees, payroll clerks, and administrative assistants.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Poor Control Of Signed Checks", "back": "Unfortunately, employees are often able to intercept signed checks because of poor internal controls. For instance, many employees simply find signed checks left unattended in the work areas of the individuals who signed them or the people charged with their delivery. In these cases, it is easy for the perpetrator to steal the check. Another common breakdown occurs when the person who prepares a check is also involved in the delivery of that check once it", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Theft Of Returned Checks", "back": "Checks that have been mailed and are later returned to the victim for some reason, such as an incorrect address, are often targeted for theft by fraudsters. Employees with access to incoming mail are able to intercept these returned checks and convert them by forging the A manager took and converted approximately $130,000 worth of checks that were returned due to noncurrent addresses (also stealing outgoing checks, cashing them, and then declaring", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Re-Routing The Delivery Of Checks", "back": "Employees might also misappropriate signed checks by altering the addresses to which those checks are mailed. These perpetrators usually replace the payee’s legitimate address with an address where the employee can retrieve the check, such as the employee’s home or a post office box the employee controls. In other instances, the perpetrator might purposely misaddress a check so that it will be returned as undeliverable. The employee steals the check", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Converting The Stolen Check", "back": "Once a check has been intercepted, the perpetrator can cash it by forging the payee’s signature, hence the term forged endorsement scheme. Depending on where they try to cash the check, the perpetrator might or might not need fake identification at this stage. If a perpetrator is required to produce identification to cash their stolen check, and if they do not have a fake ID in the payee’s name, they might use a dual endorsement to cash or deposit the", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The second type of intercepted check scheme", "back": "altered payee scheme. This is a form of check tampering in which an employee intercepts a company check intended for a third party and alters the payee designation so that the employee or an accomplice can convert the check. (See the “Altered Payee Schemes” flowchart that follows.) The employee inserts their own", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Altering Checks Prepared By Others: Inserting A New Payee", "back": "The method used to alter the payee designation on a check depends largely on how that check is prepared and intercepted. (Incidentally, the amount of the check might also be altered at the same time and by the same method as the payee designation.) Checks prepared by others can be intercepted by any of the methods discussed in the forged endorsements section. When the perpetrator intercepts a check that has been prepared by someone else,", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Altering Checks Prepared By Others: Tacking On", "back": "The other method that can be used by perpetrators to alter checks prepared by others is tacking on additional letters or words to the end of the real payee designation. For instance, checks payable to “ABC” company might be altered to read “A.B. Collins.” The employee then cashes the checks in the name of A.B. Collins. In these cases, the simple inclusion of a filler line after the payee designation would prevent the loss.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Altering Checks Prepared By The Fraudster: Erasable Ink", "back": "When the perpetrator prepares the check that is to be altered, the schemes tend to be a bit more sophisticated. The reason for this is obvious: If the perpetrator is able to prepare the check themselves, the perpetrator can prepare it with the thought of how the payee designation will be changed. One of the most common ways to prepare a check for alteration is to write or type the payee’s name (and possibly the amount) in erasable ink. After an", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Altering Checks Prepared By The Fraudster: Blank Checks", "back": "The most egregious example of poor controls in the handling of signed checks is one in which the perpetrator prepares a check, leaves the payee designation blank, and submits it to an Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements authorized maker who signs the check and returns it to the employee. Obviously, this makes it quite easy for the perpetrator to designate themselves or an accomplice as the payee.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Converting Altered Checks", "back": "As with all other types of fraudulent checks, conversion is accomplished by endorsing the checks in the payee’s name. Conversion of fraudulent checks has already been discussed in previous sections and will not be re-examined here. The final check tampering scheme, the authorized maker scheme, might be the most difficult to defend against. An authorized maker scheme occurs when an employee with signature", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Overriding Controls Through Intimidation", "back": "When a person is authorized to sign company checks, preparing the checks is easy. The employee simply writes and signs the documents the same way they would with any legitimate check. In most situations, check signers are owners, officers, or otherwise high-ranking employees and thus have or can obtain access to all the blank checks they need. Even if company policy prohibits check signers from handling blank checks, the perpetrator can", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Poor Controls", "back": "Although overriding controls is the most obvious way to execute an authorized maker scheme, it is not the most common. Far more of these schemes occur because no one is paying attention to the accounts and few controls are present to prevent fraud. Some employees who write checks to themselves or to purchase items for themselves simply code the checks to expense accounts that they know are not likely to be reviewed.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Concealment of the fraud", "back": "not only hiding the criminal’s identity, but also hiding the fact that a fraud has even occurred. The most successful frauds are those in which the victim organization is unaware that it is being robbed. Obviously, once a business learns that it is being victimized, it will take steps to find the source and put a stop to the scheme.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Fraudster Reconciling The Bank Statement", "back": "A large percentage of those who perpetrate check tampering frauds are involved in reconciling the company’s bank statement. The bank statement that a company receives Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements normally includes the canceled checks that have been cashed in the preceding period. A person who reconciles the accounts is therefore in a position to hide the existence of any fraudulent checks they have written to themselves. They can remove the fraudulent checks,", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: perpetrator", "back": "one who reconciles the account, it is unlikely that anyone will even notice that the check is missing. The problem with simply omitting the fraudulent check from the disbursements journal is that the bank balance will not reconcile to the book balance. For instance, if the perpetrator", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Re-Alteration Of Checks", "back": "In altered payee schemes, remember that it is common for the perpetrator to take a check intended for a legitimate recipient and then alter the check so that the perpetrator becomes the designated payee. But a canceled check payable to an employee will obviously raise suspicions of fraud. Therefore, some employees re-alter their fraudulent checks when the bank statement arrives. It has already been discussed how employees can alter checks by", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Miscoding Fraudulent Checks", "back": "Rather than omit a fraudulent check from the disbursements journal or list it as void, perpetrators might write a check payable to themselves but list a different person as the payee on the books. Usually, the fake payee is a regular vendor⎯a person or business that receives numerous checks from the victim company. Employees tend to pick known vendors for these schemes because one extra disbursement to a regular payee is less likely to be noticed", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Re-Issuing Intercepted Checks", "back": "In intercepted check schemes, the fraudster faces detection not only through their employer’s normal control procedures but also by the intended recipients of the stolen checks. When the real payees do not receive their checks, they are likely to complain. These complaints, in turn, could trigger a fraud investigation. One way for a fraudster to avoid this problem is to issue new checks to the intended payees.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Payment Fraud", "back": "An influx of new payment technologies balanced against the need to retain traditional methods has resulted in a period of great change in the payment industry. Countless payment methods, ranging from cash to cryptocurrency, allow items and services to be bought online or in-person. As such, a burgeoning variety of fraudulent schemes aimed at exploiting this transitional era have appeared in recent years. Fraud examiners must ensure that their", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: financial institution’s ability to detect it. Check kiting", "back": "practice of recording the deposit of an interbank transfer before recording the disbursement, thus briefly double counting the amount of cash. In a kiting scheme, multiple bank accounts are opened, and money is “deposited” from account to account; however, the money does not exist.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The cashier or teller", "back": "frontline defense in preventing check fraud. It is important that these individuals receive the training necessary to identify fraudulent checks. They should: • Be aware of magnetic routing numbers. • Use extra care in examining a check drawn from a nonlocal bank and require", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: more difficult. One of the features", "back": "use of a pattern of colors that is difficult to separate even with special cameras, filters, and film. Another technique is scrambled indicia printing, which is a seemingly random pattern of tiny colored dots printed on the paper. Using a colored filter to view the check makes a word or pattern develop.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Check Washing Precautions", "back": "As mentioned previously, check washing involves the use of acid-based chemicals to erase the name of the payee, the amount payable, or both. Individuals with business accounts are at a much greater risk when it comes to check washing. If the business does not have strict controls in place to protect its checks, it is likely that if any money is stolen from its accounts, the bank will not return the money. Therefore, business checks should be locked securely", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Forensic Document Examination", "back": "Through handwriting, an individual can be positively identified, as is the case with DNA or fingerprinting. When investigating check fraud, a forensic document examiner focuses on the signature and the handwriting itself.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Signature", "back": "When investigating a forged signature, a fraud examiner should compare the suspicious signature to a sample of the actual one, noting any discrepancies between the two. While one’s signature might change over time, it would be close to impossible for a forger to duplicate a signature with 100% accuracy; minute identifying characteristics mark people’s writing and are not reproducible.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Handwriting", "back": "Similar to fingerprints, handwriting is unique to an individual. Consequently, if the narrative portion of the check is handwritten, it offers a document examiner a greater opportunity to", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Electrostatic Detection Apparatus", "back": "An electrostatic detection apparatus allows fraud examiners to detect indented writing from the top page of a pad of paper up to five pages below the original. This tool uses photocopier toner to develop the areas of indentation after a document has been covered with an electrically charged plastic film. In the best of cases, when the document is processed with the electrostatic device and the toner image is developed, the writing impressions are clearly", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Payment card fraud", "back": "misuse of credit or debit card information to make purchases without the cardholder’s authorization. Payment card fraud is successful because it is unlikely that the fraudster will be caught and prosecution is not ensured. Retailers have identified payment card thieves and contacted law enforcement, but they often receive little or no response", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: upon receipt of payment. This", "back": "deducting the payment amount from the balance of the card account before the check or other payment instrument clears the bank. Experienced fraud rings can easily exploit such a vulnerability. Using a forged or counterfeit check, an advance or overpayment is made on a stolen credit", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The internet", "back": "primary venue for trafficking stolen payment card information. Thieves find payment cards or lists of cardholders and their corresponding account numbers, and then make them available to a larger group, which uses the information to obtain goods and services in the authorized cardholder’s name. Payment card and personal information is", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: reproduction process. However, the hologram", "back": "most difficult aspect of a payment card to accurately reproduce. True holograms use a lenticular refraction process; counterfeits", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The essential part of any detection program", "back": "education of the tellers and merchants who are responsible for handling the transactions. It is widely suspected that the majority of store clerks and cashiers do not check payment card signatures or request identification from a customer who presents a card as payment.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Review statements via electronic", "back": "rather than waiting for paper statements. If possible, cancel paper statements altogether. Destroy expired cards. Never reveal a card number to someone who has offered you a prize via a phone call.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Parasitic Viruses", "back": "Parasitic viruses (sometimes called binary file infectors) attach themselves to program files (i.e., executables). When a user launches a program that has a parasitic virus, the virus is also launched. The parasitic virus is given the same rights as the program to which the virus is attached because the operating system considers it to be part of the program. These rights allow the virus to replicate, install itself into memory, or release its payload.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Multi-Partite Viruses", "back": "Multi-partite viruses use a combination of methods to infect files; if they cannot infect a system using one method, they try another.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Directory Viruses", "back": "An operating system finds files by looking up the path (composed of the disk drive and directory) in which each file is stored, and directory viruses corrupt a directory entry so that it points to itself instead of the file it is replacing. That is, these viruses change the paths that indicate the location of a file. If a user executes a program (file with the extension .exe or .com) that has been infected by a directory virus, the user unwittingly runs the virus program", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Stealth Viruses", "back": "Stealth viruses use multiple techniques to conceal themselves from users and virus scanners. They constantly change their patterns to blend into the system. Stealth viruses also encrypt their virus code to evade anti-viral software, and they remove their code from any infected files before a requesting program accesses the file.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Resident Viruses", "back": "A virus can be either a resident virus or a direct action (nonresident) virus. A resident virus installs itself in the infected computer’s memory. Upon execution, this type of virus searches for other files or programs to infect.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Direct-Action (Nonresident) Viruses", "back": "In contrast to resident viruses, direct-action viruses load themselves onto the target system’s memory, infect other files, and then unload themselves.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Network Viruses", "back": "Network viruses use network protocol, commands, messaging programs, and data links to spread. These viruses are generally developed to attack the file servers.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "File Infectors", "back": "File infectors are viruses that attach themselves to programs or executable files (files with an .exe or .com extension). When an infected file or program is run, whether directly or indirectly, the virus is activated, producing the damaging effects it is programmed to execute.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "File Allocation Table Viruses", "back": "These viruses attack the file allocation table (FAT), a type of file system used to organize data and locate files. A FAT virus can be especially dangerous because it prevents access to certain parts of the disk where important files might be stored. These viruses can cause damages resulting in information losses from individual files or entire directories.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Companion Viruses", "back": "Companion viruses can be considered file-infector viruses. They are known as companion viruses because once they get into the system, they accompany other files that already exist on the infected system; that is, once these viruses attach themselves to a legitimate program, they create a program with a different filename extension; when the system’s user tries to execute the legitimate program, they execute the companion virus instead.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Polymorphic Viruses", "back": "A polymorphic virus is a virus that mutates itself and changes its structure to avoid detection. Some polymorphic viruses use different encryption schemes and require different decryption routines. Thus, the same virus might look completely different on different systems or even within different files. Other polymorphic viruses vary instruction sequences and use false commands to thwart antivirus software.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Macro Viruses", "back": "Macro viruses exploit macros in application programs. A macro is a stored series of commands that automate repetitive tasks. For example, a macro can tell Microsoft Word to spell-check a document automatically every 15 minutes. Many common applications (e.g., word processing, spreadsheet, and slide presentation applications) use macros. Considered a subclass of a virus, a computer worm is a malicious self-replicating computer", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Prevention", "back": "best approach to combating malware. Although prevention efforts can reduce the number of successful attacks, absolute protection is generally impossible to achieve. But even so, the following measures can help avoid infection from a malicious program: • Use anti-malware software to scan all incoming email messages and files.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: emerging security problems concerning email", "back": "huge volume of space required to archive old messages. In some organizations, people are regularly asked to cull through their old email messages and delete those that are no longer needed. Likewise, some organizations will delete any old email messages left on the mail server machines after a certain amount of time", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Electronic commerce, or e-commerce,", "back": "process of two or more parties making business transactions via computer and some type of network (e.g., a direct connection or the internet). This includes business-to-business (B2B) transactions, online retail, and the digitalization of the financial industry.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Authentication", "back": "the validation of a customer’s identity. E-commerce entities must ensure that they can determine with whom they (or their computers) are communicating. Transaction authentication protects two parties that exchange messages from any third party, but it does not protect the two parties from each other. The digital signature is the most", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Non-repudiation", "back": "a method to guarantee that the parties involved in an e-commerce transaction cannot repudiate (deny) participation in that transaction. That is, concerning information security, non-repudiation is a method to guarantee that the sender of a message cannot later deny having sent the message and that the recipient of the message cannot deny", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Cybersecurity", "back": "protection of computer systems and networks against unauthorized use, disclosure, modification, or destruction. Because certain controls inhibit productivity, security typically involves a compromise in which security officers, system users, and system operations and administrative personnel work together to achieve a balance between security", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Although criminal activity", "back": "focus of the material, a complete security system should blend elements of prevention and detection for all potential threats, including physical damage, natural hazards, environmental hazards, and threats to supporting utilities.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Examples Of Physical Controls", "back": "Examples of physical controls include: • Selecting sites that minimize the physical risks to computer-based assets (e.g., sabotage, arson, earthquakes, tornadoes, floods, or hurricanes) • Putting security fences around the perimeter of a computing facility", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Physical Access Controls", "back": "For computer security purposes, physical access controls are a notable type of physical control. Access control is a process by which users are identified and granted certain privileges to information, systems, or resources, and with access control systems, management can control access to information, systems, a physical facility’s areas, or resources. Physical access controls refer to the process by which users are allowed access to physical objects (e.g.,", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Locks And Keys", "back": "Locks and keys are the most common method used to control access to physical objects. Locks and keys are inexpensive and easy to install, and therefore, they are commonly used for controlling access to restricted areas. But because keys are easily lost or duplicated, many organizations use cipher locks (i.e., combination locks containing buttons that open the lock when a particular code is punched in). With cipher locks, care must be taken to", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Electronic Access Cards", "back": "Many organizations use electronic access cards that verify to an electronic card reader that the cardholder has the right to access particular areas. Electronic access cards and card readers offer several advantages. Management of an organization with an electronic access card system can deny access rights without having to change locks or re-code cipher locks and limit access to physical areas to certain times. This type of system can provide audit trails for", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Biometric Systems", "back": "Biometric technology systems control access by measuring some physiological or behavioral characteristics to label and describe individuals. Common physiological characteristics measured include fingerprints, palm prints, and iris patterns. These systems use such physiological properties to verify user access. Behavioral biometrics are related to the behavior of a person, and they include typing rhythm, gait, and voice, among others.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Logical access", "back": "the process by which users are allowed to use computer systems and networks, and logical access control refers to a process by which users are identified and granted certain privileges to information, systems, or resources. These controls are designed to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of informational resources.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: networks, and logical access control", "back": "a process by which users are identified and granted certain privileges to information, systems, or resources. These controls are designed to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of informational resources. In fact, one of the most effective methods for preventing system attacks by hackers,", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Identification", "back": "When users start to interact with an information system, they are required to provide an identifier (e.g., a username, employee number, or account number), and the system must recognize the user who is attempting to access a resource. Each user’s identifier should be unique, unlikely to change, and need not be kept secret. Thus, employees should not have the same type of usernames because it makes it easier for an attacker to spoof or log in using an", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Authentication", "back": "Once users are identified, they must be authenticated. There are three primary considerations associated with user authentication: A user must be prevented from fooling the computer system into thinking they are someone else. (False positive verification must be avoided.)", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Passwords", "back": "Passwords are the most common method to authenticate users for logical access. Password authentication uses a secret string of characters to control access to a particular resource. Passwords should only be known to the user and the access control system. Weak passwords are often exploited to breach system security; therefore, effective password administration is extremely important for maintaining security. Organizations should enforce", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Card-Based Systems", "back": "Again, a unique personal possession such as a coded card can be used to identify individuals accessing a system. There are various types of technology that can be used to verify the identity of persons attempting to gain access to a system, including smart cards. Smart cards—cards embedded with a built-in chip for onboard data storage or computation—are similar to automated teller machine (ATM) cards; like ATM cards, they are susceptible to loss", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Biometric Systems", "back": "To review, biometric systems measure physiological properties to identify and authenticate users. Common physiological characteristics measured include fingerprints, palm prints, and iris patterns, with facial and vocal recognition being used more frequently as well. Behavioral biometrics software authenticates users by monitoring their statistical characteristics, such as typing speed and keystroke touch.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Multifactor Authentication", "back": "Organizations should consider implementing a multifactor authentication security system. Multifactor authentication requires the presentation of two or more authentication factors to verify the legitimacy of a transaction, and it is a preferred method for preventing attackers from cracking passwords. To review, methods of authentication include: • Something the user knows (e.g., a password, personal identification number [PIN],", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Authorization", "back": "Authorization determines the privileges a user has on a system once they have been authenticated; that is, once a user has been verified and authenticated, the system should check each request to determine whether it is legitimate for that user. Some users might be authorized to perform only certain functions and to have access only to certain data. Moreover, each employee should only be allowed access to the information that they need to", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Network security", "back": "protection of the network perimeter, as well as the segmentation of the internal corporate network. Oftentimes, management devotes resources to protecting its network from outsiders but fails to properly segment its internal network based on risks. Much like logical access control, network resources and segments should only be made available to", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Firewalls", "back": "Firewalls are network hardware and software that block unauthorized or unverified access to computer systems and network assets. These tools survey incoming and outgoing transmissions and decide what type of traffic to permit onto an organization’s internal network based on factors such as origination or destination address, content of the message, protocol being used to transmit the message, and other filtering methods.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Intrusion Detection Systems", "back": "An intrusion detection system (IDS) is a device or software application that monitors an organization’s inbound and outbound network activity and identifies any suspicious patterns of activity that might indicate a network or system attack or security policy violations. An IDS alerts administrators when someone or something is trying to compromise the information system through malicious activities or security policy violations. These systems are designed to", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Tracing Corrupt Payments", "back": "Other techniques for tracing corrupt payments can be found in the “Tracing Illicit Transactions” chapter in the Investigation section of the Fraud Examiners Manual. A conflict of interest occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence their professional role. These schemes involve self-dealing by an employee or agent", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: in bribery schemes and conflict of interest schemes", "back": "fraudster’s motive. For instance, if an employee approves payment on a fraudulent invoice submitted by a vendor in return for a kickback, they have committed bribery. But if an employee approves payment on invoices submitted by their own company (and if their ownership is undisclosed), they have", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Interest In The Acquisition Of Assets", "back": "Not all purchasing conflicts occur in the traditional vendor-buyer relationship. Sometimes purchasing conflicts involve employees negotiating for the purchase of some unique, typically large asset such as land or a building in which the employee had an undisclosed interest. It is in the process of these negotiations that the fraudster violates their duty of loyalty to their employer. Because they stand to profit from the sale of the asset, the employee does not", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Turnaround Sales", "back": "A purchasing scheme that is sometimes used by fraudsters is called the turnaround sale, or the flip. In this type of scheme, an employee knows their employer is seeking to purchase a certain asset and takes advantage of the situation by purchasing the asset themselves (usually in the name of an accomplice or shell company). The fraudster then turns around and resells the item to their employer at an inflated price.", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Underselling", "back": "The first and most harmful is the underselling of goods or services. Just as a corrupt employee can cause their employer to overpay for goods or services sold by a company in which they have a hidden interest, so, too, can they cause the employer to undersell to a company in which they maintain a hidden interest. Also, many employees who have hidden interests in outside companies sell goods or services", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Writing Off Sales", "back": "The other type of sales scheme involves tampering with the victim company’s books to decrease or write off the amount owed by the company in which the employee has a hidden interest. For instance, after an employee’s company purchases goods or services from the victim organization, credit memos might be issued against the sale, causing it to be written off to contra accounts such as Discounts and Allowances. A large number of reversing entries to", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: A final type of conflict of interest", "back": "appearance of a conflict of interest. The appearance of a conflict is nearly as problematic as the existence of a true conflict. Examples involving the appearance of a conflict of interest include ownership in a blind trust, in which the employee has no authority to make investment decisions, or an external auditor owning a minority", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Contract And Procurement Fraud", "back": "The procurement system is the collection of processes, procedures, and entities involved in purchasing goods and services by public or private entities. And because the primary objective of an effective procurement policy is to achieve the best value of money, it is important that procurement processes avoid incidences of fraud. This section will address fraud in the procurement process, focusing on the following topics:", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: specifications,", "back": "attempts by contractors to deliver goods or services to the procuring entity that do not conform to the underlying contract specifications. Once contractors deliver goods that do not conform to the contract, they bill and receive payment for conforming goods or services without informing the purchaser of the deficiency.", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Red Flags Of Nonconforming Goods Or Services Schemes", "back": "The following is a list of potential red flags for nonconforming schemes: • High percentage of returns for noncompliance with specifications • Missing, altered, or modified product compliance certificate • Compliance certificates signed by employees with no quality assurance responsibilities • Materials testing done by supplier, using the supplier’s own personnel and facilities • Evidence that test or inspection results were falsified (e.g., documents appear altered or", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Detecting Nonconforming Goods Or Services Schemes", "back": "To detect nonconforming schemes, the fraud examiner should, at a minimum, examine the • Contract or purchase order (PO) specifications • Contractor’s statements, claims, invoices, and supporting documents • Test and inspection results for the relevant period, searching for discrepancies between tests and inspection results and contract specifications", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Red Flags Of Change Order Abuse", "back": "When a change order occurs, fraud examiners should immediately be concerned about whether the change was accidental or planned. The following list of red flags can help make • Poor contractor internal controls over determining the need for change orders (e.g., management officials fail to ensure that all proposed change orders are necessary for work that was not known or contemplated at the time the contract was awarded)", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Detecting Change Order Abuse", "back": "Fraud examiners can detect change order abuse by engaging in the following activities: • Examining contract change orders that add new items Examining contract change orders that increase the scope, quantity, or price of the", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Red Flags Of Cost Mischarging Schemes", "back": "Red flags of cost mischarging schemes include: • Contractor refuses, delays, or is unable to provide complete supporting data. • Contractor’s supporting documents are missing or unavailable for review. • Contractor’s supporting documents are of poor quality.", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Three Main Types Of Cost Mischarging Schemes", "back": "Generally, contractors commit one of three types of mischarges:", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Accounting Mischarges", "back": "Accounting mischarges occur when a contractor knowingly charges unallowable costs to the buyer by concealing or misrepresenting them as allowable costs, or by hiding them in accounts, such as office supplies, that are not usually closely audited. A variation of this type of scheme involves circumventing the limits for certain cost categories by charging those expenses to other cost categories that do not have such limits. For example, a contractor", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Material Mischarges", "back": "Occasionally, material costs are mischarged, both as to their reasonableness and their allocability. Material means physical inventory and component deliverables. It includes raw material and purchased parts, as well as subcontractor and intercompany transfers. In most cases, material cost mischarging is confined to instances involving raw material or interchangeable parts. Mischarges of finished materials are infrequent because the nature of", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory And Other Assets", "back": "Employees target inventory, equipment, supplies, and other noncash assets for theft in several ways. These schemes can range from the theft of a box of pens to the theft of millions of dollars’ worth of company equipment. These schemes can even entail an individual stealing and selling sensitive or confidential data, such as customer information. The term inventory and other assets is meant to encompass the misappropriation schemes involving any assets held by a", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The obvious problem with this kind of scheme", "back": "fact that the receiving report does not match the vendor’s invoice, which will likely cause a problem with payment. In the previous example, if the vendor bills for one thousand units but the accounts payable voucher only shows receipt of nine hundred units of merchandise, then someone will have to explain", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: missing assets. This", "back": "concealing the shrinkage that occurs from asset theft. Inventory and other assets are typically tracked through a two-step process. The first step, the perpetual inventory, is an ongoing count that records how much inventory should be available. When new shipments of merchandise are received, for instance, this merchandise is entered", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: inventory purchased", "back": "same and there is no change in the manufacturing process or purchase price. If sales and cost of sales change from $5,650,987 and $2,542,944 to $6,166,085 and $2,981,880, respectively, what are the data telling the fraud examiner? For one thing, sales have increased by 9.12%, whereas cost of sales increased by 17.26%. The profit", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Corruption", "back": "Corruption can be found in any business or organization, and it is one of the three major categories of occupational fraud and abuse (along with asset misappropriation and financial statement fraud). An organization that understands the specific factors involved in corruption schemes can take steps to prevent, detect, and investigate them. Corruption is a term used to describe various types of wrongful acts designed to cause an", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Official bribery", "back": "the corruption of a public official to influence an official act of government. The term official act stems from traditional bribery statutes that only proscribe payments made to influence the decisions of government agents or employees. In contrast, commercial bribery refers to the corruption of a private individual to gain a commercial", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In contrast, commercial bribery", "back": "the corruption of a private individual to gain a commercial or business advantage. In commercial bribery schemes, something of value is offered to influence a business decision rather than an official act, as is the case in official bribery. Commercial bribery may or may not be a criminal offense. For example, in the United States,", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Employees With Approval Authority", "back": "In most instances, kickback schemes involve overbilling. In these schemes, a vendor submits inflated invoices to the victim organization, and the false invoices either overstate the cost of actual goods and services or reflect fictitious sales. To ensure that the inflated invoices get approved, the corrupt vendor offers kickbacks to an employee of the victim organization who has the authority to approve payment of the fraudulent invoices. By enlisting the help of an", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fraudsters Lacking Approval Authority", "back": "While the majority of kickback schemes involve individuals with authority to approve purchases, this authority is not an absolute necessity. When employees cannot approve fraudulent purchases themselves, they can still orchestrate a kickback scheme if they can circumvent accounts payable controls. In some cases, they can do this by filing a false purchase requisition. If a trusted employee tells their superior that the company needs certain", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Financial Institution Fraud", "back": "External fraud schemes are those committed by outside entities, typically by individuals or groups of individuals against organizations. Fraud schemes committed by outsiders usually occur within specific industries. Therefore, the following chapters are organized by type of industry, starting with financial institution frauds. Because some schemes are committed by collusion between an organizational insider and an outsider, some frauds can be classified as", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Embezzlement", "back": "wrongful taking or conversion of the property of another by a person to whom it has been lawfully entrusted (or to whom lawful possession was given). Misapplication of bank funds is a type of embezzlement in which bank employees wrongfully take or convert another party’s property, often from customer accounts, for the benefit of the employee or", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: A suspense account", "back": "the section of an organization’s books where unclassified debits and credits are recorded. Placing an entry in a suspense account is designed to be a temporary measure, pending the ultimate disposition of the transaction. Employees often use suspense accounts to perpetrate fraud against their employer at both financial institutions and other", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Estimates Of Costs To Complete", "back": "When borrowers approach a lending institution for construction financing, they typically have a development plan, complete with an engineering report, appraisal, and budget for construction costs. The construction cost budget is, by definition, an estimate. As the project is built out, the budget will be revised to reflect actual expenses. Budgets are delineated by specific line item, such as foundation, exterior glass, grading, landscaping, and tenant", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Developer Overhead", "back": "It is not uncommon in construction financing to have a budget line item for developer overhead (also called general conditions). This creates an opportunity for the developer to use it to their advantage. The purpose of developer overhead is to supply the developer with operating capital while the project is under construction. This overhead allocation should not include a profit percentage, as the developer realizes profit upon completion.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: whose ultimate collateral", "back": "property and not some other short-term collateral. Historically, troubled construction loans or foreclosures due to fraud have been totally disbursed in the developer overhead category.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Draw Requests", "back": "Construction loan advances are generally supported by draw requests. A draw request is the documentation substantiating that a developer has incurred the appropriate construction expenses and is now seeking reimbursement or direct payment. A typical fraud scheme that occurs in a draw request involves requesting advances on the loan for inappropriate costs, such as personal expenses and/or construction costs for an unrelated project. Draw requests", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: contract on file.", "back": "request appropriate for the terms and conditions of the contract? Has the contract/purchaser been approved? Financial Institution Fraud", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Retainage", "back": "The final area of major concern in construction lending is retainage (sometimes called the holdback). Retainage is the amount withheld from each draw request until the construction is complete and the lien period has expired. There are at least two reasons why construction loans contain a retainage provision. The first reason is to keep the contractor’s interest in the project until all the work has been completed and accepted by the owner. The amount of the", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Loan File", "back": "Missing documents in the loan file are another cause for concern. It is important to determine if missing documents have been misplaced or were never received. A waiver of certain documents is one common way for lenders to conceal fraud schemes. The documentation required to obtain loans for real estate and real estate development is fairly standard. The following are some of the more important documents that should be", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Disbursement File", "back": "Copies of all checks issued at closing Lien releases issued at closing (i.e., architect, engineers)", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Letter Form Report", "back": "The letter form report is used when a client is familiar with the area, and, therefore, supporting data are not necessary. The report consists of a brief description of the property, the type of value sought, the purpose served by the appraisal, the date of valuation, the value conclusion, and the signature of the appraiser. Financial institutions do not normally use this", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Short Form Report", "back": "Financial institutions typically use the short form report for residential real estate loans (sometimes referred to as consumer loans). The report varies from one to four pages and consists of check sheets or spaces to be filled in by the appraiser about pertinent property data.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Narrative Report", "back": "The narrative form includes all pertinent information about the area and the subject property, as well as the rationale for the estimated value. It includes maps, photographs, charts, and surveys or plot plans. Financial institutions use narrative reports to support real estate lending and investment decisions on large commercial real estate transactions. Any other type of appraisal report (i.e., letter form or short form) on these complex transactions would likely be", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fair Market Value", "back": "This is the estimated price at which the property would sell if freely offered on the open market with both a willing seller and a willing buyer.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Sales Price", "back": "Sales price is the actual price paid for the property. It might be higher or lower than fair", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Loan Value", "back": "Loan value is the percentage of a property’s value (fair market value or sales price) a lender", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Sales Comparison Approach", "back": "The sales comparison approach is suitable for the appraisal of land, residences, and other types of improvements that exhibit a high degree of similarity, and where a ready market exists. Compared to the other approaches, this method has greater influence on residential portfolio valuations. This method is the least complicated to understand and apply. Subject property is compared with similar property that is either offered for sale or has", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Cost Approach", "back": "The cost approach generally does not exert much influence on the appraiser’s final value estimate. It serves as a benchmark against which the sales comparison and income approaches are measured. The cost approach is more accurate for new properties. It views the value of a parcel as the combination of the land value if vacant and the cost to construct a new building on the given date, less the accrued depreciation the existing building would", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Income Capitalization Approach", "back": "Under this approach, the property value is based on its capacity to continue producing income. This method is particularly effective in the valuation of complex commercial properties. The net income the property produces is an important consideration. Net income is the amount of money over the remaining life of the property and its improvements that a fully informed person, using good management, is warranted in receiving.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Income capitalization", "back": "mathematical process of estimating the present value of income property based on the anticipated annual net income it will produce. Key to the application of this approach is the capitalization rate that is used. There are three types of capitalization rates: interest rate, recapture rate, and overall capitalization rate. Interest rate is the rate of return earned on", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: this approach", "back": "capitalization rate that is used. There are three types of capitalization rates: interest rate, recapture rate, and overall capitalization rate. Interest rate is the rate of return earned on investment capital. Recapture rate is the rate of return originally invested funds provided the owner. Overall capitalization rate is a combination of the interest and recapture rates.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: investment capital. Recapture rate", "back": "rate of return originally invested funds provided the owner. Overall capitalization rate is a combination of the interest and recapture rates. Fraudulent Appraisals Fraudulent appraisals result from any number of situations, some of which are:", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Loan officer", "back": "representative of the mortgage lender that finds and assists borrowers in", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Mortgage Lenders", "back": "Today, the secondary market has overtaken deposit gathering as the source of funding for mortgage lending. Loans are sold in the secondary market at origination, thereby providing the bank with a steady supply of capital needed to make additional loans. Without the need for a lot of capital (deposits on the books), mortgage lenders started to evolve. Consequently, a smaller percentage of bankers are keeping their loans than in the past. Even", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Mortgage Brokers", "back": "Mortgage brokers are intermediaries who find and negotiate mortgage loans on behalf of Historically, mortgage loans were originated by the loan officer at the bank. Mortgage lenders, however, started relying on third-party originators (TPOs) to broker their loan products. Brokers could be paid a commission rather than a salary, an option that worked well for minimally capitalized mortgage lenders. As a result, the industry has seen the evolution of mortgage brokers.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Commission-Driven Business", "back": "Because the incomes of mortgage brokers and other third parties are proportional to the number of mortgages they originate, their goal is to produce and close as many loans as possible. When there are multiple players involved with vested interests to close a loan, the", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Lender Competition", "back": "The mortgage industry is very competitive, forcing some in the industry to cut costs and accept more risk. Consequently, previously unusual approaches to securing borrowers, such as reducing the time from origination to closing and introducing new loan products, have", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Loan Products", "back": "Competition for loans motivates investors, lenders, and brokers to generate more attractive products for a wider spectrum of borrowers to make money and capture market share.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Loan Volume", "back": "During boom periods in the real estate industry, high mortgage loan volumes mean an emphasis on production, often at the expense of quality-control efforts. As a result of the record volume of mortgage transactions in recent years, many lenders have been less than thorough in their pre-funding and quality-control reviews. This lack of controls and due diligence has contributed to increased occurrences of fraud.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Subprime Lending Market", "back": "While there is no industry-accepted definition of subprime, generally a subprime loan is one offered to people who have credit problems or who have demonstrated excessive use of credit. The loan’s interest rate is higher than the prevailing rate available to those with more", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Technology", "back": "Because most loan applications are received and processed electronically, the faceless nature of these transactions creates an environment susceptible to fraud. • Loan documentation is easy for the fraudster to fabricate using readily obtainable photoediting software. • Prepaid mobile phones and mail drops are used for false verification since it is difficult to trace the owner. To falsify current employment, a fraudster might rent a mailbox to be", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "New Players In The Industry", "back": "Traditionally, finance-related occupations, including accountants, mortgage brokers, and lenders, are the most common suspect occupations associated with reported mortgage fraud. Perpetrators in mortgage industry occupations are familiar with the mortgage loan process and therefore know how to exploit vulnerabilities in the system. However, organized crime is an increasing problem. In an environment where the", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Builder Bailout", "back": "A builder bailout scheme flourishes in a downturned economy. It usually occurs when a builder is left with stagnant inventory. The builder might be suffering from financial difficulties with these lingering homes and might need to sell them quickly to pay off delinquent debts. To dispose of the remaining properties, the builder might undertake a variety of schemes that could include, but are not limited to, the use of hidden seller financing", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Example Of A Builder Bailout Scheme", "back": "A builder bailout scheme might unfold like this: • The builder (or third party) recruits a straw borrower to purchase the property with no down payment and receive cash back at closing. The builder obtains an inflated appraisal that is used as a basis for the loan amount. This", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Characteristics Of A Builder Bailout", "back": "The following characteristics are common in builder bailout schemes: • New construction or renovated condo conversions in an overbuilt market • Slight decrease in sales and volume, followed by a spike in both volume and sales price • Non-local borrowers with no knowledge of the local market are recruited to purchase the", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Air Loans", "back": "Some builders might have debt on vacant land for which they do not have sufficient capital to construct a home. To get out from under the debt, the builder, in collusion with other industry insiders, might undertake an air loan scheme. An air loan is a loan for a nonexistent property—with air symbolizing the loan’s fraudulent absence of collateral. Most or all of the documentation is fabricated, including the borrower, the", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Identity Fraud Schemes", "back": "Identity fraud is defined as the misrepresentation of data underpinning one’s identity (such as using another person’s government identification number). Mortgage fraud is not immune to schemes involving the improper use of identifying data. The individuals in the best position to use a person’s identifying information for purposes of committing mortgage fraud are industry insiders. For example, mortgage brokers with access", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Health Care Fraud", "back": "Health care fraud may be defined as an intentional act to defraud a health care benefit program or to obtain through false representations money or other property owned by a health care benefit program. This type of fraud involves a deception or misrepresentation that an individual or entity makes, knowing that the misrepresentation could result in some unauthorized benefit to the individual, entity, or some other party. The most common fraud", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Another concept", "back": "self-insured plan, in which an employer accepts the financial risk of the health care costs of its employees. The employer administers its own health insurance benefits. Rather than shift the risk to a health insurance entity, the organization assumes the costs of health care for its employees or members and their dependents.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The term durable medical equipment (DME)", "back": "medical equipment that can withstand repeated use, such as wheelchairs and specialized patient beds. Fraud schemes perpetrated by DME suppliers frequently involve: • Falsified prescriptions for DME", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Pharmaceutical fraud", "back": "largest source of provider fraud in the health care industry, and can involve pharmaceutical manufacturers, pharmacies, and providers who prescribe such products. Fraud schemes stemming from pharmacy transactions include: • Merchandising—substituting something of value for a prescription drug", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: verification process", "back": "same as the procedures listed under the alteration process.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "International Classification Of Diseases Codes", "back": "The International Classification of Diseases (ICD) is a diagnostic coding system that is used to classify diseases and related health problems. It is published by the World Health Organization (WHO). More than one hundred countries use ICD codes to report mortality data, and many countries also use ICD codes to allocate resources and determine provider reimbursement. The ICD codes are updated periodically to reflect new diagnoses and other changes in the", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Procedural Codes", "back": "ICD is a diagnostic coding system. Some countries use a procedural coding system for the purpose of reimbursement. The United States, for example, uses a procedural coding system called Current Procedural Terminology (CPT), which is maintained by the American Medical Association (AMA). Each five-digit CPT code corresponds to a specific medical service. For example, the codes “90658” and “99214” refer to “flu vaccine” and “physician", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Unbundling", "back": "Because health care procedures often have special reimbursement rates for a group of procedures typically performed together (e.g., blood test panels by clinical laboratories), some providers attempt to increase profits by billing separately for procedures that are actually part of a single procedure. This process is called unbundling. Simple unbundling occurs when a provider charges a comprehensive code, as well as one or", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Mutually Exclusive Procedures", "back": "A variation of unbundling, this scam involves billing for procedures that are either impossible to perform together or, by accepted standards, should not be performed together.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Global Service Period Violations", "back": "Some dishonest providers will bill for a major procedure—such as a surgery—as well as related procedures when the fee for the major procedure already includes the fee for related procedures during the predefined time period (the global service period). Detecting these abuses can be difficult because the fraud examiner must determine which services are related to the surgery and which are not. This difficulty is compounded by the fact that such services", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: One form of medical fraud", "back": "billing for experimental use of new medical devices that have not yet been approved by the jurisdiction’s health care authority. Some hospitals deliberately mislead third-party payers by getting them to pay for the manufacturer’s research. Many of the doctors involved are alleged to have stock in the manufacturing companies.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Another common scheme", "back": "charging of additional hours of anesthesia. Patients should be billed from when they enter the surgery room to when they leave the surgery room. The revenue firm pads the bill by increasing the time billed to include time spent in a recovery room, or before the patient went into the operating room.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: these individuals with", "back": "of communication when they believe fraud is occurring. Disadvantaged populations must also be informed about the negative impacts of participating in such schemes, such as health risks and criminal liability. Health care programs must educate from within. Investigation units should be established to", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Insurance Fraud", "back": "The insurance business, by its very nature, is susceptible to fraud. Insurance is a risk distribution system that requires the accumulation of liquid assets in the form of reserve funds, which are in turn available to pay loss claims. Insurance companies generate a large steady flow of cash through insurance premiums. Steady cash flow is an important economic resource that is very attractive and easily diverted. Large accumulations of liquid assets make", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Equity funding", "back": "process of using existing premium/policy values to finance new businesses. As long as the insured is aware of what is being done by the agent and fully understands the long-range method of payment on the new contract, there is no apparent underwriting irregularity.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: though it is not absolute proof that a vehicle exists, it", "back": "basis for the issuance of insurance policies. Collecting on a phantom vehicle has been shown to be easy to do. Note that the term phantom vehicle might also refer to vehicles involved in uninsured motorist claims wherein the vehicle and driver that purportedly caused the damage in question cannot be identified.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Swoop And Squat", "back": "A victim of this scheme is passed by two cars while driving. The car in the lead cuts in front of the second, forcing it to stop abruptly. The victim rear-ends the second car while the other driver speeds away. Victims often accept responsibility for the accident, thinking it was their fault for not paying attention. The rear-ended vehicle usually contains the maximum amount of passengers, all of whom claim injuries.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: A home or car that has been burglarized", "back": "basis for filing a claim for recoveries of monies lost. However, as with items “destroyed” by fire, the items never existed or were", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: carrier for the employer. It", "back": "insurance carrier who pays for the perpetrator’s fraudulent medical bills and unnecessary absences. Nevertheless, the employer is a tertiary victim of these crimes, as the fake claims can result in higher premiums for the company in the future.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Employee Classification", "back": "Workers’ compensation rates vary depending on an employee’s job classification. Employees that have a higher risk for injury on the job will have a higher premium rate. For example, clerical employees have a lower probability for an injury than truck drivers or construction workers, and thus their premiums should be lower. Therefore, to lower their premium rate, an employer might intentionally misclassify employees.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Understatement Of Payroll", "back": "The premium for a specific job classification is based on the total payroll for that classification. The employer might understate the amount of the payroll for higher-risk classifications. Two men pleaded guilty to charges of conspiracy and mail fraud in connection with a fraudulent scheme to reduce workers’ compensation claims for a construction company. The men falsely reported that workers in high-risk trades were engaged in less dangerous", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "History Of Past Losses", "back": "The modification or mod factor is a multiplier that is used to determine premium rates. The multiplier is derived by comparing the employer’s claims history with other employers’ claims histories in the same industry. The higher the claims loss, the higher the mod, and thus the higher the premium. A new business starts with a neutral mod for that type of business. Employers that have a high mod factor might become a “new” business that does not have a", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Corporate Gerrymandering", "back": "The risk pool assigned to an employer accepts any business regardless of its claim experience. However, it does not have to accept any employer that owes premiums. Some employers create a new corporate entity to obtain coverage or avoid higher premiums due to past heavy losses. An insurance company was awarded a $15 million judgment against an entertainment company in a suit involving a workers’ compensation fraud scheme. The entertainment", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Forged Documents", "back": "Some employers forge or alter prior certificates showing coverage to collect payment for work done or as proof of coverage to authorities.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Premium Theft", "back": "Agents issue certificates of coverage indicating the customer is insured, but they never forward the premium to the insurance company.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Conspiring To Reduce Premiums", "back": "An agent might alter the application for coverage completed by the employer to be able to offer a lower premium to their client. The agent might also improperly advise the employer as to how to complete the application or advise the employer to transfer a group of employees into a lower risk classification to avoid the experience modifier. Even though the employer might not be aware that the schemes are a violation of law, the", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Injury Fraud", "back": "In this type of fraud, false information about the injured worker is submitted to the workers’ compensation carrier. The report describes the injury and states that the employee is either totally or partially disabled and either unable to work or only able to work part-time. In many of these schemes, the fraud is helped along by a doctor who, for a fee, will provide a false diagnosis and false medical records for phony treatments.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Secondary Employment", "back": "Employees who are collecting workers’ compensation benefits might also secure a job with another employer—either part-time or full-time. The employee might fake their identity or assume someone else’s identity to receive compensation. Organized fraud schemes are composed of the united efforts of a lawyer, a capper, a doctor, and the claimant. This scheme is used not only in workers’ compensation cases but also in", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Lawyer", "back": "Lawyers are usually the organizers of the schemes and the ones who will profit the most. The majority of workers’ compensation cases are accepted on a contingency fee basis. If no settlement is awarded, then the lawyers will not be paid. This is a high-volume business, and the lawyers do not want the cases to be litigated. They are relying on the insurance company’s desire to settle as quickly as possible.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Capper", "back": "Cappers, also known as runners or steerers, are used to recruit patients for the scheme. They might be employed by either the attorney or doctor and are paid—either on a percentage of the total or on a per-person basis—for bringing in patients. Cappers might approach patients at unemployment compensation lines, work sites, scenes of accidents, or at any other type of organized gathering. Patients are brought into the scheme with promises of enrichment.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Doctor", "back": "Doctors might be organizers or players in the scheme, but they must be a part of it for it to work properly. Doctors are used to make the scheme appear authentic, and they are well compensated for their efforts. The doctors bill for services that they might or might not render, as well as for unnecessary services. In addition, if patients have regular health insurance, doctors might double bill for the services. If an injury is the result of an", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Address Similarity Reports", "back": "Address similarity reports electronically compare multiple payments going to the same address. These reports are extremely useful because they might show a payment defalcation or funds going to another insurance company, broker, or fictitious payee.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "File Comparison Tools", "back": "A comparison of issue files to disbursement files can determine if funds are being used to place new policies by using the equity of old policies. For example, computer-assisted audit tools and techniques (CAATTs) are used to download and compare electronic files.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Electronic Confirmations", "back": "Electronic confirmations should be sent to verify that company records agree with policyholder records. These types of confirmations can be sent to policyholders when disbursements have been mailed for premiums that are in force (i.e., active) or lapsed or when there has been a change of address on an account.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Exception Or Manual Override Reports", "back": "Computerized reports that list all exceptions to normal electronic processing can be produced. All human intervention can appear on a periodic management information report and can be test-checked by management. It is imperative that management review all exception reports for possible frauds on an ongoing basis. Many insurers have implemented special investigation units (SIUs) within their organizations", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fraud Risk Assessments", "back": "Insurance companies must be aware of the risks faced both within and outside of their organizations to prevent this type of fraud from occurring. Conducting a fraud risk assessment is one of the most efficient tools that insurance companies can use to assess and respond to fraud. A fraud risk assessment is a process aimed at proactively identifying and addressing an organization’s vulnerabilities to both internal and external fraud. By doing so,", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Underwriting And Claims-Handling Processes", "back": "To prevent fraudulent insurance claims from being paid to claimants, insurance companies need to have efficient underwriting and claims-handling processes in place. Artificial intelligence is increasingly being used by insurance companies in their claims and underwriting processes to save time and identify potentially fraudulent claims as they occur. There is software available that allows insurance companies to identify patterns in customer", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Aggressive Prosecutions", "back": "Often, fraudsters believe the large financial incentive of successfully committing insurance fraud far outweighs the risk of being caught. Offenders should be prosecuted aggressively to combat insurance fraud. Penalties such as jail, probation, or fines imposed in criminal court might prevent some individuals from engaging in this type of fraudulent behavior.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Consumer Fraud", "back": "Consumer fraud embodies a wide variety of misleading practices related to advertising, marketing, or the selling or buying of goods and services. It can arise when a product or service does not operate as intended and can involve the concealment or overcharging of fees. It can also occur when a seemingly legitimate company urges a customer to agree to unfair terms just to complete a transaction or when a victim purchases a product that appears", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In an adoption scheme where the birth mother", "back": "perpetrator, she agrees to give her unborn child to multiple adopting families in exchange for money. The birth mother requires an up-front payment from each family, but she has no plans for them to adopt her child. In frauds perpetrated by the adopting parents, they might verbally agree to let the birth mother", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Verifiers", "back": "Next, the caller is passed to a verifier, who reads some vague words about the deal and records the person’s agreement. These recordings intentionally exclude important details, recording only the customer’s consent. The customers of fraudulent telemarketing operations are not the only victims. Fronters are often poorly educated and easily taken advantage of by the career criminals who manage the operations. Salespeople might face hidden costs in a work agreement, similar to the ones", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "International Factoring Companies", "back": "Factoring through Asian and European merchants is becoming increasingly common. Factoring companies in these countries tend to charge a lower price for their services than some other countries—between 9% and 10% of the gross. Regardless of their locale, factors have the opportunity to make a great profit. They also, however, risk that banks will put a hold on their accounts or sue them for excessive chargebacks. In response to the losses", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Another convenient tool that the telemarketer can use", "back": "check-cashing store. If a boiler room operation wants to avoid the risks of setting up a bank account that might be traced or seized, customers’ personal checks are taken to a company that cashes them for a small fee. These establishments rarely require any identification to cash the checks. Customers might", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Timeshares", "back": "Another scam sells timeshares in condominiums for travelers. Telemarketers pass themselves off as brokers to condominium owners and purport to specialize in selling timeshares. Some real estate ads try to coax investors into buying “options” on property. Supposedly, the option locks in a present-day price on behalf of the purchaser, who can exercise the option later if they wish to buy the land or to sell it at a profit. Sometimes the investor has bought", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Developed Property", "back": "Various developed property schemes have been identified globally. These scams often involve a large deposit toward a property in a paradisiacal location such as Belize or Costa Rica that might or—more likely—might not be refunded dependent upon contractual technicalities. Those who do buy property through these schemes often find that their property is not as advertised or is heavily restricted from further development. In one example, the General", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Identity Theft", "back": "Identity theft is a common type of fraud that is non-discriminatory. Anyone can be targeted; the victim might be a college student, a retiree, a schoolteacher, or a successful attorney. Even businesses can be victims of identity theft. Although there is not a universal definition of identity theft, most law enforcement organizations use a definition similar to the following: Identity theft is a crime in which someone wrongfully obtains and uses another person’s", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Shoulder surfing", "back": "practice of observing another person (e.g., looking over the person’s shoulder) to gather personal information. Shoulder surfing is especially effective in crowded areas where a fraudster can stand close to a victim without being noticed. While in close proximity, the fraudster can eavesdrop on the victim’s telephone conversation, view the", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In the context of identity theft, social engineering", "back": "the psychological manipulation of people to trick them into revealing personal or business information. Social engineering exploits the natural tendencies of humans to be cooperative and to trust others. After researching a victim, social engineers often impersonate someone the victim can trust, such as", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Computer hacking", "back": "the use of technology to gain unauthorized access to sensitive information on a computer system. Computer hackers target companies’ computer networks for multiple reasons. If the personal information of a company’s customers is compromised, this is known as a data", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Theft Of Data And Intellectual Property", "back": "Today, information is a valuable asset, and organizations must protect their intellectual property. A business’s worth is no longer based solely on tangible assets and revenue-making potential; the information it develops, stores, and collects accounts for a large share of a To a considerable degree, businesses, government administrations, and society as a whole have come to depend on the efficiency and security of information technology, resulting in", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: intentions. In contrast, espionage", "back": "the use of illegal, clandestine means to gather information; therefore, it does not cover legitimate intelligence collection and analysis using legal means. Espionage, however, can be further subdivided into two categories: traditional and corporate. Traditional espionage refers to government-sponsored or sanctioned espionage", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: and corporate. Traditional espionage", "back": "government-sponsored or sanctioned espionage conducted to collect protected information from a foreign government. Corporate espionage (also known as industrial espionage) is the term used to describe the use of illegal, clandestine means to acquire information for commercial purposes.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: (also known as industrial espionage)", "back": "term used to describe the use of illegal, clandestine means to acquire information for commercial purposes. Competitive intelligence is a legitimate business function that aligns with marketing and research and development (R&D), as well as general business strategy and the newer", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: information (such as trade secrets)", "back": "right to access it. Open-source information is available to anyone who wants to collect it, without legal consequences. Nonpublic information, however, is not open to the public. Access to nonpublic records is restricted. Obtaining nonpublic records without appropriate authority violates the law.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Physical surveillance", "back": "real-time observation of a target’s actions or communications. Observing and recording a target’s movements is useful for several reasons. Such surveillance can be used to identify real property or other assets; additional targets; individuals who might possess valuable information, such as lawyers, accountants, or bankers; businesses; patterns", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Mobile Surveillance", "back": "Mobile surveillance involves observing and following persons. When conducting mobile surveillance, an intelligence professional must be flexible and imaginative. For example, placing a reflective stripe on the back of the subject’s car makes it more distinctive at night and therefore easier to follow. If legally permissible, an intelligence professional might place a GPS tracking device on the subject’s car so that its path can be traced 24 hours a day. Also, if", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fixed Surveillance", "back": "Fixed surveillance is a situation in which an individual secretly observes an area or a person from a distance. This method, however, has a key disadvantage: the base from which the surveillance is conducted might be spotted by the target or other people passing by. Therefore, intelligence professionals must camouflage fixed surveillance campaigns, and to do so, they must be familiar with their surroundings and choose a cover that will not draw attention.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Technical surveillance", "back": "practice of covertly acquiring audio, visual, or other types of data from targets through the use of technical devices, procedures, and techniques. Technical surveillance, however, can be costly; it is labor intensive, highly intrusive, and fraught with potential legal problems.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Physical infiltration", "back": "process whereby an individual enters a target organization to spy on the organization’s employees. Often, corporate spies use physical infiltration when there is a tight time schedule, a lack of available recruits, or expense constraints; however, spies might also use physical infiltration when they have specialized knowledge that makes them the best", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Gather Intelligence About The Target", "back": "To conduct a successful social engineering attack, social engineers must gather information about the target and the target’s environment. The more information a social engineer has about their target, the greater the chances that their attack will be successful. For example, a social engineer will have a greater chance of success if they know their target’s internal processes, jargon, and organizational structure.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Select The Tactic", "back": "Once the social engineer has collected an appropriate amount of information about the target, they will determine which tactic would be most suitable to achieve the desired goals. Social engineers use various tactics, including:", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Pretexting", "back": "Pretexting is the act of impersonating someone else or making false or misleading statements to persuade a target to release information or perform some action. Pretexting can occur inperson, over the phone, or through some other form of communication. Social engineers often engage in pretexting by posing as a person of authority, a member of tech support, someone who has legitimate access to the target’s network, an individual who", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Shoulder Surfing", "back": "Shoulder surfing involves observing an unsuspecting target from a nearby location while the target enters a username and password into a system, talks on the phone, fills out financial forms, or performs some other task from which the engineer can obtain valuable information.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Spam And Chain Emails", "back": "Social engineers use spam and chain emails to carry out their attacks. Email is a common method used in social engineering attacks because it is widely used, and social engineers can send emails designed to look like they come from popular, trusted sources. Also, social engineers can include infected attachments or links directing targets to malicious sites in such emails. Moreover, social engineers can design emails to contain specific content particular to", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reverse Social Engineering", "back": "In reverse social engineering schemes, social engineers make targets think that the engineers can help them by providing security-related services. These schemes involve three phases. Theft of Data and Intellectual Property First, social engineers sabotage the target’s network or make the target think that the network has been sabotaged. This can be done by launching a network attack against a target website", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Contact And Build Trust With The Target", "back": "Once social engineers have collected an appropriate amount of information about their targets and selected the tactic, they will contact their targets, seeking to build trust with them. The trust that social engineers gain will be used to elicit information that can be exploited to reach the goals of their attack. Building trust serves several purposes, including: • Putting targets at ease and making them more comfortable", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Elicitation Skills", "back": "Although social engineering does not require a high level of technical expertise, it does require social skills and other components. The social skills and components needed to be a • Adaptability (i.e., ability to adapt communications to fit the environment and situation) • Relationship and bonding skills (i.e., ability to build bonds or relationships with", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Common Elicitation Tactics", "back": "Social engineers use numerous tactics to elicit information. Some common elicitation • Appealing to the target’s ego: Social engineers often appeal to their targets’ egos to coax them into a conversation that otherwise would not take place. Likewise, appealing to a target’s ego will tend to make the target more self-assured, which tends to remove logical awareness that a potential breach might be occurring.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Again, technical surveillance", "back": "practice of covertly acquiring audio, visual, or other types of data from targets through the use of technical devices, procedures, and techniques. When Theft of Data and Intellectual Property corporate spies resort to the use of technical surveillance, it is usually to gather", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: become common", "back": "by which intelligence professionals can monitor their competition. The spy has two primary considerations in a wiretapping campaign: where to insert the surveillance equipment and which of the various technologies to employ.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Insertion Point", "back": "In identifying the insertion point, the spy must choose an area where proprietary information is likely to be discussed or displayed and where background noise and electronic interference remain minimal. Spies frequently choose areas with proximity to computers and telecommunications equipment carrying proprietary data as an insertion point. Spies might also target areas conducive to employee conversations. This can include any place", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "back": "Much of our understanding of criminal behavior can be attributed to B. F. Skinner, described by many as one of the greatest social scientists of the 20th century. Skinner promised that he would revolutionize not just psychology, but all of human society with his theories of behaviorism. According to Skinner, human behavior should be approached scientifically. By analyzing people’s actions, the behaviorist hoped to alter or direct behavior for the greater", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: room. Good. Here", "back": "key to the car.” The behavior (cleaning) is reinforced by the awarding of the positive stimulus (the car key). In contrast, a negative reinforcement withdraws a negative stimulus in exchange for the desired response. Continuing the example, the parent might say, “I will stop hassling you if you clean this room.” The negative stimulus (hassling) is", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: game, and it", "back": "game of their lives. Behaviorists agree. Money is a “generalized reinforcer,” directly linked with many positive factors and often taking on a symbolic power of its own, thereby yielding a condition of strength. Skinner says, “We are automatically reinforced, apart from any particular deprivation, when we successfully control the physical world.”2 So, an", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Psychological Variables", "back": "The Chicago Study was designed to gauge the difference between citizens’ concerns for favorable outcomes and procedural fairness. It also measures the extent to which fairness influences reactions to experience. The experience in question is of the everyday, averagecitizen variety—the type of encounter most of us have with authorities over relatively minor matters. Participants reported calling the police for a number of reasons: accidents,", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Legitimacy And Experience", "back": "People are more likely to accept unfavorable rulings if they believe their case was handled fairly. Thus, fair procedures can lessen the severity of an outcome that is to one’s disadvantage, without damaging the authorities’ legitimacy. Of course, fair procedures can only go so far. If fair procedures consistently produce unfavorable results, the fairness of the procedures will come into question. People typically place importance on procedure for several reasons. The first is simplicity.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Meaning Of Procedural Justice", "back": "Another important issue is how people evaluate procedures for fairness. Previous efforts to study this question have focused on control. Two areas of control with which people are generally concerned are decision control (control over the actual decisions made) and process control (control over the opportunity to state one’s case). To better illustrate, consider an attorney representing a client in court. While the client", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: allocation process. Consistency", "back": "the uniform and unbiased treatment of all of the affected parties. Suppression of bias guarantees that those involved with the outcome have no personal, vested interest in the case. This also prohibits a participant’s reliance on previously formed opinions rather than just the evidence at hand, as when a juror votes", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Influence Of Control On The Meaning Of Procedural Justice", "back": "The Chicago Study assessed process control by questioning respondents about how much opportunity they had to state their case or present their problem. Decision control was measured by asking how much influence participants had over the determinations made by the third party in control. Most participants felt they had a high (43%) to moderate (20%) level of process control. In contrast, a number of participants felt they had little decision", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Target hardening", "back": "preventive controls that aim to reduce or avoid the likelihood of a crime occurring. Examples include locking doors, separating duties, physically safeguarding assets, and using online two-factor authentication. Deterrence theory states that punishment should be swift, certain, and severe for it to be an effective deterrent. Thus, if someone in an", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Another psychological theme is that frustration", "back": "precursor of aggression. The theory suggests that the expression of aggression, such as a fraud perpetrator retaliating against their employer, will alleviate the frustration and allow the organism to return to a more", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: society favors (e.g., wealth and power) and the", "back": "by which those goals are achievable. To explain crime, these theories tend to focus on poverty, poor education, the presence of neighborhood subcultures (e.g., gangs), a lack of employment opportunities, and the pressure to be materially successful.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: achieve such ends", "back": "cornerstone for explaining criminal behavior. Merton’s theory of anomie (that is, normlessness) was derived from the work of Émile Durkheim, a French sociologist who contextualized the term in his effort to explain suicide rates among different social groups. Merton’s theory characterizes the discord between goals", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: and the legitimate", "back": "available to achieve them as anomie. Strain theory argues that this disconnect inevitably leads to crime, as individuals struggle to fulfill their desires. Understanding Criminal Behavior Under Merton’s theory, the strain experienced by people can be either structural or", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: individual. Structural strain", "back": "societal-level processes, such as the way the government or economy functions, that gradually affect individuals. These structures might affect individuals’ opportunities and their general perceptions of society. Conversely, individual strain refers to the stress people feel and the difficulties they face when attempting to satisfy", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Institutional-Anomie Theory", "back": "An extension of anomie theory, specifically building on Robert Merton’s idea of structural strain, is the institutional-anomie theory (IAT). This theory attempts to explain differences in cross-cultural crime by the way a particular culture behaves economically, the expected behavior of its citizens, and the “opportunities [the culture provides] for its citizens to reach those expectations.”6 According to this theory, more crime occurs in countries where the", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "White-Collar Crime", "back": "Part of the study of criminology involves exploring the differences in various categories of crimes and the individuals who commit them. Understanding what makes fraud and other white-collar crimes different from other types of criminal acts can be extremely helpful in designing systems to prevent and detect them, as can recognizing the characteristics of the people who perpetrate these schemes. Since the term was first used, there have been constant disputes regarding what is (or should", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: definition of the concept in a footnote: White-collar crim", "back": "e was said to be “Crime in the upper, white-collar class, which is composed of respectable, or at least respected, business, and professional men.” These crimes were confined to acts performed by white-collar persons in occupational roles, thereby excluding “most of their cases of murder, adultery, and", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: and that, once a conviction is attained, higher status often", "back": "a stiffer sentence. Whitecollar crime does have a unique place in criminology, but the split is not between an underworld of the desperate poor and an elite universe of high-stakes fraudsters. White-collar crime has some relation to both of these mythological worlds, but is largely the province of the middle classes, where organizational position is more important than social or", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: “had lived beyond their", "back": "for some time before deciding to embezzle.”5 Crimes of the Middle Classes later extended this statement more generally, remarking, “The most interesting fact about the white-collar offenders’ aggregate financial status is not the value of their assets but the extent of their liabilities.” Offenders often “have the material goods associated with successful", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: organizations can invite fraud as a", "back": "of obtaining goals. Economist Oliver Williamson noted that, because of a department’s concern with reaching its goals, managers might well tend to maximize their department’s own interests to the detriment of the organization. Organizations can also be criminogenic because they encourage loyalty. According to Diane", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: giving attention to the", "back": "by which they are obtained, employees might have an easier time rationalizing misconduct in the pursuit of success. Corporate Executives and Criminal Liability Many of the ethical and legal problems of a corporation result from the corporate structure", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Deterrence", "back": "As a strategy to control crime, deterrence is designed to detect law violations, determine who is responsible, and penalize offenders to deter future violations. Deterrence systems try to control the immediate behavior of individuals, not the long-term behaviors targeted by Deterrence theory assumes that humans are rational in their behavioral patterns. Humans seek profit and pleasure while they try to avoid pain. Deterrence assumes that an individual’s", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Increased Enforcement", "back": "Formal levels of current enforcement in white-collar crime are, by all measures, extremely low. One view holds that increased enforcement can only come with a complete and total revision of the criminal justice system. Currently, people have little fear of detection because they know that the police and courts cannot keep up with the pace of criminal offenses. It is not necessary or even desirable to advocate longer prison sentences for offenders because we do not have the", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Importance Of Solving The Problem In Secret", "back": "Since Cressey’s study was done in the early 1950s, the workforce was obviously different from today’s workforce. But the employee faced with an immediate, non-shareable financial need has not changed much over the years. That employee still must find a way to relieve the financial pressure that bears down upon them. Simply stealing money, however, is not enough; Cressey found it was crucial that the employee be able to resolve the financial", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: share the fact that they were resorting to illegal", "back": "to relieve that pressure. To do so would be to admit that the problems existed in the first place. An interesting thing to note is that it is not the embezzlement that creates the need for secrecy in the perpetrator’s mind; it is the circumstances that led to the embezzlement (e.g., a", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: secrecy in the perpetrator’s mind; it", "back": "circumstances that led to the embezzlement (e.g., a violation of incurred obligation, a business reversal). Cressey said: In all cases [in the study] there was a distinct feeling that, because of activity prior to the defalcation, the approval of groups important to the trusted person had been lost, or a", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: with. Cressey observed, “It", "back": "next step which is significant to violation: the application of 31 Ibid., pages 66–67.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The third and final factor in the Fraud Triangle", "back": "rationalization. Cressey pointed out that rationalization is not an ex post facto means of justifying a theft that has already occurred. Significantly, rationalization is a necessary component of the crime before it takes place; in fact, it is a part of the motivation for the crime. Because embezzlers do not view themselves as", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: rationalization is not an ex post facto", "back": "of justifying a theft that has already occurred. Significantly, rationalization is a necessary component of the crime before it takes place; in fact, it is a part of the motivation for the crime. Because embezzlers do not view themselves as criminals, they must justify their misdeeds before they ever commit them. The rationalization", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Independent Businesspeople", "back": "The independent businesspeople in Cressey’s study were individuals who were in business for themselves and converted “deposits” that had been entrusted to them.37 Perpetrators in this", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Long-Term Violators", "back": "Cressey defined long-term violators as individuals who converted their employer’s funds, or funds belonging to their employer’s clients, by taking relatively small amounts over a period of time.39 Similar to independent businesspeople, the long-term violators generally preferred the “borrowing” rationalization. Other rationalizations of long-term violators were described, too, but they almost always were used in connection with the “borrowing” theme: (1) They", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Absconders", "back": "The third group of offenders Cressey discussed was absconders—people who take the money and run. Cressey found that the non-shareable problems for absconders usually resulted from physical isolation. He observed that these people, “usually are unmarried or separated from their spouses, live in hotels or rooming houses, have few primary group associations of any sort, and own little property. Only one of the absconders interviewed had held a higher status", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Projecting Total Fraud Losses Based On Imperfect Data", "back": "Even with these limitations on projecting the total amounts lost to fraud, the ACFE knows that such a projection has an important place in the fight against fraud. Consequently, the ACFE asked survey participants, based on their professional experience, what percentage of revenues they believe a typical organization loses to fraud each year. The median response provided by these CFEs is that organizations lose 5% of their annual revenues to fraud.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Fraud Costs We Know", "back": "Determining total fraud losses—whether globally, regionally, by industry, or within a specific organization—is outside the primary scope of the ACFE’s study. Instead, the focus is on analyzing known data to better understand the risks posed by occupational fraud. To that end, the ACFE examined the losses incurred in the actual cases of fraud reported to them to learn about how fraud affects its victims.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Categories Of Occupational Fraud", "back": "Of the three primary categories of occupational fraud, asset misappropriation is by far the most common, occurring in 86% of the cases in the ACFE’s study, as shown in Figure 2. However, asset misappropriation is also the least costly, causing a median loss of $100,000. Corruption schemes are the next most common form of occupational fraud, with 43% of the cases in the study involving some form of corrupt act. These schemes resulted in a median", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation Sub-Schemes", "back": "Within the category of asset misappropriation, the ACFE’s research shows that there are several distinct subcategories of schemes. The heat map in Figure 5 illustrates the relative frequency and cost of each of these scheme types. The schemes that fall in the darkest area of the heat map—check and payment tampering,64 billing, and theft of noncash assets—rank among the most common and costliest scheme types and thus typically pose the greatest risk", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Duration Of Fraud Schemes", "back": "Examining how long frauds tend to last can also provide insight into how they affect their victims. The median duration for all of the fraud cases in the ACFE’s study was 14 months. However, it stands to reason that the longer a fraud goes undetected, the larger the scheme will grow. Figure 6 shows that frauds that last over sixty months are nearly 15 times as costly as those that are caught in the first six months. The data also indicate that fraudsters tend to", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Initial Detection Of Occupational Frauds", "back": "Figure 9 shows that the leading detection methods are tips, internal audit, and management review. This finding is not surprising, as these have been the three most common means of detecting occupational fraud in every edition of the report since 2010. Collectively, these three detection methods were cited in 70% of the cases in the ACFE’s most recent study. Tips were by far the most common means of detection for 43% of cases—more than internal", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Tips were by far the most common", "back": "of detection for 43% of cases—more than internal audit (15%) and management review (12%) combined.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Source Of Tips", "back": "Since tips are the most common detection method, it is important to understand where those tips come from. Figure 10 shows that half of all tips (50%) were provided by employees of the victim organizations. Meanwhile, more than one-third (35%) of the tips that led to fraud detection came from people outside the organization: customers, vendors, and competitors. Active cultivation of tips and complaints, such as the promotion of fraud hotlines, is often", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Median Loss And Median Duration By Detection Method", "back": "In addition to determining the most common methods of detection, the ACFE also analyzed the median loss and duration of fraud schemes based on how they were uncovered. The results indicate that there is a correlation between the way in which occupational fraud schemes are detected and the severity of the fraud. More importantly, these data point to steps organizations can take to detect fraud proactively and, in doing so, mitigate losses.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Type Of Victim Organization", "back": "As shown in Figure 14, 70% of the frauds in the study occurred at for-profit organizations, with 44% of the victim organizations being private companies and 26% being public companies. The private companies in the study suffered the greatest median loss, at $150,000. Not-for-profit organizations were the victim in only 9% of frauds and had the smallest median loss of $75,000; however, for many not-for-profit entities, financial resources are", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Size Of Victim Organization", "back": "The size of an organization’s staff can directly affect both the opportunity for fraud and the ability to enact certain anti-fraud mechanisms. Larger entities typically have more resources to invest in their anti-fraud programs, as well as a greater ability to separate duties among staff members to help prevent fraud; however, the large staff size can also mean more potentially dishonest employees who might attempt schemes and more complex processes and", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Industry Of Victim Organizations", "back": "In addition, reported cases were examined based on the industry of the victim organization. Figure 19 provides a breakdown of the extent to which industries were affected by occupational fraud. The greatest number of cases in the study occurred in the banking and financial services, manufacturing, and government and public administration sectors. It should be noted that these data likely represent the industries that most often employ CFEs,", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Anti-Fraud Controls At The Victim Organization", "back": "The presence of a robust system of anti-fraud controls can be a powerful deterrent, as well as a proactive prevention and detection mechanism, in the fight against fraud. Thus, organizations can benefit from knowing which anti-fraud controls are commonly used by their peers, as well as which tend to be the most effective. To help explore this information, survey respondents were provided with a list of 18 entity-level, anti-fraud controls and", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Effectiveness Of Anti-Fraud Controls", "back": "Demonstrating the return on investment in anti-fraud initiatives can be a difficult task, as it is nearly impossible to measure the amount of fraud prevented by a specific control. However, many anti-fraud professionals find themselves needing to make a business case to justify additional fraud prevention and detection initiatives. To provide some visibility into the relative effectiveness of various anti-fraud controls, the ACFE compared the losses", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Behavioral Red Flags Displayed By Perpetrators", "back": "Individuals who are engaged in occupational fraud schemes often exhibit certain behavioral traits or warning signs associated with their illegal activity. Survey respondents were presented with a list of 17 common behavioral red flags, and they were asked to report on which, if any, of these red flags had been displayed by the perpetrator before the fraud was discovered. Figure 41 shows the frequency of behavioral red flags in the 2020 cases. The six most", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Corporate Governance", "back": "The term corporate governance refers to a corporation’s government; the term is broadly used to describe the oversight responsibilities of different parties for an organization’s direction, operations, and performance. More specifically, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development’s (OECD) “Glossary of Statistical Terms” defines corporate governance as: [The] procedures and processes according to which an organisation is directed and controlled.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Nominating Committee", "back": "The nominating committee is responsible for identifying, evaluating, and nominating new directors to the board. It also facilitates the election of the new directors by shareholders. Although management nominates board members as well, an effective nominating committee will select new members to ensure independence. Responsibilities of the nominating committee include, but are not limited to: • Reviewing current directors’ performance", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: to enforce these standards", "back": "responsibility of individual governments. The Principles cover six main areas, which are divided into chapters. The Principles: • Request that governments have in place an effective legal, regulatory, and institutional", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: as the election of board members, or other", "back": "of influencing the board’s composition, amendments to the company’s organic documents, approval of extraordinary transactions, and other basic issues as specified in company law and internal company statutes. This Section can be seen as a statement of the most basic rights of shareholders, which are", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: authority to engage in those acts. Apparent authority", "back": "that a third party would reasonably believe the employee is authorized to perform the act on behalf of the company. Therefore, an organization could be held liable for something an employee does on behalf of the organization even if the employee is not authorized to perform that act.", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: internal sources. Risk", "back": "the possibility that an event will occur and adversely affect the achievement of objectives.” Risk assessment involves the identification and assessment of the risks the entity faces in achieving its organizational objectives. This process is dynamic and iterative, and it forms the basis for determining how risks will be managed.", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Monitoring", "back": "process that assesses the effectiveness of a control system over time. This component should include both ongoing, automated evaluations and periodic, separate evaluations, the findings of which should be evaluated against predefined criteria. The following are the Framework principles supporting this component:", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: significant aspects of auditing. The following", "back": "full text of the Principles as released by IOSCO’s Technical Committee:5 3 The material in this section is compiled from materials and resources issued by the International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO). For more information about this organization, please see www.iosco.org.", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Introduction", "back": "1. Investor confidence is fundamental to the successful operation of the world’s financial markets. That confidence depends on investors having credible and reliable financial information when making decisions about capital allocation. 2. The objectives of securities regulation include the protection of investors; ensuring that markets are fair, efficient, and transparent; and the reduction of systemic risk. In pursuit", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Oversight Principles", "back": "1. Oversight of auditors can occur in several ways, including within audit firms, by professional organizations and public or private sector oversight bodies, and through government oversight. In addition, oversight may be provided by supervisory boards and audit committees representing investors in matters relating to individual companies. 2. Within a jurisdiction, auditors should be subject to oversight by a body that acts and is", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Organization", "back": "The PIOB comprises individuals from a number of professions and all branches of regulation. Its ten members were nominated by IOSCO, the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision (BCBS), the International Association of Insurance Supervisors (IAIS), the World Bank, and the European Commission.", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Responsibilities", "back": "The PIOB oversees IFAC’s Public Interest Activity Committees (PIACs) comprising the IAASB, International Accounting Education Standards Board (IAESB), International Ethics Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities Standards Board for Accountants (IESBA), their respective Consultative Advisory Groups (CAGs), and the Compliance Advisory Panel (CAP). In this capacity, the PIOB: • Ensures that the processes of standard development under its oversight follow due", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Communicating And Reporting About Fraud", "back": "In addition, the Practice Guide provides guidance about internal audit’s role in communicating fraud-related issues with management and the board of directors. In specific, the Practice Guide notes that “internal auditors, through the unique role they play, are well positioned to elevate the importance of fraud prevention and detection programs with In support of IIA Standard 2060, Reporting to Senior Management and the Board, the Practice", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: INTOSAI Guidance, which", "back": "third level, provides practical assistance to SAIs in implementing the framework in their individual constituencies. Portions of the first two elements of this framework are summarized in the", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: INTOSAI-P 1 – The Lima Declaration", "back": "foundation of the INTOSAI professional framework. It contains a comprehensive yet concise list of all goals and issues relating to government auditing. The main purpose of INTOSAI-P 1 – The Lima Declaration is to call for independent", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fundamental Principles Of Public-Sector Auditing", "back": "The principles contained in this section are fundamental to the conduct of an audit. Although auditing is a cumulative and iterative process, for the purposes of presentation, the fundamental principles are grouped by principles related to the SAI’s organizational requirements, general principles that the auditor should consider prior to commencement and at more than one point during the audit, and principles related to specific steps in the", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Organizational Requirements", "back": "Each SAI should establish and maintain procedures for ethics and quality control on an organizational level that will provide it with reasonable assurance that the SAI and its personnel are complying with professional standards and the applicable ethical, legal, and", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "General Principles", "back": "Ethics and independence—Auditors should comply with the relevant ethical requirements and be independent. Ethical principles should be embodied in an auditor’s professional behavior. The SAIs should have policies addressing ethical requirements and emphasizing", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: in the circumstances of the audit. The audit risk", "back": "risk that the audit report may be inappropriate. The auditor performs procedures to reduce or manage the risk of reaching inappropriate conclusions, recognizing that the limitations inherent to all audits mean that an audit can never provide absolute certainty of the condition of the subject matter.", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Principles Related To The Audit Process", "back": "− Auditors should ensure that the terms of the audit have been clearly established. Audits may be required by statute, requested by a legislative or oversight body, initiated by the SAI, or carried out by simple agreement with the audited entity. In all cases, the auditor, the audited entity’s management, those charged with governance, and others, as applicable, should reach a common formal understanding of the terms of the audit", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fraud-Related Standards For Financial Audits", "back": "ISSAI 200 – Fundamental Principles of Financial Auditing provides key principles and standards related to an audit of financial statements in the public sector.10 According to ISSAI 200, the auditor has the following objectives when conducting such an engagement: 10 ISSAI 200 – Fundamental Principles of Financial Auditing is available at www.intosai.org/fileadmin/downloads /documents/open_access/ISSAI_100_to_400/issai_200/issai_200_en.pdf.", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: A significant part of a fraud prevention program", "back": "expressed commitment of the board and senior management. This commitment forms the basis of the organization’s anti-fraud culture. A strong corporate culture can most often be observed by its outcome, rather than by any individual component. Fostering a culture of ethics and compliance is more beneficial than", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Background", "back": "The corporate anti-fraud policy is established to facilitate the development of controls that will aid in the detection and prevention of fraud against ABC Corporation. It is the intent of ABC Corporation to promote consistent organizational behavior by providing guidelines and assigning responsibility for the development of controls and the conduct of investigations.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Scope Of Policy", "back": "This policy applies to any irregularity or suspected irregularity involving employees, as well as shareholders, consultants, vendors, contractors, and outside agencies doing business with employees of such agencies, and/or any other parties with a business relationship with ABC Corporation (also called the Company). Any investigative activity required will be conducted without regard to the suspected wrongdoer’s length of service, position/title, or", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Constituting", "back": "The terms defalcation, misappropriation, and other fiscal irregularities refer to, but are not limited to, the following: • Any dishonest or fraudulent act • Misappropriation of funds, securities, supplies, or other assets • Impropriety in the handling or reporting of money or financial", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Irregularities", "back": "Irregularities concerning an employee’s moral, ethical, or behavioral conduct should be resolved by departmental management and the Employee Relations Unit of Human Resources (HR) rather than If there is any question as to whether an action constitutes fraud, contact the Director of ______________ for guidance.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Responsibilities", "back": "The ______________ Unit has the primary responsibility for the investigation of all suspected fraudulent acts as defined in the policy. If the investigation substantiates that fraudulent activities have occurred, the ______________ Unit will issue reports to appropriate designated personnel and, if appropriate, to the Board of Directors Decisions to prosecute or refer the examination results to the", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Confidentiality", "back": "The ______________ Unit treats all information received confidentially. Any employee who suspects dishonest or fraudulent activity will notify the _____________ Unit immediately and should not attempt to personally conduct investigations or interviews/interrogations related to any suspected fraudulent act (see REPORTING PROCEDURES", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Investigating", "back": "• Free and unrestricted access to all Company records and premises,", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Suspected Fraud", "back": "• The authority to examine, copy, and/or remove all or any portion of the contents of files, desks, cabinets, and other storage facilities on the premises without prior knowledge or consent of any individual who might use or have custody of any such items or facilities when it is within the scope of their investigation", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Procedures", "back": "Great care must be taken in the investigation of suspected improprieties or irregularities so as to avoid mistaken accusations or alerting suspected individuals that an investigation is under way. An employee who discovers or suspects fraudulent activity will contact the _____________ Unit immediately. The employee or other complainant may remain anonymous. All inquiries concerning the activity under investigation from the suspected individual, their", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Acting In Good", "back": "Anyone reporting any irregularity that is detected or suspected must be acting in good faith and have reasonable grounds for believing the information provided. Allegations made maliciously or with knowledge of their falsity will not be tolerated. People making such allegations may be subject to institutional disciplinary action and/or legal actions by the individuals accused of fraudulent conduct.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Protection", "back": "Employees of ABC Corporation may not retaliate against a whistleblower for reporting an activity which that person believes to be fraudulent or dishonest with the intent or effect of adversely affecting the terms or conditions of employment (including, but not limited to, threats of physical harm, dismissal, transfer to an undesirable job assignment, demotion, suspension, or impact on salary or wages). A whistleblower is defined as an employee who informs a", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Termination", "back": "If an investigation results in a recommendation to terminate an individual, the recommendation will be reviewed for approval by the designated representatives from HR and the Legal Department and, if necessary, by outside counsel, before any such action is taken. The _____________ Unit does not have the authority to terminate an employee. The decision to terminate an employee is made by the employee’s management. Should the _____________ Unit believe the", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Administration", "back": "The Director of _____________ is responsible for the administration, revision, interpretation, and application of this policy. The policy will be reviewed annually and revised as needed. __________________________________ (CEO/Senior Vice President/Executive)", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Definition Of Gifts", "back": "Gifts are items and services of value that are given to any outside parties, but do not include • Normal business entertainment items, such as meals and beverages, are not to be • Items of minimal value, given in connection with sales campaigns and promotions or employee service, safety, or retirement awards are not to be considered gifts for purposes", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Definition Of Supplier", "back": "Supplier includes not only vendors providing services and material to the company, but also consultants, financial institutions, advisors, and any person or institution that does business No employee or member of their immediate family shall solicit or accept from an actual or prospective customer or supplier any compensation, advance loans (except from established financial institutions on the same basis as other customers), gifts, entertainment, or other", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reporting Gifts", "back": "An employee who receives, or whose family member receives, an unsolicited gift prohibited by these guidelines should report it to their supervisor and either return it to the person making the gift or, in the case of a perishable gift, give it to a nonprofit charitable organization.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Discounts", "back": "An employee might accept discounts on a personal purchase of the supplier’s or customer’s products only if such discounts do not affect the company’s purchase price and are generally offered to others having a similar business relationship with the supplier or customer.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Business Meetings", "back": "Entertainment and services offered by a supplier or customer may be accepted by an employee when they are associated with a business meeting and the supplier or customer provides them to others as a normal part of its business. Examples of such entertainment and services are transportation to and from the supplier’s or customer’s place of business, hospitality suites, golf outings, lodging at the supplier’s or customer’s place of business, and", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Population Of Fraud Risks", "back": "The fraud risk identification process requires an understanding of the universe of fraud risks and the subset of risks that apply to a particular organization. It includes gathering information about the business itself, including its business processes, industry, and operating environment, as well as all associated potential fraud risks. Such information can be obtained from external sources—such as industry news outlets; criminal, civil, and regulatory", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fraudulent Financial Reporting", "back": "Potential fraudulent financial reporting risks include: • Inappropriately reported revenues, expenses, or both • Inappropriately reflected balance sheet amounts, including reserves • Inappropriately improved or masked disclosures • Concealed misappropriation of assets • Concealed unauthorized receipts, expenditures, or both • Concealed unauthorized acquisition, use, or disposition of assets", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriations", "back": "Potential asset misappropriation risks include misappropriation of: • Proprietary business opportunities", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Corruption", "back": "Potential corruption risks include: • Payment of bribes or illegal gratuities to companies, private individuals, or public officials • Receipt of bribes, kickbacks, or illegal gratuities by employees or agents of the company Aiding and abetting of fraud by outside parties, such as customers or vendors", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "External Fraud", "back": "• Fraud committed by customers (e.g., fraudulent customer payments) • Fraud committed by vendors (e.g., overbilling by a vendor or collusion between bidding contractors to inflate contract price) • Fraud committed by competitors (e.g., corporate espionage) • Fraud committed by unrelated third parties (e.g., hacking)", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Risk Of Regulatory And Legal Misconduct", "back": "Regulatory and legal misconduct includes a wide range of risks, such as conflicts of interest, insider trading, theft of competitor trade secrets, anti-competitive practices, environmental violations, and trade and customs regulations in areas of import and export. Depending on the particular organization and the nature of its business, some or all of these risks might be applicable and should be considered in the fraud risk assessment process.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reputation Risk", "back": "Reputation risk must be considered as part of the organization’s risk assessment process because fraudulent acts can damage an organization’s reputation with customers, suppliers, capital markets, and others. For example, fraud leading to a financial restatement can damage an organization’s reputation in capital markets, which can increase the organization’s cost of borrowing and depress its market capitalization.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Risk To Information Technology", "back": "IT is a critical component of fraud risk assessment. Organizations rely on IT to conduct business, communicate, and process financial information. A poorly designed or inadequately controlled IT environment can expose an organization to threats to data integrity, threats from hackers to system security, and theft of financial and sensitive business information. Whether in the form of hacking, economic espionage, web defacement, sabotage of data,", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Assess The Likelihood Of Occurrence Of The Identified Fraud Risks", "back": "The likelihood of occurrence of each fraud risk can be classified as remote, reasonably possible, or probable. The fraud risk assessment team should consider the following factors in assessing the likelihood of occurrence of each fraud risk:", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Assess The Significance To The Organization Of The Fraud Risks", "back": "The fraud risk assessment team should consider qualitative and quantitative factors when assessing the significance (sometimes referred to as the impact) of identified fraud risks to the organization. For example, a particular fraud risk that might only pose an immaterial direct financial risk to the organization, but that could greatly affect its reputation, would be deemed a significant risk to the organization.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Preventive Controls", "back": "Preventive controls, which are intended to prevent fraud before it occurs, include: • Bringing awareness of the fraud risk management program to personnel throughout", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Detective Controls", "back": "Detective controls, which are intended to detect fraud if it does occur, include: • Establishing and marketing the presence of a confidential reporting system, such as a • Implementing proactive controls for the fraud detection process, such as independent reconciliations, reviews, physical inspections and counts, analysis, and audits", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The fraud risk trend (i.e.,", "back": "scheme becoming riskier for the organization, less risky, or staying the same?) The fraud risk velocity (i.e., How quickly would the impact of the fraud be felt?) The roles or teams in the organization that would be able to perpetrate the scheme,", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Larry Cook, CFE, who", "back": "principal author of the ACFE Fraud Risk Assessment Tool (ACFE.com/fraud-risk-assessment.aspx), suggests that management can use one or a combination of the following approaches to respond to the organization’s residual", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: bond. The cost to the organization", "back": "premium paid for the insurance or bond. The covered risk of loss is then transferred to the insurance company. Transferring risk through insurance coverage is not just a strategy to protect against employee frauds; it should be considered for certain third-party risks as well. For example, as part of its vendor", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Iso 31000", "back": "The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) has developed ISO 31000, a set of international standards providing principles and guidance on risk management. Most organizations with a risk management function that do not follow the COSO ERM model follow the ISO model. Some organizations have developed a customized model that incorporates elements of both the COSO and ISO models. The ISO 31000 family of standards includes:", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Simplified due diligence", "back": "lowest level of due diligence that can be performed on a potential customer. Conducting simplified due diligence procedures would be most appropriate in situations where there is little opportunity or risk of a customer engaging in illegal activity. The only requirement for simplified due diligence is to identify the customer.", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Expected method of payment (i.e.,", "back": "customer requesting to use a higher-risk payment method, such as a personal check or line of credit?)", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: An affirmation process", "back": "requirement for directors, employees, and contractors to explicitly affirm (typically via electronic or manual signature) that they have read, understood, and complied with the organization’s code of conduct, fraud control policy, and other such documentation that supports the fraud risk management program. In determining whether to", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: organization’s fraud risks", "back": "foundation for an effective fraud risk management program. Such an assessment is not a onetime endeavor, but rather should be performed on a systematic and recurring basis. Additionally, the assessment should consider all relevant fraud schemes and scenarios, and the results should be used to map mitigating controls to those", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Professional Admission Standards", "back": "Professional fields are also characterized by an admissions process that is governed by standards of professional qualifications. Some industries govern admission to their ranks by qualifications contained in law, but legal recognition is not required. Conversely, many professions are not regulated by legal statutes. For instance, the certified internal auditor (CIA) has the status of a profession without the benefit of licensing laws. The", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recognition And Acceptance By Society: A Reciprocal Relationship", "back": "No group of practitioners can become a profession merely by declaring itself to be one. Society must acknowledge the group as a professional body. At present, fraud examiners are at the stage of becoming a self-declared profession. Historically, other professions had the same starting point. Modern medicine overcame its roots in magic. Accountants rose from the level of bookkeepers. Internal auditors advanced social goals by presenting a responsible", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Standards Of Conduct", "back": "Professional fields are also characterized by the adoption of and adherence to a code of professional ethics and standards of conduct, and such codes and standards can help a profession achieve full social recognition. Codes of ethics serve as a reference and benchmark for ethical guidance. Like professionals in other fields, ACFE members are required to adhere to an explicit code of ethical conduct—", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "A Professional Organization", "back": "Professional fields are typically characterized by a dedicated organization devoted to the advancement of the group’s obligations. For example, the ACFE is an association of professionals comprising CFEs and associate members who have made a commitment to work together for the common goal of detecting and preventing fraud, waste, and abuse. Professionalism for the Individual Fraud Examiners Additionally, professionalism exists for the individual fraud examiner. But when the focus of", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Independence In Attitude And Appearance", "back": "Independence of attitude requires impartiality and fairness in conducting fraud examinations and in reaching resulting conclusions and judgments. Fraud examiners must also be sensitive to the appearance of independence so that conclusions and judgments will be accepted as impartial by knowledgeable third parties. Fraud examiners who become aware of a situation or relationship that could be perceived to impair independence, whether or not actual", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Objectivity", "back": "Objectivity refers to the ability to conduct fraud examinations without being influenced by one’s own personal feelings or the feelings and motives of others. To ensure objectivity in performing examinations, fraud examiners must maintain an independent mental attitude, ACFE Code of Professional Ethics reach judgments on examination matters without undue influence from others, and avoid being placed in positions where they would be unable to work in an objective professional", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Additionally, integrity", "back": "that a fraud examiner should have a well-developed sense of moral philosophy—an ability to analyze situations where no rules of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics are specifically applicable and to be able to distinguish right from wrong. It does not mean, however, that an ACFE member must be perfect in all technical", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: competence", "back": "how well fraud examiners do their job. Determination of competence always depends on the specific facts and circumstances of the assignment. Competence is best understood in the context of the prudent practitioner. The idea of a prudent professional practitioner is present in other social science theories; for example,", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: required. It", "back": "responsibility of a fraud examiner to ensure that necessary skills, knowledge, ability, and experience are acquired or available before proceeding with a fraud examination. Sources of Interference with Professional Competence Professional competence also demands attention to three kinds of interference that can", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Programming", "back": "Fraud examiners must remain free from interference by managers who try to restrict, specify, or modify the procedures they need to perform, including any attempts to assign personnel or otherwise control the examination work. Occasionally, client or employer managers try to limit access to information or to other personnel, or to limit the amount of time available for", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Investigation", "back": "When appropriate, fraud examiners must have free access to books, records, correspondence, and other evidence. They must have the cooperation of managers or other employees without any attempt to interpret or screen evidence.", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reporting", "back": "Client or employer managers should not be allowed to overrule the fraud examiner’s judgments on the appropriate content of a report. Integrity is destroyed and judgment is subordinated when the fraud examiner is compelled to alter a report or to omit important information or to misstate facts. Fraud examiners must not let any feelings of misguided loyalty to the client, employer, or other sources of conflicts of interest interfere with their", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Cfe Code Of Professional Standards", "back": "(Adopted by the Board of Regents, October 1, 2020) The Association of Certified Fraud Examiners is an association of professionals committed to performing at the highest level of ethical conduct. Members of the Association pledge themselves to act with integrity and to perform their work in a professional manner. Members have a professional responsibility to their clients, the public interest, and each other,", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: these Standards, the term “fraud examination”", "back": "an assignment or engagement, a substantial purpose of which involves the prevention, detection, investigation, or resolution of fraud or fraud-related conduct. CFE Code of Professional Standards", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Bibliography", "back": "Akers, Ronald. Deviant Behavior: A Social Learning Approach, 2nd ed. (Belmont, CA: Wadsworth, 1977). Albrecht, W. Steve., Conan C. Albrecht, Chad O. Albrecht, and Mark F. Zimbelman. Fraud Examination, 4th ed. (Mason, OH: South-Western, 2011). Albrecht, W. Steve, Keith R. Howe, and Marshall B. Romney. Deterring Fraud: The Internal Auditor’s Perspective (Altamonte Springs, FL: The Institute of Internal Auditors Research Foundation, 1984).", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}], "fc_by_topic": {"Interview Theory and Application": [{"front": "Preparing for Interviews", "back": "• To effectively prepare for the interview phase of an investigation, the fraud examiner must first develop a plan. This might involve:\n• Contemplating what the interview is intended to accomplish\n• Determining the necessary order of interviews\n• Deciding which evidentiary documents to take into the interview and which to request from the subject", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Interview Mechanics", "back": "• Rules for note-taking during interviews\n• Consider recording interviews electronically and covertly if permissible.\n• Err on the side of taking too few notes rather than too many.\n• Other interviewing best practices\n• Maintain eye contact as much as possible during the interview.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Interview Questions", "back": "• Five types\n• Introductory questions 1. Used to provide an introduction and to get the respondent to verbally agree to the interview\n• Admission-seeking questions 1. Reserved specifically for individuals whose culpability is reasonably certain 2. Designed to obtain a legal admission of wrongdoing", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Introductory Questions", "back": "• Designed to meet four objectives:\n• To provide an introduction 1. The interviewer generally should indicate their name and company, but they should avoid stating their title when appropriate.\n• Methodology\n• Sensitive questions and emotive words should be avoided during the introductory phase because they tend to put people on the defensive and make them more reluctant to answer and cooperate. 1. Use word", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Informational Questions", "back": "• Asked for the purpose of gathering unbiased, factual information\n• Commonly used when:\n• Conducting an interview to gain an understanding of accounting control systems\n• Sequence\n• As a general rule, questioning should proceed from the general to the specific (general information before detailed information).", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Dealing with Difficult Situations", "back": "• Resistance\n• Possible excuses for refusing a request for an interview 1. “I’m too busy.”\n• Defuse by stressing that:\n• The interview will be short.\n• The interviewer needs help. 2. “I don’t remember.”", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Closing Questions", "back": "• Seek to close the interview positively\n• Three main purposes\n• To reconfirm facts", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Assessment Questions", "back": "• Designed to establish the respondent’s credibility\n• Should be asked when the interviewer has reason to believe the respondent is being deceptive (i.e., when the interviewer considers previous statements by the respondent to be inconsistent because of p\n• The interviewer must observe the subject’s verbal and nonverbal responses to assess their credibility.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Establishing a Baseline", "back": "• The process of observing behavior before critical questions are asked, as opposed to doing so during questioning\n• The best way to establish a baseline with a witness is by asking noncritical questions on background information, place of employment, etc.\n• Assessment questions, which ask the subject to agree with matters that go against the principles of most honest people, should then be presented; people who seem truthful typically answer one way, and\n• After observing the respondent’s verbal and nonverbal behavior while answering noncritical questions, the interviewer can later compare an interviewee’s behavior during critical questions (if the admi", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Understanding Indicators of Stress", "back": "• The human body attempts to relieve the stress of lying through verbal and nonverbal actions, which provide clues to deception.\n• When evaluating signs of deception, no single behavior should be isolated and no single conclusion should be drawn from it.\n• Factors to consider when assessing signs of deception\n• Signs of stress do not always mean that a subject is lying. 1. Not all stress exhibited during an interview is caused by lying; an honest interview subject might feel stress simply by being asked poin\n• Verbal clues", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Admission-Seeking Questions", "back": "• Designed to obtain a legal admission of wrongdoing\n• Normally, the interviewer should ask accusatory or admission-seeking questions when all the following are true:\n• There is a reasonable probability that the respondent has committed the act in question.\n• Three purposes\n• To distinguish innocent (non-culpable) individuals from potentially guilty ones", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Preparing the Interview Room", "back": "• The interviewer should consider how private the room is.\n• The door should be closed but not locked.\n• There should be no physical barriers preventing the suspect from leaving.\n• The suspect should be made aware that they are free to leave.\n• Distractions should be kept to a minimum.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Presence of Outsiders", "back": "• Where allowed by law, no observers, other than the subject and up to two fraud examiners, should be permitted in the admission-seeking interview.\n• The presence of third parties could have liability consequences.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "General Rules for Conducting Admission-Seeking Interviews", "back": "• Convey absolute confidence in the admission-seeking interview.\n• Only conduct an admission-seeking interview when there is sufficient privacy and when time is not a factor.\n• Do not express disgust, outrage, or moral condemnation about the accused’s actions.\n• Be firm but also project compassion, understanding, and empathy.\n• Offer a morally acceptable reason for the accused’s behavior.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Steps in the Admission-Seeking Interview", "back": "• Make a direct accusation.\n• The accusation should be made in the form of a statement, not a question.\n• Observe the accused’s reaction.\n• When accused of wrongdoing, guilty individuals often react with silence.\n• Repeat the accusation.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Information to Obtain During the Verbal Admission", "back": "• That the accused knew the conduct was wrong\n• Intent is required in all matters involving fraud. The accused not only must have committed the act but also must have intended to commit it.\n• Facts known only to the subject (estimate of number of instances/amounts)\n• These facts include—at a minimum—the accused’s estimates of the number of instances of wrongful conduct and the total amount of money involved.\n• Motive for the offense", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Interview Theory and Application", "back": "• There is no legal requirement that a statement must be completely in the handwriting or wording of the declarant.\n• It is better for the fraud examiner to draft the statement.\n• It is recommended to have two people witness the signing.\n• There should not be more than one written statement for each offense.\n• Omitted facts can be added later as an addendum to the original statement.", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}], "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools": [{"front": "The Data Analysis Process", "back": "• Planning phase\n• Understand the data. 1. As a first step in the planning process—before determining which tests to run—the fraud examiner must know what data are available to be analyzed and how those data are structu\n• Preparation phase\n• Identify the relevant data.\n• Known errors", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Core Data Analysis Software Functions", "back": "• Sorting\n• Arranges data in a meaningful order so users can quickly determine what is important\n• Joining files\n• Combines fields from two sorted input files into a third file\n• Correlation analysis", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "back": "• Structured data are the type of data found in a database, consisting of recognizable and predictable structures.\n• Unstructured data, by contrast, are data not found in a traditional spreadsheet or database, such as email and social media activity.", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Advanced Data Analytics", "back": "• Advanced analytic methods examine large amounts of data using sophisticated techniques that go beyond traditional data analysis to generate new information, recognize patterns, and predict precise out\n• Common types include:\n• Artificial intelligence 1. Refers to computer systems that perform human tasks, such as visual perception and decision-making 2. Includes a subset known as machine learning, which is a learning algori\n• With supervised machine learning, humans identify patterns for the programs to look for in data sets, and the programs identify any data that fit the patterns.\n• With unsupervised machine learning, a program identifies similarities, patterns, or anomalies within a data set without the involvement of a human.", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Data Analysis Queries", "back": "• Accounts payable\n• Audit paid invoices for manual comparison with actual invoices.\n• Verify vendor tax forms (e.g., U.S. Form 1099 or value-added tax [VAT] forms).", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Textual Analytics", "back": "• A method of using software to extract usable information from unstructured text data\n• Sources of unstructured data 1. Emails 2. Journal entry explanations 3. Social media posts and comments\n• Can be used to categorize unstructured data to reveal patterns, sentiments, and relationships that are indicative of fraud through the application of linguistic technologies and statistical techniques\n• Provides the ability to uncover warning signs of potentially fraudulent employee behavior\n• For example, an analysis of email communications might help fraud examiners to gauge the pressures/incentives, opportunities, and rationalizations to commit fraud that exist in an organization.", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Visual Analytics", "back": "• Link analysis\n• Visual representations (e.g., charts with lines showing connections) of data from multiple data sources to track the movement of money; demonstrate complex networks; and discover communications, patte", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}], "Tracing Illicit Transactions": [{"front": "What Is Tracing?", "back": "• The search for evidence for the purpose of showing what has happened to property, identifying the proceeds of property, and identifying those who have handled or received property or the proceeds of p\n• Might be undertaken to assist:\n• A victim of fraud who wants a tracing search to facilitate the recovery of criminal proceeds", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Direct Approach to Tracing Financial Transactions", "back": "• Employs direct evidence of the subject’s books and records (or financial transaction records belonging to third parties) to analyze the relationship between a suspect’s receipt and subsequent disposit\n• Contrasts with the indirect approach, which relies on circumstantial proof\n• Requires access to the subject’s financial records\n• Involves tracing funds the subject used to purchase assets or make deposits back to the source", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Records from Financial Institutions for Tracing", "back": "• Records from financial institutions are perhaps the single most important financial source available to a fraud examiner for tracing purposes.\n• Can be used to:\n• Identify witnesses and other evidence.\n• Identify locations where assets are stored.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Wire Transfers for Tracing", "back": "• Wire transfer records might contain evidence that money has been moved abroad.\n• Information contained on most wire transfers:\n• The amount of the transfer\n• The routing number of the originating bank or financial institution", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Correspondent Banking Records for Tracing", "back": "• A correspondent banking relationship is generally defined as an arrangement in which one bank maintains a correspondent account at another bank for the purpose of settling transactions for itself or i\n• A foreign correspondent relationship involves a correspondent banking relationship between foreign and domestic institutions.\n• Due to risks of illicit transactions, such as money laundering, most jurisdictions require financial institutions to obtain information from other financial institutions with which they maintain a for\n• The institution’s ownership details", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Electronic Payment Records for Tracing", "back": "• The term electronic payments (or e-payments) refers to any type of noncash payment that does not involve a paper check.\n• Records of these transactions can reveal:\n• Assets the subject has purchased\n• Payments made to nonexistent employees with direct deposit\n• The true owner of a property", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Loan Records for Tracing", "back": "• When a bank makes a commercial loan to an individual, it requires detailed statements of assets and liabilities from the borrower.\n• The loan file might also include the results of credit inquiries regarding paying habits, loan amounts, and present unpaid balances.\n• Loan records generally maintained by a bank credit department include:\n• The credit or loan file 1. Includes the customer’s loan application, financial statements, and general economic history\n• If a fraud examination involves a loan with proceeds that have been disposed, the fraud examiner should trace the disposition of the loan’s proceeds.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Credit Card Records for Tracing", "back": "• Credit card records might show card purchasing limits, previous payment history, account balance, when and where the subject has traveled, and assets the subject has acquired.\n• These records show the movements and habits of the person to whom the records pertain.\n• Credit card statements contain the name of the credit card issuer, the cardholder’s account number, a summary of the transactions on the account,\n• Credit card charges might provide leads to identifying hidden assets.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Indirect Approach to Tracing Financial Transactions", "back": "• In contrast to the direct approach method, which relies on specific transactions, the indirect approach relies on circumstantial proof.\n• An indirect analysis can reveal that a suspect has more money available or has acquired more assets than can be accounted for from legitimate sources.\n• Two of the basic approaches that use circumstantial proof to prove a subject’s sources of funds are the asset method (net worth) and the expenditures (source and application of funds) method.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using the Asset and Expenditures Methods to Examine Sources of Income", "back": "• The asset method\n• Use when the subject has invested illegal funds to accumulate wealth and\n• The expenditures method\n• When the subject spends illicit income on consumables (e.g., travel and entertainment), use this method because the illicit income will not cause an increase in net worth.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "–", "back": "• Asset hiders usually conceal assets in financial products that are:\n• Liquid\n• Financial products are used to obscure links between the initial receipt of the assets and their final disposition.\n• Common ways fraudsters hide assets include:\n• Hiding assets in someone else’s name (e.g., the name of a spouse, other relative, friend, business partner)", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Locating Assets Hidden Through Cryptocurrency", "back": "• Cryptocurrency is a type of digital currency that uses public or private key encryption in the currency’s creation and transfer.\n• While cryptocurrency transactions can be difficult and complicated to trace, most cryptocurrencies rely on public blockchains (digital ledgers, or databases, of transactions that allow data to be dist\n• Blockchain entries do not include direct identifying information, but they do contain senders’ and recipients’ cryptographic addresses for each transaction.\n• Cryptocurrencies are stored and transmitted through digital wallets, which act as financial accounts that securely hold and organize a user’s payment information, passwords, and transaction history.\n• Many digital wallet providers now record identifying information about their clients that can be useful in tracing efforts.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Asset Recovery", "back": "• Once fraud has been documented and the associated illicit transactions have been traced, victims might want to pursue recovery of assets.\n• A fraud examiner must often be able to evaluate the potential for asset recovery due to the fact that fraudsters often spend most, if not all, of their ill-gotten gains, leaving little to recover.\n• The following questions should be considered before commencing a legal action to recover assets:\n• Are there nonlegal recovery methods or remedies available?", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Define: Bulk-cash smuggling, which", "back": "smuggling of cash out of the country where it was earned for deposit in foreign jurisdictions with lax financial institutions or to fund criminal enterprises, is also on the rise. The rise in bulk-cash smuggling is due to the increasingly effective AML policies and procedures at financial institutions. In typical bulk-cash smuggling operations,", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Over- And Under-Invoicing Schemes", "back": "In over- and under-invoicing schemes, importers and exporters conspire to misrepresent the price of the goods or services being traded, thus transferring additional value between the importer and exporter. These schemes can be used to create a complex paper trail for the colluding parties to launder illicit funds. The amount available to launder is the difference between the market value of the goods and the invoiced amount.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Over- And Under-Shipment Schemes", "back": "Like over- and under-invoicing schemes, over- and under-shipment schemes can be used to create a complex paper trail for the colluding parties to launder money. In an over-shipment scheme, money launderers understate the quantity of goods that are shipped. More goods are shipped than the company invoices for. For example, Company A invoices 100,000 widgets to Company B at a price of one dollar per widget. However, Company A", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Duplicate Invoicing Scheme", "back": "In a duplicate invoicing scheme, the exporter issues more than one invoice for the same trade transaction. By issuing duplicate invoices, a money launderer can justify multiple payments for the same goods or services.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "False Descriptions In Invoices", "back": "Money launderers can conceal their illicit funds by misrepresenting the quality or type of goods or services provided. For example, an exporter can substitute products or materials of lesser quality than specified in the invoice; use lower quality staff than specified; use counterfeit, defective, or used parts to produce goods; or make any other deliberate departures specified in the invoice.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Black Market Peso Exchange", "back": "Among the most notorious of trade-based money laundering operations is the Black Market Peso Exchange, a scheme where brokers purchase proceeds from narcotics in the United States from cartels and exchange them for clean pesos in Colombia.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Red Flags Of Trade-Based Money Laundering", "back": "Some red flags of trade-based money laundering schemes include: • The goods or services traded seem unrelated to the usual business of the importer • The shipping route is unusual, passing through one or more countries for no • The goods or services do not match the description, value, quantity, or quality stated in", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: assets in their own right. As", "back": "case with most assets, they can become part of a money laundering scheme. Due to the recent growth in the financial products offered by insurance agents and brokers (including savings products, investment products, and tax planning services), the insurance industry has become increasingly attractive to money launderers. One", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Legal Systems", "back": "Under the FATF Recommendations, countries should adopt legislation that effectively criminalizes acts of money laundering and establishes the widest possible range of predicate offenses. In reference to money laundering, a predicate offense is a crime whose proceeds must be converted into a legitimate form. At a minimum, every serious offense should constitute a predicate offense, regardless of where it is committed. In addition, countries", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Financial Institutions And Related Professions", "back": "The FATF Recommendations were revised over time to set stricter guidelines for financial institutions and professionals who are routinely involved in substantial financial transactions. Such professionals specifically include casinos, real estate agents, lawyers, and dealers in precious metals and precious stones. The measures address customer due diligence (CDD), reporting suspicious transactions, deterring money laundering and terrorist financing, and", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Anti-Money Laundering Programs", "back": "Under the FATF Recommendations, countries should require financial institutions to implement AML and terrorist financing programs. A financial institution’s AML program is highly dependent on which jurisdictions it operates in, as well as the services that it offers. Generally, financial institutions should adopt the AML policies and procedures in the FATF Recommendations, but they need to tailor their programs to the requirements of the specific", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Customer Due Diligence", "back": "The FATF Recommendations set out the fundamental measures that financial institutions must take to identify and verify the identity of customers and beneficial owners. Although it is most important to conduct due diligence when a business relationship is first established, due diligence should be exercised on an ongoing basis. These requirements set firm, more detailed standards while also providing flexibility and allowing adaptation to new industry", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Deterring Money Laundering And Terrorist Financing", "back": "Within certain limits, countries and institutions are free to determine the extent of measures appropriate to the specific risk of money laundering or terrorist financing they face. However, all countries are required to (1) establish an FIU to receive reports regarding suspicious transactions, (2) designate law enforcement agencies for AML/CFT investigations, and (3) involve financial supervisors in AML/CFT initiatives. These authorities should have", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reporting Of Suspicious Transactions", "back": "Under the FATF’s Recommendation 20, a financial institution should be required to file a report when it “suspects or has reasonable grounds to suspect that funds are the proceeds of a criminal activity, or are related to terrorist financing.” Some jurisdictions also set additional requirements for reporting suspicious transactions, such as if a cash transaction surpasses a certain threshold amount. The name of these reports varies by jurisdiction, but they are", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Regulation And Supervision", "back": "All countries need adequate measures to ensure that financial institutions and other businesses and professions are complying with their obligations. The required measures take into account the risks and the regulatory structures that already exist in the relevant sectors. • Financial institutions and casinos should not be owned or managed by criminals. • The measures applicable to banks, insurance, and securities firms for prudential purposes", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Large Cash Transactions", "back": "Under the best practices provided in the FATF Recommendations, countries should implement a reporting requirement for financial institutions and DNFBPs that engage in cash transactions above the jurisdiction’s designated threshold. The reports should cover domestic and international cash transactions. Many jurisdictions implement this reporting requirement.", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Cross-Border Transfer Of Currency", "back": "Under the FATF’s Recommendation 32, countries should implement disclosure requirements for individuals who are physically carrying currency or currency equivalents (i.e., bearer instruments) into or out of the country in amounts that are above the country’s designated reporting threshold. Generally, individuals who are carrying currency or the equivalent above the reporting threshold while attempting to cross jurisdictional borders should be required to", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "International Cooperation", "back": "The FATF Recommendations contain several provisions that address international cooperation. Notably, the Recommendation on mutual legal assistance covers several concepts that are in the 25 Non-Cooperative Countries and Territories Criteria discussed below. The most significant provisions deal with cooperation between administrative and law enforcement authorities concerned with combating money laundering and terrorist", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: efforts. The most prevalent", "back": "Anti-Money Laundering Directive (now in its sixth iteration and referred to as the Sixth Directive). The Sixth Directive applies to the financial sector as well as to lawyers, notaries, accountants, real estate agents, casinos, and company service providers. Its scope also encompasses all providers of goods when cash payments are made or received in", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "New Deposit Accounts", "back": "For individual deposit accounts, minimum identification standards should be established. The information to be obtained should include:", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "New Loan Accounts", "back": "An institution should perform due diligence in establishing a new loan account because, if the customer is engaged in money laundering, there is a risk of forfeiture of collateral pledged on the loans. Real or personal property that is traceable to drug sales or that is purchased with laundered funds is subject to seizure by the government. If the property seized is pledged as collateral, the financial institution must prove that it was an innocent lienholder of the", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}], "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination": [{"front": "What Is Fraud Examination?", "back": "• The process of resolving allegations of fraud from inception to disposition\n• The primary function of the anti-fraud professional\n• Tasks involved:\n• Obtaining evidence", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Examination Methodology", "back": "• Assume litigation will follow.\n• Each fraud examination should be conducted with the assumption that the case will result in legal proceedings.\n• Act on predication.\n• Fraud examinations should not be conducted without proper predication—the totality of circumstances that would lead a reasonable, professionally trained, and prudent individual to believe that a fraud\n• Begin with the general before moving to the specific.", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Develop a Fraud Response Plan", "back": "• A fraud response plan details the actions that members of an organization will take when suspicions of fraud arise.\n• Because every fraud is different, response plans should not specify how all fraud examinations should be conducted; instead, such plans should help organizations manage their responses and create envi\n• A response plan allows management to respond to suspected and detected incidents of fraud in a consistent and comprehensive manner.\n• Having a response plan in place sends a message that management takes fraud seriously.\n• Elements of a fraud response plan", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Planning and Conducting a Formal Investigation", "back": "• Assemble an investigation team.\n• To determine who should be involved in the investigation, management must identify the needed skills.\n• Develop an investigation plan.\n• When developing an investigation plan, those responsible should: 1. Review what is known and gain a basic understanding of key issues. 2. Define the goals of the investigation. 3. Identify whom to kee\n• Prepare the organization for the investigation.", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Structure the Investigation to Preserve Confidentiality", "back": "• Failure to preserve confidentiality could compromise an entire investigation and make employees reluctant to report future incidents.\n• To help preserve confidentiality, team members should:\n• Avoid alerting the suspected fraudsters. 1. Know who is being investigated and what they can access. 2. Limit the extent of any discussions. 3. Inform only those who need to know. 4. Inform employees ", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}], "Digital Forensics": [{"front": "Recovering Data", "back": "• Digital forensic experts can recover, among other things, the following types of information from computer systems:\n• Deleted files and other data that have not been overwritten (e.g., deleted documents, images, link or shortcut files, and email messages)\n• Websites visited, even where the browser history and cache have been deleted\n• The time and date information about files (e.g., when files were created, accessed, modified, installed, deleted, or downloaded)", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Volatility of Digital Evidence", "back": "• Digital evidence is more volatile than tangible evidence because data can be altered or destroyed more easily than tangible information.\n• Digital information can be altered by seemingly harmless actions, such as shutting down a running system, starting up a system, or looking through files on a running computer.\n• Data that have been altered or destroyed have had their data integrity violated, and once the integrity of digital evidence has been violated, it usually cannot be restored.\n• Digital evidence that is destroyed when litigation is expected, or in progress, might give rise to claims of spoliation—intentionally or negligently destroying documents relevant to litigation—of evid\n• If litigation occurs, the failure to preserve the integrity of digital evidence could result in evidence being deemed inadmissible in a legal proceeding or, even if admitted, not being given much weig", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Computer System Files to Be Recovered", "back": "• User-created files\n• Created under the user’s direction\n• Computer-created files\n• Evidence might also be found in information generated by a computer’s operating system.\n• Files that contain information about who wrote a document; who received, opened, copied, edited, moved, or printed the document; and when these events occurred 2. Registry", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Places to Search for Digital Evidence", "back": "• Printers\n• Many printers have internal hard drives or other storage mechanisms that can contain information relevant to a fraud examination.\n• Copiers, scanners, and multifunction devices\n• Many modern copiers have a hard drive that stores images of documents the machines have copied, scanned, or emailed.\n• Fax machines", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Digital Forensic Investigation Phases", "back": "• Planning\n• Involves taking steps to help ensure that the evidence will be admissible 1. Determine whether there are any privacy issues in the item(s) to be searched. 2. Determine appropriate procedures for any r\n• Seizing\n• Involves ensuring that all relevant evidence is seized and secured in a forensically sound manner so that the evidence is not tainted or destroyed\n• Document the scene with photographs or a diagram.", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Challenges of Cloud Forensics", "back": "• A lack of frameworks and specialist tools\n• A lack of information accessibility (no physical access)\n• A lack of data control\n• A lack of knowledge\n• Jurisdiction of storage", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}], "Report Writing": [{"front": "Types of Reports Created by Fraud Examiners", "back": "• Fraud examination report\n• Documents the results of a fraud examination\n• Expert report\n• Written by fraud examiners who serve as expert witnesses", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Characteristics of a Good Report", "back": "• Accuracy\n• Inaccuracies damage the credibility of the report and the report’s author.\n• Clarity\n• Convey pertinent information in the clearest possible language.\n• Impartiality and relevance", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Attachments", "back": "• Copies of important documents can be included in the report, but do not include originals.", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Rules for Including Conclusions and Opinions", "back": "• Conclusions should be self-evident and do not need to be pointed out.\n• Opinions regarding guilt or innocence are not allowed.\n• Opinions regarding technical matters are permitted if the fraud examiner is qualified as an expert in the matter being considered.\n• Fraud examiners should not include any statement of opinion as to the integrity or veracity of any witness.", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Analyzing the Reader of Fraud Examination Reports", "back": "• The fraud examination report should be prepared with the expectation that it will likely be read by the general public and adverse parties.\n• Other potential readers include company insiders, attorneys, defendants and witnesses, media outlets, and judges or juries.\n• A fraud examination should provide a full understanding of the investigation and its findings without the need for additional clarification.", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Suggested Structure for Fraud Examination Reports", "back": "• Background\n• Executive summary\n• Scope\n• Approach\n• Findings", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Appendix A: Engagement And Advisory Letters", "back": "Fraud Examination Engagement Letters Fraud Examination Advisory Letters", "topic": "Report Writing", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}], "Sources of Information": [{"front": "Internal Sources", "back": "• Generated and kept within the subject organization\n• Are often the only resource for certain types of documents, such as accounting and business tax records, copies of canceled checks, or employee personnel files, unless the fraud examiner secures the s", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "External Sources", "back": "• Used to:\n• Locate missing assets.\n• Document suspects’ lifestyle and background information.", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Public Records", "back": "• Documents that a governmental agency is required to keep by law or that are necessary to discharge the duties imposed by law\n• Can supply invaluable background information on entities, employees, suspects, and witnesses\n• Can be used to corroborate or refute witness statements\n• Can help investigators track the flow of stolen money or other assets\n• Can aid in efforts to recover losses", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Local Records", "back": "• Building inspector records\n• Building permit records\n• Health and fire department records\n• Birth and death records\n• Public school records", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Marriage records", "back": "• Court records (civil and criminal) are typically maintained by a clerk or administrative office of the court that heard the case.\n• It is rare for there to be a central public database that maintains all court records at every level of a jurisdiction, and there are no parties that maintain a comprehensive database of court records\n• Types include:\n• Civil court records, which might include: 1. Personal injury suit records 2. Financial suit records 3. Divorce records\n• Names of individuals with an interest in the deceased’s estate", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Property Records", "back": "• Real property records\n• Most jurisdictions have a land registry office that maintains various information on real property and its owner(s), such as deeds, grants, and transfers and mortgages of real estate.\n• Property tax records\n• Many jurisdictions assess property taxes and require parties that purchase real estate to register as taxpayers with the jurisdiction’s property tax records system.\n• An idea of the estimated value, for tax purposes, of the property listed", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Names of former property owners", "back": "• Most jurisdictions require business entities to file various types of records that contain information useful in a fraud examination, including:\n• Organizational filings 1. If an individual wants to conduct business in a name other than their own, the law requires that they file documents, such as an organizational filing, to claim ownership of \n• Corporate name\n• Ownership information\n• Names of initial shareholders", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Nonpublic Records", "back": "• Information about a person or business considered to be private and confidential\n• Might be difficult or impossible to obtain because fraud examiners do not have an absolute right to see these personal records\n• The government usually will not share nonpublic records with a fraud victim during an investigation into the underlying fraud.\n• Types of nonpublic records\n• Banking records 1. Can be obtained through:", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Improper Pretexting", "back": "• In general, pretexting is the act of impersonating someone else or making false or misleading statements to obtain, sell, or buy information about a person or organization.\n• Some jurisdictions have prohibited pretexting against financial institutions even if no fraudulent intent is present.\n• In this context, pretexting is the act of obtaining or attempting to obtain customer information from financial institutions through deceptive tactics (e.g., pretending to be the customer or an author\n• Fraud examiners should not impersonate a member of law enforcement or an actual person (particularly the individual being investigated). To do so may lead to charges of identity theft.", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)", "back": "• A regulation designed to protect the personal data of European Union (EU) residents and harmonize data protection laws throughout Europe\n• Applies to organizations that are based in the EU that collect or process the personal data of any person, regardless of where the person is located\n• Applies to organizations that are not based in the EU if they collect or process the personal data of any person located in the EU for the purpose of:\n• Offering goods or services to the person, regardless of whether payment is required\n• Applies to most companies that have customers in the EU even if the companies have no physical presence in the EU", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using the Internet in Fraud Examinations", "back": "• The best way to use a search engine is to use two or three keywords that best describe the topic, but such searches often return too many or irrelevant results.\n• In such situations, users can employ special query words or symbols called advanced search operators (or Boolean operators) to increase the precision of a search phrase.\n• For example, placing quotation marks around a word or set of words returns pages containing the exact word or set of words. A search for “money laundering” returns pages in which the exact phrase mone", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Online Public Database Searches", "back": "• To locate people using online records, the fraud examiner should obtain a past address of the subject, and search activities should begin with that information.\n• The fraud examiner should know the most powerful and useful types of searches.\n• There are several limitations to be aware of when conducting searches for public records using online databases:\n• Online availability of public records varies widely across jurisdictions.\n• Fraud examiners must validate information retrieved from online databases to determine if it is accurate and up to date.", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Deep Web", "back": "• Web content that is not indexed by standard search engines\n• Also known as the invisible web\n• Resources include websites without any links pointing to them, certain file formats that search engines cannot handle, websites that have been blocked from access by web crawlers (i.e., scripts that c\n• An important resource for fraud examiners because standard search engines only search a small portion of the web", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Dark Web", "back": "• Websites that are only accessible through specialized web browsers meant to anonymize the origins of user traffic\n• The most popular web browser is Tor, short for “the onion router.”\n• Tor software layers encrypted communications and offers increased anonymity to users by preventing someone who is monitoring a user’s internet traffic from knowing what sites the person visits and pre", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Internet Archives", "back": "• Archived versions of web pages that have since been updated or are no longer available online\n• The most popular tool for searching the internet archives is the Wayback Machine, located at https://archive.org, which allows users to see archived versions of web pages throughout time.\n• Searching the internet archives can uncover historical information, such as:\n• A photo posted on a website that has been removed", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Social Media Sites", "back": "• The popularity of social media sites makes it easy for fraud examiners to find information about individuals who use such sites.\n• Relevant social media evidence can include photographs, status updates, a person’s location at a certain time, and direct communications.\n• Fraud examiners can use social media to:\n• Investigate complaints.", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Privacy Issues When Collecting Social Media Evidence", "back": "• Fraud examiners are free to search and extract information from a subject’s page if it is open to the public, but there are limitations to the information fraud examiners can access on a social media \n• Accessing information on social media sites that is restricted by privacy settings could result in liability for fraud examiners due to the violation of users’ privacy rights.\n• Due to confidentiality, privacy, and security concerns, courts might not allow evidence obtained by someone who misrepresents themselves to gain access to a subject’s private social network.\n• Take screen captures of relevant information.\n• Print the content.", "topic": "Sources of Information", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}], "Covert Operations": [{"front": "What Is a Covert Operation?", "back": "• An investigation technique designed to obtain evidence by use of agents whose true intentions are not communicated to the target\n• Mistakes made during a covert operation can cause irreparable damage to an investigation; mistakes may also have reputational, financial, and legal consequences.\n• Fraud examiners should only resort to covert operations after conventional methods of gathering evidence have been exhausted and proven unsuccessful.", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Forms of Covert Operations", "back": "• Undercover operations\n• Often use deception and disguise to obtain evidence directly from those involved in the illicit activity.\n• Surveillance operations\n• Use observation to gather information about individuals suspected of misconduct.", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Information to Document", "back": "• Before conducting a covert operation, document the basis of the operation, preferably in a memorandum that clearly states:\n• The information upon which the covert operation will be based", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Legality of Recordings", "back": "• Many jurisdictions have laws that impose restrictions on electronic audio or video recordings that are not done pursuant to a search warrant or other court order.\n• Factors to consider when determining the legality of recording audio or video without a court order include:\n• The consenting party 1. For a recording of a private conversation to be permissible, most jurisdictions require consent from at least one of the parties involved in the conversation. 2. Jurisdictions ", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Entrapment", "back": "• Occurs when law enforcement officers or government agents induce a person to commit a crime that they are not previously disposed to commit\n• Poses a legal problem in covert operations because the defendant might not be found liable if it appears that they were improperly induced to commit the crime; thus, it is imperative that these operat", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Procedures When Using Sources and Informants", "back": "• Make any payments in cash and obtain a receipt for documentation purposes.\n• If a source or informant will not sign a receipt, then do not pay that person.\n• Keep the informant’s identity as confidential as possible.\n• Use symbols to denote identities when reporting contacts.", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Promises of Confidentiality", "back": "• Fraud examiners generally cannot offer unqualified confidentiality to informants. Therefore, any promises made to an informant or source should be qualified with the caveat that no absolute assurances", "topic": "Covert Operations", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}], "Collecting Evidence": [{"front": "Types of Evidence", "back": "• The three primary types of evidence that fraud examiners must consider and gather when conducting their investigations are:\n• Testimonial evidence 1. Involves statements made by witnesses, neutral third parties, and suspects during interviews and/or when testifying at trial", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "General Rules for Collecting and Organizing Documents", "back": "• Obtain original documents where feasible.\n• Do not touch originals any more than necessary.\n• Maintain a dependable filing system for the documents.\n• Segregate the documents by either witness or transaction.\n• Make a key document file for easy access to the most relevant documents.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods for Obtaining Documentary Evidence", "back": "• Preferred method is by consent if both parties agree.\n• Consent can be oral, but consent should ideally be in writing when obtaining information from possible adverse witnesses or the examination’s target.\n• Documents can also be obtained through legal action.\n• Usually a subpoena or other court order is issued.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Handling Documents as Physical Evidence", "back": "• Documents should be handled carefully and stored properly in a sealed, initialed, and dated paper folder or envelope to avoid damage or contamination.\n• If necessary, make a working copy and preserve the original document for submission to a forensic document examiner.\n• Other than making unobtrusive initials for identification, do not write or mark on original documents.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Chain of Custody", "back": "• Both a process and a document that memorializes who has had possession of an object and what they have done with it\n• In general, to establish the chain of custody, fraud examiners must make a record via a memorandum when they, or any other member of the fraud examination team, receive an item and when it leaves thei\n• What items were received", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Disposal of Evidence", "back": "• Once an investigation or examination has concluded, fraud examiners might need to direct or participate in the disposal of evidence that was collected during an engagement.\n• Factors that could potentially affect evidence disposal following the conclusion of a fraud investigation or examination are:\n• The personal information about suspects or witnesses that is documented in the evidence\n• General document retention policies implemented by the organization\n• Any of these factors could require the evidence to be retained, disposed of, or returned to its owner in a specific manner.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Define: entitled to pretrial discovery. Discovery", "back": "the formal process whereby the parties collect evidence and learn the details of the opposing side’s case, and pretrial discovery is intended to clarify the claim against the defendant, and to permit each side to examine the evidence that will be used in court by the other side.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: whereas in inquisitorial processes, the judge", "back": "driving force. In other words, instead of the parties seeking evidence from each other, the judge seeks evidence from the parties and", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In general, the term remedy", "back": "any process, procedure, or consequence of a legal wrong by which a victim can be redressed for their loss. Thus, if the defendant is found liable in a civil case, the remedy to which the plaintiff is entitled must be considered.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: loss. Submitting a timely proof of loss", "back": "responsibility of the insured; the carrier will not conduct nor assist in any investigation efforts to obtain proof of a loss, and the carrier will not reimburse the investigative or legal costs that the insured incurred in making a claim. Most policies have express subrogation provisions providing that if the insurance company", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Arbitration", "back": "process whereby a dispute is submitted to an impartial third person (known as an arbitrator) who then decides the outcome of the case (i.e., which party should win). The Civil Justice System The arbitrator acts as a judge or jury by deciding the case on its merits. Arbitration can be", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Basic Principles Of Evidence", "back": "In general, evidence consists of anything that can be used to prove something. In a legal sense, evidence refers to the testimony, documents, exhibits, and other tangible objects offered to prove or disprove the existence of an alleged fact during court proceedings. In legal systems, the use of evidence is often regulated by an intricate set of principles that have been developed and refined over hundreds of years, designed to ensure that only", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Real evidence", "back": "physical objects that played a part in the issues being litigated. The term includes both documentary evidence—such as canceled checks, invoices, ledgers, and letters—as well as other types of physical evidence. Therefore, a printer in a case involving questioned documents is clearly real evidence, as is a tape recording since members of the", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Demonstrative Evidence", "back": "Demonstrative evidence refers to a tangible item that illustrates some material proposition. It differs from real evidence in that demonstrative evidence is not part of the underlying event; it is created specifically for the trial. Its purpose is to provide a visual aid for the jury. An exhibit used for purely “illustrative purposes” is a type of demonstrative evidence. Demonstrative evidence includes charts, graphs, and summaries that help to simplify", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Business Records And Other Documents", "back": "Business records can encompass a broad range of documents, from all sorts of organizations, including corporations, small businesses, nonprofit operations, and community groups. Like other evidence, a party offering business records must provide testimony that the exhibit is the business record in question. For proper authentication, the party offering the evidence should be able to establish the following two things:", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Government Documents", "back": "The requirements for government documents are the same as for other business records. The distinction between government and business records arose because of narrow interpretations of the law that separated nonprofit from for-profit enterprises. Today, most records, regardless of origin, are called business records.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Phone Records", "back": "To be admitted into evidence, phone records typically must meet the same authentication", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Digital Records", "back": "Courts typically accept digital files and documents as evidence. In fact, courts themselves are using more digital resources because many aspects of litigation can now be conducted Generally, to be admissible, digital records must meet the same authentication standards as hard copy records (i.e., to show that the item is what the proponent claims). Thus, to prove that a particular electronic record is authentic, those offering the evidence must demonstrate", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Text And Instant Messages", "back": "As the use of text and instant messages continues to grow, parties are offering these types of records as evidence in an increasing number of cases. The most likely methods to authenticate text and instant messages are: • Witness with personal knowledge (e.g., a witness testifies that they recognize a copy of messages that they received or drafted)", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Website Data", "back": "As with all evidence, the proponent of website evidence must be prepared to establish that the evidence is authentic. In some courts, authenticity can be established by the testimony of a witness. Like any other demonstrative exhibit, parties can authenticate a website with the testimony of a witness who verifies that the exhibit at issue accurately reflects what they observed after logging on to the site and reviewing what was there.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Photographs", "back": "Concerning the admissibility of photographs, it is necessary to establish their fidelity to the object they claim to represent. This means that the offering party must prove that the picture is unaltered and shows what the proponent claims it shows. Generally, it is enough to have a witness familiar with the object or space in a photo to corroborate it (e.g., “Yes, that is the hallway running between our two buildings.”). The matter gets more complicated when a", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: of the individual who", "back": "subject of the evidence. Similarly, juries might afford character evidence too much weight, or they might choose to punish a defendant for perceived bad character, rather than actual guilt. Additionally, character evidence is subject to Basic Principles of Evidence", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Show the accused’s ability and", "back": "of committing the crime (possession of a weapon, tool, or skill used in the commission of the act). Show the accused’s opportunity to commit the crime. Show threats or expressions of ill will by the accused.", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "domain": "Investigation", "source": "manual"}], "Overview of the Legal System": [{"front": "Types of Judicial Systems", "back": "• Common law systems\n• Courts are usually bound by two sources of substantive law: 1. Common law\n• A system of legal principles developed by judges through decisions made in court (thus, often referred to as judgemade law)\n• Consists of the usages and customs of a society as interpreted by the judiciary 2. Statutory law\n• Laws created by a legislature or other governing authority", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fact-Finding Processes", "back": "• The approach that courts take to discover (i.e., search for) evidence in a case\n• Two main types\n• Adversarial process 1. The parties to a proceeding drive the discovery process\n• The parties to the litigation gather and present the evidence to the court (usually through legal counsel) by questioning fact and expert witnesses.\n• The fact finder of the court, which can be a judge, jury, or administrator, is unaware of the details of the case until the parties present evidence.", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Overview of the Legal System", "back": "• The power of a court to hear and decide a given case\n• Refers to the subject matter or people over which lawful authority may be exercised by a court\n• For example, a country might have a system of probate courts that only have jurisdiction to hear cases whose subject matter is related to wills, inheritance, and other probate matters.\n• A particular court’s jurisdiction is defined by the laws of its country, but there are three common elements:\n• Does the court hear cases of the type in question?", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "International Issues in Fraud Cases", "back": "• Choice of law\n• Courts must choose which jurisdiction’s laws to apply to each issue in a case; this could lead to problems if the outcome of a case depends on which jurisdiction’s laws are applied.\n• Enforcement of judgments\n• A domestic judgment against a foreign defendant is usually helpful for recovering the defendant’s assets located in the domestic country, but it might be worthless for obtaining the defendant’s assets", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Civil and Criminal Actions for Fraud", "back": "• Fraud may be prosecuted criminally, civilly, or both, in sequence or simultaneously.\n• Criminal action\n• Begins with a complaint brought by the government, acting on behalf of citizens and the interest of the jurisdiction, against a person accused of violating a law\n• Civil action\n• An action for wrongdoing that does not result in a criminal fine or incarceration", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Administrative Proceedings", "back": "• Non-judicial proceedings conducted by government agencies\n• Generally operate like civil courts with their own rules of evidence and procedure\n• The ultimate decision-maker can be a special administrative judge, board, or tribunal\n• Common types of administrative penalties include:\n• Monetary fines and penalties", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Overview Of The Legal System", "back": "By its nature, fraud examination is a law-intensive field. Legal issues related to fraud are often complex, and their interpretation might require professional legal assistance. CFEs should always consult with legal advisors if legal questions arise during a fraud examination. Even with the availability of legal guidance, however, a fraud examiner should be familiar with certain aspects of the law. Often, the success of an investigation hinges on the fraud", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Constitutional law", "back": "body of law established by a sovereignty’s constitution, and it deals with the fundamental principles by which a government exercises its authority. Constitutions are government charters. They establish and empower the various branches of government, and they set up the rights and obligations of individuals under the", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: International law", "back": "body of legal rules, regulations, and accepted practices observed by nations, and it defines nations’ legal responsibilities in their conduct with each other and with private individuals and transnational companies. International law is enforced primarily through diplomacy and for reasons of courtesy or expediency.", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: criminal law. Civil law", "back": "body of law that provides remedies for violations of private rights, and a civil action is a legal action that does not result in a criminal fine or incarceration. A civil suit in this context has nothing to do with whether the legal system used by the particular government is a civil law jurisdiction or a common law jurisdiction. Most often, civil refers to", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Adversarial Processes", "back": "Adversarial processes are those in which the parties to a proceeding drive the discovery process (the search for evidence). The theory behind this approach is that the competing interests of the parties will serve to expose the relevant facts of the case. In adversarial systems, the parties to the litigation gather and present the evidence to the court. For example, the parties (usually through legal counsel) conduct questioning of fact", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Inquisitorial Processes", "back": "An inquisitorial process refers to a fact-finding approach that places the primary responsibility of discovering evidence on the presiding judge. In an inquisitorial process, the primary goal is to find the truth. Rather than serving as a referee over the parties’ production of evidence, the judge is actively involved in discovery. For instance, judges may request relevant documents on their own accord and ask factual", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Role Of Juries", "back": "While juries can be found in both adversarial and inquisitorial jurisdictions, most adversarial jurisdictions actively use juries as the fact-finding body, while the judge decides issues of law. However, some cases in adversarial jurisdictions (often called bench trials) are decided factually The judge in an inquisitorial process both serves as the traditional fact finder and makes determinations on issues of law. However, some inquisitorial systems use juries, laypersons,", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: and decide a given case; it", "back": "both the subject matter and people over which lawful authority may be exercised by a court. For instance, a country might have a system of probate courts that only have jurisdiction to hear cases whose subject matter is related to wills, Overview of the Legal System", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}], "Individual Rights During Examinations": [{"front": "Overview of Employees’ Rights", "back": "• Employees involved in investigations of suspected fraud have certain duties and rights, whether they are merely bystanders who might have some information relevant to the investigation or are suspecte\n• These duties and rights vary among jurisdictions, but generally apply to employees who work in private-sector and government workplaces; thus, both private and government employers can inadvertently v", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Employees’ Duty to Cooperate", "back": "• In most jurisdictions, a duty to cooperate exists in every employer-employee relationship.\n• Though the duty to cooperate varies, it generally extends to workplace investigations; therefore, employees have a duty to cooperate during an internal investigation if what is requested from them is ", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Employees’ Duty to Preserve Relevant Information", "back": "• Employees may have a duty to preserve relevant information, depending on their jurisdiction.\n• Common law jurisdictions: The duty to preserve relevant evidence typically arises when litigation is reasonably anticipated or contemplated; a violation occurs when information that is relevant to ant\n• In applicable jurisdictions, violating the duty to preserve relevant information can result in several adverse sanctions for the offending party.\n• Such sanctions can arise from both intentional acts and accidental acts through negligence.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Employees’ Contractual Rights", "back": "• An employee may have contractual rights that limit the employer’s ability to compel full cooperation in a fraud examination.\n• Employers and employees may enter into contracts that govern the employment relationship, and, if the employer violates the contract, then the employee can sue for breach of contract.\n• Such contracts can be express or implied.\n• Often, employee contractual rights at issue during investigations arise from a union contract, a collective bargaining agreement, or an employment contract.\n• For example, if the employee is a member of a union, then the union contract or collective bargaining agreement might contain certain restrictions on the company’s investigatory procedures.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Whistleblower Protections", "back": "• Many jurisdictions have whistleblower laws designed to encourage individuals to bring forth complaints of wrongdoing by providing protections for those who report unlawful conduct.\n• Most of these laws protect employees from any adverse employment action or retaliatory action from their employers, but they do not prevent individuals from being terminated for engaging in unrelated ", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Employees’ Privacy Rights", "back": "• Employees have certain privacy rights that can affect numerous aspects of the employer-employee relationship, such as conducting investigations, surveillance and monitoring, and workplace searches.\n• An employee’s privacy rights can arise from, and be protected by, various sources of law, including constitutional law, statutory law, common law, human rights law, labor law, data protection law, con\n• Countries vary in how they approach workplace privacy, but in some jurisdictions, privacy laws generally prohibit unreasonable searches and surveillance in areas where employees have a reasonable expe\n• The key issue to consider when assessing the existence of a reasonable expectation of privacy is whether a reasonable person would expect the area or item to be free from intrusion—the employee does n\n• Nearly every country prohibits covert employee monitoring unless a specific criminal activity has been identified; therefore, nearly every employer is required to notify its employees before implement", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Protections Relating to Government Search and Seizure", "back": "• Most countries have laws that provide the public with the right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities.\n• Though interpretation may vary, this right sometimes requires that the government obtain a search warrant before it conducts a search of a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime.\n• A search warrant is a court order that grants government authorities the right to search a premises or property for information pertinent to a case.\n• Consent searches\n• Individuals are always free to consent to searches.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Defamation", "back": "• An unprivileged publication of a false statement about a person that causes harm to that person’s reputation\n• Whether defamation is a criminal offense or a civil wrong varies by jurisdiction.\n• Elements that generally must be proven include:\n• The defendant made an untrue statement of fact.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Invasion of Privacy", "back": "• Intrusion into an individual’s private matters (intrusion upon seclusion)\n• Harm that occurs when an individual intentionally intrudes into an area where another individual has a reasonable expectation of privacy and the intrusion would be highly offensive or objectionable to\n• Public disclosure of private facts\n• Civil wrong that occurs when one party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Intentional Infliction of Emotional Distress", "back": "• Any unprivileged conduct that is so outrageous and egregious that it exceeds all bounds usually tolerated by civilized society and that is intended to cause injury (or was committed with reckless disr\n• Such conduct is mainly actionable in common law countries.\n• Elements\n• The defendant engaged in extreme and outrageous conduct.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "False Imprisonment", "back": "• The unlawful restraint by one person of the physical liberty of another without consent or legal justification\n• False imprisonment laws protect against unlawful confinement in many countries.\n• Elements\n• The defendant used words or actions intended to restrain the plaintiff.\n• A claim of false imprisonment might arise if an employee is detained in any way during a search or interview.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Data Privacy Laws", "back": "• Most countries have data privacy laws (also known as information privacy or data protection laws) that protect personal information about individuals from disclosure, unauthorized access, and misuse.\n• General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)\n• A regulation designed to protect the personal data of European Union (EU) residents and harmonize data protection laws throughout Europe\n• Organizations must have a lawful basis for collecting or processing personal data (e.g., the consent of the data subject, a legitimate interest of the organization, or compliance with a legal obligati\n• The lawful basis must be documented in a commonly used electronic format and include the name of the specific lawful basis, an explanation, and supporting facts.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Data Transfer Laws", "back": "• Data transfers cover any sharing, transferring or disclosing, giving access to, or otherwise making available information to third parties (e.g., corporate entities and government authorities).\n• Many countries have adopted legal restrictions on international data transfers; however, even when countries provide protection for cross-border data transfers, there are discrepancies in the implemen\n• Nevertheless, there are three options by which management can legitimize cross-border transfers of personal information:\n• Obtain the consent of the data subject.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Principle Of Offset", "back": "One of the features of commodity futures markets that make them so liquid and cost effective is the principle of offset. In a futures contract, the delivery or sale of the product is assumed, and the investor has an obligation to fulfill the contract; therefore, buying or selling a futures contract does not necessarily mean that the investor will accept or make delivery of the actual commodity itself. But the obligation of the buyer (to accept future delivery) and the", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The primary", "back": "of fulfilling one’s obligation under a future’s contract is to enter into an offsetting contract. An off-setting contract is one in which a purchase (sale) of futures contracts is liquidated through the sale (purchase) of an equal number of futures contracts with the same delivery month, thus closing out a position. This legally cancels the outstanding obligation. Each futures exchange has its own clearing organization that provides clearing services with", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: respect to futures contracts. Clearing", "back": "process by which a clearing organization acts as a third-party intermediary to futures contracts and assumes the role of the buyer and seller in such contracts so that it can reconcile the orders between the transacting parties. That is, the clearing organization matches futures transactions and becomes counterparty to", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Trading On Margin", "back": "Futures are traded on margin, which is the initial amount of money that is invested by both buyers and sellers of futures contracts to ensure performance on the terms of the contract (the making or taking delivery of the commodity or the cancellation of the contract by a subsequent offsetting trade). A margin in futures is not a down payment, as in securities, but rather a performance bond. A buyer puts up an initial margin at the time a futures market", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Trading Basics", "back": "A trader who buys futures contracts (assuming this is not an offsetting transaction) is long in the market and will profit if prices rise (e.g., if a trader bought a December corn contract at $2.70 per bushel and the price rose to $2.80 per bushel, they would have an unrealized profit of $500 [10 cents x 5,000 bushels]). Because open commodity positions (transactions that are not offset) are marked to market at the end of the trading day, this $500 profit will", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The transaction counterpart of the long buyer", "back": "short seller. Using the previous example, if the trader sold a December corn contract at $2.70 per bushel and the price rose to $2.80 per bushel, they would have an unrealized loss of $500 (.10 cents x 5,000 bushels). Again, open commodity positions are marked to market at the end of the trading day, meaning that", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: value of the underlying", "back": "main (but not only) factor from which the option contract", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: date. A put option", "back": "right, but not the obligation, to sell the underlying security at the strike (exercise) price by the option’s expiration date.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In options transactions, the seller of a call option", "back": "call writer, while the seller of the put option is the put writer. Option buyers pay a premium to option writers for the options they buy. Option writers (sellers) collect this premium for the options they write and are obligated to deliver the underlying security if the option is exercised.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Relationship Of The Underlying Security To An Option", "back": "Options are derivatives; therefore, their value is derived primarily from the value of their underlying instruments. For example, XYZ common stock closed today at $88.29 per share and the strike prices of the October 2008 XYZ calls ranged from $65 per share to $135 per share. The more that the share price of XYZ is above a particular strike price, the greater the value of that option. The stock price of $88 per share is about $23 over the strike price of the", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Option Values And Premiums", "back": "There are two values that make up option premiums: intrinsic value and time value. To have any intrinsic value, an option must be in the money. Out of the money options have only time value. Returning to the previous example, the XYZ $85 call closed today at a premium of $5.70 per share. This call option is $3 in the money because the underlying XYZ stock closed above the strike price at $88 per share. The premium has $3 intrinsic value, while", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Over-The-Counter Options", "back": "Again, options can be traded OTC. A security that does not trade on a major exchange is said to trade OTC. Unlike the floor trading in physical exchanges, OTC trading is conducted electronically, through direct contact with a market maker, or through communication among professional buyers and sellers. Banks, large brokerage firms, insurance companies, and many other businesses are active in the OTC options markets.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: requirement", "back": "the success of the investor is dependent on the efforts and success of those seeking the investment of third parties (typically the promoter). The third party, who provides the entrepreneurial skill, shares in the profits (or losses) with the investor. The investment was made with expectations of making a profit. Profit is generally defined as either", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The most disturbing aspect of this case", "back": "severe handicap investigators faced because of jurisdictional questions. “This could be a monumental scam that will be nearly impossible to prosecute,” said a private investigator working on the case. “No one really has jurisdiction. The salting [of the gold samples] took place in Indonesia, but what laws were really broken", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Motive And Expectation", "back": "First, consider the issuer and buyer’s primary motives. If the issuer’s primary motive is to raise money for the general use of a business enterprise, then the note may be a security. Is the buyer motivated to make a loan or an investment-type transaction? What is a reasonable investor thinking? What are their expectations?", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Plan Of Distribution", "back": "Second, consider the plan of distribution. If there is some form of common trading, a security", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Regulation", "back": "Third, determine if there is some other regulatory system that significantly reduces the risk of the transaction, thereby rendering it unnecessary to apply the securities laws. If the transaction is deemed appropriately regulated in ways other than through the application of the securities laws, then it is less likely that securities laws will apply. Securities Laws and Regulations Securities regulation refers to laws, rules, and procedures enacted by a legislative body and", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Securities regulation", "back": "laws, rules, and procedures enacted by a legislative body and administered by dedicated agencies that govern the way in which companies, consumers, and financial professionals behave when trading securities. To be effective, securities regulation must balance the legitimate needs of businesses to raise", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Securities exchanges are largely self-regulatory, which", "back": "that they regulate themselves. That is, self-regulatory exchanges exercise some degree of authority to create and enforce industry regulations and standards in the markets they organize. Although exchanges have regulatory authority, they are also regulated entities to the extent that they are subject to", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Overview Of The Iosco Principles Of Securities Regulation", "back": "The IOSCO Principles are based on the following three objectives: • Ensuring that markets are fair, efficient, and transparent • The reduction of systemic risk There are local differences in market structures; however, these objectives form a basis for an effective system of securities regulation. Although members pledge to implement IOSCO standards in their home countries, the", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Protection Of Investors", "back": "Investors should be protected from misleading, manipulative, or fraudulent practices, including insider trading, front running or trading ahead of customers, and the misuse of Full disclosure of information material to investors’ decisions is the most important means for ensuring investor protection. Investors are, therefore, better able to assess the potential risks and rewards of their investments and, as a result, to protect their own interests. As key", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: dispute resolution) or", "back": "of redress and compensation for improper behavior. Effective supervision and enforcement depend upon close cooperation between regulators at the domestic and international levels.", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Reduction Of Systemic Risk", "back": "Although regulators cannot be expected to prevent the financial failure of market intermediaries, regulation should aim to reduce the risk of failure (including through capital and internal control requirements). Where financial failure nonetheless does occur, regulation should seek to reduce the impact of that failure, and, in particular, attempt to isolate the risk Market intermediaries should, therefore, be subject to adequate and ongoing capital and other", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Revised Principles For Securities Regulations", "back": "In response to the global financial crisis that began in 2008, IOSCO published a revised version of the IOSCO Principles in 2010. The purpose of the revision was to incorporate the lessons learned from the crisis and prevent future occurrences. Eight principles were added, bringing the total to 38. The latest principles address hedge funds, credit rating agencies, information service providers, and auditor independence. IOSCO also made minor revisions", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}], "Criminal Prosecutions": [{"front": "United Nation’s (UN) International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR)", "back": "• Commits those countries who have signed and ratified the covenant to recognize various rights of citizens, including the following rights for those accused of crimes:\n• Freedom from arbitrary arrest or detention 1. Under the ICCPR, individuals have the right to liberty and shall not be subject to arbitrary arrest or detention. 2. A custodial arrest occurs whenever a \n• Adequate time to prepare a defense\n• The ability to be represented by legal counsel of the defendant’s choosing and to freely communicate with counsel\n• The right to have accusations and the procedures explained through a translator for free, if necessary", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Corporate Criminal Liability", "back": "• In many jurisdictions, corporations and similar business entities may be vicariously liable (the absolute liability of one party for the misconduct of another party) for criminal and civil violations.\n• In such jurisdictions, a business entity is liable for the acts of its employees if those acts occur within the scope of employment and with some intent to benefit the corporation (doctrine of respond\n• Generally, vicarious liability is very broad and imposes liability on a corporation even if those in management had no knowledge of or participation in the underlying events.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prosecutorial Discretion and Bargaining Agreements", "back": "• Whether criminal cases are brought to trial generally depends on prosecutorial discretion, meaning that the decision to prosecute is left to the discretion of the appropriate jurisdictional authority.\n• Another method of disposing of cases in a growing number of countries is through bargaining agreements, which occur when a defendant makes an agreement with prosecutors to plead guilty or submit a rec\n• It is usually within the prosecution’s discretion as to whether to offer a bargain.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Corporate Deferred Prosecution Agreements", "back": "• Used in some of the jurisdictions that allow for corporate criminal liability\n• Typically occur when prosecutors file criminal charges against a company, but then they agree not to prosecute the claims if the company successfully complies with the deferral agreement’s terms\n• Focus on getting the business to reform its policies and reduce the risk of illegal practices\n• Used to help companies avoid indictment, trial, and conviction while providing a jurisdiction’s justice system with another channel for disposing a corporate case that punishes misconduct and effectua", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Trial Process", "back": "• Fact finders\n• Common law systems 1. Juries are typically, but not always, used in criminal proceedings.\n• A jury trial might not be available for cases involving minor criminal offenses (although jury trials are typically available for serious cases).\n• Many common law jurisdictions allow the defendant to waive the right to trial by jury.\n• When no jury is present, the judge serves as the fact finder.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Punishment", "back": "• When a defendant is found guilty of a crime, there are a variety of sanctions available, depending on the jurisdiction. Sanctions may include:\n• Probation 1. The suspension of an offender’s sentence in return for a promise of good behavior 2. Typically imposed prior to (and instead of) imprisonment 3. Laws vary by jurisdiction, but the offende\n• Parole refers to the status of offenders after they have been released from prison and are placed under supervision in the community.\n• Criminal forfeiture 1. The defendant must transfer specific property (generally property that was used to commit the crime or that was purchased with the proceeds of the crime) to the government as pa", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Appeal", "back": "• The procedure for obtaining review by a higher court to ensure that the trial was conducted in a lawful manner and that the judgments comply with the law\n• Generally, appellate courts will not accept an appeal unless the petition is filed in a timely manner (e.g., no later than thirty days after the trial court’s judgment).\n• In many jurisdictions, an appellate court will reverse a conviction only if it finds an error that likely affected the trial’s outcome and denied the defendant a fair trial.\n• Common law systems\n• In most common law countries, appellate courts consider potential errors of law de novo (meaning they evaluate them independently of the trial court’s determinations), but they generally adopt the fac", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Define: The right to counsel", "back": "right of criminal defendants to have a lawyer assist in their defense, even if they cannot afford to pay for one. Thus, if an individual is the subject of a criminal investigation by government authorities, they may have some type of right to consult an attorney or have an attorney appointed. This right is generally found in both civil and", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Consent Searches", "back": "Consent is a recognized exception to the requirement that government agents must obtain a warrant before they search a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime. Individuals are always free to consent to searches. If a suspect consents to a search or seizure by police or government agents, the consent eliminates the need for a search warrant. That is, the consent to search waives the person’s right to be free from government searches. Thus, the", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Evidence In Plain View", "back": "In many countries with a warrant requirement, the plain-view doctrine is an exception to the general rule that the government must obtain a search warrant before conducting a search of a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime. Under this doctrine, evidence in plain view of a law enforcement officer who has a right to be in a position to observe it may be seized without a warrant. The plain-view doctrine applies when a government official", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Generally speaking, defamation", "back": "the unprivileged publication of false statements about a person that causes harm to that person’s reputation. Defamation can be a crime or a civil violation, and the law varies by jurisdiction as to whether it is a criminal offense or a civil wrong. For example, defamation actions can be brought", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: slander. Libel", "back": "defamatory statements in writing, and slander refers to spoken statements, although the distinction often is blurred in cases involving electronic media. Thus, the key difference between libel and slander is the form in which the defamatory statement is made. In other jurisdictions, there is no distinction between libel and slander. For example,", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: the key difference between libel and slander", "back": "form in which the defamatory statement is made. In other jurisdictions, there is no distinction between libel and slander. For example, German law makes no distinction between libel and slander. The threat of a defamation lawsuit is always present when allegations of wrongdoing are", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Untrue Statement Of Fact", "back": "To be defamatory, a statement must be a statement of fact (not opinion) and be untrue. Thus, truth is an absolute defense to defamation.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Communicated To Third Parties", "back": "To be defamatory, a statement must be published, either orally or in writing, to a third party. Defamation does not occur when one accuses another directly and in the presence of no other parties; to be defamatory, a statement must be heard or read by a third party.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "On An Unprivileged Occasion", "back": "Also, for a statement to qualify as defamatory, the occasion in which the statement is made must be an unprivileged one. If the statement is made on a privileged occasion, then no liability can attach to the declarant. Basically, the law recognizes that there are some circumstances in which the need to share information is so important that people will be allowed to make mistakes from time to time without having to worry about being sued for", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Public Disclosure Of Private Facts", "back": "Public disclosure of private facts occurs when one party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern. For instance, disclosing information obtained in an interview conducted as part of a fraud investigation to individuals not involved in the investigation might constitute public disclosure of private facts. To establish liability for public disclosure of private facts, the plaintiff must prove all of the", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The gist of this civil wrong", "back": "unwarranted publicity of private facts, not the discovery of private facts. In the United States, courts have held that the publicity must be broad and pervasive for liability to attach. Thus, one case found no liability when a bank gave the account information of one of its customers to the customer’s employer, and another court exonerated", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "European Union", "back": "The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) is a regulation designed to protect the personal data of EU residents and harmonize data protection laws throughout Europe. The Council of the EU adopted the GDPR in 2016, and it took effect on May 25, 2018. When it became effective, the GDPR replaced the EU Data Protection Directive of 1995 (also known as Directive 95/46/EC), which previously established the blueprint for data privacy laws", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Lawful Basis", "back": "The GDPR requires organizations to have a lawful basis for collecting or processing personal data. There are multiple lawful bases identified in the GDPR, such as the consent of the data subject, a legitimate interest of the organization, compliance with a legal obligation, the performance of a contract, or the performance of a task carried out in the public interest. The GDPR requires the lawful basis for the processing of personal data to be documented in", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Right To Access", "back": "Upon a data subject’s request, an organization must confirm or deny that it possesses the data subject’s personal data. The organization must also provide the data subject with a free copy of the personal data and any other specified information, such as the purpose of the data collection or the length of time that the information will be stored.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Right To Data Portability", "back": "Under the GDPR, data subjects may request the transfer of their personal data from one organization to another. Organizations must store personal data in a structured, commonly used, and machine-readable format so that they can comply with such transfer requests.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Right To Erasure", "back": "Under some circumstances, organizations can be compelled to delete personal data upon request. For example, a data subject may request the erasure of personal data if the data are Individual Rights During Examinations no longer necessary in relation to the purpose for which they were collected, the data subject withdraws consent, the data were unlawfully collected or processed, or the data subject was a", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Data Security", "back": "The GDPR requires organizations to implement appropriate technical and organizational measures to ensure a level of data security that is appropriate to the risk, including the encryption and pseudonymization of personal data.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Data Protection Officers", "back": "An organization must designate a data protection officer if its business involves the processing of sensitive personal data on a large scale or the regular and systematic monitoring of data subjects on a large scale. Data protection officers must have expert knowledge of data", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Privacy By Design And Default", "back": "The GDPR incorporates the concept of privacy by design, which requires organizations to take data protection into account when designing business processes. The regulation also adopts the concept of privacy by default, which means that organizations must set their default privacy settings at a high level. For example, organizations should not collect personal data unless absolutely necessary. In addition, organizations should limit access to personal data to those", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Data Breaches", "back": "An organization must report data breaches to its member country’s designated supervisory authority within 72 hours after becoming aware of the breach. Also, the organization must notify all affected data subjects without undue delay if the breach is likely to result in a high risk to their rights and freedoms. However, the organization is not required to notify data subjects if the breach only involved encrypted or otherwise unintelligible data or if the organization", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recordkeeping", "back": "The GDPR requires organizations to maintain electronic records of their data collection and processing activities. Such records must include the organization’s lawful bases for collecting Individual Rights During Examinations and processing personal data. Upon request, the records must be made available to the designated supervisory authority of the organization’s member country.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Penalties", "back": "For serious violations of the GDPR, organizations may be fined up to EUR 20 million or 4% of their global annual turnover, whichever amount is greater. The GDPR is a lengthy and complex regulation; it contains many details that are not discussed here. Any organization that is subject to the regulation should seek expert legal advice to develop a GDPR compliance program.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "United States", "back": "The United States does not have a comprehensive federal data privacy law. Instead, the United States uses a sectoral approach in which different economic sectors operate under different legal requirements. This approach, which relies on a combination of legislation, regulation, and self-regulation, creates a system in which privacy standards emerge from a complex interplay of overlapping state and federal laws and regulations, as well as industry practices.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: most significant state data privacy law to emerge", "back": "California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), which took effect on January 1, 2020. However, in November 2020, California voters approved the California Privacy Rights Act (CPRA), which amends the CCPA and takes effect on January 1, 2023. The CCPA and CPRA apply to certain domestic and foreign", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: imprisonment", "back": "unlawful restraint by one person of the physical liberty of another without consent or legal justification. To recover for a claim of false imprisonment, the plaintiff generally must prove all of the", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Intentional infliction of emotional distress", "back": "any unprivileged conduct that is so outrageous and egregious that it exceeds all bounds usually tolerated by civilized society and is intended to cause injury (or was committed with reckless disregard for the likelihood of its causing injury) to another. It is a civil action available mainly in common law countries.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Of particular significance", "back": "fact that most jurisdictions have restrictions concerning the ways in which employers can conduct interviews. Such restrictions might originate from employment contracts, collective labor laws, laws protecting labor rights, the common law, laws protecting fundamental rights, other applicable statutes, and so on.", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Criminal Justice System", "back": "Criminal law deals with offenses of a public nature, whereas civil law is the body of law that provides remedies for violations of private rights. A criminal defendant has certain rights, but these rights vary substantially from jurisdiction to jurisdiction. This chapter describes several procedures and issues in criminal cases that fraud examiners should be aware of. International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}], "Basic Principles of Evidence": [{"front": "Definition of Evidence", "back": "• Anything perceivable by the five senses that is presented to the fact finder to prove or disprove a fact in issue\n• Testimonial evidence 1. The oral or written statements made by witnesses under oath\n• Evidence is simply anything that relates to proving or disproving a fact that is of consequence in a case.", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Two Basic Categories of Admissible Evidence", "back": "• Direct evidence\n• Evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue directly, such as eyewitness testimony or a confession.\n• Circumstantial evidence\n• Evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue indirectly, by inference.\n• Many fraud cases are proved entirely by circumstantial evidence, or by a combination of circumstantial and direct evidence, but seldom by direct evidence alone.", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Admissibility of Evidence", "back": "• Relevance\n• A basic requirement of admissibility in both common and civil law systems is that evidence must be relevant (i.e., tends to make some fact that is in dispute more or less likely than it would be witho\n• Authentication\n• Common law systems 1. Evidence, other than testimonial evidence, must be properly authenticated to be admissible at trial; that is, the party offering the item must produce some evidence (e.g., testim\n• Testimony from a witness who has personal knowledge", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Impeachment", "back": "• The practice of questioning a witness’s knowledge or credibility\n• In systems using adversarial processes, the adverse party is usually entitled to offer evidence to impeach the testimony or credibility of a witness.\n• Most inquisitorial systems do not allow cross-examination of witnesses.\n• There are numerous ways an attorney might impeach a witness, but the most common include efforts to show that the witness:\n• Is influenced by bias or self-interest", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Privileges and Protections", "back": "• Prevent certain types of evidence from being discovered or produced during trial\n• The privileges and protections available and requirements for each vary substantially by jurisdiction.\n• Common law systems generally offer broader evidentiary protections than civil law systems.\n• Common types of privileges include:\n• Legal professional privilege (e.g., attorney-client privilege) 1. Precludes disclosure of confidential communications between a professional legal advisor (e.g., solicitor, barrister, or attorney) and", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}], "The Law Related to Fraud": [{"front": "Definition of Fraud", "back": "• Any intentional or deliberate act to deprive another of property or money by guile, deception, or other unfair means", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraudulent Misrepresentation of Material Facts", "back": "• The specific elements of proof required to establish a misrepresentation claim vary somewhat according to where the fraud occurred and whether the case is brought as a criminal or civil action.\n• The elements normally include:\n• The defendant made a false statement (i.e., a misrepresentation of fact).\n• The victim suffered damages because of the misrepresentation.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Bribery", "back": "• Official bribery\n• The corruption of a public official to influence an official act of government\n• Commercial bribery\n• The corruption of a private individual to gain a commercial or business advantage", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Conflict of Interest", "back": "• Occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence their professional role\n• Elements of a typical civil claim for conflict of interest include:\n• The defendant is an agent of a principal or employer.\n• For a conflict of interest claim to be actionable, the conflict must be undisclosed.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Breach of Fiduciary Duty", "back": "• People in a position of trust or fiduciary relationship—such as officers, directors, high-level employees of a corporation or business, and agents and brokers—owe certain duties to their principals or\n• The two principal fiduciary duties are:\n• Duty of loyalty 1. Requires that the employee/agent act solely in the best interest of the employer/principal without any self-dealing, conflicts of interest, or other abuse of the principal for perso", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Conspiracy", "back": "• A situation in which two or more people agree to commit an illegal act\n• The essential elements that must be shown to prove a conspiracy typically include:\n• The defendant entered into an agreement with at least one person to commit an illegal act.\n• Generally, to prove a conspiracy, the government must establish that the defendant knew of the conspiracy’s existence and its objective, but it does not need to establish that the defendant knew all t\n• Under most conspiracy laws, the purpose of the conspiracy need not be accomplished for a violation to occur, but at least one of the co-conspirators must have executed at least one overt act in furthe", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Mail Fraud", "back": "• Occurs when a country’s mail system is used to perpetrate fraud\n• Mail fraud laws only exist in some jurisdictions, such as Canada and the United States.\n• In the United States, the mail fraud statute also applies to the use of private interstate commercial carriers (e.g., FedEx, UPS, and DHL) in connection with a fraud scheme.\n• Mail fraud laws generally give the government broad authority to prosecute fraud schemes, even if parts of the scheme occur in another country.\n• For example, an international Ponzi scheme perpetrated from Nigeria could be prosecuted under the U.S. mail fraud statute if the Nigerian fraudsters used the U.S. mail system to advance the scheme in ", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Wire Fraud", "back": "• A U.S. statute that makes it a crime to defraud a victim of money or property by means of wire or other electronic communications (e.g., computer, telephone, radio, or television) in foreign or inters\n• Requires an interstate or foreign communication to constitute a violation\n• While unique to the United States, the wire fraud statute gives the U.S. federal government broad jurisdiction over a wide range of fraudulent activity, including some fraud schemes that originate out", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Obstruction of Justice", "back": "• Occurs when an individual engages in an act designed to impede or obstruct the investigation or trial of other substantive offenses\n• Jurisdictions might have several criminal obstruction statutes, but some common types are those that prohibit:\n• Influencing or injuring any officer of the court or juror by force, threats of force, intimidating communications, or corrupt influence\n• Destroying documents related to a future proceeding", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Perjury", "back": "• An intentional false statement given under oath on a material point at issue\n• The basic elements include:\n• The defendant made a false statement.\n• Laws that criminalize perjury generally do not require that the false statement be given in a court of law.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "False Claims and Statements to Government Agencies", "back": "• Laws prohibiting false claims and statements to government agencies make it illegal for a person to lie to, or conceal material information from, a government agency.\n• A false claim is an assertion of a right to government money, property, or services that contains a misrepresentation.\n• An individual can be found guilty for making a false statement or claim only if the individual knew the statement or claim was false at the time it was made.\n• Generally, to prove a violation, the government must show that the defendant:\n• Knowingly and willfully (or with reckless disregard for truth or falsity)", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "International Initiatives Against Fraud and Corruption", "back": "• The OECD Recommendation on Combating Bribery in International Business\n• Published by the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), an intergovernmental institution dedicated to democracy and the market economy\n• The U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA)\n• Prohibits making corrupt payments to foreign officials or political organizations\n• Make it unlawful to bribe foreign government officials to obtain or retain business. 2. Accounting provisions", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Law Related To Fraud", "back": "Countries use a wide variety of laws and regulations to prohibit fraud and related crimes. This chapter covers some of the most common types of offenses, as well as several important laws and initiatives designed to combat fraud and corruption. It is important to keep in mind, however, that the legal systems in different countries or jurisdictions can vary dramatically. Thus, fraud examiners should always consult with counsel regarding local laws and regulations.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: material facts case. Materiality usually", "back": "statements sufficiently important or relevant to a reasonable person in acting or making a decision. For example, a claim that a company enjoyed a 50% growth in profits would probably be material to a prospective investor, The Law Related to Fraud", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Official Bribery", "back": "Official bribery refers to the corruption of a public official to influence an official act of government. Illegal payments to public officials can be prosecuted as official bribery, and they can result in severe penalties. The elements of official bribery vary by jurisdiction, but they • The defendant gave or received (offered or solicited) a thing of value. • The recipient was (or was selected to be) a public official.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Commercial Bribery", "back": "In contrast, commercial bribery refers to the corruption of a private individual to gain a commercial or business advantage. That is, in commercial bribery schemes, something of value is offered to influence a business decision rather than an official act. In some countries, commercial bribery might be referred to as secret commissions. Commercial bribery may not be a crime in every jurisdiction. For example, in the United", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Embezzlement", "back": "wrongful appropriation of money or property by a person to whom it has been lawfully entrusted (or to whom lawful possession was given). Embezzlement involves a breach of trust, although it is not necessary to show a fiduciary relationship—a relationship of confidence, trust, or good faith—between the parties. The elements of embezzlement vary", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Misappropriation", "back": "intentional, illegal use of the property, funds, or ideas of another person for an unauthorized purpose. In the fraud context, misappropriation claims generally involve trade secrets or other proprietary information. Trade secrets include not only secret formulas and processes, but the term also refers to more", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The information", "back": "subject of reasonable efforts to maintain its secrecy. The elements of a typical claim for misappropriation of trade secrets are: • The defendant possessed information of value. • The information was treated confidentially.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Civil Action For Misappropriation Of Trade Secrets", "back": "In most jurisdictions, a victim of trade secret theft may file a civil action for damages or request an injunction—a court order by which a party is required to perform, or is restrained from performing, a specific act—under various types of laws. Civil damages for misappropriation of trade secrets might include reimbursement for actual losses caused by the defendant, such as lost profits, reimbursement of development expenses and overhead costs,", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: that has been recognized in some jurisdictions", "back": "duty imposed on each party to deal with each other in good faith. If a party to a contract, including employment contracts, breaches the duty of good faith, the non-breaching party may have a civil claim for breach of contract. Breach of Fiduciary Duty", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The duty of care", "back": "that people in a fiduciary relationship must act with such care as an ordinarily prudent person would employ in similar positions. Corporate officers, directors, or high-level employees, as well as other people in a fiduciary relationship, must conduct their business affairs prudently with the skill and attention normally exercised by people in similar", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Conspiracy", "back": "a situation in which two or more people agree to commit an illegal act. In most jurisdictions, the crime of conspiracy is actually a separate criminal offense from the underlying crime, meaning that the underlying crime (e.g., bank fraud, bribery, securities fraud) and the conspiracy to commit it are two separate offenses.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: binding agreements. Soft law", "back": "guidelines, resolutions, codes of conduct, and other quasilegal instruments that are not directly enforceable. The OECD Recommendations discussed below are examples of soft law. In contrast, the OECD Convention on Combating Bribery of Foreign Public Officials in International Business Transactions is a legally binding agreement. At present, the OECD consists of 38 member countries: Australia, Austria, Belgium, Canada,", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "In International Business Transactions", "back": "The OECD Convention on Combating Bribery of Foreign Public Officials in International Business Transactions (OECD Anti-Bribery Convention) is a legally binding agreement that sets a uniform, minimum standard that signatory countries must implement through national legislation. Of course, countries may adopt laws that exceed that standard; the following section provides several examples of such legislation.", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Officials", "back": "In 2009, the Working Group issued two additional recommendations for further combating bribery of foreign public officials in international business transactions. For the most past, these instruments merely reinforce the earlier Recommendation and OECD Anti-Bribery Convention. They encourage member countries to review, evaluate, and, where necessary, strengthen the laws and regulations relevant to the fight against foreign bribery. Members are", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}], "Testifying": [{"front": "Types of Testimony", "back": "• Lay (factual) testimony\n• Witnesses testify about what they have experienced firsthand and their factual observations.\n• Expert testimony\n• Testimony from a person who, by reason of education, training, skill, or experience, is qualified to render an opinion or otherwise testify in areas relevant to resolution of a legal dispute", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Experts", "back": "• Testifying expert\n• Gives opinion testimony when specialized knowledge is needed to help the fact finder understand evidence or determine a fact in issue\n• Consulting expert\n• Hired to provide technical assistance to the attorney in preparing the case; typically does not testify at trial", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Procedural Divergences Regarding Expert Witnesses in Adversarial and", "back": "• Adversarial jurisdictions (typically common law jurisdictions)\n• Most expert witnesses are chosen by the parties to the litigation (although adversarial courts may also appoint independent experts).\n• The fact finder (i.e., the judge or jury) must evaluate these competing expert opinions.\n• Inquisitorial jurisdictions (typically civil law jurisdictions)\n• The court usually hires its own expert witnesses for technical issues that require guidance; in other words, the primary experts in inquisitorial jurisdictions are typically appointed by the court (i.", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Qualifying to Testify as an Expert Witness", "back": "• Adversarial jurisdictions\n• Generally, a judge will make three determinations before allowing an expert to testify before the jury: 1. Is the person qualified as an expert witness? 2. Will the expertise of the witness assist the\n• A person does not have to be a CFE to testify as an expert on fraud prevention, detection, or investigation techniques if that person has sufficient practical experience in those techniques, but the C\n• Inquisitorial jurisdictions\n• Most inquisitorial jurisdictions have more standardized requirements for qualifying to testify and allow expert witnesses to offer their services in court more often than in adversarial jurisdictions.", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Direct Examination of Witnesses", "back": "• The initial questioning of a witness\n• Adversarial jurisdictions: Conducted by the party who retained the witness\n• Usually a nonconfrontational questioning aimed at exposing the facts and issues of the case", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods of Presenting Expert Testimony During Direct Examination", "back": "• Written reports\n• In adversarial jurisdictions, experts typically create written reports in the pretrial stage and then testify to their findings during direct examination.\n• Narratives\n• Narrative questions are broad, open-ended questions that allow experts to state their opinions in their own words with minimal prompting.\n• Hypotheticals", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Cross-Examination of Witnesses", "back": "• The questioning of one side’s witness by the opposing side\n• Allows the questioning party either to clarify or make points at the witness’s expense\n• Adversarial jurisdictions\n• During cross-examination, the witness’s credibility is constantly scrutinized.\n• If this occurs, or if asked a long or imprecise question, then the witness should ask for a question to be rephrased in smaller components. 2. Attempt to take psychological control of a witness by:", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Cross-Examination Strategies to Discredit Witnesses", "back": "• When applicable in the jurisdiction, the questioning party might employ various methods to discredit an expert witness or diminish the importance of the witness’s testimony:\n• Myopic vision", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Testifying", "back": "Testimonial evidence is evidence presented in the form of statements made during a legal proceeding, such as a trial, an administrative hearing, or a deposition. All testimonial evidence has specific requirements governing its admissibility that depend on the type of witness and the manner in which the witness is testifying. The judge or administrator applies these requirements to determine who can testify and what they can testify about.", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: throughout their careers. For CFEs, that", "back": "completing Continuing Professional Education (CPE), regularly reading publications in the specific field, and actively seeking new developments. Fraud schemes and the investigation and prevention measures associated with them are always evolving, so the ideal expert will stay on top of these issues.", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: rationales. Caution", "back": "byword for expert witnesses throughout the legal process. Reports and supporting documents used by experts might have to be disclosed to the opposing side in adversarial processes, and the parties in inquisitorial processes might also have a chance to review such documents. Therefore, experts should be cautious about what records they have.", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In many countries, depositions are available as a", "back": "of gathering testimonial evidence. A deposition is sworn testimony given by a party or witness upon questioning by counsel for one of the parties before trial and outside of court. A deposition serves as a powerful discovery device that may be used to compel anyone associated with the case to give oral testimony", "topic": "Testifying", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}], "Civil Actions": [{"front": "Beginning the Civil Action", "back": "• A civil action begins when the plaintiff files a pleading with the appropriate court, usually in the jurisdiction in which the defendant or the plaintiff resides, or where the claim originated.\n• The pleading sets out the complaint against the defendant and the remedy that the plaintiff is seeking.\n• The required contents of the plaintiff’s pleadings vary somewhat between jurisdictions, but most jurisdictions require fact pleadings, meaning the plaintiff must identify:\n• The grounds for legal relief", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Counterclaims", "back": "• Claims filed by a defendant against the plaintiff in a civil action\n• Level a claim against the original plaintiff, who is now the defendant of the counterclaim", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Preservation of Evidence", "back": "• Most civil litigation concerning fraud involves many documents, tangible items, or digital information that might serve as evidence, and each jurisdiction has rules for how this potential evidence sho\n• Common law systems\n• Generally impose a duty on parties in civil litigation to take affirmative steps to preserve relevant evidence\n• Civil law systems\n• Tend to have a narrower scope of what evidence is required for litigation", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Gathering Evidence", "back": "• After the parties submit pleadings to the court, the evidence-gathering process, which varies by jurisdiction, begins.\n• Common law systems\n• Each party is entitled to pretrial discovery (the formal process whereby parties collect evidence and learn the details of the opposing side’s case).\n• Civil law systems\n• In the inquisitorial process commonly found in civil law jurisdictions, the evidence is gathered contemporaneously with the trial, as opposed to the common law method of having the parties gather evid", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Standard of Proof", "back": "• Common law systems\n• Generally, the standard of proof in a civil suit is referred to as the preponderance of the evidence, meaning that it is more probable than not that the defendant is liable.\n• Civil law systems\n• The standard of proof in civil law jurisdictions typically does not change in criminal and civil trials, so the inner conviction of the judge, or conviction intime standard, also applies in civil suit", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Civil Trial Process", "back": "• Common law systems\n• Jury composition and verdict\n• It is common for the minimum number of jurors to be lower for civil cases.\n• Civil trials are less likely to require a unanimous jury verdict than criminal trials.\n• Courts sometimes have the authority to seize assets or property temporarily while a lawsuit is pending.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Appeals", "back": "• Generally, both sides in a civil case may appeal from an adverse judgment, either as to liability or damages.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Legal Remedies", "back": "• Any processes, procedures, or consequences of a legal wrong by which a victim can be redressed for their loss\n• The remedy to which the plaintiff is entitled depends upon a number of factors, such as the relief sought, the facts of the case, and the authority given to the court to grant specific relief.\n• The three most common civil remedies are:\n• Damages (monetary remedies) 1. Remedies for the victim’s recovery of money from the defendant because of, and as compensation, reimbursement, or reparation for, the defendant’s legal offense", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fidelity Insurance", "back": "• A method that is often overlooked for recovery of losses due to internal fraud\n• Under fidelity insurance policies, the insured entity is covered against losses caused by the dishonest or fraudulent acts of its employees.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Alternative Dispute Resolution", "back": "• A means for parties to an action to resolve their disputes without the necessity of a trial\n• In fraud cases, this usually involves one of two types of methods:\n• Mediation 1. The process whereby an impartial third person (known as a mediator) assists the parties in reaching a resolution to the dispute 2. The mediator does not decide who should win, but instead", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Over- And Under-Shipment Schemes", "back": "Like over- and under-invoicing schemes, over- and under-shipment schemes can be used to create a complex paper trail for the colluding parties to launder money. In an over-shipment scheme, money launderers understate the quantity of goods that are shipped. More goods are shipped than the company invoices for. For example, Company A invoices 100,000 widgets to Company B at a price of one dollar per widget. However, Company A", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Duplicate Invoicing Scheme", "back": "In a duplicate invoicing scheme, the exporter issues more than one invoice for the same trade transaction. By issuing duplicate invoices, a money launderer can justify multiple payments for the same goods or services.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "False Descriptions In Invoices", "back": "Money launderers can conceal their illicit funds by misrepresenting the quality or type of goods or services provided. For example, an exporter can substitute products or materials of lesser quality than specified in the invoice; use lower quality staff than specified; use counterfeit, defective, or used parts to produce goods; or make any other deliberate departures specified in the invoice.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Black Market Peso Exchange", "back": "Among the most notorious of trade-based money laundering operations is the Black Market Peso Exchange, a scheme where brokers purchase proceeds from narcotics in the United States from cartels and exchange them for clean pesos in Colombia.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Red Flags Of Trade-Based Money Laundering", "back": "Some red flags of trade-based money laundering schemes include: • The goods or services traded seem unrelated to the usual business of the importer • The shipping route is unusual, passing through one or more countries for no • The goods or services do not match the description, value, quantity, or quality stated in", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: assets in their own right. As", "back": "case with most assets, they can become part of a money laundering scheme. Due to the recent growth in the financial products offered by insurance agents and brokers (including savings products, investment products, and tax planning services), the insurance industry has become increasingly attractive to money launderers. One", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Legal Systems", "back": "Under the FATF Recommendations, countries should adopt legislation that effectively criminalizes acts of money laundering and establishes the widest possible range of predicate offenses. In reference to money laundering, a predicate offense is a crime whose proceeds must be converted into a legitimate form. At a minimum, every serious offense should constitute a predicate offense, regardless of where it is committed. In addition, countries", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Financial Institutions And Related Professions", "back": "The FATF Recommendations were revised over time to set stricter guidelines for financial institutions and professionals who are routinely involved in substantial financial transactions. Such professionals specifically include casinos, real estate agents, lawyers, and dealers in precious metals and precious stones. The measures address customer due diligence (CDD), reporting suspicious transactions, deterring money laundering and terrorist financing, and", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Anti-Money Laundering Programs", "back": "Under the FATF Recommendations, countries should require financial institutions to implement AML and terrorist financing programs. A financial institution’s AML program is highly dependent on which jurisdictions it operates in, as well as the services that it offers. Generally, financial institutions should adopt the AML policies and procedures in the FATF Recommendations, but they need to tailor their programs to the requirements of the specific", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Customer Due Diligence", "back": "The FATF Recommendations set out the fundamental measures that financial institutions must take to identify and verify the identity of customers and beneficial owners. Although it is most important to conduct due diligence when a business relationship is first established, due diligence should be exercised on an ongoing basis. These requirements set firm, more detailed standards while also providing flexibility and allowing adaptation to new industry", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Deterring Money Laundering And Terrorist Financing", "back": "Within certain limits, countries and institutions are free to determine the extent of measures appropriate to the specific risk of money laundering or terrorist financing they face. However, all countries are required to (1) establish an FIU to receive reports regarding suspicious transactions, (2) designate law enforcement agencies for AML/CFT investigations, and (3) involve financial supervisors in AML/CFT initiatives. These authorities should have", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reporting Of Suspicious Transactions", "back": "Under the FATF’s Recommendation 20, a financial institution should be required to file a report when it “suspects or has reasonable grounds to suspect that funds are the proceeds of a criminal activity, or are related to terrorist financing.” Some jurisdictions also set additional requirements for reporting suspicious transactions, such as if a cash transaction surpasses a certain threshold amount. The name of these reports varies by jurisdiction, but they are", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Regulation And Supervision", "back": "All countries need adequate measures to ensure that financial institutions and other businesses and professions are complying with their obligations. The required measures take into account the risks and the regulatory structures that already exist in the relevant sectors. • Financial institutions and casinos should not be owned or managed by criminals. • The measures applicable to banks, insurance, and securities firms for prudential purposes", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Large Cash Transactions", "back": "Under the best practices provided in the FATF Recommendations, countries should implement a reporting requirement for financial institutions and DNFBPs that engage in cash transactions above the jurisdiction’s designated threshold. The reports should cover domestic and international cash transactions. Many jurisdictions implement this reporting requirement.", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Cross-Border Transfer Of Currency", "back": "Under the FATF’s Recommendation 32, countries should implement disclosure requirements for individuals who are physically carrying currency or currency equivalents (i.e., bearer instruments) into or out of the country in amounts that are above the country’s designated reporting threshold. Generally, individuals who are carrying currency or the equivalent above the reporting threshold while attempting to cross jurisdictional borders should be required to", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "International Cooperation", "back": "The FATF Recommendations contain several provisions that address international cooperation. Notably, the Recommendation on mutual legal assistance covers several concepts that are in the 25 Non-Cooperative Countries and Territories Criteria discussed below. The most significant provisions deal with cooperation between administrative and law enforcement authorities concerned with combating money laundering and terrorist", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: efforts. The most prevalent", "back": "Anti-Money Laundering Directive (now in its sixth iteration and referred to as the Sixth Directive). The Sixth Directive applies to the financial sector as well as to lawyers, notaries, accountants, real estate agents, casinos, and company service providers. Its scope also encompasses all providers of goods when cash payments are made or received in", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "New Deposit Accounts", "back": "For individual deposit accounts, minimum identification standards should be established. The information to be obtained should include:", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "New Loan Accounts", "back": "An institution should perform due diligence in establishing a new loan account because, if the customer is engaged in money laundering, there is a risk of forfeiture of collateral pledged on the loans. Real or personal property that is traceable to drug sales or that is purchased with laundered funds is subject to seizure by the government. If the property seized is pledged as collateral, the financial institution must prove that it was an innocent lienholder of the", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Services For Non-Account Holders", "back": "Banks often issue cashier’s checks, money orders, and traveler’s checks and perform currency exchanges, wire transfers, or check cashing services for non-account holders. Strict identification requirements should be established for transactions with persons who are not regular bank customers. In fact, regulations require that in some instances, banks keep a record of the identity of persons who are not established customers. Such regulations usually", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Monitoring Accounts", "back": "While identification of customers is important, it is equally important to monitor the activity of accounts. The institution should identify unusual transactions that might not be consistent with the normal business of the customer. Unusual and dramatic changes in wire transfer, monetary instrument, and check transactions are important to identify. If unusual transactions or activities are noted, the institution should take some action to protect itself. The", "topic": "Civil Actions", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}], "Securities Fraud": [{"front": "What Constitutes a Security?", "back": "• A security is a negotiable financial instrument that represents an interest or a right in something else.\n• Countries define the term differently, so what is considered a security varies from country to country.\n• Types of investments most commonly recognized as securities include stocks, bonds, and certificates of deposit.\n• In many countries, the term security includes investment contracts.\n• Generally, a contract, transaction, or scheme is an investment contract if: 1. There is an investment of money or another asset. 2. The investment is in a common enterprise. 3. The investment was made", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Securities Laws and Regulation", "back": "• Securities regulation refers to laws, rules, and procedures enacted by a legislative body and administered by dedicated agencies that govern the way in which companies, consumers, and financial profes\n• To be effective, securities regulation must balance the legitimate needs of businesses to raise capital against the need to protect investors.\n• Additional purposes include:\n• Promoting an active and competitive market", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO)", "back": "• An international organization comprised of securities commissioners and administrators responsible for securities regulation and the administration of securities laws in their respective countries\n• Recognized as the international standard-setter for securities markets\n• Main objectives are to assist its members to:\n• Cooperate to promote high standards of regulation in order to maintain just, efficient, and sound markets.", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Self-Regulatory Organizations (SROs)", "back": "• Nongovernmental entities that exercise some level of regulatory authority over the operations, standards of practice, and business conduct of an industry or profession\n• SROs oversee the markets in which they operate and police the members and member firms participating in those markets.\n• SROs’ regulatory responsibilities might include:\n• Creating rules to protect the integrity of the market in which they operate\n• Many SROs play an important role in the resolution of disputes arising from market transactions.", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Securities Fraud Schemes", "back": "• Churning (excessive trading)\n• The excessive trading of a customer account to generate commissions while disregarding the customer’s interests\n• Unsuitable recommendations\n• In many countries, broker-dealers who make recommendations or provide advice to clients regarding purchases of investment products are subject to a suitability requirement.\n• Securities broker-dealers must know their customers financially to effectively service their accounts and minimize the risk of recommending an inappropriate investment.", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}], "Money Laundering": [{"front": "Definition of Money Laundering", "back": "• The disguising of the existence, nature, source, control, beneficial ownership, location, and disposition of property (typically) derived from criminal activity", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Money Laundering Process", "back": "• Three stages\n• Placement 1. In this first stage, the launderer introduces their illegal profits into the financial system. 2. It is at this stage that legislation has been developed to prevent launderers from deposi", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using a Front Business to Launder Funds", "back": "• One of the most common methods of laundering funds is to filter the money through a legitimate business, known as a front business.\n• A front business provides a safe place for organizing and managing criminal activity, where the comings and goings of large numbers of people will not arouse undue suspicion.\n• In addition, a front that conducts legitimate business provides cover for delivery and transportation related to illegal activity. The expenses from illegal activity can be attributed to the legitimat\n• A red flag of a front business is the observation of minimal customers during peak operating hours.\n• Two methods commonly used to hide assets or launder money through a front business are:", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Money Laundering", "back": "• Digital currencies are currencies that exist and are traded in a digital format.\n• Among the most popular digital currencies is bitcoin, a cryptocurrency that features a peer-to-peer network that allows users to send units of the currency to each other online without the use of a tr\n• Digital currencies are vulnerable to money laundering because:\n• Many of them function as international person-to-person (P2P) payment systems that cross jurisdictional boundaries, creating difficulties for authorities pursuing enforcement or legal actions.", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Trade-Based Money Laundering to Launder Funds", "back": "• Defined by the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) as “the process of disguising the proceeds of crime and moving value through the use of trade transactions in an attempt to legitimize their illicit o\n• Schemes generally involve importers and exporters who collude to misrepresent the price, quantity, or quality of imported or exported goods or services.\n• Trade-based money laundering schemes can be used to create artificial profits for the purpose of laundering money between countries; to create a complex paper trail; and to avoid taxes, customs duties\n• Some common schemes include:\n• Over- and under-invoicing schemes 1. Importers and exporters conspire to misrepresent the price of the goods or services being traded, thus transferring additional value between the importer and expor", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Money Services Businesses to Launder Funds", "back": "• Money services businesses (MSBs) refer to non-depository financial service providers that transmit or convert money and operate in one or more of the following capacities:\n• Currency exchangers\n• Prepaid access providers or sellers\n• MSBs offer an alternative to depository institutions for both financial services and money laundering, so an individual unable to transfer illegal funds into the traditional depository banking system \n• Most MSBs operate under less strict regulations than traditional financial institutions.", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Using Alternative Remittance Systems to Launder Funds", "back": "• Alternative remittance systems are methods of transferring funds from a party at one location to another party (whether domestic or foreign) without the use of formal banking institutions.\n• These systems do not require a direct physical or digital transfer of currency from the sender to the receiver.\n• In the typical alternative remittance system, the payer transfers funds to a local broker who has a connection to another broker in the region where the payee is located. The second broker then distri\n• The relative anonymity and lack of a paper trail afforded by alternative remittance systems makes them attractive to money launderers, as well as to people involved in terrorist financing.", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) on Money Laundering", "back": "• An intergovernmental body established to develop and promote standards and policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing at both the national and international levels\n• The FATF Recommendations, revised in 2012, created the most comprehensive standard with which to measure a country’s AML, counterterrorism, and nuclear proliferation laws and policies, and they serve \n• Some of the key measures in the FATF Recommendations provide that countries should:\n• Use a risk-based approach when setting AML policies.\n• Require financial institutions to: 1. Keep certain records and establish AML policies. 2. Avoid correspondent banking with shell banks. 3. Continuously monitor wire transfers.", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Civil Justice System", "back": "This section reviews the legal aspects of actions by private parties—including fraud examiners, auditors, accountants, security personnel, private investigators, and lawyers—to investigate and recover losses due to fraud. Many of these cases will be resolved in the civil A civil action or civil suit arises when individuals or business entities (such as corporations or partnerships) disagree on a legal matter. A civil action usually involves a dispute over something", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The person who sues", "back": "plaintiff, and the person being sued is the defendant. Procedure in Civil Cases The procedure in a civil case can be quite complex. Furthermore, the terminology describing steps in the process is not consistent in legal systems throughout the world. This discussion", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: members of the European Union (EU)—there", "back": "potential for a criminal violation of such laws. Therefore, fraud examiners should consult with legal counsel on how to preserve evidence gathered during an examination.", "topic": "Money Laundering", "domain": "Law", "source": "manual"}], "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud": [{"front": "Common Types of Bankruptcy Filings", "back": "• Liquidation\n• The most basic type of bankruptcy proceeding\n• Typical items that may not be liquidated include the debtor’s primary residence, items of nominal value, or assets deemed necessary for the debtor to maintain employment.\n• Reorganization\n• Allows the debtor respite from creditors so that the debtor can reorganize its financial affairs and continue as a going concern", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Bankruptcy Schemes", "back": "• Concealed assets\n• The most common type of bankruptcy fraud scheme is the concealment of assets rightfully belonging to the debtor’s estate to avoid forfeiting the assets in bankruptcy.\n• The planned bustout\n• A scheme involving a planned bankruptcy to defraud creditors", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/ Debtor Regimes", "back": "• A distillation of international best practices for designing a national insolvency system that is designed to be flexible enough to serve as a benchmark for the insolvency system of any country\n• Under the World Bank Principles, countries should adopt the following anti-fraud policies:\n• Administrative powers 1. Most bankruptcy processes appoint a person or group with administrative powers (e.g., an administrator, trustee, receiver, examiner, or supervisor) to oversee the process. 2. \n• The right to cancel fraudulent contracts or transactions entered into by the debtor\n• The power to collect, preserve, and dispose of the debtor’s property", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}], "Tax Fraud": [{"front": "What Constitutes Tax Fraud?", "back": "• Tax fraud refers to intentional actions that a taxpayer commits to defraud the government of owed tax dollars.\n• The intent of the taxpayer to wrongly file a return or provide other false tax information determines the difference between tax evasion and tax avoidance.\n• Tax evasion refers to any fraudulent actions that a taxpayer commits to avoid reporting or paying taxes.\n• The primary distinguishing characteristic of tax evasion as compared to tax avoidance is that tax evasion is illegal, but tax avoidance is legal.", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Willfulness vs. Good Faith Misunderstanding of the Law", "back": "• The most important distinction in determining whether an individual or company committed tax evasion is whether the party acted with criminal intent; most jurisdictions require a willful attempt to ev\n• A good faith or legitimate misunderstanding of the applicable law typically negates willfulness, the voluntary, intentional violation of a known legal duty.\n• Willfulness might be inferred from conduct such as:\n• Keeping a double set of books (not to be confused with keeping separate books and tax records, which might require different recording techniques)\n• Covering up sources of income", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Tax Evasion Schemes", "back": "• Income and wealth tax evasion\n• Fraudsters falsify or omit material information in regard to taxes on periodic income or wealth.\n• Falsifying tax deductions\n• Fraudsters inappropriately use tax deductions (the itemized expenses subtracted from gross income or assets in determining the taxable amount) to reduce the taxpayer’s total tax liability.\n• Tax credit schemes", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Tax Fraud", "back": "• No tax deficiency\n• To prove innocence of tax fraud matters, the defendant can establish that there is no tax deficiency and therefore no tax liability.\n• Avoidance, not evasion\n• Establishing that the taxpayer was engaging in tax avoidance and not evasion provides a defense to tax fraud.\n• Reliance on an attorney or accountant", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Ineffective Defenses Against Tax Fraud", "back": "• Death of taxpayer\n• Fraud penalties survive the taxpayer’s death.\n• Bankruptcy\n• Liabilities owed as a result of tax evasion may not be discharged in bankruptcy proceedings.\n• Amended or delinquent return", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "domain": "Law", "source": "workbook"}], "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts": [{"front": "Categories of Cash Receipts Schemes", "back": "• Two types\n• Skimming\n• The difference depends completely on when the cash is stolen.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Skimming", "back": "• The removal of cash from a victim entity prior to its entry in an accounting system\n• Employees steal sales or receivables before they are recorded in the company books.\n• Known as off-book frauds, meaning cash is stolen before it is recorded in the victim organization’s accounts\n• Difficult to detect due to the lack of audit trail", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Sales Skimming", "back": "• Unrecorded sales scheme\n• An employee sells goods or services to a customer and collects the customer’s payment but makes no record of the sale.\n• Understated sales scheme\n• The transaction in question is posted to the books but for a lower amount than what the perpetrator actually collected.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Skimming Receivables", "back": "• More difficult to conceal than sales skimming because payments are expected (victim organization knows the customer owes money and is waiting for the payment)\n• When receivables are skimmed, the absence of the payment appears on the books as a delinquent account.\n• To conceal a skimmed receivable, a perpetrator must account for the payment that was due but never received.\n• Lapping schemes\n• The crediting of one account through the abstraction of money from another account", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Detection of Skimming Schemes", "back": "• Receipt- or sales-level detection\n• Vertical, horizontal, and ratio analysis of sales accounts\n• Journal entry review\n• Examine journal entries for: 1. False credits to inventory to conceal unrecorded or understated sales 2. Write-offs of lost, stolen, or obsolete inventory 3. Write-offs of accounts receivable accounts\n• Confirming customers’ outstanding account balances", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention of Skimming Schemes", "back": "• General controls\n• Sales entries and general ledger access controls should include documented policies and procedures from management.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Cash Larceny", "back": "• The theft of cash that has already been recorded on the victim company’s books\n• Types of cash larceny schemes\n• Theft of cash from the register 1. Involves opening the register and removing currency or checks 2. Often committed while a sale is being conducted so that it appears to be part of the transaction", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Detection of Cash Larceny", "back": "• Cash register log totals should be reconciled to the amount of cash in the drawer.\n• The bank deposit should be made by someone other than the cashier or the accounts receivable clerk.\n• A person independent of the cash receipts and accounts receivable functions should compare entries to the cash receipts journal with:\n• Authenticated bank deposit slips\n• All employees should have unique access codes to the cash registers, and the time periods that each access code is used should be checked against employee work schedules to ensure an employee’s access", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "back": "• Separation of duties\n• Cash receipts\n• Bank reconciliations\n• Assignment rotation\n• Many internal fraud schemes are continuous in nature and require ongoing efforts by the employee to conceal the fraud, so mandatory job or assignment rotations should be implemented to uncover the con", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "back": "Asset misappropriation is the most common form of occupational fraud by a considerable degree. There are three major categories of asset misappropriation schemes. Cash receipts schemes are discussed in this section, fraudulent disbursements of cash are addressed in the next section, and the following section covers schemes involving the theft of inventory and Cash is the focal point of most accounting schemes. Cash, both on deposit in banks and on", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: skimming schemes", "back": "they leave no direct audit trail. Because the stolen funds are never recorded, the victim organization might not be aware that the cash was ever received. Consequently, it can be difficult to detect that the cash has been stolen. This is the primary advantage of a skimming scheme to the fraudster.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Off-site skimming is by no", "back": "limited to the apartment rental industry. The schemes described previously can easily translate into any position where those who generate or collect revenues operate in an independent fashion. A prime example is the insurance agent who sells policies to customers, and then neglects to file the policies with the carrier. Most customers", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "False Discounts", "back": "Those employees with the authority to grant discounts might use this authority to skim sales and receivables. In a false discount skimming scheme, an employee accepts full payment for an item but records the transaction as if the customer had been given a discount. The employee skims the amount of the discount. For example, on a $100 purchase, if an employee granted a false discount of 20%, the employee could skim $20 and leave the company’s books", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: fact that the stolen checks are not posted", "back": "that some customers’ accounts are in danger of becoming past due. If this happens, the perpetrator’s scheme is in danger because these customers will almost surely complain about the misapplication of their payments. However, the misapplied payments can be concealed on the books by forcing account totals, stealing", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: skimming. Lapping", "back": "crediting of one account through the abstraction of money from", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Debits To Expense Accounts", "back": "An employee might conceal the skimming of funds by making unsupported entries in the victim company’s books. If a payment is made on a receivable, for instance, the proper entry is a debit to cash and a credit to the receivable. Instead of debiting cash, the employee might choose to debit an expense account. This transaction still keeps the company’s books in balance, but the incoming cash is never recorded. In addition, the customer’s receivable", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Debits To Aging Or Fictitious Receivables", "back": "The same method discussed previously is used when employees debit existing or fictitious accounts receivable to conceal skimmed cash. For example, an employee who has skimmed one customer’s payments might add the stolen amounts to aging accounts that will soon be written off as uncollectible or to very large accounts where a small debit might go unnoticed. Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts Some perpetrators also set up completely fictitious accounts and debit them for the cost of", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Writing Off Account Balances", "back": "Some employees cover their skimming by posting entries to contra revenue accounts such as discounts and allowances. If, for instance, an employee intercepts a $1,000 payment, the employee would create a $1,000 “discount” on the account to compensate for the missing money. Another account that might be used in this type of concealment is the bad debts A billing manager was authorized to write off certain patient balances as hardship", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: A problem for fraudsters in some skimming schemes", "back": "victim organization’s inventory. Off-book sales of goods (skimming schemes) will always leave an inventory shortage and a corresponding rise in the cost of goods sold. When a sale of goods is made, the physical inventory is reduced by the amount of", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: know the exact balance of their account. If this", "back": "case, it might be more effective to confirm by invoice and reconstruct the account balance using the source documents in the files and the results of the confirmation. If fraud is suspected, ask the customer or the bank to return a copy of both the front and the back of the check(s) used to pay specific invoices.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: cash larceny", "back": "intentional taking of an employer’s cash (the term cash includes both currency and checks) without the consent and against the will of the employer. However, recall that skimming also involves the intentional taking of an employer’s cash. The difference between skimming and cash larceny is that skimming is the theft of cash before it appears on the books.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: skimming and cash larceny is that skimming", "back": "theft of cash before it appears on the books. Cash larceny schemes involve the theft of money that has already appeared on a victim company’s books. Accordingly, cash larceny schemes are easier to detect than skimming schemes because they leave an audit trail.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: currency—rarely varies. It", "back": "methods that perpetrators use to avoid getting caught that distinguish larceny schemes. Oddly, in many instances the perpetrators have no plan for avoiding detection. A large part of fraud is rationalization; employees convince themselves that they are somehow entitled to what they are taking or that what they are doing is not", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reversing Transactions", "back": "Some employees conceal cash larceny by processing reversing transactions, which cause the register log to reconcile to the amount of cash on hand after the theft. By processing false voids or refunds, an employee can reduce the cash balance reflected on the register log. A cashier received payments from a customer and recorded the transactions on their system. The cashier stole the payments from the customers and then destroyed the company’s receipts", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Register Manipulation", "back": "Instead of using reversing entries, an employee might manually alter the register log. Again, the purpose of this activity is to force a balance between the cash on hand and the actual cash received. An employee might use correction fluid to cover up a sale where the proceeds were stolen or might simply cross out or alter the numbers on the tape so that the register total and the cash drawer balance. This type of concealment is not common because the alterations will", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Altering Cash Counts", "back": "Another method for concealing cash larceny is to alter the cash counts on registers. When cash from a register is totaled and prepared for deposit, an employee simply records the wrong amount so that the cash on hand appears to balance with the total on the register log. Obviously, employees who deal with the receipt of cash should not be charged with verifying the amount of cash on hand in their own register, but this control is often overlooked.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Destroying Register Logs", "back": "If the fraudster cannot make the cash and the tape balance, the next best thing is to prevent others from computing the totals and discovering the imbalance. Employees who are stealing from the register sometimes destroy detail tapes that would implicate them in a crime. When detail tapes are missing or defaced, it might be because someone is trying to Other Larceny of Sales and Receivables Not all receipts arrive via the cash register. Employees can just as easily steal money", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property": [{"front": "What Is Intellectual Property?", "back": "• Intangible proprietary information that includes a business’s ideas, designs, and innovations, howsoever expressed or recorded", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Competitive Intelligence vs. Espionage", "back": "• Competitive intelligence is the process by which competitor data are assembled into relevant, accurate, and usable knowledge about competitors’ positions, performance, capabilities, and intentions.\n• A legitimate business function that businesses use to anticipate competitors’ research and development strategies and to determine their operating costs, pricing policies, financial strength, and capa\n• Espionage refers to the use of illegal, covert means to gather information.\n• Does not cover legitimate intelligence collection and analysis using legal means", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Basic Sources of Information", "back": "• Open-source information\n• Information in the public domain (i.e., publicly available data that anyone can lawfully obtain by request, purchase, or observation)\n• Dumpster diving\n• Involves obtaining sensitive information by looking through someone else’s trash (e.g., via dumpsters and other trash receptacles)\n• Scavenging", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "How Information Is Lost or Stolen", "back": "• Accident and negligence, such as through:\n• Conference speeches and papers\n• Poor information security procedures\n• Organizations should employ and regularly update a system for protecting and disposing of confidential information.\n• Calendars", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "back": "• A task force\n• Should include managers and staff from departments that deal with proprietary information (e.g., research and development and production), as well as representatives from the corporate security, human\n• Awareness training\n• Employees must be educated as to what information is proprietary, as well as the dangers of electronically communicating that information.\n• Nondisclosure agreements", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Theft Of Data And Intellectual Property", "back": "Today, information is a valuable asset, and organizations must protect their intellectual property. A business’s worth is no longer based solely on tangible assets and revenue-making potential; the information it develops, stores, and collects accounts for a large share of a To a considerable degree, businesses, government administrations, and society as a whole have come to depend on the efficiency and security of information technology, resulting in", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: intentions. In contrast, espionage", "back": "the use of illegal, clandestine means to gather information; therefore, it does not cover legitimate intelligence collection and analysis using legal means. Espionage, however, can be further subdivided into two categories: traditional and corporate. Traditional espionage refers to government-sponsored or sanctioned espionage", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: and corporate. Traditional espionage", "back": "government-sponsored or sanctioned espionage conducted to collect protected information from a foreign government. Corporate espionage (also known as industrial espionage) is the term used to describe the use of illegal, clandestine means to acquire information for commercial purposes.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: (also known as industrial espionage)", "back": "term used to describe the use of illegal, clandestine means to acquire information for commercial purposes. Competitive intelligence is a legitimate business function that aligns with marketing and research and development (R&D), as well as general business strategy and the newer", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: information (such as trade secrets)", "back": "right to access it. Open-source information is available to anyone who wants to collect it, without legal consequences. Nonpublic information, however, is not open to the public. Access to nonpublic records is restricted. Obtaining nonpublic records without appropriate authority violates the law.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Physical surveillance", "back": "real-time observation of a target’s actions or communications. Observing and recording a target’s movements is useful for several reasons. Such surveillance can be used to identify real property or other assets; additional targets; individuals who might possess valuable information, such as lawyers, accountants, or bankers; businesses; patterns", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Mobile Surveillance", "back": "Mobile surveillance involves observing and following persons. When conducting mobile surveillance, an intelligence professional must be flexible and imaginative. For example, placing a reflective stripe on the back of the subject’s car makes it more distinctive at night and therefore easier to follow. If legally permissible, an intelligence professional might place a GPS tracking device on the subject’s car so that its path can be traced 24 hours a day. Also, if", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fixed Surveillance", "back": "Fixed surveillance is a situation in which an individual secretly observes an area or a person from a distance. This method, however, has a key disadvantage: the base from which the surveillance is conducted might be spotted by the target or other people passing by. Therefore, intelligence professionals must camouflage fixed surveillance campaigns, and to do so, they must be familiar with their surroundings and choose a cover that will not draw attention.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Technical surveillance", "back": "practice of covertly acquiring audio, visual, or other types of data from targets through the use of technical devices, procedures, and techniques. Technical surveillance, however, can be costly; it is labor intensive, highly intrusive, and fraught with potential legal problems.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Physical infiltration", "back": "process whereby an individual enters a target organization to spy on the organization’s employees. Often, corporate spies use physical infiltration when there is a tight time schedule, a lack of available recruits, or expense constraints; however, spies might also use physical infiltration when they have specialized knowledge that makes them the best", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Gather Intelligence About The Target", "back": "To conduct a successful social engineering attack, social engineers must gather information about the target and the target’s environment. The more information a social engineer has about their target, the greater the chances that their attack will be successful. For example, a social engineer will have a greater chance of success if they know their target’s internal processes, jargon, and organizational structure.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Select The Tactic", "back": "Once the social engineer has collected an appropriate amount of information about the target, they will determine which tactic would be most suitable to achieve the desired goals. Social engineers use various tactics, including:", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Pretexting", "back": "Pretexting is the act of impersonating someone else or making false or misleading statements to persuade a target to release information or perform some action. Pretexting can occur inperson, over the phone, or through some other form of communication. Social engineers often engage in pretexting by posing as a person of authority, a member of tech support, someone who has legitimate access to the target’s network, an individual who", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Shoulder Surfing", "back": "Shoulder surfing involves observing an unsuspecting target from a nearby location while the target enters a username and password into a system, talks on the phone, fills out financial forms, or performs some other task from which the engineer can obtain valuable information.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Spam And Chain Emails", "back": "Social engineers use spam and chain emails to carry out their attacks. Email is a common method used in social engineering attacks because it is widely used, and social engineers can send emails designed to look like they come from popular, trusted sources. Also, social engineers can include infected attachments or links directing targets to malicious sites in such emails. Moreover, social engineers can design emails to contain specific content particular to", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reverse Social Engineering", "back": "In reverse social engineering schemes, social engineers make targets think that the engineers can help them by providing security-related services. These schemes involve three phases. Theft of Data and Intellectual Property First, social engineers sabotage the target’s network or make the target think that the network has been sabotaged. This can be done by launching a network attack against a target website", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Contact And Build Trust With The Target", "back": "Once social engineers have collected an appropriate amount of information about their targets and selected the tactic, they will contact their targets, seeking to build trust with them. The trust that social engineers gain will be used to elicit information that can be exploited to reach the goals of their attack. Building trust serves several purposes, including: • Putting targets at ease and making them more comfortable", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Elicitation Skills", "back": "Although social engineering does not require a high level of technical expertise, it does require social skills and other components. The social skills and components needed to be a • Adaptability (i.e., ability to adapt communications to fit the environment and situation) • Relationship and bonding skills (i.e., ability to build bonds or relationships with", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Common Elicitation Tactics", "back": "Social engineers use numerous tactics to elicit information. Some common elicitation • Appealing to the target’s ego: Social engineers often appeal to their targets’ egos to coax them into a conversation that otherwise would not take place. Likewise, appealing to a target’s ego will tend to make the target more self-assured, which tends to remove logical awareness that a potential breach might be occurring.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Again, technical surveillance", "back": "practice of covertly acquiring audio, visual, or other types of data from targets through the use of technical devices, procedures, and techniques. When Theft of Data and Intellectual Property corporate spies resort to the use of technical surveillance, it is usually to gather", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: become common", "back": "by which intelligence professionals can monitor their competition. The spy has two primary considerations in a wiretapping campaign: where to insert the surveillance equipment and which of the various technologies to employ.", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Insertion Point", "back": "In identifying the insertion point, the spy must choose an area where proprietary information is likely to be discussed or displayed and where background noise and electronic interference remain minimal. Spies frequently choose areas with proximity to computers and telecommunications equipment carrying proprietary data as an insertion point. Spies might also target areas conducive to employee conversations. This can include any place", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Consumer Fraud": [{"front": "Common Types of Con Schemes", "back": "• Advance-fee schemes\n• Schemes structured to obtain an illegal gain by falsely promising the delivery of a product or service\n• Debt consolidation schemes\n• Often involve the consolidation agency collecting money from the debtor but not forwarding it to the creditors\n• Scavenger or revenge schemes", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Common Types of Elder Fraud Schemes", "back": "• Home improvement schemes\n• Fraudsters recommend a “friend” who can perform needed home repairs for an older individual at a reasonable price. In some cases, this friend then overcharges the individual for home repair work that \n• Travel, vacation, and timeshare schemes\n• Fraudsters post advertisements for vacation properties that are nonexistent, significantly different than promised, or not available for rent.\n• Tech-support schemes", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Ponzi Schemes", "back": "• A Ponzi scheme is generally defined as an illegal business practice in which new investors’ money is used to make payments to earlier investors.\n• The investment opportunity is typically presented with the promise of uncommonly high returns.\n• The key element in a Ponzi scheme is that initial investors are paid with subsequent investors’ money with minimal or no legitimate commerce occurring.\n• A Ponzi scheme is a pyramid scheme, but it masquerades as some type of investment.", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Red Flags of Ponzi Schemes", "back": "• Sounds too good to be true\n• Promises of low risk or high rewards\n• History of consistent returns\n• High-pressure sales tactics\n• Pressure to reinvest", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Pyramid Schemes", "back": "• Illegal pyramids generate revenue by continually recruiting new members. These operations might offer merchandise or services for sale, but the only significant revenues come from recruitment.\n• The distinguishing factor of the illegal pyramid is the continual need for new investors or members.\n• Unlike Ponzi schemes, illegal pyramids are promoted as pyramids.\n• An operation is likely to be classified as an illegal pyramid scheme if the company emphasizes the recruitment of new members over product sales and promises that riches can only be obtained through r", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Consumer Fraud", "back": "Consumer fraud embodies a wide variety of misleading practices related to advertising, marketing, or the selling or buying of goods and services. It can arise when a product or service does not operate as intended and can involve the concealment or overcharging of fees. It can also occur when a seemingly legitimate company urges a customer to agree to unfair terms just to complete a transaction or when a victim purchases a product that appears", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In an adoption scheme where the birth mother", "back": "perpetrator, she agrees to give her unborn child to multiple adopting families in exchange for money. The birth mother requires an up-front payment from each family, but she has no plans for them to adopt her child. In frauds perpetrated by the adopting parents, they might verbally agree to let the birth mother", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Verifiers", "back": "Next, the caller is passed to a verifier, who reads some vague words about the deal and records the person’s agreement. These recordings intentionally exclude important details, recording only the customer’s consent. The customers of fraudulent telemarketing operations are not the only victims. Fronters are often poorly educated and easily taken advantage of by the career criminals who manage the operations. Salespeople might face hidden costs in a work agreement, similar to the ones", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "International Factoring Companies", "back": "Factoring through Asian and European merchants is becoming increasingly common. Factoring companies in these countries tend to charge a lower price for their services than some other countries—between 9% and 10% of the gross. Regardless of their locale, factors have the opportunity to make a great profit. They also, however, risk that banks will put a hold on their accounts or sue them for excessive chargebacks. In response to the losses", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Another convenient tool that the telemarketer can use", "back": "check-cashing store. If a boiler room operation wants to avoid the risks of setting up a bank account that might be traced or seized, customers’ personal checks are taken to a company that cashes them for a small fee. These establishments rarely require any identification to cash the checks. Customers might", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Timeshares", "back": "Another scam sells timeshares in condominiums for travelers. Telemarketers pass themselves off as brokers to condominium owners and purport to specialize in selling timeshares. Some real estate ads try to coax investors into buying “options” on property. Supposedly, the option locks in a present-day price on behalf of the purchaser, who can exercise the option later if they wish to buy the land or to sell it at a profit. Sometimes the investor has bought", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Developed Property", "back": "Various developed property schemes have been identified globally. These scams often involve a large deposit toward a property in a paradisiacal location such as Belize or Costa Rica that might or—more likely—might not be refunded dependent upon contractual technicalities. Those who do buy property through these schemes often find that their property is not as advertised or is heavily restricted from further development. In one example, the General", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Identity Theft": [{"front": "Methods of Committing Identity Theft", "back": "• Traditional identity theft\n• Involves a fraudster stealing an individual’s personal information and pretending to be that individual\n• Synthetic identity theft\n• Involves a fraudster using entirely fabricated personal information or a combination of real and fabricated information to create a new identity", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "How Identity Thieves Steal Information", "back": "• Dumpster diving\n• Discarded devices\n• Mail theft\n• Shoulder surfing\n• The practice of observing another person (e.g., looking over their shoulder) to gather personal information", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods of Identity Theft Prevention for Individuals", "back": "• Create complex passwords or passphrases that have at least eight characters and contain upper- and lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols.\n• Do not reuse passwords.\n• Never send personal information, such as a password or government identification number, via email.\n• When available, use biometric authentication (e.g., fingerprints, voice recognition).\n• Create unique answers for security questions.", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods of Identity Theft Prevention for Businesses", "back": "• Limit the personal information collected from customers (e.g., do not collect government identification numbers from customers unless legally required to gather that information).\n• Restrict employees from accessing the personal information of customers and coworkers.\n• Do not retain personal information for longer than necessary.\n• Use encryption to protect all personal information stored by the company or sent to third parties, as well as information sent over the company’s wireless network.\n• Restrict the use of laptops to those employees who need them to do their jobs.", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Identity Theft", "back": "Identity theft is a common type of fraud that is non-discriminatory. Anyone can be targeted; the victim might be a college student, a retiree, a schoolteacher, or a successful attorney. Even businesses can be victims of identity theft. Although there is not a universal definition of identity theft, most law enforcement organizations use a definition similar to the following: Identity theft is a crime in which someone wrongfully obtains and uses another person’s", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Shoulder surfing", "back": "practice of observing another person (e.g., looking over the person’s shoulder) to gather personal information. Shoulder surfing is especially effective in crowded areas where a fraudster can stand close to a victim without being noticed. While in close proximity, the fraudster can eavesdrop on the victim’s telephone conversation, view the", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In the context of identity theft, social engineering", "back": "the psychological manipulation of people to trick them into revealing personal or business information. Social engineering exploits the natural tendencies of humans to be cooperative and to trust others. After researching a victim, social engineers often impersonate someone the victim can trust, such as", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Computer hacking", "back": "the use of technology to gain unauthorized access to sensitive information on a computer system. Computer hackers target companies’ computer networks for multiple reasons. If the personal information of a company’s customers is compromised, this is known as a data", "topic": "Identity Theft", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Accounting Concepts": [{"front": "Accounting Basics", "back": "• The accounting equation\n• Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity\n• Accounting methods\n• Cash-basis accounting 1. Involves recording revenues and expenses based on when a company receives or pays cash 2. The advantage is its simplicity—the only thing a company must track is cash being rec", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Accounting Concepts", "back": "• Balance sheet (or statement of financial position)\n• Provides insight into a company’s financial situation at a specific point in time, generally the last day of the accounting period\n• Includes cash, accounts receivable, inventory, and prepaid items 2. Long-term or noncurrent assets—assets that will likely not be converted to cash within one year\n• Includes fixed assets (e.g., land, buildings, equipment) and intangible assets (e.g., patents, trademarks, goodwill)\n• Liabilities are presented in the following categories in order of maturity: 1. Current liabilities—obligations expected to be paid within one year", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "120,000", "back": "• The rules by which a company’s financial transactions are recorded into their appropriate account classifications and properly reported as part of the entity’s financial statements\n• Publicly traded companies must follow the specific financial reporting practices of their jurisdiction, which differ among regions.\n• Currently, there is not a universally accepted accounting recording and reporting system in existence.\n• Commonly used accounting frameworks include U.S. GAAP and International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS), the latter of which is permitted or required by 166 international jurisdictions.\n• U.S. GAAP is a rules-based framework.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "International Financial Reporting Standards", "back": "• Qualitative characteristics of useful financial information under IFRS\n• Relevance 1. Any financial information that might affect a decision made by a user of the financial statements is considered relevant. 2. To be relevant, the information must have a predictive value (\n• An item is considered material if its omission or misstatement would affect the judgment of a reasonable person who is relying on the financial statements.\n• Complete (includes all information necessary to understand the data presented)\n• Neutral (no bias in the selection or presentation of financial information)", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Circumstances Meriting Departures from GAAP", "back": "• As with rules for most things, departures from GAAP are sometimes required, regardless of whether you are using U.S. GAAP, IFRS, or another set of accounting standards.\n• Therefore, the standard-setting bodies recognize that, upon occasion, there might be an unusual circumstance when the literal application of GAAP would render the financial statements misleading. In t\n• There is concern that assets or income would be overstated and expenses or liabilities would be understated (the conservatism constraint requires that, when there is any doubt, one should avoid overst\n• If a transaction is considered immaterial (i.e., it would not affect a decision made by a prudent reader of the financial statements), then it need not be reported.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Accounting Concepts", "back": "Fraudulent acts are usually interconnected with money and finances. The fraud examiner must therefore understand the source and flow of financial transactions and how they affect an organization’s accounting records. Additionally, the fraud examiner should have an understanding of both financial terminology and accounting theory. Merriam-Webster.com defines accounting as “the system of recording and summarizing business", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: accounting equation, as shown below,", "back": "basis for all double-entry accounting: Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity By definition, assets consist of the net resources owned by an entity. Examples of assets include cash, receivables, inventory, property, and equipment, as well as intangible items of", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The following", "back": "income statement for XYZ Company for its first year of operations based on the sample transactions previously listed.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: on the income statement. The term net", "back": "that the amount shown is the company’s total sales minus any sales refunds, returns, discounts, or allowances. Conversely, gross revenues refer to the company’s total sales during the accounting period before any deductions are made. From net sales, an expense titled cost of goods sold or cost of sales is deducted. Regardless of the", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Relevance", "back": "Any financial information that might affect a decision made by a user of the financial statements is considered relevant. Financial information is relevant if it has predictive value, confirmatory value, or both. Predictive value is present if the information can be used as an input to processes employed by users to predict future outcomes. Confirmatory value indicates the information provides feedback about previous evaluations.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Materiality", "back": "The amount of an item is material if its omission or misstatement would affect the judgment of a reasonable person who is relying on the financial statements. Materiality is an entityspecific aspect of relevance based on the nature or magnitude, or both, of the items to which the information relates in the context of an individual entity’s financial report.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Faithful Representation", "back": "Financial information must faithfully represent the economic data of the enterprise that it purports to represent. Every effort shall be made to maximize the qualities of perfectly faithful representation: complete, neutral, and free from error. A complete depiction includes all information necessary to understand the data presented. A neutral depiction is without bias in the selection or presentation of financial information. Free from error means there are no", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Comparability And Consistency", "back": "Users of financial statements base their decisions on comparisons between different entities and on similar information from a single entity for another reporting period. Comparability is the qualitative characteristic that enables users to identify and understand similarities and differences between such items. Information about a company is more useful if it is comparable with similar information about other entities and with similar information", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Verifiability", "back": "Verifiability helps assure users that information is accurate and faithfully represents the financial position of the entity. Verifiability means that different knowledgeable and independent observers could reach consensus, although not necessarily complete agreement, that a particular depiction is a faithful representation.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Timeliness", "back": "Timeliness means providing information to decision-makers in time to be capable of influencing their decisions. In general, the older the information is, the less useful it is.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Understandability", "back": "Classifying, characterizing, and presenting information clearly and concisely makes it understandable. However, some economic data are fundamentally complex. Therefore, enough information should be provided about such events so that a reasonable financial statement user can understand what occurred. An entity’s financial statements should include all information necessary for users to make valid decisions and must not mislead them.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Going Concern", "back": "A company’s management is required to provide disclosures when existing events or conditions indicate that it is more likely than not that the entity might be unable to meet its obligations within a reasonable period of time after the financial statements are issued. There is an underlying assumption that an entity will continue as a going concern; that is, the life of the entity will be long enough to fulfill its financial and legal obligations. Any evidence to the", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Recognition", "back": "process of incorporating an item that meets the definition of an element and satisfies the criteria for recognition into the balance sheet or income statement. It involves the depiction of the item in words and by a monetary amount and the inclusion of that amount in the balance sheet or income statement totals. Items that satisfy the recognition criteria should", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Probability Of Future Economic Benefit", "back": "The concept of probability is used in the recognition criteria to refer to the degree of uncertainty that the future economic benefits associated with the item will flow to or from the entity. The concept provides for the uncertainty that characterizes the environment in which an entity operates. Assessments of the degree of uncertainty attaching to the flow of future economic benefits are made on the basis of the evidence available when the financial", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reliability Of Measurement", "back": "The second criterion for the recognition of an item is that it possesses a cost or value that can be measured with reliability. In many cases, cost or value must be estimated; the use of reasonable estimates is an essential part of the preparation of financial statements and does not undermine their reliability. When, however, a reasonable estimate cannot be made, the item is not recognized in the balance sheet or income statement.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recognition Of Assets", "back": "An asset is recognized in the balance sheet when it is probable that the future economic benefits will flow to the entity and the asset has a cost or value that can be measured reliably.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recognition Of Liabilities", "back": "A liability is recognized in the balance sheet when it is probable that an outflow of resources embodying economic benefits will result from the settlement of a present obligation and the amount at which the settlement will take place can be measured reliably.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recognition Of Income", "back": "Income is recognized in the income statement when an increase in future economic benefit related to an increase in an asset or a decrease of a liability has arisen that can be measured reliably. This means, in effect, that recognition of income occurs simultaneously with the recognition of increases in assets or decreases in liabilities (e.g., the net increase in assets arising on a sale of goods or services or the decrease in liabilities arising from the waiver of a", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recognition Of Expenses", "back": "Expenses are recognized in the income statement when a decrease in future economic benefit related to a decrease in an asset or an increase of a liability has arisen that can be measured reliably. This means, in effect, that recognition of expenses occurs simultaneously with the recognition of an increase in liabilities or a decrease in assets (e.g., the accrual of employee entitlements or the depreciation of equipment).", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: conservatism in accounting", "back": "use of the lower of cost or net realizable value as it relates to inventory valuation. If a company’s financial statements intentionally violate the conservatism constraint, they could be fraudulent.", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Financial Statement Fraud": [{"front": "Definition of Financial Statement Fraud", "back": "• The deliberate misrepresentation of the financial condition of an enterprise accomplished through the intentional misstatement or omission of amounts or disclosures in the financial statements to dece", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Forms That Financial Statement Fraud Typically Takes", "back": "• Overstated assets or revenue\n• Falsely reflects a financially stronger company by the inclusion of fictitious asset costs or artificial revenues\n• Understated liabilities and expenses\n• Accomplished through the exclusion of costs or financial obligations", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Five Classifications of Financial Statement Schemes", "back": "• Fictitious revenues\n• Involve the recording of sales of goods or services that did not occur\n• Timing differences\n• The recording of revenues or expenses in improper periods to move revenues or expenses between one period and the next, increasing or decreasing earnings as desired\n• Revenue is recognized when (or as) an entity satisfies a performance obligation by transferring a promised good or service (asset) to a customer.", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Financial Statement Analysis", "back": "• Vertical analysis\n• A technique for analyzing the relationships among the items on an income statement, balance sheet, or statement of cash flows during a specific accounting period by expressing components as percentage\n• Horizontal analysis\n• A technique for analyzing the percentage change in individual line items on a financial statement from one accounting period to the next\n• Ratio analysis", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Financial Statement Fraud", "back": "Financial statement schemes are one of a large category of frauds that comprise the Occupational Fraud and Abuse Classification System, most commonly referred to as the Fraud Tree. Occupational fraud and abuse is defined as “the use of one’s occupation for personal enrichment through the deliberate misuse or misapplication of the employing organization’s resources or assets.” Simply stated, occupational frauds are those in which an employee,", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Financial statement fraud", "back": "deliberate misrepresentation of the financial condition of an enterprise accomplished through the intentional misstatement or omission of amounts or disclosures in the financial statements to deceive financial statement users. Note that financial statement fraud, much like all types of fraud, is an intentional act. As", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Financial statement fraud is usually a", "back": "to an end rather than an end in itself. When people manipulate financial records, they might be stalling, so they can quietly “fix” business problems that prevent their company from achieving its expected earnings or complying with loan covenants. It might also be done to obtain or renew financing that would not be granted,", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Example Of Multiple Fraud Schemes", "back": "In February of 2008, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) filed financial fraud charges against Bally Total Fitness Holding Corporation (Bally), a nationwide commercial operator of fitness centers, alleging that Bally violated the antifraud, reporting, books and records, and internal control provisions of the federal securities laws (United States Securities and Exchange Commission v. Bally Total Fitness Holding Corporation).", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Example Of Fictitious Revenues", "back": "In one case, a foreign subsidiary of a U.S. company recorded several large fictitious sales to a series of companies. It invoiced the sales but did not collect any of the accounts receivable, which became severely past due. The manager of the foreign subsidiary arranged for false confirmations of the accounts receivable for audit purposes and even hired actors to pretend to be the customers during a visit from U.S. management. Background checks on the customers would have revealed", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Deceptive Sales And Customers", "back": "In what has become India’s largest corporate scandal, Satyam Computer Services Limited (Satyam) founder and chairman, B. Ramalinga Raju, suddenly quit in January 2009, confessing that he had falsified company accounts for years. In his four-and-a-half-page resignation letter, Raju revealed he had overstated the company’s reported cash balance by Satyam (renamed Mahindra Satyam in 2009), a foreign private issuer, is a large information", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: inventory costing method used. This", "back": "that inventory must be initially valued at its acquisition cost, except when the cost is determined to be higher than the net realizable value, in which case the difference should be recognized as a loss in earnings in the period it occurs. If the utility of the goods is no longer as great as their cost, the difference should be recognized as", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fictitious Accounts Receivable", "back": "Fictitious accounts receivable go hand in hand with fictitious sales, as discussed in the previous section. They are common among companies with financial problems, as well as with managers who receive a commission based on sales. The typical entry under fictitious accounts receivable is to debit (increase) accounts receivable and credit (increase) sales. Of course, these schemes are more common around the end of the accounting period, since", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Failure To Account For Uncollectible Accounts", "back": "In general, accounts receivable should be reported at net realizable value—that is, the amount of the receivable less the amount expected not to be collected. As such, companies are generally required to write off uncollectible receivables as bad debt expense. Managers can overstate their company’s accounts receivable balance by failing to record bad debt expense. Bad debt expense is recorded to account for any uncollectible accounts", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Booking Fictitious Assets", "back": "One of the easiest methods of asset misrepresentation is the recording of fictitious assets. This false creation of assets affects account totals on a company’s balance sheet. The corresponding account commonly used is the owners’ equity account. Because company assets are often physically found in many different locations, this fraud can sometimes be easily overlooked. One of the most common fictitious asset schemes is to simply create", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Misrepresenting The Value Of Fixed Assets", "back": "Fixed assets should be recorded at historical cost. Although assets might appreciate in value, this increase in value should generally not be recognized on company financial statements unless recognizing a gain upon sale in a separate balance sheet account. Many financial statement frauds involve the reporting of fixed assets at higher market values rather than the lower historical (acquisition) costs, or at even higher inflated values", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Capitalizing Non-Asset Costs", "back": "Interest and finance charges incurred in the purchase are excluded from the recorded cost of a purchased asset. For example, when a company finances a capital equipment purchase, monthly payments include both principal liability reduction and interest payments. On initial purchase, only the original cost of the asset should be capitalized. The subsequent interest payments should be charged to interest expense and not to the asset. Without a reason for", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements": [{"front": "Types of Fraudulent Disbursement Schemes", "back": "• Register disbursement schemes\n• Electronic payment schemes\n• Billing schemes\n• Payroll schemes\n• Expense reimbursement schemes", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Register Disbursement Schemes", "back": "• False refunds\n• Fictitious refund scheme 1. An employee processes a transaction as if a customer were returning merchandise, even though there is no actual return. 2. The employee takes cash from the register in the \n• False voids\n• Typically, when an employee sets about processing a fictitious void, the employee withholds the customer’s receipt at the time of the sale.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Register Disbursement Scheme Red Flags", "back": "• There is inappropriate separation of duties for employees.\n• Cashiers have access to refund and void controls.\n• Cashiers are authorized to void their own transactions.\n• Register refunds are not carefully reviewed.\n• Multiple cashiers operate from a single cash drawer without separate access codes.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Electronic Payment Tampering", "back": "• Dishonest employees access their employer’s electronic payment system to fraudulently initiate or divert electronic payments to themselves or their accomplices.\n• Some of these fraudsters abuse their legitimate access while others gain access through social engineering, password theft, or by exploiting weaknesses in their employer’s internal control or electron", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Electronic Payment Tampering", "back": "• Internal controls\n• The most important practice for preventing and detecting electronic payment fraud is separation of duties. 1. For example, in the case of online bill payments, such as those made through a bank’s webs\n• Bank security services\n• Automated clearing house (ACH) blocks allow account holders to notify their banks that ACH debits should not be allowed on specific accounts.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "back": "• Invoicing via shell companies\n• Forming a shell company 1. Shell companies are business entities that typically have no physical presence (other than a mailing address) or employees and generate little, if any, independent economic \n• Invoicing via nonaccomplice vendors\n• Pay and return schemes 1. An employee intentionally mishandles payments that are owed to legitimate vendors. 2. The employee then requests the vendor to return the payment and intercepts the funds. 3.\n• Personal purchases with company funds", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Billing Schemes", "back": "• Detection methods include analytical review, data analytics, statistical sampling, vendor or outsider complaints, site visits, and audit programs.\n• Prevention methods include employee education and training, appropriate compensation, proper documentation, proper approvals, separation of duties, hotlines, and competitive bidding.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Payroll Fraud Schemes", "back": "• Ghost employees\n• The term ghost employee refers to someone on the payroll who does not work for the victim company.\n• Scheme requirements", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Payroll Fraud Schemes", "back": "• Detection methods include independent payroll distribution, analysis of payee address or accounts, duplicate identification numbers, overtime authorization, commissions, and analysis of deductions fro\n• Other methods for detecting ghost employees include:\n• Comparing employee names, addresses, government identification numbers, and bank account numbers to determine if there are any unexpected duplicates\n• Prevention methods include separation of duties (payroll preparation, payroll disbursement, payroll distribution, payroll bank reconciliations, and HR department functions) and periodic review and ana", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Expense Reimbursement Schemes", "back": "• Mischaracterized expense reimbursements\n• Employees request reimbursement for a personal expense by claiming that the expense is business related.\n• Overstated expense reimbursements\n• Some employees overstate the cost of actual business expenses.\n• Fictitious expense reimbursements", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Expense Reimbursement Schemes", "back": "• Review and analyze expense accounts.\n• Two methods: historical comparisons or comparisons with budgeted amounts\n• Require detailed expense reports and conduct a close review of them.\n• Expense reports should contain the following information: 1. Receipts or other support documentation 2. Explanation of the expense, including specific business purpose", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "back": "In fraudulent disbursement schemes, an employee makes a distribution of company funds for a dishonest purpose. Some examples of fraudulent disbursements include submitting false invoices for payment, altering time cards, and making personal purchases with company funds. Outwardly, the fraudulent disbursements do not appear any different from valid disbursements of cash. In many cases, the fraudster tricks the victim company into remitting payment. For", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: is not required. Where this", "back": "case, employees simply process numerous refunds that are small enough that they do not have to be reviewed. Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Employees With Access To Company Checks", "back": "One cannot forge a company check unless one first possesses a company check. Most forgery schemes are committed by accounts payable clerks, office managers, bookkeepers, or other employees whose duties typically include the preparation of company checks. These are people who have access to the company checkbook on a regular basis and are therefore in the best position to steal blank checks. Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Employees Lacking Access To Company Checks", "back": "If perpetrators do not have access to the company checkbook through their work duties, they will have to find other means of misappropriating a check. The method by which a person steals a check depends largely on how the checkbook is handled within a particular company. In some circumstances, the checkbook is poorly guarded and left in unattended areas where anyone can get to it. In other companies, the check stock might be kept in a restricted area,", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "To The Perpetrator", "back": "Once a blank check has been obtained, the perpetrator must decide to whom it should be made payable. In most instances, forged checks are made payable to the perpetrator so that they can be easily converted. Canceled checks that are payable to an employee should be closely scrutinized for the possibility of fraud. If the perpetrator owns their own business or has established a shell company, they will", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "To An Accomplice", "back": "If a fraudster is working with an accomplice, the fraudster can make the forged check payable to that person. The accomplice then cashes the check and splits the money with the employee-fraudster. Because the check is payable to the accomplice in their true identity, it is easily converted. An additional benefit to using an accomplice is that a canceled check payable to a third-party accomplice is not as likely to raise suspicion as a canceled check to an", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "To Vendors", "back": "Not all fraudsters forge company checks to obtain cash. Some employees use forged maker schemes to purchase goods or services for their own benefit. These fraudulent checks are made payable to third-party vendors who are uninvolved in the fraud. For instance, an employee might forge a company check to buy a home computer. The computer vendor is not involved in the fraud at all. Furthermore, if the victim organization regularly does", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Forging The Signature", "back": "After the employee has obtained and prepared a blank check, they must forge an authorized signature to convert the check. The most obvious method, and the one that comes to mind when one thinks of the word forgery, is to simply sign the name of an authorized maker.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Free-Hand Forgery", "back": "The difficulty a fraudster encounters when physically signing the authorized maker’s name is in creating a reasonable approximation of the true signature. If the forgery appears authentic, the perpetrator will probably have no problem cashing the check. In truth, the forged signature might not have to be particularly accurate. Many fraudsters cash forged checks at liquor stores, grocery stores, or other institutions that are known to be less than diligent in", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Photocopied Forgeries", "back": "To guarantee an accurate forgery, some employees make photocopies of legitimate signatures. The signature of an authorized signer is copied from some document (such as a business letter) onto a transparency, and then the transparency is laid over a blank check so that the signature copies onto the maker line of the check. The result is a check with a perfect signature of an authorized maker.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Automatic Check-Signing Mechanisms", "back": "Companies that issue a large number of checks sometimes use automatic check-signing mechanisms in lieu of signing each check by hand. Automated signatures are produced with manual instruments, such as signature stamps, or they are printed by computer. Obviously, a fraudster who gains access to an automatic check-signing mechanism will have no trouble forging the signatures of authorized makers. Even the most rudimentary control procedures", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Converting The Check", "back": "To convert the forged check, the perpetrator must endorse it. The endorsement is typically made in the name of the payee on the check. Since identification is typically required when one seeks to convert a check, the perpetrator usually needs fake identification if they forge checks to real or fictitious third persons. As discussed earlier, checks payable to “cash” require the endorsement of the person converting them. Without a fake ID, the perpetrator", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Employees Involved In Delivery Of Checks", "back": "Obviously, the employees in the best position to intercept signed checks are those whose duties include the handling and delivery of signed checks. The most obvious example is a mailroom employee who opens outgoing mail containing signed checks and steals the checks. Other personnel who have access to outgoing checks might include accounts payable employees, payroll clerks, and administrative assistants.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Poor Control Of Signed Checks", "back": "Unfortunately, employees are often able to intercept signed checks because of poor internal controls. For instance, many employees simply find signed checks left unattended in the work areas of the individuals who signed them or the people charged with their delivery. In these cases, it is easy for the perpetrator to steal the check. Another common breakdown occurs when the person who prepares a check is also involved in the delivery of that check once it", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Theft Of Returned Checks", "back": "Checks that have been mailed and are later returned to the victim for some reason, such as an incorrect address, are often targeted for theft by fraudsters. Employees with access to incoming mail are able to intercept these returned checks and convert them by forging the A manager took and converted approximately $130,000 worth of checks that were returned due to noncurrent addresses (also stealing outgoing checks, cashing them, and then declaring", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Re-Routing The Delivery Of Checks", "back": "Employees might also misappropriate signed checks by altering the addresses to which those checks are mailed. These perpetrators usually replace the payee’s legitimate address with an address where the employee can retrieve the check, such as the employee’s home or a post office box the employee controls. In other instances, the perpetrator might purposely misaddress a check so that it will be returned as undeliverable. The employee steals the check", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Converting The Stolen Check", "back": "Once a check has been intercepted, the perpetrator can cash it by forging the payee’s signature, hence the term forged endorsement scheme. Depending on where they try to cash the check, the perpetrator might or might not need fake identification at this stage. If a perpetrator is required to produce identification to cash their stolen check, and if they do not have a fake ID in the payee’s name, they might use a dual endorsement to cash or deposit the", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The second type of intercepted check scheme", "back": "altered payee scheme. This is a form of check tampering in which an employee intercepts a company check intended for a third party and alters the payee designation so that the employee or an accomplice can convert the check. (See the “Altered Payee Schemes” flowchart that follows.) The employee inserts their own", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Altering Checks Prepared By Others: Inserting A New Payee", "back": "The method used to alter the payee designation on a check depends largely on how that check is prepared and intercepted. (Incidentally, the amount of the check might also be altered at the same time and by the same method as the payee designation.) Checks prepared by others can be intercepted by any of the methods discussed in the forged endorsements section. When the perpetrator intercepts a check that has been prepared by someone else,", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Altering Checks Prepared By Others: Tacking On", "back": "The other method that can be used by perpetrators to alter checks prepared by others is tacking on additional letters or words to the end of the real payee designation. For instance, checks payable to “ABC” company might be altered to read “A.B. Collins.” The employee then cashes the checks in the name of A.B. Collins. In these cases, the simple inclusion of a filler line after the payee designation would prevent the loss.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Altering Checks Prepared By The Fraudster: Erasable Ink", "back": "When the perpetrator prepares the check that is to be altered, the schemes tend to be a bit more sophisticated. The reason for this is obvious: If the perpetrator is able to prepare the check themselves, the perpetrator can prepare it with the thought of how the payee designation will be changed. One of the most common ways to prepare a check for alteration is to write or type the payee’s name (and possibly the amount) in erasable ink. After an", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Altering Checks Prepared By The Fraudster: Blank Checks", "back": "The most egregious example of poor controls in the handling of signed checks is one in which the perpetrator prepares a check, leaves the payee designation blank, and submits it to an Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements authorized maker who signs the check and returns it to the employee. Obviously, this makes it quite easy for the perpetrator to designate themselves or an accomplice as the payee.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Converting Altered Checks", "back": "As with all other types of fraudulent checks, conversion is accomplished by endorsing the checks in the payee’s name. Conversion of fraudulent checks has already been discussed in previous sections and will not be re-examined here. The final check tampering scheme, the authorized maker scheme, might be the most difficult to defend against. An authorized maker scheme occurs when an employee with signature", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Overriding Controls Through Intimidation", "back": "When a person is authorized to sign company checks, preparing the checks is easy. The employee simply writes and signs the documents the same way they would with any legitimate check. In most situations, check signers are owners, officers, or otherwise high-ranking employees and thus have or can obtain access to all the blank checks they need. Even if company policy prohibits check signers from handling blank checks, the perpetrator can", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Poor Controls", "back": "Although overriding controls is the most obvious way to execute an authorized maker scheme, it is not the most common. Far more of these schemes occur because no one is paying attention to the accounts and few controls are present to prevent fraud. Some employees who write checks to themselves or to purchase items for themselves simply code the checks to expense accounts that they know are not likely to be reviewed.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Concealment of the fraud", "back": "not only hiding the criminal’s identity, but also hiding the fact that a fraud has even occurred. The most successful frauds are those in which the victim organization is unaware that it is being robbed. Obviously, once a business learns that it is being victimized, it will take steps to find the source and put a stop to the scheme.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Fraudster Reconciling The Bank Statement", "back": "A large percentage of those who perpetrate check tampering frauds are involved in reconciling the company’s bank statement. The bank statement that a company receives Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements normally includes the canceled checks that have been cashed in the preceding period. A person who reconciles the accounts is therefore in a position to hide the existence of any fraudulent checks they have written to themselves. They can remove the fraudulent checks,", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: perpetrator", "back": "one who reconciles the account, it is unlikely that anyone will even notice that the check is missing. The problem with simply omitting the fraudulent check from the disbursements journal is that the bank balance will not reconcile to the book balance. For instance, if the perpetrator", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Re-Alteration Of Checks", "back": "In altered payee schemes, remember that it is common for the perpetrator to take a check intended for a legitimate recipient and then alter the check so that the perpetrator becomes the designated payee. But a canceled check payable to an employee will obviously raise suspicions of fraud. Therefore, some employees re-alter their fraudulent checks when the bank statement arrives. It has already been discussed how employees can alter checks by", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Miscoding Fraudulent Checks", "back": "Rather than omit a fraudulent check from the disbursements journal or list it as void, perpetrators might write a check payable to themselves but list a different person as the payee on the books. Usually, the fake payee is a regular vendor⎯a person or business that receives numerous checks from the victim company. Employees tend to pick known vendors for these schemes because one extra disbursement to a regular payee is less likely to be noticed", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Re-Issuing Intercepted Checks", "back": "In intercepted check schemes, the fraudster faces detection not only through their employer’s normal control procedures but also by the intended recipients of the stolen checks. When the real payees do not receive their checks, they are likely to complain. These complaints, in turn, could trigger a fraud investigation. One way for a fraudster to avoid this problem is to issue new checks to the intended payees.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Payment Fraud": [{"front": "Check Fraud Rings", "back": "• Check fraud rings thrive because the items needed to commit check fraud are easily obtainable and the cost is minimal.\n• Often, the only necessary equipment for a check fraud ring is a scanner, printer, and personal computer.\n• The chances of being arrested and prosecuted for check fraud are low, and the penalties are relatively mild in most jurisdictions.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Payment Card Fraud", "back": "• The misuse of credit or debit card information to make purchases without the cardholder’s authorization\n• Schemes are successful because it is unlikely that the fraudster will be caught and prosecution is not ensured.\n• Types of payment card fraud schemes\n• Unauthorized use of a lost or stolen payment card 1. Fraudulent activity normally occurs within hours of the loss or theft of a card, before most victims have called to report the loss.\n• This scheme often works in conjunction with a corrupt and collusive merchant or a merchant’s employee. 2. Other counterfeit cards are wholly manufactured using highspeed printers and are used in assoc", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prepaid Card Fraud", "back": "• Involves prepaid gift and debit cards, which are commonly used by those who do not have a bank account or who prefer relatively anonymous payment methods\n• Prepaid cards are attractive to fraudsters because they can be purchased at countless retailers and are difficult to track after they have been purchased and activated.\n• Among the schemes that prepaid cards are used to facilitate are payment (i.e., credit or debit) card theft schemes.\n• Thieves use stolen payment cards to purchase prepaid debit or gift cards, thus quickly converting the illicit payment card funds into a legitimate cash equivalent.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Smart Cards", "back": "• Plastic, credit-card-sized cards that are embedded with a microchip\n• These cards can identify the user through encrypted information on the chip and must be inserted into a card reader connected to the credit provider’s network.\n• Unlike regular magnetic stripe payment cards, smart cards cannot be easily replicated or counterfeited; thus, they are generally more secure.\n• Smart cards include a wide variety of hardware and software features capable of detecting and reacting to tampering attempts and countering possible attacks.\n• If someone tries to tamper with a chip on a smart card, the card detects the intrusion and shuts itself down, rendering the card useless.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Electronic Bill Payment and Person-to-Person Payments", "back": "• Automatic payments can be set up via a bank or credit card website to pay bills.\n• Individuals can pay each other for goods or services through the person-toperson (P2P) system.\n• An electronic funds transfer (EFT) is any transfer of funds, other than one originated by a check or similar paper instrument, that is initiated through an electronic terminal, telephonic instrument, \n• Examples of EFT fraud include: 1. A biller might send a bill for services not rendered or for goods never sent. 2. A person who has obtained information about another person’s bank account might instr", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Electronic Funds Transfer Fraud", "back": "• Specific safeguards that banks can perform to reduce the risk that they or their customers become victimized by unauthorized EFTs include:\n• Send a welcome letter to the address on the application with the bank’s return address so that the letter is returned if the applicant does not live there.\n• Always mail PINs separately from other information, such as usernames, with which they are associated.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Account Takeover Fraud", "back": "• Occurs when a fraudster surreptitiously takes control of a payment account (e.g., credit cards, banking, brokerage, or online retail accounts)\n• To take over an account, thieves obtain email addresses or other login information and use various means to obtain passwords, such as phishing emails or password-cracking botnet attacks.\n• Because consumers often use the same username and password for multiple accounts, hackers commonly write code that can run credentials obtained from a data breach at one company to see if they are val\n• Once the thief overtakes an account, communication methods and contact information are altered to keep the account holder unaware of the fraudulent activity, leaving the thief free to place orders usi", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Mobile Payments", "back": "• Typically made through contactless technology, such as digital wallets or applications—also known as in-app payments.\n• Common mobile payment applications include Apple Pay, Google Pay, Zelle, PayPal, Cash App, and Venmo.\n• Most mobile payments require users to authenticate themselves.\n• The technology in many mobile devices allows for biometric authentication, such as a partial fingerprint or three-dimensional facial scan, which is difficult for fraudsters to bypass.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Payment Fraud", "back": "An influx of new payment technologies balanced against the need to retain traditional methods has resulted in a period of great change in the payment industry. Countless payment methods, ranging from cash to cryptocurrency, allow items and services to be bought online or in-person. As such, a burgeoning variety of fraudulent schemes aimed at exploiting this transitional era have appeared in recent years. Fraud examiners must ensure that their", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: financial institution’s ability to detect it. Check kiting", "back": "practice of recording the deposit of an interbank transfer before recording the disbursement, thus briefly double counting the amount of cash. In a kiting scheme, multiple bank accounts are opened, and money is “deposited” from account to account; however, the money does not exist.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The cashier or teller", "back": "frontline defense in preventing check fraud. It is important that these individuals receive the training necessary to identify fraudulent checks. They should: • Be aware of magnetic routing numbers. • Use extra care in examining a check drawn from a nonlocal bank and require", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: more difficult. One of the features", "back": "use of a pattern of colors that is difficult to separate even with special cameras, filters, and film. Another technique is scrambled indicia printing, which is a seemingly random pattern of tiny colored dots printed on the paper. Using a colored filter to view the check makes a word or pattern develop.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Check Washing Precautions", "back": "As mentioned previously, check washing involves the use of acid-based chemicals to erase the name of the payee, the amount payable, or both. Individuals with business accounts are at a much greater risk when it comes to check washing. If the business does not have strict controls in place to protect its checks, it is likely that if any money is stolen from its accounts, the bank will not return the money. Therefore, business checks should be locked securely", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Forensic Document Examination", "back": "Through handwriting, an individual can be positively identified, as is the case with DNA or fingerprinting. When investigating check fraud, a forensic document examiner focuses on the signature and the handwriting itself.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Signature", "back": "When investigating a forged signature, a fraud examiner should compare the suspicious signature to a sample of the actual one, noting any discrepancies between the two. While one’s signature might change over time, it would be close to impossible for a forger to duplicate a signature with 100% accuracy; minute identifying characteristics mark people’s writing and are not reproducible.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Handwriting", "back": "Similar to fingerprints, handwriting is unique to an individual. Consequently, if the narrative portion of the check is handwritten, it offers a document examiner a greater opportunity to", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Electrostatic Detection Apparatus", "back": "An electrostatic detection apparatus allows fraud examiners to detect indented writing from the top page of a pad of paper up to five pages below the original. This tool uses photocopier toner to develop the areas of indentation after a document has been covered with an electrically charged plastic film. In the best of cases, when the document is processed with the electrostatic device and the toner image is developed, the writing impressions are clearly", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Payment card fraud", "back": "misuse of credit or debit card information to make purchases without the cardholder’s authorization. Payment card fraud is successful because it is unlikely that the fraudster will be caught and prosecution is not ensured. Retailers have identified payment card thieves and contacted law enforcement, but they often receive little or no response", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: upon receipt of payment. This", "back": "deducting the payment amount from the balance of the card account before the check or other payment instrument clears the bank. Experienced fraud rings can easily exploit such a vulnerability. Using a forged or counterfeit check, an advance or overpayment is made on a stolen credit", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The internet", "back": "primary venue for trafficking stolen payment card information. Thieves find payment cards or lists of cardholders and their corresponding account numbers, and then make them available to a larger group, which uses the information to obtain goods and services in the authorized cardholder’s name. Payment card and personal information is", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: reproduction process. However, the hologram", "back": "most difficult aspect of a payment card to accurately reproduce. True holograms use a lenticular refraction process; counterfeits", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The essential part of any detection program", "back": "education of the tellers and merchants who are responsible for handling the transactions. It is widely suspected that the majority of store clerks and cashiers do not check payment card signatures or request identification from a customer who presents a card as payment.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Review statements via electronic", "back": "rather than waiting for paper statements. If possible, cancel paper statements altogether. Destroy expired cards. Never reveal a card number to someone who has offered you a prize via a phone call.", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Cyberfraud": [{"front": "Recognizing Computer Intrusion", "back": "• It is important for fraud examiners and other computer system users to recognize common signs that intruders have accessed or affected a computer system or network, such as:\n• Unusual inbound or outbound network traffic 1. Abnormal traffic, which includes emails and data transmitted to or from the internet, can be an indication that an attacker has gained access to an organ\n• Geographical irregularities related to network access and traffic\n• Contacts receiving strange messages from email accounts\n• Redirected web searches", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Conditions Conducive to Insider Cyberfraud", "back": "• Access privileges are beyond those required to perform assigned job functions.\n• Exception reports are not reviewed and resolved.\n• Access logs are not reviewed.\n• Production programs are run at unusual hours.\n• Lack of separation of duties exists in the data center.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods Used to Gain Unauthorized Access to a Computer System", "back": "• Social engineering\n• A method for gaining unauthorized access to a computer system in which the attacker deceives victims into disclosing personal information, such as their password, or convinces them to commit acts that\n• Business email compromise (BEC)\n• Scheme in which fraudsters target employees who can make large payments or who have access to sensitive proprietary information\n• Pharming 1. A type of attack in which users are fooled into entering sensitive data (such as a password or credit card number) into a malicious website that imitates a legitimate website 2. Different ", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Common Carriers of Malware", "back": "• Unknown or unchecked application software\n• Infected websites\n• Banner ads\n• Software or media that employees bring to work\n• Files downloaded from the internet", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Malware", "back": "• Worms\n• Computer programs that replicate themselves and penetrate operating systems to spread malicious code to other computers\n• Trojan horse\n• A program or command procedure that appears useful but contains hidden code that causes damage\n• Spyware", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Information Security Goals", "back": "• All branches of an information system, including the e-commerce branch, should strive to achieve the following information security goals for users and asset holders:\n• Confidentiality of data 1. The information involved in an information system transaction must only be accessible to authorized parties.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Technical Security and Controls", "back": "• Technical security involves the use of safeguards incorporated into computer hardware or systems, operations or applications software, communications hardware and software, and related devices.\n• Technical controls protect systems against threats like unauthorized use, disclosure, modification, destruction, or denial of service.\n• Common types include: 1. Logical access controls\n• Process by which users are identified and granted certain privileges to information, systems, or resources 2. Network security\n• Firewalls", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Administrative Security and Controls", "back": "• Administrative security consists of management constraints, operational procedures, accountability procedures, and supplemental administrative controls established to provide an acceptable level of pr\n• Administrative controls ensure safeguards against system and network infiltration on an organizational level.\n• Common types include: 1. Security policies and awareness training 2. Separation of duties\n• Achieved by diffusing the tasks and associated privileges for a specific security process among multiple individuals to ensure that no person acting alone can compromise security controls 3. Data clas\n• Describe the actions an organization will take when a data breach occurs.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Parasitic Viruses", "back": "Parasitic viruses (sometimes called binary file infectors) attach themselves to program files (i.e., executables). When a user launches a program that has a parasitic virus, the virus is also launched. The parasitic virus is given the same rights as the program to which the virus is attached because the operating system considers it to be part of the program. These rights allow the virus to replicate, install itself into memory, or release its payload.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Multi-Partite Viruses", "back": "Multi-partite viruses use a combination of methods to infect files; if they cannot infect a system using one method, they try another.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Directory Viruses", "back": "An operating system finds files by looking up the path (composed of the disk drive and directory) in which each file is stored, and directory viruses corrupt a directory entry so that it points to itself instead of the file it is replacing. That is, these viruses change the paths that indicate the location of a file. If a user executes a program (file with the extension .exe or .com) that has been infected by a directory virus, the user unwittingly runs the virus program", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Stealth Viruses", "back": "Stealth viruses use multiple techniques to conceal themselves from users and virus scanners. They constantly change their patterns to blend into the system. Stealth viruses also encrypt their virus code to evade anti-viral software, and they remove their code from any infected files before a requesting program accesses the file.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Resident Viruses", "back": "A virus can be either a resident virus or a direct action (nonresident) virus. A resident virus installs itself in the infected computer’s memory. Upon execution, this type of virus searches for other files or programs to infect.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Direct-Action (Nonresident) Viruses", "back": "In contrast to resident viruses, direct-action viruses load themselves onto the target system’s memory, infect other files, and then unload themselves.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Network Viruses", "back": "Network viruses use network protocol, commands, messaging programs, and data links to spread. These viruses are generally developed to attack the file servers.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "File Infectors", "back": "File infectors are viruses that attach themselves to programs or executable files (files with an .exe or .com extension). When an infected file or program is run, whether directly or indirectly, the virus is activated, producing the damaging effects it is programmed to execute.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "File Allocation Table Viruses", "back": "These viruses attack the file allocation table (FAT), a type of file system used to organize data and locate files. A FAT virus can be especially dangerous because it prevents access to certain parts of the disk where important files might be stored. These viruses can cause damages resulting in information losses from individual files or entire directories.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Companion Viruses", "back": "Companion viruses can be considered file-infector viruses. They are known as companion viruses because once they get into the system, they accompany other files that already exist on the infected system; that is, once these viruses attach themselves to a legitimate program, they create a program with a different filename extension; when the system’s user tries to execute the legitimate program, they execute the companion virus instead.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Polymorphic Viruses", "back": "A polymorphic virus is a virus that mutates itself and changes its structure to avoid detection. Some polymorphic viruses use different encryption schemes and require different decryption routines. Thus, the same virus might look completely different on different systems or even within different files. Other polymorphic viruses vary instruction sequences and use false commands to thwart antivirus software.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Macro Viruses", "back": "Macro viruses exploit macros in application programs. A macro is a stored series of commands that automate repetitive tasks. For example, a macro can tell Microsoft Word to spell-check a document automatically every 15 minutes. Many common applications (e.g., word processing, spreadsheet, and slide presentation applications) use macros. Considered a subclass of a virus, a computer worm is a malicious self-replicating computer", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Prevention", "back": "best approach to combating malware. Although prevention efforts can reduce the number of successful attacks, absolute protection is generally impossible to achieve. But even so, the following measures can help avoid infection from a malicious program: • Use anti-malware software to scan all incoming email messages and files.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: emerging security problems concerning email", "back": "huge volume of space required to archive old messages. In some organizations, people are regularly asked to cull through their old email messages and delete those that are no longer needed. Likewise, some organizations will delete any old email messages left on the mail server machines after a certain amount of time", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Electronic commerce, or e-commerce,", "back": "process of two or more parties making business transactions via computer and some type of network (e.g., a direct connection or the internet). This includes business-to-business (B2B) transactions, online retail, and the digitalization of the financial industry.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Authentication", "back": "the validation of a customer’s identity. E-commerce entities must ensure that they can determine with whom they (or their computers) are communicating. Transaction authentication protects two parties that exchange messages from any third party, but it does not protect the two parties from each other. The digital signature is the most", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Non-repudiation", "back": "a method to guarantee that the parties involved in an e-commerce transaction cannot repudiate (deny) participation in that transaction. That is, concerning information security, non-repudiation is a method to guarantee that the sender of a message cannot later deny having sent the message and that the recipient of the message cannot deny", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Cybersecurity", "back": "protection of computer systems and networks against unauthorized use, disclosure, modification, or destruction. Because certain controls inhibit productivity, security typically involves a compromise in which security officers, system users, and system operations and administrative personnel work together to achieve a balance between security", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Although criminal activity", "back": "focus of the material, a complete security system should blend elements of prevention and detection for all potential threats, including physical damage, natural hazards, environmental hazards, and threats to supporting utilities.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Examples Of Physical Controls", "back": "Examples of physical controls include: • Selecting sites that minimize the physical risks to computer-based assets (e.g., sabotage, arson, earthquakes, tornadoes, floods, or hurricanes) • Putting security fences around the perimeter of a computing facility", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Physical Access Controls", "back": "For computer security purposes, physical access controls are a notable type of physical control. Access control is a process by which users are identified and granted certain privileges to information, systems, or resources, and with access control systems, management can control access to information, systems, a physical facility’s areas, or resources. Physical access controls refer to the process by which users are allowed access to physical objects (e.g.,", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Locks And Keys", "back": "Locks and keys are the most common method used to control access to physical objects. Locks and keys are inexpensive and easy to install, and therefore, they are commonly used for controlling access to restricted areas. But because keys are easily lost or duplicated, many organizations use cipher locks (i.e., combination locks containing buttons that open the lock when a particular code is punched in). With cipher locks, care must be taken to", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Electronic Access Cards", "back": "Many organizations use electronic access cards that verify to an electronic card reader that the cardholder has the right to access particular areas. Electronic access cards and card readers offer several advantages. Management of an organization with an electronic access card system can deny access rights without having to change locks or re-code cipher locks and limit access to physical areas to certain times. This type of system can provide audit trails for", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Biometric Systems", "back": "Biometric technology systems control access by measuring some physiological or behavioral characteristics to label and describe individuals. Common physiological characteristics measured include fingerprints, palm prints, and iris patterns. These systems use such physiological properties to verify user access. Behavioral biometrics are related to the behavior of a person, and they include typing rhythm, gait, and voice, among others.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Logical access", "back": "the process by which users are allowed to use computer systems and networks, and logical access control refers to a process by which users are identified and granted certain privileges to information, systems, or resources. These controls are designed to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of informational resources.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: networks, and logical access control", "back": "a process by which users are identified and granted certain privileges to information, systems, or resources. These controls are designed to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of informational resources. In fact, one of the most effective methods for preventing system attacks by hackers,", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Identification", "back": "When users start to interact with an information system, they are required to provide an identifier (e.g., a username, employee number, or account number), and the system must recognize the user who is attempting to access a resource. Each user’s identifier should be unique, unlikely to change, and need not be kept secret. Thus, employees should not have the same type of usernames because it makes it easier for an attacker to spoof or log in using an", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Authentication", "back": "Once users are identified, they must be authenticated. There are three primary considerations associated with user authentication: A user must be prevented from fooling the computer system into thinking they are someone else. (False positive verification must be avoided.)", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Passwords", "back": "Passwords are the most common method to authenticate users for logical access. Password authentication uses a secret string of characters to control access to a particular resource. Passwords should only be known to the user and the access control system. Weak passwords are often exploited to breach system security; therefore, effective password administration is extremely important for maintaining security. Organizations should enforce", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Card-Based Systems", "back": "Again, a unique personal possession such as a coded card can be used to identify individuals accessing a system. There are various types of technology that can be used to verify the identity of persons attempting to gain access to a system, including smart cards. Smart cards—cards embedded with a built-in chip for onboard data storage or computation—are similar to automated teller machine (ATM) cards; like ATM cards, they are susceptible to loss", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Biometric Systems", "back": "To review, biometric systems measure physiological properties to identify and authenticate users. Common physiological characteristics measured include fingerprints, palm prints, and iris patterns, with facial and vocal recognition being used more frequently as well. Behavioral biometrics software authenticates users by monitoring their statistical characteristics, such as typing speed and keystroke touch.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Multifactor Authentication", "back": "Organizations should consider implementing a multifactor authentication security system. Multifactor authentication requires the presentation of two or more authentication factors to verify the legitimacy of a transaction, and it is a preferred method for preventing attackers from cracking passwords. To review, methods of authentication include: • Something the user knows (e.g., a password, personal identification number [PIN],", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Authorization", "back": "Authorization determines the privileges a user has on a system once they have been authenticated; that is, once a user has been verified and authenticated, the system should check each request to determine whether it is legitimate for that user. Some users might be authorized to perform only certain functions and to have access only to certain data. Moreover, each employee should only be allowed access to the information that they need to", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Network security", "back": "protection of the network perimeter, as well as the segmentation of the internal corporate network. Oftentimes, management devotes resources to protecting its network from outsiders but fails to properly segment its internal network based on risks. Much like logical access control, network resources and segments should only be made available to", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Firewalls", "back": "Firewalls are network hardware and software that block unauthorized or unverified access to computer systems and network assets. These tools survey incoming and outgoing transmissions and decide what type of traffic to permit onto an organization’s internal network based on factors such as origination or destination address, content of the message, protocol being used to transmit the message, and other filtering methods.", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Intrusion Detection Systems", "back": "An intrusion detection system (IDS) is a device or software application that monitors an organization’s inbound and outbound network activity and identifies any suspicious patterns of activity that might indicate a network or system attack or security policy violations. An IDS alerts administrators when someone or something is trying to compromise the information system through malicious activities or security policy violations. These systems are designed to", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Corruption": [{"front": "What Is Corruption?", "back": "• The wrongful use of influence to procure a benefit for the actor or another person, contrary to the duty or rights of others", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Forms of Corruption", "back": "• Bribery\n• The offering, giving, receiving, or soliciting of corrupt payments (i.e., items of value paid to procure a benefit contrary to the rights of others) to influence an official act or business decision\n• Kickbacks\n• Improper, undisclosed payments made to obtain favorable treatment\n• Illegal gratuities", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Methods of Making Corrupt Payments", "back": "• Gifts, travel, and entertainment\n• Cash payments\n• Checks and other financial instruments\n• Hidden interests\n• The payer might give a hidden interest in a joint venture or other profit-making enterprise.", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Corruption", "back": "• Three ways\n• Use an inside witness.\n• Suspected on-book schemes are best approached from the point of payment.\n• Off-book schemes are most easily identified at the suspected point of receipt, through the use of an inside witness, or through surveillance.", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Conflict of Interest", "back": "• Occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence their professional role", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Tracing Corrupt Payments", "back": "Other techniques for tracing corrupt payments can be found in the “Tracing Illicit Transactions” chapter in the Investigation section of the Fraud Examiners Manual. A conflict of interest occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence their professional role. These schemes involve self-dealing by an employee or agent", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: in bribery schemes and conflict of interest schemes", "back": "fraudster’s motive. For instance, if an employee approves payment on a fraudulent invoice submitted by a vendor in return for a kickback, they have committed bribery. But if an employee approves payment on invoices submitted by their own company (and if their ownership is undisclosed), they have", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Interest In The Acquisition Of Assets", "back": "Not all purchasing conflicts occur in the traditional vendor-buyer relationship. Sometimes purchasing conflicts involve employees negotiating for the purchase of some unique, typically large asset such as land or a building in which the employee had an undisclosed interest. It is in the process of these negotiations that the fraudster violates their duty of loyalty to their employer. Because they stand to profit from the sale of the asset, the employee does not", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Turnaround Sales", "back": "A purchasing scheme that is sometimes used by fraudsters is called the turnaround sale, or the flip. In this type of scheme, an employee knows their employer is seeking to purchase a certain asset and takes advantage of the situation by purchasing the asset themselves (usually in the name of an accomplice or shell company). The fraudster then turns around and resells the item to their employer at an inflated price.", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Underselling", "back": "The first and most harmful is the underselling of goods or services. Just as a corrupt employee can cause their employer to overpay for goods or services sold by a company in which they have a hidden interest, so, too, can they cause the employer to undersell to a company in which they maintain a hidden interest. Also, many employees who have hidden interests in outside companies sell goods or services", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Writing Off Sales", "back": "The other type of sales scheme involves tampering with the victim company’s books to decrease or write off the amount owed by the company in which the employee has a hidden interest. For instance, after an employee’s company purchases goods or services from the victim organization, credit memos might be issued against the sale, causing it to be written off to contra accounts such as Discounts and Allowances. A large number of reversing entries to", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: A final type of conflict of interest", "back": "appearance of a conflict of interest. The appearance of a conflict is nearly as problematic as the existence of a true conflict. Examples involving the appearance of a conflict of interest include ownership in a blind trust, in which the employee has no authority to make investment decisions, or an external auditor owning a minority", "topic": "Corruption", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Contract and Procurement Fraud": [{"front": "Methods of Procurement", "back": "• Competitive bidding using sealed bids\n• Contracting by negotiation\n• Simplified acquisition procedures", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Phases in the Procurement Process", "back": "• The presolicitation phase\n• Need recognition\n• The solicitation phase\n• Bid solicitation\n• The bid evaluation and award phase", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "back": "• Complementary bidding\n• Competitors submit token bids that are not genuine attempts to win the contract.\n• Bid rotation\n• Two or more contractors conspire to alternate the business among themselves on a rotating basis.\n• Bid suppression", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Red Flags of Schemes Involving Collusion Among Contractors", "back": "• The industry has limited competition.\n• The same contractors bid on each project or product.\n• The winning bid appears too high.\n• All contractors submit consistently high bids.\n• The winning bidder subcontracts work to one or more losing bidders or to nonbidders.", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Schemes Involving Collusion Between Contractors and Employees", "back": "• Need recognition\n• Procurement employees convince their employer that it needs excessive or unnecessary products or services.\n• Bid tailoring\n• An employee with procurement responsibilities, often in collusion with a contractor, drafts bid specifications in a way that gives an unfair advantage to a certain contractor.\n• Bid manipulation", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Performance Schemes", "back": "• Nonconforming goods or services (product substitution)\n• Attempts by contractors to deliver goods or services to the procuring entity that do not conform to the underlying contract specifications\n• Cost mischarging\n• A contractor charges the procuring entity for costs that are not permissible, are not reasonable, or cannot be allocated to the contract directly or indirectly.\n• A contractor knowingly charges unallowable costs to the buyer by concealing or misrepresenting them as allowable costs, or by hiding them in accounts, such as office supplies, that are not usually clo", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention and Detection of Contract and Procurement Fraud", "back": "• Monitoring procurement activities\n• Companies should implement a continuous, self-auditing program to monitor the performance of their procurement activities.\n• Vendor management\n• Management should take steps to prevent and detect criminal conduct by its vendors, such as: 1. Vendor background checks\n• Management must conduct adequate due diligence to identify and select competent and qualified vendors, such as reviewing their business reputation, financial soundness, and experience. 2. Controls for", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Contract And Procurement Fraud", "back": "The procurement system is the collection of processes, procedures, and entities involved in purchasing goods and services by public or private entities. And because the primary objective of an effective procurement policy is to achieve the best value of money, it is important that procurement processes avoid incidences of fraud. This section will address fraud in the procurement process, focusing on the following topics:", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: specifications,", "back": "attempts by contractors to deliver goods or services to the procuring entity that do not conform to the underlying contract specifications. Once contractors deliver goods that do not conform to the contract, they bill and receive payment for conforming goods or services without informing the purchaser of the deficiency.", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Red Flags Of Nonconforming Goods Or Services Schemes", "back": "The following is a list of potential red flags for nonconforming schemes: • High percentage of returns for noncompliance with specifications • Missing, altered, or modified product compliance certificate • Compliance certificates signed by employees with no quality assurance responsibilities • Materials testing done by supplier, using the supplier’s own personnel and facilities • Evidence that test or inspection results were falsified (e.g., documents appear altered or", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Detecting Nonconforming Goods Or Services Schemes", "back": "To detect nonconforming schemes, the fraud examiner should, at a minimum, examine the • Contract or purchase order (PO) specifications • Contractor’s statements, claims, invoices, and supporting documents • Test and inspection results for the relevant period, searching for discrepancies between tests and inspection results and contract specifications", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Red Flags Of Change Order Abuse", "back": "When a change order occurs, fraud examiners should immediately be concerned about whether the change was accidental or planned. The following list of red flags can help make • Poor contractor internal controls over determining the need for change orders (e.g., management officials fail to ensure that all proposed change orders are necessary for work that was not known or contemplated at the time the contract was awarded)", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Detecting Change Order Abuse", "back": "Fraud examiners can detect change order abuse by engaging in the following activities: • Examining contract change orders that add new items Examining contract change orders that increase the scope, quantity, or price of the", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Red Flags Of Cost Mischarging Schemes", "back": "Red flags of cost mischarging schemes include: • Contractor refuses, delays, or is unable to provide complete supporting data. • Contractor’s supporting documents are missing or unavailable for review. • Contractor’s supporting documents are of poor quality.", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Three Main Types Of Cost Mischarging Schemes", "back": "Generally, contractors commit one of three types of mischarges:", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Accounting Mischarges", "back": "Accounting mischarges occur when a contractor knowingly charges unallowable costs to the buyer by concealing or misrepresenting them as allowable costs, or by hiding them in accounts, such as office supplies, that are not usually closely audited. A variation of this type of scheme involves circumventing the limits for certain cost categories by charging those expenses to other cost categories that do not have such limits. For example, a contractor", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Material Mischarges", "back": "Occasionally, material costs are mischarged, both as to their reasonableness and their allocability. Material means physical inventory and component deliverables. It includes raw material and purchased parts, as well as subcontractor and intercompany transfers. In most cases, material cost mischarging is confined to instances involving raw material or interchangeable parts. Mischarges of finished materials are infrequent because the nature of", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets": [{"front": "Misuse of Inventory and Other Assets", "back": "• Two ways a person can misappropriate a company asset\n• The asset can be misused (or “borrowed”) (e.g., company vehicles, supplies, computers).", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Inventory Theft Schemes", "back": "• Larceny schemes\n• Larceny is “the wrongful and fraudulent taking and carrying away by one person of the mere personal goods of another from any place, with a felonious intent to convert them to his (the taker’s) use, a\n• Purchasing and receiving schemes\n• Dishonest employees can also manipulate a company’s purchasing and receiving functions to facilitate the theft of inventory and other assets.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Concealing Inventory Shrinkage", "back": "• When inventory is stolen, the perpetrator’s key concealment issue is shrinkage.\n• Inventory shrinkage is the unaccounted-for reduction in the company’s inventory that results from error or theft.", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "back": "• Altered inventory records\n• Involves changing the perpetual inventory record so that it matches the physical inventory count\n• Fictitious sales and accounts receivable\n• When the perpetrator makes an adjusting entry to the perpetual inventory and cost of sales accounts, there is no sales transaction on the books that corresponds to these entries.\n• Write-off inventory", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Detection of Inventory Schemes", "back": "• Analytical review\n• Example: Sales and cost of goods sold should move together since they are directly related. However, if the cost of goods sold increases by a disproportionate amount in relation to sales and there hav", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Prevention of Inventory Schemes", "back": "• Proper documentation\n• The following items should be prenumbered and controlled: 1. Purchase orders 2. Receiving reports 3. Perpetual records 4. Raw materials requisitions 5. Shipping documents 6. Job cost sheets\n• Separation of duties\n• Different personnel should be responsible for the following duties: 1. Requisition of inventory 2. Receipt of inventory 3. Disbursement of inventory 4. Conversion of inventory to scrap 5. Receipt of p\n• Independent checks", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory And Other Assets", "back": "Employees target inventory, equipment, supplies, and other noncash assets for theft in several ways. These schemes can range from the theft of a box of pens to the theft of millions of dollars’ worth of company equipment. These schemes can even entail an individual stealing and selling sensitive or confidential data, such as customer information. The term inventory and other assets is meant to encompass the misappropriation schemes involving any assets held by a", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The obvious problem with this kind of scheme", "back": "fact that the receiving report does not match the vendor’s invoice, which will likely cause a problem with payment. In the previous example, if the vendor bills for one thousand units but the accounts payable voucher only shows receipt of nine hundred units of merchandise, then someone will have to explain", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: missing assets. This", "back": "concealing the shrinkage that occurs from asset theft. Inventory and other assets are typically tracked through a two-step process. The first step, the perpetual inventory, is an ongoing count that records how much inventory should be available. When new shipments of merchandise are received, for instance, this merchandise is entered", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: inventory purchased", "back": "same and there is no change in the manufacturing process or purchase price. If sales and cost of sales change from $5,650,987 and $2,542,944 to $6,166,085 and $2,981,880, respectively, what are the data telling the fraud examiner? For one thing, sales have increased by 9.12%, whereas cost of sales increased by 17.26%. The profit", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Corruption", "back": "Corruption can be found in any business or organization, and it is one of the three major categories of occupational fraud and abuse (along with asset misappropriation and financial statement fraud). An organization that understands the specific factors involved in corruption schemes can take steps to prevent, detect, and investigate them. Corruption is a term used to describe various types of wrongful acts designed to cause an", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Official bribery", "back": "the corruption of a public official to influence an official act of government. The term official act stems from traditional bribery statutes that only proscribe payments made to influence the decisions of government agents or employees. In contrast, commercial bribery refers to the corruption of a private individual to gain a commercial", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: In contrast, commercial bribery", "back": "the corruption of a private individual to gain a commercial or business advantage. In commercial bribery schemes, something of value is offered to influence a business decision rather than an official act, as is the case in official bribery. Commercial bribery may or may not be a criminal offense. For example, in the United States,", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Employees With Approval Authority", "back": "In most instances, kickback schemes involve overbilling. In these schemes, a vendor submits inflated invoices to the victim organization, and the false invoices either overstate the cost of actual goods and services or reflect fictitious sales. To ensure that the inflated invoices get approved, the corrupt vendor offers kickbacks to an employee of the victim organization who has the authority to approve payment of the fraudulent invoices. By enlisting the help of an", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fraudsters Lacking Approval Authority", "back": "While the majority of kickback schemes involve individuals with authority to approve purchases, this authority is not an absolute necessity. When employees cannot approve fraudulent purchases themselves, they can still orchestrate a kickback scheme if they can circumvent accounts payable controls. In some cases, they can do this by filing a false purchase requisition. If a trusted employee tells their superior that the company needs certain", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Financial Institution Fraud": [{"front": "Types of Embezzlement Schemes", "back": "• False accounting entries\n• Employees debit the general ledger to credit their own accounts or conceal a theft from a customer account (i.e., employees adjust the general ledger to conceal the stolen amount).\n• Unauthorized withdrawals\n• Employees make unauthorized withdrawals from customer accounts.\n• Unauthorized disbursement of funds to outsiders", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Types of Loan Fraud Schemes", "back": "• Double-pledging collateral\n• Borrowers pledge the same collateral (i.e., an item of value used to secure or guarantee a loan) with different lenders before liens are recorded without telling the lenders.\n• Reciprocal loan arrangements\n• Insiders in different banks cause their banks to lend funds or sell loans to other banks with agreements to buy their loans, which is done to conceal loans and sales.\n• Residential loan fraud", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Proof of developer contribution, if applicable", "back": "• High turnover in developer’s personnel\n• Typically, when a developer experiences a high degree of turnover, something is wrong with the internal operation.\n• Change order abuse\n• The key characteristic that fraud examiners should look for in change orders is abnormality. 1. An increase in the number of change orders or amounts on change orders might indicate that construction \n• Missing documentation", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Financial Institution Fraud", "back": "• Air loan\n• Loan for a nonexistent property\n• Fraudulent sale\n• The fraudulent acquisition of a homeowner’s property by filing a fraudulent deed or respective real estate document that makes it appear that the property legally belongs to the criminal; it might occ\n• Fraudulent second lien", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "New Account Fraud", "back": "• Fraud that occurs on an account within the first ninety days that it is open\n• Fraud is much more likely to occur in new accounts than in established accounts.\n• Some common methods of new account fraud include:\n• False identification", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Financial Institution Fraud", "back": "External fraud schemes are those committed by outside entities, typically by individuals or groups of individuals against organizations. Fraud schemes committed by outsiders usually occur within specific industries. Therefore, the following chapters are organized by type of industry, starting with financial institution frauds. Because some schemes are committed by collusion between an organizational insider and an outsider, some frauds can be classified as", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Embezzlement", "back": "wrongful taking or conversion of the property of another by a person to whom it has been lawfully entrusted (or to whom lawful possession was given). Misapplication of bank funds is a type of embezzlement in which bank employees wrongfully take or convert another party’s property, often from customer accounts, for the benefit of the employee or", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: A suspense account", "back": "the section of an organization’s books where unclassified debits and credits are recorded. Placing an entry in a suspense account is designed to be a temporary measure, pending the ultimate disposition of the transaction. Employees often use suspense accounts to perpetrate fraud against their employer at both financial institutions and other", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Estimates Of Costs To Complete", "back": "When borrowers approach a lending institution for construction financing, they typically have a development plan, complete with an engineering report, appraisal, and budget for construction costs. The construction cost budget is, by definition, an estimate. As the project is built out, the budget will be revised to reflect actual expenses. Budgets are delineated by specific line item, such as foundation, exterior glass, grading, landscaping, and tenant", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Developer Overhead", "back": "It is not uncommon in construction financing to have a budget line item for developer overhead (also called general conditions). This creates an opportunity for the developer to use it to their advantage. The purpose of developer overhead is to supply the developer with operating capital while the project is under construction. This overhead allocation should not include a profit percentage, as the developer realizes profit upon completion.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: whose ultimate collateral", "back": "property and not some other short-term collateral. Historically, troubled construction loans or foreclosures due to fraud have been totally disbursed in the developer overhead category.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Draw Requests", "back": "Construction loan advances are generally supported by draw requests. A draw request is the documentation substantiating that a developer has incurred the appropriate construction expenses and is now seeking reimbursement or direct payment. A typical fraud scheme that occurs in a draw request involves requesting advances on the loan for inappropriate costs, such as personal expenses and/or construction costs for an unrelated project. Draw requests", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: contract on file.", "back": "request appropriate for the terms and conditions of the contract? Has the contract/purchaser been approved? Financial Institution Fraud", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Retainage", "back": "The final area of major concern in construction lending is retainage (sometimes called the holdback). Retainage is the amount withheld from each draw request until the construction is complete and the lien period has expired. There are at least two reasons why construction loans contain a retainage provision. The first reason is to keep the contractor’s interest in the project until all the work has been completed and accepted by the owner. The amount of the", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Loan File", "back": "Missing documents in the loan file are another cause for concern. It is important to determine if missing documents have been misplaced or were never received. A waiver of certain documents is one common way for lenders to conceal fraud schemes. The documentation required to obtain loans for real estate and real estate development is fairly standard. The following are some of the more important documents that should be", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Disbursement File", "back": "Copies of all checks issued at closing Lien releases issued at closing (i.e., architect, engineers)", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Letter Form Report", "back": "The letter form report is used when a client is familiar with the area, and, therefore, supporting data are not necessary. The report consists of a brief description of the property, the type of value sought, the purpose served by the appraisal, the date of valuation, the value conclusion, and the signature of the appraiser. Financial institutions do not normally use this", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Short Form Report", "back": "Financial institutions typically use the short form report for residential real estate loans (sometimes referred to as consumer loans). The report varies from one to four pages and consists of check sheets or spaces to be filled in by the appraiser about pertinent property data.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Narrative Report", "back": "The narrative form includes all pertinent information about the area and the subject property, as well as the rationale for the estimated value. It includes maps, photographs, charts, and surveys or plot plans. Financial institutions use narrative reports to support real estate lending and investment decisions on large commercial real estate transactions. Any other type of appraisal report (i.e., letter form or short form) on these complex transactions would likely be", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fair Market Value", "back": "This is the estimated price at which the property would sell if freely offered on the open market with both a willing seller and a willing buyer.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Sales Price", "back": "Sales price is the actual price paid for the property. It might be higher or lower than fair", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Loan Value", "back": "Loan value is the percentage of a property’s value (fair market value or sales price) a lender", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Sales Comparison Approach", "back": "The sales comparison approach is suitable for the appraisal of land, residences, and other types of improvements that exhibit a high degree of similarity, and where a ready market exists. Compared to the other approaches, this method has greater influence on residential portfolio valuations. This method is the least complicated to understand and apply. Subject property is compared with similar property that is either offered for sale or has", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Cost Approach", "back": "The cost approach generally does not exert much influence on the appraiser’s final value estimate. It serves as a benchmark against which the sales comparison and income approaches are measured. The cost approach is more accurate for new properties. It views the value of a parcel as the combination of the land value if vacant and the cost to construct a new building on the given date, less the accrued depreciation the existing building would", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Income Capitalization Approach", "back": "Under this approach, the property value is based on its capacity to continue producing income. This method is particularly effective in the valuation of complex commercial properties. The net income the property produces is an important consideration. Net income is the amount of money over the remaining life of the property and its improvements that a fully informed person, using good management, is warranted in receiving.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Income capitalization", "back": "mathematical process of estimating the present value of income property based on the anticipated annual net income it will produce. Key to the application of this approach is the capitalization rate that is used. There are three types of capitalization rates: interest rate, recapture rate, and overall capitalization rate. Interest rate is the rate of return earned on", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: this approach", "back": "capitalization rate that is used. There are three types of capitalization rates: interest rate, recapture rate, and overall capitalization rate. Interest rate is the rate of return earned on investment capital. Recapture rate is the rate of return originally invested funds provided the owner. Overall capitalization rate is a combination of the interest and recapture rates.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: investment capital. Recapture rate", "back": "rate of return originally invested funds provided the owner. Overall capitalization rate is a combination of the interest and recapture rates. Fraudulent Appraisals Fraudulent appraisals result from any number of situations, some of which are:", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Loan officer", "back": "representative of the mortgage lender that finds and assists borrowers in", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Mortgage Lenders", "back": "Today, the secondary market has overtaken deposit gathering as the source of funding for mortgage lending. Loans are sold in the secondary market at origination, thereby providing the bank with a steady supply of capital needed to make additional loans. Without the need for a lot of capital (deposits on the books), mortgage lenders started to evolve. Consequently, a smaller percentage of bankers are keeping their loans than in the past. Even", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Mortgage Brokers", "back": "Mortgage brokers are intermediaries who find and negotiate mortgage loans on behalf of Historically, mortgage loans were originated by the loan officer at the bank. Mortgage lenders, however, started relying on third-party originators (TPOs) to broker their loan products. Brokers could be paid a commission rather than a salary, an option that worked well for minimally capitalized mortgage lenders. As a result, the industry has seen the evolution of mortgage brokers.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Commission-Driven Business", "back": "Because the incomes of mortgage brokers and other third parties are proportional to the number of mortgages they originate, their goal is to produce and close as many loans as possible. When there are multiple players involved with vested interests to close a loan, the", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Lender Competition", "back": "The mortgage industry is very competitive, forcing some in the industry to cut costs and accept more risk. Consequently, previously unusual approaches to securing borrowers, such as reducing the time from origination to closing and introducing new loan products, have", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Loan Products", "back": "Competition for loans motivates investors, lenders, and brokers to generate more attractive products for a wider spectrum of borrowers to make money and capture market share.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Loan Volume", "back": "During boom periods in the real estate industry, high mortgage loan volumes mean an emphasis on production, often at the expense of quality-control efforts. As a result of the record volume of mortgage transactions in recent years, many lenders have been less than thorough in their pre-funding and quality-control reviews. This lack of controls and due diligence has contributed to increased occurrences of fraud.", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Subprime Lending Market", "back": "While there is no industry-accepted definition of subprime, generally a subprime loan is one offered to people who have credit problems or who have demonstrated excessive use of credit. The loan’s interest rate is higher than the prevailing rate available to those with more", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Technology", "back": "Because most loan applications are received and processed electronically, the faceless nature of these transactions creates an environment susceptible to fraud. • Loan documentation is easy for the fraudster to fabricate using readily obtainable photoediting software. • Prepaid mobile phones and mail drops are used for false verification since it is difficult to trace the owner. To falsify current employment, a fraudster might rent a mailbox to be", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "New Players In The Industry", "back": "Traditionally, finance-related occupations, including accountants, mortgage brokers, and lenders, are the most common suspect occupations associated with reported mortgage fraud. Perpetrators in mortgage industry occupations are familiar with the mortgage loan process and therefore know how to exploit vulnerabilities in the system. However, organized crime is an increasing problem. In an environment where the", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Builder Bailout", "back": "A builder bailout scheme flourishes in a downturned economy. It usually occurs when a builder is left with stagnant inventory. The builder might be suffering from financial difficulties with these lingering homes and might need to sell them quickly to pay off delinquent debts. To dispose of the remaining properties, the builder might undertake a variety of schemes that could include, but are not limited to, the use of hidden seller financing", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Example Of A Builder Bailout Scheme", "back": "A builder bailout scheme might unfold like this: • The builder (or third party) recruits a straw borrower to purchase the property with no down payment and receive cash back at closing. The builder obtains an inflated appraisal that is used as a basis for the loan amount. This", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Characteristics Of A Builder Bailout", "back": "The following characteristics are common in builder bailout schemes: • New construction or renovated condo conversions in an overbuilt market • Slight decrease in sales and volume, followed by a spike in both volume and sales price • Non-local borrowers with no knowledge of the local market are recruited to purchase the", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Air Loans", "back": "Some builders might have debt on vacant land for which they do not have sufficient capital to construct a home. To get out from under the debt, the builder, in collusion with other industry insiders, might undertake an air loan scheme. An air loan is a loan for a nonexistent property—with air symbolizing the loan’s fraudulent absence of collateral. Most or all of the documentation is fabricated, including the borrower, the", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Identity Fraud Schemes", "back": "Identity fraud is defined as the misrepresentation of data underpinning one’s identity (such as using another person’s government identification number). Mortgage fraud is not immune to schemes involving the improper use of identifying data. The individuals in the best position to use a person’s identifying information for purposes of committing mortgage fraud are industry insiders. For example, mortgage brokers with access", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Health Care Fraud": [{"front": "Provider Fraud", "back": "• Practices by health care providers (including practitioners, medical suppliers, and medical institutions) that cause unnecessary costs to health care programs or patients through reimbursement for unn\n• Common types include:\n• Fictitious providers 1. Corrupt providers or other criminals fraudulently obtain and use another provider’s identification information and steal or purchase lists of patients’ identifying information.\n• Falsified prescriptions for DME\n• Intentionally providing excessive DME", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Inflated Billing Schemes", "back": "• Altered claims\n• Altering valid claims can be accomplished using a pen; photocopier; or scanner, computer, and printer. Common alterations include: 1. Amounts 2. Date of service 3. Name of patient\n• Added services\n• Some fraudsters add on services never rendered to dates of actual services.\n• Code manipulation schemes", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "If Correctly Billed", "back": "• Common types of patient fraud perpetrated against government health care programs and private insurers include:\n• Fictitious claims 1. Beneficiaries or insureds might attempt to perpetrate a fraud by submitting fictitious claims for medical services that did not occur or for nonexistent dependents.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud by Insurance Companies", "back": "• The following fraud schemes might occur in countries that offer private insurance:\n• Submission of false documents 1. If the insurance company works in tandem with government health care programs (e.g., by acting as an intermediary for the payer), then the insurance company commits fr\n• Requesting rate increases based on fraudulent data 1. Insurance companies or carriers needing regulatory approval for rate increases might use fraudulent cost data to justify their increases. The act ", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Health Care Fraud", "back": "Health care fraud may be defined as an intentional act to defraud a health care benefit program or to obtain through false representations money or other property owned by a health care benefit program. This type of fraud involves a deception or misrepresentation that an individual or entity makes, knowing that the misrepresentation could result in some unauthorized benefit to the individual, entity, or some other party. The most common fraud", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Another concept", "back": "self-insured plan, in which an employer accepts the financial risk of the health care costs of its employees. The employer administers its own health insurance benefits. Rather than shift the risk to a health insurance entity, the organization assumes the costs of health care for its employees or members and their dependents.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The term durable medical equipment (DME)", "back": "medical equipment that can withstand repeated use, such as wheelchairs and specialized patient beds. Fraud schemes perpetrated by DME suppliers frequently involve: • Falsified prescriptions for DME", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Pharmaceutical fraud", "back": "largest source of provider fraud in the health care industry, and can involve pharmaceutical manufacturers, pharmacies, and providers who prescribe such products. Fraud schemes stemming from pharmacy transactions include: • Merchandising—substituting something of value for a prescription drug", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: verification process", "back": "same as the procedures listed under the alteration process.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "International Classification Of Diseases Codes", "back": "The International Classification of Diseases (ICD) is a diagnostic coding system that is used to classify diseases and related health problems. It is published by the World Health Organization (WHO). More than one hundred countries use ICD codes to report mortality data, and many countries also use ICD codes to allocate resources and determine provider reimbursement. The ICD codes are updated periodically to reflect new diagnoses and other changes in the", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Procedural Codes", "back": "ICD is a diagnostic coding system. Some countries use a procedural coding system for the purpose of reimbursement. The United States, for example, uses a procedural coding system called Current Procedural Terminology (CPT), which is maintained by the American Medical Association (AMA). Each five-digit CPT code corresponds to a specific medical service. For example, the codes “90658” and “99214” refer to “flu vaccine” and “physician", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Unbundling", "back": "Because health care procedures often have special reimbursement rates for a group of procedures typically performed together (e.g., blood test panels by clinical laboratories), some providers attempt to increase profits by billing separately for procedures that are actually part of a single procedure. This process is called unbundling. Simple unbundling occurs when a provider charges a comprehensive code, as well as one or", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Mutually Exclusive Procedures", "back": "A variation of unbundling, this scam involves billing for procedures that are either impossible to perform together or, by accepted standards, should not be performed together.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Global Service Period Violations", "back": "Some dishonest providers will bill for a major procedure—such as a surgery—as well as related procedures when the fee for the major procedure already includes the fee for related procedures during the predefined time period (the global service period). Detecting these abuses can be difficult because the fraud examiner must determine which services are related to the surgery and which are not. This difficulty is compounded by the fact that such services", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: One form of medical fraud", "back": "billing for experimental use of new medical devices that have not yet been approved by the jurisdiction’s health care authority. Some hospitals deliberately mislead third-party payers by getting them to pay for the manufacturer’s research. Many of the doctors involved are alleged to have stock in the manufacturing companies.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Another common scheme", "back": "charging of additional hours of anesthesia. Patients should be billed from when they enter the surgery room to when they leave the surgery room. The revenue firm pads the bill by increasing the time billed to include time spent in a recovery room, or before the patient went into the operating room.", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: these individuals with", "back": "of communication when they believe fraud is occurring. Disadvantaged populations must also be informed about the negative impacts of participating in such schemes, such as health risks and criminal liability. Health care programs must educate from within. Investigation units should be established to", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Insurance Fraud": [{"front": "Agent/Broker Fraud", "back": "• Cash, loan, and dividend payments\n• A company employee requests cash, a loan, or a dividend payment without the knowledge of an insured or contract holder and either deposits the money into their bank account or a fictitious account.\n• Premium theft\n• An agent collects the premium but does not remit the payment to the insurance company. Thus, the insured unknowingly has no coverage available upon a qualifying event.\n• Fictitious death claims", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Vehicle Insurance Schemes", "back": "• Ditching\n• Disposing of a vehicle to collect on an insurance policy or to settle an outstanding loan\n• Sometimes, the scheme involves a homeowner’s insurance claim for property that was supposedly in the vehicle when it was “stolen.”\n• Past posting\n• A person is involved in an automobile accident but does not have insurance. After the accident, the person gets insurance, waits a short time, and then reports the vehicle as having been in an acciden", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Red Flags of Insurance Fraud", "back": "• The claim is made soon after the policy’s inception or after an increase or change in the coverage under which the claim is made.\n• The insured has a history of multiple insurance claims and losses.\n• The insured previously asked an insurance agent hypothetical questions about coverage in the event of a loss similar to the actual claim.\n• In a burglary loss, the claim includes large, bulky property, which is unusual for a burglary.\n• In a theft or fire loss claim, the claim includes a lot of recently purchased, expensive property, but the insured cannot provide receipts, owner’s manuals, or other documentary proof of purchase.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Computer-Generated Detection Tools", "back": "• Fraud examiners can use the following data analysis tools to detect insurance fraud schemes:\n• Address similarity reports 1. These reports electronically compare multiple payments going to the same address and might show a payment defalcation or funds going to another insurance company, broker,", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Insurance Fraud", "back": "The insurance business, by its very nature, is susceptible to fraud. Insurance is a risk distribution system that requires the accumulation of liquid assets in the form of reserve funds, which are in turn available to pay loss claims. Insurance companies generate a large steady flow of cash through insurance premiums. Steady cash flow is an important economic resource that is very attractive and easily diverted. Large accumulations of liquid assets make", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Equity funding", "back": "process of using existing premium/policy values to finance new businesses. As long as the insured is aware of what is being done by the agent and fully understands the long-range method of payment on the new contract, there is no apparent underwriting irregularity.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: though it is not absolute proof that a vehicle exists, it", "back": "basis for the issuance of insurance policies. Collecting on a phantom vehicle has been shown to be easy to do. Note that the term phantom vehicle might also refer to vehicles involved in uninsured motorist claims wherein the vehicle and driver that purportedly caused the damage in question cannot be identified.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Swoop And Squat", "back": "A victim of this scheme is passed by two cars while driving. The car in the lead cuts in front of the second, forcing it to stop abruptly. The victim rear-ends the second car while the other driver speeds away. Victims often accept responsibility for the accident, thinking it was their fault for not paying attention. The rear-ended vehicle usually contains the maximum amount of passengers, all of whom claim injuries.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: A home or car that has been burglarized", "back": "basis for filing a claim for recoveries of monies lost. However, as with items “destroyed” by fire, the items never existed or were", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: carrier for the employer. It", "back": "insurance carrier who pays for the perpetrator’s fraudulent medical bills and unnecessary absences. Nevertheless, the employer is a tertiary victim of these crimes, as the fake claims can result in higher premiums for the company in the future.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Employee Classification", "back": "Workers’ compensation rates vary depending on an employee’s job classification. Employees that have a higher risk for injury on the job will have a higher premium rate. For example, clerical employees have a lower probability for an injury than truck drivers or construction workers, and thus their premiums should be lower. Therefore, to lower their premium rate, an employer might intentionally misclassify employees.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Understatement Of Payroll", "back": "The premium for a specific job classification is based on the total payroll for that classification. The employer might understate the amount of the payroll for higher-risk classifications. Two men pleaded guilty to charges of conspiracy and mail fraud in connection with a fraudulent scheme to reduce workers’ compensation claims for a construction company. The men falsely reported that workers in high-risk trades were engaged in less dangerous", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "History Of Past Losses", "back": "The modification or mod factor is a multiplier that is used to determine premium rates. The multiplier is derived by comparing the employer’s claims history with other employers’ claims histories in the same industry. The higher the claims loss, the higher the mod, and thus the higher the premium. A new business starts with a neutral mod for that type of business. Employers that have a high mod factor might become a “new” business that does not have a", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Corporate Gerrymandering", "back": "The risk pool assigned to an employer accepts any business regardless of its claim experience. However, it does not have to accept any employer that owes premiums. Some employers create a new corporate entity to obtain coverage or avoid higher premiums due to past heavy losses. An insurance company was awarded a $15 million judgment against an entertainment company in a suit involving a workers’ compensation fraud scheme. The entertainment", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Forged Documents", "back": "Some employers forge or alter prior certificates showing coverage to collect payment for work done or as proof of coverage to authorities.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Premium Theft", "back": "Agents issue certificates of coverage indicating the customer is insured, but they never forward the premium to the insurance company.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Conspiring To Reduce Premiums", "back": "An agent might alter the application for coverage completed by the employer to be able to offer a lower premium to their client. The agent might also improperly advise the employer as to how to complete the application or advise the employer to transfer a group of employees into a lower risk classification to avoid the experience modifier. Even though the employer might not be aware that the schemes are a violation of law, the", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Injury Fraud", "back": "In this type of fraud, false information about the injured worker is submitted to the workers’ compensation carrier. The report describes the injury and states that the employee is either totally or partially disabled and either unable to work or only able to work part-time. In many of these schemes, the fraud is helped along by a doctor who, for a fee, will provide a false diagnosis and false medical records for phony treatments.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Secondary Employment", "back": "Employees who are collecting workers’ compensation benefits might also secure a job with another employer—either part-time or full-time. The employee might fake their identity or assume someone else’s identity to receive compensation. Organized fraud schemes are composed of the united efforts of a lawyer, a capper, a doctor, and the claimant. This scheme is used not only in workers’ compensation cases but also in", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Lawyer", "back": "Lawyers are usually the organizers of the schemes and the ones who will profit the most. The majority of workers’ compensation cases are accepted on a contingency fee basis. If no settlement is awarded, then the lawyers will not be paid. This is a high-volume business, and the lawyers do not want the cases to be litigated. They are relying on the insurance company’s desire to settle as quickly as possible.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Capper", "back": "Cappers, also known as runners or steerers, are used to recruit patients for the scheme. They might be employed by either the attorney or doctor and are paid—either on a percentage of the total or on a per-person basis—for bringing in patients. Cappers might approach patients at unemployment compensation lines, work sites, scenes of accidents, or at any other type of organized gathering. Patients are brought into the scheme with promises of enrichment.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Doctor", "back": "Doctors might be organizers or players in the scheme, but they must be a part of it for it to work properly. Doctors are used to make the scheme appear authentic, and they are well compensated for their efforts. The doctors bill for services that they might or might not render, as well as for unnecessary services. In addition, if patients have regular health insurance, doctors might double bill for the services. If an injury is the result of an", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Address Similarity Reports", "back": "Address similarity reports electronically compare multiple payments going to the same address. These reports are extremely useful because they might show a payment defalcation or funds going to another insurance company, broker, or fictitious payee.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "File Comparison Tools", "back": "A comparison of issue files to disbursement files can determine if funds are being used to place new policies by using the equity of old policies. For example, computer-assisted audit tools and techniques (CAATTs) are used to download and compare electronic files.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Electronic Confirmations", "back": "Electronic confirmations should be sent to verify that company records agree with policyholder records. These types of confirmations can be sent to policyholders when disbursements have been mailed for premiums that are in force (i.e., active) or lapsed or when there has been a change of address on an account.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Exception Or Manual Override Reports", "back": "Computerized reports that list all exceptions to normal electronic processing can be produced. All human intervention can appear on a periodic management information report and can be test-checked by management. It is imperative that management review all exception reports for possible frauds on an ongoing basis. Many insurers have implemented special investigation units (SIUs) within their organizations", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fraud Risk Assessments", "back": "Insurance companies must be aware of the risks faced both within and outside of their organizations to prevent this type of fraud from occurring. Conducting a fraud risk assessment is one of the most efficient tools that insurance companies can use to assess and respond to fraud. A fraud risk assessment is a process aimed at proactively identifying and addressing an organization’s vulnerabilities to both internal and external fraud. By doing so,", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Underwriting And Claims-Handling Processes", "back": "To prevent fraudulent insurance claims from being paid to claimants, insurance companies need to have efficient underwriting and claims-handling processes in place. Artificial intelligence is increasingly being used by insurance companies in their claims and underwriting processes to save time and identify potentially fraudulent claims as they occur. There is software available that allows insurance companies to identify patterns in customer", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Aggressive Prosecutions", "back": "Often, fraudsters believe the large financial incentive of successfully committing insurance fraud far outweighs the risk of being caught. Offenders should be prosecuted aggressively to combat insurance fraud. Penalties such as jail, probation, or fines imposed in criminal court might prevent some individuals from engaging in this type of fraudulent behavior.", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "source": "manual"}], "Understanding Criminal Behavior": [{"front": "Overview of Behavioral Analysis", "back": "• Behavioral studies, such as those conducted by B. F. Skinner, show that:\n• Punishment is the least effective method of changing behavior.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Reinforcement vs. Punishment of Behaviors", "back": "• Reinforcement and punishment of behavior are distinguished by the way that positive and negative forces are applied.\n• Reinforcement 1. A positive reinforcement presents a positive stimulus in exchange for the desired response. 2. A negative reinforcement withdraws a negative stimulus in exchange for the response.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Conditioning Behaviors", "back": "• Skinner suggests conditioning incompatible behavior that interferes with a person’s undesired acts by encouraging the improper behavior’s opposite (e.g., by rewarding a child for controlling emotional\n• Destructive behaviors should be offset by incompatible productive ones.\n• Since fraud involves dishonesty, secrecy, and antagonistic behaviors, an astute manager finds ways to reward the opposite behaviors—honesty, openness, and cooperation.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Theories of Crime Causation", "back": "• Rational choice theory\n• Asserts that the decision to commit a crime is a rational and careful choice on the perpetrator’s part with the goal of an intended benefit\n• Routine activities theory\n• Asserts that both the motivation to commit crime and the supply of offenders is constant\n• If someone thinks it is likely that they will be caught or there is not a suitable target, then they are less likely to commit a crime.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "back": "Much of our understanding of criminal behavior can be attributed to B. F. Skinner, described by many as one of the greatest social scientists of the 20th century. Skinner promised that he would revolutionize not just psychology, but all of human society with his theories of behaviorism. According to Skinner, human behavior should be approached scientifically. By analyzing people’s actions, the behaviorist hoped to alter or direct behavior for the greater", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: room. Good. Here", "back": "key to the car.” The behavior (cleaning) is reinforced by the awarding of the positive stimulus (the car key). In contrast, a negative reinforcement withdraws a negative stimulus in exchange for the desired response. Continuing the example, the parent might say, “I will stop hassling you if you clean this room.” The negative stimulus (hassling) is", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: game, and it", "back": "game of their lives. Behaviorists agree. Money is a “generalized reinforcer,” directly linked with many positive factors and often taking on a symbolic power of its own, thereby yielding a condition of strength. Skinner says, “We are automatically reinforced, apart from any particular deprivation, when we successfully control the physical world.”2 So, an", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Psychological Variables", "back": "The Chicago Study was designed to gauge the difference between citizens’ concerns for favorable outcomes and procedural fairness. It also measures the extent to which fairness influences reactions to experience. The experience in question is of the everyday, averagecitizen variety—the type of encounter most of us have with authorities over relatively minor matters. Participants reported calling the police for a number of reasons: accidents,", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Legitimacy And Experience", "back": "People are more likely to accept unfavorable rulings if they believe their case was handled fairly. Thus, fair procedures can lessen the severity of an outcome that is to one’s disadvantage, without damaging the authorities’ legitimacy. Of course, fair procedures can only go so far. If fair procedures consistently produce unfavorable results, the fairness of the procedures will come into question. People typically place importance on procedure for several reasons. The first is simplicity.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Meaning Of Procedural Justice", "back": "Another important issue is how people evaluate procedures for fairness. Previous efforts to study this question have focused on control. Two areas of control with which people are generally concerned are decision control (control over the actual decisions made) and process control (control over the opportunity to state one’s case). To better illustrate, consider an attorney representing a client in court. While the client", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: allocation process. Consistency", "back": "the uniform and unbiased treatment of all of the affected parties. Suppression of bias guarantees that those involved with the outcome have no personal, vested interest in the case. This also prohibits a participant’s reliance on previously formed opinions rather than just the evidence at hand, as when a juror votes", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Influence Of Control On The Meaning Of Procedural Justice", "back": "The Chicago Study assessed process control by questioning respondents about how much opportunity they had to state their case or present their problem. Decision control was measured by asking how much influence participants had over the determinations made by the third party in control. Most participants felt they had a high (43%) to moderate (20%) level of process control. In contrast, a number of participants felt they had little decision", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Target hardening", "back": "preventive controls that aim to reduce or avoid the likelihood of a crime occurring. Examples include locking doors, separating duties, physically safeguarding assets, and using online two-factor authentication. Deterrence theory states that punishment should be swift, certain, and severe for it to be an effective deterrent. Thus, if someone in an", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Another psychological theme is that frustration", "back": "precursor of aggression. The theory suggests that the expression of aggression, such as a fraud perpetrator retaliating against their employer, will alleviate the frustration and allow the organism to return to a more", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: society favors (e.g., wealth and power) and the", "back": "by which those goals are achievable. To explain crime, these theories tend to focus on poverty, poor education, the presence of neighborhood subcultures (e.g., gangs), a lack of employment opportunities, and the pressure to be materially successful.", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: achieve such ends", "back": "cornerstone for explaining criminal behavior. Merton’s theory of anomie (that is, normlessness) was derived from the work of Émile Durkheim, a French sociologist who contextualized the term in his effort to explain suicide rates among different social groups. Merton’s theory characterizes the discord between goals", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: and the legitimate", "back": "available to achieve them as anomie. Strain theory argues that this disconnect inevitably leads to crime, as individuals struggle to fulfill their desires. Understanding Criminal Behavior Under Merton’s theory, the strain experienced by people can be either structural or", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: individual. Structural strain", "back": "societal-level processes, such as the way the government or economy functions, that gradually affect individuals. These structures might affect individuals’ opportunities and their general perceptions of society. Conversely, individual strain refers to the stress people feel and the difficulties they face when attempting to satisfy", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Institutional-Anomie Theory", "back": "An extension of anomie theory, specifically building on Robert Merton’s idea of structural strain, is the institutional-anomie theory (IAT). This theory attempts to explain differences in cross-cultural crime by the way a particular culture behaves economically, the expected behavior of its citizens, and the “opportunities [the culture provides] for its citizens to reach those expectations.”6 According to this theory, more crime occurs in countries where the", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}], "White-Collar Crime": [{"front": "What Is White-Collar Crime?", "back": "• According to Albert J. Reiss, Jr., and Albert Biderman, “Those violations of law to which penalties are attached that involve the use of a violator’s position of economic power, influence, or trust in", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Organizational Opportunity", "back": "• The determinant aspect of white-collar crime\n• Organization and complexity make a larger difference than the offender’s social status.", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Contributing Factors to the Rise of White-Collar Crime", "back": "• The economy increasingly runs on credit, which often means an increase in personal debt.\n• New information technologies mean that the opportunity for wrongdoing is growing.\n• Government programs distributing large amounts of money make an enticing target for embezzlement.\n• There is an overarching culture based on affluence and ever-higher levels of success. Media sources, and advertising in general, promise that no one has to settle for second best.", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Referring White-Collar Criminals to Law Enforcement", "back": "• According to the ACFE’s Occupational Fraud 2022: A Report to the Nations, 58% of occupational fraud cases were referred to law enforcement for prosecution.\n• The study also found that of perpetrators who were disciplined internally, 61% were terminated, 12% were either placed on probation or suspended, and 11% were permitted or required to resign.\n• For organizations that chose to handle fraud cases internally instead of referring them to law enforcement for prosecution, 50% of companies declined to refer cases because they believed their organiz", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Organizational Crime", "back": "• Organizational vs. occupational crime\n• Organizational crime is that which is committed by businesses, particularly corporations, and the government.\n• Effect of organizational structure on criminal behavior\n• Complex companies are more prone to misbehavior due to isolation of departments and locations.\n• Criminogenic nature of organizations", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Occupational Fraud", "back": "• Donald R. Cressey’s findings\n• Came up with the Fraud Triangle model to explain why people commit fraud\n• Dr. Steve Albrecht’s findings\n• The most highly ranked factors from the list of personal characteristics that contribute to fraud were: 1. Living beyond their means 2. An overwhelming desire for personal gain 3. High personal debt 4\n• Findings from the ACFE’s Occupational Fraud 2022: A Report to the Nations", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "White-Collar Crime", "back": "Part of the study of criminology involves exploring the differences in various categories of crimes and the individuals who commit them. Understanding what makes fraud and other white-collar crimes different from other types of criminal acts can be extremely helpful in designing systems to prevent and detect them, as can recognizing the characteristics of the people who perpetrate these schemes. Since the term was first used, there have been constant disputes regarding what is (or should", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: definition of the concept in a footnote: White-collar crim", "back": "e was said to be “Crime in the upper, white-collar class, which is composed of respectable, or at least respected, business, and professional men.” These crimes were confined to acts performed by white-collar persons in occupational roles, thereby excluding “most of their cases of murder, adultery, and", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: and that, once a conviction is attained, higher status often", "back": "a stiffer sentence. Whitecollar crime does have a unique place in criminology, but the split is not between an underworld of the desperate poor and an elite universe of high-stakes fraudsters. White-collar crime has some relation to both of these mythological worlds, but is largely the province of the middle classes, where organizational position is more important than social or", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: “had lived beyond their", "back": "for some time before deciding to embezzle.”5 Crimes of the Middle Classes later extended this statement more generally, remarking, “The most interesting fact about the white-collar offenders’ aggregate financial status is not the value of their assets but the extent of their liabilities.” Offenders often “have the material goods associated with successful", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: organizations can invite fraud as a", "back": "of obtaining goals. Economist Oliver Williamson noted that, because of a department’s concern with reaching its goals, managers might well tend to maximize their department’s own interests to the detriment of the organization. Organizations can also be criminogenic because they encourage loyalty. According to Diane", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: giving attention to the", "back": "by which they are obtained, employees might have an easier time rationalizing misconduct in the pursuit of success. Corporate Executives and Criminal Liability Many of the ethical and legal problems of a corporation result from the corporate structure", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}], "Corporate Governance": [{"front": "What Is Corporate Governance?", "back": "• Refers to a corporation’s government\n• Broadly used to describe the oversight responsibilities of different parties for an organization’s direction, operations, and performance\n• More specifically, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development’s (OECD) “Glossary of Statistical Terms” defines corporate governance as:\n• [The] procedures and processes according to which an organisation is directed and controlled. The corporate governance structure specifies the distribution of rights and responsibilities among the dif\n• Sir Adrian Cadbury, chairman of the committee that developed the foundational corporate governance guidance, The Cadbury Report, stated that the purpose of corporate governance is “to encourage the ef", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Parties Involved in Corporate Governance", "back": "• The board of directors\n• Made up of individuals who are generally elected by the entity’s voting members (e.g., shareholders in the case of a corporation or members in the case of an association)\n• Oversees business operations by assessing the strategy and underlying purpose of management’s decisions and actions\n• Management\n• Responsible for making the daily decisions that affect company performance and, ultimately, shareholder wealth", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Treadway Commission’s Audit Committee Recommendations", "back": "• The Treadway Commission was formed in the United States in 1985 with the purpose of defining the auditor’s responsibility in preventing and detecting fraud.\n• It made several major recommendations designed to reduce the probability of fraud in financial reports, including:\n• The board of directors should have a mandatory independent audit committee made up of outside directors.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Role of Corporate Governance in Fighting Fraud", "back": "• As stated in the Fraud Risk Management Guide, a joint publication by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) and the ACFE, fraud risk governance is one of the princ\n• Managing the Business Risk of Fraud: A Practical Guide, the predecessor to the Fraud Risk Management Guide, expands this point, noting, “Effective governance processes are the foundation of fraud risk", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Principles of Corporate Governance", "back": "• Accountability\n• To ensure that the organization operates effectively and efficiently, there must be mechanisms in place to ensure that management is accountable to the board and that the board is accountable to the s\n• Transparency\n• Refers to the clarity, accuracy, completeness, and timeliness of the financial statements and other information provided by management to shareholders\n• Fairness", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Establishing a Corporate Governance Framework", "back": "• The G20/OECD Principles of Corporate Governance state that “there is no single model of good corporate governance.”\n• Corporate governance structure and practices vary widely and should be determined based on each organization’s specific needs.\n• In developing a corporate governance framework for an organization, directors and management must consider the legal, regulatory, institutional, cultural, and ethical environments in which the company\n• Good corporate governance maintains the ability to find a different course when its current direction runs into barriers, such as changes in the corporate landscape, new regulations or legal requireme", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Sources of Corporate Governance Guidance", "back": "• Although there is not a universal law or set of rules for corporate governance, legislators, regulators, and other bodies around the world have issued guidance that provides best practices and require\n• In many jurisdictions, organizations—particularly those that are publicly traded—are subject to specific corporate governance requirements that might take the form of legislation or conditions set for\n• As a result, companies should be familiar with the existing guidance specific to all the regions in which they operate, and those charged with governance should ensure compliance with the laws and reg", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "G20/OECD Principles of Corporate Governance", "back": "• Regarded as one of the primary sources of guidance for corporate governance practices for organizations throughout the world\n• “Intended to help policymakers evaluate and improve the legal, regulatory, and institutional framework for corporate governance with a view to support economic efficiency, sustainable growth, and fina\n• Nonbinding, as their implementation must be adapted to different legal, economic, and cultural circumstances\n• This is a key strength of the Principles that makes them a useful tool worldwide, both in developed economies and in emerging markets.\n• Includes six broad principles:", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Deterrence", "back": "As a strategy to control crime, deterrence is designed to detect law violations, determine who is responsible, and penalize offenders to deter future violations. Deterrence systems try to control the immediate behavior of individuals, not the long-term behaviors targeted by Deterrence theory assumes that humans are rational in their behavioral patterns. Humans seek profit and pleasure while they try to avoid pain. Deterrence assumes that an individual’s", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Increased Enforcement", "back": "Formal levels of current enforcement in white-collar crime are, by all measures, extremely low. One view holds that increased enforcement can only come with a complete and total revision of the criminal justice system. Currently, people have little fear of detection because they know that the police and courts cannot keep up with the pace of criminal offenses. It is not necessary or even desirable to advocate longer prison sentences for offenders because we do not have the", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Importance Of Solving The Problem In Secret", "back": "Since Cressey’s study was done in the early 1950s, the workforce was obviously different from today’s workforce. But the employee faced with an immediate, non-shareable financial need has not changed much over the years. That employee still must find a way to relieve the financial pressure that bears down upon them. Simply stealing money, however, is not enough; Cressey found it was crucial that the employee be able to resolve the financial", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: share the fact that they were resorting to illegal", "back": "to relieve that pressure. To do so would be to admit that the problems existed in the first place. An interesting thing to note is that it is not the embezzlement that creates the need for secrecy in the perpetrator’s mind; it is the circumstances that led to the embezzlement (e.g., a", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: secrecy in the perpetrator’s mind; it", "back": "circumstances that led to the embezzlement (e.g., a violation of incurred obligation, a business reversal). Cressey said: In all cases [in the study] there was a distinct feeling that, because of activity prior to the defalcation, the approval of groups important to the trusted person had been lost, or a", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: with. Cressey observed, “It", "back": "next step which is significant to violation: the application of 31 Ibid., pages 66–67.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The third and final factor in the Fraud Triangle", "back": "rationalization. Cressey pointed out that rationalization is not an ex post facto means of justifying a theft that has already occurred. Significantly, rationalization is a necessary component of the crime before it takes place; in fact, it is a part of the motivation for the crime. Because embezzlers do not view themselves as", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: rationalization is not an ex post facto", "back": "of justifying a theft that has already occurred. Significantly, rationalization is a necessary component of the crime before it takes place; in fact, it is a part of the motivation for the crime. Because embezzlers do not view themselves as criminals, they must justify their misdeeds before they ever commit them. The rationalization", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Independent Businesspeople", "back": "The independent businesspeople in Cressey’s study were individuals who were in business for themselves and converted “deposits” that had been entrusted to them.37 Perpetrators in this", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Long-Term Violators", "back": "Cressey defined long-term violators as individuals who converted their employer’s funds, or funds belonging to their employer’s clients, by taking relatively small amounts over a period of time.39 Similar to independent businesspeople, the long-term violators generally preferred the “borrowing” rationalization. Other rationalizations of long-term violators were described, too, but they almost always were used in connection with the “borrowing” theme: (1) They", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Absconders", "back": "The third group of offenders Cressey discussed was absconders—people who take the money and run. Cressey found that the non-shareable problems for absconders usually resulted from physical isolation. He observed that these people, “usually are unmarried or separated from their spouses, live in hotels or rooming houses, have few primary group associations of any sort, and own little property. Only one of the absconders interviewed had held a higher status", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Projecting Total Fraud Losses Based On Imperfect Data", "back": "Even with these limitations on projecting the total amounts lost to fraud, the ACFE knows that such a projection has an important place in the fight against fraud. Consequently, the ACFE asked survey participants, based on their professional experience, what percentage of revenues they believe a typical organization loses to fraud each year. The median response provided by these CFEs is that organizations lose 5% of their annual revenues to fraud.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "The Fraud Costs We Know", "back": "Determining total fraud losses—whether globally, regionally, by industry, or within a specific organization—is outside the primary scope of the ACFE’s study. Instead, the focus is on analyzing known data to better understand the risks posed by occupational fraud. To that end, the ACFE examined the losses incurred in the actual cases of fraud reported to them to learn about how fraud affects its victims.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Categories Of Occupational Fraud", "back": "Of the three primary categories of occupational fraud, asset misappropriation is by far the most common, occurring in 86% of the cases in the ACFE’s study, as shown in Figure 2. However, asset misappropriation is also the least costly, causing a median loss of $100,000. Corruption schemes are the next most common form of occupational fraud, with 43% of the cases in the study involving some form of corrupt act. These schemes resulted in a median", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriation Sub-Schemes", "back": "Within the category of asset misappropriation, the ACFE’s research shows that there are several distinct subcategories of schemes. The heat map in Figure 5 illustrates the relative frequency and cost of each of these scheme types. The schemes that fall in the darkest area of the heat map—check and payment tampering,64 billing, and theft of noncash assets—rank among the most common and costliest scheme types and thus typically pose the greatest risk", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Duration Of Fraud Schemes", "back": "Examining how long frauds tend to last can also provide insight into how they affect their victims. The median duration for all of the fraud cases in the ACFE’s study was 14 months. However, it stands to reason that the longer a fraud goes undetected, the larger the scheme will grow. Figure 6 shows that frauds that last over sixty months are nearly 15 times as costly as those that are caught in the first six months. The data also indicate that fraudsters tend to", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Initial Detection Of Occupational Frauds", "back": "Figure 9 shows that the leading detection methods are tips, internal audit, and management review. This finding is not surprising, as these have been the three most common means of detecting occupational fraud in every edition of the report since 2010. Collectively, these three detection methods were cited in 70% of the cases in the ACFE’s most recent study. Tips were by far the most common means of detection for 43% of cases—more than internal", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Tips were by far the most common", "back": "of detection for 43% of cases—more than internal audit (15%) and management review (12%) combined.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Source Of Tips", "back": "Since tips are the most common detection method, it is important to understand where those tips come from. Figure 10 shows that half of all tips (50%) were provided by employees of the victim organizations. Meanwhile, more than one-third (35%) of the tips that led to fraud detection came from people outside the organization: customers, vendors, and competitors. Active cultivation of tips and complaints, such as the promotion of fraud hotlines, is often", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Median Loss And Median Duration By Detection Method", "back": "In addition to determining the most common methods of detection, the ACFE also analyzed the median loss and duration of fraud schemes based on how they were uncovered. The results indicate that there is a correlation between the way in which occupational fraud schemes are detected and the severity of the fraud. More importantly, these data point to steps organizations can take to detect fraud proactively and, in doing so, mitigate losses.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Type Of Victim Organization", "back": "As shown in Figure 14, 70% of the frauds in the study occurred at for-profit organizations, with 44% of the victim organizations being private companies and 26% being public companies. The private companies in the study suffered the greatest median loss, at $150,000. Not-for-profit organizations were the victim in only 9% of frauds and had the smallest median loss of $75,000; however, for many not-for-profit entities, financial resources are", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Size Of Victim Organization", "back": "The size of an organization’s staff can directly affect both the opportunity for fraud and the ability to enact certain anti-fraud mechanisms. Larger entities typically have more resources to invest in their anti-fraud programs, as well as a greater ability to separate duties among staff members to help prevent fraud; however, the large staff size can also mean more potentially dishonest employees who might attempt schemes and more complex processes and", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Industry Of Victim Organizations", "back": "In addition, reported cases were examined based on the industry of the victim organization. Figure 19 provides a breakdown of the extent to which industries were affected by occupational fraud. The greatest number of cases in the study occurred in the banking and financial services, manufacturing, and government and public administration sectors. It should be noted that these data likely represent the industries that most often employ CFEs,", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Anti-Fraud Controls At The Victim Organization", "back": "The presence of a robust system of anti-fraud controls can be a powerful deterrent, as well as a proactive prevention and detection mechanism, in the fight against fraud. Thus, organizations can benefit from knowing which anti-fraud controls are commonly used by their peers, as well as which tend to be the most effective. To help explore this information, survey respondents were provided with a list of 18 entity-level, anti-fraud controls and", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Effectiveness Of Anti-Fraud Controls", "back": "Demonstrating the return on investment in anti-fraud initiatives can be a difficult task, as it is nearly impossible to measure the amount of fraud prevented by a specific control. However, many anti-fraud professionals find themselves needing to make a business case to justify additional fraud prevention and detection initiatives. To provide some visibility into the relative effectiveness of various anti-fraud controls, the ACFE compared the losses", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Behavioral Red Flags Displayed By Perpetrators", "back": "Individuals who are engaged in occupational fraud schemes often exhibit certain behavioral traits or warning signs associated with their illegal activity. Survey respondents were presented with a list of 17 common behavioral red flags, and they were asked to report on which, if any, of these red flags had been displayed by the perpetrator before the fraud was discovered. Figure 41 shows the frequency of behavioral red flags in the 2020 cases. The six most", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Corporate Governance", "back": "The term corporate governance refers to a corporation’s government; the term is broadly used to describe the oversight responsibilities of different parties for an organization’s direction, operations, and performance. More specifically, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development’s (OECD) “Glossary of Statistical Terms” defines corporate governance as: [The] procedures and processes according to which an organisation is directed and controlled.", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}], "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities": [{"front": "Overview of Management’s Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "back": "• Management is ultimately responsible for the prevention and detection of fraud within an organization.\n• Management holds the primary responsibility for:\n• Designing, implementing, overseeing, and ensuring the effectiveness of the anti-fraud program", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Management’s Responsibility for Internal Controls", "back": "• It is management’s job to ensure that the proper internal controls are in place to prevent and detect fraud.\n• Although management might not execute all the controls, management is also responsible for monitoring, assessing, and remediating the internal controls to ensure they are effectively designed and oper", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "COSO Internal Control—Integrated Framework", "back": "• Based on the Treadway Commission’s recommendations, the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) was formed to provide guidance for organizations’ internal controls.\n• COSO is responsible for issuing the Internal Control—Integrated Framework (the Framework), which is meant to apply to both public and private entities, regardless of size.\n• According to the Framework, “Internal control is a process, effected by an entity’s board of directors, management, and other personnel, designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the achievem\n• Operations objectives pertain to the effectiveness and efficiency of the organization’s operations.\n• To meet these objectives, the Framework identifies five interrelated components of internal control:", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Nominating Committee", "back": "The nominating committee is responsible for identifying, evaluating, and nominating new directors to the board. It also facilitates the election of the new directors by shareholders. Although management nominates board members as well, an effective nominating committee will select new members to ensure independence. Responsibilities of the nominating committee include, but are not limited to: • Reviewing current directors’ performance", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: to enforce these standards", "back": "responsibility of individual governments. The Principles cover six main areas, which are divided into chapters. The Principles: • Request that governments have in place an effective legal, regulatory, and institutional", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: as the election of board members, or other", "back": "of influencing the board’s composition, amendments to the company’s organic documents, approval of extraordinary transactions, and other basic issues as specified in company law and internal company statutes. This Section can be seen as a statement of the most basic rights of shareholders, which are", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: authority to engage in those acts. Apparent authority", "back": "that a third party would reasonably believe the employee is authorized to perform the act on behalf of the company. Therefore, an organization could be held liable for something an employee does on behalf of the organization even if the employee is not authorized to perform that act.", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: internal sources. Risk", "back": "the possibility that an event will occur and adversely affect the achievement of objectives.” Risk assessment involves the identification and assessment of the risks the entity faces in achieving its organizational objectives. This process is dynamic and iterative, and it forms the basis for determining how risks will be managed.", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Monitoring", "back": "process that assesses the effectiveness of a control system over time. This component should include both ongoing, automated evaluations and periodic, separate evaluations, the findings of which should be evaluated against predefined criteria. The following are the Framework principles supporting this component:", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}], "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities": [{"front": "External Audit Standards Related to Fraud", "back": "• International Standard on Auditing (ISA) 240—The Auditor’s Responsibility Relating to Fraud in an Audit of Financial Statements\n• Purpose 1. To establish standards and provide guidance on the auditor’s responsibility to consider fraud in an audit of financial statements 2. To expand on how other auditing standards and guidance s\n• Misstatements arising from fraudulent financial reporting\n• Misstatements arising from the misappropriation of assets 3. For the purposes of the ISAs, the auditor is concerned with fraud that causes a material misstatement in the financial statements.\n• According to the ISAs, “Information is material if omitting, misstating or obscuring it could reasonably be expected to influence the decisions that the primary users of general purpose financial stat", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Internal Audit Standards Related to Fraud", "back": "• IIA Standard 1210—Proficiency\n• Internal auditors must possess the knowledge, skills, and other competencies needed to perform their individual responsibilities.\n• IIA Standard 1220—Due Professional Care\n• Internal auditors must apply the care and skill expected of a reasonably prudent and competent internal auditor.\n• IIA Standard 2060—Reporting to Senior Management and the Board", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The IIA’s IPPF—Practice Guide: Internal Audit and Fraud", "back": "• The Practice Guide states that, in conducting audit engagements, the internal auditor should:\n• Evaluate the organization’s structures and process for fraud risk governance.\n• Report to senior management and the board on the adequacy and effectiveness of the fraud risk governance and management at an engagement and organization-wide level.\n• The Practice Guide also provides guidance about the internal audit function’s role in communicating any significant fraud risk, control, and governance issues with senior management and the board of d\n• Is fraud risk management comprehensive, continuous, and aligned with the organization’s strategic objectives?", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Government Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "back": "• The International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI) operates as an umbrella organization for the external government audit community and\n• INTOSAI provides high-quality standards in the form of International Standards of Supreme Audit Institutions (ISSAI) for the public sector to promote good governance.\n• ISSAI 1240 provides supplementary guidance regarding the applicability of ISA 240 to public-sector financial statement audits.\n• States that ISA 240 is applicable to auditors of public-sector entities in their role as auditors of financial statements and includes several specific considerations in applying ISA 240 to public-sec\n• The objectives of a financial audit in the public sector are often broader than expressing an opinion as to whether the financial statements have been prepared, in all material respects, in accordance", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Define: significant aspects of auditing. The following", "back": "full text of the Principles as released by IOSCO’s Technical Committee:5 3 The material in this section is compiled from materials and resources issued by the International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO). For more information about this organization, please see www.iosco.org.", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Introduction", "back": "1. Investor confidence is fundamental to the successful operation of the world’s financial markets. That confidence depends on investors having credible and reliable financial information when making decisions about capital allocation. 2. The objectives of securities regulation include the protection of investors; ensuring that markets are fair, efficient, and transparent; and the reduction of systemic risk. In pursuit", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Oversight Principles", "back": "1. Oversight of auditors can occur in several ways, including within audit firms, by professional organizations and public or private sector oversight bodies, and through government oversight. In addition, oversight may be provided by supervisory boards and audit committees representing investors in matters relating to individual companies. 2. Within a jurisdiction, auditors should be subject to oversight by a body that acts and is", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Organization", "back": "The PIOB comprises individuals from a number of professions and all branches of regulation. Its ten members were nominated by IOSCO, the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision (BCBS), the International Association of Insurance Supervisors (IAIS), the World Bank, and the European Commission.", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Responsibilities", "back": "The PIOB oversees IFAC’s Public Interest Activity Committees (PIACs) comprising the IAASB, International Accounting Education Standards Board (IAESB), International Ethics Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities Standards Board for Accountants (IESBA), their respective Consultative Advisory Groups (CAGs), and the Compliance Advisory Panel (CAP). In this capacity, the PIOB: • Ensures that the processes of standard development under its oversight follow due", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Communicating And Reporting About Fraud", "back": "In addition, the Practice Guide provides guidance about internal audit’s role in communicating fraud-related issues with management and the board of directors. In specific, the Practice Guide notes that “internal auditors, through the unique role they play, are well positioned to elevate the importance of fraud prevention and detection programs with In support of IIA Standard 2060, Reporting to Senior Management and the Board, the Practice", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: INTOSAI Guidance, which", "back": "third level, provides practical assistance to SAIs in implementing the framework in their individual constituencies. Portions of the first two elements of this framework are summarized in the", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: INTOSAI-P 1 – The Lima Declaration", "back": "foundation of the INTOSAI professional framework. It contains a comprehensive yet concise list of all goals and issues relating to government auditing. The main purpose of INTOSAI-P 1 – The Lima Declaration is to call for independent", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fundamental Principles Of Public-Sector Auditing", "back": "The principles contained in this section are fundamental to the conduct of an audit. Although auditing is a cumulative and iterative process, for the purposes of presentation, the fundamental principles are grouped by principles related to the SAI’s organizational requirements, general principles that the auditor should consider prior to commencement and at more than one point during the audit, and principles related to specific steps in the", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Organizational Requirements", "back": "Each SAI should establish and maintain procedures for ethics and quality control on an organizational level that will provide it with reasonable assurance that the SAI and its personnel are complying with professional standards and the applicable ethical, legal, and", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "General Principles", "back": "Ethics and independence—Auditors should comply with the relevant ethical requirements and be independent. Ethical principles should be embodied in an auditor’s professional behavior. The SAIs should have policies addressing ethical requirements and emphasizing", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: in the circumstances of the audit. The audit risk", "back": "risk that the audit report may be inappropriate. The auditor performs procedures to reduce or manage the risk of reaching inappropriate conclusions, recognizing that the limitations inherent to all audits mean that an audit can never provide absolute certainty of the condition of the subject matter.", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Principles Related To The Audit Process", "back": "− Auditors should ensure that the terms of the audit have been clearly established. Audits may be required by statute, requested by a legislative or oversight body, initiated by the SAI, or carried out by simple agreement with the audited entity. In all cases, the auditor, the audited entity’s management, those charged with governance, and others, as applicable, should reach a common formal understanding of the terms of the audit", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fraud-Related Standards For Financial Audits", "back": "ISSAI 200 – Fundamental Principles of Financial Auditing provides key principles and standards related to an audit of financial statements in the public sector.10 According to ISSAI 200, the auditor has the following objectives when conducting such an engagement: 10 ISSAI 200 – Fundamental Principles of Financial Auditing is available at www.intosai.org/fileadmin/downloads /documents/open_access/ISSAI_100_to_400/issai_200/issai_200_en.pdf.", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}], "Fraud Risk Assessment": [{"front": "What Is Fraud Risk?", "back": "• The vulnerability that an organization faces from individuals capable of combining all three elements of the Fraud Triangle", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Inherent and Residual Fraud Risk", "back": "• Risks that are present before the effect of internal controls (including targeted anti-fraud controls) are described as inherent risks.\n• Risks that remain after the effect of these controls are described as residual risks.\n• The objective of an organization’s anti-fraud controls is to reduce the residual risk to a level that is significantly lower than the inherent risk.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Factors That Influence Fraud Risk in an Organization", "back": "• The nature of the business in which it is engaged\n• The environment in which it operates\n• The effectiveness of its anti-fraud controls\n• A good system of anti-fraud controls, with the right balance of preventive and detective controls, can greatly reduce an organization’s vulnerability to fraud. 1. Preventive controls stop something ba\n• The ethics and values of the company and its employees", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "back": "• An ongoing, continuous process aimed at proactively identifying and addressing an organization’s vulnerabilities to both internal and external fraud\n• What gets evaluated and how it gets assessed should be tailored to the organization, as there is not an approach that is suited to all organizations.\n• The objective of a fraud risk assessment is to help an organization recognize what makes it most vulnerable to fraud.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Why Organizations Should Conduct Fraud Risk Assessments", "back": "• To improve communication and awareness about fraud\n• A fraud risk assessment can be an effective way for an organization to start communication and raise awareness about fraud.\n• To identify where the company is most vulnerable to fraud and what activities put it at the greatest risk\n• Management must know where the company is most vulnerable to fraud to prevent it from happening.\n• To know who puts the organization at the greatest risk", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Elements of a Good Fraud Risk Assessment", "back": "• Collaborative effort of management and auditors\n• The fraud risk assessment is most effective when management and auditors share ownership of the process and accountability for its success.\n• The right sponsor\n• The sponsor must be senior enough in the organization to command the employees’ respect and elicit full cooperation in the process.\n• Independence and objectivity of the people leading and conducting the work", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "back": "• Assemble a multi-disciplinary team to lead and conduct the fraud risk assessment.\n• The team should consist of individuals with diverse knowledge, skills, and perspectives to lead and conduct the assessment.\n• Identify the information to be gathered and determine the most effective techniques to use in conducting the fraud risk assessment.\n• Information to be gathered includes: 1. The identification of inherent fraud risks 2. Discussion of past known fraud incidents and how they were handled\n• Obtain the sponsor’s agreement on:", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Identifying Potential Inherent Fraud Risks and Schemes", "back": "• Brainstorm to identify the inherent fraud risks that could apply to the organization.\n• Brainstorming should include discussions regarding:\n• Incentives, pressures, and opportunities to commit fraud\n• Fraudulent financial reporting (e.g., inappropriately reported revenues, expenses, assets, or liabilities)\n• Asset misappropriation (e.g., theft of tangible or intangible assets)", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Identifying and Mapping Existing Preventive and Detective Controls to the", "back": "• Preventive controls\n• Intended to prevent fraud before it occurs\n• Detective controls\n• Intended to detect fraud if it does occur", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Ways Management Can Respond to Residual Fraud Risks", "back": "• Avoid the risk.\n• Management might decide to avoid the risk by eliminating an asset or discontinuing an activity if the control measures required to protect the organization against an identified threat are too expensi\n• Transfer the risk.\n• Management might transfer some or all of the risk by purchasing fidelity insurance or a fidelity bond.\n• Mitigate the risk.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "back": "• The success of the fraud risk assessment process depends on how effectively the results are reported and what management then does with those results.\n• When reporting the results of the assessment:\n• Report only the facts, and keep all opinions and biases out of the report.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Making an Impact with the Fraud Risk Assessment", "back": "• Management should use the assessment results to:\n• Begin a dialogue across the company.\n• Modify or create the code of conduct or ethics policy.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Fraud Risk Assessment and the Audit Process", "back": "• The fraud risk assessment should play a significant role in informing and influencing the audit process.\n• The fraud risk assessment should motivate thinking and awareness in the development of audit programs for areas that have been identified as having a moderate-to-high risk of fraud.\n• Auditors should validate that the organization is appropriately managing the moderate-to-high fraud risks identified in the fraud risk assessment by:\n• Identifying and mapping the existing preventive and detective controls that pertain to the moderate-to-high fraud risks identified in the fraud risk assessment", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Define: A significant part of a fraud prevention program", "back": "expressed commitment of the board and senior management. This commitment forms the basis of the organization’s anti-fraud culture. A strong corporate culture can most often be observed by its outcome, rather than by any individual component. Fostering a culture of ethics and compliance is more beneficial than", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Background", "back": "The corporate anti-fraud policy is established to facilitate the development of controls that will aid in the detection and prevention of fraud against ABC Corporation. It is the intent of ABC Corporation to promote consistent organizational behavior by providing guidelines and assigning responsibility for the development of controls and the conduct of investigations.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Scope Of Policy", "back": "This policy applies to any irregularity or suspected irregularity involving employees, as well as shareholders, consultants, vendors, contractors, and outside agencies doing business with employees of such agencies, and/or any other parties with a business relationship with ABC Corporation (also called the Company). Any investigative activity required will be conducted without regard to the suspected wrongdoer’s length of service, position/title, or", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Constituting", "back": "The terms defalcation, misappropriation, and other fiscal irregularities refer to, but are not limited to, the following: • Any dishonest or fraudulent act • Misappropriation of funds, securities, supplies, or other assets • Impropriety in the handling or reporting of money or financial", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Irregularities", "back": "Irregularities concerning an employee’s moral, ethical, or behavioral conduct should be resolved by departmental management and the Employee Relations Unit of Human Resources (HR) rather than If there is any question as to whether an action constitutes fraud, contact the Director of ______________ for guidance.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Responsibilities", "back": "The ______________ Unit has the primary responsibility for the investigation of all suspected fraudulent acts as defined in the policy. If the investigation substantiates that fraudulent activities have occurred, the ______________ Unit will issue reports to appropriate designated personnel and, if appropriate, to the Board of Directors Decisions to prosecute or refer the examination results to the", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Confidentiality", "back": "The ______________ Unit treats all information received confidentially. Any employee who suspects dishonest or fraudulent activity will notify the _____________ Unit immediately and should not attempt to personally conduct investigations or interviews/interrogations related to any suspected fraudulent act (see REPORTING PROCEDURES", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Investigating", "back": "• Free and unrestricted access to all Company records and premises,", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Suspected Fraud", "back": "• The authority to examine, copy, and/or remove all or any portion of the contents of files, desks, cabinets, and other storage facilities on the premises without prior knowledge or consent of any individual who might use or have custody of any such items or facilities when it is within the scope of their investigation", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Procedures", "back": "Great care must be taken in the investigation of suspected improprieties or irregularities so as to avoid mistaken accusations or alerting suspected individuals that an investigation is under way. An employee who discovers or suspects fraudulent activity will contact the _____________ Unit immediately. The employee or other complainant may remain anonymous. All inquiries concerning the activity under investigation from the suspected individual, their", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Acting In Good", "back": "Anyone reporting any irregularity that is detected or suspected must be acting in good faith and have reasonable grounds for believing the information provided. Allegations made maliciously or with knowledge of their falsity will not be tolerated. People making such allegations may be subject to institutional disciplinary action and/or legal actions by the individuals accused of fraudulent conduct.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Protection", "back": "Employees of ABC Corporation may not retaliate against a whistleblower for reporting an activity which that person believes to be fraudulent or dishonest with the intent or effect of adversely affecting the terms or conditions of employment (including, but not limited to, threats of physical harm, dismissal, transfer to an undesirable job assignment, demotion, suspension, or impact on salary or wages). A whistleblower is defined as an employee who informs a", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Termination", "back": "If an investigation results in a recommendation to terminate an individual, the recommendation will be reviewed for approval by the designated representatives from HR and the Legal Department and, if necessary, by outside counsel, before any such action is taken. The _____________ Unit does not have the authority to terminate an employee. The decision to terminate an employee is made by the employee’s management. Should the _____________ Unit believe the", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Administration", "back": "The Director of _____________ is responsible for the administration, revision, interpretation, and application of this policy. The policy will be reviewed annually and revised as needed. __________________________________ (CEO/Senior Vice President/Executive)", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Definition Of Gifts", "back": "Gifts are items and services of value that are given to any outside parties, but do not include • Normal business entertainment items, such as meals and beverages, are not to be • Items of minimal value, given in connection with sales campaigns and promotions or employee service, safety, or retirement awards are not to be considered gifts for purposes", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Definition Of Supplier", "back": "Supplier includes not only vendors providing services and material to the company, but also consultants, financial institutions, advisors, and any person or institution that does business No employee or member of their immediate family shall solicit or accept from an actual or prospective customer or supplier any compensation, advance loans (except from established financial institutions on the same basis as other customers), gifts, entertainment, or other", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reporting Gifts", "back": "An employee who receives, or whose family member receives, an unsolicited gift prohibited by these guidelines should report it to their supervisor and either return it to the person making the gift or, in the case of a perishable gift, give it to a nonprofit charitable organization.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Discounts", "back": "An employee might accept discounts on a personal purchase of the supplier’s or customer’s products only if such discounts do not affect the company’s purchase price and are generally offered to others having a similar business relationship with the supplier or customer.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Business Meetings", "back": "Entertainment and services offered by a supplier or customer may be accepted by an employee when they are associated with a business meeting and the supplier or customer provides them to others as a normal part of its business. Examples of such entertainment and services are transportation to and from the supplier’s or customer’s place of business, hospitality suites, golf outings, lodging at the supplier’s or customer’s place of business, and", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}], "Fraud Risk Management": [{"front": "What Is Risk Management?", "back": "• In Enterprise Risk Management—Integrating with Strategy and Performance, the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) defines enterprise risk management (ERM) as “the cu\n• Involves the identification, prioritization, treatment, and monitoring of risks that threaten an organization’s ability to provide value to its stakeholders\n• Involves balancing risk appetite—how much risk management is willing to accept—with the ability to meet the organization’s strategic, operational, reporting, and compliance objectives", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "COSO Enterprise Risk Management—Integrating with Strategy and Performance", "back": "• Composed of a set of principles organized into five components and twenty supporting principles that are based on a holistic view of an organization’s risk portfolio\n• The five components are:\n• Governance and culture 1. The organization’s governance and culture form the foundation for the ERM program. 2. Governance sets the organizational tone, reinforces the importance of risk management, a\n• Under this component, the organization:\n• Assesses substantial changes that might affect its strategy and objectives", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "ISO 31000", "back": "• The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) has developed ISO 31000:2018, a set of international standards providing principles and guidance on risk management.\n• The following eight ISO 31000:2018 principles provide that an effective and efficient risk management program:\n• Is integrated into all organizational activities\n• Is dynamic and responsive to change", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Managing Third-Party Fraud Risks", "back": "• To protect themselves from risks, it is important for organizations to implement proper due diligence procedures and compliance requirements when engaging in transactions with third parties, such as v\n• Customer due diligence (CDD)\n• There are three levels of due diligence procedures that organizations can use based on the level of risk a potential customer presents. 1. Simplified CDD\n• The lowest level of due diligence\n• Most appropriate in situations where there is little opportunity or risk of a customer engaging in illegal activity", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Who Is Responsible for Managing Fraud Risk?", "back": "• According to the Fraud Risk Management Guide, a joint publication by COSO and the ACFE, “personnel at all levels of the organization—including every level of management, staff, and internal auditors—h", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "back": "• Recognize the true and specific risks of fraud to the organization, as well as their potential impact, and respond by:\n• Setting an appropriate tone and realistic expectations of management to enforce an anti-fraud culture\n• Overseeing the organization’s fraud risk management activities", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Audit Committee’s Role", "back": "• Oversee the organization’s financial, accounting, and audit matters and report to the full board of directors.\n• Actively oversee the assessment and monitoring of the organization’s fraud risks by:\n• Receiving regular reports on the status of reported or alleged fraud\n• Providing external auditors with evidence that the audit committee is dedicated to effective fraud risk management", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Senior Management’s Role", "back": "• Hold the primary responsibility for designing, implementing, monitoring, and improving the fraud risk management program, which involves:\n• Being extremely familiar with the organization’s fraud risks\n• Taking all reports of fraud seriously and undertaking investigations for any such reports deemed reliable", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "The Objectives of a Fraud Risk Management Program", "back": "• Fraud risk management programs must address fraud before, during, and after it occurs.\n• Such programs must incorporate policies and procedures designed to prevent, detect, and respond to fraud.\n• Fraud prevention 1. Activities focus on proactively identifying and assessing fraud risks and taking steps to address those risks.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Fraud Risk Management Principles", "back": "• To help meet the objectives of a fraud risk management program, the Fraud Risk Management Guide describes five broad principles of fraud risk management:\n• Fraud risk governance 1. The organization establishes and communicates a fraud risk management program that demonstrates the expectations of the board of directors and senior management and their comm\n• Fraud risk management monitoring activities 1. The organization selects, develops, and performs ongoing evaluations to ascertain whether each of the five principles of fraud risk management is present", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Developing a Fraud Risk Management Program", "back": "• Define program objectives.\n• Tailor detailed objectives of the fraud risk management program to the organization’s specific needs and goals.\n• Define risk appetite.\n• Without an adequate understanding and articulation of just how much risk those charged with governance are willing to accept, any stated objectives of the fraud risk management program will be inaccur\n• Examine previous fraud incidents.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Population Of Fraud Risks", "back": "The fraud risk identification process requires an understanding of the universe of fraud risks and the subset of risks that apply to a particular organization. It includes gathering information about the business itself, including its business processes, industry, and operating environment, as well as all associated potential fraud risks. Such information can be obtained from external sources—such as industry news outlets; criminal, civil, and regulatory", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Fraudulent Financial Reporting", "back": "Potential fraudulent financial reporting risks include: • Inappropriately reported revenues, expenses, or both • Inappropriately reflected balance sheet amounts, including reserves • Inappropriately improved or masked disclosures • Concealed misappropriation of assets • Concealed unauthorized receipts, expenditures, or both • Concealed unauthorized acquisition, use, or disposition of assets", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Asset Misappropriations", "back": "Potential asset misappropriation risks include misappropriation of: • Proprietary business opportunities", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Corruption", "back": "Potential corruption risks include: • Payment of bribes or illegal gratuities to companies, private individuals, or public officials • Receipt of bribes, kickbacks, or illegal gratuities by employees or agents of the company Aiding and abetting of fraud by outside parties, such as customers or vendors", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "External Fraud", "back": "• Fraud committed by customers (e.g., fraudulent customer payments) • Fraud committed by vendors (e.g., overbilling by a vendor or collusion between bidding contractors to inflate contract price) • Fraud committed by competitors (e.g., corporate espionage) • Fraud committed by unrelated third parties (e.g., hacking)", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Risk Of Regulatory And Legal Misconduct", "back": "Regulatory and legal misconduct includes a wide range of risks, such as conflicts of interest, insider trading, theft of competitor trade secrets, anti-competitive practices, environmental violations, and trade and customs regulations in areas of import and export. Depending on the particular organization and the nature of its business, some or all of these risks might be applicable and should be considered in the fraud risk assessment process.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reputation Risk", "back": "Reputation risk must be considered as part of the organization’s risk assessment process because fraudulent acts can damage an organization’s reputation with customers, suppliers, capital markets, and others. For example, fraud leading to a financial restatement can damage an organization’s reputation in capital markets, which can increase the organization’s cost of borrowing and depress its market capitalization.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Risk To Information Technology", "back": "IT is a critical component of fraud risk assessment. Organizations rely on IT to conduct business, communicate, and process financial information. A poorly designed or inadequately controlled IT environment can expose an organization to threats to data integrity, threats from hackers to system security, and theft of financial and sensitive business information. Whether in the form of hacking, economic espionage, web defacement, sabotage of data,", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Assess The Likelihood Of Occurrence Of The Identified Fraud Risks", "back": "The likelihood of occurrence of each fraud risk can be classified as remote, reasonably possible, or probable. The fraud risk assessment team should consider the following factors in assessing the likelihood of occurrence of each fraud risk:", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Assess The Significance To The Organization Of The Fraud Risks", "back": "The fraud risk assessment team should consider qualitative and quantitative factors when assessing the significance (sometimes referred to as the impact) of identified fraud risks to the organization. For example, a particular fraud risk that might only pose an immaterial direct financial risk to the organization, but that could greatly affect its reputation, would be deemed a significant risk to the organization.", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Preventive Controls", "back": "Preventive controls, which are intended to prevent fraud before it occurs, include: • Bringing awareness of the fraud risk management program to personnel throughout", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Detective Controls", "back": "Detective controls, which are intended to detect fraud if it does occur, include: • Establishing and marketing the presence of a confidential reporting system, such as a • Implementing proactive controls for the fraud detection process, such as independent reconciliations, reviews, physical inspections and counts, analysis, and audits", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: The fraud risk trend (i.e.,", "back": "scheme becoming riskier for the organization, less risky, or staying the same?) The fraud risk velocity (i.e., How quickly would the impact of the fraud be felt?) The roles or teams in the organization that would be able to perpetrate the scheme,", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Larry Cook, CFE, who", "back": "principal author of the ACFE Fraud Risk Assessment Tool (ACFE.com/fraud-risk-assessment.aspx), suggests that management can use one or a combination of the following approaches to respond to the organization’s residual", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: bond. The cost to the organization", "back": "premium paid for the insurance or bond. The covered risk of loss is then transferred to the insurance company. Transferring risk through insurance coverage is not just a strategy to protect against employee frauds; it should be considered for certain third-party risks as well. For example, as part of its vendor", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}], "Fraud Prevention Programs": [{"front": "Procedures and Mechanisms to Prevent Fraud", "back": "• Increasing the perception of detection\n• Most experts agree that it is much easier to prevent fraud than to detect it.\n• Proactive audit procedures\n• Can be used to demonstrate management’s intention to aggressively look for possible fraudulent conduct instead of waiting for instances to be reported\n• Employee anti-fraud education", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Creating an Anti-Fraud Policy", "back": "• A written anti-fraud policy should specifically indicate who in an organization manages varying fraud matters under differing circumstances.\n• Among other things, the anti-fraud policy might include:\n• A policy statement that formally defines fraud and outlines management’s position or attitude toward fraud in the workplace", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Communicating the Anti-Fraud Policy", "back": "• Management must periodically and appropriately communicate the company’s anti-fraud policy to all employees and third parties.", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Legal Considerations Regarding the Anti-Fraud Policy", "back": "• It is best to detail specific unacceptable conduct to avoid legal problems in terminating a dishonest employee.\n• Management should consult legal counsel regarding any necessary legal considerations with respect to the anti-fraud policy.\n• One of the most important legal considerations is to ensure that all allegations and offenders are managed uniformly.", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Developing an Ethics Program", "back": "• A written ethics policy enables management to objectively communicate its ethical philosophy and provides a foundation for a successful ethics program.\n• Should be shared among both new and old employees\n• Key considerations when developing an ethics program include:\n• Understanding why good people can commit unethical acts\n• Ascertaining how board members, stockholders, management, employees, and any other important members of the organization define success", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Developing an Effective Corporate Compliance and Ethics Program", "back": "• An effective compliance program can be defined as one that is reasonably designed, implemented, and enforced so that it generally will be effective in preventing and detecting criminal conduct.\n• To have an effective compliance and ethics program, the organization should:\n• Exercise due diligence to prevent and detect criminal conduct.\n• Elements of an effective compliance and ethics program\n• The following seven factors are minimally required for a corporate compliance program to be considered effective: 1. Established standards and procedures to prevent and detect criminal conduct 2. Prop", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Iso 31000", "back": "The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) has developed ISO 31000, a set of international standards providing principles and guidance on risk management. Most organizations with a risk management function that do not follow the COSO ERM model follow the ISO model. Some organizations have developed a customized model that incorporates elements of both the COSO and ISO models. The ISO 31000 family of standards includes:", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Simplified due diligence", "back": "lowest level of due diligence that can be performed on a potential customer. Conducting simplified due diligence procedures would be most appropriate in situations where there is little opportunity or risk of a customer engaging in illegal activity. The only requirement for simplified due diligence is to identify the customer.", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Expected method of payment (i.e.,", "back": "customer requesting to use a higher-risk payment method, such as a personal check or line of credit?)", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: An affirmation process", "back": "requirement for directors, employees, and contractors to explicitly affirm (typically via electronic or manual signature) that they have read, understood, and complied with the organization’s code of conduct, fraud control policy, and other such documentation that supports the fraud risk management program. In determining whether to", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: organization’s fraud risks", "back": "foundation for an effective fraud risk management program. Such an assessment is not a onetime endeavor, but rather should be performed on a systematic and recurring basis. Additionally, the assessment should consider all relevant fraud schemes and scenarios, and the results should be used to map mitigating controls to those", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}], "Ethics for Fraud Examiners": [{"front": "Purpose of a Code of Ethical Conduct", "back": "• Serves as a reference and benchmark for ethical guidance\n• Makes explicit the conduct that is expected in a particular profession\n• Provides direct solutions not available from general ethics theories\n• Enables individuals to have a better understanding of what is expected of them\n• Makes practical enforcement and internal discipline throughout a profession easier because members are put on notice of the standards", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Ethics and Legality", "back": "• Ethics refers to the appropriateness of a decision in consideration of morality. That is, ethics stress standards or codes of behavior expected by the group to which the individual belongs.\n• Legality refers to lawfulness by conformity to a legal statute.\n• The law is the lowest reference level for moral decisions.\n• The law might permit an action that is prohibited by a profession’s code of ethics.", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "ACFE Code of Professional Ethics", "back": "• An ACFE Member shall, at all times, demonstrate a commitment to professionalism and diligence in the performance of their duties.\n• Diligence 1. Exercised by properly planning assignments and supervising assistants and colleagues, avoiding conflicts of interest, performing with competence, obtaining sufficient evidence to establis\n• An ACFE Member shall not engage in any illegal or unethical conduct, or any activity which would constitute a conflict of interest that has not been properly disclosed to the appropriate parties.\n• Illegal conduct 1. While some activities might be obviously illegal, the legality of others might not be as apparent. 2. Fraud examiners are generally not entitled to claim ignorance of the law.\n• A fraud examiner employed full time by a company should not engage in other jobs that create a hardship or loss to the employer.", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "workbook"}, {"front": "Professional Admission Standards", "back": "Professional fields are also characterized by an admissions process that is governed by standards of professional qualifications. Some industries govern admission to their ranks by qualifications contained in law, but legal recognition is not required. Conversely, many professions are not regulated by legal statutes. For instance, the certified internal auditor (CIA) has the status of a profession without the benefit of licensing laws. The", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Recognition And Acceptance By Society: A Reciprocal Relationship", "back": "No group of practitioners can become a profession merely by declaring itself to be one. Society must acknowledge the group as a professional body. At present, fraud examiners are at the stage of becoming a self-declared profession. Historically, other professions had the same starting point. Modern medicine overcame its roots in magic. Accountants rose from the level of bookkeepers. Internal auditors advanced social goals by presenting a responsible", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Standards Of Conduct", "back": "Professional fields are also characterized by the adoption of and adherence to a code of professional ethics and standards of conduct, and such codes and standards can help a profession achieve full social recognition. Codes of ethics serve as a reference and benchmark for ethical guidance. Like professionals in other fields, ACFE members are required to adhere to an explicit code of ethical conduct—", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "A Professional Organization", "back": "Professional fields are typically characterized by a dedicated organization devoted to the advancement of the group’s obligations. For example, the ACFE is an association of professionals comprising CFEs and associate members who have made a commitment to work together for the common goal of detecting and preventing fraud, waste, and abuse. Professionalism for the Individual Fraud Examiners Additionally, professionalism exists for the individual fraud examiner. But when the focus of", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Independence In Attitude And Appearance", "back": "Independence of attitude requires impartiality and fairness in conducting fraud examinations and in reaching resulting conclusions and judgments. Fraud examiners must also be sensitive to the appearance of independence so that conclusions and judgments will be accepted as impartial by knowledgeable third parties. Fraud examiners who become aware of a situation or relationship that could be perceived to impair independence, whether or not actual", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Objectivity", "back": "Objectivity refers to the ability to conduct fraud examinations without being influenced by one’s own personal feelings or the feelings and motives of others. To ensure objectivity in performing examinations, fraud examiners must maintain an independent mental attitude, ACFE Code of Professional Ethics reach judgments on examination matters without undue influence from others, and avoid being placed in positions where they would be unable to work in an objective professional", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: Additionally, integrity", "back": "that a fraud examiner should have a well-developed sense of moral philosophy—an ability to analyze situations where no rules of the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics are specifically applicable and to be able to distinguish right from wrong. It does not mean, however, that an ACFE member must be perfect in all technical", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: competence", "back": "how well fraud examiners do their job. Determination of competence always depends on the specific facts and circumstances of the assignment. Competence is best understood in the context of the prudent practitioner. The idea of a prudent professional practitioner is present in other social science theories; for example,", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: required. It", "back": "responsibility of a fraud examiner to ensure that necessary skills, knowledge, ability, and experience are acquired or available before proceeding with a fraud examination. Sources of Interference with Professional Competence Professional competence also demands attention to three kinds of interference that can", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Programming", "back": "Fraud examiners must remain free from interference by managers who try to restrict, specify, or modify the procedures they need to perform, including any attempts to assign personnel or otherwise control the examination work. Occasionally, client or employer managers try to limit access to information or to other personnel, or to limit the amount of time available for", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Investigation", "back": "When appropriate, fraud examiners must have free access to books, records, correspondence, and other evidence. They must have the cooperation of managers or other employees without any attempt to interpret or screen evidence.", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Reporting", "back": "Client or employer managers should not be allowed to overrule the fraud examiner’s judgments on the appropriate content of a report. Integrity is destroyed and judgment is subordinated when the fraud examiner is compelled to alter a report or to omit important information or to misstate facts. Fraud examiners must not let any feelings of misguided loyalty to the client, employer, or other sources of conflicts of interest interfere with their", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Cfe Code Of Professional Standards", "back": "(Adopted by the Board of Regents, October 1, 2020) The Association of Certified Fraud Examiners is an association of professionals committed to performing at the highest level of ethical conduct. Members of the Association pledge themselves to act with integrity and to perform their work in a professional manner. Members have a professional responsibility to their clients, the public interest, and each other,", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Define: these Standards, the term “fraud examination”", "back": "an assignment or engagement, a substantial purpose of which involves the prevention, detection, investigation, or resolution of fraud or fraud-related conduct. CFE Code of Professional Standards", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}, {"front": "Bibliography", "back": "Akers, Ronald. Deviant Behavior: A Social Learning Approach, 2nd ed. (Belmont, CA: Wadsworth, 1977). Albrecht, W. Steve., Conan C. Albrecht, Chad O. Albrecht, and Mark F. Zimbelman. Fraud Examination, 4th ed. (Mason, OH: South-Western, 2011). Albrecht, W. Steve, Keith R. Howe, and Marshall B. Romney. Deterring Fraud: The Internal Auditor’s Perspective (Altamonte Springs, FL: The Institute of Internal Auditors Research Foundation, 1984).", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "source": "manual"}]}, "topics": [{"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Interview Theory and Application", "summary_short": "[From CFE Workbook] To effectively prepare for the interview phase of an investigation, the fraud examiner must first develop a plan. This might involve: Contemplating what the interview is intended to accomplish", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Preparing for Interviews"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To effectively prepare for the interview phase of an investigation, the fraud examiner must first develop a plan. This might involve:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Contemplating what the interview is intended to accomplish"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Stating the interview’s objective"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reviewing the case file to ensure that it does not contain important information that might have been overlooked"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Selecting appropriate members of the investigative team as interviewers"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Determining the necessary order of interviews"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Determining what information witnesses might offer and how to obtain it"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Selecting a comfortable and secure venue"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Planning for circumstances that might prevent an in-person interview (e.g., remote working)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Formulating a brief outline of main points to discuss during the interview"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Deciding which evidentiary documents to take into the interview and which to request from the subject"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Considering the legal or administrative issues specific to all the jurisdictions involved (e.g., whether interviewees can be compelled to cooperate, whether a legal representative is required to be present for the interview, or whether the use of information obtained during the interview is limited)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Consulting with local legal counsel or company representatives when conducting an investigation that spans multiple jurisdictions or is international in scope"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Researching cultural norms and practices (e.g., greetings, personal space, eye contact, and body language) to avoid missteps and ensure that interviews in unfamiliar jurisdictions are not compromised"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Interview Mechanics"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Rules for note-taking during interviews"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Consider recording interviews electronically and covertly if permissible."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Record notes for each interview separately, regardless of whether they are handwritten or electronically recorded."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Do not try to write down all the information provided during an interview; only write down the pertinent facts."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Avoid slowing down the interview process for note-taking."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Err on the side of taking too few notes rather than too many."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Avoid making notes regarding overall opinions or impressions of a witness and their guilt or innocence."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Avoid showing excitement or other emotions when taking notes."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Expound the interview notes as soon as possible after concluding the interview."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Other interviewing best practices"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Maintain eye contact as much as possible during the interview."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Do not prepare a list of predetermined questions to ask the subject; instead, let the interview flow freely."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Only question one person at a time."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Conduct interviews under conditions of privacy."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Interview Questions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Five types"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Introductory questions 1. Used to provide an introduction and to get the respondent to verbally agree to the interview"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Informational questions 1. Used to gather facts 2. Can be open, closed, or leading"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Closing questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Used to reconfirm facts, gather additional facts, and maintain"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Assessment questions 1. Used to establish the respondent’s credibility 2. Involve observing the subject’s verbal and nonverbal responses"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Admission-seeking questions 1. Reserved specifically for individuals whose culpability is reasonably certain 2. Designed to obtain a legal admission of wrongdoing"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Introductory Questions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Designed to meet four objectives:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To provide an introduction 1. The interviewer generally should indicate their name and company, but they should avoid stating their title when appropriate."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "To establish rapport 1. Rapport is defined as a “harmonious accord or relation that fosters cooperation, communication, or trust.” 2. The interviewer must establish some common ground with the respondent before they begin the fact-gathering portion of the interview. 3. Interviewers usually establish rapport by spending a few minutes engaging the respondent in casual conversation."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "To establish the interview theme 1. The interviewer must state the interview’s purpose, or establish the interview theme, prior to the commencement of serious questioning. 2. The goal of the theme is to get the respondent to make a commitment to assist."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "To observe the respondent’s reactions 1. The interviewer must be skilled in interpreting the respondent’s reactions to questions. 2. Social scientists say that more than half of the communication between individuals is unspoken; therefore, the interviewer must systematically observe the various responses the respondent gives throughout the conversation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Methodology"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Sensitive questions and emotive words should be avoided during the introductory phase because they tend to put people on the defensive and make them more reluctant to answer and cooperate. 1. Use words with a softer meaning (e.g., inquiry or review instead of investigation)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Move from comfortable questions to more sensitive ones."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Do not invade personal space—remain at a distance of 4–6 feet during the interview."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Informational Questions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Asked for the purpose of gathering unbiased, factual information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Commonly used when:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Conducting an interview to gain an understanding of accounting control systems"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Conducting interviews concerning documents"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Gathering information regarding business operations or systems"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Conducting pre-employment interviews"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Sequence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "As a general rule, questioning should proceed from the general to the specific (general information before detailed information)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Begin by asking questions about known information and then work toward unknown areas."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Three main types"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Open 1. Worded so it is difficult to answer “yes” or “no” 2. To stimulate conversation, the majority of questions asked during this phase should be open ones."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Closed 1. Require a precise answer, such as “yes” or “no” 2. Also deal with specifics, such as amounts, dates, and times 3. Typically should be avoided during the interview’s informational phase"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Leading 1. Contain a suggested answer 2. Commonly used to confirm facts already known"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Types of questions to avoid"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Double-negative 1. Have two forms of negation within a single clause"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Complex 1. Are too complicated to be easily understood, cover more than one subject or topic, require more than one answer, and/or require a complicated answer"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Dealing with Difficult Situations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Resistance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Possible excuses for refusing a request for an interview 1. “I’m too busy.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Defuse by stressing that:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The interview will be short."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The interviewer is already there."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The project is important."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The interview will not be difficult."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The interviewer needs help. 2. “I don’t remember.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Defuse by remaining silent while the person is deliberating or posing an alternate, narrower question."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Difficult people"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Do not react; manage your emotions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Disarm the person (listen, acknowledge the point, and agree wherever possible)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Change tactics (direct attention back to the problem and interests of both sides—e.g., ask the respondent what they would do to solve the problem)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Make it easy to say “yes.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Make it hard to say “no.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Volatile interviews"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An interview that has the potential to bring about strong emotional reactions in the respondent"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "There should be two interviewers involved in potentially volatile situations."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Surprise should be employed in any interview that is considered potentially volatile so that the respondent is unprepared."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The interviewer should ask questions out of their natural sequence to keep the volatile respondent from knowing the exact nature of the inquiry and where it is leading."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Hypothetical questions are ideal for potentially volatile interviews because they are less threatening."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Closing Questions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Seek to close the interview positively"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Three main purposes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To reconfirm facts"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "num", "text": "To ensure that the interviewer understood the information that"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the witness provided, they should review the key facts during the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "closing phase of the interview."}, {"type": "num", "text": "The interviewer should not attempt to revisit all the information"}, {"type": "para", "text": "provided by the subject, only the facts that are most relevant."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "To gather additional facts 1. The closing questions should seek to obtain facts previously unknown to provide the respondent with further opportunity to say whatever they want about the present matter."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "To conclude the interview in a manner that maintains goodwill 1. Generally, the interviewer should ask the subject if they believe they have been treated fairly and should obtain permission to call the subject with any additional questions."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Assessment Questions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Designed to establish the respondent’s credibility"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Should be asked when the interviewer has reason to believe the respondent is being deceptive (i.e., when the interviewer considers previous statements by the respondent to be inconsistent because of possible deception)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The interviewer must observe the subject’s verbal and nonverbal responses to assess their credibility."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Establishing a Baseline"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The process of observing behavior before critical questions are asked, as opposed to doing so during questioning"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The best way to establish a baseline with a witness is by asking noncritical questions on background information, place of employment, etc."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Assessment questions, which ask the subject to agree with matters that go against the principles of most honest people, should then be presented; people who seem truthful typically answer one way, and those who seem untruthful generally answer them differently."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "After observing the respondent’s verbal and nonverbal behavior while answering noncritical questions, the interviewer can later compare an interviewee’s behavior during critical questions (if the admission-seeking phase of the interview proceeds) to help determine whether the subject shows signs of potential deception."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Understanding Indicators of Stress"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The human body attempts to relieve the stress of lying through verbal and nonverbal actions, which provide clues to deception."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When evaluating signs of deception, no single behavior should be isolated and no single conclusion should be drawn from it."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Factors to consider when assessing signs of deception"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Signs of stress do not always mean that a subject is lying. 1. Not all stress exhibited during an interview is caused by lying; an honest interview subject might feel stress simply by being asked pointed questions about uncomfortable subjects."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "If the respondent is mentally unstable or under the influence of alcohol or drugs, their behavioral clues are unreliable and they might be unsuitable to interview."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Verbal clues"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Changes in speech patterns 1. Deceptive people often speed up their speech, slow it down, or speak louder. 2. A deceptive person might experience a change in their voice pitch because the vocal cords constrict as a person becomes tense. 3. Deceptive people also tend to cough or clear their throats during times of deception."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Repetition of the question 1. Repeating the question is a means for a deceptive respondent to gain more time to think of what to say."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Comments regarding the interview 1. Deceptive people will often complain about the physical environment of the interview room, such as, “It’s cold in here.” 2. They will also sometimes ask how much longer the interview will take."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Selective memory 1. Deceptive people will have a fine memory for insignificant events, but when it comes to the important facts, they will say something like, “I just can’t seem to remember.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Oaths 1. Dishonest persons frequently use expressions such as “I swear to God,” “Honestly,” “Frankly,” or “To tell the truth” to add credibility to their lies."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Answering with a question 1. Instead of denying the allegations outright, dishonest people are more likely to answer with a question, such as, “Why would I do something like that?”"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Feigned unconcern 1. The dishonest person will often try to appear casual and unconcerned, will frequently adopt an unnatural slouching posture, and might react to questions with nervous or false laughter or feeble attempts at humor."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Nonverbal clues"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Full-body motions 1. When asked sensitive or emotive questions, the dishonest person will sometimes change their posture completely, as if moving away from the interviewer."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Illustrators"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Motions made primarily with the hands that demonstrate points"}, {"type": "num", "text": "During threatening questions, the respondent’s use of illustrators"}, {"type": "para", "text": "might increase or decrease."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Hands over the mouth 1. Dishonest people will commonly cover the mouth with the hand or fingers when being deceptive."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Manipulators 1. Displacement activities that reduce nervousness 2. Include motions like picking lint from clothing, playing with objects such as pencils, or holding one’s hands while talking"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fleeing positions 1. During the interview, dishonest people will often posture themselves in a fleeing position."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The respondent’s head and trunk might be facing the interviewer, but their feet and lower body might be pointing toward the door in an unconscious effort to flee from the interviewer."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Admission-Seeking Questions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Designed to obtain a legal admission of wrongdoing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Normally, the interviewer should ask accusatory or admission-seeking questions when all the following are true:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There is a reasonable probability that the respondent has committed the act in question."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "All other reasonable investigative steps have been completed, and as much information as possible has been developed from other sources."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The interviewer can reasonably control the interview’s location or venue, time, and subject matter."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Three purposes"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To distinguish innocent (non-culpable) individuals from potentially guilty ones"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "To obtain a valid admission of guilt"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "To convince the accused to sign a written statement acknowledging the facts of the case"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Preparing the Interview Room"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The interviewer should consider how private the room is."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The door should be closed but not locked."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There should be no physical barriers preventing the suspect from leaving."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The suspect should be made aware that they are free to leave."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Distractions should be kept to a minimum."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Chairs should be placed about four to six feet apart."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The accused should not be permitted to sit behind any physical barriers."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Presence of Outsiders"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Where allowed by law, no observers, other than the subject and up to two fraud examiners, should be permitted in the admission-seeking interview."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The presence of third parties could have liability consequences."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "General Rules for Conducting Admission-Seeking Interviews"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Convey absolute confidence in the admission-seeking interview."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Only conduct an admission-seeking interview when there is sufficient privacy and when time is not a factor."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Do not express disgust, outrage, or moral condemnation about the accused’s actions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Be firm but also project compassion, understanding, and empathy."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Offer a morally acceptable reason for the accused’s behavior."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Steps in the Admission-Seeking Interview"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Make a direct accusation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The accusation should be made in the form of a statement, not a question."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Avoid emotive words such as steal, fraud, and crime."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The accusation should be phrased as though the accused’s guilt has already been established, trapping the accused with no way out."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Observe the accused’s reaction."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When accused of wrongdoing, guilty individuals often react with silence."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Conversely, innocent people sometimes react with genuine shock at being accused."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "It is not at all unusual for an innocent person, wrongfully accused, to react with anger. In contrast to the guilty individual, the typical innocent person will strongly deny committing the act or acts in question."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Repeat the accusation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If the accused does not strongly object after the accusation is made, the interviewer should repeat the accusation with the same degree of conviction and strength."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Interrupt denials."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Once the accused utters a denial, it might become extremely difficult for them to change their response because doing so would be an admission that they lied."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The interviewer must prevent an outright denial, thereby making it easier for the subject to make an admission of guilt or culpability at a later time."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Techniques for interrupting denials 1. Delays"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Interviewer should not argue with the accused but rather attempt to delay the outright denial: “Ethan, I hear what you are saying, but let me finish first. Then you can talk.” 2. Repeated interruptions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Occasionally, it might be necessary to repeatedly interrupt the accused’s attempted denial: “Carmen, if you keep"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "para", "text": "interrupting, I am going to have to terminate this"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Reasoning"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If delays and repeated interruptions are unsuccessful, the interviewer can attempt to reason with the accused and employ some of the tactics normally used for defusing alibis."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Under these tactics, the accused is presented with implicating evidence. The interviewer, however, normally should not disclose all the facts of the case, but rather reveal small portions incrementally."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Example: “I know what you say, Ethan, but that does not reconcile with these invoices here in front of me. Look at the invoice in the amount of $102,136. The facts clearly show you are responsible.” (Do not ask the accused to explain the evidence at this point.)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Example: “Carmen, I have talked to many people before I sat down here with you. I am not asking you if you are responsible; I know you are. This is your opportunity to tell your side to someone who can understand.” (Do not disclose the identity or number of the witnesses who have been interviewed.)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Establish rationalization."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Try to convince the respondent that confessing is the most advantageous option available."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "To do this, offer a morally acceptable reason that allows the accused to confess to a misdeed without feeling ashamed."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Common themes used to establish rationalization 1. Unfair treatment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The interviewer can attempt to take advantage of the accused’s feelings of unfair treatment and their attempt to achieve equity by suggesting that the accused is a victim. 2. Financial problems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Internal criminals, especially executives and upper management, frequently engage in fraud to conceal their true financial condition—either personal or business. 3. Altruism"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The action was for the benefit of others. Interviewer might say something like, \"I know you didn't do this for yourself. I think you did this to help your spouse, didn't you?\" 4. Depersonalizing the victim"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The accused is better able to cope with the moral dilemma of their actions if the victim is a faceless corporation or agency."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Defuse alibis."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The interviewer must defuse alibis by convincing the accused of the weight of the evidence against them."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Ways to defuse alibis 1. Discuss the testimony of witnesses."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The objective is to give enough information about what other people might say without providing too much."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ideally, the interviewer’s statement will cause the accused to think that people are able to contradict the story that the accused is providing. 2. Discuss the accused’s prior deceptions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The goal is to appeal to the accused’s logic and not to scold or degrade."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "This technique is particularly useful in cases with a lack of physical evidence."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "As with other interview situations, the word lying should be avoided. 3. Display specific evidence."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When a suspect continues to offer a reason why they could not have committed the act in question, fraud examiners should show the suspect a piece of evidence discovered during the investigation, if available, that directly contradicts the suspect’s reason."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Encourage admission using evidence."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "After the interviewer defuses the accused’s alibis, the accused often becomes quiet, withdrawn, or emotional."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "At this point, the interviewer can encourage the suspect that an admission is in their best interest by continuing to reference the evidence obtained during the investigation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Obtain a verbal admission."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Transition to the verbal statement of admission when the accused provides the first detailed information about the offense."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Thereafter, it is the interviewer’s job to probe gently for additional details, including those that would only be known by the subject."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Confirm the general details of the offense before returning to the specifics."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Three basic approaches to obtaining a verbal admission 1. Chronologically 2. By transaction 3. By event"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most fraudsters lie about one or more aspects of the offense; note discrepancies but proceed as though falsehoods have been accepted as truth."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Information to Obtain During the Verbal Admission"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "That the accused knew the conduct was wrong"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Intent is required in all matters involving fraud. The accused not only must have committed the act but also must have intended to commit it."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Facts known only to the subject (estimate of number of instances/amounts)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "These facts include—at a minimum—the accused’s estimates of the number of instances of wrongful conduct and the total amount of money involved."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "It is common for the accused to underestimate the amount of funds involved, as well as the number of instances of misconduct."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Motive for the offense"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Important element of establishing the offense"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Might be the same as the theme the interviewer developed earlier—or it might not"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The most common response is, “I don’t know,” but the interviewer should probe for additional information."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When the offense commenced"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When/if the offense was terminated"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If others were involved"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Physical evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The interviewer should typically ask the accused to voluntarily surrender their banking records for review, if applicable."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Location of assets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The interviewer should ask the accused “What is left?” rather than asking “Is there anything left?”"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "para", "text": "General Rules for Obtaining Signed Statements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There is no legal requirement that a statement must be completely in the handwriting or wording of the declarant."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is better for the fraud examiner to draft the statement."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is recommended to have two people witness the signing."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There should not be more than one written statement for each offense."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Omitted facts can be added later as an addendum to the original statement."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Separate statements should be prepared for unrelated offenses."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "When conducting a routine interview of someone who does not know her, it is usually best for"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Beth, a Certified Fraud Examiner (CFE), to omit her title when introducing herself."}, {"type": "para", "text": "How many interviewers should typically be used in a potentially volatile interview?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Interview Theory and Application"}, {"type": "para", "text": "When preparing a room for an admission-seeking interview, the suspect’s chair should be:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Behind a desk or table"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. About two feet away from the interviewer’s chair"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. As comfortable as possible"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Within full view of the fraud examiner"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Jenkins, a Certified Fraud Examiner (CFE), contacts Smith for the purpose of conducting a"}, {"type": "para", "text": "routine, information-gathering interview. Smith says that she’s happy to talk to Jenkins, but her"}, {"type": "para", "text": "coworker, Billings, really should be there too because he’s been at the company longer. Jenkins"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Conduct the interviews together"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Conduct the interviews separately"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Agree to allow Billings to be present if Smith insists"}], "ai_summary": "[From CFE Workbook] To effectively prepare for the interview phase of an investigation, the fraud examiner must first develop a plan. This might involve: Contemplating what the interview is intended to accomplish"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools", "summary_short": "[From CFE Workbook] Understand the data. 1. As a first step in the planning process—before determining which tests to run—the fraud examiner must know what data are available to be analyzed and how those data are structured. 2. Understanding the existing data’s structure ensures that the fraud examiner builds workable tests to run on the data and helps identify areas for exploration that might otherwise have been overlooked", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "The Data Analysis Process"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Planning phase"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Understand the data. 1. As a first step in the planning process—before determining which tests to run—the fraud examiner must know what data are available to be analyzed and how those data are structured. 2. Understanding the existing data’s structure ensures that the fraud examiner builds workable tests to run on the data and helps identify areas for exploration that might otherwise have been overlooked"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Define examination objectives."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Build a profile of potential frauds. 1. To maximize the potential success of detecting fraud through data analysis, the analysis performed should be based on an understanding of the entity’s existing fraud risks. 2. To do so, the fraud examiner must first build a profile of potential frauds by identifying the organization’s risk areas, the types of frauds possible in those risk areas, and the resulting exposure to those frauds."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Determine whether predication exists."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Preparation phase"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identify the relevant data."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Obtain the data."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Verify the data."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Cleanse and normalize the data."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Depending on how the data were collected and processed, as well"}, {"type": "para", "text": "as the results of the data verification process, the fraud examiner"}, {"type": "para", "text": "might need to cleanse and convert the data to a format suitable"}, {"type": "para", "text": "for analysis before executing any data analysis tests."}, {"type": "num", "text": "For example, certain field formats (e.g., date, time, or currency)"}, {"type": "para", "text": "might need to be modified to make the information consistent"}, {"type": "para", "text": "and ready for testing."}, {"type": "num", "text": "The data must also be normalized so that all data being imported"}, {"type": "para", "text": "for analysis can be analyzed consistently."}, {"type": "num", "text": "Additionally, the following inconsistencies in the data must be"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Known errors"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Special/unreadable characters in the data"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Other unusable entries"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Testing and interpretation phase"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Analyze the data. 1. Run tests. 2. Identify possible indicators of fraud, including unusual trends, anomalies, and control breakdowns."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Address false positives."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Post-analysis phase"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Respond to the analysis findings."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Monitor the data."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Core Data Analysis Software Functions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Sorting"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Arranges data in a meaningful order so users can quickly determine what is important"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Data Sorted by Invoice Number"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Data Sorted by Amount"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Joining files"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Combines fields from two sorted input files into a third file"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Used to match data in a transaction file to records in a master file, such as matching invoice data in an accounts receivable file to a master list of approved vendors File 1"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The JOINED Exception File"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Correlation analysis"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Used to determine the relationships among different variables in raw data Independent Variable"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Number of days traveling"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Number of documents printed"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Number of houses built"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Compliance verification"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Determines whether company policies are met by employee transactions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Duplicate testing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Used to identify transactions with duplicate values in specified fields"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Gap tests"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Used to identify missing items in a sequence or series"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Benford’s Law analysis"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Provides that the distribution of the digits in multi-digit natural numbers is not random; instead, it follows a predictable pattern"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Requires distinguishing between natural and non-natural numbers 1. Natural numbers are those numbers that are not ordered in a particular numbering scheme and are not human-generated or generated from a random number system. 2. Non-natural numbers are designed systematically to convey information that restricts the natural nature of the number (e.g., employee identification numbers and telephone numbers). 3. Benford’s Law cannot be applied to data sets with non-natural numbers."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Maintains that when natural numbers are present, certain digits show up more than others do 1. A 1 appears as the first non-zero digit roughly 30% of the time; 2 is the leading digit almost 18% of the time; and 9 leads only 4.6% of the time. 2. 0 is most likely to be the second digit, appearing 12% of the time."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The goal is to identify potentially fictitious numbers based on those that do not conform to Benford’s Law. First"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Structured vs. Unstructured Data"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Structured data are the type of data found in a database, consisting of recognizable and predictable structures."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unstructured data, by contrast, are data not found in a traditional spreadsheet or database, such as email and social media activity."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Advanced Data Analytics"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Advanced analytic methods examine large amounts of data using sophisticated techniques that go beyond traditional data analysis to generate new information, recognize patterns, and predict precise outcomes."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common types include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Artificial intelligence 1. Refers to computer systems that perform human tasks, such as visual perception and decision-making 2. Includes a subset known as machine learning, which is a learning algorithm that enables programs to identify patterns and outliers in large data sets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "With supervised machine learning, humans identify patterns for the programs to look for in data sets, and the programs identify any data that fit the patterns."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "With unsupervised machine learning, a program identifies similarities, patterns, or anomalies within a data set without the involvement of a human."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "With deep learning, layered artificial neural networks (i.e., systems that simulate the processes and functions of a brain) are used to accommodate more data and more sophisticated algorithms to identify complex patterns."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Predictive analytics 1. Uses historical data, analyses, statistics, and machine learning components to build a mathematical model that depicts important trends and creates a quantitative projection or prediction about future events or outcomes"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Robotic process automation (RPA) 1. A technology that allows for the configuration of a program that imitates and integrates the actions of a human to execute certain business processes"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Data Analysis Queries"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Accounts payable"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Audit paid invoices for manual comparison with actual invoices."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Summarize large invoices by amount, vendor, etc."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Identify debits to expense accounts outside of set default accounts."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reconcile payment registers to disbursements by vendor invoice."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Verify vendor tax forms (e.g., U.S. Form 1099 or value-added tax [VAT] forms)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Create vendor detail and summary analysis reports."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Review recurring monthly expenses and compare to posted/paid invoices."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Generate a report on specified vouchers for manual audit or investigation."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Textual Analytics"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A method of using software to extract usable information from unstructured text data"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Sources of unstructured data 1. Emails 2. Journal entry explanations 3. Social media posts and comments"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Instant messages and chat logs"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Videos"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Voice files"}, {"type": "num", "text": "User documents"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Mobile phone software applications"}, {"type": "num", "text": "News feeds"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Sales and marketing material"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Presentations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Can be used to categorize unstructured data to reveal patterns, sentiments, and relationships that are indicative of fraud through the application of linguistic technologies and statistical techniques"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Provides the ability to uncover warning signs of potentially fraudulent employee behavior"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "For example, an analysis of email communications might help fraud examiners to gauge the pressures/incentives, opportunities, and rationalizations to commit fraud that exist in an organization."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Pressure 1. Many people commit fraud because of something that has happened in their life that motivates them to steal, such as finding themselves in debt or needing to meet a certain goal to qualify for a performance-based bonus. 2. Keywords that might indicate pressure include deadline, quota, short, problem, and concern."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Opportunity 1. Think of words that would indicate someone has the opportunity or ability to commit fraud. 2. Keywords that might indicate opportunity include override, write off, recognize revenue, adjust, discount, and reserve/provision."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Rationalization 1. Most fraudsters do not have a criminal background. Therefore, justifying their actions is a key part of committing fraud. 2. Keywords that might indicate a fraudster is rationalizing their actions include reasonable, deserve, and temporary."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Visual Analytics"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Link analysis"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Visual representations (e.g., charts with lines showing connections) of data from multiple data sources to track the movement of money; demonstrate complex networks; and discover communications, patterns, trends, and relationships"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Very effective for identifying relationships that are not closely related and is particularly useful when investigating money laundering or fictitious vendor (shell company) schemes"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Alpha, a fraud examiner, believes that vendors might be submitting invoices twice in the hope"}, {"type": "para", "text": "that they will be paid multiple times. Which of the following data analysis functions would be"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the easiest way to identify such invoices?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Benford’s Law analysis"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Correlation analysis"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Black, a fraud examiner, is conducting textual analytics on emails sent to and from specific"}, {"type": "para", "text": "employees that her client has identified as fraud suspects. She is using the Fraud Triangle to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "create a list of fraud keywords to use in her search. Which of the following words found in"}, {"type": "para", "text": "email text might indicate a fraudster is rationalizing their actions?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Data Analysis and Reporting Tools"}, {"type": "para", "text": "When conducting a data analysis engagement to detect fraud, it is important to build a profile"}, {"type": "para", "text": "of potential frauds before identifying, obtaining, and analyzing the data."}], "ai_summary": "[From CFE Workbook] Understand the data. 1. As a first step in the planning process—before determining which tests to run—the fraud examiner must know what data are available to be analyzed and how those data are structured. 2. Understanding the existing data’s structure ensures that the fraud examiner builds workable tests to run on the data and helps identify areas for exploration that might otherwise have been overlooked"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Tracing Illicit Transactions", "summary_short": "Send and accept payments from any user in the world with an internet connection for Send or accept payments without the need for any identifying information (other than the Conduct transactions in unlimited volume (assuming funds are available).", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "What Is Tracing?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The search for evidence for the purpose of showing what has happened to property, identifying the proceeds of property, and identifying those who have handled or received property or the proceeds of property"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Might be undertaken to assist:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A victim of fraud who wants a tracing search to facilitate the recovery of criminal proceeds"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A potential plaintiff who wants a tracing search to determine if the potential defendant can pay a court-ordered sum if a judgment is ordered"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A judgment creditor who needs to identify the judgment debtor’s assets"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Direct Approach to Tracing Financial Transactions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employs direct evidence of the subject’s books and records (or financial transaction records belonging to third parties) to analyze the relationship between a suspect’s receipt and subsequent disposition of funds or assets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Contrasts with the indirect approach, which relies on circumstantial proof"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Requires access to the subject’s financial records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves tracing funds the subject used to purchase assets or make deposits back to the source"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using Records from Financial Institutions for Tracing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Records from financial institutions are perhaps the single most important financial source available to a fraud examiner for tracing purposes."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Can be used to:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identify witnesses and other evidence."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Uncover criminal profits."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Identify criminal assets."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Locate assets that can be used to satisfy a judgment."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Tracing Illicit Transactions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identify locations where assets are stored."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Determine the lifestyle of an account holder."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Determine the financial health of an organization."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Determine the source of funds placed into the account."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Determine the use of the funds from the account."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using Wire Transfers for Tracing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Wire transfer records might contain evidence that money has been moved abroad."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Information contained on most wire transfers:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The amount of the transfer"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The date of the transfer"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The purpose of the transfer"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The name of the sender or originator"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The routing number of the originating bank or financial institution"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The identity of the designated beneficiary or receiver of the funds"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The routing number of the recipient bank"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using Correspondent Banking Records for Tracing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A correspondent banking relationship is generally defined as an arrangement in which one bank maintains a correspondent account at another bank for the purpose of settling transactions for itself or its customers (i.e., one financial institution has the authority to provide certain financial services on another institution’s behalf)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A foreign correspondent relationship involves a correspondent banking relationship between foreign and domestic institutions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Due to risks of illicit transactions, such as money laundering, most jurisdictions require financial institutions to obtain information from other financial institutions with which they maintain a foreign correspondent relationship, such as:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Tracing Illicit Transactions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The institution’s ownership details"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The identities of agents authorized to conduct business on the institution’s behalf"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The institution’s anti-money laundering (AML) and know-your-customer (KYC) processes"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The institution’s licenses or certifications"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using Electronic Payment Records for Tracing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The term electronic payments (or e-payments) refers to any type of noncash payment that does not involve a paper check."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Records of these transactions can reveal:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Assets the subject has purchased"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The locations of the subject’s assets"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The locations of the subject’s residences and businesses"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Loans the subject has obtained"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Payments made to nonexistent employees with direct deposit"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The cities and countries in which the subject conducts business"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Transfers of funds between individuals without an established business relationship"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Assets ostensibly owned by family members or close associates but effectively controlled, held, or gifted by the subject"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Hotel payments"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The true owner of a property"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The absence of a recurring payment might indicate a cash payment or payment of an expense by a third party, which in turn could suggest possible undisclosed source income."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using Loan Records for Tracing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When a bank makes a commercial loan to an individual, it requires detailed statements of assets and liabilities from the borrower."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Tracing Illicit Transactions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The loan file might also include the results of credit inquiries regarding paying habits, loan amounts, and present unpaid balances."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Loan records generally maintained by a bank credit department include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The credit or loan file 1. Includes the customer’s loan application, financial statements, and general economic history"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The liability ledger 1. Contains the customer’s past and present liability to the bank"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The collateral file 1. Contains a complete description of the items pledged as security for loans"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If a fraud examination involves a loan with proceeds that have been disposed, the fraud examiner should trace the disposition of the loan’s proceeds."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Tracing loan proceeds helps determine if hidden accounts were used for loan payments and whether proceeds were deposited into hidden accounts; it can also be used to uncover hidden assets or unknown witnesses."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Tracing loan proceeds helps determine whether a subject took out a loan for someone else."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners should also trace the source of loan payments for leads."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using Credit Card Records for Tracing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Credit card records might show card purchasing limits, previous payment history, account balance, when and where the subject has traveled, and assets the subject has acquired."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "These records show the movements and habits of the person to whom the records pertain."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Credit card statements contain the name of the credit card issuer, the cardholder’s account number, a summary of the transactions on the account,"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Tracing Illicit Transactions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "payment information, and a list of all the transactions that occurred during that"}, {"type": "para", "text": "month’s billing cycle."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Credit card charges might provide leads to identifying hidden assets."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Indirect Approach to Tracing Financial Transactions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In contrast to the direct approach method, which relies on specific transactions, the indirect approach relies on circumstantial proof."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An indirect analysis can reveal that a suspect has more money available or has acquired more assets than can be accounted for from legitimate sources."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Two of the basic approaches that use circumstantial proof to prove a subject’s sources of funds are the asset method (net worth) and the expenditures (source and application of funds) method."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using the Asset and Expenditures Methods to Examine Sources of Income"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The asset method"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Use when the subject has invested illegal funds to accumulate wealth and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "acquire assets or pay down debts, causing their net worth (the difference"}, {"type": "para", "text": "between a person’s assets and liabilities at a particular point in time) to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "increase from year to year."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Prior year’s net worth"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Income (or expenditures)"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Funds from known sources"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Funds from unknown sources"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When using the asset method: 1. Value assets at historical cost."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Tracing Illicit Transactions"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Estimate funds available from legitimate sources generously."}, {"type": "num", "text": "Estimate expenditures conservatively."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The expenditures method"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When the subject spends illicit income on consumables (e.g., travel and entertainment), use this method because the illicit income will not cause an increase in net worth."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When using the expenditures method: 1. Establish the subject’s known expenditures for the relevant year. Expenditures include the use or application of funds for any purpose, including deposits to bank accounts, purchase of major assets, travel and entertainment expenses, and payment on debts. 2. Identify all sources of funds available to the subject, including loans and gifts, as well as cash on hand from previous years 3. Compare the suspect’s known expenditures and known sources of funds during a given period of time. 4. If the suspect’s spending exceeded the known income sources, unaccounted-for funds might be inferred to come from illicit or hidden income. Expenditures (application of funds)"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "–"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Funds from known sources"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Funds from unknown sources"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Locating Hidden Assets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Asset hiders usually conceal assets in financial products that are:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Liquid"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Untraceable"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Secure"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Accessible"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Tracing Illicit Transactions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Financial products are used to obscure links between the initial receipt of the assets and their final disposition."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common ways fraudsters hide assets include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Hiding assets in someone else’s name (e.g., the name of a spouse, other relative, friend, business partner)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Prepaying on a home mortgage"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Using as'sets to pay down debt (e.g., mortgages, credit card balances)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Transferring assets into tax havens"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Transferring assets into trusts (particularly foreign trusts/asset protection trusts)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Using assets to purchase insurance products (e.g., life insurance policies with cash surrender value)"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Locating Assets Hidden Through Cryptocurrency"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cryptocurrency is a type of digital currency that uses public or private key encryption in the currency’s creation and transfer."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "While cryptocurrency transactions can be difficult and complicated to trace, most cryptocurrencies rely on public blockchains (digital ledgers, or databases, of transactions that allow data to be distributed and stored on multiple computer systems at once) that provide visibility into every transaction that takes place."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Blockchain entries do not include direct identifying information, but they do contain senders’ and recipients’ cryptographic addresses for each transaction."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Therefore, by carefully examining blockchain data, fraud examiners can identify patterns that link certain users to criminal activity."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cryptocurrencies are stored and transmitted through digital wallets, which act as financial accounts that securely hold and organize a user’s payment information, passwords, and transaction history."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many digital wallet providers now record identifying information about their clients that can be useful in tracing efforts."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Tracing Illicit Transactions"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Due to money laundering risks associated with cryptocurrencies, most jurisdictions require cryptocurrency exchanges, digital wallet providers, and cryptocurrency automated teller machine (ATM) operators to comply with customer due diligence (CDD) or know-your-customer (KYC) regulations. 1. These requirements generally involve recording personal information about clientele, such as name, date of birth, or address."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners who believe a suspect might be hiding illicit proceeds through cryptocurrency ownership can potentially identify cryptocurrency assets held by subjects through:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Analysis of bank statements that feature transactions involving currency exchanges"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Statements made by investigation subjects on social media or in casual conversation with friends, family members, or colleagues"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Court orders targeting cryptocurrency exchanges, digital wallet providers, and cryptocurrency ATM operators"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Asset Recovery"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Once fraud has been documented and the associated illicit transactions have been traced, victims might want to pursue recovery of assets."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A fraud examiner must often be able to evaluate the potential for asset recovery due to the fact that fraudsters often spend most, if not all, of their ill-gotten gains, leaving little to recover."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The following questions should be considered before commencing a legal action to recover assets:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Are there nonlegal recovery methods or remedies available?"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Will the case be referred for criminal prosecution?"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Do one of more defendants have sufficient property or money to satisfy a money judgment?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Tracing Illicit Transactions"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Are pretrial attachment procedures available and should they be invoked to protect and ensure the plaintiff’s ability to satisfy a money judgment at a later time?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Tracing Illicit Transactions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is a common method that fraudsters use to hide their ill-gotten gains?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Prepaying a home mortgage"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Purchasing a life insurance policy"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Transferring assets into foreign trusts"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The expenditures method (also known as the sources and application of funds method) for"}, {"type": "para", "text": "proving illicit income involves identifying all assets held by the subject that were acquired"}, {"type": "para", "text": "earlier, identifying the amount of the subject’s current liabilities, and taking the difference"}, {"type": "para", "text": "between the two values."}], "ai_summary": "Send and accept payments from any user in the world with an internet connection for Send or accept payments without the need for any identifying information (other than the Conduct transactions in unlimited volume (assuming funds are available)."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination", "summary_short": "[From CFE Workbook] The process of resolving allegations of fraud from inception to disposition The primary function of the anti-fraud professional", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "What Is Fraud Examination?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The process of resolving allegations of fraud from inception to disposition"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The primary function of the anti-fraud professional"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Tasks involved:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Obtaining evidence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reporting"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Testifying to findings"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Assisting in fraud detection and prevention"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Fraud Examination Methodology"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Assume litigation will follow."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Each fraud examination should be conducted with the assumption that the case will result in legal proceedings."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "This assumption will ensure that the fraud examiner maintains compliance with the proper rules of evidence and remains well within the guidelines established by the legal systems."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Act on predication."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examinations should not be conducted without proper predication—the totality of circumstances that would lead a reasonable, professionally trained, and prudent individual to believe that a fraud has occurred, is occurring, or will occur."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Predication is the basis upon which a fraud examination is commenced."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Begin with the general before moving to the specific."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examinations should begin with general information that is known and then transition to details that are more specific."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Usual order of interviews"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Neutral third-party witnesses, starting with the least"}, {"type": "para", "text": "knowledgeable and moving to those who are more"}, {"type": "para", "text": "knowledgeable about the matters at issue"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Parties suspected of complicity, starting with the least culpable"}, {"type": "para", "text": "and moving to the most culpable"}, {"type": "num", "text": "The primary suspect(s) of the examination"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Use the fraud theory approach."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fraud theory approach is an investigative framework designed to help organize and direct fraud examinations based on the information available at the time."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Four steps 1. Analyze available data. 2. Create a hypothesis. 3. Test the hypothesis. 4. Refine and amend the hypothesis."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Develop a Fraud Response Plan"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A fraud response plan details the actions that members of an organization will take when suspicions of fraud arise."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Because every fraud is different, response plans should not specify how all fraud examinations should be conducted; instead, such plans should help organizations manage their responses and create environments that minimize risk and maximize the potential for success."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A response plan allows management to respond to suspected and detected incidents of fraud in a consistent and comprehensive manner."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Having a response plan in place sends a message that management takes fraud seriously."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Elements of a fraud response plan"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Reporting protocols"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A response team responsible for conducting an initial assessment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Factors used to determine the course of action"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Litigation hold procedures"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Principles for documenting the response plan"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A template or form to report fraud incidents"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Planning and Conducting a Formal Investigation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Assemble an investigation team."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To determine who should be involved in the investigation, management must identify the needed skills."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "It is critical to identify those who can legitimately assist in the investigation and have a legitimate interest in its outcome."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A successful fraud examination also depends on the individual team members’ characteristics that facilitate team interaction and functioning."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Common types of professionals to include 1. CFEs 2. Legal counsel 3. Local international counsel 4. Accountants or auditors (internal or external) 5. Forensic accounting investigators 6. Audit committee members 7. Security personnel 8. Human resources (HR) personnel 9. A management representative 10. IT personnel 11. Digital forensic experts 12. Data analysis specialists 13. External consultants 14. Industry specialists"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Develop an investigation plan."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When developing an investigation plan, those responsible should: 1. Review what is known and gain a basic understanding of key issues. 2. Define the goals of the investigation. 3. Identify whom to keep informed. 4. Determine the scope of the investigation. 5. Establish the investigation’s time frame. 6. Assess the need for law enforcement assistance or notification. 7. Define members’ roles and assign tasks. 8. Address operational issues. 9. Outline the course of action. 10. Adapt the necessary resources to conduct an investigation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Prepare the organization for the investigation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Prepare the managers of the employees who will be involved in the investigation, especially if they do not know about the issue."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Notify the following parties when the investigation is about to begin: 1. Key decision-makers 2. In-house or outside counsel"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Structure the Investigation to Preserve Confidentiality"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Failure to preserve confidentiality could compromise an entire investigation and make employees reluctant to report future incidents."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To help preserve confidentiality, team members should:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Avoid alerting the suspected fraudsters. 1. Know who is being investigated and what they can access. 2. Limit the extent of any discussions. 3. Inform only those who need to know. 4. Inform employees of the consequences of a confidentiality breach."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Work discreetly without disrupting the office’s normal course of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "business so that employees do not know that an investigation is"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Work fast."}, {"type": "num", "text": "Investigate during nonbusiness hours."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Request participants’ confidentiality. 1. Remind participants to refrain from discussion."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Guard case information. 1. Store all confidential documents in locked file cabinets or rooms accessible only to those who have a need to know. 2. Clear desks of any case information before stepping away. 3. Avoid talking about the investigation in public or in any place where other employees can hear the communications. 4. Avoid using email or other electronic means (e.g., text messages or instant messages) to transmit confidential case information."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Consider conducting the investigation under any applicable evidentiary privileges or protections."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Carter, a Certified Fraud Examiner (CFE) for Universal Design, learns that Wendi, a shrewd"}, {"type": "para", "text": "salesperson with a reputation for bending or ignoring rules, has close relationships with several"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Universal Design customers. Carter also knows that Wendi has excessive gambling habits."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Carter has sufficient predication to:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Accuse Wendi directly of having committed fraud."}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Alert management that Wendi might have committed fraud."}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Check Wendi’s phone, computer, and messages for evidence of wrongdoing."}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Conduct discreet inquiries about Wendi’s work as a salesperson."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is the MOST ACCURATE statement about a fraud investigation plan?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. An investigation plan should inform employees at all levels about the investigation."}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. An investigation plan should establish the investigation’s time frame."}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. An investigation plan should establish which individuals violated the law."}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. An investigation plan should make a commitment to eradicate the fraudulent activity."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Planning and Conducting a Fraud Examination"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is INCORRECT regarding fraud response plans?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. A fraud response plan should be complex and extremely detailed to ensure its"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. A fraud response plan should take both previous fraud cases and industry-related risks"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. A fraud response plan should be flexible and allow appropriate responses based on the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. A fraud response plan should create an environment that minimizes risk and maximizes"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the potential for success."}], "ai_summary": "[From CFE Workbook] The process of resolving allegations of fraud from inception to disposition The primary function of the anti-fraud professional"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Digital Forensics", "summary_short": "[From CFE Workbook] Digital forensic experts can recover, among other things, the following types of information from computer systems: Deleted files and other data that have not been overwritten (e.g., deleted documents, images, link or shortcut files, and email messages)", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Recovering Data"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Digital forensic experts can recover, among other things, the following types of information from computer systems:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Deleted files and other data that have not been overwritten (e.g., deleted documents, images, link or shortcut files, and email messages)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Files deleted through computer-automated processes"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Temporary auto-save files"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Print-spool files"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Websites visited, even where the browser history and cache have been deleted"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Communications sent via email, chat, or instant message (IM)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Financial-based internet transactions"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Documents, letters, and images created, modified, or accessed, even if the data were not saved on the computer"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Data that have been copied, corrupted, or moved"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The time and date information about files (e.g., when files were created, accessed, modified, installed, deleted, or downloaded)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Data from a drive that has been defragmented or reformatted"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Hidden files"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Volatility of Digital Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Digital evidence is more volatile than tangible evidence because data can be altered or destroyed more easily than tangible information."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Digital information can be altered by seemingly harmless actions, such as shutting down a running system, starting up a system, or looking through files on a running computer."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Data that have been altered or destroyed have had their data integrity violated, and once the integrity of digital evidence has been violated, it usually cannot be restored."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Digital evidence that is destroyed when litigation is expected, or in progress, might give rise to claims of spoliation—intentionally or negligently destroying documents relevant to litigation—of evidence."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If litigation occurs, the failure to preserve the integrity of digital evidence could result in evidence being deemed inadmissible in a legal proceeding or, even if admitted, not being given much weight due to questionable authenticity. It could also result in fines or sanctions for failure to properly preserve the evidence."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The rules regarding the admissibility of digital evidence in court are no different from those pertaining to the admissibility of any other type of evidence."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Computer System Files to Be Recovered"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "User-created files"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Created under the user’s direction"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Include text-based documents, spreadsheets, databases, emails, address books, presentation slides, audio/video files, image files, and internet bookmarks."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Computer-created files"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Evidence might also be found in information generated by a computer’s operating system."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Common examples of computer-generated data 1. Metadata"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Files that contain information about who wrote a document; who received, opened, copied, edited, moved, or printed the document; and when these events occurred 2. Registry"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Event logs"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Record events or transactions on a computer. 4. System logs"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Record events executed on an operating system, including those generated during system start-up. 5. Internet activity 6. Temporary files"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Show websites that were recently visited and images previously viewed online. 7. Deleted data"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Places to Search for Digital Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Printers"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many printers have internal hard drives or other storage mechanisms that can contain information relevant to a fraud examination."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "In general, any information sent to and stored by a printer is recoverable unless the printer has overwritten the data."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When seizing a computer for forensic analysis, it is generally necessary to seize any printers connected to it."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Copiers, scanners, and multifunction devices"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many modern copiers have a hard drive that stores images of documents the machines have copied, scanned, or emailed."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "As with most file systems, it might be possible to retrieve deleted information."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When seizing a computer for forensic analysis, it is generally necessary to seize any copiers and scanners connected to it"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fax machines"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Backup devices"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Removable storage devices"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "CD-ROMs, DVDs, USB flash drives, external hard drives, mp3 players, and various other devices provide users with the ability to store large"}, {"type": "para", "text": "amounts of data and files that go undetected by anyone accessing the"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Smartphones"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Mobile phones that can be used to store personal data, search the internet, check email, send messages via IM, make video calls, download/upload content to and from the internet, take pictures, and record video"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Digital Forensic Investigation Phases"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Planning"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves taking steps to help ensure that the evidence will be admissible 1. Determine whether there are any privacy issues in the item(s) to be searched. 2. Determine appropriate procedures for any remote evidence collection. 3. Make appropriate preparations if the investigation involves the use of a legal order. 4. Ensure that all equipment used in a forensic capacity is legitimate and reliable. 5. Ensure that only trained professionals use any digital forensic tools during an engagement and that the equipment is employed in the manner for which it was designed."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Seizing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves ensuring that all relevant evidence is seized and secured in a forensically sound manner so that the evidence is not tainted or destroyed"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "To ensure that a machine can be fully analyzed, the fraud examiner should adhere to the following practices: 1. Examine and document the machine’s surroundings."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Document the scene with photographs or a diagram."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Look around for notes that might appear to be passwords since many people write down or record their passwords near their computers. 2. If the computer is off, leave it off. 3. Consider collecting volatile data “live.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves collecting evidence from a suspect system while the system is open and running via its normal interface 4. If the computer is on, do not turn off the system using normal shutdown routines. 5. Do not look through the files."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Evidence on a running computer can be altered by seemingly harmless actions (e.g., time stamps change when a file is touched)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Imaging"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves using a standalone hard drive duplicator or similar device to make a duplicate or exact copy of a hard drive or other digital media"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Allows a fraud examiner to view and analyze a computer’s contents without altering the original data in any way, as analysis should not be performed directly on suspect devices"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Steps 1. Acquire the original storage media. 2. Create the forensic image of the original storage media. 3. Verify the image of the original storage media."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Processing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves processing and filtering the digital information to reduce the amount of data that has been collected by identifying relevant information and by setting aside duplicates and other information that is not relevant due to its type, origin, or date"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Methods for filtering large amounts of data"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Keyword searches"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Deduplication filtering"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Date-range filtering"}, {"type": "num", "text": "File-type filtering"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Analyzing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves the use of specialized software designed to identify, extract, collect, examine, and store digital artifacts that will be used as evidence in the investigation"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "It is best to use a combination of the various analytical review tools during the analysis phase, which allows for the identification and recovery of more information."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The fraud examiner should look for inculpatory evidence (i.e., evidence that serves to incriminate the subject of the investigation) and exculpatory evidence (i.e., evidence that serves to disprove the subject’s involvement in the misconduct)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The primary concern when analyzing digital data is to always maintain the data’s integrity."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Reporting and testifying"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves reporting the results of the analysis process fairly and objectively"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Challenges of Cloud Forensics"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A lack of frameworks and specialist tools"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A lack of information accessibility (no physical access)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A lack of data control"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A lack of knowledge"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Jurisdiction of storage"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Electronic discovery"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Preserving chain of custody"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Resource sharing"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "If you are seizing a computer for forensic analysis, it is generally unnecessary to seize any"}, {"type": "para", "text": "printers and copiers connected to it."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding the types of information that digital forensic experts"}, {"type": "para", "text": "can typically recover from computer systems?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Digital forensic experts can recover information about websites that were visited on the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Digital forensic experts can recover time and date information about files, such as when"}, {"type": "para", "text": "they were created or modified"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Digital forensic experts can recover deleted emails, link files, and documents"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Turning on a computer has little effect on the files contained on the computer system."}], "ai_summary": "[From CFE Workbook] Digital forensic experts can recover, among other things, the following types of information from computer systems: Deleted files and other data that have not been overwritten (e.g., deleted documents, images, link or shortcut files, and email messages)"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Report Writing", "summary_short": "[From CFE Workbook] Types of Reports Created by Fraud Examiners Documents the results of a fraud examination", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Reports Created by Fraud Examiners"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examination report"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Documents the results of a fraud examination"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Conveys all evidence necessary to evaluate the case"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Can be used to support previously known facts"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Adds credibility to the fraud examiner and their work"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Expert report"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Written by fraud examiners who serve as expert witnesses"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Informs the parties, the judge, and the jury (if applicable) about the expert’s opinion of the case, as well as the expert’s credibility for commenting on such issues"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Characteristics of a Good Report"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Accuracy"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Inaccuracies damage the credibility of the report and the report’s author."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Clarity"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Convey pertinent information in the clearest possible language."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Convey only objective facts."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Avoid jargon."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Impartiality and relevance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Report all relevant facts without bias, regardless of which side a particular fact favors or what it proves or disproves."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Include only those matters that are relevant to the examination."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Timeliness"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The timeliness of reports and the information they contain enhances the accuracy of witness testimony."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "All interviews should be documented in a memorandum of interview as soon as possible after the questioning—preferably on the same day of the interview—to ensure the inclusion of more accurate information when assembling the final report."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Attachments"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Copies of important documents can be included in the report, but do not include originals."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Rules for Including Conclusions and Opinions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Conclusions should be self-evident and do not need to be pointed out."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Opinions regarding guilt or innocence are not allowed."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Opinions regarding technical matters are permitted if the fraud examiner is qualified as an expert in the matter being considered."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners should not include any statement of opinion as to the integrity or veracity of any witness."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Analyzing the Reader of Fraud Examination Reports"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fraud examination report should be prepared with the expectation that it will likely be read by the general public and adverse parties."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Other potential readers include company insiders, attorneys, defendants and witnesses, media outlets, and judges or juries."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A fraud examination should provide a full understanding of the investigation and its findings without the need for additional clarification."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Suggested Structure for Fraud Examination Reports"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Background"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Executive summary"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Scope"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Approach"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Findings"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Summary"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Impact"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Follow-up/recommendations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally an optional section in a written fraud examination report"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Identifies any aspect of the investigation that remains outstanding"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "States what action is necessary or recommended for an organization to take, including remedial measures such as a review of internal controls, the introduction of a fraud reporting system, or an increase in security"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Might include recommendations related to the organization’s procedures and controls; however, it is better for fraud examiners to convey recommendations related to flawed internal controls or organizational failings to management in person or in a separate document"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "If, during a fraud examination, a Certified Fraud Examiner (CFE) obtains a written admission of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "guilt from the suspect, it is permissible to indicate in the written report that the suspect is guilty"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is a function of a fraud examination report?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. To convey all the evidence necessary for parties to evaluate the case"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. To document the results of the fraud examination"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. To add credibility to the fraud examination and the fraud examiner’s work"}], "ai_summary": "[From CFE Workbook] Types of Reports Created by Fraud Examiners Documents the results of a fraud examination"}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Sources of Information", "summary_short": "[From CFE Workbook] Generated and kept within the subject organization Are often the only resource for certain types of documents, such as accounting and business tax records, copies of canceled checks, or employee personnel files, unless the fraud examiner secures the subject’s consent or a legal order to obtain those documents from other parties.", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Internal Sources"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generated and kept within the subject organization"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Are often the only resource for certain types of documents, such as accounting and business tax records, copies of canceled checks, or employee personnel files, unless the fraud examiner secures the subject’s consent or a legal order to obtain those documents from other parties."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "External Sources"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Used to:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Locate missing assets."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Locate witnesses and suspects."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Determine ownership in vendors, competitors, and other related parties."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Research the suspects’ assets and financial condition."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Document suspects’ lifestyle and background information."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Public Records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Documents that a governmental agency is required to keep by law or that are necessary to discharge the duties imposed by law"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Can supply invaluable background information on entities, employees, suspects, and witnesses"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Can be used to corroborate or refute witness statements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Can help investigators track the flow of stolen money or other assets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Can aid in efforts to recover losses"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Local Records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Building inspector records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Building permit records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Health and fire department records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Birth and death records"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Public school records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Coroner’s register"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Voter registration records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Utility records i."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Marriage records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Court records (civil and criminal) are typically maintained by a clerk or administrative office of the court that heard the case."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is rare for there to be a central public database that maintains all court records at every level of a jurisdiction, and there are no parties that maintain a comprehensive database of court records on a global basis."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Types include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Civil court records, which might include: 1. Personal injury suit records 2. Financial suit records 3. Divorce records"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Criminal court records"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Probate records 1. May show claims against the estate and the dispersal of assets after a subject’s death, including:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Names of individuals with an interest in the deceased’s estate"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The subject’s financial position at the time of death"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The names and addresses of heirs to the deceased"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Some indication of the value of the property willed to them"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Bankruptcy records"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Property Records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Real property records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most jurisdictions have a land registry office that maintains various information on real property and its owner(s), such as deeds, grants, and transfers and mortgages of real estate."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Both the level of government where these records are found and the information the records contain vary by jurisdiction."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Property tax records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many jurisdictions assess property taxes and require parties that purchase real estate to register as taxpayers with the jurisdiction’s property tax records system."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "There might also be a tax assessor who keeps records on real property and owners of such property. 1. These records can provide:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An idea of the estimated value, for tax purposes, of the property listed"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The identity of the owner of a vacant piece of land or a piece of property"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The name of the last person to pay taxes on the property"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Legal descriptions of property"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Delinquency status of taxes f."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Names of former property owners"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Business (Corporate) Filings"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most jurisdictions require business entities to file various types of records that contain information useful in a fraud examination, including:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Organizational filings 1. If an individual wants to conduct business in a name other than their own, the law requires that they file documents, such as an organizational filing, to claim ownership of that name."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Organizational filings usually include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Corporate name"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ownership information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Names of initial shareholders"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Names of the directors and officers"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Location of the principal office"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Date of incorporation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Standing/status"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Tax-related filings 1. Generally, tax records, including tax returns, are private, but it is sometimes possible to obtain tax information."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In general, publicly traded companies must file regular statements with government securities agencies; if made public, such records can provide information on a company’s tax filings."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Law enforcement officials might be able to gain access to corporate, business, and personal tax returns."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Some tax revenue departments require certain businesses to obtain licenses or permits (e.g., a sales tax permit) that are often public record."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Other sources of corporate filings include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Regulatory securities records 1. Companies with publicly traded securities generally have rules designed to make sure that investors are reasonably informed about stock they purchase through various disclosures. 2. Different securities regulators have varying disclosure requirements, but these records might include the following information:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Corporate financial statements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identification of officers and directors"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identification of significant owners (e.g., those with more than 10% of a business’s stock)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A description of the registrant’s properties and businesses"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A description of the significant provisions of the security to be offered for sale and its relationship to the registrant’s other capital securities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identification of events of interest to investors"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identification of accountants and attorneys"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A history of the business"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Nonpublic Records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Information about a person or business considered to be private and confidential"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Might be difficult or impossible to obtain because fraud examiners do not have an absolute right to see these personal records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The government usually will not share nonpublic records with a fraud victim during an investigation into the underlying fraud."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Types of nonpublic records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Banking records 1. Can be obtained through:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Consent from the individual to whom the records pertain"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A subpoena or other legal processes, such as depositions, interrogations, and document requests, if a legal action is filed"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A search warrant (although search warrants are only available to law enforcement)"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Tax records 1. Might provide indirect evidence of illicit payments, such as profits or losses from hidden business ventures or interest and dividends on hidden investments 2. Government investigators generally have broader access to these documents while private parties must usually obtain the subject’s consent or take legal action to obtain them."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Credit records of individuals 1. Some jurisdictions regulate how consumer credit information is collected and stored, as well as who may access it and for what purpose. Generally, in such jurisdictions:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Individuals must be notified and consent to the use of their consumer credit records and personal data."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A fraud examiner needs a legally acceptable reason for accessing this information from third parties—simply suspecting an individual of fraud is generally insufficient grounds. 2. Exceptions for allowing the processing and dissemination of credit and personal data typically include circumstances in which:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The individual has given consent."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is necessary for the extension of credit or to enter into a contract with the subject."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is necessary to protect the subject’s vital interest."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is necessary to comply with other legal requirements."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An employer is conducting a background check for hiring or other employment purposes. (Consent is still required in many jurisdictions.)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is necessary to serve the public interest."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Phone records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Credit card account records"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Personal health care records"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Internet service provider (ISP) records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Methods for obtaining nonpublic records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Obtain consent from the individual to whom the records pertain (i.e., request the records)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Obtain a subpoena or use other legal processes, such as depositions, interrogatories, and document requests, if a legal action is filed."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Obtain a search warrant (although search warrants are only available to law enforcement)."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Improper Pretexting"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In general, pretexting is the act of impersonating someone else or making false or misleading statements to obtain, sell, or buy information about a person or organization."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Some jurisdictions have prohibited pretexting against financial institutions even if no fraudulent intent is present."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In this context, pretexting is the act of obtaining or attempting to obtain customer information from financial institutions through deceptive tactics (e.g., pretending to be the customer or an authorized individual to obtain account information)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners should not impersonate a member of law enforcement or an actual person (particularly the individual being investigated). To do so may lead to charges of identity theft."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A regulation designed to protect the personal data of European Union (EU) residents and harmonize data protection laws throughout Europe"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Applies to organizations that are based in the EU that collect or process the personal data of any person, regardless of where the person is located"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Applies to organizations that are not based in the EU if they collect or process the personal data of any person located in the EU for the purpose of:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Offering goods or services to the person, regardless of whether payment is required"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Monitoring the person’s behavior"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Applies to most companies that have customers in the EU even if the companies have no physical presence in the EU"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using the Internet in Fraud Examinations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The best way to use a search engine is to use two or three keywords that best describe the topic, but such searches often return too many or irrelevant results."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In such situations, users can employ special query words or symbols called advanced search operators (or Boolean operators) to increase the precision of a search phrase."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "For example, placing quotation marks around a word or set of words returns pages containing the exact word or set of words. A search for “money laundering” returns pages in which the exact phrase money laundering appears."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Online Public Database Searches"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To locate people using online records, the fraud examiner should obtain a past address of the subject, and search activities should begin with that information."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fraud examiner should know the most powerful and useful types of searches."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There are several limitations to be aware of when conducting searches for public records using online databases:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Online availability of public records varies widely across jurisdictions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Online public records searches are limited in the area they cover."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Often, online public records are brief abstracts of the original public record."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The source of the information compiled in an online database must be reliable."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners must validate information retrieved from online databases to determine if it is accurate and up to date."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The public records compiled in an electronic format might cover only a limited period."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Online searches can be erratic in the information they return."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Deep Web"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Web content that is not indexed by standard search engines"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Also known as the invisible web"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Resources include websites without any links pointing to them, certain file formats that search engines cannot handle, websites that have been blocked from access by web crawlers (i.e., scripts that create copies of visited web pages that are indexed by a search engine), password-protected websites, and information stored in databases."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An important resource for fraud examiners because standard search engines only search a small portion of the web"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Dark Web"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Websites that are only accessible through specialized web browsers meant to anonymize the origins of user traffic"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The most popular web browser is Tor, short for “the onion router.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Tor software layers encrypted communications and offers increased anonymity to users by preventing someone who is monitoring a user’s internet traffic from knowing what sites the person visits and preventing the visited sites from learning the user’s location."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Sites with a .onion address are designed to only be accessible by people using a Tor web browser."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Internet Archives"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Archived versions of web pages that have since been updated or are no longer available online"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The most popular tool for searching the internet archives is the Wayback Machine, located at https://archive.org, which allows users to see archived versions of web pages throughout time."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Searching the internet archives can uncover historical information, such as:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A photo posted on a website that has been removed"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Content, views, writing, and opinions rescinded by an author"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A company’s old job ads, statements, affiliations, or product lines"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using Social Media Sites"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The popularity of social media sites makes it easy for fraud examiners to find information about individuals who use such sites."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Relevant social media evidence can include photographs, status updates, a person’s location at a certain time, and direct communications."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners can use social media to:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Investigate complaints."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Discover potential witnesses."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Research the accused."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Learn about the accusers."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Privacy Issues When Collecting Social Media Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners are free to search and extract information from a subject’s page if it is open to the public, but there are limitations to the information fraud examiners can access on a social media site due to privacy settings and anonymity."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Accessing information on social media sites that is restricted by privacy settings could result in liability for fraud examiners due to the violation of users’ privacy rights."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Due to confidentiality, privacy, and security concerns, courts might not allow evidence obtained by someone who misrepresents themselves to gain access to a subject’s private social network."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "para", "text": "XVIII. Social Media Data Collection Best Practices"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Take screen captures of relevant information."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Print the content."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Use screen-recording software to create a digital recording of a screen’s output."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Convert web pages into another format (e.g., PDF)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Use a website capture tool that navigates to each link on a web page and captures all the content on each link, including embedded files and source code."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "If a fraud examiner was gathering information about a fraud suspect, which of the following"}, {"type": "para", "text": "types of information would likely require access to nonpublic sources of information to be"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. The subject’s habits and lifestyle"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Where the subject currently resides"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. The subject’s home phone records"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Madelyn, a Certified Fraud Examiner (CFE), is investigating Chloe, who is active on an online"}, {"type": "para", "text": "social media site in which she voluntarily shares information about herself. Madelyn wants to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "search for and extract information from Chloe’s social media profile. Which of the following is"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the MOST ACCURATE statement about the privacy of information Chloe shared through her"}, {"type": "para", "text": "social media profile?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Madelyn could be liable for violating Chloe’s privacy rights if she hacks or breaks into"}, {"type": "para", "text": "areas of the social media site Chloe has designated as private."}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. The Privacy of Social Networks Treaty is an international law that makes it illegal for"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Madelyn to seek the log-in credentials from Chloe’s social media account."}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. To search for information that Chloe posted and made available to the public through"}, {"type": "para", "text": "her social media profile, Madelyn must provide Chloe notice beforehand."}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. To access any information posted on Chloe’s social media profile, Madelyn must obtain"}, {"type": "para", "text": "some type of legal order from the jurisdiction in which Chloe resides."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sources of Information"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Freddie calls Alex’s bank and claims to be Alex with the intention of stealing Alex’s identity."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Freddie tells the bank representative that he needs to make sure the bank has the correct"}, {"type": "para", "text": "government identification number on his account because he noticed an error on his"}, {"type": "para", "text": "statement. The bank representative refuses to give the number, so Freddie hangs up. Assuming"}, {"type": "para", "text": "that each of the following is illegal in the relevant jurisdiction, which of the following crimes did"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Pretexting with a financial institution"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Fraud in the inducement"}], "ai_summary": "[From CFE Workbook] Generated and kept within the subject organization Are often the only resource for certain types of documents, such as accounting and business tax records, copies of canceled checks, or employee personnel files, unless the fraud examiner secures the subject’s consent or a legal order to obtain those documents from other parties."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Covert Operations", "summary_short": "[From CFE Workbook] An investigation technique designed to obtain evidence by use of agents whose true intentions are not communicated to the target Mistakes made during a covert operation can cause irreparable damage to an investigation; mistakes may also have reputational, financial, and legal consequences.", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "What Is a Covert Operation?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An investigation technique designed to obtain evidence by use of agents whose true intentions are not communicated to the target"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Mistakes made during a covert operation can cause irreparable damage to an investigation; mistakes may also have reputational, financial, and legal consequences."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners should only resort to covert operations after conventional methods of gathering evidence have been exhausted and proven unsuccessful."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Forms of Covert Operations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Undercover operations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Often use deception and disguise to obtain evidence directly from those involved in the illicit activity."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Might involve posing as the co-conspirator’s agent and engaging the suspect in conversation to gather information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Surveillance operations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Use observation to gather information about individuals suspected of misconduct."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Might involve observing a suspect from afar while they meet with a potential co-conspirator"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Information to Document"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Before conducting a covert operation, document the basis of the operation, preferably in a memorandum that clearly states:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The information upon which the covert operation will be based"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The information that is expected to be gained from the operation"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The identities of suspects, if known"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Operatives under the fraud examiner’s care, custody, or control"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Legality of Recordings"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many jurisdictions have laws that impose restrictions on electronic audio or video recordings that are not done pursuant to a search warrant or other court order."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Factors to consider when determining the legality of recording audio or video without a court order include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The consenting party 1. For a recording of a private conversation to be permissible, most jurisdictions require consent from at least one of the parties involved in the conversation. 2. Jurisdictions with higher standards of privacy might require the consent of multiple or, in some cases, all parties."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The setting 1. Restrictions on recording might depend on whether the conversation or interaction to be recorded occurs in public or in private"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A combination of audio and video 1. In some jurisdictions, fraud examiners might only be allowed to record audio or video of a public interaction between two or more unsuspecting parties but not audio and video."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Entrapment"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Occurs when law enforcement officers or government agents induce a person to commit a crime that they are not previously disposed to commit"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Poses a legal problem in covert operations because the defendant might not be found liable if it appears that they were improperly induced to commit the crime; thus, it is imperative that these operations be properly predicated"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Procedures When Using Sources and Informants"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Make any payments in cash and obtain a receipt for documentation purposes."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If a source or informant will not sign a receipt, then do not pay that person."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Only make payments after the informant has delivered the information."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Keep the informant’s identity as confidential as possible."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Use symbols to denote identities when reporting contacts."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Promises of Confidentiality"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners generally cannot offer unqualified confidentiality to informants. Therefore, any promises made to an informant or source should be qualified with the caveat that no absolute assurances of confidentiality can be given."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "In preparing a memorandum of information furnished by a confidential source, how should the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "source usually be identified on paper?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. By a code name or a symbol"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Confidential source information should not be written in a report"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following factors should a fraud examiner consider when determining the legality"}, {"type": "para", "text": "of electronic recordings?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Whether the parties involved in the conversation have consented to being recorded"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Whether the interaction to be recorded will take place in a public or private setting"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Whether the jurisdiction allows a combination of audio and/or video to be recorded"}], "ai_summary": "[From CFE Workbook] An investigation technique designed to obtain evidence by use of agents whose true intentions are not communicated to the target Mistakes made during a covert operation can cause irreparable damage to an investigation; mistakes may also have reputational, financial, and legal consequences."}, {"domain": "Investigation", "topic": "Collecting Evidence", "summary_short": "After the parties submit pleadings to the court, the evidence-gathering process begins. The system for collecting evidence varies from country to country, especially along the lines of adversarial processes (generally common law systems) and inquisitorial processes (generally", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The three primary types of evidence that fraud examiners must consider and gather when conducting their investigations are:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Testimonial evidence 1. Involves statements made by witnesses, neutral third parties, and suspects during interviews and/or when testifying at trial"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Digital evidence 1. Consists of information stored in electronic form on a wide array of computer and storage devices used by individuals and organizations"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Documentary evidence 1. Consists of records that help prove or disprove the existence of fraud or another relevant fact of a case 2. Common types include memoranda, ledgers, letters, minutes of meetings, receipts, and financial records."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "General Rules for Collecting and Organizing Documents"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Obtain original documents where feasible."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Do not touch originals any more than necessary."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Maintain a dependable filing system for the documents."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Segregate the documents by either witness or transaction."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Make a key document file for easy access to the most relevant documents."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Establish a database early in the investigation."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Methods for Obtaining Documentary Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Preferred method is by consent if both parties agree."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Consent can be oral, but consent should ideally be in writing when obtaining information from possible adverse witnesses or the examination’s target."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Some types of records, like bank records, can be obtained by consent only if the subject of the records consents in writing."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Documents can also be obtained through legal action."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Usually a subpoena or other court order is issued."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Handling Documents as Physical Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Documents should be handled carefully and stored properly in a sealed, initialed, and dated paper folder or envelope to avoid damage or contamination."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If necessary, make a working copy and preserve the original document for submission to a forensic document examiner."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Other than making unobtrusive initials for identification, do not write or mark on original documents."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Chain of Custody"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Both a process and a document that memorializes who has had possession of an object and what they have done with it"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In general, to establish the chain of custody, fraud examiners must make a record via a memorandum when they, or any other member of the fraud examination team, receive an item and when it leaves their care, custody, or control. It should state:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "What items were received"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When they were received"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "From whom they were received"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Where they are maintained"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Disposal of Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Once an investigation or examination has concluded, fraud examiners might need to direct or participate in the disposal of evidence that was collected during an engagement."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Factors that could potentially affect evidence disposal following the conclusion of a fraud investigation or examination are:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The personal information about suspects or witnesses that is documented in the evidence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Jurisdictional regulations"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The likelihood of further litigation related to the engagement"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Organizational policies related to the disposal of sensitive information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "General document retention policies implemented by the organization"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Litigation holds related to the engagement"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Any of these factors could require the evidence to be retained, disposed of, or returned to its owner in a specific manner."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is generally NOT a recommended practice when organizing physical"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Segregating original documents from working copies"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Making a key document file with the most relevant documents"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Establishing a database early in the investigation"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Filing all documents in chronological order"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Black, a Certified Fraud Examiner (CFE), has obtained an oral confession from Green, a fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "suspect. Black wants to examine Green’s bank accounts. Which of the following would be the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "LEAST EFFECTIVE way to obtain permission to examine Green’s bank records?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Obtain a subpoena."}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Obtain Green’s written consent."}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Obtain Green’s oral consent."}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Obtain a court order."}], "ai_summary": "After the parties submit pleadings to the court, the evidence-gathering process begins. The system for collecting evidence varies from country to country, especially along the lines of adversarial processes (generally common law systems) and inquisitorial processes (generally"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Overview of the Legal System", "summary_short": "By its nature, fraud examination is a law-intensive field. Legal issues related to fraud are often complex, and their interpretation might require professional legal assistance. CFEs should always consult with legal advisors if legal questions arise during a fraud examination.", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Judicial Systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Courts are usually bound by two sources of substantive law: 1. Common law"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A system of legal principles developed by judges through decisions made in court (thus, often referred to as judgemade law)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Consists of the usages and customs of a society as interpreted by the judiciary 2. Statutory law"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Laws created by a legislature or other governing authority"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Judges may decide disputes by analyzing prior cases with similar circumstances and applying the basic principles set forth in those cases. 1. Past decisions that establish particular legal principles are called precedent. 2. Lower courts are bound to follow the precedents of higher courts until or unless the rule of law established is overturned by a higher court or the legislature."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Civil law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Courts are bound by an accepted set of codified principles or compiled statutes."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Courts are not bound by previous court decisions (i.e., precedent)—a civil law judge usually just applies the various codified principles to each case."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The main distinction between the two systems is that judges under common law systems are bound by precedent while judges under civil law systems are not; instead, judges under civil law systems are bound by the civil code."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Overview of the Legal System"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Fact-Finding Processes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The approach that courts take to discover (i.e., search for) evidence in a case"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Two main types"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Adversarial process 1. The parties to a proceeding drive the discovery process"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The parties to the litigation gather and present the evidence to the court (usually through legal counsel) by questioning fact and expert witnesses."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fact finder of the court, which can be a judge, jury, or administrator, is unaware of the details of the case until the parties present evidence."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Judges facilitate the production of evidence between the parties, but generally do not seek evidence on the court’s behalf. 2. Defendants in criminal adversarial proceedings may provide testimony but are generally not required to do so. 3. Usually favored by common law systems but can be used in civil law jurisdictions as well"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Inquisitorial process 1. The presiding judge has the primary responsibility of discovering evidence."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The judge is actively involved in discovery and often requests relevant documents or asks witnesses questions themselves."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Attorneys play a smaller role in the evidentiary process than in a system that uses an adversarial process. 2. Defendants in criminal inquisitorial proceedings are generally required to provide testimony. 3. Usually favored by civil law systems but can be used in common law jurisdictions as well"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Overview of the Legal System"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The power of a court to hear and decide a given case"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Refers to the subject matter or people over which lawful authority may be exercised by a court"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "For example, a country might have a system of probate courts that only have jurisdiction to hear cases whose subject matter is related to wills, inheritance, and other probate matters."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Some countries have low-level trial courts that only have jurisdiction to hear matters under a certain monetary amount."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A particular court’s jurisdiction is defined by the laws of its country, but there are three common elements:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Does the court hear cases of the type in question?"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Does the court have the authority to exercise its power over a particular defendant or piece of property?"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Does the court have proper venue (the physical location where the lawsuit is to be tried)?"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "International Issues in Fraud Cases"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Choice of law"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Courts must choose which jurisdiction’s laws to apply to each issue in a case; this could lead to problems if the outcome of a case depends on which jurisdiction’s laws are applied."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Conduct that is fraudulent in one jurisdiction might be legal, carry different penalties, or result in different remedies in another jurisdiction."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Enforcement of judgments"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A domestic judgment against a foreign defendant is usually helpful for recovering the defendant’s assets located in the domestic country, but it might be worthless for obtaining the defendant’s assets in a foreign country."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Overview of the Legal System"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Some, but not all, countries enforce foreign judgments concerning parties or assets within their jurisdiction."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Whether the country will enforce a foreign court’s judgment usually depends on the internal laws of the jurisdiction and whether the two countries of each court have an enforcement treaty."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Civil and Criminal Actions for Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud may be prosecuted criminally, civilly, or both, in sequence or simultaneously."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Criminal action"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Begins with a complaint brought by the government, acting on behalf of citizens and the interest of the jurisdiction, against a person accused of violating a law"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Civil action"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An action for wrongdoing that does not result in a criminal fine or incarceration"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Parallel proceedings"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Simultaneous criminal and civil actions against the same defendant that are based upon a single set of facts 1. For example, a victim of fraud might sue the fraudster in civil court while the fraudster is being prosecuted in criminal court."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Some jurisdictions permit parallel proceedings while others do not."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Administrative Proceedings"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Non-judicial proceedings conducted by government agencies"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally operate like civil courts with their own rules of evidence and procedure"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The ultimate decision-maker can be a special administrative judge, board, or tribunal"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common types of administrative penalties include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Monetary fines and penalties"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Overview of the Legal System"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Imposed to punish the defendant for violating a law and can"}, {"type": "para", "text": "include the payment of monetary damages, which are awarded to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "compensate victims for damages caused by fraud"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "License suspension or revocation 1. Involves the suspension or revocation of a professional license 2. For example, a government medical board might revoke a doctor’s license to practice medicine after determining that the doctor engaged in health care fraud."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Debarment 1. Debars, or excludes, individuals and businesses from participating in government programs 2. For example, a contractor who engages in procurement fraud might be prohibited from bidding on government contracts in the future. 3. Debarment can be temporary or permanent, and debarred parties are often added to a list that is maintained by the government agency and viewable by the public."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Overview of the Legal System"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following BEST describes the primary source(s) of law in civil law jurisdictions?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Codified principles or statutes (e.g., a civil code)"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. A combination of judge-made law and codified principles or statutes"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following refers to a court’s power to hear and decide a given case?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Overview of the Legal System"}, {"type": "para", "text": "In a jurisdiction that features an inquisitorial judicial process, the parties primarily drive the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "evidence-gathering portion of judicial proceedings and conduct the questioning of witnesses."}], "ai_summary": "By its nature, fraud examination is a law-intensive field. Legal issues related to fraud are often complex, and their interpretation might require professional legal assistance. CFEs should always consult with legal advisors if legal questions arise during a fraud examination."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Individual Rights During Examinations", "summary_short": "CDs are intended to be held until maturity, at which time the money may be withdrawn together with the accrued interest. Many banks impose penalties on money that is withdrawn Numerous securities fraud schemes involve futures contracts, option contracts, and over-thecounter (OTC) options (i.e., an option that does not trade on a major exchange). Futures and", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Overview of Employees’ Rights"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees involved in investigations of suspected fraud have certain duties and rights, whether they are merely bystanders who might have some information relevant to the investigation or are suspected of committing fraud."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "These duties and rights vary among jurisdictions, but generally apply to employees who work in private-sector and government workplaces; thus, both private and government employers can inadvertently violate their employees’ legal rights if they do not understand the rules."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Employees’ Duty to Cooperate"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In most jurisdictions, a duty to cooperate exists in every employer-employee relationship."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Though the duty to cooperate varies, it generally extends to workplace investigations; therefore, employees have a duty to cooperate during an internal investigation if what is requested from them is reasonable."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Employees’ Duty to Preserve Relevant Information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees may have a duty to preserve relevant information, depending on their jurisdiction."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common law jurisdictions: The duty to preserve relevant evidence typically arises when litigation is reasonably anticipated or contemplated; a violation occurs when information that is relevant to anticipated or existing litigation is lost, destroyed, or otherwise made unavailable."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Civil law jurisdictions: There are no specific rules requiring litigants to preserve information for discovery because there is no common-lawstyle discovery in civil law systems; thus, civil law systems tend to have a narrower scope of what evidence is required for litigation, and the issue of when to take affirmative steps to preserve evidence is established by the court."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Individual Rights During Examinations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In applicable jurisdictions, violating the duty to preserve relevant information can result in several adverse sanctions for the offending party."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Such sanctions can arise from both intentional acts and accidental acts through negligence."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The adverse consequences can include, but are not limited to, monetary penalties (e.g., paying the opposing party’s legal fees and costs), the drawing of adverse inferences of fact, and criminal penalties."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Situations that could result in sanctions include intentionally or accidentally: 1. Erasing computer files relevant to anticipated or existing litigation 2. Losing or destroying physical evidence relevant to anticipated or existing litigation 3. Losing, destroying, or altering documents or records relevant to anticipated or existing litigation 4. Failing to suspend routine destruction of electronic data relevant to anticipated or existing litigation"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Employees’ Contractual Rights"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An employee may have contractual rights that limit the employer’s ability to compel full cooperation in a fraud examination."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employers and employees may enter into contracts that govern the employment relationship, and, if the employer violates the contract, then the employee can sue for breach of contract."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Such contracts can be express or implied."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Often, employee contractual rights at issue during investigations arise from a union contract, a collective bargaining agreement, or an employment contract."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "For example, if the employee is a member of a union, then the union contract or collective bargaining agreement might contain certain restrictions on the company’s investigatory procedures."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Individual Rights During Examinations"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Other employees might have a written employment agreement containing provisions concerning the employees’ rights during an investigation."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Whistleblower Protections"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many jurisdictions have whistleblower laws designed to encourage individuals to bring forth complaints of wrongdoing by providing protections for those who report unlawful conduct."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most of these laws protect employees from any adverse employment action or retaliatory action from their employers, but they do not prevent individuals from being terminated for engaging in unrelated fraudulent behavior."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Employees’ Privacy Rights"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees have certain privacy rights that can affect numerous aspects of the employer-employee relationship, such as conducting investigations, surveillance and monitoring, and workplace searches."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An employee’s privacy rights can arise from, and be protected by, various sources of law, including constitutional law, statutory law, common law, human rights law, labor law, data protection law, contract law, and other sources."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Countries vary in how they approach workplace privacy, but in some jurisdictions, privacy laws generally prohibit unreasonable searches and surveillance in areas where employees have a reasonable expectation of privacy."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The key issue to consider when assessing the existence of a reasonable expectation of privacy is whether a reasonable person would expect the area or item to be free from intrusion—the employee does not need to have an ownership interest in, or legal custody over, the area or item."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Another important factor is the amount of control an individual exercises over the area or item. If an employee has exclusive control over an area or item, this tends to show that the employee has a reasonable expectation of privacy in it."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Individual Rights During Examinations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Nearly every country prohibits covert employee monitoring unless a specific criminal activity has been identified; therefore, nearly every employer is required to notify its employees before implementing an employee monitoring program."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The notice should be clear, comprehensive, and made in writing."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Protections Relating to Government Search and Seizure"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most countries have laws that provide the public with the right to be free from unreasonable search and seizure by government authorities."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Though interpretation may vary, this right sometimes requires that the government obtain a search warrant before it conducts a search of a person, location, or vehicle for evidence of a crime."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A search warrant is a court order that grants government authorities the right to search a premises or property for information pertinent to a case."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The requirements for search warrants or other similar authorization, however, do not apply to private parties acting on their own accord because the right to be free from unreasonable searches and seizures does not protect against actions by such parties—only from actions by government authorities."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Thus, to determine whether a search warrant or similar authorization is required for a search to be conducted in an investigation, it is necessary to first determine whether government authorities are involved in the search."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Consent searches"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Individuals are always free to consent to searches."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "If a subject consents to a search or seizure by police or government agents, then the consent eliminates the need for a search warrant; that is, the consent waives the person’s right to be free from government searches."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The courts closely scrutinize any such “consent” to make sure it was truly voluntary, particularly when it leads to the seizure of incriminating evidence."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Individual Rights During Examinations"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Consents to searches by government agents obtained by force, duress, or bribery are generally held to be involuntary and therefore invalid."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There is generally no requirement that government agents warn suspects that they have a right to refuse consent."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Defamation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An unprivileged publication of a false statement about a person that causes harm to that person’s reputation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Whether defamation is a criminal offense or a civil wrong varies by jurisdiction."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Elements that generally must be proven include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The defendant made an untrue statement of fact."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The statement was communicated (published) to third parties."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The statement was made on an unprivileged occasion."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The statement damaged the subject’s reputation."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Invasion of Privacy"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Intrusion into an individual’s private matters (intrusion upon seclusion)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Harm that occurs when an individual intentionally intrudes into an area where another individual has a reasonable expectation of privacy and the intrusion would be highly offensive or objectionable to a reasonable person"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Elements 1. An intentional intrusion 2. Into an area where an individual has a reasonable expectation of privacy 3. The intrusion would be highly offensive or objectionable to a reasonable person"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Public disclosure of private facts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Civil wrong that occurs when one party makes public statements about another party’s private life that are not of public concern"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Individual Rights During Examinations"}, {"type": "num", "text": "For instance, disclosing information obtained in an interview"}, {"type": "para", "text": "conducted as part of a fraud investigation to individuals not"}, {"type": "para", "text": "involved in the investigation might constitute a public disclosure"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Can arise even if the statements at issue are true"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Key is that the information must be private in nature and not a matter of public interest"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Elements 1. The defendant made public statements about another party’s private life. 2. The statements were not of public concern. 3. The statements would be highly offensive to a reasonable person."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Intentional Infliction of Emotional Distress"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Any unprivileged conduct that is so outrageous and egregious that it exceeds all bounds usually tolerated by civilized society and that is intended to cause injury (or was committed with reckless disregard for the likelihood of its causing injury) to another"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Such conduct is mainly actionable in common law countries."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Elements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The defendant engaged in extreme and outrageous conduct."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The defendant acted intentionally or recklessly (i.e., the defendant intended for their conduct to cause severe emotional distress, or they acted recklessly with regard to whether their actions would cause severe emotional distress)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The victim suffered emotional or mental distress as a result of the defendant’s conduct."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "False Imprisonment"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The unlawful restraint by one person of the physical liberty of another without consent or legal justification"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Individual Rights During Examinations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "False imprisonment laws protect against unlawful confinement in many countries."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Elements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The defendant used words or actions intended to restrain the plaintiff."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The defendant’s words or actions resulted in the restraint of the plaintiff without the plaintiff’s consent (i.e., against the plaintiff’s will) and without legal justification."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The plaintiff was aware that they were being restrained."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A claim of false imprisonment might arise if an employee is detained in any way during a search or interview."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Data Privacy Laws"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most countries have data privacy laws (also known as information privacy or data protection laws) that protect personal information about individuals from disclosure, unauthorized access, and misuse."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A regulation designed to protect the personal data of European Union (EU) residents and harmonize data protection laws throughout Europe"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Applies to EU-based organizations that collect or process the personal data of any person, regardless of where the person is located"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Some of the major provisions include: 1. Lawful basis"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Organizations must have a lawful basis for collecting or processing personal data (e.g., the consent of the data subject, a legitimate interest of the organization, or compliance with a legal obligation)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The lawful basis must be documented in a commonly used electronic format and include the name of the specific lawful basis, an explanation, and supporting facts."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Individual Rights During Examinations"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Notice"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Before collecting or processing personal data, organizations must give the data subject notice of:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "What information will be collected or processed"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The purpose of the collection or processing"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "How long the data will be retained"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The identity of the organization"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The contact information for the organization and its data protection officer (if any) 3. Consent"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Organizations must obtain the consent of data subjects before collecting or processing their personal data."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Data subjects must be informed that they can withdraw their consent at any time, and withdrawal of their consent must be as easy as providing consent. 4. Right to access"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Upon a data subject’s request, an organization must confirm or deny that it possesses the data subject’s personal data. 5. Right to erasure"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Under some circumstances, organizations can be compelled to delete personal data upon request."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "For example, a data subject may request the erasure of personal data if: 1. The data are no longer necessary in relation to the purpose for which they were collected. 2. The data subject withdraws consent."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Individual Rights During Examinations"}, {"type": "num", "text": "The data were unlawfully collected or"}, {"type": "num", "text": "The data subject was a child when the data"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Organizations must respond to such requests without undue delay. 6. Data security"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Organizations must implement appropriate technical and organizational measures to ensure a level of data security that is appropriate to the risk. 7. Data breaches"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An organization must notify all affected data subjects without undue delay if a data breach is likely to result in a high risk to their rights and freedoms."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "However, the organization is not required to notify data subjects if the breach only involved encrypted or otherwise unintelligible data or if the organization took actions after the breach that substantially minimized the risk to data subjects."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Data Transfer Laws"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Data transfers cover any sharing, transferring or disclosing, giving access to, or otherwise making available information to third parties (e.g., corporate entities and government authorities)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many countries have adopted legal restrictions on international data transfers; however, even when countries provide protection for cross-border data transfers, there are discrepancies in the implementation and application of such protections."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Individual Rights During Examinations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Nevertheless, there are three options by which management can legitimize cross-border transfers of personal information:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Obtain the consent of the data subject."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Establish a contract between the entities that are exchanging the information (i.e., between the transmitting entity and the receiving entity)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "If transmitting from the EU to non-EU countries, rely on adequacy decisions by the European Commission (i.e., limit the transfer of data to countries that offer an adequate level of protection, as determined by the European Commission)."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Individual Rights During Examinations"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "In the context of an employee interview, all the following actions could result in liability for"}, {"type": "para", "text": "false imprisonment EXCEPT:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Locking the door to an interview room"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Standing in front of an exit to an interview room"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Telling the interviewee that they may not leave the room"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Telling the interviewee that they are required to answer questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Gilda and Jones are both employees of the Smithstone Corporation. Management tasked Gilda"}, {"type": "para", "text": "with investigating Jones after receiving an anonymous tip that Jones was guilty of misconduct."}, {"type": "para", "text": "During her investigation, Gilda discovered that Jones was cheating on his spouse. Gilda then"}, {"type": "para", "text": "went on to share this true information with several of their coworkers who were not involved"}, {"type": "para", "text": "with the investigation. Under these facts, and assuming all the following are prohibited by law"}, {"type": "para", "text": "in Smithstone’s jurisdiction, Jones may be able to sue and recover against Gilda for:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Intentional infliction of emotional distress"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Invasion of privacy"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Individual Rights During Examinations"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following statements about the consent exception to the requirement that"}, {"type": "para", "text": "government agents must obtain a warrant before conducting a search for evidence of a crime is"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Government agents do not need a warrant to perform a search if a person with proper"}, {"type": "para", "text": "authority consents to the search."}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. To be valid, an individual’s consent to a search by government agents must be"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Generally, government agents do not have to warn subjects that they have a right to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "refuse to consent to a search."}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Even if obtained by bribery or force, consent to search constitutes a valid waiver of the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "person’s right to be free from unreasonable searches."}], "ai_summary": "CDs are intended to be held until maturity, at which time the money may be withdrawn together with the accrued interest. Many banks impose penalties on money that is withdrawn Numerous securities fraud schemes involve futures contracts, option contracts, and over-thecounter (OTC) options (i.e., an option that does not trade on a major exchange). Futures and"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Criminal Prosecutions", "summary_short": "criminal suspects must be informed of their right to remain silent before any interrogation. However, not all civil law systems impose such requirements. The right to counsel is the right of criminal defendants to have a lawyer assist in their defense,", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "United Nation’s (UN) International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Commits those countries who have signed and ratified the covenant to recognize various rights of citizens, including the following rights for those accused of crimes:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Freedom from arbitrary arrest or detention 1. Under the ICCPR, individuals have the right to liberty and shall not be subject to arbitrary arrest or detention. 2. A custodial arrest occurs whenever a government officer has a person in custody (i.e., the officer has indicated that the person is not free to leave). 3. It is important to determine when an arrest occurs to establish what rights the subject of the arrest had at a given time. 4. Generally, the government may not make an arrest unless there is good reason to believe that the suspect committed an offense."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Right of the accused to be informed of criminal charges 1. Once a person is arrested, they have a right to be informed of the charges brought against them in a prompt manner. 2. The charges must be presented in a language the suspect can understand."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Right to a fair hearing (with publicized results) 1. The ICCPR states that all people accused of crimes are entitled to a fair hearing before a court or other tribunal and that the results of the trial should be made public to protect the transparency of the system. 2. This right includes:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Adequate time to prepare a defense"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The ability to be represented by legal counsel of the defendant’s choosing and to freely communicate with counsel"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Criminal Prosecutions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The right to have accusations and the procedures explained through a translator for free, if necessary"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The right to be tried for charges without undue delay"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The right to examine or have examined the witnesses against the accused"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Freedom from testifying against oneself or compelled confessions"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Presumption of innocence until proven guilty according to law"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Right to appeal a criminal conviction and sentence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Right to privacy and protection from privacy violations"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Corporate Criminal Liability"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In many jurisdictions, corporations and similar business entities may be vicariously liable (the absolute liability of one party for the misconduct of another party) for criminal and civil violations."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In such jurisdictions, a business entity is liable for the acts of its employees if those acts occur within the scope of employment and with some intent to benefit the corporation (doctrine of respondeat superior, or “let the master answer” in Latin). Therefore, the employee needs to have committed each element of the crime for liability to be transferred to the corporation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally, vicarious liability is very broad and imposes liability on a corporation even if those in management had no knowledge of or participation in the underlying events."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Prosecutorial Discretion and Bargaining Agreements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Whether criminal cases are brought to trial generally depends on prosecutorial discretion, meaning that the decision to prosecute is left to the discretion of the appropriate jurisdictional authority. However, some jurisdictions require prosecutions for any violation when there is credible evidence."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Criminal Prosecutions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Another method of disposing of cases in a growing number of countries is through bargaining agreements, which occur when a defendant makes an agreement with prosecutors to plead guilty or submit a recorded confession in exchange for lesser criminal charges or a reduced sentence."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is usually within the prosecution’s discretion as to whether to offer a bargain."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Bargaining agreements are controversial in many countries and are not as widely used in civil law jurisdictions as in common law jurisdictions."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Corporate Deferred Prosecution Agreements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Used in some of the jurisdictions that allow for corporate criminal liability"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Typically occur when prosecutors file criminal charges against a company, but then they agree not to prosecute the claims if the company successfully complies with the deferral agreement’s terms"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Focus on getting the business to reform its policies and reduce the risk of illegal practices"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Used to help companies avoid indictment, trial, and conviction while providing a jurisdiction’s justice system with another channel for disposing a corporate case that punishes misconduct and effectuates changes in a company’s culture"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Trial Process"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fact finders"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common law systems 1. Juries are typically, but not always, used in criminal proceedings."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A jury trial might not be available for cases involving minor criminal offenses (although jury trials are typically available for serious cases)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many common law jurisdictions allow the defendant to waive the right to trial by jury."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When no jury is present, the judge serves as the fact finder."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Criminal Prosecutions"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Civil law systems 1. The judge typically serves as the fact finder and decides matters of law. 2. Juries are usually reserved for serious crimes if they are used at all. 3. Several civil law systems feature a mixture of judges and laypersons when juries are used. 4. Alternatively, some countries feature criminal trials with a panel of both professional and lay judges."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The burden of proof"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The evidence one party must present to prove each element of a cause of action"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "In most common law systems, the burden of proof is beyond a reasonable doubt, meaning that the fact finder must be as certain as possible that the defendant is guilty of the charges against them."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "In most civil law systems that use an inquisitorial process, the burden of proof is sometimes called the conviction intime or inner conviction of the judge, meaning that the judge (or other fact finder) needs to be convinced on an inner, deep-seated level. 1. This standard is thought to be somewhat less rigorous than beyond a reasonable doubt. 2. Civil law systems typically do not change the standard between civil and criminal cases."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Discovery"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The formal process whereby the parties to litigation collect evidence and learn the details of the opposing side’s case"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Adversarial jurisdictions (usually common law systems) 1. The parties involved in litigation primarily drive the process. 2. Occurs primarily during the pretrial stage of litigation"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Criminal Prosecutions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Adversarial processes are usually divided into pretrial and trial stages. 3. The prosecution works with law enforcement to gather all evidence on the government’s behalf. 4. The prosecution and defense may request limited information from each other although some evidence will not be available to a party until the opposing party introduces it as evidence during the trial. 5. Alleged failures to comply with evidentiary rules may be submitted to the judge, who may then order a party to comply. 6. The entirety of each party’s evidence is produced and recorded at trial."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Inquisitorial jurisdictions (usually civil law systems) 1. A judge primarily drives the process."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Some inquisitorial systems have two types of judges:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Examining judges, who oversee the evidencecollection process"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Trial judges, who preside over the trial by presenting evidence collected previously, questioning witnesses, hearing arguments, and making rulings 2. Occurs primarily during the investigative and examining phases of criminal proceedings"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Inquisitorial processes are typically divided into three phases:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In the investigative stage, the public prosecutor, judge, or both (depending on the jurisdiction’s process) collect documentary and tangible evidence regarding the case. The investigating party then decides whether there is sufficient evidence to submit the case for prosecution."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Criminal Prosecutions"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "If there is sufficient evidence, the case moves to the examining phase, which is mostly conducted in writing. The judge completes a written record of the evidence (called an evidentiary record or trial dossier) and may also collect testimony and additional evidence. If the judge certifies that there is a valid case against the accused, the matter moves to trial."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The trial commences with the exhibition of the examining record before the parties and the trial judge, jury, or panel. The parties argue their case before the trial judge (or jury, if applicable). 3. The entire evidentiary record, as submitted by the judge presiding over the examining stage of the litigation, is provided to the parties before the trial phase commences."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Punishment"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When a defendant is found guilty of a crime, there are a variety of sanctions available, depending on the jurisdiction. Sanctions may include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Probation 1. The suspension of an offender’s sentence in return for a promise of good behavior 2. Typically imposed prior to (and instead of) imprisonment 3. Laws vary by jurisdiction, but the offender is generally placed under the control and guidance of a government agent who ensures that the conditions of probation are met."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Imprisonment 1. Sentence may be made under rules that dictate a determinate sentence (e.g., 5 years) or an indeterminate sentence (e.g., 5–10 years)."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Criminal Prosecutions"}, {"type": "num", "text": "In some jurisdictions, defendants may be eligible for parole after"}, {"type": "para", "text": "serving a part of their sentence."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Parole refers to the status of offenders after they have been released from prison and are placed under supervision in the community."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Fines 1. The defendant is ordered to pay a sum of money as punishment for their offense."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Restitution 1. The defendant must pay money to the victim for incurred losses or otherwise cooperate in the victim’s efforts to recover money or property."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Criminal forfeiture 1. The defendant must transfer specific property (generally property that was used to commit the crime or that was purchased with the proceeds of the crime) to the government as part of their sentence."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Appeal"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The procedure for obtaining review by a higher court to ensure that the trial was conducted in a lawful manner and that the judgments comply with the law"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally, appellate courts will not accept an appeal unless the petition is filed in a timely manner (e.g., no later than thirty days after the trial court’s judgment)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In many jurisdictions, an appellate court will reverse a conviction only if it finds an error that likely affected the trial’s outcome and denied the defendant a fair trial."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In most common law countries, appellate courts consider potential errors of law de novo (meaning they evaluate them independently of the trial court’s determinations), but they generally adopt the factual findings of the trial court."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Criminal Prosecutions"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "No trier of fact is present, and there is typically no new evidence entered into the record."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Therefore, appeals are typically limited to issues of law."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Very rarely will an appellate court reverse a factual finding of the trial court in a common law jurisdiction, such as when there is an egregious and obvious mistake."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Civil law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The appellate court can usually perform de novo reviews of both the factual and legal determinations by evaluating the compiled evidentiary record."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Therefore, courts can typically review cases for both issues of fact and law."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Criminal Prosecutions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is a criminal sanction that requires defendants to pay back victims for"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the money or property that they lost?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Criminal forfeiture"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Determinate sentence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "In most common law jurisdictions, to prevail in a criminal case, the prosecution must prove its"}, {"type": "para", "text": "case _____________________."}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Beyond a reasonable doubt"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. By a preponderance of the evidence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. True beyond any possible doubt"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. With clear and convincing evidence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Criminal Prosecutions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following outcomes to criminal allegations of fraud against an organization occurs"}, {"type": "para", "text": "when prosecutors agree not to prosecute claims if the organization reforms its practices and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "reduces the risk of illegal activities?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Sentencing agreement"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Plea bargaining agreement"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Deferred prosecution agreement"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Judgment notwithstanding the verdict"}], "ai_summary": "criminal suspects must be informed of their right to remain silent before any interrogation. However, not all civil law systems impose such requirements. The right to counsel is the right of criminal defendants to have a lawyer assist in their defense,"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Basic Principles of Evidence", "summary_short": "[From CFE Workbook] Anything perceivable by the five senses that is presented to the fact finder to prove or disprove a fact in issue Testimonial evidence 1. The oral or written statements made by witnesses under oath", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Definition of Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Anything perceivable by the five senses that is presented to the fact finder to prove or disprove a fact in issue"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Testimonial evidence 1. The oral or written statements made by witnesses under oath"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Real evidence 1. Physical objects that played a part in the issues being litigated 2. Includes both documentary evidence—such as canceled checks, invoices, ledgers, and letters—and other types of physical evidence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Demonstrative evidence 1. A tangible item that illustrates some material proposition (e.g., a map, a chart, or a summary) 2. Differs from real evidence in that demonstrative evidence was not part of the underlying event; it was created specifically for the trial 3. Purpose is to provide a visual aid for the fact finder (e.g., jury or judge) 4. Can be considered by the fact finder in reaching a verdict"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Evidence is simply anything that relates to proving or disproving a fact that is of consequence in a case."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Two Basic Categories of Admissible Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Direct evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue directly, such as eyewitness testimony or a confession."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Basic Principles of Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Circumstantial evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Evidence that tends to prove or disprove a fact in issue indirectly, by inference."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many fraud cases are proved entirely by circumstantial evidence, or by a combination of circumstantial and direct evidence, but seldom by direct evidence alone."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Admissibility of Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Relevance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A basic requirement of admissibility in both common and civil law systems is that evidence must be relevant (i.e., tends to make some fact that is in dispute more or less likely than it would be without the evidence). 1. Common law systems: Evidence must be relevant to material issues in dispute. 2. Civil law systems: Evidence is admitted if the presiding judge determines it is relevant."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Whether a particular piece of evidence is relevant or not depends on what the evidence is offered to prove—an item of evidence might be relevant and admissible if offered to prove one thing, but it might be irrelevant and inadmissible if offered to prove something else."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "In common law systems using adversarial processes, the fact that an item of evidence is relevant does not automatically mean that it will be admitted; relevant evidence might be excluded if it: 1. Is unduly prejudicial 2. Threatens to confuse or mislead the jury 3. Threatens to cause unnecessary delay or a waste of time 4. Is merely cumulative"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Basic Principles of Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Authentication"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common law systems 1. Evidence, other than testimonial evidence, must be properly authenticated to be admissible at trial; that is, the party offering the item must produce some evidence (e.g., testimony from a person who has firsthand knowledge) to show it is, in fact, what the party says it is and that it is in the same condition as when it was seized. 2. The authentication requirement serves to ensure that the evidence is what the party claims it is and that it is genuine, not a forgery. 3. If an exhibit (i.e., a tangible object presented as evidence) cannot be authenticated, it will not be admitted even if it is plainly relevant."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Civil law systems 1. While there is no requirement of authenticity for the admission of evidence, authenticity is a factor to be considered by the fact finder in deciding, given all the evidence presented at trial, just how much weight to give the evidence. 2. Authenticated evidence tends to be deemed more reliable than unauthenticated evidence."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Writings 1. In general, authentication of a writing consists of establishing who authored the document."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Digital records 1. Generally, to be admissible, digital records must meet the same authentication standards as hard copy records (i.e., to show that the item is what the proponent claims). 2. The most likely methods of authenticating digital records are:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Basic Principles of Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Testimony from a witness who has personal knowledge"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Circumstantial evidence of distinctive characteristics"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Certified copies of business records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Chain of custody"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In common law and civil law systems, chain of custody is both a process and a document that memorializes (1) who has had possession of an object and (2) what they have done with it"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A means of establishing that there has not been a material change or alteration to a piece of evidence from the time it was collected through its production in court"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Impeachment"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The practice of questioning a witness’s knowledge or credibility"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In systems using adversarial processes, the adverse party is usually entitled to offer evidence to impeach the testimony or credibility of a witness."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most inquisitorial systems do not allow cross-examination of witnesses."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There are numerous ways an attorney might impeach a witness, but the most common include efforts to show that the witness:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Is influenced by bias or self-interest"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Has an impaired ability to observe"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Made prior inconsistent statements"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Has been convicted of a felony or equivalent crime"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Has a reputation for untruthfulness"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Privileges and Protections"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Prevent certain types of evidence from being discovered or produced during trial"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The privileges and protections available and requirements for each vary substantially by jurisdiction."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common law systems generally offer broader evidentiary protections than civil law systems."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Basic Principles of Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common types of privileges include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Legal professional privilege (e.g., attorney-client privilege) 1. Precludes disclosure of confidential communications between a professional legal advisor (e.g., solicitor, barrister, or attorney) and the legal advisor’s clients. 2. The requirements vary among jurisdictions, but the following elements usually must be present for communications to be protected:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A communication between a legal professional and a client"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The communication was made to seek or give legal advice"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The parties intended the communications to be confidential 3. It is not necessary that the communication take place after a lawsuit has been filed. 4. In most jurisdictions, the privilege extends to communications with third-party consultants hired to help provide legal advice to the client (e.g., fraud examiners, accountants, bankers, or other experts). 5. Subject to waiver"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Because these privileges only protect confidential communications, the protection they provide may be waived for communications disclosed to third parties who have little or nothing to do with the client’s pursuit of legal representation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The waiver occurs when the client, who holds the privilege, voluntarily discloses (or consents to or encourages someone else into disclosing) any significant part of the privileged communications."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Though the client holds the privilege, the privilege can be waived by the client or inadvertently waived by the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Basic Principles of Evidence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "attorney or a third party (someone other than the"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Litigation privilege 1. Protects documents and other items that are prepared in anticipation of litigation 2. Arises once litigation is reasonably anticipated, so a communication is only privileged if litigation was contemplated at the time it was created; documents that were created prior to this time are not privileged 3. Protection offered may extend to communications of, and documents created by, third-party agents (e.g., consultants or fraud examiners) in preparation for litigation."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Basic Principles of Evidence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The litigation privilege (if available) extends to not only information and documents prepared"}, {"type": "para", "text": "by a party or the party’s attorneys but also by the consultants and examiners hired by the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The process of determining who had possession of physical evidence and what they have done"}, {"type": "para", "text": "with it is known as establishing the:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Basic Principles of Evidence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "In most common law jurisdictions, for a document to be admitted into evidence, it must be"}, {"type": "para", "text": "properly _______; that is, the party offering the document must produce some evidence to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "show that it is, in fact, what the party says it is."}], "ai_summary": "[From CFE Workbook] Anything perceivable by the five senses that is presented to the fact finder to prove or disprove a fact in issue Testimonial evidence 1. The oral or written statements made by witnesses under oath"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "The Law Related to Fraud", "summary_short": "Countries use a wide variety of laws and regulations to prohibit fraud and related crimes. This chapter covers some of the most common types of offenses, as well as several important laws and initiatives designed to combat fraud and corruption. It is important to keep in mind,", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Definition of Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Any intentional or deliberate act to deprive another of property or money by guile, deception, or other unfair means"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Fraudulent Misrepresentation of Material Facts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The specific elements of proof required to establish a misrepresentation claim vary somewhat according to where the fraud occurred and whether the case is brought as a criminal or civil action."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The elements normally include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The defendant made a false statement (i.e., a misrepresentation of fact)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The false statement was material (i.e., the statement was sufficiently important or relevant to influence decision-making)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The defendant knew the representation was false."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The victim relied on the misrepresentation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The victim suffered damages because of the misrepresentation."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Bribery"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Official bribery"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The corruption of a public official to influence an official act of government"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The elements of official bribery vary by jurisdiction, but they generally include: 1. The defendant gave or received (or offered or solicited) something of value. 2. The recipient was (or was selected to be) a public official. 3. The defendant acted with corrupt intent. 4. The defendant’s scheme was designed to influence an official act or duty of the recipient."}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Law Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Commercial bribery"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The corruption of a private individual to gain a commercial or business advantage"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The elements of commercial bribery vary by jurisdiction, but they typically include: 1. The defendant gave or received something of value. 2. The defendant acted with corrupt intent. 3. The defendant’s scheme was designed to influence the recipient’s action in a business decision. 4. The defendant acted without the victim’s knowledge or consent."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Conflict of Interest"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence their professional role"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Elements of a typical civil claim for conflict of interest include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The defendant is an agent of a principal or employer."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The agent takes an interest in a transaction."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The agent’s interest is actually or potentially adverse to the principal (i.e., the interest is one that could cause the agent or employee to place their personal interests ahead of the principal or employer)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The agent did not disclose the interest and obtain approval by the principal."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "For a conflict of interest claim to be actionable, the conflict must be undisclosed."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Breach of Fiduciary Duty"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "People in a position of trust or fiduciary relationship—such as officers, directors, high-level employees of a corporation or business, and agents and brokers—owe certain duties to their principals or employers, and any action that runs afoul of such fiduciary duties constitutes a breach."}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Law Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The two principal fiduciary duties are:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Duty of loyalty 1. Requires that the employee/agent act solely in the best interest of the employer/principal without any self-dealing, conflicts of interest, or other abuse of the principal for personal advantage 2. Corporate directors, officers, and employees are barred from using corporate property or assets for their personal pursuits or taking corporate opportunities for themselves."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Duty of care 1. Requires that people in a fiduciary relationship must act with such care as an ordinarily prudent person would employ in similar positions 2. Corporate officers, directors, or high-level employees, as well as other people in a fiduciary relationship, must conduct their business affairs prudently with the skill and attention normally exercised by people in similar positions. 3. Fiduciaries who act carelessly or recklessly are responsible for any resulting loss to the corporate shareholders or other principals."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Conspiracy"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A situation in which two or more people agree to commit an illegal act"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The essential elements that must be shown to prove a conspiracy typically include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The defendant entered into an agreement with at least one person to commit an illegal act."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The defendant knew the purpose of the agreement and intentionally joined in the agreement."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "At least one of the conspirators knowingly committed at least one overt act in furtherance of the conspiracy."}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Law Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally, to prove a conspiracy, the government must establish that the defendant knew of the conspiracy’s existence and its objective, but it does not need to establish that the defendant knew all the details or objectives, or that the defendant knew the identity of all the conspiracy participants."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Under most conspiracy laws, the purpose of the conspiracy need not be accomplished for a violation to occur, but at least one of the co-conspirators must have executed at least one overt act in furtherance of the conspiracy."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Mail Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Occurs when a country’s mail system is used to perpetrate fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Mail fraud laws only exist in some jurisdictions, such as Canada and the United States."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In the United States, the mail fraud statute also applies to the use of private interstate commercial carriers (e.g., FedEx, UPS, and DHL) in connection with a fraud scheme."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Mail fraud laws generally give the government broad authority to prosecute fraud schemes, even if parts of the scheme occur in another country."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "For example, an international Ponzi scheme perpetrated from Nigeria could be prosecuted under the U.S. mail fraud statute if the Nigerian fraudsters used the U.S. mail system to advance the scheme in a significant way."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Wire Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A U.S. statute that makes it a crime to defraud a victim of money or property by means of wire or other electronic communications (e.g., computer, telephone, radio, or television) in foreign or interstate commerce."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Requires an interstate or foreign communication to constitute a violation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "While unique to the United States, the wire fraud statute gives the U.S. federal government broad jurisdiction over a wide range of fraudulent activity, including some fraud schemes that originate outside of the United States."}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Law Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Obstruction of Justice"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Occurs when an individual engages in an act designed to impede or obstruct the investigation or trial of other substantive offenses"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Jurisdictions might have several criminal obstruction statutes, but some common types are those that prohibit:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Influencing or injuring any officer of the court or juror by force, threats of force, intimidating communications, or corrupt influence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Influencing a juror through a writing"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Stealing or altering records or processes by parties that are not privy to the records"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Using force or threats of force to obstruct or interfere with a court order"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Destroying documents related to a future proceeding"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Tampering with a witness, victim, or an informant"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Influencing, obstructing, or impeding a government auditor in the performance of their official duties"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Obstructing the examination of a financial institution"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Perjury"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An intentional false statement given under oath on a material point at issue"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The basic elements include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The defendant made a false statement."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The defendant made the false statement while under oath."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The false statement was material or relevant to the proceeding."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The defendant made the statement with knowledge of its falsity."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Laws that criminalize perjury generally do not require that the false statement be given in a court of law."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "False Claims and Statements to Government Agencies"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Laws prohibiting false claims and statements to government agencies make it illegal for a person to lie to, or conceal material information from, a government agency."}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Law Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A false claim is an assertion of a right to government money, property, or services that contains a misrepresentation."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A false statement is an oral or written communication, declaration, or assertion that is factually untrue."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An individual can be found guilty for making a false statement or claim only if the individual knew the statement or claim was false at the time it was made."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally, to prove a violation, the government must show that the defendant:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Knowingly and willfully (or with reckless disregard for truth or falsity)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Made a false claim or statement (or used a false document)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "That was material (i.e., sufficiently important or relevant to influence decision-making)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Regarding a matter within the jurisdiction of a government agency"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "With knowledge of its falsity"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally, the falsity at issue must only have been capable of influencing a governmental department or agency. Thus, an individual can be found guilty of making a false claim or statement even if:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The claim or statement was not made directly to the governmental entity (i.e., it could have been made to a third party if it involved a matter within the governmental entity’s jurisdiction)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The governmental entity was not actually deceived by the falsity, did not rely on it, or did not suffer a loss in reliance on it."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "International Initiatives Against Fraud and Corruption"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The OECD Recommendation on Combating Bribery in International Business"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Published by the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), an intergovernmental institution dedicated to democracy and the market economy"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Designed to combat corruption in international business by urging member states to adopt effective measures to detect, prevent, and combat bribery of foreign public officials in international business"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Law Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Urges member states to deter and penalize the bribery of foreign public officials by taking “concrete and meaningful steps” to improve the following areas within their respective infrastructures: 1. Criminal, civil, commercial, and administrative laws 2. Tax systems and regulations 3. Banking and accounting requirements and practices 4. Laws and regulations related to public subsidies, licenses, and contract procurement"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Prohibits making corrupt payments to foreign officials or political organizations"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Only enforced in the United States, but has international reach because businesses within its scope may violate the statute anywhere in the world"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Two principal components 1. Anti-bribery provisions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Make it unlawful to bribe foreign government officials to obtain or retain business. 2. Accounting provisions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Require publicly traded companies subject to the FCPA’s jurisdiction to keep accurate books and records and adopt internal controls to prevent improper use of corporate funds."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "U.S. jurisdiction over corrupt payments to foreign officials depends on whether the violator is a regulated party. Regulated parties include: 1. A domestic concern—any U.S. citizen, national, or resident, or any business entity that has its principal place of business in the United States or that is organized under the laws of a U.S. state, territory, possession, or commonwealth"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Law Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "num", "text": "An issuer—a corporation that has issued securities that have been"}, {"type": "para", "text": "registered in the United States or an entity that is otherwise"}, {"type": "para", "text": "required to file periodic reports with the U.S. Securities and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Exchange Commission (SEC)"}, {"type": "num", "text": "The agents, subsidiaries, or other third-party representatives of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "domestic concerns and issuers"}, {"type": "num", "text": "A foreign national or business that takes any act in furtherance of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "a corrupt payment within U.S. territory"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The FCPA anti-bribery provisions do not prohibit all payments to foreign officials—there is an exception for facilitating payments, or grease payments, made to expedite or secure performance of a routine governmental action by a foreign official, political party, or party official that relates to the performance of that party’s ordinary and routine functions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The UK Bribery Act"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Exercises broad jurisdiction over all individuals and corporate entities for acts of corruption when any part of the offense occurs in the United Kingdom (UK)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Liability also exists for acts committed outside the UK by individuals and entities with a close connection to the UK, including: 1. British citizens, overseas citizens, overseas territories’ citizens, and any person declared a British subject under the 1981 British Nationality Act 2. Individuals who normally reside in the UK 3. An entity incorporated under the law of any part of the UK"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Foreign companies that have offices in the UK, employ UK citizens, or provide any services to a UK organization are responsible for complying with the UK Bribery Act."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Comparison with U.S. FCPA"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Law Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Both the UK Bribery Act and the FCPA make it a crime to offer"}, {"type": "para", "text": "foreign public officials bribes or to accept bribes from them in"}, {"type": "para", "text": "connection with international business transactions, but the UK"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Bribery Act has an even broader application."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Whereas the FCPA only prohibits bribes involving foreign government officials, the Bribery Act goes further by making commercial bribery—bribes paid to people working in the private sector—a crime. 2. Even if an organization’s anti-corruption program is sufficiently robust for the purposes of complying with the FCPA, it might not be sufficient to comply with the UK Bribery Act. 3. Unlike the FCPA, the UK Bribery Act does not make an exception for facilitating payments."}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Law Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The UK Bribery Act has a broader application than the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA)"}, {"type": "para", "text": "because, unlike the FCPA, it makes commercial bribery a crime."}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development’s (OECD) Recommendation on"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Combating Bribery in International Business (the Recommendation) urges member states to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "combat the bribery of foreign public officials by taking steps to improve which of the following"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Tax systems and regulations"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Banking and accounting requirements and practices"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Laws and regulations related to public subsidies, licenses, and contract procurement"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Law Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Paula is on the boards of two companies that compete in the highway construction industry."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Paula does not disclose this conflict, and she does not step down from the board of either"}, {"type": "para", "text": "company. If Paula’s acts are discovered and she is sued for violating her fiduciary duties, under"}, {"type": "para", "text": "what theory is the suit MOST LIKELY to be filed?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Violating the duty of fair competition"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Violating the duty of care"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Violating the duty of loyalty"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Violating the duty to disclose"}], "ai_summary": "Countries use a wide variety of laws and regulations to prohibit fraud and related crimes. This chapter covers some of the most common types of offenses, as well as several important laws and initiatives designed to combat fraud and corruption. It is important to keep in mind,"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Testifying", "summary_short": "CFEs should keep in mind that the above methods of impeachment may be used not only on the defendant and defense witnesses, but also on witnesses for the prosecution. Inquiries should be made before trial to determine if a prosecution or defense witness is subject to", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Testimony"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Lay (factual) testimony"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Witnesses testify about what they have experienced firsthand and their factual observations."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Fraud examiners typically provide lay testimony based on observations made during the investigation."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Generally, fact witnesses can only testify about the things they have personally observed and cannot give opinions or conclusions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Expert testimony"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Testimony from a person who, by reason of education, training, skill, or experience, is qualified to render an opinion or otherwise testify in areas relevant to resolution of a legal dispute"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Qualified witnesses provide opinion testimony when specialized knowledge is needed to help the fact finder understand evidence or determine a fact in issue."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Expert testimony is usually used when a trial involves issues that are complex or unfamiliar to most people."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Experts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Testifying expert"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Gives opinion testimony when specialized knowledge is needed to help the fact finder understand evidence or determine a fact in issue"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Consulting expert"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Hired to provide technical assistance to the attorney in preparing the case; typically does not testify at trial"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Procedural Divergences Regarding Expert Witnesses in Adversarial and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Inquisitorial Jurisdictions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Adversarial jurisdictions (typically common law jurisdictions)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most expert witnesses are chosen by the parties to the litigation (although adversarial courts may also appoint independent experts)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The parties to the litigation are usually allowed to retain these experts to either consult or testify in proceedings, meaning the parties pay the experts directly."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Each party might obtain its own expert, and it is common to have competing expert testimony in a proceeding."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The parties are given an opportunity to both question their own expert in front of the judge or jury, as well as cross-examine the other party’s expert to potentially reveal weaknesses in that expert’s methods or analysis."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fact finder (i.e., the judge or jury) must evaluate these competing expert opinions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Inquisitorial jurisdictions (typically civil law jurisdictions)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The court usually hires its own expert witnesses for technical issues that require guidance; in other words, the primary experts in inquisitorial jurisdictions are typically appointed by the court (i.e., by the judge)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The expert provides the court with information, and the judge has the discretion to determine whether to apply the expert’s testimony when deciding issues."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Usually, all the expert’s activities related to the case are controlled by the judge, who also determines the scope of the expert’s testimony and analysis, the expert’s authority to access certain items of evidence, whom the expert can interview, and several other functions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "It is primarily the judge’s responsibility to elicit the testimony from the expert; however, the parties’ representatives can ask the expert questions and can sometimes challenge the expert’s qualifications or testimony."}, {"type": "num", "text": "Parties are usually allowed to raise limited objections to an expert"}, {"type": "para", "text": "witness if they believe the expert is biased and are often allowed"}, {"type": "para", "text": "to question the expert’s analysis or methods used."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Qualifying to Testify as an Expert Witness"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Adversarial jurisdictions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally, a judge will make three determinations before allowing an expert to testify before the jury: 1. Is the person qualified as an expert witness? 2. Will the expertise of the witness assist the jury in understanding the evidence or determining a fact at issue? In other words, is the proposed testimony relevant to the facts of the case? 3. Is the testimony reliable?"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The process of evaluating whether an expert is qualified mainly centers on the candidate’s formal education and work experience."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "There is no standard educational requirement for expert testimony; a witness with no formal education may be qualified based on either special training or experience."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Other factors that may be considered when determining whether an expert is qualified include the candidate’s: 1. Awards and honors 2. Licensing or certification 3. Technical training 4. Published books and journal articles 5. Positions in professional associations, societies, and organizations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A person does not have to be a CFE to testify as an expert on fraud prevention, detection, or investigation techniques if that person has sufficient practical experience in those techniques, but the CFE credential substantiates the expert witness’s testimony."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Inquisitorial jurisdictions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most inquisitorial jurisdictions have more standardized requirements for qualifying to testify and allow expert witnesses to offer their services in court more often than in adversarial jurisdictions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Many jurisdictions maintain lists of experts in certain fields from which the courts may choose; these experts are generally qualified if they meet national standards, such as being certified in a specific field."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "After being initially selected by the judge, expert witnesses are usually required to submit a report to the court and are subject to questioning by the parties to the litigation."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The parties’ representatives may ask questions concerning the expert’s qualifications, potential biases, and report, but they are generally more limited in the scope of questioning than parties in adversarial proceedings."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The judge makes the final determination of whether the expert is qualified."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Direct Examination of Witnesses"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The initial questioning of a witness"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Adversarial jurisdictions: Conducted by the party who retained the witness"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Inquisitorial jurisdictions: Conducted by the judge"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Usually a nonconfrontational questioning aimed at exposing the facts and issues of the case"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Methods of Presenting Expert Testimony During Direct Examination"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Written reports"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In adversarial jurisdictions, experts typically create written reports in the pretrial stage and then testify to their findings during direct examination."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "In inquisitorial jurisdictions, written reports are generally the preferred method for presenting expert testimony, but a direct examination of the expert by the judge might also occur."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Narratives"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Narrative questions are broad, open-ended questions that allow experts to state their opinions in their own words with minimal prompting."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The expert witness in cases dealing with fraud issues will often begin testimony by recounting the narrative background of a case, the tests and experiments that were performed during the investigation, and a summary of the findings based on the witness’s professional expertise."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Examples: 1. “Could you please tell us about the background of this case?” 2. “What procedures did you perform in your examination?”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Hypotheticals"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fictional situations, analogous to the act in question, that clarify and highlight particular aspects of the dispute"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Cross-Examination of Witnesses"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The questioning of one side’s witness by the opposing side"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Allows the questioning party either to clarify or make points at the witness’s expense"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Adversarial jurisdictions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "During cross-examination, the witness’s credibility is constantly scrutinized."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Goals of the opposing counsel during cross-examination 1. Diminish the importance of the testimony presented by the witness. 2. Get the witness to testify in support of the opposing position by providing a series of assumptions. 3. Show inadequacies in the witness’s report or expert opinion (as applicable), thereby discrediting the opinion, the report, and the witness."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Opposing counsel’s general rule is to cross-examine only if it would benefit the case, so opposing counsel usually knows the answers to the questions it poses."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "General tactics used by opposing counsel during cross-examination 1. Pose very complex questions to convolute the witness’s responses."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If this occurs, or if asked a long or imprecise question, then the witness should ask for a question to be rephrased in smaller components. 2. Attempt to take psychological control of a witness by:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Using physical presence to intimidate"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Making nonstop eye contact"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Challenging the witness’s space"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Asking questions at a fast pace to confuse the witness"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Not allowing the witness to explain or deviate from the exact question"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Inquisitorial jurisdictions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Given that most witnesses in inquisitorial jurisdictions are called by the judge, the closest thing to cross-examination in inquisitorial systems occurs when the parties object to or examine the witness."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "In some jurisdictions, the parties typically do not ask questions directly, but may submit suggestions for inquiries to the judge. If parties are allowed to directly question witnesses, the questioning is usually less aggressive and less confrontational than in adversarial systems."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Cross-Examination Strategies to Discredit Witnesses"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When applicable in the jurisdiction, the questioning party might employ various methods to discredit an expert witness or diminish the importance of the witness’s testimony:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Myopic vision"}, {"type": "num", "text": "The questioning party might get the expert witness to admit to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "excessive time being spent on a specific matter, and then select"}, {"type": "para", "text": "an area to highlight in which the witness is unsure or has not done"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Bias 1. The questioning party may seek to show that the expert witness is biased. Bias refers to partiality that prevents a witness from objectively considering an issue or situation."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Sounding board 1. The questioning party may seek to use the expert witness as a sounding board to reacquaint the judge or jury with the favorable aspects of the questioning party’s theory. This technique often uses the “Is it not true?” and “Would you agree with me?” approach."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Willing to Say Anything for a Price 1. The questioning party may portray the expert witness as an individual who is willing to form their opinion in favor of the side that paid them. This technique seeks to suggest that the testimony was purchased or that the witness was paid to overlook facts contradictory to the conclusions reached."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Harris is retained to provide an opinion involving specialized knowledge in the accounting field"}, {"type": "para", "text": "for use at a trial. Which of the following BEST describes his role?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following types of questions is an expert witness MOST LIKELY to be asked during"}, {"type": "para", "text": "direct examination in an adversarial jurisdiction?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. A two-part question"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. A leading question"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. A hostile question"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. A narrative question"}, {"type": "para", "text": "_____________ is the cross-examination technique that entails getting the expert to admit a"}, {"type": "para", "text": "great amount of time being spent on a specific matter, and then selecting an area to highlight in"}, {"type": "para", "text": "which the expert has not done much work."}], "ai_summary": "CFEs should keep in mind that the above methods of impeachment may be used not only on the defendant and defense witnesses, but also on witnesses for the prosecution. Inquiries should be made before trial to determine if a prosecution or defense witness is subject to"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Civil Actions", "summary_short": "In an under-invoicing scheme, the exporter invoices goods or services to the importer at a price below their market value. This scheme transfers value to the importer because the amount the importer pays for the goods or services is less than the amount they can be sold for on the", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Beginning the Civil Action"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A civil action begins when the plaintiff files a pleading with the appropriate court, usually in the jurisdiction in which the defendant or the plaintiff resides, or where the claim originated."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The pleading sets out the complaint against the defendant and the remedy that the plaintiff is seeking."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The required contents of the plaintiff’s pleadings vary somewhat between jurisdictions, but most jurisdictions require fact pleadings, meaning the plaintiff must identify:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The grounds for legal relief"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A summary of the evidence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The specific facts on which the party’s claim relies"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Counterclaims"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Claims filed by a defendant against the plaintiff in a civil action"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Level a claim against the original plaintiff, who is now the defendant of the counterclaim"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Preservation of Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most civil litigation concerning fraud involves many documents, tangible items, or digital information that might serve as evidence, and each jurisdiction has rules for how this potential evidence should be handled."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally impose a duty on parties in civil litigation to take affirmative steps to preserve relevant evidence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The duty to preserve relevant evidence typically begins when the litigation in question is reasonably anticipated."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Civil law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Tend to have a narrower scope of what evidence is required for litigation"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Typically, the issue of when to take affirmative steps to preserve evidence is established by the court, meaning the court dictates what evidence must be preserved and produced by the parties or others with relevant information. 1. Even without such an order, a judge might draw a negative inference against a party that fails to preserve and produce relevant evidence."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Gathering Evidence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "After the parties submit pleadings to the court, the evidence-gathering process, which varies by jurisdiction, begins."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Each party is entitled to pretrial discovery (the formal process whereby parties collect evidence and learn the details of the opposing side’s case)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "In most common law jurisdictions, each party must file an affidavit of documents, or affidavit of records, which lists and describes all documents in its possession that are relevant to any matter in the case. 1. The party filing the affidavit must allow the other party to inspect or copy any such documents. 2. If any of the documents are privileged, the privilege should be asserted in the affidavit of documents. 3. If requested, the judge will examine the documents to determine if the privilege applies."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A party may be examined or questioned by the other party either orally or by written questions. 1. A written examination for discovery, or interrogatory, is a list of questions that the party, usually through a lawyer, is required to answer in writing."}, {"type": "num", "text": "A pretrial oral examination, or deposition, is sworn testimony given"}, {"type": "para", "text": "by a party or witness upon questioning by counsel for one of the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "parties before trial and outside of court, usually in a lawyer’s office."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Civil law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In the inquisitorial process commonly found in civil law jurisdictions, the evidence is gathered contemporaneously with the trial, as opposed to the common law method of having the parties gather evidence over time and enter it into the record all at once during the trial stage."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The judge usually orchestrates the questioning of witnesses and is also responsible for collecting documents and physical evidence."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Standard of Proof"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally, the standard of proof in a civil suit is referred to as the preponderance of the evidence, meaning that it is more probable than not that the defendant is liable."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Unlike in criminal cases, the plaintiff does not have to prove liability beyond a reasonable doubt."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Civil law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The standard of proof in civil law jurisdictions typically does not change in criminal and civil trials, so the inner conviction of the judge, or conviction intime standard, also applies in civil suits."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "This standard requires stronger evidence than the common law preponderance of the evidence standard used in civil trials but not as much as the common law beyond a reasonable doubt standard used in criminal trials."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Civil Trial Process"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Jury composition and verdict"}, {"type": "num", "text": "When juries are used, the requirements are typically less stringent"}, {"type": "para", "text": "than in criminal trials."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is common for the minimum number of jurors to be lower for civil cases."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Civil trials are less likely to require a unanimous jury verdict than criminal trials."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Trial phases 1. Pretrial stage"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Courts sometimes have the authority to seize assets or property temporarily while a lawsuit is pending."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In most jurisdictions, plaintiffs in fraud cases can seek a court order, generally called a prejudgment attachment, to prevent the defendant or a third party from disposing of, spending, damaging, transferring, or concealing assets or property while the lawsuit is pending. 2. Trial stage"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Trial process 1. Usually begins with the plaintiff presenting the evidence against the defendant 2. The plaintiff calls witnesses to testify as to facts and to present documents, photographs, or other kinds of evidence. 3. The defendant may then cross-examine the plaintiff’s witnesses to test their evidence. 4. Once the plaintiff has presented their case, the defendant can present their own evidence, which may include calling witnesses. 5. The plaintiff can then cross-examine the defendant’s witnesses."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Civil law systems"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Structure"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Civil law trials are a continual series of meetings and written"}, {"type": "para", "text": "correspondences, rather than a single event, as in common law"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Throughout the process, evidence is introduced and evaluated by"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the court, and motions are submitted and decided on by the judge."}, {"type": "num", "text": "The division between pretrial and trial stages found in common"}, {"type": "para", "text": "law civil trials does not apply in the typical civil law setting."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Trial process 1. Throughout the trial, the judge evaluates evidence and records it in the trial record."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The record is generally a summary of the evidence, rather than a word-for-word transcript of the proceedings. 2. After presenting the evidence in court, the judge, jury, or judge panel (depending on the jurisdiction and type of case) rules on the issues in the case."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Appeals"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally, both sides in a civil case may appeal from an adverse judgment, either as to liability or damages."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Legal Remedies"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Any processes, procedures, or consequences of a legal wrong by which a victim can be redressed for their loss"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The remedy to which the plaintiff is entitled depends upon a number of factors, such as the relief sought, the facts of the case, and the authority given to the court to grant specific relief."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The three most common civil remedies are:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Damages (monetary remedies) 1. Remedies for the victim’s recovery of money from the defendant because of, and as compensation, reimbursement, or reparation for, the defendant’s legal offense"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Main purpose is to compensate the plaintiff for the loss caused by"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Declaratory remedies 1. Remedies in which the court states or declares the rights of the parties"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Equitable remedies 1. Remedies used when the legal remedy (such as damages) by itself would be inadequate compensation for the wrong suffered 2. One of the primary equitable remedies is the injunction, which is a court order by which a party is required to perform, or is restrained from performing, a specific act."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Fidelity Insurance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A method that is often overlooked for recovery of losses due to internal fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Under fidelity insurance policies, the insured entity is covered against losses caused by the dishonest or fraudulent acts of its employees."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Alternative Dispute Resolution"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A means for parties to an action to resolve their disputes without the necessity of a trial"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In fraud cases, this usually involves one of two types of methods:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Mediation 1. The process whereby an impartial third person (known as a mediator) assists the parties in reaching a resolution to the dispute 2. The mediator does not decide who should win, but instead works with the parties to reach a mutually agreeable settlement. 3. Any mediation agreement will be enforced as a binding contract."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Arbitration"}, {"type": "num", "text": "The process whereby a dispute is submitted to an impartial third"}, {"type": "para", "text": "person (known as an arbitrator) who then decides the outcome of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the case (i.e., which party should win)"}, {"type": "num", "text": "The arbitrator acts as a judge or jury by deciding the case on its"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Arbitration can be either binding or nonbinding."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following BEST describes the standard of proof for civil trials in civil law"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Clear and convincing"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. The inner conviction of the judge"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Preponderance of the evidence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. More likely than not"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Two parties entered into a real estate contract for various properties, but the vague nature of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the contract led to confusion about who owned a particular property. The parties took the issue"}, {"type": "para", "text": "to court, and the court interpreted and stated the rights of each party under the contract. What"}, {"type": "para", "text": "type of remedy did the court provide?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Declaratory relief"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A prejudgment attachment is a court order that prevents a defendant or a third party from"}, {"type": "para", "text": "disposing of, spending, damaging, transferring, or concealing assets or property while a lawsuit"}], "ai_summary": "In an under-invoicing scheme, the exporter invoices goods or services to the importer at a price below their market value. This scheme transfers value to the importer because the amount the importer pays for the goods or services is less than the amount they can be sold for on the"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Securities Fraud", "summary_short": "[From CFE Workbook] A security is a negotiable financial instrument that represents an interest or a right in something else. Countries define the term differently, so what is considered a security varies from country to country.", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "What Constitutes a Security?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A security is a negotiable financial instrument that represents an interest or a right in something else."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Countries define the term differently, so what is considered a security varies from country to country."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Types of investments most commonly recognized as securities include stocks, bonds, and certificates of deposit."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In many countries, the term security includes investment contracts."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally, a contract, transaction, or scheme is an investment contract if: 1. There is an investment of money or another asset. 2. The investment is in a common enterprise. 3. The investment was made with expectations of making a profit. 4. The profits are to come solely from the efforts of people other than the investor."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Securities Laws and Regulation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Securities regulation refers to laws, rules, and procedures enacted by a legislative body and administered by dedicated agencies that govern the way in which companies, consumers, and financial professionals behave when trading securities."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To be effective, securities regulation must balance the legitimate needs of businesses to raise capital against the need to protect investors."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Additional purposes include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Promoting an active and competitive market"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Maintaining market confidence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reducing financial crime"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Discouraging behavior that might harm the market"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An international organization comprised of securities commissioners and administrators responsible for securities regulation and the administration of securities laws in their respective countries"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Recognized as the international standard-setter for securities markets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Main objectives are to assist its members to:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cooperate to promote high standards of regulation in order to maintain just, efficient, and sound markets."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Exchange information on their respective experiences in order to promote the development of domestic markets."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Unite their efforts to establish standards and an effective surveillance of international securities transactions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Provide mutual assistance to promote the integrity of the markets through a rigorous application of the standards and effective enforcement against offenses."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Self-Regulatory Organizations (SROs)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Nongovernmental entities that exercise some level of regulatory authority over the operations, standards of practice, and business conduct of an industry or profession"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "SROs oversee the markets in which they operate and police the members and member firms participating in those markets."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "SROs’ regulatory responsibilities might include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Creating rules to protect the integrity of the market in which they operate"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Establishing the standards and rules under which their members operate"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Offering professional training, testing, and licensing to individuals in their industry"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Monitoring compliance with and enforcing the rules of the markets in which they operate through market surveillance programs, trading analysis, and examinations of member firms’ trading operations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many SROs play an important role in the resolution of disputes arising from market transactions."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Securities Fraud Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Churning (excessive trading)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The excessive trading of a customer account to generate commissions while disregarding the customer’s interests"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unsuitable recommendations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In many countries, broker-dealers who make recommendations or provide advice to clients regarding purchases of investment products are subject to a suitability requirement."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Such a requirement prohibits securities broker-dealers from recommending investments or investment strategies that are unsuitable for their clients."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Two rules relating to suitability 1. Know-your-customer (KYC) rule"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Securities broker-dealers must know their customers financially to effectively service their accounts and minimize the risk of recommending an inappropriate investment."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A violation of this rule occurs when a broker recommends an investment or an investment strategy to a client without having conducted due diligence to ascertain relevant personal and financial information about the client. 2. Suitability rule"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Prohibits a broker-dealer from making a recommendation to a client if the broker does not have reasonable grounds for believing that the recommendation is suitable for the client"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A violation of this rule occurs when a broker recommends an investment, recommends an investment strategy, or makes an investment that is inconsistent with the client’s objectives, and the broker knows or should know the investment is inappropriate."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Operating without a license or registration"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Brokerages are required to register and meet certain financial thresholds, and broker-dealers must register with the appropriate regulatory authority."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Red flags 1. Agents with criminal records 2. Unexplained gaps in a promoter’s work history 3. Prior customer complaints 4. A history of regulatory problems 5. Questionable credentials 6. Website lacks background information or contains generic contact information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Insider trading"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Occurs when an insider—someone who possesses inside (material, nonpublic) information—buys or sells securities based on material information about the security that is not available to the public"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Material misrepresentations and omissions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Securities laws require that the investor receive full and fair disclosure of all material information, and they make it unlawful for anyone to obtain money or property by using a material misstatement or omission in the offer or sale of any securities."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Information is material if a reasonable investor would want to know this information to make an informed decision."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Misrepresentation occurs when an advisor gives an investor or prospective investor false or misleading information in an investment suggestion or a trading strategy they suggest a client undertake."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "An omission occurs when the issuer, in connection with the offer or sale of securities, omits a material fact, or when the professional fails to inform the investor of material facts."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "In general, for a contract, transaction, or scheme to be classified as an investment contract, the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "instrument must be purchased by investors who display management activity in the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "instrument’s enterprise and have expectations of making profits that are to be generated from"}, {"type": "para", "text": "To determine if a misrepresentation in the offer or sale of any securities is material, a fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "examiner should consider which of the following?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Whether the person who made the representation believed that it was suitable for"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Whether the person who made the representation had authorization to make the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Whether a reasonable investor would want to know the information to make an"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Whether the person who made the representation intended to mislead potential"}], "ai_summary": "[From CFE Workbook] A security is a negotiable financial instrument that represents an interest or a right in something else. Countries define the term differently, so what is considered a security varies from country to country."}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Money Laundering", "summary_short": "This section reviews the legal aspects of actions by private parties—including fraud examiners, auditors, accountants, security personnel, private investigators, and lawyers—to investigate and recover losses due to fraud. Many of these cases will be resolved in the civil", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Definition of Money Laundering"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The disguising of the existence, nature, source, control, beneficial ownership, location, and disposition of property (typically) derived from criminal activity"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Money Laundering Process"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Three stages"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Placement 1. In this first stage, the launderer introduces their illegal profits into the financial system. 2. It is at this stage that legislation has been developed to prevent launderers from depositing or converting large amounts of cash at financial institutions or taking cash out of the country. 3. One placement method involves structuring (sometimes called smurfing), which occurs when the launderer breaks up illicit funds into smaller amounts—often just under the jurisdiction’s reporting threshold—and then makes multiple deposits into bank accounts or purchases cashier’s checks, traveler’s checks, or money orders. 4. Money laundering schemes are most often detected at the placement stage."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Layering 1. Once the funds have been deposited into a financial institution, a launderer can move them around by using layers of financial transactions designed to confuse the audit trail. 2. The money can even be transported out of the country."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Integration"}, {"type": "num", "text": "In the final stage of the laundering process, money is integrated"}, {"type": "para", "text": "back into the economy in a way that makes it appear to be part of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "a legitimate business transaction."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using a Front Business to Launder Funds"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "One of the most common methods of laundering funds is to filter the money through a legitimate business, known as a front business."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A front business provides a safe place for organizing and managing criminal activity, where the comings and goings of large numbers of people will not arouse undue suspicion."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In addition, a front that conducts legitimate business provides cover for delivery and transportation related to illegal activity. The expenses from illegal activity can be attributed to the legitimate enterprise, and the illegal revenues can be easily placed into the enterprise."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A red flag of a front business is the observation of minimal customers during peak operating hours."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Two methods commonly used to hide assets or launder money through a front business are:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Overstating reported revenues and expenses 1. Occurs when the money launderer records more income on a business’s books than the business actually generates 2. The fictitious revenue accounts for the illegal funds that are secretly inserted into the company. 3. If a company overstates its revenue, it will also need to overstate its expenses to offset its tax liability."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Depositing but not recording revenue 1. Launderers deposit illicit cash into the front company’s bank account rather than disguising the funds by recording them as revenue. 2. These funds appear like a loan in the company’s books."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Money Laundering"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Using Digital Currencies to Launder Funds"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Digital currencies are currencies that exist and are traded in a digital format."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Among the most popular digital currencies is bitcoin, a cryptocurrency that features a peer-to-peer network that allows users to send units of the currency to each other online without the use of a traditional financial institution."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Digital currencies are vulnerable to money laundering because:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many of them function as international person-to-person (P2P) payment systems that cross jurisdictional boundaries, creating difficulties for authorities pursuing enforcement or legal actions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Money launderers can complicate fund-tracing efforts by distributing digital currencies among many addresses—unique identifiers that represent the destination where cryptocurrency can be sent—or digital wallets in complex transactions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "As is typical with developing payment systems, digital currencies generally face regulations that are less strict than they are for payments made through traditional financial institutions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Many jurisdictions now require service providers that exchange or otherwise deal with digital currencies to have effective customer identification or recordkeeping practices; therefore, digital currencies do not provide complete anonymity."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using Trade-Based Money Laundering to Launder Funds"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Defined by the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) as “the process of disguising the proceeds of crime and moving value through the use of trade transactions in an attempt to legitimize their illicit origins”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Schemes generally involve importers and exporters who collude to misrepresent the price, quantity, or quality of imported or exported goods or services."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Trade-based money laundering schemes can be used to create artificial profits for the purpose of laundering money between countries; to create a complex paper trail; and to avoid taxes, customs duties, and capital controls."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Some common schemes include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Over- and under-invoicing schemes 1. Importers and exporters conspire to misrepresent the price of the goods or services being traded, thus transferring additional value between the importer and exporter. 2. These schemes can be used to create a complex paper trail for the colluding parties to launder illicit funds; the amount available to launder is the difference between the market value of the goods and the invoiced amount. 3. In an over-invoicing scheme, the exporter invoices goods or services to the importer above their market value."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Value is transferred to the exporter because the exporter collects the amount of the higher price that was invoiced, which is more than the goods or services can be sold for on the open market."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Example: Company A sends a shipment of widgets worth $100,000 to Company B but invoices Company B for $200,000. Company A then deposits the extra $100,000 into an account controlled by Company B. 4. In an under-invoicing scheme, the exporter invoices goods or services to the importer at a price below their market value."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Value is transferred to the importer because the amount the importer pays for the goods or services is less than the amount they can be sold for on the open market."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Example: Company A sends a shipment of widgets worth $200,000 to Company B but only invoices Company B for $100,000. Company B then sells the widgets on the open market for $200,000 and deposits the extra $100,000 into an account controlled by Company A."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Over- and under-shipments schemes 1. These schemes can be used to create a complex paper trail for the colluding parties to launder money."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In an over-shipment scheme, money launderers understate the quantity of goods that are shipped; more goods are shipped than the company invoices for."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Example: Company A invoices 100,000 widgets to Company B at a price of one dollar per widget. However, Company A ships 200,000 widgets to Company B. Company B then sells the widgets on the open market for $200,000 and deposits the extra $100,000 into an account controlled by Company A."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In an under-shipment scheme, the quantity of goods that are shipped is overstated; the company invoices for more goods than it actually ships."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using Money Services Businesses to Launder Funds"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Money services businesses (MSBs) refer to non-depository financial service providers that transmit or convert money and operate in one or more of the following capacities:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Currency exchangers"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Check cashers"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Issuers, sellers, or redeemers of traveler’s checks, money orders, or stored value"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Money transmitters"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Prepaid access providers or sellers"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "MSBs offer an alternative to depository institutions for both financial services and money laundering, so an individual unable to transfer illegal funds into the traditional depository banking system might turn to an MSB."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most MSBs operate under less strict regulations than traditional financial institutions."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Using Alternative Remittance Systems to Launder Funds"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Alternative remittance systems are methods of transferring funds from a party at one location to another party (whether domestic or foreign) without the use of formal banking institutions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "These systems do not require a direct physical or digital transfer of currency from the sender to the receiver."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In the typical alternative remittance system, the payer transfers funds to a local broker who has a connection to another broker in the region where the payee is located. The second broker then distributes funds to the payee."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The relative anonymity and lack of a paper trail afforded by alternative remittance systems makes them attractive to money launderers, as well as to people involved in terrorist financing."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) on Money Laundering"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An intergovernmental body established to develop and promote standards and policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing at both the national and international levels"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The FATF Recommendations, revised in 2012, created the most comprehensive standard with which to measure a country’s AML, counterterrorism, and nuclear proliferation laws and policies, and they serve as a basic framework of laws that FATF members should have. They serve as a basic framework of laws that its members should have."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Some of the key measures in the FATF Recommendations provide that countries should:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Use a risk-based approach when setting AML policies."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Create policies that increase cooperation and coordination with other countries."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Specifically criminalize money laundering and terrorist financing."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Enable authorities to trace, suspend, and confiscate assets suspected in laundering and terrorist financing."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Require financial institutions to: 1. Keep certain records and establish AML policies. 2. Avoid correspondent banking with shell banks. 3. Continuously monitor wire transfers."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Key provisions in the FATF Recommendations include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "AML programs 1. Countries should require financial institutions to implement AML and terrorist financing programs. 2. According to the FATF Recommendations, AML programs should include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The development of internal procedures and controls, including adequate screening procedures to ensure high standards in employee hiring"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ongoing employee training programs on money laundering risks"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An independent audit function to test the effectiveness of the programs"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The designation of a compliance officer at the management level 3. AML programs are highly dependent on the jurisdictions in which they operate, so financial institutions should generally begin by adopting the policies and procedures in the FATF Recommendations and then tailor their programs as needed."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Customer due diligence (CDD) 1. The FATF Recommendations set out the fundamental measures that financial institutions must take to identify and verify the identity of customers and beneficial owners."}, {"type": "num", "text": "Measures to be taken include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identifying the customer and verifying the customer’s identity through reliable, independent source documents or data"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identifying the beneficial owner of the account or service, including the ownership and control structure of organizations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Obtaining information and understanding the purpose and intended nature of the business relationships involved in the account or service"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Conducting ongoing due diligence on the business relationship and transactions of the customer to ensure that they are consistent with the customer’s profile"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reporting of suspicious transactions 1. Under the FATF Recommendations, a financial institution should be required to file a report when it “suspects or has reasonable grounds to suspect that funds are the proceeds of a criminal activity, or are related to terrorist financing.” 2. The name of these reports varies by jurisdiction, but they are generally called suspicious activity reports (SARs) or suspicious transaction reports (STRs). 3. In addition to financial institutions (e.g., traditional banks, MSBs, securities brokers or traders), the parties that should file SARs or STRs include the following designated nonfinancial businesses and professions (DNFBPs):"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Casinos (including internet- and ship-based casinos)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Real estate agents"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Dealers in precious metals and stones"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Legal professionals at professional firms"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Trust and company service providers"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Large cash transactions 1. According to the FATF Recommendations, countries should implement a reporting requirement for financial institutions and DNFBPs that engage in cash transactions above the jurisdiction’s designated threshold. 2. The reports should cover domestic and international cash transactions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cross-border transfers of currency 1. Countries should implement disclosure requirements for individuals who are physically carrying currency or currency equivalents (i.e., bearer instruments) into or out of the country in amounts that are above the country’s designated reporting threshold."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "______________ is a method of disguising money acquired from illegal sources by recording"}, {"type": "para", "text": "more income on a business’s books than the business actually generates."}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Overstating revenues"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Depositing but not recording revenue"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Over time, Annika stole $500,000 in cash from her employer. She deposited the cash in small"}, {"type": "para", "text": "increments into a bank account to avoid reporting requirements. She then transferred the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "stolen funds to an overseas account and proceeded with several additional transfers and fake"}, {"type": "para", "text": "loans to foreign entities that she controlled. Finally, she moved the funds back home, disguising"}, {"type": "para", "text": "them as profits from investments. Which of the following stages of money laundering was"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Annika performing when she engaged in transfers and fake loans to foreign entities?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which type of trade-based money laundering scheme involves understating the quantity of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Over-shipment scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Inflated shipment scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Over-invoicing scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Duplicate invoicing scheme"}], "ai_summary": "This section reviews the legal aspects of actions by private parties—including fraud examiners, auditors, accountants, security personnel, private investigators, and lawyers—to investigate and recover losses due to fraud. Many of these cases will be resolved in the civil"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud", "summary_short": "[From CFE Workbook] Common Types of Bankruptcy Filings The most basic type of bankruptcy proceeding", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Common Types of Bankruptcy Filings"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Liquidation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The most basic type of bankruptcy proceeding"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Involves accounting for all dischargeable debts the subject owes, identifying all the subject’s assets, and liquidating nonexempt assets to pay off creditors"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Allows the debtor to get a court or administrative order under which some or all debts may be eliminated"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Each jurisdiction determines what exceptions exist regarding debts that may not be discharged and assets that may not be liquidated."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Typical items that may not be liquidated include the debtor’s primary residence, items of nominal value, or assets deemed necessary for the debtor to maintain employment."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Reorganization"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Allows the debtor respite from creditors so that the debtor can reorganize its financial affairs and continue as a going concern"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The hope is that the debtor will be able to pay the creditors back more of the debt in the long run by staying in business than if the entire business was ended and liquidated."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Debt is often restructured and reduced to some extent; some reorganization proceedings involve putting the debtor’s business under receivership for a certain period to ensure as much debt is paid back as possible."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Bankruptcy Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Concealed assets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The most common type of bankruptcy fraud scheme is the concealment of assets rightfully belonging to the debtor’s estate to avoid forfeiting the assets in bankruptcy."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Concealed assets might include cash, consumer property, houses, interests in partnerships and corporations, lawsuits in which the debtor is a plaintiff, and the debtor’s books and records."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A fraudulent conveyance is a concealed assets scheme in which a debtor attempts to conceal their assets by transferring the assets to another person or company for the purpose of hindering, delaying, or defrauding a creditor."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The planned bustout"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A scheme involving a planned bankruptcy to defraud creditors"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The basic approach is for an apparently legitimate business to order large quantities of goods using credit, and then dispose of those goods through legitimate or illegitimate channels."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The perpetrator then closes the business, absconding with the proceeds and leaving the suppliers unpaid."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The World Bank Principles for Effective Insolvency and Creditor/ Debtor Regimes"}, {"type": "para", "text": "(World Bank Principles)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A distillation of international best practices for designing a national insolvency system that is designed to be flexible enough to serve as a benchmark for the insolvency system of any country"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Under the World Bank Principles, countries should adopt the following anti-fraud policies:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Administrative powers 1. Most bankruptcy processes appoint a person or group with administrative powers (e.g., an administrator, trustee, receiver, examiner, or supervisor) to oversee the process. 2. The World Bank Principles recommend that the administrator have broad powers, including:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The right to cancel fraudulent contracts or transactions entered into by the debtor"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The power to collect, preserve, and dispose of the debtor’s property"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The ability to interfere with contracts to meet the objectives of the insolvency process"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The power to examine the debtor, the debtor’s agents, or other people who have knowledge of the debtor’s affairs and compel them to provide relevant information"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Governance and management 1. In liquidation proceedings, an independent insolvency representative who has the authority to manage the estate in the interest of creditors should replace a company’s management. 2. According to the World Bank Principles, there are three preferred approaches in reorganization proceedings:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Exclusive control of the proceeding is entrusted to an independent insolvency representative."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The entity’s management retains governance responsibilities."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Supervision of management is undertaken by an impartial and independent insolvency representative or supervisor."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Bankruptcy (Insolvency) Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The MOST COMMON type of bankruptcy fraud scheme is the concealment of assets."}, {"type": "para", "text": "A bustout is a planned bankruptcy. To perpetrate this type of scheme, in which order must the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "following steps be taken by the underlying business?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "I. Close the business and file bankruptcy."}, {"type": "para", "text": "II. Purchase large quantities of goods using credit."}, {"type": "para", "text": "III. Obtain credit from vendors."}, {"type": "para", "text": "IV. Sell the inventory at a significant discount."}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. I, then IV, then III, then II"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. III, then II, then I, then IV"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. III, then II, then IV, then I"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. II, then III, then IV, then I"}], "ai_summary": "[From CFE Workbook] Common Types of Bankruptcy Filings The most basic type of bankruptcy proceeding"}, {"domain": "Law", "topic": "Tax Fraud", "summary_short": "[From CFE Workbook] Tax fraud refers to intentional actions that a taxpayer commits to defraud the government of owed tax dollars. The intent of the taxpayer to wrongly file a return or provide other false tax information determines the difference between tax evasion and tax avoidance.", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "What Constitutes Tax Fraud?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Tax fraud refers to intentional actions that a taxpayer commits to defraud the government of owed tax dollars."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The intent of the taxpayer to wrongly file a return or provide other false tax information determines the difference between tax evasion and tax avoidance."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Tax evasion refers to any fraudulent actions that a taxpayer commits to avoid reporting or paying taxes."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Tax avoidance refers to a legal means of lowering one’s tax bill through legitimate deductions, credits, and shelters."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The primary distinguishing characteristic of tax evasion as compared to tax avoidance is that tax evasion is illegal, but tax avoidance is legal."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Willfulness vs. Good Faith Misunderstanding of the Law"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The most important distinction in determining whether an individual or company committed tax evasion is whether the party acted with criminal intent; most jurisdictions require a willful attempt to evade or defeat the tax in an unlawful manner."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A good faith or legitimate misunderstanding of the applicable law typically negates willfulness, the voluntary, intentional violation of a known legal duty."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Willfulness might be inferred from conduct such as:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Keeping a double set of books (not to be confused with keeping separate books and tax records, which might require different recording techniques)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Making false entries or alterations or creating false invoices or documents"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Destroying books or records"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Concealing assets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Covering up sources of income"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Moving taxable assets beyond the government’s reach"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Engaging in misleading or deceitful conduct"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Tax Evasion Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Income and wealth tax evasion"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraudsters falsify or omit material information in regard to taxes on periodic income or wealth."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Common forms 1. Failing to submit a report of one’s taxable income (if required) 2. Intentionally misrepresenting one’s income or wealth 3. Pretending to transfer assets to another person or entity to lower tax liability 4. Intentionally failing to withhold the taxable portion of an employee’s income (if required) 5. Failing to report foreign bank accounts or other taxable assets (if required) 6. Falsely claiming income was earned in another jurisdiction to lower tax liability"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Falsifying tax deductions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraudsters inappropriately use tax deductions (the itemized expenses subtracted from gross income or assets in determining the taxable amount) to reduce the taxpayer’s total tax liability."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Examples 1. Falsifying expenses, such as recording fictitious salaries to nonexistent employees 2. Fraudulently inflating expenses, such as bribing a supplier to inflate an invoice"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Submitting false information to qualify for improper deductions,"}, {"type": "para", "text": "such as pretending to qualify for a tax deduction for having"}, {"type": "para", "text": "children living at home"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Misclassifying nondeductible expenses as deductible"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Tax credit schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraudsters might attempt to evade taxes by misrepresenting their eligibility for a tax credit—an amount subtracted from a person’s or entity’s tax liability that could be used to obtain a tax refund if the credits are greater than the person’s total tax liability."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Consumption tax schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraudsters attempt to avoid consumption taxes, or those collected from the proceeds of the sale of goods or services."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Common types of consumption taxes include: 1. Sales tax"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A tax on goods or services, usually assessed at the consumer level and collected by the retailer or seller at the point of sale 2. Value-added tax (VAT)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A system that imposes a tax on an item that is assessed incrementally based on its increase in value at each point along a supply chain; the tax is collected by the seller in each transaction, and only the difference between the price paid by the initial purchaser and the price paid by the subsequent purchaser is taxed 3. Excise tax"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A tax on a narrow class of goods or services, usually assessed one time (per jurisdiction) at the manufacturer or wholesaler level"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Tax Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Common Defenses to Tax Evasion Allegations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "No tax deficiency"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To prove innocence of tax fraud matters, the defendant can establish that there is no tax deficiency and therefore no tax liability."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "This is generally the best defense."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Avoidance, not evasion"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Establishing that the taxpayer was engaging in tax avoidance and not evasion provides a defense to tax fraud."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Reliance on an attorney or accountant"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "One can assert a defense of reliance on an attorney or accountant if all the following conditions are met: 1. The taxpayer specifically relied on the advice from an expert. 2. The expert is qualified, which is determined by a facts-andcircumstances test. 3. The taxpayer gave full disclosure of the facts to the expert."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Mental illness"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Certain mental illnesses and incapacitating conditions will negate criminal intent."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Ineffective Defenses Against Tax Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Death of taxpayer"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud penalties survive the taxpayer’s death."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Bankruptcy"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Liabilities owed as a result of tax evasion may not be discharged in bankruptcy proceedings."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Amended or delinquent return"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If a person commits a tax fraud offense, amending fraudulent information held by the government will not generally relieve the taxpayer of criminal liability."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Tax evasion is legal, but tax avoidance is not."}, {"type": "para", "text": "In most jurisdictions, a taxpayer cannot be guilty of a tax-related crime if they had a good faith"}, {"type": "para", "text": "or legitimate misunderstanding of the law’s requirements."}], "ai_summary": "[From CFE Workbook] Tax fraud refers to intentional actions that a taxpayer commits to defraud the government of owed tax dollars. The intent of the taxpayer to wrongly file a return or provide other false tax information determines the difference between tax evasion and tax avoidance."}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Accounting Concepts", "summary_short": "Fraudulent acts are usually interconnected with money and finances. The fraud examiner must therefore understand the source and flow of financial transactions and how they affect an organization’s accounting records. Additionally, the fraud examiner should have an", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Accounting Basics"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The accounting equation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Assets represent the net resources owned by an entity (e.g., cash, receivables, inventory, property, patents, licenses, trademarks)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Liabilities represent an entity’s obligations or an outsider’s claims against the company’s assets (e.g., accounts payable, interest payable, long-term debt)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Owners’ equity represents the investment of a company’s owners plus accumulated profits (revenues minus expenses)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Accounting methods"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cash-basis accounting 1. Involves recording revenues and expenses based on when a company receives or pays cash 2. The advantage is its simplicity—the only thing a company must track is cash being received or paid 3. This method makes it easier for companies to track their cash flow."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Accrual-basis accounting 1. Requires revenues to be recorded when they are earned (generally, when goods are delivered or services are provided to a customer) without regard to when cash is exchanged 2. Expenses are recorded in the same period as the revenues to which they relate. 3. Provides immediate feedback to companies on their expected cash inflows and outflows, which makes it easier for them to manage their current resources and efficiently plan for the future"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Accounting Concepts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Balance sheet (or statement of financial position)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Provides insight into a company’s financial situation at a specific point in time, generally the last day of the accounting period"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Lists a company’s assets on one side and its liabilities and owners’ equity on the other side"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Two sides of the statement should balance"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Assets are generally presented in the following categories in order of liquidity (e.g., how soon they are expected to be converted to cash): 1. Current assets—assets that are expected to be converted to cash, sold, or used up within one year"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Includes cash, accounts receivable, inventory, and prepaid items 2. Long-term or noncurrent assets—assets that will likely not be converted to cash within one year"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Includes fixed assets (e.g., land, buildings, equipment) and intangible assets (e.g., patents, trademarks, goodwill)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Liabilities are presented in the following categories in order of maturity: 1. Current liabilities—obligations expected to be paid within one year"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Includes accounts payable and the portion of long-term debts that will come due within the next year 2. Long-term liabilities—liabilities that are not due for more than a year"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Includes bonds, notes, and mortgages payable."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Owners’ equity generally represents amounts from two sources: 1. Owner contributions (usually referred to as common or capital stock and paid-in capital) 2. Undistributed earnings (usually referred to as retained earnings)"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Transactions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Total Current Liabilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Long-Term Liabilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Total Long-Term Liabilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Less: Accumulated Depreciation"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Total Liabilities and Equity"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Income statement (or statement of profit or loss and other comprehensive income)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Details how much profit (or loss) a company earned during a period of time, such as a quarter or a year"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Income statement accounts are temporary; at the end of each fiscal year, they are reduced to a zero balance (closed), with the resulting net income (or loss) added to (or subtracted from) retained earnings on the balance sheet."}, {"type": "para", "text": "For the Year Ended December 31, 20XX"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Less: Cost of Goods Sold"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Total Operating Expenses"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Two basic types of accounts are reported on the income statement— revenues and expenses. 1. Revenues represent amounts received from the sale of goods or services during the accounting period."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most companies present net sales or net service revenues (i.e., total sales minus any sales refunds, returns, discounts, or allowances) as the first line item on the income statement."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Gross revenues refer to the company’s total sales during the accounting period before any deductions are made."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "From net sales, the cost of goods sold or cost of sales (i.e., the amount a company spent to produce the goods or services that were sold during the current period) is deducted."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The difference between net sales and cost of goods sold is gross profit or gross margin, which represents the leftover amount from sales to pay the company’s operating expenses. 2. Operating expenses are those costs that a company incurs to support and sustain its business operations."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Includes advertising, salaries, office supplies, repairs and maintenance, rent, utilities, depreciation, interest, and taxes."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Accrual-basis accounting requires that these items be included on the income statement in the period in which they are incurred, regardless of when they are paid."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A company’s net profit (also known as net income or net earnings) for the period is determined after subtracting operating expenses from gross profit. 1. If total expenses were greater than total revenues and the bottom line is negative, there was a net loss for the period. 2. Commonly, a profitable company will distribute some of its net income to its owners in the form of dividends. 3. Whatever income is not distributed is transferred to the retained earnings account on the balance sheet."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Statement of changes in owners’ equity (or statement of retained earnings)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Details the changes in the total owners’ equity amount listed on the balance sheet 1. The balance of the owners’ equity at the beginning of the year is the starting point for the statement. 2. The transactions that affect owners’ equity are listed next and are added together. 3. The result is added to (or subtracted from, if negative) the beginning-of-the-year balance, which provides the end-of-theyear balance for total owners’ equity."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Because it shows how the amounts on the income statement flow through to the balance sheet, it acts as the connecting link between the two statements."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Transactions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Statement of Changes in Owners’ Equity"}, {"type": "para", "text": "For the Year Ended December 31, 20XX"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Owners’ equity, January 1, 20XX"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Investment by owners during the year"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Net income for the year"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Increase in owners’ equity"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Owners’ equity, December 31, 20XX"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Some companies present a statement of retained earnings rather than a statement of changes in owners’ equity. 1. Similar to the statement of changes in owners’ equity, this statement starts with the retained earnings balance at the beginning of the year. XYZ Company Statement of Retained Earnings For the Year Ended December 31, 20XX"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Retained earnings, January 1, 20XX"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Net income for the year"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Increase in owners’ equity"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Retained earnings, December 31, 20XX"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Statement of cash flows"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Reports a company’s sources and uses of cash during the accounting period"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Comprises three main sections: 1. Cash flows from operating activities 202"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Cash flows from investing activities"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Cash flows from financing activities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Statement of Cash Flows—Direct Method"}, {"type": "para", "text": "For the Year Ended December 31, 20XX"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Cash flows from operating activities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Cash received from customers"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Cash paid for merchandise"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Net cash flows from operating activities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Cash flows from investing activities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Cash paid for purchase of equipment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Net cash flows from investing activities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Cash flows from financing activities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Cash received as owners’ investment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Cash received from issuing note payable"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Cash paid on note payable"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Net cash flows from financing activities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Cash balance at the beginning of the year"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Cash balance at the end of the year"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "120,000"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The rules by which a company’s financial transactions are recorded into their appropriate account classifications and properly reported as part of the entity’s financial statements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Publicly traded companies must follow the specific financial reporting practices of their jurisdiction, which differ among regions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Currently, there is not a universally accepted accounting recording and reporting system in existence."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Commonly used accounting frameworks include U.S. GAAP and International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS), the latter of which is permitted or required by 166 international jurisdictions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "U.S. GAAP is a rules-based framework."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "IFRS is a principle-based framework."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "International Financial Reporting Standards"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Qualitative characteristics of useful financial information under IFRS"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Relevance 1. Any financial information that might affect a decision made by a user of the financial statements is considered relevant. 2. To be relevant, the information must have a predictive value (can be used as an input to processes employed by users to predict future outcomes), confirmatory value (provides feedback about previous evaluations), or both. 3. Materiality is an entity-specific aspect of relevance based on the nature or magnitude, or both, of the items to which the information relates in the context of an individual entity’s financial report."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An item is considered material if its omission or misstatement would affect the judgment of a reasonable person who is relying on the financial statements."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Faithful representation 1. Financial information must faithfully represent the economic data of the enterprise that it purports to represent. 2. Qualities of a perfectly faithful representation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Complete (includes all information necessary to understand the data presented)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Neutral (no bias in the selection or presentation of financial information)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Free from error (no material errors or omissions in the financial reporting data or process used for reporting it)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Comparability and consistency 1. Comparability"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Enables users of financial statements to understand and base their decisions on comparisons between different entities and on similar information from a single entity for another reporting period 2. Consistency"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The use of the same methods for the same items, either from period to period within a reporting entity or in a single period across entities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Helps achieve the goal of comparability 3. Comparability and consistency do not prohibit a change in an accounting principle previously employed."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A change is permitted if required by a standard or if it results in the financial statements providing more reliable and relevant information."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Such changes must be fully disclosed in the financial statements."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Verifiability 1. Helps assure users that information is accurate and faithfully represents the entity’s financial position"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Timeliness 1. Involves providing information to decision-makers in time to be capable of influencing their decisions"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Understandability 1. Enough information should be provided about events so that a reasonable financial statement user can understand what occurred. 2. An entity’s financial statements should include all information necessary for users to make valid decisions and must not mislead them."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Going concern 1. There is an underlying assumption that an entity will continue as a going concern; that is, the life of the entity will be long enough to fulfill its financial and legal obligations. 2. Any evidence to the contrary must be reported in the entity’s financial statements."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Recognition of financial statement elements under IFRS"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Recognition is the process of incorporating an item that meets the definition of an element and satisfies the criteria for recognition into the financial statements."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Criteria for recognition 1. It is probable that any future economic benefit associated with the item will flow to or from the entity. 2. The item has a cost or value that can be measured with reliability."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Revenue recognition 1. Generally, revenue is recognized to represent the transfer of promised goods or services to a customer in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services."}, {"type": "num", "text": "Revenue should not be recognized for work that is to be"}, {"type": "para", "text": "performed in subsequent accounting periods, even though the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "work might currently be under contract."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Matching principle 1. Involves the simultaneous or combined recognition of revenues and expenses that result directly and jointly from the same transactions or other events 2. Under the matching principle, expenses are recognized in the income statement on the basis of a direct association between the costs incurred and the earning of specific items of income. 3. For example, the various costs associated with producing a specific product are recognized at the same time as the income derived from the sale of that product."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Measurement of the elements of financial statements under IFRS"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Historical cost 1. Assets are recorded at the amount of cash or cash equivalents paid or the fair value of the consideration given to acquire them at the time of their acquisition."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most financial reporting standards require use of historical cost for recording many assets, including property, plant, and equipment. 2. Liabilities are recorded at the amount of proceeds received in exchange for the obligation, or, in some circumstances (e.g., income taxes), at the amounts of cash or cash equivalents expected to be paid to satisfy the liability in the normal course of business."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Current (replacement) cost 1. Assets are carried at the amount of cash or cash equivalents that would have to be paid if the same or an equivalent asset were acquired currently."}, {"type": "num", "text": "Liabilities are carried at the undiscounted amount of cash or cash"}, {"type": "para", "text": "equivalents that would be required to settle the obligation"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Realizable (settlement) value 1. Assets are carried at the amount of cash or cash equivalents that could currently be obtained by selling the asset in an orderly disposal. 2. Liabilities are carried at their settlement values; that is, the undiscounted amounts of cash or cash equivalents expected to be paid to satisfy the liabilities in the normal course of business."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Present value 1. Assets are carried at the present discounted value of the future net cash inflows that the item is expected to generate in the normal course of business. 2. Liabilities are carried at the present discounted value of the future net cash outflows that are expected to be required to settle the liabilities in the normal course of business."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fair value 1. Assets are carried at the price that would be received to sell an asset in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. 2. Liabilities are carried at the price that would be paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Circumstances Meriting Departures from GAAP"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "As with rules for most things, departures from GAAP are sometimes required, regardless of whether you are using U.S. GAAP, IFRS, or another set of accounting standards."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Therefore, the standard-setting bodies recognize that, upon occasion, there might be an unusual circumstance when the literal application of GAAP would render the financial statements misleading. In these cases, a departure from GAAP is the proper accounting treatment. Examples include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There is concern that assets or income would be overstated and expenses or liabilities would be understated (the conservatism constraint requires that, when there is any doubt, one should avoid overstating assets and income or understating expenses and liabilities)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "It is common practice in the entity’s industry for a transaction to be reported a particular way."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The substance of the transaction is better reflected (and, therefore, the financial statements are more fairly presented) by not strictly following GAAP."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A departure produces results that are reasonable under the circumstances, especially if following GAAP produces misleading financial statements and the departure is properly disclosed."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If a transaction is considered immaterial (i.e., it would not affect a decision made by a prudent reader of the financial statements), then it need not be reported."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The expected costs of following GAAP exceed the expected benefits of compliance."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following represents the CORRECT accounting model?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Assets + Liabilities = Owners’ Equity"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Assets = Liabilities − Owners’ Equity"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following could be used to balance the accounting equation if cash were stolen?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Increasing another asset"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Reducing a liability"}], "ai_summary": "Fraudulent acts are usually interconnected with money and finances. The fraud examiner must therefore understand the source and flow of financial transactions and how they affect an organization’s accounting records. Additionally, the fraud examiner should have an"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Financial Statement Fraud", "summary_short": "Financial statement schemes are one of a large category of frauds that comprise the Occupational Fraud and Abuse Classification System, most commonly referred to as the Fraud Tree. Occupational fraud and abuse is defined as “the use of one’s occupation for personal", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Definition of Financial Statement Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The deliberate misrepresentation of the financial condition of an enterprise accomplished through the intentional misstatement or omission of amounts or disclosures in the financial statements to deceive financial statement users"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Forms That Financial Statement Fraud Typically Takes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Overstated assets or revenue"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Falsely reflects a financially stronger company by the inclusion of fictitious asset costs or artificial revenues"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Understated liabilities and expenses"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Accomplished through the exclusion of costs or financial obligations"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Five Classifications of Financial Statement Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fictitious revenues"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involve the recording of sales of goods or services that did not occur"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Fictitious sales most often involve fake customers but can also involve legitimate customers."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Accounts receivable stay on the books as an asset until they are collected. If the outstanding accounts are never collected, they will eventually need to be written off as bad debt expense."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Mysterious accounts receivable on the books that are long overdue are a common sign of a fictitious revenue scheme."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Timing differences"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The recording of revenues or expenses in improper periods to move revenues or expenses between one period and the next, increasing or decreasing earnings as desired"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Statement Fraud"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Common schemes 1. Premature revenue recognition"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Revenue is recognized when (or as) an entity satisfies a performance obligation by transferring a promised good or service (asset) to a customer."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Consequently, even if the seller has received payment for a service, revenue cannot be recognized until the service has been performed, thus satisfying the performance obligation. 2. Long-term contracts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The percentage-of-completion method recognizes revenues and expenses in proportion to what percentage of the project is complete, but this method is particularly vulnerable to manipulation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Managers can often easily manipulate the percentage-ofcompletion and the estimated costs to complete a construction project to recognize revenues prematurely and conceal contract overruns. 3. Recording expenses in the wrong period"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The timely recording of expenses is often compromised due to pressures to meet budget projections and goals or due to a lack of proper accounting controls."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "As the expensing of certain costs is pushed into periods other than the ones in which they occur, they are not properly matched against the income that they help produce."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Improper asset valuations"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Statement Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Usually involve: 1. Inventory valuation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Under U.S. generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP), International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS), and many countries’ accounting standards, inventory should be recorded at the lower of cost, market value, or net realizable value, depending on the inventory costing method used."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Failing to write down or write off inventory results in overstated assets and the mismatching of cost of goods sold with revenues."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Other methods by which inventory can be improperly stated include manipulation of the physical inventory count, inflation of the unit costs used to price out inventory, and failure to adjust inventory for the costs of goods sold."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fictitious inventory schemes usually involve the creation of fake documents, such as inventory count sheets and receiving reports. 2. Accounts receivable"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Accounts receivable are subject to manipulation in the same manner as sales and inventory, and in many cases the schemes are conducted together."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The two most common schemes involving overstated accounts receivable are recording fictitious receivables and the failure to properly account for uncollectible customer accounts."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fictitious receivables commonly arise from fictitious revenues."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Statement Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In general, accounts receivable should be reported at net realizable value—the amount of the receivable less the amount expected not to be collected."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Companies are generally required to write off uncollectible receivables as bad debt expense; thus, managers can overstate their company’s accounts receivable balance by failing to record bad debt expense."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Concealed liabilities and expenses"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Three common methods for concealing liabilities and expenses 1. Liability/expense omissions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Simply failing to record liabilities/expenses 2. Improperly capitalized costs"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Another way to increase income and assets and make the entity’s financial position appear stronger"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If ineligible expenditures are capitalized as assets and not expensed during the current period, income will be overstated; as the assets are depreciated, income in following periods will be understated."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Expensing capital expenditures"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Just as capitalizing expenses is improper, so is expensing costs that should be capitalized."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The organization might want to minimize its net income due to tax considerations or to increase earnings in future periods. Expensing an item that should be depreciated over a period of time would help accomplish that—net income is lower and, therefore, so are taxes. 3. Failure to disclose, or improper recording of, warranty costs and product-return liabilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Statement Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Improper disclosures"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management has an obligation to disclose all significant information appropriately in the financial statements and in management’s discussion and analysis."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The disclosed information must not be misleading."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Improper disclosures usually involve: 1. Contingent liabilities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Typical omissions include the failure to disclose contingent liabilities or the potential obligations that will materialize only if certain events occur in the future."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A corporate guarantee of personal loans received by a company officer and potential losses from ongoing litigation are examples of contingent liabilities that must be disclosed."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Current accounting standards require entities to disclose contingent liabilities in the notes to the financial statements if it is reasonably possible that an outflow of cash will be required to settle a present obligation in the future. 2. Subsequent events"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Events occurring or becoming known after the close of the period could have a significant effect on the financial statements and should be disclosed."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraudsters typically avoid disclosing court judgments and regulatory decisions that undermine the reported values of assets, that indicate unrecorded liabilities, or that adversely reflect upon management’s integrity."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Statement Fraud"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Management fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management has an obligation to disclose to the shareholders significant frauds committed by officers, executives, and others in positions of trust. 4. Related-party transactions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Generally occur when a company does business with another entity whose management or operating policies can be controlled or significantly influenced by the company or by some other party in common"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Not inherently wrong but must be fully disclosed 5. Accounting changes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In general, three types of changes must be disclosed:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Accounting principles"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Estimates"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reporting entities"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Financial Statement Analysis"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Vertical analysis"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A technique for analyzing the relationships among the items on an income statement, balance sheet, or statement of cash flows during a specific accounting period by expressing components as percentages of a specified base value within the statement being analyzed"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "On the balance sheet, total assets are assigned 100% on the asset side and total liabilities and equity are expressed as 100%. 1. In turn, each line item on the balance sheet is stated as a percentage of total assets (or total liabilities and equity)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Horizontal analysis"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A technique for analyzing the percentage change in individual line items on a financial statement from one accounting period to the next"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ratio analysis"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Statement Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A means of measuring the relationship between any two different financial statement amounts"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Important ratios include: 1. Current ratio"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Calculated by dividing current assets by current liabilities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A measure of liquidity 2. Quick ratio"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Calculated by dividing the total of cash, securities, and receivables by current liabilities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Compares quick assets (i.e., those that can be immediately liquidated) to current liabilities 3. Debt-to-equity ratio"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Calculated by dividing total liabilities by total equity"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Heavily considered by lending institutions because it provides a better understanding of the relative risk assumed by the creditors and owners 4. Asset turnover ratio"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Typically calculated by dividing net sales by average total assets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Used to determine the efficiency with which assets are used during the period"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Statement Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Recording expenses in the wrong period and early revenue recognition are classified as what"}, {"type": "para", "text": "type of financial fraud scheme?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Timing differences"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Improper disclosures"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Improper asset valuations"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Fictitious revenues"}, {"type": "para", "text": "James runs an electronics store. One of the main challenges in his business is keeping up with"}, {"type": "para", "text": "technological advances. Because of this, his auditors want to ensure inventory is not"}, {"type": "para", "text": "fraudulently overstated on the store’s balance sheet. Which of the following actions should the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "auditors take to ensure inventory is NOT overstated?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Ensure that inventory is recorded at the lower of cost or net realizable value"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Ensure that James has written off obsolete inventory"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. View the inventory and conduct a physical count"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Statement Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is the CORRECT calculation of the quick ratio?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Current assets divided by current liabilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Cash plus marketable securities divided by accounts payable"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Cash plus marketable securities plus receivables divided by current liabilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Cash plus receivables divided by current liabilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The asset turnover ratio, which is used to determine how efficiently assets are used to produce"}, {"type": "para", "text": "sales, is calculated by dividing net sales by the asset balance at the end of the period."}], "ai_summary": "Financial statement schemes are one of a large category of frauds that comprise the Occupational Fraud and Abuse Classification System, most commonly referred to as the Fraud Tree. Occupational fraud and abuse is defined as “the use of one’s occupation for personal"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts", "summary_short": "Asset misappropriation is the most common form of occupational fraud by a considerable degree. There are three major categories of asset misappropriation schemes. Cash receipts schemes are discussed in this section, fraudulent disbursements of cash are addressed in the", "structured": [{"type": "para", "text": "Occupational Fraud and Abuse Classification System"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Categories of Cash Receipts Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Two types"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Skimming"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Larceny"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The difference depends completely on when the cash is stolen."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Skimming"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The removal of cash from a victim entity prior to its entry in an accounting system"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees steal sales or receivables before they are recorded in the company books."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Known as off-book frauds, meaning cash is stolen before it is recorded in the victim organization’s accounts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Difficult to detect due to the lack of audit trail"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Sales Skimming"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unrecorded sales scheme"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An employee sells goods or services to a customer and collects the customer’s payment but makes no record of the sale."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Understated sales scheme"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The transaction in question is posted to the books but for a lower amount than what the perpetrator actually collected."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Skimming Receivables"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "More difficult to conceal than sales skimming because payments are expected (victim organization knows the customer owes money and is waiting for the payment)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When receivables are skimmed, the absence of the payment appears on the books as a delinquent account."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To conceal a skimmed receivable, a perpetrator must account for the payment that was due but never received."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Lapping schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The crediting of one account through the abstraction of money from another account"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Customer A’s account is funded by customer B’s payment, customer B’s account is funded by customer C’s payment, etc."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Detection of Skimming Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Receipt- or sales-level detection"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Vertical, horizontal, and ratio analysis of sales accounts"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Methods to detect inventory shrinkage include statistical sampling, trend analysis, reviews of receiving reports and inventory records, verification of material requisition and shipping documentation, and physical inventory counts."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Journal entry review"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Examine journal entries for: 1. False credits to inventory to conceal unrecorded or understated sales 2. Write-offs of lost, stolen, or obsolete inventory 3. Write-offs of accounts receivable accounts 4. Irregular entries to cash accounts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Confirming customers’ outstanding account balances"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Prevention of Skimming Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "General controls"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Sales entries and general ledger access controls should include documented policies and procedures from management."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "They generally cover: 1. Separation of duties and access control procedures 2. How to properly record transactions 3. Effective measures to safeguard access to the accounting systems and company assets"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Video monitoring of all areas where employees handle cash"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Independent reconciliations of accounts"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Since skimming is an off-book fraud, routine reconciliation of the register records to the cash in the drawer is not likely to prevent or detect a skimming scheme; however, reconciling the physical inventory count with the perpetual inventory records might reveal that there is shrinkage."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Cash Larceny"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The theft of cash that has already been recorded on the victim company’s books"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Types of cash larceny schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Theft of cash from the register 1. Involves opening the register and removing currency or checks 2. Often committed while a sale is being conducted so that it appears to be part of the transaction"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Cash larceny from the deposit 1. Occurs when the person responsible for physically taking the company’s currency and checks to the bank takes a portion of the money before making the deposit"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Detection of Cash Larceny"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cash register log totals should be reconciled to the amount of cash in the drawer."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The bank deposit should be made by someone other than the cashier or the accounts receivable clerk."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A person independent of the cash receipts and accounts receivable functions should compare entries to the cash receipts journal with:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Authenticated bank deposit slips"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The deposit per the bank statements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "All employees should have unique access codes to the cash registers, and the time periods that each access code is used should be checked against employee work schedules to ensure an employee’s access code was not used in their absence."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Prevention of Cash Larceny"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Separation of duties"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cash receipts"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Cash counts"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Bank deposits"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Deposit receipt reconciliations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Bank reconciliations"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Posting of deposits"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Cash disbursements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Assignment rotation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many internal fraud schemes are continuous in nature and require ongoing efforts by the employee to conceal the fraud, so mandatory job or assignment rotations should be implemented to uncover the concealment."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Mandatory vacations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Another individual should continue to perform the normal workload of an absent employee."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Surprise cash counts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees should know that cash will be counted on a periodic and unscheduled basis."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The removal of cash from a victim organization before the cash is entered in the organization’s"}, {"type": "para", "text": "accounting system is:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. A fraudulent disbursement"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. An illegal gratuity"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sterling collected $1,000 in cash for a sale. However, Sterling recorded the sale as $700 on the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "cash register and kept the remaining $300. This is an example of which of the following"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. An unrecorded sales (skimming) scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. A cash larceny scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. A false billing scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. An understated sales (skimming) scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Cash Receipts"}, {"type": "para", "text": "All of the following are measures that would be helpful in preventing cash larceny schemes"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Assigning an employee’s duties to another individual when that employee goes on"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Having all employees use the same cash register for their transactions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Sending out a company-wide communication informing employees of the company’s"}, {"type": "para", "text": "surprise cash-count policy"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Ensuring that the duties of making bank deposits and performing bank reconciliations"}, {"type": "para", "text": "are assigned to different individuals"}], "ai_summary": "Asset misappropriation is the most common form of occupational fraud by a considerable degree. There are three major categories of asset misappropriation schemes. Cash receipts schemes are discussed in this section, fraudulent disbursements of cash are addressed in the"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements", "summary_short": "In fraudulent disbursement schemes, an employee makes a distribution of company funds for a dishonest purpose. Some examples of fraudulent disbursements include submitting false invoices for payment, altering time cards, and making personal purchases with company funds.", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Fraudulent Disbursement Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Register disbursement schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Electronic payment schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Billing schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Payroll schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Expense reimbursement schemes"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Register Disbursement Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "False refunds"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fictitious refund scheme 1. An employee processes a transaction as if a customer were returning merchandise, even though there is no actual return. 2. The employee takes cash from the register in the amount of the false return. 3. A debit is made to the inventory system showing that the merchandise has been returned to the inventory (inventory is overstated)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Payment card refund scheme 1. The perpetrator records a refund on a payment card (e.g., credit card or debit card) sale even though the merchandise is not being returned. 2. The employee credits their own payment card number rather than the customer’s, resulting in the item’s cost being credited to the perpetrator’s payment card account."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "False voids"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Typically, when an employee sets about processing a fictitious void, the employee withholds the customer’s receipt at the time of the sale."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The employee then voids the sale and removes whatever money the customer paid for the item from the register as though it is being returned to the customer."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The copy of the customer’s receipt is attached to the void slip to verify the transaction’s authenticity."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Register Disbursement Scheme Red Flags"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There is inappropriate separation of duties for employees."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cashiers have access to refund and void controls."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cashiers are authorized to void their own transactions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Register refunds are not carefully reviewed."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Multiple cashiers operate from a single cash drawer without separate access codes."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Personal checks from cashiers are found in the cash register."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Voided transactions are not properly documented or approved by a supervisor."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Voided cash receipt forms or supporting documents are not retained. i."}, {"type": "para", "text": "There are missing or obviously altered register logs."}, {"type": "para", "text": "There are gaps in the transaction numbers on the register log."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There are excessive refunds, voids, or no-sales on the register records. l."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Inventory totals appear forced."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There are multiple refunds or voids for amounts just under the review limit."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Electronic Payment Tampering"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Dishonest employees access their employer’s electronic payment system to fraudulently initiate or divert electronic payments to themselves or their accomplices."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Some of these fraudsters abuse their legitimate access while others gain access through social engineering, password theft, or by exploiting weaknesses in their employer’s internal control or electronic payment system."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Prevention and Detection of Electronic Payment Tampering"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Internal controls"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The most important practice for preventing and detecting electronic payment fraud is separation of duties. 1. For example, in the case of online bill payments, such as those made through a bank’s website or a third-party business-tobusiness payment service, separate individuals should be responsible for maintaining payment templates, entering payments, and approving payments. 2. For wire transfers, duties for creating, approving, and releasing wires should be segregated."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Companies should consider segregating their bank accounts to maintain better control over them. 1. For example, separate accounts can be used for paper and electronic transactions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Account monitoring and reconciliation should be performed daily to quickly spot and notify the bank of any unusual transactions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Bank security services"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Automated clearing house (ACH) blocks allow account holders to notify their banks that ACH debits should not be allowed on specific accounts."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "ACH filters enable account holders to provide their banks with a list of defined criteria against which banks can filter ACH debits and reject any unauthorized transactions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "With positive pay for ACH, banks match the details of ACH payments with those on a list of legitimate and expected payments provided by the account holder. Only authorized electronic transactions are allowed to be withdrawn from the account; exceptions are reported to the customer for review."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Types of Billing Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Invoicing via shell companies"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Forming a shell company 1. Shell companies are business entities that typically have no physical presence (other than a mailing address) or employees and generate little, if any, independent economic value. 2. They might be nothing more than a fabricated name and address that an employee uses to collect disbursements from false billings. 3. Since the checks received are made in the shell company’s name, the perpetrator normally also sets up a bank account in their new company’s name so they can deposit and cash the fraudulent checks."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Purchases of services rather than goods 1. Most shell company schemes involve the purchase of services rather than goods because services are not tangible. 2. If an employee sets up a shell company to make fictitious sales of goods to their employer, these goods will obviously never arrive. 3. By comparing its purchases to its inventory levels, the victim organization might detect the fraud. It is much more difficult for the victim organization to verify that the services were never rendered."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Pass-through schemes 1. Actual goods or services are sold to the victim company. 2. Usually undertaken by employees who oversee purchasing on behalf of the victim company 3. Instead of buying merchandise directly from a vendor, the employee sets up a shell company and purchases the merchandise through that fictitious entity. They then resell the merchandise to their employer from the shell company at an increased price, thereby making an unauthorized profit on the transaction."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Invoicing via nonaccomplice vendors"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Pay and return schemes 1. An employee intentionally mishandles payments that are owed to legitimate vendors. 2. The employee then requests the vendor to return the payment and intercepts the funds. 3. Common methods include purposely paying an invoice twice and intentionally paying the wrong vendor."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Personal purchases with company funds"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Many fraudsters purchase personal items with their company’s money."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Company accounts are used to buy items for employees, their businesses, or their families."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Prevention and Detection of Billing Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Detection methods include analytical review, data analytics, statistical sampling, vendor or outsider complaints, site visits, and audit programs."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Prevention methods include employee education and training, appropriate compensation, proper documentation, proper approvals, separation of duties, hotlines, and competitive bidding."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Payroll Fraud Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ghost employees"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The term ghost employee refers to someone on the payroll who does not work for the victim company."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Through the falsification of personnel or payroll records, a fraudster causes paychecks to be generated to a nonemployee, or ghost."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The fraudster or an accomplice then converts these paychecks."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The ghost employee might be a fictitious person or a real individual who does not work for the victim employer. When the ghost is a real person, they are often the perpetrator’s friend or relative."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Scheme requirements"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements"}, {"type": "num", "text": "The ghost must be added to the payroll."}, {"type": "num", "text": "Timekeeping and wage rate information must be collected."}, {"type": "num", "text": "A paycheck must be issued to the ghost."}, {"type": "num", "text": "The check must be delivered to the perpetrator or an accomplice."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Prevention and Detection of Payroll Fraud Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Detection methods include independent payroll distribution, analysis of payee address or accounts, duplicate identification numbers, overtime authorization, commissions, and analysis of deductions from payroll checks."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Other methods for detecting ghost employees include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Comparing employee names, addresses, government identification numbers, and bank account numbers to determine if there are any unexpected duplicates"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Comparing employee payroll records to human resources employee files to ensure all individuals receiving payroll checks are employees"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Examining payroll checks for dual endorsements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Prevention methods include separation of duties (payroll preparation, payroll disbursement, payroll distribution, payroll bank reconciliations, and HR department functions) and periodic review and analysis of payroll."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Expense Reimbursement Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Mischaracterized expense reimbursements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees request reimbursement for a personal expense by claiming that the expense is business related."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Examples of mischaracterized expenses include claiming personal travel as a business trip or listing dinner with a friend as “business development” or “client entertainment.”"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Employees might submit the receipts from their personal expenses along with their expense reports and invent business reasons for the incurred costs."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The false expense report induces the victim organization to issue a check, reimbursing the perpetrator for personal expenses."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Overstated expense reimbursements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Some employees overstate the cost of actual business expenses."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Altered receipts 1. An employee alters a receipt or other supporting documentation to show a higher cost than what the employee paid."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fictitious expense reimbursements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees sometimes seek reimbursement for fictitious expenses."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Instead of overstating a real business expense or seeking reimbursement for a personal expense, an employee invents an expense to request reimbursement."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Producing fictitious receipts 1. One way to generate a reimbursement for a fictitious expense is to create fraudulent support documents, such as false receipts. 2. Using basic computer software, it is easy for employees to create realistic-looking counterfeit receipts."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Multiple reimbursements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees submit a single expense more than one time."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The most frequent example of a multiple reimbursement scheme is the submission of several types of support for the same expense."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Prevention and Detection of Expense Reimbursement Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Review and analyze expense accounts."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Two methods: historical comparisons or comparisons with budgeted amounts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Require detailed expense reports and conduct a close review of them."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Expense reports should contain the following information: 1. Receipts or other support documentation 2. Explanation of the expense, including specific business purpose"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Time period when the expense occurred"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Place of expenditure"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Amount"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When possible, require employees to submit original paper receipts."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is NOT a type of expense reimbursement scheme?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Mischaracterized expenses"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Overstated expenses"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Multiple reimbursements"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Skimmed reimbursements"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A ________________ is a fictitious entity created for the sole purpose of committing fraud."}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Nonaccomplice vendor"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Fraudulent invoice"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Fraudulent Disbursements"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Zach was booking travel arrangements for a business trip. He purchased an airline ticket online"}, {"type": "para", "text": "using his own funds and obtained a receipt for the ticket via email. Using photo-editing"}, {"type": "para", "text": "software, Zach increased the ticket price on the electronic receipt and submitted the altered"}, {"type": "para", "text": "receipt to his employer for reimbursement. This is an example of what type of fraud scheme?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Personal purchases with company funds"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Mischaracterized expense scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Multiple reimbursement scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Overstated expense scheme"}], "ai_summary": "In fraudulent disbursement schemes, an employee makes a distribution of company funds for a dishonest purpose. Some examples of fraudulent disbursements include submitting false invoices for payment, altering time cards, and making personal purchases with company funds."}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Payment Fraud", "summary_short": "An influx of new payment technologies balanced against the need to retain traditional methods has resulted in a period of great change in the payment industry. Countless payment methods, ranging from cash to cryptocurrency, allow items and services to be bought online", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Check Fraud Rings"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Check fraud rings thrive because the items needed to commit check fraud are easily obtainable and the cost is minimal."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Often, the only necessary equipment for a check fraud ring is a scanner, printer, and personal computer."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The chances of being arrested and prosecuted for check fraud are low, and the penalties are relatively mild in most jurisdictions."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Payment Card Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The misuse of credit or debit card information to make purchases without the cardholder’s authorization"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Schemes are successful because it is unlikely that the fraudster will be caught and prosecution is not ensured."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Types of payment card fraud schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unauthorized use of a lost or stolen payment card 1. Fraudulent activity normally occurs within hours of the loss or theft of a card, before most victims have called to report the loss."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Counterfeit cards 1. One method involves using blank plastic cards, or plastic the size of a payment card that is embossed with account numbers and names"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "This scheme often works in conjunction with a corrupt and collusive merchant or a merchant’s employee. 2. Other counterfeit cards are wholly manufactured using highspeed printers and are used in association with organized crime groups. 3. Common tools in the reproduction process include desktop computers, embossers, tipping foil, and laminators."}, {"type": "num", "text": "The hologram is the most difficult aspect of a card to reproduce."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Skimming or shimming 1. Requires a device that stores a large amount of payment card numbers"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A skimmer is a device that scans magnetic strips from cards."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A shimmer is a device that reads microchips in smart cards. 2. More frequent in businesses where an employee can remove the card from the customer’s view to process the transaction before returning it to the customer"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Prepaid Card Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves prepaid gift and debit cards, which are commonly used by those who do not have a bank account or who prefer relatively anonymous payment methods"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Prepaid cards are attractive to fraudsters because they can be purchased at countless retailers and are difficult to track after they have been purchased and activated."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Among the schemes that prepaid cards are used to facilitate are payment (i.e., credit or debit) card theft schemes."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Thieves use stolen payment cards to purchase prepaid debit or gift cards, thus quickly converting the illicit payment card funds into a legitimate cash equivalent."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "These schemes have prompted many retailers to insist on cash or debit cards with personal identification numbers (PINs) as the only payment methods allowed for the purchase of prepaid gift and debit cards."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Smart Cards"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Plastic, credit-card-sized cards that are embedded with a microchip"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "These cards can identify the user through encrypted information on the chip and must be inserted into a card reader connected to the credit provider’s network."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unlike regular magnetic stripe payment cards, smart cards cannot be easily replicated or counterfeited; thus, they are generally more secure."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Smart cards include a wide variety of hardware and software features capable of detecting and reacting to tampering attempts and countering possible attacks."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If someone tries to tamper with a chip on a smart card, the card detects the intrusion and shuts itself down, rendering the card useless."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Smart cards have significantly reduced fraud for card-present (CP) transactions, but much of the fraud has displaced to card-not-present (CNP) transactions on the internet."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Electronic Bill Payment and Person-to-Person Payments"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Automatic payments can be set up via a bank or credit card website to pay bills."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Individuals can pay each other for goods or services through the person-toperson (P2P) system."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An electronic funds transfer (EFT) is any transfer of funds, other than one originated by a check or similar paper instrument, that is initiated through an electronic terminal, telephonic instrument, or computer or magnetic tape that orders or purports to authorize a financial institution to debit or credit an account."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Examples of EFT fraud include: 1. A biller might send a bill for services not rendered or for goods never sent. 2. A person who has obtained information about another person’s bank account might instruct a biller to obtain payment from the other person’s account. 3. A hacker might obtain passwords and usernames from an aggregator and use that information to direct transfers from a consumer’s bank account. 4. An employee at the site providing electronic bill presentment and payment (EBPP) services who knows consumers’ usernames and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "passwords might use that information to direct transfers from"}, {"type": "para", "text": "consumers’ bank accounts."}, {"type": "num", "text": "A bank employee might use customer information to direct"}, {"type": "para", "text": "transfers from a customer’s account."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Prevention and Detection of Electronic Funds Transfer Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Specific safeguards that banks can perform to reduce the risk that they or their customers become victimized by unauthorized EFTs include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Send a welcome letter to the address on the application with the bank’s return address so that the letter is returned if the applicant does not live there."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Verify by phone or additional mailings any change of address requests in the same way that new account applications are verified."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "If a customer reports the loss or theft of an access device, cancel the existing card, PIN, or other form of access and issue a new one."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "If a customer reports that a person previously authorized to use an access device no longer has that authority, cancel all cards, PINs, or other access devices and issue new ones to the customer."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Always mail PINs separately from other information, such as usernames, with which they are associated."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Separate the responsibility of bank employees who have custody of information relating to access devices from those who have responsibility for issuance, verification, or reissuance of PINs."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Account Takeover Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Occurs when a fraudster surreptitiously takes control of a payment account (e.g., credit cards, banking, brokerage, or online retail accounts)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To take over an account, thieves obtain email addresses or other login information and use various means to obtain passwords, such as phishing emails or password-cracking botnet attacks."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Because consumers often use the same username and password for multiple accounts, hackers commonly write code that can run credentials obtained from a data breach at one company to see if they are valid at another."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Once the thief overtakes an account, communication methods and contact information are altered to keep the account holder unaware of the fraudulent activity, leaving the thief free to place orders using stored payment information, transfer funds, or request duplicate payment cards."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Mobile Payments"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Typically made through contactless technology, such as digital wallets or applications—also known as in-app payments."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common mobile payment applications include Apple Pay, Google Pay, Zelle, PayPal, Cash App, and Venmo."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most mobile payments require users to authenticate themselves."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The technology in many mobile devices allows for biometric authentication, such as a partial fingerprint or three-dimensional facial scan, which is difficult for fraudsters to bypass."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Mobile payments that do not require or offer biometric authentication can be more vulnerable to cyberattacks due to the common practice of using the same log-in credentials for multiple applications."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is an example of a way in which an electronic funds transfer (EFT) fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "scheme can be committed?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. A person who has stolen information about another person’s bank account instructs a"}, {"type": "para", "text": "biller to obtain payment from that account"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. An employee of a person-to-person (P2P) provider misappropriates a customer’s"}, {"type": "para", "text": "account and password information"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. A hacker obtains the account and password information of consumers to direct funds"}, {"type": "para", "text": "If a customer reports the loss or theft of an access device, the financial institution should"}, {"type": "para", "text": "attempt to prevent fraud related to electronic funds transfers (EFTs) by canceling the existing"}, {"type": "para", "text": "card, personal identification number (PIN), or other form of access and issuing a new one."}], "ai_summary": "An influx of new payment technologies balanced against the need to retain traditional methods has resulted in a period of great change in the payment industry. Countless payment methods, ranging from cash to cryptocurrency, allow items and services to be bought online"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Cyberfraud", "summary_short": "Parasitic viruses (sometimes called binary file infectors) attach themselves to program files (i.e., executables). When a user launches a program that has a parasitic virus, the virus is also launched. The parasitic virus is given the same rights as the program to which the virus is", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Recognizing Computer Intrusion"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is important for fraud examiners and other computer system users to recognize common signs that intruders have accessed or affected a computer system or network, such as:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unusual inbound or outbound network traffic 1. Abnormal traffic, which includes emails and data transmitted to or from the internet, can be an indication that an attacker has gained access to an organization’s network and might include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Geographical irregularities related to network access and traffic"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Contacts receiving strange messages from email accounts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Redirected web searches"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Anomalies in user access to network files 1. Most organizations employ a system that restricts access to sensitive files or information on their network to those who require that access as part of their organizational role; thus, abnormalities or outliers in usual access patterns could indicate that a network has been compromised and might include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Bundles of data in the incorrect place"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Higher volumes of unsuccessful or suspicious system log-in attempts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Large number of requests for the same file"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Passwords not working"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Unusual network or computer performance 1. Some unusual performance issues that could indicate that a computer or network is compromised include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Slowed access to files"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Disconnection from the internet"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fake antivirus messages appearing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unusual hard drive activity that results in loud noises"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unwanted browser toolbars and pop-up ads appearing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unwanted or unknown software installed"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Conditions Conducive to Insider Cyberfraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Access privileges are beyond those required to perform assigned job functions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Exception reports are not reviewed and resolved."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Access logs are not reviewed."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Production programs are run at unusual hours."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Lack of separation of duties exists in the data center."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Methods Used to Gain Unauthorized Access to a Computer System"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Social engineering"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A method for gaining unauthorized access to a computer system in which the attacker deceives victims into disclosing personal information, such as their password, or convinces them to commit acts that facilitate the attacker’s intended scheme"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Phishing 1. Occurs when a fraudster manipulates victims into providing sensitive information by falsely claiming to be from an actual business, bank, internet service provider (ISP), or other entity with which the target does business 2. Phishers typically use emails to direct internet users to imitation websites that look legitimate, such as log-in portals for online banks, retailers, or government agencies. Phishers control these imitation websites and use them to steal sensitive information, such as bank account details and passwords."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Business email compromise (BEC)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Scheme in which fraudsters target employees who can make large payments or who have access to sensitive proprietary information"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Typically involve fraudulent emails that appear to be from the company’s own chief executive officer (CEO) or from the head of a foreign supplier"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "These emails often request confidential information or a transfer of funds to an account owned by the fraudster."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Vishing 1. The act of leveraging Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) in using the telephone system to falsely claim to be a legitimate enterprise to scam users (both consumers and businesses) into disclosing personal information or executing an act that furthers a scheme"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Smishing 1. A hybrid of phishing and short message service (text messaging) 2. The attacker uses text messages or other short message systems to dupe an individual or business into providing sensitive data by falsely claiming to be from an actual business, bank, ISP, or other entity with which the target does business."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Pharming 1. A type of attack in which users are fooled into entering sensitive data (such as a password or credit card number) into a malicious website that imitates a legitimate website 2. Different from phishing because the attacker does not have to rely on users clicking a link in an email or other message to direct them to the imitation website"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Exploits a vulnerability in the domain name system (DNS) server"}, {"type": "para", "text": "software that allows a hacker to acquire the domain name for a site"}, {"type": "para", "text": "and redirect the website traffic from a legitimate site to a false one"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Common Carriers of Malware"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unknown or unchecked application software"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Infected websites"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Banner ads"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Software or media that employees bring to work"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Files downloaded from the internet"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Infected software from vendors and suppliers"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Uncontrolled and shared program applications"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Files uploaded from storage devices, such as USB flash drives i."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Demonstration software"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Freeware and shareware files"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Email attachments"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Malware"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Worms"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Computer programs that replicate themselves and penetrate operating systems to spread malicious code to other computers"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Self-contained but, unlike a virus, a worm does not need to be part of another program to propagate itself"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Often designed to exploit the file-transmission capabilities of computers (e.g., email) and are almost always spread through email, networks, and online chat"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Trojan horse"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A program or command procedure that appears useful but contains hidden code that causes damage"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When the hidden code is activated, it performs some unwanted or harmful function."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Spyware"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A type of software that collects and reports information about a computer user without the user’s knowledge or consent"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ransomware"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A form of malicious software that locks a user’s operating system and restricts access to data files until a ransom is paid"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Many victims never regain access to their files even after meeting the demands."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Keyloggers"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A form of malware designed to capture a user’s keystrokes, providing a method to collect passwords or other authentication information"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Information Security Goals"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "All branches of an information system, including the e-commerce branch, should strive to achieve the following information security goals for users and asset holders:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Confidentiality of data 1. The information involved in an information system transaction must only be accessible to authorized parties."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Integrity of data 1. Transactions must be incapable of modification by unauthorized parties."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Availability of data 1. Information resources must be available. Businesses that offer products or services are very concerned with their accessibility because each moment their resources are not available results in lost opportunities."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Technical Security and Controls"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Technical security involves the use of safeguards incorporated into computer hardware or systems, operations or applications software, communications hardware and software, and related devices."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Technical controls protect systems against threats like unauthorized use, disclosure, modification, destruction, or denial of service."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common types include: 1. Logical access controls"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Process by which users are identified and granted certain privileges to information, systems, or resources 2. Network security"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Firewalls"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Intrusion detection systems (IDSs)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Intrusion prevention systems (IPSs)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Network access controls 3. Operating system security 4. Encryption"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The deliberate scrambling of a message so that it is unreadable except to those who hold the key for unscrambling the message 5. Application security"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Controls implemented at the application level to prevent data from being accessed, stolen, modified, or deleted by unauthorized users"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Administrative Security and Controls"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Administrative security consists of management constraints, operational procedures, accountability procedures, and supplemental administrative controls established to provide an acceptable level of protection for computing resources."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Administrative controls ensure safeguards against system and network infiltration on an organizational level."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common types include: 1. Security policies and awareness training 2. Separation of duties"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Achieved by diffusing the tasks and associated privileges for a specific security process among multiple individuals to ensure that no person acting alone can compromise security controls 3. Data classification 4. Computer security risk assessments 5. Security audits and tests 6. Incident response plans"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Describe the actions an organization will take when a data breach occurs."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The recommended methodology for responding to cybersecurity incidents includes the following steps:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Preparation 1. Involves the creation and implementation of the incident response plan"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Detection and analysis 1. Involves identifying incidents of breach as quickly as possible"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Containment and eradication 1. Involves mitigating the attack effectively and efficiently by restoring control of the affected systems and limiting the damage"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Breach notification 1. Involves management determining whether it is obligated to notify customers of the security breach"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Recovery and follow-up 1. Involves returning the affected systems to an operational level, monitoring them to ensure they are functioning adequately, and reviewing the experience to determine how well the response plan worked and what improvements should be made in the future 242"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is the definition of the computer manipulation technique known as a"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Searching for valid access codes or trap doors"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Installation of a program or command procedure that appears useful but contains"}, {"type": "para", "text": "hidden code that causes damage"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Gaining information about a system using deception, such as someone else’s password"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Using several networks in a series to avoid detection"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is NOT an indicator that a computer or network might have been"}, {"type": "para", "text": "accessed or compromised by an unauthorized user or entity?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. A user in the IT department detects geographical irregularities in network traffic."}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. An authorized user is denied access to an area in the network that is part of their role."}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Users are prompted to install unusual software or patches onto their computers."}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Users receive a notification to update their system passwords before they expire."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Logical access controls, encryption, and application security are all technical security controls"}, {"type": "para", "text": "used to safeguard computer systems and communication networks."}], "ai_summary": "Parasitic viruses (sometimes called binary file infectors) attach themselves to program files (i.e., executables). When a user launches a program that has a parasitic virus, the virus is also launched. The parasitic virus is given the same rights as the program to which the virus is"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Corruption", "summary_short": "Other techniques for tracing corrupt payments can be found in the “Tracing Illicit Transactions” chapter in the Investigation section of the Fraud Examiners Manual. A conflict of interest occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "What Is Corruption?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The wrongful use of influence to procure a benefit for the actor or another person, contrary to the duty or rights of others"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Forms of Corruption"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Bribery"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The offering, giving, receiving, or soliciting of corrupt payments (i.e., items of value paid to procure a benefit contrary to the rights of others) to influence an official act or business decision"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Does not necessarily involve direct payments of cash or goods"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Kickbacks"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Improper, undisclosed payments made to obtain favorable treatment"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "In the government setting, kickbacks are the giving or receiving of anything of value to obtain or reward favorable treatment in relation to a government contract."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Illegal gratuities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Items of value given to reward a decision, often after the recipient has made the decision"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Illegal gratuity schemes do not necessarily involve an intent to influence a particular decision before the fact."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Occur when an item of value is given for, or because of, some act"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Typically limited to employees or agents of a government entity in reference to “official acts”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Economic extortion"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Present when an employee or official, through the wrongful use of actual or threatened force or fear, demands money or some other consideration to make a particular business decision"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Methods of Making Corrupt Payments"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Gifts, travel, and entertainment"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cash payments"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Checks and other financial instruments"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Hidden interests"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The payer might give a hidden interest in a joint venture or other profit-making enterprise."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The recipient’s interest might be concealed through a straw nominee, hidden in a trust or other business entity, or included by an undocumented verbal agreement."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Loans"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An outright payment falsely described as an innocent loan"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A legitimate loan in which a third party—the corrupt payer—makes or guarantees payments to satisfy the loan"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A legitimate loan made on favorable terms (e.g., an interest-free loan)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Credit cards"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The payer might use a credit card to pay a recipient’s transportation, vacation, or entertainment expenses, or pay off a recipient’s credit card debt."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The recipient might carry and use the corrupt payer’s credit card."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Transfers not at fair market value"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The corrupt payer might sell or lease property to the recipient at a price that is less than its market value, or the payer might agree to buy or rent property from the recipient at an inflated price."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The recipient might also “sell” an asset to the payer but retain the title or use of the property."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Promises of favorable treatment"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Corruption"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Methods of Proving Corrupt Payments"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Three ways"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Use an inside witness."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Secretly infiltrate or record ongoing transactions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Identify and trace corrupt payments through audit steps."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Suspected on-book schemes are best approached from the point of payment."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Off-book schemes are most easily identified at the suspected point of receipt, through the use of an inside witness, or through surveillance."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Conflict of Interest"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on behalf of a principal—has an undisclosed personal or economic interest in a matter that could influence their professional role"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is TRUE regarding the methods typically used for making corrupt"}, {"type": "para", "text": "payments in corruption schemes?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Payers often make corrupt payments by selling property to recipients at prices lower"}, {"type": "para", "text": "than the property’s market value"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Payers often make corrupt payments by paying off the recipient’s credit card debt"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Payers often make corrupt payments by offering recipients loans on extremely favorable"}, {"type": "para", "text": "When an employee or official uses force or fear to demand money in exchange for making a"}, {"type": "para", "text": "particular business decision, that individual is engaging in:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. An illegal gratuity scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Economic extortion"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following scenarios is an example of a conflict of interest?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. An employee has an undisclosed personal relationship with a company that does"}, {"type": "para", "text": "business with their employer."}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. An employee for a phone installation company works as a fishing guide on weekends"}, {"type": "para", "text": "but does not tell the phone company about the other job."}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. An employee for a pharmaceutical company has an economic interest in a company that"}, {"type": "para", "text": "does business with their employer and discloses it to their employer."}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. An employee is related to someone who works for one of their company’s vendors and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "informs their employer of the relationship."}], "ai_summary": "Other techniques for tracing corrupt payments can be found in the “Tracing Illicit Transactions” chapter in the Investigation section of the Fraud Examiners Manual. A conflict of interest occurs when an employee or agent—someone who is authorized to act on"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Contract and Procurement Fraud", "summary_short": "The procurement system is the collection of processes, procedures, and entities involved in purchasing goods and services by public or private entities. And because the primary objective of an effective procurement policy is to achieve the best value of money, it is", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Methods of Procurement"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Competitive bidding using sealed bids"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Contracting by negotiation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Simplified acquisition procedures"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Phases in the Procurement Process"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The presolicitation phase"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Need recognition"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Development of specifications"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Determination of the method to use for acquiring the goods or services"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Development of award criteria"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The solicitation phase"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Bid solicitation"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Bid preparation"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Bid submission"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The bid evaluation and award phase"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The procuring employees evaluate the bids or proposals, conduct discussions and negotiations, and give the bidders an opportunity to revise their proposals."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Procuring employees then select the winning bid or proposal."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The post-award and administration phase"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The parties that were contracted fulfill their respective duties through the performance of their contractual obligations."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Activities that occur during this phase include contract modifications (i.e., change orders); review of completed portions and release of monies; and assessment of deliverables for compliance with the contract terms, including quality control."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Contract and Procurement Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Schemes Involving Collusion Among Contractors"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Complementary bidding"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Competitors submit token bids that are not genuine attempts to win the contract."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Token bids give the appearance of genuine bidding, but, by submitting token bids, the conspirators can influence the contract price and who is awarded the contract."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Bid rotation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Two or more contractors conspire to alternate the business among themselves on a rotating basis."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Bid suppression"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Two or more contractors enter into an illegal agreement whereby at least one of the conspirators refrains from bidding or withdraws a previously submitted bid to ensure that a particular competitor’s bid is accepted."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Market division"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Competitors agree to divide and allocate markets and to refrain from competing in each other’s designated portion of the market."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Red Flags of Schemes Involving Collusion Among Contractors"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The industry has limited competition."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The same contractors bid on each project or product."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The winning bid appears too high."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "All contractors submit consistently high bids."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The winning bidder subcontracts work to one or more losing bidders or to nonbidders."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Some bids fail to conform to the essential requirements of the solicitation documents."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fewer competitors than usual submit bids on a project or product."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When a new contractor enters the competition, the bid prices begin to decline. i."}, {"type": "para", "text": "There is a pattern indicating that the last party to bid wins the contract."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Contract and Procurement Fraud"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Schemes Involving Collusion Between Contractors and Employees"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Need recognition"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Procurement employees convince their employer that it needs excessive or unnecessary products or services."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Often, purchasing entity employees receive a bribe or kickback for convincing their employer to recognize a need for a particular product or service."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Red flags 1. An organization has unusually high requirements for stock and inventory levels. 2. An organization’s materials are not being ordered at the optimal reorder point. 3. An organization has a large number of surplus items written off as scrap. 4. An organization has a need that is defined in a way that can only be met by a certain supplier or contractor. 5. An organization fails to develop a satisfactory list of backup suppliers."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Bid tailoring"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An employee with procurement responsibilities, often in collusion with a contractor, drafts bid specifications in a way that gives an unfair advantage to a certain contractor."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Three primary methods 1. Drafting narrow specifications: A corrupt employee tailors the bid specifications to accommodate a vendor’s capabilities and to eliminate other competitors so that the favored contractor is effectively guaranteed to win the contract."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Contract and Procurement Fraud"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Drafting broad specifications: A corrupt employee of the buyer"}, {"type": "para", "text": "designs unduly broad qualification standards to qualify an"}, {"type": "para", "text": "otherwise unqualified contractor."}, {"type": "num", "text": "Drafting vague specifications: The buyer’s personnel and the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "contractor collude to write vague specifications or intentionally"}, {"type": "para", "text": "omit bid specifications, enabling subsequent contract amendments"}, {"type": "para", "text": "and allowing the contractor to raise the contract’s price."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Red flags 1. Weak controls over the bidding process 2. Only one or a few bidders respond to bid requests. 3. The contract is not rebid even though fewer than the minimum number of bids are received. 4. Unusual or unreasonably narrow or broad specifications for the type of goods or services being procured 5. Requests for bid submissions do not provide clear bid submission information. 6. Unexplained changes in contract specifications from previous proposals or similar items 7. High number of competitive awards to one supplier 8. High number of change orders for one supplier"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Bid manipulation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A procuring employee manipulates the bidding process to benefit a favored contractor or supplier."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Some common ways to commit these schemes include: 1. Using obscure publications to publish bid solicitations 2. Publishing bid solicitations during holiday periods 3. Accepting late bids or falsifying the bid log 4. Altering bids 5. Extending bid opening dates without justification"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Contract and Procurement Fraud"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Opening bids prematurely"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Discarding or losing a bid or proposal"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Disqualifying bids for improper reasons (e.g., voiding bids for"}, {"type": "para", "text": "alleged errors in specifications)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Red flags 1. Weak controls over the bidding procedures are present. 2. There is evidence of changes to bids after they were received. 3. Winning bid is voided for errors and job is rebid or awarded to another contractor. 4. A procurement employee accepts late bids. 5. Bid deadlines are changed. 6. Despite receiving fewer than the minimum number of bids, the contract is not rebid."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Performance Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Nonconforming goods or services (product substitution)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Attempts by contractors to deliver goods or services to the procuring entity that do not conform to the underlying contract specifications"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Detection methods 1. Review contract or purchase order (PO) specifications. 2. Examine contractor’s statements, claims, invoices, and supporting documents. 3. Review correspondence and contract files for indications of noncompliance regarding specifications. 4. Review inspection reports to determine if work performed and materials used in a project were inspected and considered acceptable. 5. Interview procurement personnel about the presence of any red flags or other indications of noncompliance."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Contract and Procurement Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cost mischarging"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A contractor charges the procuring entity for costs that are not permissible, are not reasonable, or cannot be allocated to the contract directly or indirectly."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Three main types 1. Accounting mischarges"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A contractor knowingly charges unallowable costs to the buyer by concealing or misrepresenting them as allowable costs, or by hiding them in accounts, such as office supplies, that are not usually closely audited. 2. Material mischarges"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Material costs are mischarged, both as to their reasonableness and their allocability."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Detection methods"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Determine if the costs of the contract have exceeded or are expected to exceed the value of the contract."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Compare contract charges to determine if materials are properly charged to the job."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Examine materials ordered and charged in excess of contract requirements."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Examine seemingly unrelated materials charged on routing slips. 3. Labor mischarges"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The contractor charges the procuring entity for work that was not actually performed."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Detection methods"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Examine time cards, total the hours expended on the contract, and compare them to hours billed."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Contract and Procurement Fraud"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Review the standard and actual labor rates to determine if there are significant differences between the two."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Compare direct and indirect labor account totals from the prior year to the current year and note the percentage change."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Change order abuse"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A corrupt contractor submits a low bid to ensure that it wins the contract award, but, after the procuring entity awards the contract, the corrupt contractor increases its price with subsequent change orders (written agreements between the procuring entity and the contractor to make changes in a signed contract)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Typically involves collusion between the contractor and personnel from the procuring entity"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Detection methods 1. Examine change orders that add new items to the contract. 2. Examine change orders that increase the scope, quantity, or price of the existing contract. 3. Interview complaining contractors, unsuccessful bidders, and procurement personnel about the presence of any red flags. 4. Search and review external records for any history of misconduct."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Prevention and Detection of Contract and Procurement Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Monitoring procurement activities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Companies should implement a continuous, self-auditing program to monitor the performance of their procurement activities."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Vendor management"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management should take steps to prevent and detect criminal conduct by its vendors, such as: 1. Vendor background checks"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Contract and Procurement Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management must conduct adequate due diligence to identify and select competent and qualified vendors, such as reviewing their business reputation, financial soundness, and experience. 2. Controls for vendor master file management"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A procuring entity must establish clear procedures for setting up new vendors and changing vendor master files."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A vendor master file is a database that contains a record of all vendors with whom a company conducts business."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Procuring entities should require accounts payable personnel to verify new vendors by conducting a vendor background check before entering them into the vendor master file."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Vendor master files should be accurate and kept up to date; an inaccurate or incomplete vendor master file can result in greater risks of duplicate payments, unfavorable payment terms, and noncompliance regarding regulations."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The person responsible for the vendor master file should not be authorized to approve payments for invoices or to sign checks. 3. Vendor monitoring"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Procuring entities must use monitoring and auditing systems reasonably designed to detect criminal conduct by their vendors."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The procedures used to monitor vendors are similar to those used to evaluate vendors and should address red flags of vendor schemes that pose the greatest risk."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Contract and Procurement Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "AD&N Railway solicits bids to lay several miles of new railroad track. Bob, who works for AD&N,"}, {"type": "para", "text": "writes the specifications for the project to provide that AD&N will only contract with companies"}, {"type": "para", "text": "that have more than 25 years of experience. Bob knows that only B&P Track Co., one of the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "prospective bidders, has more than 25 years of experience. What type of procurement fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "scheme has taken place?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Bid tailoring by drafting narrow specifications"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Bid tailoring by drafting broad specifications"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A contractor who delivers materials of lesser quality than specified in the contract or uses a"}, {"type": "para", "text": "lower quality staff than specified in the contract might be involved in which of the following"}, {"type": "para", "text": "types of procurement fraud schemes?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Nonconforming goods or services fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Product division fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Contract and Procurement Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is NOT a red flag that might indicate the existence of a need recognition"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. The purchasing entity has unusually high requirements for stock and inventory levels."}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. The purchasing entity does not have a satisfactory list of backup suppliers."}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. The purchasing entity has a large number of surplus items written off as scrap."}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. The purchasing entity’s materials are being ordered at the optimal reorder point."}], "ai_summary": "The procurement system is the collection of processes, procedures, and entities involved in purchasing goods and services by public or private entities. And because the primary objective of an effective procurement policy is to achieve the best value of money, it is"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets", "summary_short": "Employees target inventory, equipment, supplies, and other noncash assets for theft in several ways. These schemes can range from the theft of a box of pens to the theft of millions of dollars’ worth of company equipment. These schemes can even entail an individual stealing", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Misuse of Inventory and Other Assets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Two ways a person can misappropriate a company asset"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The asset can be misused (or “borrowed”) (e.g., company vehicles, supplies, computers)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The asset can be stolen."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Inventory Theft Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Larceny schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Larceny is “the wrongful and fraudulent taking and carrying away by one person of the mere personal goods of another from any place, with a felonious intent to convert them to his (the taker’s) use, and make them his [the taker’s] property, without the consent of the owner.”"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Most noncash larceny schemes are committed by employees with access to inventory or supplies."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "In a false sale scheme, the employee-fraudster’s outside accomplice pretends to buy merchandise, but the employee does not record the sale."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Purchasing and receiving schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Dishonest employees can also manipulate a company’s purchasing and receiving functions to facilitate the theft of inventory and other assets."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "In a falsifying incoming shipments scheme, a person charged with receiving goods on the victim company’s behalf—such as a warehouse supervisor or receiving clerk—falsifies the records of incoming shipments."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Concealing Inventory Shrinkage"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When inventory is stolen, the perpetrator’s key concealment issue is shrinkage."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Inventory shrinkage is the unaccounted-for reduction in the company’s inventory that results from error or theft."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Methods for Concealing Inventory Shrinkage"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Altered inventory records"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves changing the perpetual inventory record so that it matches the physical inventory count"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Also known as a forced reconciliation of the account"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fictitious sales and accounts receivable"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When the perpetrator makes an adjusting entry to the perpetual inventory and cost of sales accounts, there is no sales transaction on the books that corresponds to these entries."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "To fix this problem, a perpetrator might enter a debit to accounts receivable and a corresponding credit to the sales account so that it appears the missing goods have been sold."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Write-off inventory"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Writing off inventory as obsolete, damaged, or unsellable allows employees to remove assets from the books before or after they are stolen, and it eliminates the shrinkage problem that inherently exists in all noncash asset misappropriations."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Physical padding"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Making it appear as though there are more assets present in the warehouse or stockroom than there actually are"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Detection of Inventory Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Analytical review"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Example: Sales and cost of goods sold should move together since they are directly related. However, if the cost of goods sold increases by a disproportionate amount in relation to sales and there have been no changes to the purchase prices, quantities purchased, or quality of products purchased, then the cause of the disproportionate increase in cost of goods sold might be one of three things:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Ending inventory has been depleted by theft"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Someone has been embezzling money through a false billing"}, {"type": "para", "text": "scheme (i.e., submitting invoices and collecting the payments for"}, {"type": "para", "text": "inventory that was never delivered)"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Someone has been skimming sales revenue"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Prevention of Inventory Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Proper documentation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The following items should be prenumbered and controlled: 1. Purchase orders 2. Receiving reports 3. Perpetual records 4. Raw materials requisitions 5. Shipping documents 6. Job cost sheets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Separation of duties"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Different personnel should be responsible for the following duties: 1. Requisition of inventory 2. Receipt of inventory 3. Disbursement of inventory 4. Conversion of inventory to scrap 5. Receipt of proceeds from disposal of scrap"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Independent checks"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Someone independent of the purchasing or warehousing functions should conduct physical observation of inventory."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The personnel conducting the physical observations should also be knowledgeable about the inventory."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Physical safeguards"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "All merchandise should be physically guarded and locked; access should be limited to authorized personnel only."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Asset Misappropriation: Inventory and Other Assets"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "___________ is the unaccounted-for reduction in a company’s inventory that results from error"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is a method that would help prevent the theft of company inventory?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Using prenumbered shipping documents, perpetual inventory records, and inventory"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Restricting inventory access to authorized personnel"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Separating responsibility for incoming shipments and completing the inventory"}], "ai_summary": "Employees target inventory, equipment, supplies, and other noncash assets for theft in several ways. These schemes can range from the theft of a box of pens to the theft of millions of dollars’ worth of company equipment. These schemes can even entail an individual stealing"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Financial Institution Fraud", "summary_short": "External fraud schemes are those committed by outside entities, typically by individuals or groups of individuals against organizations. Fraud schemes committed by outsiders usually occur within specific industries. Therefore, the following chapters are organized by type of", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Embezzlement Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "False accounting entries"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees debit the general ledger to credit their own accounts or conceal a theft from a customer account (i.e., employees adjust the general ledger to conceal the stolen amount)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unauthorized withdrawals"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees make unauthorized withdrawals from customer accounts."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unauthorized disbursement of funds to outsiders"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees might abuse their authority to approve fraudulent (i.e., counterfeit, forged, or stolen) instruments or otherwise make an unauthorized disbursement of funds to an outsider."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Moving money from customers’ dormant or inactive accounts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Persons with apparent authority create journal entries or transfer orders not initiated by customers to move money among accounts. The accounts used are typically dormant or inactive accounts, which are those accounts that show little or no activity."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Types of Loan Fraud Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Double-pledging collateral"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Borrowers pledge the same collateral (i.e., an item of value used to secure or guarantee a loan) with different lenders before liens are recorded without telling the lenders."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Reciprocal loan arrangements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Insiders in different banks cause their banks to lend funds or sell loans to other banks with agreements to buy their loans, which is done to conceal loans and sales."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Institution Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Residential loan fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unqualified borrowers misrepresent personal creditworthiness, overstate their ability to pay, and misrepresent characteristics of a housing unit they intend to occupy or treat as an investment property to qualify for a loan."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Such acts might include reporting inflated income, moving debt into a dependent’s name, reporting inflated square footage of the collateral, or even bribing an appraiser to value the home at a higher amount than market value."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Construction loans"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Draw requests 1. The documentation substantiating that a developer has incurred the appropriate construction expenses and is now seeking reimbursement or direct payment 2. A typical fraud scheme that occurs in a draw request involves requesting advances on the loan for inappropriate costs, such as personal expenses and/or construction costs for an unrelated project. 3. A draw request should be accompanied by the following documents:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Paid invoices for raw materials"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Lien releases from each subcontractor"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Inspection reports"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Canceled checks from previous draw requests"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Bank reconciliation for construction draw account for previous month"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Loan balancing form, demonstrating that the loan remains in balance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Change orders, if applicable"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Institution Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Wiring instructions, if applicable i."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Proof of developer contribution, if applicable"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Red Flags of Loan Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "High turnover in developer’s personnel"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Typically, when a developer experiences a high degree of turnover, something is wrong with the internal operation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Change order abuse"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The key characteristic that fraud examiners should look for in change orders is abnormality. 1. An increase in the number of change orders or amounts on change orders might indicate that construction changes have occurred that would alter the originally planned project to such an extent as to render the underwriting inappropriate. 2. Alternatively, some projects, especially large ones, tend to have many change orders, so it might be more abnormal to have few or no change orders."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Change orders can have the same impact on a project as altering the original documents and could indicate collusive bidding."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Change orders might indicate that the original project was not feasible and that shortcuts are uncovering other problem areas."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Change orders should be approved by the architect and engineer on the project in addition to the lender’s inspector."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Missing documentation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Missing or altered documentation is a red flag for any type of fraud scheme."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Because concealment is a key fraud element, missing documents are a definite giveaway."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Missing documents are of particular concern in construction lending."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Financial Institution Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Common Types of Mortgage Fraud Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Air loan"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Loan for a nonexistent property"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraudulent sale"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fraudulent acquisition of a homeowner’s property by filing a fraudulent deed or respective real estate document that makes it appear that the property legally belongs to the criminal; it might occur without the homeowner’s knowledge decades after the property was originally sold"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraudulent second lien"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A person assumes a homeowner’s identity and takes out an additional loan or a second mortgage in the homeowner’s name. If there is not enough equity in the home to warrant a second loan, an inflated appraisal is obtained."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Property flipping"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The process by which an investor purchases a home and then resells it at a higher price shortly thereafter"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The property is typically sold twice in rapid succession at a significant increase in value (also known as an ABC transaction, whereby the property moves from party A to party B to party C very quickly)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The title agent often closes the second transaction (the B/C transaction) first, thereby using the lender’s funds to C to fund the acquisition of the property in the A/B transaction."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "New Account Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud that occurs on an account within the first ninety days that it is open"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud is much more likely to occur in new accounts than in established accounts."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Some common methods of new account fraud include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "False identification"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Institution Fraud"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Fraudsters use false identification to open new accounts and steal"}, {"type": "para", "text": "money before the bank collects funds."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Mobile deposit fraud 1. Fraudsters take advantage of mobile deposits, which involve sending a digital image of a check or similar payment order to a depository institution so that the paper document never has to be received or processed. 2. Mobile deposits are at relatively high risk of new account fraud because there is no face-to-face transaction required and digital images are often taken by a camera or scanner, making it easier to make forged or counterfeit deposits."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Automated teller machine (ATM) deposits 1. At higher risk because ATM deposits do not require in-person transactions, despite having cameras to help identify users"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Financial Institution Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A draw request on a construction loan should be accompanied by all the following EXCEPT:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Lien releases from subcontractors"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Inspection reports"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Change orders, if applicable"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Expenses from similar contracts"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Karl finds a residential property with a nonresident owner. He then forges contractual property"}, {"type": "para", "text": "documents showing that the owner is transferring ownership of the property completely to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Karl, such as would normally happen during a property sale. The property owner is unaware"}, {"type": "para", "text": "that Karl has created and filed the documents. Later, Karl takes the falsified documents to a"}, {"type": "para", "text": "lender and borrows money against the property. Which of the following MOST ACCURATELY"}, {"type": "para", "text": "describes Karl’s scheme?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Unauthorized draw on home equity line of credit"}], "ai_summary": "External fraud schemes are those committed by outside entities, typically by individuals or groups of individuals against organizations. Fraud schemes committed by outsiders usually occur within specific industries. Therefore, the following chapters are organized by type of"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Health Care Fraud", "summary_short": "Health care fraud may be defined as an intentional act to defraud a health care benefit program or to obtain through false representations money or other property owned by a health care benefit program. This type of fraud involves a deception or misrepresentation that an", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Provider Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Practices by health care providers (including practitioners, medical suppliers, and medical institutions) that cause unnecessary costs to health care programs or patients through reimbursement for unnecessary or excessive services, or services that do not meet the recognized standards for health care"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common types include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fictitious providers 1. Corrupt providers or other criminals fraudulently obtain and use another provider’s identification information and steal or purchase lists of patients’ identifying information. They then use the fictitious provider’s information to bill the insurance provider or government health care program for medical services never performed."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Fictitious services 1. Health care providers charge or bill a health care program for services that were not rendered at all."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Clinical lab schemes 1. A provider advises a patient that additional medical testing is needed to diagnose a problem when the testing is not actually required or advisable. The fee for unnecessary work is often split with physicians."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Equipment and supplies schemes 1. Fraud schemes by organizations and individuals providing medical equipment and supplies are also common. 2. Common durable medical equipment (DME) supplier schemes involve:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Falsified prescriptions for DME"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Intentionally providing excessive DME"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "DME not being delivered"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Billing for DME rental beyond when the DME is returned"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Billing for DME not covered by the insurance policy or health care program"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Red flags"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Lack of supporting documentation for claims under review"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Details in supporting documents that do not match the claim"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Medical records that have been altered"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Medical records that were created long after the alleged patient visit"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Medical records that seem sloppy, disorganized, or otherwise unprofessional"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Missing pages of medical records that would cover the period of time under review"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "An unusually high volume of patients"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "An unusually large number of claims for reimbursement"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Unusually high profits compared to similar businesses in the same geographic region"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Matching addresses on the claim form for the patient and the provider"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "High percentage of coding outliers"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Pressure for rapid processing of bills or claims"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Threats of legal action for delay in making payments"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Inflated Billing Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Altered claims"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Altering valid claims can be accomplished using a pen; photocopier; or scanner, computer, and printer. Common alterations include: 1. Amounts 2. Date of service 3. Name of patient"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Added services"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Some fraudsters add on services never rendered to dates of actual services."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Code manipulation schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unbundling 1. Some providers attempt to increase profits by billing separately for procedures that are actually part of a single procedure."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Upcoding 1. Occurs when a provider bills for a higher level of service than actually rendered As Billed PROCEDURE CODE 58150 58720 49000 44955 58740"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "If Correctly Billed"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Removal of ovaries and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Exploration of abdomen"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Knee arthroscopy with"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Knee arthroscopy with"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Common types of patient fraud perpetrated against government health care programs and private insurers include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fictitious claims 1. Beneficiaries or insureds might attempt to perpetrate a fraud by submitting fictitious claims for medical services that did not occur or for nonexistent dependents."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Multiple claims 1. The patient files multiple claims for reimbursement for the same medical service. 2. Patients might seek reimbursement for the same medical service from both the government and a private insurer, two different private insurers, or two different government health care programs."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Misrepresentations on applications 1. Patients sometimes make misrepresentations on their insurance applications to circumvent coverage restrictions. 2. Misrepresentations can include false information or the omission of relevant information."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Third-party fraud 1. Involves the unauthorized use of an insured’s identity to obtain their insurance benefits"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Fraud by Insurance Companies"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The following fraud schemes might occur in countries that offer private insurance:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Submission of false documents 1. If the insurance company works in tandem with government health care programs (e.g., by acting as an intermediary for the payer), then the insurance company commits fraud when it improperly bills the government or submits false cost reports or audits."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Failure to investigate questionable claims 1. When an insurance company acts as an intermediary administering a government health care program, the insurance company has a duty to try to detect false claims by providers and beneficiaries. Although it is impossible to detect every fraudulent claim, if a company bypasses its own claims verification procedures, it can be found guilty of fraud in some jurisdictions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Failure to pay legitimate claims 1. An insurance company might commit fraud when claims are consistently rejected even though the required information has been submitted."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Charging unapproved rates 1. An insurance company might improperly begin charging an unapproved rate before it is allowed to do so."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Requesting rate increases based on fraudulent data 1. Insurance companies or carriers needing regulatory approval for rate increases might use fraudulent cost data to justify their increases. The act is fraudulent if they purposefully submit false cost data to get a raised rate."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Failure to apply discounts 1. An insurance company might be guilty of fraud if it fails to apply discounts that have been negotiated with providers. 2. The alleged overcharging occurs when an insurance company negotiates a discount on a medical bill. If the company does not provide the discount, then the consumer’s copayment is made on the full price rather than the discounted price, causing the consumer to pay a higher percentage of their bill than they should."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "An insurance company might be guilty of fraud if it negotiates discounts with its medical"}, {"type": "para", "text": "providers and fails to apply those discounts to its customers."}, {"type": "para", "text": "A health care provider’s practice of charging a comprehensive code, as well as one or more"}, {"type": "para", "text": "component codes, by billing separately for subcomponents of a single procedure is known as"}, {"type": "para", "text": "____________________."}], "ai_summary": "Health care fraud may be defined as an intentional act to defraud a health care benefit program or to obtain through false representations money or other property owned by a health care benefit program. This type of fraud involves a deception or misrepresentation that an"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Insurance Fraud", "summary_short": "The insurance business, by its very nature, is susceptible to fraud. Insurance is a risk distribution system that requires the accumulation of liquid assets in the form of reserve funds, which are in turn available to pay loss claims. Insurance companies generate a large", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Agent/Broker Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cash, loan, and dividend payments"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A company employee requests cash, a loan, or a dividend payment without the knowledge of an insured or contract holder and either deposits the money into their bank account or a fictitious account."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Premium theft"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An agent collects the premium but does not remit the payment to the insurance company. Thus, the insured unknowingly has no coverage available upon a qualifying event."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fictitious death claims"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An agent or employee obtains a fictitious death certificate and requests that a death claim payment be issued. The agent then steals the payment."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Sliding"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The inclusion of additional coverage in an insurance policy without the insured’s knowledge"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The extra charges are hidden in the total premium, and, since the insured is unaware of the coverage, few claims are ever filed."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Vehicle Insurance Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ditching"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Disposing of a vehicle to collect on an insurance policy or to settle an outstanding loan"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The vehicle is normally expensive and purchased with a small down payment."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The owner falsely reports the vehicle as stolen while orchestrating its destruction or disappearance in some way, such as by having it stripped for parts, burned, or submerged in a large body of water."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "In some cases, the owner just abandons the vehicle, hoping that it will be stolen."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Sometimes, the scheme involves a homeowner’s insurance claim for property that was supposedly in the vehicle when it was “stolen.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Past posting"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A person is involved in an automobile accident but does not have insurance. After the accident, the person gets insurance, waits a short time, and then reports the vehicle as having been in an accident, thus collecting for the damage previously incurred."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Red Flags of Insurance Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The claim is made soon after the policy’s inception or after an increase or change in the coverage under which the claim is made."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The insured has a history of multiple insurance claims and losses."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The insured previously asked an insurance agent hypothetical questions about coverage in the event of a loss similar to the actual claim."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In a burglary loss, the claim includes large, bulky property, which is unusual for a burglary."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In a theft or fire loss claim, the claim includes a lot of recently purchased, expensive property, but the insured cannot provide receipts, owner’s manuals, or other documentary proof of purchase."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In a fire loss claim, the claim does not include personal or sentimental items, such as photographs or family heirlooms, that would usually be listed among the lost property."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The insured cannot remember or does not know where they acquired the claimed property, especially unusual items, or cannot provide adequate documentation."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Computer-Generated Detection Tools"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners can use the following data analysis tools to detect insurance fraud schemes:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Address similarity reports 1. These reports electronically compare multiple payments going to the same address and might show a payment defalcation or funds going to another insurance company, broker, or fictitious payee."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Electronic confirmations 1. Confirmations should be sent to verify that company records agree with policyholder records. 2. They can be sent to policyholders when disbursements have been mailed for premiums that are in force (i.e., active) or lapsed or when there has been a change of address on an account."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Exception or manual override reports 1. Computerized reports that list all exceptions to normal electronic processing can be produced and should be reviewed by management on an ongoing basis."}, {"type": "para", "text": "One type of vehicle insurance scam involves the owner of a vehicle abandoning it and falsely"}, {"type": "para", "text": "reporting it as stolen. This type of scam is called:"}], "ai_summary": "The insurance business, by its very nature, is susceptible to fraud. Insurance is a risk distribution system that requires the accumulation of liquid assets in the form of reserve funds, which are in turn available to pay loss claims. Insurance companies generate a large"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Consumer Fraud", "summary_short": "Consumer fraud embodies a wide variety of misleading practices related to advertising, marketing, or the selling or buying of goods and services. It can arise when a product or service does not operate as intended and can involve the concealment or overcharging of", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Common Types of Con Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Advance-fee schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Schemes structured to obtain an illegal gain by falsely promising the delivery of a product or service"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Debt consolidation schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Often involve the consolidation agency collecting money from the debtor but not forwarding it to the creditors"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Another variation occurs when customers are guaranteed that they will receive a loan or a credit card regardless of their credit rating."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Scavenger or revenge schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involve the company that initially defrauded the consumer"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Using a different company’s name, the outfit contacts the consumer again and asks if they would like to help put the unethical company out of business and get their money back."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "An up-front fee is required to finance the investigation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Affinity fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Targets groups of people who have some social connection"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Neighborhoods chiefly populated by racial minorities, especially immigrant groups, are often the target of affinity frauds."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Other targets include older individuals and language minorities."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Religious and professional affiliations are often exploited as well."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Giveaway schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The most common giveaway scheme is known as the 1-in-5, in which a consumer receives a letter or postcard in the mail informing them that they have already won a prize."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Victims might receive items of minimal or no value or coupons redeemable only for the company’s substandard merchandise."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Victims might be asked to pay a processing fee or to prepay the taxes on their winnings."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Common Types of Elder Fraud Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Home improvement schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraudsters recommend a “friend” who can perform needed home repairs for an older individual at a reasonable price. In some cases, this friend then overcharges the individual for home repair work that has been performed improperly or fools the homeowner into signing over the title of their house to the repairperson."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Travel, vacation, and timeshare schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraudsters post advertisements for vacation properties that are nonexistent, significantly different than promised, or not available for rent."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Tech-support schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The goal of these schemes is to convince victims to pay for unnecessary computer services to repair nonexistent viruses or other problems."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Grandparent schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "These schemes involve a fraudster calling an older individual and impersonating their grandchild or family member to swindle money from them."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Ponzi Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A Ponzi scheme is generally defined as an illegal business practice in which new investors’ money is used to make payments to earlier investors."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The investment opportunity is typically presented with the promise of uncommonly high returns."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The key element in a Ponzi scheme is that initial investors are paid with subsequent investors’ money with minimal or no legitimate commerce occurring."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A Ponzi scheme is a pyramid scheme, but it masquerades as some type of investment."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Red Flags of Ponzi Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Sounds too good to be true"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Promises of low risk or high rewards"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "History of consistent returns"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "High-pressure sales tactics"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Pressure to reinvest"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Complex trading strategies"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Lack of transparency or access"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Lack of a separation of duties"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Pyramid Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Illegal pyramids generate revenue by continually recruiting new members. These operations might offer merchandise or services for sale, but the only significant revenues come from recruitment."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The distinguishing factor of the illegal pyramid is the continual need for new investors or members."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Unlike Ponzi schemes, illegal pyramids are promoted as pyramids."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An operation is likely to be classified as an illegal pyramid scheme if the company emphasizes the recruitment of new members over product sales and promises that riches can only be obtained through recruitment."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Maria, a successful restaurateur, has been informed of an unusually attractive investment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "opportunity by a recent acquaintance and decides to invest in it. Several months and a couple"}, {"type": "para", "text": "of underwhelming payments later, Maria grows frustrated with the diminishing disbursements"}, {"type": "para", "text": "and attempts to withdraw her money. After several weeks of delay, she realizes that the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "promoter seems to have vanished, along with her investment. Maria is the victim of which of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the following fraudulent ploys?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. An illegal pyramid"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. A fly and buy scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. A dog and pony scam"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Victoria, a Certified Fraud Examiner (CFE), was contacted by a client. The client told Victoria"}, {"type": "para", "text": "that he prepaid a commission to an individual to help him obtain some government grants. He"}, {"type": "para", "text": "later found out that the individual had taken his money and now cannot be located. This is a"}, {"type": "para", "text": "consumer fraud scheme known as a(n):"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Bait and switch scheme"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Advance-fee scheme"}], "ai_summary": "Consumer fraud embodies a wide variety of misleading practices related to advertising, marketing, or the selling or buying of goods and services. It can arise when a product or service does not operate as intended and can involve the concealment or overcharging of"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Identity Theft", "summary_short": "Identity theft is a common type of fraud that is non-discriminatory. Anyone can be targeted; the victim might be a college student, a retiree, a schoolteacher, or a successful attorney. Even Although there is not a universal definition of identity theft, most law enforcement", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "Methods of Committing Identity Theft"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Traditional identity theft"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves a fraudster stealing an individual’s personal information and pretending to be that individual"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Examples 1. In an account takeover, a fraudster might use an individual’s name, government identification number, and date of birth to impersonate the individual and gain access to the individual’s bank account. 2. In true name fraud, a fraudster uses an individual’s personal information to open a new account under the individual’s name."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Synthetic identity theft"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves a fraudster using entirely fabricated personal information or a combination of real and fabricated information to create a new identity"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "How Identity Thieves Steal Information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Dumpster diving"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Discarded devices"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Mail theft"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Shoulder surfing"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The practice of observing another person (e.g., looking over their shoulder) to gather personal information"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Examples include eavesdropping on telephone conversations, viewing a victim’s credit card number, watching victims enter PINs at ATMs, and watching victims fill out bank deposit slips at their banks."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Social engineering"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Baiting"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Fraudsters leave flash drives, CD-ROMs, or similar items that have"}, {"type": "para", "text": "been infected with malware in places where people will find"}, {"type": "para", "text": "them, such as parking lots."}, {"type": "num", "text": "When the item is inserted into the victim’s computer, the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "computer or network is infected, giving the identity thief access to"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Methods of Identity Theft Prevention for Individuals"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Create complex passwords or passphrases that have at least eight characters and contain upper- and lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Do not reuse passwords."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Never send personal information, such as a password or government identification number, via email."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When available, use biometric authentication (e.g., fingerprints, voice recognition)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Create unique answers for security questions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Protect computers with strong and regularly updated firewall and antivirus software, and promptly install all security updates and patches."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Avoid using unsecured, public Wi-Fi networks."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Limit the amount of personal information shared on social media. i."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Secure physical mailboxes with a lock, check physical mail regularly, and instruct"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the postal service to suspend mail during vacations."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Methods of Identity Theft Prevention for Businesses"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Limit the personal information collected from customers (e.g., do not collect government identification numbers from customers unless legally required to gather that information)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Restrict employees from accessing the personal information of customers and coworkers."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Do not retain personal information for longer than necessary."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Use encryption to protect all personal information stored by the company or sent to third parties, as well as information sent over the company’s wireless network."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Restrict the use of laptops to those employees who need them to do their jobs."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Where permitted by law, perform background checks on prospective employees."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Do not use government identification numbers as employee identification numbers or print them on paychecks."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Perform regular audits of practices involving the handling of information, network security, and other internal controls."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is a recommended step that individuals should take to protect"}, {"type": "para", "text": "themselves from identity theft?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Limit personal information shared on social media"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Create unique answers for security questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Use passwords that have at least eight characters"}, {"type": "para", "text": "To help prevent identity theft, businesses should strive to limit the personal information they"}, {"type": "para", "text": "collect from customers."}], "ai_summary": "Identity theft is a common type of fraud that is non-discriminatory. Anyone can be targeted; the victim might be a college student, a retiree, a schoolteacher, or a successful attorney. Even Although there is not a universal definition of identity theft, most law enforcement"}, {"domain": "Financial Transactions and Fraud Schemes", "topic": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property", "summary_short": "Today, information is a valuable asset, and organizations must protect their intellectual property. A business’s worth is no longer based solely on tangible assets and revenue-making potential; the information it develops, stores, and collects accounts for a large share of a", "structured": [{"type": "h2", "text": "What Is Intellectual Property?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Intangible proprietary information that includes a business’s ideas, designs, and innovations, howsoever expressed or recorded"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Competitive Intelligence vs. Espionage"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Competitive intelligence is the process by which competitor data are assembled into relevant, accurate, and usable knowledge about competitors’ positions, performance, capabilities, and intentions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A legitimate business function that businesses use to anticipate competitors’ research and development strategies and to determine their operating costs, pricing policies, financial strength, and capacity"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Espionage refers to the use of illegal, covert means to gather information."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Does not cover legitimate intelligence collection and analysis using legal means"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Two types 1. Traditional espionage: Government-sanctioned espionage conducted to collect protected information from a foreign government 2. Corporate (industrial) espionage: The use of illegal, covert means to acquire information for commercial purposes"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Basic Sources of Information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Open-source information"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Information in the public domain (i.e., publicly available data that anyone can lawfully obtain by request, purchase, or observation)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Can be free or available for a fee"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Dumpster diving"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves obtaining sensitive information by looking through someone else’s trash (e.g., via dumpsters and other trash receptacles)"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Scavenging"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves collecting information left around computer systems (e.g., on desks or workstations)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Human intelligence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Information gathered from subject matter experts and informed individuals"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Approaches include: 1. Posing as a customer of the target entity 2. Employment interviews (real and fake) 3. False licensing negotiations 4. False acquisition or merger negotiations 5. Hiring an employee away from a target entity 6. Planting an agent in a target organization 7. Social engineering"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "How Information Is Lost or Stolen"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Accident and negligence, such as through:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Conference speeches and papers"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Publications (e.g., newsletters or reports to shareholders)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Leaks to the press"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Company websites"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Poor information security procedures"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Organizations should employ and regularly update a system for protecting and disposing of confidential information."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reasonable measures to protect manual file systems (which are composed of all human-readable files and documents) include: 1. Placing sensitive documents in high-grade locked filing cabinets 2. Using a cross-cut shredder for sensitive documentary waste or having sensitive trash disposed of by a bonded waste-disposal company"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Receiving and sending mail at a secure site"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Securing auxiliary materials such as:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Calendars"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Works in progress, such as reports, notes, and graphics on sensitive cases"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Mailing lists"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Dry erase boards or other meeting room displays that might contain diagrams, charts, or sensitive notes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Printouts of sensitive data"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Physical infiltration"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Entering a target organization to spy on the organization’s employees"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Common methods 1. Securing a position or posing as an employee or contract laborer 2. Stealing or fabricating employee badges"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Social engineering"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves the use of trickery, persuasion, or threats to manipulate targets into releasing information."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Used to gain unauthorized access to systems, obtain confidential communication, intrude into networks, steal another party’s secrets, commit identity theft, or engage in some other nefarious act"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Technical surveillance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The practice of covertly acquiring audio, visual, or other types of data from targets through the use of technical devices, procedures, and techniques"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Typically used to gather nondocumentary evidence or information that cannot be found through open sources"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Components of a Program for Safeguarding Proprietary Information (SPI)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A task force"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Should include managers and staff from departments that deal with proprietary information (e.g., research and development and production), as well as representatives from the corporate security, human resources, records management, data processing, and legal departments"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Should identify the information that is to be protected by determining those areas that give the company its competitive edge (e.g., quality of the product, service, price, manufacturing technology, marketing, and distribution)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Should ask: “What information would a competitor like to know?”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Awareness training"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees must be educated as to what information is proprietary, as well as the dangers of electronically communicating that information."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Nondisclosure agreements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Written agreements providing that signatories must keep confidential all trade secrets and proprietary information learned during their employment"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "One of the least expensive and most efficient methods for controlling the loss of proprietary information"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Should be signed by everyone involved with the organization, both at the outset and upon termination of employment"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Employees must be clearly informed as to what information is considered confidential upon hiring, upon signing a nondisclosure agreement, and during exit interviews. 1. Lack of employee education concerning nondisclosure agreements is one of the primary reasons employees communicate confidential information to outside parties."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Often, employees are willing to abide by nondisclosure"}, {"type": "para", "text": "agreements, but they do not understand that the information"}, {"type": "para", "text": "they are communicating might be confidential."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Noncompetition agreements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Agreements whereby employees agree not to work for competing companies within a certain period of time after leaving their current employer"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Should generally be used on an as-needed basis, rather than as a broad requirement for all employees"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "If management determines that an agreement is appropriate for certain employees, legal counsel should be consulted to ensure that it is valid and enforceable under the applicable laws."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When employees leave a company, it is a good idea to have them sign a statement in which they acknowledge that they understand the noncompetition agreement’s terms and that they will abide by its provisions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Data classification"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Establishes what protections must be afforded to data of different value and sensitivity levels"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Data minimization"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Collecting and storing the minimal amount of information necessary to perform a given task"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Monitoring of visitor access"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Visitors should: 1. Be required to sign in and out of an organization logbook. 2. Wear a badge that identifies them as a nonemployee. 3. Be escorted by a host for the entirety of their visit. 4. Be kept away from areas containing sensitive information."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Locks on doors leading to secure areas should also be changed or reprogrammed regularly."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Quiet room"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An area that is acoustically and radio-frequency shielded so that conversations that occur within the room cannot be monitored or heard outside the room"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Used to prevent corporate spies from listening to meetings"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Both corporate espionage and competitive intelligence are legitimate forms of information"}, {"type": "para", "text": "gathering that businesses engage in to anticipate competitors’ research and development"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is a common method used by fraudsters to physically infiltrate and spy"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Secure a position as an employee"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Fabricate or steal an employee badge"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Pose as a contractor"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Theft of Data and Intellectual Property"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is NOT a recommended method for safeguarding an organization’s"}, {"type": "para", "text": "proprietary information?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Constructing a quiet room to prevent eavesdropping"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Changing locks and reprogramming door access codes regularly"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Creating an incident response plan after a data breach occurs"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Classifying data into categories according to value and sensitivity levels"}], "ai_summary": "Today, information is a valuable asset, and organizations must protect their intellectual property. A business’s worth is no longer based solely on tangible assets and revenue-making potential; the information it develops, stores, and collects accounts for a large share of a"}, {"domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "topic": "Understanding Criminal Behavior", "summary_short": "Much of our understanding of criminal behavior can be attributed to B. F. Skinner, described by many as one of the greatest social scientists of the 20th century. Skinner promised that he would revolutionize not just psychology, but all of human society with his theories of", "structured": [{"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Overview of Behavioral Analysis"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Behavioral studies, such as those conducted by B. F. Skinner, show that:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Punishment is the least effective method of changing behavior."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Punishment brings a temporary suppression of an undesirable behavior, but the behavior typically returns as soon as the punishment is discontinued."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Behavior is most effectively modified by managing and altering desires through reinforcement (i.e., replacing destructive behaviors with productive ones, instead of trying to punish an already existing impulse)."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Reinforcement vs. Punishment of Behaviors"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Reinforcement and punishment of behavior are distinguished by the way that positive and negative forces are applied."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Reinforcement 1. A positive reinforcement presents a positive stimulus in exchange for the desired response. 2. A negative reinforcement withdraws a negative stimulus in exchange for the response."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Punishment 1. Involves either applying a negative stimulus or withdrawing a positive stimulus 2. Works by providing negative consequences—administering penalties and taking away desirables"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Conditioning Behaviors"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Skinner suggests conditioning incompatible behavior that interferes with a person’s undesired acts by encouraging the improper behavior’s opposite (e.g., by rewarding a child for controlling emotional outbursts rather than punishing the child for having a tantrum)."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Understanding Criminal Behavior"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Destructive behaviors should be offset by incompatible productive ones."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Since fraud involves dishonesty, secrecy, and antagonistic behaviors, an astute manager finds ways to reward the opposite behaviors—honesty, openness, and cooperation."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Theories of Crime Causation"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Rational choice theory"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Asserts that the decision to commit a crime is a rational and careful choice on the perpetrator’s part with the goal of an intended benefit"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Before committing a crime, the offender performs a cost-benefit analysis that evaluates the possibility of getting caught and the severity of the consequences against the benefits of committing the crime."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Criminal activity will occur when the opportunity to engage in it is present. Therefore, the best way to reduce crime is by making it more difficult to commit."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Rational choice theory presents crime as a conscious choice that must be met with reduced opportunities for criminal activity and increased personal risk for deterrence methods to be successful."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Routine activities theory"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Asserts that both the motivation to commit crime and the supply of offenders is constant"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "There will always be a certain number of people, motivated by greed, lust, and other forces, who are inclined toward lawbreaking."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Three important elements that influence crime include: 1. The availability of suitable targets, such as companies and individuals 2. The absence of capable guardians, such as auditors and security personnel 3. The presence of motivated offenders, such as unhappy or financially challenged employees"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Understanding Criminal Behavior"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Crime is likely to occur when the three elements come together."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "If someone thinks it is likely that they will be caught or there is not a suitable target, then they are less likely to commit a crime."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Theory of differential association"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Asserts that people learn the values, attitudes, techniques, and motives for criminal behavior by communicating with and participating in intimate personal groups"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Main points made by criminologist Edwin Sutherland: 1. Criminal behavior is learned. 2. It is learned from other people in a process of communication. 3. Criminal behavior is acquired through participation with intimate personal groups. 4. Learning criminal behavior involves all the mechanisms of other learning. 5. Learning differs from imitation. 6. While criminal behavior is an expression of general needs and values, it is not explained by these needs and values."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Social control theory"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Suggests that if a person fails to become attached to the variety of control agencies of the society, that person’s chances of violating the law increase"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "People confronted with the possibility of violating a law are likely to ask themselves questions such as, “What will my family or friends think if they find out?”"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Individuals believe that other people whose opinions are important to them will be disappointed or ashamed, and to the extent that they care deeply that these people will feel this way, they will be deterred from committing a criminal act."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Understanding Criminal Behavior"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Differential reinforcement theory"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "States that whether deviant or criminal behavior begins or persists depends on the degree to which it has been rewarded or punished, as well as the rewards or punishments attached to its alternatives"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Behavior is reinforced when rewards are gained (positive reinforcement) or punishment is avoided (negative reinforcement)."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "It is weakened by negative stimuli (punishment) and loss of reward (punishment)."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Understanding Criminal Behavior"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "According to B. F. Skinner, the MOST EFFECTIVE way to modify a person’s behavior is through:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Positive reinforcement"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Negative reinforcement"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Social control theory suggests that the farther an individual strays from the norms of society,"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the more likely they are to commit a crime."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Understanding Criminal Behavior"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The theory of differential association is used frequently to explain white-collar criminality."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is one of the assertions or principles of differential association?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. People are genetically predisposed to be criminals."}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Criminal behavior is acquired through participation with intimate personal groups."}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Criminal behavior is explained by an individual’s general needs and values."}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Learning is the same as imitation."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is one of the three elements that have the most influence on crime"}, {"type": "para", "text": "according to the routine activities theory?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. The availability of suitable targets"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. The absence of capable guardians"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. The presence of motivated offenders"}], "ai_summary": "Much of our understanding of criminal behavior can be attributed to B. F. Skinner, described by many as one of the greatest social scientists of the 20th century. Skinner promised that he would revolutionize not just psychology, but all of human society with his theories of"}, {"domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "topic": "White-Collar Crime", "summary_short": "Part of the study of criminology involves exploring the differences in various categories of crimes and the individuals who commit them. Understanding what makes fraud and other white-collar crimes different from other types of criminal acts can be extremely helpful in", "structured": [{"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "What Is White-Collar Crime?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "According to Albert J. Reiss, Jr., and Albert Biderman, “Those violations of law to which penalties are attached that involve the use of a violator’s position of economic power, influence, or trust in the legitimate economic or political institutional order for the purpose of illegal gain, or to commit an illegal act for personal or organizational gain”"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Organizational Opportunity"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The determinant aspect of white-collar crime"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Organization and complexity make a larger difference than the offender’s social status."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Contributing Factors to the Rise of White-Collar Crime"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The economy increasingly runs on credit, which often means an increase in personal debt."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "New information technologies mean that the opportunity for wrongdoing is growing."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Government programs distributing large amounts of money make an enticing target for embezzlement."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There is an overarching culture based on affluence and ever-higher levels of success. Media sources, and advertising in general, promise that no one has to settle for second best."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Referring White-Collar Criminals to Law Enforcement"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "According to the ACFE’s Occupational Fraud 2022: A Report to the Nations, 58% of occupational fraud cases were referred to law enforcement for prosecution."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The study also found that of perpetrators who were disciplined internally, 61% were terminated, 12% were either placed on probation or suspended, and 11% were permitted or required to resign."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "For organizations that chose to handle fraud cases internally instead of referring them to law enforcement for prosecution, 50% of companies declined to refer cases because they believed their organization’s internal discipline mechanisms were sufficient, 30% did so for fear of negative publicity, 20% thought prosecution would be too costly, 10% said there was a lack of evidence, and 5% chose to pursue civil suits instead."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Organizational Crime"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Organizational vs. occupational crime"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Organizational crime is that which is committed by businesses, particularly corporations, and the government."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Occupational crime involves legal offenses committed by individuals in the course of their occupation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Effect of organizational structure on criminal behavior"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Complex companies are more prone to misbehavior due to isolation of departments and locations."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Information about what one part of a company is doing might be unknown in another part, which makes it less likely that criminal behavior will be detected and punished."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The larger a company grows, the more specialized its subunits tend to become, and this specialization thereby breeds a higher risk of fraud."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Specialization helps hide illegal activity because people do not know particulars about how things work."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Criminogenic nature of organizations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Assertions of sociologist Edward Gross 1. All organizations are inherently criminogenic (i.e., prone to committing crime), though not necessarily criminal. 2. This tendency is due to their reliance on the bottom line. 3. Without necessarily meaning to, organizations can invite fraud as a means of obtaining goals."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Diane Vaughan findings 1. Organizations can also be criminogenic because they encourage loyalty. The reasons are that:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization tends to recruit and attract similar individuals."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Rewards are given out to those who display characteristics of unyielding loyalty."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Long-term loyalty is encouraged through company retirement and benefits."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Loyalty is encouraged through social interaction, such as company parties and social functions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Frequent transfers and long working hours encourage isolation from other groups."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Specialized job skills can discourage personnel from seeking employment elsewhere."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management links employee performance goals with company performance goals."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Findings of criminologist Charles McCaghy 1. Profit pressure is “the single most compelling factor behind deviance by industry, whether it be price fixing, the destruction of competition, or the misrepresentation of a product.”"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Findings related to obedience 1. Organizations display criminogenic tendencies due to their reinforcement of obedience to people in positions of authority. 2. Human beings have an innate instinct to do as they are instructed, which can lead individuals who are otherwise ethical to commit wrongdoing to please management or another figure of authority because they feel they have no other choice."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Dr. Stanley Milgram, a social psychologist, conducted an"}, {"type": "para", "text": "experiment to understand why people follow certain orders when"}, {"type": "para", "text": "doing so conflicts with their personal values, morals, and ethics."}, {"type": "para", "text": "His study found that 60% of people were willing to shock another"}, {"type": "para", "text": "person when pushed to do so by an authority figure."}, {"type": "num", "text": "In hierarchal organizations that encourage obedience and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "engage in fraudulent behavior at the highest levels, lower-level"}, {"type": "para", "text": "staff members’ resistance to disobey people in positions of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "authority can result in them feeling like they must take part in"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the fraudulent behavior, even when such behavior is"}, {"type": "para", "text": "inconsistent with their personal moral code."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Effects of white-collar crime"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The direct cost of fraud relates to the amount of financial damages and losses resulting from a fraud scheme. 1. Direct costs can include calculable financial loss or costs due to fines, penalties, and regulatory sanctions, and they can result in difficulty paying back loans or lines of credit."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "It is much more difficult for organizations to estimate the indirect costs associated with fraud. 1. Indirect losses include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Reputational damage"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Loss of competitive advantage"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Loss of employee confidence in job security"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Loss of employee productivity"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management’s role in supporting criminal conduct"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Silk and Vogel found several actions used by businesses to rationalize"}, {"type": "para", "text": "criminal conduct in an organization:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Government regulations are unjustified because the additional"}, {"type": "para", "text": "costs of regulations and bureaucratic procedures significantly"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Regulation is unnecessary because the matters being regulated"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Although some corporate violations involve large sums of money,"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the damage is so spread among a large number of consumers"}, {"type": "para", "text": "that, individually, there is little loss."}, {"type": "num", "text": "Violations are caused by economic necessity; they aim to protect"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the value of stock, to ensure an adequate return for stockholders,"}, {"type": "para", "text": "and to protect employees’ job security by ensuring the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "corporation’s financial stability."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Controlling organizational crime"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Efforts to control corporate crime follow three approaches: 1. Voluntary change in corporate attitudes and structure 2. Strong intervention by the government to force changes in corporate structure, accompanied by legal measures to deter or punish 3. Consumer action"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Studies have shown that mass media publicity about law violations probably represents the most feared consequence of sanctions imposed on a corporation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Enforcement strategies for preventing and reducing fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Two main theories 1. Compliance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Designed to achieve conformity to the law without having to detect, process, or penalize violators"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves providing economic incentives for voluntary compliance to the laws and using administrative efforts to control violations before they occur"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Designed to detect law violations, determine who is responsible, and penalize offenders to deter future violations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves the effort to control individuals’ immediate behaviors, not the long-term behaviors targeted by compliance systems"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Occupational Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Donald R. Cressey’s findings"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Came up with the Fraud Triangle model to explain why people commit fraud"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Three sides of the Fraud Triangle 1. Perceived non-shareable financial need (pressure) 2. Perceived opportunity 3. Rationalization"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "All three elements generally must be present for a trust violation to occur."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Dr. Steve Albrecht’s findings"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The most highly ranked factors from the list of personal characteristics that contribute to fraud were: 1. Living beyond their means 2. An overwhelming desire for personal gain 3. High personal debt 4. A close association with customers 5. Feeling pay was not commensurate with responsibility"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The most highly ranked factors from the list dealing with organizational environment were: 1. Placing too much trust in key employees 2. Lack of proper procedures for authorization of transactions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Inadequate disclosures of personal investments and incomes"}, {"type": "num", "text": "No separation of authorization of transactions from the custody"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Lack of independent checks on performance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Findings from the ACFE’s Occupational Fraud 2022: A Report to the Nations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Cost of occupational fraud 1. The typical organization loses an estimated 5% of annual revenues to fraud."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "How occupational fraud is committed 1. Asset misappropriation is the most common category of occupational fraud and is the least costly. 2. Financial statement fraud causes the greatest median loss."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Detection of fraud schemes 1. Tips are by far the most common detection method for cases of occupational fraud."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The perpetrators 1. Median loss in owner/executive cases was two and a half times larger than the median loss caused by managers and six times larger than that of employees. 2. A sizeable majority of the fraudsters in the study were males, and men caused larger median losses than females. 3. Only 6% of the perpetrators in the study had been previously convicted of a fraud-related offense prior to committing the crimes in the study. 4. The most frequently cited behavioral red flag in the reported cases involved the fraudster living beyond their financial means."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following statements BEST exemplifies the rationalization component of the Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. “Management is dishonest, so why shouldn’t I be?”"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. “I’m in so much debt; I don’t have any other way to pay my bills.”"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. “I’m confident I won’t get caught.”"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. “I need the money to repay my drug dealer so that no one will find out about my habit.”"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following are the two main theories to control corporate criminal behavior?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Prevention and detection"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Deterrence and enforcement"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Assessment and reliance"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Compliance and deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The managements from several IT consulting firms conspire to take turns submitting the lowest"}, {"type": "para", "text": "bids for all contracts in their area; this is considered an organizational crime."}, {"type": "para", "text": "The findings in the ACFE’s Occupational Fraud 2022: A Report to the Nations include which of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. The most commonly reported red flag displayed by fraud perpetrators prior to the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "detection of their crime is being employed by the victim entity less than six months."}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. The median losses caused by executives are lower than those caused by staff-level"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. More occupational frauds are committed by men than by women."}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. The majority of fraudsters have been previously convicted of a fraud-related offense."}], "ai_summary": "Part of the study of criminology involves exploring the differences in various categories of crimes and the individuals who commit them. Understanding what makes fraud and other white-collar crimes different from other types of criminal acts can be extremely helpful in"}, {"domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "topic": "Corporate Governance", "summary_short": "As a strategy to control crime, deterrence is designed to detect law violations, determine who is responsible, and penalize offenders to deter future violations. Deterrence systems try to control the immediate behavior of individuals, not the long-term behaviors targeted by", "structured": [{"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "What Is Corporate Governance?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Refers to a corporation’s government"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Broadly used to describe the oversight responsibilities of different parties for an organization’s direction, operations, and performance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "More specifically, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development’s (OECD) “Glossary of Statistical Terms” defines corporate governance as:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "[The] procedures and processes according to which an organisation is directed and controlled. The corporate governance structure specifies the distribution of rights and responsibilities among the different participants in the organisation—such as the board, managers, shareholders and other stakeholders—and lays down the rules and procedures for decisionmaking."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Sir Adrian Cadbury, chairman of the committee that developed the foundational corporate governance guidance, The Cadbury Report, stated that the purpose of corporate governance is “to encourage the efficient use of resources and equally to require accountability for the stewardship of those resources. The aim is to align as nearly as possible the interests of individuals, corporations, and society.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Solid corporate governance practices are most necessary in an organization in which the owners are not also responsible for setting the company’s strategy and executing its business activities (e.g., in publicly traded companies)."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Parties Involved in Corporate Governance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The board of directors"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Made up of individuals who are generally elected by the entity’s voting members (e.g., shareholders in the case of a corporation or members in the case of an association)"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Elected directors might be: 1. Major shareholders or executives of the organization (i.e., inside directors) 2. Completely independent of the organization aside from their role on the board (i.e., independent directors or outside directors)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Represents the intermediary between the corporation’s owners (i.e., shareholders) and those executing its activities (i.e., management)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Acts as the guardian of the organization’s resources and assets"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Oversees business operations by assessing the strategy and underlying purpose of management’s decisions and actions"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Might delegate members to focused subcommittees to aid in oversight of specific issues; examples include: 1. Audit committee 2. Compensation committee 3. Nominating committee 4. Governance committee 5. Risk committee"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Responsible for making the daily decisions that affect company performance and, ultimately, shareholder wealth"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Roles relating to corporate governance include: 1. Establishing strategic goals and operating objectives under the board’s oversight 2. Directing employees to execute business activities and managing their performance of those tasks 3. Determining the use and allocation of company resources and assets 4. Evaluating the organization’s successes or failures and recalibrating the strategic approach accordingly"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Holding responsibility for the design and operation of the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "organization’s internal controls"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Setting the organization’s true ethical tone"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Shareholders"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The owners of corporations"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Can be individual investors or institutional investors, such as pension funds, mutual fund groups, investment trusts, or insurance companies"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Roles relating to corporate governance include: 1. Remaining informed on company operations and performance 2. Reading annual reports and other communications from management to the shareholders 3. Attending shareholder meetings 4. Electing capable individuals to serve as board directors 5. Holding the board of directors accountable for proper governance and oversight 6. Appointing or ratifying the audit committee’s appointment of the organization’s independent auditors 7. Voting on other significant issues, such as specific changes relating to business operations, the company’s corporate governance framework, and the rights and responsibilities of the board of directors and executive managers"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Treadway Commission’s Audit Committee Recommendations"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The Treadway Commission was formed in the United States in 1985 with the purpose of defining the auditor’s responsibility in preventing and detecting fraud."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It made several major recommendations designed to reduce the probability of fraud in financial reports, including:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The board of directors should have a mandatory independent audit committee made up of outside directors."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Companies should develop a written charter that sets the duties and responsibilities of the audit committee."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The audit committee should have adequate resources and authority to execute its responsibilities."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The audit committee should be composed of members who are informed, vigilant, and effective."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Role of Corporate Governance in Fighting Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "As stated in the Fraud Risk Management Guide, a joint publication by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) and the ACFE, fraud risk governance is one of the principles of effective fraud risk management, and “the board of directors and senior management provide a solid foundation of fraud risk management.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Managing the Business Risk of Fraud: A Practical Guide, the predecessor to the Fraud Risk Management Guide, expands this point, noting, “Effective governance processes are the foundation of fraud risk management. Lack of effective corporate governance seriously undermines any fraud risk management program.”"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Principles of Corporate Governance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Accountability"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To ensure that the organization operates effectively and efficiently, there must be mechanisms in place to ensure that management is accountable to the board and that the board is accountable to the shareholders."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Transparency"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Refers to the clarity, accuracy, completeness, and timeliness of the financial statements and other information provided by management to shareholders"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The organization’s governance processes must include policies and procedures designed to ensure transparent disclosure of all material matters that the shareholders need to be able to make timely and informed decisions regarding their investment in the company."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fairness"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Sound corporate governance practices ensure that all stakeholders are treated equitably and given just and appropriate consideration."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Responsibility"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Applies both to the duty of internal parties (e.g., employees, managers, directors, and owners) to act in the best interest of the organization and to the duty of the organization to act in society’s best interest"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Establishing a Corporate Governance Framework"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The G20/OECD Principles of Corporate Governance state that “there is no single model of good corporate governance.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Corporate governance structure and practices vary widely and should be determined based on each organization’s specific needs."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In developing a corporate governance framework for an organization, directors and management must consider the legal, regulatory, institutional, cultural, and ethical environments in which the company operates."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Good corporate governance maintains the ability to find a different course when its current direction runs into barriers, such as changes in the corporate landscape, new regulations or legal requirements, or shifts in organizational strategy."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Sources of Corporate Governance Guidance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Although there is not a universal law or set of rules for corporate governance, legislators, regulators, and other bodies around the world have issued guidance that provides best practices and requirements that organizations should enact as appropriate, such as the G20/OECD Principles of Corporate Governance."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In many jurisdictions, organizations—particularly those that are publicly traded—are subject to specific corporate governance requirements that might take the form of legislation or conditions set for companies listed on stock exchanges."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "As a result, companies should be familiar with the existing guidance specific to all the regions in which they operate, and those charged with governance should ensure compliance with the laws and regulations governing their organization."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "G20/OECD Principles of Corporate Governance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Regarded as one of the primary sources of guidance for corporate governance practices for organizations throughout the world"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "“Intended to help policymakers evaluate and improve the legal, regulatory, and institutional framework for corporate governance with a view to support economic efficiency, sustainable growth, and financial stability,” per the OECD"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Nonbinding, as their implementation must be adapted to different legal, economic, and cultural circumstances"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "This is a key strength of the Principles that makes them a useful tool worldwide, both in developed economies and in emerging markets."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The legislation needed to enforce these standards is the responsibility of individual governments."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Includes six broad principles:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Request that governments have an effective legal, regulatory, and institutional framework to support good corporate governance practices. 1. This framework typically comprises elements of legislation, regulation, self-regulatory arrangements, voluntary commitments, and business practices that are the result of a country’s specific circumstances, history, and tradition."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Call for a corporate governance framework that protects the exercise of shareholders’ rights and supports the equal treatment of all shareholders, including minority and foreign shareholders. 1. Includes providing all shareholders the opportunity to obtain effective redress for violation of their rights"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Address the effect of institutional investors and other intermediaries in stock markets and the resulting corporate governance implications."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Recognize the importance of the role of stakeholders in corporate governance. 1. The framework should recognize the rights of stakeholders established by law or through mutual agreements and encourage active cooperation between corporations and stakeholders in creating wealth, jobs, and the sustainability of financially sound enterprises."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Examine the importance of timely, accurate, and transparent disclosure mechanisms. 1. Such disclosure is not expected to place unreasonable administrative or cost burdens on the company."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Address board structures, responsibilities, and procedures. 1. The corporate governance framework should ensure the strategic guidance of the company, the effective monitoring of management by the board, and the board’s accountability to the company and the shareholders."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Good corporate governance is based on a framework that:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Considers the organization’s cultural and ethical environment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Is appropriate for the organization’s legal and regulatory environment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is NOT one of the core principles of sound corporate governance?"}], "ai_summary": "As a strategy to control crime, deterrence is designed to detect law violations, determine who is responsible, and penalize offenders to deter future violations. Deterrence systems try to control the immediate behavior of individuals, not the long-term behaviors targeted by"}, {"domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "topic": "Management's Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "summary_short": "The nominating committee is responsible for identifying, evaluating, and nominating new directors to the board. It also facilitates the election of the new directors by shareholders. Although management nominates board members as well, an effective nominating committee", "structured": [{"type": "para", "text": "Management’s Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Management’s Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Overview of Management’s Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management is ultimately responsible for the prevention and detection of fraud within an organization."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management holds the primary responsibility for:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Designing, implementing, overseeing, and ensuring the effectiveness of the anti-fraud program"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Setting the organization’s ethical tone and reinforcing an anti-fraud culture"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Demonstrating that fraud will not be tolerated at any level"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Responding appropriately to instances of fraud"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Management’s Responsibility for Internal Controls"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is management’s job to ensure that the proper internal controls are in place to prevent and detect fraud."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Although management might not execute all the controls, management is also responsible for monitoring, assessing, and remediating the internal controls to ensure they are effectively designed and operating to prevent and detect fraud."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "COSO Internal Control—Integrated Framework"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Based on the Treadway Commission’s recommendations, the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) was formed to provide guidance for organizations’ internal controls."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "COSO is responsible for issuing the Internal Control—Integrated Framework (the Framework), which is meant to apply to both public and private entities, regardless of size."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "According to the Framework, “Internal control is a process, effected by an entity’s board of directors, management, and other personnel, designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the achievement of objectives relating to operations, reporting, and compliance.”"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Management’s Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Operations objectives pertain to the effectiveness and efficiency of the organization’s operations."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reporting objectives pertain to the reporting of financial and nonfinancial information to internal and external parties."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Compliance objectives pertain to the organization’s adherence to the laws and regulations to which it is subject."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To meet these objectives, the Framework identifies five interrelated components of internal control:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Control environment 1. Provides the foundation for the internal control system throughout the entire organization 2. Established by the directors and senior management 3. Formal assessment can be made of the ethical and moral culture of the organization, which reinforces the importance of internal controls and expected standards of conduct 4. Five principles supporting the design and implementation of an effective control environment:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Personnel at all levels demonstrate a commitment to integrity and ethical values."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The board of directors is independent from management and oversees the development and performance of internal control."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "With board oversight, management establishes the structures, reporting lines, and appropriate authorities and responsibilities in the pursuit of organizational objectives."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization demonstrates a commitment to attract, develop, and retain competent individuals in alignment with objectives."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Management’s Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization holds individuals accountable for their internal control responsibilities in the pursuit of objectives."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Risk assessment 1. Involves the identification and assessment of the risks the entity faces in achieving its organizational objectives 2. Involves the following principles:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization sets sufficiently clear objectives to enable the identification and assessment of risks relating to the objectives."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization identifies risks to the achievement of its objectives across the entity and analyzes these risks as a basis for determining how the risks should be managed."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization considers the potential for fraud in assessing risks to the achievement of objectives."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization identifies and assesses changes that could significantly impact the system of internal control."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Control activities 1. The policies and procedures that enforce management’s directives intended to mitigate risk 2. Involves the following principles:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization selects and develops control activities that mitigate risks to the achievement of objectives to acceptable levels."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization selects and develops general control activities over technology to support the achievement of objectives."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization deploys control activities through policies that establish what is expected and procedures that put policies into action."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Management’s Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Information and communication 1. Relates to the exchange of information in a way that allows employees to carry out their internal control responsibilities and achieve the organization’s objectives 2. Involves the following principles:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization obtains or generates and uses relevant, quality information to support the functioning of internal control."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization internally communicates information— including objectives and responsibilities for internal control—necessary to support the functioning of internal control."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization communicates with external parties regarding matters affecting the functioning of internal control."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Monitoring 1. The process that assesses the effectiveness of a control system over time 2. Should include both ongoing, automated evaluations and periodic, separate evaluations, the findings of which should be evaluated against predefined criteria 3. Involves the following principles:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization selects, develops, and performs ongoing and/or separate evaluations to ascertain whether the components of internal control are present and functioning."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The organization evaluates and communicates internal control deficiencies in a timely manner to those parties responsible for taking corrective action, including senior management and the board of directors, as appropriate."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Management’s Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The effectiveness of internal controls can be determined from an assessment of whether:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Each of these five components is in place and functioning effectively."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The five components are operating together in an integrated manner."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Management’s Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following parties is ultimately responsible for the prevention and detection of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "fraud within an organization?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Board of directors"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The evaluation and communication of internal control deficiencies in a timely manner to those"}, {"type": "para", "text": "parties responsible for taking corrective action is a principle related to which component of the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission’s (COSO) Internal"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Control—Integrated Framework?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Information and communication"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Control activities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Management’s Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "According to the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission"}, {"type": "para", "text": "(COSO), internal control is a process “designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "achievement of objectives relating to operations, reporting, and compliance.”"}], "ai_summary": "The nominating committee is responsible for identifying, evaluating, and nominating new directors to the board. It also facilitates the election of the new directors by shareholders. Although management nominates board members as well, an effective nominating committee"}, {"domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "topic": "Auditors' Fraud-Related Responsibilities", "summary_short": "Communications to Management and with Those Charged with Governance If the auditor has identified a fraud or has obtained information that indicates that a fraud may exist, the auditor shall communicate these matters on a timely basis to the appropriate", "structured": [{"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "External Audit Standards Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "International Standard on Auditing (ISA) 240—The Auditor’s Responsibility Relating to Fraud in an Audit of Financial Statements"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Purpose 1. To establish standards and provide guidance on the auditor’s responsibility to consider fraud in an audit of financial statements 2. To expand on how other auditing standards and guidance should be applied in relation to the risks of material misstatement due to fraud"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Characteristics of fraud 1. Misstatements in the financial statements can occur from error or fraud, depending on whether the underlying action that results in the misstatement is intentional or unintentional. 2. Two types of intentional misstatements are considered relevant for audit purposes:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Misstatements arising from fraudulent financial reporting"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Misstatements arising from the misappropriation of assets 3. For the purposes of the ISAs, the auditor is concerned with fraud that causes a material misstatement in the financial statements."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "According to the ISAs, “Information is material if omitting, misstating or obscuring it could reasonably be expected to influence the decisions that the primary users of general purpose financial statements make on the basis of those financial statements, which provide financial information about a specific reporting entity.”"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Materiality is often considered in quantitative terms within an audit (e.g., by establishing a threshold amount, or quantitative materiality threshold, by which the financial statements must be misstated to be considered materially misstated), but qualitative aspects of fraud can, and often do, override the general quantitative materiality threshold."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Example: An intentional manipulation of an account for an amount just under the determined quantitative materiality threshold might still be deemed material for purposes of the audit, as it indicates management’s intent to “omit, misstate, or obscure” information to influence the decisions of the financial statement users. 4. Although the auditor might suspect or, in rare cases, identify the occurrence of fraud, the auditor does not make legal determinations of whether fraud has occurred."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Identification and assessment of the risks of material misstatement due to fraud 1. Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement due to fraud at the financial statement level, as well as at the assertion level for classes of transactions, account balances, and disclosures. 2. Obtain an understanding of the entity’s related controls, including control activities, relevant to such risks."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Responses to the assessed risks of material misstatement due to fraud 1. Determine overall responses to address the assessed risks of material misstatement due to fraud at the financial statement level, including:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Assignment and supervision of personnel"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Evaluation of the entity’s selection and application of accounting policies"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Incorporation of an element of unpredictability in auditing procedures"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Evaluation of audit evidence 1. Evaluate whether analytical procedures that are performed when forming an overall conclusion as to whether the financial statements are consistent with the auditor’s understanding of the entity and its environment indicate a previously unrecognized risk of material misstatement due to fraud. 2. If a misstatement is identified, whether material or not, and there is reason to believe that it is or may be the result of fraud and that management is involved, then reevaluate the assessment of the risks of material misstatement due to fraud and its resulting impact on the nature, timing, and extent of audit procedures to respond to the assessed risks."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Also consider whether circumstances or conditions indicate possible collusion involving employees, management, or third parties when reconsidering the reliability of evidence previously obtained."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Communications to management and with those charged with governance 1. Communicate the identification of a fraud or information that indicates a fraud might exist to the appropriate level of management and those charged with governance on a timely basis. 2. If management is suspected of being involved in the fraud, communicate these suspicions to those charged with governance"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "and discuss with them the nature, timing, and extent of audit"}, {"type": "para", "text": "procedures necessary to complete the audit."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Communications to regulatory and enforcement authorities 1. Determine whether there is a responsibility to report the occurrence or suspicion of a fraud to a party outside the entity that overrides the duty of client confidentiality."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "International Standard on Auditing (ISA) 265—Communicating Deficiencies in Internal Control to Those Charged with Governance and Management"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Provides guidance regarding the auditor’s responsibility to communicate an organization’s internal control deficiencies that could result in a misstatement of the financial statements appropriately with management and those charged with governance"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Auditor requirements upon identifying one or more deficiencies in internal control include: 1. Determine, based on the audit work performed, whether, individually or in combination, they represent significant deficiencies. 2. Communicate in writing significant deficiencies in internal control identified during the audit to those charged with governance on a timely basis. 3. Communicate to management at an appropriate level of responsibility on a timely basis:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In writing, significant deficiencies in internal control that the auditor has communicated or intends to communicate to those charged with governance, unless it would be inappropriate to communicate directly to management in the circumstances"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Other deficiencies in internal control identified during the audit that have not been communicated to management"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "by other parties and that, in the auditor’s professional"}, {"type": "para", "text": "judgment, are of sufficient importance to merit"}, {"type": "para", "text": "management’s attention"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Written communication requirements regarding significant deficiencies include: 1. A description of the deficiencies and an explanation of their potential effects 2. Sufficient information to enable those charged with governance and management to understand the context of the communication, including that:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The purpose of the audit was for the auditor to express an opinion on the financial statements."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The audit included consideration of internal control relevant to the preparation of the financial statements in order to design audit procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of internal control."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The matters being reported are limited to those deficiencies that the auditor has identified during the audit and that the auditor has concluded are of sufficient importance to merit being reported to those charged with governance."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Internal Audit Standards Related to Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "IIA Standard 1210—Proficiency"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Internal auditors must possess the knowledge, skills, and other competencies needed to perform their individual responsibilities."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The internal audit activity collectively must possess or obtain the knowledge, skills, and other competencies needed to perform its responsibilities."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "IIA Standard 1220—Due Professional Care"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Internal auditors must apply the care and skill expected of a reasonably prudent and competent internal auditor."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Due professional care does not imply infallibility."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "IIA Standard 2060—Reporting to Senior Management and the Board"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The chief audit executive (CAE) must report periodically to senior management and the board of directors on the internal audit activity’s purpose, authority, responsibility, and performance relative to its plan and on its conformance with The IIA’s Code of Ethics and its International Standards for the Professional Practice of Internal Auditing."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reporting must also include significant risk and control issues, including fraud risks, governance issues, and other matters that require the attention of senior management and/or the board of directors."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The IIA’s IPPF—Practice Guide: Internal Audit and Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The Practice Guide states that, in conducting audit engagements, the internal auditor should:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Evaluate the organization’s structures and process for fraud risk governance."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Perform an assessment of the organization’s fraud risks."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Evaluate the design and operationalization of the fraud risk management program."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Communicate results and assurance to senior management and the board."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Report to senior management and the board on the adequacy and effectiveness of the fraud risk governance and management at an engagement and organization-wide level."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Conduct periodic and ad hoc assessments of the fraud risk management program using a suitable framework as appropriate to inform their approach."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Provide insight and advice to senior management and the board on opportunities to improve the organization’s fraud risk management."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Evaluate the indicators of fraud and decide whether any further action is necessary or whether an investigation should be recommended."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Contribute to the organizational fraud risk awareness and training at the request of senior management."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The Practice Guide also provides guidance about the internal audit function’s role in communicating any significant fraud risk, control, and governance issues with senior management and the board of directors by stating that CAEs may include the following matters in reports to these parties:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Is fraud risk management comprehensive, continuous, and aligned with the organization’s strategic objectives?"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Is the fraud risk management program documented and supported by an organization-wide level of awareness?"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Are arrangements for governance of fraud risk management adequate and effective, including an anti-fraud culture led by senior management and the board?"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Does management possess the necessary skills, resources, and inclination to provide effective fraud risk management?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Did management cooperate with the assessment of the organization’s fraud risk governance and management, or was there any resistance?"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Are there any significant residual fraud risks?"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Has management accepted a level of fraud that is consistent with the board’s risk appetite and the objectives of the organization? If not and the CAE has been unable to resolve the matter, has this been communicated to the board?"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Government Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI) operates as an umbrella organization for the external government audit community and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "provides an institutionalized framework for supreme audit institutions (SAIs) to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "foster the exchange of ideas, knowledge, and experiences."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "INTOSAI provides high-quality standards in the form of International Standards of Supreme Audit Institutions (ISSAI) for the public sector to promote good governance."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "ISSAI 1240 provides supplementary guidance regarding the applicability of ISA 240 to public-sector financial statement audits."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "States that ISA 240 is applicable to auditors of public-sector entities in their role as auditors of financial statements and includes several specific considerations in applying ISA 240 to public-sector audits, including: 1. Broader audit objectives"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The objectives of a financial audit in the public sector are often broader than expressing an opinion as to whether the financial statements have been prepared, in all material respects, in accordance with the applicable financial reporting framework."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The audit mandate arising from legislation, regulation, ministerial directives, government policy requirements, or resolutions of the legislature may result in additional objectives or there may be general public expectations related to reporting noncompliance with authorities or the effectiveness of internal controls. 2. Consideration of the concept of abuse"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Public-sector auditors must remain alert throughout the audit for occurrences of abuse (i.e., behavior that is deficient or improper when compared with behavior that a prudent person would consider reasonable and necessary business practice given the facts and circumstances)."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When information is obtained indicating that abuse might have occurred, public-sector auditors must consider whether such possible abuse could significantly affect the financial statements. 3. Inability to withdraw from the engagement"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Public-sector auditors do not normally have the option to withdraw from an audit engagement."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Public-sector auditors must consider the impact on the audit opinion and any requirements for other forms of reporting, including whether it may be appropriate to report separately to the legislature or to issue classified or restricted reports. 4. Additional communications about fraud-related matters"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Public-sector auditors may be required or may decide to communicate matters with other parties, such as the legislature, in addition to those charged with governance."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The requirements for reporting of fraud in the public sector may be subject to specific provisions of the audit mandate or related legislation or regulation."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In some environments, public-sector auditors might have a duty to report circumstances that might indicate the possibility of fraud or abuse to investigative bodies, jurisdictional bodies, or the appropriate part of the government or legislature, such as prosecutors, the police, and affected third parties."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Public-sector auditors need to be familiar with applicable laws and regulations regarding reporting, communication, and documentation of indications or suspicions of fraud."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Auditors’ Fraud-Related Responsibilities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The primary purpose of International Standard on Auditing (ISA) 240, The Auditor’s"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Responsibilities Relating to Fraud in an Audit of Financial Statements, is to:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Establish standards and provide guidance on the auditor’s responsibility to consider"}, {"type": "para", "text": "fraud in an audit of financial statements"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Establish auditors as being primarily responsible for the prevention and detection of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "fraud within an organization"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Establish requirements for auditors related to designing and implementing fraud-related"}, {"type": "para", "text": "According to The Institute of Internal Auditors’ (IIA) International Standards for the Professional"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Practice of Internal Auditing, internal auditors must apply the care and skill of an expert whose"}, {"type": "para", "text": "primary responsibility is investigating fraud."}], "ai_summary": "Communications to Management and with Those Charged with Governance If the auditor has identified a fraud or has obtained information that indicates that a fraud may exist, the auditor shall communicate these matters on a timely basis to the appropriate"}, {"domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Assessment", "summary_short": "A major concern of individuals who wish to report misconduct in the workplace is the fear of being retaliated against for their disclosure. Retaliation occurs when an employer takes any adverse action against an employee that would dissuade a reasonable person from raising a", "structured": [{"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "What Is Fraud Risk?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The vulnerability that an organization faces from individuals capable of combining all three elements of the Fraud Triangle"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Inherent and Residual Fraud Risk"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Risks that are present before the effect of internal controls (including targeted anti-fraud controls) are described as inherent risks."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Risks that remain after the effect of these controls are described as residual risks."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The objective of an organization’s anti-fraud controls is to reduce the residual risk to a level that is significantly lower than the inherent risk."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Factors That Influence Fraud Risk in an Organization"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The nature of the business in which it is engaged"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The environment in which it operates"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The effectiveness of its anti-fraud controls"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A good system of anti-fraud controls, with the right balance of preventive and detective controls, can greatly reduce an organization’s vulnerability to fraud. 1. Preventive controls stop something bad from happening before it occurs. 2. Detective controls identify something bad that has already occurred."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "No system of anti-fraud controls can fully eliminate the risk of fraud, but well-designed and effective anti-fraud controls can deter the average fraudster by reducing the opportunity to commit the fraud and increasing the perception of detection."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The ethics and values of the company and its employees"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "What Is a Fraud Risk Assessment?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An ongoing, continuous process aimed at proactively identifying and addressing an organization’s vulnerabilities to both internal and external fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "What gets evaluated and how it gets assessed should be tailored to the organization, as there is not an approach that is suited to all organizations."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The objective of a fraud risk assessment is to help an organization recognize what makes it most vulnerable to fraud."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Why Organizations Should Conduct Fraud Risk Assessments"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To improve communication and awareness about fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A fraud risk assessment can be an effective way for an organization to start communication and raise awareness about fraud."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To identify where the company is most vulnerable to fraud and what activities put it at the greatest risk"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management must know where the company is most vulnerable to fraud to prevent it from happening."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To know who puts the organization at the greatest risk"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The actions of certain individuals can significantly increase the company’s vulnerability to fraud."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The risk can emerge from the way in which someone makes decisions, behaves, or treats others within and outside the organization."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To develop plans to mitigate fraud risk"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When management knows where the greatest fraud risks are, it can proactively enact measures to reduce or mitigate those risks."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The results of the fraud risk assessment can be used to gain alignment among stakeholders and advance preventive action."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To develop techniques to investigate and determine if fraud has occurred in high-risk areas"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fraud risk assessment is useful for identifying areas that should be proactively investigated for evidence of fraud."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To assess anti-fraud controls"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Although an effective internal control system, including targeted antifraud controls, is critical in fraud prevention and detection, it is a dynamic system that requires constant reevaluation of its weaknesses."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Performing a fraud risk assessment provides management the opportunity to review the effectiveness of the company’s anti-fraud controls, with consideration of the following factors: 1. Controls that might have been eliminated due to restructuring efforts (e.g., elimination of separation of duties due to downsizing) 2. Controls that might have eroded over time due to reengineering of business processes 3. New opportunities for collusion 4. Lack of anti-fraud controls in a vulnerable area 5. Nonperformance of control procedures (e.g., control procedures compromised for the sake of expediency) 6. Inherent limitations of anti-fraud controls, including opportunities for those responsible for a control to commit and conceal fraud (e.g., through management and system overrides)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To comply with regulations and professional standards"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud risk assessments can assist management and auditors (internal and external) in satisfying regulatory requirements and complying with professional standards pertaining to their responsibility for fraud risk management."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Elements of a Good Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Collaborative effort of management and auditors"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fraud risk assessment is most effective when management and auditors share ownership of the process and accountability for its success."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The right sponsor"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The sponsor must be senior enough in the organization to command the employees’ respect and elicit full cooperation in the process."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Ideally, the sponsor would be an independent board director or audit committee member; however, a chief executive officer or another internal senior leader can be equally as effective."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Independence and objectivity of the people leading and conducting the work"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The people leading and conducting the fraud risk assessment must remain independent and objective throughout the assessment process and must be perceived as independent and objective by others."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A good fraud risk assessment can be conducted effectively by people inside or outside of the organization."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The people leading and conducting the work should be mindful of any personal biases they might have regarding the organization and the people within it, and they should take steps to reduce or eliminate all biases that might affect the fraud risk assessment process."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Functional knowledge of the business"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fraud risk assessor must know, beyond a superficial level, what the business does and how it operates."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Access to people at all levels of the organization"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is crucial to include members of all levels of the organization in the risk assessment process to ensure that all relevant risks are addressed and reviewed from many different perspectives."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Thinking like a fraudster"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A necessary part of conducting an effective fraud risk assessment involves thinking like a fraudster."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Thoughts of “it couldn’t happen here” should not be allowed to moderate the evaluation of fraud risk."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Preparing the Company for a Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Assemble a multi-disciplinary team to lead and conduct the fraud risk assessment."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The team should consist of individuals with diverse knowledge, skills, and perspectives to lead and conduct the assessment."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The size of the team should depend on the size of the organization and the methods used to conduct the assessment."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The team members can include internal and external sources, such as: 1. Accounting and finance personnel who are familiar with the financial reporting processes and anti-fraud controls 2. Nonfinancial business unit and operations personnel who have knowledge of daily operations, customer and vendor interactions, and issues within the industry 3. Risk management personnel who can ensure that the assessment process integrates with the enterprise risk management program 4. The general counsel or other members of the legal department 5. Members of any ethics or compliance functions 6. Internal auditors 7. Internal security or investigative personnel who are familiar with investigations of past fraud incidents 8. External consultants with fraud and risk expertise 9. Any business leader with direct accountability for the effectiveness of the organization’s fraud risk management efforts"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identify the information to be gathered and determine the most effective techniques to use in conducting the fraud risk assessment."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Information to be gathered includes: 1. The identification of inherent fraud risks 2. Discussion of past known fraud incidents and how they were handled"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Compilation of complaints from all sources"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Assessment of the likelihood and significance of identified risks"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Perceptions regarding the overall control environment"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Perceptions regarding the operating effectiveness of specific antifraud controls"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Possible techniques for gathering information include: 1. Interviews 2. Focus groups 3. Surveys 4. Anonymous feedback mechanisms"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Obtain the sponsor’s agreement on:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The scope of work that will be performed"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The information-collection techniques that will be used"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The individuals who will participate in the chosen methods"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The content of the chosen methods"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The form of output for the assessment"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Educate employees and openly promote the process."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Communications should be visibly disseminated in a format that is most appropriate for the culture of the organization."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Process should be visible and communicated throughout the business."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Sponsors should be strongly encouraged to openly promote the process."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Identifying Potential Inherent Fraud Risks and Schemes"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Brainstorm to identify the inherent fraud risks that could apply to the organization."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Brainstorming should include discussions regarding:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Incentives, pressures, and opportunities to commit fraud"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Risk of management overriding controls"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Population of fraud risks 1. Fraud risks can be classified into the following major areas:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraudulent financial reporting (e.g., inappropriately reported revenues, expenses, assets, or liabilities)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Asset misappropriation (e.g., theft of tangible or intangible assets)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Corruption (e.g., bribes, kickbacks, aiding and abetting vendor fraud)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "External fraud (e.g., fraud committed by customers, vendors, competitors, or other third parties) 2. Other areas of fraud risk to consider include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Risk of regulatory and legal misconduct (e.g., anticompetitive practices, conflicts of interest, insider trading)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Reputational risk"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Risk to information technology"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Identifying and Mapping Existing Preventive and Detective Controls to the"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Preventive controls"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Intended to prevent fraud before it occurs"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Include: 1. Bringing awareness of the fraud risk management program to personnel throughout the organization 2. Performing background checks on employees (where permitted by law) 3. Hiring competent staff; providing them with anti-fraud training 4. Conducting exit interviews 5. Implementing policies and procedures 6. Separating duties 7. Implementing physical security measures 8. Implementing security measures to restrict electronic access to data"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Ensuring proper alignment between an individual’s authority and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "level of responsibility"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Reviewing third-party and related-party transactions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Detective controls"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Intended to detect fraud if it does occur"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Include: 1. Establishing and marketing the presence of a confidential reporting system, such as a whistleblower hotline 2. Implementing proactive controls for the fraud detection process, such as independent reconciliations, reviews, physical inspections and counts, analysis, and audits 3. Implementing proactive fraud detection procedures, such as data analysis and continuous auditing techniques 4. Performing surprise audits"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Ways Management Can Respond to Residual Fraud Risks"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Avoid the risk."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management might decide to avoid the risk by eliminating an asset or discontinuing an activity if the control measures required to protect the organization against an identified threat are too expensive."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Transfer the risk."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management might transfer some or all of the risk by purchasing fidelity insurance or a fidelity bond."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Mitigate the risk."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management can mitigate the risk by implementing appropriate countermeasures, such as prevention and detection controls."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Assume the risk."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management might choose to assume the risk if it determines that the probability of occurrence and impact of loss are low."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Reporting the Fraud Risk Assessment Results"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The success of the fraud risk assessment process depends on how effectively the results are reported and what management then does with those results."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "When reporting the results of the assessment:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Report only the facts, and keep all opinions and biases out of the report."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Report the results in a way that is easy to understand and resonates with management."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Present the report in a way that focuses on what matters; clearly highlight points that are most important and that will make the most impact on the organization’s fraud risk management efforts."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Include key recommendations for actions that are clear and measurable and that will decrease fraud risks."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Making an Impact with the Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management should use the assessment results to:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Begin a dialogue across the company."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Look for fraud in high-risk areas."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Hold responsible parties accountable for progress."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Keep the assessment process active and relevant."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Modify or create the code of conduct or ethics policy."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Monitor key controls."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Fraud Risk Assessment and the Audit Process"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fraud risk assessment should play a significant role in informing and influencing the audit process."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fraud risk assessment should motivate thinking and awareness in the development of audit programs for areas that have been identified as having a moderate-to-high risk of fraud."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Auditors should validate that the organization is appropriately managing the moderate-to-high fraud risks identified in the fraud risk assessment by:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identifying and mapping the existing preventive and detective controls that pertain to the moderate-to-high fraud risks identified in the fraud risk assessment"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Designing and performing tests to evaluate whether the identified controls are operating effectively and efficiently"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Identifying within the moderate-to-high fraud risk areas whether there is a moderate-to-high risk of management overriding internal controls"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Developing and delivering reports that incorporate the results of auditors’ validation and testing of the fraud risk controls"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The risk that an organization might be victimized by an individual who is able to combine the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "three elements of the Fraud Triangle is called ______________."}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Environmental risk"}, {"type": "para", "text": "In response to a risk identified during a fraud risk assessment, management chooses to accept"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the risk rather than implement any responsive measures. This approach is known as:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Transferring the risk"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Mitigating the risk"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Assessment"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following factors influences the level of fraud risk encountered by an"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. The geographic regions in which it operates"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. The effectiveness of its anti-fraud controls"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. The ethics of its leadership team"}], "ai_summary": "A major concern of individuals who wish to report misconduct in the workplace is the fear of being retaliated against for their disclosure. Retaliation occurs when an employer takes any adverse action against an employee that would dissuade a reasonable person from raising a"}, {"domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Risk Management", "summary_short": "What pressures and opportunities exist that enable fraud within the organization? How might a fraud perpetrator exploit weaknesses in the system of controls? How could a perpetrator override or circumvent controls?", "structured": [{"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "What Is Risk Management?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "In Enterprise Risk Management—Integrating with Strategy and Performance, the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO) defines enterprise risk management (ERM) as “the culture, capabilities, and practices, integrated with strategy-setting and its performance, that organizations rely on to manage risk in creating, preserving, and realizing value.”"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves the identification, prioritization, treatment, and monitoring of risks that threaten an organization’s ability to provide value to its stakeholders"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves balancing risk appetite—how much risk management is willing to accept—with the ability to meet the organization’s strategic, operational, reporting, and compliance objectives"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "COSO Enterprise Risk Management—Integrating with Strategy and Performance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Composed of a set of principles organized into five components and twenty supporting principles that are based on a holistic view of an organization’s risk portfolio"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The five components are:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Governance and culture 1. The organization’s governance and culture form the foundation for the ERM program. 2. Governance sets the organizational tone, reinforces the importance of risk management, and establishes the oversight responsibilities for managing risks, while culture is reflected in decision-making."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Strategy and objective-setting 1. ERM is integrated into the organization’s strategic plan through the formal process of setting strategy and defining business objectives."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Management"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Performance 1. The actual performance of ERM within an organization involves identifying and assessing risks that might affect the organization’s ability to meet its strategic and business objectives and then prioritizing and responding to those risks."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Review and revision 1. As part of its ERM activities, the organization should review how well the ERM capabilities and practices have increased value over time and how they will continue to drive value for the organization."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Under this component, the organization:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Assesses substantial changes that might affect its strategy and objectives"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reviews its risk and performance"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Pursues improvement in ERM"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Information, communication, and reporting 1. Communication is defined as “the continual, iterative process of obtaining information and sharing it throughout the entity.” 2. Management must use information gathered from both internal and external sources to support ERM."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "ISO 31000"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) has developed ISO 31000:2018, a set of international standards providing principles and guidance on risk management."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The following eight ISO 31000:2018 principles provide that an effective and efficient risk management program:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Is integrated into all organizational activities"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Is structured and comprehensive"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Management"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Is customized and proportionate to the organization’s operations and objectives"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Is inclusive and provides for appropriate and timely consideration of stakeholders’ knowledge, views, and perceptions"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Is dynamic and responsive to change"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Is based upon the best available information"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Takes human and cultural factors into account"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Facilitates continuous improvement"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Managing Third-Party Fraud Risks"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To protect themselves from risks, it is important for organizations to implement proper due diligence procedures and compliance requirements when engaging in transactions with third parties, such as vendors and customers."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Customer due diligence (CDD)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "There are three levels of due diligence procedures that organizations can use based on the level of risk a potential customer presents. 1. Simplified CDD"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The lowest level of due diligence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most appropriate in situations where there is little opportunity or risk of a customer engaging in illegal activity"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Only requirement is to identify the customer 2. Standard CDD"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most widely used in situations where the customer presents a risk (i.e., there is some opportunity for the customer to engage in illegal activity), but it is unlikely that the risk will manifest"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Involves identifying the customer and verifying their identity"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Management"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Enhanced CDD"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Used when customers present higher risks for engaging in illegal activity"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Prompted by factors such as high-profile customers, largevalue transactions, or foreign business dealings in countries known for corruption"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Under enhanced due diligence procedures, the following customer elements should be examined with a greater level of scrutiny:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Identity (i.e., Is the customer who they claim to be?)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Source of income and overall net worth (i.e., Can the customer pay for the transaction, especially if they are requesting to pay on credit?)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Expected pattern of purchasing (i.e., Is this a onetime transaction or a series of transactions?)"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Expected value (i.e., How large is the cumulative financial risk?)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Expected method of payment (i.e., Is the customer requesting to use a higher-risk payment method, such as a personal check or line of credit?)"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Vendor due diligence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management should conduct proper due diligence when seeking new vendors or evaluating the relationship of existing vendors to prevent and detect misconduct."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Effective practices that organizations should take when developing a vendor due diligence program include: 1. Using third-party questionnaires"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Management"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Before entering into a relationship with a new vendor, management should seek to obtain information from the vendor by using a questionnaire."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Questionnaires provide background information about the vendor that can be cross-referenced during a background check. 2. Assessing vendor commitment to compliance and ethics"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An organization can assess a vendor’s commitment to compliance and ethics by performing the following due diligence procedures:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ensure that vendors have their own ethics and compliance program before engaging in any transactions."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Provide the vendor with the organization’s code of conduct and require the vendor’s agents to sign and agree to abide by the code."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Inquire about the vendor’s internal audit department and the types of audits the vendor is subject to."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Include contract clauses that require vendors to report any misconduct."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Alert the vendor that they will be liable for any unethical conduct that occurs in doing business with the organization."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Who Is Responsible for Managing Fraud Risk?"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "According to the Fraud Risk Management Guide, a joint publication by COSO and the ACFE, “personnel at all levels of the organization—including every level of management, staff, and internal auditors—have responsibility for managing fraud risk.”"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Management"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The Board of Directors’ Role"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Recognize the true and specific risks of fraud to the organization, as well as their potential impact, and respond by:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Setting an appropriate tone and realistic expectations of management to enforce an anti-fraud culture"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Gaining sufficient knowledge of the organization’s activities and the environments in which it operates"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Raising awareness of the risks of fraud throughout the organization"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Developing a strategy to assess and manage fraud risks that aligns with the organization’s risk appetite and strategic plans"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Overseeing the organization’s fraud risk management activities"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Maintaining open communications with senior management and other personnel"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Audit Committee’s Role"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Oversee the organization’s financial, accounting, and audit matters and report to the full board of directors."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Actively oversee the assessment and monitoring of the organization’s fraud risks by:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Receiving regular reports on the status of reported or alleged fraud"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Being aware of fraud risks that are common in the organization’s industry"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Meeting regularly with key internal parties (e.g., the chief audit executive [CAE] or other senior financial persons) to discuss identified fraud risks and the steps being taken to prevent and detect fraud"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Understanding how internal and external audit strategies address fraud risk"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Providing external auditors with evidence that the audit committee is dedicated to effective fraud risk management"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Engaging in open conversations with external auditors about any known or suspected fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Management"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Seeking advice of legal counsel whenever it deals with allegations of fraud"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Senior Management’s Role"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Hold the primary responsibility for designing, implementing, monitoring, and improving the fraud risk management program, which involves:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Being extremely familiar with the organization’s fraud risks"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Ensuring that the organization has specific and effective internal controls in place to prevent and detect fraud"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Setting a tone at the top and monitoring the company culture to ensure that it appropriately supports the organization’s fraud prevention and detection strategies"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Clearly communicating—both in words and actions—that fraud is not tolerated"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Taking all reports of fraud seriously and undertaking investigations for any such reports deemed reliable"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Punishing perpetrators of discovered fraud appropriately"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Taking any steps necessary to remediate weaknesses that allowed frauds to occur"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reporting to the board of directors on a regular basis regarding the effectiveness of the organization’s fraud risk management program"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "The Objectives of a Fraud Risk Management Program"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud risk management programs must address fraud before, during, and after it occurs."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Such programs must incorporate policies and procedures designed to prevent, detect, and respond to fraud."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud prevention 1. Activities focus on proactively identifying and assessing fraud risks and taking steps to address those risks."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Fraud detection"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Management"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Activities seek to identify fraud occurrences as soon as possible"}, {"type": "para", "text": "after they begin to limit the damage done."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Fraud response 1. Investigating the allegation to determine the party or parties responsible, the means of the infraction, and the extent of the resulting damage 2. Punishing the perpetrator, whether through employment sanctions or legal action 3. Remediating the control weaknesses that allowed the fraud to be undertaken 4. Rebuilding stakeholders’ confidence in the organization"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Fraud Risk Management Principles"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To help meet the objectives of a fraud risk management program, the Fraud Risk Management Guide describes five broad principles of fraud risk management:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud risk governance 1. The organization establishes and communicates a fraud risk management program that demonstrates the expectations of the board of directors and senior management and their commitment to high integrity and ethical values regarding managing fraud risk."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Fraud risk assessment 1. The organization performs comprehensive fraud risk assessments to identify specific fraud schemes and risks, assess their likelihood and significance, evaluate existing fraud control activities, and implement actions to mitigate residual fraud risks."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Fraud control activities 1. The organization selects, develops, and deploys preventive and detective fraud control activities to mitigate the risk of fraud events occurring or not being detected in a timely manner."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Fraud investigation and corrective action"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Management"}, {"type": "num", "text": "The organization establishes a communication process to obtain"}, {"type": "para", "text": "information about potential fraud and deploys a coordinated"}, {"type": "para", "text": "approach to investigation and corrective action to address fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "appropriately and in a timely manner."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud risk management monitoring activities 1. The organization selects, develops, and performs ongoing evaluations to ascertain whether each of the five principles of fraud risk management is present and functioning, and communicates deficiencies in the fraud risk management program in a timely manner to parties responsible for taking corrective action, including senior management and the board of directors."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Developing a Fraud Risk Management Program"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Define program objectives."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Tailor detailed objectives of the fraud risk management program to the organization’s specific needs and goals."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Balance the following factors in determining the program’s objectives: 1. The investment in anti-fraud controls 2. The prevention of frauds that are material in nature or amount 3. Management’s risk appetite"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Define risk appetite."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Without an adequate understanding and articulation of just how much risk those charged with governance are willing to accept, any stated objectives of the fraud risk management program will be inaccurate."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Risk appetite should be expressed in a manner that is appropriate for the organization’s culture and operations, and it can be measured and expressed either qualitatively—low, medium, or high, for example—or quantitatively, using a numeric scale."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Examine previous fraud incidents."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Management"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Examine previous occurrences of fraud and explore how management’s ideal fraud risk management program would have prevented, detected, and responded to them."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ensure compliance."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The fraud risk management program must include systems specifically designed to monitor, identify, and address breaches in compliance. 1. Such breaches might include failures in the design or operation of anti-fraud controls, as well as outright occurrences of fraud."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A specific individual or team should be assigned responsibility for monitoring compliance with the fraud risk management program and for managing suspected instances of noncompliance."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Formal sanctions for intentional noncompliance must be well-publicized and carried out in a consistent and firm manner."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Risk Management"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Of the following parties, who is responsible for developing a strategy to assess and manage"}, {"type": "para", "text": "fraud risks that aligns with the organization’s risk appetite and strategic plans?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. The legal department"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. The audit committee"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. The board of directors"}, {"type": "para", "text": "As part of its fraud-related responsibilities, the audit committee of an organization’s board of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "directors should meet regularly with key internal parties, such as the chief audit executive"}, {"type": "para", "text": "(CAE), to discuss identified fraud risks and the steps being taken to prevent and detect fraud."}], "ai_summary": "What pressures and opportunities exist that enable fraud within the organization? How might a fraud perpetrator exploit weaknesses in the system of controls? How could a perpetrator override or circumvent controls?"}, {"domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "topic": "Fraud Prevention Programs", "summary_short": "15. The organization assesses substantial changes that might affect its strategy and objectives. 16. The organization reviews its risk and performance. COSO ERM 2017 defines communication as “the continual, iterative process of obtaining", "structured": [{"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Procedures and Mechanisms to Prevent Fraud"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Increasing the perception of detection"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Most experts agree that it is much easier to prevent fraud than to detect it."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Increasing the perception of detection might be the most effective fraud prevention method."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Controls are not very effective in preventing theft and fraud if those at risk do not know of the presence of possible detection."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Proactive audit procedures"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Can be used to demonstrate management’s intention to aggressively look for possible fraudulent conduct instead of waiting for instances to be reported"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Such techniques include the following: 1. Use of analytical review procedures 2. Data and transaction monitoring and analysis 3. Fraud assessment questioning 4. Surprise audits where possible"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employee anti-fraud education"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Each entity should have a policy for educating managers, executives, and employees about fraud. 1. Can be accomplished through memoranda, organization-wide emails and voice mails, formal training programs, and other intercompany communication methods"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Every employee within the organization should be required to participate in the fraud awareness training program."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Managers and executives should receive special training that addresses the added fraud prevention and detection responsibility—and ability— provided by their authority positions."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention Programs"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Formal fraud awareness training should be an ongoing process that begins at the time of hire."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees should also participate in refresher training at least annually to help keep the program active and engrained in their minds."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "All employees should sign an annual statement acknowledging their understanding of and commitment to the program."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Formal anti-fraud training can take many forms, including live, in-class instruction; recorded video or animated courses; or interactive self-study programs."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The organization can use other informal means to reinforce its anti-fraud stance on a more constant basis, such as periodic newsletters, notices in break rooms, and other casual reminders."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The following topics should form the basis of a company’s fraud awareness training: 1. What fraud is, including examples of what behavior is acceptable and what is not 2. How fraud hurts the organization 3. How fraud hurts employees 4. Common characteristics that lead individuals to commit fraud 5. How to identify fraud (i.e., specific examples of financial, transactional, and other red flags to watch out for) 6. How to report fraud 7. The punishment for dishonest acts, including examples of past transgressions and how they were managed"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Effective management oversight"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Employees who steal often use the proceeds for lifestyle improvements (e.g., expensive cars or extravagant vacations), so managers should be educated to be observant of these signs."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention Programs"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Employees should know that supervisors are watching for unexplained or suspicious anomalies of this nature."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Reporting programs"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An anonymous reporting channel, such as an ethics hotline, is an integral part of an anti-fraud control system."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Employees must be made aware of the existence of the reporting mechanism, taught how to use it, and able to trust that they can report suspicious activity anonymously or confidentially (where permitted by law) without fear of reprisal."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "It should be made clear to employees that reports of suspicious activity will be promptly and thoroughly evaluated."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The following should be emphasized when educating employees about the reporting program: 1. Fraud, waste, and abuse occur in nearly all companies. 2. Such conduct costs the company jobs and profits. 3. The company actively encourages any employee with information to disclose it. 4. The employee can provide information anonymously and without fear of retaliation for good-faith reporting. 5. There is an exact method for reporting an incident (e.g., a telephone number or online form). 6. The report need not be made to one’s immediate superiors."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Whistleblower support and protections"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A major concern of individuals who wish to report misconduct in the workplace is the fear of being retaliated against for their disclosure."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Regardless of available legal protections for whistleblowers, organizations can empower employees who wish to disclose information without fear of negative consequences by creating a safe environment for them to voice their concerns. This can be accomplished"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention Programs"}, {"type": "para", "text": "by implementing a clear whistleblower policy that details standard"}, {"type": "para", "text": "reporting protocols and the consequences for retaliating against"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "The whistleblower policy should: 1. Emphasize that it applies to all employees, regardless of their positions or seniority, as well as to anyone external to the organization who has knowledge of potential wrongdoing by any employees or on the company’s part. 2. Detail what types of misconduct to report, how to report concerns, and any rewards available for disclosing credible information. 3. Include an anti-retaliation component that details the protections the organization affords to whistleblowers and how people will be punished if they violate the policy."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "It is important for management to establish and publicize the organization’s whistleblower procedures so that individuals both inside and outside the organization are aware of the appropriate channels for reporting misconduct."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Tone at the top"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To achieve an organizational culture with a strong value system founded on integrity, management must show employees through its words and actions that dishonest or unethical behavior will not be tolerated."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Management must create an environment in which employees feel safe to challenge management’s decisions or speak up if they think something is wrong."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A culture that encourages employees to share their concerns can reduce the risk of fraud significantly because employees often feel more loyal to their superiors."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention Programs"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Such a culture might also prevent unethical behavior because issues of anger or stress can be addressed before they escalate to the point of a fraud."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management must demonstrate ethics to model the behavior that is expected of the staff."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When management believes and acts as though it is “above the law” with respect to company policies, staff members are much less likely to follow rules."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When management acts ethically and follows organizational policies, the staff tends to respect and appreciate the behavior and copy it."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Organizational structure"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A well-designed organizational structure—with key areas of authority and clear and proper lines of reporting—can be an effective fraud prevention measure."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Establishing and communicating the proper flow of information to everyone in the organization (e.g., through the use of flowcharts displaying organizational and departmental hierarchies) is an essential component of a well-designed organizational structure. i."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Before hiring anyone, management should conduct a background check (where and to the extent permitted by law) to find out as much as possible about the employee’s previous experience with employers and law enforcement."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "At a minimum, employers should check the background of any employee who will have access to cash, checks, credit card numbers, or any other items that are easily stolen."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Background checks should also be conducted on existing employees who are being promoted or moved to positions that include access to sensitive or valuable company resources."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention Programs"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When possible and legally permissible, employers should conduct a background check in which they verify position, dates of employment, and eligibility for rehire with past employers. j."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Performance management and measurement"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is important to place employees in situations where they can thrive without resorting to unethical conduct."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Organizations should provide employees with well-defined job descriptions and performance goals."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Performance goals should be routinely reviewed to ensure that they do not set unrealistic standards."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Training (including ethics training) should be provided on a consistent basis to ensure that employees maintain the skills needed to perform their tasks effectively."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Care should be taken to set performance goals that motivate employees to challenge themselves but are not so ambitious that the only way they can meet them is to perpetrate fraud."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Including ethics-based metrics as a component of performance goals and evaluation can be an especially effective way to foster ethical behavior and reinforce the importance of ethics as the guiding factor in making business decisions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Handling known fraud incidents"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It must be emphasized to all employees that the company maintains a policy of zero tolerance for fraud."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "By not consistently punishing perpetrators, a company renders its fraud prevention program less effective or useless."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Reporting known incidents of fraud to law enforcement can be an effective step in making the organization’s zero-tolerance stance clear. l."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Minimizing employee pressures"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention Programs"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Organizations should be mindful of the pressures (e.g., financial hardships or family problems) that can lead to fraud and should take steps to increase managers’ awareness of such potential problems, as well as to assist an employee who might be experiencing difficult times."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Ways to minimize pressures include: 1. Open-door policies"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An open-door policy that allows employees to speak honestly about pressures can provide management with the opportunity to alleviate such pressures before they become acute, which will help prevent fraud. 2. Fair personnel policies and procedures"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ensuring that personnel policies and procedures are fair and equitably applied can boost morale and thereby reduce fraud risk. 3. Employee support programs"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Examples include programs providing alcohol and drug assistance, as well as counseling for gambling, family and marital problems, and financial difficulties."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Making such programs available to employees who are facing personal problems shows employees that management cares for their well-being, which can reduce an employee’s ability to rationalize a dishonest act."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Creating an Anti-Fraud Policy"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A written anti-fraud policy should specifically indicate who in an organization manages varying fraud matters under differing circumstances."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Among other things, the anti-fraud policy might include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A policy statement that formally defines fraud and outlines management’s position or attitude toward fraud in the workplace"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A section defining who is responsible for fraud prevention and detection"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention Programs"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A section detailing specific examples of actions that constitute fraud so management has the legal grounds to investigate and punish violators"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "A section explaining who will investigate suspected irregularities and to whom such irregularities will be reported"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Communicating the Anti-Fraud Policy"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management must periodically and appropriately communicate the company’s anti-fraud policy to all employees and third parties."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Legal Considerations Regarding the Anti-Fraud Policy"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is best to detail specific unacceptable conduct to avoid legal problems in terminating a dishonest employee."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Management should consult legal counsel regarding any necessary legal considerations with respect to the anti-fraud policy."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "One of the most important legal considerations is to ensure that all allegations and offenders are managed uniformly."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Developing an Ethics Program"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A written ethics policy enables management to objectively communicate its ethical philosophy and provides a foundation for a successful ethics program."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Should be shared among both new and old employees"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Should be given to vendors and posted on the company’s website or social media platforms"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Gives the message that fraud is not tolerated"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Key considerations when developing an ethics program include:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Understanding why good people can commit unethical acts"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Defining current—as well as desired—organizational values"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Determining if organizational values have been properly communicated"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Determining if ethics is currently a leadership issue in the organization"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ascertaining how board members, stockholders, management, employees, and any other important members of the organization define success"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Producing written ethics policies, procedures, or structures"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention Programs"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The following components are necessary to develop, implement, and manage a comprehensive ethics program:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Focus on ethical leadership"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Vision statement"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Values statement"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Code of ethics"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Designated ethics official"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Ethics task force or committee"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Ethics communication strategy"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Ethics training"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Ethics help and fraud reporting hotlines"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ethical behavior rewards and sanctions"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Comprehensive system to monitor and track ethics data"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Periodic evaluation of ethics efforts and data"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Developing an Effective Corporate Compliance and Ethics Program"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An effective compliance program can be defined as one that is reasonably designed, implemented, and enforced so that it generally will be effective in preventing and detecting criminal conduct."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "To have an effective compliance and ethics program, the organization should:"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Exercise due diligence to prevent and detect criminal conduct."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Otherwise promote an organizational culture that encourages ethical conduct and a commitment to compliance with the law."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Elements of an effective compliance and ethics program"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The following seven factors are minimally required for a corporate compliance program to be considered effective: 1. Established standards and procedures to prevent and detect criminal conduct 2. Proper assignment of responsibility and oversight for the compliance program"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention Programs"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Due diligence in the hiring process to ensure the ethics of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "individuals who exercise a substantial measure of discretion in"}, {"type": "para", "text": "acting on an organization’s behalf"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Periodic and practical communication of the compliance policy"}, {"type": "para", "text": "through effective training programs and other means"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Steps to ensure program compliance through monitoring,"}, {"type": "para", "text": "auditing, periodically evaluating the program’s effectiveness, and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "having a publicized reporting system"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Promotion and consistent enforcement of the program through"}, {"type": "para", "text": "appropriate incentives for compliance and appropriate"}, {"type": "para", "text": "disciplinary measures for violations"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Reasonable response to any discovered criminal conduct to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "prevent further similar criminal conduct, including making any"}, {"type": "para", "text": "necessary modifications to the organization’s compliance and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention Programs"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Unless specific unacceptable conduct is detailed in an anti-fraud policy, there can be legal"}, {"type": "para", "text": "problems in terminating a dishonest employee."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Which of the following is NOT a topic that should be covered in employee anti-fraud training?"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. How fraud hurts the organization and its employees"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. What constitutes fraud, including examples of acceptable and unacceptable behavior"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Specific controls and procedures that the organization uses to detect fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "D. Common characteristics that lead individuals to commit fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention Programs"}, {"type": "para", "text": "To reinforce an anti-fraud culture, management should:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Show employees that unethical behavior will not be tolerated"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Create an environment in which employees feel safe challenging management’s"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. Visibly adhere to the same set of ethics policies that is required of all employees"}], "ai_summary": "15. The organization assesses substantial changes that might affect its strategy and objectives. 16. The organization reviews its risk and performance. COSO ERM 2017 defines communication as “the continual, iterative process of obtaining"}, {"domain": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence", "topic": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners", "summary_short": "knowledge truly unique unto itself, but it should have one that requires study, comprehension, and practice beyond the everyday abilities other people might possess. In many fields, continuing education is a hallmark of professionalism, and ongoing efforts to", "structured": [{"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Purpose of a Code of Ethical Conduct"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Serves as a reference and benchmark for ethical guidance"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Makes explicit the conduct that is expected in a particular profession"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Provides direct solutions not available from general ethics theories"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Enables individuals to have a better understanding of what is expected of them"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Makes practical enforcement and internal discipline throughout a profession easier because members are put on notice of the standards"}, {"type": "h2", "text": "Ethics and Legality"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Ethics refers to the appropriateness of a decision in consideration of morality. That is, ethics stress standards or codes of behavior expected by the group to which the individual belongs."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Legality refers to lawfulness by conformity to a legal statute."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The law is the lowest reference level for moral decisions."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "The law might permit an action that is prohibited by a profession’s code of ethics."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Laws, rules, and regulations function as standards by which to judge whether an action is legal or illegal but not whether the behavior is right."}, {"type": "h2", "text": "ACFE Code of Professional Ethics"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An ACFE Member shall, at all times, demonstrate a commitment to professionalism and diligence in the performance of their duties."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Diligence 1. Exercised by properly planning assignments and supervising assistants and colleagues, avoiding conflicts of interest, performing with competence, obtaining sufficient evidence to establish a basis for opinions, maintaining confidential relations, and avoiding distortion of facts"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An ACFE Member shall not engage in any illegal or unethical conduct, or any activity which would constitute a conflict of interest that has not been properly disclosed to the appropriate parties."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Illegal conduct 1. While some activities might be obviously illegal, the legality of others might not be as apparent. 2. Fraud examiners are generally not entitled to claim ignorance of the law."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Conflict of interest 1. Exists when a fraud examiner’s ability to objectively evaluate and present an issue for a client is impaired by a current, prior, or potential future relationship with parties to the fraud examination 2. General rules"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A fraud examiner employed full time by a company should not engage in other jobs that create a hardship or loss to the employer."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A fraud examiner should not be a spy who is employed by one company but retained by another company or person to infiltrate the employer and transmit inside information (unless the employing company agrees to the arrangement to apprehend other parties employed by the company)."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "A fraud examiner should not accept engagements from both sides to a controversy—just like lawyers are prohibited from representing both parties in a transaction, lawsuit, or trial."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Independence and objectivity"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners are responsible for maintaining independence in attitude and appearance and for approaching and conducting fraud examinations in an objective and unbiased manner."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Independence of attitude requires impartiality and fairness in conducting fraud examinations and in reaching resulting conclusions and judgments."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Objectivity refers to the ability to conduct fraud examinations without being influenced by one’s own personal feelings or the feelings and motives of others."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "To ensure objectivity in performing examinations, fraud examiners must maintain an independent mental attitude, reach judgments on examination matters without undue influence from others, and avoid being placed in positions where they would be unable to work in an objective professional manner."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "All possible conflicts of interest should be disclosed."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An ACFE Member shall, at all times, exhibit the highest level of integrity in the performance of all professional assignments, and will accept only assignments for which there is reasonable expectation that the assignment will be completed with professional competence."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Integrity 1. Requires honesty, truthfulness, trustworthiness, and confidentiality 2. Requires prioritizing the interests of clients, employers, and the public over desires for personal gain"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Requires independence of mental attitude and avoidance of"}, {"type": "para", "text": "conflicts of interest"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Requires an ability to analyze situations where no professional"}, {"type": "para", "text": "rules are specifically applicable and determine right from wrong"}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Professional competence 1. Refers to how well fraud examiners do their job 2. Fraud examiners must be competent in their respective areas and disciplines, and they shall not accept assignments where competence is lacking. 3. Fraud examiners cannot be expected to have an expert level of skill and knowledge for every circumstance that might be encountered in a fraud examination. 4. Nevertheless, fraud examiners must have sufficient skill and knowledge to recognize when additional training or expert guidance is required."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Professional skepticism 1. As part of exercising professional integrity and competence, fraud examiners must always perform their work with a mindset of professional skepticism and begin assignments with the belief that something is wrong or someone is committing a fraud. 2. Fraud examiners should relax their attitude of skepticism only when the evidence shows no signs of fraudulent activity. 3. At no time is a fraud examiner entitled to assume a fraud problem does not exist. 4. Professional skepticism can be dispelled only by evidence. 5. Opinions or attestations about a fraud-free environment are absolutely prohibited for ACFE members."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An ACFE Member will comply with the lawful orders of the courts, and will testify to matters truthfully and without bias or prejudice."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "ACFE members must comply with all lawful court orders, and they will testify to matters truthfully and without bias or prejudice."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Fraud examiners should not flee from a summons or subpoena issued by a court."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "When responding to questions in a testimonial setting, fraud examiners must deliver their answer without bias or prejudice."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An ACFE Member, in conducting examinations, will obtain evidence or other documentation to establish a reasonable basis for any opinion rendered. No opinion shall be expressed regarding the guilt or innocence of any person or party."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners must obtain evidence to establish a reasonable basis for any opinion rendered."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Fraud examiners must collect evidence, whether exculpatory or incriminating, that supports fraud examination results and will be admissible in subsequent proceedings. 1. To do so, the fraud examiner must obtain and document evidence in a manner that ensures that all necessary evidence is obtained and that the chain of custody is preserved."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "This rule also prohibits ACFE members from making statements of opinion as to the guilt or innocence of any person or party."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Determining whether a person is guilty or innocent of a crime is a decision reserved for a judge or jury, not fraud examiners."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners may draw reasonable conclusions based on the evidence; however, they must be very circumspect when doing so. Conclusions are based on observations of the evidence, whereas opinions call for an interpretation of the facts."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Opinions regarding technical matters generally are permitted if the fraud examiner is qualified as an expert in the matter."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An ACFE Member shall not reveal any confidential information obtained during a professional engagement without proper authorization."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Confidential information 1. Fraud examiners must not disclose confidential information obtained during a professional engagement without appropriate authorization. 2. Confidential information is any and all information a fraud examiner might obtain in the course of work, whether it be from the company or client for whom the work is performed or from any other source consulted during the work. 3. If the client or employer consents to disclosure of information otherwise considered confidential, then the fraud examiner can transmit it to others."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners should be careful to let the client or employer know what the consent covers."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "It is still best to let the client or employer make the actual disclosure themselves. 4. Fraud examiners are not bound by confidentiality when doing so would violate the law."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Fraud examiners can reveal client confidences when responding to a legal court order. 5. The confidentiality rule does not permit disclosure after a case concludes, and fraud examiners are not permitted to disclose confidential information if they resign, retire, or are fired from an employing organization."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Privileged information 1. Fraud examiners must not disclose privileged information obtained during a professional engagement without appropriate authority."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Privileged information is information that cannot be demanded,"}, {"type": "para", "text": "even by a court; it is information that is protected by law from"}, {"type": "num", "text": "Even though the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics does not"}, {"type": "para", "text": "assume a privileged status for the fraud examiner-client/employer"}, {"type": "para", "text": "relationship, fraud examiners must not disclose privileged"}, {"type": "para", "text": "information without proper authorization from the fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "examiner’s client or employer."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "Confidentiality and whistleblowing 1. Fraud examiners are not obligated to blow the whistle on clients or employers, but circumstances might exist in which they are morally and legally justified in making disclosures to appropriate outside parties. 2. Such circumstances include when a client or employer has intentionally involved a fraud examiner in its illegal conduct or when a client or employer has distributed misleading reports based on the fraud examiner’s work. 3. A fraud examiner should not promise absolute or unconditional confidentiality or leniency to an informant to obtain testimony."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An ACFE Member shall reveal all material matters discovered during the course of an examination, which, if omitted, could cause a distortion of the facts."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "Material 1. Information is material if having knowledge of such information might reasonably be expected to influence a client’s or employer’s decisions based on a fraud examiner’s report. 2. An item of information that would change a user’s perceptions and conclusions if it were omitted from a report is considered material."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners"}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "An ACFE Member shall continually strive to increase the competence and effectiveness of professional services performed under their direction."}, {"type": "bullet", "text": "This rule instructs ACFE members to progress toward greater expertise so they can better service their clients and employers."}, {"type": "sub", "text": "CFEs must obtain twenty hours of continuing professional education (CPE) each year."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Ethics for Fraud Examiners"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Fraud Prevention and Deterrence"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Sample Prep Questions"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Robert, a Certified Fraud Examiner (CFE), is hired by a client to conduct a fraud examination. At"}, {"type": "para", "text": "the conclusion of the engagement, he issued a written report to the client and closed his file. A"}, {"type": "para", "text": "year later, Robert receives a legal order from the local prosecutor’s office to provide the report."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Under the ACFE Code of Professional Ethics, he will NOT be able to respond."}, {"type": "para", "text": "In the context of a fraud examination, a mindset of professional skepticism means:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "A. Fraud examiners should always begin their assignments with the belief that something is"}, {"type": "para", "text": "B. Fraud examiners should relax their attitude of skepticism only when the evidence shows"}, {"type": "para", "text": "C. A fraud examiner may not provide opinions or attestations about a fraud-free"}, {"type": "para", "text": "ABOUT THE ASSOCIATION OF CERTIFIED FRAUD EXAMINERS"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Founded in 1988 by Dr. Joseph T. Wells, CFE, CPA, the ACFE is the world’s largest anti-fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "organization and premier provider of anti-fraud training and education. Together with more than"}, {"type": "para", "text": "90,000 members in more than 180 countries, the ACFE is reducing business fraud worldwide and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "providing the training and resources needed to fight fraud more effectively."}, {"type": "para", "text": "The ACFE provides educational tools and practical solutions for anti-fraud professionals through"}, {"type": "para", "text": "initiatives including:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "• Global conferences and seminars led by anti-fraud experts"}, {"type": "para", "text": "• Instructor-led, interactive professional training"}, {"type": "para", "text": "• Comprehensive resources for fighting fraud, including books, self-study courses, and articles"}, {"type": "para", "text": "• Leading anti-fraud publications, including Fraud Magazine, The Fraud Examiner, and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "• Local networking and support through more than 170 ACFE chapters worldwide"}, {"type": "para", "text": "• Anti-fraud curriculum and educational tools for colleges and universities"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The positive effects of anti-fraud training are far reaching. The best way to combat fraud is to"}, {"type": "para", "text": "educate anyone engaged in fighting fraud on how to effectively prevent, detect, and investigate it."}, {"type": "para", "text": "By educating, uniting, and supporting the global anti-fraud community with the tools to fight fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "more effectively, the ACFE is inspiring public confidence in the integrity and objectivity of the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Immediate access to world-class anti-fraud knowledge and tools is a necessity in the fight against"}, {"type": "para", "text": "fraud. Members of the ACFE include accountants, internal auditors, fraud investigators, law"}, {"type": "para", "text": "enforcement officers, lawyers, business leaders, risk and compliance professionals, and educators,"}, {"type": "para", "text": "all of whom have access to expert training, educational tools, and resources. Members from all"}, {"type": "para", "text": "over the world have come to depend on the ACFE for solutions to the challenges they face in their"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Whether their careers are focused exclusively on preventing and detecting fraudulent activities or"}, {"type": "para", "text": "they simply want to learn more about fraud, anti-fraud professionals turn to the ACFE for the"}, {"type": "para", "text": "essential tools and resources to accomplish their objectives. To learn more, visit ACFE.com or call"}, {"type": "para", "text": "(800) 245-3321 / +1 (512) 478-9000."}, {"type": "para", "text": "ABOUT THE ASSOCIATION OF CERTIFIED FRAUD EXAMINERS"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Certified Fraud Examiners"}, {"type": "para", "text": "The ACFE offers its members the opportunity for professional certification. The Certified Fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "Examiner (CFE) credential is preferred by businesses and government entities around the world"}, {"type": "para", "text": "and indicates expertise in fraud prevention and detection."}, {"type": "para", "text": "Certified Fraud Examiners (CFEs) are anti-fraud experts who have demonstrated knowledge in"}, {"type": "para", "text": "four critical areas: financial transactions and fraud schemes, law, investigation, and fraud"}, {"type": "para", "text": "prevention and deterrence. In support of CFEs and the CFE credential, the ACFE:"}, {"type": "para", "text": "• Provides bona fide qualifications for CFEs through administration of the CFE Exam"}, {"type": "para", "text": "• Requires CFEs to adhere to a strict code of professional conduct and ethics"}, {"type": "para", "text": "• Serves as the global representative for CFEs to business, government, and academic"}, {"type": "para", "text": "• Provides leadership to inspire public confidence in the integrity, objectivity, and"}, {"type": "para", "text": "professionalism of CFEs"}], "ai_summary": "knowledge truly unique unto itself, but it should have one that requires study, comprehension, and practice beyond the everyday abilities other people might possess. In many fields, continuing education is a hallmark of professionalism, and ongoing efforts to"}]};